I'm Julien Le Breton and as my name doesn't suggest, I was born and live in New Caledonia.
Here, I'd like to introduce you to Leptomyrmex and here, Rhytidoponera.
These are two ant species native to New Caledonia.
I've had the opportunity to study ants for a number of years, and the thing that fascinated me with ants, like with many of you I guess, was their self-organization. Ants do not have leaders, yet all of them, wherever they are and with the information available to them in their immediate environment, do well, so consequently the collective progresses well.
After a few years, I earned a PhD in Community Ecology on the subject of invasive ants.
These ants, when introduced into areas, see their populations exploding, and they have a major impact on biodiversity.
Here is the yellow crazy ant, originated in India, and the awful fire ant, a monster of 1.5 mm in size but with such a violent sting that in the areas it lives, everyone ends up leaving.
In New Caledonia, invasive ants are considered one of the biggest threats to our biodiversity.
Convinced by the need to protect this biodiversity, my first reflex has been to fight them, and I've been involved in many extensive eradication programs in which we were using helicopters to spread poison bait over the forests.
However, when I looked closely at my data, my years of observations, the tens of thousands of remarks collected from all over the country, I realized that these ants are only present and only truly invasive, in areas disturbed or damaged by humans - and we know well how to do this! -
in the areas where we throw our waste, in the places that we destroy in order to take the resources, in environments burnt down by fires.
I took this photo yesterday, in my community in Païta where 1,600 hectares of vegetation disappeared in just one day.
And the craziest part is that it's in the environments where we produce our own food that we have the least biodiversity: a single plant species and almost no animals.
I started to ask myself, does the ants really deserve this fight?
Was eradicating invasive ants really going to have a positive impact on the biodiversity on our island?
When I was a child, I imagined that the future was like this, full of technology, and that all this technology was going to help us in our development.
However, when we look at resource consumption, we see that we're arriving at a peak.
At the energy level resources will run out, but also the other resources.
And in New Caledonia, we know that we'll have to choose between exploiting these resources and protecting our environment.
Numerous signs are showing that now, our civilization is on the verge of collapse.
It has already happened in the past and it might come true again.
And what is likely to happen won't be like Star Trek but more like Mad Max.
And in that case, the strongest will fight for control of resources, and I'll surely play no part in that.
So, I wanted to make a change, do something different, something more resilient for Nature.
After having fought against the ants at first, I fought against the perpetrators or rather those I held responsible: the big multinationals, the media, certain political entities... And throughout meetings where I met other activists - I was one myself - I realized that many people who were fighting wanted the decision-makers to impose policies for them to change their own lives.
And some of them had been waiting for thirty years for these policies to take place.
I'm not a big fan of waiting.
So, I started to act independently and decided to regain the control over the fulfillment of my needs.
And my needs, what are they?
They're the same as most animals.
The first one is the need for water and food; the second is a suitable habitat; and the third, strong social relationships.
We are social animals; without these social relationships, we'd wither.
So my family and I decided to buy a plot of land in the forest and go back to a more autonomous lifestyle.
The problem was I wasn't from an agricultural background.
But I studied ecology, so I thought that'd be enough.
When we found ourselves in this forest, our first thought was to cut all the trees down, loosen the soil, plant some seeds and water them.
The first year, results were amazing, the second year, a bit less, and the third year, nothing.
We had managed to destroy the soil despite being in a forest.
That's when, thanks to the internet, and especially to all the discussions of those experimenting in the world and sharing their knowledge on YouTube through videos, we then discovered permaculture, the concept of permaculture.
Permaculture's mantra is to take Nature as a model.
We thought, "Why not, in our fields, our agricultural world, draw inspiration from Nature too?"
Indeed, when we look at a forest, it definitely doesn't need humans to function.
It doesn't need watering, fertilizer, nor someone to take care of its seeds, yet everything works.
Even in the city, just look at the neglected uncultivated lands: withing a few months, the vegetation comes back on its own.
So why not apply that when we work on a field?
What motivated me most are all these before-and-after images.
In a few months, we can come up with something greatly productive, either in a small scale or a bigger scale.
In Nature, basically, plants are what will create the first bricks of life.
Through photosynthesis, they capture light energy, CO2, and create the first building blocks that will then feed the entire system.
That's what we've done in our gardens.
Everything we typically call "green waste",
hop! we lay it on the ground.
It allows us to cover the ground, and covering the ground is very, very important!
A bare land is like a house without a roof.
From afar, it all sounds good, but you can't live in it.
Sun's rays would roast anything inside it, and if it rained, everything would be flooded.
So, covering the ground is crucial.
Further more, covering it will bring lots of fungi and other insects that will work at breaking it down and convert it into humus, just like in forests, a layer of humus on the ground's surface.
We see humus all over the forests but never in our fields.
Here it is, this is our field.
As you can see there's no bare ground - everything is covered - and there is also a wide diversity of plants.
Now, I'd like you to meet all my co-workers, from the smallest to the biggest!
And in many fields including organic ones, animals are separated into two main categories.
On one side we have our helpers who are beneficial and desirable, and on the other side, the harmful pests, those we never want to see there.
But if we give forests a closer look, these harmful pests are in fact decomposers.
They are the ones that support natural selection, that will remove all the weak plants and ensure that the grand cycle of Nature runs on its own.
If we take them out, the system stops working.
And since our goal is to produce food in the most natural way, we use all these animals, especially pests, as assistants to natural selection.
Now they are the best helpers to select the plants that are best suited to our environment.
Something else I learned during all these years is that previously, when I'd put a plant in the ground, I'd think it will be able to make it on its own, it will manage to find resources where it was and grow.
However, what modern science and agroecology show us, is that the organism isn't the plant we grow.
In Nature, the organism is the entire forest, and each plant is just an organ within it.
Each plant serves a purpose.
Our heart, if it is removed from us, if it's not nourished, if there is no water, no vitamins, on its own, it can't stay alive.
That's exactly what happens in our agricultural system: when we isolate a tree, we must water it, add fertilizer, and take care of it because it's disconnected from the other trees.
In Europe's big forests, it's been shown that in the fall, when the deciduous trees lose their leaves, they become weak.
And the conifers are the ones, via their roots and fungi network, that feed them to help them through this difficult period.
At springtime, when the deciduous trees regain life and grow leaves again, they give back to the conifers the nutrition given earlier.
And that is very important.
Here is the fungus mycelium that provides the connections between all these plants.
This mycelium is found in the humus layer, hence the importance of having this layer.
Everything happens on the surface.
We often think that it happens underneath, but a large amount of things happen on the surface.
Here is the field.
In recent months, my colleague and I have been putting fresh wood on the ground to encourage all these myceliums and the interconnection between all the plants.
We joke saying we're working for "Plant Telecom".
We install an optical fiber between all our plants through which they'll on their own be able to exchange food, water, and most importantly, information.
Yes, plants exchange information, particularly when one of them is attacked by, let's say, the pest.
In fact, it will transmit the information to all the rest, so the other plants can prepare.
All of this has also been an opportunity to rediscover a lot of vegetables that I didn't know from Europe but have been present in the Pacific for thousands of years.
All those plants have been selected by our friends the pests, so they're particularly adapted to our area.
Because a major problem in Caledonia is that our stomachs were often left behind in Europe, meaning that we eat European vegetables and we haven't transitioned to all these plants.
Yet, these plants have many advantages.
Here is the "chou kanak," a type of edible hibiscus.
The WHO has said that it's the first vegetable we should give to young babies.
Well, the WHO is no small fish; I think it can be trusted.
After a few years, since we started producing slightly more than our consumption, we decided we're going to go to the markets to showcase all these vegetables to consume-actors, trade and start living from it.
The first time, we came back home with all our vegetables because people didn't know them.
They didn't really feel like eating them.
So we figured that we needed to process them.
We started by making flour with the different taros, yams, and pigeon peas.
And at the markets, here is what we offer.
Apart from the salt and oil, everything is from our field, even the banana leaf packaging.
What is awesome with this is that we've increased the value of these vegetables four-fold, if not eight-fold.
It means that we started to have an economic system that works, and that's very important!
Another economic system is the permacultural farm called Bec Hellouin, in France.
Maybe some of you have heard of it.
The INRA has just proved that by using this kind of agriculture on 1;000 m2, a vegetable producer can have an income that matches or even exceeds what could be earn using other agricultural systems.
Another example of abundance is in an place in Brazil that shares the same environmental conditions with Caledonia regarding the soil and the climate.
Ernst Gotsch developed a system called "syntropy," 25 years ago.
It's also agroecology, but he called it syntropy.
In this system, you can produce up to 66 tons per hectare per year without any input from external elements.
It means the whole system produces food for the whole system to work.
And that's very important in New Caledonia.
The administrative services did a 10-year study that shows that here, in order to maintain a steady agricultural production, double the amount of fertilizer was necessary.
It's an indicator that our soils are truly exhausted, and that if we don't act quickly, we will encounter major problems.
No matter the agricultural policies we apply to achieve food autonomy, it won't do any good if we need outside fertilizer.
So, we really need to develop systems able to function internally.
And this is one of them, and it is important..
I assure you that once these principles are implemented, everybody can start to produce naturally as of tomorrow.
Once our bellies are full, we can think about housing.
Once again, we took our responsibilities and were ahead of the rules at the time, and we decided to build our house ourselves, with ecological materials that were recyclable for the most part: wood, earth, and stone.
This house is completely bioclimatic, and autonomous in electricity; it doesn't need air conditioning; and only 200 watts are needed to turn on all the lights.
That was how much we used for a single room when I was a child.
We also collect rainwater and use a phytopurification system and dry toilets, that way, we integrate our entire system in the cycle.
We live in a relatively isolated place, but thanks to social media, we're able to organize workshops very quickly, to which we invite people we don't know.
We send our offers to social networks, people respond, attend, and it allows us to experiment, exchange ideas, and allows people who come to take a step towards change because oftentimes, daring is difficult at home whereas it is less risky at someone else's place.
So, it's an awesome system!
It enables us to stay in touch because I'm no longer working outside from Monday to Friday.
Like I said, if I stay all alone self-reliant, in my corner, I don't see the appeal.
So, this type of workshop is very, very important.
Permaculture is about common sense.
People use that word "permaculture" but otherwise, it's common sense, a common sense that ties in with Nature's major balances and not with administrative rules.
Permaculture can also be viewed as a flower, whose first petal, that of the belly, represents agroecology which we just saw.
But this shift, permaculture's mantra is to take example from Nature.
It can be applied to various aspects of our lives, such as our housing which we also spoke about, tools and technologies: the internet has been key to gather useful information for us to move forward.
But technology can also take this form too: Do you see this leaf? It's a wild mulberry
that grows everywhere.
We can replace all badges with this leaf after today.
That's technology too!
Culture and education: by living this now, we are somehow actors of culture.
And since we have some time, I've been able to focus a bit more on music.
As for education, we've taken back the responsibility of educating our children.
Since I almost no longer live in a stressful system, you could say I feel healthier, and we've become more in tune with Nature and all its medicinal plants.
Finance and economy: when taking up alternative systems, we don't think much about it, yet money is a very important form of energy.
It's even primordial.
If we don't have enough of it, we can't leave the system.
We'll be stuck, it always bring us back.
You've to move past it, just like passing
the break of whitewater in surf.
It's the same: you need to earn enough money to get there, then this money is redistributed once your system is abundant enough.
That's exactly what happens in Nature, with water or other things: everything is shared.
And finally, living this way keeps alive both our heritage - for real, since we're in it - and our communities because we create plenty of connections through our workshops and presence at the markets in particular.
We create a kind of little network through which we exchange lots of information.
A network where you exchange lots of information sounds a bit like what I said about plants and the fungi.
And this, right here, is a network of fungi that organized itself in a box.
And here is another network you'll recognize right away: the internet.
When we put these two networks side by side, we see how similar they are.
It is rules similar to the ants' self-organization, that are doing all this and enabling the useful information to flow.
Today, when people ask me, "Julien, what do you do in life?"
I have trouble defining it because we often define ourselves by the job we have, and me, actually, I do all this.
I'm a farmer, a professor, a builder, an electrician, an active citizen, a herbalist... And all this gives more meaning to my life.
It's what enables me to be happy today.
Thank you.
(Applause)
The Mediterranean is a pair of chapped lips, whose top lip speaks in Latin, and whose bottom lip speaks in Arabic.
And when it tries to swallow, when it closes its lips, it hurts and it stings.
It suffers because there are all these borders, barbed wire, sentries and checkpoints around the Mediterranean, which prevent it from speaking.
In 2011, I was in Marseille at the time of the Arab Springs, and it felt like there were free individuals there who were speaking out again, who were refusing to be taken away in these barbed wire sacks, and were taking back their right to exist and to say what they wanted to say.
In that moment, I thought that the right thing to do was to go and listen to them.
Meaning, to no longer view the Mediterranean as a group of Nation States that do not talk to each other, but as a community of inhabitants that don't know each other very well, and to go listen to them and create a giant library, a communal database, copyright free, a library of true stories from the inhabitants of the Mediterranean, in every Mediterranean language.
In 2013, I proposed this in Marseille, which was then Cultural Capital.
So, from December 2011, I embarked on my little speaking tour.
I started in Barcelona, I wasn't too sure how to do it at first, so I went to see people on benches, and little by little, we came up with a number of options to collect these stories.
You can collect true stories, just by being face-to-face with someone you've met.
It's possible to do this together here. You'll all come up and tell a true story.
We can have candlelight vigils, we can make discussion tables, etc.
There are so many ways to collect them.
There are so many ways to reproduce these stories, too.
All of the arts obviously can retell these stories.
So I began like this in Spain.

Next I was in Morocco in January of 2012.
Then in Algeria, and there, the project took off because there was a huge amount of Algerian stories that came in both in text-form on the website, which gathered them, and then I met tons of people.
So there, the collection really got going in February 2012.
Then I was in Tunisia, and there as well, there were really amazing meetings.
Following that, I wasn't able to go to Libya with what was going on, and so I went to Egypt.
I arrived in Lebanon and continued to collect stories. I was in Beirut a lot. At one point, I was invited to Hammana, which is a little town on the uplands of Mount Lebanon, a little town with a Christian majority, about 45 minutes from Beirut.
I arrived there and the people were waiting for me.
Everyone was in the library, it was like a candlelight vigil, but in the middle of all these books.
And there, we all took turns speaking. I told a story, and the people, the eldest, the youngest, in French, in Arabic, told their stories to each other.
They chose - and this is what I asked the people each time - from the story of their lives, from birth up until now, "What would be the story that you want to share with the rest of the world?
What would be the incredible anecdote you have in your heart, that's dear to you and that you want to pool in a large library?"
And with that, I had tons of stories, and then we met for drinks at the end. There was a woman named Samira Fakhoury who was the library head, who said to me, "There is one story that I haven't told."
It takes place in 1976.
It was the first year of the Lebanese civil war, it was also the year when the Syrian army came to occupy Lebanon.
Especially in Hammana, they set up channels to bombard Beirut, and waited for the counterattack.
When Samira and her husband saw this, they decided to get the children to safety in the Beqaa Valley, next to Zahlé, while they stayed in Hammana to take care of the family houses so that they wouldn't be pillaged.
So there were three homes, and they stayed, they had a grandmother in one of the other houses, and the other was requisitioned by Syrian officers, so they lived in one of their houses.
They were neighbors,
and in the Spring, like every year, Samira and her husband argue.
And they always argue over the same thing: the poplars.
They have four poplars that are next to the garden, and I don't know if you've seen, but the poplars make little cotton balls, buds, and those balls get all over the gardens, and every Spring, it's the same thing, Samira's husband tells her, "This is the last year, 'khalass', those poplars, I'm going to get rid of them, I'm going to chop down the poplars."
And Samira tells him, "But you don't want to do that!
We've got to live with the trees, they give us shade in the summer."
And at that moment, there's a Syrian officer who's passing by and hears this and it's the first time he's heard them argue.
He says, "Is there a problem, Mrs.Fakhouri?"
She is so upset after her husband, and maybe it's the tension linked to the occupation and the war as well. She looks at the officer like this and says, "It's my husband, he's going to divorce me.
that's it. He wants to divorce me."
The Syrian officer there and hears this, and we don't know what he has, but it just so happens that he's moved, maybe it's been months since he's seen his wife too, and there he says,
"But why? He can't do that...
He can't make this decision. He has to reflect on it longer!
Mariage is sacred!
He can't divorce you like that, Mrs.Fakhouri.
You are a very good wife, etc." Samira says to him, "He wants to divorce me, and Mister Syrian Officer, I'll tell you why."
The Syrian officer says, "No, I don't want to know anything.
Listen, it's your personal history.
It's your private life, I don't want to know anything."
She says to him, "Yeah, yeah, yeah, I want to tell you why.
You see these poplars, Mister Syrian Officer, you see these four poplars, well they make those little cotton balls.
They fall and get all over his garden. He was to cut down the poplars, and I don't want him to, so he's going to divorce me."
The Syrian officer looks at her like this, and says, "That's your problem, Mrs.Fakhouri?"
That's your problem?"
So he goes back and calls his soldiers.
He calls them like animals,
he says, " 'Hayawan'! Come my soldiers.
Gather around Mrs.Fakhouri's garden."
All the soldiers gather.
The officer says, "You see these four poplars?"
The soldiers, "Yes, we see the four poplars."
"Well soldiers, you're going to pick all the buds from the poplars."
And then Samira says to me, "I saw the Syrian army, climbing three-by-three up into my poplars - I wanted to take a photo, but I didn't dare - and delicately pick the buds from these poplars, then climb down and put them in bags.
And I thought, "Now, this Syrian officer has a heart!
He was scared for my marriage."
She tells me this, and with that, the evening was over.
And then I continue my trek.
I went to Turkey next, a lot of time in Izmir.
In Greece, in Athens.
In Sicily, I only did Sicily in Italy.
I finished with Israel, where I spent bit of time in Tel-Aviv, in the Kibbutz, in Haifa, in Nazareth.
And then in Palestine, where I started in Hebron, which was a real shock, then Ramallah, then Nablus, then Bethlehem.
And then I spent some time writing from all these stories that had been collected, in two different forms: the stories, to redistribute them, to retell them to the people.
In book form, "The Moon in the Well" which is the collection of true stories, where I give the example, and that's what I would like us all to try together, each time we tell each other a true story, I don't know if you've done it when I told you this story about the poplars in bloom, but we'll end by reflecting on ourselves in the mirror, on our own true stories.
And so in this book, "The Moon in the Well", I am also telling my own true stories, from birth up until now.
I did it, I made sound creations for ARTE Radio, and then a few months ago, with a group of people who all have different competences, we created an association that is called The Mediterranean's True Story, and I initiated that, so far, there are 1,500 true stories that are in this library, in this database, and the idea is to have thousands and thousands of them, and to move forward, and so we will send authors, artists of all kinds, researchers to the four corners of the Mediterranean, so that they can get closer to the inhabitants in their homes, to listen to people, because this is what is really necessary today. It starts from the individual.
I think the Mediterranean is a good scale, from the moment we don't consider it on the Nation-State level, or consider it apart from, or beyond its borders.
And it's on the individual level where it seems like we can rebuild something, that's why it's very important to me to make this gesture, to go and listen to people, whoever they may be, to initiate this conversation, these narratives, these true stories together, and then perhaps, the Mediterranean can finally be made.
(Applause)
This evening, I will show you something that you won't be able to see.
And it's precisely because you can't see it that you will see it.
And to start us off, one little question: What is the colour of gold?
Yellow.
Golden.
Yes, you're right.
Look.
In this vial, I have some water and some little flakes of gold, somewhat like in a snow globe.
The gold is beautiful and golden.
But my gold ... is not golden.
My gold, it's this colour here.
My gold is ruby-red.
In this vial, I have some water and some nanoparticles of gold.
The nanoparticles of gold are little grains of material, infinitely small, invisible to the eye.
However, I can show them to you, I took a photo of them.
Here they are.
Aren't they magnificent?
This gold, I heard about it for the first time at university, in my second year.
One morning, I went to a lecture, a little tired from revising the night before,
and I remember the professor coming in -
he had a splendid, white beard -
and he put down on the demonstration bench in front of the board a hot plate with a beaker that had some water in it.
He mixed in two liquids, switched on the device, and started his lecture.
20 minutes later, the solution that had been transparent - it had been water - became red, red like in my vial, ruby-red, red like TEDx!
He had just made nanoparticles of gold.
I was blown away.
I wanted to know more.
The colour!
The colour.
And the colour comes from an interaction between the light and my nanoparticles of gold.
We call this phenomenon localised surface plasmon resonance.
I fell in love with it.
(Laughter) Afterwards, when I spoke about my nanoparticles of gold to people around me, generally, it was something they had never heard of,
and sometimes, those who had already heard about it tended to view it with incertainty, negatively.
They associated it with sanitary or ecological risks.
And I can understand why.
Because historically, there are many examples of materials that have proved dangerous to man.
For example, does anyone recognise this object?
It's not a quiz, you just need to guess it's a water jug.
It's a water jug that was sold in the 1910s in the United States.
Let's look at the advertisement.
"Here's Health!"
That's the promise it makes.
Let's read the text. "To keep that health, you must keep Nature's laws.
They are simple and easy to keep; but if they are broken, Nature exacts a heavy penalty from each and every one.
Get plenty of sleep, exercise and wholesome fun.
Avoid overwork, all other excesses, eat fresh, natural foods, breathe fresh air, and drink plenty of fresh, invigorating, natural ... radioactive water from the Radium-Spa."
Yes, this object offers you, provides you with, water that is radioactive.
Don't start saying that it's typically American.
We had the same thing in France: Tho-Radia, a company that sold cosmetics at the same time.
"Healthy lipstick!"
And what did Tho-Radia put in their cosmetics?
Ah well, some radium and thorium.
For those who don't know, these are two chemical elements that are extremely radioactive:
ultimately, these cosmetics won't give you anything but cancer.
(Laughter)
That was meant to be serious.
To sum it up, when you think about it, a simple, naïve, overtrusting ignorance, mixed with some negligence, made way for a catastrophe.
It's what gave way to a distrust in the population today in relation to this kind of novelty.
That's understandable.
But is it really the fault of radium?
Radium isn't a problem in itself; it's the ignorance we had about it.
We know today that we don't need to dismiss ignorance, on the contrary.
We should interested ourselves in it, confront it, study it, understand it better ...
and take advantage of it.
Get to know it ... let's get to know my nanoparticles.
Well, I've already shown you the red ones, which are spherical and of gold.
But if, instead of the spheres, we have some minute gold rods, my gold is going to be blue.
If instead of using gold, I change the metal, and I try silver, it can be orange, or it can be purple, or it can be - what do I have in my pocket? -
yellow.
It'll be more helpful with a photo.
You can see in the photo that should come up that, in general, we can have different colours just by changing whether its gold or silver, by changing the shape of these particles.
We can even go a little bit further.
I have one last thing in my pocket.
It's a little disc.
And if you look at this sheet here ...
if I put the disc above my lamp, you might say, "Well, the disc must be blue!"
However, if I show you the colour of the disc, this one is opaque and orange.
This phenomenon is called bichromatism,
a property of nanoparticles, where the colour of the object itself is different from that projected.
However, there's something - Before I go on, you mustn't put words into my mouth.
Here, I'm showing you some gold, some nanoparticles, but I'm not saying that they are harmless.
In this case, it's in solution, in water, or in some solid material, there's no problem.
If I had, for example, some mercury, or radium, which, of course, is radioactive, you would need to take more precautions because it would be dangerous.
Put succinctly, you just need to handle it appropriately.
You just have to be careful.
Well, just what are these nanoparticles useful for?
Well, I personally, during my work at university, used this gold to develop a gas sensor, a hydrogen sensor, for applications in energy.
But that's not what I want to talk to you about this evening.
This evening, I want to show you that this gold is also your treasure.
To show this, I have this image.
Here we have a cell.
We see its body in green, the nucleus in blue, where the DNA is, the heart of the cell.
The little carpet of red stars are my gold nanoparticles.
So, why do scientists mess around putting my gold nanoparticles in their cells?
Well, the fact is that this cell is a human cell and it is cancerous.
It is diseased.
But the effect that gives the red colour to my gold will have another effect:
my nanoparticles will heat up.

Not a lot, my vial isn't hot,
but enough to heat up the cancerous cell, and it will die.
Healthy cells, they will survive.
Ultimately, in this vial I have a potential treatment for cancer that today shows very promising results for patients taking part in clinical trials.
And it's very often the case that nanoscience, nanotechnology, comes up with some very interesting findings with the potential to really improve our daily lives.
We have learned a great deal in recent decades.
But what I can tell you is, is that, yes, when you wake up in the morning and on the radio there's about a peak in particle pollution, you should worry. Because then, yes, they are dangerous.
But it is still no time to completely forget science.
It's no time to be taken in by hype,
it's no time to fall for marketing propaganda.
Let's take a totally idiotic example.
We all more or less agree that a diet of natural food is considered a good thing.
But that's not all there is to it: tobacco is natural,
radium is natural and yet ...
We must take a critical approach, whether it's GMO or organic food, or climate change, and so on, and so on. Ultimately then, with education and a critical approach, we will have confidence in science, confidence in our researchers.
That way, we will generate innovation, and thereby learn even more.
For the people here tonight who are themselves scientists, researchers, academics of whatever discipline, I have a favour to ask of you:
Don't let non-experts speak in your name.
Don't leave a void to be filled in by whomever or whatever.
We need to hold out a hand.
Just as here this evening at TEDx, we must be accessible, we must be open.
For those of you who work in other fields, those of you who aren't academic staff members, don't hesitate to look to us,
be prepared to have faith in us.
Come to meet us, in person.
Any day you like, you can send us an email with a question you have.
Because all this learning, all this knowledge, it needs to be accessible to everyone.
It must be allowed to create beauty in our world, and form a legacy, one of our humanity.
Thinking about it, coming back to my nanoparticles, they're a bit like people:
there are good ones, there are bad ones,
and you can even fall in love with them.
Thank you.
(Applause)
"Take the first step in faith. You don't have to see the whole staircase, just take the first step.” Martin Luther King.
In February 2009, I lost my job as a marketing director, I was all dynamic, in London, when suddenly one day, I lost my job.
It was a real slap in the face but I told myself, "it's time to live your dream, I want to inspire millions of people, nothing less, I want to put videos online for free. I don't know how I'm going to make a living from it but this is what I want to do.
Now is the time to do it because I've been fired.
Let's do it!"
I already had two, three million views on Youtube, so I thought the time was right.
I also thought it was time to write a book.
Why not?
I had just lost a job, After all, I had been practicing self-improvement for years, I had attended training courses, if all that, the meditations, do work, it may be time to try them and to put them into practice.
So I wrote a book about it and by the end of 2009, I had a book in my hands, which had been made very quickly, but not a cent on my bank account.
I ended up broke, in London, a very very expensive city, and at the age of 32, I had to go back to my parents', well, to mum's, my parents were divorced.
That's a real blow to your ego, for sure, but I didn't have any other choice, it was that or finding another regular marketing job, working for someone that didn't suit me or at least, I wouldn't get along with and I thought, no, I want to live my dream, I don't know how, but I would rather go back more or less to square one, live what I must live with my parents and not do that job again.
So I stayed but I still didn't know how to make a living from my passion.
My book had known a bit of success but not enough to make a living.
On January, 11, 2011 I decided to go on tour across the United States, Mexico and Canada, a 12-month tour of interviews, during which I would interview authors, people that I thought were nice, authors mainly. I wanted to learn from them so I brought my small camera, my very small camera, a little bit ashamed of coming over with such a small camera, they were so famous! I showed up there and I started to interview them, to ask the questions I had always wanted to ask and I broadcast it on Internet. But you are probably
wondering how I paid for it.
Because traveling for twelve months costs a lot, it can be very expensive. I simply put a donation button, a Paypal button, on the website.
I had no idea that it would work when I started my tour.
It showed no sign.
So it was a big leap of faith, and the day before the tour started, I was in New Mexico, I was ready to do my first interview, and a donation happened. It was the exact amount for the computer I needed, that I just bought to upload these videos on Youtube.
I was blown away!
I was like: "What? Someone just made
a donation so that I can live my dream, I didn't even really ask, I didn't even say what I need, and someone make me a donation!"
It was like everything became more colorful, more alive, and it blew me away.
Of course these steps transformed my life, it changed me, they were difficult steps, challenges, leaps into the unknown, almost quantum leaps, and it transformed my life.
10 years after uploading my first video on Youtube in March 2006, I got my first "like" and my first view, it was very exciting, well, ten years later, I have put 3,000 videos online, got around 2,000 interviews in several languages, in French and English since I am French-American, I am doing it in both languages.
I have traveled in a lot of countries, I am just back from Martinique, Guadeloupe and Thaïland,
45 millions of people have watched my videos, so it has produced a snowball effect thanks to the social media and all that, these videos inspire people to move forward.
Lately I interviewed Mantak Chia in Thaïland for example, who has written lots of books about longevity, on having a blooming sexuality.
Then I am going to interview Professor Henri Joyeux on nutrition, or Frédéric Laloue on Reinventing Organizations, so the new economic models for companies.
In short, I am having a ball!
I am going from one person to another, I upload everything on Youtube.
But to tell you the truth, I absolutely have no idea, I still don't see the whole staircase.
In other words, I answer the call every time, every time I feel this impulse, this intuition, this desire, when something resounds inside me, I say yes, but I don't know where I am headed.
What I can tell you is I am having a ball, What I can tell you is I am enjoying myself, that I am filled with gratitude and joy of life, that I am feeling more and more myself, and since the day I lost my job, and found myself broke, this is when my real life began. It makes me laugh because when I look back, I was so afraid of opening myself to others, I would have been so afraid of talking in public, of making a video, I needed to do everything on my own, I needed to protect myself, I was afraid of being manipulated, of being betrayed, I was afraid of being everything you can imagine, I was protecting myself. Especially since that time when I had no money,
because it was the hardest thing I had to live, being an entrepreneur at the age of 23 and achieving success, even a financial one, to find myself in this situation has been the most beautiful gift after all, because it has opened myself again to life, to gratitude, to care about myself, rather than being hard on myself, it has helped me to look beyond differences, beyond appearances, particularly to tell real 'yes' to life, to learn to say 'no' when needed, to follow this intuition, to listen to my intelligence, the intelligence of the heart, that comes at the service of the intelligence which is up there, and to learn to let go, to trust life and admit that, maybe, this is not a threatening universe.
This is the principle of this world 2.0 that I offer versus the 1.0 one, that I feel has reached its limits.
Today we are in a world asking us to be joyful, to be spontaneous, to be grateful for small things, to understand we don't need to suffer to move forward, that we all have something unique inside us, that you have something unique, you even have a responsibility, a responsibility to life, to yourself, and in order to live this responsibility, we need to be brave, we need to be ourselves. We need to go draw within ourselves.
It is far from being an easy path but, at least, we become ourselves, and we really can help change the world.
I think we got here, to the point where we have this ability, and you know we have this ability to help, to contribute, if only we want to make a positive impact on the world, but it's up to us to decide, to say yes, to not hesitate to also ask life to support us, and to have visions that are bigger than us.
I remember watching a TED talk by Jacques Attali, who said : "What's most important is to undertake your life" I totally agree with that of course, because I think it's deeply connected, life, our company and our professionnal life
and to blossom like that. So I ask you tonight to look at what your role in this society is, what role you want to play, and what your commitment is, what excites you, and what you would like to answer your grandchildren if, one day, you had a conversation with them and they asked about the influence
you have had on this world.
Thank you.
(Applause)
(applause) The majority of us have no concrete idea of what it truly takes to feel happy.
This happens even after we have completed the successive steps towards an accomplished adult life.
I often hear people say, "You see, Mathilde, I have everything.
I have a job that allows me
to make a good living.
I have a car. I have a house.
I have a cat, a dog.

I have a family. I am married."
Or, alternatively,
"We went to Disneyland this summer.
I bought myself the newest Thermomix that cooks in my place, but it cost me a month of salary.
Still, something is still missing."
So, in this room today, let's be honest with each other. Please raise your hand if you have the feeling that you are in search of a kind of greater good.
Let me see.
OK.
So, lots of people.
It's not good but it's good.
Because by the end of this talk, you will realize that... Needless to say, it's useless to contemplate the larger significance of your life on a sofa eating pretzels.
We have to become actors rather than spectators.
So, I tell myself, "In my case, I found happiness through travelling."
It dawned on me that we live in a paradoxical world, where on the one hand, we take everything for granted, and, on the other, we are always unsatisfied.
My trips allowed me to realize what is really important to me,
what thrills me, what makes me get up every morning.
My trips allowed me to put things into perspective and to say, "In fact, I already have happiness."
They allowed me to say, "Yes, I am happy.
Because I'm worth it."
(Laughter) So my trips allowed me to reconnect with certain values that I think have kind of disappeared in today's society.
I rediscovered what it means to share.
I was traveling in the Phillippines, where I was on a bus, hot and hungry, and all of a sudden, we stopped at a rest stop in the middle of nowhere.
There were these ladies outside, in baskets.
No, they weren't in baskets.
(laughter) (applause)
Ok, I'm done. I'm leaving.
(laughter) Well okay, they were selling something wrapped in banana leaves; there we go.
So the lady sitting next to me had bought one and she was unfolding it very meticulously. Inside the wrapping were rice balls, sticky... but appetizing.
She broke them apart and gave them to her four little sons, who were scattered around us, amid chickens of all colors.
When she saw me looking over her shoulder, she spontaneously tore away one end of the rice ball and handed it to me.
Her gesture surprised me.
The most surprising part is the fact that her gesture surprised me.
I also rediscovered what safety means.
I lived in Cape Town, South Africa,
and one day, I said to myself, "It's no big deal if I leave work at 18:15 instead of 18:00. The only difference is that
it will be just after dusk."
When I was walking in the street towards the minibuses that would take me home, across the street, two men showed up and gave me a dirty look.
I had butterflies in my stomach. When passing by me, one of them tapped me on the shoulder and said these three words, "You are white."
It was not a threat.
It simply meant: "At this hour, you should be at home."
And I realized what it means to be able to walk outside without worrying about the time of day, without worrying about the fact that I'm a young light-skinned woman, and to be able to naturally answer my cell phone without feeling scared.
I realized what true generosity means when earlier this year, I launched a slightly crazy project with a friend of mine, who is German —maybe that's why.
So we decided to go and volunteer at a small school in West Kenya. that offers free education to 200 orphans in the village.
We said to ourselves, "We will launch a program called 'Cheap Impact.'
With the two of us and 3000 euros in South Africa, what we will do is travel through South Africa, Zimbabwe, Zambia, Malawi, Tanzania, Uganda, and eventually go all the way to Kenya,
hitchhiking 5200 kilometres."
That took us three months.
And out of exactly 94 days, we paid for four nights' stay,
because we were trying to get ourselves
a free bed and a blanket—especially a bed—
and to save all that money.
In fact, we had to pay for those four nights' stay only because we found ourselves in the deep hinterland of Tanzania and it became impossible for us to explain the mission of our project, and after all, they also deserved our contribution.
We got there with our 3000 euros.
Thanks to our friends, our families, and to those who heard about our project through social networks and on our website and made donations,
but most importantly, thanks to those who met us on the way and gave us everything, although they had nothing themselves.
We finally got there, and we thought, "If we give them these 3000 euros, we will only pay off debts."
We hadn't spent three painful months being at the end of our ropes, having frayed nerves, eating strange things, getting sick, getting tired, waiting in the sun and in the dust only to pay off debts.
We wanted something lasting.
One day, I was in a classroom.
A little girl raised her hand and asked, "Sir, where is Alaska?"
Her question came out of nowhere, like most questions of all kids that age, anyway.
I saw the teacher look at me with puzzled eyes, as if saying, "Can you answer that question?
I have no idea."
I said okay, and took
the tiny piece of chalk.
I drew a map of the world, roughly, on the gray slate that served as a blackboard.
Before showing them where Alaska was, and showing off my knowledge, I turned around and I asked them, "Can one of you show me Africa?"
Their silence left me speechless.
And that's when it clicked.
Since then, "Cheap Impact" became a volunteer program, where people like you and me can spend a few weeks responding to the millions of questions asked by these little kids,
because we were lucky enough to have parents who knew the answers,
to have books, TV, Internet, and teachers—real ones, not the local volunteers who barely knew how to read and write, and struggled to teach a curriculum they themselves didn't understand.
Because in the end, generosity is also the sharing of knowledge.
I realized how lucky I was to have grown up in a country where education is mandatory.
How ironic that I should be saying this at a university.
During that adventure in Africa, when I was in Malawi, we were waiting beside a road, hoping that a car would pass by.
In a nearby field, there was this little boy who was guarding his cows and looking at us curiously.
As the hours passed —and quite a few passed— he came closer, slowly becoming bolder, until he started to talk to us.
During the conversation, I asked him, "Today's Tuesday, and it's not vacation. You're not in school?"
He looked at me with a resigned smile, shrugged his shoulders and said, "You know, going to school is my dream.
But who would look after my cows?"
At that moment, I could see in the back of my mind all these little children that we see every day hanging onto the door of their preschool, begging their mothers, screaming, whining and crying, not to leave them to their teacher's fangs.
All these children pretending to be ill only to avoid a day of learning,
all these adolescents—I see you here— who love to skip school,
and all these college students who go to class still half intoxicated from drinking too much the night before.
So I looked at this little boy with a mix of discomfort and sympathy.
I realized how healthy I was when meeting people who were not:
those children of the Vietnam War who suffer from all levels of autism,
those 30-year-old widows who lost their husbands to illness,
those orphans and disabled people who don't have the services and infrastructure that we do to accommodate our various disabilities.
So today, I realize that I am standing in front of all of you,
looking at you, and listening to you.
I can explain to you clearly all my sensible ideas.
And I still have several good years potentially ahead of me.
So yes, all is well.
And by the way, this morning, like all of you, I got up, and I ate breakfast.
I had the choice between hot and cold food, coffee, milk, juice, sometimes all three, fruit, cereal, bread, croissants and chocolate croissants.
And then like all of you, I hope, I went to take a shower.
I didn't have to ask myself whether water would come out of the tap.
And I could even conveniently adjust its temperature.
I had soap: energizing lemon-mint or summer freshness raspberry-peach.
I put on my clothes with the daily thought, "I have nothing to wear", while facing an overfilled wardrobe.
Like you, I drove my car to come here.
I posted this event on social media to get "likes" from my friends,
using the cell phone I bought three months ago although my old one still worked, but everyone does that.
And also, at noon today, I'll go eat, even though I won't even have started to feel hungry.
So yeah, all is well.
And I am happy.
Because I do not have any valid reason not to be.
Okay, I am not glorifying poverty here.
I am not hammering you with the old "Finish your food; people are dying of hunger",
which only leads to the excellent reply, "Even if we waste less food, they won't have more to eat."
That's true. OK.
Nor do I recommend that we return to the Stone Age.
I'm only saying that from time to time, it's nice to stop for five minutes to contemplate our lives from an external perspective and to realize how fortunate we are.
I'm aware that I'm the narrator, but more importantly, the actress of my life.
And even though I cannot master all the elements of the story, I decide the way in which I tell it.
I deliberately decide to control my reaction to negative emotions.
When something stressful happens, I force myself to ask myself: "Mathilde, is this within your sphere of influence?
Can you do something about it?"
If the answer is no, I'll try to make myself impermeable to its impact.
If the answer is yes, I'll force myself to act in order to improve the situation.
Because it's useless to become hysterical when stuck a traffic jam,
even if we're going to the world's most important appointment,
because our degree of anger isn't proportional to the speed of the cars in front of you.
(laughter) One of you identifies with that.
So what I would like you to remember today is this little boy in Malawi that we ran into by sheer coincidence.
This little boy, who had a dream, a hope, that was so easily attainable for us, yet didn't wear him down.
He was aware of the fact that his actions would not make any difference.
So he was focused on what he had, and on his job as a shepherd.
He was neither hateful, nor bitter, nor unhappy, nor envious.
He was simply there, kind and gentle,
enjoying encounters and appreciating the present moment.
So let's be like him now and then. Let's appreciate the present moment without bitterness, for we find happiness within ourselves.
Thank you.
(applause)
When I have the privilege of creating a show at Cirque du Soleil, something inspires me a lot: it is the fact that the company was born from the street.
It was founded in the 80's by public entertainers, and it influences the way we create shows.
I'm going to talk to you today about something I'm passionate about, the creation process of Cirque du Soleil, I hope that will inspire you in your various spheres of activity.
The first thing a public entertainer does even before starting his show, it is this: (Music) This circle tells the public that there are two realities: everyday reality, and the other reality, that of all possibilities.
Inside this circle, the usual rules no longer apply, we can do anything!
And we can be different.
In fact, and we must be different because we must capture the attention of the public walking in the street with something visceral, something personal, something unusual, so that they change their trajectory and come before you, and that they become your audience.
Street performance is the only form of entertainment where the public will pay but only after the performance, and that changes everything.
The creative process at Cirque du Soleil is similar to this circle.
It creates a space of all possibilities, but it's a demanding space where everyone has surpass themselves and everyone will take a risk like an acrobat.
But he is not alone since this circle is a circle of collaboration. I never have powerpoints but this is the ancestor of the powerpoint and as a public entertainer, it keeps constant eye contact with the audience and it listens to the slightest reactions.
The circle is omnipresent in the reality of the circus.
Most of our stages have this circular shape.
"Circus" comes from the word "circle".
The first thing we do when you arrive in a new city, we draw a circle on the ground to set up the tent there.
In each of the 19 shows across the planet, there is always near the backstage this red and round circle; we call it our red carpet.
This is where at least once a week the whole company gathers, and there we give the good and bad news, or we say our home truths looking in the eye.
In front of the circus headquarters, there is this vegetable spiral which represents the creation process of our shows at Cirque du Soleil, and I'll tell you a little more about it in a minute.
But before that, I'm going to show you something that I really like: it is how we set up our tent.
(Music) (Vídeo) Man: Basically, we have three tents held by 1,200 stakes.
The week before we arrive, teams come to place all the tents.
On Thursday, we built the artistic tent, then we set up the poles, the next morning, we are ready to set up the tent. (Music) Man: Let's go, it goes up! (Music)
Man: This is the last tent to put the canvas up.
After all these years, we still push all these poles by hand.
It's very impressive when all these guys are aligned and you yell, "1,2,3 push!" Two, three, push!
It's really amazing!
It takes 5 or 10 minutes and everything is up.
The last section, guys!
Two three four !
(Music) (Shouts) (Applause) (Video ends) Two three push, two three push.
It is a rallying cry that finds its echo everywhere in the creative process and throughout the company.
And if the challenge is big, this attitude becomes completely indispensable.
At the head office, for each show, there is a place reserved for it, a very special creative room.
And it's reserved for the duration of the creation, it can be two years, two and a half years... it is our little cave where we will dream the show.
When I started working on my first tour show, "Kurios, Cabinet of Curiosities," I asked right away to see the room.
I went with my colleague Chantal Tremblay, the creative director, we opened the door and immediately I said, "There is a problem."
She told me, "What?"
"The table!" "The table, what?"
"The table is rectangular, it does not make sense, it's like a board table, I'm going to stand at the end and then I'll talk, people will listen to me respectfully, it does not make sense!
We cannot work like that, it would take a table that allows for a more equal relationship between people something that really allows us to do art!"
And then I remembered a mythical round table which was used by the first creative team at Cirque du Soleil.
I said, "You have to find this table, go everywhere, do everything possible."
And after two weeks, they came back and said, "Michel, we went everywhere: to the basements, the warehouses in Anjou, warehouses in Saint-Michel," - and it's quite a distance between Anjou and Saint-Michel - "and we did not find the table."
So I said, "Well, ok, what we should do, is spend our first dollars on the making of our round table."
And that changed everything.
In fact I love this table so much that I brought it with me to Cannes, for you.
So I would ask you to kindly welcome directly from Cirque du Soleil's creative studios in Montreal, the creative table!
(Applause) Thank you!
With the training studios, with the rehearsal rooms and the stage, for me, the creative table is truly paradise on Earth.
This is where we have the privilege to gather and to create worlds, better worlds, new worlds.
Around this table, there is everyone.
It's not "director meets scenographer" then "director meets costume designer."
At the circus, everyone is invited to the table at the same time.
There are the scenographer, the lighting designer, the costume designer, the makeup designer, the designer of acrobatic apparatus, acrobatic movement, the production manager, the creative director, the composer, so we're pretty tight!
And all these people gather for weeks and months to dream up the show.
I could talk to you for hours, but to be a little more concise, I will call on the music.
(Music) Because the process of creating the circus is something inside which begins as a dance, very slowly, and takes you by the guts.
It starts at the beginning by the director who comes up with the idea of a show theme.
It comes from the circus creative, Jean-François Bouchard, or from himself.
So when I do the staging, I propose this idea, I propose this theme, and immediately everyone reacts emotionally.
And everyone will say, "Well, it inspires me this, it inspires me that." We'll talk about the creative challenges we want to get started to get out of our own beaten track.
Then everyone brings sources of inspiration so that can be the drawing of a flower that grows bravely in the middle of the desert, it can be a sepia photo collection because we like the sepia color, it can be a poem extract, it can be the excerpt of a film that marked us, memories of our childhood, an object that comes from home.
And during all those weeks, this maelstrom begins to accumulate, it is the spiral of creation in all its width.
Everything is open, it's an organic process.
It does not have to be logical, we all have to understand it.
There are things that are discarded after a few days, new ideas coming in, and this spiral keeps moving.
What we follow is not a recipe, it's not a plan, it's our intuition.
It's a lot harder because you have to create without a net.
After a few weeks, the director proposes the beginning of a story.
It will be a dramatic link which will link all the acrobatic numbers and the theatrical substance of the show.
Everyone will discuss, portions of the story will be abandoned, others will be generated by this discussion, and the creative room is starting to get lined with the storyboard of acrobatic numbers, costumes illustrations, the scenographer arrives with his preliminary model for the decor; it gives new ideas to lighting designers, to the make-up designer and all the while, the composer listens, he takes notes... of music.
Then comes an unforgettable moment, the artists, there is nothing more beautiful, when they come from all over the planet, that you've been writing this character for months and they come to you and say, "Hello, my name is Karl, I will be Mr Microcosmos."
"Priviet, I am Antonina and I will be Mini Lili."
The show is incarnated, the circle of creation opens to welcome all these artists' dreams, acrobatic coaches, artistic coaches, the choreographers, we start setting up the acts, the circle gets bigger, the spiral narrows, because there are things we cannot do, do not want to do, the show slowly begins to take shape and the spirit emerges like a breath.
We start setting up the show, all the staging of the acts, but also transitions, the opening that will change three times, the final that will be found a week before the first. And precisely: three weeks before the opening, we do something that I think we're the only circus to do, we open the doors of the big tent, while the show is not ready at all.
It's like a little creature that starts to take shape, it requires a lot of courage and humility.
Because we will give the show to 200 people.
Friends, colleagues who are the most uncompromising judges, and that's what we want!
We will see what works and what doesn't work with the public, what to change or what to abandon altogether.
Everything is done for the public. After this intimate performance, we will sometimes make major changes, we will change the order of the acts, bring a new music, a new costume, sometimes a new artist and we proceed twice in two weeks to this difficult exercise.
It requires a lot of courage but at the same time it allows us to check the strength of this team spirit that we have created for months around this table.
And then of course it's time, the heart or the spiral concentrated in a single point and that's actually the heart of what we do, it's the first of the show.
There is something I'd like to share with you before you leave: this year, we created a show in Latin America, based on the music of a band we did not know at all, called Soda Stereo. People there listen to them and worship them as much as the Beatles.
They tell us all: "We grew up with this music, if a film was made about my life, Soda Stereo's music would certainly be the soundtrack."
With great humility, we thought, "What can we do to feel this music and give to the public there the show they deserve?"
What we did, for the first time in our history, we have enlarged the circle of creation to let the spectators in, to let the audience in.
And as I told you, it's something we've never done before.
So you see, we opened the door of the room, the round table was there, and, over the internet, people were allowed to connect with us.
And at the beginning, we said, "We have no idea, they will be 100, 200..." Five seconds in the first live session, they were 8,000.
After 15 minutes, someone writes on a piece of paper for me, they were 86,000! Wow!
We asked for comments
after the session, it came to 4,000.
And from these comments, they were keywords, public dreams, I wrote the beginning of a story for this painting.
So we invited them to create an act of the show with us.
And every month for a year, we met them.
They did all the stages of the creation process: characters, costumes, choice of acrobatic number, choreographies, all that.
The reason I present all this to you today it's that - I want to let it roll - it was really a process that represented a risk for us, we had never done that, nobody had ever done that, I had the impression that by taking the risk of opening, on the electronic highway, we walked in the footsteps of the founders of the circus and we were like them, in the street, and we looked at the public, with the modern technological means, right in the eye to adjust our creative shot and to be inspired by their attention to give them the show they deserve.
When we did Kurios, sorry, Sept7Imedia, the second show, I asked that we built a second round table.
And right now, I'm creating two more shows so I asked that we make two more round tables.
People often ask me how many shows I'd like to create, for sure, as an artist, I have a lot to say, I would like to do several, but basically I believe like all of you that what I am trying to do, it's to create a maximum of round tables where people come together to create beauty for other human beings.
The last thing a public entertainer does before leaving his circle it is to thank his audience.
Thank you very much.
(Applause)
Europe, for us, European citizens who have the freedom to travel, live and work wherever we like, means cities like Paris, Berlin, London and Barcelona.
These are also cites where refugees dream of living. But for them, it's a different map, Europe is something very different.
It means places like Lampedusa, Ventimiglia, Idomeni and Kos.
These are places where they find themselves stranded on their road to exile after fleeing from war and misery in their homelands.
The response to this humanitarian crisis by the member states of the European Union merely by means of a paranoid border protection, is the policy of burying your head in the sand, of pretending that the problem doesn't exist.
It's about being as unwelcoming possible, and about discouraging and rejecting people.
But these refugees or refugees in general, continue to cross borders.
They always get through them
and have always done so.
The closing off of borders by EU member states makes no sense,
and it is very costly in terms of human lifes. It's both financially and morally costly.
But, the good news is that once across the border, this national dimension is less relevant.
The refugees' dream is an urban dream.
It's believed that 80% of new arrivals in Europe want to live in a big city.
This is where are found the reception networks, families, friends and fellow countrymen.
This is where you have the best shot of finding housing, a job, training, and of furthering your education.
It turns out to be a good thing because the urban setting is what will determine the success or failure of integration policies.
I work for this network of cities called "Eurocities."
My job is to help these cities with their integration policies, to help them exchange ideas and best practices, the successes and failures.
The approach used by integrating cities is not ideological. It's about being practical.
And being practical for the mayor of a large city means safeguarding social cohesion, public order and public health.
It is not a policy against immigrants, refugees and diversity that will achieve this, but a policy of openness and inclusiveness, backed by the certainty that a city of this size can resolve this type of situation.
I work with mayor's offices, elected officials, and administrations who received almost the same message:
"We can't. There is no room.
We don't have the resources.
The general public is not ready, they wouldn't understand.
Now is not the time."
Well, it's never the time...
In reality, dozens of major European cities are proving us wrong every single day.
About the statement: "The public wouldn't understand," a city like Vienna, Austria, for example, has bet the opposite.
When refugees that were trapped in Budapest by the Hungarian government, chose to walk all the way to Austria, the first welcome they received was by the Viennese.
When they arrived, they were welcomed at the Vienna train station, with this letter from city officials.
It started with: "You're welcome" and ended with: "Don't be afraid!"
What a great change already!
Vienna was able to do this because months ahead of time, they had set up a coordination system with all those of goodwill - NGOs, churches, public officials and private sector - and also because the mayor of Vienna, Michael Häupl, instructed all of his municipal employees to pitch in ; this was their priority now.
He did this just a few weeks before the municipal elections.
He staked his entire political career on a policy based on humanism, welcomeness and openness.
And in his city, he easily defeated the extreme right in the second round.
The general public is not stupid.
Public opinion can recognize strong political leadership.
Several months after the municipal elections, were the presidential elections.
The extreme right lost in Vienna by 30% in the second round.
There are 50,000 refugees
in Vienna who can't vote.
Yet, Vienna has welcomed today every single last one of them.
We're also told, of course that there is no room, we can't allow these masses of people in, or that we don't have the means to accommodate them.
Yet, look at Berlin. It's believed that 80,000 refugees has arrived since September 2015 and that 50,000 of them remained there.
The city is in charge of their reception, integration, accommodation, children's education, and of course, public order and security.
They were not ready for that
and there was a lot of tension.
Plenty of bad press aimed at the city government.
But with a lot of perseverance and will, the situation is working itself out little by little, thanks particularly to the help of civil society.
For example, the city requisitioned empty housing, office buildings, and provided temporary shelters.
It opened up new classes for children.
There's a talk of 10,000 refugee children in Berlin, in 900 rapid integration courses.
Berlin has also created a more sustainable approach by developing the 'container village' model.
These are places that allow people to live in community, where they can cook their own food.
These places have been built in the hearts of neighborhoods, not like jungles along highways but in the heart of communities with the intent to integrate the refugees.
All of this is very expensive.
Hamburg for exemple spent more than 360 million in 2014 to welcome refugees, and spent twice as much in 2015.
But this, in reality, costs less than inaction.
This costs less than an overcautious and indecisive policy.
All of this investment has positive returns for the local economy.
This is far from perfect, and everyone knows it. But a city like Berlin currently hosts more than 50,000 refugees and welcomes new ones everyday.
Finally, we're told... that integration is not going to work anyway,
and that we don't know how to do it
and don't have the skills.
It is true that always applying the same formulas can be a problem.
Cities where public services are already stretched thin might be pushed to the limit with more arrivals.
But this crisis is precisely the perfect opportunity to develop new ideas.
Sweden received 160,000 people in 2015, but 30,000 in 2010, it's a huge change in scale.
These people don't want to go to Lapland, Sweden’s northernmost region.
They want to go to Malmö, Gothenburg, Stockholm.
These are very attractive cities that draw large amounts of immigrants, as well as Europeans who want to settle down there.
These cities had proactively created a partnership with a start-up called "Mobilearn" in order to provide integration services directly to refugees.
This service is offered in Somali, Persian, Arabic and Kurdish and it enables you to follow the process step by step when it comes to education, training, health care, looking for a job or housing. It enables you to start learning Swedish in your own native language. And it enables you essentially to get appropriate local information.
This earns money for cities, or at least, saves them money. It saves you tons of time, and frees you up for other endeavors.
Best of all, refugees can start integrating from the get-go, not after six months spent in a shelter once the asylum request has been approved.
That brings significant time savings.
Integration will never work if we always respond with the same ideas.
We need new approaches, new solutions.
A colleague of mine who lives in a large Dutch city, told me jokingly, "This crisis is amazing!
All the ideas and projects I had shoved away in my drawers are now being fast-tracked by leaders on a policy level."
Indeed, we need these solutions, and the urban setting is perfect for experimentation and innovation.
These are the cities of today: they are welcoming and active, because the values of solidarity and mutual co-existence cannot be abstract ideas.
Countries build walls.
Cities try to build bridges.
I believe cities must be fully recognized as a player in migration and integration policies because that's where everything will be decided.
That's where they will succeed of fail.
Cities are powerless without civil society.
In all of these examples, civil society, associations and volunteers played a key role.
So, integration is a two-way street.
It's a responsibility shared between refugees and the host society.
So it's up to us, citizens of European cities, to guarantee that we win the bet on integration.
Thank you.
(Applause)
In 2011, at 26, I got my first tattoo.
I'll show it to you so you can understand what I'm talking about.
Here it is, right here.
This tattoo is a code; it's a secret.
Apart from my mother and some friends, I never shared its meaning.
But tonight, I’m going to tell you all what it represents.
This code is the date of my 30th birthday,
October 20, 2014.
By this date, I promised myself I will have accomplished a list of specific goals in my career. By this date, I promised myself that I will have accomplished some of my dreams.
However, the closer I got to my 30th birthday and began to achieve my goals, the more I began to have doubt and feel lost.
The day of my 30th birthday, I was completely emptied.
Today, a few years later, with a little bit of distance, I realize that everything on this list does not interest me anymore or even saddens me, and above all, I have other desires and a new vision of ambition.
My mother asked me if I regretted having gotten the tattoo, and then I realized that I had the chance to have the biggest lesson of my life printed on me until my death.
So, it's convenient, every morning when I put deodorant, I have a little reminder of why I'm here.
Have you ever wanted something at all costs, did everything to get there, dreaming of it day and night, then achieving your goals, get what you want, and finally feeling dissatisfied, or worse, wanting something else?
What if our dreams were not really ours?
What if some of our expectations and ambitions took us away from what makes us happy?
What if today's society conditioned us from childhood to a certain vision of success and ambition?
From a very young age, I liked the theater.
When I was young, I preferred to stay in the classroom during the recess to play small scenes with a friend.
I liked to disguise, to rehearse - but to make a career out of it? Not sure.
Today, I realize that what I liked was communicating and sharing.
By the way, that's why I'm here tonight.
My goals and my ambitions have been influenced, like many of us, by, one, my social and cultural conditioning and, two, my personal story.
For my part, I grew up feeling that I wasn't respected, protected and heard.
So I took refuge in what I saw on TV and in magazines.
And then, I quickly understood that the more people had success and possessions, the more they were respected.
So obviously, I, who needed to be reassured and seen, tried to copy what society imposed on us as success.
In general, artists are admired. But I sing like a wailing cat, and since I was already doing theater, I told myself : "I'm going to act.
I'll show the world what am I capable of!"
I set dreams and ambitions to heal my childhood wounds.
I have been an actress for more than 10 years.
I played in TV series on France 2 and TF1, and at 26, I went to Los Angeles to realize my dreams - the ones from the tattoo - and I decided to be an actor in Hollywood.
I started to live the life style that I always dreamed of,
and I got small roles in American movies.
Even if I didn't end up on a billboard, I was lucky to shoot with actors that I admired.
But to tell the truth, every time I shot, I was bored.
I saw the difference between me and the actors who were there for their passion;
it was completely different.
I started to feel frustrated, wanted something different, and I felt ashamed.
I felt ashamed because I was afraid of being judged, and seeing this as a failure.
I had been sacrificing myself for this career for 10 years; I couldn't change my mind now.
I started acting at the same time as the arrival of social networks,
in my early 20s.
I am part of the Millennial generation. I became an adult with the internet, social networks and cell phones.
It affected me a lot more than I thought.
To be clear, I'm not here to criticize the internet. I think it's an incredible way to connect, to create and advance our societies.
But are we really aware of what is happening before our eyes and of its impact?
Our feeds on Facebook and Instagram, our research on Google, news site ads - and that's just to name a few examples - are all filtered by algorithms.
So what we look at and what we listen to all day is indirectly chosen for us.
Facebook, which has over two billion members, is currently accused by some of its employees of manipulating our emotions and decisions.
A former Facebook executive recently said in the press, "Your behavior, you do not realize, is programmed."
Their only goal is to get you to spend time on their platform.
Social networks cause addictions, comparable to alcohol, tobacco or drugs.
So what do we do everyday?
We stage our lives
via photo galleries or posts.
Not only must we face our egos, but in addition we must deal daily with the ones of others.
Society pushes us to idealize the lives of others and makes us think we're not enough.
We're not young enough, not old enough, not rich enough, not poor enough, not zen enough, not brunette enough, not unicorn enough - For me, it has enormously decreased my confidence.
I started wanting things that did not fit me and sometimes were even the opposite of my values.
I admired, I judged, I compared. And I liked, I liked, I liked -
When I wasn’t feeling good, I used to post selfies.
After few hours, I started to feel better thanks to the rush of likes.
And naturally, when the evening was approaching, I started feeling bad again and had to post another picture.
It never ended.
The problem with my filtered selfies is that I was sending the message to my followers and young people that to be respected, you have to rely on superficial values.
Here is an example.
Voilà.
This first photo, which I posted after the last professional
photo shoot that I did three years ago,
received 461 likes.
This first image is false.
I was made up and had my hair done for more than two hours. My skin is retouched. I look sure of myself and sexy, but I was cold.
And the only reason I did this shoot was to have a sexy photo to get attention and compliments to boost my self-esteem.
The second is a photo that I took six months later.
I posted this one with a caption that told the story of this photo.
I met this man during a visit to a program against illiteracy in Nepal.
There was a discussion with a group of women who had joined the program.
This man was sitting in the back of the classroom.
He got up, approached the board, and slowly began to write a word. Then he turned to us and said:
"All my life, I felt stupid.
Now I can read and write.”
We asked him what he preferred.
He answered, "I can write my name."
In five words, this man taught me what was humility, courage, and determination.
This post had 68 likes.
Appearances, perfection, and competition are built up to the detriment of compassion, acceptation, and reality.
According to Facebook, more than 100 million hours of videos are viewed each day on their site.
Common Sense Media revealed that teens spent an average of nine hours per day consuming media.
Pew Research shows that 24% of teens go online “almost constantly,” facilitated by their smartphones.
How can a teenager learn to know himself, develop his personality and feel free to make choices if he is constantly conditioned by the media?
The world around us is conditioning us to view success as superficial, power and money-oriented.
The problem with that is that some of us, including myself, have been blinded to the impact this vision has on society and the environment.
Our ambitions are to produce more and more, sell more and more, consume more and more.
In business, a company is successful purely based on financial success - the actual human and environmental impact isn’t part of the picture.
Obviously, this is not sustainable.
Fed up with this? Want more meaning in your life too?
Are you ready to start a revolution?
First: Together, we could limit and prevent this, to reduce our insatisfactions, depression, and conditioning;
we could reduce our consumption of media and social media.
It sounds simple and obvious, and to be honest, I'm in the middle of it myself.
This is one of my resolutions in 2018. We are the 12th of January, and I already broke my promises 372 times.
Don't use me as an example.
It proves how bad the situation is. Tristan Harris, the former Chief Ethical Designer of Google, advises to impose precise schedules for internet use.
Also it is important to avoid at all costs checking our phones, emails, news, or social networks, upon waking.
It might seem like a minor detail, but it increases our impression of missing something.
Unconsciously, we think we have missed things during the night,
and we have an urge to check. Second step: love.
Perhaps we could reconnect to ourselves to others and the environment.
The time gained from reducing our media consumption could be used for self reflection and mindfulness.
What helps me daily is meditation,
taking time for myself, and walking in nature.
We often forget that Nature is our best guide.
She teaches us with humility our place in the world.
She grounds us, inspires us.
Also, maybe we could go to the cafe down the street to share a moment with our neighbor instead of talking through messenger for 30 mins.
These are wonderful tips to discover who we are and take off the mask.
Self reflection made me look at my fears and stop running away from them.
It helped me accept my imperfections, vulnerability, and my need for love.
Love became my rebellious act to face the system.
And our third step:
redefining success in a world that needs us more than ever.
We could use consciously our like, share, and play buttons.
We should be celebrating the people who are preserving our environment and bringing together our societies - not the paper-thin celebrities of Instagram and Twitter.
Did you know that the Dalai Lama has less than 1 million followers on Instagram and a reality TV star more than 104 million?
We could put our technologies and our media even more at the service of values,
at the service of society, innovations, science, well-being -
We could finally create the society we want to live in and not the one that our consumerist society has imposed on us until now.
What if success was about integrity, ethics, and meaning?
What if success was about finding our values and turning them into action.
What if success was about protecting our planet rather than destroying it,
and helping support one another rather than competing?
What if success was being happy, being able to love, and hurt as little as we can?
From selfie to service, from ego system to eco-system, from competition to altruism. Our future emerges as we decide to create it.
So two years ago, I had the idea to make a documentary.
I asked a friend, Marine Billet, to co-direct it with me.
The documentary is a quest on four continents to understand love and its impact in the world.
We want to show what kind of society could emerge if we all reconnected to love.
The documentary is called: I Love Therefore I Am.
Since then, my life has been the biggest adventure I could wish for.
I dream less but live more.
I started to accept myself.
I became a director and started to write. I focus on causes that make my heart sing. For this, I left everything behind.
I quit acting, left my house, ended up with no money.
I couldn't afford a rent,
so I put my life in 17 boxes in a storage, and I traveled from couch to couch for 18 months, with two suitcases and my dog.
Two years later, we are still in production of the documentary.
I still have a dog, I don't sleep on couches anymore, and I am really happy.
Now I have two questions for you: What are your dreams? The real ones.
And, are you ready to start your own revolution?
(Applause)
Good evening.
I'm delighted to be here tonight to share a vision, a social project.
Since I turned 20, I've been trying to find solutions to change the world with all my energy and beliefs.
Through searching, I realized that we had a partner of choice with us, a partner we tend to forget and even mistreat.
It's not just any partner but a laboratory, an incredible laboratory with 3 billion years of experience.
It's the laboratory of the living.
Nature has developed incredible technologies to overcome all the challenges it has been confronted with, that are energy-efficient since they only work with solar energy, that are resilient, know how to adapt, and do not produce any waste.
Gaudi used to say, "The architect of the future will build by imitating Nature, for it is the most rational, long-lasting and economical of all methods."
And he was right.
We became capable of flying a helicopter from the observation of dragonflies.
Japanese engineers, although brilliant, performed a simple copy-paste of the nose of the kingfisher to design their high-speed train.
Drawing one's inspiration from Nature is called "biomimetics".
American Janine Benyus, a pioneer in that field, wrote an incredible and interesting book on the subject.
This 600-page book, references all the clean and circular solutions that could be adapted from Nature to our societal issues with regard to energy, transportation, health, business management, and food.
She dedicates the first chapter of her book to agriculture.
She concludes these 70 first pages by saying, if we are sincerely convinced that a new world must be created for the good of future generations, then the base on which to build this new paradigm is agriculture.
So I got very interested in this subject and I understood quite a few things, notably how the history of food and agriculture had been remodeled in a context of cheap oil.
In 50 years, we divide our energy efficiency by 25 in order to produce food.
In 1940, we could produce 2.4 food calories with one fossil calorie.
Today, we need 7 to 10 fossil calories to produce one food calorie. Is that not incredible?
But why is that?
Well, it is due to our production methods such as tractors that burn 25 liters of gasoline per hour.
It's due to the massive spreading of petrochemical products. It's due to packaging and the fact that, when you eat a cooked dish, it has traveled 900 miles before landing on your plate.
Fortunately, concerning food and agriculture, Nature has so much to teach us.
A forest, for example, produces 600 times more biomass than a wheat field.
Finding our inspiration in Nature to do farming is called "permaculture". It comes from "permanent culture".
If we want to be strict, permaculture is the art and philosophy of designing balanced human ecosystems.
So strictly speaking, it is not an agricultural method.
Permaculture can be done by managing our company or our family which have to be balanced human ecosystems.
It can be done by constructing a positive-energy building, or by producing object from waste using 3D printing.
So what does Nature teach us?
It teaches us quite a few things.
The first lesson we can learn from her is that the ground should never be left bare.
You will never see, in Nature, a piece of land without anything on it.
As soon as a ray of sun hits the ground, a plant develops and grows through photosynthesis.
And that's a good thing because it is thanks to plants that there is life in the soil.
You can imagine that in the Beauce cereal plains that are exposed for the most part of winter, earthworms have nothing to eat, decomposers have nothing to decompose.
And when there are no plants, there are no roots either, so when it rains, nothing retains the soil and it erodes, the ground disintegrates, and we lose tons of humus and fertility every year.
You can clearly see it in the rivers at the end of the winter, all the carried soil coming from our fields.
Now to avoid this in permaculture, we mulch, we cover the ground with straw, or with grass cuttings, or with RCW - Ramial Chip Wood.
We can also make green fertilizers.
They are plants that we put between two crops, in a rotation.
These green fertilizers fix nitrogen in the soil, so they fertilize.
And that is what's awesome in permaculture. It is that one action may have several incidences, several functions.
When we throw straw on the ground, this creates organic material and keeps the soil alive.
It also helps to avoid the growth of adventitious plants, weeds, because it obscures the ground, so It saves a lot of weeding.
But the straw also allows to save water, since it limits the evapotranspiration of the ground, thus preserving a freshness, a true humidity.
So this is the kind of ideas we can have thanks to Nature with regards to farming.
Another important Nature's teaching is the culture of diversity.
It's impossible to know how many living species there are in 100m2 of forest, there are so many!
And this is precisely the key to productivity, it is diversity.
In permaculture, we try to do the same and maintain as many species as possible.
We combine plants, grow trees,
and try to get closer to edible forests.
We try to make it friendly for insects and animals.
To control aphids, we rely on ladybirds.
To avert slugs, we welcome hedgehogs or frogs.
If we were fighting aphids chemically, the ladybird larvae would have nothing to eat, so they would never come back,
and the following year, we would be obliged to use pesticides.
So it's this kind of ideas that we should take from Nature to cultivate differently.
Following my interest in this in 2010, I discovered the farm of Bec Hellouin.
It's an absolutely incredible farm, in Normandy, inspired by permaculture.
It's a lush farm, a kind of garden of Eden.
It's so productive that it is the subject of an INRA study that proves that on a planted area of 1000m2, they're able to generate €50,000 of turnover.
That's how much they made last year.
It's huge, it's ten times more than in conventional agriculture.
There are a lot of farms that function like this one.
There is an impressive farm in Quebec, the Grelinette farm, which inspires lots of followers.
So as I was convinced of the relevance and the power of the project, I met the INRA head of research who is leading this study of Bec Hellouin and asked him how to help duplicate this type of farm on the territory.
He told me that, as a researcher, his purpose was to follow a farm at a cruise pace, like this one that gives real hopes in terms of healthy intensive production. But he was interested in following a farm in its installation stage because it's a period a bit complicated.
And it is this stage that serves as an alibi to many unions and many agricultural lobbies, to leave the current model as it is.
Yet this current model is on its very last legs, isn't it?
In 50 years, we have lost 1.5 million farms in France.
At the same time, we went from 10% farmers to 2%.
We lost between one third and one half of all the organic matter of our lands.
And we have no magic spell to recover it.
Tomorrow's model will have to pollute less, consume less resources and employ more people.
And to employ more people, it will be necessary for some citizens to agree to go back and live in the countryside to recreate balanced human ecosystems in France's abandoned villages.
Now it was easy for me to say this from my little Parisian universe.
Since I had never planted a tomato, I doubted I was really credible.
So, since I felt like it, I decided to give it a try myself.
At the time, I was running a publishing company.
I was making educational boards on sustainable development, working with Louis Albert of Broglie, nicknamed the "prince gardener".
He's created the National Conservatory of the Tomato not far from here, with 650 varieties of tomatoes.
We decided we would make this experimental farm, on his land, on 1.4 hectares.
So I quit my job and trained in organic farming,
I visited a lot of farms, set up a team, and we created an association called "Fermes d'Avenir."
We defined one challenge and several objectives.
First, the challenge is to scientifically prove that agroecology can be more profitable than conventional agriculture.
We know this for sure, and it is what we are doing on this farm.
Our farm, on 1.4 hectares, will cost us less than a tractor, and it will not consume any oil.
If everything goes well, in year 4, we'll be economically balanced, and we would have created three jobs on 1.4 acres.
Comparatively, three jobs in conventional market gardening, it's rather on 9 acres.
So we can employ six times more people thanks to this type of agriculture.
Now, our objectives.
The first objective is to give INRA researchers all the numbers they need in order to evaluate the economic model.
So we note everything at the farm.
We note the work time, the cost, the evolution of productivity, then they enter them into their program, and compare it to the traditional model.
The second objective is to create a tool box that would allow anyone to recreate this experience, to replicate this type of farm because it is one of the real revolutions of this project.
One of the true revolutions that permaculture can bring is to say that, to become farmer, we no longer need 50 or 100 ha.
We can do it from one or two acres, and this changes everything because one or two acres can be found everywhere.
Many landowners - either individuals, businesses or local communities - would be willing to make available one or two acres of land, for example, to provide for the canteen of a school.
The third objective isn't the simplest one.
It's evaluating the ecosystem services provided by this kind of agriculture.
Basically, we say farmers are not here just to produce food.
They preserve biodiversity, maintain the quality of water, cultivate people's health when they makes good products, imprison carbon, shape landscapes, create dynamics on the territory.
It's super complicated to evaluate what this represents.
Imagine a system where worms create fertility for free, and another where we don't have worms anymore and we need to create this fertility artificially.
How much must we spend to match the efficiency of the worms?
Similarly, you probably know that bees are becoming extinct.
In China right now, they're paying people to pollinate by hand the apple trees growing in orchards.
Is it not utterly absurd?
So to evaluate all this, with our association, we've created a scientific committee that estimates the positive impacts and try to put a figure on it.
If we succeed, we'll be able to convince the politicians that it's smarter to finance now this type of agriculture than paying fortunes in a few years to repair the damage.
They don't really need our numbers to start.
Are you familiar with endocrine disruptors?
It costs 80 billions a year in France,
and it's just because of pesticides.
It is said that we don't have enough money to stop pesticides, but in fact in doing so, we save 80 billions.
So we can finance this right now.
You understand that we're trying to give a societal or even political dimension to our project.
So we want to make it part of an economic reality because this is the only condition for us to be able to spread it and duplicate it on the territory.
So there's a number we need to keep in mind. It is that 70% of fruit and vegetables in France are sold in supermarkets or in hard discount stores.
So from the start, we wanted to associate to this approach large-scale retailers because we won't be able to change the agricultural model without them.
Therefore, we went to meet them and, surprisingly, they welcomed us.
Well, it was not totally surprising since when we met them, it was the horse meat lasagna crisis.
So they were trying to find solutions to win their customers back, to work on the traceability of their suppliers.
Maybe it was a bit a PR stunt, but it was more than that because economically, it is very profitable for them, it's logical.
Today, they're buying tomatoes that come for Spain.
They know very well that when the oil barrel'll be worth $300 or 500, Spansih tomatoes will no longer be able to compete with local tomatoes or even organic ones.
Concretely, we launched this farm one year and a half ago.
We are up to our objectives.
We are very satisfied to see that Nature is generous.
If we take good care of it, it gives it back.
Personally, I've discovered a job.
I became a market gardener, I put my hands in the soil.
It's a fascinating job with a lot of things to do and in the open air.
I lost five kilos, I'm tanned all year round.
I'm quite happy.
Still, we should not idealize farmer's job.
There are quite a few things left to invent.
An agriculturist's job remains a complicated one.
You must be technically good, be diligent, manage your bills, be in top form all the time, sell well and buy well.
It's a very complete and complex job.
You have to be a bit like Superman.
So if we want to create 200 or 500,000 jobs in agriculture, we won't find 200 or 500,000 Superman volunteers.
So there are quite a few jobs to invent.
We thought of something - well, it's a bit of a big word - a job that does not exist today but will exist tomorrow, and it is "farm manager".
We think that a motivated agriculturist can easily create 5 to 10 micro-farms like that of the Bourdaisiere.
That way, they'd pool many things, administration, marketing, tools such as a tractor, a crusher, or a transformation unit, why not?
This job, we call it "countryculturist". because we think that they're people who will cultivate a country, cultivate something very local and get involved in their territory.
And this thing is missing.
So you have it, it's the project I wanted to talk about tonight.
It seems to me that we can all participate in this dynamic.
Quite a few people are in search of meaning, thinking they don't really know what the point of their work is, who would perhaps like to live in the countryside.
Well, they can try and become part-time countryculturists or market gardeners.
They can invent other jobs in distribution and transformation.
Those who don't necessarily want to change jobs, you can still consume local and organic, it's really important.
People say consuming organic products is expensive but, in fact, it's not.
It's just that junk food is totally subsidized.
We pay for it several times: with our taxes, with the CAP, and with the induced health costs.
There is another very important lever, it's financing this type of activity. Because conventional banks like conventional agriculture.
A few years ago, when I discovered this, I set up a crowd-funding platform called Blue Bees.
It allows Internet users, citizens, to give or to lend money to projects, like this one, agroecological projects.
Thanks to this, when you lend, you can get 2 to 3% interests,
two to three times what you get
from your saving account. It's better than leaving your money to a banker who will finance offshore platforms in Antarctica, right?
With your grey matter, your arms, your wallet or your plate, you can all participate in this movement.
In the meantime, we will go on experimenting, creating projects, developing jobs, and lobbying for politicians to accompany this movement with incentive policies and tax arrangements.
We're maybe less strong than the lobbies and have less elements of persuasion than the food lobbies, but we're much more numerous, and the world that we're promoting is much more desirable, isn't it?
It's a world in which we would reconcile Nature and the city, travel and pleasure, alimentation and health.
Victor Hugo once said: "It's sad to think that Nature speaks and men is not listening."
So I propose to you that for once, we prove Mr Hugo wrong and all together, we build a society of common sense, a resilient and fertile world.
Thank you.
(Applause)
Hello everybody.
I'm here to talk about tin cans and their use in the making of musical instruments.
When we think of tin cans and music, we think of the poor man's instrument, of resourcefulness, something we play for lack of a better one, of a budding percussionist's first drums, of street drummers who only have cans to play their music, but, what else?
They are used in some musical traditions, notably in the United States with the banjo can, the "canjo," used to play folk music, jug music accompanied by the spoons, the washboard, and the washtub bass.
They are used in Central Africa, where children start playing music on an instrument they simply call a "guitar," which is a tin can with a bent branch and a brake cable from a bike.
African instruments are quite interesting because they mostly come from everyday objects.
When you live there, when you're in the village, when you go outside, what do you find?
You find calabashes, goat skins, branches, fishing lines, and if you put this all together, you get a kora.
Now, as more and more Africans live in urban zones, when they go outside, what do they find?
They find a wire and a tin can,
but the procedure is almost the same.
We can also talk about the Caribbean, where they use a bigger version: a 216-liter barrel.
They created, by stamping the lid and hammering it to tune it, the steel drum, a very interesting instrument because this one, unlike the others I have mentioned, isn't an imitation of an existing musical instrument.
It's really an acoustic creation that depends completely on the object.
Before looking at all this, let's go through the types of instruments.
There are four:
the aerophones, the chordophones, the membranophones, and the idiophones.
The aerophones, easy: the sound of air.
It's an instrument in which air is the vibrating and sound matter.
You don't have that with tin cans.
I looked for it, I tried, I did some tests, but it really wasn't any good, so I won't show it to you.
Let's move on to chordophones.
The chordophones - sound with strings: so, every instrument with strings.
Here are some, we're going to talk about them later on.
The membranophones, it's the drum family: all those that have an elastic membrane stretched over a resonator or a frame.
Here, we're not quite there with a tin can, but not far either.
It means that the lid, as it's welded onto the body of the can, can be imagined as a sort of metallic membrane stretched over the resonator.
But not really.
And the idiophones.
So here, let's look at its etymology;
"idiophone": the prefix "idios" comes from Greek.
It means, and it's a bit upsetting, it means "one's own,"
and "phone" means "sound,"
so it's the sound of the object itself.
It's the biggest family, because, basically, everything is an idiophone.
My tin can - it's an idiophone,
the table: an idiophone,
the floor: and idiophone, as well.
I'm also an idiophone.
(Body beat boxing) I'm also an aerophone
(Whistling) and a membranophone.
(Face beat boxing) (Laughter) The idiophone family, is the one we first think of for the tin can.
How can we make a sound with a tin can? Easy, we hit it.
I mentioned the steel drum that is tuned with a hammer.
We can tune a tin can in the same way.
These ones were hammered to be tuned.
It allows us to have different sounds.
(Making different tin can sounds) (Applause) Another way of tuning the cans is to inflate them.
How can you inflate a tin can?
A big box, a piece of pipe, and a hermetic taped seal.
And when I inflate it, it makes a lower note.
(Making a low sound) When I deflate it, it's higher.
(Making a higher sound out of the tin can) We can play with this.
(Music) (Applause) You might have heard the sound of the pipe, which also makes a sound.
We can easily play it.
(Making sounds with the pipe) You will notice that I discretely slipped an aerophone and a membranophone into the conference.
That's good.
(Laughter) I've respected the quotas.
We can cut it into little lamellae, like the African Sanza.
(Making sounds using the lamellae) Quite a raw sound.
We can also fix it to a rod and hit it like a bell.
(Making sounds) It's not very convincing like that.
But if I hold it the other way round (Making a sound using the rod)
(Laughter) it's a bit more interesting.
The rod is making the note.
It's the length of the rod that helps to tune it.
But the can is important for the resonance because if I suppress it, (Making a sound using the rod) it'll resonate a lot less than if I let it vibrate.
What is interesting is that, as the rod gives the pitch, with the same type of can we can create many notes.
I managed five octaves, which means 61 notes.
I'll let you imagine the instrument, it was quite bulky.
Imagine the amount of canned fruit in syrup I had to eat to create the instrument.
It was a difficult time for my family, a few painful months.
(Laughter) I didn't bring the big version.
I brought the portable one.
This instrument makes three different sounds.
There are the rods
(Making sounds using the rods) the tin cans
(Making sounds using the cans) and a sound in between, the edges of the cans (Making sounds using the cans)
whose sound is between the two.
Let me play a little bit for you.
(Music) (Applause) With a tin can, once it's open, we don't have just one object, but two.
We also have the lid; we have to find a use for it.
How do you make a sound with the lid of a tin can?
The real difficulty is to know how to hold it.
Depending on where we hold it, we change the vibrations.
The place where we hold it is the vibration node, where it doesn't vibrate.
If I hold it in my whole hand, it goes
(Making a dull sound by knocking the lid) (Laughter) If I hold it like a cymbal, by putting my fingers in the middle, the edges vibrate
- The risks of live conferences! -
(Making a sound) and if we hold it like a gong, the center vibrates.
(Making the lid sound like a gong) We can also use it by laying it down.
This way the sound is made by the can bouncing.
(Making sounds using the can) Here there's some fabric so it's not obvious.
But I have the finished version
With small nails, to stop it from moving about.
(Making sounds using the lid) I also have smaller versions.
(Laughter) With all this, I've got the start of a drum set.
See, the cymbals.
(Making cymbal-like sounds) (Applause) I was talking about cymbals.
Fixed, it sounds a bit like this.
So we tune it by cutting off more or less... (Making cymbal-like sounds) cutting off more or less from the edges
of the lid, we tune the instrument,
so the drum set's becoming more complex.
(Making cymbal-like sounds) And to finish the drum set, let's add a can of duck confit.
(Laughter) This confit box will have two purposes.
The two purposes of it:
we put it on a hi-hat stand, which will allow me to play the small lids at the bottom, with my foot
(Making drum-like sounds) (Laughter) and as it's a tin can, I can also hit it, obviously
(Making drum-like sounds) and hitting it more or less, the note changes.
(Making drum-like sounds) (Applause) The next one is a little strange.
We can't really put a label on it.
I didn't know which family to put it in.
There's this spring from a roller blind winder, a steel rope, and a tin can.
The rope is used to transfer the vibrations to the tin can that is the resonator.
And this should... (Making sounds using the spring) It has a life of its own.
With this one, it's almost a string instrument,
which is good, as it's a good transition.
So, string instruments - with tin cans, we are going to look at the harp family.
Why harps?
Acoustically, it's the most powerful.
The difference between a harp and a zither or a lyre is the position of the strings in relation to the resonance chamber.
On a harp, the strings are perpendicular to the surface.
On a zither or a lyre, they're parallel.
This one resembles a harp,
but not quite
because, acoustically, it's six little single string harps attached together on a stand.
I still call it a harp, don't worry.
I'm just nitpicking for the conference.
(Making harp-like sounds) (Applause) It's the same for the next instrument, I call this one a cimbalom.
I drew inspiration from the Hungarian cimbalom which is a kind of big, hammered string zither.
But acoustically, it's still six small harps on one stand.
(Making cimbalom-like sounds) (Applause) This one is the most harp-like of them all.
It's almost the same shape, with just one resonator this time (Making harp-like sounds) except that as it's a tin can; we can try out effects that we can't get with wood.
I'm going to fill it with water, and the water in the resonator will serve as a harmonic filter.
It's going to move around the bottom and create an aquatic sound.
(Making aquatic sounds using the tin harp) (Laughter) (Applause) This one is also a harp because the strings are perpendicular;
and inspired by the slide guitar.
I play it with a piece of metal and slide it across the strings.
It's similar to a blues guitar. (Making blues guitar-like sounds)
(Applause) From here, let's move on to guitars.
(Laughter) I brought one in, my size.
This one is quite minimalist.
A neck, a string, and a tin of sardines, a microphone, so we can hear.
And so, when it's plugged in (Making guitar-like sounds) - a bit limited, maybe -
but if we add some effects (Making guitar-like sounds and sound effects) a bit of rhythm
(Making guitar-like sounds and beat boxing) we're getting there.
(Applause) And finally,
the electric guitar, the big guns:
(Laughter) a complete guitar neck, two tins of duck confit
(Laughter) an electric guitar microphone, so we can hear, to get the strings' vibrations.
And this should ... (Making electric guitar-like sounds) (Music) (Audience clapping to the rhythm) (Riffing) (Applause) (Cheers) Thank you.
