Studio reporter: Watch out Fanny, there is a huge wave behind you!
(Laughter) Ok wait. Your cameraman must have had a bit of trouble the wave was bigger than expected.
Fanny, are you still there?
Fanny: I was expecting a shower this morning!
Sr: There it is! It's bracing, Fanny!
F: I was expecting a shower and it really wakes you up!
(Applause) Hello, I do not know this girl, I don't know who she is.
I think that after that I'm good for bloopers until the end of my life.
It was not so long ago, after all. It was last February, in St. Malo, it was an outside broadcast on the spring tides. And that day, I have to admit I felt ridiculous.
So completely ridiculous.
You see, strangely, I didn't feel ridiculous facing the camera.
Rather, that day, I felt ridiculous facing Nature, facing the power of the elements and the strength of the water.
I already knew it, but that day, I believe that I truly experienced it and I paid the price because it really hurts.
In front of the Nature, we are nothing.
We humans are ridiculous!
And yet we must admit and realize that we have become a force which influences this planet.
Life on Earth, it is only made possible through fundamental mechanisms which are generally very fragile and subtile.
And one of those mechanisms is called the greenhouse effect.
Okay, now I'm going to shatter a misconception about the subject.
Despite all the bad things that one can say about it, the greenhouse effect is beneficial.
Yes, I swear to you, the greenhouse effect is beneficial.
It is not only beneficial, the greenhouse effect is essential to life.
If there wasn't a greenhouse effect on the planet, the mean global temperature would be between -16°C and -18°C.
So there would be places on Earth where one could no longer live because of the cold.
The greenhouse effect is essential to life.
Everything starts with the sun, obviously.
The sun emits energy and as the Earth is not totally black, it absorbs a portion, that's true, but the rest is emitted as infrared radiation, returned to sender, back into space.
And that's where the greenhouse mechanism comes into play.
It traps this heat so the Earth is not completely cold.
And for the greenhouse effect to happen, there have to be tiny molecules in suspension.
That's the gas, the greenhouse gas.
We're going to take a little quiz.
Do you know what's the main greenhouse gas found in the atmosphere?
You have four choices.
Vote by a show of hands, that's simpler.
First choice: methane.
Does anyone out there think it's methane?
Not many people, mustn't be that.
Second choice: water vapor, why not?
Why not water vapor?
There is also CO², the famous carbon dioxide, the CO².
Ah, maybe CO². And the option D is "The option D". (Laughter) It is for people who don't want to answer or for climate sceptics.
I don't know if there are any of them here.
Against all expectation, the right answer is B, water vapor.
There was a big trap.
The primary greenhouse gas in the atmosphere is natural.
It's water vapor.
If there was no water vapor on the planet, there wouldn't be anything much at all: no weather and let alone climate. There would be no clouds, no rain, no snow, no typhoons, no cyclones, no storms, there would be nothing, absolutely nothing at all.
Life is only possible on the planet through the greenhouse mechanism.
But it is a mechanism which is subject to variation.
20,000 years ago, we were in an ice age and the landscape that we have today is nothing like the landscape
as it was then. For example: you could easily walk to England, because at that time the North Sea and the English Channel were covered by ice. The ice even extended to the South of France. There was ice as far as Marseille.
I have a great example to show you. It's a cave.
This cave is really brilliant. It's awesome.
This cave could have become as famous as Lascaux.
Only it's a bit difficult to get to because you have to go underwater in the rocky inlets of Marseille.
And when you reach this cave, this cavity, you see that people painted on the walls the world which was theirs a very long time ago, thousands of years ago.
And on the wall they didn't paint bisons, they painted penguins.
Yes, at that time, there were penguins in Marseille.
No, it's not a joke.
It only took an average rise in global temperature of 5 tiny degrees for all this ice to melt, for the level of the oceans to rise by 120 meters
and for all middle latitude zones to become cultivatable.
You all know that when we turn up our thermostats 2 or 3 degrees, the effect is not negligible.
2°C, 3°C even 1°C, changes everything, absolutely everything.
5 degrees, 5 little degrees, are what separates us from an ice age.
Of course there are cycles, the climate is changing all the time.
Glacial and interglacial periods, melting and freezing, sometimes heating, sometimes cooling. It's changing all the time.
The climate has always changed throughout the ages.
It's a function of astronomic parameters.
The Earth is not always situated at the same place on it's axis, and necessarily from time to time, it's a little further from the sun and this is what determines the climate cycles.
The climate hasn't waited for man in order to change.
Only it has taken time, these changes take thousands of years.
So we have a big problem, a really big problem.
Over several decades, since the Industrial Revolution actually, the climate machine has accelerated at the mind-blowing rate of 1/10th of a degree per decade.
Remember, we gained 5 degrees in 20,000 yeas and here we have gained nearly one degree in a century. The scale is changing. And sea level has already risen by 19 centimeters.
There are for sure discussions about the question.
Man is responsible, mend of discussion.
So by our industrial activities, we release all sorts of things into the atmosphere and here I come back to our greenhouse mechanism.
There is already a lot of natural water vapor.
With our industrial activities we add a little more of it, but that's not really what influences the climate.
It's other gases like CO², carbon dioxide.
Carbon dioxide is very nasty, very, very perverse because in fact it remains in the atmosphere for a long time.
It has a very strong warming power and above all a strong inertia.
What we produce today, we will still find in several decades time.
What we produce today will still be in the atmosphere in 2050.
That is really the problem.
This is a very, very pretty image from NASA.
It's very beautiful.
If you didn't know what it was, you would find it almost artistic.
But actually no.
What you see in red is pollution.
NASA has modeled the carbon cycle, with the different sources of emissions, the United States, Europe, Asia, and all of that is going to revolve in the atmosphere for dozens of years, a real pressure cooker effect,
and it's the same for lots of other gases.
It is the same for nitrous oxide, methane obviously, and flourine, there's plenty of that.
We release lots of things into the atmosphere.
A true pressure cooker effect.
Incidentally, this image, this metaphor, is not bad, it's rather eloquent.
You need to keep it in mind, you can imagine the Sun as the flame, the pressure cooker is our Earth, it's the atmosphere, this big pressure cooker is all of that, and more what is inside, the gas. It's gas that is going to boost, amplify, and activate the warming.
And the Earth gets warmer and warmer.
We don't seem to want to turn off the gas.
It's not in our plans, apparently.
In any case, it's not what we're doing when we tap into our fossil fuels reserves, or even worse, when we drill for new oil and gas fields.
We don't really seem to want to turn off the gas, and the Earth goes on getting warmer.
But this heat is not exactly going where we think.
There's another misconception around the issue, too.
All this heat, is not stored in the atmosphere, but in the oceans.
Yes, in the oceans. These are the true radiators of the world.
90% of that heat will get stored there. It's the oceans that really drive the climate machine.
You have to remember that 70% of the Earth's surface is water.
Multiply that by 4000 m of avarege depth and that creates an absolutely enormous heat tank.
The starting point for violent weather events is the heat contained in the oceans.
And here's where I put my weather forecaster's hat on to tell you that beasts like Haiyan in the Philippines or Katrina, Sandy, etc. in the United States, all drew their energy from the heat contained in the oceans.
It happens at the level of the equator.
The temperature must exceed a critical threshold of 26°C on average to a depth of 50 meters and there, that's where those monsters arise.
The more the oceans warm up, necessarily, the more we can expect a resurgence of these violent phenomena.
There are also heat waves, which testify to this rapid climate change.
We have to underline, that to be meaningful, climate data has to be analyzed over at least 30 years.
And that's the point, when you look back, the global average temperature curve is climbing.
If we look at the last ten hottest years since weather records began, those ten hottest years all took place in the 21st century, without exception.
A real balloon effect, with two notable examples which are very recent, 2014 and 2015.
A few months ago, records were broken all over the world.
A spectacular and unusually early heatwave in Spain.
It was the same in France too, last June, and in Egypt, Israel, and Pakistan.
There was a fatal heatwave in India, while on the other side of the planet, California is fast becoming completely aris, with fires breaking out everywhere at this very moment.
So what happens when these heatwaves take hold?
There are droughts, a threat to agriculture, a direct threat to people, a threat to geopolitical stability, and ultimately a threat to peace.
And we are not all exposed in the same way to the climate changes that are occurring.
I'm thinking for example, about those small, low-lying Pacific islands which are in the front line as the waters rise.
Over there, at this moment, those little countries are not hatching a future change plan, but quite clearly, an evacuation plan.
In all events, those little islands are doomed to disappear.
There is an image that personally I find really terrifying.
I find it absolutely horrible.
Also, it's an image which could, become common in the future.
It's the biggest fence in the world. It was built in stone and barbed wire by the Indians to prevent inhabitants of Bangladesh from migrating North, because they are fleeing their coast which is constantly being hit by typhoons.
There is a saying by Paul Valery that I really love
and it strikes a chord with me. Paul Valery, the great poet, said, "Man quite often knows what he is doing, but he never knows what he does causes".
In other words, Man believes he can control everything but he is often unaware of the consequences of what he does.
And yet, it's time to take action. It's time to act to make a positive impact on nature.
2°C is our target.
Or rather, it is the threshold that must not be crossed.
2°C is our challenge, and above all, that's what's at stake at COP21, the major climate conference that France is getting ready to host quite soon now, in a few weeks time.
It starts at Le Bourget in Paris on November 30th.
Of course, the negotiations are the business of our heads of state, it's the business of our leaders, but it's our problem too, all of us each one of us, all of you in this room.
We must be convinced and climate-aware.
There's no time left.
Not more than 2° by the end of the century.
That's exactly what will give us time to adapt what will allow us to avoid the most serious climate effects.
And especially, it will give us a certain level of control over the climate situation.
Facing the Nature, we are nothing, we are absolutely ridiculous.
And yet, paradoxically, we are capable of upsetting the fundamental balances that enable life on this planet.
Facing the Nature, we are nothing, we are ridiculous, and yet, our scope for action is immense.
That's what I want to tell you, it's good news. It's excellent news.
This climate crisis is an amazing opportunity, a chance to to give meaning to progress once more.
What will our world, our society, or our planet look like in a few decades time? Well, it's really just a question of becoming conscious and making choices.
(Applause)
A standard, yet another standard, but don't worry, this isn't a standard like the others.
POETCom, you're wondering what it is, aren't you?
It is simply a regional organisation that promotes development using its organic quality.
It is hosted by the Pacific Community, that most of you undoutably know of, the former SCP, is now called POETCom.
I'm lucky enough to have been part of POETCom for the last eight years, and for the last four, part of its board of directors.
So what good has POETCom done in the last eight years?
It has created a standard, the first, of organic farming in Oceania.
Of course, it was applied in the field, mostly on the west coast of the Pacific for various geopolitical reasons, this may change when French Polynesia integrates the forum, but we shall see.
So, things that have changed on the west coast of the Pacific, and now, we have got to this famous biotourism standard, in its final stages of development, but it is pratically functional.
Who is it financed by?
By the organisations, whose logos you see here, and you're also going to say "ecotourism standard," there are many around the world, indeed there are many, but this is about pushing ecotourism towards biotourism.
The idea is also to associate organic production and tourism, for the cohesion of sustainable development and potential identity.
And to what end?
To a mutual, environmental and cultural enhancement.
Our values that must be upheld.
For this we need a reference point, a standard, and its application.
What is this organic quality that I mentioned?
All over the world, you have been able to see an inevitable progression, in the product market, but now also in cosmetics, we have surpassed farming, texile too, and now services are also certified organic.
In Oceania, concepts are added, the standard evolves, in short, the added concept, it that of nature and of culture, certified, of course.
And the notion of "care" is also added, which means treatment, concern and goodwill, a notion that is found in organic production, but also in tourism and through the first of these criteria in Oceania, culture and traditions, which are guides and pillars of social balance.
The second pillar, ethics and fairness, that also represent the pillars of sustainable development.
Ecology and biodiversity are key to balance of life on Earth.
Finally, health and sustainability, you can't have sustainable development without public health, of course.
I'm going to add a notion, through all those I have already introduced, which is that of adjustment to climate change, and which already apears in the Pacific Organic Standard.
As for the challenges concerning the application of this standard. We can name the costs of the certification and the procedures that can be problematic, also the fraudulent claims that can cause problems, requests for local products that can be unsuitable, and we are going to see why. A precarious supply can cause problems, and the evolution of the legislation. In Fenua, we have a national law that regulates organic production, the national law 2001-1, and which is sadly limited to food products, while there is a high demand for flowers, which is significant in tourism, isn't it? Traditional oils, seeds and now services.
See, some examples, a series of operators that are efficient in the Pacific and who defend the culture, a culture that shapes the environment and conversely, an environment that shapes the culture.
We now use the term cultural landscape. A notion that really means something to our visitors.
Regarding its feasability, Eden Park has already tried it.
If Eden Park now advises and trains, it used to be a botanical garden from 1986 to 2006, with over five hectares and all its products were certified.
The products used in its restaurant, for its fruit juice bar and for a dozen of its agri-food products, a park energised by radient and thriving staff, and by 100% renewable energy.
The operators concerned are displayed here.
You glimpsed the organic quality logo, there's a French and an English version, POETCom wants this to be a regional pennant used for cohesion.
Always more cohesion, always stronger.
We can tangibly and strategically imagine the intra-Pacific channels, with connected paths. An attraction to a single ticket, there's diversity in discovery. It's a question of mutualising the attraction for visitors who take home the strong values the world needs so much.
The different types of certification that are being considered today, but other options are being assessed. Firstly, full certification in the context of complete hotel structures who can be fully certified, or just the restaurant, or simply part of the menu, or dishes from the restaurant.
For the next steps, POETCom is working on a guarantee scheme. So, the implementation of procedures, there are two different things, the standards and their control systems and implementation systems, it's a guarantee scheme that is being developed.
(Applause)
I'd like to introduce Hugo.
Hugo is 17 years old, he's spent the past 6 years of his life in a school for the mentally impaired.
Thanks to the persistent help of his parents and teachers, he's made some significant progress recently.
But Hugo does not speak, most of the time, he doesn't seem to understand anything we tell him.
When he gets anxious, he has repetitive compulsions, like rocking back and forth with his head between his hands.
In fact, Hugo is autistic.
And because his brain is wired differently than most, Hugo perceives sensory stimulation at 100 times the intensity you or I would.
For example, when Hugo sees a face, it's as if 1,000 photos get stored in his memory.
That's what makes it so difficult for him to look others in the eyes.
He needs time to take in all this information.
To live in such a world would make difficult, almost impossible, any form of communication or social interaction.
And so Hugo is an exceptional child, but he's not alone.
Today, one child in 100 is born autistic.
They represent over 70 million people in the world.
And we, for our part, have limited or no means to communicate and interact with them.
So this is the mission we've given ourselves: helping exceptional children to get outside of their own bubble.
And from this idea Leka was born, an extremely cute little ball of a robot, that I'm happy and proud to present to your today.
(Applause) Leka was developed hand in hand with the kids, with their parents, and with professionals, to be sure that he responds well to their needs.
Because, to interact with children, a cute little companion is the ideal object.
Leka possesses a few key qualities: he's stable, never tired to repeat the same thing 100 times, he's predictable, since all his behaviors were programmed in advance, he's autonomous, no need for a tablet or smartphone to function, and he's interactive: when someone interacts with him, he responds.
If I flip him over, he turns himself right side up, if I'm gentle with him, he's happy, if I'm mean to him, he's sad.
All these qualities make kids eager to play with Leka.
And this play is like the trojan horse of education.
For example, we learned from some kids playing hide-and-seek,
That seems basic, but there's a lot of rules at work: collaboration, taking turns, patience, all tricky concepts for autistic children.
However, thanks to Leka, the kids have succeeded in playing completely autonomously.
So, a robot that rolls, I'll admit that's not revolutionary.
But where Leka is unique is in the applications we've placed inside, that enable him to adapt to each child.
And a robot to help in the care of exceptional children that is a small revolution.
Today, Leka is the best friend of 70 kids.
Our tests show true improvement to the communication and the engagement of the children in the program.
This is only the beginning.
Today, we're working to bring our product to market, so every child in the world can have this cute little companion to help them play, learn, and grow.
The name Leka comes from Swedish, meaning "to play" and "to care for."
That's exactly what we're going to do.
Today, 1 in every 100 children is limited in how they interact with our world, it's time to give them that ability.
Thank you.
(Applause)
Sometimes, I wonder if I’m not a bit masochistic, because to spend your life trying to understand how the brain works you kind of have to be so.
That said, I may have mitigating circumstances.
After having been born into a Jewish family in Cairo; spoken Hebrew at home, then Arab, and French of course; gone to a Catholic school St Jean-Baptiste de la Salle, to learn catechism; learned a grasp of the Coran; then lived in Israel and seen the other side of the fence, I concluded: one, a secular atheist country is pretty cool, and two, we can approach any subject no matter how complicated.
Now, life is complicated, for sure.
The brain is very complex. There are a million billion
connections in the human brain,
a million billion connections and each one of them is far more complicated than a mobile phone, because it learns and the phone doesn’t.
That would mean that each human being possesses the equivalent of 200,000 mobile phones.
We can understand why this "telephone exchange" is so complex
and tends to be overloaded. So, in 1986, I was appointed unit director at the INSERM, in Paris, at Port Royal, in a maternity ward that had four floors where there were women giving birth, planned cesareans, premature births, etc. I was in charge of the top floor.
I took over the post after a great guy, Alexandre Nikovski, who was the first to understand that pregnant women need protection because pregnancy is the period "of living dangerously."
He fought to ensure that during pregnancy, there could be some time off, etc. He was a really great person.
My wife and I went with him out to lunch after my appointment, and he said finally, "All is well! We’re replacing an Azhkenazi Jew with a Sephardic Jew. Your wife is fairly smart, so necessarily, you must be good!"
So apparently, proficiency was not the main criterion.
So, I began to work on the development of the brain about which we know very little.
These are unborn childs. One seems to be working on a math problem, scratching his head. This one wants to go out as the food isn’t very good. And this one can’t decide if he wants to play football with OM or PSG.
Why am I showing you this? What does this mean?
Well, it means there are lots of things happening in the womb.
In a monkey's brain for example, a cortical neuron has 7,000 connections before birth and 10,000 after birth.
So this is not at all a period of inertia.
The first thing to take from this is that the brain in utero moves a lot, develops rapidly and is highly active.
Obviously, to make a comparison, a brain is a lot more complex than a plane, a submarine or a boat.
The major difference is that when we assemble a plane - I’ve never built a plane but I can imagine - the engine isn’t running, but in this case, it is.
The engine is running while the brain is being built. The process is identical: an architect creates a blueprint, then there are site meetings to ensure all is going well, otherwise everything would go wrong.
So the first thing to understand is that the brain in utero works a lot.
The second thing to understand is that not only it does all this work, but the electric currents - brain electric currents are my specialty - the currents that are generated by these neurons as they’re being formed are nothing like those of adults.
The immature brain is not a small adult brain.
It has its own language, one that’s totally different from that of the adult.
By the way, this explains the reason why it took me years to convince the administrators that we can't give to a baby the drug of an adult and just split the dose. It makes no sense because the processes are totally different.
We must understand how the brain develops in order to heal it.
Now why this image? Well, Imagine I’m a conductor - unfortunately, I’m not - and we're going to play Brahms' Second Symphony with Jascha Heifetz on violon, then I’m telling you they should be playing Brahms during the rehearsals. Well, in this case, they didn't.
A group is playing rock. Another is playing Bach, and yet another is playing whatever.
Then, comes showtime, and they all play Brahms.
So it has nothing to do with an adult brain.
The question to ask, obviously, is why is it like that?
Let's take the visual system. The human retina is formed almost at the end of the first trimester of pregnancy.
We see nothing, we forget everything.
In all animal species, the retina generates an activity caled "retinal waves" which does not enable vision at all, but which is critical because if we block it, the visual system develops badly.
So here is this activity that is not related to the senses but has a major function.
So, with my friend Nick Spitzer, we came up with what we called: "the checkpoint theory." The idea is while something is being built, this building or anything else, we have to check what’s being done.
The construction of the brain isn't like pushing a button, and then from one cell I get a brain, thanks to genetics. That's ridiculous!
Indeed, there are checks. So we proposed to call them "checkpoints."
For example, when the Channel tunnel was built, there were these enormous machines on both sides of the Channel - they hadn’t left Europe at the time - that drilled until they came face to face.
Without GPS, they could have gone like this or this, but not like this.
It takes continuous checking.
What I proposed was that this continuous checking is this electrical activity present during the brain development.
While the cell is maturing, just like an apple, it sends electrical signals that indicate its state and its stage of construction.
The aim of this activity in the retina is to tell the visual brain "I’m here, not there,"
like basically, a GPS.
All that sounds good but you’ll probably ask, "That’s interesting but what happens when things goes wrong?"
We see cases of neurological and psychiatric illnesses and, as you know, we’ve been trying to treat them for centuries without success
for lots of reasons, in part because they arise very early, and we don’t know what they do to the brain.
But if we think a little bit, there're two ways to go about it. The first is like in "The Imaginary Invalid" by Moliere, when Argan's servant says, "The lungs! The lungs, I say to you."
Well, geneticists say, '"The genes! The genes! it’s all genetic!"
Now, after pondering a little more, I proposed a concept called "neuro-archeology."
The idea's very simple: if one day this building collapses, we’ll discover that in one spot, there was a poorly built post that rose out of one floor that itself collided something else, and at one point, everything collapsed.
The idea is exactly the same: during the maturation of the brain, there are sequences of maturation as I told you before, in case something happens in the womb such as a gene, a mutation, pesticides, stress, alcohol, whatever that can happens in life or in the environment basically. This is important because, if we come back to genetics for a second, contrary to what is told, the vast majority of psychiatric illnesses are not of genetic origin. They do not involve genetics
such as Alzheimer or Parkinson. They may involve mutations in very few patients. They are not monogenic, which means that if, for example, a kid who has a mutation that predisposes him to be diabetic, goes to McDonald's everyday, he’ll indeed be diabetic.
If he chooses to live on an island and eats fresh fish and pesticide-free tomatoes, he probably won’t be diabetic.
So it is about susceptibility. what we call "epigenetic." It means that the environment creates a susceptibility that will be expressed as an illness in some cases and not in others.
Now, the second way is the following. It consists in trying to understand how the brain is built, how the sequence of maturation is deviated, and from there, start to think.
Imagine the fundamental thesis is confirmed, I believe it will be a major step forward in the understanding and the treatment of neurological and psychiatric illnesses. I’m saying that when there is an "attack" in the womb, whatever the cause may be, genetic or not, it modifies the sequence of maturation,
and the neuron that was supposed to mature does not mature,
just like an apple that doesn’t ripen.
It doesn't connect where it should, it doesn't go where it should. So the thesis is that this misplaced neuron remains immature in the adult brain.
In this perspective, many neurological or psychiatric ailments would be due to displaced neurons that have kept immature electrical characteristics.
Ar first, I explained that the developing brain has a different function than the adult one.
Those neurons that are here, here or there, produce activities that interfere with their surroundings.
So, what I propose is a kind of pharmacological intervention using drugs that only block these immature neurons in an adult brain since their properties are precisely different, right?
That's the idea and it needed to be proved.
This can’t be demonstrated on humans but on experiments with animals, be it for Parkinson, Alzheimer or autism.
In fact, we have noticed that a neuron is an electrical machine.
Ions come in and go out: potassium, sodium, calcium, chlorine, etc. It produces electricity that codes what we are.
Everything that we integrate is just that.
Among the ions that play an important role, one is particularly important: chlorine.
We have discovered that in an adult naive neuron, there's very little chlorine.
In a young naive neuron, there is a lot of chlorine.
It completely changes the neuron' stability.
We also discovered that in animal models of autism, the situation is somewhat similar to that of an immature brain.
So, it's just like what I said. A neuron that is young has a lot of chlorine. it matures, and then has none. If it matures "in the wrong way," it retains a lot of chlorine.
So, as you see, the consequence is that chlorine comes in here, but here it goes out, so the electrical response is totally different.
Me and my friend Éric Lemonnier, one of the best French experts on the treatment of autism, who has been working with autistic children for ages, we've thought ... Well, chance has a role. Five or six years ago, I didn’t know what autism was. I wasn’t working on it at all.
I was helding a conference for parents of autistic children and spoke about chlorine and so on, and Eric said to me, "You know, if there’s a lot of chlorine, there’s reason to think that these kids are autistic due to clinical reasons, since when we give them Valium, instead of going to sleep as adults would, they get extremely agitated, so this probably means there’s a lot of chlorine inside."
So we made the extremely naive hypothesis that we could reduce the chlorine levels, by using a diuretic which is a molecule that, when ingested,
makes you need to urinate. Why?
Because the same happens in the kidneys.
The same system that exists in the kidneys, exists in the brain.
There are diuretics on the market that people have used for a long time to treat hypertension and cerebral edema. We took five kids in Brest and gave them a diuretic and it seemed to have a positive effect. We did a second trial with about 50 children, a double blind trial and it worked. I’m going to show you one of those kids.
You’re going to see a child before and after treatment using diuretics for three months.
(Video) Woman: ... for baby’s birthday.
So for baby's birthday ...
Please come, Allan!
Y.B.A.: Notice that he doesn’t make eye-contact. (Video) Woman: Come!
(Child' screams) Y.B.A.: He stimulates himself by playing with the light, you'll see. (Child' screams) Child: Mama ... Y.B.A.: She has a lot more patience than me.
(Video) Woman : And on baby’s birthday cake, I put some candles.
Please come and put the candle on?
Put the candle on.
Put the candle on.
Y.B.A.: Not once did he look her in the eye.
Here is three months after treatment.
(Video) Woman: For baby's birthday, let's make a cake.
Let's stick the candles on top.
Do you want to put one on?
Hop!
Hop!
Good job!
Let's light the candles. It’s hot!
And let's sing: Happy Birthday to you. (Singing) Happy Birthday to you. Y.B.A.: Notice, he’s looking her in the eye.
(Video: Child blows the candles out) Woman clapping hands:
Yay! Good job, Allan!
Let’s take the candles off.
Y.B.A.: You’ve probably guessed I don’t believe in miracles,
and this is no miracle.
This child wasn’t speaking before and he still isn’t, okay?
But parents are all telling us the same thing : "There are more present. They interact with us more."
That’s important because with autism, it’s not just the children that suffer but parents as well.
So the fact that they become more sociable is extremely important. It means they participate more in society. I don’t think there will be a pill that will cure this illness such as one can take an aspirin for a headache
because, if you’ve understood what I’ve told you so far, it's an early occurring condition that modifies parts of the brain, and this can't be undone with some miracle cure.
However, schooling will cure it.
If we can get these kids into school, it will make them more sociable.
Why am I showing you this image?
The not-so-young among you will know. It's an extract from "Who’s afraid of Virginia Woolf ?"
with Richard Burton and Elizabeth Taylor. Indeed, you see what’s going on: they’re screaming at each other because he made a move on this one, etc.
But if you were looking at the plate here, as an autistic child would do when avoiding eye-contact, you wouldn't understand anything.
So, it’s not that they're not empathetic but they don’t look where they should.
If you don’t look at peoples eyes, you don't know if the other is crying or laughing.
With Nouchine Hadjikhani, we chose some autistic children and showed them pictures that were sad or joyful, before and after the treatment, and we noticed that they watched the eyes more than before as parents have confirmed.
So, it works but it’s not a miracle cure. It’s a treatment with secondary effects such as less potassium in the blood which must be kept under control, but for the moment, no other medication on the market can help those kids.
We've initiated a second phase. Recently, we were authorized by the European authorities to do a phase 3.
Now, I’m focusing on the brain during birth about which we know very little.
How does a brain get ready for birth?
How complex that is!
What does it do?
What happen if things go wrong?
The mother might have hyper tension or diabetes, whatever.
How does that work? What are the consequences?
It’s one of the major public health issues we’re not dealing with since neither the pharmaceutical industry nor our politicians are interested because obviously, it’s a complicated issue.
In conclusion, art and science are not the same thing.
But sometimes, they do have similarities.
The process we call "creativity" is precisely as follow:
a process by which we leave the beaten path, we leave all orthodoxies behind, and we think about things differently.
The last picture I will show you is this because I’m a fan of Modigliani. When he painted that cellist, one student said to his master at the Grande Chaumière school: "That arm isn’t right, it’s too long,"
to which the master answered majestically: "An arm that is so well painted is never too long."
He expressed what creativity expresses, that is the leaving of the beaten path to really show what a cellist does.
Thank you.
(Applause)
Good evening.
My name is Bernard Lavallée; I'm a nutritionist;
and I hate talking about nutrients and calories.
These days, we talk more about nutrients than about food as such.
For example, someone might say, "A balanced meal must contain at least 15 g of protein" or for example, "Omega 3 is important for the brain, eat fish!"
or "This low-fat yogurt is going to keep you trim" or, the worst, "Oh no thanks! I don't eat gluten."
We live under the dictatorship of nutritionism, a concept created by Gyorgy Scrinis, a Food Politics professor at the University of Melbourne-Australia.
Nutritionism is our inclination to think of our food in terms of its components, the vitamins, minerals, antioxidants, carbohydrates, lipids, and calories that are contained in it.
Nutritionism is born out of the science of nutrition because, officially, nutrition is a science that examines the connection between food and health.
But in reality, nutrition was born when we discovered that our food contains components that can have an effect on our health depending on how much of them we eat.
So the more we embedded the science of nutrition into our food, the more we began to accept the idea that to remain in good health, we should consume the right amount of nutrients and calories.
The day we agreed to this, then we agreed that to eat well, we should eat things we can't see, smell, taste or quantify;
since as consumers, we don't have the means to know or feel what is in the apple that we are eating.
So we have become dependant on nutrition specialists.
We need specialists who say, "This is good for you, eat it.
This is not, don't eat it." because, as a simple consumer, I don't know any more because I have no tools to know it.
It's a real problem because talking about nutrients and stressing their importance don't work in real life.
It wouldn't be so bad if it worked, but it doesn't,
so my aim in this presentation is to show you that we should stop focusing on nutrients and calories alone.
First it must be understood that no one lives in a laboratory. and that the most credible health studies are known as "double-blind randomized controlled trials."
So for instance, when we want to develop a medicine, we give the new medicine to a group of patients and a placebo to another group.
We give the placebo because, for some reason, people feel better for following a treatment, even if the treatment is fake.
So it's important that in testing a medicine, more people be cured by the drug than by the placebo.
But with food, it's extremely difficult or even impossible to use a placebo.
How can you hide from people the fact that it's a banana they are eating?
or that they are eating five fruits and vegetables a day?
It's impossible.
So as a result, we've started to conduct studies more on the components of food themselves in the form of antioxidant extracts, powdered fruits, fish oils, etc., and less on food as a whole.
But we don't live in a laboratory.
We eat whole foods.
So results that talk about an antioxidant extracted in a lab don't make sense because we eat lots of foodstuffs all at the same time.
Now let's do an exercise.
A bit of interaction, I'm sorry!
(Laughter) First, please raise your hand if you know someone - it might be you - who suffers or has suffered from an illness such as diabetes, a heart disease, or cancer.
Please raise your hands.
Most people raise their hands -
now you can lower it.
We're going to redo the same exercise.
Please raise your hand if you know someone who suffers from an illness such as scurvy, beriberi or rickets.
No one?
Nutritional science was developed in a very different context than the food and health systems today.
Back then, nutritional deficiencies were more common than today.
But to remedy a nutritional deficiency is really easy.
Scurvy, for example, has a cause and a solution.
The person is sick, you give vitamin C,
and poof! She or he is healed.
It's so easy: a cause and a solution.
And since nutrition was developed in this context, we started to believe that to heal health problems, we just needed to find either the nutrient that saves or the nutrient that caused harm.
However today, nutritional deficiencies are no longer the main issue.
What disease kills the most people in Canada nowadays is heart problems, cancer, and diabetes.
But these problems are caused by a whole range of different factors that go even beyond the field of nutrition.
Yet, we are still thinking in the same way and are still searching for the nutrient responsible for all our problems.
So we say "It is fat! ... No, it's sugar!
... No, it's salt! ...No, it's gluten!..."
We are always pointing the finger
at the one we need to eliminate
from our diet to heal.
In reality, we can no longer think this way because we'll never find the culprit for all today's illnesses since they are caused by many different things.
So we must change how we think about it.
Let's do another exercise.
I'm going to show you five foods: bananas, oranges, milk, spinach and eggs.
I'm going to name the nutrients, and you all are going to tell me in which food we find that nutrient.
So, in which food do we find potassium?
(Audience) Bananas!
In which food do we find calcium?
(Audience) Milk!
In which food do we find vitamin C?
(Audience) Oranges!
In which food do we find iron?
(Audience) Spinach!
How is it that in our heads, bananas equals potassium, milk equals calcium, spinach equals iron, and oranges equals vitamin C?
What has made us create these associations between one food and one nutrient?
Well, I mean no offense, but most of the foods I've shown you contain many other nutrients besides the ones that are here.
Each food item contains hundreds of different molecules.
Yet we, as humans, we have decided that in bananas, potassium is the most important nutrient.
But a banana isn't potassium,
a banana is a banana.
In fact, a banana is 99% not potassium,
yet in our heads, banana equals potassium.
Why is it so dangerous to keep thinking this way?
Well, because we assign the role of a nutrient to the foodstuff itself.
And the agri-food industry uses this strategy to sell us their products.
So let's say we decide that in linseed the beneficial thing is Omega 3,
then the agri-food industry could decide to manufacture a chocolate biscuit, add Omega 3 from linseed in it and say to us "My biscuit really is the best for you because we use Omega 3 from linseed."
And we already know that linseed is good because of its Omega 3 content.
In reality, eating a chocolate biscuit or eating linseeds do not have the same impact on our health.
So a food is much more than the sum of its nutrients.
Next, we have to understand that a food is alive.
When an apple tree is grown for exemple, the type of apple, the soil in which it grows, the water we use, the fertilizers, the quality of sunlight, the climate during summer, whatever, all are going to affect the nutritional value of the apples we'll harvest.
Now let's go further and take the same apple tree and the same branch. The apple grown at the branch's end and the one grown in the middle do not have the same nutritional value.
So when you eat an apple, you don't know exactly what nutrients are in it.
It's impossible to determine "I got 23 milligrams of this,
32 milligrams of that," no! Impossible!
Besides, even the agri-food industry can't do this.
So on the "nutritional facts" table where are indicated figures, well, the industry is allowed a 20% margin of error because it's next to impossible to calculate the exact figure since food is alive.
So we can't control precisely what we eat.
And actually, even if we could, once we shallow it, we still can't control what is absorbed by our body.
I usually like to give almonds as an example.
Let's take exactly the same quantity of almonds.
So whether we eat them raw and whole, or as almond butter or almond oil, we are not going to absorb the same amount of calories.
Why?
Because if you've ever eaten almonds, you know that when you bite them, some little bits get stuck between your teeth. Well, it happens the same in our belly.
It doesn't become a totally crushed almond butter in our belly.
Our intestines aren't as effective as a machine producing almond butter.
And this is on purpose.
It means that these small bits are going to pass straight through because our body can't digest them.
However, our body has evolved over thousands of years to absorb certain things and not others, and that's okay.
This is how we have evolved while consuming real food.
So even if we could control what we ingest, we would not know what is absorbed after ingestion.
The other important thing to understand is that food processing can totally change the effect of a nutrient.
For example, we know pretty well by now that when we ingest the sugar found in oranges as a beverage that we drink or as a whole orange that we eat, this sugar is not absorbed in the same way by our body and does not have the same effect on our health.
Another example I like to give is butter and margarine.
In the 60s, we discovered that butter contained saturated fats that could have a harmful impact on our heart's health.
So we started to tell people, "Stop eating butter, it's extremely dangerous.
You'll have a heart attack if you eat it.
Stop! Instead, eat margarine."
Margarine is made from vegetable oils that contain polyunsaturated fats.
These fats seem to have a beneficial effect on the heart.
But the problem with oils is that they're liquid at room temperature.
So we had to work out a way to solidify them.
Then, a process called "hydrogenation" was used.
Hydrogenation transforms those liquid oils into solid fats at room temperature, and we can spread them like butter.
So it became an ideal replacement for butter, that contained unsaturated fats good for our heart.
So for a long time, people were told "Eat margarine, it's better for you,"
until we realized that... Oops!
Hydrogenation causes a modification of the fatty acids and transforms those polyunsaturated fats to what we call "trans fats" that are so bad for our health that they're now banned.
In Canada, we can't use them anymore.
So it means that we couldn't known
as long as we hadn't studied its effects.
Right? So today they're banned because we've done some research and we know that they have an harmful impact on the heart.
However, today in Quebec, one out of two calories we consume comes from ultra-processed foods such as margarine, fizzy drinks, ready meals, cereal bars, biscuits, cakes, etc.
All these foods undergo tons of different processings, and we still don't know the impact of these processes on the nutrients these foods contain.
Now let's take this even further. I have already told you that partially hydrogenated oils that are the main source of trans fats, are currently banned in Canada.
But last I heard, you can still spread your margarine,
and it is still in the solid form.
Have you ever wonder why you can still spread your margarine although hydrogenation is prohibited?
Well, it's because industry has found out new processes, notably what is known as "interesterification."
This process changes the structure of the fatty acids, the components of the oil, and make them solid at room temperature.
But the new molecules that are created don't exist anywhere in Nature.
I'm not telling you "It's man made,
so it's necessarily harmful." No!
But we have basically no studies on the effect of these new unknown molecules on our health.
Yet, at the moment, people are told "There's no more trans fat in margarine. Eat up! It's good for you!
And we added in some avocado oil, it's even better!"
Are we going to say ten years later, "Oops!"?
(Laughter) So if focusing on the nutrients is not the solution to eat well, then what is the solution?
What are the five scientific tricks that would enable us to stop this reductionist thinking about food?
Well first, we need to eat a variety of foods because by eating lots of different foods, you'll get lots of different nutrients.
It doesn't matter if we know them or not, or their impact on our body. It's fine because the more you vary your diet, the more your body is able to find all that it needs.
Secondly, we need to eat less ultra-processed foods.
We don't know precisely why this type of food is harmful, but we know that the more we consume it, the more our food quality worsens, and this leads to various health problems such as obesity, cardiovascular diseases, and diabetes.
Next, we need to rely on vegetables, because today's focus of many studies is on the Mediterranean diet, and the vegetarian diet.
So people who fill their plates with fruits, vegetables, legumes, whole grains and nuts, seem to be in greater health than others and to suffer less from the ailments that kill most Canadians annually.
Next, we need to listen to the signals sent by our body.
Today, we are constantly connected to the notifications sent by our phones and we are no longer connected to the notifications sent by our body.
Yet it has a whole arsenal of messages to tell us when we should eat and when we should stop eating.
And often, as we age, we stop listening to them.
Yet it would be simpler, and we'd have fewer problems if people followed the simple rule of eating when they're hungry and then stopping when they are no longer hungry.
To conclude - but I could have started by saying this - we need to give place to enjoyment because nowadays, we talk about food in terms of science or of nutrients, due to the nutritional dictatorship in which we live.
But the reality is that food is much more than a bunch of nutrients.
Food connects us to our culture, our family. Although it should be a streaming source of pleasure in our lives, it's become a source of anxiety due to excessive intellectualization.
But I guarantee you if you follow these five steps, not only your will be in better health than the majority of people living in industrialized countries, but you'll be able, just like me, to stop talking about nutrients and calories.
Thank you.
(Applause)
I am going to talk about the way a news report considerably changed my whole life.
Yet, it's the kind of report you may have seen before, we have all seen reports like this.
It's about war, about victims, and about trauma.
But for me at that moment, it really triggered something.
Maybe because I was 23 years old, a student in psychology, I was more sensitive to this.
So in this report, there was a little girl, a little girl who had tics, you know, these little convulsive twitching that can't be controlled.
Her eyes were affected by
these convulsive movements. In the report, she was filmed at her school in Aleppo, and she was glued to her teacher and blinking so often that she almost couldn't see the world around her. At that moment,
things clicked in my mind.
That little girl touched me because she really made me become aware of all the neural disorders that can occur following a death threat.
She truly made me understand what is Post-Traumatic Stress Disorder (PTSD)
Post-Traumatic Stress Disorder is something that can happen after a death threat and cause the appearance of long-term symptoms.
It may be feelings of insecurity, feelings of constant danger, but also nightmares and feeling overwhelmed.
PTSD can also bring about depressive affects.
You inevitably feel worse and potentially suffer from anxiety.
Now you survived and you are alive, but you are destroyed inside.
So something had to be done. Working on PTSD obviously means working on thoughts, but working on our thoughts is not that easy.
Have you tried sometimes to control your thoughts?
Does it work?
Let's try a little exercise together.
I am going to ask you to close your eyes.
Yes, go ahead, close your eyes.
Imagine a polar bear.
Please answer my questions in your heads, otherwise it will get hard to understand.
So are you seeing the polar bear?
In your heads!
(Laughter)
Is it big? Small?
Are you seeing it from afar? Or up close?


From the side? From a three-quarter view?
Is its mouth open or closed?

Does it seem rather nice or threatening?
OK, that's it, you can
open your eyes again.
Now you can think of anything but a polar bear.
And raise your hand once you have lost.
(Laughter) Oh, wow!
You can see now how hard it is to work on your thoughts, to control our thinking process.
So I got involved.
I started as a volunteer for a humanitarian association that was intervening in Syria by facilitating the transit of medical material and food parcels, and the sponsorship of orphans.
I then became a trainee and ended up as a humanitarian project manager.
That's when I was assigned the task to conceive a new project.
Intuitively, I thought of creating a school, that would contain in the same location a psychological support center.
We would take care of the educational and psychological aspects, and both were expected to support each other.
The project saw the light of day.
And we saw results: many things were implemented in terms of therapy.
We did art-therapy, exposure therapy, but we could still tell something more was possible. We felt that something could be further improved, that we had to dig deeper to find results.
So I started looking into it, reading litterature, and I found the work of Prof. Wissam El-Hage, a university professor here in Tours, and his colleague Prof. Alain Brunet, researcher in Psychology in Canada.
They had developed a short therapy called "Potentiation Therapy".
It is very simple: you go over with your patients the story of their trauma, meaning you go over and write the trauma they went through.
Then, you expose them to their own traumatic story.
And you add to this exposure therapy a medication called Propranolol.
It is a beta blocker that blocks stress responses, and it is supposed, when you read again the traumatic story, to separate the emotional charge from the memory.
And thus, you can decrease the symptoms.
We've applied this protocol within an association I created called "No Lost Generation," which was founded in Northern Syria, within the territory in a refugee camp.
All of these children are part of it.
Two hundred fifty-eight children attend the center everyday.
And 121 of them went through the protocol that I just described.
When they went through the protocol, before doing the statistical analysis as researchers do, we observed a few things.
We saw children who started to live again, to smile and play again.
We saw children coming back to life, opening up to others, having fun, doing also silly things, and who had resumed their children lives.
This little boy you see in the middle, we could not photography him before the protocol.
Even from above or with a big lens far away in another room, it was very complicated.
And here in this picture, you can see him, he had taken the initiative to organize a drawing workshop with other children.
He was the child the most withdrawn socially.
Then we statistically processed the data.
We did our research work.
And the results also told us a lot.
We have in average of 40% improvement in the health of children on all the dimensions we tested: anxiety, depression, everything linked with avoidance - 40% over a week, it is a massive result.
Of course, we're going to keep pushing, to look for other things.
We will try to find even more effective solutions, try to use different means for the most resistant ones.
But in these moments, about which I have share a bit of this life path, there is also a message.
And the message I really wanted to spread is that getting involved is not something easy.
Some say it is within our reach, and there is not much to do, but that's false.
Commitment requires a lot of time and energy.
It can drastically change your life, as it has for me.
But looking back on everything that happened and everything we were able to do, I can ensure you that it is worth it.
Thank you.
(Applause)
Alla... the evening is going to be fine, relax!
(Laughter) I'm delighted to see everyone.
Well, it's a little hypocritical of me, but I'm happy to be among you, happy to be welcomed by TEDx Arts and Crafts.
Let's have a round of applause for the team that has struggled for a year to make this happen.
(Applause) I'm delighted to be among you to talk about progress.
"Progressus" from "progredi..." it's always so stylish when you say something in Latin.
I'm going to talk about progress, mainly what inspires progress that oscillates between necessity and fascination, and between progression and sometimes even regression.
And the question that I'm going to ask you in this kind of "one-man show of awareness" is: Is progress a necessity?
But before that, given that I'm up here by myself and I'm egocentric and narcissistic, let's talk a little about me. (Laughter)
I was born in Alger, I grew up in Marseille, I'm bald, handicapped, binational, Muslim, in short, I'm in deep trouble.
(Laughter) No seriously, I grew up in Marseille and at the age of 17 I was diagnosed with pigment retinopathy, a progressive degeneration of the retina.
And it was then that I learned I was going to progressively lose my vision.
I was put in an institute for young blind people called "The Rainbow".
I studied for a long time.
I studied first philosophy and after that languages,
I got a Master in Strategy, a Master of Science in Financial Engineering.
I've also been able to work for big companies.
All of that is a form of progress that I discovered within myself.
And I've learned that ultimately, every one of us is endowed with a phenomenal capacity for resilience and for finding tricks to make up for any lack, any natural deficiency, which just shows that Nature is well-designed.
And that is progress as well, but I still hope for medical progress!
So that growth, I have experienced it differently than your everyday pace of progress, your relationship with progress, since there're different types of progress: social progress, technological progress, economic progress, moral progress.
And within every dimension of our society, whether it be historical, philosophical, or economic, you find progress.
Back then, our friends, the Greeks, were already having cat-fights.
You all know Pythagoras and Thales, although...
I've asked my grand-nephew, "Do you know Thales?"
He told me, "Yeah, that's Son Goku's cousin in Dragon Ball." Wow!
(Laughter)
So already back then, there was a huge debate between two schools of thought, two paradigms.
Some people who were esoteric or even religious, thought that progress is nothing more than a form of decline and that humanity is doomed for failure, for its own disappearance, that Man is born in heaven, or in Olympus, or, in the great monotheistic religions, in Paradise, and that Man is bound to fail by that form of progress that is nothing but the idle pursuit of luxury and time saving.
The other school of thought, more modern, are all the authors like Bacon, Diderot, etc., that brought encyclopedias and the Enlightenment movement, who think that humanity should progress, and that through progress humanity will achieve its ideal state.
Through this ambivalence, that can be found throughout the evolution of different civilizations, I wanted to raise a few questions today about the way we inspire progress.
Does progress come from necessity, or does it instead come from our fascination, our curiosity?
Well, most of the time, it oscillates between the two.
So necessity is the necessity to treat and cure diseases, but we can see that this ambivalence still exists since some illnesses have disappeared from our so-called "civilized" country but still exist in other more complex countries that have developments and systems of production that are not "evolved" from our point of view.
And there are other forms of progress that are much more advanced like new technologies.
Remember our dear deceased friend: "This is a revolution!"
It's true, it's a revolution,
and it's what enabled me to adapt quickly because I use other parts of my brain that for you are hogged by your vision.
That's why I haven't used any support today.
Today, you all are like me, visually impaired.
By the way, let's turn off the lights.
... No, I'm just kidding. (Laughter)
This ambivalence can be found in scientific progress, in medical progress, and in social progress as well.
We created paid leave, vacations, etc., to have more time, but that time, we don't spend it like the Greeks who, in Antiquity, dedicated it to contemplation.
And it's precisely that contemplation that tips us over from necessity to fascination.
And Humanity has always been fascinated, by the Heavens for example.
We had Icarus, and today we have Interstellar.
Well, that's not exactly the same... Imagine Thales, Socrates, Pythagoras, and Plato eating popcorn while watching Interstellar?
I'm sure they would faint!
Ultimately, that fascination has always given rise to progress - we have seen it in the two previous presentations, an immeasurable progress that is going faster and faster.
And behind this willingness to make progress, what is really the inspiration?
Again, through this same ambivalence between the two trends of thoughts, some people who have a Manichean vision between good and bad, the good guys and the bad guys, will say: "We make progress, but technology is perverting the human being."
Why? Because for example,
when the Facebook network was created to enable researchers and friends to connect between universities there was a kind of virtuous circle.
Today, you see posts like: "I ate cornflakes."
People take photos of their plates.
So the danger is precisely to fall into a virtual reality, a virtual reality that exists in the digital world.
We are not machines, until proven otherwise.
If we take all the futuristic novels like those written by Isaac Asimov or George Orwell, and we transpose them to today, well, either their are visionary or they had a crystal ball.
And this begs the question, what is the true source of progress?
I think, and it's my personal story that I'm going to tell you, that we are the progress.
We are the source of our own progress.
Again, in the same ambivalence, some think Man is God, and God is Man.
Others think precisely the opposite, that, in a primitive way, Man tends towards his own destruction.
But in my personal case, when I began to progressively lose my vision, I told myself, "Now I am powerless against people who are able to see."
Now I don't know how I did it, but I naturally discovered that being in two worlds, that of the sighted and the partially sighted, was giving me an outside and objective view that allowed me to question my environment and understand in a different way more strategical or even tactical how the environment functions, and I had to find new solutions.
At first, at school, I was reading with a lamp.
People called me Aladdin throughout my entire schooling, it was horrible!
(Laughter) At the end, I could not read anymore.
So I used a type of software that made me discover that auditory memory is immensely more powerful and more anchored in time than visual memory.
And by listening to my lessons and no longer being able to read the board, I started developing a kind of "hypermnesic" memory which is the opposite of "amnesia".
And from there, I began to develop a spatial memory, and I have a good sense of direction, it's rather paradoxical.
It is what I call a "topographic vision".
I've developed a topographical vision.
I specifically say "vision" because seeing is a mechanical action that depends on the eyes - in the primary visual cortex, vision is inverted and you see - whereas perceiving is about discernment and requires abstraction, a sort of astral vision...
I haven't been smoking anything!
(Laughter) So I was able to develop this topographic vision thanks to a discipline that was key in my personal growth, but I'm not going to talk about it.
Rather we're going to see it, you're going to be surprised, I think.
(Video) (Music) [January 21, 2017] [Marseille, France] Any volunteer?
(Laughter) Martial arts have guided my whole life.
I first started with French boxing, then I did judo, aikido, I even practiced Japanese sword fighting, the handling of weapons, and of course English boxing.
This video was from a gala in January against a former world champion light heavyweight.
Now you may think "How does he do?"
since I can't see anything coming.
My opponents don't dare to hit me, so I tell them, "Go for it, I bump into posts, walls, sidewalks, go ahead!"
(Laughter) They don't want to, but let's take a volunteer.
Come on, Pierre... I'm going to show you with an experiment, it will make better sense.
Human beings are gifted with senses, we all agree - I'm not Daredevil - and all the senses are interconnected within our brain that distributes them like in a nuclear power plant, more or less equally.
Sight is a sense that consumes a lot of energy.
When I stop seeing, what is left is not hearing but rather logic.
If Pierre talks and he is here, his voice is over there, right?
Now he's going to recite the alphabet... and his head is right here.
So I don't need more details.
His head is here, his family jewels are around here... (Laughter) Thank you, Pierre.
That experiment, you can do it yourselves with your fingers, your sense of touch.
When you go back home in the evening and there is no light, you all have this instinct to turn on the light in order to insert your key into the lock.
Yet all you have to do is use your finger - some people do it - and you can directly find the lock's keyhole.
You just have to concentrate internally on what senses are left when you're disabled so that you develop the capacity to be resilient and to be just as "able-bodied as any other able-bodied person".
I'm not saying "normal" because normality isn't really a norm.
All of that to tell you that progress, to me, is the inspiration that we have and should have for what is, for us, humanity.
What is humanity?
It is the human race.
It is to live in society, to live in a collegial way, etc.
Capitalism, neo-liberalism, all of that, are not necessarily modern ideas.
The needy and the wealthy have always existed throughout History.
Technical, technological and medical progress must enable Humanity to move forward but especially to question its own behavior.
Today, we see the emergence of new movements such as degrowth, frugal innovation, or biomimicry.
By the way, I invite you all to go see and read Idris Averkamp's lectures, an triple Doctor Emeritus, who talks about Humanity's rebirth through this new technological era.
But rebirth needs to be the search for the ideal state of Humanity, and not the prolongation of Humanity.
That's the big question we should ask ourselves.
Are we bound to live eternally?
Google and all the tech giants invest billions of dollars in eternal life, in replacing our organs, and so on. I would be the first one to happily have my eyes replaced.
But are we destined to live a thousand
years? Two thousand years?
And this is really where the gift of ubiquity, meaning being everywhere simultaneously all the time, experiencing everything idly is kind of our intrinsic defect that question us saying: "Is progress taking advantage of everything or just taking the time to observe, contemplate and understand Nature and not trying subjugate it?
You can't fight against a typhoon or a drought.
Our technology can help us to adapt, not to fight against Nature.
So in conclusion, I invite you to wonder what could help us progress as human beings, especially during the troubled times in which we are currently living.
Who knows, maybe next week I'll return to my village?
(Laughter) What is valuable about human beings?
Is it the fact that they're all the same, they resemble each other, or the fact that they're all different?
Difference is a virtue, a strong value, it's not an obstacle.
Being handicapped is an asset.
I even invite you to blindfold yourselves sometimes to feel things.
We should inspire progress, it is not progress that should inspire us.
We need to master it, be its master rather than its slave.
And it's time for me to progress towards the exit, and for you, to continue to progress in this conference.
Thank you very much.
(Applause)
Seven years ago, I joined a film school while I knew nothing about the French New Wave.
Three years ago, I started a production company while I knew nothing about how it worked.
And a year and a half ago, I ended up in Henry Kissinger's office ignoring who he was.
I think the path we take isn't necessarily the one we intended to take.
Originally, I wanted to go into horse riding, but unluckily, I had an accident.
I got expelled twelve times from school,
(Laughter) and on the twelfth time, I make the radical decision to go to the school's secretary office and ask to be officially removed from register, so I was expelled once and for all from the French school system. Then I registered at the CNED, the corespondance courses.
From then on, it was great because I could follow my own pace: I would linger in the morning, work on my lessons and visit museums in the afternoon, and at night I'd draw go-go dancers in the bars of the Marais.
(Laughter) So in the middle of my final year with the CNED, I got over my carelessness and had to choose a career, a path.
I was rather creative, I drew, as you have seen, I also played the harp, did theatre and dance.
So I was looking for a manual and creative career.
Eventually, I found out about film production on a brochure for BTS studies.
It said you had to be lively, dynamic and resourceful with an artistic sensibility.
That was a total discovery for me because, film production, the media, nobody in the family was in that line of work or knew anything about it.
In the first months of my studies, I thought field work would be interesting so I went into block realease training in a production company.
There, I worked on TV fictions and magazines, it was very enriching because what I'd learn at school finally made sense on the field when I was at my desk.
Pretty soon, I knew I had really found a career I liked, that was to become the career I have today.
After three years in that company, I must confess I was getting a little bored and a little voice inside me was saying: "you've got plans and your own ideas, go for it, grab your opportunity!"
So I started my own company.
Not giving it a second thought.
In my mind, at the time, I felt everything was possible.
And I'm still totally convinced about it today.
That's my care bear side speaking; in fact, that's the nickname my grandmother gave me when I was litle.
But when I started my company, I thought, "OK, I have great projects, the best team, so everybody will want us to make their films!"
I must say that reality is quite different from this.
Picking up the phone and calling a TV channel is not enough, you have to struggle to get some funding.
So I built a little armour to my care bear and I persevered until it paid off.
I didn't know many people in this milieu, so I would waver between total euphoria when I'd read the scripts and give feedback to my authors, and absolute panic when I had to call a TV channel to make an appointment.
Actually, I remember, on my first appointment with a TV channel, I was in such panic that before going, I was thinking: "What should I wear, what would I take with me, what will I say to that lady?"
I had put in my purse a bunch of ludicrous things, even a pocket calculator, because, you never know… it could prove very, very useful.
Finally, I think panic only starts in the second before you jump in.
I remember that at that moment, I thought: "At worst, what could happen to me?
They'll just say no."
That sentence really changed my life.
Basically, it was like removing the training wheels from a bike: you may not ride very straight, you bump into things, you fall, but you pick yourself up and get back on the bike because it's so cool to ride without training wheels!
I did it all, I fell, didn't go straight, bumped into obstacles but if I had to start over again, I wouldn't change a thing.
In 2012, due to a combination of factors, I ended up with a script for a documentary about the Vietnam war.
The friend who brought it to me was very enthusiastic and said: "You'll see, it's absolutely great, they've even planned to interview Henry Kissinger."
I can confess it now, as soon as I was back at my desk, I googled "Henry Kissinger"
So that tells you
I didn't master the subject at all, the story is quite complex, it's light years away from the TV fictions and magazines I'd been working on during my training.
But I was tempted by this new playing field.
That documentary will represent close to two years' work so two years of my life.
For two years, my team and I had as a main goal to make a beautiful film that would be didactic and innovating.
We didn't want to make an umpteenth film about the Vietnam war.
We wanted to tell the story differently, to go and dig up what would really enrich the public.
First you must know we started from scratch.
We had no pictures, no funding, no archives, all we had was a few lines written in a notebook.
We chose to talk about secret diplomacy, about the exchanges that took place mostly at Choisy-le-Roi, France, between Le Duc Tho and Henry Kissinger.
You must know that those two men negociated peace in Vietnam in pavilions in the Paris suburbs, which is incredible.
I still find it funny, what you can see behind me is what my film looked like a year and a half ago.
I'm going to let you get a glimpse of what it has become.
(Voice-over) Choisy-le-Roi.
In this quiet street, half an hour from Paris, the few pensioners who live there are intrigued.
They only have eyes for a pavilion situated at number eleven.
In the greatest secrecy, behind closed shutters, two men are facing each other.
And still today, nobody knows that the hundreds of hours of their talks were recorded.
HK: "I thought yesterday we had reduced the issues of the text to only two.
And now I find that there are seventeen.
These sudden changes present the gravest difficulties for us in terms of good faith."
Everything sets them apart: their culture, ideology, career.
They're at war.
How will they make peace?
Man: Let's hope for the best outcome, that war is getting quite long.
(Applause) I must say it's totally magic, because those two years of work precisely come to make sense when the film is completed.
I must have seen it hundreds of time while we were working on it, while editing, calibrating and mixing.
I think the best moment was when I watched it when completed, show in a film thatre.
At the moment I have some 22 projects, including 20 documentary projects, plus a feature film and we're also setting up an urban culture festival.
Here you have some pictures of things
we did these past few years.
In fact, when I created Al Di Sopra, which means "rise above", I chose to a picture of a pelican to make my logo, and this is that picture,
which I took in Venezuela.
In Venezuela, I observed pelicans take off and you can all picture a pelican, a very heavy bird, quite clumsy when it's on the ground but when it takes off, it seems it will never make it.
But as soon as it's getting higher, its flight is majestic; it flies in flock, and can do it for hours without getting tired.
I thought it was quite a good image.
I think being an entrepreneur is just like being a pelican.
To become a good entrepreneur, you have to kick your own ass, and accept to put on a brave face even when the going gets tough.
For me, starting a business is being daily in unchartered territory because you have to root your vision while following the principles that rule how society and companies traditionally work, but you must also know how to adapt and reinvent yourself.
Starting a business, in fact, it's close to madness!
You look absolutely weird when you follow your dreams and ideas.
What will I be when I grow up? Am I reasonable? Those questions may seem strange, but they are sincere.
We all grow up every day but when you are running a business, it actually grows along with you.
You're probably looking at me and thinking that I'm only 25, but from my point of view, it's the contrary, I'm already 25 and I've only produced about 1% of the films I want to make and I believe in.
I live with the idea that when you don't do things, they die with you.
So my race is to produce all the films I truly and firmly believe in.
I created Al Di Sopra with that motivation, to work on topics differently and develop them and make them exist.
I consider my trade as a really boisterous profession.
We're at the same time in a very generous, sharing-oriented line of work, but it's a work that forever will be boisterous and generous.
My team and I have tried to shape our company to our image.
We try to work in a joyous atmosphere.
Actually we do work in a joyous atmosphere.
I'm convinced it's possible to work and remain light, happy and joyful.
We make jokes all day, and after three jokes, a good idea comes up.
I really don't cultivate difference for the sake of being different but rather to propose another vision and I think with another vision, you can move frames and propose other contents and make them evolve, transform them.
In fact, if I produce media, I think I'm also here to prompt debate.
Whether it is in very small theatres like we did last year, in Le Creusot or in Arcueil with a small audience, much smaller than here today, but our films, the idea is that we also make them so that some people watch them.
Whether it is in schools, high schools, on the internet, on smartphones, in fact our films are made to be seen.
The idea is that we pass them on to you.
We pass on projects we've worked on so that their contents hold water.
We hope you will write to us, that in your turn you will give us a prod, ask us questions, interact with what you have seen.
I feel that today, we need that kind of exhange more and more for our mutual enrichment and to keep
asking questions together.
So that's the story of my own chance, of a little piece of paper that eventually became my calling.
So I came here to tell you that you have the greatest power, your greatest power is to choose the person you are.
Mostly, remember that to set up a project, that's what my demonstration was about, you don't need to have a network, you don't need to be rich, you absolutely don't need to gather theoretical knowledge during ten years, you don't need to be old, you just need to be (Laughter) (Applaudissements) there, there, I'm not done yet!
You don't need to be anything else than the person you already are.
(Applause) Thank you very much.
Good evening ladies and gentlemen.
You are certainly thinking it's starting rather badly.
(Laughter) But, don't doubt yourselves,
one plus one in mathematics does make two.
I'm going to explain to you how I arrived at this result and this equation by putting arithmetic to one side and focusing predominantly on biology.
I'm Xavier Bailly and I work in an institute of marine biology, the Biological Station in Roscoff, not far from here.
To illustrate what I'm speaking about, I came with my favorite animal that has become kind of my pet these last fifteen years because it is both my study and my research subject.
It's a little sand worm called "Roscoffensis".
This is its latin name.
To keep things simple, we're going to call it "the Roscoff worm".
You'll find it on all the Atlantic coastlines, principally on sandy beaches.
On Brittany beaches, if you look for example at these green areas, and even a little bit closer, this is what you can see: a multitude of little green worms, that move in colonies - millions of individuals - at the surface of the sand, sea water ditches or in puddles, at low tide.
As soon as the tide rises, the entire colony takes refuge in the sand and remains there throughout the high tide.
As soon as the tide drops, all the colony reappears at the surface of the sand, and this goes on with the rhythm of the tides, in a vertical movement: on the sand when the tide is low, in the sand when the tide is high.
You've probably noticed its green color that is rather characteristic.
Many zoologists, when they began to describe and examine this worm, were intrigued by this color, it's origin and it's nature.
And if we look closer with this photo taken under a microscope of a young Roscoff worm, we can see a collection of tiny green cells that are evenly distributed in the tissues.
Notice that I said "in the tissues," inside the tissues.
These are microalgae.
These microalgae can reach a staggering number in an adult worm, around a hundred thousand units.
They interact with the animal in a very peculiar way.
That is, they are capable of producing the energy that will feed the animal.
In other words, the animal never feeds itself.
When it is young, the animal is translucent.
It must find its microalgae partners.
. You can see it here.
To survive, the juvenile Roscoff that is still in its protective cocoon, must ingest and definitely not digest these microalgae.
Now you're going to say, "But how can I survive if I don't digest what I ingest?
Well, it is the living microalgae that are able to perform a biological process called "photosynthesis".
Let me do a slight digression on photosynthesis,
taking us back to our high school benches.
All that was a long time ago.
On Earth's surface, all plants whether they be terrestrial or marine, including microalgae, are able to carry out a complex bio-chemical reaction, that combines light energy, carbon dioxide - the atmospheric CO2 or the CO2 dissolved in the sea - as well as water and mineral salts.
And at the end of this reaction, sugars, lipids and proteins are produced that are going to help the plant develop itself and grow.
When you transpose this to the scale of the Roscoff worm, you understand that it's the microalgae that produce these nutritional compounds and transfer a share to the worm.
But that's not all.
The microalgae are also capable of using and recycling the metabolic waste of the worm.
You see, this exchange, this communication, this constant and permanent transfer between the algae and the animal, is what we call "a photo-symbiosis".
Now, many authors have said of the Roscoff worm that it was a "plant-animal".
But, I prefer to call it an "animalgae", animal + algae, two words in one.
This way, it makes perfect sense.
This organism is really more than the sum of the two partners.
It's more of a functional and lasting association, an intimate relation, this famous photo-symbiosis.
You've just understood and solved with me this equation: 1 + 1 = 1.
We're not going to stop here.
In our laboratory, we work extensively on understanding this way of living.
How does an animal, at a given moment, become photosynthetic?
How does it acquire this capability plants have to use light energy?
We ask ourselves how this partnership takes place.
And to show you the importance of light in this species, here is a little funny experiment where a culture of Roscoffensis is exposed to light on one side - for you, here, it is on the right side - and then the source of light is suddenly moved to the other side.
What you can see is the sudden migration of these worms from the side where the light was to the other side where it reappears.
You can understand that the animals are going towards the light energy, where they're going to find that energy to produce proteins and lipids and transfer them to the worm.
I hope you haven't given too much importance to those that were spinning around themselves.
I know, in fact, you've mainly watched this!
(Laughter)
Well, I thought you were a lot more serious.
(Laughter) We don't know why they do that.
Is it to clown around?
That's not impossible.
Anyway, to cultivate and host algae in one's own tissues, is much more serious than that and it necessitates some special adaptions.
Let me tell you about three biological feats the Roscoff worm performs: first, it is resistant to sunlight, strong lights, and strong solar rays; second, it can regenerate its brain; third, it can control its cell proliferation.
Earlier, I forgot to tell you that one of the products of photosynthesis is also oxygen, that same oxygen we all breath.
Well, the worm that spends several hours under the sun receives solar radiation, including ultraviolet rays, but there is also oxygen that builds up in its tissues.
The combination of these two effects generates what we call "oxidative stress".
In our body, this can even be the trigger of cancers.
Interesting thing, the Roscoff worm does not need UV sunscreen, and furthermore, it doesn't
get sunburn. Isn't it inspiring?
Secondly, the regeneration of the brain.
Take a Roscoff worm, anaethetise it - important - and then cut off its head.
You wait around twenty days, and you can see the complete regeneration of the missing part, both the envelop and what is inside it, the brain and all its neural connections.
Can you imagine, if we were able to have this capacity of regenerating our own cerebral tissues when they are damaged or age too quickly or too early ?
The third feat is the control of cell division, or we should say "cell proliferation".
I'm sure that you've seen and understood that microalgae intensely divide and proliferate in the young worm until they cover the whole body of the animal.
It looks like the proliferation of tumor or cancerous cells.
Well, here again, the worm has developed a mechanism that enables him to control this wave of proliferating cells.
Such a mechanism would be interesting to understand since it controls this population and maintains it alive.
I think it could inspire medicine.
So, as you've guessed, this little worm makes me dream, among other things, and since we know each other a lithe bit better now, let me talk about another project close to my heart - a draft project - that is related to another possible use of the Roscoff worm, and has a direct link to space conquest.
In the ISS, a jewel of technology, the problem is breathing, the consumption of energy, and how to be completely autonomous.
So ISS is connected by a fragile umbilical cord that is a vessel coming roughly quarterly to bring its resources - water, oxygen, food - and take away the waste to be recycled on Earth.
If we had to leave for long journeys lasting several months or several years in space, bringing so much material, so many resources, would be impossible, as for now.
Therefore, we need to imagine means to produce resources inside the ISS and recycle them.
Now that the Roscoff worm's biology is less and less of a secret, I believe you can see what I am getting at.
The Roscoff worm performs great functions to invent and to create what we could call "a biotechnological ecosystem", for the purpose of: producing oxygen, the one astronauts breathe; recycling CO2, the one astronauts emit; recycling part of their metabolic waste; and why not, feeding them with microalgae since some of them are edible.
I'm not saying that the Roscoff worm is the solution.
But, it is certainly an important and, I think, interesting inspirational model.
To conclude, I suggest that we come back down to the beach of Roscoff worms.
I'm going to tell you about something I find particularly motivating, that consists in conveying, transferring, teaching, and sharing what I have presented to you this evening.
Several years ago, I created an educational kit, a teaching tool to educate people about marine biology that we called the "Roscoff marine worm discovery kit".
It enables us to send to middle and high schools, to French or European universities. the Roscoff worm with or without its algae, or the algae alone, etc., all of the stages of its development.
What I really hope is that, beyond the experiments, beyond the manipulation, the observations, and even beyond the teaching of great phenomenons of biology such as photosynthesis, photo-symbiosis, the world of microalgae, etc., I hope the 20-year-old youths will be able to understand what I myself understood at 50 and sometimes with difficulty.
And the cherry on the cake, I must admit, would be that the future generations get really inspired not only by the Roscoff worm and its biology, but get inspiration from the animal itself to imagine a different world, to raise awareness that we must take care of the earth and sea environments, in short, to use it as a model.
It turns out that I met a young girl earlier called Lucile.
I would like - since I came with my favorite pet - to entrust it to you so that you make the best use of it, watch it, show it to your parents, your friends, your teachers, and take great care of it.
I'll explain to you later how to take good care of it.
Here you go.
(Applause) I believe that you've sensed that the Roscoff worm, beyond its green color, gives me lots of hope.
Above all, it gives me the desire to reach for the moon, And as Norman Vincent Peale said, "Shoot for the moon. Even if you miss, you'll land among the stars."
(Applause)
I have a question.
Do you happen to know Auguste Maquet, a Gaspard de Cherville, Gérard de Nerval, and Xavier de Montépin?
They aren't very famous at all. Yet all of you present here have read one or more of their books.
The Count of Monte Cristo, Queen Margot, or, of course, The Three Musketeers.
Because these three gentlemen belong to a group of ghostwriters employed by Alexandre Dumas.
Alexandre Dumas is a great writer, a great man in the spotlight, and yet, many men were at his side, unknown, and in the shadow. These men contributed to Dumas' success, to carving out with their pen the heroic Alexandre Dumas that we know.
To use an image, imagine Mariah Carey - and I'm taking a risk here, with Mariah Carey at a TEDx - (Laughter) I can handle this, yes, I can. Imagine that we believe that Mariah Carey, in the morning, when she wakes up, is wearing a well-tailored little dress, that her skin looks perfect, and that she has naturally great hair.
Well no. In fact, in the morning, Mariah Carey looks just like us.
Even Mariah Carey has sticky skin, puffy eyes, and flat hair in the morning.
Because to look like the diva we know, Mariah Carey needs dozens of assistants by her side who work for her and on her looks in the shadows, all day long, and who create this famous heroine look, that she wants us to believe is natural.
She is a unique heroine, with many people around her, in the shadows.
When you think about it, the myth of exceptional hero, of incredible figure, isn't somehing new.
Yesterday, for example, not yesterday, but some centuries ago, Velázquez signed this extraordinary painting, that he took months to paint. Except it wasn't painted by him, not by him alone. He was assisted by dozens of painters who spent months in the shadows painting this exquisite work.
The truth is, Velázquez came on the last day, he added a few bits of paint, and signed his name.
I appreciate the irony of this work, because he is represented in the painting, at the top on the left. It's really a "mise en abyme" of the hero making sure he is very visible. [accidentally says "pregnant"]
I didn't mean he is "pregnant", while the speaker before me clearly was, (Laughter) and if she wants to do a money pot for the baby's birth, I can give a hand. (Laughter) (Applause) Yes, there are many heros, and yet, I believe that there is always a team backing up every hero. Above all, I believe that we can create and start businesses differently.
I believe that being 30 in 2016 means yearning for a different kind of work. it means yearning for different ways of exchanging ideas, and it means yearning for making things happen in novel ways.
This science is called, when you study it, the science of exchange, receiving from the community, and giving to the community.
The Austrian philosopher, Hayek, coined it "Catallactics."
The core idea is that together, we are better. Together, we can be productive.
I strongly believe in this idea. I'm convinced that we can do things better and even in a more prolific way.
You too, you know many examples of the science of exchanges applied, of its many achievements.
Wikipedia for example, the biggest encyclopedia in the world, doesn't belong to anyone. But it is our mission to expand it, so that everyone can learn from the knowledge of others.
I am fond of another case, not so famous though. It is the Polymath.
In 2009, two mathematical researchers asked for help from the community.
So they posted their unresolved math problem on a blog, for the community to engage with it. They asked the community this : "Let's try to solve this math problem, and let's look forward to the final destination of this mathematical quest."
The result was extraordinary.
Obviously, someone, somewhere, succeeded in solving this problem. In fact, many people succeeded, and in many different ways.
This means that the community outperformed the researcher's expectations and it produced new knowledge. It created value for the community and in very different ways.
This story is outstanding. Should we be in the position to grant the Fields medal, the equivalent of the Nobel Prize in mathematics, to Polymath, we wouldn't know who to grant it to. I find this very funny.
So I really believe the idea that you can create things in a different way, that the group has much value, and even that we can be richer and stronger together.
A few years ago, I was a student in business school. with my fellow students, and you can see them on the screen. We decided to go on a trip one weekend. 'Integration weekend,' as we called it, is a place for students to drink beer, to play soccer, and have fun together.
We needed to finance this weekend. So, off I went, collecting donations in a paper envelope. The classroom was similar to here, but less crowded. My point was to collect money from everyone to finance the weekend.
And of course, one guy said, "Oh no, Céline, I only have my cheque book on me."
Another one, "Oh no, Céline, I don't have any cash."
And another one, "Oh, I don't know if I'm there one night or two."
I just thought, "Thank you guys, that's very nice!"
So I had to make an advance payment of the cost of our weekend, 400 euros, with my student pocket money.
I'm a student. Mum and Dad, I'm going to rely on you,
I can't really afford this. This experience tells me that there must be some online service for this. You can do anything online, right? You should be able to raise money and manage it collaboratively too.
But there wasn't any.
So I told myself that fortune favors the bold. I was going to start this adventure and create a money raising pot online to allow several people to raise money together.
And then, a fellow friend told me: "That's actually a really great idea! Besides it could also be used for other things such as birthday presents." Indeed, birthdays, as my tongue slipped earlier.
This how Leetchi was created.
First, I was on my own. Then I recruited employees, and we were in the flow of the Leetchi adventure getting huge.
The incredible happened: progressively, we got our first clients. A dozen of clients turned into hundreds, and soon enough, thousands of clients. Today millions of clients create thousands of money pots for birthday presents, for farewell parties, wedding lists, etc. Leetchi grew that big.
It was magic because our idea grew beyond us. We let it grow. From time to time I would ask myself, remembering Jacques Attali, "Is it useful, this Leetchi idea?"
My answer was always yes, it's nice, we make it easy for people to organize a gift together, to give a present with a nicer gift. But are we really changing the world?
I discovered we did, indeed, change the world. That's the story I would like to share with you today.
I would like to talk about two money pots.
The first one was created for Charlie Hebdo after the terrorist attack.
A young man, David, decided that he wanted to help the magazine after the attacks. He wanted to raise money to give it to Charlie Hebdo to contribute to relaunching the magazine.
Within in a few days, more than 5,000 people made donation to David's money pot. They have raised more than 300,000 euros.
It was incredible. It was the first time we witnessed this at Leetchi.
People wanted to express their generosity. They wanted to show their support.
Maybe you remember too, but, during the attacks and the donations pouring in, Google made an announcement about its 200,000 euros donation .
The LCI news channel titled its article with an really cool title: "People competing with Google and crushing it."
Because together, thanks to this money pot, we raised more money than Google.
It means that, together, we can be much stronger than any of the biggest organizations in the world.
It may not be possible to rival alone. But together we are stronger.
What an amazing story!
(Applause) There is a second money pot that I would like to tell you about. I was not aware of its existence, before I met Morgane.
A couple of months ago, I was invited to a company called Allo Resto - you must know it. They tell my story and Leetchi's to its employees.
At the end of the conference, a young women walked up to me. She looked moved and a bit worried, she was nearly shaking. So I thought : "Oh! what stupid thing did I say during the conference?" And this lady is definitely walking over to me.
Then she tells me her story.
She has a young nephew, called Kérian, who's two years old. Kérian is suffering from a rare disease, called cerebral palsy, so he can't walk.
But there is hope he may walk one day. if he can get a surgical operation in the United States. But it costs 40,000 euros, including travel, accommodation, and assistance.
She's been trying to find this money for several months now. She has asked her relatives but to no avail.
And one day, she decided to create a money pot on Leetchi, and to share it with her relatives and see what happened.
And in a few days, 700 people that Morgane doesn't know contributed to the pot and helped her raise the 40,000 euros. Her hope came true that her nephew could walk again some day.
It's really amazing when you contribute to change the world of someone!
I would also like to share something funny with you. Morgane was so moved to meet me. She thinks that I am Leetchi. She thinks of me as an incarnation of Leetchi.
But, frankly speaking, it's not about me.
It's about all the people who helped her. It's about the 700 men and women who made a donation to her pot. The employees of Leetchi too. They work every day to help me develop this adventure. Together, we develop an adventure called Leetchi. But Leetchi isn't ours anymore, because it belongs to its community members.
I will conclude with a word about my team because they are very important to me. I would like to tell you a last anecdote.
A month ago, we spent a weekend together, a team building thing.
Team building is the grown-up version of a student integration weekend, I guess. Obviously, the idea was to spend a good time together.
The 70 members of the company went to Porquerolles, not far from here. We were walking in the streets of Porquerolles, and one of my employees, Jean-Marc, said this to me: "Céline, you must be so proud to see all these people here, surrounding you, because of who you are!"
And I answered him: "Actually Jean-Marc, it's not about me. It's our story to all of us. We built this firm together, we develop it every day, all together."
Jean-Marc's reply was so beautiful that I'd like to share it with you: "Without you, we wouldn't be here, and without us, you wouldn't be here."
My word of the end will be Three Musketeers' motto: "All for one and one for all!"
(Music) (Applause)
If I tell you: "The voice is unique to humans," you will all tell me: "Yeah, obviously."
Well it isn't, the voice is not unique to humans, the voice is everywhere.
The word is unique to humans.
But the voice is everywhere.
All the animals have a voice: mammal, terrestrial or marine animals, all the birds, obviously, even some amphibians have a voice.
We also understand perfectly the intonations of our four-legged companions.
Indeed we say that they only lack the words, not the voice!
They do have the voice.
The voice is not unique to humans.
The voice is everywhere.
So much so that it has now entered the technology of our everyday life.
And it seemed so natural that we hardly realized it.
Today, the call platforms make us interact vocally with answering machines, the voice of our GPS tells us the way to go and we can even have a conversation with our mobile phone, can't we?
Synthetic voice: I do not doubt it, Johanna.
JR: How are you?
Voice: Hunky Dory.
JR: Great.
What you see here is not a Lady Gaga concert.
Alys is her producers' little darling.
She is never sick, never sings out of key, and she does not ravage her hotel room.
Because Alys is a hologram.
She is computer-programmed and her voice is as virtual as her presence on stage.
(Music) It's crazy, right?
All these voices are synthetic voices.
They are perfectly intelligible, extremely powerful and better still, they are infallible.
Yet, they remain perfectly recognizable.
Voice: Hum, hum, sorry, but I do not agree.
JR: Yes, sorry, I forgot to introduce you to someone.
The voice you've just heard is a synthetic voice that I programmed specifically for this TEDx.
I called it HAL as a tribute to Stanley Kubrick's computer.
Voice: I love Stanley Kubrick.
JR: We're very happy to hear that, Hal, but like it or not, your role today is to demonstrate the gap that exists between us.
And more specifically, between your synthetic voice and my human voice.
Voice: I do not know what you mean.
JR: Well, I'm getting there.
What separates us is not what we say, that's how we say it.
Let's take an example: could you, HAL, read the sentence on the screen, please?
Voice: Gladly; I did not say you stole the money.
JR: Great. Now repeat it
insisting on the fact that it was not you who said it.
Voice: Easy. I did not say
you stole the money.
JR: Well, that's what I meant when I was talking about a gap between us.
The synthetic voice has no intention.
It is neutral, in all circumstances.
Moreover, if we look at the curves representing the melody of its voice, we realize that between the two productions, it did exactly the same thing.
While I could say: <i>I</i> did not say that you stole the money.
I did not SAY that you stole the money.
I did not say that YOU stole the money.
And just with the sound of my voice, not only will I give a different meaning to a sentence that contains identical words, but also, I will convey all my intentions.
So when you compare my curves with HAL's, you realize that whenever I want to insist on a word, my voice becomes louder, more high-pitched, and it is immediately followed by a pause.
But HAL is not the only one for whom the transmission of intentions is difficult.
Even the most powerful computers have difficulties and are limited by their prosody.
John Oliver: Be honest, is that really the highest honor you've ever received?
Stephen Hawking: Yes.
JO: Well, discerning your tone of voice is a bit difficult. By saying that, are you being sarcastic?
SH: Yes.
Voice: Okay, but can't it be programmed?
JR: Yes, technically, it's feasible.
On the other hand, what I will never be able to give it is a personality.
Because beyond the sounds that come out of our mouth, what makes our voice human is it's going to convey all the most intimate aspects of our personality.
Our voice says everything about us.
At the moment we open our mouth, our interlocutor immediately decodes information about our identity, and in particular, our gender and our age.
Why?
Well, all or almost all at the beginning depends on the size of the larynx.
By the way, when Titze creates a mathematical model of a very small larynx, with 2 mm vocal cords, and that he plays it on his computer, here is what it is like.
(Baby crying) Then, he takes exactly the same model without changing anything at all, except the size, to get 5 cm vocal cords, and that's what you get.
(Lion roar) Titze deduces that the only difference between the two is the size of the vocal cords.
In humans, it works in pretty much the same way, that's what will allow us to make a difference between a man's voice and a woman's voice, an adult voice and a child's voice.
Finally, most of the time, since to any rule, there are always exceptions.
What we see on this curve, is that there is a common area for men's voices and women's voices, between 145 and 165 hertz.
Within this area, there are high-pitched men's voices and low-pitched women's voices.
In my practice as a vocologist, I treat broken voices or I optimize the voice of those with specific needs: lawyers, lecturers, business managers.
When I work, for example, on feminizing a transsexual's voice, that is to say, a biological man who lives his life as a woman, this is the area I'm trying to reach.
By the way, I will perhaps surprise you if I tell you that we are all capable, at the mere listening of a voice, to estimate the age of its speaker, more or less five years.
Which is incredible as a level of precision.
From birth to adulthood, it's a matter of growth, so always a matter of size of the larynx.
Then it will be a matter of aging.
It's not magic, vocal cords age like the rest of the body.
Muscles lose tonicity, volume, and the voice gets breathy.
Hal's voice has neither age nor sex.
The only thing we can say is that it's an adult's voice.
Neither a child's nor an elderly person's.
Hal: I do not know what you mean.
JR: By the way, when measuring the pitch of its voice, we realize that it is 160 hertz.
Right in the ambiguity zone.
So, no sex, no age, HAL's voice has no personality and does not convey any emotion,
because it doesn't feel any, precisely.
When we think of emotions, we always think about their psychic dimension, but emotions have a physical, biochemical starting point, quite concrete inside our body.
For example, when you're scared, there's an adrenaline rush that makes your heart beat faster, your breathing accelerates and all the muscles in your body get tense to be ready to face the situation.
Well, as our larynx uses both the air of our lungs and the muscles of our vocal cords, it can be heard in the voice.
Because it also conveys emotions, our voice is a real sound face.
That of our loved ones conveys the whole relationship we have with them, all the heritage of our common history.
That voice, Voice: He lost them all in the same way.
JR: It doesn't remind you of anything, of course.
But this voice, it moves me because it is my grandmother's voice.
When I hear it, it all comes back to me: my holidays at her house, our complicity, her smile and, of course, her face.
All this, technology is not able to reproduce it.
In your opinion, why, otherwise, almost 50 years apart, these two directors would have chosen real actors' voices to "embody" the voice of their computers?
For Kubrick in '68, one can easily imagine that he did not have the technology.
But for Spike Jones in 2014, the choice of Scarlett Johansson is perfectly clear.
Because when one wonders about the reality of things and their representation, then you have to consider that... Voice: This is not a voice.
JR: It's a word-speaking machine.
Voice: But then you mean that I will never be able to be a real voice?
JR: Research is making progress, technology too, at a hallucinating speed.
The young woman you see here, and her incredible realism, able to have facial expressions of emotions, is actually a robot.
Already, she is programmed to respond to a real actress.
Tomorrow, with the progress of artificial intelligence, she may be capable of free will, therefore of subtle and autonomous interaction with human beings.
Tomorrow she will be your perfect secretary.
Tomorrow, she will be your perfect babysitter.
Tomorrow, she may be the woman of your life.
Voice: Or a TEDx speaker.
JR: Or a TEDx speaker.
(Applause)
I'm going to talk about an encounter, aa encounter with a long haired body, one that's as beautiful as a star. It's a very special encounter because it's with a comet.
The encounter always starts with a bright light.
The bright light is that tiny speck in the sky which suddenly becomes a comet, a moving object, something that releases gas and spreads dust.
But what are comets?
In history, comets were stars which foretold catastrophy.
On the battlefield they were synonymous with defeat, but if you think about it, though there were indeed losers, there were also winners.
Thus for the winners the comet meant victory.
So you could make them say whatever you wanted.
However, comets are objects which give us the best show in the heavens.
And here is one example.
This happened in 2007. Unfortunately, we didn't see it here: it was in the southern hemisphere. but this is the effect a comet can have in the skies. It's an extraordinary thing and if one should pass by soon, I suggest you take a look at it.
OK, what are comets?
They are small objects which can, however, have very long tails,
as long as the distance between the Earth and the Sun.
That's really gigantic.
In this case, two tails.
As you can see, it has a blue tail, which is a tail of ionised atoms, it's a luminous tail, and then there's also a white dust tail, which is reflected by the sunlight.
In the middle of this slightly odd ball, there is something that we can't see.
That's the nucleus.
What is the nucleus of a comet?
In fact, we know very little about comet nuclei, I'm going to show you five, the only five we are familiar with.
Well, their bodies are shaped rather like peanuts, if you like.
The most well known is the nucleus of Halley's comet, because in 1986, Europe, with Giotto and Russia, with Vega, went to take a look at this, the world's most famous comet, and they saw this nucleus, it already had these jets, and this is why we had the idea of going to encounter with it.
Halley's Comet, seen in this image comes round every 75 years, but it has already reached the orbits of Neptune and Pluto.
There are others which you may not have heard of.
Most notably, Hyakutake, a comet which passed close by a few years ago.
This one will not return in 100, 1000, or in 10,000 years, but in 100,000 years time.
So as you can see, comets are very rare, and they're out in the freezing cold,
a long way from the sun. As you know when you put stuff in a freezer, you can keep it for months on end.
Here, it's been preserved for 4.5 billion years.
So stuff in comets hasn't changed since the solar system was formed, that is, the sun, the planets, the comets and the asteroids,
that's all been going round the sun for about 4.5 billion years.
And in the case of comets, it hasn't changed.
This is why we are so interested in studying these objects.
Now, I'm going to show you something that surprised us.
We saw two objects stuck together.
We asked ourselves, "What's happening here?"
My daughter said, "Gosh, it's a hobbit's foot."
It's true, from a distance, it does look like a hobbit's foot.
Up close, it no longer brings that to mind.
Later on, we called it a duck, it has a head and a body, overall, it looks like a piece of dried-up fruit.
If you leave an apple in a cupboard for a month, it'll end up a bit like a comet.
It loses its water - and it's the same with a comet,
because comets are very rich in frozen water. So what happens in a comet is, it loses its water
and this creates the nucleus.
A shrivelled up piece of fruit. It's 4 kilometers long, that's about the size of a mountain, smaller than Mont-Blanc. Nevertheless, it's an object we want to do a lot of things with, we'll study it.
In order to study it, we need to go and meet it.
In order to go and meet it we had to make a vehicle, this one. This is Rosetta, which is a reference to the Rosetta stone which allowed us to decipher hieroglyphs.
We're going to decipher the solar system's history, how it was formed 4.5 billion years ago.
It's an enormous vehicle, it weighs three tons, the giant cube is about 3m long, the solar pannels are larger than this stage -
32m long - because it'll be a long way from the sun.
It's going as far out as Jupiter.
It's taken 10 years to make this vehicle, because in space travel everything takes time, and of course, it's complicated. In addition, it took 10 years to reach the comet.
It's that white trail.
It went round the sun four times, the wide trail at the bottom is Jupiter.
It almost touched Jupiter, and the small white spot, that's where it is today as I'm talking to you.
It's taking a look.
The encounter has taken place.
And it's done what we often do, it's taken a selfie.
And there you are, a beautiful selfie of the comet, a solar pannel viewed from the edge, it's a bit like industrial espionage for those who know about that, and behind it is the comet, which still has its small head and long body.
The aim of Rosetta, is to study the comet's activity the start of that activity.
We wanted to meet the comet a long way from the sun, when it was going to start being active, now it is active.
Here you can see the activity, you can see the jets just leaving, between the head and the body, that's its active part, and although you can't see the gas, it drags dust along with it, and it's the dust which you can see here.
In fact, the entire comet is active and this will increase. We are going to stay with it for a year and a half, and we hope we won't be hit by any of the large blocks the size of basket balls.
So, we're going to proceed cautiously, and approach the comet with care.
Obviously there are a lot of instruments, I won't list them because it would take over an hour, but we're going to study the nucleus and the dust and we're going to study the gas.
We're going to look in the visible, the infrared at all wavelengths.
There's even radar, as we want know about the inside of the comet.
So, we're doing all that.
But that's not all, we want to do something a bit more complicated, we'd like to give it a kiss.
We've made a kind of landing craft, there it is, we've called it Philae.
Philiae, you might not know, is the obelisk which also helped Jean-François Champollion to decipher hieroglyphs.
So, Philae is a vehicle about 1 metre square, with 3 feet and we're going to jettison it and land it on the comet.
I can give you the time and date, 16:35 on November 12th, that's when it should touch down.
However, to land it, we need to find a place to land it.
But, we didn't known where, since the end of July,
we've been looking around. Take a look. Would you like to land there?
It would be like being on a mountain of granite, you can see some blocks... To put it in terms you'll understand, each point in the image, is a metre in length.
These blocks are 10m wide, so you could land on a building.
It looks as though these blocks are suspended in space.
But, in fact, which way is up?
It's not necessarily where you think.
This rock isn't falling, it's simply lying in a horizontal position, and gravity is very weak.
We looked and eventually we found,
we found the best place to land, and if I may say so, it is not a great spot.
It's where the red cross is, there are still some 10m long blocks, there are some 60 degree cliffs, and 60 degrees isn't good for us.
We can't land on a 60 degree cliff, it would flip over.
So, for better or worse, we hope that this is going to work, it could be successful or it could fail, we will find out on the 12th November.
What will happen?
There's a video camera.
Imagine a videocamera on a non-existant long pole, which is fixed in regard to Philae.
The comet will come closer, in fact, we will be approaching the comet.
Then at a precise moment and place, Philae will be jettsioned, and after it has been jettisoned it will fall for seven hours.
Philae will not move, of course, because of the fixed videocamera.
It's the comet which will move, it turns on itself every twelve hours, it's a monster, a mountain, and whatever happens, we'll descend, very slowly. We'll land at 3km an hour.
Everything is very slow around a comet because gravity is very weak.
There's the famous ellipse we're going to land in there. This red spot is where we hope we'll be but we know that for a variety of reasons we could land anywhere in the ellipse.
And that's it, we'll land at 16:35 on November 12th
The landing is the most nerve-wracking, the most difficult part.
Our vehicle weighs 100kg on Earth and when it lands on the comet it'll weigh 2 grams. How will we do it?
As soon as it lands it'll cling to the ground.
There's a sort of rocket which you can't see here, which will fix the battery at the moment of impact.
When it's on the ground, the two small projections underneath, these are harpoons,
these two harpoons will be fired, because two are better than one, if one doesn't work there's always the second. We hope that one of them will get a hold.
Cables will then be extended to anchor it down.
That's the theory, if all goes well, it'll happen on November 12th.
Then, as soon as it's landed... Don't worry, the comet's head is not as large as in the image. We've no idea what the head looks like from the ground.
The first thing that we'll do is take a 360 degree panorama, and that'll be sent immediately to Earth, beacuse everybody wants to see it, and those of us on the project, I've been working on it for 20 years, I'd really like to know it's landed.
The best proof that it's landed will be to see this view.
Then we'll do the science, that's what we're there for, it's the aim of the mission.
We'll use the radar that I told you about, and the radar will involve Rosetta sending a wave. Philae will receive this, and will cross the nucleus and take some sections.
If we find that the core is very homogenous we'll be able to say that it formed slowly and gently, 4.5 billion years ago.
If on the other hand, we find big blocks, 10 or 100m long, we'll say, yes, it all came together, but with a bang, there were some big collisions the comet broke up and then later it was all shaken up and it was reassembled.
And we think that this is what we are going to find.
In other words, there were some very violent events, and that's what the radar is for.
However, the most important thing, is what comes next.
Next, we're going to drill into the comet.
We'll use this drill to bore down and take a sample from the bottom...
Why? Because comets are very ice-rich, and when they get close to the sun, obviously, they act like a presure cooker jets of water come out carrying dust with them.
And the dust interests us a lot, since comets are very rich in carbon, we've already detected 25 carbon molecules from the ground, but there's some material, as black as coal perhaps, we don't know what this is.
So, the aim of this drilling is to analyse this carbon, which is probably very complex, it's been likened to soot.
And lastly, there's carbon and water and comets are objects, which we know, bombarded Earth 4 billion or so years ago.
Water arrived and filled the oceans, carbon ditto, then the carbon got into the water, and as the ocean was very hot at that time complex molecules were created, membranes were formed, cells came into being, life began.
So, to conclude, in the end what really interests us about this extraordinary story of landing on a comet, is understanding our origins.
We'll understand the solar sytem, how it was formed, but we'll also find out how life came into being, starting from this carbon and water from the comets.
So don't forget the appointment - 16:30 on November 12th.
Thank you.
(Applause)
A good evening to all.
The Nobel Prize in Physics 2014 was awarded to three scientists.
. Three researchers from Japan, for their fundamental role in developing new light sources: the blue light emitting diodes called LEDs.
These light sources are effective and environmentally-friendly.
And then these light sources will be, as I put it here, the lights of the 21st century.
LED lights will be the lighting of the 21st century, like Edison's lamp was the lighting of the 20th century.
This is a technological breakthrough.
A technological breakthrough that is based on a theory, the quantum theory.
In fact, this quantum theory was born in the early 20th century and led to a number of important and fundamental applications: the transistor, which is the basis of electronics; but also an object that was very mysterious at first: the laser,
which has become a valuable tool for doctors in surgery but that is more commonly found at every cash deck for reading bar codes.
So initially, however, quantum theory was not accepted.
It was not accepted because it was questioning our vision of physics.
In fact, it was a breakthrough.
Breaks are rarely accepted easily.
At the same time, in the early 20th century there was a break in art.
Yes, abstract painting.
Abstract painting also changed the vision we had of the world, of representation.
So, what did quantum physics actually bring?
What did it proposed?
It proposed new objects.
Neither particle nor wave, "totally crazy things", to quote the great physicist Richard Feynman.
It proposed another vision of the microscopic world.
It proposed to enter a Terra Incognita which physicists occupied pretty soon.
And in fact, this evolution of science was possible only because science freed itself from dogma.
Science has gained its independence.
This long history of science is the history of intelligence against obscurantism, of critical minds against dogmatism.
This is the story of reason and doubt against certainty.
It's a long and beautiful story.
We should tell it to our children,
explain the perseverance of scholars, explain that scientists had to fight against those who did not accept the ideas they were bringing because it was thought these ideas would disturb beliefs.
And, yes, scientists have had to fight against a concept of knowledge locked inside a single idea of what the truth was.
Whereas, on the contrary it is necessary to promote a knowledge open to the world, to civilizations.
This is what Kheireddine, whom you see here, who was Prime Minister of Tunisia in the second half of the 19th century, wanted to introduce in a new education system which was fundamental for the evolution of Tunisia, this teaching called the Sadikian education.
What did Kheireddine want to do?
Kheireddine wanted Tunisia to catch up in science because for centuries, Tunisia had forgotten science, like other Arab-Muslim countries.
Yes, the Arab-Muslim world forgot the science of its ancestors.
Let me tell you the last episode
of Arabic astronomy.
In Istanbul, in 1577, an observatory was built.
Beautiful... with the most efficient instruments of the time, like this other observatory that was designed in... "the North" by the great Danish physicist Tycho Brahe, (at the time, the term would have been astronomer, not physicist).
And this observatory was installed in the Palace of Uraniborg.
The two observatories, in Istanbul and in this northern country, had completely opposite fates after the appearance of a comet in the northern sky.
For Brahe, it was fundamental observations which subsequently led to the extraordinary development of astronomy in the European world.
I think everyone knows about it.
But in Istanbul, unfortunately, that was the end of a beautiful scientific adventure.
Why? Because in fact, this comet
had been interpreted differently.
In Istanbul, on the orders of the Sultan, the observatory was destroyed in 1580 because the Sultan had not accepted the astronomer's omen.
So today, we know more about comets, you know more now... we even make appointments from Earth!
Science is also at the heart of economic development.
Europe was built, was economically developed thanks to scientific development.
And Kheireddine, whom I mentioned earlier, understood this.
Kheireddine who said we had to take science wherever it comes from.
Yes, we had to take science wherever it comes from and our children had to discover it early.
We had to educate our children in this double culture.
Give them a traditional instruction, of course, - at the time, in the 19th century, it was hard to say otherwise - but also give them the teaching of modern science, of foreign languages.
Yes, it is thanks to this double culture that modernity came into Tunisia.
Yes, this modernity that is in me, that I carry with me, that I am proud of.
My parents taught me this modernity, they instilled it in me.
My grandfather, a French and Arabic teacher.
My father, a pharmacist-biologist.
Look at this picture.
This photo - my father is one of those pupils.
These pupils of the French-Arab school of Sfax.
It was the school year 1921-1922.
All dressed in jebba, except the teacher, and all loving the values of equality and freedom: the values of the French Revolution.
All for opening up to other cultures.
Yes, openness to other cultures... This is what allows to know the other, what allows to respect the other, what allows sharing.
This must be at the heart of the education system.
Yes, a teacher's mission is a rich one.
They are passers of knowledge.
They are passers of cultures.
They are also passers of values.
Values to share everywhere on the planet, I mentionned equality: equality for all.
Equality for women and men.
Yes, equality for women and men.
So as a Tunisian woman, I want to say that being from a country of Muslim culture, I believe that women in Islamic countries do not have to undergo
an inferior status. I do.
Already, this principle of equality between men and women, was stated by Tahar Haddad, a Tunisian theologian, in 1930 and his famous work "Our woman, Islamic law and society " was translated into French - you see here the book cover. And at the end of the book,
a figure which may surprise you.
We don't have time to comment on that but I'm going to read the small caption: "Our woman, between a faded past and a promising present."
Let's talk about the present.
We are worried. We are.
We are concerned by the violence,
by the acts of barbarism in the region.
Yes, we are worried.
March 18, Tunisia, my country, the Bardo Museum was attacked, there were victims.
I pay tribute to them, but the Bardo Museum is the museum of the Mediterranean.
This is the museum where all the Tunisian history is present.
Tunisia was Berber, Punic, Roman, Byzantine, Vandal then Muslim and Arab.
So what can we do?
How to deal with this violence?
Yes, we must protect our children.
We must protect our children from those who invite to camp in "the field of the curse to maintain the henchmen of the Demon and the sequence of destructive hatred".
This is a quote from a great Tunisian thinker Abdelwahab Meddeb, who died recently.
I pay tribute to him
Yes, this violence... how to react to this violence?
Well all together, each of us
in our own way. Each of us where we are.
So as a teacher and a scientist, I would like to mention very quickly two examples.
One is the story of my colleague, Aroua Saida, a biologist and didactician, who understood that, in fact, students, our students in their final year, studying the theory of evolution had a... shall we say composite understanding of the diversity of life.
They muddled up the scientific and theological references.
And she worked with them.
And the students understood.
They understood you had to step into the researcher's shoes
That you had to accept the keys to science, to knowledge, to accept questioning and critical thinking.
The second example concerns the scientific community.
The scientific community must fight against obscurantists, who unfortunately, are currently investing the Web.
Yes, the scientific community that of Academies of Sciences made a declaration.
It gathered the Academies of Sciences of 68 countries Europe, Latin America, USA, Africa, Asia, and among these countries Arab Muslim countries: The Islamic Republic of Iran, the Kingdom of Morocco Turkey, Palestine... perhaps I forgot some of them but anyway... What did this declatation say?
It shows that it is important to teach the theory of evolution that is so attacked on social networks, on the Internet and that teaching this theory which is actually accepted by the scientific community, will bring students important knowledge since the theory of evolution is one of the great advances of knowledge.
And this declaration called teachers, policy makers, parents to educate their children so they can understand science.
But it also reminds of something interesting: that number of questions cannot be explained by science.
Then we should take other approaches: philosophical, social, cultural, religious.
These approaches have different fields of action.
They have different fields of action and owe each other mutual respect.
So this declaration is a wonderful call.
A wonderful call from a scientific community, of different culture, diverse culture.
But a call for young people to understand what science is.
For young people to understand that science is universal.
And I would add, because that is what is implied in that declaration, human rights too, are universal.
And it is this universality I'm fighting for.
Thank you.
(Applause)
Hello.
If you can hear me, clap your hands once.
(Clap) If you're enjoying TEDx, clap your hands twice.
(Claps) I want to talk to you about a project involving prosthetic hands for amputees, which resulted from a collaborative project that began in the LabFab in Rennes.
Strength doesn't come from muscles; it comes from helping each other.
I really like that sentence, firstly because strength lies in unity, and secondly, because I don't have Sylvester Stallone's arms.
That suits me.
If I take you back to 2012, what do you think of?
Do you remember what happened that year?
2012 was the year of change.
(Laughter) It was the year of change.
There were presidential elections in several countries: Venezuela, Senegal, the United States, Russia and France.
The slogan in France was "Change is now".
We're still waiting.
And what else happened in 2012?
Geomagnetic reversal, the end of the Mayan calendar, and so the end of the world.
I was feeling down in 2012.
I didn't have a lot of work, I felt a bit lonely and like I didn't fit in anywhere.
So I was waiting for change pretty impatiently.
In fact, that's all I was waiting for.
All the more so since I'd been wearing a myo-electric prosthesis for 10 years, which allows me to be independent. I found out that new prosthetics were coming on to the market that were much more sophisticated.
So I talked to my prosthetist, who said: "These prosthetics are great, but they cost an arm and a leg!"
(Laughter) (Applause) "They cost 40,000 euros and, above all, they're not covered by health insurance."
I was really disappointed, because when my accident happened, I'd imagined my future and wondered: "Where will I be in 10 years' time?"
Will I have grieved?
Will I have a normal life?
Will I have accepted my disability?
Will I have met a wizard in Brocéliande forest who makes me drink lizard juice
to help my hand grow back? Maybe.
None of them happened.
In 2012 I found life a bit unfair, because I think that disabled people should have access to health care, but I also realise how lucky I am to live in France,
because we have a welfare system.
Anyway,
I was walking down a street in Rennes one day in October 2012,
when I saw a building with lights
and people inside. It was free, so I went in. I saw some guys working on machines -
they were 3D printers, but I didn't know what those were at the time.
It all looked very sci-fi.
At the time, I didn't think my prosthesis was very nice to look at, and I was particularly jealous of robots in sci-fi films, whose hands are always great and so sophisticated. I said to myself: "How is it that Hollywood can spend millions of dollars on robots who are just used for films, when real people are in need and have nothing?"
I saw this machine, which made me think of the future, and I walked over timidly. I didn't know what to say, and then I suddenly said: "Hi. Would it be possible to make a robotic hand?"
The guy looked at me, and said: "Of course!"
(Laughter)
"Oh, good." Then I said to him: "This is my prosthesis." When people see my prosthesis, they normally look a bit awkward. But not those guys. They said: "Wow! It's great...it moves!
How do you do that? Show us!"
They almost wanted me to take it off!
The guy said: "Of course we can make a prosthesis. Look."
He went on to a website and said: "This site is called Thingiverse.
You can download a hand."
So we found a hand. "That's InMoov.
This guy seems to be using Arduino - it's open source and free.
So let's go for it."
I said: "I didn't understand any of that."
(Laughter) But he replied: "With open-source technology, we can download designs online, and make a hand that will be available worldwide to those in need."
That moment there was my change.
It was my own change, because it gave a reason for my disability, and gave it all a meaning.
It explained to me why this had happened. It was because I had to become interested
in my disability.
I left and walked home, and I remember seeing Rennes station and it was somehow different.
I saw walls and found that the gray colour I usually hated was now beautiful to me.
Everything was different. That was my 2012.
It was my 21st December.
That was in October 2012.
I got home and went online, looking for Thingiverse and InMoov. I found a video
where an engineer shows a hand moving like that and explains how it works. He presses a few keys and the fingers close.
I thought: "That's amazing."
I was sure that if he could control the hand with his computer, those guys could definitely use their Arduino card to put sensors on my prosthesis, so that I could control it.
I started imagining it all, as I often did, and I sent an email to this person - in English, because he seemed English. He replied a few days later.
I thought: "This is real change.
Engineers who actually reply to you! (Laughter) I've got nothing against them, but since I'm not an engineer, I tend to think they look down on us a bit.
But that's wrong.
Five months passed, and my euphoria had subsided. I thought it was all over, but then I met the people from the Rennes LabFab again, and Hugues Aubain - the guy who had made me all starry-eyed five months earlier.
I realised the guys recognised me: "It's Nicolas, the guy who wants to make a hand." I wasn't really in the mood,
but they had already printed a hand and were really keen.
I said: "That's cool.
But the hand I want is the InMoov hand."
He said: "Alright.
That looks complicated, but ok."
We launched the project in February 2013.
What happened from that point
was really important. It had a spiral effect, and we realised that the creator of the InMoov robot was French. He was Gael Langevin and he lived in Paris. So we found his number, called him, and said:
"We'd really like to make a prosthesis.
Would that interest you?"
And he said: "Why not?"
The LabFab guys began work on printing a hand, finding muscular sensors available online in the States, and working with people in Brazil.
I watched it all happen from afar, because, as luck would have it, I'd finally found work.
Suddenly it was June 2013, and Hugues turned up with a cardboard box. Inside was the hand he had made.
The hand was made from a fishing line, a Nesquik box, (Laughter) and little 10-euro motors. He said: "Nicolas, I've tried it on me. It works, but we'll see!"
In June, we went to the Rennes digital festival and I put the Nesquik box on, to test it.
I switched on the sensors and it worked.
People asked us what it was, and we said:
"It's a prosthetic hand made from a 3D printer."
Simple as that.
(Laughter) The organisers of Maker Faire were there that day.
Maker Faire is basically a chance for geeks, makers and experimenters to meet up and show off their inventions. They saw the hand and said: "Ok, you're invited.
We're inviting you to the Maker Faire."
The guys said: "Go!
It'll boost your project. It's great."
And so I asked them what exactly a Maker Faire was.
(Laughter)
"It's great. It's where geeks meet up. You should go."
"Well if they're inviting us, then ok."
So we went to Italy...
But before that, back in October, I really threw myself into the project.
From that moment on, we started playing around with it.
I learnt how to use a 3D printer, which allowed me to print a hand, and we worked in Samy's and some friends' garages.
We fitted the hand with muscular sensors,
and tried to see the contractions involved in opening and closing the hand.
We used a fishing line, kitesurfing line,
an Arduino card and a timer, and we fitted it all together. By October, when we turned up at the Maker Faire in Rome, I was shaking everyone's hands.
(Laughter)
Except that they were all Italians.
So what I said was: (in Italian) "It's a prosthetic hand made from a 3D printer." (Laughter) (Applause)
It was great.
The organisers of the Geek Picnic festival were there, too.
"What's that?"
(Laughter) "It's pretty much the same thing,
except this one's in Moscow."
"In Moscow?"
(Laughter)
"Yes, in January - you want to come?"
"Ok then."
(Laughter) So what did I do in Moscow?
I shook everyone's hands, (Laughter) but this time in Russian.
(in Russian) "This is a prosthetic hand made from a 3D printer." (Laughter and applause) Just last weekend, I went to the Maker Faire in San Francisco, chewing Hollywood gum since I was in America, and so I said: "This is a prosthetic hand made with a 3D printer, man." (Laughter and applause) Thanks.
That's not all I did. I used it as a chance to visit a few research centres, including one in Chicago that's working on bionic prosthetics. I presented our project to them, and explained our aim and where we wanted to go with it.
I also visited Johns Hopkins University, which recently got funding from DARPA, the US army agency. I met Doctor Chi there, who's known worldwide for his work and who has helped to fit many people with prosthetics, including many servicemen.
In this photo, you can see three prosthetics. Can you guess their total cost?
Together, they cost exactly 100,040,200 euros.
Let me be clear: The arm made by Doctor Chi, which was funded by DARPA, is worth 100 million euros.
Fabrice, who I went to the US with, is wearing a professional prosthesis which is worth 40,000 euros.
And my prosthesis - the one I'm wearing now - is worth 200 euros.
(Applause) Obviously, this arm is still just a prototype. None of it could have worked without people, without humans.
Above all, it's a human story.
That's how it works.
That's the only way it can work.
The conclusion? I met with the LabFab yesterday, and they said:
"We'll lend you a hand."
(Laughter) Today, it's TEDx,
and tomorrow...
Well, I'm hoping for two hands. Mostly, I hope that people will share thousands of ideas, and who knows? Hopefully an enhanced human body.
One day, there might even be a third hand for doctors, experimenters, or just those who don't want to get their hands dirty on the subway.
(Laughter) I'm sure that would interest some people.
There could be a cosmetic hand,
that didn't cost too much and was available for developing countries as well as for me.
It could match my personality, and transform prosthetics from medical objects into a part of the owner's personality.
It would look like me,
and I would be proud to wear it.
Above all, this project is all about developing a myo-electric prosthesis which is low-cost, affordable and robust, in a co-operative way -
through a worldwide collaborative project.
Also, ...I've forgotten what I was going to say.
Sorry.
(Laughter) When I had my accident in 2002, I wondered where I would be in 10 years' time. Today, in 2014, I wonder where we will have got with this 10 years from now.
This is becoming an international project which is open to everyone, and which has allowed me to find myself again, and regain my self-confidence. I'm sure it could allow other people to find themselves again, and develop their own projects or be involved so that they can feel useful.
Unemployment levels are high in France, which is pretty hard, but that also represents a lot of people who potentially have time and are available to work on projects close to their heart,
just like I'm doing.
I also want to add that we live in a world where we think like lions.
We think in terms of strength, power and pride, whereas if we thought like ants, it would be all about unity.
Finally, in the words of the great American philosopher, Sylvester Stallone, (Laughter) "Remember the mind is your best muscle. Big arms can move rocks, but big words can move mountains." I hope I've done that today.
(Applause) Thank you.
(Applause).
Hello.
My name is Ingrid Stanson.
I am originally from Malmö in Sweden.
I'm tall, I'm blonde, I have blue eyes, and I am 23 years old.
I'm single, and I love going out in the evening partying.
(Laughter) (Applause) Yes, I knew the reaction would be something like that.
If I wanted to attract a very large number of people on my social networks, if I wanted to make a lot of friends in a very short time, especially among the men - True, gentlemen? -
that's exactly what I'd do.
That's exactly how I'd go about it.
Yes, it would be easy.
But no, my name is Neila Benzina Atruz.
I am Tunisian, I'm married, I have two children, I am entrepreneur, and I'll soon be 40.
(Applause) So now, imagine that Ingrid Stanson is Mohammed Al Baghdadi, recruiter for ISIS, the Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant.
Mohammed Al Baghdadi seeks to draw into his sphere, his Jihad sphere, a very large number of young people who are desperate and lost, searching for something to hold on to, searching for guidance.
Young people, yes, hundreds of thousands of young people who would find themselves trapped, who are unable to go back and retrace their steps.
Yes, he would be capable of turning them into human bombs.
Mohammed Al Baghdadi, you know what?
He didn't hesitate to do it.
He's already doing it today, massively and uncontrollably.
The Internet and social media unleashed all passion.
The Internet and social media have allowed a great effervescence allowed things to boil up like nothing else.
The Internet and social media today provide a place for all fantasies, but also, unfortunately, for all forms of manipulation.
So, what is it really?
The power of Twitter and Facebook is much-vaunted in revolutionary movements.
Consider the speed with which all those messages, all those slogans were sent.
The impact that it had on us. It all inspired us, gave us power. We felt united, standing in solidarity against the opponent,
in a position, finally, to be able to change things.
Yes, we felt able to change things, our destiny finally belonged to us.
Yes, everything was possible.
Except one also realized states' ability to use all the data and information for themselves in their own interests.
We realized, worse still, and more serious still, the capacity of all types of terrorists, and one must say, of all types, to have unlimited access to the world, to propagate their fascistic and nauseous theories,
to manipulate, animate all their networks, Jihadist, terrorist, murderous, bloodthirsty.
Yes, that's how they had unlimited access to the world.
After the enthusiasm that followed the Arab Spring, or what we like to call the beginning of the Tunisian spring, after the events on Independence Square in the Ukraine, we began to allow ourselves to dream that finally the voice would be restored to the people, and that the peoples would make good use of it.
Yes, it would be possible.
We were going to be able to build a better world together in which there would be greater synergy, more collaboration, greater possibilities, more opportunities.
You can imagine this world able to break down barriers, to abolish borders, allow us to get closer, and to seek all that would be beneficial beyond the interests of the individual and the individualist.
It would finally be possible.
Except that one realized also, unfortunately, that the use of this new freedom would be far more complicated than it seemed.
Digital democracy is difficult to put in place.
The path is still long and difficult.
Yes, the use of this new freedom has brought a lot of disappointments.
And these disappointments lead us today, unfortunately, to put in question this pseudo-libertarian model.
It's sad to use the term 'pseudo-libertarian'
because finally it's libertarian only for well-established, safe democracies.
Authoritarian states have nothing to fear from these giants of the Internet, from these players on the Internet, from these mad sources of information, which, it should also be noted in passing, are there first and foremost for business.
They are there first and foremost with commercial interests.
They are there first and foremost to monetize and make money from your passage through their environment, through their system.
Yes, they know how to pull in the cash as soon as you enter their sphere.
Well, authoritarian states are no longer afraid of that because they have completely mastered their operational modes.
Look how Google has yielded to China.
See how Russia has required that its data be stored on its own territory.
Look again how the NSA has enabled itself to have access to all the information and all the data of GAFA: Google, Amazon, Facebook and Apple, and many others besides.
Today, one poses the question, in fact: In the end, is all this nothing but an illusion?
Governments appear to have complete control over the modes of operation of the Internet.
At first they had difficulties, they struggled to master the tools of the web.
They were taken short by the tidal wave that was the web.
And then, over essentially the last four, five years they have reorganized themselves.
They've made massive investment to regain control.
And all content today, whether written
or oral, is monitored.
It's all known. It's all under control.
And the threat that justifies such surveillance is real.
Except that there is a paradox.
While we have seen put in place this arsenal, and this power of control, in the end we have seen complete control was not achieved.
Abuses are still here and they are much greater than before.
We have seen the proliferation of all the dishonest use of the Internet, of all the unhealthy uses: cybercrime, fraud, hacking everywhere.
Never has so much been monitored, so much been controlled, and never has control been so lost as it is now.
Maybe this paradox can be explained today by the absence of a legislative framework that was adequate, that was appropriate, that was well configured for the world of the Internet.
Probably there is a defect, which is not carried in its genes, in its DNA, the possibility to be able to act effectively upstream and downstream.
It is as if today the reality is that we have informers everywhere, snitchers, what we like to call snitchers.
These snitchers keep an eye on us, watch us.
They see potential criminals, they see criminals prepare their acts, they see offenders walking around, but they can't act, they can only observe; they cannot prevent them from committing their crimes, and they cannot bring them to trial when offenses have been committed.
For lack of police, lack of judges, lack of a suitable legal and judicial framework.
So probably today it's for the Internet government, to take the lead and to organize itself.
Regulation should come from inside, from this 'government' of the Internet.
It's for it to find the solutions.
It's for it to seek mechanisms that will enable it to propose a model which has all the advantages of the Internet without the disadvantages.
Yes, it is possible, but we must think it over.
For example, one might think about better personal ID, about better traceability of content.
This personal ID would require everyone to show their face, to assume simply who we really are, according to what we write, what we say, what we relate.
Because suppose you hide behind pseudonyms, insult everyone, say whatever you want.
Of course you're going to have fun.
What I'm calling for is for more taking of responsibility, more accountability of Internet users.
And obviously, this is possible only if we advance openly, if we are obliged to show ourselves clearly and fully.
In order to do so, I propose a digital identity card, a numerical identity card.
This digital identity card would replace all those cookies that trace and track us already without our knowledge.
It's better that we do it openly and always.
Yes, it is possible.
This identity card would be a real asset for the world of the Internet.
This identity card would be a revolution for the Internet model.
Some will say to me, "And the right to be forgotten?
And the wish to remain anonymous, what about that?"
We need to think about that, of course, but what I think is, is that if one weighs the two up, me, I would prefer a model where finally everyone accounts for what he says and what he writes.
I think that this model offers us the best the virtual world has to offer.
So, if I might return to Ingrid Stanson, you will still be able to get acquainted with her, and to see who it is behind the screen.
At the same time, with this digital identity card you will have the possibility of checking, verifying, the veracity of what she says.
And that would be a real asset, because at least you will not be chatting way with a bearded man behind the screen.
Equally, Ingrid Stanson herself would probably be pleased to know that it is you who is on the other end of the line.
So yes to digital democracy, that digital democracy that still needs several steps for it to be put in place.
Among these steps, I recommend a digital identity card, a numerical identity card, whereby we would have a much healthier ecosystem, a much more aware ecosystem, an ecosystem in which we have more confidence, an ecosystem of benefit to everyone.
Thank you.
(Applause)
I can imagine that in this room, most of you have a Facebook or Twitter account.
If that's the case, these past few weeks, you may have seen this image: a firefighter who was assaulted during an intervention and lost one eye.
If you haven't, perhaps you have seen this other image: the image of a priest also assaulted at the beginning of the year in Avignon.
Or maybe you've heard about the 40,000 migrants who sleep every night at the hotel at the expense of French taxpayers, or maybe you have heard about Saudi Arabia's campaign funding for certain candidates or the newly granted voting right to all French prisoners.
These news items seem totally unrelated.
And yet, they share two common points: the first is that they are all false; the second is that they've all been shared tens or even hundreds of thousands of times on social networks in the past two months.
The spreading of rumors, false information, fake news, conspiracy theories on social networks, has grown to such an extent in recent years that it has become a real social problem.
The media have talked a lot about it, notably during the UK Brexit referendum campaign or the US election campaign last fall, and more recently in the context of the French election campaign.
Yet rumors are not really a new phenomenon.
They are even regarded as the oldest media in the world.
You, like me, when we were at school, I am sure that we all participated in spreading dozens of rumors or urban legends.
Where is the problem then?
The problem is that these rumors, this false information, have become direct competitors of the information produced by traditional media.
Social networks have taken a very important place in the media landscape in recent years, to the point of becoming one of the main sources of online information, and even becoming the main source of information for the youngest of us, even surpassing search engines.
So this evolution at first seems innocuous, but it isn't.
When using a search engine, to find information, the information comes to you according to a logic of popularity.
When you make a query on Google, Google will isolate sites that address the topic you want to be informed about, and its algorithm, PageRank, will look at how the sites are connected.
It will bring you as the first result the site that received the most links from other sites.
Google actually considers that when you, as an Internet user, propose a link from one site to another, in a way, you vote for it.
So Google thinks, "The most important information is the one the Internet community considered to be the most relevant."
On Facebook, the logic is very different: it is not a principle of popularity that prevails but one of proximity.
The most visible information in your Facebook news feed is that of your closest friends.
How does Facebook go about evaluating this proximity?
Quite simply depending on the intensity of your interactions.
The more you like, the more you comment, the more you share the information posted by one of your contacts and the more the edge rank, the Facebook algorithm considers that this person is important to you, thus that the information they publish must be brought to your attention.
Again, you will tell me, after all, being informed first of the people you are closest to rather than those from whom we are most distant, what is the problem?
The problem is that when Facebook becomes our first source of political information, the machine seizes up a little.
You, me, we all have in our Facebook contacts people whose beliefs or interests we do not share.
We all have this somewhat racist old uncle who posts on the network the same kind of jokes that wreck family meals, or that childhood friend who suddenly discovers they have a political fiber and begins to flood the network with information from an obscure micro-party.
I don't know about you, but anyway, I have that kind of friends, but when these friends post this type of information, I do not like their posts, I do not comment them, I do not share them.
Facebook interprets this lack of interaction like this: it thinks that in fact, this person is not important to me and that what they say does not matter to me.
The weeks pass, as and when, what these people post will begin to disappear from my news feed, to the point of disappearing totally.
And you see what the problem is: the problem is that if we use nothing but Facebook to get informed, in the long term, we will be confronted, only to information which confirms our opinions.
This is called ideological confinement, ideological bubbles on social networks, the idea that when you get your information on social networks, you only see information that reinforce our opinions while for public debate to function properly in a democracy, it is necessary to be confronted to contradictory arguments.
Yet, ideological bubbles weren't invented by Facebook, far from it.
In our everyday lives, we all live in more or less hermetic ideological bubbles.
It's a safe bet that your vote is fairly close to your spouse's, or you share a number of beliefs with your close friends, in the same way, the news media you consume say a lot about your political orientations.
What is the problem then?
The problem is that with Facebook, ideological confinement, ideological bubbles have become a real business.
Why?
First, because of Facebook's economic model: how does Facebook make money?
Facebook makes money by exposing you, the users, to advertising.
In another era, we'd have said that Facebook sells available brain time to advertisers.
We do not say that anymore.
Yet the principle is exactly the same.
The more time you spend on the platform, the more Facebook makes money.
And how does Facebook make you spend time on the platform?
Simply by offering you the contents you like, which is the one you loved yesterday, from your closest contacts, whose beliefs and interests you share.
But this goes even further: with Facebook, the production of rumors has entered a new era.
It has entered a click economy which generated a real industrialization of the production of rumors.
You may have heard about this case, during the US election campaign: some journalists at Buzzfeed realized that a large number of pro Trump fake news emanated from sites hosted in Eastern Europe, particularly in Macedonia.
They wondered why hundreds of sites in Macedonia started to produce information, fake news, pro Trump, anti Clinton.
Intuitively, they thought that the candidate's campaign team had paid networks in Eastern Europe to produce that false news.
They traveled to the area and the reality was quite different.
They actually found out teenagers, 15, 16 or 17 years of age, unrelated to the Republican candidate's campaign team.
Not only did they have no connection to the Republican candidate's campaign team, but their motivation was absolutely not political.
It was much more pragmatic: they wanted to make money.
These Macedonian teenagers realized that pro Trump information was the most shared information on Facebook.
They thought, maybe we could get some of their income by inventing false news about Trump, by posting it on Facebook, bringing US Internet users to our sites to expose them to advertising and make money.
Their bet was a successful one since for those who managed best among them, in any case those who were the most productive, they could generate an income of $ 5,000 per month while the average monthly income in Macedonia is less than 400 euros.
So you can see that the problem of false news on the internet is also an economic problem.
But it is not just an economic problem because, after all, to generate so much income there has to be people who share this piece of information.
And there are many such people.
The real question to ask is why people share false information, why do people share rumors?
You will say, maybe the Internet makes us stupid, gullible to the point of sharing anything.
The reality is a little more complex.
Psychology studies looking at rumors have shown that people who share rumors may in fact keep a critical distance from their contents.
It's not so much that people believe it; it is rather that they adhere to the world view that is conveyed by this rumor.
And what do rumors tell us today, the one I told you about earlier?
They tell us about the betrayal of elected representatives, they tell us about the confiscation of speech by the mass media, they tell us of a certain number of anxieties linked to globalization; we can see what's behind fake news, it is a much deeper problem, which is a sense of exclusion felt by an increasing share of society, exclusion from the common space, the public space, the media space.
And this sense of exclusion is reflected in a growing distrust of the political and intellectual elites in our country.
What the Internet has done since the early 2000s is precisely to allow those people excluded from the media space to make their voices heard, to be able to disseminate their arguments in the public debate.
So, of course, this irruption does not always occur very politely, or very courteously, it is not very pleasant.
But at least it has the merit of forcing us to face reality.
And the reality is that today we live in a very pluralistic society.
And I'm not talking about pluralism of opinions, I am talking about a pluralism of values, a pluralism of ways of seeing, ways of conceiving life in society.
So the challenge for the coming years will be to succeed in building spaces of common debate that respect this pluralism, that is to say respecting the principle of absolute and unconditional equality of all citizens to speak and make their voices heard, but at the same time, spaces of debate allowing people who share completely different values and ways of seeing the world to join the discussion.
So how do we do it?
Maybe, in the end, we each have our truth.
Maybe we cannot compare values.
On the other hand, the criteria from which we distinguish true from false, fair from unfair, desirable from undesirable, can be compared.
As for the fake news, a number of journalists have understood it, who have embarked on fact-checking initiatives.
Their logic is to say: we will check the rumors on social networks, but we will not judge the information according to what they say, we will judge it according to the method by which they were produced.
Do they respect the basic principles of journalism?
Crossing their sources, argumenting from evidence, separating the facts from the comments.
So for the media, the posture is a bit tricky to be both judge and party, judging competitors in this information market.
But this posture is to say, "We can compare the producers of information depending on the method they follow." and it is relevant.
So no, do not censor fake news, because in that case, the solution could be much worse than the problem.
No, let's learn to live in a loudspeaker society where everyone can make their voice heard, learn to debate in a pluralistic public space, teach children and adolescents to learn and evaluate the quality of the information based on the method followed by its producer.
And then also adopt a combative posture.
Let's stop leaving the web and social networks to the most retrograde voices.
This has been understood in particular by a number of associations or civil society organizations which today offer counter-discourse platforms.
If you are on a social network and you come across homophobic, racist, anti-Semitic, misogynist information, you can go on these platforms to try to find counter-arguments and post them on social networks.
The challenge is not to convince the one facing you.
Spoiler: you can't.
No, the challenge is to occupy the land, to show that other voices can be heard.
What is coming in the next few years, is a true information war, and in this information war, we all have a role to play.
Thank you.
(Applause)
I must tell you a secret: I love food.
It does not show on me, but I love food.
I love to eat it. I love to prepare it, to go to the market to choose the right ingredients from small local producers who prove to be really exceptional people each time.
I love the thought of gathering together in my sewing workshop and create clothes, but it often ends around a dish of couscous.
And I realize that somehow, saying "no way" to junk food is something that matters.
There is no junk food at home because eating well - and we are all aware of it - means respecting one's life.
And from junk food to "junk clothes", there's just a step away.
A few years ago, I set up my fashion house, and I actually decided to scavenge the trash of haute couture.
I dumpster dived.
I had the good fortune do receive the Kering Foundation award, and the only thing that I asked for was to be able to pick up the discarded fabrics and make beautiful clothes with the remains.
And I realized that by creating my "Front de Mode," which is a store that sells fashion, trend, beautiful things, we sell good things, yes, but we sell things that apply at least one of the three pillars of sustainable development: environmental, economic and social.
I think we, all the creators together, are leading a real fight, that really is to realize a strong, intense breakthrough so that these women who wear these clothes can actually show that they really are these elements of color, light and beauty of society.
At the end of the Second Empire, there were these women, idle women, who reinvented high society in the context of a crisis at the imperial court.
But it was without considering something magical which was happening and which, in any case, changed my life.
It really changed my life; I was a kid, I was just 17, and there I saw this freedom, the freedom that was brought by a Gabrielle Chanel, a Balenciaga, a Schiaparelli, a Poiret , that suddenly set women's bodies free.
And there is also one thing which really amazed me. When I was 20 years old, I saw these women who had to both carry on their shoulders the roles of mother, housewife, executive woman, who had to be really impeccable women and seductive and I thought that more and more, we, fashion designers - well, I was not yet in fashion, I was still a kid - but the shoulders of these women, the shoulders of the jackets were getting larger and larger.
I said to myself that anyway, it's absolutely not faisable, and that, at some point, we will have to work for the reunification of her identity, that is to say, we could be all that simultaneously, but in freedom, in freedom, in calm and stress free. that is to say, being these committed characters and affirming somewhere inside us all the levels of society, all this strength to be both these women, but free at the same time.
I often tell my clients that you have to know how to demand beauty, color and light.
When this tragedy happened in Bangladesh,
I went there, I flew to Bangladesh.
And I met exceptional women, and we saw the really squalid conditions in which they live.
They work in difficult conditions but I knew that every single one of them were saying to themselves: "I come here and I know why I come here: to feed my children, to feed my family." When we, fashion designers, we were coming saying, for example, myself I told them:
"What fascinates me is desire;
"what fascinates me is light;
it's not necessarily about making money;"
they did not understand all that.
As for me, I remain convinced that earning a lot more money, always more money, has never lit any light.
I tried but it didn't turn any light on.
I met a lot of people who are making a lot of money through what they do, but they are not necessarily very bright.
So, I decided that I was going to fight for only one thing: making sustainable fashion but without compromising aesthetics.
The more we became passionate about this commitment to aesthetics, this commitment to style and this commitment to social issues, the more I felt I had the duty to make clothes that make people bright.
Desires, for me, I always say, "It is desire that reignites the light."
In fact, desires lead to enlightenment.
You should try, it works!
I opened a workshop in the 18th district in Paris.
Personally, I call it: "The social fabric workshop."
I was lucky to start very quickly by being in the "in" calendar of haute couture designers, and so making a fashion show at the Carrousel du Louvre.
But what I liked the most was when all of a sudden ...
Actually I had models that were 1,80m tall, who had perfect teeth, who were the fashionable girls of the moment.
I remember that I was told, "Brazilian women are in fashion, we must have some. "
But personally what interested me was the fashion for human.
What did I enjoy the most?
It was to be there at the Carrousel du Louvre, but with fat, skinny, thin, small and tall women, to have the most beautiful of podiums.
The most beautiful of podiums is that of the street.
It's the social podium.
It's the democratic podium where finally, all the types of bodies can be found.
For me, desire is always present.
When we see a woman like this one, who is magnificent, she shows something very, very deep in her garment.
But as time goes by, I realize that everywhere I go - because I'm organizing fashion shows in prisons - whether it be at the women's detention house of Fleury-Mérogis, at the Carrousel du Louvre, or at Crillon, each time, each time, it is this light that intensifies the garment.
It is this light that shows that this silhouette is extraordinary.
I come from far away.
I haven't told you but I come from far away: from the Comoros.
And when I was a kid, I had an extraordinary grandmother!
She was a witch, an unbelievable witch!
In the morning, we'd get up and draw our dreams on the slate walls. Our houses were made of sheet metal, and we had slates;
we would draw our dreams and she would tell us what they meant.
As for me, as we say in Marseille,
"Diantre! " I dreamed that people in France lived in drawers.
Wow! I did not want
to go and live in a drawer.
This was the first picture I had of my mother who was at the window of a building.
It was the first time that I saw a building of five, six, seven floors.
So this place was a pretty magical place, because I was raised under the Sharia law and I learned how to read, how to write with words that I did not understand.
I learned the Qur'an without knowing what I was saying.
At the end, I arrived in Marseille, and discovered Boris Vian, Paul Eluard, and then, all of a sudden, it was magic, I could understand what I was saying.
We pressed the ON-button of charisma of the "made in France" and "made in Madagascar", because I didn't know, at some point, whether to manufacture in France or elsewhere.
Today, my fashion house for integration is located in a Go Zone.
We put 10 people on a literacy plan; we did four fashion weeks in the favelas; we found 17 homes for people; and all that, with crazy laughs, beams of light, and for one thing only: one must know how to turn poison into an elixir.
We must really revive our childhood dreams.
It's what is the most important.
We must learn to start over.
Thank you very much.
(Applause)
When I first spoke with the organizer about the idea of this talk, he told me, "Sylvain, the liberated company, that's your topic."
At this point I said, "Stéphane, we're getting off the wrong foot.
I don't believe in the liberated company."
And yet, I co-founded one.
I am 32, my name is Sylvain, I have been living in Vietnam for the past 9 years.
I was born in the Vosges area.
I followed a pretty classic path: high school, college, engineering degree.
Not much questioning indeed.
In 2006, like many other young engineers, I start looking for a "graduation internship"
with a self-proclaimed "cream of the crop" degree in my bag, I land a last-minute interview at an audit firm, Mazars.
They told me I was not suitable
for the job; they were right.
I go back to my internship seeking, time is running out.
That's when I have the encounter that is going to change my life.
"How about coming to Vietnam?"
I don't know anything about Vietnam, I have never been to Asia.
That said, I know
how to use chopsticks... I accept.
Three weeks later, at 23 year old, I land in Saigon.
That's the first step in my liberation.
All expats will tell you that: nothing better than being abroad to see what's going wrong in France.
And spending your time observing it while living in the world's most optimistic country, Vietnam, that helps too.
At first it starts with cliches.
Yeah, we French are a bunch of grumpy people.
And then little by little, I start refining my judgment.
I also realize how lucky I am: I made a first step outside of the box.
On the work side, our company is in its infancy.
It's just three of us, everything is yet to be done.
How does a company work?
I learn everything thanks to two strong allies on my side: books and experience.
To be honest, at first, we did not try to reinvent the wheel.
We stick to what works.
Well, what supposedly works.
I read classic books, the ones with corporate world's buzzwords: budget, reporting, evaluation, performance.
My life is made of business trips, demanding customers, 60-hour workweeks.
It goes on like that for six years.
And my close relationships seem to live the same life as I do.
All my friends work for large corporations, They all report to a manager, and for most of them, he's an "asshole."
A rebel side starts waking up in me.
Questions are going through my mind: Does it really work?
Is there any better way?
What are managers useful for?
Two opposing visions are growing in my mind: on one hand, I am wearing a mask, I am just pretending.
Like these poorly cut suits I wear for business meetings.
On the other hand, I want to be myself, to say what I truly think.
One morning, on a business trip in Paris, I open my eyes.
The clock shows 10:45 a.m.; I overslept.
Long day, hard night, work till 2 a.m.
The thing is, that day, I am supposed to attend a business meeting, at 11 a.m.
What excuses am I going to come up with?
Then I remember these Sunday nights I used to spend in front of the TV, when I was suddenly realizing I had to take a math test the next day.
These Monday mornings going to school filled with fear, knowing I'd score an F.
I arrive at the meeting, I sit down, I let out, "I overslept."
Awkward silence.
Oversleeping, that's not a common word in a company's user guide.
I look around, these people judging me have their own lives too, sometimes even tougher than mine.
They have kids crying until three in the morning, they fight with their significant other during lunch breaks, they get stuck in commute.
But the thing is, in most companies, having a life is forbidden.
"I overslept," that sentence represents the second step of my liberation.
I then decide that my life and my work will become one.
Not a balance, but a true fusion.
Starting with the way I dress.
So I go to work wearing t-shirt
and flip-flops on Monday; it's Vietnam.
My customers become my friends, and vice-versa.
Facebook replaces LinkedIn.
No more business trips for two days,
no, I travel. Singapore, Tokyo.
My trips get longer.
I take that chance to start photography.
I don't join meetings anymore, I meet people.
Worst, I pay attention to them.
Then during a random bar conversation in Paris, a friend asks me a question that is going to take me here today, "But are you sure that we can wish everyone this lifestyle?"
The answer seems obvious, but the question comes around so often that it becomes a legitimate one, even for me.
I fly back to Vietnam one more time.
We're now a large 300-people company.
Coincidentally, a few of us are going through the same phase, having both feet outside of the box.
It's decided, if we want to prove that it is indeed possible, that yes, we can wish everyone this lifestyle, Let's put back people at the heart
of our company, let's liberate it.
But how do you liberate a company?
Well, not with textbooks.
There's no textbook for that anyway.
So you feel your way,
you test, iterate, you make mistakes.
Lots of mistakes.
Like that one day when we had the genius idea to say, "No more managers."
In theory, the idea seemed
like a good one. But the thing is, managers are not only a symbol of our organizations.
Becoming a manager is
a career evolution, it's a social status.
It's the guarantee of a high income.
Managers are also supposed to embody the leadership that we all need.
On the salary topic, we also couldn't do as everybody else does.
So we said: each person can decide of their own salary.
I still remember the day when a team of ten people decided to take a 50% pay raise.
So we sulked, we did not expect this.
On one hand, if a co-founder refused this pay raise, it was probably end of story, no more autonomy.
On the other hand, if it went through, pay raises would probably escalate, and the company would probably collapse.
Well guess what, it did not go through.
Anyone could indeed take a 50% pay raise, but they had to tell everybody else.
In full transparency.
And when people started knowing about it, someone raised their hand to ask a question, a rather nice one, "So you want a 50% pay raise, fair enough.
Could you explain how it'll help us
move forward in our mission?" And then another person raised their hand, and a third one.
Unpleasant questions this time, "Hey, are you sure you deserve this 50% pay raise?"
The team suddenly became accountable, but not to the manager, not to the boss; to their colleagues.
And each person became responsible for their own decision.
Thanks to these experiments, these mistakes, we started understanding what are the keys to a liberated company.
A liberated company is first and foremost people gathered around a cause.
We believe in the same ideas, we have the same mission and the same values: let's work together.
The mission becomes the new shareholder.
We work at its service, and every single decision, including pay raises, are made with the mission in mind.
The mission also helps us choose our customers, for instance, or guide us to decide which new services to launch.
At this point, we share a mission, we know where we're going.
But how do we organize ourselves?
We figured we all need some sort of leadership, so we came back to a definition of leadership that we liked.
What is a leader?
Well a leader is someone that people decide to follow.
So we simply ask everyone to share who they were following.
And that's what came out.
No more pyramid, each person decides.
Leaders change depending on projects and colleagues, people are linked with commitment towards each other, with mentoring relationships, and with trust by default.
We transition from a hierarchy based on power to a hierarchy based on influence.
By the way, this is nothing new.
Instead of relationships defined by a pyramid, we simply revealed natural relationships.
Now we share a mission, we know where to go and how to organize ourselves. But how to move forward?
Well, we can work from any place, whenever we want, on any topic we choose.
We self-manage, and we regularly share what we are working on.
Sharing what we work on, this part is critical.
It helps build trust, as well as to synchronize with others.
Anaïs decides to work from home, she advises her colleagues.
And since we trust each other, she can even afford to be a bit humorous.
That example comes from Google+: Google+ is our tool for transparency, the same transparency that allowed a certain salary balance, or helped us to synchronize.
But we also discovered and even more interesting way to use it: we share our doubts, our everyday troubles.
That's where I can say, "Sorry guys, I overslept."
Yeah, it still happens.
We also share our joys, our successes, and cat pictures.
Can you imagine e-mailing a cat picture to your CEO?
Well thanks to Google+, we uncovered a form of intelligence that is still rarely used in the corporate world, the emotional intelligence.
Not only do we share what we do but we share how we feel, what we like.
Each individual can show sympathy or empathy, towards one another. Each person can trust their feelings to become a sensor of the company's mood.
Finally, each person can start taking off their mask and be truly themselves.
Through this unique and liberated usage, Google+ becomes a more human tool, a truly social network.
These are some key points that helped us to understand how a liberated company works.
You surely noticed that these key points are not processes.
Today we hear a lot about liberated companies.
Documentaries are showed on TV, articles are written in management magazines, debates are piling up.
And with all these documentaries, articles, and debates, a single question comes: does it actually work?
Well that's the kind of liberated company I don't believe in.
The one that is simplified, turned into cliches and processes, advertised through clickbait titles, "the end of management" for instance. The kind of liberated company that is only evaluated through revenue and growth.
Liberating a company is not another management process that is going to singlehandedly change everything.
True, the decision to liberate a company has to come from management.
It's actually the last strategic decision that management makes.
Obviously, claiming to be a liberated company doesn't just make it true.
It's more than just a decision, it requires deep motivation from a company's founder.
It means accepting to show fragility, and to be able to sometimes say, "I screwed up."
It also means accepting to take some distance from profits, growth, or people turnover rate.
Because a resignation can actually be a good thing, if it allows someone to liberate themselves, if the person leaving decides to pursue our mission through other means.
A conflict can be seen as an opportunity for each to share their doubts, and to move forward towards more integrity.
Liberating a company requires from each of its members to get out of habits that they took or learnt, to bring back feelings, emotions, and individual responsibility to the front stage.
I know what you're going to say, "I don't want that."
And yet, I can't help but wish all this to you.
The kind of company I believe in allows each of its members to free themselves from a certain type of organization and relationship,
which allows a kind of individual liberation.
Today cases of liberated companies are still quite rare.
Too rare if you ask me.
But I believe there are many things to learn from this real-life experiment that more and more people are making.
No matter the team, the department, no matter the scale, we can all experiment and open the door to a corporate world in which everyone, every day, can decide to become wiser, happier and more open.
Thank you.
(Applause)
Listen up, prepare well, do your homework the evening before, Reread your text before going... OK, OK.
That is all very good advice - very useful for succeeding, learning and advancing.
But I think that it's also very useful to know how to improvise.
Because knowing how to improvise is knowing how to take risks.
The risk of giving an unexpected answer because you haven't prepared it. The risk of expressing yourself in an original way because you've been caught off-guard.
And knowing how to improvise is also knowing how to bounce back.
Bouncing back after having been disappointed. Bouncing back after having displeased someone. That is to say, bouncing back after what is commonly called a failure.
Don't get me wrong, I am not telling you that in order to succeed at what you undertake, you don't have to work and simply expand your experiences.
I don't think that. I in fact think the exact opposite.
Before being able to go off the beaten track, you have to first thoroughly know the well-worn paths.
Before inventing a new form, you have to time and again go through the tried and tested motions.
Nor am I telling you that, in order to invent, you have to systematically put yourself in danger, especially if it's to flee reality.
Facing reality rather than fleeing it often demands more courage, especially if you realise that you do not conform with the majority, and that it's going to take effort to find your niche.
Finding your niche is often more difficult than being put in one, but it's also more interesting.
To illustrate my points I will draw on an example from my experience.
The business which I manage today, Théâtre à la Carte, was, at the beginning, an improvisation.
Today, it's a business which employs over 100 people - actors, teachers and consultants - and which operates over 5 continents in almost every language.
And yet, at the beginning, we had our work cut out because theatre and business are two words - two worlds - that we do not naturally want to combine, and which do, however, work very well together.
It works because we don't use artists' knowledge and talents to make art out of business - to transform every employee into an artist.
No. We use these talents and knowledge to free speech, to diffuse sometimes contentious situations, and to stimulate and develop professional behaviours.
In short, thanks to theatre, we create management, but a form which puts all its importance back on the human dimension.
And it also works because businesses today increasingly rely on stereotypical procedures - on globalised norms which reassure them.
But at the same time, they paradoxically want to emancipate themselves, as they realise that they are lacking creativity.
We therefore offer them, thanks to a reverse way of teaching, an original solution: go and search deep down inside yourself for unknown resources, and make use of them to advance. That is to say,
we put the importance back on the following principle which is essential to successful learning: confidence.
Learning how to improvise is useful for accepting failure and bouncing back with courage.
How do you learn how to improvise?
You have to work on what we call the pillars of improvisation - there are 5 of them.
I am going to introduce 3 of them to you: acceptance, leadership and letting go.
I am also going to try to show you that these are three very useful skills in the professional world.
First of all, acceptance.
Rejection is natural for man.
It's instinctive, a form of self-protection, and a force of inertia against change and everything which is different to me and my opinions.
On the other hand, acceptance demands effort; it's not natural.
That is why it's useful to work on your ability to accept others.
A good improvisation - a successful, theatrical improvisation - is one which is first of all founded on the acceptance of your colleagues' ideas.
Because if you refuse them, the improvisation stops and immediately comes to a dead-end.
In the professional world, this skill is essential when it comes to teamwork.
You have to perceive your colleagues - different stakeholders - as partners rather than as enemies or challengers.
Now for leadership.
A leader is someone who knows how to unite a group and set them off in the same direction.
In a theatrical improvisation, the improviser is constantly alternating between the position of the person who is leading, who is giving the impetus, and the position of the person who is receiving the impetuses of their partner and adapting to them.
We therefore learn that having leadership is something fleeting; it's a position which is useful to have on some occasions but not on others.
It is useful in a professional context when it comes to organising a group and giving that group an impetus.
It unleashes proactive behaviors and taking initiative; in short, managerial leadership.
Finally, let's look at letting go.
Being creative is not reserved for artists.
Everyone can, I believe, be creative.
You just have to be relaxed, trust yourself,
and let things come to you.
It's essential in an improvisation because it's about creating a story out of nothing.
In a professional context, it's very useful for getting out of situations where you are at stand-still.
You have to then find new initiatives and create new alternatives; in short, act outside of the box.
With these three skills, I have tried to show you that improvising is very professional, because it makes us consider failure and the unknown not as a punishment or a danger, but rather as levers from which you can develop.
I also hope to have given you, with the theatre of business, an example of a new line of work, created out of a successful improvisation.
There are plenty of new lines of work to be created, and not only for geeks and I.T. enthusiasts.
So, get thinking of them!
(Applause)
"Take your fate into your own hands."
I have often asked myself what this expression could mean:
take your fate into your own hands.
On the other hand, the expression, "You can't escape your fate," is one that I understood very quickly.
My father did not escape his fate, and he has shaped mine.
I am the daughter of a dead man.
It is July 30, 1971. I am nine months old.
My father is leaving on a military airplane with his cadets from Saint-Cyr for parachute jump training.
On board, 37 people.
They were never able to jump.
The plane crashed.
There were no survivors.
My father was 31.
To explain death to a child, Françoise Dolto said, "We die when we have finished living."
But my father died before he truly finished living.
As a young child, I didn't understand.
And besides, for a child, death is reversible.
It's like when you play cowboys and Indians: you die, and then you get back up.
You die and then you live again.
And so of course, me, I was alive, but devastated, lost.
I felt death, his death, like a prolonged absence and then like a separation, and then later like an abandonment.
Because I didn't know him, I could not be sad.
At least, that's what my family and those around me said.
Because for them, losing someone you don't know was not as serious as losing someone you do know.
I was not truly the daughter of my father because my father died before I knew him.
I was nine months old; at nine months, you don't remember anything.
So I called him by his first name, Michel, never Daddy.
And yet, when I was a child, I had a dream, a constantly recurrent dream.
In this dream, I am in the middle of an almost infinite row of soldiers.
I don't see their faces.
I walk toward them, and I look for him, this father whose face escapes me.
But with every face I look at, I do not find him.
It's not him.
I can't find him because each one of these figures has his face erased, like drawings that were never finished.
And so, in this dream, I scream and shout,
I panic. I can't breathe.
What's worse, I never manage to see him
neither in my oldest memory nor even in my imagination.
For my entire childhood, my adolescence, I cried, I cried a lot.
But when you're the daughter of a military man you're not supposed to show your emotions, you are to remain dignified.
When I was told to stop being sad, what I heard was, "You cannot be sad.
We knew him, so it's normal,
but you didn't."
I was imposed a way of mourning and living in his absence.
A bearable one:
mourning without mourning,
mourning without visiting a grave.
The army and my family as well, asked me to be silent and not ask any questions.
What happened that day?
How does a plane crash happen in peacetime?
What happened?
I didn't know.
They didn't talk to me about it.
And so around 15, I found myself in the Beaubourg libraries searching for clues, newspaper articles,
scraps of history, his story, my story.
I never found or understood a thing.
It was absurd wanting to know the details of the accident.
It was sordid and so not to be spoken of.
It was absurd to want to go and find the truth which was horrible, a human carnage: every one of them burned alive.
It was morbid to be so obsessed with his death; it was not normal to cry each time I saw a uniformed man.
It was the past; I needed to forget it.
This way of mourning was imposed on me, but I wanted to try to do it otherwise.
First, his grave.
I didn't know where it was my father's grave.
I wasn't allowed to go there.
And yet, there must be a grave.
I went looking for it when I was 35 years old.
It was in a small cemetery not far from Pau, where the accident happened.
My father's grave was there, simply engraved, "Captain Michel Rémy, died in military service July 30, 1971."
And so I had another plaque made, which reads, "Michel Rémy, husband, father, and grandfather."
Because he was also a husband, a father, and a grandfather.
So I began to take care of him, to clean his grave, to plant flowers, talk to him, cry,
building up this father-daughter relationship, different from the one that was imposed.
Six months later, while taking care of family affairs, I dug up the "Paris Match" from July, 1971.
The plane crash in Pau was on the front page;
and accident in peacetime was a national tragedy.
When my father died, he wasn't alone, but with 36 others, his cadets from Saint-Cyr, the pilot, the co-pilot, and other officers.
All of them married, with wives and children.
In this "Paris Match," I discovered photos of the plane crash and also photos of the victims.
Tiny ID photos in black and white of each of these men, there in a double-page spread.
Their names were written and then, in smaller text, the number of children they had.
50 children in total.
I don't know what's driving me, or why I decide to do what I set out to do, but I know that I need to do something for us, for the children.
I decide to do the opposite of what everyone told me to do.
I want to witness my father's funeral.
I had this somewhat strange idea: the idea of organizing a memorial for us, for the children, in the same place where the plane accident took place, in Pau, at the air force base.
But first I need to find these children, who had become adults, 35 years later.
And so, I go looking for them.
Finding them was not simple.
Firstly, because the army did not give me permission to go through them.
The Army forced me to go through the mothers, the widows who had lived through this nightmare, and who had preferred to escape it in silence.
Some of them allowed me to contact their children, others refused.
Every encounter caused terrible pain,
every conversation, every phone call. This pain, this suffering was almost insurmountable.
In total, I spend ten years looking for these children.
Finally, on October 12, 2007, almost every one of us is there.
The weather is beautiful, the sky is blue, that deep Mediterranean blue.
The trees are golden. There was a particular silence, like a form of respect.
A Nord Atlas, a similar plane to the one that crashed, was draped with a parachute spread out over one of its wings.
An army priest was there with the officials, infantry men, the general officers.
We all came together for the burial.
We were going to hold a mass in their honor in the presence of their children.
The memorial was starting.
I took the floor, I spoke about the absence of my father, from which I had created a presence.
I talked about him, and how proud I was to be his daughter, and how much I missed him.
I also talked about the other men who died with him that day, and then after the mass there was a salute to the dead,
a military ritual held at this type of memorial.
I had suggested to the army that during this salute, each child might respond when their father's name was called with the phrase, "Died in military service."
So for each name that was called, a child answered, "Died in military service."
The list seemed so long.
When I heard the name of my father, Captain Michel Rémy, I was able to answer, "Died in military service."
And when I said this, in front of all these soldiers, standing in front of me, I remembered my childhood dream, this almost infinite row of soldiers with their faces erased.
Time stopped.
There was such an intense silence, and I saw him.
My father appeared like in my dream.
He broke ranks, turned around, he looked at me, smiled at me, even laughed.
His eyes were blue, so blue, the same color as those of my son, Max.
He had an air of serenity.
And then he left.
That blurred face from my childhood dream was finally drawn before my eyes.
And it was not just a face; he was there.
He came to see me, his daughter.
This story, this childhood dream, has made me, has helped me to become the person I am today.
What I learned is that you don't need to accept what is imposed on you.
Of course, you can't change history, but you can free yourself, even from the most tenacious, tragic things.
We all carry heavy things which we need to free ourselves from in order to go on, in order to live.
We all have the power to carry on and to evolve in our history, as complicated or tragic as it might be, to not get hung up, or stuck on the inside like in a bad dream we can't control and which escapes us. A dream we always wake from too soon.
Above all, what I learned is that if a dream is not finished and if it haunts us, inhabits us insistently, it is perhaps because we have to do something about it.
Move forward, change things, maybe; take action, for sure.
If a dream is not complete, we can complete it, even if we don't know where that could lead us.
Thank you.
(Applause)
Hello, my name is Gala, and today, I want to talk about something very important in my life.
I'm 10 years old. I'm a normal girl like any other.
I'm a fifth-grader in the Spanish School in Paris.
I do ballet, flamenco, and I play the guitar.
One day, in the car with my mother and my brother Gabriel, we saw a huge sign on a tall tower in Paris.
On this sign, there was a picture of a little boy with an angry face and crossed arms, which read, "Having cancer at the age of seven, seriously?"
"Seriously, Mom?
But how is that possible, Mom?" And she replied:
"It is the injustice of life.
We are lucky to be healthy, and we must support the medicine to cure all these children."
And every day I take the bus, I see people on the ground in the rain, in the cold.
And every night, my parents receive letters from associations that show unbearable images.
You see these between-life-and-death emaciated children, three-year-olds, two-year-olds, ten-month-olds?
It's a shame!
And from the depths of my heart, I never want to see that.
It's unfair that some have and others don't.
Historically, I see that there are many injustices.
That's why I created an association which allows us to combat poverty and help hospitalized children.
This association is called "Red Clover."
The clover signifies happiness and luck for everyone.
Yes, everyone!
And "red," because it reminds me of the Red Cross, which always helps and cares.
What I'm asking you is not to save your money for nothing.
If you give, you help;
therefore, you save. I'm not Abbé Pierre or Coluche or Sister Emmanuelle. I'm Gala.
And I, Gala, a 10-year-old, I'd rather save 10 children than no one.
(Applause) Sister Emmanuelle said something very important for me: "Listen, understand to better meet the needs of the poorest.
And then everything is possible."
I, now, for my birthday, I'll ask my friends and family to donate to my association and stop giving me all this stuff that invades my room and that doesn't make me happier.
If everyone did that, then the world would be a much better place.
Generosity knows no age; we can all give.
All these children happy in their lives, I invite them to give a little bit. This is what gives meaning to life, and this is what gives meaning to my life.
And do not tell me it's impossible!
Thank you.
(Applause) Thank you.
Every individual needs energy to live and to make his body work.
You, I, that refugee in Syria, each of us needs energy.
The amount of energy that we need, I can express it as a definite quantity: 25 cl of petrol.
This is the energy equivalent that we consume and need daily.
Our society, our civilisation has developed a set of technologies that enables us to guarantee our comfort but actually consumes much more energy.
So, first, we produce waste: each of us produces 2 kg of waste daily, 30% of which is organic waste, that is, the residue of the food we eat, the food that Nature gives us.
We consume energy: 5 litres of petrol is the daily average in Switzerland.
The problem is that we burn it and, as a result, it releases CO2: 14 kg every day.
Fourteen kilos per day, imagine if it were solid, you'd have to leave home each morning with two packs of six bottles of water and put them on the pavement.
Fourteen kilos per day ... Luckily, it is a gas. So it dissipates into the atmosphere, we don't see it.
Too often we tend to forget that it keeps on accumulating in the atmosphere.
We ourselves don't feel it, but Teddy-x here is already seeing its effect.
We thought it was important to save Teddy-x and come up with a solution to limit our CO2 emissions.
To do so, we need to study the energy system.
So we took Switzerland and looked where energy was consumed. Forty-seven per cent of Switzerland's energy consumption is for keeping ourselves warm and illuminating our buildings.
This energy consumption occurs mainly in winter when it's cold and we need to heat, mainly in the form of heat.
Only 25% of our energy consumption is electricity, the rest is heat.
To this 47%, I'll add transport which uses 36%, and our society's driving force, industry, which needs about 20%.
Each square here represents 100 litres of petrol per inhabitant, and every red square represents one CO2 emission.
When we observe cities, we see that they tend to concentrate the population.
It is said that, in the future, 75% of the population will live in cities.
When it concentrates the population, it takes up space.
In Geneva, each square metre of floor area equals a square metre of heated area.
This means that energy is consumed.
The Swiss average is 260 million litres per year for the population in Geneva's city centre.
It means that one million tons of CO2 is emitted.
Cities also produce waste, 100,000 tons of solid waste plus 40,000 tons of organic waste, and they have opportunities.
In Geneva there's the lake on the one hand, and on the other hand, we have the sun that shines on all our roofs.
If we convert the amount of energy that we receive daily into litres of petrol, we can see that there are 620 million litres of petrol that come to our roof each year.
We can see that there is more energy available than the energy that is consumed today.
So, together with some of my colleagues and industrial partners, we have asked ourselves if we could make cities really energy-autonomous.
'Energy-autonomous' means ideally that we would no longer emit CO2, we would not need to import energy, that we would not have to knock down all the buildings to rebuild them later but would use the city as it is, and we would not bankrupt ourselves, of course.
So, how did we do this?
As engineers, the first thing we do is to look at the needs.
We don't need energy, and the best would be precisely not to need it.
So we look at the minimum we need.
We call on science and thermodynamics.
Carnot, a French scientist specialised in thermodynamics, showed that in order to heat a building up to 21°C when the environment is at 0°C, we need to buy one unit of energy to deliver 10 of it.
This is an important element because it can guide and motivate us.
Where is the motivation?
If I look at the amount of energy I spend using a very good boiler that has 90% efficiency, uses gas and so burns and produces CO2, I realise that for the same amount of heat, that is 10 units, I must buy 11 units.
Here emerges a new question: why do we consume 10 times more than the minimum indicated by thermodynamics, while producing CO2 on top of it?
The answer is to be found in the heat pump.
What is a heat pump?
You all have a fridge at home.
This fridge works on the following principle: you take electricity, you extract heat to cool the inside of the fridge, and in doing that you heat your room.
The heat pump does exactly the same: it takes the outside heat and with the help of electricity it increases the temperature in order to provide you with heat.
Thermodynamics tells us two things.
The first is that the lower the temperature at which you have to heat, the less energy you have to spend. That's why the recommendation is to install low temperature heating systems and not high temperature ones.
Thermodynamics also tells us that the higher the source temperature, in other words the environment, the better.
The problem is finding that source.
Cities are dense ; there are buildings everywhere, so it is very difficult to make only one heat pump. So we thought of splitting the heat pump into two: On one side, we will use a heat pump that will find the good heat sources in the environment.
For example, if I have water in the lake, a river or underground, I can extract this heat and carry it where I need it. Then I can use a second heat pump which gives me exactly the temperature that I need.
You have a heating system at low temperature, so you will pay less than someone who has a high temperature heating system.
In order to carry the heat, the idea is to use the CO2.
What we can do is use two tubes: one tube with CO2 in the liquid state, one tube with CO2 in the vapour state.
We can take the steam, condense it, and in this way we can deliver heat, and we can use a heat pump to reach the temperature we need.
Now, if someone wants to be cooled, I can take the liquid and boil it off.
I can then cool my buildings down directly.
Because they are connected with a pipe, I can also cool the building that needs to be cooled with the building that needs to be heated. This ultimately allows me to save a good amount of energy.
Then, on the way, we can identify all the good heat sources that we have. For example, the waste water that leaves your house at around 20°C can be used to heat the buildings. as well as the water in the lake, or the water that leaves the water treatment plant, or geothermal energy.
So now, I have a system that enables me to exchange energy between the different users.
Another important element is that I use CO2.
CO2 has a high energy density which means we don't need large pipes.
We can insert pipes in the pavement and don't have to bury them because CO2 doesn't freeze.
We don't have to go very deep.
Therefore we can manufacture precast pavement that enable us to transport the energy that you need.
So, here is a complex system that, thanks to a heat pump, allows us to warm up, to be directly cooled, that also enables refrigeration in shopping centres, for example, where fridges or freezers are needed, that also enables us to recycle the heat of our waste when we burn it, and that uses all the opportunities that the environment has to offer.
Now the question is: is it more efficient than the traditional system?
To get the answer, we did a case study:
an area in Geneva where there are offices, appartments, banks, shops - for those who know it, it is the "Rues Basses" area.
We calculated the amount of energy that is needed and used today to provide heating and cooling and we saw that we need 12 energy units, 10 in the form of heat and natural gas and two in the form of electricity.
We also saw that the natural gas is mainly used in winter, while electricity is used in summer for cooling.
The same system with the CO2 network only needs two units. We made a factor of six in our energy consumption.
We only need 16% of the energy that we consume today without changing the buildings.
Obviously, if we insulate the buildings we will save even more.
Of course, everybody said, 'Yes, but it's going to be too expensive'.
And the answer is: 'Yes, it's very expensive at present.
But in fact, the system we propose will cost less and will be profitable, while today's system is not profitable'.
Now. I've almost achieved my goal,
but I still need to provide electricity to the system so I am not quite self-sufficient yet.
I have to provide electricity in winter,
so now the question is: how do we make electricity in winter?
We can import electricity from outside but then, we will emit a lot of CO2 and so lose many benefits.
I can also use new technologies such as the gas combined cycle which has a better efficiency and emits far less CO2 because it uses natural gas.
But I can also say, 'Why not use renewable energies to make my heat pumps work?'
The problem is that renewable energies are mainly available in summer. The sun shines a lot in the summer, far less in the winter.
We can also use a different kind of technology.
The EPFL has patented a new concept that combines a fuel cell and a gas turbine, that has 80% electrical efficiency, much higher than the best gas power plant, and that separates CO2 for free.
So now, I have some CO2 in a tube, and that's perfect since I already have a tube.
I have residual heat because I'm at 80%. I still have 20% left which is great since I have the means to carry it towards my users.
So now, my system enables me to produce electricity, to catch CO2 and to meet my heat needs.
But I’m still using fossil fuel because I’m using natural gas.
So here, we must go back to look into History and see what gifts Mother Nature has given us.
In fact, Nature has given us two things.
On the one hand, we have a treasure.
The treasure is something that never gets refilled.
It is there and we can only use it, and this is what we do: we take a part of the treasure and burn it to produce CO2.
And Teddy-x is not very happy actually.
What you can observe is that the reservoir has run out and nobody is refilling it.
That means our children will have less than what we've received from our parents.
We can also look at Nature’s current and savings accounts which are renewable energies
that come in different forms.
We have the sun, the wind, the water and the biomass.
The biomass is much like the savings account because it is stored.
I can therefore take the biomass and convert it into gas.
Organic and chemical processes exist that enable us to convert the biomass into gas.
When the process is not efficient, it generates heat and I have a tube to use that heat so it's great when I need heat.
As for the gas, I can use it in fuel cells.
I’m also trying to learn from Nature. If I think carefully, I need energy, where do I find it?
I find it in food which is stored energy.
I don’t feel variations like I do with the sun that changes from hour to hour and from season to season.
How did Nature do that?
By photosynthesis.
It took CO2 from the atmosphere, used the photons coming from the sun, used water, and created carbohydrates that make up my food and the trees as well.
We can do the same with a technical system. I can take the sun, transform it into electricity with photovoltaic cells,
then I can take these, CO2 and water, and create methane.
And what I'm going to do is to take the CO2 I stored and create methane in the liquid state to store as well.
It's going to become quite a complex system because, in the summer, I'll take liquid CO2 to make liquid methane by means of the shining sun, and in the winter, I'll take the liquid methane and feed it into the fuel cell to produce the electricity that I need for heating and lighting, then, I'll capture the CO2, bring it back into my tube and convert it into liquid CO2.
By doing so, I’ll have a system that seems very complicated, but don’t forget that you have many tubes coming into your houses every day.
You have the electrical cable, the Internet cable, and also the drinking water and the waste water leaving your home. So adding a new tube is not necessarily as difficult as it seems.
It's a system that enables us to warm up, to cool down, to refrigerate, to add value to all of our waste, and to store the solar energy produced during the summer on our roofs to make it available during the winter.
If I can do that, I'll have a system entirely autonomous in energy.
The system I had before burnt a large quantity of energy to meet my needs, emitted a lot of CO2, and emptied my treasure.
Today, with an investment - the installation of new infrastructure with heat pumps, fuel cells and storage - I will be able to fulfil the same needs. I don't need to change the buildings or to change your comfort, you will still have the same temperature in all your rooms. You will simply have solar panels on your roof, You will have fuel cells that generate electricity from the methane produced during the summer.
You will recycle the heat from the hot water poured in the sewer because you will be able to use it in your heat pumps. You will recycle energy from your waste, and in the end, in fact, you're going to export electricity, an electricity available on request. That means that you'll be able to decide when to export it when you have too much, and it'll be stored as methane.
As a point of interest, the storage space required for this is 10 times smaller than the amount of tanks we would need in all the buildings if we heated everything with fuel oil.
And that's my conclusion.
Anyway, Teddy-x can thank us, because if you are able to transform cities into independent electricity producers without CO2 emissions, he may have the opportunity to find a more secure block of ice.
Thank you very much.
(Applause)
Let me take you on a journey, a quick but faraway journey, a journey into the future.
Let's go to Mars, the red planet.
We're in 2050, we traveled 500 million kilometers.
We are comfortably installed in a Martian village.
500 million km, is about 4 times the distance between Earth and the Sun.
When an Earthling sends us a message, we have to wait 10 minutes for it to reach us.
It's not easy to communicate.
The 3.8G gravity makes us weigh about 40% of our weight on Earth.
This is peculiar, but rather fun!
But there are less pleasant things.
The atmosphere is unattractive: a 6 millibar pressure, that is an atmosphere about 150 times less dense than on Earth.
But above all, it is composed of 96% CO2, carbon dioxide, so it is not breathable at all.
So you'd better be warmly-dressed and have your oxygen generator with you.
Gardening is anything but simple. The sun, much farther, only bring us 35 to 50% of the energy received on Earth.
The temperature therefore varies from -3 ° to -130 °.
-130 °... even Canadians find it cold!
(Laughter) The winds and dust storms are permanent.
Solar radiation, cosmic rays are stopped neither by the atmosphere nor by the absent magnetic field.
Here's a tip: do not get out of this room.
However, today, Mars has become a suburb of the Earth.
And if we can now spend some time, safely and comfortably on this planet, it is thanks to pioneering missions that allowed our knowledge of this planet to advance by leaps and bounds.
Remember, it was on March 14, 2016.
A space mission, called ExoMars, was beginning with the launch of a Proton rocket from Baikonur, Kazakhstan.
The objective: to conquer this new horizon and land on it the first European probe named Schiaparelli.
That day, the tension was at its peak for the engineers and scientists working on the project.
They had the ambition to innovate, to be those who would advance our knowledge.
Their dream, for 10, 15 years, to land their baby that far away, after so many efforts, was becoming reality.
Years of work, months of verifications weeks of preparation in Kazakhstan, then the take-off, the long wait to be placed on the right path, Video: the rocket now launched, relief is visible.
JJJ: Receiving signals from that space newborn, indicating its good health.
Moments of intense emotion.
At the time, we were looking for traces of life on Mars.
With its scientific instruments our sniffer satellite was going to analyze the Martian atmosphere.
The crucial question of the presence of methane on Mars was about to be answered.
Methane is an indicator of potential biological life.
A neutron detector would indicate whether - and where - water was to be found in the Martian ground.
Stereo images would provide details of the Martian landscape.
But above all, this mission was to prepare for the arrival of a vehicle, a Rover, which left Earth in 2018.
A very long time ago, Mars and Earth were similar, with huge liquid oceans on their surface.
The environment and chemical processes were similar, like on twin planets.
Then Mars suffered a terrible climate change 3.5 billion years ago.
From that moment, Mars became arid, barren, cold, hostile.
On its surface anyway.
The solar radiation and the thin atmosphere forbade all life on the surface.
The cosmic radiation chopped any potential organic molecules.
But what happened deep down, protected from these attacks?
A new mission was to penetrate this secret.
But landing on Mars was so perilous then.
The heat shield entered the atmosphere at 21,000 km/h and 120 km altitude and it reaches 1,500 degrees.
The parachutes open at 1700 km/h and slow the probe down to 250 km/h, at approximately 1 km altitude.
Then the retro-rockets finish the descent that has not lasted more than 6 minutes.
Then our vehicle unfolds.
Then it will begin its journey on the surface of Mars.
This vehicle is equipped with a drill capable of reaching 2m deep.
Thanks to its onboard lab, it will analyze the extracted rocks and sediments.
Finally, for the first time we were going to get an answer to this fundamental question: Is life present, or has it been present elsewhere than Earth?
So how can we look at Earth in 2050?
The exploration of Mars has been a huge challenge for scientists and engineers.
The analysis of the atmosphere of Mars has allowed us to progress in our understanding of Earth's phenomena and climate.
Conquering Mars has allowed us to progress in our technical management and treatment of water of waste reprocessing.
But above all, the spirit of conquest and exploration shared by all those involved, allowed to contribute to a more fraternal, solidary world, and therefore more peaceful.
By the way, be careful, do not get lost, because you've already seen that if you stay "alone on Mars," the situation will be tricky to manage.
(Laughter) So after this short Martian stay, I suggest you return to Earth, France, Cannes, late April 2016.
(Applause)
Like many, many of you, I am Wonder Woman, Mrs. Perfect.
Yes, that's me here. (Laughter)
Mrs Perfect is actually the Goddess Shiva, one who carries a baby bottle in one hand, a carton of milk in the other, a computer, a mobile phone, the written speech of her boss, the tickets for the show - "Don’t forget, sweetie!" - and also slightly soggy cookies that her kids have kindly left in her coat pocket.
And, of course, Mrs Perfect has one foot in a plane, and the other in her Louboutin stiletto heels.
She lives at 500 km/h. She is successful in everything she does. And ... her pantyhose does not get torn!
(Laughter) Yes!
In 2010 - I really wished to tell you this story - I was working for an international company, and I had a boss, in Madrid, who was known for his Homeric fits of anger.
When I say "Homeric," I mean there was blood on the walls!
Each of us had a monthly update meeting with him,
and, like the others, I would go. I'd say first ''Hello'' and then next, ''I had to say such and such.''
He'd reply ''No.''
''Well, I must insist, you need to understand such and such."
He'd say ''No.''
''For the last time, let me tell you such and such.''
And he'd say "yes" or "no" but in any case, there was no drama, we remained both calm.
Then, when this man went back to his country, he told me goodbye and said, ''I must ask you something.
Why are you not afraid?''
This concerned me because honestly, I had no answer, so I said something silly like, ''Well, we're not in Narcos movie. You're not going to shoot me the next minute!''
(Laughter)
Then, somehow the question stuck with me and, the other day, while I was thinking about you and Wonder woman, I thought "Why is Wonder woman Wonder woman ?"
Well, it's because she does not listen to her fear.

Okay, but you know what?
She doesn't listen to herself either.
What about you? Are you listening right now?
So, we all came into this life
one day, that's the way it is.
I was born in the sixties - please do not calculate my age.
I am a woman, until proven otherwise, and I was born in Paris to a family that was not ideal.
By the way, if you know the ideal family, please inform me.
Anyway, I was in a family,
but it was so far from being ideal that at birth, I got an extra card. This card was a 50% chance of ending up in a bin,
and that actually happened to my twin brother.
And I must say, when you draw such a card at the beginning of your life, it gives you a certain perspective on things and an acute sense of survival.
So the beliefs on which I structured and built myself, were: ''I don't feel pain," "Nothing can hurt me," "I am all-powerful."
Now, you see, beliefs are a little bit like crutches during our early life.
They enable us to find our balance, and then one day, we no longer need them.
I do not have crutches anymore.
Well, I still have this one, but let's speak about this later.
In short, it is with these beliefs that I framed my role as Wonder woman. And you know what? It was the perfect time
because my professional life started in the eighties, the glamour years, the money years. So back then, being a Wonder woman was really trendy.
Therefore, I jumped immediately at full speed in my professional life.
At the beginning of my career, I got the most prestigious jobs, the most charismatic managers, the most staggering budgets, the greatest products and brands, etc. Yeah, all that.
Indeed, I did understand the movie quite a bit. I knew there were two keys to what I called "happiness".
The first was financial independence. Believe me, it worked for me,
and this enabled me to leave my family.
The second was conformity to social and professional model because to succeed, you must please, and to please, what do you need?
Well, you must give up your dreams
because teenage dreams, the most audacious and adventurous dreams - such as, among others, my dream of being a writer -
honestly, they are not going to keep a woman fed.
So, they are brushed under the carpet.
Then there is something else we all share. You know, this little voice inside you? The one inside there that tells you, ''Are you happy with what you do?
Do you really love yourself?
Are you really satisfied?
What happened to your dream of becoming a writer?''
Ah! This one, frankly, got on my nerves. I replied, ''You shut up. I don't want to listen to you, silence!''
And as a matter of fact, I didn't hear it for a number of years.
So, here I was in the eighties ... Oops! I've forgotten something! I've just forgotten one tiny detail. In my teens, in this family that ... - well, it would take forever! -
I had a scoliosis that had not been treated. Seriously, confidently, scoliosis is nothing.
If I were to ask you to raise your hand, 25% of you in this room would say they have a little scoliosis, It's a curvature of the spine.
The other 25% would have a cold.
Actually, scoliosis is to the vertebrae what the common cold is to the nose, meaning nothing at all.
So I had no time for that, meaning no time for me, no time to listen to myself, no time for Mrs. Perfect, Mrs. Demanding of herself and much of others, but still funny after all. I tell you, I did party like crazy. (Laughter)
But what about the body?
(Sigh) Well, it had merely to follow.
Then came midlife, the love of my life, maternity, three magnificent girls. And, I kept on working.
Yeah, they are gorgeous, thank you! (Applause)
Really, that's the most perfect achievement!
Then I went on with the job, the travels, the buddies and friends,
and everything was like this, forever.
And as a matter of fact, it was perfect. I was in my bubble, my comfort zone, my cocoon.
Nothing could happen to me.
Everything was for granted.
Nothing could hurt me.
Except that fate - you know, "fatum" in latin - was thinking there, in a corner, ''It's time for this girl to understand she has to do something of her life.''
So it knocked a first time, I didn't hear anything.
It knocked a second time, and I didn't hear, so it got upset.
It got angry because what we resist, persists.
Therefore it punched, punched, punched until I eventually was knocked out.
In reality, it knocked me out.
My body reminded me of its presence in 2013.
My body, I had negated it, denied it, and disavowed it.
At that point, it reminded me it was there and not in a gentle manner.
My teenage scoliosis had transformed into a double curve up to 73 degrees.
It is huge!
To give you an idea, it's similar to those old ladies you see walking, bended almost horizontally, their nose on the pavement, forever.
I was so good at denying that none of my family or my girlfriends, nobody noticed my condition.
In fact, I just collapsed physically,
and let's be frank, I was the only one responsible for it.
So I knew I needed to do
something. I had no choice.
I tried very creatively all the bad solutions, until only one was left.
The solution I had to accept, I warn you, is not going to be appealing to you.
It is called an "arthrodesis".
Here is it. It's pretty, it's my back.
It is an arthrodesis of the spine,
a ten-hour operation in which they open your spine from cervicals to lumbars,
insert two titanium rods, and straighten
whatever vertebrae they can.
Now don't ask me how!
I don't know and don't want to know.
Next, they screw everything back together
And hup! I found myself as straight as the letter "I".
(Applause)... But!
Well, that was a wrong move, folks, because yes, my friends were saying I'll look like Madonna
while I was saying "like Frida Kahlo," but the surgeon was telling me, ''Your torso will be slightly rigid,
you won't dance the Zumba very much, but you will have good legs"
and "Don't worry! I do surgeries like yours every week.
You'll be back to normal life in two months."
Well, I had already doubts about my normal life. I had no choice,
so on October 14th, 2014, I entered the hospital with my two legs.
They woke me up in the intensive care unit on October 15th, 2014.
I don’t know why there are dates
we don't forget! And they were all there at the foot of my bed, in white and blue, a solemn expression on their faces. Was it a jury or verdict? I wasn't sure.
But the whole medical team
was there, and they told me, "Miss, your bone marrow has been damaged.
You will never walk again.
You are paraplegic.''
I was stunned.
By "stunned" I don't mean surprised, but dumbfounded.
Because my life had been crushed.
From being the actor of my life, I was now its spectator. From being independent, I found myself in dependency. From being hyperactive, Wonder woman, I became incapable of even reading or writing.
My body and I were treated as objects that were given injections, washed, that were probed, auscultated, and pinched.
From my hospital bed, I had only access to what my hands could reach.
It was not much.
Then for nine months, I was no longer anybody. I was nothing: no longer a mum, no longer a woman, no longer a lover, no longer a manager, no longer anything!
So one day, my body had become my master.
For example, it was my body that decided what I could do and when I could do it.
One day, I came home to my family and I discovered - or rather "they" discovered - that Wonder woman had become a burden.
As for me, I discovered that my loved and loving ones had become my helpers.
It wasn't that great a discovery.
And there was also a new life for me.
I found out all that was now impossible for me to do such as walking alone on the street, getting out unexpectedly, or going to the shop ... in short, living like them, living like you.
My family was shattered.
I'm saying this because a family is a system, and all of us, both I and they had to morn a loss - I, the loss of my former self, and they, the loss of the mother and the woman they knew.
And mourning is extremely important in adversity.
Morning is synonymous of anger, of sadness, of denial, of negotiation.
And we know that these are phases we go through time and again, until we finally accept.
Acceptance is neither abandonment nor flight. It means that you need to accept, accept, accept for the transformation to occur.
But you don't need to become paraplegic to transform.
Come on, take a nice breath!
In fact, whatever ordeal you are confronted with, whether it be a divorce, unemployment, a frustration, a death, or an illness, you must respect it.
It is important that you respect it as well as yourself. What is essential in adversity is that the only benchmark is the individual, how he or she deals with it and feels,
but above all, what he or she
makes of it - meaning you and also me.
Now let me still speak to you about my ordeal with kindness
because it ended up being an initiation actually.
It was my third birth, a regeneration,
and for two reasons.
The first is my damned character.
That is, I never believed I will not walk again, never.
Therefore, the very first or second day after the surgery, I partnered with my body and, at its pace, we began the verticalization protocol
until I reached the point I could stand straight after spending many weeks working with a verbalization table,
without vomiting or fainting, which was cool!
Following that, I was hooked to parallel bars. And then, I learned how to get by obstacles. Next, I wobbled around using a walking aid, and later walking canes.
So it was my regeneration for this reason, and because I reached a point where I thought, ''Nope. That's not possible!
I can’t let my life be stolen again."
And this time, I could hear my voice.
I listened to my little voice saying, '' You had your life stolen at birth and during your teenage years. Later on, you stole it from yourself. Enough is enough!"
As I was hearing and listening and respecting this voice, at that moment, my limiting beliefs ceased to be limiting.
This is because, you see, beliefs are really simple.
Your beliefs or your identity, call it
whatever you want, is like a medallion,
and this medallion has two sides: the yin and yang, etc.
On the flip side, you give your beliefs power over your life,
Don't blame yourself, we can't do otherwise during childhood.
And they delight.
They become limiting,
blocking and enslaving. They just become odious!
It was my feeling of being all-powerful, my stubbornness, my fear of life, and my fear of dying too.
Then came the day, the day I gave myself love, respect, tenderness, time, attention, light ...
That day, turning the other side of the medallion, those same beliefs exploded in all their splendor!
They became strength, desire for life, creativity, wholeness, femininity.
They became all of this!
And all became possible.
They opened the entire field of possibilities, my possibilities, by way of embodiment, by aligning heart, body and spirit vertically, physically, emotionally and intellectually.
Nothing happens to us by accident.
My heart had to surrender for me to find myself. My body had to surrender.
And since dreaming was not forbidden, actually ... ... I allowed myself to live the dream I had when I was 18.
Today, I am a writer, as I wanted to be.
(Applause) I wrote my first book called,
"Le roseau penchant, histoire d'une merveilleuse opération"
meaning "The bent reed", you know, the one that bends down? Yet it never breaks! So you have it, but wait!
Get ready for this: it came out exactly three years, day for day, after my surgery.
Now you may not believe in destiny, but l really do.
And I won't need an arthrodesis to write my second book.
Whoever you are, whatever the ordeal, we all have the ability to transmute it.
Today, I have within me my first, tough and rich 59 years of existence: my romances, my friends, my hardships, my joys, my mistakes, my wake-up call while I was kept prisoner at the hospital.
I am not the victim of anything or anyone.
I have a disability that is today nearly invisible but still major. But I am not my disability, absolutely not.
Life is slower, different, less warlike but more battle-hardened.
I convey and I share, as I am doing it tonight.
You decide.
Your beliefs' solar phase, would you not like to go and see it?
That's it.
(Applause)
During primary school, a child a little older than me who held me responsible for all the world's problems often tried to hit me, to humiliate me; and strangle me.
At times like these, I became frozen, completely paralyzed.
I wanted to call desperately for help but no words would leave my mouth.
Yet, only about 20 metres away, my teachers and my peers were playing peacefully.
Constant punches and insults shaped my school experience until the end of high school.
Then after consulting with my family, my friends and my fellows, I realized that bullying affects a lot people
and that even if we all face it, we do nothing about it.
By "all" I mean the one being bullied, the bully of course, but also the bystander who doesn't do anything.
I'd like to show you how easy it is to move from one category to another and how they're not all that different.
The first category, the first perspective is that of the bullied, the victim.
Although I am openly discussing it on stage, some of you might have suffered the effects of bullying just like me.
As bullied, we often tend to allow it to happen.
Surprisingly, it's even the first piece of advice we receive: "Just ignore them, they will move on."
However for me, this is a huge mistake.
Whether we show it or not, each insult can potentially hurt us.
None of us are immune to it no matter how much we pretend.
I was often told to let go.
At large, this was all the teachers would say, believing that the bullying would stop.
So I let the bullies insult, mock and isolate me because it was inevitable that they would stop one day.
But obviously they continued.
And within me, although I really didn't want to show it, each of their act of scorn hurted me more than the previous one.
Ignoring them meant silencing my sadness.
Without help and support, we retreat into our shells we isolate ourselves from everything, from the perpetrators of harassment but above all from everyone around us.
Allowing the bullying to continue is the worst mistake possible because we internalize the insults that we receive - regardless of our age.- especially if they are repeated every day.
By allowing this bullying to become a routine, we trivialize our own suffering and eventually destroy ourselves slowly.
Our brain is such that by listening and absorbing all of this, a very nasty question inevitably comes up and starts torturing us: "What if they are right?"
When this question came to my mind, the bullying became a real mental torture.
I stopped believing in myself.
I no longer felt the joy of going to school.
What was the point if I had to suffer insults and let it happen?
By allowing bullying to become a routine, we are trivializing our own suffering;
and we are therefore destroying ourselves.
When I allowed the bullying to continue, I began my downward spiral to hell.
This hands off policy was more destructive in my life than helpful.
First and foremost, I hated my bullies.
Then I began hating school, its place and its system that encouraged me to not act.
And finally, I started hating myself.
We should never allow bullies to do what they do.
Let's talk about it with our families, the people around us and those who can help us;
but let's never resign ourself to pretending to ignore it.
After having spoken about the bullied, let's now talk about the bully.
Although these words are antonyms, they can both be used to describe the same person.
I'm not going to talk about sheer sadism because, in most cases, it is not the real motive behind the bullying.
I see two main reasons that can easily make us start bullying someone.
Firstly, it may be a defence mechanism that we can use if we ourselves are bullied,
so that we can hurt someone else in order to make ourselves feel better about our own bullying, or to boost our self-confidence.
From this moment onwards, bullying becomes a form of therapy where destroying others seems to rehabilitate us.
When I was being bullied, I was also a bully.
And I do not know anyone who suffered more from the effects of my own bullying than my own brother.
I was immensely jealous of him; I envied his popularity but above all, of the fact that he wasn't being bullied.
So I was resentful towards him.
And the victim became the executioner.
This is how we let ourselves replicate those very acts that have hurt us so much.
You can see that the gap between the bullied and the bully is not that big.
A bullied justifies his mocking by telling himself that his experience was worse.
Whether we are aware of the bullying that we reenact or not, we are still bullies.
And with each snide comment that we make to someone, we can hurt that person irrespective of what we have suffered in the past.
Personally, I was telling myself that I wasn't hurting my brother because I had experienced much worse.
By allowing this to continue, we can become an unconscious executioner whilst also being a conscious victim.
The second reason why we can easily become a bully is the collective bullying.
In a group, we bully in order to feel that we are part of it.
This way, we also rid ourselves of all responsibility since the blame falls upon the collective.
It does not matter whether we are in a group or not, or whether we were bullied or not, or whether we realize it or not,
this colleague to whom I make endless remarks, maybe he took offense?
What if he is suffering without showing it?
What if I am myself someone I have never believed I would be: a bully?
The "laissez-faire" attitude is not just the privilege of the bullied and the bully but it's sadly all too often linked to the inaction of the bystanders.
Generally, bullying doesn't take place in tiny isolated alleyways during the night.
It happens publicly in broad daylight,
maybe at school, in the workplace, or in public transport.
Bullying often takes place while there are lots of people present.
In my case, a playground full of my peers bore witness to my experiences.
Does it mean they are responsible?
They didn't hit me or humiliate me, yet it was their duty to act;
just as it is ours in similar situations.
By being a spectator, we have the possibility of putting an end to any action that can destroy a person.
Yet, most of the time, we don’t act.
Why?
Well, because of fear.
Fear is one of the main reasons why we do not act.
It is the fear of the bully or bullies that prevents us from stopping what is happening in front of us.
Yet; we should stop what is happening because bullying has unimaginable consequences in our psyche.
Personality, I am aware of where this leads to.
Nevertheless, even I fall
into the "laissez-faire" attitude, not out of sadism but out of fear of being again stigmatized as "different," as being the one who is going to help another while the crowd stays silent and pretends not to see.
So it's not a case of fearing the bully but fearing the others around us.
And if I don't put a stop to what is happening someone else will do it, isn't it?
Well, maybe.
Or maybe no one will intervene.
In such case, we passersby, share part of the responsibility in the bullied's descent into hell.
If we were to put ourselves in the shoes of the bullied, what would happen?
Let's imagine how we'd see things from the point of view of the victim.
I’m sure that you have all, at least once, felt what it's like to be bullied.
So don’t let someone else experience it.
That person could be you. It could be your children your brothers, your sisters, or your friends.
That person is a human being, yet still, you're allowing him or her tobe slowly destroyed in front of your eyes.
So, what if we stopped letting people bullying others?
Thank you.
(Applause)
Good evening ladies and gentlemen.

Many thanks for attending today,
and a special thank you for giving me the opportunity to share a tool with you that has truly changed my life.
I learned this tool from reading a book called "Heal your wounds and find your true self" by Lise Bourbeau.
But before that, first things first, let me introduce myself.
So, I'm Carolina.
I'm what you might call a "YouTuber".
For three and a half years now, I've been making YouTube videos in which I share my concerns, my soul-searching, and lots of things about the human experience because this what I do all the time: wondering and trying to understand the how, why and what of absolutely everything that happens to me.
I read a book, "Heal your wounds and find your true self" that helped me change my relationship with myself and thus my relationships with others as well.
Before we begin, I'd like to make a disclaimer as I usually do in my videos.
It's that I'm going to present a model that I consider simple, understandable, and very attainable that really speaks to me. However, this model is presented among a bunch of the author's other beliefs that are a matter of faith.
For example, she talks about reincarnation about the apparition of wounds on the body, etc., things in which I personally do not believe.
So you need to take some distance while you read it.
If it speaks to you then good for you, otherwise take away what you can, it's still very interesting.
So, what does Lise Bourbeau talk about?
As the book's title indicates, she talks about the soul's wounds.
In our society as we know it, it is true that the emotional body is often put on the back burner in terms of the attention and care that we give it.
But of course, if we get hurt - although some of you may put off going to the doctor or hospital - usually when we get hurt, we seek treatment such as when we break a limb or feel pain somewhere.
But when it comes to the emotional body and what's going on in our minds and in our souls, it is much more complicated to see that indeed, we may have wounds, and indeed, we may even suffer from them.
So Lise Bourbeau explains that we can classify the wounds made to the emotional body into five large categories of negative emotions.
Later on, I'll present them in detail but just to list them, these are betrayal, abandonment, rejection, humiliation, and injustice.
We all pretty much know what these emotions feel like.
We've all experienced them before.
But Lise Bourbeau says that these emotions leave a mark on us from a very young age and play a part in forming our ego.
Now there are plenty of different definitions of "ego".
It depends on your affinity with different fields because you can study the ego in a lot of different domains.
Lise Bourbeau explains that, in fact, these wounds create in us
the need to protect ourselves.
How? By using what she calls "a mask".
I'll show you that later.
If we were to make a comparison between this mask and a physical trait, we could compare it to a glove that we put on a wounded hand, the wound being this emotion that affected us as young children.
So I'm going to show you a little table.
There's a lot of information, but I'm going to explain everything.
So she tells us that these wounds that I was telling you about are sometimes things that we experienced unconsciously, things that perhaps we don't remember anymore because it seems to me that human memory really begins around age five - correct me if I'm wrong.
So obviously, within five years of living, we've had the opportunity to experience many different emotions.
These emotions that are listed here in the first column, create in us behaviors aimed at protecting the ego, listed in the second column, that we call "the mask".
So this mask, according to our previous metaphor, is a glove with which we cover our wound.
We all know that when we get hurt, to stop the pain we need treatment.
So in this case, when we use the mask, that is when we put a glove over this wound, we don't take into account the pain that the wound can inflict upon us.
And sadly, if someone reaches out to try to help us and touches it, we are likely to have a rejection response
and react in a way where we misunderstand the other person.
We're going to say, "Why are you
hurting me? Don't touch me."
But others can't know that we're hurt if we wear a glove.
They only see that we're hurt.
And so Lise Bourbeau's model helps us understand how these masks create a barrier between us and others but also between us and ourselves because oftentimes, we're not aware of them.
We don't know why we use them.
We don't know what they are or what they are trying to protect.
Now rest assured, we don't always wear these masks.
We only wear them in situations in which the ego is afraid of getting hurt again and suffering from these large wounds that we carry within ourselves.
So, for the first ...
For the first wound, the associated mask is the mask of "the controller".
Personally, I relate to this one. Why? Because acting in a controlling manner in any situation, wanting to keep control of it, is a way of ensuring that nothing and no one can betray us.
Obviously, if I call over and over to be sure that we'll be on time, that we'll be at the given place, that I'm not going to be let down, etc., I'm making sure that I won't be betrayed, so I'm wearing the mask of the controller.
For the second wound, abandonment, we will use the mask of "the dependent".
Why?
Because if I act as if I depend on the other, this way I reassure myself that he or she will not abandon me.
It's a way of ensuring I won't be alone and this person won't let me down in the same circumstances where I felt abandoned in the past.
And so the dependent mask serves to hide the wound of abandonment.
For the third wound, rejection, we'll use the mask of "the fugitive".
Why?
Because when we flee a situation, it's a way of anticipating getting rejected.
If I'm facing someone and start imagining that this person is going to reject me, by fleeing, I deprive him or her of the opportunity to reject me.
By doing so, I avoid the situation in which I might feel rejected.
For the fourth wound, humiliation, the mask is that of "the masochist".
The masochist is the person who always puts himself down, belittles himself, or may excessively self-deprecate.
And consequently, like the fugitive, the masochist prevents others from doing it.
If I spend my time putting myself down, making bad jokes about myself, and showing that I am stupid, ugly, and so on, it doesn't leave room for others to humiliate me since I'm already doing it.
So this allows me to protect myself from the wound of humiliation.
And to conclude, the fifth wound, injustice, is associated with the mask of "the rigid".
When we act in an unyielding way, consistently within a framework or a protocol so to speak, and when we don't want to leave our little boxes or our beaten tracks, it's a way of making sure that there won't be any injustice and that we won't experience unfairness.
It's similar to the controller but in a more precise context and within very precise limits.
So Lise Bourbeau says that, unfortunately, one of these five wounds is likely to dominate over the others.
Maybe you can see yourself in one of those five, or maybe in several, in any case, some are usually more present than others.
Often, we created these wounds during our first encounters with humans when we arrived on little Planet Earth.
It could be the presence of our parents and our relationship with them just as it could be their absence.
You can imagine that if I was a child born an orphan, the main wound would perhaps be that of abandonment or rejection.
But the fact remains that even if we had parents, and even if we had the opportunity to live with them, our first interaction with them can potentially cause these wounds in our emotional body.
And so we grow up through our life with behaviors sometimes protective and sometimes not, but behaviors that seem completely innate, natural to us, that are part of our identity our personality, while in fact, for many of them, it"s just a way to believe that we are protecting ourselves and doing all we can to not suffer.
So, this prevents us from getting to the third column, which I named "Solution".
In the solutions - again, I'm going to go through them one by one - we can see how we need to let go if we use the mask of controller to hide the wound of betrayal.
It's very difficult, and I'm proof when it comes to betrayal.
It's true that many times in my life, I had a hard time letting go in certain situations because I always wanted to control everything.
Ultimately, instead of truly protecting myself from suffering, it kept me from being happy when I should have let go in certain situations when I needed to.
For the second, how can we become autonomous in circumstances in which we should, if we always use the mask of dependency to ensure we won't be abandoned ?
That's quite difficult!
For the third, having to confront situations is something extremely painful and hard to do if we always use the mask of the fugive to avoid the wound of rejection.
It's the same for self-esteem regarding the wound of humiliation: How can we develop self-esteem when we spend our time putting ourselves down and end up believing what we say about ourselves?
We often say that it's humorous and for fun, and we know it makes people laugh, but in reality, there's a big chance that when we put ourselves down, there's some truth behind it, or we end up believing it.
So that's what we use to hide, the wound of humiliation.
And the last is flexibility. How to succeed in having a certain degree of flexibility in any situation, if we spend our time having a strict behavior so as to avoid injustice?
It's quite complicated.
Personally, reading this book helped me a lot, to the extent that I guess, studies have been made in psychology and neuroscience that have tried to explain this in a much more Cartesian and scientific manner.
It helped me a lot because it allowed me to stop identifying with my suffering, and stop believing that I was inherently somebody like this, that is, controlling - indeed, I do have concerns for others, don't worry.
So she enabled me to realize that there are times where we can spot ourselves using our masks.
There's certainly a moment in your lives or maybe several, when you've asked yourself more or less regularly, "Why on Earth did I react like that?
That didn't make sense."
Sometimes, a misunderstanding occurred with people who didn't mean harm, but we had no doubt that they wanted to abandon us, reject us, humiliate us, or we deemed the situation unjust or they had betrayed us.
Yet, on their side, that was not necessarily the case.
Therefore, instead of protecting us, these masks do nothing more than limit us.
Now this does protect us at times.
The ego protects us in some cases and it's necessary.
But very often, it's just an obstacle in our personal fulfillment and in our self-understanding.
Once we realize when we wear the mask, we can ask ourselves where it comes from, where it originates, when did we start wearing it, with whom do we wear it, in which moments of our lives, and when was it most difficult to take it off.
This enables us to get past our toxic behaviors towards ourselves
and even sometimes the wall we put between ourselves and others, so that we can try to discover another part of us, another facet of our personality, that matches more closely with the person we'd like to be.
So if you're interested, I invite you to read Lise Bourbeau's work,
but also see if you can find this kind of model in other fields - I'm sure there is.
But most importantly, I invite you to take off your mask.
Thank you.
Who in this room knows journalists?
Does any of you have journalist friends, a journalist in his family, acquaintances?
Please, raise you hands.
Ah, not bad!
There're a few out there.
If you know them, you might have noticed a surprising phenomenon: when January comes, French journalists are all feeling blue, a bit depressed ; they don't feel good.
It's neither due to the weather nor the winter in Clermont-Ferrand which can be truly harsh by the way.
It has to do with a poll published by the newspaper La Croix since 1987. This poll measures public confidence in the media and journalists.
In January, we are reminded that about 50% of people reached by journalists, reached by us, 50% of people have no confidence in what is said to them.
Radio broadcasting is a bit better: it rises to 60%.
However, if you work on the web, it is worse still with a drop to 30%.
Basically, these results aren't very good.
The question I ask myself every January, and maybe we should all ask ourselves is: "How did we get there?"
"What have we done to bring about so much distrust, such that journalists are rejected, as are politicians, authorities and the elite in general?"
If you ask your journalist friend this question, he would likely reply that if people don't trust them, it's because they are bad.
If they are bad, it is because of external constraints.
These constraints can be the pressure from shareholders or from advertisers - some advertisers say, "We want such and such information to put our advertisement, our screen or our advertisement page not such and such one." There's also the race for audience - journalists hate it and say they're forced to try to generate more clicks on the internet -
and media centralization, which are more and more concentrated in big industrial groups with ill-defined editorial strategies and editorial teams that might be a little at lost in this universe of digital transformation.
These are the constraints; but in real
life, there're not only constraints,
there's also what you do with these constraints.
This is what Sartre told us when he said, "The important thing is not what people make of us but what we shall do with what they make of us."
That's worthy of a tweet!
(Laughter) What do we do with these constraints?
How do we evolve internally ? And how do we work as journalists within the constraints that I've listed?
A sensitive question arises here: Generally speaking, do journalists perform their job well individually?
Do they exercise rigour,
possess high intellectual requirement?
Do they have this satisfaction of a job well done?
These are questions professionals don't like to ask themselves regardless of the profession.
While preparing this talk, I discovered that it was a question I had already explored after several experiences which I'm going to share with you now.
I have been a web journalist since 2007, and since then, I have been interested in what we call "data journalism."
Data journalism is a new tool in the tool box of journalists in the same way as are interviews, reportages, investigations, and documentation work.
It consists of using networks and computers to work on figures and tables in order to analyze the information that we call "data" or "big data."
We analyse them, depict them, create graphs and make classifications out of them, and we try to tell stories from these data.
What I do regularly is to use data journalism to work on journalism itself.
Let me explain, it will all become clear.
One of the first think I did regarding data journalism on journalism was to work on clichés, common expressions used in the media.
What I call "cliché" is for example, an expression such as "the cherry on the cake."
You also have "the cat among the pigeons," "the tip of the iceberg", and all kind
of stock phrases like these. And generally, when you study journalism, you are told:
"Try to avoid these. It's a little clumsy,
and using clichés isn't elegant." That's what we learn usually;
there are even courses to write without clichés, and books on the subject.
Myself, I'd made a little robot which I'd connected to Twitter and this robot was programmed to detect clichés, the series of expressions like those I have shown you, on French news sites.
So each time it catched one, hop! It tweeted it.
It has been functioning for years.
As you see, it's on top form.
It has found 72,000 of them.
Later, I was able to classify them and determine which media was the most "cliché," that type of things.
It was a first experiment and a little unscientific.
It was funny, but it didn't go very far.
A year and a half ago, I tried a different experiment.
I asked myself if the media was having a tendency to distort our vision of the world.
If the media distorts our vision of the world, how does it do it?
How much is the distorsion?
Can we try to represent that world according to the media?
So, to do so, I created maps.
More precisely, I created anamorphosis.
What's an anamorphosis?
You take a map with different countries, for example, and you misrepresent the country according to criteria.
As it happens the criteria that I've chosen here is the number of citations for each country, on a given media.
The bigger the country on the map, the more it has been cited, showing greater media interest.
Whereas, the smaller it is, the less it has been cited showing less media interest.
Here is the world according to the daily Libération.
As you see, it isn't the map of the world as we know it.
So, the media do not have a neutral representation of the world.
Indeed, that's not very surprising. But it's a confirmation and it's very visible, thanks to those maps.
Now here is the world according to Le Monde Diplomatique.
You can see that the map of the world has changed once again.
South America has grown a lot, the Maghreb as well.
This newspaper clearly doesn't have the same geographical priorities as Libération.
Here's the world of Radio France Internationale, which is widely listened to in Africa, so the African continent is huge.
Those of you with good eyesight can see that the West Indies are bigger than the original.
And here is the world according to BFM TV which is very different from that of RFI since the information is more focused on France, the neighbouring countries, Europe, a little on the US, but not really on southern countries.
This summer, I wanted to go a little further.
I wanted to be a little more analytical, somewhat naughty.
So, I found a new subject to investigate,
that which I called: "Fake information."
What is fake information?
It's information that circulates on the web or social networks which can sometimes be picked up by the media, even by responsible media, as we shall see.
I wasn't necessarily interested in the origin or the circulation of those fake news.
There is already rather interesting research work on this.
What interested me was to know what happens when the media fall into the trap, publish a fake information, and realize, several hours or days afterwards that the information was false.
Do they correct the articles?
Do they ban them?
Do they inform the readers?
Do they change the title?
Do they add a footnote, an addendum, the type of update that you usually learn to do at journalist school?
So I needed a sample, a base line.
So I headed for five stories, more or less eccentric, but all false.
To give you an example of such a story, there was this Quebecer teenager who pretended to have discovered a new Mayan city unknown to archaeologists, by looking at the stars and I believe, the constellations on Google Earth.
This info had been taken up by the media across the world and a great deal in France -
it had fascinated the French journalists.
Unfortunately, several days later, more reliable archaeologists were asked whether it was possible to discover a new Mayan city this way, just by looking at Google Earth or Google Maps.
Very quickly, they replied, "No, it does not work that way.
It's very unlikely that there's a Mayan city in the designated area.
This teen has done this in good faith and is definitely passionate but archaeology doesn't work like that."
Another example that amuses me is that of the dwarf strip-teaser.
It's about a future wife that might have fallen pregnant and given birth to a dwarf baby because nine months before, she got married and at her hen party there was a dwarf strip-teaser.
She'd have supposedly slept with him and nine months later, given birth to a dwarf baby.
(Laughter) None of this is true!
Well, strip-teasers exist, as well as hen parties and dwarves, and perhaps dwarf strip-teasers, but it stops there. You see, nevertheless,
the news is on Le Point,
more precisely, it was on Le Point.
You'll understand, I'll come back to this.
It is a reliable paper nevertheless.
Third example of fake information: it was a video as it happens.
A snowboarder was followed by a bear while she was filming herself coming down a piste or a snow covered slope.
We could see the bear charging towards the snowboarder,
a very impressive clip ;
it was a raw image, scary...
This video is interesting because it is part of a series of eight produced by an agency called The Woolshed Company.
They find it funny to do these rigged videos, very well rigged.
It isn't easy to see the special effects used in the video, that the bear, for example, has been added to the image.
Perhaps a special effects specialist can see it but most people would be fooled.
They did this one and also a video of a lion huntress who posed in front of the dead body of a lion she had just killed on safari.
Suddenly, another lion arrived and threw itself on her.
And again, this video is as striking.
There's also a guy who enters a tornado while filming himself going into the tornado.
So, eight "viral" videos as we say, that circulate easily. The Woolshed Company agency assessed what happened to these videos.
Once on YouTube, what happened to them?
Are they adopted?
Are they taken up by the internet surfers themselves via social network?
Are they taken up by the media?
The response, sadly, is yes, since a huge amount of televisions has taken up these fake videos.
In fact, some of them said, "This video might be a fake, but we are showing it to you anyway;" this included the French media that I studied.
It's the tactic of one who hides: we pick up the video, but.... This also, in terms of journalism, we don't do it.
Usually, we'd try to go back to the origin of the video, to learn about the snowboarder,
and perhaps would go to interview the bear, if we are very brave.
(Laughter) Or, at least, we would try to find the original media or the people around the material in order just to check it before publishing it.
So, I had five stories. Five stories.
Then, I selected 30 French news sites among the most popular, among those you probably watch every day or at least once a week -
thirty news sites, national and local, reliable sites, and not so serious ones, a varied sample of this kind.
Five stories and 30 websites makes 150 searches to do to verify if the information had been taken up and what had become of the articles involved, the contents, when the information had been proven fake, when they had learnt it was false.
I honestly did not expect to find very much.
I told myself, "Here we are in 2016, the web is no longer that young, journalists have been duped many times with crazy stories that they have shared too quickly without paying attention.
And especially, we've learnt that on the internet, it's possible to correct an article after its release. You can add a warning and change the title. This is what some do anyway.
So I said to myself, "Maybe you'll come to naught."
Well, in 41 cases out of the 150 researches, 41 times, I bumped into those fake news that had been refuted and nothing allowed the reader to be informed that since the release of the article in question, they learnt from another source that the information was false.
41 out of 150, that's almost a third.
As a result, I contacted the chief editors of some of the sites involved.
It was difficult conversations: "Hum ... There's a problem on your site, because ..." I gathered their reactions and put them in my article.
They're more or less convincing.
They explain how the info is fabricated and why they occasionally choose not to modify an article that's already online.
They didn't give the real explanation. They didn't explain that it is a form of resignation from the journalists.
In a nutshell, people tell themselves when they've done this silly thing,
"Well, It's not that bad; it's old news,
nobody has died."
When someone dies, then they correct it.
For example, when AFP announced the death of Martin Bouygues, lots of sites shared AFP's information.
AFP is a recognized agency, strong, which rarely makes mistakes.
So, when AFP announces something, it's shared on all sites.
When AFP said they were mistaken, all sites removed the articles involved
for it was then a very important issue.
So, there's a form of resignation that you can sense from certain editors.
Personally, this resignation drives me mad.
I believe it drives mad all the journalists who struggle to keep on performing their work and circulating accurate information and who think, in addition, that those are important in a modern democracy where we vote and have to select those who are governing us.
It drives me crazy because for me, it explains people's lack of trust. It explains it not entirely but partially,
Journalism is a distinctive profession.
You may meet amongst journalists, people who are two weeks away from retirement and still have a fire in their belly.
They're ready to leave for Syria to cover the war.
They're ready to investigate to pull out a scoop because they've had wind of something ... They're ready to produce the best paper on Earth with the best photos and the more powerful headings.
They still have a fire in their belly.
On the other side, you have people who came out of school just two months ago and are already a bit cynical or blasé.
I have two good news for them.
The first is that while performing this study, at the point of publishing it and a little afterwards, some reporters and chief editors reacted, among them France Bleu for example, which has taken down the relevant articles
which is not necessarily the best thing to do.
I would have preferred them to keep the article and modify it.
Anyway, it's good to respond as did France Bleu.
You are feeling less alone when you can see that other journalists out there have that high level of requirement.
More recently, Rue89 published an article to explain that they have been scammed by a fake information.
As it happens, it was about a teen girl who had lodged a complaint against her parents for photos of her shared on Facebook.
Maybe you've heard about it;
this teen girl wasn't happy and it'd been shared everywhere.
And it was fake. There was nothing true about it.
Rue89 had been fooled and what did they do?
They published an article explaining that they had been fooled. Furthermore they apologized to their readers for having shared false information.
It doesn't happen that often that's why I mention that story.
The second good news which I'll leave you with is that it isn't necessarily difficult to improve information.
A message is sometimes enough to induce a response from editors who you think are somewhat apathetic or disillusioned.
For example, to prepare for this TED Talk, I've made some screenshots.
You remember the screenshot of Le Point with the story of the dwarf strip-teaser.
The day before yesterday when I fell back on this story, and saw that it was still online although I had called them and published my article;
then I tweeted for fun, a little naughty tweet.
What happened last night, when I tried to post this article?
Well, it no longer exists.
It had been taken down.
See? It just took a single well shared tweet for someone somewhere at Le Point to wake up and say to himself, "Enough of this dwarf strip-teaser story. Let's remove it."
(Laughter) And this brings me to the idea I'd like to leave with you this evening.
It is the idea that you must be demanding with journalists.
You must notify them when there are errors.
You must put a friendly pressure on them so that they do their job better.
The more the public are active, the more journalists will react, and the better the information will be.
Because it is through your demands that we'll be able to rebuild confidence.
Thank you.
(Applause)
Imagine a world without communication problems, a world where everyone has a superpower, the power to read other people's minds.
It would be magical, right?
Please sir, I wrote a word on this sheet of paper.
Do you have any idea what it could be?
No?
No.
We should give him a round of applause, that's exactly what I wrote. (Laughter)
Thank you very much.
(Applause) I have always loved trying to understand how things work.
So imagine how happy I was when I learned my first magic tricks.
And it was really after evolving in this universe, in this world, that I discovered the real secret behind each of these tricks.
This secret is communication.
I mean, how can a magician get you to look exactly where he wants?
How is a mentalist able to influence your thoughts or predict your behavior?
One possible answer would be that they both hold the keys, the keys to the doors of your brain.
And today, I would like to share these keys with you.
I would like to offer you some techniques, reveal some of the mentalist's secrets, for you to communicate better.
Before that, let's do a small experiment.
I'm going to ask you to stand up.
Go on, stand up!

Great, please stay in front of your seat.
Great!
Close your eyes for a moment, trust me.
Now I'm going to ask you to imagine
a simple geometric shape.
Once it's done, focus on one color, an easy one.
When you're done, you can open your eyes.
I see quite a few people have already opened their eyes.
I will now ask everyone who has a circle in mind to sit down.
Not bad!
Now I am asking those who have the color red in mind to sit down as well, go ahead!
(Laughter) We can see how with this simple experiment, we can already guess what is in the head of about 75% of the people here.
But I reassure you, the idea is to go a little further.
Those who are still standing, don't worry, it just means that you think differently from others.
It also means there are a few psychopaths among you, but no worry. (Laughter)
I'd like to ask someone to join me
on stage, for example, sir here.
Hello, your name?
Philippe, give it up for Philippe.
(Applause) You can sit back down.
Nice to meet you, how are you?
Philippe: Very well.
AD: Great, please stand over here, Philippe.
We're going to do a short experiment together.
It's going to be quick.
Are you familiar with this object?
P: Yes, it is a deck of cards.
AD: Exactly.
I see you know the terminology.
Philipe, a deck of cards is kind of my favorite object.
Inside are 52 personalities and each one is different: faces, colors, figures, letters and numbers.
Now I'm going to ask you to take one whichever one you want.
Wonderful!
Show it to everyone, except me of course.
I'm not looking at the camera feed, so you can show it to the camera there.
Okay, can I turn around?

Thank you. I am borrowing it for a moment.
Let's lose it in the middle here.
Are you right or left-handed?
Can you hold out your right hand?
Now put the other on top to hang on to the cards.
Hold out your arms.
Great, how are things going?
P: Alright.
AD: Wonderful.
I have a little question: are you used to bluffing?
P: Absolutely not.
AD: So it is going to be easier for me.
Now the idea is to go into your mind for a moment, to go into your brain.
I would like you to first focus on the color of your card.
Either red or black, it's easy, please repeat it over and over in your head.
Okay, thank you.
Now that I know it's red - right? - it could be either Hearts or Diamonds.
Thank you very much for the information.
Now I want you to repeat over and over again the value of your card, repeat it over and over, okay?
It can be an ace, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6, 7, 8, 9, 10, jack, queen, king.
OK. (Laughter)
Let's start with that.
I admit I have some doubts, but it shouldn't be bad.
For the first time, was your card red or black?
P: Red.
AD: Red, we agree.
Was it Hearts or Diamonds?
P: Diamonds.
AD: Diamonds.
Well, we were off to a good start.
And in terms of value?
P: Not far from 7.
AD: Not far from 7; please give a strong round of applause because the 7 of diamonds is exactly what I found.
Thank you, Philippe.
(Applause) I suggest we now dwell on the details of this experiment to try to better understand how communication really works.
In fact, we are used to seeing it as a whole, but when we look at it more closely, we realize it has three axis.
The first axis is precisely the communication channels.
There are three channels, and you know them all, you use them daily.
The first is verbal, it is the words we use to express ourselves.
The second is para-verbal, it is the tone of voice we use.
And the third, probably the most interesting in our case, is non-verbal, it is the body language, gestures.
Imagine if I had arrived on stage earlier this way: "Hello, I'd like to talk to you about a very interesting subject that is communication."
(Laughing) I think you would already be asleep.
Fortunately, when we take a closer look at this, we see that verbal communication is very good at conveying a message, but non-verbal and para-verbal communications are even better when it comes to bolster this message and influence the listener.
And precisely, we can not only influence others non-verbally but also influence ourselves.
Studies give evidence of this. When you adopt a position of strength for example, an open position before an oral exercise, you have a much better chance of success.
Why not try it next time before a job interview?
In fact, the reason is simple, it's because you boost your self-confidence.
So we understand how we communicate, we know that it is important to communicate well - and it's probably the most important skill today - yet, we are talking of at least $35 billion in losses each year due to communication problems.
It's huge, and it probably shouldn't happen today, and that's why I'd like to give you five techniques, five mentalist's secrets that we use in our shows to better bluff you and attract you into our universe, that you'll be able to use to improve your communication.
The first is first impression.
It's often said that it occurs within the first 5 seconds, and that's true.
Earlier, when I arrived on stage, you already decided before I even started speaking, in a totally unconscious way, whether or not you were going to like me.
I hope that is the case.
The second technique is the language of others.
We all have our own language, our own expressions, our own gestures that we make, and they are transmitted between us.
Imagine the impact you could have if you were adapting your message to the language of your interlocutor.
Typically, we don't address in the same manner a creative who is responsible for innovation in a company, or the head of a sales department who has been in that post for more than ten years.
The third technique is synchronization.
We saw earlier what it'd be like if we didn't synchronize our own channels together.
But again imagine the impact you could have if you were synchronizing your three channels to those of your interlocutor.
The fourth technique is listening.
Today, I think there is a strong tendency to listen in order to reply, not to understand.
And this is where good leaders excel.
They listen to everything: the market, their clients, their employees.
That's here that we can distinguish who'll be able to solve a problem, and who'll not even identify it.
The fifth and final technique, my favorite, is empathy.
We are not computers,
we are not algorithms, we are human, and we all have emotions.
I think we should not be afraid to use, show and share them, so as to succeed in touching people at the core.
Moreover, in marketing, you probably know storytelling, it actually uses this empathy.
And today, studies show that we buy a product for its history rather than for the product itself.
Obviously, these five techniques are by no means comprehensive, there are plenty others all more interesting; but I'm really convinced that with these five techniques, you will already be able to improve your communication. However be careful! We are saying "to improve it" not "to be perfect."
We can't be perfect in a lot of things in my opinion, let alone in communication.
And this is the second axis, that of perception.
We can adapt and improve our message, but it is always the interlocutor, the person whom we address, who'll receive it.
And this message will enter our brain and be processed through filters, which are, for example, our experiences, our beliefs, or the context.
Speaking of context, I propose we do another little experiment.
Hmm... Hi, nice to meet you, your first name?
Jérome, if you could join me...
Give him a round of applause.
(Applause)
Nice to meet you. If you could stay right here, that's perfect.
Jérome, with me is someone great who inspires me a lot, you all know him, I'm sure.
He's one of the greatest detectives in the world.
His name is Sherlock Holmes. ... that of Arthur Conan Doyle.
Jérome, I have a quick question for you, how many pages are there in this book approximately?
You can say it.
J: Can I look inside?
AD: Sure, go ahead.
J: 202.
AD: 202, exactly.
Now let's turn our backs, if you don't mind. We're going to have our backs turned, that way you're sure I can't cheat.
If I try to cheat, you will feel my back move, and you will see me trying
to look. Are we clear?
J: Yes.
AD: Great.
Jérome, I want you open the book to the page you want.
It is done?
J: Yes.
AD: Wonderful. Can you tell me
the page number you opened it to?
J : 110.
AD: Sorry, excuse me?
J: 110.
AD: Page 110.

OK. Do you want to change?
J: No.
AD: No.
Concentrate on page 110, Jérome.
I feel like on page 110, "There is much less talk today.
It is the proof of a moral demotion which, added to the decline of his fortune, seems to indicate some vices."
Is it what is talked about on page 110, Jérome?
J: Yes.
Give him a strong round of applause.
Thank you Jérome. Congratulations.
J: It is yours.
AD: It's for you.
Do you have any idea how I did it?
J: I guess you did not
memorize everything, so no.
AD: No, I didn't memorize it all.
Should I give you a clue?
J: Yes.
(Laughter) J: Fine!
AD: I know Jérome, no hard feelings.
There is still a difference between your book and mine.
Should we show it to everyone?
In reality, Jérome, my book is entirely, entirely blank.
Please, give him a round of applause.
Thank you, Jérome.
(Applause) Why and how did your brain get tricked?
This is our third and last axis: heuristics.
"Heuristic" is a slightly complicated word we are not used to that says something very simple: an heuristic is a "shortcut", a shortcut that our brain has learned completely unconsciously or not, and that it uses to think and react faster, Typically here, you saw a book in my hand, and I guess you deduced that it was exactly the same as Jerome's.
This is where your brain fooled you since it was completely blank, as you saw.
Another thing, you saw that I was wearing glasses, and your brain also taught you that glasses equal vision problems.
In reality, there's nothing wrong with my eyesight.
And by the way, these glasses don't even have lenses.
(Laughter) Heuristics are pretty good, but as we have just seen, they lead to errors, errors that are called "biases."
I used several biases today.
For example, in the first experiment, I used what is called "the illusion of correlation."
Again, this sounds complicated, but, when I snapped my fingers, did it have a real impact on the rest of the trick, or was it just a subterfuge placed there to bluff you?
Another thing, Jérome - with Jérome I used another bias, another illusion, "the illusion of choice."
Did he really open the book to the page he wanted, or have I somehow managed to influence him?
We can't escape biases, that's clear, but we can do two things when we are aware of it.
The first one is to use them.
It's kind of what I just did here today, to try to fool you and entertain you.
And the second one is trying to identify them in order to avoid them, and that idea would rather apply in everyday life or in the workplace.
Finally, I think we can say that a magician, a mentalist, uses very rational techniques to make you believe in things that are much less so.
And these techniques, you can use them to improve your communication, even if, as we have seen, the way our brain works means it will always be impossible to communicate perfectly.
There may be one last question to ask,
am I cheating? is it a gift?
I let you fancy the answer and leave it to your imagination, but let us admit though that without trick, it's magic, but when there is one, it is even stronger.
Thank you.
Thanks, bye-bye.
No, just joking.
My name's Abraham.
My stage name is Tismé, that spells "mixed race" backwards.
You guys don't have stage names, do you?
Well don't worry.
I want to share with you my simple guide for stimulating creativity.
You don't need a stage name
to be an artist. We're all artists at different levels.
We all need to be creative or be inspired, whatever we do in life.
I'm a rapper, singer, slammer, writer, composer, beatboxer, producer, DJ, drummer, part-time sound engineer, party and event organizer.
People tell me that's a lot, I spread myself too thin.
Yes, I am spreading myself but I try to spread myself positively.
What I learn from one project I apply to another.
I enjoy multi-tasking, I need it, that's the way it is.
Quite early in life, I felt the need to get organized. to be very self-demanding, to find a way to make the creative process more effective.
(Laughter) It wasn't easy.
Today, I want to share with you five very simple ideas to stimulate and boost creativeness.
They're things I found out myself and they could help you too.
First idea: the morning.
(Laughter) The morning's the first secret that helps me be inspired, creative and productive.
I love getting up before 7 a.m.
I find getting up early is like seeing your day from the top of a mountain.
You can prepare your day better and then enjoy it more.
When I was a kid, my mother used to talk about morning ideas.
The first thoughts that come into our heads in the morning, when we wake early, we should listen to them, give them our attention.
Now, when I wake up later and don't have this little ritual, I feel lost, I feel like my day is wasted, like I missed a train that only passes once a day.
In the morning, I have ideas so clear they darken immediately.
Inspiration is a sea and I'm way out of my depth.
Can you just do something very simple?
Just this. (Finger clicking) Fine, not too quick.
If you can't do it, just pretend.
A little slower, there.
It needs to groove, to swing a bit.
(To a rap beat) It's 6 a.m. and yet my day is being played out right now.
Time and again, I've tried to reach this state.
But the mind has its reasons which reason can't suspect
Between a dream and wake I think I can see my fate being sketched out pushing me to try everything, not to undervalue myself.
If we try, we can go where we want.
No matter if the concrete scratches our knees because every day we rise stronger,
climbing the stairway at our own pace.
We talk, we cough, we fail,
we have our rhythms.
We try to lift our feet off the ground, burdened by all those daily chores.
A backing track, some ink, a few ideas and I take off.
I can see the inspiration, it bursts and the words flow.
Blessed be those mornings when my pen seems to skate.
It seems like my verses are meant for this refrain.
I write my thoughts instinctively.
Blessed be those mornings when my pen seems to skate.
I make a gift of this morning. My beautiful morning will fulfill this new day
Thank you.
(Applause) (Imitates wind blowing) Solitude.
Solitude isn't really fashionable these days,
I mean that blissful solitude that helps us focus, think, take stock and listen to our inner thoughts.
What are our secret wishes?
That doesn't seem important nowadays.
We pretend we don't have time.
Smart phones and social media stop us enjoying those lovely moments of solitude.
We're always connected
yet we're on our own. TV series, websites give us the impression of having something to do, something to watch.
Some people can't bear to face themselves.
That's understandable because it isn't easy.
I've got a little piece on that, if I can remember how it goes. Excuse me.
Alone, you're sane.
People bug you, trample on you.
Alone, you unwind, you listen, you're cool about things. It's your picnic, you've got time to face yourself, make room. In time, you're sucked into the spiral. We're docile and passive, gullible and hasty. Let's react and be strong, play games that go to the soul.
We're hooked, we're together.
Let's contemplate new horizons
for a while as we stay...
Alone, I'm independent, alone my heart leaps.
Alone, I climb the stairway, I'm inspired.
Alone, I'm swinging, I'm shining
What do you say about being alone?
What's good about being alone is that you're free. You can do what you like.
You can pursue your fantasies, your mad ideas.
You can be true to yourself.
To be honest with other people, it's best to be honest with ourselves first.
