Respect for the idea.
Creativity breeds inspiration,
by that I mean that it often comes from simply deciding to get down to it.
Let me role play a simple situation.
I've just woken up.
I don't have my hat on when I wake up.
I don't have that either, but don't worry.
It's 6 a.m. I've just woken up.
I'm alone.
I have an idea, a tune in fact.
Dum, dum, dee, dum... I can do one of two things: either I record myself or I have breakfast because I'm very hungry.
(Laughter)
Should I record? But I'm ravenous.
I don't know..
If I record myself, it may take... (Goes on humming) Right, I'll record it.
(Hums and improvises the backing track) Subway, subway subway, go to work, go to bed.
Even if we took a snapshot a day the image would be the same.
Same faces, same places, same faces without change. Same things, same... (Applause) Thank you.
If I hadn't chosen to record that idea, I wouldn't have created that piece.
Inspiration needs cultivating.
When we have what we think is a good idea, we need to write it down, record it, film it, phone a friend to tell them, paint it, sculpt it.
When you're in the shower, time is your own, you feel good, you're quiet, you unwind, it's great.
And then, you have an idea. (Laughter) And that idea seems amazing.
It'll surely be the best idea of the week.
So you say, right..
Obviously, you don't have a pen handy.
(Laughter) So you say to yourself, If I stay in the shower, I might forget my idea,
but if I come out of the shower and go to my room to write it down, I'll flood the apartment.
I should get out and get dried.
But drying will take time,
so maybe I'll forget the idea.
If I don't forget it and I write it down, should I go back to the bathroom?
It's a really tough situation.
My method is to repeat the idea over and over, even out loud - after all, who cares - until I'm out of the bathroom.
The problem is it stops me having other ideas.
So I'm not sure it's such a good method.
The more we respect inspiration, and our ideas big and small, the more we're inspired. (Makes a sound like a door
creaking on its hinges) Confronting your fears and doubts.
When you have an idea, whether for a project, a piece, a melody you're working on, you often think you've failed, it's garbage, nobody likes it.
As a real example, two weeks ago, I was thinking about this talk. I thought, why should it interest them?

What if I sputter or forget my lines
or no tune comes into my head when demonstrating point 3, respect for the idea?
You're filled with doubt, fear of the unknown, of failure.
It can seem very basic and it's easier said than done, but you have to fight that idea and show yourself to be strong.
We are our own limits and those limits start here, from the start, in our heads.
Who will believe in our idea if we're not convinced ourselves?
we're good at doubting, at underrating ourselves.
It's so much more comfortable not to take risks.
But when you do take risks, you feel so much better, it's so rewarding.
To demonstrate point 4, facing your doubts and fears, I'm sure you'll be scared at the idea of beatboxing.
Beatboxing.
It's easy, we'll divide the hall in two.
