(Stone being carved) How can I describe myself?
I'm a stone carver, sculptor, and ornamental mason.
I've carved lots of headstones and memorials.
I wanted a term to cover all that.
I don't know if I coined the expression,
I wanted to describe myself
as a "man of stone",
simply because I thought it covered the whole of my work.
I said, you love the material you work with, you are a man of stone now, be proud of that.
On this photo, you can see a quarry, and I feel as if I'm made of lava and created from the raw material.
We can feel in this matter the full force of those lava flows, and it is a truly living substance.
Since the 12th century, in the Auvergne region, especially at Volvic, people have been shaping the lava to build cathedrals, and our houses and monuments.
Until the 1980s, funerary art was the main business at Volvic.
Here is a carved Madonna created in the 1940s.
And here is my Madonna,
I carved her when I was 13 years old.
I won't deny that when I look at her now, I find her features coarse, her nose... She needs a good facelift,
but it was my first piece.
I carved it because in the workshop, at that time, we only carved funerary art, and I'd seen my father and grandfather sculpt heads of Christ, Madonnas, and all kinds of funerary art.
Just to tell you that I'm the son, grandson, and great-grandson of sculptors and stonemasons, and I've been carving stone since I was 10 years old.
I don't know whether I could even ride a bike by then, but I was always hanging around my dad, and here's the result.
For the record, about the photo, we were asked to pose, and we posed. But just before the photo was taken, we took up our stances and Dad didn't even look at me.
Which shows we are father and son and crossing blades is in our blood.
Here we wanted to bring a bit of sensuality to our workshop.
Karine works with us and she has created this decorative object we call the Kube.
And here are my companions.
I have six workmates, all exceptional people. People with a passion who share their daily lives with me.
And it's clear that these guys project my ideas with their hands.
When we are working on monumental sculptures, I can't do everything myself, and they execute my blueprints, all the work I've drafted beforehand.
In 1998, when I was starting out as a sculptor, I'd just graduated from my art college, a firm in Clermont, which makes tires, was refurbishing its head office and they asked me to sculpt the Michelin Man, Bibendum.
I didn't want to take on the mascot that everyone is familiar with, and I thought, why not try and make a Thierry Courtadon-style Bibendum?
That's why I wanted to tell Bibendum's story on a page of lacework and especially, to fashion Bibendum in this way, with the idea, the first small idea, of Bibendum as a pile of tiny tires.
When you are working on a monumental sculpture like this, you always start with a scale model,
this one is to a fifth scale.
Just on the model, there's already something like two months work.
We don't count the hours we spend.
When you're working to the timescale of a stonemason or a sculptor, You working in days, months, and sometimes years.
There's two months' work on the model.
And then, the monumental sculpture, which is about three meters high, took about 10 months.
Here, set in stone, in the writing, which is quite serious and enigmatic, the workmanlike Bibendum has learned the lesson of his fellows' sad fate.
This figure has crossed the century,
been created from all kinds of materials.
In the 21st century, it is made of stone,
and it has always bounced back.
There's movement in it too, as Bibendum strides across this page of history.
And I wanted to convey that the sculpture is on the banks of a little stream, in the the Carmes factory, at its very heart.
On one side were the workshops, on the other, the white-collar staff, the thinkers.
And I wanted to show that the thought process can't happen without the blue-collar workers.
There, that's the image,
and at the time, I was very proud.
I can remember stories being told by people from the workshops who didn't often cross this bridge to the white-collar side.
The day the sculpture was erected, they came to see it.
And they realized that someone like them, with just two hands, working with his hands, could create an emotion.
There were all kinds of stories,
one of them a bit sadder.
The day the head of this company died, it rained really hard.
The sculpture is on a plinth, and a few days later, water seeped out from the plinth.
And it was said, so I was told, that the sculpture was weeping for that person.
And it's true, it's quite moving, touching, because the man himself had come to the workshop to see the sculpture,
He had put the scale model in his office.
Maybe it was also his child,
so it's quite a sad story.
Here's a bit of a change in the way we work.
It's true, we're stone workers.
We've carved tombstones, and memorials, and monuments. Then here, a major car manufacturer asked us to create a sofa.
It was very interesting for us because we realized that with cutting-edge technology and contemporary materials such as carbon fiber we could create a graceful object with raw stone and carbon.
So that's a sofa.
I've tried it and, to be honest, it's not very comfortable.
Technically, we were really proud because we realized the raw material, with the drawn-out carbon fiber came over really well.
We have an elegant object, with a nice transition between the two materials.
This sculpture was exhibited at the Milan Design Week and then, I think, it went off to Beijing.
And there it is in the showroom of the car manufacturer on the Champs Elysées.
So we are a tiny bit proud.
Because technically, it required an enormous amount of work.
The carbon fused with the stone, and it was all done by hand.
We didn't have digital tools to help us
so it was quite hard. And here, my heart beats for this one, no pun intended. I wanted the stone, the raw material, to express what I feel, as you do maybe, every time I drive back from Paris or Lyon, when I get to the top of this hill, and I can see my volcano, and I say to myself, that's it, I'm home.
I wanted to carve an electrocardiogram.
And at a particular moment on the ECG, you have the heartbeat.
It's simply said, I'm sorry, no philosophical discussion here, but it's what I feel,
and I hope you feel too, whenever I get to the top of that hill and wow, that's it, I'm home
I don't know if you recognize this because the signature is a finger print.
We're living in the 21st century now and even we stone carving folk up at Volvic station use CAD.
And we realized that at the design level, in the carving of certain stones, and in the shaping work we could attain a high degree of precision.
And that is a full-size finger print.
That's to say we were able to carve a finger print on 3/10ths of a millimeter
So why did I want to express and execute this work?
Because I had become aware that techniques were evolving, and that I now had the ability.
And I realized that my grandfather, whom I'd followed around the workshops and who sadly died when I was 14, had never seen my work.
And I was disappointed he'd never seen the work I was doing now.
If I had his finger print carved in stone, it would be my most cherished possession.
That's why I had the idea of carving that,
because, I told myself, that's really him, he worked with his hands all his life.
We weren't being morbid, in fact I found it very beautiful.
And that way, I wanted to tell the story of a family, our family, how we leave a legacy, maybe in our image, which lasts forever.
Here's another technical feat, more like levitation.
We'll have a go at anything.
When designing a sculpture, a scale model, we work without limits. In other words, we design and build our model to a fifth of a scale.
That's easy clearly because the weight and size of the stones are within our limits.
I never ask questions because I say,
we're living in the 21st century, and whatever happens, we'll find a solution.
I'm not on my own, I can get help.
There are guys out there, engineers maybe, who can help me with the suspension.
Here's a practical example,
this sculpture is 7 meters high and weighs about 45 tons.
Here's the actual sculpture,
it's outside a supermarket. The client wanted a tribute to the founder of the store chain.
The family were passionate book lovers.
I wondered what I could I say to them through a sculpture.
I thought about twisting the material, twisting the stone.
In fact, I didn't twist the stone as you might twist a piece of metal, using a blowtorch to shape the material.
No, we started from a solid block and chiseled out the raw stone.
On this sculpture, I remember, I carved 9,000 letters.
That's about one year's work.
There, you can see in more detail... When you are carving a sculpture, you only have to drop your hammer or your chisel and the piece smashes, that's the risk,
and it's what makes the work interesting.
You can take nothing for granted until it's finished.
The tiniest glitch, and imagine the frustration.
It's already happened, as I was telling someone the other day. I'd been working on a piece for three months. I turned round, caught my feet in the trestle, and it fell.
It's a dream, I told myself calmly, I'll turn round and the piece will be on the trestle. It's impossible, just impossible.
It cannot be, I've had a nightmare.
And it happens quickly, I turned round, and there it was on the floor, smashed to pieces.
At the time it was hard, obviously.
I went running for 20 minutes,
that calmed me down a bit.
Then, day by day, I gathered up the lacework pieces of that sculpture,
and I said, what shall I do with them?
Shall I load them in my wheelbarrow and put them on the tip?
We'll see. I said, we'll wait a bit,
we might be sorry.
Then yesterday, a visitor said to me, wow, that sculpture looks like a globe, it's really lovely!
And I said to myself, it worked.
In fact, I'd gathered up all my bits of lacework and stacked them up to make a 3-dimensional view and it became a sculpture.
Obviously, I'm very proud of that piece. It's not a story I tell everyone,
but that little mishap goes to show
just how frustrated you can get. You think you are working with matter that's indestructible.
It has a melting point
of 1280°C, it's stone,
and we so want to push it to the limits of its brittleness, to deform it, to give it movement, that we take enormous risks.
We try to push the limits and that's the risk.
Here's another 1/5th scale model of a sculpture in a town hall where the mayoress asked me to tell the story of her town.
And thereby hangs a tale.
The day before, I was due to show her my project, I had done nothing. I was as sick as a dog, I'd produced absolutely nothing.
What was I to do?
I found myself staring at two sheets of paper to design the sculpture, but no ideas, no drawings.
I took the sheets of paper,
I twisted them; Ah, maybe...
Next day, sheepishly, I met my client, and I said, here's what I'll do for you.
I twisted the sheets of paper before her eyes.
Don't worry, I said, I'll be back in a month with the scale model.
Here's the result, two blocks
which really are twisted and interwoven.
Technically speaking, just to say how frustrating things are, the initial weight of the blocks, of those two sheets, was 11 tons.
So it was fairly difficult
for us to manage the volume.
I'm very proud because my grandfather had stashed away those blocks for 50 years.
A quarry, as we saw at the beginning, is a fragmented mass of lava.
I said to myself, those blocks will be just right for that.
I was proud that my grandfather had kept those slabs of stone because workable blocks of that size are extremely rare.
And I produced those sheets
from 11 tons of stone. And the curved piece is chiseled out like lace.
At the end, the piece only weighed 600 kg.
So over 10 tons of stone went to waste.
I was telling you earlier how easy it is to make a scale model.
There, that's exactly the principle.
We set out to create a 60-cm sphere
with pieces like this one.
We stuck the pieces and shaped the sphere.
Easy as pie, and the customer was really happy.
I'd put spacers in the center, as you can see.
But the day we started the real sculpture-- and by the way, the real sculpture weighs 40 tons.
In a quarry, we don't have blocks that are three meters wide.
So I had to stick each piece, segment by segment.
And that's when our problems began.
Because we couldn't get hold of the right resins and dowels.
Whenever we lifted a segment, it broke.
On top of that, each part had a specific location.
We'd calculated the diameter and the curve precisely so that when the parts were assembled, we would have a perfect curve.
And then, perhaps for the first time, I nearly gave up because it was hard, very, very hard.
We said, we won't give up, and by sheer obstinacy we managed to do it, and it worked.
And the way it's balanced shows that even if we are stonemasons, we sometimes work to 1/1000th of a millimeter.
The first part supporting the sphere is 45 cm across and 2 cm thick.
This piece is so finely balanced that if we'd erred by a few thousandths of a millimeter, the sphere would have started rolling,
which would have been a bad sign. My one concern in life is I won't have time to do everything.
We all have something to worry about,
and that's my one concern.
I've got so many things going on in my head, I'm so hyperactive, as you can see,
that I wonder how I will manage.
We're in the 21st century, and we use CAD tools to machine wood and metal.
I decided to look into it,
and I discovered a pretty remarkable tool,
computer-aided design.
Why? Well, it's going to help me buy time,
it's going to enable me to create blueprints.
A few months ago, I could create everything I could design.
I was already proud of creating what I designed.
Now, I can create everything I dream of,
that's the difference.
Here’s a practical example of a piece,
a kind of monumental spring.
A piece like that, just to produce a rough outline, needs 150 hours of work with your hands.
Now, with the machine, it takes 8 hours.
Obviously, it doesn't take away the creativity. You always have to create the work, to imagine it.
I thought up this piece 20 years ago.
It was hidden away in a corner of my sketchbook, but I'd never dared execute it because I didn't have the time,
and that's what's interesting about this.
There's another piece, fretted baroque picture frames, still quite simple.
Some more examples where we're working on very contemporary designer items.
So that's a new approach to my work.
I've always exhibited indoors, and I wanted to work with the elements.
I realized I was attracted to nature, and I wanted to work with matter, and with trees and nature.
So I wanted to create some vaguely land art forms, and here's an example.
When I was talking earlier about the 10 or 11 tons of waste, here's what I do with it,
it doesn't all go in the bin. I manage to think up and create works from it.
I've created a work in levitation.
That's my latest piece of lacework,
8 months' work for a piece like that.
Since I was a kid, with my father, when we pick up stones, not very thick stones, we've noticed a slight bending.
We said, that's funny, stone is slightly elastic.
I wanted to convey that, and I asked myself, what can best convey the distortion and the movement?
And I said, I'll try and make a spring.
I made several, quite a number in fact,
and here's the result.
I won't let you try because I know you,
you think it's made of metal, and you'll break it.
But you can see that it moves a little.
Look, it moves about a centimeter and a half.
You've all thrown stones and never seen one bounce.
And you can see that stone is elastic.
Beyond the artistic aspect, especially, it creates an emotion.
Stone isn't necessarily static, there can be movement to it.
There, I'm a man of stone, son, grandson, and great-grandson of stonemasons.
I'm lucky enough to have a marvelous job.
I'm lucky enough to be able to dream and be able, the next day almost, to make my dream come true.
And all these works, if they are not vandalized or smashed in the future, will last forever.
(Applause)
I am a shepherdess, but I work in Seine-Saint-Denis.
Well, since you don't believe me, I brought Twiggy with me.
Michel, could you bring Twiggy?
He's always dreamed of being a shepherd.
(Applause) Before meeting Twiggy, I was a concrete construction foreman,
In 2012, along with five of my friends, I embarked on an urban farming project.
But what we wanted were animals.
So we started with sheep, because they are autonomous and aren't too big, and because they need to graze on a daily basis we reckon the easiest way to move them around is to practice urban transhumance.
We met many people, who smiled and told us the city became more bearable thanks to them.
Then our herd grew bigger.
We needed more pastures and we were offered some grassland by universities, companies, and military bases,
that have been successfully grazed and naturally fertilized by our sheep because doing nothing about it would have been truly a shame.
Thus, we were able to reseed, maintain, and harvest these spaces.
Through sheep grazing we have also managed waste such as leaves, branches, or rotten fruit, and since we were in town, residents used to bring us leftover food as well.
We were "the right opportunity."
We were brought bread to avoid food waste
and soon we found ourselves buried in a pile of garbage and had to resort to outsourcing.
To chickens.
(Laughter) Thus, once sorted out and decomposed this waste returned to the earth as fertilizer, improving the soil and yielding more crops,
such as pumpkins, tomatoes, or beans, anyways, a fantastic harvest.
And without us even knowing it, we found ourselves involved in the whole production cycle;
locally-owned, fair trade, and above all, delicious farming.
Today we own three sheep pens, 22 hectares of pasture, 54 sheep, chickens, a vegetable garden, fruit trees, and soon, vineyards, wine, grain, and why not, a dairy farm.
Currently, we consume part of our production.
We eat the fruit or our labor.
We live off our town.
We have become farmers.
But urban ones.
We could have stopped there, could've eaten our tomatoes whilst looking after our sheep, except we weren't alone.
It was as if the town and its inhabitants, were waiting for someone to take the plunge and prove it was feasible.
So today, we want to employ our farming views for the benefit of towns in transition.
We want to enable companies and communities to be a part in this change
because the city is, by no means, a vacant lot
but full of crevices, curbs, parks, and rivers.
These sad, green spaces, I'd say, almost sanitized, turned lush and dynamic
because we believed in their farming potential.
We believe that this land lacks rather farmers than green space technicians.
And we are comitted to transform the city, grassplot after grassplot.
Thank you.
(Applause)
Let me introduce to you the emperor, 45 meters high and a circumference of 4 meters.
Quite impressive, isn't it?
It is 250 years old.
This means that this pine tree was born before the French Revolution.
It was 35 years old when Beethoven composed the ''Ode to Joy,'' 100 years old during the Universal Exhibition in Paris, 200 years old when the Universal Declaration of Human Rights was written.
It overlooks the 250 acre of forest that I manage.
Think for a moment ...
Since its seed sprouted, it has experienced one thousand seasons, 250 times the spring mildness, then the heat and the summer drought.
It has seen its friends, the beech trees, lose their leaves 250 times, as well as the winter's harshness, the wind, the cold, the snow.
In fact, in my work as forest manager, my relationship with time is a bit different than the majority of you.
When I cut a 200-year-old tree I imagine the forest aisle, the clearing that it will create, and the seeds that will then sprout, grow, evolve, and become trees.
I visualize my action at the level of a tree and the forest area, but above all, I am led to exercise my foresight.
Once they become trees, what makes those seeds form the future forest ?
I anticipate my interventions in a management plan, or a "life plan" if you prefer, for one year, five years, thirty years ... a hundred years.
My perspective is the century.
What does this teach me?
Well, it is first humility, intellectual honesty.
I don't cheat with time.
I can't pull the tree to make it grow faster.
I have to work with an exiting forest that Nature and foresters have shaped centuries before I came.
My task is to continue this work for the centuries to come while providing people with the wood they need.
And when I make choices, my responsibility is to respect the history of each forest.
What will be useful to it?
What could galvanize its collective strength?
Because a forest is primarily a society.
It's a tree and another tree and another tree, just like drops of water add up to make streams, rivers, and oceans.
Each tree gives what it can and takes what it needs, no more no less.
The trees' stillness makes us believe that they are inactive, but they are permanently active.
They extend their leaves, their branches, their crowns towards the light at all times.
They capture the smallest photon,
the smallest drop of water in order to develop, to strengthen their roots and their trunk.
Each tree is beneficial in its own way.
One brings shade, another a shield from the wind. This one gives its leaves to produce humus. That one spreads its roots to capture water deep below.
All of them produce oxygen, clean up the air, purify the water, fix the ground, regulate the climate, produce fruits and wood, and participate in the balance of the forest and the world.
Each one gives what it can,
but one tree does not constitute a forest.
It is part of the stand.
It brings its will, its vital impulse.
In my daily work, I have noticed that the forest's strength is in symbiosis, an intimate and lasting association between individual trees, a community of interest if you prefer.
I could see how trees work in synergy.
Young beeches grow under the cover of old pines, and young pines grow under the cover of old beeches.
However, there are also competitive relationships and rivalry at an early age to find a place as a dominant or as a dominated in adulthood among the stand.
Then these relationships slowly become an interaction and cooperation phenomena.
At that point, the dominants protect the dominated,
and the dominated ensure the stand's stability against the wind.
Personaly, I have noticed that the forest does not build its strength on uniformity but on diversity.
So based on one-century perspective, what am I going to do to favour this symbiosis?
Here, I've made a clearing which light enables seeds to sprout.
Elsewhere, I've made a clearing that has strengthened the trunk of the trees against the wind.
Somewhere else, I selected some trees to produce timber.
It may seem surprising, but when you cut a tree, the overall potential of the forest is increased.
With each decision, I chose which tree stays and which one falls.
This obliges me to step away before I take them.
I must constantly sharpen my sense of observation, look at the forest in its entirety, and learn its functioning.
The forest is my school of life.
It helped me and is still helping me to better understand the world and even myself sometimes.
Personally, what I see in it is like various paths of human life.
Some seeds have grown far from their parents.
They are light.
Winds and birds have carried them far away.
They are frugal, and they are content with low quality soil to grow and create some shade for their offspring and form a new community.
Other seeds, much heavier, fall at the feet of their parents and grow in their fold, protected but at the same time under a guardianship that obliges them to make their way between parental branches in order to find light.
When I look at the size of a seed, and see that with just some earth, water and light
it produces this,
for me it's magical, It's fascinating!
We are just like these seeds. We have a huge potential in ourselves. And they show us that there's little needed to make great things, one goal - capturing the light - and the enthusiasm to go further and higher every day, for a thousand seasons.
So what about me, what is my goal?
What is my plan for life?
What will make my deeds beneficial to others, to our future and to our children's future?
Before that, life was for me about finding the right balance between enjoyment and work. They were two opposite elements.
Enjoyment means burning the candle at both ends, having fun ... It's the passion for life.
Work on the other hand is tedious, laborious and not very exciting.
The tree showed me a third path: building.
I can develop my potential
and feel fulfilled when I try to accomplish, even partially, a work bigger than myself that I will not see completed in my lifetime.
Each day, I know that what I do brings me excitement because it involves something both natural and immense.
Look at the trees!
Let yourself be carried by their majesty, by this feeling of eternity that they spread, this kind of calm and resolute energy.
Look at their diversity and their complementarity.
Now me and you, just like the emperor and his companions, the beeches, what are we building?
What is our goal,
our "plan for life" so to speak?
Using a century as perspective, let's be trees!
And together, let's be a forest!
Thank you.
(Applause)
This bowl is here because it represents life, my own life, but also yours, as in life itself. We can observe patterns on the inside, reflections, because sometimes it's like if life handed us a mirror.
There are irregularities, cracks and hollows, because life is that too, it's made out of ups and downs.
Overall, you can agree, life is rather beautiful. Most of the time, everything goes goes, everything goes well
And like this bowl, everything is smooth, everything is round, everything is soft.
Only, sometimes, not everything happens exactly ... (Interruption of sound) (Laughter) (while laughing) OK!
(Applause) Mic problem!
Should I start again?
(Audience) No.
No?
Really?
OK.
Only sometimes not everything happens exactly as planned, simply because we cannot always predict everything, control everything.
If you decide to move forward with your life, you will take risks, for example, when walking- maybe the risk of tripping.
And while juggling with all the elements of your life, there too, you will take risks, the risk of taking a plunge and almost falling!
Finally, we are all looking for the same thing, that is, a certain balance.
So, sometimes, this balance, we think we will reach it, we are almost there.
it hangs only by a thread. But it hangs!
So this is the moment when we start to relax, we may even release our grip
Come on, Should we try?
Just a second.
(Clinking of the bowl that breaks) But sometimes, we fall.
Sometimes we break up.
And like this bowl broken into three pieces, we all have fault lines.
Pain is something very personal.
Sometimes, it is a physical pain that we experience. For example, an accident, a disability, the aging body, an illness
And sometimes, it is a more emotional pain: for example a dismissal, a mourning, a divorce, depression
But regardless of the type of suffering, we have all experienced it, in one way or another.
We all have scars.
Today, as you may have guessed, I will talk to you about pain, and suffering. but also about repair and resilience.
So, what is resilience in physics?
It's the ability to absorb shocks.
And in psychology, for the human being, it's exactly the same thing:
it's the ability to absorb the shocks in our life, and to bounce back, to rebuild.
And there is an art that perfectly symbolizes the spirit of resilience.
This art is called kintsugi.
"Kin" in Japanese means gold.
"Tsugi" means “ join”.
The art of golden joining.
This art consists of highlighting with gold, the scars of a broken object, when you could have chosen to hide these repairs, or just throw it in the trash.
And it's the perfect metaphor for resilience: because, paradoxically, the object becomes more beautiful, stronger, and more precious, for having been broken!
And for us, as human beings? Well, it's the same thing.
I'm going to prove it to you, by asking you all here, a little question: Since you were born, in percentage, how many difficult tests have you survived, so far?
In fact, I don't need to ask each of you individually your answers, because all answers will be the same.
Because if you are here and alive, it's because you have survived 100% of the tests in your life, so far.
And sometimes, there are even cases where you could be transformed on the way.
And that is the famous saying: "What doesn't kill me makes me stronger".
You may be wondering how this art was invented, who had the crazy idea one day to put gold on an object, when they could have decided to throw it in the trash.
In fact, it is an art dating back to the 15th century in Japan.
The Shogun of Japan , these were the chief of the armies, used his favorite tea bowl every day, a beautiful Chinese bowl.
Only one day, like this bowl, he broke it.
So he decides to send it back to China for repair.
He is ready to wait months for that.
You can imagine at the time, the transportation, all the waiting time.
After all this time, the bowl comes back with a repair called "staples". with metal staples along the crack.
So, the problem is that not only is it quite visible as a repair - it's not very discreet - but in addition, it does not solve the problem at all since the bowl still has its crack, it is not waterproof.
So the Shogun, not very happy asks his Japanese craftsmen to find a better solution.
And it was that day that the art of kintsugi was born.
Like many other Japanese arts it is an art that is extremely meticulous, delicate, rigorous, and requires a lot of preparation and concentration.
But what is really wonderful about kintsugi is that beyond the final result, which is really fabulous, that speaks to us, that speaks to our subconscious, every step of the creation of a kintsugi is significant: because in each phase you take a step closer to your own healing.
There are six of these steps.
I will explain them one after the other, because it can give you the keys to your own transformation if one day you have to face a test in your life.
So the very first step is the one where we are like this bowl: broken!
We feel shocked.
We even have the impression that we will never be able to get up.
We are literally in "a thousand pieces".
Yet, the first thing to do is to get some perspective on the situation. to evaluate it, to observe where the pieces are, how many there are, and what they look like.
It's about gathering together, as one would pick up pieces of a puzzle that would have been scattered on the floor.
Then comes the second step: the one where we start to pick up the pieces.
We will gather the pieces with the sabi, a mixture of flour and lacquer.
We were talking about a puzzle earlier: it's like a puzzle indeed, but in 3D.
In terms of emotional healing, it's the same principle. It's the moment when you start to pick up your pieces, to heal, to fill your gaps.
Only sometimes, as in this picture, we may miss a piece of our puzzle.
And in these cases, we must not hesitate to use another object and integrate it into our repair, because it means that in life we ​​can rely on others to rebuild.
You have to look for it on an object that is even more different because it's going to make very interesting mixes, which defy the imagination, where one plus one equals three.
Then comes the third step; It's the step of patience.
We will put our our object delicately in a box for several days to let it dry.
We have to be very careful, as the scars are still fresh.
We would all like to heal our pain, our suffering, in a snap, a second, a session.
But, kintsugi is there to remind us that sometimes, there isn't another solution other than to let time take its course, to let time do its work.
This is not necessarily obvious, in the society in which we currently live.
On the contrary, everything accelerates.
Who here still has the patience to wait?
Whether to seek information on the internet, to download a movie or a series, to date ... What we tend to forget is that if we are too impatient, the wounds, that are still fresh, may reopen, even get infected.
So you really have to learn not to rush the steps
And I invite you to think about it for yourself.
In your life, do you tend to be a little too impatient and to hurry?
Then comes step number four, the repair phase.
So we'll take the object out of the box.
It has now dried up nicely.
And we will sand each of its fault lines.
And we'll put a first coat of lacquer, a layer of black lacquer.
This is important because it will make the object completely waterproof, So our Shogun will be happy!
Then we will put it back in the box, let it dry, take it out, re-sand it, and then we had a second layer of lacquer, a layer of red lacquer.
What does it remind you of, these beautiful bright red lines?
It depends on people but, personally, it reminds me of a blood network, veins.
And it's a bit like that: it's as if life was returning to the object, as if it were revived, as if its heart was beating again.
And for us, it's the same thing.
It's the moment when we feel ready to relive, to put life back into our lives, to catch a second wind.
And maybe our heart starts beating again, for the first time in a long time.
For now we are ready, we are ready for phase five.
This is the phase we have been waiting for since the start the moment when we will finally be able to put gold on the wounds.
On the last layer of lacquer, the layer of red lacquer, which is still wet, still fresh, we will gently sprinkle a powder of pure gold.
And each particle of gold will interact, mix intimately with the lacquer, until recreating the illusion of a flow of gold.
And for us, it is an extremely powerful moment, because it is the moment when we are ready to bloom!
We are ready to recognize our own value, because we too, after all, like a living kintsugi, deserve to put pure gold on our wounds.
And finally comes step six.
This is the final step.
So our object, from the beginning, was gathered, healed, sanded, sealed, covered with gold, it has been restored.
But what we must not forget is that gold is a metal.
So, like every metal, we can polish it.
So, for our kintsugi, we will make it sparkle.
And there it will emerge in all its splendor.
And for us, it is this very important moment where we are finally ready to accept the beauty of our scars.
And that's important!
Because it means accepting the beauty of our past, the beauty of our entire journey, with all of its flaws.
It is accepting oneself in our entirety, with our strengths and our weaknesses.
And like an object that has been through the whole process of kintsugi, all that healing energy, there is a moment when one is ready to expose oneself.
Me, if I'm here in front of you today, exposing myself, it is because I have reached this stage.
Personally, it took me two years. two years, day to day, because it's pretty amazing. It was on January 29, 2017, that I discovered kintsugi for the first time.
And I remember, because I took notes, because I felt it would be important.
But then I didn't know it was going to take me there.
So here is the context of the time.
15 days earlier, I had just learned that I was going to divorce again. My second divorce. That I would be raising my two daughters alone, including a four-month-old baby.
So you can imagine my emotional state.
That day, by chance - but is there such a thing as chance? -
I bought a magazine that I never usually buy.
Why did I buy it?
Because on the cover it said: "How to make a successful divorce!"
(Laughter) So that appealed to me!
So I open it, and there I see the word "kintsugi".
I had never heard of it!
But there is my little inner voice, and a kind of thrill that runs through me that says to me: "Go see, it's important for you".
And one must always follow one's intuition.
So I went to see: I typed "kintsugi" on the internet, and there I saw these beautiful golden lines that spoke to me, that resonated with me.
It's as if the soul of kintsugi resonated with mine.
It's as if I already knew kintsugi.
It's as if, seeing these lines, I told myself: "Remember, in the past you have managed to survive other trials, perhaps even more difficult ones. And here you will survive again!"
And then I discovered the six steps I told you, and every step of the way there were pieces of me that are still repairing themselves until today. Until this bowl.
This bowl represents life. My own life, but also yours, with all the force of resilience.
I think this bowl is more interesting than before.
It has a strength in it, the strength of its journey
It has the beauty of its imperfections.
It's perfectly imperfect, like me.
It looks like me.
So now, I'm facing a dilemma because I have a choice between two solutions.
The first solution is that I can put this bowl in a cabinet.
It will be well protected, nothing will ever happen to it again.
I will be able to look at it it every day.
Then, there is a second solution, The one I prefer.
I will tell you, I tend to follow my instinct and this is the solution that attracts me the most.
This bowl, I will use it every day.
And then, I will surely take new risks the risk to move forward, maybe to stumble perhaps to fall, maybe break or hurt myself again.
BUt now, I know that it is OK. Because I will always be able to put new fault lines in gold, and it will be even more beautiful!
Finally, kintsugi is a nearly alchemic process that speaks of transmutation, because as in alchemy, one seeks to reveal eternally the beauty of an object as a long life elixir would do. And as in alchemy, one seeks to change one's own lead into gold.
The kintsugi speaks of transformation, your transformation.
We don't know what the future will look like.
Life, as we said earlier, is made of ups and downs, and we cannot predict anything.
I don't wish it, but it is possible that you will face new challenges in your life.
If that's the case, I invite you to connect to the energy of kintsugi, to remain optimistic, to remember that you also will survive the shocks of your life.
You also deserve to put pure gold on your wounds.
You as well will become more beautiful, stronger, and more precious for having been broken!
I really invite you to turn your fault lines into lines of strength.
Thank you
(Applause)
OK.
I am going to tell you
a story. A true story.
Something that happened to me, but also something that I have done.
I'm sure that at some point, you will recognize yourself in this talk.
Last year I was in Italy on an Erasmus exchange in Padua, a student town near Venice.
As the weather got better, and the sky was completely clear, we decided with a group of friends to go up into the mountains.
We were quite a sporty bunch of people.
With "sporty" I mean some jogging every other week.
The idea was to go and do some running in the mountains, to see what these famous Dolomites would look like.
We did put on our shorts and sneakers, and this Saturday morning we took the first train to Bassano Del Grappa, a lovely town on the edge of the Alps.
We started running at the foot of the mountain following the Monte Grappa hiking trail.
Quite soon we realized that the slope was so steep that it became almost impossible to keep running.
We quickly decided to walk.
All morning the surrounding landscape was really sensational, really beautiful.
After a lunch break, we decided to keep on walking along the same path.
But we did not have the faintest clue about the height we were at or the distance we had already walked.
But we kept on walking.
A few hours later, we reached the snow.
Then it became more complicated, because with every step we could do our feet sank into 20 cm of snow.
We started to wonder whether it really had been a good idea to keep on walking.
After a while, the group was divided. I decided to go with those who were not yet tired of seeing panoramas which became ever more impressive.
We kept on walking, even though it became tiresome. After a while, as the sun was setting, we could see the top of Monte Grappa, which, with its shadows, seemed just a few kilometers away.
So, of course, we decided to go for it.
After a good deal of walking and even some climbing, we reached the summit of Monte Grappa.
We had a stunning view of the other side of the mountain, the chain of the Alps at our feet.
A very rewarding moment.
Then we took a short break at the shelter at the top to eat a strudel.
Apparently, we were not far from Austria.
Only then we started to worry about the journey back home.
This time we decided to take the mountain road and to hit it running.
Yes, very fast, because when we began our journey back, we could see the sunset.
Then the sun disappeared completely, and finally the night fell.
We did not stop running.
And for a good reason: the last train to Padua, to take us back home, was leaving two hours later.
While running, I saw regularly a panel with a number listed without units of measurement.
After a while I realized that it had to be kilometers.
I do not remember how many of them I have seen, but more than ten, that's for sure.
After some two hours of running, we stopped at a balcony overlooking the entire city of Bassano and its lights.
Probably we would not be in time to catch our train.
But whatever, we kept on running.
One of the few cars taking this mountain road, almost empty at night, took the four of us for a ride down.
(Sigh of relief) Saved!
A few minutes later, we fell down, literally, on the seats at the station.
The next morning when I was barely able to walk, my legs were stiffen, I did receive a message from Georg, my German friend who had come up with this idea to go and run in the mountains.
On a website he had retraced the route we had taken to measure the length of it.
We had been walking and running a distance of 38 kilometers with a height difference of 1,600 meters, both up and down.
I said to myself I did run almost a complete marathon yesterday, and not in Paris, in the Alps!
I really would not have believed you if you would have told me two days earlier I was going to do such a thing.
That's for sure, because during that day, we did not really know what we were doing.
We did what we did by doing it, really.
We were not mentally prepared.
No one on the train really knew we were going to make such a long walk.
Going up we did not know how far we could go.
And even on the way down, we ignored time, knowing that, one way or the other, we would know what to do afterwards.
I sincerely think this has been beneficial to us.
Really.
We really knew what we were doing, and we knew that in the end everything would be all right.
Our ignorance has brought us a lot.
In the end, knowing what you are doing may not be a very good idea after all.
Because you are... Here in this room there are entrepreneurs, there are students, who want to innovate, who want to create, who want to act and develop things.
But when they wonder when they will reach their goal, when they will finish their project, they get discouraged.
They have reasons to get discouraged because the road is long and tedious, and they do not see the end of it.
But fortunately, this road is dotted with beautiful moments.
The kind of moments that make us go further and keep on walking.
Sometimes it might not be a good idea to try to get to know what we are doing or where we are and what still needs to be done.
Maybe, in some cases, you should not know what you are doing at all to get further and higher
Maybe you should just keep on walking.
Thank you.
(Applause)
Imagine.
Imagine a living room.
It's evening.
A television broadcasts a black and white cartoon.
We are in the 1960s, so it's an old Émile Cohl movie.
A little four-year-old girl is sitting, watching the TV.
A hand on a black screen is drawing a character in white lines.
The hand's movement is fluid and with each drawing, the character comes to life.
Something special is happening this very evening.
The little girl is captivated.
She is totally focussed.
What she is seeing is magical: a space in which a drawing could become reality, a space in which a drawing could come to life.
Could such a space really exist?
And if it could, how could the drawing be made accurate?
that the drawing be so good that it could actually occur in real life?
Something has happened that she didn't understand,
but what has become clear is that she would be this drawing hand, and it would be by drawing that she would realize her dreams and in that way, find her purpose.
That little girl, that was me.
Since that day, I have never stopped drawing.
I would look at everything around me. I'd capture it, understand it and reproduce it.
I wanted to create my world.
I then quite quickly realized that drawing wasn't considered a very serious thing.
I felt even guilty sometimes when I was drawing.
Until I had an encounter with my 6th grade art teacher.
Seeing my very intensive use of Canson drawing papers, format 25x32.5 cm, she invited me to her house.
I felt really special.
I went into her studio totally unknown and yet immediately familiar.
She showed me a big blank drawing board,
a huge board, huge.
Well, that's how it seemed to me. I was only eleven.
Its size was 100x130 cm.
At that point, she said to me, "Go ahead! Express yourself,"
and she left me there.
I was facing infinity, the infinity of possibilities.
I felt excited and frighten
at the same time. Because obviously, I really didn't know how to go about it,
and it felt paralyzing.
I didn't have any technical knowledge.
So how was I going to represent the ideas I had in my head?
Well, there was no going back.
I had come this far, so I went ahead.
I started to throw on the board what was in my head.
I filled it up without limitations.
At that very moment, I understood.
The key was to do it without asking any questions, without trying to master the technique, but rather just "be" what I was doing.
Suddenly extraordinarily, everything around me disappeared.
I was what I was doing.
I was immersed in the world of possibilities.
And it was beautiful.
Since that day, I have known that nothing would be beautiful enough, big enough, crazy enough.
This permission to draw that my highschool art teacher offered me finally freed me from one thing, something very important: it is that drawing isn't difficult.
She freed me from the idea that to draw meant to do well.
Because, ultimately, what is drawing?
What is drawing?
Drawing is essentially three things: observation, internalization, and reproduction. Observation, internalization, reproduction.
We start by observing our surroundings, that's observation. Then, we infuse ourselves with what we have observed. We feed it with our personal experiences, with our imaginations, this is the internalization phase.
Then, we express it outwardly with lines, colors and shapes.
And this is reproduction.
We do this naturally as children.
Watch children drawing. They look at their surroundings in order to understand it, to grasp it, to modify it, just like when they throw a stone in the water and watch the wave-like effects, just to feel alive.
They see what's most important.
They see in the same way they feel.
They see in 3D.
For them, to reproduce in 2D on paper is not a problem.
They draw intuitively.
They represent their world in their way.
From this back and forth,
do they derive pleasure in drawing. If drawing was such a pleasure in childhood, why do we stop drawing in adulthood?
So we grow up, we get older, and we go to school.
There, serious things happen.
They happen when the child try to communicate, to make himself understood by adults,
because to make ourselves understood, we need landmarks and recognition.
In our repeated interactions with adults, as a child, we realize quickly that there's a right way to make things happen.
We learn what I call the "concept of effectiveness."
We imitate. We do like everybody.
Then, the beautiful sun which green tentacles were covering the whole page becomes now a yellow quarter-round at the top right of it.
Promoted by adults, technique becomes gradually a know-how, something that kills intuition and originality.
Now, we see and we learn about the world through knowledges: anatomy, object lesson, physics, abstraction ... Consequently, we forget everything.
We lose the ability to reproduce the way we used to as a child.
We just reproduce a code.
Here comes a simple constatation. As the observation, internalization and reproduction of what we must draw become increasingly complex due to the build-up of knowledges, the technique to achieve it become insuperable, unless, of course, you dedicate to it all your time, all your energy, or even all your life.
And that's why we stop drawing.
And that's why you stopped drawing.
Drawing has become an order, an education, a discipline, an expert's work, tedious and difficult to study.
In fact, some words are widely used such as "rendition," "execution."
These are the words that we, designers, are using.
I believe that those words express fairly what I'm trying to explain to you.
This special characteristic that is this iterative experimental process - which is the core of drawing - is reduced to technical know-hows, technical know-hows that, for most of them, have always tried to draw the 3D in 2D, namely: perspective, maps, orthonormal spaces, until digital 3D.
They all have been, in History, manifestations of attempting to find this universal language in order to communicate by the mean of drawing.
And it turns out that this code that we are still using today when we make 2D drawings has not changed since the 16th century. We perceive the world in 3D with our senses.
Yet at some point, mastering a technique can become pleasurable. that is, when technique becomes again a tool we're familiar with.
Then at that time, it becomes the vehicle of a quest, the playing field to express creativity.
In my case, I can't imagine myself thinking without drawing.
Drawing, sketch, diagram, all forms of drawing, are for me all thinking processes, and it has nothing to do with the fact that I'm a designer.
It is about one thing, that is the fact that I move.
When I draw, my hand moves.
Nietzsche used to say that his thinking was better while walking. That's because we engage our body.
So, we perceive the world in 3D. Therefore we are prompt to think that basic research is to try as far as possible to reproduce it in 3D
where our imaginations are generated - they come about in 3D.
Then here comes a new constatation. If you consider a paper, a painting, or our screens whether they're very small or very big, they are all flat surfaces.
We think in 3D but we interact in 2D.
So, in order to imagine our cities, our houses, our vehicles, our life preferences, you can figure out that the ultimate quest is to think in 3D and to reproduce in 3D.
It is this quest that motivated a lot of artists.
They tried to deconstruct this 16th century's convention, to break the code.
To do so, they only had collaging and painting to reproduce the 3D model.
Picasso wanted to go farther.
He invented a light stylus that, when he was drawing, captured the trace of his thought on a snapshot,
Picasso challenged technique like designers today. We challenge technique
because what we must replicate is always more than what technique allows us.
So, I am currently working with a team of designers and developers, a multidisciplinary team, and we share a dream: the dream of making drawing accessible to everyone, and experiencing it in 3D at the same time.
What I'm going to show you now is the research that has resulted in this device that I'm really fortunate to show you live.
I am in a 3D world in which I'm going to draw for you.
(Solfegio music) I'm going to draw for you ... a horse.
As you can see, I feel, I know that it's a horse, but I experience this drawing, I build it ... in lines.
It's like it is.
And the pleasure I derive from drawing comes from the act of drawing.
And what's wonderful, as you see, is that I have a drawing in 3D.
Do you remember that little girl?
Do you remember that little girl and the hand drawing?
And life that springs up?
I'm going to add a little mane ... ... of fire!
Some yellow ... That's it!
I could stay in that space for hours,
but I think that you're waiting for me.
I still have to make sure that the horse cannot escape, so I'm going to create some reins.
Here we are. And of course, I am connecting them to my hands ...
So you see, that little girl's dream has become reality.
This drawing, this space, this technology is available today, and I'm almost sure that you'll be motivated to use it.
I am a designer.
I work on the borderline between art and technique.
I believe that my role is to be at the crossroad between technologies and the creation of practices that are desirable and relevant such as creating and developing devices that will enable each one of you to go farther, and to make sure that technology will never be a problem anymore.
I took up arms for you all to enjoy.
If you're thinking that from now on, you don't need to stop drawing anymore, if you can imagine yourself drawing the world that you like, and feel like a child again, then let me ask you, at what age are you going do draw again?
Thank you.
(Applause)
26th of May 2014, at quarter past 11 in the morning.
Here's what I wore to work.
I'm on a scientific mission on the Mauna Loa volcano in Hawaii at an altitude of 2,500 metres and an hour and a half's drive away from the nearest town.
I'm on a scientific mission and on that morning, our main mission, was to empty our dry toilet.
The bacteria that was supposed to disintegrate our waste hadn't developped correctly.
And when this photo was taken, we were getting ready to empty two months worth of waste produced by three people.
Imagine that this misadventure is happening in space.
Imagine that it's happening on Mars.
Because we were on Mars.
Or at least, we were simulating a mission on Mars with all the constraints it implies.
Limited resources, water, and energy.
An obligation to go out in a space suit.
On Mars, the constraints are such that the astronauts have to live in a closed loop with their environment.
On Earth, we don't ask these kind of questions.
Besides, until today we always considered that Earth was an open system in which we can use the resources indefinitely and reject our waste indefinitely.
But this era is over.
If we want to face the energy and space constraints of tomorrow, we'll have to do things differently.
Doing things differently, involves many things.
It involves a better understanding of our ecosystems and terrestrial equilibrums.
A better way of sorting through what is really necessary for our survival and what is superfluous.
This also means becoming more effective in the way we recycle our waste.
And also, learning to live together in a world with limited ressources.
As long as the vast spaces that are oceans, lands, the atmosphere, are big enough to serve as buffers, the terrestrial equilbrums will be robust and resilient.
But the way things are going, we will soon be able to compare our planet to a confined space.
And in a confined space, the smallest variation can have dire effects on the equilibrum of our entire system.
For example, the problem that we had with our dry toilets was due to temperatures that were too low.
Here, a simple variation of a few degrees almost caused a sanitary disaster in the confined space that was our dome.
In the same way, for a long time we believed that plants couldn't develop correctly in Earth's orbit because of the conditions of weightlessness.
Yet plants more or less know how to adapt to weightlessness.
The problem was the lack of ventilation.
The atmosphere was airless and ethylene accumulated.
Ethylene is a hormone produced by plants.
This is what helps fruit ripen.
But in a space station, which is a confined space, ethylene accumulates, surpassed a critical threshold and inhibited the plants' growth.
So, what do we really need to survive?
Every day, we need 800 grams of oxygen which corresponds to all the oxygen found in 3,000 litres of air at sea level.
More or less, the volume of a changing room.
We also need 3.2 kg of water.
This water, we find it in what we drink, but also in what we eat.
And we need 600 grams of dry matter.
We find this in what we eat, and it is mostly made of carbon.
For a 1,000 day mission, with a six person team, to Mars for example, this vital minimum still represents 30 tonnes.
30 tonnes, that's a big truck.
And what about waste?
Because, every day, we also expel 900 grams of carbon dioxide.
We expel 3.6 kg of water.
It's the water we find in our urine, but also in our stool, in our sweat and respiration.
And we expel 100 grams of dry matter that our organism hasn't consumed.
Regarding the sanitation water, we need a minimum of 15 litres per day per person.
It's the water that we need to groom, to wash our clothes or the dishes.
Just for the comparison, in France today, the average consumption of water per day per person is 100 litres.
By the way, a shower for you, how long does it take?
10 minutes?
15 minutes?
Because for me, when I was on Mars, I was allowed eight minutes of water ... per week.
(Laughter) And I managed to use just four.
So, four minutes of water per week, that means a one minute to one and a half minute shower, every two or three days.
And that was a luxury, because the astronauts on the International Space Station, don't have a shower.
They use wipes throughout their stay of five to six months.
And they also recycle their urine.
They don't have a shower, but they can boast that they drank the same coffee every day for six months.
(Laughter) The four fundamental pillars of survival are: air renewal, water recycling, food production, and waste treatment.
A main project of the European Space Agency which I'm lucky enough to be working on, the MELiSSA project aims to include these four pillars in a closed loop entirely based on biological processes.
The aim was to artificially recreate a lake's ecosystem.
Germs disintegrate the teams' organic waste.
By organic waste, I'm not only talking about vegetable peelings, I am talking about feces and urine.
Germs disintegrate this waste, and as a result we get a kind of compost that is used to feed plants and algae.
And these plants and algae, as you know, absorb the carbon dioxide in the air and produce the oxygen that we can breathe.
The big advantage in renewing the air with these plants, is that is also allows the production of food.
And double advantage, plants also allow water to be recycled.
Because, when they sweat ... Yes, plants sweat too.
They sweat and they produce water vapor, pure water, so the water is recycled. Actually, at this precise moment,
in Barcelona, this MELiSSA loop is being demonstrated.
Rats are breathing oxygen produced by algae and the algae is using the CO2 exhaled by the rats to grow.
And we have a nice closed loop.
This even exists in Antartica, on the Concordia Research Station.
Antarctica, it's a very hostile environment, supplies are very rare.
The water treatment system at Concordia is entirely based on MELiSSA technologies.
Recycling, caring for our ecosystems, it's good.
But it's not enough.
Will we know how to live together when there are ten billion of us on Earth in a world with limited ressources?
Experiments in confined spaces, like the one I took part in, show that we also need to make progress in this area.
For four months, I noticed that being together 24-7, tensions started to appear.
But we didn't have a choice, we couldn't get away or change collaborators.
We had to make do till the end of the mission.
We found ways to lighten the atmosphere, that were based on games and humor.
And in particular, we had one game,
the rover game, that consisted in hiding a little magnetised rover like the one you can see behind me.
We would hide it somewhere inside the dome and the next day, the person who would find it would not only win points, but also the privilege of hiding it the next day.
Me, I always lost this game, I could never find it.
And this lead to many jokes from my teammates, but it was a great way to bring the team together.
One time, I came back from an outing and my room was entirely plastered with post-its.
They were everywhere.
On the walls, on the floor, on the desk ...
It was incredible!
Put yourselves in my place.
It had been three months, three and a half months, since a spontaneous event had happened in my life.
And now, my teammates had decided to play a big joke on me.
It was magical that night, the atmosphere was really great, we all had a laugh.
An important thing that comes out of these simulations, of these missions in confined spaces, is that, in these cases, we can't put our own personal interests and comfort before those of the team and the mission.
If we do, we're bound to fail.
We will never be able to acheive the mission in good conditions.
In the same way, we are all here together on this spaceship we call Earth, and if some countries continue to consider that Earth is an open space with unlimited ressources, without worrying about the rest of the planet, it's a guaranteed failure for us all.
End of July 2014, I emerged from four months of isolation.
When I entered the dome, it was the end of winter.
I came out in the middle of summer.
One of the things that I possibly missed the most that year, was spring.
When I emerged, I took a deep breathe of fresh air.
The sun stroked my skin.
It was the first time in four months.
Later that day, I smelled cut grass.
You know, that characterstic smell when you've just cut the lawn.
I heard birds singing.
And I dived into the ocean.
And then, it hit me, I was rediscovering all the things that I'd taken for granted all my life, that were normal for me, the seasons, fresh air, the heat of the sun, the oceans, the surrounding fauna and flora
And what if one day, all these things ceased to exist?
You think it's the stuff of science fiction?
So was going to the moon in the last century.
No, it's real.
In the medium-to-long term, if we don't change the way we use the planet's ressources, all these things that surround us will disappear.
So, I ask you: could our houses, our towns, learn from these closed loops and become recycling machines to enable us all to live on Earth sustainably?
Thank you.
(Applause)
The Earth. You have all already seen this image.
At least on the cover of your geography book, and certainly somewhere else, as it is the most reproduced photo in the History of Mankind.
Why?
This is only one we have, it is unique.
It is the only portrait we had of the Earth fully illuminated.
This was until last year.
The story of this photo is less known.
It's called Blue Marble.
It was taken on December 7th 1972 by the astronauts of the Apollo 17 mission.
This mission was the last one of the Apollo program.
In all the previous missions, the Earth was never completely lit.
So it was the first photo of the Earth we received but also the last one.
This photo, when we received it-- it has changed everything.
For the first time, humanity saw its home.
It revealed that the Earth was round.
We knew it, we were told before,
and we had the proof of it. This photo has also made us understand that the Earth was magnificent, but it was also fragile, lost in a gloomy and black space.
It made us want to protect it.
This photo started a movement called planetary consciousness.
It started in 1972, exactly when the environmental issues started to be global, and it helped the rise of environmental movements.
Unfortunately, the effect of the photo faded away with the decades.
My history with the Earth started exactly 20 years ago.
In 1996, a friend from engineering school, who was doing an internship in aerospace, gave me a book that changed my life.
I couldn't imagine at the time how far it would take me.
This book was named "Clairs de Terre." It was published by the Association of Space Explorers.
It's a name a little pompous to designate the Alumni Association of astronauts.
(Laughter) I looked through this book, and I saw breathtaking photos of the Earth, taken from space.
But that wasn't what really intrigued me, it was the text next to the photos.
It was quotes from astronauts, written like beautiful poetry.
It seemed like they were touched by the divine grace and they expressed a love I've never seen for the Earth.
I thought there may be something to dig here, to change things and make the world a better place.
Eugene Cernan, who was the last man to walk on the Moon, for example, wrote in this book: "We left to discover the Moon, we discovered the Earth." The sultan Al Saoud, who is a member of the royal family of Saudi Arabia, and who spent time in the International Space Station, also wrote these beautiful words: "The first day, we were pointing at our country, on the 3rd day, our continent, starting from the 5th day, we only paid attention to the Earth." In this book, through the dozens and dozens of quotes, we see astronauts, men, women, of all ages, of all nationalities, with this immeasurable love for the Earth.
Something seems to have touched them.
This effect has been studied and is called the "Overview Effect."
It has been shown scientifically that the effect of weightlessness combined with fear, silence, and the wide exposure to the Earth seen from space which is turning at a majestic pace creates all the necessary conditions for a mystical and ecstatic experience that marked the rest of their lives.
These astronauts became persuaded that the Earth was an interconnected living being that needed absolutely to be preserved.
The only problem was that only 500 people had been through this transformation.
And we needed to make it global.
Fortunately, a man had a dream.
This man was the Vice President Al Gore.
In February 1998, he was wondering how to gather people around the challenge of climate change.
It was two months after the negotiations for the Kyoto Protocol, where he was deeply involved as Vice President of the United States.
One night, inspired by Blue Marble and what it had changed when he was younger, he had the dream to send a probe in space to record in real time and broadcast on the Internet, that had just started -- these images, in order for people to always be able to see the lighted face of Gaia.
The advantage when you are Vice President of the United States is that you can throw out a challenge to NASA.
After talking to some experts to make sure that it was not completely stupid idea, the Vice President office, through a press release, challenged NASA to send a satellite in space to collect these images and if possible by the end of 2000, the start of the third millennium,
so basically, they had 2 years.
The problem is that obtaining these images is really difficult.
If you want to have in real time images of the Earth completely lit up, you need to stay on the Earth-Sun axis which is the only one where the Earth is always fully lighted.
If you are too close to the Sun, its gravitational force will pull you, if you are too close to the Earth, its force will pull you, and there is only one point between them which is called Lagrangian point L1 where the two forces cancel each other.
Unfortunately, it's about 1.5 million kilometers away from Earth.
NASA took the challenge.
In a very short time, they built the satellite called Triana, that was ready to head to the L1 point before the end of the millennium.
Triana was the name of one of Christopher Columbus's friends who was on board of the Pinta, at the top of the mast, and was the first one to see the New World.
Al Gore himself chose the name of this satellite and called it Triana.
At the time, I was a mathematics researcher in the United States, I was so fascinated by this project, that I was ready to quit my job and go work for NASA to promote these images, because I thought there was something extraordinary here.
But things got complicated--
(Laughter) (Applause) Things got complicated, when Al Gore got the bad idea to race for the White House against George W. Bush.
Even before his defeat, the Republicans who held the Congress did everything they could to slow down the mission so it could not go before year 2000.
But that wasn't the worst part.
One of the first decisions of George W. Bush and Dick Cheney when they got into office in 2001, was to completely stop the Triana mission.
It was a premiere in the History of NASA.
The mission was built, ready to go.
It was just to make Al Gore pay, both, having been a strong opponent in the presidential race and also for the Kyoto Protocol in which he was deeply involved.
When I saw that, for me a dream shattered.
I couldn't understand how we could have such a cynical view of the world.
I went through every kind of emotions.
First one, sadness.
Second one, rage.
And then, I came back to this sense of wonder state and I thought that this is not possible, these images must exist.
As I wasn't Vice President of the United States, I wasn't able to start a counter-mission.
I was just a mathematician and I thought that through a novel, I could make my readers feel what is the Overview Effect.
It took me 10 years, I wrote two novels that talk about the consciousness shift and the revolution that would happen if these images were to exist.
The dream was still on at least in my mind and my readers' minds.
And in 2013... Miracle!
I was writing an article about the Overview Effect, and while doing some research, I discovered that the Obama administration had secretly decided to relaunch Al Gore's mission.
They had taken huge protection measures.
Firstly, the name of the mission was changed from Triana to DSCOVR.
Secondly, they changed the purpose of the mission.
It wasn't anymore to film the Earth, but to observe the Sun, which is also very visible at point L1, in order to warn the Earth in case of solar eruptions that can destroy our electromagnetic equipments.
For this project, they took other agencies on board.
There was NASA, the US Air Force, which has a lot of of equipment in orbit, and also NOAA, the US meteorological administration.
To spice this all up, the NASA decided to entrust the launch to a private firm, the young start-up, SpaceX, from Elon Musk. But I trusted the visionary Elon Musk to lead this mission to its end.
That was in 2013.
During 2 years, I didn't sleep, waiting for the mission to leave.
The launch was postponed three times, but on February 2015, DSCOVR left.
It took off in the direction to L1 point, 1.5 millions kilometers away.
It's about 4 times the distance
between the Earth and the Moon. It arrived there in June last year, 2015.
I was waiting for the first images and especially those images Al Gore promised us that would trigger the Overview Effect for everyone.
It took another month and on July 21st 2015, the second portrait of Gaia was revealed by NASA.
Here it is.
You see, it's not the same photo of the Earth, since you don't have Africa on the forefront as we always see on the Blue Marble picture.
Here, it is focused obviously on the United States.
(Laughter) There you go. But in the NASA press release, I was expecting a link to this much awaited real-time video,
but there was no such link.
But they were promising a website in September.
So again, two more months of waiting.
On September 2015, NASA kept its promise and published this website, in which there were no videos but only images.
About 10 to 20 images everyday, taken from different angles, of the Earth as it was turning.
Nobody talked about these photos,
nobody used them,
no Overview Effect was triggered.
And a profound distress laid on me.
(Laughter) All that fuss for nothing.
(laughter) And then, something shifted in me, after the Paris attacks in November 2015.
When I saw all this darkness, I thought, "We really need poetry in this world."
I didn't have the courage or the time to take care of these NASA images alone.
I sent a message to my readers saying: "Who would like to help me make something out of these images?"
And here, miracle! My friend Michaël Boccara, who is now in Israel and who is here tonight, contacted me.
He was the one who gave me this book, "Clairs de Terre."
He told me: "I would like to help you."
We started this adventure together and we were to finish it together.
We spent nights trying to see what we could do with these images.
And then, one night, Eureka!
We said that if we had several images of the Earth taken from different angles, and we project them on a sphere while interpolating them, we should be able to create this missing video.
We spent another amount of nights, unfortunately for our wives, on the Internet between France and Israel.
And one night, we saw the Earth turning for the first time in front of our eyes.
It was very late, we called each other, we were mesmerized.
And tonight, you are going to see these images too.
(Applause) These images were taken right before the preparation of this conference.
They date back from May 29th.
They were taken from this L1 point, so imagine you are at this point, admiring the Earth.
If it's possible to turn off the lights completely, I'm going to let you experience the Earth.
(Music) (Applause) The story doesn't end here.
After making this first video, we decided to test people's reaction and we uploaded it on the Internet, on Instagram, and we tagged NASA.
Well -- (Laughter) A couple of hours later, we received an e-mail from NASA, who congratulated us and was wondering how we made this video.
(Applause) I think it was one of the most significant moments, where we were communicating with the head of the mission DSCOVR and more specifically in charge of the camera filming the Earth, asking him billions of questions and he wanted to understand too, how we made it.
After this conversation with NASA, we thought, maybe, we made something important, and we thought: we will follow our dream.
This dream is that we all own these images.
For everyone to have the feeling of this collective common asset that we have to preserve.
In order for everyone to own these images, we needed to share them on any type of screens, and we have screens everywhere.
We could project them on skyscrapers, but also on the smart phones in the palm of our hands.
So we created a project called " Blueturn", and on the website www.blueturn.earth, you can find for free all these images and videos.
And we will add this summer an app that will allow you-- on tablets or smartphones-- to explore for free and always see the latest images of the Earth, and to fulfill Al Gore's dream which became ours.
With these images-- (Applause) With these images, we hope to generate a new enthusiasm about this planet, and especially unprecedented artistic, meditative and educational projects.
We hope these projects will immerse every one of us into this Overview Effect, and take us to the next stage of global consciousness.
When the astronauts of Apollo 17 took this photo, they had no idea what would happen.
We neither, we don't know at all what will happen.
These images are yours, now its your turn.
Thank you.
(Applause)
The financial market at the end of the day? -
He's being hard on us.
But bear with me for a few minutes.
In fact, the financial market is terribly simple.
For 30 years, I've been dealing with financial risks.
I was on the executive committee of a bank for six years.
I have acquired a very strong conviction that I would like to share with you tonight.
It is that the big banks, corrupted by the financial market, have become public menaces.
It's our responsibility as citizens, to bring the banks back to serving the public interest.
To begin with, let's first try to understand the difference between the traditional bank and the financial market.
The traditional bank is the one we know.
It grants us credit, keeps our accounts.
It's an organization of general public interest.
Firstly, because bankers must put our interest before theirs.
We know nothing or next to nothing about it.
Then, because the community must support the banks.
If a bank goes bust, all our savings go down the drain.
But even the whole economy can go down the drain,
and so, it is tied to public interest.
The financial market is a small part of finance.
Some people call it financial speculation.
But there are two things for sure.
First, it has nothing to do with public interest.
Second, it's an extremely dangerous activity.
It's easy to understand why.
A typical activity of the financial market is borrowing money to buy shares, hoping they will go up.
Then, alas, the market collapses, and there's no selling them.
I'm ruined, I can't repay my loan, and so I go bankrupt.
That's exactly what happened in 1930 when a number of banks engaged in this kind of activity went bankrupt.
Governments everywhere in the world made a simple decision.
They said, "No more activity of the banks in the financial market."
Basically, "No more risking public interest activity with dangerous activities."
For many years, it worked well.
Then, some thirty years ago, a number of new financial products blew apart all constraints on speculation.
For example, in the past, we had to wait several hours to speculate,
to buy and resell.
Now, we can speculate for just a second, even for just a fraction of a second.
We can buy and sell.
Second example. In the past, speculation was on real financial products.
Now, financial products can be invented.
That is to say, for example, having virtual barrels of oil.
We are able to create as much as we like.
Bankers have seen this potential, they are no idiots.
They went to meet the public authorities. They said, "Look, there's
a huge potential risk, it's dangerous.
Big and serious people, like us, the banks, must do something,
or it will be a blood bath."
The public authorities, almost everywhere, were persuaded.
And so, market finance has returned to the heart of banks.
And from then on, for thirty years, banks engaged in this activity in wonderful ways, putting all their resources into it.
And let us remember, they are nevertheless private organizations, the most powerful ones on the planet.
This impressive development has resulted in four negative consequences for us.
It's very expensive.
It's useless.
It's dangerous.
And it's completely immoral.
Let's take a quick look at them one by one.
It's very expensive, as we know.
They say, "Yes, it's expensive.
Yes, the financiers are paid like professional footballers."
Right. So that's true.
Well, a football team has, until decided otherwise, eleven players.
In the "team" of a large bank, you can have 11,000 players.
Secondly, in general, the footballers play with a football.
Our market players need immensely expensive computers.
And so it all ends up as something ultraexpensive.
And it's we who pay for it.
But you say to yourself, "Well, anyway, me, I never bought those things."
And you are mistaken, because, in fact, it is not we who buy them.
That's done by companies, and we buy products of those companies.
And so, in a way, it's just like advertising, where, obviously, we ultimately pay as consumers.
We pay for all those 11,000 players with their computers and for the bonuses paid to their leader.
It's very expensive.
It's useless.
We say, "He exaggerates, no one can create something so enormous that is useless."
Let's stop and consider for a second how speculation works.
My example just now: I bought shares.
The enemy of the speculator is price stability.
Why?
Because if I bought my share, and, at the end of six months, it didn't move,
then I gained nothing, I lost nothing.
But I still have to pay my 11,000 players and their computers.
I'm screwed.
And so for thirty years, all the intelligence of the finance community has developed towards one objective: keep prices moving every minute, every second, never mind the sense of it.
And you've noticed that all prices move frantically on the markets.
To achieve this, there are the old, old methods, those of rumour.
It's rumoured, "Oil's going up.

It's coming down. It's going up again."
Or, "It will be there in three months.
In two days. In an hour."
And so it has become
an industry in itself.
But there are methods far more modern, sophisticated, computerized.
We execute buy and sell orders, tens, hundreds of thousands of them, by computer, giving the impression there is movement.
There's a movement. Here we go.
Then there's 100,000 orders in the other direction: "No, in fact, it's going down."
The result is that every time you see prices move, you say to yourself, "It's just a fluctuation. Nothing much to it."
No, there is something to it: every price movement generates profits.
Problem.
We, our companies, the real economy, we don't like price movements.
And then, the financial market comes up with a great innovation saying, "Wait, I've invented some products that will protect you a little against price movements.
You see, finally, I was useful."
But what we should have told them is: We're on a boat, and you shake the boat like a plum tree.
We are seasick, and you sell us a product for seasickness.
But if you were to stop shaking the boat, we'd not have seasickness,
and we'd not need your anti-seasickness products.
So, it's very expensive, it's useless, and it is dangerous.
Because if you shake the boat, it eventually sinks.
It took time to realize this because finance invented an absolutely incredible story.
It succeeded in making everybody believe the more speculators there are, the safer it is.
How did they get to that?
They used very complicated words, but they ended up with my little example of just now:
the speculator buys, the share price drops, and he can't sell.
And so, they explained, with their complicated words.
Mostly they talked about liquidity.
They said, "Yes, if it's a few individual speculators, it's catastrophic.
But if there are thousands of speculators backed by banks with almost endless pockets, our speculator in a tight corner will immediately find another speculator who will take his shares."
They succeeded in persuading us that the boat would be all the more secure, the more people shaking it.
It's phantasmagorical, but it worked.
And it was facing a world of financial incredulity that the crisis of 2007-2008 arrived, just like all the crises over the past 500 years.
That is to say, we've discovered that when a bubble bursts, everyone thinks the same.
That is, it will fall like a stone.
And at that moment, you can have one, ten, a thousand speculators, and nobody wants your shares.
And so naturally, the crisis took place.
With two differences, unfortunately, to the usual crises.
The first is that, obviously, since there were more speculators, it was bigger.
And the second is that the speculators were actually the banks.
And so, our state, and then we behind it, the taxpayers, we found ourselves in the extremely uncomfortable situation of having to save the speculators.
Because nobody could afford to see the banks go down.
It's expensive, it's useless, it's dangerous, but most serious of all, in my opinion, is that it is totally immoral.
The enormous development of the financial market has led to the development of these "values".
That is to say, the idea that you can pocket in one day as much as in one year working in a hospital;
the idea that pay gap ratios vary from 1 to 100 is quite normal;
the idea that the more you run on credit, the better.
And these ideas, and the idea you can cheat for years and not go to jail, have destroyed part of our social fabric.
And some of the rise of extremism, the disgust in politics, the falling apart of a number of values ​​that hold us together, is largely due to the financial market.
Symbolic of all this is the banks, which, before, were relatively credible organizations in which one could have confidence. Today, there's not a quarter of the financial year without a bank scandal.
And it's not me saying this.
I take the "Financial Times", Europe's major financial daily.
Its best editorial writer is Martin Wolf.
What did Martin Wolf tell us a few weeks back?
The financial elites of today are greedy, incompetent and irresponsible.
The most "prestigious" bank in the financial world is Goldman Sachs.
Its leaders are on salaries beyond belief.
Their remuneration and their bonuses depend on the bank's performance.
And this year, catastrophe: the bank was caught, fingers in the till, in an ugly affair cheating its customers.
It was fined very heavily; its net earnings plummeted.
What do you think the directors of Goldman Sachs did?
Well, they retrospectively fiddled the rules for their remuneration to maintain their bonuses despite lower earnings.
Avid, incompetent, irresponsible.
I'm convinced that, within a few years, our grandchildren will not understand how a whole generation has been able to expend so much mental energy on such a detrimental activity.
And so, what's to be done?
Let's call for a change financial policy, just as there's a change in energy policy.
There is too much carbon on the planet, and also too much finance on the planet.
So what is the first measure to take for financial reform?
Correcting the error made thirty years ago is simple:
get banks out of financial market activity.
With two immediate measures, two immediate consequences.
Firstly, the bank will get back to refocusing on what should always have been its mission: act in the interests of its clients and not against its clients.
And the second consequence is that the financial market, leaving behind the banks, will no longer be protected by the big bank, which, itself, is protected by us, the taxpayers.
The banks will be out there alone, like the plumber, the baker, the butcher, without bankruptcy protection, being very careful.
And it will become just like it was 30 years ago: much more cautious.
It will not disappear.
It will become a miniature model of the financial market.
And as we like little things, it will become likeable again.
Of course, it will not be easy.
But if we believe in it, if we ask, in our associations, in our social networks, obviously of our politicians, for this financial reform, the climate is now favourable towards our success.
We can, if we all call for it, obtain the financial reform.
And if despite all, some evenings, you have a moment of doubt, and you need to prop up your optimism, I will conclude by recommending my own remedy, which is to watch that marvellous Frank Capra film "It's a Wonderful Life".
It is probably one of the most moving humanist films you can see, and also, it contains the most beautiful description of what a good bank can be.
That is, a bank that does not divide a community, but on the contrary, a bank that welds a community together.
Thank you.
(Applause)
Hello everyone.
For several years now I've been collecting stories about Nobodies with extraordinary destiny, men and women we were not told about at school, but whose stories collided with history.
In doing this research, I discovered stories of extraordinary lives like, for example, the story of Tsutomu Yamaguchi.
He is a Japanese businessman who happened to be in Hiroshima in 1945; August 6, 1945 more exactly, which was not the best day to be in Hiroshima, since it was on that day that an atomic bomb fell on the city, inadvertently killing 140,000 victims.
70% of the buildings were destroyed.
But Tsutomu managed to take shelter, and he survived.
He suffered extensive burns, but he was still fit enough to go back home three days later, and then go back to work. And to him, home was in Nagasaki.
(Laughs) So he goes back to the office, and there, his colleagues badger him with questions on what he saw, since it was the first time any atomic bomb had fallen on civilians.
He explains what happened, the lighting flash, the buildings evaporating in front of his eyes ... Incidentally his boss is quite dubious, because it's quite a far-fetched excuse for not going to work, and at that precise moment, a second atomic bomb falls on Nagasaki, and this time, it kills 70,000 people.
But Tsutomu survives it, and dies 65 years later, in 2010, at the age of 93.
He is the only person acknowledged by the Japanese government as having survived two atomic bombs.
That's exactly the kind of story I like to discover and share with people. When I was transcribing these stories, I realized that there was some common thread, of people, for example, who changed the world just because they dared to act or to think differently.
One of my favorite examples is Jadav Payeng.
He was a 16-year-old boy in 1979, he lived near the Brahmaputra River in India.
One day, he was shocked by a terrible scene: he sees hundreds of dead reptiles on a sandbank on the river.
He decides to do something about it because this vision moves him deeply.
He contacts the forest authorities but they explain to him that there is nothing much to do because the sandbank is too dry, too sterile, and no tree can grow there.
So he says he's still going to try.
So he begins to plant bamboos on this sandbank.
After a few years of hard work, where there was nothing at all, he managed to grow a bamboo plantation.
And since it works pretty well, he decides to plant real trees.
And ten years later, he created a forest where there was nothing at all a few years before, where animals will come to find shelter, even some endangered species; rhinos, tigers. Today, more than 30 years after he started his work, Jadav has managed to create a 500-hectare jungle, bigger than Central Park. Today, this jungle accommodates 100 elephants every year and it was by tracking them that the Ministry of Forests discovered Jadav's work.
They eventually started to help him in 2008.
Jadav's idea was crazy but it was a good one.
And it ended up being supported.
Sometimes it takes time.
Jadav had a huge impact on the environment. Among these forgotten heroes of history, some have sometimes saved thousands of people.
This is particularly the case with Ignace Semmelweis.
He was a Hungarian doctor who lived in the 19th century, and you should know that back then, women might prefer to give birth in the street rather than in the hospital because their mortality rate was around 20% in hospitals.
The culprit was an infectious disease, puerperal fever, and it was thought at the time that it was incurable.
It was taken for granted that one in five women died in childbirth.
That's quite a quota!
And that's where Ignace Semmelweis comes in: in 1846, he is appointed head of a large Austrian clinic and he is determined to eradicate this plague.
He starts to correlate elements and realizes that the mortality rate in his department is directly related to the fact that doctors caring for pregnant women also perform autopsies.
They fiddle with the corpses before tending to delivering women.
You should know that at the time, the concept of microbes does not exist, so the link is not easy to make.
But Ignace has an intuition: he thinks that there must be a kind of cadaverous substance that emanates from the body and that doctors pass it on to laboring women.
He has this revolutionary and crazy idea: he will ask the doctors to wash their hands before examining the patients.
The mortality rate will drop drown from 18 to 1.3%.
It's a huge success, but against all odds, he is putting the scientific
community against him for two reasons: the first reason is that doctors consider that his method is not scientific but rather superstitious, since he does not know exactly why washing hands avoids the disease; and the second reason is by accepting this method, doctors recognize somehow that they have helped killing thousands of patients.
So Ignace is supported by the government, but he is still despised by his colleagues and suffers a lot from this situation.
He will have a nervous breakdown, and he will end his days in a psychiatric hospital.
The case is so unfair that he gave his name to a psychological effect, the Semmelweiss effect, designating the tendency to reject any new idea if it upsets our habits, even if it is supported by facts.
And ironically, a few years later, Ignace Semmelweiss will be avenged by science with the discovery of the existence of microbes.
But Ignace's idea was weird at the time.
Nevertheless, it was a good idea, and it ended up being accepted.
Sometimes it takes time.
The man I'm going to talk about now played an even bigger role as he saved the world.
Stanislav Petrov is a Russian officer you have probably never heard about, but who probably saved your lives.
In 1983, he was assigned to a very important task: he was in charge of the surveillance of Russian airspace so he was responsible for detecting possible US missile attacks.
One day, he watches his screen, and he sees five missiles coming towards Russia. He just has to press a big red button to alert his hierarchy who will send an immediate counterattack and start a world nuclear war.
But he knows that humanity's future depends on his move.
And this makes him hesitate; there is something wrong. There are too few missiles coming up compared to the huge US military arsenal and on top of that, there is a ground radar that does not confirm the observations of the satellite.
So Stanislav decides to tell his superiors that it is a false alarm,
or a bluff, as far as he knows, he couldn't say which.
This is one of the biggest bluffs in history.
History proved him right since it was a bug in the system.
It was a real close call for the end of the world thanks to the small hesitation of a Russian officer.
(Laughter) You might think he was hailed as a hero, but it was not quite the case: he was suspected of treachery and pushed out of the army.
15 years passed before one of his colleagues wrote down what he had witnessed that day and before the story of Stanislas was unveiled to the citizens.
For that, he was bestowed a decoration, and honored by the United Nations.
If you ask him whether he considers himself a hero, he answers that he just did his job.
The quintessence of any hero statement.
(Laughter) Stanislav's idea was risky but it was a good idea that ended up being acknowledged.
Sometimes it takes time.
Like in comics, with Stanislav comes a negative hero, a man who almost destroyed the world all by himself: Thomas Midgley.
He looks pretty cool on this picture.
Thomas Midgley is an American chemist working in 1911 for General Motors. He was working on noisy combustion engines.
While working on this problem, Midgley discovers that by putting lead in gasoline, engines run much more smoothly and quietly.
It's an international success, General Motors will sell gallons of leaded gasoline. But there's just one small problem, that is lead is a violent poison.
So it gets massively spread into the atmosphere.
It is not until the early 2000s that leaded petrol was withdrawn from the market.
Its dangerousness was already known at the time.
Public health is starting to suffer, and even Thomas Migley suffers from side effects. But he washed his hands with his gasoline in front of the journalists to show that it is harmless - he had the sense of marketing.
(Laughter) To make up for that, he decides to dive into another problem: leaking fridges.
At the time, when a fridge was leaking, people would die because there was toxic gas inside the fridge.
So Migley tries to come up with an alternative.
He will create freon, the first CFC, chlorofluorocarbons.
Everything works perfectly well. He inhales freon in front of the press since he is consistent with himself, to show that it's harmless. It was not until the 70s, 30 years after Migley's death, that the real effects of CFCs were known.
A big hole in the ozone layer was found.
Thank you very much, Thomas Migley!
He kind of caused the hole in the ozone layer all by himself.
Migley's ideas seemed good, but they had catastrophic consequences.
And that too, to know it, it sometimes takes time.
We could draw lots of lessons from these stories: the first, if you can unleash a nuclear war, it is better to think first, if you can.
But beyond that, there is the idea that a single person can have a huge impact on the rest of the world without being rich, famous or powerful at first.
It is sometimes enough to dare to think differently.
All these ideas that you prefer to put aside because they are too crazy, too risky or too weird, please give them a chance. If they are good,
time will do them justice.
Thank you.
(Applause)
Being in a couple is about tenderness and loving one another.
You dream of having kids together.
You picture a future filled with laughter and loving embraces.
And then, one day,
you come back down to earth, and that's not exactly how it goes every single time.
One day, with our partner, as with our kids, things are bound to get out of hand.
Sometimes, we overreact.
I could never have imagined having such feelings of violence rise up inside of me towards the people I love most in the world.
I'm a psychotherapist, and, my whole life, I've tried to figure out what makes us behave the way we do.
Why do adults behave in such an over-the-top way?
And why don't children just do as they're asked?
(Laughter) In order to answer these questions, I looked at scientists for my research.
These days, everyone talks about stress.
It was the professor Hans Selye who introduced the concept, in the 1950s, to describe the way the body adapts in response to any kind of stimulation.
Stress is therefore an adaptive response.
To ensure our survival, a little gland in our brain keeps watch, the amygdala.
Since the dawn of time, at the slightest hint of danger, it has set the body's alarm bells ringing, adrenaline, cortisol.
Our body is prepared for fight or flee.
If I can't fight, or flee, I freeze, I play dead, my body goes numb.
Danger, or even frustration, or pressure, can trigger stress in young and older alike.
Stress can be recognized as a physical response, adrenaline, cortisol, coursing through my body, increased heart rate, muscles tensed, jaw clenched, we get the feeling in our arms of wanting to thump and to throw things, our legs want to stamp, to run.
We, as adults, are able to bring this stress response under control.
Though it's not always easy when our partner doesn't tidy up, or a two-year old child doesn't want to put their boots on.
But a child's brain doesn't yet allow them to control this stress.
When our child acts up, everyone always says, "You should set some boundaries!" And we embark upon a struggle
to be the strongest
even if it means we lose our strength along the way because that's what happens.
Fighting to come out on top means that everyone loses.
Sometimes, we think we've managed to get a child to see reason.
Because he stops.
He's not being well-behaved.
He's just... frozen as a reaction to stress.
Setting boundaries is like putting a lid on boiling milk.
It boils over, all the same.
It must be held firmly.
You have to clean up around it.
No question of simply watching the milk boil over without doing anything.
And what if I turned off the gas?
I'm going to tell you about how, one day, my mother managed to turn off the gas when I'd boiled over.
I was 13 years old.
I slapped my mother.
That's right, I slapped my mother.
The action wasn't entirely voluntary.
And she understood that.
Of course, at the time, she slapped me back.
But, after that knee-jerk reaction, she came to talk to me about it.
To make me talk about it.
She knew that when a child goes to the doctor to have an injection, when they get home, all they want to do is to give everyone else injections.
They're on the safe side of the syringe.
My mother wanted to know where that slap came from.
I was on my way back from a friend's house, and I told my mother about the scene that had shaken me up.
My friend had had a huge fight with her mother, who had slapped her, and my friend had slapped her back.
I was transfixed.
I didn't understand.
I made my way home on autopilot.
Unable to think, to feel, to speak, to even understand what was going on inside of me, until I saw my mother.
At that moment, getting back to my mother, my safety net, it was as if my body had been given permission to come out of its frozen state.
And then, the tension, pent up inside since witnessing the slapping at my friend's house, came rushing back up to the surface.
Adrenaline, cortisol, my body was waking up.
My muscles tightening, I started to feel like I was getting angrier and angrier and more and more tense.
As I'd started feeling this aggression since seeing my mother, I thought it was because of her.
I got into a fight with her over next to nothing.
And then, my body did something that stunned me.
It reenacted the slap.
My brain, unable to find the words to explain things to my mother, had led my body to show my mother the slap that had upset me so.
So that she would help me.
And she did help me.
She helped me to put my feelings into words.
She helped me to turn off the gas under the milk that was boiling inside of me.
I could trust her.
Another situation.
In the street, a mother and her child.
The child is walking quietly down the street.
There's traffic, and the mother gets annoyed and says, "Hold my hand right now!"
The child avoids holding his mother's hand and moves away.
To the child, avoidance isn't a conscious decision.
It's an autonomic stress response.
Our stress puts stress on our children, and triggers a biological reaction in their brain that disconnects the outer layers of their brain.
Sometimes, we ask a child who is acting up to think on their behaviour, to little effect.
Obviously, since their brain is no longer connected.
How can we reconnect our children's brains?
How can we shut off the stress circuit?
That's where the white knight, oxytocin, comes in.
Oxytocin, the hormone of love, of relationships, the hormone that helps to reduce this stress.
Touching a child,
looking at them lovingly,
communicating warmly with them, helps them to fully recover their brain, and to manage stress.
That's what my mother did with me.
"But isn't that rewarding unacceptable behavior?"
some would say.
Most of us have learned to think of love as a reward.
Neuroscience has shown that showing our children love triggers the release of oxytocin, increases the number of oxytocin receptors in the brain, reduces stress hormones, boosts the immune system, and develops neuronal circuits in the prefrontal area of the brain.
The prefrontal area of the brain, which allows us to feel empathy, enables self-control, helps us to regulate our emotions, anticipation, the ability to understand and identify the impact of our actions, responsibility, that's the kind of brain we want our children to develop.
Through a gesture, a smile, a show of attentiveness, we are preparing our children for happiness.
We are literally equipping them to handle stress.
We are helping them to learn not to overreact, not to overreact later on when they have children of their own.
Love is the fuel we need to manage stress.
Specifically speaking, I want to share with you a little technique we've developed, my partner and I.
Picture the scenario, it's 7 p.m., I've been with the kids all day, he's running slightly late, and gets home having forgotten to do the shopping I asked him to do.
Then I freak out.
My other half feels guilty.
He sits down in front of the television or goes off to the pharmacy.
That's normal; men aren't allowed
to hurt women.
He can't fight. He flees.
But if he goes back out to do the shopping I asked him to do, that's totally out of line.
Because, really, the shopping, the pharmacy, was just an excuse.
What I needed him to do was to hold me.
Why didn't I just ask him?
Clearly, it doesn't make sense to yell at him.
But, even so, you have to see that it makes sense.
I feel helpless, powerless, all day long.
So I have to summon up a little power, act tough, pull myself together, for one thing at least.
So I shout, I attack, I'm under stress.
That's where our technique comes in.
He approaches me when I'm getting all worked up, and takes me gently in his arms.
He says to me,
"There you go. There you go."
Well, then, I push him away, obviously.
Because that would be too easy.
(Laughter) And then I'm not sure if he'd still love me if I were stronger and without flaws.
It's amazing when you think about it.
I attack him or I push him away, so that he will love me.
Then I say to him, "Cut it out! Can't you see
I've got stuff to do?
And that's all you can think about!"
(Laughter) I flee, because I can't attack anymore.
I'm still under stress.
If he holds me for seven seconds, oxytocin starts to flood my brain.
I feel better.
The oxytocin triggers feelings of well-being, confidence, kind thoughts towards others.
After 20 seconds, I feel much better.
I start to unwind, and cry on his shoulder.
Of course, that doesn't work for everybody.
Sometimes, certain people really can't stand being held.
The kind of people who, when they were children, experienced a great deal of rejection by their own parents.
They have fewer oxytocin receptors.
They have a hyperactive stress circuit, and are highly impulsive.
But that can be repaired, with love.
Love is also highly effective with our children.
Love is also highly effective with our children.
Remember the milk?
Love is a super-effective way to turn off the gas.
The next time you feel a power struggle developing, you will have something new to try out, I breathe, I reconnect with the love I feel for my child, and I take them in my arms.
At the very least, I let them see the affection in my eyes.
He might not calm down straight away.
He may need to release a little more tension first.
The most important thing is to stay connected to one another.
When we are connected, I reconnect his brain.
I recover mine, and I regain the ability, in the street, to calmly give the command,
"Hold my hand in the street."
And to send my other half a text containing a single word, "Pharmacy."
Responding with love, when the going gets tough, takes care and effort that is very soon rewarded.
It's a huge time saver.
And what if you topped up your anti-stress fuel tank
first thing each day? What if you prepared in advance, to better face the day ahead?
What if five minutes of tender loving care every morning changed your life?
It's worth a try!
Thank you.
(Applause)
"Hey Mom, will I have long and smooth hair like Stephanie one day?
"My daughter, you are black.
You have frizzy hair, and you'll have it for your whole life."
Following my mother's answer, I had terrible fits of crying.
I was seven years old.
I wanted to integrate into the dominant group.
My blond classmates with smooth hair, I had understood that they represented the norm.
How does one live with frizzy or curly hair in a society with standards?
Do we really give ourselves the freedom to live our singularities?
Well, this is the story of my life.
I became aware that I am different the day others hurled at me in the school yard, "F***g darkie!"
Do you recall - at least some of you - this cartoon that featured "Darkie," a stupid black cow who was spending her time complaining to her doctor,
"Hello, Doctor? I don't feel well."

I hated that cartoon.
It's true, at the time, there were so few images that I could latch on to, so few positive images in the media.
So, things accumulated in my head. In the school yard, all the mockery, the daily teasing where people would grab my hair without my permission, where they would compare it to lamb's wool, well, all of this grew into something big inside my head. And all these negative representations of me, I made them my own.
They became my truth.
Do you know what we mean by "cognitive bias"?
It's a thought process that creates a deviation in judgment.
In fact, roughly speaking, it is when we appropriate a prejudice by virtue of being associated with it. And psychologists say that five positive actions are needed to enable the cancellation of one insult or one malicious gesture and bring things back into balance.
So in the end, I need five times the dose of love or empathy to be able to make things right in my head again..
You can imagine how quickly prejudice spread: First, in a school yard, then at university, and then in the workplace.
Now on the scale of an entire society, the whole thing becomes immediately very heavy.
Indeed, both images and words are building identities, the identity of an individual - and even more so that of a child - because they nourish our imagination and create our reference points.
Back then, my reference points, my role models, well, they were my Barbie dolls.
They looked a lot like me,
don"t you think? With their long smooth blond hair and their superb blue eyes ... I was very fond of my dolls
and spent hours playing with them.
Also, on the screen, there was Empress Sissi played by Romy Schneider.
How magnificent is Sissy!
And at the root of all this, back then, was of course, Cinderella.
As it was for many little girls, she made me dream.
We were still a long way away from the superb Afro, Pam Grier in "Coffy," whom I discovered much later.
So yes, the norm can make us dream, but it can also lead us to a place of non-being, and maintain us in the illusion that we are all equal, all brothers, and that the price of our freedom resides in our capacity to deny our singularities and level our differences.
"Normal" revealed itself to me when I was seven years old bearing insults in the school yard.
And then, during the seven years that followed, well, I was in a zone of total alienation where ultimately goodness, success, beauty, were this "other" I will never attain.
Then at 14, after constantly putting pressure on our mom, my sister and I got our hair straightened for the first time.
Yes!
At last I achieved beauty.
Well that's what I thought and felt, and it was enormous.
To describe how it was, it was the same haircut that Michael Jackson had back then, curly hair like this, a type of perm with big loose curls.
Anyway, I thought it was wonderful ... ... until my hair fell out some months later.
I could have said to myself, "The dream is over. Enough!", but the social pressure, people's glances, and the fact that I had touched upon this ... (Laughing) "extreme" beauty, well, I had to go back to it.
So I let my hair grow for a while and then I had it straightened again.
And then, I lost my hair again. And I straightened it again, but this time, I still remember the terrible feeling of my scalp burning because the hairdresser had left the product in 45 minutes instead of 20.
"Yes, Miss, it's because your hair is so frizzy, if you want results, you have to be patient."
Now the result was that my scalp was indeed burned. And I gathered clumps of my hair in my hands.
I am 15,
I shave my head,
and soon again, I find myself with short frizzy hair, a far cry from what I viewed as beauty at the time.
Finally, that day, I had to face it.
I had to drop this mask, this "me" I pretended to be, and accept that my hair always grows towards the sun, and that my hair undoubtedly had something to tell me.
So I took a break.
I did some research. And I uncovered my history.
I discovered that my ancestors were not the Gauls unlike what I had learned at school.
Nope!
They were in fact Africans, with a very rich history that began well before slavery, with queens, kings and kingdoms.
I read a lot.
I read Cheikh Anta Diop.
I read Aimé Césaire, Frantz Fanon, Malcolm X, Martin Luther King and so many others.
I was building my own truth.
Finally, I was embodying my own identity.
So ...
Well, what I showed off, now that I had declared my natural frizzy hair to the world, I was well aware that it was annoying people.
"You didn't do your hair, did you?"
"Of course I did. That's how
my hair grows naturally."
Actually, our hair challenges people.
It has always done so since ancient Egypt, including China, the United States, France.
Hair always carries a political message.
In China, for example, Prince Siddhârtha Gautama cut his hair in order to enter the spiritual world and become Buddha.
In the 1920s, having a boyish cut was a must for women because it was their way of expressing their social rebellion.
More recently, Christiane Taubira in France, or Solange Knowles, Lupita Nyong'o in the United States, wear their frizzy hair as an expression of their freedom.
So in 2001, willing to break the rules in matters of beauty and to propose alternatives, I founded with my sister an event called "Boucles d'Ébène," the first platform in France that celebrates frizzy, curly and looped hair in their natural state.
In the beginning, we numbered 70, and then 200.
And six years later, we were 10,000.
The market at the time didn't really take notice.
Yet, with the work of sociologist Juliette Smeralda and the first exhibition of Boucles d'Ébène in 2005, we provided an impetus for self-awareness, a movement promoting a return to the natural.
In the end, this movement grew,
and it went global, international.
It is commonly known as "the nappy movement."
Today, it has become a veritable ecosystem of its own, with its influencers.
Other events have been created subsequently, as well as products and brands.
In 2014, l'Oréal purchased the best brand of the natural trend in the US, Carol's Daughter, that was worth 27 million dollars back then ...
This tells you something!
Well, there has been some progress.
Yet ...
Yet, I am a mother today.
I am a mom, and I wonder about the way the Republic instills fraternity in its children, when I can still read today in a French hair styling manual that frizzy hair is a congenital or hereditary disorder, and it is dealt with in the chapter about abnormalities.
I wonder, indeed, when even today so-called "traditional" hairstylists train only on one type of hair, the very one that I dreamed of for many years, the smooth Caucasian hair.
So, most recently, I created a hair salon, "Boucles d'Ébène Studio", that caters to all hair types and particularly natural curls.
We train hair professionals, and we also communicate to parents and children the secrets of this hair to create a little more equality in the end.
And I am part of a more global movement that has projects in the United States, such as Afro Art that showcases children with frizzy hair to validate them.
Now it's coming along, yes.
But for a moment, last week, I thought that everything I had established had come to nothing when my daughter said to me, "You know what, Mum? I really wish I could be White with blue eyes and smooth hair." (Sigh)
At that point, I took a deep breath, and I asked her why.
"Because it's beautiful, Mum!"
How to compete with everything she experiences at school without me?
Yet I know that the seed I have sown and water every day with a lot of love and self-esteem, will end up growing.
And one day, she will tell, she will proclaim to the world her freedom.
She will declare who she is without artifice, without theatricality.
What if, in the end, changing the world and creating more harmony was within everyone's grasp,
and was simply a matter of teaching that differences are treasures and allow the creation of something much greater?
I act daily in that direction.
And you?
How are you going to create more humanity and allow your neighbours, your colleagues, your friends, to live their uniqueness?
Try to have the courage to be.
Try simply love.
I am Aline Tacite.
Thank you for listening.
(Applause)
Good evening.
Tonight I would like to talk to you about landscapes and especially about the landscapes in which we live our lives, in which we work or move through every day and which are, at this very moment, being created, transformed or destroyed.
These constantly changing areas are what I call the "contemporary landscape," and for the last decade, they have been at the heart of my photographic work.
It interests me because we live in it. Since we have built it, it ends up saying more about us than about itself. It enables us to see how our society is changing and almost gives us a glimpse of our future identity.
That's what I try to show in my projects, in my images, and it's what I would like to share with you. First by trying to define this landscape and to see what it can allow us to learn about ourselves.
Then by exploring how we can represent it and see it with fresh eyes.
To look at this landscape, really, it took some time at first to see it, to understand it.
And 10 years ago, when I started at the Art School in Orléans, I began to create my own definition of what a landscape is.
At the beginning, for me, a landscape was that.
This canvas by Le Lorrain, painted in the 17th century - incidentally not long after the word "landscape" first appeared - illustrates the dictionary definition of a landscape perfectly.
It is actually two things: first, it's an objective reality, that of a limited part of our world that is presented to and pre-exists our act of looking.
It's also a subjective representation, a painting, a work that the artist decided to make by choosing the boundaries of the space, the technique and the emotion that he or she wants to transmit to us.
Here, Le Lorrain chose to paint a pastoral scene, one that is peaceful and particularly beautiful at nightfall, and he painted it as precisely as possible, in a naturalist way.
He was in tune with his time, one in which a landscape was an aesthetic object, was "what is worthy of being painted."
A landscape is also that.
200 years later, this canvas by Turner seems to have nothing in common with the preceding painting despite the fact that the scene it illustrates is essentially the same:
a countryside, some water, some animals, low-angled light.
But Turner did not want to represent the beautiful or to transcribe it precisely. He was interested in the movement of particles and matter in the air.
He thus tells us that a landscape can also be a theater for observing something totally different from a landscape, that it can become a model that conveys the subject the artist wants to address.
Turner shows us that there is no such thing as the truth of a landscape; instead there are as many truths as there are eyes, your eyes, to see them and as there are artists to represent them.
So, since the end of the 19th century, that is what a landscape has also become.
Although painters in the West followed Turner and gradually turned to abstract art, photography, with its precision, revolutionized naturalist representation, as in, for example, this Ansel Adams photo from the first half of the 20th century.
In Adams' work, there is all the intention, composition and light that we find in a painting by Le Lorrain.
I'll pause here for a moment because the imagery of Le Lorrain or Adams is essential: it's what we all have in our minds unconsciously, what we grew up with, it's our frame of reference.
We can only see a real landscape because we have learned to see a landscape that has been depicted.
This is why, when we see a lake, when we visit rural areas, the seaside or the mountains, no one ever doubts that what we are seeing is a landscape, because for centuries in Western art, these kinds of places have been the subject of landscape paintings, and these representations have shaped our own mental constructs of the scenery.
In any case, photography revolutionized how we document our world, how we deal with what happens, and this also takes place in landscape photography from the '50s or for example here, in this Lewis Baltz from the '60s-'70s.
During that period, economic liberalism was inflicting major societal changes, changes that were exemplified first in our landscapes.
For the first time, a "way of life" was being universally applied to the land, and we are all quite familiar now with the new structures that sprang up on a massive scale: suburban settlements and housing complexes, storage and transportation platforms, and commercial and industrial zones.
Basically, the items that, for the last three or four decades, have totally transformed the horizons of our cities.
Then, in the '80s, the geographer Jackson sketched out a picture of these changes, sizing them up by observing them through the lens of the vernacular.
The vernacular is everything specific to a given, identified region.
It also includes language, customs, art or food. Around here, in "the sticks," the vernacular is the "chti" dialect, bricks and belfries, beer and maroilles cheese. And this also applies to the surrounding landscape.
The vernacular is how the question of identity is asked - the question of the cultural, historical and interpersonal connections that the landscape maintains with the era and the community that lives there.
We see that it isn't simple to define what a landscape is, but doing this teaches us a lot about ourselves.
This is an extremely complex piece of anthropological data because, as we have just seen, it involves all sorts of issues that are not only political, demographic, economic but also historical, cultural and related to identity.
In this light, how is it possible to represent a landscape that incorporates all these problems and components?
That is what I was asking myself as I began my studies at the Beaux-Arts, especially when I started photography with a project on the farmlands in Beauce.
What struck me then was the surgical precision of the way the land was worked.
I found patterns in the ground that were as precise as textiles, with multiplications and repetitions of textures in fractal form. Essentially, an almost obligatory ubiquity of technology, even in the most ordinary places.
On the ground, with my camera, I very quickly found myself unable to transcribe what I saw in its totality.
To do that, I had to take a step back, get some distance, and that is how I decided to try taking photos from aboard small airplanes.
In 2009, I finished my "Occupied Territories" collection on the vernacular landscapes of the Loire Valley.
I had wanted to bring the familiar images we all have of this region - which involve Renaissance chateaus, vineyards and the "Garden of France" - face to face with the reality of the contemporary landscape I found there.
My initial idea had been to take a zenithal perspective in order to shed light on this, building precision that I had seen on the ground so that they would seem like plans that had been drawn up and which ended up corresponding perfectly to what we expected.
It took nearly two years for my eyes to adjust, to circumscribe the scenery into confined spaces and to take photos successfully.
As you can imagine, an airplane is not exactly the most practical tool for taking aerial photos. It moves around fast and shakes, making you sick, but it has the advantage of being affordable. At about 100 euros an hour, it's four or five times less expensive than a helicopter, and that gave me the financial freedom to go back to each site quite a few times and follow how it changed, and polish my composition.
And these were images that I could not have taken with a drone, which was impossible for technical reasons involving altitude, weight and distance, but even more so because to compose these kinds of images, which are both precise and abstract, you truly have to see the landscape with your eyes, not on a screen.
In any case, the project cost me 3,000 euros over two years,
to give you a sense of its scope, which is about the same as the price of a single day in a studio in Paris for a fashion photo shoot, which puts a bit of perspective on things. In 2010, I began to think about finding a more defined and personal approach to my work.
So, I decided to remove the documentary aspect from my images in order to distance myself from what had been happening in aerial photography up to that point, and also to give myself the freedom to express my own pictorial influences.
To that end, I began to force myself to follow a precise working procedure, one that I still use today and which helps me to create coherent series.
The first step is choosing the territory.
For three to six months, I undertake documentary research, looking for development projects and learning about the issues and dynamics specific to the territory by going through the local media, the newsletters put out by metro areas.
This research suggests a theme: In 2010-2011, I worked in the Angers area, focusing on migration of economic activity between the Loire and the A85 highway, which had just been built.
In 2012-2013, I worked in the Paris area on the idea of the urban-rural boundary.
And in 2014-2015, I completed a project on the repurposing of industrial sites in the Eurometropolis of Lille-Courtrai.
In each of these areas, I would identify around 40 places that I had never seen before and never visited, but which were of interest to, meaningful and consistent with my theme and my research on the landscape.
I then did flyovers of all these sites, and you can see the GPS tracks here.
I flew over each site 10 to 12 times over 2 years - two years being the minimum time needed to be sure to have several days of good weather in the North. Sadly ... (Applause) I then flew over each territory at the same altitude - 1,500 feet or about 450 meters - using the same fixed lens so that each landscape, each image would always have the same scale.
Finally, I always shot the photos at the same time, around noon, when the sunlight could not be used to beautify the images, such as, for example, in Le Lorrain's use, but instead crushed the colors, canceled out the depth and flattened the scenery.
The resulting flatness allowed me to deliver a particularly objective vision of the landscape.
Thus through the choice of locations and the use of this shooting procedure, I came to have an approach, my own approach to representing the landscape, while incorporating all the issues and components that shape it.
And despite all this, the result converges on a high degree of abstraction.
The question of the gaze comes in here, and its interplay with abstraction has become a real terrain of conceptual and artistic experimentation for me.
Artistic first, because abstraction allowed me to express the pictorial influences I've mentioned from the abstract expressionism of painters such as Soulages, Noland, Newmann, De Staël, Tàpies. Perhaps even Rothko, like here, for example.
Then conceptually, abstraction proves to be very rich in its dialogues with both photography and landscapes.
None of these images has been touched up; nothing has been added or removed.
Yet when we see them for the first time, we first think of drawings or paintings rather than of photos.
Abstraction thus allows us to question the extent to which the medium of photography is able to transcribe the real because here it is hard to tell whether what we see is, in fact, real.
When Damien Selosse asked me to speak at this TEDx, he told me, "What I like about your images is that they no longer resemble landscapes."
And it's true that while it's trying to describe what we do see, we are almost unable to understand it.
Abstraction also leads us to wonder whether the real itself is able to make sense.
We can even ask ourselves if all these landscapes, if this abandoned parking lot with that pile of dirt still fall within any law of identity.
I spoke of the vernacular earlier.
Here, it is impossible to tell if we are in Chicago, Shanghai or Rio.
Even though we are in Villeneuve d’Ascq, just five kilometers from here.
Or here we are in Croix: a roof with black patches.
And here we are north of Courtrai, at a coal storage yard with some lime.
Here we could think we are in the Sahara, but it's a limestone quarry south of Paris.
Can you guess what this is?
If I tell you it's nearby Angers, that won't help much.
And for me too, it took a long time to understand that, among other things, this track was being used by trucks to practice going around traffic circles.
(Laughter) Incidentally, I find these images even more interesting because they weren't taken in Chicago or Shanghai, where it would be less surprising.
That's why I keep working in very small regions that have strong identities and where we would not expect to find these kinds of places.
A minute ago, I said there is no one "truth of a landscape," but there are trends that can be observed, and globalization is one of the most prominent.
We develop our land today in terms of identical forms and schemas, for identical purposes and uses.
The landscape is built to respond to issues involving emergencies, profitability and efficiency, and there is no longer time for worrying about the historical or cultural specificities of the people who live within it.
It's as if the vernacular is no longer relevant. And I don't know if you've noticed this, but there's nobody in any of these photos.
The places seem deserted, empty, dehumanized.
People are absent but also present everywhere.
While it is certainly willful on my part, this allows me to highlight a paradox that has crept into the landscape.
The primary objective of most of the places that we build today is to bring together the largest possible number of people in spaces where we go to be alone:
parking lots, shopping malls, waiting areas, highways, subways, railways. It makes you wonder whether our modern world is able to create ways for us to live together in harmony.
Further when we look at a photo like this, the communal aspect doesn't exactly leap out at us.
You might say it's not even a landscape.
Many words could come to mind to describe what we see, none of them really belongs to the vocabulary of landscapes.
It's as if this place without an identity, this wasteland with its puddles of black water located near Tournai has been stripped of its privileges, as if it only exists in its demise or is noticed only in its absence from the landscape.
Don't misunderstand this - what I'm saying is not a judgment. It's simply the reality of a time that has sped up, a time whose effects on the landscape are even more complex for us to grasp.
We still haven't taken the time to understand and see this world that surrounds us, which will have a different appearance tomorrow.
So, how can we represent this world?
How can we look at it with fresh eyes?
There's no good answer to these questions, but what this image tells us is that pictorial abstraction may well be the only possible aim if we want to represent and look at a world that has itself become abstract.
Not abstract in its essence, for there is nothing more concrete than these bands of asphalt on the ground, but abstract in our view of them.
I explained earlier that the landscape that we see, that we understand is more like something from Le Lorrain or Adams.
Yet these places can be found everywhere around us, throughout our daily lives, all around our cities.
But we don't see them. It's as if they are blotted out of our vision as soon as they emerge on our horizon.
The frame of reference that would let us to accept them remains to be created. The semantics have yet to be invented.
In response to this, I've chosen to propose abstract photographic images, especially to avoid a nihilistic or catastrophic vision of our world.
In escaping from the documentary register, these photos are not intended to support any political project or to illustrate any activist position.
On the contrary, they do not prescribe any morality and therefore let each viewer have a completely autonomous reading of the work, his or her own vision of the landscape.
You can choose to remain in the fantasy or in a pictorial approach, and that's perfectly fine: to see Lego bricks in this gravel storage near Hénin-Beaumont or some models or a board game in this construction site near Lens.
It's also possible to take the time, and we have less and less time with images, the time to find the clues hidden within them - a creased tarp, a forgotten pallet, a tread-mark of a tractor - which, bit by bit, allow us, in our minds, to rebuild these images from our familiar point of view and, as a result, to decipher for ourselves what we are seeing.
The message that emerges from this, whatever it may be - that's not what's important, at least for me - this message will be even more powerful because it belongs to us, it belongs to you, completely.
That, perhaps, may be the only goal of my work: to transfigure the landscape in order to shift our vision and to present a world that is in continual motion, a world that is increasingly invisible because it is increasingly abstract.
And to change this world, to recover a desire for architecture, for unity and for harmonious social life, we have to begin by accepting what it really is, by allowing ourselves to see it.
For you, just like for me, seeing the landscape becomes almost a form of introspection. It is, in any case and more than ever, a true exercise in sincerity.
Thank you.
(Applause)
I have some good news for you, since tonight's topic is optimism.
In a few minutes, you can go get a drink.
Stay strong!
So, when I was asked to come and talk tonight at this TEDx, I was really happy, and I thought, "Great, me too,
I can do what the other TED speakers do. I can talk with passion about a passionate topic, make you cry, move you." And at the end, I imagined a vibrant standing ovation; it was perfect!
I'd forgotten just one little detail: I don't have a passion. (Laughter) It's a bit of a problem if you want to do a passionate TEDx.
And when they confirmed that I was coming, I thought, "That's what I'll talk about: not having a passion. That it's been ruining my life for a long time; that'll be my TED topic!"
At the same time, it's a complicated topic.
How many of you can tell me, honestly, that they have finally found their path?
Finally found their passion?
Not many, right? The rest of you, are you alright?
Are you doing OK?
My goal for tonight is for all those who, like me, struggled with not having a passion, leave here with a smile.
Because my smile, I lost it for a long time, while looking for my passion.
For years, I was convinced that I would also find my passion.
And whenever I thought about the big questions, I asked the people around me what I could do, and they always gave me that piece of advice that we all know, that someone has - no doubt - given you, "Hey, you just need to find your passion!"
Has this advice ever helped you in any way?
Not me.
I went on Amazon thinking that I'd find answers in a book.
So I searched and found 2,000 books.
2,000 books that explain how to find your passion.
Of course, when you see this, it means there's something to this passion thing.
And when those 2,000 books aren't brain washing us, it's Steve Jobs, you remember, who inspired thousands with his famous "Follow Your Passion!"
When the guy who created Apple gives you a piece of advice, you think, "I'll listen to him."
That's what I did, I listened to Steve Jobs!
And I started searching for my passion, too!
And I didn't find it.
So I started to think there was something wrong with me in comparison with those people who are successful,
those people who rub their passion into your face, "I'm passionate about brand content, I'm passionate about design. I'm passionate about everything!"
It feels like they succeed because they are passionate.
And me, as I was passionate about nothing, I thought that I would fail at life.
Obviously.
And I really didn't want to fail at life!
So I started to search for my passion.
Like a madman, like a soldier... (Laughter) Lara!
(Laughter) (Applause) Thank you!
It became an obsession.
So to find this passion, I tried a few things.
I set up a business, and thought,
"That's it! I've found it!"
But no.
I did some financial communication, consulting, and thought, "I have my thing, finally!"
But no.
I did some parachuting, diving, martial arts.
Every time, I thought, "That's it, OK, I have my thing."
But I didn't, every time.
I wrote books, I set up businesses.
Every time, I really felt I'd finally found my thing, that I could flaunt my passion, that I would succeed.
But every time, it would collapse like a souffle.
And actually, this problem is that every time, I thought, in front of clients, "Who am I, really?"
And professionally, it started to pose consistency problems, because we live in a world that likes experts.
An expert has a passion, he performs, he can be put in a box.
And I didn't fit in any boxes.
On the contrary, people would say that I was a jack of all trades, a little wayward, with little focus, inconsistent.
Has anybody ever said this about you?
It hurts when you spend your days and nights trying to find focus!
It hurt me.
So, after four years five years of hard work, asking myself what my passion was, I finally had an epiphany, finally!
I don't have a passion!
(Laughter) And I probably never will.
And it doesn't matter!
And if you don't have one, it doesn't matter!
You won't be fail at life.
However, what I have understood, because I have experimented, is that we can fail at life searching for a nonexistent passion.
That's what I did.
And it's what I want to spare you from, this evening, by trying, for a few minutes to give you some of the tips that I picked up during these difficult years.
One of the first things I understood, was that, actually, for those who are lost and searching for their thing, we can look at life as a blank page.
And on this blank page, you're going to draw.
It's your drawing.
You know those pictures for children with dots they have to connect?
Those sort of things?
Well, imagine that each dot is an experience that you've had,
a professional experience.
If you don't have enough dots, it will never make a shape.
And I've tried joining dots to find a shape, but I didn't have enough dots so I couldn't find a shape.
However, if you have enough dots, you'll end up with a shape, at some point.
What I wanted to say, is that you have to create as many dots as possible, - in all directions even, if possible - you'll see the shape it'll take.
And while you're there, if you can, create dots in every direction, and be inconsistent, don't be too focused, be wayward, because nothing is more boring than a straight line!
The second thing I realized is that this passion thing, finding your passion, is, I think, the most stupid advice ever.
It's stupid because it is based on a hypothesis.
This hypothesis is that we all have, in our personal software, pre-installed at birth, a passion.
It's there.
And then you just need to find it, press on it and bam!
everything will be OK.
It's stupid advice for two reasons. Firstly, I seriously doubt that we are all born with a passion pre-installed in our personal software that you just need to find for everything to be OK.
I'm not convinced.
Which means that if, like me, you don't have a passion pre-installed at birth, - there are some, it happens, "blondes" for example... - well, like me, you'll start to chase it... nothing!
And spend years chasing after nothing, it's annoying!
The second reason why this hypothesis is vicious it simply that once you start firmly believing that somewhere, in time and space, your passionate life exists, from that moment on, daily life, - drinking coffee - becomes absolutely unexciting.
I went through terrible emotions and started to hate every minute of my unexciting life, with the fantasy that one day, everything will be totally awesome!
And the problem, is that, when we're are like this, stuck in this belief that a passion is waiting for us, and that an exciting life is waiting for us outside, well, you waste a lot of time chasing after a pipe dream.
I had no wish to waste time.
I didn't want to fail at life - since I was convinced that I was going to - and to miss out on life, it's a topic that has particularly worried me since I was around 17 years old, precisely 17 years old, since is was at that time that I lost my mother to cancer.
I'm not saying this for the emotional minute of this TEDx, but since that time, I became blisteringly aware that life is distressingly short.
It's very, very short.
It's so short that, to put it another way, we can consider that we all have a stock of time on our shoulders.
And this stock of time is limited.
The problem is we don't know how much is left
and we can never, ever, fill it back up.
Which is just as reassuring, I think, as planning a long road trip, without thinking about how much fuel you'll need. And when we realize this, we realize something really simple: that on this Earth, in your lives, in my life, the most precious resource there is is not petrol, it's not gold; it's time.
You can never, ever, get the 12 minutes - or maybe more - of this talk back.
Never.
And you also won't be able to get the years you spent in a boring life back.
So me, I was blistering aware that I really had to optimize my stock of time, as I don't know what's left.
Each drop of time should be optimized.
So I wanted to really go for it, to succeed.
We all want to succeed, but have you ever asked yourselves, "What does it mean, to succeed?"
In thinking about this day and night, we discover that there is another trap.
I know this because I fell into it yet again.
It's a existential habit, I think.
This trap is to mistake prestige for success.
Prestige is a very powerful force.
An excessively powerful force, that is defined by society, by culture, by our education, your parents, television, advertisements, but not by you.
It's sort of the Dark Side.
It can force you to work, not on something you like but on something you'd like to like.
For example, I can convince myself that I want a bigger salary to buy a bigger car or house.
But this might not even be true, it won't make me happy.
And in this way, it's a very powerful force, I see it a bit like a neon sign, a big and powerful artificial neon sign.
And this light is so powerful that it outshines every other light and blinds us.
A light, to my mind, more important:
is your own little light.
Your own. We all have one.
It took me a long time to realize that it's on this light that we have to focus and not on the light of prestige. Particularly because, if sometimes, the light of success can lead to prestige, by contrast, I am quite convinced that prestige doesn't lead to success.
Because if this was the case, every rich and powerful person on this Earth would all be extremely happy!
I don't think this is what we can see. So, there I was on my existential quest, with the idea that passion is a trap - and I did fall into it - and prestige, is an illusion.
And so I understood what was needed, and this was to focus on success.
The question is how do we have a successful life?
This is a very broad question, highly subjective, but I'm going to suggest a factor that is possibly universal and possibly applies to you and me.
This factor, is not your salary, it's not the size of your house, it's not the size of your car.
The factor of a successful life, for me, is boredom.
Since time is the most precious thing, to waste your stock of time in a life that really bores you, - I don't mean an hour or two - I mean real boredom, structural boredom.
Wasting your stock of time in a life that bores you, it's like throwing gold out the window!
Would you throw gold
out the window? No!
Yet, you know as well as I do, an incredible amount of people, at the office or on the train, who look like people who are truly bored.
Those people are throwing their stock of time out the window as if it was diamonds.
Because they have forgotten that this stock of time is limited.
And our Anglo-Saxon friends - before leaving Europe - they have a word, a word that for me is the exact opposite of boredom; it's the "flow."
Do you know this word: "flow"?
This wonderful feeling of the body and mind being aligned, to lose the sense of time, to lose the sense of space.
You know this feeling.
You've all felt it many times.
Do you know when?
When you were children.
Everyone!
And I am convinced that behind our grown-up looks, behind our suits and ties, our makeup, our responsible facade, is hiding a person who is an expert in going with the flow, who has a PhD in the flow.
This person is the mini you. (Laughter) When I was a mini me, before becoming big, bald, and annoying, when I was a mini me, I spent all my spare time drawing, inventing stories, and I had fun, I loved it, I created my own universes, I was in them all day long!
Do you remember this feeling, how great it was?
It's a fabulous feeling.
That's how I spend all my spare time.
And then, years went by, and little by little, I lost sight of my mini me.
Because I fell into the trap that is passion, and I was blinded by the light of prestige.
So I couldn't see him anymore. And then one day, somewhat by chance, - that's another story - I was asked to write a book.
So I wrote a book, and I wrote this book in 11 days, while I was on holiday, without anyone forcing me to, and I loved it.
I recaptured this flow feeling from when I was small.
I drew, told stories, threw some jokes in, that the editor took out because they were rubbish.
I had a blast, I was like a kid.
I'm telling you this because, after this book, I was invited to conferences.
In life, I hadn't planned on speaking at conferences.
But I thought, "Why not?
It'll be another dot on the page of my life; we'll see if it helps me find a shape."
So I said, "Let's go!"
A business school invited me to a quirky conference on entrepreneurship.
And I had, they told me, "carte Blanche."
I'll let you guess, as soon as they said "carte blanche", who took the reins?
Mini me.
I had a blast, I was like a kid.
I drew, told jokes, made up stories, etc.
I had a blast, and had even more fun speaking at this conference.
I remember the feeling very well.
I was talking to my students: a story that I had invented, showing them some drawings I had done.
And I felt, right at that moment, that feeling of alignment people often talk about.
Right at that moment.
I was doing exactly what I liked to do, what I wanted to do, and what I had to do.
It's really important, because that day, mini me was sitting on my shoulders, and I think - I felt it that way - that I had a sparkle in my eye.
So, it was a really important experience for me.
Because, as I see it in everyday life, there is no such thing as chance, and today, in my professional life, most of what I do, and what I enjoy the most, is speaking at conferences, telling stories, and putting my drawings in the slides.
That's what I enjoy the most.
However, one thing you can't forget about the mini you: is that mini you is a child.
Children are easily scared, and when you doubt something, when you're worried, when you're questioning your responsibilities, etc., for all the mini yous out there, all that are monsters.
Doubt, worry, fear, are monsters.
And every time mini you sees a monster, he disappears back into his cave with your little flame, and we can't see you anymore.
And again the light of prestige dazzles and blinds you.
Me, every time I doubt, worry and am afraid, - it happens - my mini me disappears.
I think that it's your adult duty to fight these monsters to let that mini you exist.
A child won't fight.
It's your duty to protect him, because in return, he'll protect you.
So I would like to leave you with three small things.
The first is: stop, for those who are a little clueless about passion, stop chasing a passion that doesn't exist outside of you.
This passion, is inside you this little flame, it's already inside you.
However, if you want to see it, start by turning off
the light of prestige. This light blinds you, blinds us, and prevents us from seeing what matters: your little flame.
It's the most beautiful thing you have to offer the world, who really needs it. And for this flame to turn on, you need someone who knows how to turn it on to take back the reins: that's mini you. Let him take the reins, for as long as you can, as much as you can, because he knows how to turn it on.
He knows how because every time your eyes sparkle, every time mini you is around, every time you have the flame, your eyes gleam.
And no one can ignore that for long.
Thank you.
(Applause)
Do you like to eat well?
What's "eating well" to you?
For me, it's what delights my taste buds, it's taking care of my health, it's having energy, and it's also togetherness, if possible.
But it's also a constraint.
It demands time,
and it can also demand a budget.
Let's remember that for centuries, eating well meant eating enough.
And it still exists unfortunately.
Today, in industrial countries, shops offer lots of products that are ready to eat. And there is also mass catering.
It's practical when you're busy.
By the way, let me take this opportunity to ask you : Do you know how much fried food we're allowed to eat by week?
Let me help you: one, three or five?
Many, especially teenagers, are surprised to learn that we shouldn't eat more than one portion of fried food a week, not more than one portion of fried food a week.
Eating well, filling your stomach, has become easy, but with what?
So now, myriads of dietary regimens are offered to us.
We know that dietary regimens don't work in the long term.
Dieting means frustration, so it's impossible on a long term basis.
Dieting can mean unbalanced nutrition, therefore it can be dangerous in the long term.
There are also health professionals who help you change your life habits and your eating habits.
And ... ... there's .. ... the Internet.
The Internet gives us tons and tons of information on the microbiota, the acid-base balance, gluten, and lots of others.
Here again, if the diet is unbalanced, it can be dangerous in the long run, even if at first you feel better.
Is it because I chose new foods or because I removed a lot of industrially-made products?
I, myself, have been what they name in English a "healthy".
"Healthy" means "taking care of your health everyday through nutrition."
My family, who were worried about me because maybe I took it a bit too far, did some research. In medical terms, it has a name, "orthorexia," the obsession with eating healthy food.
What I liked about this diet was that I discovered lots of foodstuffs, loads of nuts, peas, loads of roots, sweet potatoes of course, but also manioc, artichockes ... drinks such as kefir.
I continue to share them with those around me.
And I also noticed that offers in shops changed probably because of public demand.
Could this be our power as "consum'actors" that is doing its work?
Further more, national recommendations also are starting to evolve.
Do you know "Manger Bouger", "Five fruits and veggies"?
It's the national nutrition and health plan.
In the 2017-2021 new guidelines, they recommend that we eat a handful of nuts, walnuts, almonds, unsalted of course, every day.
They also recommend that at least twice a week we eat dry vegetables, peas, apricots.
About that, do you know that they have to be soaked in cold water over night, then get rid of the water before cooking them?
It's to remove the phytic acid, an anti-nutrient.
They also recommend to decrease our consumption of red meat and fish.
And the recommendations for dairy products have dropped from three-four... to two.
National recommendations are evolving.
The approach to patients is also evolving.
Four years ago, I trained in patient's therapeutic education.
This approach changed my life.
In this approach, we start with the patients, their point of view, what motivates them.
We are aware of the stages of change.
It's the Prochaska wheel of change.
They may be in "pre-contemplation" where they don't feel concerned.
They may be in "contemplation," in "preparation," in "action" where he is doing, or in "maintenance."
When they're in the maintenance period continuing an action, there are two outcomes: either the patients carry out this new diet daily and succeed, or they fail.
Failure is part of this coaching.
For me, it was very difficult.
It was very difficult to see people who wanted to change their lifestyle habits just couldn't do it.
It was also very difficult for me to realize that some people didn't care.
It was very difficult to realize that some people found that burdensome and were destroying their health by eating carelessly.
What more could I do?
What more could I do?
So, I spoke about it to my friends.
I spoke about it to the associations I go to.
And I spoke about it to Jarry's FabLab.
Have you heard of FabLab?
For those who don't know, Fablabs can be found all over the world.
They are places of exchange where people pool materials, and above all their skills and their ideas for projects on a voluntary basis, of course.
And imagine! A modeler, a graphic artist from the FabLab was interested in my idea: to convey a dietary message in a simple and entertaining way so that learning how to eat well becomes fun.
So we worked on my first project, a "serious game" as they say.
Let me explain.
You have a card game, you can take it anywhere, and you have one mission a day.
The mission is expressed in simple words, accessible to all and a bit humorous.
So we try to carry out this mission.
Was it natural, pleasant, difficult or horrible for you?
So with one mission a day, we are progressing step by step -
one mission a day, if I wish to. It doesn't have to be everyday.
The mission, if you choose to accept it - hmmm, no, not this one, not this one ... This one!
"Don't snack in between meals."
I love this one.
We just have to try, when bringing something to our mouth, to remember to count the number of bites, and instantly, our behavior changes, our attitude changes, it's like magic!
So, step by step, we change our habits through play because finding our diet, the right eating for us, when we know how to organize ourselves, when we enjoy what we eat, and when we keep conviviality, we have everything to gain from it.
Health, breathing, well-being, good spirits, we have everything to gain from it.
Hmm, is that all?
Maybe not all, maybe not the kilos !
Shouldn't it be our responsability to choose the best for our health, for our children, for our island, for our planet? So,
what does "eating well" mean to you?
Me, I have made my choice.
(Applause)
Here we will cover stories of confidence lost and confidence rediscovered.
So in the year 2000 I was very happy.
Having worked in communication for several years, I'd started my own business.
I had a very charismatic partner with human qualities.
We called our business 'Rouge', We were in the business of revolutionary solutions.
And being the business of revolutionary solutions, we liked to dress up in the red army's rags.
And you see that here, even with a ridiculous hat, I was engaged.
Big brands put their trust in us, including Microsoft,
And we grew, we were two, then four, then we were ten, and then 20, 30, 50.
We wanted to grow even more.
And so we did a fundraiser.
But the fundraising collapsed, and we found ourselves in debt, Lots of debt.
So we turbo-charged on tender competition.
This system can be very toxic for advertisement businesses, as it requires working for free without the certainty of results.
We were tired to the point of exhaustion.
and I started to doubt my career. I asked myself: "But what does driving people to consume more really achieve?
What does demanding more and more engagement really achieve, if those subjects are meaningless?"
In 2013, in the swirl of a year of crisis, the business fell into receivership.
As partners, we had invested large amounts of money in the business.
A solution had to be found,
We shopped the market, and approached the third best French group for communication out there.
They were entrepreneurs, they were benevolent, innovative and dynamic, and they wanted us.
We made a deal.
It was fantastic, now we were part of a big group.
It was the dawning of a new era.
And yet, I felt like my world was disintegrating.
Sparks were flying at home.
My family, my partner, it had really knocked my confidence.
I felt worthless.
Then, the world was looking bad too.
I found it tough, I found it unjust.
I found it indecipherable.
It was the dark night of the soul.
And as is often the case when everything is going badly, the people we encounter become the light at the end of the tunnel.
For me, it started with my brother Gilles,
Gilles Malençon, who works as a scriptwriter.
For the needs of a storyline, he had trained in hypnosis. He said to me: "You know, you should think about trying this,
Hypnosis is paying attention to subjectivity."
Subjectivity was something I'd sidelined in my life.
Altered states of consciousness, dreams, emotions, intuitions, the non-verbal.
So I went to train with Jean Dupré and Kévin Finel, the second and third lights in this story, and learned about hypnotic communication.
Or hypnosis in service of techniques of communication.
Here I found myself among many very different people.
there were therapists, students, and coaches, but there were also many negotiators, of all levels.
There were people running start-ups, police officers, trade unionists,
and being here taught me a very important lesson.
It taught me that the world is made up of our perceptions of it.
What I can objectively tell you about objectivity, is that objectivity does not exist, for exactly this reason:
we are subjective.
In fact, hypnosis is a bit like being at the cinema, when you get comfortable.
We watch a film, and regardless of whether or not it's true, we believe in it, and that is what matters.
And just like at the cinema, it would be awful to have to watch the same film over and over, wouldn't it?
In hypnosis, I learned something, that if my representations of the world weren't showing me what I wanted them to, then hey, I am free to change them.
I am free to change them, and we were taught to distinguish between these beliefs, to identify them and retain those that are useful for the self.
Keeping the beliefs that were useful for my self, and changing my representation, I went back over my failure as though it was in a film, and started to bring forward the lighter sides of my story.
And here, a fourth character arrived.
It was still my brother, Gilles, playing the role of rouser of consciousness, he is attracted by slightly bizarre things, and he placed a book in my hands.
This book was about physics.
As you all know, I am a 100% literary person, so physics ...
But still, I read a few pages, and then we decided to go to a talk given by a certain Philippe Guillemant, a researcher at the CNRS.
What he is trying to do is to determine the existence of consciousness
using physics and its tools.
We made it to his talk, but there was no space left. We were very disappointed by this fact. After our long journey, we went to the cafe next to the conference hall and it just so happened that behind us, was a man with a ponytail, and a big hat, and we spoke and got on well with him, and this man turned out to be Philippe Guillemant himself, who not only invited us to watch him speak, but dined with us afterwards.
In the talk, I learned several things.
The first thing that I learned is that what I believe to be emptiness is not in fact empty.
A vacuum is filled with energy.
There is even 10 to the power of 120 times more emptiness inside a vacuum than there is in matter.
So straight away after that, I visualised this vacuum as an ocean, filled with energetic vibrations constantly interacting.
I apologise to the scientists my literary brain is interpreting what I've heard about physics.
What is the nature of these interactions?
In fact, these interactions represent possibilities.
They present all possible possibilities
In fact, what this ocean is filled with is potential events offset by potential anti-events none of which have been realised.
So the vacuum is not really empty, and what has not happened has happened, a little bit.
I find this world really, very strange.
Among Philippe Guillemant's research tools, is the game of snooker.
In fact, he puts together thousands of snooker balls, to calculate their trajectories and collisions, using advanced algorithms.
A little bit like this.
And then, he discovered something.
He discovered that after hundreds of thousands of trajectories determinism gives way to something interesting.
His hypothesis was that the universe - and here the word universe refers to all of the phenomena that surround us and that we cannot perceive - the universe would update itself, to close certain possibilities as and when it is needed, and to open others.
And what would allow the universe to update in this way?
In part, our intentions.
And what are our intentions?
They are our thoughts, and they are our emotions.
So when I set out an intention, I densify its probability of happening.
He has a funny formula for that, he calls it "exciting the void".
So for me, exciting the void to promote the happening of the future ...
As it happens, it seemed to me I'd tried this many times.
I had tried hard, but hadn't had much to show for it.
"Yes," said Guillemant, through the intermediary of his book, we speak virtually through his book, He said: "It's that you haven't really tried, not properly.
Because on the one hand, when we state an intention, if we vibrate with an energy that is different, if you vibrate with an energy of fear, with an energy of anger, or with an energy of sorrow, as all of that relates to energy, you will create more of this same energy.
After declaring your intention, the interesting thing to do consists of letting that intention go.
Because by detaching yourself, you have a chance to see the future, the signs of the future, to watch it come, and the future is made up of synchronicities.
Synchronicities are non-causal coicidences which hold the intention of this universe.
Philippe Guillemant, for example, who appeared behind us in the cafe, the moment that we arrived at his conference, there were no seats left.
Is it the past that creates the present, or is the future that we wish to have that creates the present?
I think that both are true, and everybody here in this room must have their own opinion.
What I can say to you, is that, with these two discoveries, which are hypnosis and the quantum, Simultaneously, I have succeeded both in changing my representations of the past, and creating the energy to redefine my future, as well.
So, finally, how does all of this work?
It works a little bit like a wish list.
I believe that we have all written wish lists to Santa Claus?
Well, what I suggest is that you set out an intention.
Define your future, and make it as amazing as you can possibly hope it to be.
And then visualise it, and visualise it in detail.
And then, once you have visualised it, put it to one side, detach yourself from the results,
and then, look out for the signs of the future as it puts itself before you.
Thank you very much.
(Applause)
I'm very happy to be with you, tonight, here at the Opera Theatre.
I come from Fez, the spiritual and cultural capital of Morocco.
I want to take you there: millions of tourists come to visit it, to discover its old Medina, which has more than 1200 years of history.
But also to discover its ancestral handicrafts: its tanneries, paper mills, potteries and textile production.
Unfortunately, these handicrafts lead to a lot of waste and used water which add to the industrial and domestic waste.
A few years ago, we began to notice the first effects of this pollution.
Most notably on the Sebou River, which is a very important river in Morocco, and particularly in Fez, as it irrigates the crops and is the source of drinking water for the inhabitants and animals in the region.
These craft industries are in large part responsible for the pollution of our environment.
But also each one of us is also, in small part,
because we constantly release into our environment toxic products that contribute to the pollution and may present a danger to our health.
The problem of toxic products - and here I'm talking about synthetic toxic products, from chemical processes, that we know about more or less, but also natural toxic products.
Like, for example, cyanide.
Everyone knows cyanide to some extent. But did you know that bacteria synthesize it, that it can also be found in the seeds of many fruits?
Such as grapes, apples - and it's also present in almonds.
It only takes six milligrams per kilo of cyanide to kill you,
which might well mean, that if one day you eat about fifty almonds, you might well die of cyanide poisoning.
And again, here we have the problem with toxic products: even small quantities, in minute concentrations, have a direct impact on your health.
Some of these products degrade more or less easily, and quickly; whereas others don't degrade at all.
To better understand the concept, imagine I had some plastic bags with me.
Yes, yes, those well-known plastic bags, that you use every day.
They're practical, easy to use, cheap to produce, and seem harmless.
But we're not fooled: we all know that plastic bags need a lot of time to degrade.
Hundreds of years.
That's not really what we want to leave to our children, to the future generation.
That is what got me into action.
It is with respect to this that I formed my thesis subject,
together with a few questions.
How can I play my part in the battle against the pollution of my environment?
How can we stop so many products accumulating? How can we get rid of them?
The conventional solution would be treatment plants,
but these plants have their limits.
There are malfunctions,
more and more every year.
Why are there these malfunctions?
For many reasons, but in most cases, it's because of water, which is either in large quantity, as for example after a flood, or is too polluted.
In both cases, this water passes through several filters, to remove the largest particles.
I'm thinking of tyres, shoes, those well-known plastic bags.
After that, it's left to settle, so that the smallest particles settle out under gravity.
Finally, we have to get rid of all the tiny particles: those invisible to the naked eye, the microorganisms, the heavy metals, the toxic products.
And we invariably add chlorine to this water.
And if necessary, other detergents, chemical products, so that in the end, the problem is not solved, it is merely contained.
Just as we have plastic bags floating about everywhere, we accumulate chemical products in our water.
The result is that we're surrounded, whether we pollute or whether we depollute, by toxic products.
But can we get out of this vicious circle?
That is the main subject of my research.
My solution: to look for, taking inspiration from nature, an alternative to these toxic products.
Because, yes, if we start out with products that degrade easily, we will have less pollution and therefore require less effort to clean up.
To find, therefore, an alternative to these toxic products, so that craftsmen and industry can continue to produce, can continue to use these industrial processes, that work so well,
without having this accumulation of products and so much pollution.
These processes used by the crafts and by industry are extreme.
They are aggressive processes
in terms of temperature, in terms of media, which can be saline, alkaline or acid.
With my wanting to be inspired by nature, you've every right to say to me, today: "But Leila, what organism is able to live in such conditions?
In such severe conditions?"
That's a whizz, because, in nature, there are microorganisms able to survive in such unimaginable conditions.
We call these microorganisms "halophilic".
And for my research, I've focused on bacteria, halophiles, therefore, that survive in very high concentrations of salt. There are even some that need salt to live, to develop, to grow.
And, furthermore, being so special in themselves, these bacteria synthesize enzymes.
An enzyme, that's a big molecule that degrades all sorts of products.
Even us, we synthesize enzymes.
In our mouths, they help us to degrade food, but also in our stomachs, they help us to digest better.
These enzymes could be used everywhere, because the interest in these enzymes is that, for one, they're active in these conditions, like the halophilic bacteria, withstanding these extreme conditions,
and for another, that they degrade easily and don't accumulate.
And the cherry on the cake: these enzymes, when they are suitably conditioned, are reusable.
They're therefore perfect candidates for this kind of job, which was above all to do with toxic products.
But don't rush yet.
We need to make sure everything works, we need to ask the right questions, to be able to find the right bacteria and enzymes.
And, especially, to think about the consequences.
So, a good bacteria, what is it?
First of all, it's a non-pathogenic bacteria: it should have no impact on your health.
It should be effective, too, so that industry can use it in their processes.
And lastly, the enzymes that it synthesizes must be able to perform well in these processes too.
Where are they to be found?
In nature.
But not just anywhere.
For example, I found them in the salt mines in the Fez region, but also in hot salt water springs.
These have allowed me to have now, in the laboratory, a collection of more than 200 halophilic bacteria that synthesize all kinds of different enzymes that could tackle all sorts of different problems.
These enzymes, from microorganisms and halophilic bacteria, could be used in many complex industrial processes, such as paper and food processing, or biosynthesis and washing processes.
In concrete terms, we could replace, for example, a product in laundry and other detergents with an outlandish name: 2-butoxyethanol.
It's a chemical product that cleans very well.
So well, that it may cause some people skin irritations, allergies and more serious issues, such as blood and kidney problems.
We could replace them with enzymes that won't damage your skin, that only work against stains on your clothes,
and only under very specific conditions, such as those in your washing machine.
All of this is promising.
But, unfortunately, there is a "but".
And this damned "but" is financial.
I'm sure that's not surprising.
Today, it is five to ten times more expensive to use enzymes from bacteria, than using products that are already on the market.
We're still at the research stage.
And research in Morocco to deal with these many problems uses the simpler solutions because of limited resources.
And these constraints have forced us to greater inventiveness.
This has allowed me, for example, to produce an enzyme from a bacteria in a minimal medium.
As its name suggests, it's water, with a little bit of salt and some minerals.
This is without stirring, at room temperature.
Realize that, regarding energy, it costs nothing.
I love very much a quote from Jalâl ad-Dîn Rûmi, which says, and sums up well, all these constraints and opportunities: "Moonlight floods the whole sky from horizon to horizon; How much it can fill your room depends on its windows."
And here, a window has opened: a perspective can be seen.
I'm aware that we still have a long way to go, to see its direct application in industry.
But I am not less confident,
because, who knows, it may be in our universities that we find the best solutions to our problems, which are often yours as well.
Thank you.
(Applause)
