Me, it boosted me, it energized me.
First of all, to dream; it's the genesis.
Everything is possible when we dream.
Dreams help create ambition, and for this ambition to solidify, to strengthen, we need to believe in our dreams.
So, it creates a kind of circle; yes, that's how I draw a circle, it's a bit ridiculous, especially since I do it for a long time.
It creates a sort of circle that may seem easy to do, but it's not quite so easy.
Antoine de Saint-Exupéry once said, "Make your life a dream, and a dream, a reality." So, let's get things clear straight away, there are dreams we have when we sleep, like the one where I kiss Julia Roberts, and the dreams we have when we're awake, projection.
It's what we do when we're lost, when we look into the distance, when we smile like idiots because we're imagining a bright future.
I'm talking about that dream.
For this dream to become an ambition, it's up to the person themselves to say that yes, it's possible it won't just be a dream for all our lives.
And secondly, it's also, up to this person's acquaintances to condition, motivate them, and to tell them, "Yes, mate, it'll take work, but you can do it." And, as I told you before, to go from dream to ambition I believe it just takes a little spark.
I believe it takes self-confidence to help create this little spark.
You know this better than me, self-confidence, often takes nothing at all.
I remember a teacher in high school who was called Mister Lacombe, quite a stocky guy, 2 meters and 5', with a small beard, he was a maths teacher, and he would say at the start of the year, "Try to solve this problem." And then after three months, I don't know why, he started to say, "We'll see how long it takes you to find the solution." And in hindsight, because despite my young age, I can look back at my years in high school with hindsight, I remember that we didn't experience the exercises in the same way.
In the first case, Mr Lacombe spoke of a problem, in the second, he spoke of a solution.
In the first case, he asked us to try, in the second, he says that we will succeed.
It's really simple, it's true.
Thanks for interacting.
But, in any case, it's really motivating.
Dreams are the genesis, ambition is the driving force, and to create your action plan, you must, wait, this is planned, "Dare."
It's timed! It's not easy to dare.
And I'm not sure if it's in man's nature to dare.
I think man is easily pleased, this is my view, and it's dangerous.
It can't just be the elite that dares, otherwise it's not fun.
Everyone can and must dare, in their own time, however they want, with their own means.
For example, daring to say no to, "We will do your parents' job,"
if we don't want to, is already a hard and substantial thing to do.
Besides, about this, just a little interlude here, for parents, if there are any here, who tend to want to impose their passions and their work on their children, you know the film "Billy Elliot"?
Watch it.
There, I'm just saying...
Watch it, enjoy it or not, it doesn't matter, understand the message, that's all.
On my small scale, I remember, a few years ago, I dared to skip school and to go against my parents to go and interview celebrities in Paris.
Now, it seems laughable, but at the time, it was something.
Daring to move beyond your world, discovering new things, for young people, is complicated but necessary.
My world, at the time, and that of many young people today, amounted to school, home, bus, Internet, Facebook, Twitter, SnapChat, Instagram, YouPorn, Uh, YouTube!
Sorry, I don't know...
YouPorn? Don't know what it is.
Is it a cooking website?
I don't know what it is, it just slipped out like that.
Daring to discover, daring to experiment, daring to have confidence, daring to take the journey we want for ourselves, is to difference ourselves from others.
Daring, is to put ourselves in danger.
Daring is to lose our grounding.
Whereas doing nothing, is to be sure of what we'll do tomorrow.
And to dare, there is a great advantage, it's courage.
As the famous French jazzman Claude Nougaro once said, "I have the heart but not the stomach." Stomach, we need some to dare.
Let's use the analogy of Tony, that friend we all had in school, I think you had him. Tony was that stylish guy, a little bigger than the rest, who listened to rock music, who had a Mohican and a gold chain.
We all hated him. Why?
Because he went out with all the girls,
while we spent our evenings on YouTube.
So, what were we afraid of?
Of the unknown, of girls.
We were afraid to talk to her, of being turned down, of being mocked at school.
I left high school a long time ago, around two weeks, and it's now obvious to me that Tony was right.
We should surpass and jump this barrier that was only psychological, and dared to say, "Hi, Melanie!" Yes, I had braces at the time.
"Hi Melanie, it'th Panayotich." "No, I'm not new here, we've sat nexth to each other in class for two years." "I wanted to thay: you look a lot like Julia Roberths." Yes, that was my pick-up line. I thought that telling a girl she looks like Julia Roberts
was to get on her good side.
but no, it's not a problem.
In any case, flirting, it's something you have to "work" on.
Did you see that?
The transitions aren't bad!
(Laughter) I'm working on it.
"To work" - what will be determinant, is to not work.
Everybody does it.
It's to know why we work, what's the meaning behind it all.
I think that finding a goal for all these efforts is a priority.
I'm not talking about the "work" we do at the weekend to earn a bit of cash.
No, I'm talking about the work that has a deep meaning.
The one that will bring you experience and self-confidence.
It won't necessarily have a tangible or direct impact on your bank account, but that will give you something even more important.
From the age of 12 to 15, I carried out a dozen interviews.
At the start, it was limiting.
I didn't go out with friends at the weekend, because I had some editing to do.
I went to bed late, because I had editing to do.
I didn't have a girlfriend, because I didn't know how to flirt.
But it also brought me various skills, some were technical: how to use a camera, edit, mix, calibrate, some were social: becoming more tactful with people, more self-confident, expanding my address book.
I made a lot of friends with whom I still work with today.
It also taught how to deal with stress, how to deal with big responsibilities, to acquire a sense of priorities.
For example, when I received my first actor's wage, yes, I'm sometimes an actor.
When I get my first actor's wage, without hesitation I bought myself a Mac, to go on YouTube in the evenings, and a some editing software, to practice editing.
And it was from that moment that I started to direct all my choices, even the simplest ones, according to my passion and my work.
It wasn't limiting, it was a pleasure.
Working, finding a goal behind all this, is crucial, I think.
Working in class, okay, why not?
But if we knew why we work in class in school, if we knew it wasn't necessarily time we were spending on things that don't really interest us, but if we tell ourselves that it's for our future, we won't see it as a waste of time.
We see this as something to help us build a bright future.
Now, we've dreamt, we've dared, we've worked, there's one thing left to do, but it's not the least, it's, "Don't give up." We encounter, and it's normal, on our journey, more and more obstacles that weaken the little flame inside us.
Obstacles, small or big.
Me, I don't have much experience, so I haven't experienced or encountered any big obstacles yet.
Touch wood, I'll never encounter any big ones.
But for now, I have encountered small ones.
And these obstacles weaken this small flame inside us, that told us, "Yes, of course you can become a surgeon!" "Of course, you can become, a basketball player, a doctor, a physio!" "You can be an extra in a Julia Roberts film to try to kiss her at the end of filming!" Sorry, that for me, was my passion.
Julia Roberts is magnificent.
The danger is that this small flame will go out, and that we'll forget our dream.
When we dreamt of becoming a surgeon, and we told ourselves, "It's good to be a surgeon." and we worked to achieve this, and that we first dared to say, "It's possible." And we don't have to stop just because we killed a few patients.
That's maybe not a good example.
(Laughter) It's not a good example, I'm sorry.
Although, I like this example.
But, in any case, in order to not abandon, to maintain this flame of motivation and ambition, I can suggest a little something that really helped me, it is to meet your idols, or the influential people of the world in which you want to enter. For me, this was this famous young director Xavier Dolan, who I was lucky enough to meet an hour after his speech, "I think everything is possible for those who dream, dare ..." Sorry, I just spit something enormous, it doesn't matter, we might have to clean up for the next speaker.
And I was lucky enough the meet him an hour after this famous speech.
I saw him in a corridor, because I was invited to the Cannes Film Festival after sending two or three emails, about a hundred, to the accreditation committee, and they got fed up of receiving so many emails so they thought, "Go on, we'll invite him." So, I was lucky enough to bump into him in a corridor an hour after his speech.
I wanted to seem confident, I said, "Hello, Panayotis." But I was actually thinking, "Fuck, it's Xavier Dolan!
He's less than three metres away, pretend you didn't see him!" "Hi, hello!" So I went to see him, and I said to him, "Hello Xavier, Panayotis." And we had a chat.
For me, it was a superb, a fantastic chat.
I was on a cloud.
For him, it was a mundane chat, but I didn't care.
We chatted for ten minutes, and I remember that after this rewarding and interesting chat, he left, and I watched him like an idiot.
I forgot everything I'd just been through, the small obstacles I'd encountered just before, meaning failed auditions, not many views for my videos, videos that weren't even published, problems in school because I'd skip class to make the videos, etc.
All that, was forgotten, was gone.
I had just one thing in mind, which was, "It's true, that's why I want to do this job.
This is why I want to do this fucking job." I had a big smile, I was all set for another three years of this infamous journey to achieve my goal!
And, as I'm sort of a pro, I went after him, and as my goal was for us to become coworkers or colleagues, I gave him my business card.

Not really! I took a selfie.
Each to their own, and young people take selfies.
In any case, there's a second thing I want to talk about, Hello!
You didn't think there was going to be any interaction!
Bad luck, there's no wall here!
If I want you to talk, you will!
The other thing that I want to talk about, it's to deepen your understanding of the area in which you want to evolve.
For me, from the start, I wanted to be an actor, but I tried a bit of filmmaking, writing skits, staging, etc. What makes us want to eat cake more than going back and forth in front of the display case?
There's a last point, yes, there are many in this section, I thought, "We're going to have loads of points!" The last little point, that was a huge help for me too, was to relativize the notions of failure and success.
At the time, and I know many young people who think like this, I thought that there are two paths: the path of success and the path of failure.
This is wrong.
I think that there is only one path, that leads, if we persevere, to success with a capital "s."
This unique path entails small failures, small successes, small failures, small successes.
You can't stop at the first failure thinking, "I'm on the path to failure." It's wrong.
You have to carry on, continue.
And on this path, to keep with this almost spiritual metaphor, we encounter numerous people who help us continue, who hold our hands, who give, or give back that small spark, and who see it in our eyes.
It's true that success, can also be felt through other people's eyes.
Creating a gang, a team working with people in perfect harmony, is something that I was lucky enough to experience.
Let me tell you that when you hang out with bright minds who have the same ambition as you, who see this famous path in the same way as you, it's worth maybe ten bright minds, looking in different directions.
To conclude, I would like to share with you the best advice that I was given in my life, even though it's been short, I'm not that old, but I'm going to say "in my life" just for show.
The best advice I was given in my life, is not the most academic advice I could have been given, but it was the one that stuck with me.
When I was eleven or twelve, I interviewed Orelsan, who is one of the most famous French rappers.
I was super happy, the interview went well.
I just forgot to turn the microphone on.
So half --
Hey! That's enough!
(Laughter) So half of the interview went straight in the bin.
We were able to retrieve some sound with iPhones, it was shitty...
I remember that I finished the editing, showed it to my dad.
He looked at me and said, "You flunked it!
Take a breathe, work on it, you'll do better next time." Thanks for listening to a youngster.
Thank you very much.
(Applause)
Good evening.
Today, producing electricity with the wind or the sun has, in most cases, become cheaper than using conventional and polluting energies.
Actually, renewable energies are not only greener, but they have also become less expensive.
So the question is "why aren't they developing faster?"
Well, it’s because they are intermittent.
This means that they are not producing energy constantly.
And in many cases, when wind turbines or solar panels are set up somewhere, there are also gas plants or fuel plants not far away that are powered up to produce electricity when there is no more wind or no more sun.
Because of this, many people consider that renewable energies are not green at all.
And others say,
"No, indeed they are. We just need to store energy."
The problem is that storing electricity is extremely expensive today.
Now a length of time with no sun lasts approximately for 12 hours.
It’s called "night."
And periods without wind can last even longer.
Now if we wanted to store in batteries the electric production for 12 hours of a country like France, we would have to invest 300 billion euros.
It's more or less five times the budget of the Department of Education.
And this investment would have to be repeated every 10 years, since it is the lifetime of a battery today.
But there are other ways to store energy.
You may have heard of hydrogen or compressed air,
and there are many more. However, all those solutions are even more expensive, except one.
It is the pump-storage power-generating stations.
They are also called "energy-transfer pumping stations."
Actually, these are hydroelectric power plants that are able to operate in reverse.
So when there is a surplus of electricity on the grid, we can use this system to pump water from a downstream reservoir to an upstream reservoir. It transforms this electric energy into potential energy
that could then be used later when there's a power shortage on the grid.
Then it would be working in reverse.
The upstream reservoir empties itself in the pipe that was used to fill it,
and it fills the downstream reservoir while powering a hydroelectric turbine.
Now there are two problems with such a solution.
First, it's not much cheaper than a battery.
Secondly, such systems can only be located in selected mountainous areas because the two water reservoirs that constitute this system must not only be located at very different altitudes in order to maximize the storage of energy, but also, they cannot be too far apart, otherwise, the cost of the pipe connecting them would increase exponentially.
Now some of these systems already exist in the world.
The hydropower plants were obviously located in areas with the best economical performance.
So, future sites will be located in areas where the costs are going to increase continually.
Here is it.
Whether we use batteries or pumped storage hydropower plants, we can consider that energy storage is above all an economical problem.
So as a result, this considerably restrains the speed at which the energy transition occurs.
As an engineer; I had the opportunity to work for a decade in the automotive industry, on rationalization and cost reduction functions.
And one day I realized that if it was possible to reduce costs in an industrial sector that has been mature for many decades - we still can reduce costs in this field - we should be able to reduce costs in the field of energy storage too, knowing that this issue is much more recent.
And that's how I was led to design two ways to strongly reduce the cost of energy storage that I'm going to show you. Now for the first solution, let's leave the mountains and go to the sea because at sea, there are important elevation differences between the sea bottom and the sea surface.
The average depth of the ocean is more or less 13,000 feet or 4000 m.
Imagine a very big concrete weight that we are placing on the sea bottom.
Then on the sea surface, we are putting a barge armed with an electric hoist.
Then with a long cable, we are hanging the weight and lifting it along the 13,000 feet elevation.
In so doing; the hoist is transforming electric energy into potential energy.
Now along 13,000 feet elevation, it is possible to store as much energy in two pounds of concrete as in one pound of battery.
But, two pounds of concrete are a hundred times cheaper than one pound of battery.
So this gives you an idea of the huge savings that can be made.
It then became necessary to find a solution that would enable us to apply this concept to the electrical grid.
Well, it's very simple.
We just need to connect the barge to the electrical grid with a submarine power cable, the same kind of cable used for connecting offshore wind turbines.
So when there is surplus electricity on the grid, the surplus is injected, via the underwater cable, to the barge, and the barge lifts concrete weights one by one from the sea bottom to the surface.
And when there is an electricity shortage, it works in reverse.
The weights are sent back down one by one, and as they pull the hoist, it works as an electric generator almost like a dynamo.
Now in order to maximize the storage capacity, we use several dozens of weights for one single hoist.
This allows us to increase the storage capacity without increasing the cost of the hoist and the barge.
And to achieve this, it is necessary to keep them near the surface when they are stored near the sea surface.
So for example, we can hang them on floats.
And to prevent the floats from drifting away during a storm, those floats are anchored with long anchoring cables, just like those used on some offshore oil rigs.
And at sea, when we size, when we build a boat, an oil rig or anything else, we must take into account exceptional circumstances that may happen once every 50 or 100 years.
So to make it survive exceptional storms, we need to use very thick steel cables, and they have to be very long because the depth is considerable.
And the sum of those cables is going to be very expensive.
So all the benefits of using weights made of concrete, which is a cheap material that can store plenty of energy along a high elevation, will be lost due to cables that are far too costly.
Well, I invented and patented several technical solutions that enable us to make sure those floats do not stay on sea surface, exposed to winds and waves, but rather several dozen feet below the sea level, permanently.
One way to do this is to gather all those floats on a single supporting body and to anchor this supporting body to the sea bottom with anchoring cables.
Now you're going to say, "Still, anchoring cables are expensive."
Yes, but here we can adapt the floating capacity of the supporting structure in accordance with the number of weights to be hung.
So every time we hang on a new weight, we inject compressed air in a float which will then start to float, so that we never have more than the equivalent of one weight as tension strength in the anchoring cables.
So this allows for a big reduction in the cost of this component.
There is a small energy consumption in doing so since it requires to compress air.
But we can demonstrate that it is approximately 1% of the total storage capacity along a 13,000 feet elevation, because we are at around 130 feet depth for the floats.
Now the main interest of this solution is its investment cost.
When we add up the cost of all the components - the concrete, 100 times cheaper than batteries, to which we must add the anchoring cables, the floats, a barge, and if we include the cost of the submarine power cable that carries electricity sometimes over distances greater than 60 miles - then the total investment cost is about ten times lower, ten times lower than today's best batteries.
It may seem difficult to believe but it can be easily verified because these components are already being used in a marine environment, for other installations of course, usually in the offshore oil industry.
Therefore their cost and life time are well known.
So this is a very interesting system from an economic point of view, that must be deployed at sea, and then connected onshore to solar or wind turbine farms, and to the final consumer as well.
When we have an electrical grid located a few hundred miles away from the shore, the cost is pretty fair and acceptable.
However, as soon as distances increase over several thousand miles, as for example in central North America or in the center of Asia, this solution is no longer interesting from an economical point of view since the cost to transport electricity becomes too high.
So for those specific cases, I have imagined another way to reduce the cost of energy storage.
So now, let's leave the sea, get back on dry land and move toward areas that are completely flat.
We have just seen that pumped storage hydropower plants can only be installed in mountainous areas.
On the contrary now, we go on purpose to flat areas,
and we dig a big cone-shaped hole which shape looks a bit like big open-pit mines and prevents landslides.
We chose a rather conservative pit land slope.
And with all the rocks we excavate, we build a circular embankment dam right next to it.
So that way, we build two reservoirs that will be filled with water, that are not at the same elevation nor too far apart.
And this solves the main problem of pumped storage hydroelectricity.
We can dig these holes everywhere, including in completely flat areas
such as Picardy (north of France) for example.
Obviously, if such a simple system could at the same time be cost-saving, it would be too good to be true!
Well de facto, when we look at the cost, doing little calculations on a generic case, we get an investment cost about twice the cost of batteries, for pits that are 30 feet deep.
But let's look at what happens if we increase the size of the facility.
Let's double the measurements.
If we double the depth, the width and the length of the pit and also the size of the dam, it means that we multiply the volumes by height. So now we are able to store eight times as much water; we have to excavate eight times more rock, and it is eight times more expensive.
However, the energy storage capacity depends not only on the water volume but also on the elevation difference, which itself is doubled.
So the energy storage capacity in such case is multiplied by 16, while the cost is only multiplied by eight.
This creates savings on scale.
By increasing the size, the energy storage capacity is increased faster than the cost.
And the question is no longer "How too expensive is energy storage?"
The question becomes "What size must it have to be economically attractive?"
So if we dig a pit ...
Well, the Eiffel tower is only a scale.
The aim is not to dig a big hole in Paris and bury half of the districts under 30 feet of rocks!
So if we dig a 1300 feet-deep pit, then we can achieve an investment cost that is two times cheaper than batteries.
And in addition, the life time of the system becomes longer.
So the total updated cost is something around five to six times more economically advantageous.
However; this requires to store very important quantities of energy on one single site - we're talking about 50 GWh.
But it is totally realistic.
So going back to the example of France and the 12-hours' storage capacity, in this case, we would have to build 20 sites of that size.
And for your information, the present French energy mix which is mostly nuclear consists of 60 nuclear reactors which are spread on 20 different sites.
So in terms of power concentration, it is not a problem.
Now you might think that digging 1300 feet deep pits is far too big and utopian.
Not at all. The biggest open pit mines in the world are twice as deep and 10 times more voluminous.
The highest embankment dams in the world are three times higher.
And the total land surface required for such facilities is about two square miles altogether.
So if we wanted to build 20 sites in a country like France, the total area required would be more than 1000 times smaller than the agricultural land.
Thus it would be insignificant compared to the environmental and economic impact it would have.
So I took France as an example because it is more relevant to us.
But indeed for France, which is still a maritime country, the solution using the concrete weight system offshore would be by far the most advantageous.
But here is what the energy mix of the future would look like relative to the energy storage capacity.
About 3/4 of the storage would use sea-based solutions, and the rest would be more conventional land-based solutions with bigger size facilities and economies of scale.
I’m sometimes asked why such simple and inexpensive solutions are not developed today.
I should point out that I started releasing those ideas about four years ago.
I first started to present them to the Energy and Industry Departments, in several European countries, and also to several major energy companies in Europe, because this is a huge environmental and economical issue and there are a great deal of job creations at stake.
I have had the opportunity to meet numerous experts in the various disciplines concerned by those systems,
and until now nobody has questioned the economic assumptions. Indeed, I have used very prudent assumptions. Similarly, the technical feasibility has not been questioned.
Yet today retrospectively, I've noticed a certain reluctance, on the part of the major stakeholders in the energy sector, to promote storage systems that are really low cost and allow to compete with fossil thermic backups that are developed today to be combined with new renewable energies.
For that reason, I thought it would be appropriate to start communicating to a broader public including through a TEDx talk.
Thank you for your attention.
(Applause)
Good evening every one. So, slow-life is a huge subject.
Is it really possible and that easy to confront fast-life, opt for an alternative route and switch to slow-life?
Five years ago, I made a switch from legal officer to yoga teacher.
And, as my employment councilor at the time rightly said, I was « doing the splits »,
no pun intended, of course.
To summerize my yoga story, it was something that happened by chance.
I wanted to change my sports routine a bit. I wanted to try a class in the gym I was a member of.
So I tried it, and it was a revelation.
From the first class, I felt the benefits.
It was the first time in months that I slept really well.
So, I started to practice more and more. I started with two classes a week, which then became every day.
Some studies show that yoga is a drug stronger than coffee, and I must admit that I totally agree with this theory since I was literally an addict.
The more I practiced, the more different I felt, I was calmed.
I have a hyperactive, nervous and impulsive nature, but all of a sudden I felt lighter, peaceful, calmer.
I started to understand that what matters in life is to look after yourself and others.
So, I started to increase my practice, and I felt reconnected with my body.
I started to be aware of what I was eating, and of my relationship with others.
Above all, yoga started to put things in order in my head, highlighting certain things, and making me realize that I wasn't happy at work and that I wasn't thriving.
At the time, I didn't ask myself many questions. I just continued to do yoga, practice,
until the day it actually became obvious that I had to leave my job because something else was waiting for me.
Eventually, the switch went quite fast. After only of a few months of practice, I decided to quit my job and devote myself to this passion of yoga.
So, I started to have a new outlook on life where it is important to do good to oneself and take care of others.
And it was at that moment that I really entered the « slow-living ».
Obviously, the problem was how could I take on this alternative route that is slow-life?
Indeed, in relation to others, it's not easy. There's social pressure, there really is.
So, how do you do it with respect to others?
Other people's lives are bound to be very different.
So naturally, some supported me through my process.
However, some others tried to discourage me saying that I was making a huge mistake, that it was non sense to quit such a comfortable job as a legal officer, that it was a waste to get a Corporate Jurist Diploma and then just stop doing law, and that it was rare to be a member of a company's executive committee at the age of 27!
Well, in the end, I didn't listen to other people's responses,
and I continued to believe in this way of living.
So, I opted for the slow-living,
but it's true, it wasn't easy. Because we need to recognize that we live in a society that has always the foot on the gas, a fast-living society,
a society of busy-ness.
The busier we are, the better it is.
Admittedly, it's typically more accepted to be busy all the time because the busier you are, the more successful you'll be.
It should be noted that we are in this fast-living society where everything goes faster and faster, and everything has become quicker because of the new technology and social media.
Faced with that, the problem is how can we slow down?
Faced with this fast-living society, I wanted to move against the tide. I wanted to just take the time to live, to think about myself, to readjust my rhythm.
But what is slow-living?
Well, we face a society that is constantly accelerating, so it's important to slow down the pace.
Slowing down doesn't necessarily mean doing things slowly, but it's rather functioning differently.
Do do this, new gestures must be adopted, periods of relaxation must be secured in our schedule, and we must relearn how to live.
I'm not hiding the fact that, for an overactive person like me, it wasn't easy to slow down.
I had to become aware of lots of things such as my bad habits. I had to adopt new gestures such as practicing yoga daily, even if only for five minutes, as well as practicing meditation, spending time in Nature, cooking instead of ordering ready meals on home delivery apps - which is something we do a lot now -
listening to an inspiring podcast, reading books, all these moments of relaxation that make us feel great, that, in the end, are not practiced enough.
And the question we can ask is: "Why don't we really try to do all these things?"
And the response that keeps coming back is simply "guilt".
We deprive ourselves of these moments because we too often associate inactivity with slowness and laziness.
Yet, we should detach ourselves from this feeling of guilt that is often attached to inactivity.
Inactivity doesn't mean laziness.
Slowness doesn't mean laziness.
Through slow-living, I learnt to appreciate these little nothings that, until then, were imperceptible.
I discovered gratitude.
When we don't need anything, when we have time to take our time, we simply become grateful for being happy.
Of course, you're going to tell me, « Well, that's too easy! It's all well and good, but concretely, how do we do? ».
Well, to slow down you need to escape stress. You need to take the time to live, let go, and live intensely in the present moment.
And for all those who think that I risk losing myself in this voluntary approach of simplicity, I want to share with them this quote by Franck Michel in "Voyage au bout de la route": "With speed, we may know everything we've earned, in time and in money especially, but we don't know yet all that we've lost."
So, what I'm trying to explain to you is that we too often forget that by overloading our days and scheduling too many activities, we miss the point. We forget the simple and fundamental existential values.
That's why we should really return to these values and to the simple things, take the time to live, slow down to live better.
However, what I'm not going to hide is that even if we try to slow down, technology and this fast-living society are always catching up with us.
Actually, I must confess that personally, for example, I have great difficulty in detaching myself from my smartphone because I'm someone who is hyper-connected.
I'm very connected to social media, Instagram especially.
Now the problem is that, in fact, I use technology to slow down.
For example, I use apps to meditate. I use apps to track my sleep to make sure I get enough of it because sleep is important, that's important to remember.
Also, I use Instagram as a way of communicating.
What I'm trying to show is that there is a true paradox.
We use technology to slow down because we now have loads of apps that enable us to do that, and enable us to embark on this new slow-life way of living.
And ultimately, we are always overtaken by it.
Who didn't notice the most recent notifications on our smartphones that show us how long we've spent looking at the screen?
It's completely paradoxical. Personally, I look at it again because it appears when I don't want to. That stresses me more than anything else
because I start thinking I spend too much time looking at screens, that's not okay.
In the end, even if we try to slow down, technology is always there, and somehow, it follows us.
If the concept of slow-life speaks to me so much, that's not only because it's inherent in yoga and its associated way of life,
but because I also really see it as a corrector for my hyperactive personality,
and as a response to my hyper-connection as well.
In a world in search of meaning, I think that it's important to go back to the basics of what makes us really happy and serene.
Every day, ask yourself this question: "Did I take some time for myself today?"
Now to close this talk, I'm going to propose you a very simple exercise that you can do every day, several times a day, in order to restore calm, slow down the pace, take care of yourself, and reconnect with yourself.
(Music) So slowly, you're going to relax your arms and place them on your knees.
Close your eyes, relax your shoulders.
Slowly relax.
You're going to try to reconnect with yourself and your breathing.
Then, slowly lift your arms towards the ceiling.
Bring your hands to prayer in front of your chest, in front of your heart center.
Take a few moments to feel the beating of your heart.
See if you can feel your heart beating.
Together, let's take three breaths.
Inhale through your nose ...
and exhale through your mouth.
Now two more times, inhale ...
and exhale.
Last time, a big inhale ...
and a big exhale.
Then slowly, you can open your eyes
and gently release your arms.
Thank you.
