Betty &amp; Germaine: Hello everyone!
Betty: My name is Betty.
I am deaf.
I come from a hearing family.
I work with young children.
Germaine: My name is Germaine.
I am hearing, I have no deaf family.
I also work with young children,
I am an art-therapist and baby sign teacher.
Betty: We were trained by Monica Companys, the founder of the concept of baby sign workshops,
the mother of baby sign Betty &amp; Germaine:... in France!
Betty: Thanks to Monica, we met each other. Germaine: And it was clear to us we should deliver workshops together.
So we created "Island of Signs" studio.
Betty: "Island of Signs" -
I always work in trust with the children.
And I talk to them in sign language.
I find that the children are more attentive when I use sign language.
You know, deaf people see French language and reproduce it in a precise gestural communication method.
Sign language is not just a communication system, it is a language!
Germaine: Why, as a deaf person, do you sign with hearing children?
Betty: Because it is my preferred language!
I always sign and talk with children.
It gives the children words that reassures them on a deeper level.
And what about you Germaine, why do you sign with hearing children?
Germaine: Well, because I felt like it, perhaps it was my Martiniquais and Italian heritage,
but ever since I was small, I loved to observe adults to understand how they talk, how they express themselves how they communicate verbally to express themselves and to tell each other things.
I quickly observed and found that adults are capable of saying things that don't match their words.
So I became an actor to better understand this then an art therapist to help others.
Today, I work with young children, I'm a teacher, I work with the children and their parents, and other people who work with young children for the adults to develop and improve their relationship and communication with their children.
For me the aim of combining sings with words is to aide in understanding of both verbal and non verbal communication
to really speak to the children!
So Betty, you know a lot of hearing people, you work with a hearing person, you know that we, hearing people, can say things like, "I am very happy."
()Laughter) Or, as we often do with children, "I'm not angry so stop that now!"
(Laughter) Betty: If you express something different to what you say, a child cannot understand.
Even I cannot understand.
It is best to sign with precision and add in a facial expression,
"I am sad,"
"I am stressed,"
"I am angry."
Germaine: Emotions are clearly expressed.
There are no detours, no false sentiments,
"Tree," "to see," "to say," "to listen," and that then stimulates the concept of mental representation because the words become palpable and visual.
The concept of mental representation is what allows us to think about things, to imagine them, to dream them before saying them and for them to become a reality.
If I say the word "apple" to you.
What do you see in your mind's eye?
What kind of apple is it?
Is it round?
How does it look?
(Audience) Green.
Germaine: Green?
it it crisp? What is your apple like?
Betty: Red!
Germaine: Red? Well!
(Laughter) Perhaps you are influenced by your dress; red dress, red apple!
The apple of Snow White!
You have that in your head, because I said it?
Everyone sees their own apple which depends on your own personal taste, your culture, even your experience with apples.
And it is the same for a child.
They see the apple, they taste it, they experience it, they can picture the apple.
but "an apple", that is easy, it's and object, it's established.
Now, if I say, "leave," "return," "work;"
there, those ideas are more fluid.
They are more abstract ideas.
This words blend with your life experiences; happier or less happy.
We, in our everyday professional life we often see this situation arising, in the mornings, when the parents drop off their children.
I'll describe it to you to make it easier to understand.
He's not looking at me, he's looking away
I'll take this opportunity to leave because every time he sees me go, he cries.
So, I'll just slip away now.
