to leave like that, because the child will feel abandoned.
It is much better to explain to the child what is happening in sign language,
"Mummy is going to work.
She is coming back for you this evening.
I’m thinking of you."
Germaine: When Betty signs and speaks, this is what happens:
you give the child the choice to understand the adult through signs or through words.
Before speaking, all children point.
They communicate in their non-verbal language; they gestures, their expressions, their cries, their tears, certain signs.
By signing, you respect the child and use their own communication method.
Betty: You all, you all know a natural sign language, hearing people!
You know these natural signs!
How do you say "sleep"?
Yes, they all know it, they do this... "Eat"?
Yes, that's it!
"Drink"?
Germaine: There is someone who is drinking from a glass, Betty.
There is someone who drinks like this.
(Laughter) Betty: The signs give us better quality exchanges, pleasure, sharing moments, and involvement.
Germaine: More interaction!
Because in order to sign to a child, we have to meet them at their level, face to face, eye to eye.
Betty: We don't sign the whole phrase.
It's like underlining the key words in a phrase.
Germaine: For example, "We are going to walk in the forest, with your shoes, and your coat."
Giving these words to the children allows them to better understand the adult, and better understand the words, and as a consequence say them better.
Children can learn how to sign quickly.
They see it: it's easy.
Speech takes a lot longer to develop.
So, often, Betty and I are asked
- perhaps you were wondering this, too -
I'll now ask Betty this question, "Betty, when hearing children learn the sign language, do they develop speech later?"
Betty: Of course not!

No! In fact, it is the opposite.
It supports children's speech and language skills.
Children feel they can understand better.
It calms them down.
And their parents feel helped.
And mutual attention can develop.
Germaine: We don't sign so that the children sign.
They do it if they want, if they feel like it.
We sign so that the adults can develop and improve the way they communicate with young children.
I am going to give you the example of Youenn.
Youenn is one year old.
He is with his nanny who has learnt baby sign. and then at noon, he is at a table with seven people with a lot of conversations going on around him, and at one point, he raises his hand, and does this sign.
Everyone goes quiet, looks at Youenn, looks at his hand, and asks him, "What do you want Youenn?"
And Youenn, with a smile says, "Wawa."
This sign means he wants, "Water."
Betty: I am amazed when I see a child starting to sign.

