Good evening.
Before I introduce myself and start to talk to you, I would like to ask all adults to do a small exercise.
I would like to ask all adults to go back in time, and find the 12-year-old child they once were.
Remember when you were 12 years old.
Done?
Alright!
Today, I'm going to talk to him, not to you, but to him.
I know, it's been a long time you haven't seen the younger version of yourself.
It has not changed, did you see?
My name is Abdallah, I am 11 , and I am in 6th grade.
I am just a normal boy, and I 'm passionate about reading.
Two books stood up for me.
"The Little Prince" is the first book I read, and I read it every year.
And the second book?
"Iron Man - In extremis" because the character, Tony Starck, created an armor to save the world, thanks to nanotechnology, another passion of mine.
When I read it, I imagine myself older, doing the same thing.
It's since I read it that I would like to be an engineer later.
I have many dreams, and we, children, are spending our lives dreaming without always trying to make them possible.
We think we have to wait until we are grown up to realize them, although it's possible to make our dreams come trough today.
Often, we limit ourselves to dreaming and imagining in our heads how we will be in the future, what we will do, and we tell ourselves "Everything will be possible when I'm an adult.
Sure, I'll become someone."
But in reality, we are already someone.
We are on this Earth, and we have a role.
The truth is we are already here!
but it's also our future.
We share the same planet, the same space, the same time, and we have the same brain.
Our brain has the same capabilities than the one of adults.
One day, one of my cousins ​​told me, "You're funny, how do you want to do that?
You forget that we are only children.
Do you think that you will save the world just like Iron Man?"
It's true, I'm a comic fan, but I don't have superpowers.
However, all we need is just look around us, and try to find solutions to help others, and also ask friends to reflect with us and do not think we are alone.
And indeed, there are adults who can help us.
"The Little Prince" of Saint-Exupery allowed many adults to not forget the child they were.
When my mother gave me this book, I didn't understand why it was so important for her and my dad.
I remember this ski trip where my father couldn't come.
My sister Inaya, at 4 years old, asked just before the trip if we could pretend to drink coffee in a doll's tea set.
I was ashamed.
I saw my mother was upset; she told Inaya, "My daughter, why pretend when you can do it in real life?"
I was shocked.
Inaya was really happy, but I was shocked.
And from there, we started to have tea time, all together as a family, in a toy tea set.
The following week, we went skiing and we had this infamous tea time which comprised mini glasses, a mini sugar bowl, a mini milk jug.
My father couldn't come; he had gone to Egypt.
Every day at the bar, we drank tea in front of everybody, in this porcelain toy tea set - I was so ashamed!
When my mother phoned my father, I thought he'd reason with her and tell her how embarrassing it was.
But no, he found the idea great.
I didn't understand why she was doing that with my sister.
When I asked her, she simply replied, "I don't want her to pretend.
She has a role to play, so I train her to take her place."
I was not ashamed any more because I understood why.
That day, I understood that we, children, we must take our place.
I will tell you how this idea changed my life.
My best friend is my sister.
One day, the family was together and we were organizing an event for an associative project,
Basically, we had to do a street art activity.
My sister and I have been taking classes for two years now.
At one point, my mother told us that she could not participate because of her disability in her arms and neck, and that instead, she would take pictures.
I saw she was sad, in fact very sad, too disappointed not to do it.
It was the first time that I saw my mother not trying to find a solution - really, it was too hard for me.
I said, "Don't worry, you're going to do it with us!
And be sure we're going to find a solution!"
I don't know what came over me that day, but I knew it, I was sure.
I understood what she had told me speaking about "a role to play."
My father was proud of me, he said, "Figure it out, son!"
For hours, I tried to find out how to do it.
I had the base of a spray gun but that didn't solve the problem.
At my grandma's home, in the bedroom of my aunt Naima, I found a selfie stick.
And at that moment, I understood what my mother keeps telling me: "Open your mind, look around you.
Make connections between worlds."
Without a second thought, I said to my sister, "I found it!"
She followed me straight away.
She said, "I create the layout. You, you assemble your stuff."
She didn't hesitate one second.
I talked to my mother who also followed me immediately.
But well, she also followed my sister for a tea time in a toy tea set!
My sister is now six, and we still have this tea time!
We visited a fab lab and asked them to make the object in 3D.
Nobody in my family could help me technically.
I'm proud today to have dared to believe that it was possible and to have believed in me.
I can now answer my cousin, "I can't save the world, but I can help my world."
And I realized what this thing could provide to my mother.
(Applause) I realized what this object provided to my mother but also to other people.
It can help people in a wheelchair to do street art, to repaint their fence, to use any spray in height and on the ground.
We should forget that we're children and believe in ourselves.
We shouldn't listen to this little voice inside us that says it's not possible.
We must twist its neck.
It's important to become our best friend and encourage ourselves, otherwise, this voice gains more and more strength.
There is one thing we really don't want to become, it is this adult who says, "When I was young, I dreamed of being ..."
We must stop pretending because tomorrow, we won't pretend to be an adult.
We have the ability to achieve what we want.
We need to believe in ourselves first for others to believe in us.
That's how we start to build today the adult we're going to be and the world of tomorrow.
But not just any adult!
And not without giving ourselves an objective and a mission, that is to become an adult who is responsible and humane.
This adult we are going to be should be the best friend of the child we are today.
And when asked to remember the 12-year-old child we once were, we should be proud to present to him this adult.
And now, I would like to talk to the adults.
If at the beginning, I asked you to return to the child you once were, it's to show you how much you forgot him/her, and I'm sure you missed him/her.
We need you today to help us and to believe in ourselves.
You should let us speak and let us take our place in the world.
My whole family always tells me, "Ah, if I were young again!
Enjoy Abdallah, you are lucky to be a child, adult life is really tough."
Really, if it's so difficult for you, maybe it's because dreaming is no longer part of your life.
Well, you just need to remember the child you once were.
It's easy, you just have to want it.
Adults and children must learn to help each other.
You can teach us to fulfill our dreams, to be actors of change, and to prepare our future ourselves.
As for us, we can help you to find the child you once were.
So?
Are you ready?
