What's going on?
How do they do it?
Giants, appearing to come from the Internet, disarm with ease the traditional leaders of all the industries, one by one.
Where do they get such power from?
Most importantly, can I, as a citizen, make it mine and use it for my well-being?
Let me take you beyond the material economy of trade in goods and money.
As human beings, our interactions have three dimensions: firstly, knowledge, used to describe the world around us.
Secondly, trust, which becomes reputation when it multiplies.
And thirdly, emotions of all kinds.
Knowledge, trust, emotion.
These exchanges are embarrassing for this science of rarity called the economy.
First of all, they are not measurable.
Do you say, "I have 13.37 trust in my doctor"? (Laughter)
If you want him to repair your car, it will surely be another story.
Then, they are abundant.
When I share some knowledge with you, I do not forget it.
I do not need to take back my trust in Isabella in order to give to Stephanie.
And finally, they are impermanent.
You see, this frame on the table.
If I leave here, and I come back tomorrow, it will still be here, still the same frame.
But you, if you are cheerful and I lock you up 24 hours in the dark, will you remain cheerful?
See?
Juggling knowledge, trust and emotion, it is a delicate exercise.
So, for years, we have tried to hide them, to neglect them.
We've defined in our lives a kind of bubble, a parenthesis, called professional life, in which they were not welcome.
Crying at the office is not "professional".
We do not trust one another we sign contracts instead, etc. Some corporations employing thousands of employees have replaced small artisans and local merchants.
The bookseller in my neighborhood, who knew me, and advised me in his charming little shop full of emotions and feelings, has been optimized.
Except -- Except that the emerging new world, Information is fluid.
It travels across the world without friction, it breaks up into tiny droplets, it is shape-shifting, it adapts to fit the best contours of each vessel, that is to say of each brain.
Delivered in the right format, at the right time, in right place.
And this is a revolution --
Liquid information makes the world transparent.
Transported by digital technology, knowledge, trust and emotion become observable.
Still not measurable, certainly, but we can grasp them, keep their footprint, develop them.
All the emerging platforms take care of it.
With a billion and a half users, the largest social network in the world is just that.
The knowledge we publish there is permanently moved around, and we associate to it our emotions with smileys, and then trust is expressed with "likes", comments, shares.
Ah, indeed!
There are also hybrid streams.
This gigantic accumulation of non-commercial exchanges converts into cash flow through commissions on transactions.
Big data, machine learning, neural networks, here the names of the tools used to handle the three non-market flows.
They're actually used to interpret the myriad of weak signals that are our daily interactions with our environment, our environment in the broader sense.
Not just the 150 people that we have a conscious relationship with but the 5,000 ones whose existence we may not even be aware of.
This neighbor who buys like me, this indignant that signs the same petition as me, all those that we call our weak ties.
In each platform to which we have subscribed, we have a virtual alter ego, a digital model of ourselves of who we are.
And handling them gives some individuals running these platforms Immeasurable power.
And that's scary!
(Cymbals sound)
Alright? Are you afraid now?
(Laughter) Many technophobes flatly refuse to accept this evolution sometimes continuing to think Facebook is not a dangerous toy.
Today, I invite you to explore another lead.
What if we could, each of us, take back our share of this power?
Regain control of our virtual alter ego to put it at the service of our freedom?
What would the world be like if, left free to fully express themselves in our lives, knowledge, trust and emotion, to engage with our 5,000 weak links?
The impact, the most striking contrast will probably be on the scale of large companies.
Take for example, the case of a pyramid chart.
In a human-centered approach, I'm not exclusively at a single person's orders.
I'm actually the reality of every organization, I'm actually under the cumulative influence of all the people who matter to me, either because I see them a lot or because I admire them and they are a model for me.
And with an intensity laid on those personal bonds of trust with full transparency you get a follower-monitoring system just like Twitter, which presents itself as a social graph.
Each point is an individual, each arrow is an influence.
But let's take it further: what would companies become in a world where trust, knowledge, emotion, would be fully legitimate?
What force can set people free to come together to execute
the vision of an entrepreneur?
An ideal. A noble ideal!
Transparency oblige.
Companies would become open clubs of men and women united by the causes they share.
And our need for self-realization, through the satisfaction of contributing to the world, serving these causes our best.
So... Putting profit at the service of sustainability, selling causes instead of selling products, maximizing one's social impact, a neo-hippie dream or the economic reality of the 21st century?
Well, come and see us in Vietnam and we will show you.
Because all this is not fiction.
In 2006, we went to Vietnam to found an offshore digital services company.
Originally, the goal was to build a Vietnamese technology giant
in order to contribute to the development of the country, but also, truth be told, to enjoy the freedom of not having to report to a boss anymore.
But in 2012, the cookie crumbled.
First, some customers turn out to be worse than the worst bosses.
More importantly, we realize that we have formed below us a pyramid of 200 Vietnamese who all had a boss.
200 people whose freedoms were sacrificed for our independence which in the end we did not even have!
We had even less and less of it as the structure grew.
It was time to go back to square one and take advantage to incorporate the three non-market flows, and fluid information at the heart of our governance.
The organization that has resulted today has no HRD, has no salespeople, no bosses anymore.
It actually includes 300 free individuals, employees and managers.
The role that the professional world wants us to have takes us too far away from who we are, intimately.
To protect yourselves against this schizophrenic tension, dare to fully accommodate in your work the three non-market flows:
knowledge, trust and emotion, form a very useful filter, although sometimes a little uncomfortable, to inform your decisions.
Here, think of a key stage in your life:
moving houses, resigning, changing jobs.
Think back to this turning point and its consequences, and together, let's use the filter, the prism, of the three non-market flows.
Knowledge: What have you discovered since you took this decision, and what did you get others to discover?
Trust: Do you feel ready now to take more risks?
Emotion: Can you now more easily accommodate the emotions rising in you?
There is no single answer, no quantified response.
You need to go find your own answer and embrace it in all its subjectivity.
Embracing the three non-market flows is to accept being exposed to the risk of criticism from others, without being able to defend yourself with rational arguments, not being able to rely on the conventions of the consumer society.
It's to be perceived as an eccentric, sometimes even as a self-centered person.
We will find peace when we can navigate that thin line of balance between who we are inside us and our necessary harmony with society.
(Applause) (Heart beats) Embracing your vulnerability, but also taking care of it.
Entrust it to those who love you.
Find those whom you dare to expose yourself in the palm of their hand, who will have the empathy and kindness to love you unconditionally. That's perhaps
where the secret of love lies.
(Applause)
