Well yes we are not used to this in France. To talk about happiness. Maybe it'll worry them; they will ask you if you're crazy. We prefer to moan in France and say everything that is wrong in our lives. So ...
all there is left to do is to live, before you eventually die!
Ah, but yes,
because it isn’t true!
Oh, no! We are not going to die. Well, not now!
It really was not true!
We are practicing ourselves!
Ah, we are practicing ourselves because, you know, the best practice before you die, do you know what is it?
Well it is to accumulate happiness. So, train yourself well. Train yourself well. Ah yes, happiness is now, right? Right?
(Applause)
TEDx pushes us to be ambitious.
So this evening I would like to propose a very ambitious project since it aims at revitalising Europe.
That's right, nothing less!
You have to aim high!
Because Europe is an extraordinary civilizational project.
Think about it: this is the first time a geographical union the size of an empire has been built by adhesion and not by invasion.
Because beyond the common values, since ancient times, over the centuries a real convergence of civilization has been established.
Despite the separations, despite the borders, despite the differences, both leisure and business travelers feel right at home in Rome as much as in Dublin, Copenhagen, Seville or Athens.
The artistic and architectural foundations, the cultural values, the human rights, the defense of the liberties, the rules of life, love and death are the same everywhere.
And yet, after a very enthusiastic beginning, political Europe is getting nowhere.
It seems that we are stuck, something keeps us from advancing, moving forward together.
Well, some say that it's because Europe is too bureaucratic, too economic, too centralized, not political enough ... Maybe.
I for one believe that what's missing in Europe is something fundamental.
Something that all burgeoning nations have imposed, sometimes by force, on their population in order to obtain unity.
Something that is so important that the countries lacking it are at constant risk of insurrection.
This something is a common language.
A people cannot be unified without a common language.
The Roman empire had Latin, the British empire had English, the Chinese have united through their ideograms, the Muslim world with Koranic Arabic, Latin America with Spanish, while in contrast Catalonia, Belgium and Quebec suffer great difficulties related mainly to the absence of a common language.
Until the late 18th century, Europe maintained some cohesion through its elites thanks to Latin.
And then, the emergence of the nation-states was established by imposing national languages and progressively eliminating Latin as a common language.
The emergence of nationalism and the breakdown of understanding lead, as everyone knows, to the horrible wars of the 20th century, which ultimately had only one virtue: convincing us of doing everything we could to achieve peace, to find peace ... And the best solution we have found for that was the invention of political Europe.
But since then, we have found it difficult to understand each other.
24 official languages!
No less!
Well, in this picture from the European Union website, everybody looks happy, but I can assure you it is Photoshopped!
Because in reality, having 24 languages is very difficult, very expensive, and it creates tensions.
So, of these 24 languages, three are considered working languages: German, French and, above all, English, which seems to be everywhere nowadays.
But the problem is that English is not everybody's language, English is not the Europeans' language.
English is at most the language of some of the European states, and what's more, the most important of those, unfortunately, has just slammed the door on our common house.
In addition, contrary to popular belief, English is a very difficult language to master, which leads to a lot of misunderstandings and a lot of suffering.
And it also leads lots of Europeans to be very reticent to use it because they feel it as a symbol of injustice and of submission to a foreign power.
Now then, if we want to unite Europe, we need a common language that is not English!
It can't be any of the European languages either for we'd only be replacing one injustice with another.
It won't be Latin, I can assure you right now, we need to know when to turn the page.
Esperanto could have been a good candidate, but unfortunately, it has many faults, such as being too theoretical and not natural enough, which in my opinion stops it from taking hold.
So, the European language doesn't exist.
Then what can we do?
How about being ambitious?
How about we create it?
Ridiculous?
Maybe ...
So what? All the better!
It seems that all good ideas are considered ridiculous at the beginning, then dangerous, and eventually obvious.
Because creating a language, building a language, is possible, as history has proved.
Literary Arabic is a created language, Swahili, the official language of Kenya and Tanzania, is a created language, modern Hebrew is also a created language and the least we can say is that they work!
So why not us, in Europe? Well then,
what characteristics should it have?
Well, we need to build a language that is the synthesis of the European languages, without favouring any of them; a language that is common, but not unique - if I am French, I keep the French but I also speak this common language - a language that is egalitarian between men and women, to avoid inclusion issues, a language that is a reflection of our history, meaning it has its roots in Greek and Latin, and then, above all, a language that is easy, easy to read, to learn, to understand.
As an example, a classic language like German or French requires 1500 hours to achieve a correct level.
On the other hand, a created language requires 150 hours, 10 times less!
Enough to tell you that it is interesting to go there.
Since we've established that no current language corresponds to these characteristics, and since I had some time to waste - it is important to waste time every now and again - well, I have built such a language, and I've called it Europeo, naturally.
So, how did I proceed?
It turns out that apart from being passionate about languages, I am also an IT engineer, I work with software, and so, like every other IT guy, like everyone nowadays, I have access, we have access, to extraordinary tools.
And the first one when we talk about languages is Google Translate.
I have created a program called europeo.li, which everyone can use - I invite you to try it out when you have a few minutes.
It is a program in which you enter a word, it doesn't matter in which European language, whichever word, and the program will translate it thanks to Google Translate into the 24 languages of the European Union.
It also works out the average and subsequently calculates the mean, taking into account the populations that speak each of these languages.
That way we obtain the most consensual word and, in an almost democratic way, the most European word.
So you can see what it looks like, here are some examples.
The chosen word is "ambitious".
So if I enter it into the program, we'll have the 24 translations and the European word will be "ambitios".
Another example, the word "beer" will be translated as "bier".
Another word, the word "want" will become "voler".
And the last example, the word "please" will be translated as "prose".
This will give us the most indispensable sentence wherever we are in Europe: "Lo vole un bier prose".
(Applause) Well, some other examples, if you don't like beer, I can propose un cidre, un vin rod, or un vin bianc, un aqua mineral, un orange suc, un te, or un cafe.
Well, that is me saying all these, but for you to get a realistic idea, so that you understand what its music and phonetics are like, I have asked some friends from all over Europe to make a little demonstration for you.
[Sofie, Belgia: Civilization european es extraordinar...] [Veronica, Spania: ma necessita un lingua.]
[Maria, Irland: It es possible!]
[Romania: L'union european deve far li maximum...] [Sofie, Belgia: ... por crear e adoptar un lingua comun...] [Maria, Irland: e por que alle citizens parla este lingua.]
[Romania: Por li futuro de Europa...] [Sofie, Belgia: ... un lingua comun es l'ultima ambition !]
Necessita une traduction?
The magic of this story is that technology allows us to dig up a language that is buried within us and that we all understand.
It's not our language and yet, without being really able to explain why, it is our language a bit because, in fact, it's more than a language, it's our common heritage coming out, and that's what should lead the European language.
As you will have understood, whether it's Europeo or any other created language - I'm thinking specifically about interlingue, o interlingua, which I also invite you to discover - to have ambition for Europe today is to dare to state that it is possible to imagine a common language, to put it in place, obviously with the help of linguists, and that only thanks to it we will be able to build a real unity in Europe.
Thank you.
(Applause)
So, the title of my presentation is: "Free will and neuroscience".
I will start, as would a good philosopher, by defining the terms, as if I were going to write an essay, but that won't be the case, don't worry.
Free will is the capacity to choose freely, the capacity we have to determine our own will.
It is a notion first introduced by Saint Augustine of Hippo in the 4th century A.D.
Originally, it was meant to justify the existence of evil,
in that, for Saint Augustine, it was not possible that God desired evil, though evil exists, it's a fact. So, it's man that is responsible for evil, and so, man must be free in his actions and choices.
Today, the advancements of neuroscience - so, neuroscience is all those sciences that study the brain, the nervous system, bringing together anatomy, physiology, as well as psychology, informatics and mathematics.
So, all these different disciplines came together in the sixties and seventies and pooled their data and methodologies in order to study the brain.
What we find is that neuroscience tell us today that we don't have a free will.
I'd like, in the next few minutes, to examine with you whether the data are, in fact, alarming, and whether it's not the case that we actually don't have any capacity to choose freely, or if there's still a little hope for us, and we do, perhaps, have this capacity, and, if so, to what extent.
You could object: "OK, but it's nothing new, science has been telling us ever since the 18th century that cause-and-effect is a universal law, and when I know what happened at any given moment, I can predict what will happen tomorrow, or I can infer what happened in the past."
This was indeed the idea Laplace had at the beginning of the 19th century, who formulated this idea, by saying for that a supreme intelligence, an omniscient intelligence, that at any given moment knew every force driving nature and the respective positions of everything that composed it, with, furthermore, a sufficiently vast intelligence to analyse all this data, embracing in the same formula the movements of the largest bodies of the universe and those of the lightest atom, nothing would be uncertain to it, and the future, and likewise the past, would be visible to its eyes.
So, this is the idea that was fundamental to classical physics, which is still used today, since scientists try to ascertain regularities, "the laws of nature".
Well, man is part of nature.
So, do we equally obey nature's regularities, it's "laws", or do we reside outside this universe?
If we adopt a materialistic point of view, which, today, is the most common one, man is part of nature, and it should be possible to explain his behaviour, his choices, his actions, in a deterministic way.
But neuroscience yields further data to be added to this fundamental position, since the experiments of Benjamin Libet in the eighties - if I can bring it up ... there we are - the experiments of Benjamin Libet in the eighties, showed that an electric potential is produced in our brain, a few hundred milliseconds before we are conscient of our decision to act.
So, how did he show that?
He asked some participants whose heads were wired up for an electroencephalogram, with an electromyogram recording muscular activity in their hands -
already we're made to feel really free, don't you think -
he asked them to look at this dial and to just let come a spontaneous desire to raise their index finger.
Simply that.
And, to him, this was ... the ultimate representation of our free will.
Well, that's debatable.
But, anyway, while the subject stared at the dial and let the desire to flex their index finger just come to them without determining beforehand the moment they would to do it, but, nonetheless, letting known where the luminous dot on the dial was when they made the decision - all quite complicated - he asked them to indicate the moment they made their decision, while all the while their cerebral activity was recorded. They showed, Benjamin Libet and his team, that an electric potential is produced in their brain 500 milliseconds before the action, and 300 milliseconds before the subject's conscient decision to raise the finger.
This tends to indicate that our brain, in some way, initiates, triggers the action, even before we are conscient of wanting to raise our finger.
This, therefore, in effect, puts into question the tenet of free will, according to which, we are the ultimate source of our acts, of our choices. There's no ultimate source, since everything is predetermined by cerebral, unconscious events that are completely outside our conscious mind.
Perhaps I can go on to the next slide.
Yes.
Or this one, in fact.
This just shows the timescale of events.
So there, you see the electric potential in the brain, so, inconscient, there, the conscious decision, and here the motor action.
So, this is the order in which events take place.
I've tried, in my book, "Un nouveau libre arbitre" ["A new free will"], to include this data, to take it into account, and to consider whether these experiments could, nonetheless, leave room for a certain capacity of free will.
The redefinition I propose revolves around two points.
Firstly, let's say, it has been proved that certain unconscious processes can still be the subject of the conscious mind.
I'll start again: famous psychological experiments showed that when we make a choice, a decision, most of the time, we are not conscious of the causes determining our choice.
For example, a Swedish team demonstrated that when we ask a participant shown two faces to choose the one they prefer, and we magically show them the picture they didn't choose, but we ask them: "Why did you choose this picture?" -
it's totally mean - effectively, the person will rationalize that choice that they didn't make.
They will say, "That person had a nicer smile" etc, etc.
Furthermore, this protocol has been reproduced in the form of an interview where the participant is induced to maintain their attention on the cognitive processes that brought them to a particular choice.
In other words, when we ask them why they chose a particular face, most often, the most probable reasons are automatically arrived at.
They don't take the time to go back to the moment they chose the image and what precisely, conclusively, led to their choice, what they saw and felt, what they felt emotionally in relation to the face, for example.
This interview technique allows us to look at the results of the Swedish team in an opposite way.
When the participants are approached in this way, they detect the manipulation in 80% of cases,
while before, they were manipulated without realizing it and they rationalized a choice they didn't make in 80% of cases.
So, what this says is that extending our own consciousness is possible.
Inconscient processes can become conscient by redirecting our attention.
And this is one part of the definition I want to put to you today: that free will is not the capacity to be the ultimate source of our acts. There are, of course, lots of things that determine us, but we can, to a certain extent, develop this capacity, so it's a learning process, not something we can presume to have by nature, rather a training of our attentional skills.
And the other part of my redefinition - if I can go on to the next slide - There are also neuroscience experiments concerning the Stroop effect.
The Stroop effect, very well known in psychology, is the effect that we have, whereby if I ask you the colour of this word, it's easier and quicker for you to answer than if I ask you the colour of the word down here -
even more so if you are English speakers, since the words are in English -
simply because at the top, the colour of the ink matches that given by the word, while at the bottom, the colour of the ink does not match that given by the word
This effect is highly automatic, something we cannot control.
But a researcher at McGill University in Montreal, called Amir Raz, showed that this effect could actually be deautomatized.
So a very automatic effect like this one can be deautomatized by hypnotic suggestion to interpret this chain of letters as a meaningless chain.
Therefore, if we hypnotize one of the participants of the study, telling them that this chain of words means nothing, the automatic effect will be deautomatized and reduced.
This means that even some unconscious, highly automated processes can be modified.
And so some of the behaviours we exhibit every day that are highly automatic are sometimes very useful, like when driving, it's better not to continually ask ourselves questions about what we need to do with the pedals, the gearbox, etc., at some point, it becomes very automatic and so much better, while other behaviours we'd sometimes like to abandon, like, for example, smoking 30 cigarettes a day, or stuffing down a box of cookies we fancy because we haven't the self-control - these types of compulsions. It shows, in fact, that these behaviours that have become automatized with time can be deautomatized to let us find again some sort of flexibility and to expand the inventory of available actions.
So there.
So, to sum up, there's the idea that neuroscience put to us to start out with that our free will could be compromised since, effectively, there are inconscient precursors to our actions that we don't necessarily have control over, and it would seem we are dictated to by these unconscious precursors.
But then neuroscience itself shows us round this: attention is an essential ability we have that modulates what will or will not enter our consciousness.
And so, I just wanted to show you that free will still exists, but that it might be a bit more difficult to access it, that it necessitates the long-term training of our attentional skills.
And I thank you for your attention.
(Applause)
When I was little, while my friends dreamed of being police officers, firefighters, or even astronauts, I dreamed of being an entrepreneur.
I would say, "I want to be a boss, like my dad."
Indeed, my father was an entrepreneur, and my two grandfathers were entrepreneurs.
I imagined a company to be an extraordinary place, where you create products and services to improve people's lives.
My dream slipped out of reach during my academic career, which was rather painful.
I was going for a vocational degree in industrial automation, destined to become a factory worker.
But at 16, I joined the workforce through sandwich training.
Finally, something real.
I felt much more comfortable there.
And when I was 20, my uncle asked me, "Are you still dreaming of becoming an entrepreneur?"
And that's when I realised,
yes, I was still dreaming of it.
At 22, I started my own company,
a small industrial printing factory, located in Brioude in Haute-Loire.
So, as all things start, it was as difficult as it was exciting.
But my team and I were already really enjoying this adventure.
In survival mode, for the first two years, we went straight to the point: no time for meetings, objectives, rules, methods, etc. Only the drive to do well.
The result?
The third year, we launched.
We launched so well that we doubled our sales revenue and took the lead in the market.
And so, we developed, and invested in the construction of our first factory and automated machines.
At that moment, the whole scope changed, and everything dramatically shifted.
I felt a sort of general pressure. I had advice from everywhere, that was always the same: "Listen!"
"If you want your company to succeed, you need to structure yourself better, impose work methods."
At the time, this seemed logical.
I set up the company with a manager, rules, methods, processes... controls.
In short, the fun stuff.
(Laughter) But as we became a "real" company, the atmosphere degraded. The magic disappeared.
As for me, I took less pleasure in work. I even began to stress until I felt butterflies in my stomach.
I had the strange feeling I had become dependent on the company's financial results by which I was now judged - by my colleagues, by the banks, and even by my team.
And this pressure pushed me forward, where I always needed to do more.
No surprise, it was a bad year.
At that time, I was 25. The company wasn't my dream anymore.
Because, if my childhood dream was to become a boss, implicitly, I also aspired to be happy.
And that's when I realised that this wasn't the case.
So one morning, I went to the factory, and decided to explain my ill-being.
I saw only two paths: I could sell the company, or fundamentally overhaul all our modes of operation.
They were a bit surprised, but mainly relieved.
I finally understood that this wasn't working.
Our re-structuring to try to seem like a real business didn't have the desired effect at all, while our spontaneous benevolence had proved itself in our first few years.
So we decided to drop all this complexity.
Our first collective reflection brought us to think of two approaches that should become priorities.
One, satisfy the fundamental needs of the group; and two, rethink the company's mission.
So, with respect to the fundamental needs, our decisions have primarily pertained to the work environment:
What kind of work pace do we want?
Which tools would we like?
What freedoms do we wish to have?
We listed all the pressures that we could eliminate with respect to the company's mission.
In your opinion, what is the goal of a company?
To make more profit? To create more growth?
For us, it's not about always making more. It's not "growth at all costs" anymore, but simply to improve the products and services we offer by improving our working approach.
To think in terms of benefits, growth, recruitment, is to make results our priority, and it does not in any case constitute, in our eyes, a goal.
We proved that already.
So, to avoid trusting our intuition alone, I did some research on companies with different modes of operation.
And I was incredibly surprised to discover that the majority of companies that stand out and make me dream have atypical modes of operation, where the entrepreneur not only manages, but also brings deep meaning to his actions.
As Antoine de Saint-Exupéry said so well, "If you want to built a boat, don't gather your men to give them orders, to explain every detail, to tell them where to find things.
If you want to build a boat, teach them to long for the sea."
And that makes sense.
I would now like to share with you some examples that illustrate our bigger challenges.
Like the last time I did recruiting, for example. I chose someone absolutely competent, but his integration period was less than stellar.
The team asked me, "Can we try to do our own recruiting?"
The difference was that they chose someone that they could imagine working well with.
And suddenly, they were much more patient and better at teaching.
The result was just astounding.
In a few months, we had a new team member.
I also sometimes tended to think for them, to think I knew what was good for them.
And I was thoroughly committed to installing a lounge for them, with a little dining area à la Google.
I told myself, "They'll really love this."
But strangely, I felt very little enthusiasm from them.
So I pressed them, without understanding. And I asked them, "What do you really want?"
They told me, "We want to keep our couches, and just change the coffee table."
Having wanted to do good, I only created frustration.
So not only did they change the coffee table, but they even offered it to me -
a magnificent coffee table with the company logo engraved in the metal.
As you know, every mistake allows us grow.
Very early one morning, they loaded hard resin into the machine instead of soft resin.
The result? Two days of non-compliant production, around 100,000 pieces.
When the team realised the mistake, I was away for the weekend.
So, without consulting me, they took the initiative to financially compensate the client for the production loss, to cancel their Christmas vacations, and to guarantee them a delivery in time to ensure the product launch.
The most incredible thing was that I was informed by the client himself.
(Laughter) He could not believe it, whereas for the team, it was natural.
In the end, our worst case of non-compliance was also our most amazing customer experience.
At the other end of the spectrum, out of our about 900 clients, there was one with whom doing business was always complicated,
and who, despite all our efforts, remained unsatisfied.
This client represented around 15% of our sales revenue,
but 90% of our stress.
You know what I mean?
So we looked again for a solution.
They sent me to explain our lack of understanding to the client, to figure out how to work better together.
You can imagine the scene where I explain our stress problems to the client.
(Laughter) His response was, "But work is like that, it's normal, it's not my problem."
So we decided to stop working with him.
That year, we brought in less revenue and made less profit. But we were so happy!
(Laughter) (Applause) In the end, we incredibly improved our quality of life.
And this reassured us that health should always come first.
So now, you may be saying that there's something important missing.
Pleasure in work, that's great, but when we think of "work", we also think "pay".
And this could be a source of frustration.
So when it's time for annual performance reviews, let me tell you, I'm not at all comfortable doing this face-to-face, with everyone defending their case.
So, I asked the team, "What if we all talked together?"
What's incredible, is that they agreed to speak freely and as a group on this taboo topic.
And there we were, for hours and hours, trying to think up a multitude of possible ways to get paid.
Until we arrived at a solution.
And this remains, without a doubt, our most beautiful success and our greatest proof of trust.
By the way, do you know who helped me prepare this talk?
My team, of course!
In the beginning, they laughed.
But it was they who chose what was important to share with you here.
Together, we tried to create a company in which everyone wants to work, one that doesn't confuse goals with results, one where we forget the tyranny of numbers and profits, one where we prefer happiness, freedom, and fulfillment.
And you?
What kind of company do you dream of?
Thank you!
(Applause)
OK?
Now everyone please stop talking.
I'm going to ask you to remain totally silent,
absolutely silent.
I guess you should now find it quieter.
But me, well, I'm totally unaware.
It's as if no one were on this stage.
Imagine your mother's voice, imagine the noise of cars, imagine a loudspeaker at a train station, or even your alarm clock.
I have absolutely no idea of them!
Imagine watching 'Game of Thrones' on mute.
You can experience and see everything, you just can't hear anything.
That is my reality.
It can come in useful, I can sleep without being disturbed by my neighbour's music.
So, that's it. That's the truth of it.
You will have guessed:
I'm deaf.
I can't hear anything at all.
I can't explain to you why.
It's the mystery of my life.
I wasn't born deaf, nor did I suffer from an illness, but I'm talking to you here today, despite the fact that my siblings insist on making me believe that I was adopted, or that my parents found me in a bin, because no one else in my family is deaf.
You may have noticed that the way I talk is a bit strange,
more like a foreigner.
Lots of people ask me: 'What country are you from?'
I'm from Deafland.
I don't really feel handicapped.
That's what has always made me different, a boon that sets me apart equally as much among the hearing as among the deaf.
Nevertheless, my mum always wanted to make my life easier.
She wanted to teach me sign language, together with my brother and my sister and my cousins too.
Everyone was enthusiastic about learning this new language,
but not me.
I would sulk in a corner like a cat and sound off that, no, I wanted to speak out loud and understand people without using my hands.'
However - you must be wondering: 'This girl can't hear a thing.
How does she manage to cope with everyday life?'
Well, as you already know, the topic today is the relationship between man and technology.
So, I'm going to tell you three things.
We are obviously in the 21st century. I'm 24 years old, and we live in a universe where technological prowess is ever increasing.
Thus, for example, when I was seven, my mum - it was my mum who taught me to use a computer, while for those of my generation it's usually the other way round:
it's us, the young, who teach our parents how to use a computer.
That was not the case with me.
And so I was absolutely fascinated when, with the click of a button, she introduced me to the magic of Google.
I was curious as a child, and I'm still curious.
Since I wasn't able to hear the information I was picking up, unlike yourselves, I devoured every newspaper, every magazine. The Internet is a way of multiplying infinite capacities of knowledge and information.
So when I was in secondary school, I could integrate better because there were people who wrote posts about their lives on 'Skyblog'.
The content wasn't always all that interesting, but I could share interests with my classmates during break, know what they were talking about, and all of that was great.
Of course, years have gone by, and we now have more interesting blogs with more useful content.
And, obviously, Facebook has become an integral part of our social lives.
Of course, there are the downsides of social networking sites, but I can't tell you enough just how much I was born at the right time, how much I feel on a par with my hearing peers.
For example, you'll be familiar with apps like FaceTime, WhatsApp and Skype,
but RogerVoice is, without a doubt, one of the best apps available.
Deaf people can't usually make calls,
but, thanks to this, they can.
I call someone, they reply to me at full voice, and my smartphone transcribes everything they say.
In other words, long live smartphones!
But you know, I'm currently doing a Masters in European Affairs at Sorbonne University, which means I'm nearing the end of my studies.
I don't know if, without these technologies, without the help of my classmates, I'd have been like the class dumbo and have copied my classmates' notes in order to get hold of all the course material.
Who knows if I'd have been able to keep studying at this level.
But I'm a girl much taken by challenge.
Because, in fact, not only did I try to speak French, more or less correctly, but I also wanted to speak English.
So, I went on Erasmus for a year to Hungary, to Budapest.
It was a fabulous year.
At first, It was challenging to understand and speak English with people from every corner of Europe and the world.
At the end of the year, not only had I met the challenge, but, beyond that, I had realized that anything is possible when you really want it.
But myself apart, only 4% of disabled people, of deaf people, have access to higher education.
That's really not a lot, and I hope that when I'm 98 years old, there will be at least 98% of deaf people, of disabled people, engaged in higher education.
And to do this, we need researchers, we need engineers, in short, a future genius, a Steve Jobs of the future, to shine forth with ingenuity in order to improve the lives of billions of disabled people who live in this world.
Technology is not only at the service of mankind, it is also a tremendous springboard for those who are without a leg, for those who are without sight, and for those who can't hear, like me.
We really need to stop approaching the question of disability from a pessimistic angle.
On the contrary, we need to make it sexy.
Of course, this is not to downplay the difficulties that disability brings; it's rather to consider these differences as a trump card, a key that allows access to further and greater innovation. Man is not made for standing idle; on the contrary, he aspires to evolve and progress.
I would like you to be fully aware that there really is a fundamental difference between being disabled and having a disability.
And to do that, you must truly understand that more than the disability itself, it is society that disables.
Thank you for your attention.
(Applause) (Cheering)
Hello everyone.
I'm very happy to be here with you this midday today, and to introduce my story and my project.
Who among you has never had an idea for an invention, an idea which one day might revolutionize the world, but who didn't have the means to realise it?
Most people have already had this ambition.
As for me, I had this ambition at the age of five, through tools.
As I watched my dad tinker, I found it very simple.
And with plastic screwdrivers, I thought I could one day revolutionize the world. It was very modest, in my garden.
But, well, I was only five years old, and it was merely a start.
Then came high school in which we have other priorities such as, first, doing one's homework, review one's Life and Earth Sciences class.
It's: "Keep calm, do your homework and no room for more". That way, no questions would be asked.
But, fortunately for me, or rather unfortunately for my parents, I was fond of tinkering,
like taking apart my mom's hair dryer, or my dad's razor without knowing, sometimes, how to put it back together.
I had this passion, and at the end, I could see that even at a young age, I could succeed in doing things myself with my own hands.
And this has been a really important observation for me.
Ultimately, all those problems that the grown-ups have in starting their companies - the administrative issues - I ignored them; so I had some kind of naive side which allowed me to be very, very quick in procedures.
So, at age 13, I registered my first patent. It was a true adventure. My first patent at the INPI was for a machine to brew tea.
Stated like this, it does not mean anything. But in fact, it was a robotic arm that allowed you to put in a tea bag. It calculated the type of tea, the heat, then, after a while, it removed the tea bag, and you had a perfectly brewed beverage.
So, I was 13 years old.
This reinforced my acknowledgement that even as kids, we could do cool stuff.
As I worked on my inventions and filed patents, I was really enjoying myself in parallel with my school career. It didn't prevent me from going to high school and get my diploma just like everyone else.
One day, I had a big realization, a realization we've all had early, that is: waking up.
To wake up every morning was rather frustrating.
We just can't manage to slip out of our comforter.
Yet one of the biggest decisions of our days is to get out of bed. Pretty crazy!
I've had a hard time making this decision. At times I made it, at times not, depending on the day.
I told myself, "What about trying to find a new way?"
Sound, radio, light already existed. What about waking up with a scent alone?
In addition, why not with a scent
we like and chose? A bit like capsules?
That's the reason why I created the olfactory alarm Sensorwake.
It's quite simple. It's this box here.
You see, it really looks like
a classic alarm clock, except that here, there's a slot in which we can insert a cartridge of our choice.
For example here, it's a wood fragrance, for someone who likes nature.
He will wake up in two minutes with this wood smell alone.
We have cola scent, seaside scent.
And for businessmen, there's even the dollar scent.
So the selection is practically infinite.
We can place a great selection of cartridges into the alarm.
One cartridge is 60 alarms. Unlike coffee machines, everything is recyclable, so there's no problem concerning that.
The scents do not contain any solvent, any VOC, volatile organic compounds, so it's something that is 100% safe. Developing it was very dear to my heart.
This began in the garage with the famous Arduino boards, so no need to know a lot. Progressively, it began to work well. I gave a lot of myself to this.
It was during my revisions for the final exams. I was 17. I participated in a Google competition, the Google Science Fair. I had the chance to be the first Frenchman to be selected for the Google Science Fair that you'll soon see here.
It is an international science competition which gathers all the young researchers. Google selects 15 projects annually to come to Silicon Valley.
So, I had the chance to be the first selected Frenchman.
This earned me first a great joy, a beautiful experience, some practice of my English - not bad either - but above all, the recognition of an invention which sometimes is difficult to obtain.
It's good to invent, but it equally good to share it and communicate.
So, this earned me a dinner with Anne-Sophie Lapix, a question to Najat at Le Petit Journal, a meeting with Stéphane Sommier, so a true launching pad, a real exponential growth, and, thanks to this science competition, a crazy experience - that's the word - and also a preparation of myself knowing that, even at a young age, we can make our dreams come true, we can go beyond the possible, and that a simple idea can become a concrete, rather sexy project, that can be communicated, and may one day, modestly of course, change and improve our everyday lives.
So what I invite young people to do today, is: we have the chance to be in the 21st century, youths can prove that they have the means to succeed.
Before, it was harder.
Historically, we don't know of many youths who could impose their idea.
Nowadays, we have many tools, such as the Arduino boards.
With the internet, a simple idea can create a buzz, as we can see with Youtube videos.
Finally, to conclude, I can remember a phrase which greatly impressed me, which was somehow the Google Science Fair's slogan, a phrase that I had to repeat many times in front of the camera. It is: "It's your turn to change the world."
I think that in the 21st century, it's a phrase that truly resonates. And for this TEDx too, "Beyond possibilities", it really make sense.
Thank you very much.
(Applause)
How did you choose
your profession? Your job?
How did you get to where you are today?
Really, how?
Did you choose between risk and safety?
Were you pushed by your parents?
Are you scared of unemployment?
What choice did you make?
Because we all make choices.
We start when we're very young, and get asked: "Would you rather eat a spoon of maggots a day, or a tarantula a month?"
That doesn't have a huge impact, but these are your first choices.
When we get to seventh grade: Spanish or German?
Then in ninth grade: a vocational course, an academic course, or maybe other routes.
We get to 18 and have to choose our career path, when we're not even old enough to drink a beer in the US.
But how did you know that you made the right choice?
Did you already know that you'd made the right choice?
These aren't rhetorical questions, I really ask myself them.
I'm 21 and doing a masters in finance, and I'm a little scared that I was wrong.
Do you remember your childhood dreams?
What did you dream of becoming?
A schoolteacher, a cashier, an astronaut?
When I was young I dreamed of being Jamy.
You know, Jamy from "C'est pas sorcier" on France 3?
I used to love that.
About science that needed to be passed on. I thought that was great.
Today, I'm doing a masters in finance.
I wonder what happened to me?
I think to myself: "Will you stay in finance?"
And in the end, I tell myself : "Maybe not forever."
Is it really that serious to be wrong, after all?
I turned to my parents, my colleagues, my close friends, to teachers, and I said to them: "Well, what am I doing?"
Seriously, what am I doing?
After my studies, what am I doing?
In the end, there were as many answers as people asked.
I was told: "Be a trader for ten years and relax in the sun afterwards."
"Work in finance, maybe you'll like it."

"Set up a business." "Change your degree."
I got all sorts of answers.
The most interesting thing wasn't what I'd said, because frankly, I know nothing about it, but what people replied, and how much their generation was influencing their response.
And I say their generation, and not their age, because a 20 year old and a 50 year old don't have the same professional ambitions. Their generation.
I was born in 1995, making me a member of Generation Z. Do you know Generation Z?
It's the generation born after 1994, children of a society undergoing profound change, who find themselves today in the midst of all this technology. They are the latest update of the human race with a new organ transplant that you know: the smartphone.
You all have one, I imagine.
This cerebral bullet train that goes from eye to thumb, has changed everything.
Because nowadays, if at 3AM I want to know what Chinese pandas eat, well, ladies and gentlemen, I can find out.
That may not change anything for you, but it has changed everything.
It was Google in elementary school, MSN in middle school, Facebook in high school, and today, Instagram, Pinterest, and so on.
But is this generation well received?
So, imagine that last night I was reading an article on the train, a Point article, and there was such a sweet portrait of my generation.
Narcissistic social network addicts, high on 4G, drunk on WiFi, full of themselves, clearly, in short, magnificent and kind people.
But is this generation really terrible?
And yet we're going to have to collaborate, you and I.
We'll have to work together.
Because today there are three generations in the job market.
One: the baby boomers.
Born between 1950 and 1965.
They enjoyed a boom in employment.
They are more attracted by hierarchy, by structure.
Next, we have Gen X: born between 1965 and 1980.
They're the opposite.
Jobs weren't particularly good, they had to persevere, to work hard.
And then, Gen Y.
Gen Y is those born between 1980 and 1995.
They saw their parents slave away at work.
They saw them be fired after years of dedicated work.
That's when they said: "Stop, I don't want that.
I will be in charge of my own life."
So, you can imagine the bosses from Generation X and the young people from Generation Y, that's not going to work.
And there, the miracle of Gen Z comes along. It's already difficult to manage Gen Y's dreams, now we have to stamp out Gen Z, children of mother technology, brought up on Google, Facebook, Instagram, who go out chasing Pokémon.
Brilliant, we love it.
But in fact, the Zs are rather more simple.
What do they want at work, this generation ?
Studies show that 50% want
to be an entrepreneur. That's great.
But you and me, we know very well that 50% of my generation won't do that, won't set up a business.
Well, what does it mean for a young person starting out?
For a young person, it means carving a place for themselves.
It's still a very vague concept.
It's saying: "I have knowledge, I have skills, and I'm going to put them to use in a business, and in exchange, the business will give me their knowledge."
A mutual sharing of knowledge.
And that's when Gen Z think: "Like Y, I want to be in charge of my life, but better still, I want to be in charge of my knowledge.
I will learn from the business, from my degree, but equally from myself."
Because with new technology today, you have online classes, all sorts of things where you can get a degree from Harvard or l'École Polytechnique, by spending a few hours a week on the internet.
And that changes everything.
So, today, wouldn't taking action be aspiring to really know these subjects in order to master them better and to be innovative ?
So, are we really that different, us, Xs, Ys, and Zs, the baby boomers and soon the Alphas.
You're all looking at me like I'm a little too idealistic.
It's an idealistic draft.
Is my generation a generation of idealists, of dreamers, out of touch with reality?
I was born in 1995, so, like I said,
I'm a part of Generation Z. My little sister was an economic crisis.
I never knew the baguette at three francs.
I saw more cabinet reshuffles than presidents of France.
I have more faith in the Loch Ness monster than in retirement at 60.
And at school, I unfortunately learned, our planet is doomed, the final deadline being 2050.
I don't think that Generation Z is an ungrateful generation, spoiled rotten with a smartphone in its mouth.
I don't think that we're so different.
We are different because we have unequal life circumstances.
When my grandfather was 13, he saw the end of the Second World War.
When my father was 13, he saw the first oil crises which ended 30 years of economic growth.
When I was 13, it was the start of the economic crisis.
So, are we really that different?
I am not a member of Generation Z. No.
I am a member of society Z. A society which you have passed down to us with the challenges that went with it.
I am a member of a society in perpetual evolution.
I am from a composite generation, made of baby boomers, who taught us work, of Gen X, who taught us perseverance, of Gen Y, who taught us to bring out the individual and not the worker.
I am many generations.
I am you.
So, finally, can we work together and are we our degree?
Am I my degree, am I a financier?
No, I don't think so.
I think we are much more than that today, and that we can pass on even more still.
Now, perhaps when you see a young person stuck to their phone, you'll say to yourself: "I was the same, but in a different way."
As for me, I'm going to continue to take an interest in politics in the economy, in cooking, in astrology, in science, in whatever I want, in fact, because I won't have to choose my degree.
Thank you.
(Applause)
I've never been alone.
I was born with someone else. I have a twin sister called Lucie. She's amazing. She's probably the person in the world who makes me laugh the most.
If I'm telling you this, it's because being a twin has consequences.
Being a twin means creating your identity with a partner. It means always being relative to someone else and so always compare yourself.
This led me to question our education system.
I am a pure product of the national education.
Made in Henry IV High School, packaged in a prestigious university -I mean this one- I've followed "the road," sometimes more of a highway, without questioning myself too much.
Highways are convenient you can just put yourself on autopilot.
So, our education system is perfect for people like me, for certain types of talents such as people with structure who can see life as three structures and three substructures and who easily adapt.
For all the rest, people like my sister, who don't really want to adapt, those who break the mold, for them, school is often seen as a battle,
a battle to be won by getting a diploma, that little piece of paper that will allow us to begin our life at long last.
For all these people, it's only once they get out of the system that they realize they're good at something, they have talents.
Now, I can tell you that my sister is doing well and she's successful, but I've told myself all along those years that there was a problem,
a problem with waste of talents.
Why is it that my sisters' talent took so long to come out?
Why did it take her 20 years to excel?
And why was only my talent recognized in school?
Really, a talent isn't limited to being a piano virtuoso.
We have such a restrictive idea of talent that we think we don't even have any.
In the real meaning of the word, a talent is something we do naturally and without effort.
It could be being an incredibly good listener.
It could be being a super-good organizer, or being able to convince anyone in less than two minutes.
We all have talents. But the thing is we are not aware of them firstly because we exercise them without effort, and secondly because usually, they weren't valued at school and most probably, we aren't using them at work.
So, why is it important to know our talent?
Okay, let's do a quick show of hands.
Who has ever told himself, "I'm useless"?
Be honest.
Okay now, who has ever told himself, "I'm hardly in a position to do what I do"?
Okay.
And "I'll never make it"?
Now, all three?
Okay, those in that case please come and see me after, we've psychological treatment unit.
Seriously, we're all telling ourselves these things all the time.
I do it almost every day.
That's precisely why it's so important to ask yourself what your good at, what your talents are.
At what point in life do we realize our full potential?
Me, I got lucky because I was lead to ask myself some of these questions quite early on.
In fact, on arriving at this fine establishment two things happened.
The first is that I lost my talent.
I had intensely studied literature before. So I went from metaphysical questions to financial management and it was quite a shock for me. Therefore, I wasn't so good at school anymore.
That lead me to the second thing which is asking this abyssal question, "Why?"
"Why was I studying what I was studying?"
I was told about profit maximization but I found hard to believe that it was the only end goal of all my classes.
So, during this first year, I often thought about leaving, running away.
Then I said to myself I'd actually worked hard to get this far and that I should scratch below the surface.
So, I went yes, but on a journey of discovery about my university.
That's how I discovered the unlikely combination of two words: social entrepreneurship.
And I became fascinated by these two words for the eight following years.
I realized that going on a journey sometimes means making an effort to stay where you are.
But back then, I hadn't fully taken that lesson on board.
"Going on a journey" only meant for me, going far away, going somewhere else.
So, that's what I did. I traveled the world for nine months. It was amazing. Then I came back home to France,
And there, I was lost.
At the time, I wanted to leave again, I wanted to go live abroad, to be again somewhere else, to run away again.
But actually, my real journey began here.
Well, not quite here in Cergy but nearby in Paris.
It began with a meeting, the meeting of three incredible people who were reinventing the world around a bottle of a bad red wine.
They invited me to join them on their journey, an entrepreneurial adventure that allowed me to take action regarding the issue I was passionate about, the waste of talent.
So three years ago, with the help of many others, these associates and I set up "Ticket for Change."
Ticket for Change starts with the idea that everyone has talents.
I hope I've now convinced you
about that. Now, the real question is "What do we do with these talents?"
How could we enable each person to use their talents to have a positive impact on society?
How could we connect each problem in the world and one of these talents in order to solve it?
Because there are thousands of people in France who want to act but they don't know where to start.
We even did a nationwide study with the help of a consultant,
and we found out that for every 100 French, 74 say they want to take action to solve a social issue, but are not doing it.
Now, that's a waste of talent.
So, how can we go about helping all these talents to act and get involved?
Well, we are developing programs to train and educate people about entrepreneurship:
a social start-up incubator, a free online course open to all, workshops, talks ...
In three years we reached more than 53,000 people.
We brought forward more than 400 projects, and provide a long term support to 89 social start-ups, some of whom are present here.
Rather, we supported 89 talents.
We help them develop their projects from a legal and financial point of view. We introduce them to the right mentors and experts. We support them in all those things but,
what's really unique is that we help them activate their talents. And that's when they really become entrepreneurial.
Because being "an entrepreneur" is temporary. It's a job title, an occupation.
But being "entrepreneurial" is an enduring attitude.
In fact, it means being capable in any situation, be it in your private life or your professional life, of approaching each problem by asking yourself, "Is there not a solution to resolve this?"
This comes at the right time, since we'll have more than a few problems to resolve over the coming years.
There are local and global problems that are urgent and important, and you know them already, but I've got three bits of good news.
The first one is that some people are already leading the way, they are taking action and showing us that it's possible.
I told you about 89 of them, but there are thousands more in France and millions around the world.
The second is that each one of us has solutions to offer.
Each one of us has one or more talents that allows him to approach each problem of the world from their own unique perspective.
And finally, the third one is that our talents today can have a potentially massive impact.
Thanks to modern technology, thanks to these powerful computers that we carry around in our pockets, we can do extraordinary things from our living rooms.
We are potential super heroes.
So yes, go on a journey! Go on a journey, but do it in an entrepreneurial way.
Go far away if you have to, but leave asking yourself why you're leaving, and best of all, go into self-discovery, go to discover your talents.
Try this exercise: tomorrow or this week,
really try to spot situations again in your private or professional life, where you enjoy being yourself, you feel whole and unique.
Spot those moments where you feel you're realizing your potential, where you're good.
Make note of it and keep it somewhere in your mind or better yet say it, work it out.
So, it's super scary, I know, so, let me show you. I'll do it.
Me, my talent it is my ability to transmit my energy, to transmit what I have inside.
So, there it is.
Now, it's your turn.
So, on your talents ... get set ... go!
Thank you.
(Applause)
Are there any heroes in the room?
(Audience) Yes!
That's wonderful!
Well, I should leave then since we're already all heroes.
But you, heroes, can stay.
No, those who are not heroes, those who are here anyway, when you hear: "Are you a hero?", don't you feel a little scared
while wondering, "If I am asked that, then I shall be asked something more, maybe to go and give my life, to go and fight, perhaps to be the one on the raft who will be fed to the others, because someone must sacrifice himself"?
So, the hero is the one who saves the world.
If there are heroes, the world is saved but if there's none, what do we do?
And what if right now, by this door, a terrorist comes in, and aims at us?
Who will do what?
Who is going to throw himself on him to prevent him, to disarm him?
Who is going to hide, to protect his wife, his son?
Who?
And how can we know, until it has happened?
We all want to be heroes; we dream of being a hero and when the moment comes, we reveal ourselves.
Personally, it happened to me once, on a small scale; it was November 15, 2015.
Two days after the attacks against the Bataclan and the cafés in Paris, I was with many others at Place de la République and I went to pay some respect near a café, Le Carillon.
Then some friends and I went to sit on the terrace of a café, we were not even afraid!
At that moment, we heard detonations, real noises of gunshots.
Everyone rushed to the ground. I fell. We flipped the table. I cut myself. I vaguely tried to protect the person next to me.
The bartender lowered the iron curtain.
In 10 seconds, it was a war scene.
Ten seconds.
So what do we do at that time?
Because the hero is the one who precisely is ready to expose his life, to brave death for something that is beyond himself, something essential, something that he considers more important than his well-being, his comfort and perhaps even his existence.
So the hero may be the one who can arise at any moment.
Of course, there are professional heroes, whose job is to do so, so to speak.
Let's take the same example, a train, a train between Amsterdam and Paris, a Thalys precisely.
A terrorist comes out, points a gun. He is ready to shoot.
Four people, with their bare hands, interfere, intervene.
They stop him.
Among these four people, there are two American soldiers, two people trained to fight, we could say, trained to have courage, and who therefore have reflexes.
It doesn't make their gesture less heroic but still, they were prepared.
Okay, there are these professional heroes, but what about the other two?
A 23-year-old American student, and an English senior, a consultant.
This particular event, this crisis, revealed something that is essential.
So, we can always ask ourselves, "What would I have done?"
What would we have done if during German occupation, someone knocks on your door at night; we hear planes flying over us; we hear bombs.
Someone knocks on the door, and there is a 10-year-old little girl with a yellow star who says, "Hide me, there are soldiers who are looking for me."
What would I have done myself?
Would I have opened?
Would I have said, "I can't. I too have children"?
Would I have said, "Go there and hide"?
Let's rethink what happened on January 9, 2015: an hostage-taking in a kosher supermarket, a Super Kosher.
There were, two days before, the attacks against Charlie;
Paris, France, the world is in shock.
And, during this hostage-taking, a Malian employee, someone who is not directly threatened a priori, in any case, someone opens the door and hides the hostages.
He revealed himself at that moment.
Something arose we did not know about him, that maybe he himself did not know, something that is essential, something heroic.
He was able to write a book a year later called: "I'm not a hero, I didn't do anything special," as if to clear himself or nearly apologize, just as this pilot who managed to land his plane, whose engines were dead, on New York's river, the Hudson: "I did my job."
Yes, but there is the way you did it: a heroic job.
These figures, those beings whose natural vocation is not to save, protect, who are not firefighters, who are not first-aiders, who are not soldiers defending people, these ordinary men, at one extraordinary given point, during a crisis, in a dangerous situation, or in a disaster situation, have been heroic.
It means that among what makes a hero, of course, there are often qualities.
There is strength, since the Odyssey, the Iliad, Achilles with his extraordinary strength.
There're trickery and even the superpowers of our current superheroes.
There is all that.
But all these qualities are secondary qualities in the sense that they are means.
The queen of all qualities, the one that will activate all the others and give them meaning is courage; that's why at any given time, we are able to go one step further, to dare, and from then on, we become a legend, someone who acts with courage, and leaves his name in History and in memories, someone whom no one will forget what he did.
I had the chance to meet someone like this once in my life, someone who inspired me and besides, has changed a lot of things for me.
It was ten years ago, at the end of one of my shows, a woman came to see me.
She says to me, "I saw many of your shows, I liked them.
- Thank you.
- I'd like you to tell my father's story.
- Who is your father?
- His name is Haïm Lipsky,
born in Poland in a working-class Jewish family of seven children, in the 1920s, very poor, and he happened to have a passion for music.
He absolutely wanted to become a violinist.
His parents said,
"You're crazy! You can't.
You won't have enough to survive,"
but he stubbornly persisted.
He used to sneak into classical concerts.
He managed to save small pennies, buy a violin and become a violinist.
- Magnificent!
- War comes: 1939, Germany invades Poland.
Haïm finds himself locked in the Lodz ghetto.
Half of his family dies, brothers and sisters.
He survives, thanks to his violin, because he plays, and because it supports him morally and physically.
A little later, he's at the Auschwitz Orchestra, and this allows him not to be executed right away, and there too, he holds out.
Life span in concentration camps, is just a few days if you are not immediately sent to death.
He bears it for long. He bears it
eventually until the end of the war.
Afterwards, having survived, he stops music completely.
This is no longer possible.
It was his passion; it was his vocation; it was his survival; it became an impossibility.
So, he becomes an electrician.
But he passes on the passion for music to his children and grandchildren.
And today, almost all of them are international musicians: Arie, conductor in the United States; Cziffra, at the Philharmonic of Israel; Naaman in Paris; all international musicians."
[There is] something heroic in this story, so I say, "Okay, I'm going to tell this story."
It's a story worth sharing, a story that inspires.
And here I start doing my job, that is scripting stories and then staging them, materializing them, so that people see them
and become inspired as well. But then, all the obstacles emerge.
Everybody explains to me that it's impossible to show concentration camps on stage.
I say, "I don't want to show the camps.
I want to show how someone survived and transmit something he had lost.
It's totally different, it's a story about life!
It's not about death. We go through death,
but we pass beyond it."
No, everyone refuses.
People, producers, let me down.
If so, then I'll write, stage
and produce the play myself.
I borrow money. I am told I am
completely mad, but I continue.
Then one theater steps down a month before the opening, although I had already hired the team. then an actress, three weeks before the opening, and so on ... a disaster scenario, for a long period of time.
Whenever a disaster occurs worse than the previous ones, which is a threat, I am told, "Stop!"
Everyone tells me, "Stop.
You cannot go on like this!
You're going to lose everything!"
My brother who has co-produced my shows for 15 years, the person closest to me, Aïkan, tells me, "We'll lose everything, you're mad!"
I say, "No, I'm going on."
I continue because if Haïm managed to survive Auschwitz, I should be able to do a show that tells this story.
Really, it's not the same.
It's not quite the same danger, the same issue, the same level.
So, I went forward.
To make a long story short, ten years later, the show has now toured for six years.
It has been seen by tens of thousands of people.
it has received press coverage up to TF1's newscast and all daily papers.
We performed in Paris at Salle Gaveau.
We performed at La Criée, in Marseille. and we performed in London.
Yes, it was a success, and this amused me for those who explained to me that it was impossible.
The reason why it was a success, is not just the quality of the show, it's History, and it is especially this figure.
It's the fact that there was something extraordinary that was told, that was transmitted: the fact that this man had managed to go through the horror and to surpass himself, to give and to transmit.
There were essential values of will, of courage, and starting literally from scratch.
This man today is 95 years old.
He is alive and at times when he was there, I made him come on stage at the end of the show.
It was a gift for the public who wasn't aware of his presence.
And this is what Haïm did when he was on stage.
As if just by himself, he had managed to overcome and give.
I considered that I too should give and pass on this story, because at my humble level, he had inspired me.
You're going to tell me, "Yes, very well.
Again an extraordinary person with tons of courage, will, aptitude, who has a passion, a talent.
It's easy when you have 'all this', even in catastrophic contexts.
In fact, it's downright crushing to have figures that remind us that we are just in our mediocrity, our ease, our comfort.
We do not manage to be as strong and brave as them.
And besides, heroes are somehow disturbing figures."
There is like this a play by Brecht, "The Life of Galileo".
Bertolt Brecht tells that Galileo, who is an absolute scientific hero - who managed to prove something revolutionary : no, the Earth is not the center of the Universe, the Sun is, on the contrary, what revolves around it - that Galileo is a hero who holds out against the Inquisition, who holds out against everything up to a certain degree.
And at some point in the play, all those whom Galileo inspired, all his disciples, are waiting, hoping that Galileo will resist, that he will not give up, retract.
Brecht's genius is revealed when he shows the disciples waiting.
And for a moment, the bell that marks the abjuration does not ring.
After five minutes, the bell rings.
We hear Galileo say, "I abjure my theories, I give up."
Galileo is no longer a hero, he is a coward, a traitor.
He has collapsed; he hasn't stood firm; he hasn't made the truth triumph.
He enters and his main disciple says to him, "Dirty coward! Woe to the country
that has no hero."
Because heroes save the world, don't they?
Because we need heroes to inspire us.
And Galileo replies, "No, woe to the country that needs heroes."
Because if we need heroes, it means we need something outside of us to be able us to surpass ourself.
So, this question about being inspired, what is it about ultimately?
Why can heroes inspire us, what do they evoke?
They evoke a kind of greatness.
They allude to a value.
Heroes are the revelators of value.
In a world where we can think that nothing is worth anything, that nothing makes sense, the hero asks the question:
Why? What is life worth?
What is worth fighting for, standing up, speaking up?
What is worth getting committed, maybe even dying for?
Can we die for freedom?
Should we die for freedom?
Some died for freedom.
Some fought.
Two years ago, in 2015 too, I directed Lorenzaccio, a play about a man who wants to kill a tyrant because he wants to free men.
The play asks this question: should we die for freedom?
How far should we go for that?
It turns out that the opening of this show took place on January 11, 2015, four days after the Charlie attacks.
In the silent room, everyone could hear this question perfectly: can we die for freedom?
How far should we go?
And a few days later, while we were performing, one of the actors' mother was dying.
She had terminal cancer.
He leaves the stage. Then he learns
that his mother died.
The next day, he departs for Brussels where she was.
He sees the body of his mother,
I didn't know what he was going to do.
He was one of the main actors: if he didn't return, we couldn't perform.
He comes back. He performs.
Believe it or not,
he was even better than before.
I told him, "Olivier, what you did is heroic."
He replied, "No, it's not heroic.
It is we who are saying something essential,
I must be here"
because he was aware that it was not a show, a role, that we were talking, at the very time of the attacks and terror, about: "Should we die for freedom?"
it was the question we were asking.
It's because of these valuable figures that I'm staging plays.
It's one of the reason why I write, and produce plays.
It's an attempt to share these figures who can inspire us.
And it's also an attempt to ask questions.
Sometimes heroes have flaws, weaknesses.
Sometimes they are even complex fascinations such as the Joker, or Richard III, or the character of House of Cards, all these kinds of evil characters, because these figures too can fascinate us.
Pointing at them, understanding what fascinates us in them, it's also a way to differentiate them from those who claim to be heroes, who, because they shoot women and children at café terraces, say, "I am a hero, I support a cause."
But in the name of which values?
For the sake of what?
For the sake of what ?
So, I invite you to listen, deep inside, since it's about voices and vox, to what is essential.
What is essential for you?
What resonates for you when you are silent.
When you don't hear the sounds of the world, and the nihilism anymore, nor the feeling that everything is equally valid, what is essential?
What would be a person, a value, an idea, that would make you say, "This is worth it," "This makes sense and deserves my commitment," and "That drives my life"?
Well, if you hear that very voice, then you have found the fulcrum, the lever of a heroism.
And during the challenge, during the crisis, something may get activated.
So are there heroes in this room?
Yes, I think so!
Not just the official heroes, not just the self-proclaimed heroes, not just the real heroes, but each of us has something.
Each of you can activate this from a value.
During the two years I spent asking Haïm what happened in Auschwitz, during the interviews, the only thing that Haïm told me,
the only one is, "I came out of it."
It's the only thing. And the other thing he does when he sees one of the shows, is to say, "All this joy comes from me." He managed to convey that,
get this across.
So, I invite you to ask yourself: what in you can be communicated in order to inspire people?
What ultimately can resonate and make future heroes resonate?
Thank you.
(Applause)
Hello, as Alexis just said,
I'm here today to talk to you about money.
I can see some of you are already saying, what a stereotype, another Indian who's going to talk to us about money.
(Laughter) But the truth is that my interest in the subject only started when I arrived in France.
In 2006, to get over my boredom, I joined the French Foreign Legion. As a result, in 2010, I found myself in Afghanistan with my comrades in arms.
During my seven months deployment, I was struck by several things: the courage of the Afghan people, and the beauty of their country.
But what shocked me most was the gigantic amount of money we were spending on the war.
Did you know that to date the coalition has spent over seven trillion dollars on the war?
I wanted to put that sum on a slide but there were too many zeros to fit on it.
(Laughter) So I asked myself where does this money come from?
How is it created?
The war can't just be paid for out of our taxes.
I know French taxes are high but come on!
(Laughter) So to answer this question, on leaving the Legion, I took up my studies again and did an MBA.
In the business school I realised that out of the 13,000 pages of textbooks I had to read to learn how to manage and invest money, there weren't even five pages to explain how money is created.
So I started to do my own research. What I discovered was fascinating.
I realised that the history of money, like the history of humanity, is constantly evolving.
Around 4,000 years ago, in ancient Mesopotamia, clay tablets were used as currency.
2,000 years ago, in Australia, they used sea shells.
In China at the same period, they used salt.
In England, in the Middle Ages, they used polished wooden sticks called tallysticks.
And at the same time, in Russia, they used squirrels.
Well, they are Russians.
(Laughter) So in fact, what I discovered is that whatever form it took, money had three functions: it was a reserve of value, a means of exchange, and a unit of account.
It was, and still remains, a social tool to communicate and exchange between us and to develop our economy.
But about 400 years ago, things changed.
With progress in the sciences and technology, Western merchants began to trade with merchants in more exotic countries richer in resources, like India.
And to facilitate trade, they were obliged to use a currency which was accepted everywhere and by everyone.
That currency was gold.
The merchants returned from abroad with their sacks of gold, and to safeguard their gold, they deposited it with goldsmiths.
So it is not surprising the first bankers were the goldsmiths.
For his services, the goldsmith was paid a small commission while the merchant, in exchange for his deposit, got a receipt in his name.
Gradually, the goldsmiths realised only a small minority of their customers turned up again to collect their gold.
So what did they do?
They started to deliver more and more receipts which this time were nameless.
These anonymous bills were a promise of payment guaranteed by the gold they held in their vaults.
In doing so, the goldsmiths created two things: the first was paper money, and the second was the concept of payment with interest.
That is the basis of our monetary system today.
Today, the governments of almost all countries use a private enterprise to manage their economies.
Do you know what that enterprise is?
It's the Central Bank.
Just because the bank is called the Bank of France, the Reserve Bank of India, or the Federal Reserve, doesn't change the fact that it remains a private enterprise.
How does this work?
The government exchanges treasury bills for currency with the Central Bank. The exchange is made with the promise that the government will repay the debt with interest.
The government then uses the money for social or infrastructure projects or for wars, and this way the money becomes available to us.
And what do we do with this money?
We deposit it in a bank.
Here's where it gets interesting.
Today's banking rules stipulate that each bank must hold in its vaults only 10% of deposits.
The remaining 90% can be lent out.
But bankers are cunning.
Obviously, they are heirs to the goldsmiths.
So what did they start doing?
They started applying the "fractional reserve" rule to the remaining 90%.
So in fact, you deposit your money with your bank, and the bank keeps 10% and lends 90%.
Of the 90%, it keeps 10% and further lends 90%.
Of that 90%... OK, you get it.
(Laughter) In this way a bank can can create 9 times the original sum from nothing.
So that's amazing, we've found the philosopher's stone.
We can have all the money we want.
But I think we've forgotten something.
When we take out a loan from a bank, the money has to be repaid with interest.
We saw how money was created, but what about the interest? Where does that money come from?
The answer is from nowhere. It doesn't exist.
So, to pay the interest, we need more money.
But if there's more money, we have inflation.
Also, the money comes
from the Central Bank.
So the more money we have, the more debt we must repay to the banks.
That's why the amount of money in the economy will never be greater than the interest owing to the banks.
The best way to illustrate this schizophrenic relationship is this image.
(Laughter) Don't laugh, that's us.
We run after it, but never catch up.
(Applause) So after the economic crisis in 2008, many people began to wonder why we should have to depend on such a centralized system managed by just a few bankers?
We need something better suited to our needs.
And once again, technology provided the answer.
This time it wasn't sticks, but the Internet.
Maybe some of you already know what I'm going to talk about: digital or crypto currency, or Bitcoin.
I'm not here to publicize Bitcoin, but I'll use Bitcoin as an example because it's widely known.
If you're not familiar with it,
Bitcoin is very simple. The official definition is a distributed database where the order of each transaction is verified and validated by all network users.
If you don't get it,
don't worry. I don't either.
(Laughter) But if you want to sound like an expert, or get intimate with a geek, then use that definition.
I can assure you, it works every time.
But more simply, crypto currencies like Bitcoin are the money of the internet.
Obtaining the currency is very simple.
You can either exchange Euros - I think the current exchange rate is about 435 Euros to the Bitcoin, or you can earn them by a process called mining.
Becoming a miner is very easy:
you have to subscribe to a network on which Bitcoin is accepted as a means of payment.
You then have to download a Bitcoin software onto your computer.
And as such you validate every transaction taking place on the shared network.
What the miner says is this:
"I certify that each transaction on this network started at such a point and ended at such a point, and that nobody has attempted to falsify the transaction."
And for his services, the miner is paid in Bitcoin.
Today, when you do that with a bank, you get charged 3% of the transaction.
So what's the advantage?
Because the network is shared, your work can be checked by every network user.
So it's a self-protecting system.
Secondly, and here's the real difference of crypto currencies such as Bitcoin, the total quantity is limited to 21 million.
Contrary to central banks, which print limitless paper money, there can never be more than 21 million Bitcoin in circulation.
Why 21 million?
I don't know, but it's 21 million.
So as there's a predefined limit, it's inflation-free.
Over time, the value of Bitcoin will go up.
Today, I think there are already 13 million Bitcoin in circulation and we will attain 21 million around the year 2140.
So we've still got a bit of time left.
What are its advantages?
Obviously, we can already say it's democratic, to a certain extent.
But at the same time, let's not forget it's a currency that circulates on the Internet.
Today, if you sell a product or service on the Internet, your customer base is worldwide.
But did you know that only 25% of visitors to your website can trade with you?
Why is that?
It's because the payment systems we use today were developed 50 years ago.
So that's why companies like Virgin and Expedia are starting to accept Bitcoin as a means of payment.
Because they've understood by doing so they increase their customer base by 400%.
But profit isn't the only issue.
We have to understand that for the first time in human history, we have a monetary system which is decentralized, democratic, and which isn't based on debt.
This technological shift isn't just limited to crypto currency.
Look at the society.
Our society is becoming very, very social, and we are working more and more collaboratively in spite of our diversity.
Take myself. An Indian who fought in the Foreign Legion and who's talking to you about economics.
Sometimes I don't believe it myself. I know I represent this change in our society, but I'm still very doubtful.
I wonder whether technology is really improving society.
If you have a Facebook account, raise your hands please.
Most people in the hall.
What is Facebook's business model?
It uses our personal data to conduct online marketing.
That's it in short.
Are you or I paid
for our contribution? No.
And yet Facebook makes a nice fat profit.
Maybe you say to yourselves, "OK, but it's a free service why should we be paid for that?
I have a reputation thanks
to Facebook. I've got likes on my page."
Fair enough, but 'likes' don't pay the rent.
And that's important.
Look at society today.
We are a society where it's harder and harder to find a job.
Unemployment is soaring and there are more inequalities in society.
And this trend will continue.
If you don't believe me, let me outline a scenario. It's futuristic but plausible:
it's 2030, and I find myself in India.
I don't know why, but I'm in India.
And having spent some years in France, I'm familiar with French cuisine.
So I say to myself, I'm going to launch my own business making French cheese in India.
Indian Saint-Nectaire.
(Laughter) Plus, cows are sacred back home, so I think I have an advantage.
To start my business, I obviously need capital.
But instead of going to the bank, I go straight to a crowdfunding platform because interest rates are lower, and it's easier to find money.
Once I have the money, I still have to learn to make cheese.
No sweat, I can do that online too.
Then I can start to prepare my product.
I need attractive packaging to contain the cheese.
I've bought a 3D printer, and I'll use recyclable plastic as raw material.
To market my product, I can go online onto social media or specialized websites for entrepreneurs to launch their products.
My customers start to show interest in my Indian Saint-Nectaire. They want to buy it, and they start placing orders.
To deliver the orders, I don't even need to hire a driver.
There are robotic vehicles on a common logistics platform which operates more or less like a car share and which already exists.
All this happens very quickly.
Within the week, I have the money and my product. I load my robotic vehicle and off it goes to the customer.
The customer is delivered and sends me off his payment.
And then I have to wait 45 days to receive my payment.
Why?
Because the banking system hasn't changed in 50 years.
And I don't think it's going to change over the next 15 years.
But that's not all that's wrong with this scenario.
From start to finish, you saw I was able to do nearly everything myself.
A real legionnaire.
(Laughter)
And that's what worries me.
Because I ask myself, if I can do all that by myself, what'll happen to all those people who work today in marketing, finance, logistics or manufacturing?
What are they going to do?
In 2030, 50% of jobs will have been destroyed in the services and manufacturing sectors, because of the 3D printer, robotic vehicles, and 'big data' models.
And don't forget that in 2030, there will be 2 billion more people on this planet.
That's why I asked you, why shouldn't we be paid to use Facebook?
We should at least try.
If it doesn't work, it's no big deal.
I'll be treated as an idiot, but I'm used to that.
But let's try.
The base of innovation is experimentation.
We also need to ask some questions about our current financial system.
We need a financial system that will help us become a more collaborative and innovative society, which isn't the case today.
I know I'm asking you lots of questions.
But I don't really have any answers to give you, or a solution to propose.
But the advantage of being in a collaborative society is that we will find the answer together.
What's essential is to ask questions, develop ideas, and share them.
Money will always remain a social tool, and will keep its 3 traditional functions:
it should be a reserve of value, a means of exchange and a unit of account.
But the form it will take and the world in which it will be used must reflect our democratic, collaborative, and innovative society.
It's up to us to create that, not just for ourselves but for the 2 billion individuals who'll be joining us very soon.
So come along with me; together, let's create that new economy.
Thank you.
(Applause)
Think about your job, think of the week just gone, and pay attention to how you feel, while you are thinking of your professional activity.
Perhaps you feel tension, some stress, or perhaps indifference?
Perhaps a certain excitement.
Perhaps you even feel joy, while thinking about your job.
Yes, you are allowed to feel joy for your job.
You know that extraordinary feeling you get when doing something you love, at the right place, with the right people, at the right time.
If you belong to this last category, then you are indeed very lucky.
Because, unfortunately, deep down, you are not a typical member of the working population.
How many people get up on a Monday morning, thinking, as they get to work: "Roll on the evening!"
On a Tuesday morning: "Roll on the weekend!"
After the weekend: "Roll on the holidays!"
As soon as the holiday ends, upon returning to work: "Roll on the next holiday!"
"Roll on the next job, roll on a new employer."
"Roll on my retirement one day."
"Roll on retirement to free me from this burden that is work."
This is the reality facing most people today.
When young people join the workforce, the older generation say: "Look at these young people!
They don't know the value of work."
Don't forget that they have seen their parents' generation.
Wearing themselves out at work.
Not just physically.
But also mentally.
How many people around us, whom we know, have had a burn-out, or developed other stress-related illnesses?
In extreme cases they have committed suicide.
Companies today, are a total mess.
Resources are often over-exploited and yet the talent and self-motivation mechanisms are generally under-utilized.
I am actually wondering, at the end of the 21st century, what future generations will say when they look at the way we are working today.
Edgar Morin wrote at the beginning of the 2008 crisis: "The enormous global crisis is nothing more than a crisis of humanity that cannot access to humanity."
If we want to come out of the crisis, and, more importantly, if we want to restore dignity and humanity in the workplace, we will need to put our heart into it, in order to implement a real, in-depth transformation.
And I have some very good news.
This transformation is already under way.
Not just in some big Californian companies which always have the same names.
Not even in the French pioneer companies.
Everywhere, in all kinds of companies, there are visionaries and unknown utopians, who, on their level, modestly and bravely, launch initiatives, which modestly contribute to re-define what may become the professional world of tomorrow.
Ladies and gentlemen, now I would like to give you a glimpse into some of these initiatives.
And perhaps, who knows, you may decide to join the circle of these people who are working on the professional world of tomorrow.
Big transformations always begin with small steps.
So, let's get practical, as they say.
Let's concentrate on one team.
Five or six people, no more.
This may be the size of a team you manage, or it may be your team working on a project.
And initially we will examine the work environment.
Let's leave out the people for a moment, and focus exclusively on the work environment of this team.
The environment sends out messages.
What is the work environment of this team telling you?
The furniture, the layout, the view from the windows.
How do you feel when you enter this place?
Does it make you feel important?
Does it make you feel at home?
Does it make you feel welcome?
Or is leaving your only thought?
Perhaps there is room for improvement, right?
Using the small step method, let's look at this workplace, let's concentrate on the board room.
Let's carry out a shock operation,
"Zero Euro."
An important debate of our time.
In a board room, there are tables where people put their mobile phones and laptops, which are most often used for doing things not related to the meeting.
So take the tables out of the room, and make a circle of five or six chairs.
When the team enters this meeting room, they will have a moment of confusion: "It's the Alcoholics Anonymous meeting this afternoon!"
A second one will look at you and will think: "He must have watched a TED video last night."
A third one will complain: "We can't take notes!"
Send this person to the board to take notes for everybody, and then start the meeting. (Laughter)
You will observe some slight changes which will be very interesting.
For example, in the way people will relate to each other.
In the way they will discuss the usual subjects.
Their non-verbal communication will be different.
They may even start talking about subjects they haven't talked about in a very long time.
When the team become aware that this setting makes communication easier invite them to go a step further.
What can you do to the board room to make them feel even better, to make it a better place and a more effective one?
They will have ideas. One person will say:
"Let's paint the wall in a lively color."
Another will say: "We can hang an inspirational poster to put us in a better state of mind."
By association, a third one will say: "No, we can put an inspiring quote at the start of each meeting.
So that we can start the meeting with a specific purpose."
Two weeks ago I was with a team, in twenty minutes flat, they completely transformed the board room.
Moved chairs, removed tables.
They put up wall decorations.
They added a green plant.
They even set up a drinks station to act as a decompression area.
When you see the before, and then you see the after, you realise that the return on time spent is considerable.
To avoid the onset of lethargy, we can be bold and change surroundings.
One day I saw a team take a paperboard and have their meeting on the grass next to the parking.
Why not take the team out to a restaurant at close of business?
When the clients have left, have the meeting at a restaurant.
And why not have the meeting walking in a park?
Our surroundings influence our state of mind.
They influence our behaviour, influence our brain capacity.
It is worth spending time to fully understand this environment concept, and you can be sure that it will have a positive effect on you.
Now we have an environment which facilitates communication, let's get to the issues.
Let's talk about objectives.
Let's concentrate on our sphere of influence.
Each hierarchical level has its responsibility level.
Where we are in this team, there are 5 possible scenarios.
Scenario 1: Each team member meets the manager to discuss his/her annual objectives.
Scenario 2: Each team member meets the manager
to discuss them together, they agree on annual objectives for the end of the year.
Typical scenarios so far.
Scenario 3: Each team member is free to define their own annual objectives.
Scenario 4: There are no longer individual objectives,
The team is free to define its own annual objectives.
Scenario 5: No individual objectives, no annual objectives.
The team is free to define its objectives on a daily basis.
In your opinion, at the end of the year, in which scenario will the team produce its best results?
Unless your confidence in your colleagues has reached the floor long ago, it is possible that you would opt for scenarios 4 or 5.
Well done! You have earned
the opportunity to try it.
Let's do a brief critical analysis here.
Individual objectives reinforce individualistic behaviour, which often goes against the common interest.
Annual group objectives!
Wow, this will be complicated.
We will have to apply common sense to our actions.
But how do we achieve that?
We have to think about what we want to do.
Why are we doing it and for whom?

How do we put it into practice? With whom?

The team will have to ask some crucial questions.
This will take up considerable time, but it will be backed up by common sense and that has no price.
So, obviously, even if all your team members are brilliant, there is still a possibility for error.
So when you are defining the objectives for the year, or for the semester, when the team is, perhaps heading slightly off course, because of the sudden changes in its environment.
Perhaps they think: "Oops!
We may be about to make a mistake."
A few weeks or months have gone by.
What will the team do?
They will start to patch things together, trying to get back on course.
Not sure if that is the best way to avoid getting off course.
Whereas if you are aware of the objectives every day, that would not stop you from also having a more long-term vision.
What would happen?
End of the day team meeting in the boardroom, standing up because it is quicker and more efficient, and the team takes stock on what they did today, what they didn't do and why not.
Suggest improvements, set up objectives for tomorrow.
When the team is focused, this will take 15 minutes.
And at that moment, what's happening within the team?
It is about to take control of its destiny.
Each person in the team is about to pitch in and add their bit.
Without realizing it, small step by small step, the team is about to take giant steps.
Obviously, the life of a team is not a long calm river.
There are always moments when tension will arise among its members.
Especially at times of assigning tasks.
There is a new project to be carried out by the team.
Usually, the manager chooses a person and says: "OK, there you go, Frank, take over this responsibility."
And sometimes the rest of the team do not understand this.
So perhaps it can be done in a different way.
Namely by letting the team choose.
How exactly?
Very simple.
The team go to the board room, in a circle.
You ask the first team member: "Who do you think is the most suitable person to take responsibility for the new project?
Explain your choice."
Proceed to the second, third, fourth, fifth, sixth member... and then you will end up with two or three names.
At this stage, the team members will engage in a negotiation with each other, in which they not only have to think who would be most suitable to carry out the new project, but also, that this nomination will not hamper the success of others in their respective tasks.
They will start to negotiate the demarcation of responsibilities.
And when the new person is elected to this position by the group, they will be successful at the outset, because they will have the group's support 100%.
Once you see this process in action, you begin to wonder why it wasn't established long ago.
Why can't we always choose our managers in this way?
After all, while the team develops, the manager also has to evolve.
To change his function.
Move away from being a pilot, directing, deciding on the objectives and supervising, to being a co-pilot, who is actually there to make the group's work easier.
To support the team and its internal dynamics.
To ensure that nobody is left behind.
To ensure that differences within the group as well as complementary qualities, are cherished by all, like an oasis in the desert.
Like a cradle of our collective intelligence.
So, obviously, when we hear all this, we think: "Roll on a new manager!
A bold manager, who will carry out all these changes."
"Roll on a new boss, an inspiring boss, who will instil this kind of spirit.
Who will give us energy and autonomy, who will give us the opportunity to act differently."
"Roll on a new hero, here to save us."
We are in danger of having to wait a long time.
If we want to change that, let's embrace change.
Each person at their own level, let's start with those around us.
Let's start by giving them the desire to believe in a dream.
That taking pleasure in work is possible.
Let's encourage them to mobilize, to speak differently, to work together differently.
Let's mobilize ourselves too, to push the limits of organizations.
Let's be less executives and more creators.
Makers of our own future.
Let's make room for all our talents to finally find expression.
For hidden treasures to shine through in our team.
And then, all together, each in our own level, we will no doubt contribute in creating a better world for our children.
Tomorrow's heroes will be each one of us.
Thank you.
(Applause)
Good evening, everyone.
When I was first asked to speak at this New Explorers TEDx event, since I am not a shop captain, and I would not call myself an explorer,
I asked myself, how is it possible to be an explorer in the 21st century?
Knowing that the entire world has been mapped out, that people can simply move around the planet from their couch and even go to the Moon and Mars, well, I was a bit frustrated.
Luckily, there is still one unexplored territory left.
This territory is the brain.
This one here isn't mine ... it looks quite nice, actually.
This unexplored territory is the one of neuroscience.
Today, there's a real buzz around neuroscience.
In schools of architecture or design, there are programs focusing on neuroscience.
In advertising, we use neuroscience's results to improve marketing performance,
we call that neuro-marketing.
Well, why?
Well, because what's fascinating about neuroscience, for me, is that it explores the unconscious mechanisms of our brain.
This mechanism represents the majority of mental processes. It‘s like the submerged part of an iceberg.
Studying the brain more deeply, is like exploring the ocean more deeply, you can't just hold your breath; there are exceptions but we will get to those later.
So, we will use a diving suit.
In neuroscience, we don't have a diving suit. Instead, we use brain imaging.
And here is an example,
that is another explorer whose name is Vincent Ricard -
Matthieu Ricard, sorry. Vincent is someone in my team, no relation, (Laughter)
except that they share the same last name,
and that they both enjoy wearing sensors on their head.
That is for the good purpose of a scientific experiment,
performed in a strictly controlled place, a scientific laboratory in a hospital.
This enables us to measure brain activity.
But it has its limitations.
What we have learned from brain imaging is that our brain resembles Play-Doh.
Why?
Because the brain is malleable. The brain changes and adapts itself.
When you were born, you were not able to speak, nor to see or hear anything. Your brain has learned
how to do so by itself.
At this point I have some good news.
Today we don't need to go to a laboratory and cover our head with sensors, or to go to the Himalayas and shave our heads to become monks, although it must be an incredible experience.
The technology of brain training and brain exploration is now accessible to everyone.
I was not looking for the telescope but for this helmet!
It’s an example of this type of device that can measure very easily your brain activity and allows all of you in this room to become new explorers,
explorers of your own mind.
So, how does brain training work?
It is the very same principle as learning forehand in tennis, or practicing arpeggios on the piano.
Let’s take the example of Roger Federer who is known for his technique.
Well, I don’t know anything about tennis, but I have been told that,
compared to Nadal, he is the best.
(Laughter) How does he train for his tennis moves?
Well, he does it in two ways:
through his awareness and the repetition of the movement.
He manages to train his movement because he feels and sees how his arm is moving.
Same for piano. We get to improve ourselves because we hear and see what we do with the instrument.
It’s much the same if we want to train the mind.
The only difference, with an unconscious mechanism, we need to find a way that allows us to hear and see what happens in our brain.
It is exactly what this kind of device can do.
Now, you can literally connect your brain to a smart phone or computer
and be able to see and hear the unconscious mechanism of your brain.
Let’s take the example
with this headset, for example. You put it on your head - this is Marta, she works in the office in front of mine. We put the headset on her head with headphones because what she is doing is literally listening to the music that changes according to her brain activity.
This device allows her to learn how to relax and manage her stress.
And we know that stress really is a problem that can ruin our everyday life.
Other examples.
Let's take this child, for example. This child suffers from ADHD (Attention Deficit Hyperactivity Disorder).
He needs to take heavy doses of Ritalin, which is strong medication.
But thanks to this new technology that allows people to explore their brain activity, he manages to control the movement of a plane on a screen by his thought.
That's how he increases his ability to focus.
By being able to focus more easily thanks to repeated training sessions, he can reduce his drug dosage.
There was another example
at the football World Cup in Brazil in 2014.
A young paraplegic man with two paralysed legs was able to make the first kick of World Cup by controlling his exoskeleton by thought.
It was just a little kick,
the ball only moved one metre.
It didn’t run across the field doing backflips.
But this is a clear sign that it's only the beginning,
the start of a new continent, the continent of exploration and connection of our brain with machines, as well as with ourselves.
What if we go a little further?
If, right now, we could improve our own focus and relaxation, perhaps in the future we will be able to enhance all our intellectual abilities. Perhaps our memory, our sleep, our mental calculation, and who knows, even our empathy.
Maybe we will increase our ability to live together, understand each other better.
If we connect all our brains to computers and smartphones, maybe one day, we'll be able to gather a network of connected brains.
Maybe it sounds like science fiction, but it's something that can be conceived.
With all these minds connected together, each of them having access to the unconscious minds of one another.
Would that improve communication?
It could also bring many questions about morals and ethics.
Would there be someone to secure this network?
What would happen if it were hacked?
I don’t want to scare you tonight, it’s not my intention. Instead, I’m just trying to tell you, to inform you, that we are entering a new era,
an era where neuroscience will be part of our daily lives, as microcomputers and electronics are already part of our daily life, today.
There are people, who work in my company, as well as in other lab and companies, who are beginning to develop new technologies.
And if you don't decide for yourselves to take control of this brain exploration, there might be others who will do that in your place.
I hope not.
That is why we must all, collectively, make a decision together, to take control of these technologies, which are available to everyone, and start to explore our own brains.
Let’s start this adventure together. It's a journey of inner discovery, because it concerns our intimate mind, but also a collective one.
I invite you to embark on this adventure with me, together, step by step, to explore the human brain.
Thank you.
(Applause)
Since my L'Échappée talk, I've received quite a bit of media coverage,
which is excellent for an entrepreneur who's launching a startup.
I even appeared on TV.
Being on TV is fantastic.
My application is called "RogerVoice."
As you may have heard, it makes it possible for deaf people, like myself, to make phone calls.
In France alone, there are more than 500,000 profoundly deaf people who can't use the phone.
This application uses voice recognition.
As this video shows, I make a call, and when you answer,
the app writes what you say.
It's automatic. It's instantaneous.
And it works in several languages.
And since not all deaf people communicate with their voice, I can respond in two ways: by speaking or writing.
The application vocalizes what I write so that you can hear it.
I didn't create this application because I want to use the phone. I created it because you use the phone.
Doctors book their appointments by phone.
Restaurants take reservations by phone only.
And my mother loves hearing from me over the phone.
(Laughter) This application is a bridge, another link between us. It opens up the field of possibilities. That's the strength of innovation and of communication.
But that's not enough.
Are you upset by anything in this image? [suffers from deafness]
I am.
I don't suffer from deafness.
I am deaf.
I'm not a walking medical condition, or impaired, or disabled.
I assure you I'm doing well.
And it wasn't just that show. Strangely, when I read the anglophone press, the articles on RogerVoice, I don't get those feelings.
But there's something about how we generally talk about disability in France that bothers me.
When expressions systematically link a person, a being, with a medical condition, there's still a divide between the perception of some and the reality of others.
This isn't about political correctness.
Let's look at things as they are. You have brown skin. You're short. You're bald. I'm deaf.
For innovation to make sense, it has to be accompanied by a change in society and behaviour.
I created an application, but it's not enough to build bridges and create the means for communication.
It's by changing words that we change perceptions.
And that's the real revolution.
That's what we need to talk about.
So let's talk. Ready when you are.
(Laughter) (Applause)
(Video) (Orcas' sounds) (Applause) Orcas are magnificent creatures.
They don't deserve the nickname of "killer whales".
First of all, they are not whales, they belong to the dolphin family.
And second, they've never attacked any humans, in their natural habitat, that is.
The first thing you feel when you dive next to orcas is an intense joy, the joy of being accepted into their social space and be able to observe for a few dozen of minutes their underwater life.
Occasionally, they get curious and come close, very close.
In this gaze, you can spot a vast intelligence.
You feel scanned, analyzed, scrutinized, as if they had the power to access our deepest emotions.
But above all, you don't feel the fear, you don't feel the tiredness, you don't feel the cold.
You just feel a wave of emotions and energy that overwhelms you and thrills you from head to toes.
I feel it more and more each year.
Today, I know why, and I'm going to share it with you.
My first encounter with orcas goes back to 1997.
It was two days before an underwater fishing competition.
This encounter changed the course of my life.
It was like an irresistible call.
Two days later, I win this competition, and thanks to my sponsor's incentive, I'm able to finance my first trip to go dive with orcas in the north of Norway a year later.
This first expedition in 1998 was followed by a long series of others, 21 seasons without interruption during which I accumulated more than 6,000 underwater encounters closest to orcas.
This experience has enabled me to design a method to approach and interact with them respectfully that is a reference today.
I've dedicated most of my time to the study of orcas' social behavior and body language.
This presentation refers to "singing orcas" but I made my first underwater recording only in 2016.
It was near Tromsø in Kaldfjord, and it was a magical moment.
During the day just before the test, we observed dozen of humpback whales and several hundreds orcas that moved in the middle of the fjord close to our anchoring.
At nightfall, we took our aluminium craft and we went to the site.
The atmosphere was a bit special.
There was no wind which it's pretty rare.
The fjord's surface resembled a mirror, and we could see on each side of this narrow fjord, the snow on the mountains.
It was a rather breathtaking moment.
So we stopped the engine and I immersed my hydrophone in the most absolute silence at a dozen meters deep.
A hydrophone is an underwater microphone that allows you to record sounds while listening to them.
I connected the speaker, and then ... Well, come with me on the boat.
(Songs of orcas and humpback whales) A startling and perfectly orchestrated melody rised from the dephts.
I was overwhelmed by the beauty of these songs.
Our boat was at the interface between two worlds, the orcas' world and their secrets under the surface, and the sky and the stars above us.
In the magic of the moment, I imagined these two worlds connected and what connected these spaces was the songs coming from the depths.
The northern lights started just above our heads.
The singing increased in intensity and harmony. (Songs of orcas and whales) Each orca, each humpback whale was playing its own partition in what I called later "The abyss's symphony".
But above all, what was happening was going far beyond this.
It was not just an harmonious melody pleasant to the ear, I felt enveloped, permeated by those songs.
I felt a wave of energy, the same energy that flows when I dive in the vicinity of orcas.
While I dedicated all these years to the sole study of orcas' body language, I missed something important.
I realized that evening of December 2016 that sounds are of vital importance in orcas' lives, and that that was where we needed to direct our research.
A few weeks after the end of the season in March 2017, I went to Guadeloupe to meet Pierre Lavagne de Castellan.
Pierre is a bioacoustician and he's the benchmark, Mister "Song of whales and sperm whales".
He's been in that field for more than 30 years.
During our meetings, Pierre used to say, "The message is in the song."
He'd hammer it like a leitmotiv, and I was hanging on his words, saying to myself, "But what is this message?
What are they saying to each other?
What are they trying to tell us?"
I left Guadeloupe with more questions than answers.
I went back to France and I started to do research on the internet to try to understand these concepts.
I had no knowledge about sound.
So I googled "what is a sound?"
A sound is a wave. Okay.

What is a wave?
A wave is an oscillation through a transfer of energy.
Okay.
It's defined by its amplitude, its frequency.
It can be visualized by a graph.
There are electromagnetic waves, mechanical waves, stationary waves ...
All of this didn't really speak to me.
I didn't see how I could use it.
But one day, as I am searching about stationary waves, I stumble upon the work of Ernst Friedrich Chladni.
Ernst Friedrich Chladni is an engineer, physicist and musician who discovered how to visualize sounds.
He had the idea to use a copper plate, attached to a stand, on which he put a thin layer of sand, and on the periphery of which he used his violoin bow.
Look at the result, it's surprising.
(Video) (Grindings of violin bow) In this experiment, we can observe that the sand moves on the surface of the plate and forms a geometrical figure.
These geometric patterns are called "Chladni's figures" or "Chladni’s plate".
Chladni made a whole catalog of several thousands of them because what's interesting is that each frequency produces a specific image.
Now where it gets truly exciting is when Alexander Lauterwasser, who is a German researcher and nature photographer, discovered recently that the shape of some living species was the exact copy of Chladni's plates.
On this picture from his book "Water Sound Images," we can see a flower with its corresponding Chladni's figure.
It can also be the back of a turtle, or this picture taken under a microscope of the Diatom Arachnoidiscus that is the exact copy of the Chladni's figure corresponding to 5,000 Hertz frequency.
From his discovery Alexander Lauterwasser theorizes
"the shape of living beings originates from sound vibrations."
The shape of living beings originates from sound vibrations.
A few years before him, Hans Jenny, the Swiss scientist, worked on the effects of sound on matter, especially on liquids and semi-liquids.
Here's one of his experiments.
We can see that under the effect of a sound vibration, this semi-liquid paste that usually sits at the bottom of the speaker rises up, sets itself up despite the gravitational force and follows specific movements.
According to Hans Jenny, these movements are not chaotic nor random, they are perfectly organized and reproducible.
When I saw this experiment, I immediately made a connection with old pictures that I took of my first expeditions.
They show a thin liquid film that is thrown forward from the orcas' lower jaw while they swim.
Initially, I paid no attention to these pictures, but now I could see a link with Hans Jenny's experiments.
There is no reason for this phenomenon.
I asked a hydrodynamic engineer specialized in fluid dynamics. According to him, these shapes can't exist in the absence of an outside force.
Could orcas be creating this phenomenon?
Could orcas be producing this frequency that enables them to produce these ephemeral artistic shapes?
I've been studying orcas since 1998.
These creatures belong to the cetacean family.
They have a bigger brain that is potentially more powerful, more efficient than that of humans.
They're conscious of themselves and of their surroundings. I saw them solve complex problems, especially by adapting their hunting strategy depending on circumstances in an extremely reactive way.
They are organized in society, in family groups that are led by the oldest female, the matriarch.
Orcas possess acoustic organs.
They pass on their knowledge, their culture, their language, from generation to generation for millions of years.
Our civilization is 5,000 years old.
Our technology has not reached 200 years of age yet.
We, humans, are dominating the world.
We control almost all of the living.
We think we know everything, but there's still so much to discover.
Pierre Lavagne de Castellan, him again, has observed multiple times humpback whales getting together in groups and giving acoustic massages to each other.
These recent observations show that whales but also dolphins and orcas have developed throughout evolution know-hows that enable them to use sounds for something other than simple communication.
I pursue my research with the hope, maybe a bit foolish, of understanding these phenomenons because what I feel when I dive close to orcas, this well-being that I feel, is due, in my opinion, to the sounds they produce.
Our oceans are endangered because of human activities: the consequences of climate change, noise pollution, chemical pollution, overfishing, sea traffic, plastic ...
It's time to change our habits to reduce these threats.
Let's save our oceans while we still can.
Let's protect orcas, this luminous oceanic civilization.
Let's uncover the secrets of their language.
We will gain access to their knowledge and then, yes, we shall be able to heal ourselves with the songs of orcas.
Thank you.
(Applause)
Have you ever asked yourself about the actual nature of the universe?
I'm not talking about any abstract universe but our universe, the one in which we all live, the one where you are now.
Have you ever thought about what you body was really made of? Or the air you breathe or even the very chair you are sitting on?
If the answer is yes, then you might have noticed that around you you can find clues that can help you decode all that.
For example, if I grab my glass, you see there is water in it, and I throw it at you, here, some of you would move aside a little.
Nobody in this room, or anywhere else on Earth ever thought that once you throw the water, it would stop halfway in the air turn around and go back into my glass.
And why is that?
We all have this feeling that some laws of Nature actually exist,
and that those very laws cannot be broken.
The aim of theoretical physics is to figure out what those laws are.
One have to admit that, as humans, we are rather good at that.
Just to give you an idea: since Newton, we can all describe every single thing that is happening around us, including the state of objects. That, we know how to do.
But since Newton, we went a little further than that.
We even entered a world that goes beyond our senses.
A world in which our intuition no longer applies.
It is a wonderful world, and I'll tell you why.
In 1905, Albert Einstein taught us that light is made of tiny pieces of energy.
In Latin, "tiny pieces" would be translated as "quanta."
What Einstein and other fellows did, was to open us up on a new world, the world of quantum mechanics and quantum physics, a tiny world that is the world of luminous rays.
I'll ask you to imagine that, for a moment, you are in 1942 in Paris, where a young scientist just got his thesis published
He is 32, and his name is Louis de Broglie, and he states something extraordinary.
In support of his calculations, he states the light that is around us, and this matter that your bodies are made of are not that different from one another.
The matter would actually be made of those tiny pieces of energy.
That would mean that matter itself would follow the laws of quantum science.
And for this, De Broglie achieved the dream of every PhD student on earth when receiving a Nobel Prize for his thesis, 7 years later.
And that's not so bad after all.
On the founding fathers of quantum physics immediately got his hands on this idea and started to work on trying to find out how the whole world of the infinitely small works.
And guess what? He succeeded in finding an equation that he named the Schrödinger's equation. It describes the way particles behave within our universe.
In a few words, he did for the world of the infinitely small what Newton did for the world around.
If you shoot an arrow, Newton would tell you where it will land.
If you throw a particle, well, Schrödinger would tell you what it will become.
Unfortunately, in the world of the infinitely small, particles are no arrows.
They are not even like small balls.
Instead, you have to imagine a kind of cloud filled with small balls that are either present or missing, that exist or don't exist and that are overlaid and that are almost everywhere.
Schrödinger's equation describes how this cloud will evolve through time. what he eventually found was very strange.
Just to give you an idea of what it could mean from our world's perspective, he came up with a thought experiment he named the Schrödinger's cat experiment.
Here it goes: in this box, there is a cat.
(Mioawing)
It might have been sleeping. Anyhow, there is a cat.
But there is more than a cat.
It didn't sound very happy, because on its side Schrödinger placed, and so did I, a radioactive substance.
What is a radioactive substance?
It is a substance we can split into two.
That's why the first row had to sign the legal discharge earlier, it's radioactive in there.
So, we have a substance that can be split into two without us knowing in advance whether or not it will happen.
So, there is this little substance inside and with the one I place here, there is a 50/50 chance it will break, or be blown apart between now and the end of the experiment.
But Schrödinger did not only did that.
With this little substance, he added a device, as smart as sadistic, that would release a poison and eventually kill the cat in case the substance blows away.
If on the contrary the substance stays as is, the cat is safe.
The laws of quantum physics tell us as long as no-one has looked inside, as long as no-one opened the box, the radioactive substance has blown away but at the same time, hasn't.
It means the poison has and hasn't been released. Consequently, the cat inside is not dead or alive, but dead and alive.
It sounds completely insane, I agree.
But after all, that's what maths tells us, and they are positive.
If the laws of quantum physics as we know them are correct
then Schrödinger and his equation will tell you that in this box, the cat is both dead an alive.
Let's have look.
(Miaowing) Well, at least it's not dead, which is good. But you see, there was only one cat
as you might have expected
and you might be a bit relieved that the cat is alive and not dead. As for me, it disturbs a lot that there is only one cat inside.
I believe in maths and all the physics that's behind it, and if maths says that there should be two cats inside the questions is: where is the dead cat now?
It should then be there but is not. So where is it?
As crazy as it sounds, scientists are actually paid to try and answer this very question.
(Laughter) They were even paid for years.
Schrödinger published this thought experiment in 1935.
For a decade after that, maybe even two, almost all the scientist on earth have been looking for the dead cat.
Up until a young American named Hugh Everett III came up with an incredible solution.
He thought to himself that if Einstein and De Broglie were really right, which seemed to be the case, then light and matter are quantum since our whole universe is made of light and matter, then, there is no reason at all that the universe itself would not be quantum.
And consequently, a superposition within its different states, where there are many possibles.
What he means is that when I opened the box, two cats were inside and when I opened it, our whole universe split into two: one where we live now and where the cat is alive, and the other where it was dead.
This very universe would be universe parallel to ours that would remain forever.
At the end of one his lessons on quantum physics, Einstein told his students, "If you understood what I said, it means I wasn't clear enough."
(Laughter) Hugh Everett III didn't get the Nobel Prize because he published this paper with his thesis on the contrary, he abandoned physics, thinking it was rubbish.
(Laughter) He might have been right though.
But at the time, to check his theory would mean we would need to see every single atom.
See them in their overlapping state, to try them out and actually observe them.
Then again, at this time, it was experimentally out of the question.
But not now anymore.
At the end of 1990s, in the Teacher Training College's laboratories in Paris Pr. Serge Haroche's team succeeded in creating an experiment categorized as "Schrödinger's cat-like."
It wasn't with a cat, but with big atoms and light.
And from this experiment, he could see that atoms were in overlapping states.
The same kind as a cat both dead and alive.
He even saw those two states vanish to leave space for only one, and, in a certain way, to give birth to the world we got used to living in.
This very experiment got him the Nobel Prize in Physics 3 years ago.
We started in 1924 with Louis de Broglie's Nobel Prize and arrived in 2012 with Serge Haroche's, following an idea where we traveled different times and lands.
Why did I tell you all this?
Why did we follow the hare-brain ideas of all those loony scientists talking about cats dead-alive cats and parallel universe all over the place?
Is it of any use?
I could honestly understand that you wouldn't get why we actually fund research.
But, it turns out you'd be wrong.
From Broglie's discoveries to Schrödinger's equation many everyday life objects have seen the light of day: computers, mobile phones, lasers and almost all medical equipment you can find in a hospital.
But some of you will ask, "What about Haroche's discovery?"
Well, it turns out that it allows for
a new industrial and technology revolution.
By succeeding in considering the cat as both dead and alive he opened the way to computers of the future that they call quantum computers.
A quantum computer is a machine that uses the overlay of atoms state within its heart.
Does that makes sense?
Thanks to this system, those small atoms and those machines are capable of calculating as if they were in billions of different parallel universes at the same time.
This means a single one of these computers would make all of the computers we have nowadays, look like abaci. That's just that simple.
Fundamental research is a rather understated discipline, that can sometimes be completely secret.
Yet, it is the origin of many revolutions and the genies behind them can emerge anytime and anywhere.
Here is an example, Serge Haroche, the same man we talked about earlier, who was born in Casablanca, Morocco and arrived in France when he was 12.
As a small digression, I'd like to pinpoint the fact if we had closed our borders back then, France would have lost a Nobel Prize and its hypothetical and amazing applications. (Applause) Scientific knowledge belong to every single person, you, me, newborns here, or somewhere else on Earth.
It is our duty to share and pass it on.
It is for everyone's sake that I tell you this.
Besides, it is very likely that, in the future, a child from another country will hold the keys of our future here and not of a parallel universe.
Thank you very much.
(Applause)
(Documentary) Journalist: Each new attack revives her pain.
Aziza lost her son last year. He was 22 years old.
Aziza: My son did not pray, he was an ordinary kid, he liked music, girls.
J: Samy had just found a building caretaker job in Sevran.
It was actually at his workplace that he was radicalized - in four months, by a co-worker.
A: He didn't want to go to his sister's wedding because of the social mix.
He didn't want to look his site manager in the eye anymore, nor shake her hand.
J: Samy then announced to his family that he was going on a pilgrimage to Mecca, but, in fact, went to Syria.
A year later, he died in a car accident.
A: I know that he got married, that I have a granddaughter there.
And after he died, I just got a death certificate from ISIS.
J: Aziza decided to get involved by joining The Mothers' Brigade, an organization of parents worried by the rise of radicalization in their neighbourhoods.
A: Our goal is prevention, to prevent young people from leaving.
Even if we only save one, that's already a victory.
J: Disappointed by the powerlessness of the state, Aziza fights against the phenomenon that stole her son from her.
(Applause) Hello, I'm Nadia Remadna.
I'm going to tell you why I created this organization called The Mothers' Brigade.
I have several observations, but I'll just share two today.
A few years ago, I had just gotten back from vacation, from Algeria, and, on the plane, I met a mother who lives not far from my town, Sevran.
We talked a bit about terrorism in Algeria - yes, we'd lived through nine years of terrorism in Algeria - and what shocked me when we arrived at the airport, was that this mother, at Roissy, takes out a scarf, veils her head, and takes out a big dress.
I ask, "What are you doing?"
She tells me, "I don't want to go into my neighbourhood like that."
I say, "But we've just come from Algeria, a country that's had nine years of civil war, we're in France now, and you veil yourself."
I was shocked. First observation.
Second observation:
One day, my son comes running home, rings the doorbell and says to me, "Mum, please, could you take down the Christmas tree?
Because all my friends are telling me that my mum is a non-believer and that Santa Claus doesn't exist."
My son was eight years old at the time.
I go to see the kids, to find out what the problem was.
Was it the Christmas tree that upset them?

The fairy lights? The Christmas baubles?
What upset them?
"No, to be a good Muslim you must tell the truth.
You are lying to your children, you are celebrating Christmas."
Second observation.
Well, unfortunately, later, in 2005, there were riots in the suburbs.
Yes, riots in the suburbs, in 2005.
What did they propose to us?
The state appealed to whom?
Not the educators, nor the social workers, nor the mediators.
To whom did they appeal?
To older brothers.
I was a single mother with four children,
so I was excluded straight off.
I felt that they took away my parental authority.
Every time there was a problem: "Go and see the older brothers."
Me, I'm a social worker.
I told myself, "Something's got to be done."
So, I found a job as a school mediator at a high school in an Education Priority Area in the Paris commune of Sevran.
On my first day, I'm waiting for the principal. In the corridor, I see a person speak to a student asking him this question: "How come I didn't see you at the mosque yesterday?"
I watch without intervening because this was my first day at work.
The principal greets me, "Hello", - "Hello", and the young man that said "How come I didn't see you at the mosque?"
came into the office and sat down next to me. I thought he'd be about 14 or 15, so I question him, saying, "You realize that this is a state school, that France is a secular country, just how might you say to a student, 'I didn't see you at the mosque'?"
The principal says to me, "Say, Mrs. Remadna, thank goodness I have that quality of staff in my school.
If I didn't have them, you realize, the school would be a battlefield."
So I decided to start The Mothers' Brigade.
So just why this organization exactly?
Because as a social worker, there were too many barriers.
They train us for just that, barrier upon barrier: don't talk, don't act, fill out the administrative work.
I needed to dispose of all that that prevented me from seeing what was happening.
I am often asked as a woman and a mother: "Is it us, the mothers, who've educated our children badly?
What's happened?"
I set up this organization, and in setting up The Mothers' Brigade, sure enough, I was wearing two hats: I was a social worker, and president of the organization The Mothers' Brigade.
This, indeed, allowed me to do a good grassroots job.
Given that we were stripped of our parental authority, it was up to us to reclaim that parental authority and bring France back into the hearts of the neighbourhoods.
That's The Mothers' Brigade, that was my goal.
That all the mothers, all the parents, take back what was taken away from them.
Parental authority - it was given to the older brothers.
Now, we have two big projects: "The School of Mothers and the Republic" and "Bridges of Understanding".
The first has four parts.
There's philosophy.
Why philosophy?
Because it allows criticism.
Because that's it, the problem too - it's hard to say things.
Myself, I dare to say things.
It's not easy, but I do it.
And "Bridges of Understanding".
Because for me, it's easier to build bridges than walls.
Because, looking at things, I realized two things: there was prejudice on both sides.
They always say to us: "Them, they're the troublemakers, they're racists."
And from the other side, "Them, they're the thugs."
So, there were prejudices, and that's why with The Mothers' Brigade we had nerve, we were on the other side.
We got on the rapid transport train to seek out the people of Paris.
We put it to them: "To Parisians, radicalization is only a problem for suburbanites."
That's not right, it affects everyone, it concerns us all, no matter our position in society, our religion or lack of it.
We're all affected by the phenomenon which, unfortunately, exists within our local districts today.
Today, I can tell you that in these districts, we are - I often say: what I say, I say for myself - I say that our districts are Islamized. And that's why we mothers, us women, we fight ... not for freedom, but to remain free.
Because in 2016, in France, you know, we're supposed to be free.
And we're moving backwards.
The goal of The Mothers' Brigade is to reclaim our districts, reoccupy the public domain, and above all, recover what is most dear to us - our children.
And that's why we're trying to put these two projects into place, because to tell the truth, it's not easy, we need the means, etc.
We have some volunteers, but too few, especially where I come from, Seine-Saint-Denis, it's very, very difficult.
And today, I believe in it.
Why do I believe in it?
Because I say that a mum - where is there a mum among you, or a parent, a dad even - who hasn't sent their son a text saying, "Where are you, where are you?"
The reply, that's, "Don't worry, don't worry!"
(Laughter) My son once said, "Mum, in one month, you've texted me 'Where are you?' 150 times."
And he replied with "Don't worry" 150 times.
Imagine you have four kids, that's a lot of "Where are you?".
(Laughter) And with just that in mind, we say to ourselves, we can agree or disagree on many things, but what brings us all together in The Mothers' Brigade?
At The Mothers' Brigade, we've all sorts.
We have atheists, Muslims, Jews, everyone.
You know what brings us together?
I'll tell you: love of our children.
And for that alone exists the obligation to fight together.
What you saw in the news report where they showed Aziza ...
Unfortunately, we have more and more mums coming to see us because they are afraid.
And you know, I often say, when your child is having problems at school, you go to see a teacher to help you.
When you're a victim of theft or whatever, you go to the police station.
But when you have a child of 14 or 15 becoming radicalized, you go to see whom?
That's the problem,
that's the aim of this organization, to provide a place for raising awareness.
If we do nothing today, in a few years, we'll regret it.
I spoke with two or three people yesterday. They said to me, "At Avignon, it's not like that yet."
Where we live, ten years ago, it was like that, so if you do nothing, it will become just like it is where we live now.
Now is the time to get up, to get up together.
I don't know if there's any politicians among you, but I'd like to say that we shouldn't fear giving a name to things, because, today, there is a problem, and we must fight together and not against one another.
This organization is close to my heart.
Why? Because of my duty
as a French citizen, I feel I need to fulfil it.
Often the young ask me, "What is it that you do for us?"
And it's true that what we do, we must do for our children.
I've lived through terrorism in Algeria, and I can tell you, I fear for France, I fear for my children, I fear for everyone.
Well, you can join The Mothers' Brigade, you can come fight with us, you can come see the reality of the situation, and then dare to say, "No, we shouldn't stigmatize, it's not true, it's just a minority."
I can tell you that this is a reality.
I am confident that together we can save our children and save France.
Thank you.
(Applause)
Do you know this music?
(Music) Django Reinhardt, one of the greatest guitarists in history.
Did you know that he only had three working fingers on the left hand?
Three fingers to create that swing, what a genius!
Surely, he was often told that it was impossible.
How many times in my life have I been told that it would be impossible?
I was not born in this wheelchair.
I grew up nearby, in Noirétable, in the heart of Auvergne, surrounded by mountains.
And as a child, I dreamed of getting away, of traveling.
I had only one thing in mind: becoming a pilot just like my heroes of the French Airmail, Mermoz, Guillaumet, Saint-Exupéry.
Some of these pilots have accomplished extraordinary achievements and have ended up having accidents.
For me, my life began with an accident when I was a young student-pilot at the Auvergne flying club.
On the 12th of May, 1991, I was 16.
I got into the back of one of the small airplanes to go to Marseille.
The conditions were not good, suddenly, We found ourselves in a cloud, thick, dense, that forced the pilot to rely on autopilot.
According to statistics, when a pilot who is not used to flying on autopilot and gets into a dense cloud, there are 180 seconds left before hitting the ground.
180 seconds, and then it’s all over.
When I woke up, I had no idea what had happened.
I had no idea where I was.
Around me, there was silence, cold, snow, pain, fear and the long hours that waited ahead before being rescued.
I was the only survivor.
From that day on, I was told that I’d be paraplegic, that I’d have to learn how to live again as a person with reduced mobility, like you, it’s something I knew nothing about.
That’s what I was told at the time that I’d never fly again.
In any case, being disabled wasn’t going to be an excuse.
Remember that I was only 16.
I wanted freedom, adventure, passion
But I had a problem, all the planes were controlled using legs.
And steered using feet.
But I couldn’t believe that for technical reasons, I’d never fly again.
Two years after, I learned that in Toulouse there was a plane in which the controls had been transferred to hand control.
It is called a "malonnier".
So, I went there, I worked hard, I did my hours.
My new friends encouraged me.
I felt pride all around me.
In April 1995, four years after my accident, I got my pilot certificate.
It was my first big achievement.
For flying a plane, you need technique, knowledge.
You need humility, humanity.
You need to be reliable within a chain of authority where everyone is responsible for others and the information that is shared.
Solidarity and mutual aid are essential values after an ordeal and in this environment, all my friends pushed me to succeed again.
More than ever, the difficulty strengthened me.
I discovered the satisfaction of achieving a difficult goal, of feeling capable of something that I believed I was incapable of.
My pilot course began my real rehabilitation.
You are like me, you would say that finally we are all equal in the sky.
Yet on the ground, the most difficult obstacle to overcome is prejudice.
I learned that the occupation of a pilot is prohibited for the disabled.
It is impossible to do aerial tasks, training, transporting of freight.
But as you all know here, we have become accustomed to the field of aviation in taking on impossible challenges, within a century.
If a crash hasn’t stopped me from flying, it won’t be the administrative rules that will stop me from doing it.
So, I decided to take up a new challenge, very ambitiously, which was to make a change to the rules to enable the disabled to become professional pilots.
It was going to take a while, I was going to need support.
Firstly, it was Guillaume Féral, our expert in flight controls
And then Brigitte Revellin-Falcoz, one of the first women ever to be an airline pilot in France.
And Mike Smith, a disabled man, a Vietnam veteran who I met in the US.
In these missions, everyone had the same goal.
This was the way to reach it, it was going to be different needing a plan, an organization and training specific to all.
It's a great example showing that in teamwork everyone has a say, they can find their place and deploy their skills and talents.
On returning to France, I had my turn to participate in aerial forest fire surveillance missions in Lot-et-Garonne.
We had the permission of the firemen, but these missions remained unpaid and were seen as illegal by the Civil Aviation.
But it worked out.
Since this day, we proved that every profession can be adjusted, so that disabled men and women can carry out 100% of complex professional tasks with precision and reliability.
In hindsight, today, I can say that audacity pays off.
I met Dominique Bussereau, State Secretary of transport who, with a remarkable open spirit, listened to our arguments.
In November 2003, he signed the ministerial decree that allowed access to professional pilot licenses for those with lower limb paralysis.
Since then, there have been 7 graduates, including my friend Guillaume.
I was the only one not to have graduated.
But I told myself that it was impossible, that it was too hard.
It scared me.
So instead of becoming a professional pilot, I decided to take on a new challenge.
I couldn't avoid it.
I already flew with my hands.
And last year, I told myself, why don't I try flying upside-down, on my back.
I simply decided to become a stunt pilot.
And whilst doing this, I said, why not try Le Bourget?
Le Bourget, that is just the biggest aeronautic show in the world.
So of course, that was not going to be easy because at the beginning, I knew nothing about acrobatics and I was very apprehensive.
At that point, flying wasn't enough, you have to operate in three dimensions and you are completely lost very quickly.
You don't know what is going on
and where you are going.
You have your head upide-down.
And me, when flying on my back, I only fear one thing: that my straps unfasten and I pass through the plane's canopy.
Acrobatics is a challenging and physically very demanding discipline.
But with such goals, strong objectives, the impossible is only a step away.
The first obstacles were technical obstacles.
There, having manual control was not enough for acrobatics.
Flexible and responsive control was needed.
The "malonier" that equipped my acrobatics' plane answer to these specifications.
It consists of a big lever arm that is activated by a push and pull movement and that presses the rudder bars.
But having a "malonier" or not, the real difficulty in acrobatics is to manage to do a perfect figure
A lot of investment and personal work is needed to succeed
And sometimes perseverance doesn't pay off as much as we'd like.
Everything is determined by millimeters in the control position to guide the trajectory and position the plane properly in the space.
70% of the work is done on the floor.
I have to memorize my figures to acquire good reactions, repeat the sequence of figures
In aeronautics we call it "music".
This is the choreography that pilots do before each flight.
But the real obstacle was a physical obstacle.
To resist accelerations and stay in your seat, you have to be able to contract all of your muscles.
See, in a stunting, we take four G. It weighs up to four times our body weight.
We are literally crushed in our seat.
You have to be physically strong.
And me, I haven't got muscles in my legs anymore, this was an enormous setback.
So, just like any other stunt pilot, maybe a bit more than the others, I went to the weights room, and I pushed.
The other obstacle was that I'm a woman.
Well I agree with you, it shouldn't be an obstacle, and yet, on the contrary ...
For women, the arterial tension is lower increasing the risk of fainting during punchy figures
We call that the black veil.
In fact, blood stops going to the brain and we run the risk of fainting.
The solution is to wear support stockings to keep blood pressure in the upper body.
It is a bit like the equivalent of an anti-G suit for stunt pilots, but a lot less sexy.
The last obstacle, as usual, was administrative.
Civil Aviation wanted to test and test again my physical resistance before granting me a medical dispensation at the Percy hospital, the military hospital of Percy.
The most unbelievable thing was that I even had to do a flight test to check my resistance in real conditions.
Eventually, it was the highest military rank who made the decision.
He gave his agreement saying that, "If problems are caused, it will be an opportunity to find solutions."
Only two months before achieving my goal, I finally obtained the medical permission that allowed me to be able to fly as a stunt pilot on my own.
So that put me to the test but it was this pleasure of maneuvering into the third dimension that allowed me to achieve my goal.
Eventually, with Le Bourget.
(Runway agent) Wait three or four minutes more.
(Control tower) Cap 10, hello.

Request for start-up. Golf car park.
(Control tower) Yes, Cap 10, no problem.
(Control tower) Cap 10, take-off allowed.
Come on, we're off!
I tested my well-being, what a pleasure, the controlling of a plane, and more so with acrobatics.
I have the impression
that I'm describing heaven on earth.
D.B.: Nine month of preparation for three minutes thirty of joy.
What I would have become if I hadn't had this car accident, I won't know that.
The only thing I know, is that to give meaning to this story and to pursue my dreams I had more to lose by losing my joy than losing my legs.
My love in life and that passion which never left me, allowed me to do the impossible.
And at the Bourget, I was Django.
(Applause)
(Electronic piano music) Good evening everyone.
My name is Vincent Bal, and I have to admit two things.
First, I am Belgian, so that's why I might sound a bit strange.
And second, I am a "shadowologist".
Everything started with this teacup, which I bought in Vietnam.
One day, I saw the shadow of the cup on my desk, and I thought I caught a glimpse of something... (Applause) ... a little elephant.
And for me, this was a spark of inspiration.
I discovered that there is magic everywhere.
Since then, I am always on the lookout.
I look for images in shadows, and of course, shadows don't exist without... ...without light.
(Applause) I discovered there are creatures hiding in the shadows of all everyday objects.
So, I started searching around the house.
I took everything, even my children's toys.
Basically, I became... ...a thief.
(Applause) Sorry kids.
Each object on earth is hiding images, and sometimes even aliens.
(Laughter) (Applause) Yes, it became a kind of obsession, even when I am eating some good Belgian chocolate, I see things.
I'll show you.
There!
(Applause) Drawing on stage is making me thirsty.
But, luckily, it is cooler in the shade.
It is really refreshing.
(Applause) It's cool in the shadows but sometimes, it is really very, very precise.
Sometimes it comes down to a hair’s breadth.
(Laughter) (Applause) I find it crazy how energizing light can be.
It's solar energy.
And there's also music in there, especially when you're being accompanied by Thomas de Prins.
(Laughter) (Applause) In truth, watching shadows is a little bit like cloud-watching
We see things that come from our own minds, like a Rorschach test
So, of course, sometimes I see scenes from my favourite films like... (Applause) ...' Singing in the Rain' or 'Chantons sous la pluie'.
I almost forgot we are in a country that translates film titles, Where they don't say 'Jaws' but 'The Teeth of the Sea'.
Well, here are some teeth.
I hope these shadows have lightened up your life a little, like they do for me
But now it is time to get going.
Thank you!
(Applause) (Piano music ends)
One year ago, nearly to the day, I crossed the border from Iran into Turkey, just north of Syria.
On my right, Mount Ararat's immense silhouette rose up.
The legend says that Noah's ark
ran aground there. 5,167 meters Such a cone, for a paraglider like me, was like ... a vanilla ice cream cone on a summer afternoon.
I had three days.
I had very little time on the internet, but I managed to learn two things.
First, conditions were perfect for flying.
However, guides were to be avoided at all costs as they might ask for my access permit, impossible to get on such short notice.
I didn't have it.
On the second day of our climb, halfway up the slope, I was sleeping, rolled up in my paragliding wing.
It was just before dawn.
When suddenly ... (Plane noise) (Explosion) Fuck! It's war!
It was just over there.
I will freely admit that I quickly ducked behind some rocks.
Seven years earlier, on July 11, 2008 at 9:30 in the morning, I began a round-the-world trip by bicycle, an old childhood dream.
Anyone here who thinks the world is small, believe me: you're wrong.
It's enormous!
I had planned to take four years.
I knew there would be major repercussions for my life.
I had a good job; an aeronautical engineer under permanent contract.
In a way, I killed my career.
I had a partner that I loved ... my family, friends.
I gave it all up.
It may seem another irresponsible, stupid decision, like the one I just described on Mount Ararat. But in fact, it was undoubtedly, and I still think so today, the most responsible decision of my life.
Basically, what I was looking for, besides seeing the world, was to regain control of my life.
I'd lost track of myself a bit.
I'd been on the traditional route, ruled less by personal choices, than by choices imposed on me by society: education, career, family, material comfort.
I never felt as though these choices had been mine.
So, for once, I dared make a decision that would have an enormous effect on my life.
But, then, it became imperative that this decision be a very responsible one, that I seriously weigh the consequences for my life. But, from such thoughts came others, about the environmental impact.
So much so that I decided that my world tour would be essentially non-motorized.
Zero-carbon travel.
I would cross the continents on a bicycle, the oceans in a sail boat.
And, for a bit of added fun, I would take along my paraglider to view the world from above.
I called this venture, "On the road with a wing."
I had not chosen the easiest route.
To increase my chances for success, I had to be well organized.
Yep, I was still an engineer despite wanting to leave it all behind.
My approach was to make a real business plan.
For six months, I contacted the media, sponsors.
I worked on a budget, the equipment I would need.
In short, a real business plan. I love Excel. I had a lot of fun, believe me!
(Laughter) Then, I looked into visas, winter in the Andes, in the Himalayas, war zones, to create the perfect itinerary.
I knew that if I made a mistake, I would suffer the consequences.
As an example of my stupidity,
one day, I was crossing the Pamirs in Central Asia, and I met a cyclist just as shaggy and unkempt as me.
At the time, this was really something special!
So, we chatted a bit, and then he told me that he also wanted to use a sail boat to cross the ocean from Asia to America ... Whoa!
My stomach was in knots!
I had to tell him that that wasn't really possible.
Sail boats follow the trade winds, flowing around the world toward the west.
The reverse is very rare.
So, he was going to find himself at the ocean forced to take a plane after he had worked like crazy to plan a non-motorized voyage!
I, too, nearly went east.
But, fortunately, a friend came to see me, shortly before I left, and gave me this crucial information, and I was able to turn around.
The cyclist had made the exact same mistake.
When I was behind the rock on Mount Ararat, being shot at by F-16s, after the explosions ended, I thought it had been a military exercise, I continued toward the summit, where I launched the next day to fly clear of the prior day's gunfire zone.
I landed safe and sound and retrieved my bicycle and made it to the first town where I finally found someone who spoke English.
He explained to me that the mountain closed three months ago, that it was full of PKK rebels, and that the army was shooting on sight anything that moved.
(Laughter) (Applause) I had put my life in serious danger because of ignorance.
If I had only been a bit more informed, I would never have made such irresponsible choices.
Because, yes, a lack of information leads to irresponsible choices and, sometimes, even disasters.
However, having made, for the most part, choices that were informed and responsible, conscious of the consequences, I was able to make my dream a reality and go even further.
Four months later, on December 29, 2015, I crossed the finish line after 2,723 days, Seven and a half years on the road, rather than the anticipated four.
I'd travelled 105,000 km through some incredible places.
I'd met all kinds of people. I'd been able to see marvellous things. I was happy, and I'd achieved my goal.
That's how it went for me.
But, what would happen if it was like that for each and everyone of us?
And what would happen if it was like that for everyone in our country or on the planet?
Can we not imagine a society that was more conscious, and, therefore, more responsible, and more liberated?
Because a world tour, a lifetime project, or a social plan is like paragliding.
They're all full of limitations and risks that we've chosen ourselves. We do everything we can to control the consequences.
An inaccurate reading of the wind could mean death or paralysis.
But, the take-off is the ultimate instant, the moment of truth, when your choices become truly accountable, and hugely freeing. So ...
ready to fly?
Thank you.
(Applause)
What if you had four extra free time hours per day, what would you do with them?
Because four hours is a lot when you think about it.
In four hours, we can do lots of things.
So maybe you would read, learn to sew, or maybe some of you would finally start that jump-rope business you've always wanted to launch.
Well, I can't answer for you.
However, we can agree on one thing, that is, you would gain an incredible boost in free time and productivity.
Well, I am here to tell you that it's possible.
It's possible by hacking our sleep.
Now when we want to hack something, the first fundamental step is to understand what we're talking about.
So in short, what is sleep?
Well, it's very simple.
Human beings sleep a lot, around eight hours daily, which means about one-third of a day.
So as you hopefully know, when you sleep, your brain does much more than just switch off for eight hours.
When you sleep, your brain oscillates between different depths of sleep that are more or less intense.
We call these rhythms or periods "sleep cycles".
But how do we know they are sleep cycles?
We know it because a lot of research has been made on this subject.
Personally, I know it because I use a very handy little application that enables me to measure my sleep cycles.
So it provides me with graphs that resemble this.
This is very simple to understand: the higher it is, the more awake I am. the lower it is, the more deeply asleep I am.
So the orange color means I'm awake.
Green means I'm in light sleep.
And blue means I'm in what's called "deep sleep" or "REM sleep".
Maybe you've already heard about it because in fact, it's at this very time that we have dreams.
A little earlier, I spoke about sleep cycles, and here, we can see them very clearly.
We can count six of them which is a very important number.
It's so important that we've discovered that human beings absolutely need six sleep cycles, otherwise, you wouldn't be rested in the morning.
Researchers, while further exploring this subject, found out something even more important. It is that all throughout the night, only the blue zone serves a purpose.
Only the blue zone has a regenerative effect on your body.
It means that if you want to feel great in the morning, the green and orange are useless, only the blue counts.
Now if you don't believe me, I'm going to do a little demonstration for you to understand.
It's a situation that should speak to most of you.
It's about alcohol.
Here's the idea.
You come home from a party, you're totally drunk.
You drop flat on your bed and immediately fall asleep as soon as your head hits the pillow.
The next morning, you wake up, and you notice two things.
First, you have a monstrous headache.
And second, you're worn out.
Here you're going to tell me, "Well, it's just a normal hangover!"
But is that really normal?
Because you slept nine hours, which is more than enough, right?
One night is eight hours, so you should be perfectly fine.
Well, no.
It turns out that you get the chance to have in your presence someone extremely professional and conscientious.
So I made that experiment.
I experimented with it, and the result is quite telling.
Here's what I got.
Here, we can observe three things, maybe four, we'll see.
Firstly, there's a big amount of light sleep, and I explained to you earlier that light sleep is totally useless.
Secondly, I woke up after an hour, and of course, I have no memory of this at all.
Thirdly, and most importantly, I went from six to only three deep sleep cycles.
Do you see what this means?
This means when your mind is clouded, alcohol prevents your brain from having regular cycles, and that's why you feel totally drained in the morning.
So this example, in addition to being amusing, serves two main purposes: to show you that humans only need two hours of deep sleep - without which you feel tired - moreover, only deep sleep is useful.
And it's here that I'm going to put my hacker's hat back because what I've been saying this entire time is that you have eight hours of sleep but only two are good for something.
So is that not an opportunity to do something?
Indeed it is, and the thing we can do is called "polyphasic sleep".
What is polyphasic sleep?
Well, it is the discipline that aims at reducing the amount of sleep by dividing it into small naps throughout the day.
This can seem complicated, but it's really not.
It's so simple that you all already experienced a polyphasic sleep cycle.
When was that? When you were a baby.
Because as a matter of fact,
babies haven't been conditioned to the rat race schedule by society and their parents yet.
As a result, babies sleep when they want to.
They often take a big nap in the afternoon.
So they are fully rested.
But then, they are put to bed at 8 p.m.
So they wake up at 3 a.m. to the dismay of their parents.
So what does this reveal?
First, we could think that babies don't have a natural rhythm but on the contrary, they do.
We are the ones on whom society has imposed its rhythm, whereas babies do what they want and have a natural rhythm.
Let me give you a second example: skippers at sea.
Have you ever asked yourselves how a solitary skipper is able to make 90-day crossings with very little sleep?
I already asked myself this question, and in fact, I found the answer.
So it's really simple.
These guys push polyphasic sleep to the extreme, which means that the day or rather the night of a skipper at sea is going to resemble this.
The red color indicates they're sleeping, the white color when they're awake.
So it means that these guys take six 20-min naps during the day, and it's enough for them, except that six naps of 20 min makes two hours, precisely the two hours of deep sleep that we need.
So what does it show us?
Well, that shows us that these guys have 100% optimized their sleep, meaning they're awake for 22 hours daily with no problem.
That said, they never keep this kind of rhythm for more than three months since we don't know yet if going further would have negative consequences on health but, being such an extreme and brutal rhythm, it certainly has.
So I took two examples that are complete opposites.
Now, let's take a third example that's a little bit more common.
And this example is me!
Let's go back three years ago when I was in my senior year of high school.
At the time, I had no self-confidence at all.
I had less than zero esteem for myself.
I didn't have any social life, and I hided behind video games to justify this lack.
In short, I was just a normal teen.
So at the end of high school, I had to chose a vocational field. Given that I had no self-confidence, I thought, "Prep school's not for me.
What interests me?"
There were lots of things that interested me.
To be honest, I even hesitated between being an helicopter pilot or a blacksmith.
Then, I decided to do something more original, so I ended up in business school - I know, no one's perfect!
So, I wanted to go to business school, but not wanting to do prep school, I had to go through the post-undergraduate program which is pretty tricky because you get in through a competition.
At the time, these exams were not for me since they scared me.
So I told myself, "Grégoire, think broader."
I aimed for the first, second, third, and fourth, so in January, before the high school diploma, I had four exams to study for, both written and oral, and on top of that the diploma.
Today, when I look back at it, I think,"No big deal!"
But back then, it was pretty much
the challenge of my life.
What happened after is that I thought, "Grégoire, this is going downhill, and you're going to fail because your eyes were bigger than your stomach."
And I thought, "It's not over yet."
Then a friend who, like me, was into weird things, came to see me, and spoke to me about polyphasic sleep.
He explained to me the ins and outs, and he told me that if I was motivated, we could give it a try.
At that moment in my head, here's what happened.
I thought, "Okay Grégoire, if you carry on like this, you're heading for disaster, and you won't make it."
Super positive, I know ... So, I thought, "Why not try this out?"
"If anything," I added, "you could talk about it at a conference one day, and people will think it's cool.
But we'll see about that."
And that's exactly what I did.
I talked about it to my dad, and he thought it was cool.
I talked about it to my mother, and the idea horrified her, except that dad is a doctor, so, to me, that was the green light.
I wasn't going to die, so off I went!
I started polyphasic sleep in January for three months.
So I had a rhythm called the "Everyman Schedule" which is interesting because it's structured to allow people to maintain some kind of social life, emphasis on "some kind".
It's simple, it's a big three-hour night, often from 4 to 7 a.m. the pleasurable part, then three 20-minute naps spread out at different times of the day, like noon, 4 p.m., and midnight.
I truly said "some kind of social life" because back then, I was in high school, I had to go to class, and at 4 p.m. and noon, I had to find a place to sleep.
I got kicked out of the bathroom several times by the monitors because I had to lock myself in to be able to sleep soundly.
It was the only place, and it wasn't easy to explain to a monitor why I had to lock myself in the shitter due to too much noise in the study room.
Really, it wasn't that simple!
So it was not always easy, however, it was unbelievable. Why?
Because of this!
I estimate that in doing this, I gained approximately 120 hours a month.
I don't know if you realize, but if you do some consulting work at 20 euros an hour, that makes 2,400 euros a month, quite a nice little gold mine!
Of course, I had no means to be a consultant at the time.
So I contented myself being a student, and I worked, read, studied, watched documentaries and movies.
Now, when I look at this, I think it's clearly thanks to this that I got my diploma and entered the school where I am today.
Today, I'm not doing polyphasic sleep.
And the interesting question is why?
If it was so great and I could make 2,400 euros as a consultant, then I should be doing it, right? Well, actually no.
The reason why I stopped is that I had reached my goals.
Somehow, I no longer had any reason to fight.
It wasn't a big battle but a small one, at my scale, and I had attained my objective, so I took a vacation.
And that's actually my message.
It is that - you're going to have to believe me on this one - if I myself can do it, everybody can do it.
The only thing that we all lack is hunger.
The sole common denominator that we all miss to succeed in doing this kind of things, in forcing ourselves and foregoing four hours of sleep daily, is to constantly have this hunger, this unpleasant feeling in our guts that if ever you don't radically change, you are going to fail.
And it might be a little malicious to wish you that, but basically, that's the case, it's what I'm hoping for you.
I wish you get hungry because in the end, the hungrier we are, the happier we're when we sit down to eat.
Thank you.
(Applause)
Here is our ancestor, homo sapiens.
His eyes are wide open
and he's looking ahead.
He's ingenious and creative.
To face challenges and to ensure his and his group's survival, he invents tools.
He uses these tools to make clothes, to hunt, or to kill enemies.
He makes choices.
Time passes and mankind keeps inventing: the wheel, the ox-drawn cart, machines, and bang! We are in the midst
of the Industrial Revolution.
At this particular point in our History, machines increase man's mechanical powers.
And then, the race for innovation picks up again, and homo sapiens finds himself at the wheel of a car.
He learns to drive while negotiating round bends and avoiding pedestrians.
He makes choices. Either he drives too fast and causes an accident, or he helps someone out by giving him a lift.
Humans continue to evolve,
and mankind invents the computer.
This time, machines increase man's cognitive powers.
This is what enables machines to do jobs usually done by humans.
Now, we are in the midst of the Artificial Intelligence Revolution.
During this revolution, progress is seen in all fields.
Huge economic changes are made extremely fast.
In this new era, up-to-date cars no longer need a driver.
With artificial intelligence, we have a powerful tool in our hands whose implications are not yet known.
AI is going to progressively affect
all segments of society.
So we're going to need guidelines to limit its development so that it would be consistent with our human values, and, above all, so that it would bring true social progress.
And once again, we are called to make choices.
But how can we make sure that these choices are made responsibly?
How can we ensure that AI is developed
in an ethical and socially responsible way?
Well, we're very lucky here in Montreal because we have experts in ethics, in law, in public policies and in artificial intelligence
who have studied these questions and started a debate to define ethical principles based on seven key values: well-being, autonomy, justice, privacy, knowledge, democracy, and accountability.
These discussions were not held in a vacuum
but rather in the form of public debates over a period of three months, from February to April 2018, in 15 different public places, that facilitated the dialogue between hundreds of citizens, experts, and stakeholders from all walks of life.
The Montreal Declaration is the result of these deliberations, and is based on the following principles.
Well-being.
The Montreal Declaration states that AI's development
should ensure the well-being of all sentient beings.
Would I want an AI to decide by itself
to kill an animal, a human being, or to set fire to a forest?
Autonomy.
AI development should encourage
people's autonomy and control in a responsible way the autonomy of our computer systems.
So if I have an AI system
that is capable of analysing X-rays and giving a diagnosis, would I want that AI to communicate
this diagnosis directly to the patient, or would I want that a doctor should always be involved?
Justice.

AI development should promote justice.
We know that intelligent systems are trained on data bases that can be biased.
Would we want an AI to make
decisions that are racist?
Privacy.
Who does my personal data belong to?
If I'm pregnant would I want the maternity store down the road to send me targeted advertising that I didn't ask for?
The principle here is that AI
should guarantee and respect our privacy.
Knowledge.
AI development should
encourage critical thinking to protect us from propaganda and manipulation.
It's what we see with the issue of fake news which can have an impact on democracy.
Here's another scenario. If I want a medical consultation on a website and communicate via text messages, do I want to know or am I able to know who is talking to me, an artificial intelligence or a human?
Democracy.
AI development should favour
collaborations and democratic debates.
If a self-driving car is heading for an unavoidable collision, who must it protect,
the car's passengers or the pedestrians crossing the road?
Who is going to make that decision?
How are we going to make those choices?
If our driverless car causes an accident, who is to be held responsible?
So in the Montreal Declaration, we say that the actors involved in developing intelligent systems should accept responsibility so that they could manage the risks associated with these technologies.
If these ethical principles are duly applied, then artificial intelligence can bring us great benefits,
as we can see here with self-driving cars that will increase our mobility.
In the field of medicine, it's even more apparent with image processing.
We are able to detect cancers earlier on, so it has a significant impact on a patient's life expectancy.
We can also work to develop new medecines or treatments that take into account the unique genome of each human being.
So we could create a personalized medicine.
With advanced robotics and automation, production costs are reduced.
And thanks to natural language understanding and automated translation, man-machine interfaces can be improved and made easier to use, such as the personal digital assistants.
But let's face it, the advent of artificial intelligence
presents us with new challenges. One of them is targeted advertising,
because, as we've already seen earlier, it can lead to manipulation, propaganda, so we need to protect ourselves.
And that's the reason why, in Canada, advertising directed at children is prohibited.
Thus we will have to set limits on advertising.
Another issue is the incredible changes undergone in the job market.
There are jobs, as we said, that don't even exist yet.
They will soon be created but we don't know what they are yet.
Repetitive tasks are going to be automated.
Some jobs have a strong human and relationship component, in education for example.
Those kinds of jobs are going to be highly valued, as well as jobs that require extensive knowledge or a wide range of computer skills.
I said that IT jobs will be valued.
Before 1984, a lot more women were working in IT than today.
Today, these jobs are largely dominated by white males.
So how are we going to promote diversity?
According to The Harvard Business Review, two strategies have proven efficient.
It is coaching and recruitment targeted towards minorities and women.
So we can see that all these challenges brought by changes in the job market will need to be addressed by creating training courses that help people make these changes.
In Canada, Quebec, and here in Montreal, we are leading players in artificial intelligence.
And we've made a choice, that of promoting the responsible use of artificial intelligence.
I'll give you a brief overview with some practical applications from examples in which we've set up projects that will have a positive impact on humans.
The first is an application that helps the visually impaired detect and identify objects close to them.
(Video) Cellphone: Frying pan, frying pan.
Expresso, expresso, expresso.
Orange, orange, orange.
Banana, banana.
Here is a project we are doing in conjunction with the Red Cross.
Our goal is to automate the annotation of electronic maps
so that information collected on the field are kept more up-to-date.
When floods happen, with the latest information gathered, we can deal with natural disasters more effectively than with the methods we used previously.
And this will have a huge impact on many people's lives and well-being. [Boys are aggressive. Girls like cooking]
Another project is to detect gender bias in texts because we want to promote inclusion, equality and diversity.
Here, the smart system is trying to identify gender stereotypes.
Finally, as in the past, we can clearly see that this new tool we've created challenges us.
It's a new means of shaping again our world and our future,
and it's within our power to ensure that it is for the good of humanity.
Each of us has a role to play in this revolution.
It's not just a matter for experts.
And we can play this role by learning, by reading the Montreal Declaration, by using our critical minds, by taking part in decision-making, by working on projects that have a positive impact on mankind, and, collectively, by setting limits in order to control the use of artificial intelligence.
It's important to do it now.
Let's be vigilant, caring and innovative.
If we remain committed to making the right choices, then, we will also be able, like our distant ancestor, to look to the future with confidence and optimism.
Let's keep our eyes wide open!
(Applause)
Kenza Aloui: Not long ago, Ines and I were invited to another conference in Paris. The conference had much less people in the audience.
I would say about 10 times less people than this one.
At this conference, we were both introduced as ... Hold on ... a "duo for peace".
Just like one would try to make a conditioner or a vanilla indoor fragance more marketable.
Inès Weill-Rochant: Yes.
It wasn’t the first time we faced that kind of pigeonholing.
We are often introduced as Israeli and Palestinian, in that order, of course.
I reckon, it's tempting.
It is an easy simplification and an easy sell, we get it, but a false assumption.
My name is Inès.
I grew up in Jerusalem,
I lived on the Israeli side and went to primary, secondary, and high school with Palestinians.
On paper, I am neither Israeli nor Palestinian, I am French.
But beyond documentation, I am from Jerusalem, with all that it means, Holy 3 times, identity issues, therapy, and on the [TEDx] stage. KA: In some ways,
[TEDx] is like couples therapy, we are aware of that.
And today, it's our last session, and we are sharing it with you.
I am Kenza, I was born on the other side of the Mediterranean Sea, on the same side as Inès, but I grew up in Rabat, in Morocco, and I got into this quagmire much later, at age 20, when I spent my year abroad in Tel Aviv.
I never really recovered, I will try to explain why tonight.
IWR: Since we started working together, given the fact that we are two women, that we are young, and as we smile a lot, it's true, we are seen as cute, soft and pretty, and naively blossoming even!
You thought about it!
When you saw us, coming on stage, two young women coming on stage, and that’s OK, we hear it really often.
KA: It happens so often that we are not holding it against you, because Ines and Kenza translates to either Jewish and Muslim, or the classic Peace and Love, or the famous 'vivre ensemble', Very trendy the 'vivre ensemble' lately. or The Kooples, Inès and Kenza in a relationship for 2 years. Don't be disappointed, it's false.
There are topics, such as the Israeli-Palestinian conflict for example, when we are very tempted to use these binary terms because it is reassuring and it allows us not to confront the complexity of reality - it feels good sometimes - it allows us to simplify it.
KA: This is why many times, words are coupled up, not our fault: war and peace, fair and unfair, hope and despair, coupled up words that frames thinking, and makes it difficult to think outside the box.
IWR: You might have understood by now, we love danger, therefore we created a space very hostile to certainties.
We even made it our job eventually, not by putting together a peace process but an offbeat festival.
KA: Our story together, the real one,
is starting to age. We met in 2007, we were 18, and we were studying at Sciences Po.
Strangely enough, we started being close when we were living far from each other, during our semester abroad I in Tel Aviv and Ines in Cairo.
IWR: We would talk on Skype.
We had our own Tel Aviv Cairo liaison, we might have been bugged, but not to worry, our topics of conversation were not the least bit political.
After our year abroad, we came back to Paris for our masters degree, and as dedicated students, we went to conferences on this topic. We realized, like you for sure, that political debates and academic ones were mainly dogmatic and too repetitive.
KA: When we came back to France, we were shocked by all the very intense mental blocks that the conflict brought around us, and beyond, by all the deep ramifications it had in France and that we had maybe underestimated them.
IWR: We realized that the debates we were listening to made public trending "pro Israeli" or "pro Palestinian" never leave their comfort zone, comfort zone we all have.
KA: Today these categories mean everything and nothing at the same time. The people, described as "pro-Israeli" or "pro-Palestinian" rarely meet in Paris.
IWR: We proceeded to do a short survey, and we identified 3 different positions when the topic is brought up. KA: The first one, one of my favorites, includes people who have a solution to all the world’s issues, a very simple solution, that would always work: theirs.
It works everytime.
IWR: There is a category I like: the one with people in denial, who do not want to face reality a reality too ugly, and it would lead to questioning, I call this the 'burying-our-heads-in-the-sand' method or the manly method.
Sorry guys.
(Laughter) And last but not least, people who are not interested at all in the topic, who choose to leave it, because it is too complicated, don't see any way out, so they stop.
IR: Starting from there - we couldn't stop here, of course - we decided to create something raw and human, with no senseless debates.
KA: While talking to artists, going to the movies, visiting museums, being close to the artistic content we realized it was more interesting, and making a bigger impact compared to all the mumbo jumbo we had to listen to, but once again in Paris, the public who showed up had a deeper knowledge of the situation.
IR: We also understood that art was less bombastic, and allows to talk about eclectic and sensitive topics.
KA: In July 2013, we had a deal, we decided not to accept any full time position,
that was the easy part, our generation inherited a terrible job market.
IWR: Right now, our families are freaking out.
KA: The second part of our deal was to not have any plan B, so that we would be fully and only focused on plan A, the festival.
IWR: In august 2013, we pitched our idea to our parents,
a very important step,
They thought we lost our minds, we were supposed to become diplomates or journalists, and we choose art as a way to reroute the classic political approach, but let's face it, that career was not meant for us, that's it.
KA: We stayed strong and in September 2013, in one night and with a joint effort, using a Google doc, we found the name of our festival, we wrote our festival's manifesto, and in the following weeks, we started contacting artists on Facebook, with no money or venue.
In December 2013, after being rejected by almost all the Parisian venues - IWR: Yes.
KA: Our dream venue, the Bellevilloise, said yes, and gave us our first date.
IWR: To get funding, we started a crowdfunding campaign because we needed funding for this festival. We cashcowed our friends, we also asked them to edit our video - to help us shoot it - and ask them also for donations.
Regarding the logistics, we did as we could, artists played along, and we thank them for this.
We are thinking about a famous pianist who accepted to come to our festival.
We thought, "We could ask him to play my electric piano, to not go over our budget."
He said no to the idea and brought his own piano, he even came back this year.
KA: For budgetary reasons, we also booked the worst flights
with the worst layovers
for all the artists, and when they finally arrived to Paris, there was no cosy hotel waiting for them, we were lending them our own apartments.
After all these mishaps, they always happen, on May 24th 2014, around 2:10 pm, the first IsraeliPalestinian art festival was born, independent and free in Paris: Off the Wall Pilgrimage.
KA: You did not forget a thing! Good job!
IWR: Yes, I didn’t forget anything.
KA: Right on.
Of course, we knew that we were on a very dangerous territory, maybe the most slippery.
Part of our endeavor was to provoke.
You probably guessed that.
A lot of stress.
I think we reached a peek today.
IWR: Yeah we are doing pretty good right now!
KA: I think we could not be better.
Either because we are stubborn or determined, we will let you choose, we wanted to make our vision reality.
IWR: This festival is two days of eclectic artistic performances,
30 artists from Israel and Palestine, who visit Paris for two days.
KA: This festival has been created intuitively and subjectively, and we own up to this subjectivity. It is the result of stories, ambitions, real life situations and dreams from a disillusioned generation, still dreaming despite everything.
This festival is not a contemplative art,
it is the kind of art that becomes an experience, told through the perspective of artists who come with their background and their life in Paris, to meet the Parisian audience.
KA: This festival is an intense two-day experience that leaves nobody indifferent, and we would really like the people who are against the festival by principle, whatever this principle is, to come and see what it is really about.
IWR: The festival is a space of freedom, and that is important, it is financially and politically independent.
It is not a festival to make peace, and we are not asking the artists to love each other and go back to their reality; no.
KA: The festival is not a solution to a conflict lasting for decades.
It never pretended to be one. It will never be.
It is a festival that asks more questions than it brings answers.
IWR: Last confession, a friend of ours told us that our stand was very Camus-like, and that's why this festival was not sadly desperate or stupidly naive.
KA: When we accept this space between hope, despair, war and peace, and other things there are three reactions that Camus considered useful: revolt, freedom, and passion.
IWR: This festival did not change the world,
but the festival itself changed, grew,
and attracted more people.
This festival will become nomadic.
It's a pilgrimage after all.
The pilgrimage will visit different cities: London, New York, Brussels, and others, and always, always, with revolt, freedom, and passion.
Thank you (Applause)
Me and my brother are part of a generation that is deeply frustrated.
Frustrated because, due to the existing systems of production and consumption, climate change is concerning us ever more, chronic diseases like diabetes or obesity are increasing and today, one out of every six children are working in sweatshops.
And all of this in the name of what?
Profit...
We are frustrated because even in spite of the army of people who try actively to change the way that our resources are managed, we are not able to stand up to a minority elite with a suffocating power.
We feel small and powerless, unable to have a real impact...
Frustrated, yes, but we will not let go!
And, fortunately, we have good news - after all we are doing a TED !
We think we might have found a solution: A citizen's movement, based on technological tools, capable of transforming information into power.
A movement able to turn us all into change makers.
We call it CoRe, and it will unleash
the real Consumer Revolution!
We have both studied political studies, meaning, the study of power and its distribution.
And as we try to democratize a power that is ever more concentrated in the hands of a few, we got involved in causes that we believed in.
We participated in political campaigns, human rights campaigns,
we signed a lot of petitions and participated in more demonstrations than we can count... And what was the result of all our efforts?
Scarce, even marginal...
And why?
Because we continue to use the same methods to fight against the concentration of power...
be it manifestations, petitions, letters to political representatives or institutions...
Can we do more?
Are there other ways to go about this?
Yes. But we will need to use another
type of power, a much stronger kind.
Think about it:
as citizens, the most significant power we have is the vote. But it's a rare one, and not a very
effective one... often because of lobbies.
For instance, recently, faced with demands of EU citizens to put in place a 'traffic light' label system - like the one you see here - the Agrifood lobby have amassed 1 billion euros to block it at the EU Parliament.
And, of course, they succeeded!
As consumers, on the other hand, we vote every day, several times a day,
when we decide to buy one product instead of another.
As active consumers we are much more powerful to combat the negative effects of the present production system
like health problems, deforestation, human rights violations and even animal rights violations.
We noticed that to unleash this type of change, we need two things. First, we need to inform the people, and transform them into active consumers, perfectly aware of what they are buying.
And secondly, we need to harvest all of our consumer voices to be able to push producers to adapt to our needs, wishes and real values.
So, point 1: to properly inform consumers.
Presently, how is the situation?
Look at these 2 deodorants.
To see which is the best to our health, let's have a look at the information they give us.
And that's it... And that helps nobody!!
Really, for the kicks,
let's take an ingredient
and lets all try to spell it out
together shall we? As far as I know, this could be a derivative of pork mucus, and we spread it over our skin, everyday, only because the guy in the commercial is sexy... Seriously though, we come from a family with a history of breast cancer, and for me its really important to know if my deodorant contains or not potentially carcinogenic substances. And I can't tell, with this kind of information!
And the worst is that I cannot stop supporting the companies that insist on continuing to put those ingredients in their products.
I, for one, am shocked by the number of bees that die each year in Europe.
30-35% of annual losses!
And it's even worse in the US and China.
But, even despite my indignation, I know I contribute to their killing, everyday, with my purchasing decisions.
If there were a simple, easy, quick way to know what products contribute to the killing of bees, I would never buy them again.
You too, we are sure,
have your own list of needs and concerns when you buy stuff:
Like, you would like to avoid GMOs, palm oil, you're allergic to lactose or gluten...
And, well, for this the labels as we know them are not very clear nor intelligible.
And if things are not clear, we cannot buy in alignment with our own values and priorities.
So - informing the consumer is essential. But it is not enough!
We need to coordinate and become empowered to speak directly to producers.
For instance: when a mother learns that a cancer-fighting association gives a negative rating to a baby oil, it is normal that that mom tries to choose another brand,
even if it costs - say - 20, 30 cents more.
If several informed parents make the same decision, it is also normal that the brand tries to understand why they are loosing so many clients.
And that is where CoRe could help brands understand the true interests and values of their clients,
and the cost of not adapting to their demands.
This is the best recipe for an effective change.
So, a quick question: who amog you has a smartphone ?
Can I have a show of hands?
Here we are!
Almost three quarters of Europeans have one. It is the kinds of tools that CoRe wants to change to 1) easily and swiftly inform consumers so they can become agents of change 2) so they can coordinate and we can give them the power and the means to be heard by manufacturers.
And this is how CoRe is going to put at the heart of the market, not profit, but the real interests and values of consumers.
This is why the first tool that CoRe is developing is a mobile app, able to give to each consumer, in an easy and simple manner, the information he or she wants, and to make them heard by producers...
We invite you all to get to know it, and discover it, participate and co-create, and make possible this essential tool for 21st century shopping.
The cards have been dealt, now we just need to play them well.
It is possible now.
Join us and together let us unleash the real Consumer Revolution!
So probably, like you and the 7 billion of people on Earth, I have two grandfathers, two grandfathers who seemingly have nothing in common.
One is a mason.
The other is a surgeon.
One is communist, the other is more right wing, a member of the Gaullist RPR of his time.
However, even with these differences, they have two things in common which are essential to me.
They are both committed to causes that were important to them, and they are both entrepreneurs.
So, "entrepreneur", what does this mean?
What does "entrepreneur" really mean?
We hear it a lot at the moment.
Literally, "entrepreneur" means "to take in hand".
To me, being an entrepreneur means taking things in hand.
It includes creating companies, but it’s not only that.
Being an entrepreneur is also a question of posture.
Being an entrepreneur also means "taking one's life into one's hands."
And the notion of entrepreneurship, for me, is inseparable from the notion of commitment.
I would even go further.
It’s by being committed that you become an entrepreneur.
So, how did I come to this conclusion?
Through my career path, through my experiences.
And I’d like to share with you two important moments, two important moments I experienced in my path.
I also want to share with you two things that I have learnt and two messages.
So, everything began, when I was two years old.
When I was two, my parents split up, and, as you may have guessed, I grew up in two very different social backgrounds, in two very different family cultures.
And for a long time, I was sort of caught between two stools.
I struggled to find my identity.
To whom did I belonged?
So, I searched a lot, even after my High School Diploma, when I wanted to stop my studies.
Why pursue them when my older brother had stopped?
And then, my mother said something very important to me at that time.
She said to me, "Baby" ... Yes.
(Laughter) "You’re going to work for 40 years of your life, so a few years won’t make much difference," and I found that it made perfect sense.
So, I carried on, did a technical
vocational training course, then a business school.
At that time, when I arrived in Le Havre, in my business school, I discovered a new world. The first year, like many students, I partied a lot.
I had a great social life and quite a high blood alcohol level.
Perhaps one went with the other, I don’t know.
But nevertheless, during these studies, I was still asking myself a question.
"What is the point of all of this?
Where am I, and where am I going?"
And also that great question: "What am I going to do after this?"
"What am I going to do after this?"
And then one day, one day, everything changed.
I remember, it was a Tuesday.
We were in geopolitics class.
We were discovering and learning a little more about the Middle-Eastern conflict.
And then, Loïc, my friend, turned to me and said, "What if we had a look ourselves at what’s going on?”
I look at him.
I ponder the implications of his question.
I take my time in answering.
I look at him and I say,
"Yes, okay. Let’s do it."
So we met up that night.
We put the world to rights while enjoying a nice bottle of rum.
Half way through it, we changed our destination.
(Laughter) We had also done a bit of research and concluded that Iraq was not a very good idea ...
So from that "yes" that I said at that moment, from that "yes", my life changed entirely, and took on a drastically different dimension.
Basically, together with Loïc, we got involved.
We created our first non-profit organization which was a sort of social consultancy company for new projects.
We then embarked on a dozen exciting projects.
There was, for example, the creation of a training centre for solar power in Morocco.
We also worked on an audit of a cereal bank in Burkina Faso.
And, in fact, from this extraordinary experience, I learnt two important things.
The first, would you like to know it?
The first is: how great you feel when you get involved!
How good it feels to get involved in a project that is really yours and you really care about!
This commitment allowed me to meet fascinating people.
I remember, once, we drove 2,000 kilometres in one weekend to chat with a guy in Marseille for only two hours.
We were a bit crazy back then.
I don’t know if I would do it again today.
But we met very interesting people.
We also learnt many things.
This commitment I had during my studies, allowed me to reconcile myself with my personal story.
It allowed me to become more self-confident and I finally understood that I didn’t exist only through where I came from.
I existed also through who I was, through my commitment, and through what I wanted to be and to accomplish.
The second thing I learnt was faith, faith that it’s possible and even important to be able to use our skills in a meaningful way, in a good cause that inspires us.
And I realized that what I was learning at school - project management, finance, business management - that all of these are in fact tools.
They were just tools.
I realized that I had the possibility to decide on their use.
I could decide for what purpose, in which way I wanted to use them.
In reality, it’s up to us to use our skills, our talents, for good causes and in a way that seems right to us.
Ultimately, it’s up to us to adapt the world to suit our dreams, rather than to adapt the dream, our dreams, to suit the world.
And that was very significant at that time.
So, I reached the end of my studies, and I had to make decisions.
Do you remember the decisions you made at the end of your studies?
I had to choose my specialization for the final year.
I wanted to be an entrepreneur.
I had the choice between a Master’s in entrepreneurship and a Master’s in financial auditing.
Naturally, I chose financial auditing.
(Laughter) I thought that it would be the best way to make my last year worthwhile and to learn new things.
The second decision I had to make was, at last, to answer the big question: "After this, what will I do?”
I had to launch myself into the working world.
Do you remember that moment?
It’s not easy.
So, I had to decide, to make a choice.
I had the choice between security ...
I had been offered a management position in a small publishing company.
The salary was comfortable.
I knew where I was going.
I could pay back the loan I had taken out during my studies.
... Or I could choose the unknown and launch myself into the entrepreneurial adventure.
At that moment, I asked myself three questions.
The first one was: "Aymeric, what will give you the most pleasure?
Where will you, let’s say, have the most fun?
What will energize you the most?”
The second question was: "Where will I learn the most?
What will allow me to grow, to acquire new skills?"
And the third question, was the one of my little inner voice.
I asked myself: finally, my intuition, you know, the little inner compass, what does it recommend?
So, after some pondering, I decided to launch myself into the entrepreneurial adventure.
And at that exact moment, at that exact moment, I became the entrepreneur of my life, meaning that "I took my life into my own hands."
So, I pursued entrepreneurship.
I created an incubator for social entrepreneurs called: "Entrepreneurs without borders."
I co-founded La Ruche which is a collaborative workspace for social entrepreneurs in Paris.
Then, I even began to launch a team of instructors, a civic lab.
In 2010, I joined Enactus France to develop the spirit of entrepreneurship and the sense of commitment among young people and to do it by "doing", developing those skills by "doing", that is by allowing young people to set up their own social entrepreneurship project during their studies.
Basically, what we do is replicate real life conditions so that young people become the entrepreneurs of their lives through their commitment.
So, as I’m sure you’ve understood, transmission is important to me.
If I’m speaking here, it’s because I want to transmit a message to you, but not only to you.
In fact, I also got married.
I have a little daughter.
I have a little girl who will grow up too in this diverse environment in which I grew up.
She is lucky to have French grandparents as well as Tunisian grandparents.
She is lucky to grow up with a dual culture: a Christian culture and a Muslim culture.
And such diversity, it's simply magnificent!
Because life is a bit like cooking.
It’s thanks to the diversity of the ingredients that we obtain the taste.
So, the message I want to convey to Elissa - that’s the name of my little girl - when she’ll watch this on YouTube, if YouTube is not obsolete yet when she watches it, the message I want to convey to you, my daughter, and you who are listening to me, is two invitations: the first, is : become entrepreneur of your life, take control of your life.
For this, you must make decisions, make choices, and that takes courage.
So, to help you, there’s a little inner compass, here, it's what we call "intuition."
You need to work out how it works, you need to listen to it.
Personally, the very day I listened to my intuition when I was a student with Loic, my life was transformed.
So, I hope that you will have the courage to make your own decisions, to make your own choices, to launch yourself and, at worst, it works.
The second invitation I’d like to give you is simple ; it is: get involved.
Commit yourself.
Actually, when we read the newspapers, when we watch TV, when we walk down the street, when we review our own personal story, we all have good causes that affect us, that make us angry, outrage us.
And I believe that this very energy of rebellion, of outrage, can be transformed into amazingly creative energy.
Personally, I got involved in a certain way through social entrepreneurship, but there are many other ways, so it’s up to you to find yours, to find the good cause, to find the commitment that will nourish you and will allow you to reveal yourself.
To sum up, the two messages I want to convey to you is: "become entrepreneur of your life" and "get involved."
The world needs you!
Thank you.
(Applause)
According to the High Commissioner for Refugees, the H.C.R., there are 60 million of uprooted people in the world: 20 million of refugees who were forced to flee beyond the borders of their country, and 40 million of displaced people who took refuge inside their own country.
Today, in the world, one out of every 122 persons is either uprooted or refugee.
In Europe, in 2015, 1.2 million people applied for asylum.
That's 600,000 more than last year.
The curve that you can see on this graph is amazing.
Yet, there is no refugee crisis in Europe.
Because a number has more than an absolute value.
We should put it into perspective.
We need to look at the scales, the geographic scale and the historic scale.
But first, let us look at the numbers.
I agree with you: 1.2 million of refugees in Europe, that's a lot.
We already know that the arrivals are not going to decrease over the coming years.
But do you know how many people live in Europe?
508 million.
So last year in Europe, one asylum seeker for every 500 inhabitants came in.
In a visual representation, it looks like this: one red star ... lost in a sea of blue stars.
Even with the arrival of 600,000 people as was the case last year, last year, there was only one asylum seeker out of every 500 [inhabitants], and the year before, one out of every thousand.
Now, let us look at the geographical scale.
Let's try to see what is happening beyond our continent.
I am a geographer. I am involved
with these issues on a daily basis.
I am concerned about borders and migratory movements.
If we examine the statistics in the world, we can see that the reception, the weight of hosting refugees, lies on the shoulders of the poorest countries.
That's right, 86% of the refugees are received in the southern countries.
It is this "arc" of displaced refugees that has been designed by Philippe Rekacewicz.
This arc expands from Indonesia to Tanzania.
Even when war is very close to us, as is the case for Syria, refugees seldom reach us.
Of the 5 million of Syrian refugees, 2.7 are settled in Turkey today, and 1 million in Lebanon.
In Lebanon today, one person out of four is a refugee.
It is as if Europe were receiving 125 million refugees.
We are very, very far from that.
So yes, there is a refugee crisis, but not in Europe.
Europe is very little affected by this crisis.
Yet, Europe has already suffered a few refugee crises in the past.
Between August and December 1921, some 1.5 million Russian refugees fled the Soviet famine and settled all over the world and in Europe.
In 1945, at the end of the second world war, 40 million displaced and refugees were received in Europe.
More recently, from 1975, 3 million boat people who fled from the ex-French colonies of Indochina, were received somewhere in the world, including Europe.
So, yes!
Forced displacements have always existed.
That's not a new phenomenon.
And essentially, history tells us that Europe knew how to receive these people who were fleeing from wars and conflicts.
Today, as in the past, we face a world that experiences numerous crises.
Wars and political instabilities, there are many in the world.
Some are close to us.
This is the case of Syria.
There are other wars in far-off places that are less well known : Yemen, Eritrea, Sudan, Somalia, Ethiopia, Libya and Turkey.
These are the countries in red on this map.
But if, in the past, refugees were able to find a safe haven somewhere in the world, today, doors are closing.
We are erecting walls to stop their arrival, as shown in this map from Elisabeth Vallet.
There were about ten walls at the end of the cold war.
Today, they are seventy, already built or being built.
25,000 miles of borders, today in the world, are bricked up.
Thus, the word "crisis" is not used to describe a phenomenon.
It is mainly used to base policies and actions.
Talking about refugee "crisis" is calling for urgent and exceptional measures.
it is justifying the closure of borders, as the sole tool to manage human mobility.
By increasing border checks, we are forcing the refugees to travel by paths increasingly longer, and increasingly dangerous.
Today, in order to reach Europe, Syrian refugees are forced to transit through the Arctic,
through the Norwegian-Russian border,
or... through West Africa: syrian refugees fly to Mauritania, and cross the Sahara Desert to get to Europe.
These roads are not only longer but they are also more dangerous.
The consequences of the closure of borders are right in front of our eyes.
Two doors down from us, where we go swimming in the summer, in the Mediterranean, thousands of people are dying.
Since 1993, more than 30,000 bodies have already been identified.
And we know for sure, that this number is underestimated.
So, it is a humanitarian crisis.
Physical obstacles to migration are responsible for the increase of deaths on the migratory roads.
In the case of Vietnamese boat people, H.C.R. has implemented a program
for their resettlement.
Vietnamese boat people were able to benefit from these programs and stop taking dangerous roads to get to their new host countries.
These programs save the life of tens of thousands of Vietnamese.
Today, we could implement the same kind of program.
But, instead of creating fleeing roads for Somalian, Eritrean, or Syrian refugees, Europe and the other western countries, are barricading themselves.
That map from Philippe Rekacewicz represents the sanctuarization devices of the Western countries.
They are displayed in red tunes on this map.
By doing so, the states are in breach of their international obligations,
because refusing to receive refugees is violating international law.
So, the crisis is an humanitarian crisis.
But it is also a crisis of migratory policies and a crisis of the Rule of law.
Thank you.
(Applause)
I have no choice.
I'm stuck in this meeting that is useless, but I have no choice, my boss wants me to be there.
I'm stuck in this job that is not for me.
But I have no choice!
I have to pay the rent!
I'm stuck in this relationship that no longer makes sense.
But I have no choice ...
I have to protect the children.
I can see that the planet is deteriorating, but I have no choice!
I need to travel for my job.
Besides, I don't have the means to buy organic products.
I have no choice!
If you're like me, we feel quite helpless every time we say that, don't we?
So, to shake this feeling off, I invite you to explore the hypothesis of choice, formulated by Will Schutz.
It is the assumption that we do make choices, even when we feel like we're not making any ... and see what happens.
Let's consider some examples.
Who among you chose
their job, their career?
Hey, there's a few.
Great!
My first job was to be a lawyer.
And very quickly, I felt ... trapped in a job that wasn't for me.
I had studied law because my father wanted me to help him in his business.
And I felt stuck because of him.
Using the hypothesis of choice, I realized that, actually, I had chosen a career, to finally get, in my father's eyes, the significance I'd never had.
It is that pay-off I was looking for without realizing it.
My solution - to be a lawyer - had nothing to do with my problem: to be noticed by my father.
The hypothesis of choice helped me understand two things.
First, that I could find other ways to exist in my father's eyes than through my job.
Second, that he had nothing to do with that. I was the only one responsible for my choices.
With that insight, I first stopped blaming him, being a victim.
And then I chose to quit that profession.
I came out of helplessness.
I got my life back together.
I became free and responsible.
Choosing is to select, to orient oneself and to decide based on a preference.
In fact, we choose constantly.
Some studies even say that we make up to 35,000 choices every day.
That's a lot!
And, if we choose, it's because we get a payoff.
We have something to gain from it.
However, we're not always aware that we choose.
And this payoff is also not always conscious either.
So, let's take another example: illness.
As for me, I have experienced ...
I've lived with some serious illnesses.
It fell upon me, you know something that you don't foresee ... and that knocks you down.
I felt a great sense of injustice, of helplessness.
At the moment, I did not question myself.
The situation was difficult enough already, I wasn't going to add more to it.
And then ...
What if I assume that I may have chosen something there? Then, at first, I can tell myself that I haven't chosen to be ill, but that I can choose how I react to being ill.
And right there, I get rid of helplessness.
And my mindset is indeed going to help me cope.
If I push this hypothesis a bit further, telling myself that maybe, for me, being ill could have been an unconscious choice.
Here I imagine you're telling yourselves she's completely crazy!
You might be right, actually.
By making this assumption, afterwards, considering my own story.
I realized that being ill made me get a lot of attention from my relatives.
And for someone who struggles to feel important in the eyes of others, it's rather sizeable.
That's even quite a payoff.
In pursuing my exploration a bit further, I became aware that placing myself in mortal danger had allowed me to feel alive, a test at the core of each cell that I was alive.
I'd had to be sick to feel alive.
As if depriving yourself of a loved one to realize how much you're being loved.
It's completely crazy when you think about it.
Totally absurd.
And yet in my own story, it makes a lot of sense.
I don't have to be sick to feel alive.
This insight led me to choose to connect to life directly, rather than through choices that are detrimental to me.
Now I choose to do real things, where I feel fully alive.
Such as being here today, in front of you!
(Applause) The hypothesis of choice has also changed my relationships.
Indeed, if I turn the projector of choice onto the other person, then what happens?
Well, then I have in front of me a person who's capable, a person who chooses because they get a payoff, conscious or unconscious.
And that, I cannot judge.
Even though in my own logic I don't understand it.
Choice deeply changes the way I look at others.
It helps me rid myself of judgment.
And to build tolerant relationships.
Choice has become the compass of my life.
It's what helps me find meaning, orient my action, involve myself.
So, instead of saying: "I have no choice," what if we would say: "I have a choice!"
What if we could choose, much more than we imagine.
What if we had a choice for our job, our relationships, a choice for our actions for the planet?
To what extent do we choose to choose in our lives?
Thank you.
(Applause)
I am the gamifier!
Where does 'gamifier' come from?
It comes from 'gamification' or 'ludification'.
It means using the tool of 'game design' in different domains, to maybe help to communicate messages better, for example, in communication, in marketing, teaching, training, etc.
But, I almost want to say that there's a more profound gamification, which is maybe the gamification of today's society.
I can even say to you that in France, despite a certain culture, which lasted a very long time, we're currently 'germanising' ourselves, because our Germanic cousins are big fans of playing games.
For a very long time, they've been pro-games, whilst in France, people often had doubts.
It is itself a gamification of life.
Incidentally, me, I think that I made myself a gamifier -- just like that, boom! --
since I was very young, I'll say since I was six because I cannot remember before that -- and perhaps because in France people tell you: "Listen, games are great for learning different things, but school starts when you're six; so if you want to learn, you go to school; the rest, games, are just for having fun, with your parents, your friends, your cousins, etc." Me, at six years old, I actually had a very strict father who only cared about education and good colleges, and everything else was totally unimportant.
So obviously games, sports, was all put to one side.
And when I returned from a friend's house, obviously all I wanted to do was to carry on with the game we'd played.
So I began making games I'd seen at friends' houses and then to modify them.
So, I started doing DIY and gaining certain skills in that area.
I don't really want to go over the prototypes from back then except for one, which really impressed my friends.
I made a pinball machine out of cardboard with rubber bands, nails, anything I could salvage.
I was lucky because my dad worked in a print works, so I salvaged lots of paper and cardboard to make it with.
And this pinball machine was a big hit with my friends, and they came to my house to play with it.
Then, a bit later, some years on, I discover, I discover the game of all games: role-playing.
'Role' play not 'droll' play!
Maybe you know Dungeons and Dragons.
Who here knows it?
Raise your hands, please.

Ah really? We'll say, maybe, 30 percent.
Very good. Who has played
a role-playing game, table-based of course like Dungeons and Dragons?
A little bit less, but still, not bad!
Role-play, for example
like Dungeons and Dragons, is today often considered as the father of all games, never mind the format: video games, board games, all table-based games, choose-your-own-adventure books, the 'escape games' which are plentiful in Paris, as well as in the rest of the world.
We can find elements of Dungeons and Dragons in them, for example: the XP, experience points, life points, ranks, etc.
We find them everywhere in every kind of game.
It strongly influenced the look of today's games.
Role-play games have brought a lot, for personal development, for example.
When I started playing role-play, I immediately wanted to master it.
I wanted to be God, to be the supreme arbitrator.
I also wanted to be the host because a game master, is also a host.
It is him who will do everything to ensure that his players -- generally, four, five, six players -- return the next Saturday and want to keep coming back.
It's placing a good cliffhanger at the end of a part, at the point where the 'big boss' is about to strike the main character, and then stop it by saying: "OK, that was cool!
The pizzas were good.
If you want to know the rest come back next week."
Then, obviously, after 'mastering' and 'hosting', very quickly we also want to 'create'.
Role-play has this power, which grows very quickly, from the literary aspects, and also the math and the logic, the rules of the game, to make you want to create your own scenarios, make the adventures come alive, re-use elements you've seen elsewhere, often on TV, at the time, or even now actually, and reproduce them on a Saturday evening, we did it Saturday, but it can be anytime, and to reproduce them around the table with your players.
That was what drove me, and I'm not the only one, firstly, to consult long books which were written in English at the time.
Therefore, through that, I improved my English skills.
It became my best subject at high school and in my final exams.
Incidentally, I did a degree in English.
I started to translate; then I started to write, and then I got really interested in math, because of the history of probability.
Even with dice, it isn't really chance.
And of course, probability allows you to regulate chance.
So, I started to develop certain skills, naturally, without noticing it, which were useful in other domains.
Today, you know, we're post 'Revenge of the Geeks'.
Incidentally, Gary Gygax, the creator of Dungeons and Dragons -- one of the creators of Dungeons and Dragons, the one who pushed it the most anyway -- is considered by some as the grandfather of geeks. And so,
I began using role-play in other ways.
As a manager, I started putting parameters in place for my teams to know where everybody was up to etc., that's an example.
And then, because I had a strict father, I didn't do too much sport as a child, even though I really wanted to -- I started fencing, and then, I started to teach it, knowing that sport is a game.
It has rules and aims: in short, this is the definition of game.
We started to open a club in a Parisian suburb.
And like every club and society, you need to attract people to it.
You need to keep the members you have and always attract more people to keep the club alive.
So, with the kids, it was easy.
I began distilling the playful parts, the game design aspects.
I started to say to them: "You know role-play games, video games etc.?
And if, for example, we take these famous experience points, these life points, powers, etc.?"
And in fact with the kids, to liven up the bouts, we put a system in place which meant that when they had bouts, they felt like they were in a type of video game or in a role-play game.
There were also narrative elements.
I pushed them to do things a bit theatrically.
For example, they each had three life points, instead of scoring points.
So when they were hit for the first time, they could continue to fight but, injured, they had to hold one knee, to show their handicap.
If they were hit a second time, they continued to fight whilst holding their ankle, even more incapacitating!
And then, if they were hit a third time, the opponent approached with theatrical gestures
then, with a speech and all that, dealt the final blow, and he earned experience points, and the loser did too.
And with these experience points, they could buy powers, for example, fighting with two weapons.
There was the vampire weapon, which meant any time, he said: "Stop! I'm using
my vampire weapon and if I touch my opponent I take a life from him and that rewards me with a life point," etc.
The kids were crazy over it.
They asked to play it all the time.
We also created another game: Corsairs against pirates, which was two fencing strips basically next to each other, which each represented a boat, pirates one side, corsairs on the other, and the group on each side fought each other, limited by the space which represented a sea full of sharks.
If they touched it, they "fell in" and were eliminated, if they haven't already been hit by an opponent.
So all that, that enabled us to gamify the game.
Sport is a game, and there, I gamified the game.
And this, this has already been done, in certain games, for example, to change a game that everyone knows, the game of chess, which is nice and quite fun.
Someone put some rules in place which let you completely change the rules and make the game crazy;
it's called nightmare chess.
That is also an element of gamifying a game.
It's also been done with ping-pong for example, well in fact it's been done with any number of things.
By the way, thanks to our two young colleagues who made a reference,
which enabled me to create a type of combat sport with laser swords, because recently, due to new technologies, polycarbonate blades, we can really use laser swords as fighting weapons.
So you can really block an opponent's attack.
That is the same: creating this sport it was like a kind of game design.
Little by little, through fencing, with my contacts, etc. I started working professionally with games.
People would ask: "Look you do training, you teach fencing.
Can't you go to, say, the University of Paris VIII, into Information and Communication Sciences, and teach a class on games, get the students to create a game?"
Obviously, I said: "Sure, no problem".
So I worked on that, and after Paris VIII, it was other prestigious universities.
Rather than going towards video games, I arrived and said to them: 'No, you're not going to make a video game, you'll make a board game, or a role play game, or a choose-your-own-adventure book, or, recently they're everywhere, create an escape game, although on a smaller scale.
So, this type of game, which we often call 'table top' or 'tangible games', above all let us highlight certain features of society, in other words, to come together around a table.
This happened naturally, if you remember, with the Wii console.
We all gathered in front of the same thing.
It was still a video game.
For a long time, we thought that video games would kill off board games.
In fact, a few years ago, just over ten years, the Wii console: we all gathered in front of a screen, the same support, and all of a sudden, we started playing together, like the old days, in fact, like the old days! People said:
"We used to do this, before."
Yes, with board games.
For several years now, board games have become huge.
They're huge in France, as well as globally.
A few years ago, there was about 50 or so board games released in France.
Today, more than 1000 board games are being released in France.
And on a global scale, its the same: it has skyrocketed.
Now, there is a big French company, who only make gamer's games, and role-playing games, etc. who are the global market leaders.
I'm telling you, French board game designers, otherwise called 'party-games', are becoming globally known designers.
Indeed, it has become their profession.
Some of them make a living just from board games.
And when they go wherever, to Essen in Germany, to Indianapolis in the US, Tokyo, etc., they are celebrities and they sign autographs over two, three, four days.
So, there's been a real change.
I've spoken about the 'hobby' aspects but, in the work environment, there's been big developments in games.
People constantly want more.
We used to say playtime's over!
To learn, at the age of six, now, you go to school.
But we've realised for a while now -- and I've fought for this for a long time -- that play is not just for having fun: it's taking pleasure in learning, in teaching, in training, etc. More and more, I'm consulted by businesses or by training boards who ask me which elements of games they could use to, for example, make a company's employees interested in a new product which will be released
in six months.
What can we do? Could we make a game?
Yes, no problem!
Take team building, we see it in the escape games -- you use a game, not necessarily an escape game, you could work on a board game or create a board game to resolve conflicts between teams that are consistently losing money.
We did that in a really big French company.
Setting up a board game which enabled exchanges between these different teams, helped the employees to really recognize their communication issues.
You couldn't miss it!
So, you can see that actually, in a natural way, games let you resolve a lot of things.
By the bye, obviously, we can see this a bit everywhere, particularly when on transport.
Nearly everyone is playing, thanks to the smartphone, which we all carry, and which has led a lot of people towards gaming.
So, games are involved in every aspect of society, and we increasingly find it in businesses.
And all of this has resulted in a lot of good things.
And games, I don't know, but maybe they're a way to stay young.
Thank you.
(Applause)
In 2011, I had a rather unpleasant experience, on the eve of Valentine's day, I found myself in the hospital.
And the diagnosis was rather serious for me; a panic attack.
I thought I was dying, but no, it was a panic attack, following a digital burn out.
I was spending so much time online, so connected, discussing with other people that I finally cracked up.
Since I am a writer, I said to myself I need to stop for six months, and I will try to keep my distance and reflect.
I switched off. I picked up my old habits; for instance, reading books.
When you're connected, well me, I saw so much to the extent that I was unable to read books.
I started them, never finished them.
I suddenly, found time to read.
I swiftly thought of a book which I bought 2 or 3 years ago, which I hadn't read so, I said to myself, I am sure that there's an answer in this book.
I remembered that it was about the stories of writing, invented over the centuries.
Unable to find this book.
I searched everywhere.
Time passed, then I invited Narvik to the house, a renowned French blogger, a specialist in media studies, to find out what was changing in the media world, in general. Narvik arrived at my house, went to slept in a hut which we have in the garden,
and the following morning, he came for breakfast with a white book, same cover as the one which I was looking for.
He had spent the night reading.
And he told me that the author, Clarisse Arendt-Smith, wrote a theory in which mankind had successively created three writings: the first, is the writing of languages in 3,600 in Babylon the second, in 620 BC, the arithmetic writing; the third, is quite recent, tt is Alan Turing's, in the 30s, who discovered how to code and program computers.
Narvik, who read the full text over the night, told me, "It's extraordinary! When we add writing to our human possibilities, it broadens his field of consciousness, we spread what we see.
That's what I was trying to explain: being connected enables us to see the world differently, it broadens our field of consciousness in a direction, but at the same time, when we practice only one digital writing, we forget the other writings and lose certain fields of view.
My aim was not to lose any but to try to widen it.
In the morning, when Narvik told me that, I was truly thrilled.
In fact, I felt a profound happiness because he had found the book which I had been looking for; moreover, the contents of this book would enable me to progress on my way, on my quest.
That's serendipity, when it occurs in our life.
There's no point in making a great discovery, like penicillin; a little discovery like that is enough to delight us.
In order to define serendipity, it is usually said to be looking for something which you can't find, or looking for something we want but in an unexpected manner.
A little like what happened to me.
Serendipity has two levels, an unexpected event in our lives, which in a way provides us with an answer, which will make us progress.
These two criteria mean that serendipity gives us considerable pleasure.
The psychologist Isabelle Filliozat says that we are happy on two condition: the first is feeling connected to others; in a group which isn't necessarily large we feel connected, and we are not alone.
The second is to progress on as self-given quest.
Serendipity depends on a moment of connection - with Narvik, with friends -
and two: the content of the book helps me progress on my quest.
When serendipity occurs, it generally, fulfills these two dimensions, thus it gives us pleasure.
When we know this, we say to ourselves, "Well, I will wait for serendipity to fall on me."
I believe that if we begin to unravel serendipity, we'll start getting ideas to make it occur more often in our lives.
There is a dimension which is that of you connecting with others.
In order to do that, one has to come out of oneself, to move.
It is possible in the physical world, and in the digital world on the social networks.
The only important criterion is to listen to others.
If we don't want to hear what's happening on the network, be it physical or not, it's always the same.
So, one must be attentive.
The third very important criterion is that everyone on the network must be able to express, even the smallest voices.
A very tiny voice could be saying something significant which will awaken something in us.
It is the three freedoms: the liberty of movement, the freedom of listening, and the freedom of expression.
We haven't progressed much; we are already quite free in our Western countries.
In order to develop serendipity you need to be even to be freer.
I'll try to show you how we are all capable of becoming much freer and quite simply.
For instance, when you create a link on a social network, on the imaginary social network map, which interconnects all of us, we add connections just like that.
And the more we add the connections, the more the map becomes complex.
You imagine a Michelin map:
many roads, and we are constantly adding new ones.
This map represents a territory. It is the society.
The more complicated the map becomes, the more complicated society becomes, in fact.
An interaction which occurs at one place on the map will be able to spread further, on the map.
We have an enormous power: when we create links, we complicate the world.
put yourselves in the polices' shoes with their cameras, their warning signs.
New roads are constantly being constructed everywhere.
How do you control what happens on it?
If they place a camera, everyone will take the nearby road; they will be unable to control.
If the map and the territory become continuously complex, the people who should be controlling what's going on in this territory, face increasing trouble.
In 1977, the cyberneticist, Valentin Turchin, demonstrated a mathematical theorem which explained that in a system, the element of supervision, the control of the system should be as complex as the most complex part of the system.
The police require more methods, more cameras.
The controlling force can't have as many methods as the entire network; it is already lost: the organization which controls cannot control.
A new theorem appears: the more I create links, the more I complicate it; the more I complicate, the freer I am.
It's not winning in advance.
At the moment, in all the democratic countries, all the governments are enacting laws to limit our possibilities of interconnecting with one another.
In France, you've all heard of Hadopi.
Today, we're discussing laws under which, before publishing on the Internet, an authority should have validated validated the content.
Before publishing any nonsense on Facebook, someone should validate it.
Billions of us post on Facebook; billion policemen would be required to verify everything, it's impossible.
As in all stories there are two opposing camps.
On one hand, citizens who are naturally for complexity, even if they don't notice that it leads to freedom.
On the other hand, people who control who want to reduce this complexity.
Their obsession is to control.
Today, we are in a state of crisis, we need serendipity in order to interconnect.
So, it's very good, we are very powerful. You should remember that we could all connect, unite. the more we unite, the better it would be; but beware, watch out for burn-out.
It is in doing this that I exploded.
So, beware of burn-out, however, continue to unite.
(Applause)
(In spoken verse) From time to time, Would you mind Taking me away from it all, just ... Going to the sea, just ... Letting it lick our feet, just ... Pretending to forget,
Feeling every grain of sand touch our palms and soles Feeling each piece of algae caress our ankles Feeling the whole sky in our hair
Blowing.
From time to time, Would you mind Surprising me at a street corner Forgetting I asked you, saying I'm astonished, Pleasantly surprised, And after a start I jump into your arms
And after looking deep into your eyes indiscreetly to find something, I steal a kiss from you to put in my pocket and keep for when you're gone And because I'd feel alone with all these people around.
Then I'll take it slowly in the palm of my hand And slowly put it on my cheek, there.
See? Can you feel how soft it is? Can you feel it?
From time to time, Would you mind Carrying me on your back, Whisking me away lightly, far from the earth Where everything is so beautiful, Like the traces of your back, like the curves of your back, Melody of my senses, you can see how I think And my feet are so heavy and my verses are so fleeting My "if's" and my syllables grind me and plow me I leave ink footprints on the sidewalk.
So just for once, Could you carry me?
From time to time, Would you mind letting me caress you With the tip of my pen, With my fingertips? I'll redraw your face The way one sketches a landscape.
I'll do it on a misty day to hide my emotions a little And my "what-about-me's" My "I's," my games, Just for you, just for the two of us.
You know, It's so easy.
I just have one last request
I won't keep you much longer I just wanted to ask you If from time to time you wouldn't mind
Saying "You and me,"
Like in the movies saying, "We," that's all. Saying, "You send me,"
saying, "You shake me," saying, "You intoxicate me," saying "You inspire me," Saying "you" again and again at the top of your lungs because deep in my head you're overflowing. Saying, "Your kisses burn me, carry me," Saying, "I like you," And more, yes.
From time to time, Would you mind taking me away from it all, you know, just ... (End spoken verse) (Singing) Going to the sea Letting it lick our feet, just ... Pretending to forget For between you and me The one I prefer is you. (End singing)
(Speaking) It's with those lines that I won The French Slam Championship in 2005.
It's true!
(Applause) Thank you.
You probably weren't expecting a slam champion to look like this, right?
So what is "slam"?
It's an open stage where anyone in the audience can express themselves.
You have three minutes to do whatever you want.
No props, music or set decoration -
just words, voice, body.
A field of free expression, where rappers, poets, storytellers, singers or simply word lovers can meet, share. It's rather similar to what we're doing here today, although TEDx is not a slam scene. It isn't! You can't come onstage
after me, sorry!
Well, except for the people hidden backstage, waiting for their turn.
I've always been attracted to the stage, since childhood.
I'd sing all the time and imagine doing super-dramas in costume for my parents.
I thought only other people could make a living out of it.
It was a childhood dream.
Today, I'm a singer-songwriter and performer. That's my job.
Discovering slam at 17 was a catalyst.
That's when I realized how I really wanted to climb onstage, I also realized I wanted to write to be ... heard.
Suddenly everything became possible!
And when, at 20, I left everything to make a record, I wasn't afraid at all, that much was clear.
Today, I refer to that time as the most spontaneous summer of my life.
I released my first album in 2009, then a second one in 2015.
Between the two releases, the world of music changed a lot.
I self-produced the second album, "Une."
The songs were ready, and I didn't want to wait for a record company to decide whether to produce it.
I ended up being an entrepreneur, a ship captain.
Within that period of movement, of transition, I had to learn a new trade -- in fact, many trades:
producer, head of marketing, project manager, community manager, caught in a whirlwind of emails, of logistics, a flurry of goals and mandatory codes that you have to follow when you want to make a record. Gradually, I lost control, forgetting that, hidden under the multiple hats, I was an artist, first and foremost. (Singing) All around,
thoughts dancing back and forth All around, thoughts dancing back and forth I put them I put them on I put them on my boat I put them I put them on I put them onto my boat My paper boat And I let them sail away (End singing) (Applause) My record was released.
I managed to find help, partners to accompany me, I received a lot of praise but … something was wrong.
I felt disappointment, frustration and even guilt.
I felt I had somehow failed when, at my level, it was quite the opposite.
How did I get there?
I compared myself.
I constantly compared my project to other people's.
I felt they managed better than me; I was fooled by all the images of success that you see on social networks, on the Internet. In fact, many people must have thought the same about me when visiting my Facebook page, always full of good news.
We only highlight the positive.
We almost never talk about our trials.
And suddenly, we feel we are the only one facing difficulties. But of course that's not true.
We all face them.
We might be better off talking about them more often, right?
Me, I never did enough. Though I worked from morning to night seven days a week - never enough.
I spent my time on the phone or on my computer.
I wasn't spending any time writing. For me, the captain, it was a terrible inner storm.
And a downpour.
I was - am - so proud of this album. I loved every bit of it!
And despite that, I saw my glass as half empty.
I focused on what remained to be filled, rather than on the road already traveled.
I'd get up in the morning with this question looping in my head: What's the point?
It was time to sound the alarm and respond to it.
At one point, I just couldn't enjoy my success anymore, even though my childhood dream was right there, before very my eyes.
I released 2 CD’s, I won prizes. I sang at major festivals in beautiful venues like the Olympia, took part in many wonderful projects and above all, I make a living out of my art.
How lucky I am!
It should be absolute bliss!
But at one point, I forgot who I was and why I was doing all those things. But the important thing is to realize it, right?
It's normal to doubt.
It's not a straight road.
It's hectic. It's a journey.
Today, I want to look at my glass, see it as half full, and love this half, find it beautiful.
I want to continue to write, cultivate my singularity and stop comparing myself to others, because that's what paralyzes me.
Most of all, I don't want to lose sight of that one reason so fundamental, that it's the answer every time I ask, "What's the point?" -
because I love what I do more than anything else.
Because I love looking for the right words, listening to how they sound.
Because I love sharing them onstage with my voice, my hands, my face and my bare feet!
Because it is vital for me and I can't imagine doing anything else with my life.
That's why I make music, not to achieve this vision of success that the world wants to impose on us.
I have succeeded.
And it's icing on the cake if, within my words, people recognize themselves. (Singing) When silence screams It becomes deafening Tiny sounds Become a giant's cries Our words are compasses, our guides on the ocean Words as continent That's what we'll keep When the clouds speed by and we can't touch them On the tender island blue impossible to land Our words are three-masted ships sailing in these clouds Our words like sailboats That's what we'll keep. And when the sky weeps, darkening with sobs So the sounds, the colors, get caught in the scrolls Our words at arm's length
are our weapons, our torches Our words as flags That's what we'll keep. When the doors are closed and we're left outside Knocking helplessly with our hands, our bodies, Our words will remain there, etched into the decor Our words like treasure That’s what we'll keep. When my lips are sealed and I don't know what to say When I don't know what to do but cry, even though I want to smile My words softly slide to avoid the worst My words like sighs That's what I'll keep. When we'd like to keep every memory, every name To remember everything, every feeling Words are our struggles, Words are ... emotion Our words like songs That's what we'll keep. 
(Applause) Thank you.
Thank you.
That's it, that's all I want to keep, this little taste of being onstage, this need to convey with my voice, sharing words that inspire.
It's kind of what we've done together this afternoon. That's what matters to me. And I'm sure that you, too, know the answer to your "What's the point?" -
that one idea stronger than any other, that will always be there to guide us when we lose our way.
Mine, the work of 20 years, my dream since I was a little girl, I don't want to forget it anymore or all of these victories that belong only to me, and to my path full of twists and turns.
As long as they remain, I will be able to go on, despite the doubts and obstacles, the rough sea. Perseverance and passion are my allies.
So let's raise our half-full glasses and rejoice that so much room remains to keep on filling them.
To us!
(Applause)
Good evening.
Have you ever asked yourself with what will we be able to replace oil?
It's a fundamental question.
It's a fundamental question because, as you know and we know, we are in a critical transition period
that is called today "the energy transition."
This transition has accelerated at an incredible rate, particularly in 2015, with COP 21 that led to the Paris Agreement in December 2015.
The main idea of this energy transition is that oil, fossil fuels are a problem for the environment,
and we need to "de-carbonize" our economies,
and "de-carbonize" our energies.
We need to reduce our dependence on oil in order to generate less greenhouse gases,
and this is the condition of the fight against global warming.
Then, what can we use to replace these technologies that use oil?
We use what you're all familiar with: green technology
which includes solar panels, wind turbines, electric cars ...
They also include digital technology
such as mobile phones, tablets, and computers,
since we need to be digital to make these green technologies more efficient.
This is what we call "energy efficiency."
These technologies also require raw materials -
not oil, but other raw materials.
And these raw materials are so important, so essential, that the industrialists who use them, the scientists and also the heads of state are already calling some
of them "the next oil".
What are we talking about?
Nobody knows.
Yet, our 19th century ancestors knew very well the importance of coal.
In the 20th century, we knew very well that oil was a necessary component of the energy mix.
But, in the 21st century, we don't necessarily know that a greener world relies on this new oil,
that new energy balances rely on this new oil that we call "rare metals."
In Nature, there are main abundant metals.
Everyone knows them.
We're talking about iron, zinc, copper and aluminium.
But, there is much more in the Earth's crust.
In deposits, naturally mixed with these abundant metals, we also find minor metals.
We call them "rare" because their proportion in the Earth's crust is infinitely less than the main metals.
Sometimes, it's thousands of times less.
But we know how to extract them and separate them from main metals.
And for some 40 years, we have known how to use them for their amazing electromagnetic, electronic, catalytic, optical properties and more. They are components of all the green technologies.
These metals are needed to make most of wind turbines, as well as solar panels and electric cars, and to create the digital Leviathan, this whole digital world that makes these green technologies more efficient.
These metals are about 30.
If I were to name some of them, it would sound like poetry: samarium, gadolinium, lutetium, cobalt, neodymium, tungsten, tantalum.
The one I like is called
"promethium." I like that word.
We barely use this element,
but I like promethium because, when it was discovered in the 1940s, it was named by a chemist's wife who said that, with this element, it is as if fire has been stolen from the gods,
like Prometheus, the Titan who entered Olympus and stole fire from the gods to give it back to mankind.
So we called this element "promethium" because, although we don't know it, it has given us Promethean powers.
Thanks to it, all green technologies work.
And thanks to it and these 30 rare metals, all digital technologies work.
As I'm talking to you, we all have rare metals on us.
You have them in your phone, in your headphones. I have them in my earpiece. You might go home in an electric car which uses rare metals. We couldn't spend one day on Earth, not even one hour, without using these rare metals in one way or another.
So, I'm a journalist and I asked myself, "Where are we getting these metals?
These raw materials that will replace oil, at what cost to man and to the environment are we going to extract them and secure their supplies?"
Over several years, I've journeyed around the world several times, in a dozen of countries, to try to retrace the history of these new raw materials which are replacing oil as a result of the energy transition.
What I discovered has taught me a lesson about the energy transition
because I thought this transition was greener, more sober, and more responsible,
but when we look at it in terms of these minor rare metals, actually, we can see another aspect, maybe darker, of this green transition.
It's 2016 and I'm in China, and more specifically, in Jiangxi province.
The province is in southern China, near Hong Kong.
Firstly, it's a magnificent province.
It's the China we'd like to see more often, the green China with endless hills and sugar loaf mountains, and a bountiful Nature,
but Jiangxi province isn't just that.
It's also one of the main mining areas for certain rare metals, specifically rare metals that we call "rare earths"
which are a sub-category of rare metals.
So, Jiangxi province is one of the first rare earth mining areas on the planet.
You have to venture further into this region, go off the beaten track, if you want to see how these metals are mined.
Then, you are immediately shocked to see hills that are vertically cut in half to extract the metals.
You are face to face with black market mafias.
And above all, you start to understand the environmental impacts of this mining as we have to mine them despite being in tiny amounts.
Imagine the efforts needed to extract a kilo of these metals. We have to dig up
tens of thousands of stones,
and separate these metals from abundant metals.
We have to purify them using chemical products,
and, in China, things don't go as well as we'd like in terms of environment.
Those waters are discharged into the rivers.
Nothing grows there anymore.
People working in this field call these metals a "poison."
Actually, the environmental cost is extremely high.
Around the same time, a few years earlier, I was in another rare earth mining area in China, in Inner Mongolia, 700 km northwest of Beijing.
It's the biggest mining area.
It's Dante's hell there.
There are toxic lakes where is discarded all the waste containing chemical products and heavy metals
that comes from refining these metals.
We talk to people working in this industry and residents who live in villages named "cancer villages;" because there is an abnormally high cancer death rate in these villages.
According to villagers, the link with the industry is clear: they eat, drink, breathe the toxic waste from the rare metal mines and the release of heavy metal that comes from refining them.
A Chinese expert said to me, "China has sacrificed its environment to provide the rest of the world with these rare metals."
This really shocked me because I didn't understand.
I can see clearly two paradoxes that I would like to share with you.
The first paradox is that green energies, so-called "clean", are based on mining metals that are not clean, but dirty.
Renewable energies cannot exist without mining raw materials that are not renewable.
What I'm telling you about China, applies to a lot of countries where all these rare metals are mined:
cobalt in Congo, various metals in Kazakhstan.
I was also in Latin America.
It's now very difficult to open a mine there because local populations fight against mining projects because of how dirty and environmentally problematic they are.
So, I asked myself, "How come I have never realized that earlier?
How come I have only just discovered this story, these secrets of green technologies, although this industry has existed for decades?"
Around the same time, I was in the United States.
More specifically, I was in the Las Vegas area, at the border between California and Nevada.
In the 90s, there was a mine there.
It was called "The Mountain Pass."
And this mine was the first rare earths mine, one type of the Earth's rare metals.
The problem is that, in the 90s, it started to pose serious environmental issues.
It posed so many environmental problems that the mining company, called Molycorp, found itself in a lot of difficulties, and US administration further complicated things because environmental regulations were strict.
Finally, it realized that it couldn't continue mining rare earths and decided to close the mine.
In the 90s, there was another leader in rare metals: it was France.
In La Rochelle, there was a factory called Rhône-Poulenc.
It wasn't just the sponsor of the TV show "Ushuaïa" with Nicolas Hulot, it was also a chemical company that purified 50 % of the planet's rare earths.
At that time, Rhône-Poulenc faced the same problems as Molycorp, not for mining, but for refining.
The issue with the pollution
is that when rare earths are extracted, they're separated from thorium and uranium and that generates radioactivity.
The inhabitants of La Rochelle couldn't take it. There was social unrest.
Costs of purifying these metals started to skyrocket. It wasn't profitable anymore,
so Rhône-Poulenc decided to move its operations to China.
So, at the same time, you have a rare metal mining company and rare metal refining company that both decide, without consulting each other, to either close or to relocate their operations.
Then, who takes over the problem?
The Chinese, because, in those years,
as the Chinese would say, "Mao didn't go so well. The agricultural revolution wasn't as successful as expected. So, we are focusing on industry.
We have plenty of rare earth deposits and rare metal deposits in general, we can provide you copious amounts of inexpensive rare earths.
We'll have to sacrifice our environment, but it doesn't matter.
What's important to us, is economic development."
That is how we got rid of rare earths.
In doing so, we didn't just relocate our jobs and factories.
We relocated the pollution.
We relocated the pollution associated with these raw materials, this new oil needed for green technologies.
We've left other countries with the dirty work of mining and purifying these metals, so that we can buy them pure, clean, integrate them into green technologies and praise ourselves for our eco-friendly transition. To put it another way, the world has become roughly divided
between those who are dirty, and those who pretend to be clean.
So... After all of that, am I credible?
I wonder if I am credible since our electronic consomption, our consumption of green technologies is soaring,
exponentially.
We live in a world where everyone want more and more electronic devices, more and more green energies. The Chinese want to live like the French. They want to take photos in front of the Eiffel Tower, and live like Europeans, like Westerners.
Lifestyles are converging between developed and developing countries and this is going to trigger an explosion in consumer demand for these rare metals.
A report published in 2013 said that by 2035, we're going to need twice the amount of rare earths, four times more tantalum, nine times more scandium, 24 times more cobalt, 180 times more lithium
etc., etc., etc. It's exponential.
A French expert from the CNRS ended up asking himself if we could calculate the quantity of metals that our new lifestyles require.
He made a calculation that left me totally speechless.
He noticed that, given our consumption of technologies of all types, not just green and digital, and considering our future needs for the next 30 years, humanity is going to consume more metals in 30 years than all the metals that have ever been mined in the 70,000 years of existence of mankind.
It means that the generation of the next 25 or 30 years will consume more than the 2 500 generations that came before them.
We're going to need more metals,
so we're discussing opening mines everywhere.
Oceans are full of metals,
and space too.
Americans are beginning to take interest in it.
So, we are expanding the mining sector to supply both abundant and rare metals to meet our new energy and digital needs.
I'd like to highlight another paradox of this energy transition: all that in the name of "conservation,"
which then raises the issue of shortage.
We're already compiling lists of shortages showing that, at this rate of mining, we won't have such and such metal any more within such and such horizon.
We're at the dawn of a renaissance.
We are in the midst of a new technological renaissance.
This word fills everyone with enthusiasm,
even me, I'd like to believe it.
But what happens if you're in a renaissance and there aren't enough raw materials for it?
What would have happened in 1492 if Christopher Columbus, because of lack of wood, hadn't found his two boats moored in an Andalusian port?
So what can be done?
First, I think we need to reflect upon Einstein's words.
Einstein gave us a wonderful phrase, saying:
"We cannot solve our problems with the same thinking we used when we created them."
Yet we're trying to solve a problem with the same thinking that created it.
We think of this transition in a purely technological way, but we don't think of it in a more cultural or personal way.
Our problem is that we want to make technological leaps without a shift in consciousness.
We want to make technological progress without thinking about human progress.
One way of applying this maxim, might be to look at what we can concretely do to rationalize matter,
such as, for example, recycling all rare metals.
We currently recycle less than 1% of rare metals because it is too expensive.
We know how to do it, but we don't want to do it.
We could replace some metals with less energy-consuming one.
We should eco-design all the technologies to make them easier to recycle afterwards.
We should fight against the programmed obsolescence of products which is a scandal that drives us to consume more.
In Lille-France, there is a company called Vitamine T.
It generates a turnover of 60 million euros, has 3,500 employees, and recycles 40,000 tonnes of electronic waste.
Another company, Envie Nord, retrieve and put back on the market 9,000 household appliances a year.
These are very concrete examples of progress that can be made without necessarily needing to question our growth models.
But, we must rationalize the material and bear in mind what energy suppliers say beautifully, "The best energy is the one we don't use."
Finally, I would like to tell you about a conversation I had with an expert.
He shared with me this maxim full of hope and common sense.
He said, "You know, at the end of the day, our problem is not about rare material,
our only problem is a lack of brainpower."
Thank you.
Good evening.
I'm going to tell you a story.
This story begins four years ago in London.
It's 2010 and we are in the middle of the financial crisis. I am in my second year of business school and we are in the middle of the worst financial crisis of all times.
At least that's what the media and the specialists say.
But still everything seems to continue like before, nothing seems to change.
This means, the teaching stays the same.
They say to us, "The aim of an enterprise is to maximize the value of the shareholders in a short time."
And so the dream of young people is still to enter the same enterprises that are the reason for this financial crisis.
As a result, I say to myself, "Oh boy, there's something wrong there."
And I tell myself I don't feel like contributing to this.
I don't feel like helping a system that doesn't function to be more and more efficient.
I don't feel like helping a system, which causes poverty and insecurity while creating rich people, to be more and more efficient.
I didn't do all these studies to contribute to this.
So I looked differently at the problem and I told myself: "OK, which could be my dream job?"
And also, "Among all the criteria that one can imagine, I want this job to make sense.
This means that when I get up in the morning, I know to what I contribute, I know for what reason I work myself off.
The second criterion is to be effective, efficient, to feel I make a difference, to feel I can make things happen, that this goes the right way.
And the third criterion is to be passionate about what I do, and so passionate that every morning I go playing, having fun, and I don't go working.
And maybe this reasoning, these pursuits, they appeal to you.
In any case, I'm there today to encourage you to continue these pursuits, if you have them, and to tell you that it's possible.
Creating one's dream job is possible.
Creating one's dream job is possible. Well, I had the chance to meet professor Yunus, Nobel Peace Prize winner, inventor of the micro-credit, of the social business concept. And reading his books after meeting him has broadened my horizon somewhat.
I discovered the social entrepreneurship in the broader sense, which means that an enterprise can aim at optimizing the profits and not at maximizing them and that its aim is to solve the social and/or ecological problems that are neither covered by the State nor by enterprises or by associations.
And I found that brilliant because that allowed to combine the efficiency of enterprises with the social benefit of associations.
Well, the concept is awesome and my friend Jonas and I, we said, "That's cool, but what does that look like on a local scale?"
So we stroke out with our backpacks, and we traveled the world.
We had the chance to live with exceptional people.
I lived three months in the basement of this guy, Antonio Meloto, on the Philippines.
Antonio Melotto has founded Gawad Kalinga.
When he was about 40 years old, he was a senior in a big enterprise and he couldn't stand seeing 30 millions Filipinos in extreme poverty anymore, 30 millions out of 100 millions!
Whereas he lived very well.
He asked himself what he could do.
He immersed himself in slums to understand extreme poverty.
And then he initiated some experiments.
He helped 50 families to leave the slum, to build a durable house with vivid colours to help them find their dignity and their pride.
He built one village like that, then two, then three, then ten.
And in ten years he had built 2,000 for 1 million people.
After that, in India, I met the founders of Aravind Eye Care. the most successful eye clinic in the world.
There is a large number of Indians who suffer from cataract.
It's inside the eye and if you don't treat it, you go blind progressively.
Apparently this operation is expensive, it's 200 dollars.
But this hospital has found a technical innovation to reduce the price from 200 dollars to five dollars.
And above all, they have invented a system so that the most deprived don't need to pay.
It's the richer people who pay for the others, as a result, two-thirds of the patients benefit from free treatment and the others pay the costs complementary.
This hybrid economic model has allowed to give back the eyesight to 32 million people in 36 years, and the hospital has never made any losses.
Closer to us, in the North, André Dupon, who we see there on the screen, helps people with Vitamine T to reintegrate.
Vitamine T is a social integration enterprise working with economic activity.
Concretely, this helps people shattered by life to find the way to work again little by little and to find a long-lasting work.
Vitamine T is specialized in the recycling of-- (Laughter) electrical goods, and as a result this has a triple impact: economic, social, and environmental.
In 35 years, this has allowed 30, 000 people to reintegrate in society.
For me, all these examples show one thing: That the impossible is temporary.
Every time, there are people who said to themselves, "We can't go on like this.
I will launch an initiative."
The whole world made fun of them and they made it work!
This shows the impossible is temporary.
Now, what I discovered is these people, who I call entrepreneur of change, these people who have an idea and who implement it, weren't extraordinary people. They were normal people with an extraordinary determination.
And I discovered that they had four very interesting characteristics. and the most important thing is that all these features are trainable.
This means every one of us is capable of learning these features and become an entrepreneur of change.
These four features are: first, the ability to imagine a more sustainable world, to transform the problems into opportunities.
The second is the determination to make things happen, to change things.
That's the ability to say to oneself, "I deny the inevitability and I try to act in my own modest way."
The third is the potential of leadership. The ability to transform one's ideas into actions by getting others to join and realize it.
And finally, the ability to communicate one's enthusiasm to create a movement on a big scale, a movement of great size.
And again, these features are learnable.
We aren't born as an entrepreneur of change, we become one.
You will say to me, "That's all great, but these people are old, they have a lot of experience, what can you do when you're young?"
Well, this is bad excuse, sorry.
I've seen many young people all over the world who start a business, more and more, because it has never been easier to build a business or an association.
To give a first example, MakeSens is a community of 18,000 volunteers which, in four years, has found 750 resolutions for social entrepreneurs in 100 cities of the world, thanks to new technologies.
A second example, Fabien Courteille, a French who quit his studies at the time of his caesura at business school to go to the Philippines.
He realized that on the Philippines, there are only toys and teddies imported from China with plenty of chemical products.
There is no local production on the Philippines.
And he said to himself, "I will start the first social enterprise there to employ people at the base of the pyramid to create employment.
He sterted with 350 euros, and two years afterwards, he had sold 35,000 toys and had taken on 25 employees.
And nobody had believed in him when he had gone.
You will tell me, "But that's marginal, that's all small, that doesn't affect the big enterprises, that doesn't change the system."
Well, not yet, but it's happening.
The big groups are evolving.
They are inspired by this approach of the entrepreneurs of change to reinvent themselves internally.
I will give you three quick examples: Schneider Electric which is developing low-cost solar solutions to bring electrification in rural areas for the most deprived all around the world.
Danone is supporting small producers to live on their production, on their local breeding - this is an example in Senega -
and then they're developing yogurts enriched with vitamins and nutriments in Senegal or even in Bangladesh.
And Renault, closer to us, helps people to have access to sustainable transport, helps people in great poverty to have access to a vehicle or get their vehicle repaired for a reduced price to allow everyone access to mobility and to find work again.
You will tell me, "It's communication, we know, etc."
But in this case, it's really not about communication because these initiatives are carried out at the highest level of the enterprise by the top management concerning innovation and strategy and they are an engine for internal reinvention.
They are initiatives carried by social entrepreneurs who have the same characteristics I told you about before.
Well, I saw all this and I found it fascinating.
I felt like participating in this movement but I didn't know how.
And one day, I allowed myself to go on an extraordinary adventure, on a trip.
In India, I went to meet with entrepreneurs who have transformed India accompanied by 450 other young people during 15 days.
So I went to meet people who have changed the life of 1 up to 40 million people.
This lasted 15 days and I was deeply moved by this experience and I felt like starting my own journey (Laughter) since I was in fact inspired by this initiative in India, trying to copy and adapt it in France.
It's called Ticket For Change, changing one's life to change the lives of the others.
It means helping young people to reveal their potential, young and older people, so that they unveil their talent and in consequence act for the society, act to change the society through entrepreneurship.
Well, in concreto, it's a good concept, but indeed, for the first year, we got 50 young people from different social backgrounds and we took them to go on a 12-day trip around France to visit six cities: Paris, Marseille, somewhere near Valence, Lyon, Strasbourg, two days in Lille, and back to Paris.
And then we invented a super innovative educational concept with three coaches in leadership and in transformation.
An educational concept in "U" to help transform the people who don't have an idea how to change the society but who have the determination to do it.
We invented an educational concept to transform them from dreamers into actors.
This concept consists of three stages: The first one is a stage of inspiration, the meeting of 40 pioneers, people who have reconciled social impact and economic efficiency, the meeting of a healthy France, a France that dares.
We went on field trips to see the impact of their solutions.
The second stage, the valley of the U, is a stage of inspiration to help the young people to identify their talents, passions, their engines, their yearnings, so that one can better help them transform their dreams and their indignation in specific actions, which is the third stage, the stage of acting, in which there were workshops to help them transform their dreams into specific projects.
Today, there are 15 started projects and we accompany them on a long-term basis.
The aim is to create a new generation of entrepreneurs of change in our country.
This is a first edition, and we are preparing other ones to follow in the future.
Now, this dream that I had, it's been one year and a half, by now it has completely overwhelmed me.
I absolutely hadn't imagined to experience what I've experienced.
It took me less than one year to meet the president and three ministers, to raise 600,000 euros when I thought myself absolutely incapable of it.
And subsequently, I have lowered the unemployment rate in France because I've created my job instead of searching one.
(Laughter) But above all, what this means is that today I've got the impression that my fate is in my own hands and I think this is the most important thing.
If this rings a bell with you, I encourage you to continue on this way and then very humbly, I propose ten advices to help you take action.
Very humbly because it's what I've seen around the world and what I've experienced.
The first thing is explore, leave set paths, take moments of breathing, take years of caesura if you can, go and see the world, discover what it actually is.
And then multiply different experiences to see in which situations you are most comfortable and to see what you are most passionate about.
The second thing is don't put your ideas aside.
Maintain your ideas, they are the most important thing you have.
Ask yourself what is most important for you in your life.
Write it down, take a notebook, write down your ideas, your dreams.
And then return there every six months.
This is the most important thing because your ideas will help you to become the person you strive to be.
Change your attitude, become an entrepreneur of change in your attitude.
This means that every time you see a problem, stop pointing your finger at someone or searching for a culprit.
Try to ask yourself, what you, within your own range, what you can do.
Change your attitude as well if you have a choice in your life, take the more bold.
Follow your intuition, stop following the dogmas.
Become an entrepreneur of your own life.
Make decisions that you agree with, about which you have the intuition that they agree with you.
The fourth advice is try to identify the problem that outrages you the most on earth, the problem that touches you the most, the thing that is inside you and that makes you able to fight for years afterwards because you are passionate about that problem.
Don't fall in love with the solution but with the problem.
Don't hesitate to dream big.
I had help from some mentors who helped me to dream ten times bigger than I thought I could.
It's because of them that I did something eight times bigger than I thought I could.
Dream big, this helps you to get the best talents in your group.
Therefore I now get to the group: Establish a dream team, Establish a group with people that inspire you, with people you admire, who you will love to work with and with people who you will want to spend time with.
Because you will live through very strong moments, you will experience ups and downs, but also very difficult moments.
It's your new family in your entrepreneurial adventure.
So choose your people, they are the most important thing for success.
Specify, take a first step, act.
It's for nothing to have a dream if you don't do anything about it.
Take a first step today, lead a first action, prototype, try, gather feedback about your prototype, don't make a business plan during ten months, try things immediately close to your users.
Work very hard - it's an obviousness - but work very hard.
To be an entrepreneur is very difficult, so if you want to be an entrepreneur with double or triple impact, an entrepreneur who has an economic, social and environmental impact, it's two or three times more difficult, more complex.
This multiplies the problems.
So work, you need to work even harder.
And above all, be extremely demanding when it comes to quality.
About a project with general interest, one can't be laxer about the quality. On the contrary, I think.
Be super determined.
When they tell you that it's not possible that this won't work, it's obvious where this will leave you, it's a good sign. It means that you have an idea that disturbs, that you have an innovative idea and that you are ambitious.
So continue. Continue.
And in moments of doubt, because there will be some as well, there were very hard moments when I didn't know if I should go on, I reminded myself of an advice that I got on the Philippines from a social entrepreneur.
This advice is very simple. It's this, "Never give up, never give up, never give up, never dream of giving up."
For the moment, that worked.
And finally, "do it with joy".
Do it with joy because it's still awesome to have found the job we're passionate about and I'm still super happy to have a job that will make me happy for the following 40 years at the least instead of making me feel bored at work.
And this needs to be known and to be spread to inspire others to try and do the same thing.
The conclusion is very simple, it's, "Believe in your dreams."
Believe in your dreams, make them a lot oversized, work super hard, gather people around you.
Because no dream is impossible, no dream is impossible.
My dream is that every teenager in France and around the world can live that experience and ask himself what he wants to do with his life and then meet some inspiring models to find his right calling.
This is my dream.
Today we are developing this initiative that's called "Ticket for Change" so that every teenager can have access.
We are going online, we are starting an MOOC: "Become an entrepreneur of change", and the challenge, indeed, is that everyone can live that experience.
So believe in your dreams because if you believe in them, they become true.
I wish you all the best for you journey.
(Applause)
(Singing "Bear the Burden In the Heat of the Day") I'm gonna bear my burden In the heat of the day I'm gonna bear Lord Bear with the world, yes I'm gonna bear Lord Bear the burden in the heat of the day I'm gonna bear Lord Bear with the world, yes I'm gonna bear Lord Bear the burden in the heat of the day (Applause) The song that I've interpreted is a work song directly borrowed from the musical tradition of the work songs, negro spirituals, and gospel sang on the tobacco, cotton, and indigo plantations by Afro-American slaves.
Traditionally, songs have always accompanied people's lives, life's most important stages, but also daily life.
And not only the life of the Afro-American slaves.
In France too, one sang on the agricultural lands.
Laborers sang in the plants at the beginning of the 20th century.
One sang in the street, where sheet music was sold around which people gathered, without even knowing each other, to sing.
But to go back to these Afro-American slaves to whom I would like to pay a tribute today, we could ask ourselves, why their owners who didn't recognize not one of the most basic rights, why, when they denied them the right to talk in their own language, to be able to read, or write, why did they let them sing?
Actually, widely before neuroscience, slave owners had observed very fairly that the slaves were more resilient to the extremely hard life and work conditions, to the punishments, and deprivations, when they sang.
They had understood ahead of time, that singing and music were extraordinary boosters for health.
Today, research in neuroscience, related to music and singing for more then 10 years, proves that songs and music are powerful nerve stimulators.
And at the same time, sources of innovation,
In particular, in healthcare, because today, we use songs for Alzheimer sufferers to help them find again some working memory and emotional memory.
We use singing also for the sick suffering from aphasia, to help them get back
the use of speech, and it works.
Singing, source of innovation also in firms, where we are committed to bring it back today.
Source of innovation in management, collaboration, technology.
But how does it work?
What we know, thanks to our understanding of the brain today, is that singing together, from the first minutes, activates the secretion of oxytocin which is the hormone for social cohesion; activates also dopamine, the hormone for motivation and motor function; activates also the endorphins, the hormones for calming down and for our well-being.
But that's not everything.
Singing activates also the reward circuits and overrides the amygdala, which deals mainly with fear.
As fear is put aside, trust can take place.
Singing and music create a favorable context for creativity.
If I am not scared, If I have faith, then I can dare try, dare sing, but also dare generate ideas or try.
And then, it is not the neuroscience but my own experience and belief.
I think that gospel, through its generated emotions, adds a little supplement of soul and emotion that could maybe stimulate even more the desire and creativity.
Like this, traditional singing joins innovative singing.
And if singing has always formed the pattern of spiritual life, social life and life of hard work, it can as well today, maybe, form the pattern of the moment that we are sharing.
Please stand up.
