Tonight, I'd like to start by sending a big "thank you" to our ancestors, the Enlightenment philosophers.
Men are born free and equal in rights. I'm a big fan of that.
I love being free.
Free to think, say, and do whatever I want.
And by the way, tonight, I will not refrain from speaking my mind
whether you like it or not.
To be honest, there's something I don't appreciate with this Declaration of Human Rights, namely, we all took it for granted and that it only applies to white men.
Fortunately, people of all colors, as well as women demanded and were granted the same fundamental rights,
and I imagine everyone here agrees it was a great idea.
Well, tonight, I came here with a proposal: to grant these same fundamental liberties to children.
And I will tell you why I founded a school where children can do whatever they want with their day.
The adventure starts in a town with 70,000 inhabitants called Framingham, in Massachusetts.
For almost 50 years, there's been a school there where children could do whatever they want, without any time limit.
It is called Sudbury Valley School
and it was founded by Daniel and Hannah Greenberg, ex-university physics and biochemistry professors at Columbia. Daniel and Hannah worried about
the education of their children.
For them, going to school,
even at Columbia, was not an option because their parents found it to be anti-intellectual.
So they explored other alternatives that were flourishing in the 60s, but they didn't find what they were looking for.
So they simply invented their own school, based on a super simple rule with revolutionary implications, which stated children are people, too;
they're not the property of their parents, they're not the students of a teacher.
They are just like you and me, independent members of a democratic society.
Thus, their three children grew up in a world where nothing was expected of them, and where they were truly free to make their own choices on how they want to live their life and what they want to learn.
As a result, their eldest became a professional photographer and musician, and made a good living.
Five years later though, he decided to make a little challenge and opened a restaurant in New York City.
Their second child became a psychotherapist.
And the third one, after living and surviving in the forest for one year, became a farmer.
To get a better idea on how far they went with granting children full freedom in this school, I'd like to share the story of a boy who attended this institution in the 80s. His name is Dan.
Dan fell in love with fishing at the age of 10.
He would take his fishing rod to this pond everyday. I took a picture of this pond when I visited the school a few weeks ago.
He'd go fishing everyday even in winter, regardless of the weather.
And yet, there were so many other things he could do,
sports, arts, music, research, play games.
There were endless possibilities,
but he wasn't interested.
He was obsessed with fishing. And he did this for five years until he was 15 years old.
One could therefore legitimately worry about the future of a person who lived such an unconventional childhood.
You may find the end of this story rather surprising.
With 16, he falls in love with computers.
And that's a period when all his obsession about fishing shifted to the IT world with the same intensity.
At age 17, with a few of his friends, he opens a store to sell computer hardware, and he becomes rather successful, so he's already earning a living.
He then uses this money to go to the university, as a way for him to explore his passions all the way through.
And while studying in college, he's hired as an expert by Honeywell, one of the major computer companies.
At that point, there wasn't much room left for anxiety. He was on track for a beautiful career in his domain.
I heard about Dan's story three years ago
when I started working in a high school as a Math and Physics teacher.
During that time, pretty much like everyone else, I developed my doubts about the effectiveness of our education system, but let's be honest, Dan's story was way beyond anything I could imagine.
This boy didn't study a single subject in his life, and he still became a thriving contributor to our society.
This case necessarily raises some questions.
And in my case, it did more than posing questions, it completely turned my world upside down.
I don't know about you, but when I hear something so crazy, I absolutely need to know more about it.
So I set myself on a quest to better understand this alternative to the system.
And quite rapidly, I discovered that there are in fact more than 40 schools everywhere in the world that adopted this approach.
So I went to visit some of these schools, in Holland, Belgium, Germany, and more recently, Sudbury Valley School itself in the US, where I met with very smart and mature children,
and school founders who were realistic, pragmatic, sensible, who clearly knew what they were doing. I even thought some of them to be quite stern.
For these people, of course, experiments on their kids or other
people's kids are out of the question.
It is a serious educational approach, with a proven concept, which aims for human excellence.
At some point, it became obvious for me I wanted to create such a school as well,
and the good news is that it's done.
It's the first big one of them in France.
It's called Ecole Dynamique, opened about two months ago in Paris, with around 20 members of all ages, from three to 16 who do whatever they want with their lives, and spend their days together in this place.
Here is a picture of my colleagues, the co-founders of this school. They're also free to use their time however they want to help this school thrive.
So on top of being a liberated school, our organization is also liberated from traditional structures and hierarchies.
Now, besides Dan's story, I'd like to tell you another one. It's about Laura Poitras.
I love this story!
Laura also went to Sudbury Valley School from age 4 to 18.
She didn't open a single school textbook in her life.
She mostly practiced photography. And she learned how to read at age 13.
After graduation, she did a career as director of documentary films. And not just any director.
Laura is a true international superhero.
She created Citizen Four, where she films Edward Snowden in the midst of revealing the NSA's controversial schemes to the whole world.
And for this piece of work, she received the Oscar for best documentary in 2014.
I'd like to insist on the fact that she learned how to read at age 13.
This means that the age at which one starts reading and taking interest in intellectual endeavors doesn't necessarily have much to do with the future success of this person.
In fact, and I may surprise some of you, it's the opposite trend that has been observed at Sudbury Valley School.
I recently met some of the co-founders, who still work there as staff members, and they have the very rare experience of observing for 47 years young people who live without any constraints. Some of them learn how to read rather late, at age 10, 11, 12, or even 13, like Laura, and they realized that these people have a tendency to progress more towards intellectual and academic careers,
which obviously questions some well-established beliefs about education.
Of course, all the people who attended this kind of school learned how to read and write.
Otherwise, they would have closed down
a while ago already. Who in his right mind would enroll his children in a school where they wouldn't be sure they would learn how to read and write?
People often ask me the question: how do these schools teach reading?
And my answer is, I insist, we abstain from teaching how to read.
And it works just as well as abstaining from teaching your mother tongue.
Did you ever see a parent trying to teach his mother tongue to his children,
who would make them repeat sentences over and over, and who would explain all the rules of grammar and conjugation?
Of course not, it would seem absurd.
Little children feel the obvious need to learn their language and to always get better at it, and this is why they keep practicing with their relatives, such that they make visible progress day by day.
Well, just like the natural learning of their mother tongue, the natural learning process of reading and writing happens through and infinite amount of interactions with their environment.
Each person has his own method.
No one knows how they do it exactly.
No one could ever be able to dissect such a rapid and complex process.
The result is the same anyway:
they all learn how to read and write.
And now, I'm also going to tell you why we abstain from teaching math.
Yes, math! Everyone is obsessed with math.
There are quite a few observations
that lead to similar conclusions, and I'd like to focus on one of them I found to be particularly compelling.
It's the story of a study that was done in the 30s by an American superintendent and researcher called Louis-Paul Bénézet.
Bénézet felt that it was too early for primary school children to study Math.
and he thought that if we didn't teach them math, they could still attend secondary school without any problem.
So, in order to test this crazy hypothesis, he asked a few primary schools from poorer neighborhoods to simply abandon math as a school subject.
Six long years later, he measures the results hoping to prove his hypothesis. And ... surprise!
The results were far beyond his expectations.
Children from poorer neighborhoods, with only a single year of training, significantly outperformed their peers from richer neighborhoods who had six years of training.
So when I'm asked how children will learn math at Ecole Dynamique, I tell them that we leave them alone, and that it is proven by science.
In fact, they encounter quite a few math problems in their daily ordinary lives, and we trust that they will solve them by themselves or ask for help when in need.
Graduates from this type of schools therefore master fundamental skills to be effective in society,
and beyond this, well, they learn how to know themselves better and explore their own interests, apply themselves intensely, and persevere in their efforts to eventually reach excellence in their domain.
In fact, we aren't dealing here with the experiments of some mad scientist, or a tireless hippie aiming at
freeing kids for the sake of freedom, no.
It is a serious educational approach which aims for excellence.
In fact, in the end, to give you the key to what is going on here, I'll tell you now, it is that we give them the power.
All the power, to overcome the greatest challenge of a human life, that of becoming fully independent and responsible for your own life, and not only starting at age 18, but at any age.
In the end, by abstaining from educating them, we allow them to develop the confidence they need to overcome all challenges in their lives, which include getting a high school degree some day, if they need it,
and which takes, let's say, come on, at most a year of preparation if you take it seriously, as shown by the experience of these thousands of young French people who never went to school and still succeeded on exams.
And for those of you who remain skeptical, I will offer some stats which may end up convincing you.
80% of Sudbury Valley graduates went to college, and they usually got their first choice even when applying to a highly selective university, like Harvard, Berkeley, or Columbia.
And for the remaining 20%, well, they chose a track which doesn't necessarily involve a college experience, like some careers in arts, craftsmanship, or entrepreneurship.

So there are the facts. There is proof.
And there is simply common sense.
Treating children as independent persons is a Copernican revolution indeed.
We can't continue considering children blank slates adults should develop so that they can live their own lives someday,
except if we want to live in a Dark Age and stop human progress, then it's exactly what we should do.
But if, like myself, you dream of a day when humanity will become infinitely more genius than it is today, well, we don't have a choice!
Our world views need to evolve.
And tonight, I will make a political proposal which would honor this Copernican revolution.
Yup, I'm going to make a move
as a citizen of this country.
I move a proposal to change the law on compulsory education which goes back to 1882.
At that time, the 3rd Republic voted this law within a context of building the Republican French Nation, which implied getting rid of local languages and alternative ideologies, to prepare children for the industrial world and for war.
Today, the context has totally changed, and we should adapt to an era of globalization, digitization, and peace.
The problem today is not to submit all children to a standardized educational program for all of them to learn the same thing, but quite the contrary. We should diversify approaches as much as possible to free the potential of a wide variety of individuals.
We should have a law which allows for a diversity of philosophies, methods, and educational content.
We should even allow those who'd rather go back to uniforms and a more strict obedience to a master to go on with that.
And I say this without any irony. Why not?
Any point of view,
from the most traditionalists to the most progressive like Ecole Dynamique,
depends on each person's world view.
If we have the courage to make such a change, we would honor the spirit of the Enlightenment and all these pioneers, who for the past 300 years have fought so hard to push for an evolution of our culture and to free the individual, so that he may think, say, and do whatever he wants with his life.
Tonight, with my love for life, my passion for education, and for culture, I suggest to replace the law of compulsory schooling by a law for freedom of education.
And I will finish with this quote from Victor Hugo, "Nothing is more powerful than an idea whose time has come."
(Applause)
Tonight, in front of you on this stage, we are 4.
In fact, we could have been a hundred, even more. It would have been a mess, we would have been packed, but we could have done it.
But there is one thing that we couldn't have done: having just one of us here.
Because the idea we're presenting here is a collective idea. It's not the property of anyone, it belongs to all the ones who find a resonance, an echo in it.
Tonight, we're bringing you in front of THIS building.
You may have recognized it: the French Parliament, house of the people, it's our house.
And we, the citizens, we don't have its keys.
Yet, it has a huge importance, it controls the government, it votes the laws which rule our lives.
When we walk in front of it, with its double-locked doors, the building contrasts terribly with the global crisis our civilization is going through.
A general crisis: financial, economical, social, environmental.
Hopefully, some alternatives exist, - the world keeps evolving - in a totally accelerated way.
Locks are blowing up, everywhere.
Surrounded by those movements, those accelerations, democracy remains frozen.
We're living in the 21st century, but this institution still works with rules from the 19th.
It's a bit anachronistic, it's especially absurd.
Every five years, we go to vote.
We vote as we can, at the presidential, later at the general election, sometimes, besides, we abstain.
In the end, we always wake up with a hangover.
A hangover because, once we voted to elect our deputies, we don't have anymore control on them.
They decide alone, they often take decisions which run against their own promises.
They concede to the compromises, to the little agreements, they forget us.
Politics became professionals of their own interests.
So we're asking ourselves why do we still vote, since we know that immediately after, and for the 5 next years, we become again simple spectators.
This hangover, you've understood it, comes from a bug.
The bug of the "representative" democracy.
For me, this bug, I really understood it at the time of the European referendum.
This day, the French parliamentarian voted against the text which the French people themselves did refuse.
This day, I understood that we were not in the democracy that I aspired to.
For me, it was a point of no-return.
As for me, this bug, it took awareness of it, progressively,
I work with elected representatives, and I can't accept politics would be reserved to people like me, professionals, technicians, experts.
Obviously, individually, we can have the best intentions, but jointly, we can't continue to have such a concentration of political, economical, and mediatic elites.
For me, the bug, I experienced it as an associative militant.
For 10 years, I noticed that at the National Assembly, the dices are loaded: the little agreements, the cronyism.
That's it, the dices are loaded, and we, citizens, are excluded from the most important debates: Those which rule all parts of our life, form birth to death, and I can't accept it.
(Cheers) This bug in representation, it's been a long time I'm feeling it.
I like politics, I always wanted o commit myself, yet, I never did.
In fact, I never wanted to joined people persuaded to detain the truth, to be right against the other ones, always.
I didn't want to merge at those sterile fights, I was too afraid to become a politics hooligan.
Here are our four testimonies, four among a multitude of others.
At a moment, we all had this brain wave, the brain wave, it is to notice this bug and say to yourself, "This system does not satisfy us."
So now, what do we do?
We won't stay here trying nothing we must not be taken over by the fear of others the inward-looking attitudes, the apathy, the anger, the frustration.
No, we want to try something: we're going to deconstruct, analyze every single bug, egos, pointless partisan quarrels, individual processes which all say one thing: that ends justify any means.
We completely discard this idea.
What matters for us, it's not the destination, it's the journey.
So, we're moving off.
We're going to rebuild the world as we want it to be.
Yes, it's true, we don't want to elect anymore, but we want to vote, more than ever, to decide together, jointly, the rules of the society's game.
So, we group up, around an idea: we're going to hack the National Assembly.
(Cheers) Huge program.
So to make it, we're going to bear to the National Assembly some voluntary citizens, trained and selected at random, who are going to pass, during 5 years the decisions of their voters.
Each one of our voices may be heard, and respected.
Obviously, not everybody will vote at the same time, not on every text, not on every law, but the most important for us, is that this possibility exists, that we can participate, every time a law affects us, dismays us, or captivates us.
So why did we chose the random draw?
To avoid ego wars which ravage the public debate.
Personification of politics is not fate, we can exceed it, because politics is a shared concern.
So obviously, we'll need to get trained, to be comfortable when our deputies will enter at the National Assembly.
And that's why, we are going to offer a civic formation, accessible to everyone, because if we want to enter the game, we need to know the rules.
Ma Voix, you've understood it, isn't a political party.
It doesn't have a chief nor a program, Ma Voix, it's a method co-built by all those who want, including you, maybe, in a horizontal and cooperative manner, thanks to the new tools of collective intelligence.
For the first time, we can do it, technically speaking.
The digital revolution, which allows us to trade our cars, our apartments, our pictures allows us, today, to discuss, to debate, to deliberate, to take better decisions together.
Ma Voix, is an experimentation.
(Cheers) And this experimentation is based on trust, in other words, the exact opposite of the image that our leaders reflect on us continuously.
They bet on mistrust.
For a long time, they have been explaining us that we are too dumb to take care of so serious questions.
It allows them to tell us, "Don't worry, let us do the work."
We let them do, and we're in a funk.
For sure, we're not very clever, but honestly, we couldn't do much worse.
(Cheers) In any case, with Ma Voix, we're going forward, trusting each other, with self-confidence, and confidence in others.
And this trust, puts all of us in front of our responsibility, individually and collectively.
That's what I liked, and what gave me wish to commit for the first time in my life.
What really impresses me in this journey we are able to make it work horizontally, without any hierarchy.
And what is captivating me, is that the word is relieving, is lightening itself.
It's all these citizens, who come to meet us, and tell us, "Here, at least, we're in our place: we can talk, we are heard."
So we set ourselves in motion, we try things, we move forward step by step.
And, if I feel confident despite some doubts that always remain, if I believe in this experiment, it's because it is generous.
(Cheers) Yet, there's not only the yes or the no that matter, the vote, it's the path, the process, the debate, the construction, democracy is all of this.
So in 2017, I'll be 30, and the political life is not quite what I imagined.
Ma Voix won't serve my personal interests, but for the first time, I have the feeling that this experiment will get us inside our home, the French Parliament.
Ma Voix, it's an experiment for every one who wants to participate, from all origins, cultures, with their stories, their professions, their ages.
A voice equals to another one.
We can take part a day, a month, two years, seven years.
Ma Voix, it's the civic engagement, the one which force us getting out of our comfort zone, meeting the man, the woman, unique, singular, in the bars, in the country houses.
Go to meet the ones with who, in theory, you don't share anything.
Yes, I can't wait for that Sunday of June 2017, in the voting booth, for the first time, regarding my children, I will be proud of my vote.
It will be my way to tell them that inevitability does not exist, and you must set off your way even if everything seems blocked.
(Applause) Ma Voix, is this, diverse trajectories, singularities, which mount up along the way, all different, but all united around a single wish: experiment democracy.
Some citizens, simple citizens, like us, like you, at the National Assembly, and why not?
Wikipedia, in 2001, also seemed to be completely crazy.
When the project began, there were only expert who wrote encyclopedias, and all of a sudden, everyone can contribute to write the knowledge, to share it.
The project is 15 now, and we are hundreds of millions of users all around the world.
It concerns all the domains: science, medicine, education, medias, and why not the political world?
Then yes, Ma Voix is an utopia, not because the project is impossible, simply because is not realized yet.
So it's what we are going to do.
Humbly, a stone, a contribution, to the utopia of democracy.
All around the world, movements are created, all answering to the same thirst of democracy.
Germany, Mexico, Argentina, Tunisia, Italy, Spain, Iceland, Greece, Ireland, Canada, French cities and villages, everywhere in the world, initiatives carry the willing of the people to take their place at the decision-making table.
And us, here, are we ready?
(Applause) Thank you.
I found a means to solve the energy problem with concrete!
Yes, concrete!
Not to build dams or install windmills, but concrete to power the grid, make light and heat.
I am going to explain it to you.
Did you know that the cheapest energy today is solar energy?
Thanks to the dramatic drop in solar panel price, if you install now a solar panel in a sunny place, you get a kilowatthour at 2 cents.
It's half the price of classic polluting energies.
In addition to being the cheapest, solar energy is extremely abundant.
The red square in Sahara, roughly one quarter of France, represents the area of solar panels that can power the whole planet with electricity!
So, if solar energy is so cheap and so abundant, why isn't it our main energy source?
Because there is a problem: intermittence.
In the day there is sun, but in the night there is no sun.
This bell curve shows that solar energy comes concentrated, in the middle of the day,
whereas our consumption is rather
constant: this is the white line.
If we want to power the network with a lot of solar energy, it is absolutely necessary to store the excess of energy in the middle of the day, in yellow, to be able to use it in the evening and the night.
Storing energy is not a technological problem, it's an economical problem.
Energy can be stored, in batteries. But energy cannot be stored profitably with batteries.
Batteries, like the lithium ones of your phone, use a chemical reaction.
After each charge-discharge cycle, they wear, they lose some capacity.
They need to be replaced after a few years.
And when you compute the cost of storing energy in batteries, you find that it is very high.
It is estimated to be 10 cents per kilowatthour,
so that solar energy, when stored in batteries, is no more interesting.
It is not profitable: it needs subsidies, it cannot develop.
I am not a chemist, I am a mechanical engineer.
A few years ago, I was working for Total and I went to Detroit Auto Show, and I see a startup willing to replace electric car batteries with "wheels".
Not steering wheels for driving,
flywheels. A flywheel is a disc or cylinder spinning at very high speed to store energy in a form called kinetic energy.
Flywheels have been made of steel.
Recently some have been made of carbon fiber.
The very large advantage of flywheels over batteries is their unlimited life.
Unfortunately for electric cars, flywheels proved to be too heavy.
But I had the conviction that, when weight is not a problem, flywheels have a tremendous potential for storing renewable energies, and I founded my company.
With my team of four, we made flywheels with steel, then with cast iron.
We were in the quest of the graal that everybody is searching now: low cost storage.
But these classical materials are too expensive. We had to find something completely different.
Last year I had an intuition: we had to test concrete.
And I found that concrete is an extraordinary material for energy storage.
Concrete can store energy at a cost ten times lower than classical materials.
And I can tell you that, in an engineer's life, you don't often make such a large progress in so little time.
Of course you will ask: if it's so easy, why did nobody think about it before?
Because concrete is incompatible with flywheels.
Concrete does not resist traction: if you pull on concrete, it breaks.
When a flywheel spins, there is a huge centrifugal force that creates intense traction.
If you make a cylinder out of concrete, it bursts as soon as you spin it.
My solution consists in compressing the concrete with a winding in traction all around so that concrete stays compressed up to the maximum speed.
To keep things simple, we can say that we wrap it like a roast beef.
This "Flywheel for Solar Energy Storage", we called it VOSS.
How does it work?
When there is an excess of solar energy, needing to be stored, we use an electric motor to spin the flywheel faster and faster, and store kinetic energy.
Maximum speed is that of an airplane, slightly less than 1,000 km/h.
This is fast.
But there is no air drag, as we have removed the air - vacuum, so that we can keep energy for hours.
To recover the energy, the system is reversed, that is: the flywheel spins the motor, which produces electricity like an alternator.
Finally, with intuition, a lot of reflexion and some concrete, we have found a means to store energy at a low cost:
The association of concrete flywheels with photovoltaic panels produces a renewable energy, available night and day, at a lower cost than that of polluting energies.
This technology is currently under development.
Our project in the short term is to equip small networks: like Corsica, Guadeloupe, Réunion, African villages... that are currently powered by generating sets, in order to replace their fossil fuel by solar energy.
But our long term project, in 4 to 5 years, is to create large photovoltaic solar plants in highly sunny areas such as deserts, in order to power the global network with an energy that will be clean and cheap: solar energy, profitable without subsidies.
Needless to say, after all these years of research, I am impatient to see our technology reach the energy market, and revolutionize it,
because with such a low cost of storage, renewable energies will at last be able to replace polluting energies.
Thank you.
(Applause)
To talk about theatrical improvisation, I have to improvise a little.
Otherwise, I wouldn't be very credible.
Theatrical improvisation has existed since the dawn of time.
Early humans were already improvising.
Greeks improvised in forums, it was called "maieutics."
Scheherazade improvised every night to save her head and avoid being beheaded by the Sultan and did so during a thousand and one nights.
Then, came - here is the slide with an historical scene, how nice is this! -
the Italian Comedia dell'arte, the peak of theatrical improvisation, which Molière made use of.
Molière used theatrical improvisation to write his texts.
There was a man called Goldoni at the time. He is still named Goldoni, but back then, he was noticed for it. He was writing texts and selling them.
He said, "No, improvisation has to stop, because I do not want to stop selling my texts."
So, it put theatrical improvisation on the sidelines in favor of literature, although in theatrical improvisation, you "read your erasure" ("Lis-tes-ratures") ...
Okay.
(Laughter) For years in Europe, literature prevailed over theatrical improvisation.
Meanwhile, the rest of the world kept doing theatrical improvisation.
In African villages, it was called "koteba."
In Senegal, in Burkina Faso, in a lot of countries, everyone were improvising under the mango tree in order to tell the story of the day or of the week.
They were using percussion, and it was awesome. They had fun.
Then, colonization happened and they said, "No, no! This, is not theater.
Theater is Racine."
So you children, you're going to learn Racine by heart, and just leave your roots under the mango tree."
(Laughter) It was like that!
Then, children started reciting painfully texts they couldn't understand.
We still find in schools, even in Guideloupe, pupils reciting "Phedre"
with no understanding to begin with. and the audience doesn't understand.
They suffer because, on stage, they are not in line. They are slightly unbalanced.
It's a kind of "theatrical Begini."
(Laughter) They're unbalanced, lost, and unhappy. So others stop expressing themselves, thinking, "It's not my language."
So the idea is to improvise and have fun at the same time.
It is true that as far as I can remember in my life, the best nights have never been those spent in front of the TV.
True! This is important

because currently in schools, it is estimated that on average, an European teenager spends nine hours a day in front of a screen.
Between the smartphone, the iPad and the laptop, they spend nine hours a day in front of a screen,
as much time they spend sleeping.
Increasingly! I just heard
about this last week.
So children hardly learn to communicate with each other and to look into each other's eyes.
When they want to laugh, they mock people instead of enjoying each other.
Then, they upload those things on YouTube which is sometimes unbearable, but that makes them laugh. They don't laugh at themselves nor in conviviality. Whereas it's not the case
in improvisation. Who here, has tried theatrical improvisation?
Who has already improvised?
Ah, a lot less here!
Well, everyone has improvised at some point.
When you want to help your little brother to sleep and tell him a story, you improvise.
When a policeman asks you to pull over and you are drunk,
Oops! Hop! you play a character.
"Yeah, I'm doing good!
Absolutely no problem!
I am very familiar with this road, don't worry, officer."
So everyone improvises.
So we have developed a system, a method of improvisation for all, because people scare improvisation in theater for fear of ridicule.
In fact, freedom of speech is ridicule minus shame.
You're a bit ridiculous but you don't care, no shame.
For example, you're afraid of failure.
So here I go. It flops
but I don't say anything.

I suck.
But I'm not ashamed,
I don't care ... That's it!
People don't dare do this, but it's very important.
As a result, they don't dare engage in improvisation which could help them in their couple, since a couple is two people managing to solve issues that would not have existed if they were living alone.
So, it creates problems in your relationship.
You laugh but it's like in schools.
Nowadays, in 25% of couples, the guy walks off after the first child because couples do not negotiate, they do not talk.
It is about learning how to tolerate and how to discuss, and thus, how to improvise.
To say that we're wrong when we're wrong is being normal.
To say we're wrong when we're right is being married.
(Laughter) This is improvisation,
but people don't dare. So, we created a method in which the guy arrives in the morning at the workshop.
He has never done any improvisation in his life.
We always care with him, and that very night, he does a show in front of an audience and he makes everyone laugh.
It works very well because we care, because we use a sentence from Aragon that helps us: "Criticism should only be the pedagogy of enthusiasm."
It means we never make someone uncomfortable but let him express himself in accordance with himself and guide him so that he starts listening to others and starts building with the group.
I say that because as a child,
I was very shy.
"Destiny is what life makes of our desires."
My story is that I was very shy.
I was with the animals.
I wanted to live in the forest.
I wrote a small book of animal stories, and a teacher took my book and tore it.
Really, I was desperate.
I didn't know what to do, I stopped writing at this point.
Maybe that's why I'm doing improv now.
Then, I had another misfortune.
My parents left.
I was 16 years old.
I was in Rennes, an unknown town
where I didn't know anyone, no friends.
I came back home one day
and my girlfriend was with another guy. So I ended up alone in the world.
(Laughter) No, it's not funny.
I ended up alone in the world, really, friendless, rootless and without history.
That's why I named myself Gustave Parking.
Alone in the world and moreover, destitute.
It's not easy for a 17-years-old to live on the street without means. Because it's not obvious when you're already out, to get out of it.
Fortunately, I had attended a few courses in self-expression, in theater, magic tricks, and juggling.
So I went in front of a student cafeteria and started to reach out to others.
I thought, "Even if my people abandon me, the others, all the others, can recognize me provided I can do something that reach out to them and know how to speak to them."
It's the basic idea of theatrical improvisation.
So I did some shows.
I became a scholar in order to have something to bring to others.
I studied linguistics in Rennes.
And it worked.
It worked so well that I played in 75 countries.
I staged 30 plays, organized
six shows, it was a huge success.
This summer I had an article like this in "Charlie," I was super happy. So I'm very proud of myself.
I arrived in Guadeloupe, the top. Guadeloupe, a wonderful place.
(Cheers) Guadeloupe!
The problem is that when you arrive on top, you have to keep climbing, even if to do so, you have to come down to get a stepladder.
Climbing, when you're on top, is to give to others, to those around you.
I discovered that in Quebec, school violence was reduced by 25% using improvisation games in school from a very young age.
School violence was reduced by 25%.
So I asked myself "Where in Guadeloupe are people the most violent and stuck?
The prison!
The prison of Basse-Terre."
It happened that while swimming quietly at Anse Dupuy in Vieux Fort, I met with the prison warden.
"Hi, are you the warden? I'm doing improv.
- Ah, that's a good thing ..."
So we get out
in our swimsuits, half-naked.
We sympathized.
Finally, we did theatrical improvisation with the inmates in the prison, the kingpins, Caribbean monsters, pirates, guys with gold teeth.
I can assure you, it was terrible.
The idea is how to make the toughest and most stuck people, do improvisation easily enough?
I'm going to show you.
There is a method.
It's like that.
First, "mastering the body."
They are not very articulate.
They speak Creole, English, Spanish, Italian, a little French, just a few words because they use crack - yes, they tell us about that.
First, "expressing with the body" like TiMalo did a moment ago.
You tell them, "Yes, you are in a rowboat, then you're in a wheelchair, then you jump with a parachute."
You make them live all kind of physical adventures.
You also tell them, "You escape, he chases you,
and as you invent new stories,
he must try to follow you."
"Here! I'm catching you."
"Yes, I'm coming."
They were happy, they were escaping!
Anyway. They express themselves and they breathe.
When you start expressing yourself physically, you oxygenate your brain, thus you have much more imagination.
Then, you work on the second part: "the acceptance of one's own language."
It's an exercise called "logorrhea"
that starts with just a few words. Then people are asked to speak without thinking, very quickly and without thinking.
For example, "What would you do if you won a billion euros?"
"If I won a billion euros, I would have a swimming pool, pretty girls, helicopters ..." So you speak without thinking.
It's very important because you become immersed in the flow of yourself.
You don't try to be creative or to look like the other, but you're yourself, and you're creative only if you are yourself.
When you want to be the other, you fail because it's not you.
Well, this is an explanation.
So, while they are speaking without thinking, we try to work on emotions which are expressed by postures.
A posture like this reflects strength.
It is also important to say that when you play a character, after some time, you can become this character.
This way, you can play other characters in life, and it helps you to be stronger in difficult situations.
So, when they are like that, doing the logorrhea, we work on emotions, and the strongest emotion is?
Anger. Because, indeed, you are
out of control, out to lunch, you become peerless. (Laughter)
Thus you are spectacular.
We made them play the jail's biggest argument ever.
We warn the guards: "They're all going to yell at each other. It's going to be terrible."
Then, the guys start: "You piss me off, I'm sick of you TiMalo!
Why did you do that?
Where is your mother dirty whore?"
Here they go.
Now, you allow them to start. Why?

Because if you're not able of the worst, you're not able of the best.
Initially, you have to let go of the worse.
Some big guys started, "I'll cut you!"
and I was stopping them, "Very well, very well!"
(Laughter) When they were starting, it was like "Waw, okay! Okay!"
and since you made them act an artificial but real anger, they learned how to control this violence and how to control this anger.
Or else they let go, get mad, until they fail to understand each other.
Here, they control anger, then they can do the same thing: "But TiMalo, it's unbelievable!
Son of your mother, Nyctalope!"
These are not real insults and this way, it's more acceptable.
(Laughter) See, you work on your stuff.
Then even better, you tell them "Do the same but with love
and the same energy."
"TIMalo, you're such a great guy!
Your stuff is brilliant!
Oh, you're so good, I love you, TiMalo!"
That's the same energy.
You got the idea.
Then they work together,
they try to work in groups.
To work in group in theatrical improv, you learn to say?
Right, you learn to say "yes,"
to always say "yes."
"Yes" is peace. "No" is war.
So, they start improvising:
"How are you? Did you go to the butcher the other day?
- Yes, indeed, and I saw
your wife, she was amazing.
We made love in the attic,
it was great! - You did it with my wife?
What a good idea!
I went to your dog and made
meat skewers out of it.
- Oh, very well!
You ate my dog in skewers.
Let's have fun together."
So, you have fun and you create your own show.
In improvisation workshops, you laugh, you have fun, you create your own show,
and it goes very quickly. Then, we do a lot of small exercises which allow people to build stories and learn reintegration.
Outside prison for instance, we worked a lot on sale
because when you're out of jail, it's a bit hard.
There are two jobs for which you're not asked your criminal record: it's salesman ... Yeah ... and artist.
So we taught them how to sell -
"Buy my stuff, it's pretty good," and so on - and we realized that the rules of sale are exactly the same as those of theatrical improvisation.
The focus should be on the story rather than the publicity stunt or the commercial cost.
You say "I ripped him off" but you risk loosing a client.
There was a man named Volkswagen who tried to do that a while ago and they lost clients for life.
So ...
Here is it. Hop!
"Learning how to be serious."
So, you learn how to be serious.
You laugh and then, you learn how to play the characters.
Then comes "Developing
empathy," that's what we did,
"Escaping together to get closer to others," "Opening up to new possibilities," you understand it - it has become an ad.
Then, we went to schools,
high schools. There, we say "let it go," although in prisons, we say "let me go."
In high schools, if you tell him, he forgets, but if he experiences it, he learns.
We worked in several high schools in Guadeloupe on sexist stereotypes.
It means you play the role of the other so that you understand him better.
So the boys played girls, and the girls played boys.
We saw in Guadeloupe's schools kids coming in skirts.
We did things like this. Boys!
Here they say, "No!"
Yes, we did, but they're characters,
they're playing!
So they understand better what others feel.
It works very well for school bullying too.
So this is what we did in schools.
Here, you can see a teacher.
I put a white woman because she can better be spotted on the drawing.
In reality, there are teachers of every colors.
I'm just saying...
Here, she's on her knees before the students. It's very important. When we do it
in businesses, it's the same.
When the boss is playing a carrot and his secretary plays the bunny and says, "I'm going to eat my carrot" in an improvisation, their relationship after that is completely changed, (Laughter) completely changed!
It's the principle of Carnival: we switch roles.
The teacher told me, "Relationships with my pupils has changed completely since I played with them."
It's really important.
"I played with them.
For the pupil, I was no longer some kind of institution to fight but someone he can play with who, in addition, has a teacher's role."
It was very important in their relationship.
So we keep doing it.
Now I'll explain to you what I said about the history of humanity.
The first woman is Lucy.
We all owe "à-Lucy-nos-gènes," it's a well known fact.
I quite like this one ...
Ah, you have to think!
(Laughter) (Applause) At the beginning of mankind, Lucy started to talk, and she started to create society.
The problem is that society created gods in its image and that at some point, there's a degeneration into pig, because with Copernic, men realized they were not the center of the universe.
Then with humanists such as Marx, they realized that man was a wolf to himself, that Capitalism was the exploitation of men by men, and that Communism was the opposite. (Laughter)
Then with Freud, they learned that they were dominated by their unconscious.
With Saussure, a linguist - I worked with one of his disciples - they learned that they were between signifier and signified,
such that when you mean something, people hear something else.
We are no longer ourselves.
Today, the environment shows us we are not the masters of Nature and are going to be crushed by her.
So we are so scared that we increasingly take refuge in technology and in a dream, a dream that has been created by others elsewhere.
Moreover, we consume.
So we are becoming online pigs.
Personally, I would like that the online pig do improv and reach out to others -
here the man goes towards the woman,
whereas in the other he goes alone -
that he become inventive since improvisation enabled us to create,
and create many things: in improvisation, you invent by mixing two extremes.
For instance, you can mix boxing with face cloths. Both boxers are dirty and the one who ends up cleaner looses.
You can create a lot of things, you see.
Fencing with bullfight: you put an electric structure on the bull so that when you touch it, its tail lights up.
This allows you to be inventive,
and develops a creative mind.
So what I had to say to you
was substantial.
I see my allotted time has ended. As in improvisation, repartee is often when everyone has departed.
It's the same principle.
(Applause) What I wanted to say is that in improvisation and in theater in general, everything you keep to yourself is lost in the heart of others, whereas everything you give to others is forever in their heart.
Thank you and good night.
(Applause)
You can hardly imagine the impact that robots will have on your lives in the future.
We've been promised humanoids, we've been promised flying cars, but today, the reality of robotics is pancake-shaped vacuum cleaners; the reality of robotics is this: (Music)
Stop it! Enough!
I'm not going to discredit my subject before talking to you about it.
As you can see, even R2-D2 moves around better than those robots.
There's a marketing concept that says people don't really know what they want until they get it.
It is event truer when talking about robots. It's a new technology. Today, we're in the dark, waiting to see how these little robots are going to enter our homes.
Yes, indeed, they are going
to enter your homes.
For example, the development program of Pepper, that robot there:
4,000 people have one, and it's currently in development.
Jibo, an American robot -
7,500 Jibo units were sold by crowdfunding over the internet.
And then, 1,000 Buddy robots - which you see here - 1,000 Buddy robots. Here, too, it's the result of successful crowdfunding, and they will soon be ready to be cuddled at your home,
just like little Pleo, this fascinating little robot.
What's fascinating about these robots is that you can build a relationship with them, even though they are made of metal, plastic, and electronics, and not of flesh and blood.
This little dinosaur reacts to everything I do.
When I pet him, he grunts, he's happy.
You like that, don't you?
I've been working in robotics for six years now.
I chose to work with a company called Aldebaran,
which was the first company to design humanoid robots.
Why? Because they created a robot
called Nao. You can see it there.
They put kindness and benevolence at the heart of this robot.
Nao exists to make people's lives better, to enrich them, and to make them happier.
They exist to accompany you, to help you out, but not to replace you.
Each developer who is involved in creating software for this robot commits to bringing kindness into the application - not conquering the world, for instance.
And Nao is 23 inches high, so that would be complicated.
(Laughter) Nao is a robot who is curious and a bit teasing, but never patronizing.
He is specially oriented to interact with humans.
If you go back in the history of the companion robot, AIBO is the first one.
AIBO is a little dog, an animal, created by Sony in 1999.
It was a great commercial success right from the start - 5,000 units were sold in 20 minutes.
But it was also very expensive, so it barely found its way into our homes, and remained in the realm of laboratories and universities. It never really reached us.
Today, two factors are improving the situation and making sure that very soon, you will have companion robots.
First, you have technological evolution: it's getting better and better, batteries are lasting longer...
Then, you have the cost of parts. Parts get cheaper and cheaper, so robots are costing less and less.
The good news is that France
is in pole position; we create robots.
I told you about Aldebaran and its two robots. There's also Buddy, that I introduced to you.
Buddy will be here next year, and you'll be able to buy him for between 550 and 1,100 dollars.
That's the price of a computer. It's really affordable.
Now comes my question: Why wouldn't you?
Why wouldn't you adopt a companion robot?
It's a social technology.
I'm going to tell you a story to illustrate my point.
We've designed a robot called Sheldon, the big large white body here.
It's a greeter robot.
Its job is to engage with you, discuss with you and guide you.
During an event at a commercial center, Sheldon met up with Baptiste, the little boy in the photo. They had a great time together.
We gave little hearts to the children, to represent the hearts of robots, to thank them for coming to greet Sheldon and spending time with him.
Baptiste really didn't want to leave Sheldon, so Sheldon told him: "Don't worry - in a few years' time, you'll be able to adopt me. Then you'll have me at home."
A few days later, I received a phone call from Baptiste's mother. She said to me: "Hello, Maxime, I've got a problem. Baptiste left the robot's little heart behind, and he said to me: 'Mom, how will I be able to adopt a robot in a few years if I can't even take care of his heart?'"
It made me understand the bond Baptise had forged with the robot in barely five minutes,
and that it was really important for him.
These companion robots are really meaningful, not because they tell you the time, or retrieve your emails, or can do videoconferencing.
You can do that with a computer. Their meaning comes from providing these applications in a social way, with an extra social layer.
So what do I mean by triggering
our social reflexes?
Essentially, I'm talking about body language.
It's well known that if someone reflects our same body language back to us, we get along better, more easily, with that person.
If a person you don't know gets too close to you, you'll reject them.
Consequently, when a robot adopts the same body language as you, inevitably, communication will take place much more easily.
When a robot uses the same signals as you, you'll understand it.
I'll give you an example.
If the robot says "Yes" like this, you're going to say: "It's nodding its head. That means 'yes'."
If the robot tells you a joke and winks, then you'll think: "It's even got a sense of humor!" But he truth is,
he's been programmed to wink.
And when it waves "Hi" like this, the universal sign for "Hello," you'll understand that the robot is greeting you.
We, human beings, are use these signals to determine how intimate we are going to be with someone.
It's the same thing for a robot.
I'm going to show you how it works with TiKi, the robot on the scene.
Hello TiKi, could you introduce yourself, please?
TiKi: But of course, Maxime.
Hello, everyone.
My name is TiKi, and I'm very happy to be at TEDxClermont today.
Maxime Vallet: Thanks, TiKi!
What a great technological demonstration! (Laughter)
You'll have noticed two things:
I squeezed his hand to activate him, and he waved hello to you. And he triggered in you the desire to go further
in the relationship. You think: "He's going to talk more with the robot. Let's see how far he can get in the interaction."
It's this exact reflex, this beginning of a reflex, that robots can trigger in you, and yet they are machines.
And that is what's different about the IT tools we use today.
And even though, as I explained at the beginning, the technology isn't perfect yet, I believe that the important thing about robots is that they help us to be more human.
Thank you.
(Applause)
We all have a dream that we haven't yet dared to chase.
I'm going to tell you something that I learned thanks to running and that has allowed me to do so many things I'd never before have dared.
I took up running completely by accident.
One morning as I was leaving school, Madame Sarfati, the principal, made her way up to me with a big smile, and by her smile, I knew she wanted something from me. "Madame Buisson, the school's sports association is organizing the parents' cross-country next week.
3 km in the Bois de Vincennes, it's a little, casual race, as you know, it's the - ? - the taking part that counts, thank you, - and then it makes our children so happy!"
When she said that, how could I say no?
(Laughter) I was 32, reasonably in shape, and on the big day, I showed up in my old cotton tracksuit and T-shirt, I said "Hi" to my daughters, and I joined the other parents.
Straight away I knew something wasn't right. The sports gear was a bit too serious, the mums were in very good shape, and the dads were warming up like pros.
So right from the start, I knew the race wouldn't go well.
It wasn't an easy, little 3 km cross-country that had just started; it was a 3 km sprint that had just started, run by crazed parents, encouraged by their hysterical children.
(Laughter) The brutal reality hit me at the 500 meter mark, as the mum I began the race with left me behind and accelerated, and I felt like my lungs would explode, and I'd been smoking for 15 years.
Out of sheer pride, and pride only, I carried on running, and finally, in a deplorable state, crossed the finish line under the worried watch of my two daughters.
(Laughter) And worried is worse than disappointed!
(Laughter) I was running to make them happy, that they would be proud of me, and instead, they were very worried to see me completely ruined after this race.
The results were clear: I was 32, and I was not all that in shape.
At the time, my idea of a mum was that a mum should be very strong, and very tough.
And that day I learned the first life lesson that running would teach me: How could I hope to run for my children if I wasn't fit enough to run? How could I hope to be useful to my children, to raise my children, if I didn't have the strength and the energy to do so?
That's how I took up running.
I decided to train myself.
And to motivate myself to put on my sneakers every Sunday, I made it a date.
I found some running buddies, we ran for an hour or so, and most of all we talked, and told each other our stories.
Running made me feel good. I went out, got my body moving, and strangely, it was my head that breathed more easily!
That year, I met Marie-Ange and Gérard, who were training for their first marathon, an incredible feat of 26.2 miles.
They had a favor they wanted to ask of me: "Would you run with us for a bit of the marathon, from the 13th to the 19th mile?"
As I had done for the school cross-country, I said yes.
And from this extraordinary experience, I would learn two things. The first, is that running for someone else can be incredibly motivating.
You outdo yourself, you know why you run, I was running to help them accomplish something.
In fact, on that day it wasn't 6 miles I ran, but 13, because I didn't dare stop at mile 19 when they were so exhausted, both mentally and physically.
But when you run for someone else, the danger is that you forget yourself, because you adapt to their rhythm, and you don't run at your own pace.
Someone else's pace may be longer or shorter than your own, but in either case, running for too long at a pace that is not your own will exhaust you, will discourage you, or burn you out.
The second thing I learned on this marathon, I learned from Gérard.
We were between mile 15 and 16, on the banks of the Seine, and there were all these people there to encourage the runners because it was very difficult, and then from the sidelines I heard: "Go on Gégé, go on Gégé." So I turned to Gérard and I said, "Hey Gérard, you brought a lot of friends, it's great you came with so many people!"
At which point Gérard turned around, and on the back of his T-shirt I saw two big letters: G.G. (Laughter) Gérard is the first man I met who knew how to ask for help.
Gérard asks for help, because he knows, before beginning the race, that at some point or another things will get difficult.
That's also what being a runner is.
A runner isn't someone who likes to suffer; a runner is simply someone who expects difficulty.
And the longer the race - imagine the length of a lifetime - the more surely you know that at some point, it will be difficult, even painful.
Seeing my friends running inspires me, makes me want to join in.
Very quickly I signed up to some timed races of my own, starting with a 10 km, then a 15, a 20, a half-marathon, etc.
The next step up was a bit high, but one day I took the leap and signed up for the New York Marathon!
November 2nd 2008 I finished my first marathon, just before the election of Barack Obama.
Yes I can!
And this confidence inspired me to go even further.
In 2009 I took up another kind of running: trail running.
Trail running is not simply another kind of running. Trail running is a whole other world!
You run through the countryside, over long distances, with positive and negative gradients.
In other words, there are ups and downs.
It's very physically engaging, and in order to remain well nourished, the trail runner runs with a backpack. That's called autonomous running.
That as well has taught me many things.
The hundreds and thousands of steps that I run with my bag on my back are shocks that propagate through my body. And the best idea is to travel light: to take only what's me, to take only what does me good, in other words, what's useful and precious to me.
Simply put, no-one can prepare this bag for me, I've learned to know myself, I know what nourishes me, what's good for me, my lucky charms, my magic cream for my feet, the photo of my children, of course.
In July 2009, with my bag on my back, I set out on a 4 day mountain run with a group of ultra-trail-runners, and two hours into it, I say to myself that this is crazy, that this isn't going to be possible.
And then, surprisingly, my body gets used to the effort, to the hill, I find my rhythm, the mountain is incredibly beautiful - and then there are the others waiting for me a bit higher up, and I end up at the top as well, and we start the descent.
What a surprise!
Running downhill is much more complicated than running uphill.
I get scared, I tense up instead of letting go, I defy the slope instead of accepting it, my thighs are burning and I think I'm going to stop.
This ultra-runner comes and runs alongside me, looks at me, sees that I'm suffering, and says these magic words to me: "Delphine, at some point, the pain will stop. At some point, you won't hurt anymore."
And that helped me!
That helped me to carry on, and to stay in the race.
Over 7 years I would run hundreds of miles of races.
In my professional life, as in my personal life, in my private life, it gets difficult. There too I run a lot.
I'm working for the father of my children, and it's very fast-paced.
It's too fast, it's not my rhythm.
I'd like a third child, but it's not happening. Projects build up one after the other but I don't understand why.
We run side by side, but not really together.
And running without knowing why is much more complicated than just running.
Even if you have goals you can't be completely comfortable in your run if it has no purpose.
One day, while I was running, my knee gave way. It hurt so much that I had to stop.
It was the first time I'd given up, and giving up is not easy for me.
But my body understood before my head, before my heart perhaps, that this 15 year race was no longer mine, and that it was time for me to make a change.
My family was exhausted, I was exhausted, and we divorced in 5 weeks.
I lost my job in the divorce, and I had two teenagers to look after who had had a very hard year, and who had one very urgent need: for their mum to be OK.
And finally, I discovered I was pregnant.
What was I going to do?
Well, I did as I had done in the mountain: it's not my head that would decide, but my body.
I paid attention to what I felt, and then I knew.
I knew that I'd start everything again,
everything, except not not having this child I had wanted.
So I chose to bring it into the world, and I chose to live.
As I had done for my girls, I knew that to run for him and with him, I would need to be able to run for myself.
But how was I going to do it?
I was beginning a new life, another race, my personal race.
To start this race, I would do exactly as I had done for running, I would use everything running had taught me.
The first thing is that I know that no-one can run this race for me, no-one can carry this bag
for me, it's my race.
I know as well that it's difficult, but that at some point, the pain will stop, and that helps me to carry on.
Of course, after the birth of my son, I didn't run a marathon straight away. I started back with a 10 km, going after small victories that make me feel good, I meet other runners, and when it's not going so well, like Gérard, I've learned to ask for help.
I engage in all my races in the same way, whether it's at work, in my friendships, or in my relationships.
First I sign up, then I train.
It's in the sweat that I dissolve my fears.
To open my horizons I push myself to go out, to go out running of course, but also to get a new job, to go dancing, and to make love as well.
It's by running that we learn to run; not by sitting on the sidelines. And in love it's exactly the same - you have to go out and practice.
Every race I finish puts me back at a new starting line.
Since choosing my own races, I've been happier, and succeeded better.
I live a life that's mine, and I am a better woman, and a better mum to my children as well, because I am well, and because this race that I run called 'Life' has meaning again.
We all have something we dream of doing that we have not yet dared to try.
Perhaps even tonight, you have this dream, this bold desire on your mind.
What I will tell you is this: Sign up first, before you are ready, and then tell someone!
That's the secret: share it out loud.
Say out loud what it is you're going to do, tell it to people you know, and to people you don't know.
I've just signed up for the 2016 Paris Marathon, 7 years since I last ran one, and I'm a bit scared. Will I still be able to do it?
I don't know you, but in telling you, I become a bit more determined to keep my promise, and above all, I'm not alone.
And that feels good.
The first step is always to sign up and to tell someone, so that you're not alone in your dreams.
And every race starts with a first step.
Thank you.
(Applause)
I suggest, if it's OK with you, that we start this conference by replicating part of an American study, and I need all the men here today as test subjects. Do you know another way
to say "test subjects"?
Guinea pig, like the animal.
That's nice, guinea pig.
So, gentlemen guinea pigs, imagine that you're single or that your wife is definitely not jealous, and imagine one of these charming sisters offers to help you revise the positions of the Kamasutra.
So, you have to choose one.
Let me remind you that you're guinea pigs not pigs.
So, please, who would choose the one on the right?
Hands up, please, quick, hands up.
We could maybe put the lights back on.
Yes, not bad, OK.
And now, who would prefer to revise with the one in blue?
A few less.
So, exactly two thirds of you, according to professor Elliot of Rochester University, prefer the young lady in red.
If I showed you this photo, two thirds of you would have also said the young lady in red.
Why?
Well, ladies, know that, naturally, when you wear red, you awaken within us a desire, a strong desire.
25% more desire for men.
And, ladies, know that you know this, maybe subconsciously, but you know.
In a study dealing with dating sites, we looked at the color of the women's clothes on their profile pictures.
Women looking for the love of their lives are five times less likely to be dressed in red than those looking for fun.
Yes, red is the color that creates desire in men.
Know that you will get 25% more tips at a restaurant when you wear red.
Know that men are more likely to stop when you're hitchhiking, if you're in red.
Why?
Well, ladies, know that, when you wear red, you're actually telling men that you're ovulating.
(Laughter) Yes... When our great, great, great grandmother Lucy, was ovulating, her genital parts and labia were red to show her fiancee that it wasn't the time to go hunting mammoths, that he should stick around.
So, red makes you far sexier.
What about men?
Not really.
(Laughter) No, we aren't any sexier in red.
No, no, Miss, we aren't any sexier in red.
However, we are much stronger.
Our heart rate is quicker, our blood pressure is higher, we also blink much more.
Red makes us stronger.
Sports prove this.
In England, three soccer teams wear red: Arsenal, Liverpool, and Manchester.
They won 39 of the 69 last championships since the war.
In Greco-Roman wrestling, since 1896 and the start of the modern Olympics, know that 67% of the fights were won by wrestlers dressed in red.
Same results in Taekwondo.
When you wear red, you're physically stronger, your opponent looks stronger, even the referee, under equal conditions, seems stronger when you wear red.
From a practical point of view, wearing red makes you a leader.
And, if by chance, one of you is later elected president of the United States of America, his communication advisers will suggest that on the day of his investiture, he arrive with his family dressed like this.
It's not at all a coincidence.
Here is a family of leaders.
Here is a family we can trust.
Red has other qualities.
Red keeps us warm.
When we say it's a warm color, it's the truth.
You'll overestimate the room temperature by two degrees, which means that at the top of Mount Everest, they have worn red for 40 or so years, and they're right to do so.
You'll put twice as many ice cubes in Coca-Cola as in Pepsi,
because Coca-Cola seems warmer.
Color also has another advantage in marketing, it's that it allows you to recognize brands.
You recognized Coca-Cola and Pepsi in this image in one-tenth of a second.
If I showed you this picture, you'd have been lost.
80% of brand recognition, is its color.
So you understand that in marketing, when we work on brands, color is absolutely crucial.
Let me give you the 200 million dollar example that shows the importance of color.
In 2012, Google asked itself if the blue of its trade links, that we see in gray, could have an impact on the number of clicks.
So, all of us, in 2013, we tested 50 shade of... - gray -
of blue, it's a little bit gray.
And it turned out
they looked all over the world, and they determined which blue helped us click more.
It was close.
Is it a bit darker, a bit lighter, a bit greener, more purple?
The fact remains that in changing blue, the person that is the boss of Google UK, estimated that in changing blue they earned an extra 200 million dollars.
Just by changing the color of the trade link.
Studies on the importance of color on our products date back to the 50s, with Procter &amp; Gamble that is undoubtedly one of the brands that most invested in marketing, and which asked if, in their detergent, that was white at the time, the simple act of adding colorful glitter could have an impact.
Housewives tested the same detergent, but with either red, yellow, or blue glitter.
They came back two months later and gave the same results.
Beyond the researchers expectations, because, first conclusion, none of the housewives realized they were testing the same detergent three times.
They all saw a difference.
The majority of them felt the detergent with the yellow glitter wasn't efficient, didn't wash the laundry well.
Conversely, the detergent with the red glitter was very powerful, maybe too powerful and damaged the laundry.
Which meant that some didn't dare finish the detergent with red glitter.
The detergent with blue glitter, however, was a great detergent.
Not only did it respect the laundry, it washed well, but, surprise, it smelt fresh.
Yes, by simply putting
blue glitter in the detergent, the laundry seems to be fresher and smell better.
A few years later, green produced the same results as blue, and here's why, since the 50s, all detergents have red on them to signalize their efficiency, blue and green to signalize that they respect the laundry and freshness.
Yes, we smell with our eyes.
All of us, even professionals.
I'm going to give you an example: Bordeaux University, 54 oenologists tested an AOC Bordeaux blanc, that they obviously knew by heart, with an odorless red coloring.
Out of the 54 oenologists, guess how many were duped?
54.
They all tasted strawberries, leather, etc.
In short, red wine characteristics.
The same one presented a little later, without coloring, suddenly tasted lemony, buttery, etc. So white wine characteristics.
If we are duped by our sense of smell, we are also strongly influenced by our palate.
Know that we also taste with our eyes.
Every great chef in the world works the color as much as the recipe.
If a plate looks nice, the dish will be better, it's a fact.
A fun experiment that proves this was conducted by Heinz who wanted to know what was the right color for spicy ketchup.
They realized that consumers felt that the darker the ketchup, the spicier it was.
The same ketchup.
And some people felt they didn't like the spicier ketchups, they said, "I can't eat that one, it's too strong, but the lighter reds are OK."
And those who liked the spicier ketchups said, "The lighter reds aren't for me, I prefer this one, it's really much better."
So we are really, fundamentally, influenced by color.
Each color influences something.
An interesting study was conducted in England, they asked adults to play with Lego.
The instructions were simple, "Do something that's never been done."
Some had these instructions in blue, others in red.
The groups with the blue instructions used the right hemisphere of their brains and started making creative objects, art pieces that didn't make sense.
Those who had the same instructions written on a red board, used their logical brain and made functional objects:
a new house, a new car, a new dress, etc. So, by simply giving information in one color, influences the way we see it.
All of you are much more creative in a blue environment.
Your ideas will be much more relevant, your ideas will be more original, newer, and you'll have many more ideas.
Which means that today, to brainstorm, we know that we should put you in a blue environment to help you find ideas.
However, if we want to get your attention, keep you focused, we prefer a warm color scheme.
Meaning yellow, orange or red.
So, when we say warm color scheme, we don't have to have entirely red rooms.
A room like this for example, that is mostly white, appears to be red, because there are touches of red.
In here, in an office like this, productivity is excellent.
You're able to work for hours and hours, without tiring because the energy of red will help you.
Sadly, today, many of us work in here.
That's 10% less productivity, and 15% more risk of burnout.
The achromatic schemes that have existed in the west for a dozen years are, let's says, not great, to put it politely.
I suggest you wear pink, because the euphoric aspect of pink will help you -- the expression "See life through rose-tinted glasses" reflects a fact.
In England, they repainted the kindergarten classrooms that were beige, in pink, and then compared the kids' drawings over 10 years, the drawings before and after the rooms were repainted.
The kids' drawings were significantly more positive.
The smiles were wider, the suns bigger.
Pink is an euphoric and relaxing color.
Researchers looked for a use for this.
We are in Seattle, in a prison, a high security unit.
Know that in this prison, the most agitated inmates, when they're put there, when they're left alone, even for just a quarter hour, become as calm as lambs.
Some would say it's because they don't like the color and don't dare move.
The fact remains that putting inmates in here, works.
Personally, I equipped crisis units in psychiatric hospitals with pink. For the books, the workman who thought he could do the work in three days, took five.
He worked in a strong pink like this, he couldn't work, and the end results weren't great,
there were wrinkles everywhere.
So pink is an euphoric color, but I suggest you sleep in mauve bedrooms.
Yes, know that in bedrooms like this,
you will have sexual intercourse 3.5 times a week in average.
It's an English study on 2,000 couples that teaches us this.
And know that 3,5 times a week means 12 a month, and doctors say that 12 per month, means an extra 10 years of life.
If you won't do it for yourselves, do it out of altruism for your partner.
(Laughter) It's important to think about your partner's life expectancy.
And this is what we live in.
Never mind 10 years, in a color scheme like this, you'll have intercourse less than twice a week.
It's up to you.
(Laughter) This image scares me, because, I was on Google last week, and I typed the words "bedroom" and "design."
This is the first image that comes up on Google.
This means that trends in the West, push us towards this.
Push us to where there is no color.
Today, three out of four cars are gray, black, or white.
In the 50s, 75% of cars were colorful, the winning trio was green, blue, and red.
Those who are lucky enough to have been to Cuba know this.
This is how we lived not so long ago.
Not so long ago, we couldn't imagine building a library in anything but green.
Why green?
Because when you read a book, you activate at the same time your creative brain to interpret what the author is saying, and your rational brain, to stay focused on the story.
Green is the best color for reading.
That's why so many of us love reading on public benches.
Green is an excellent color, and today, how many libraries still have green globes?
Likewise for theaters.
20 years ago, we couldn't imagine building theaters other than in red.
Why?
Because you are focused.
Because the people on stage, in the theater, feel that the audience is much warmer, so the symbiosis between them is better, it's the right color.
Sadly today, cinemas often look like this.
The same film in this cinema may seem boring whereas it might be absolutely fabulous in a red environment.
20% of the French population regularly takes, or very regularly takes, antidepressants.
I'm not saying that color is everything, but when we see how happy we are to receive a bunch of flowers, that is to receive color, I would like you to ask yourselves, how would we all feel if we gladly followed Indian fashion and all dressed like this?
How would we feel if we lived in towns like this, with color everywhere?
Pierre Dac has a nice answer, it's, "If our gray matter was rosier, the world wouldn't have such dark thoughts."
Thank you.
(Applause)
Good evening everyone.
In the next few minutes, we'll be going on a journey, but before that, I'm going to start by asking you a question.
It's a question you've already heard dozen of times: what do you want to do in life?
For those who manage to find a response, it would be interesting to see if it's the same as the previous years.
In other words, are you always on course?
Personnaly, I never knew what I wanted to do in my life, And sometimes it used to annoy me.
I have never had a specific dream and therefore no clear vision of the future I wanted.
But I had passions, extra-curricular activities that I enjoyed and that shaped my character.
For me, these activities defined me as a person in all it's complexity.
Every time I was looking for a job, none seemed to perfectly suit me.
It was as if I would have to take away a part of myself each time to fit into that box.
It's surprising, isn't it?
Even without knowing exactly what we want, we sometimes have to study for a long period of time.
Three years ago, I finished - wait for it - a mechanical design engineering degree.
Mechanical design engineering, a five year course in science, post A-levels, all without knowing what I wanted?
It's a little paradoxical, isn't it?
In fact, it wasn't really because I loved learning I loved learning science, and I had time, student life was great, but I still didn't know what will be my occupation.
I only really understood it later, during my last internship.
I remember it well: I was sitting at my desk, and I had just received instructions from my boss.
He had asked me to come up with a mechanical system.
It was out of the blue, and it was going to take some time.
I was tired and depressed because my only desire was to go home and do what I love: playing music and learning photography.
I had to resign myself to the idea that that evening would be another one where I would go home just to eat and go to bed.
At last, I realised that my job
was the one I studied for, and the one I was going to do all my life.
I was almost surprised to learn this, despite the fact that for five years, I was supposed to train for it.
At that moment, I realised I had to break up, I had to stop.
I wanted a reassess my life and find a new direction.
It's true, when we are in working life or even students, we are not able to think calmly.
There's always something to do, a problem to solve.
How can we know exactly what we want if we can't even manage to think calmly?
That's when I realised I didn't need a holiday, I wanted a retreat,
(Laughing) a retreat to make a journey inward.
So I thought about going to Nepal, the emblematic symbol of meditation, and I was surprised to find it was possible to go and live in a Buddhist monastery over there for little money.
In fact, all you had to do was take part in the community.
So I jumped at the opportunity.
Once on the plane, finally, I was leaving !
I was leaving France for three months, three months of tranquillity, three months to center myself...
The beauty upon arrival is just dazzling.
Imagine a big monastery like this with a hundred of children inside and over thirty adults.
And when you arrive and pass through this monastery's doors, you leave aside all day-to-day problems.
And when I say "all problems", I really mean all.
There's no need to work, to revise, to answer emails, even planning what you have to buy to eat.
All you needed to do was to live to the rhythm of the monks, and the sound of their bells.
I was given a bed and food; it was simple, but it was enough.
At the end of a few weeks, I started to use my camera and capture the experiences I was living.
Every morning, we were awaken at 5:30 a.m. by a mad monk hitting a gong in the monastery's courtyard.
We had only 15 minutes to get to the central temple and sat.
Once on our little cushions, there was one hour of mantra chanting during a ceremony called "Puja".
When we had finished, I would see the monks coming out while pushing the temple's curtains and we would see the sun starting to enter.
It was magnificent.
Every day, we ate outside, sitting on the ground.
The food was the same, safe two or three different vegetables.
After a while, I felt my tastes were starting to change.
I sensed that I was taking more time.
I was more present in what I was doing.
In fact, there was nothing to distract me such as TV or adverts.
There were just children who were around me, were eating, and sometimes wanted to play with me or speak to me.
With them, in three months, I went from being a stranger, to being a pretty cool English teacher, (Laughing) to being sometimes more of a friend and confidant.
I remember that I witnessed amazing moments of life, such as when monks shave each others heads about once a month.
For them, it's a sign of sobriety, of renouncement of consumer and appearance-based society.
For others, it's also a good opportunity to have fun.
By the way, between the two, this one was kind of scoundrel.
In class, he wasn't very nice.
Sometimes I would leave the monastery and go for a walk in the countryside.
And I discovered another one, perched on top of a mountain
that was amazing too.
I was lucky because that day was also a day off for the children.
I came across a little group who were playing with sheets of paper.
We made an Airbus A380, of course, and we threw them from the top of a small wall.
At the end of a few weeks, I felt the euphoria started to drop.
And I discovered boredom.
Boredom is, for human, a hostile feeling that they learned to outsmart with many different strategies.
The most famous, you know it well, it is your smartphone.
Put it aside just for a few minutes, and boredom comes back each time.
I remember spending hours in my bedroom, lying on my bed in silence.
I was experiencing boredom.
I looked at the ceiling, and there was
nothing to look at, and yet... and yet I looked at it closely.
After a while, I discovered myself.
I saw many things happening inside me, things that moved.
We hear a lot of things when it's silent.
I discovered that I had tinnitus.
But after a quick search on the internet, I learnt that everyone has it.
We're just not aware of it because we're not listening to it.
After a while, I felt more in touch with myself.
I felt I could rethink the direction my life would take. I had the guts to ask myself once again the famous question asked earlier but by adding a new parameter, a parameter that changes everything.
I said to myself, "Joffrey, what would you really want to do in your life if you had no chance of failing?"
It takes a lot of time to respond such a question.
Personally, I had to break all the mental barriers I had constructed and that defined me.
In eight years, I got slowly used to the idea of becoming an engineer.
When these barriers are broken and we truly ask ourselves truthfully what occupation we want, we finally start to think.
We no longer search through the prism of our studies, we go further. We think like children who have not been shaped by their surroundings.
We think like children who were not said, "You're good at this but bad at that".
After a while, I felt I was coming with an answer.
And now it fits in one sentence: "I wish to live by always spending enough time to the development of what I am passionate about."
I wish to live by always giving myself enough time to work on what I am passionate about.
I did not talk about photography, maybe one day I'll get tired of it, but even so, I wanted to give myself the time to try.
You know, it's this little time that allows you to go from amateurism to being a professional.
In the end, it was necessary to go back, work, save money because real life continues to go forward at a crazy speed.
I had just signed up an open-ended contract as an engineer, but it was okay because I finally had my goal.
I had my motive.
I had my driving force.
I knew that to have entrepreneurial freedom and freedom to move, I needed to emancipate myself from wage-labor.
But before, I had to learn.
It continued like this for a year and a half, 1.5 year of subway-work-sleep routine.
And I assure you that after three months in a monastery, experiencing Paris' subway is not really nice.
And after a while, I started to feel depressed.
When I looked around me, everyone seemed quite satisfied with their job.
When I was considering leaving mine, what was I thinking?
Payed holidays, extra days off, job security, they're not that bad. (Laughing)
I also felt social pressure weighing down on me when I compared jobs said to be "rewarding" like engineering, with others like photography.
I was told, "Hey, you didn't do all this for nothing!
You don't feel good, ok, but don't worry, You will get better tomorrow, come on!"
My favourite, you know it?
"Five-year studies to be an engineer, and you end up as a photographer?
You know, kids!"
(Laughter) We've all heard that; well, I have anyway.
At first, it affected me, but later, it was lost on me.
One day, I felt ready, so I left.
I have now been a photographer for over a year, self-employed and working for myself.
And I was able to make a decent living this year.
I developed new skills in the Web, in computer graphics, engineering, and when I have time, I leave.
I lose myself in different countries.
Here, for example, it was in Kirghistan.
a country impossible to pronounce, and no one knows how to spell it.
There, I discovered the nomadic culture and especially hospitality.
They welcomed us, and gave us food and drink.
They had nothing.
Sometimes, I don't go to remote countries but to cities as well.
Like here. in Kathmandu, where I came across a woman.
We smiled at each other
because when I carry my backpack and feel good, the camera around my neck, I feel in the right place at the right time.
I feel in this special short moment where I think,
"Wow! I'm happy.
It's here that I should be."
So at last, I understood and I had the proof that we should trust ourselves, nurture our creativity, and never stop learning.
I realised that everything I did for eight years was coherent, but it took me eight years to see it, eight years to understand that even engineering is helping me today in my job as a photographer.
Actually, it's only when we step back far enough that we can see the whole picture.
I'm convinced that we all love many things outside of our main job, and that it's vital to maintain our curiosity.
And If we let ourselves do plenty of what we love, if we keep on doing this day after day, nurturing this little flame of curiosity and passion, then little by little and without judgement, one day, we turn around, and we finally understand the consistency in our actions.
And then, all we have to do is turn off this notorious autopilot, to start to make a change.
And now, I'd like to ask you again one last question this evening: what would you really want to make of your life if there was no chance of failing?
Thank you.
(Applause)
One out of four students struggles to fund their studies, despite grants, bank loans, or doing casual work.
This affects 600, 000 students each year.
Shocked?
Us too. That is why last January, Zélie, my associate and I, decided to launch What If Community, the first crowdfunding-based platform dedicated to higher education.
On paper, this is a promising idea.
After all, if we are willing to finance music albums, or an electric scooter, why not a study project?
During a weekend away last June, we launched our pilot platform to finance the studies of three promising students.
After a four month trial period... It didn't work out.
Following the students' feedback, we realised something: the students did not need one lump-sum to fund their studies, they needed long-term funding.
We realised that crowdfunding was not sufficient for the large number of struggling students. It was not cut out for such high demand.
Being entrepreneur means accepting when we get it wrong, and not being scared to redevelop our ideas, we have to adapt.
Funding studies involves an element of risk which is even greater than what we estimated.
Our objective remains the same but we have a new solution.
For those students who are unable to access courses due to lack of funds we have come up with an offer: not based on having a guarantor or contacts, but on the student's potential and motivation.
We will raise funds along with companies and institutions, enabling us to offer our services to students.
Once graduated, the students gradually pay back a percentage of their salary over a given period of time. This is personalised, depending on their situation and education.
Unlike loans, students only pay back if they can, according to their earnings.
No salary means no repayment.
If a student earns less than we expected,
they pay back less than what was borrowed. On the contrary, if they earn more than expected, they pay back more, allowing us to create a lasting funding system which will contribute to fund more students.
This might come across slightly mad, but this solution already exists in Germany and Latin America and has enabled almost 10, 000 disadvantaged students to access higher education.
We believe that funding study programmes is just the start.
We want to open new doors for students and help them on their journey to completely fulfill their potential.
Through sustainable and significant investment, while making a difference to as many as possible, we aim to enhance education. We believe that all students should be free to choose their future, and we are certain that, although studying can sometimes be difficult, paying for it never should be.
Thank you.
(Applause)
I am here today at 52 years old though I was born four years ago.
This equation must sound flawed and incoherent at first. But let me explain the unknown factor of this equation. You will see that the result is correct.
I have been living in survival mode for 48 years.
But these 48 long years of suffering and frustration have been followed by a peaceful and happy life.
I could have turned to classic psychotherapy to reconstruct myself, but I have found my solace by embarking on a spiritual path.
I have found notions in spirituality that are similar, sometimes identical, to classic psychology. They have been my friends during many years of authentic and deep introspection.
Einstein said, "We can't solve problems by using the same kind of thinking we used when we created them."
I had to find a new formula, an equation, a solution that would help me understand the painful experiences that have characterized my life so that I could accept them.
What is it that makes us suffer?
Suffering rises from not knowing.
Suffering rises from questions abandoned without answers.
Suffering rises from resisting events that you cannot control.
Suffering rises also from a permanent neurotic state in which you keep yourself when you are convinced that you have no choice but to endure.
I have read a lot, and my readings made me take a quantum leap to see things from another point of view.
In quantum physics, you learn that a result depends on the point of view of the observer. This is the way I transformed my past, chose a future, shifted from being a victim to being a creator, and shifted from dark resignation that anchored me to a state of complete freedom.
Above all, I understood.
I understood the origin of this misunderstanding that sneakily brought me to the verge of chaos where I nearly lost my life on several occasions.
In survival mode, it is painful, it hurts a lot, and you want only one thing: you want the suffering to end.
Three quarters of the population suffers from the same misunderstanding. It is not specific to a difficult past, even though some hardships have a decisive impact.
In my case, to give you some context, I was abandoned when I was two years old. I lived in an orphanage until I was five and a half years old, when a family that gave me my name came and adopted me.
This family came with a prestigious past. It is a family believing in values, in a sense of duty and righteousness. But it is also a family characterized by the opinion that love is a weakness.
Therefore, they were unprepared to display any affection. And you will understand that in my circumstance, I was missing affection and in great need of love.
So, I was watching my surroundings, and I was watching with envy the relationship between my friends and their parents when they were picking them up from school.
They were hugging, showing tenderness and showing much affection. But I was totally deprived of these.
I seemed to have no right to any.
I was wondering why.
As I said earlier, suffering comes from a question without answer.
So, I tried to find an answer.
I made some deductions of my own and came to the conclusion that if I had no right to love; it was because I did not deserve it.
I had been abandoned because I did not deserve the love of my biological parents.
My father, my adoptive father used to tell me something that convinced me that my conclusion was right.
He used to say, "Aline, in life, nobody will ever love you for yourself. They will love you either for your name or for your blond curly hair."
In reaction to that, I got married at the age of 18 to erase this family name, and during many years, I colored my hair and straightened them to make them disappear, in an desperate attempt to escape, yes, almost exorcise this verdict.
When my father passed away, I finally dared to ask my mother: "Why did you not show me any sign of affection?"
My mother said something that had a profound impact on me: "Aline," she said, "we were not there to love you; we were there to raise you."
Should you ask me, these are not incompatible. But I finally could understand that their high sense of responsibility annihilated any emotional spontaneity.
When you are in control, when you control appearance, you break the bond with spontaneity.
Feeling emotions is impulsive. You do not think before showing your affection.
It's a spontaneous feeling.
Love, as you know, is the fundamental quest of every human being from the very day of his birth.
You try to find love with your first landmarks: your parents. Then, you try to find it outside, and you start to identify with how others see you.
And this is the time we get confused.
Because in this quest for love, we are loosing its essence, the most important thing: we are loosing ourselves, we are loosing our identity.
And we do so in three different ways.
The first one, we identify ourselves with our emotions.
Whenever someone either turns you away or despises you or insults you, you get emotional at first.
But a child's brain is not mature enough to properly deal with its emotions.
Therefore a child will identify itself with the pain born from these emotions.
We are talking about childhood trauma.
When you feel emotions regularly, again and again, they end up building up, crystallizing into our cells, inside our bodies, feelings that usually are belittling when they are linked to a trauma.
Feelings of neglect, injustice and inferiority.
When you identify with something other than yourself, you drift away from your true self.
Even worse, in this case, we end up believing in three types of stereotypes:
The first one is the victim. People are hurting me, so I am a victim.
Then, there is the torturer.
The torturer is hurting so much that he will hurt the other first, hoping for less self-suffering.
Then, you have the savior. I know this one very well; it is familiar to me.
The savior is hurting so much that he will believe that society has no place for him.
So what does he do?
He is looking for his place and dedicates his time and actions to others.
I would even say that he will sacrifice himself for the other.
The second misunderstanding is mistaking others' interpretation of who we are to be true,
while it is merely a projection of their own inner-self.
It is the mirror effect in action.
Imagine someone tells you, "You are too extroverted!" We will take this opinion as the truth, and even worse, an unpleasant truth.
However, when we are craving for love, we crave for one thing only: to be accepted and to please the other.
So, what do you do?
You react by behaving as an introvert, in our example.
Now, imagine someone tells you this:
"You are too serious a person."
Now, you will start behaving like a clown.
There are so many choices of different disguises that you can wear in your life to please the people you meet, varying according to your relationships, and to live up to expectations.
It's easy to see how we distance ourselves from our own identity.
But it gets even worse. For while we believe we're doing the right thing, we are actually manipulating people.
As soon as you incarnate a role to get something from someone, even if your intention is commendable - to be loved and to belong, for instance - it still is a manipulation.
You are choosing superficiality and losing your authenticity.
The third misunderstanding consists of delegating to others the responsibility to quench our thirst for love.
No one but ourselves is better equipped
to quench this craving the unique way we need it. In my case, I wanted and expected expressions of affection from my parents, physical and verbal manifestation of their love for me. But they had never experienced it, so how could they do something they did not know ?
Of course, they loved me, but on their own terms, with the tools they could use.
But my own obsession for my needs and expectations made me blind to this situation.
Once such expectations persist, you are taking the risk to be deceived, to suffer and to get frustrated, just like I said in the beginning.
You know, I accompanied my mother in her last moments of life, hoping for an "I love you" that never came.
Since then, I understand that in her own way, she showed me her love.
So there you have it, the terrible unknown, the uncertainty: the identification with the reflection from the other.
Once we let that go, we can be re-born as our true self.
Every step toward your true self is a step away from the conviction that the other must fulfill your needs.
The very first condition is to do it by yourself first.
This is far from easy when your identity is rooted in simplistic feelings such as those that I have described.
But therein lies the key to our rebirth.
It means to truly become an adult, empowered and responsible, who does not need other's approval and acknowledgment, who is thus able to make her dreams come true exactly because she has overcome the limits of determination.
So, there you go. I was born four years ago, when I could love my self by forgiving the others that they could not do it the way I needed it.
Every behavior is legitimate because it stems from a personal journey.
I realized I had to stop focusing on my weaknesses, like my parents and school had instructed me, and that I had to start trusting all that they had overlooked: my intelligence and the voice of my heart.
Today, I am happy. This happiness is unstoppable because it relies on me only.
I am aware that I cannot control events that will happen in my life, but I can control the impact that they will have in my life.
So, when the storm comes, it is much wiser to bend like reeds than to resist like an oak tree.
When the storm is over, the reeds rise up again, while the oak is broken.
This does not mean that I do not connect with others.
Now, they do not fill a need anymore, so my conversations, my exchanges with them have become more selfless, authentic and sincere.
My father used to be desperate when he was reading my school results, and he would tell me, "Aline, what will you do with your life?"
Fair enough, I only got good results in philosophy and Latin. My answer was, "Well, I'll become an orator.
I will study philosophy and speak in front of people."
So my father would say, "Aline, orators have been gone since Roman times."
And today, what do I do?
I share a philosophy of life through conferences and workshops.
So, dare be yourself!
Believe in your dreams for where there is smoke there is fire, and without your potential, dreams will not come true.
Thank you.
(Applause)
I am Mohamed El Bachiri, a Belgian-Moroccan, Muslim and resident of Molenbeek.
With this name, these religious convictions and the reputation of the town where I live, I am considered, by part of the population and the world, a potential terrorist.
And that has quite an impact on me.
I am also the spouse of Loubna Lafquiri, the love of my life, my friend, the mother of my children, who passed away during the attacks in Brussels on March 22, 2016.
Loubna, a woman of incomparable beauty and infinite goodness.
Her eyes on me, her smile, her presence made me the most handsome, the luckiest and the happiest of all men.
Today, my sadness is unquantifiable, and love is the only thing that keeps me going. The love I have for my wife, for my children, for life and for humanity.
A love that inspired me to call for 'jihad' one evening, in a church, where Muslims, Christians, and others had shared a meal as brothers.
Yes, I called for 'jihad'.
Mind you, not just any 'jihad'.
I refer to the jihad that knows no hatred, as hate is a heavy burden that blackens our hearts.
I am talking about the true, the noblest, most beautiful battle for Muslims who oppose terror.
This jihad encourages us to go to the other, our brother who is different, to smile at him, understand him and show him our empathy.
This jihad loves in order to exist, seeks to embrace in order to snuff the flames of resentment, and does not impose its truth,
as it is said in the Quran: <i>La ikraha fi dine.</i> No constraints in religion.
This jihad, my jihad, cries out its love for the West, this part of the world where I was born and which has given me so much.
I am a child of the universe, your brother in humanity.
This jihad should be the answer Muslims give to those who seek to divide us and to propagate violence and terrorism.
As if they were on a battle field, the agonising cries of the defeated were a symphony to the glory of a victorious God.
Cursed be the war, cursed be terrorism.
I return to the essence, love, this cornerstone which should support all ideas, all beliefs, all humans.
It should be a universal force and the basis of all communication between us human beings.
In this relationship based on love, nothing has the pretence of holding the real truth, much less the will to impose it.
This quest for truth is inside every one of us.
It is one of the characteristics of 'the rational creature' that we are.
The journey I chose is Islam.
But this road, I chose with the objective of reaching what the Greeks called 'ataraxia', the state of having a tranquil soul. I wish that for every one of us.
The journey I chose is Islam,
but I chose this road, because I am, above all, a human being.
So, it is only logical to put my humanity above my Muslim identity.
My humanity, with all its humanistic values that come with it: the sanctity of life, free will and the brotherhood of man.
Being a Muslim humanist means accepting, savouring and considering it a privilege to live in diversity.
It is also the capacity to put into perspective certain texts of the Quran, more specifically the passages on war, and to consider them as historical accounts typical of the 7th century, which shouldn't, by any means, be used to hurt or kill other people.
Being a Muslim humanist means taking an interest in our common history, the history of humanity, with all the great men who made the world advance.
These men of Ancient Greece, of Mesopotamia, of Rome, of China, of the East and the West.
It means stopping for a moment to look at the heavens, to turn to our neighbour, to smile at him and to understand him.
And even if my neighbour is the antithesis of my thoughts, my beliefs, this is all right.
As Heraclitus said: there is truth in everything and its opposite.
I, myself, am a contradiction, divided between reason and mysticism, conviction and scepticism. But always, and until my last breath, carried by love.
In these difficult and uncertain times, I call for dialogue and exchange, and rather than lingering on the madness and the hatred of some, let us turn toward the genius and the goodness of humanity.
Those are and will remain the true sources of inspiration and hope for those who will inherit the Earth: our children.
I would also highlight the importance of culture, as it opens our minds.
When I see Averroes, a Muslim philosopher who translated, who ensured the translation of numerous Greek texts, and provided commentaries on them, who ensured the transfer of a great deal of Aristotelian thought to the West, which contributed to the Renaissance... When I see him immortalised at the Vatican Palace in a fresco painted by Raphael, I can only be overpowered by emotion and conclude that we, Muslims, can and have already contributed to the grandeur of the West and humanity.
And that, in the end, there is no 'clash of civilisations', but rather, magnificent encounters.
I would like to conclude with a text I wrote shortly after losing my wife,
as a response to those who have destroyed my life.
It is titled 'Allahoakbar'.
I believe it is the Allahoakbar of most Muslims.
<i>Allahoakbar</i> soft murmur from the heart that can't be heard, but is so much more true than the one used to destroy.
<i>Allahoakbar for the love I have</i> and for the Cherifian kingdom.
<i>Allahoakbar for beauty,</i> for art, for this oeuvre that releases such a strong emotion that it would make the coldest of hearts melt into tears.
<i>Allahoakbar for all this diversity,</i> these people with whom we discuss, exchange and accept that, in the end, each one of us has his truth in a spirit of brotherhood.
<i>Allahoakbar</i> when we disapprove of violence and we work toward peace and friendship between peoples.
<i>Allahoakbar when I smile</i> the atheist or the Christian.
<i>Allahoakbar</i> for those who have understood that God is love and the salvation of men will only come through this universal force expressed for our neighbour.
<i>Allahoakbar,</i> sweet thought and prayer for you, Loubna, my love and for all victims who will forever live in our hearts and our memories.
Thank you.
(Applause)
Good evening.
My name is Nathanaël, and I'm an immigrant.
Between the age of 5 and 25, I lived in more than 6 different countries.
I was born in Brazil. I went to Mali, passing by Thailand, Sri Lanka, Morocco and, one day, arriving in France.
And that was an absolutely incredible experience.
I have friends all over the world.
I lived very unusual, different experiences.
That's me going to school.
And I know that, today, I've picked up some bad habits,
meaning, I'm now having trouble settling down.
And all I dream about is the next time I'll live abroad.
I could dream about living in Thailand again, a country where I lived for over 7 years and where I truly feel at home.
Likewise, I could do anything to live in Morocco again, a country I call, "Brazil not too far", where I found the joy of life and hospitality that characterize my home country so well.
And today I'd like to talk to you about the reason that I felt so well in these countries.
The first reason is, very simply, that I'm part of a rather specific type of immigrants
known as "expats."
My father, in this picture, traveled the world for his job.
He was a civil engineer.
And we followed after him.
And the title "expat" grants a certain respect to the people that have it and, so, to me too.
And that helped us be accepted in those countries because we recognized the added value my dad had in their society.
The second reason I felt so good in these countries is that I was able to meet these countries.
I learned Bambara in Mali. Thai in Thailand. And that let me initiate real encounters with society.
I was able to learn the socio-cultural codes, the way these societies worked.
And these encounters allowed me to develop a sense of belonging, to feel as if these countries were, in fact, my home, were Dunkirk, Montpelier, Paris.
I'm home no matter where.
That's why I started to get involved.
I felt that I had something to give back, that I had to thank these countries back.
And this involvement brought me here in a Karen village, in north Thailand.
The Karen people are from Burma.
They're persecuted on the basis of their ethnicity and difference
and who, for a long time, took refuge in Thailand.
And I was so surprised to see that these foreigners, these immigrants, were not as well-received in Thailand as me.
They were blamed for everything,
for coming to steal jobs, for generating crime, for causing problems, in short.
And I couldn't understand why these people who I would meet and spend time with, who would wake up at 5 a.m., which for me is a bit crazy, could be accused of trying to benefit from the countries where they lived.
These people are refugees. That is, over 19 million worldwide today.
Of those 19 million, over 80% are in developing countries.
Meaning, quite far from us.
Today, France receives close to 200,000 people who are given refugee status, or a residence and work permit, which give them the same rights as us, besides the right to vote.
That makes up 0.03% of the population. Let's just say we're a bit far from invasion.
However, when you see the language used to talk about refugees, it is very negative.
We talk about refugees, much like Thailand, as people that come take advantage of the extremely favorable situation we're in today,
that they come take advantage of our benefits,
that they come cause security problems.
They're handled by the Minister of the Interior, coincidentally.
And that they, as a result, cost government money.
And that language is going to have a very negative impact on these refugees,
because they will be immediately associated with poverty and an inability to contribute.
And I'd like to show you how that language has a real impact on these people's lives.
Meet Sriyani.
Sriyani arrived 12 years ago from Sri Lanka.
Her family and her escaped a civil war that destroyed that country.
And she arrived to France with an accounting diploma and the price for best pastry chef in her country.
Once in France, she was told, "Madam, that's great, but you don't speak French.
You have to take little jobs while you learn to speak French and then we'll see."
And that's what Sriyani did.
For 10 years, she worked little jobs that didn't require her to speak French.
When she got home at night, Sriyani was worn out.
Have you ever tried to speak a language other than yours?
It's a very difficult thing to do.
And so, her kids, whom went to school, started to take over, to help her with the administrative issues, to accompany her during her appointments.
And Sriyani fell back on the only people she had contact with: the people who spoke her language.
So she completely laid aside her objectives.
Her objective to one day create a catering and pastry business.
Two years ago, Sriyani met the Singa community.
Singa is a community of over 15,000 people that matches up refugees, like Sriyani, who have a professional, entrepreneurial, artistic, or cultural project, with French people: you, me, citizens who have the same passions and the same interests.
Simply put, the objective is not just providing Sriyani better adapted support and for other professionals, better adapted support, because I'm not sure the Employment Center lady would know how to support a rap band and to change the perception of society, whom see Sriyani as a poor person and give her the expat status that we enjoy abroad.
And that's Singa's goal.
Singa is a community where we innovate, where we provide new solutions through refugees.
For example: Four months ago, we created CALM the first platform to match up refugees with housing problems and private individuals.
A bit of an unexpected success, there.
In two months, we received over 12,000 housing proposals from all over France.
Proof, if needed, that the French want to get involved in this issue.
And we had this idea because we met Carlos.
Carlos, Colombian refugee who today is president of Singa, told us that, when he arrived in France, he spent two years with a family and that the experience helped him learn French, better understand the society he was in, and develop a social and professional network,
which is something very important.
What I'd like to say is hosting is not something we do out of pity.
It's something we do out of humanity, but also common sense.
when we host well, when we let a person share with society her talents, abilities and expertise, it's all of society who wins.
Hosting is something very simple:
it's simply accepting an encounter, a dialogue, and more, if we can get along.
Thank you.
(Applause)
One in two.
One in every two French people feels that life is passing him by.
Personally, this idea makes me sick.
Four years ago, I had a car accident. Miraculously, I came out of it alive.
I didn't realise straight away but, in fact, it was an incredible opportunity to come to terms in a very significant way with something that is both familiar to all of us and abstract, and that we should be mindful of more often: life is short and everything can end very quickly.
So for me, since that day, there's no way I am letting my life pass me by.
There's no way I will spend another day on this planet doing something in which I don't feel useful, in which I don't find any meaning,
something that doesn't make me feel as if I am growing, learning, as if I am simply alive.
For me, not letting life pass you by means trying to ensure that each moment, each day, each hour, each minute and almost each second is a highly valued experience.
For me, not allowing life to pass you by means in practical terms, not missing the opportunities that are given to us, to me, to experience incredible things.
So when people say that kind of thing, they say very little, because you still don't know
how this is going to play out.
How do you take the plunge when you are scared?
You just don't know.
Personally, I've spent a lot of time alone wondering and thinking to myself: how on earth do we do this?
In fact, the only approach I can think of for now, although there must be a lot more, is to take a leap in the dark.
Actually, for me, taking such a leap doesn't really look like this.
I get vertigo so although I would really like to, I can't do it.
Taking a leap into the void looks to me more like this.
It's less sexy, I know.
I made my biggest leap into the unknown two and a half years ago, on a subway platform.
At least, this is the one I was wanting to tell you about.
Essentially, I was at the end of my studies. Perhaps like some of you, I was in business school, wondering: 'What am I going to do during the coming years?
What am I going to do for the 80 000 hours of work set out for me over my lifetime?
What will excite me?
What will inspire me? What will make me want to get up in the morning?'
I couldn't think of anything particularly. There were interesting options, but honestly, I wasn't overly excited.
At that time, there was one rather crazy project that resonated with me.
One of my best friends asked me to join up with him to launch a social entrepreneurship project.
Back then, we didn't even have a name.
The aim was to organise a tour of France for fifty youth, with the intent of meeting with pioneers in order to inspire and put into motion the future generation of change-makers.
What a program! It was very ambitious and essentially, we started all of it, absolutely all of it, from scratch.
That excited me precisely because in reality, I was scared.
I was scared because I had no idea how it was going to turn out,
neither him, nor I, nor anyone else by the way.
That scared me because I was aware that nobody was going to understand why I wanted to do it,
first of all my family, my friends, and my parents.
I was terrified because it was something I'd never thought about doing.
Never had I thought that, before the very end of my studies, I was going to become an entrepreneur, to launch a project, raise funds, persuade business partners, recruit people, manage a team,
and build from the ground up a project that hadn't existed before.
This did indeed scare me, but it excited me too.
And just like that, I don't know why, one Friday evening, I was waiting on a subway platform, on my way to a football match - I don't know why I was going to this football match either -
and I felt at that moment that it was now or never.
A little voice was saying inside me, 'Jo, what would you do if you weren't scared?'
The answer was clear, that was it.
On the spur of the moment and in a split second, I sent a text to my friend telling him, 'Okay, it's a deal! I'll do it with you.'
It was too late, it was sent.
And the split second that followed, was like this.
Right then, I was making a huge leap into the void while I remained fixed to my seat in the subway.
I had let several of them pass.
Now essentially, for two and a half years, I've been the co-founder of Ticket for Change.
Our mission is to change society through entrepreneurship,
to identify and uncover talented individuals to help them to transform society through entrepreneurship.
In two and a half years, we've become a social start-up. We have ten paid workers.
We reach almost 35 000 people across 160 countries.
The president of the Republic and several ministers know us and they request our services from time to time.
We are supported by some of the largest French companies and ministries.
We won the Google Impact Challenge a few months ago.
So, the reason why I recall that moment in the subway station is because I felt it was one of those moments you shouldn't let pass.
And I am sure that all of you can experience such moments.
But you perhaps don't realise it, or maybe you don't notice them, or maybe you are afraid.
You have doubts and questions.
So, since I got the chance to be here, I wanted to ask myself, 'How does it work for me?
What exactly is it that I do to take a leap in the dark?'
I managed to identify six small tips.
The first is to listen to that little voice inside you
but not the one that tells you, 'You can't make it.'
It's to listen to that little voice, the one that makes you dream, that inspires you.
It's to listen to those things you're passionate about, bubbling inside you.
For me, at that particular moment...
it was the fact that individuals, through an enterprise succeed in solving one of society's problems.
It was education, empowerment, and it was social entrepreneurship.
The second tip is to take one step at a time.
You don't achieve anything by changing things overnight or dropping everything.
It doesn't work like that.
You have to make small steps, progress at your own pace.
What will lead you towards your passion?
For me, there were many different stages:
outings to assist the homeless, participation in a humanitarian project. I traveled in search of entrepreneurs. I decided to partner with my friend on this project.
The third tip is to seize opportunities.
The steps are often right in front of us, but we don't see them.
It had been months since my friend had proposed me to join him.
I answered all of his questions, but not that one.
I couldn't see that it was already there in front of me.
The fourth step, certainly the most important but also the most difficult, and the most counter-intuitive too, is to accept being thrown off balance,
to accept that the perfect conditions will never coincide.
It will never be the right moment, there will always be something that doesn't work.
At that point in time, I still hadn't completed my academic career. I hadn't graduated. I had a loan. It was not the right moment, and it never will be.
The fifth tip requires a slightly more mutinous approach at which I excel particularly well, it's to commit, to jump in without delay.
It's that leap into the void that I mentioned.
It means not waiting to hear the second little voice that says, 'Are you sure?'
Once you have announced it, once you've made a decision out loud, so to speak, then it's too late, you can no longer go back.
Once I sent the email to answer about my participation in this TED talk, I could no longer ask myself that question.
The sixth piece of advice, which is close to my heart, is to give your best. It's to try and do things in such a way that at each stage, you're doing your utmost, pushing yourself to your limit, trying to be the best, give the best, and learn as much as possible.
So with these six tips, the little voice that makes you doubtful or fearful at a given moment - this thing that we call 'limiting beliefs' -
is not going to disappear with these six tips.
In reality, it will never disappear.
It's not that pleasant but we must learn to accept its perpetual presence.
With these six tips, it won't disappear, but you're going to overcome it.
You're going to surpass yourself and do things that you previously thought impossible.
A year ago, six months ago, two months ago, I never would have thought it possible to find myself here, on this side.
And really, even if we feel a bit afraid, or ask ourselves what we're going to talk about, actually, that's exactly what I wanted to get across to you.
We are often told, 'Don't be scared, jump right in.'
In reality, no.
It's not true because being scared, we don't know what to do in such situations.
For me, it's: 'Be scared, and above all, take the leap.'
Given that one in every two french people feels that life is passing him by, if I'm not mistaken, it's about half of this room. So I would like ... in any case I hope that after leaving this room, you will remember these six small steps, and you will ask yourselves the question I asked myself on that subway platform: 'What would I do if I wasn't scared?'
Thank you.
In 2030, we will work 15 hours a week and spend most of our time doing what we enjoy.
(Applause) Unfortunately, this is not my prediction, but that of the great economist Keynes.
Keynes imagined that technical advances and gains in profitability would make our world an abundant paradise, where we will all be at leisure, prosperous, and happy.
Well, things did not exactly
work out like that.
At leisure? We are certainly working less, but we expect everyone to have a job.

Prosperous? Probably, for the 1%.
Happy? Maybe, but it certainly
doesn't result from the world of work.
So, what's happened?
Well, constant advancement in technological development has had a serious effect on labor and employment, which we are having equally as hard a time evaluating as Keynes did in his time.
Let's consider Ford.
In 1929, Ford employed 130,000 people.
Less than a century later, Tesla Motors, one of the leading and most innovative car manufacturers today, employs no more than 6,000, and most are engineers.
There are not many people in Tesla factories.
Of course, I'd not teach you anything by informing you that mechanical and manual tasks are performed by robots.
Farmers, workers, right. But executives!
Not so long ago, a marketplace like the New York Stock Exchange was full of people.
There they screamed, gambled, pulled their hair out, made phone calls.
In 2012, more than half of the orders passed in the U.S. market are passed via high frequency trading, that is, using algorithms.
And as for the intellectual professions, those that require our empathy, courage, judgment, well, I present to you Wordsmith.
Wordsmith does not have a robot head, but it knows how to write a financial dispatch in less than one second.
And the list is long.
Pepper the robot, the empathetic robot, the personal assistant that knows how to learn from humans, will be sold in stores in less than a year.
We will have robot waiters, bankers, nursing aides, cashiers, and even caregivers - this famous bastion against human obsolescence - will not be spared.
We will have robots that do TedxParis in 2030.
Robot politicians -
now that's not a bad idea.
Of course, man will not become obsolete overnight, and new activities, of which we currently cannot conceive, will occupy us more than we might expect.
And, of course, it will be a few more years yet before our engineers and web developers become unemployed.
Years, but certainly not centuries, because it is clear that a large amount of the work we do today can be performed by robots.
So, what's to be done?
We can continue to maintain the myth of full employment, but then it will draw all the consequences:
Continuously reducing the cost of human labor to make it competitive with machines,
forever create new demand, with ever higher complexity, to replace just a part of the jobs that will be wiped out.
In other words, choosing to live in a society with insecure jobs for fear of having to face a rising unemployment graphic.
And that is exactly what we are living through.
For lack of vision, for lack of courage, all our governments, all our policy makers today focus their agenda on full employment.
Now, we can recognize that a social plan that focuses on full employment has become a chimera.
And, employment defines all aspects of our social, cultural, political, and economic lives.
Children are asked, "Well, what are you going to be when you grow up?"
Education, retirement, health, our entire social system has its roots deep in employment.
And not to mention public debate.
For 40 years, whether left or right, regardless of the environment, all politicians have placed full employment as their main focus, whatever the price, and with the success with which they're recognized.
Full employment cannot form the foundation of the house we will live in tomorrow, because with full employment, it's not just the plumbing that gives out, it's the whole house going up in flames.
Today we must build new homes, and we would like to have a say in the type of house in which we will live, right?
This is actually not the case.
It's not that today we lack political or social plans; it's that the majority of them are made without us.
Take Google - much has been said about Google - Google has a pretty clear vision of the world, it's transhumanism.
Well, recall that one of Google's investment arms, Google Ventures, today manages over 1.5 billion dollars invested in fields as diverse as robotics, of course, but also education, mobility, genetics, music, skills assessment and even legal services.
That is to say that Google now has the means to ensure that its vision of the world today, becomes our reality of tomorrow.
Of course, these projects may seem very surrealist, but they are not just technological.
In fact, San Francisco and Silicon Valley are now a laboratory for political plans.
Take for example, this investor who proposed in 2013 to split California into six states, in order to, and I quote, "Set the political reality in line with the economic reality."
Well, if the plan had been successful, he would have created the richest state in the United States, Silicon Valley, right next to the poorest state, Central California.
He lacked just 50,000 signatures for the plan to have a chance of success.
I'm not saying that these plans are good or bad.
I would rather tell you of a myriad of plans bringing hope in areas as varied as: the collaborative economy, social entrepreneurship, education, and the like.
Today, thousands of entrepreneurs want to give economic power back to us.
They want us to have social impact, if only on a very small scale, but today that's no longer enough, because it's no longer economic power that must be regained - and it's already still far from won - it is political power.
I know what you'll think, "How are we going to regain political power, when the steady worsening of our economic situation leaves us neither the time, nor the energy to do it?
What should we do now?
Take to the streets?
We've tried, and it doesn't work very well.
What, carry pitchforks?"
I've good news for you: the pitchforks are optional. Because at this very moment, a large number of French, European, and world citizens have formed into communities.
These communities all have a different story, they all have different ideas, but they share common objectives.
This is what they say to us, "Stop waiting for realization or stupendous reforms from above.
Take back, right now, the public debate, in the name of an interest that for long has had nothing in common with it but the name.
Become the informal government of our societies ourselves since the formal government has shut us out anyway.
Be the architects of tomorrow's world rather than its hostages."
I'll give some examples.
OuiShare, I know very well since it is a community of which I am fortunate to be part.
Well, OuiShare wants to lay the foundation for a society that's based on collaboration, cooperation, and trust.
MakeSense, that wishes to help social entrepreneurs gain real sustainability of their business model.
Zero Waste France, which brings together people, local and national, with the goal of reducing waste at the source in order to move towards zero waste.
Parlement et Citoyens, who want to help citizens to participate in the development of the law.
Or, without a label, this list of citizens of the city of Saillans who last March won elections against the incumbent mayor.
Well, a few months later, they are establishing a true participatory democracy.
And there are many others.
Alternatiba, Ars Industrialis, Colibris, Carrotmob, Noise, Movilab, P2P Foundation, Villes en Bien Communs, Collectif pour une Transition Citoyenne.
These movements are a click away.
It is thanks to them today that we can have a political platform, in any case, much more than the act of voting for the king every five years.
It is thanks to them that we can start to exercise our duty and power as citizens today.
No need to recruit, you join and leave when you want, no hard feelings.
But most importantly, these movements today need us as much as we need them.
They need us to pass to the next level and to truly weigh in on the transition.
Because the cards are still in play.
Two centuries ago, Jefferson already warned, "If once the people become inattentive to the public affairs, you and I, and Congress and Assemblies, Judges and Governors, shall all become wolves."
We no longer have the right to lock ourselves in our homes and wait for it to happen.
This is our opportunity.
Thank you.
(Applause)
It is said that humans' peculiarity is that they're the only living beings to have straightened up, and to stand up.
This is an affirmation we often hear when characterizing a human and especially differentiating them from other living species.
I propose you to come with me in the woods.
In the forest, trees line up, with their trunks standing straight, vertical, storming heaven.
Obviously, humans are not the only ones to settle in the vertical position.
Further, there is a hill, a slope where the same kind of trees grow, their trunks still upright and vertical, but they bend at their base.
And this curvature evokes movement, a straightening-up movement.
A movement? Does it mean
a tree is capable of moving?
And if it moves because it is on the slope, would it be therefore capable of feeling that it is bending?
We've bent our minds, if I dare say, to this question in my research lab in Clermont-Ferrand, France.
And we've discovered how a tree stands and stays upright for a long time, like you and I.
By the way, how do we stay upright?
How do I manage to stand in front of you today on this stage and stay on my two feet?
In order to stand up in the air, despite gravity that forces everything, every object to fall downwards, we need first of all the mechanical support of the body.
For us, this mechanical support is the skeleton, an internal skeleton made of bones that are light, rigid and resistant.
But that's not enough.
The skeleton can't stand on its own, no offense to the Lumière brothers and their dancing skeleton.
In addition to the skeleton, we need muscles to tonically maintain the vertical posture.
These muscles contract and relax continuously in my legs and in my torso.
And to coordinate this ongoing muscular work, we also need a neural control.
This neural control is the nerves that govern the muscles but also the spinal cord, the brain, and the cerebellum, that coordinate the whole.
So both our body supported by the skeleton, and the muscular tone regulated by the neural control, carry out what we call a "continuous and dynamic postural control."
"What about the tree?"
are you going to say.
Until proven otherwise, a tree doesn't have bones, muscles, nerves, nor a brain.
So its skeleton, as everyone here knows, is the wood.
This wood fills all its axes, in particular its trunk.
Wood is of a material that is lightweight, rigid, and resistant, just like our bones.
Let's look at it highly magnified under a microscope,
This wood is "lightweight" because it is porous, filled with holes.
In fact, almost all cells that make it up are dead, and only their thick walls remain, which is called the "cellulosic wall", surrounding the empty cellular lights.
It is "rigid" because this thick wall is made of cellulose whose cables that are parallel to each other are assembled and held together by numerous chemical bonds, and all is embedded in a strong, hardening, and stiffening glue called "lignin."
Finally, it is "resistant" to breakage because wood cells are organized according to two directions in space: the vertical system whose cells are elongated in the direction of the trunk's axis, and the horizontal system, whose cells are elongated in the direction of the trunk's diameter, and both systems, vertical and horizontal, interweave and assemble based on the tenon and mortise technique.
Thus wood is the material that is mechanically ideal to build high columns in the air, up to 100 meters for giant trees.
Let's come back to those trees that elegantly curve on the slope.
In my lab, for several hours, we filmed plants that were placed horizontally at the beginning of the experiment, and in these two cases - wheat germination and the flowering stem of the Thale cress - we were able to see by watching those movies at high speed that these two stalks stand up vertically by curving at the base in one direction and curving at the top in the opposite direction, so they temporarily take on an "S" shape before they stop curving and become again perfectly upright.
We've followed in the same way the straightening up of a young bent tree, a poplar.
It also do the same movement: it bends at its base, unbend at its top in the opposite direction, and it goes through the same exact "S" shape before straightening up itself vertically.
So plants in general and trees in particular, move with real movements, with movements of growth that straighten them up, and they stay upright, rectified, perfectly straight vertically.
Unlike us, however, this movement is not immediate.
It is even invisible to the naked eye, invisible to our hurried eye, to our time scale.
For a tree in the forest, this could take many years because the straightening-up movement, that particular growth, is associated with the deposit of a particular wood at the trunk's base.
This wood is called "tension wood".
It is different from regular wood.
It is clearly visible in the rings of this fir trunk.
These wood rings are thicker than regular wood rings.
This is because the trunk produces more cells on one side to readjust itself.
And since every year, a new circle of tension wood is deposited, the trunk slowly becomes oval.
Since a ring of wood is deposited each year, we can very easily - and you know it since childhood - read inside a tree all of its past.
In this fir trunk that was cut in the fall of 2016, the reading of its rings reveals what happened to it between 1999 and 2000.
Christmas 1999, do you remember?
Two incredible storms ran through the country, they swept through France from the west to the east.
The gusts tilted this young trunk of 15 years of age that was growing perfectly upright before the storms, as indicated by the wood rings at the center of this trunk.
It was not uprooted, so the following spring, the spring of 2000, it bravely resumed its growth.
Since it was bent, it then deposited this famous tension wood that pushed it up during the 16 years that followed,
up until it was cut.
And this isn't all. Remember...
The young slanted poplar in the lab, we've studied precisely the straightening mechanism of its trunk and showed that this young poplar deposits tension wood at the base of its trunk that straightens it up and also deposits tension wood at the top of its trunk but on the opposite side and this pulls the trunk in the opposite direction and adjusts it vertically.
A final question may be tickling your mind.
Okay, the tree straightens itself up, the tree adjusts itself.
But if it does all this, it's because it can feel it's bent.
How does it perceive it?
We, humans, feel verticality without knowing it, just like Monsieur Jourdain, by the perception of gravity which is called "graviperception".
This occurs in our inner ear in which there are tiny pebbles of limestone - called "otolith" - that float in a jelly and weight lightly, driven by gravity, on sensitive cells that continuously inform our brain of their position and the changes of our body positions, even minute ones.
The response is immediate: the brain orchestrates the dynamic of the muscles that contract and relax in order to instantaneously and live correct the vertical posture, just like I am currently doing in front of you.
In plants, we know since the 18th century that they are sensitive to gravity too, and that it is due to this sensitivity that their stems rise towards the sky and their roots sink into the ground.
Charles Darwin himself, during the 19th century, studied the growth movements of plants placed horizontally.
And all the researchers who followed him until today, well dissected the straightening-up mechanism of stems and roots.
The principle of verticality perception in plants is similar to ours.
There are tiny pebbles of starch - called "statoliths" - in sensitive cells that weigh inside those cells at the tip of the roots, in the barks of young stems, and in the wood of trees.
These are like thousands of bubble levels that continuously inform the plant of its bent compared to the vertical.
We thought we know everything about plants' response to gravity, but that's without counting on the troublemakers of my research team, from Auvergne-France, who did wonder if Darwin was right, as said in a song.
They asked themselves if the perception of gravity, graviperception alone, was enough to induce the straightening-up of a bent trunk and to maintain it upright.
We have simulated on a computer the straightening-up of a virtual tree placed horizontally by giving it only the ability to perceive its angle of inclination with respect to the vertical, that is to say, graviperception.
In the movie, the color code is as follows: the axis portions that curve are in red, and the portions with no curves that are perfectly straight, are in blue.
Then we've compared the behavior of this mathematical lying tree to the behavior of actual plants that straighten up.
In this model, we can see that the virtual tree, that was lying down flat at the beginning, curves at its base and a little higher uncurves and takes on this well-known "S" shape.
Surprisingly in this model, the virtual tree sways continually around the vertical, and it never straighten itself up nor find back the upright shape that living plants take on in Nature.
What is missing for this model to mimic reality?
Let's come back again to us for the last time.
We are gifted with a sense of balance that is complex, much more complex than just the perception of verticality.
As a mater of fact, our body is aware of itself.
What does it mean?
Well, it is aware, it feels the position of its limbs in space.
It is said that it feels its own shape, and this special perception is called "proprioception".
It is this particular sense that enables the beer drinkers or tea drinkers that you are, to find the glass and your mouth, even in the dark or with eyes closed.
Now in the lab, those same troublemaker researchers showed in the 2000's that a tree in the wind can perceive the wind through the mechanical distortion of its cells, and that basically, it perceives the curvatures of its axis.
So we've introduced in the model this sense of perception of the axis' curvature - the proprioception - and then ... victory!
The tree straightens up by curving at the base rectifies its position by curving in the other direction at the top and it ends up perfectly upright, as illustrated by the blue line.
Just like humans, trees perceive verticality and straighten up.
Just like humans, trees feel their own shape and correct their position.
And just like humans too, they do use a real postural control in order to stand upright, straight like an "I".
In conclusion, trees move - I hope I've convinced you of that - with real movements like humans.
Trees correct their posture like humans.
Trees incorporate different signals, either the perception of verticality or the perception of their own shape just like humans.
If humans stand up instantly, as for trees, they take their time.
And as the rushed human being needs a skeleton, muscles, nerves and a brain, the patient and thrifty tree achieves the same prowess with its wood alone.
And finally, whether we are made of wood or flesh, whether we are a tree or a human, we are all standing upright like a single human, or a single tree.
Thank you.
(Applause)
So then, "Inception":
science fiction or reality?
Is it possible to implant a memory without you knowing it? Whilst you sleep? Whilst you dream?
But before we can manipulate dreams, we need to understand what they are.
And before we can do that, we need to understand how memory works.
Because your dreams are constructed from the experiences that you have lived through or even imagined.
To get a better understanding of memory, I'll need you to go back in time to 1957.
This was the year when Henry Molaison had an operation to control his epileptic seizures.
At that time, the only possible treatment was to remove the part of the brain that was causing his seizures. This part is known as the hippocampus.
This was successful in that it stopped his epileptic seizures.
The only problem was that Henry Molaison developed total amnesia.
He could no longer form new memories of his life.
What have we learned from this tragic experience?
Firstly, that even for such a crucial reason, this part of the brain should absolutely never be removed.
Secondly, that this tiny part of the brain, your hippocampus is responsible for your memory.
Not your intelligence or your reasoning skills:
his IQ was perfectly preserved.
No, just your memory.
But to fully understand memory, knowing where it occurs is not enough.
Because, what exactly is the brain?
The brain is a collection of millions, tens of millions of neurons that communicate with each other.
They communicate using tiny electrical impulses.
A little like, if you were one of these brain neurons, the only thing you could do is tap your neighbors on the shoulder.
Sometimes, with a telescopic arm, but that's all you could do.
Yet, this very simple, basic way of communicating is responsible for all your thoughts your memories and your dreams.
How is this possible?
To try and understand this we need to be able to record the activity of the neurons.
We could implant an electrode into a particular location and monitor the activity of hundreds of neurons.
Of course, this is highly invasive, you would need a hole in the brain.
We couldn't do this to a human, without a very good reason.
So to overcome this problem, we use mice to help us to understand, in particular, spatial memory, so, the memory of how to get to the Chatelet Theater in Paris, how you got here today, where I am standing on this podium.
We put mice into a maze, where they can run around freely, going right, going left to find a piece of cheese.
While at the same time, we record their neural activity, to see how it works.
It has been found that the neurons react to specific places.
There are neurons that fire when I am in a particular place.
And in mice, there is also a neuron, for example this one here in red, that will fire when the mouse is at the exit of the maze,
and only when it is there.
If I were to record the activity on a neighboring neuron it would be active when the mouse was in the same area of the maze, but downstairs.
The neural activity is in fact electrical activity
that can be heard through a loudspeaker.
For example, when the green neuron is active, when the mouse is in the green area you can hear this.
So, if you close your eyes and listen to the noise, you could tell the exact location of the mouse.
And if we record from about 50 neurons covering the whole of the space and use mathematical algorithms called Machine Learning, we could replicate the exact location of the mouse in space.
In this short film, what you will see is a maze.
The red cross shows the actual location of the animal and the blue and green dots show the position that we have replicated using a computer.
You can see the exact path taken by the mouse.
You can tell, simply by looking at the computer screen where the mouse is.
At times, you can see things are a little more complex as though the mouse is at several places at once.
But we know that this can't be the case.
So, we think that we are able to replicate not only the actual location of the mouse but also the path that it is thinking about, the path that it is deciding to take.
Is this what we are seeing?
Indeed, the mouse goes on to take the path that we had predicted by calculating its position.
So we are able to read the mouse's thoughts, or at least where the mouse thinks it is going.
So is it possible to alter what it thinks?
That's where sleep comes into it.
If the mouse is put into this space for example, and it is given a reward right here.
Later, when it goes to sleep in its little box, we can see a specific place-cell becoming active then another, then another, as though it were dreaming about the path that it had taken whilst it was awake.
We think that this reproduction of events is very important for consolidating memories.
You relive the experience during sleep to consolidate it.
So yes, you should learn things before you go to sleep.
Is this really what happens?
To be absolutely sure,
we would need to wake up the mouse and ask it, "Were you just dreaming about walking along that path?"
There's a slight problem in that mice don't talk.
Effectively, it is an imaginary experience.
So, what would happen if, whilst it was sleeping, whilst this place cell was active. Could you give the mouse its reward during the time it was asleep?
Would it wake up and go to find its reward?
That's exactly the type of experiment that we are doing at ESPCI, not far from here, with our students who are here today: Marie Lacroix and Gaëtan de Lavilléon.
I can see you all thinking, "He is nice, but he's just a dreamer."
Because how is it possible to give a reward to a mouse when it is sleeping?
It is possible because, as I told you, brain activity is electrical.
When you give a mouse a big piece of cheese, you notice a small part of its brain becomes really active.
And so, if you implant an electrode to stimulate that precise region, you are able to recreate the reward given to the mouse.
So, we recorded the neural activity that occurred when the mouse was running around, And we saw that a particular place-cell
became active. So, we designed a machine-brain interface that works during sleep which, as soon it detects the neural activity that happens whenever the mouse dreams that it is in that particular place, it automatically triggers a sensation of being rewarded.
So when the mouse wakes up, and it is put back into the same place, it goes directly to the place where it had been rewarded whilst it was sleeping.
This experiment shows us that it is possible to create an association between receiving a reward and the activity of the neurons.
And even when we are awake, this association between a physical location and a reward is still there.
So this shows a strong relationship between neural activity.
When a neuron is active, I'm sure that the mouse is at a certain place or thinks it is at a certain place.
This also shows us that it is possible to take a memory, and put it back as a more positive one, whilst you sleep. Or even as a more negative one.
So what about humans?
As I have told you, recording neural activity is very powerful but very invasive.
You would need to open the brain with the risk of infection.
On the other hand, you could use functional MRI.
Functional MRI is a huge scanner that allows us to look at the activity of the brain without having to open up the cranium.
There was a fascinating experiment that took place at Berkeley.
American researchers presented subjects with a series of YouTube videos over a period of four to five hours.
And whilst the subjects were watching these clips, a computer program was trying to make the connections between the video clips and the brain activity recorded by the MRI.
Next, these subjects were shown a film that they had never seen before.
This film is what you can see on the right of the screen.
And on the left is the image that they were able to recreate, simply from the activity in the brain.
They managed to largely recreate, what the subjects were watching.
Through MRI, they were able to see what the subjects were thinking.
So, with the experiments on mice, and the experiments on humans, is "Inception" possible?
In theory, yes.
We can't do absolutely everything.
I can't make you learn how to speak English whilst you sleep.
But on the other hand, we can take a memory, and turn it into something more positive or more negative.
But to do that, we would have to show it to you whilst you were awake.
So we couldn't do it without you knowing.
And we would have to show it to you for about 4 or 5 hours.
And even though the computer program had coded these images, they would only work for you
not for anyone else.
So we are a long way from mass thought manipulation.
If you are afraid that we can alter your thoughts while you sleep, without your knowledge, I recommend that you pay closer attention to advertizing.
If we have no reason to fear, do we have any reason to celebrate?
Yes, because with new technology, we are able to look closely at he neural activity linked to the thought processes of the mouse.
This gives us great hope for psychiatric disorders that affect only thought processes.
And the other interesting thing as I have already told you, we are able to turn a memory into something more positive.
And we hope to be able to use this to develop new therapies for post-traumatic stress disorder.
What's post-traumatic stress disorder?
It's when patients have made a pathological association between an experience and a heightened sense of fear.
At present, the only treatment is to ask patients to put themselves back into the situation. And by making it a more pleasant, comfortable setting, try to break the pathological negative association.
The only problem is that even if you use virtual imagery to make the situation more immersive and realistic, you still know that it is not real.
And more importantly, your brain knows that it's not real.
The advantage of dreams is that everything is real.
When I am dreaming, I really am Batman.
And it's only when I wake up that I realize that I'm not.
So, if we can identify, during sleep, the moments when the subjects are reacting to these traumatic experiences, that would be the ideal opportunity to break the pathological associations.
All these potential applications, and others like them, exist because we have succeeded in creating a false memory in a tiny mouse at ESPCI, just next door, and because we have been able to do it during sleep.
So I can tell you you have no reason to fear.
You can sleep with both your eyes closed.
And have sweet dreams.
(Applause)
