(Video) This time, the rescuers arrive too late.
They reach the boat which found the deflated rubber skiff off Tripoli.
At the bottom of the raft, eight lifeless bodies: five men and three women who died asphyxiated, crushed under the weight of the 119 other persons who were on board.
Ludovic Duguépéroux: This footage is from the first rescue I took part in aboard the Aquarius.
August 2nd 2017, the Italian Navy instructs us to transfer 127 people rescued by a merchant ship, the Santa Lucia.
While approaching with two speedboats, we find out that among the eight victims are the two parents of a two-year-old girl.
This is the first time I see these people in the flesh.
Some of them are burned by the mix of sea water and fuel that spilled from the jerrycans.
Others have bloody calves, scratched by the nails of those who, in a last effort, tried to get back up from this deadly raft that I am uncovering, full of shit, vomit, clothes, babies' diapers.
They are all haggard, flabbergasted, some of them mourn their losses.
Once the transfer was over, we towed the rubber boat next to the Aquarius to transfer the remains of these eight people, to offer them one last shred of dignity.
For three days, they will be stored on the foredeck.
Every three hours, we will water them to preserve their corpses until a ship equipped with a cold room comes to retrieve them.
I am afraid, I do not understand, I have no idea what I am doing here, how this could exist? And yet I thought I was prepared for all this.
My name is Ludovic, I am a sailor.
Before working as a sailor, I was a nurse and in parallel, I sailed.
During a return transatlantic, with my friend Fredo and our esteemed master Jean-Pierre, in the middle of the Atlantic, right in the middle: eight meter high waves, 40 knots of wind, the boom broke, the foresail tore up, we have to lock ourselves up, we drifted until a yacht, a magnificent sailboat, Pink Gin, offered us and applied the duty of all sailors of the world: to provide assistance to anyone who is in distress at sea.
I set foot on land, a bit shaken, I think to myself, "Wait, wait.
Either you learn how to sail, or you never set foot on a boat again."
And I got into the Higher Maritime National School in Havre.
First year of class, summer 2016, first internship.
Childhood dream.
I board the Abeille Flandre.
The Abeille Flandre is a tugboat for deep-sea assistance and rescue.
We patrol south from Corsica and then, during my shift, we receive a distress signal.
A signal coming from off the coast of Libya: 150 people, including women and children, are sinking.
My blood runs cold in my veins and I send my first application to SOS Méditerranée.
At the end of my internship, I went back to class and went to the cinema, I went to see the documentary film "Fuocoammare", and I saw that.
(Video) LD: When I got home, I got sick and I told myself: "Ludo, who are you if you don't go?
Who are you?"
I am the grandson of an Italian immigrant who fled Mussolini.
I was brought up to respect others.
You were a nurse, you are a sailor, who are you if you do not go?
I urged and urged SOS Méditerranée and the following summer, in July 2017, I had the grim honor of boarding the Aquarius for the first time.
The second rescue in which I took part happened two days after the one from Santa Lucia.
Wooden boat, 300 people, there's wind, there are waves.
We get closer, impossible to communicate, there's a majority of young Eritreans.
The doctor from MSF cannot adequately assess the situation.
We start transferring people. Comes a very weak, very slow man, but in those moments, you need to be responsive.
I shift a bit, I girdle him, we bring him to the raft, he loses consciousness.
Later, we will find out that he had four bullets from a Kalashnikov in the stomach.
Others have broken limbs.
They explained that the day before, when they embarked, the weather was bad and the boat was too crowded.
So, they refused
to load the boat and the smugglers fired rapid shots and used crowbars.
I disembark from my first campaign and think to myself, "This is not possible, it will stop, this cannot exist, there are good reasons for it to stop: people need to stop dying at sea."
No.
June 8th 2018, back to Catane.
We head south, nothing has changed.
Saturday June 9th at 2pm, we get a call from the Italian Navy giving us the position of two boats in distress and instructing us to provide assistance.
We head there.
At 7pm, we can see both targets.
We launch two speedboats.
We go towards the first boat, we stabilize it.
We get to the second one, the night has descended, and there is no time to talk.
There are 120 people with water up until there.
The simple fact of us approaching, they turned toward us and the rubber boat was broken in two.
And then, they were shouting and yelling:
"Help me! Save my life, please!"
You are going to see the videos of the onboard camera from that time.
(Video) (Screaming) We throw life jackets, but there is wind, so some of them go too far, others come back toward us.
The first people, the first hands cling to the floats.
And then, I was flabbergasted, I felt like I was frozen.
It was very weird.
On the one hand, I spent my rescue thinking about my wife, thinking about Nour, thinking, "Don't fall Ludo, don't fall.
You should never fall, but this time you cannot.
If you fall now, you'll be a buoy, 20 people will fall on you, and it will be over."
On the other hand, we are trained, we are professionals, and we act.
Grabbing, lifting, putting down, grabbing, lifting, putting down, grabbing, lifting, putting down, constantly, until the bottom of the raft is full of people, of living beings.
I look ahead and I see my leader who is going to go overboard because too many hands are clinging to him and to his boots.
I throw myself onto him: left hand, I girdle him, and I have to punch unknown hands so that they would let go of Max because Max will go overboard, so that they let go of Max and cling on to the boat.
Max gets back up.
30 degrees starboard: someone drowned.
We go there, we get that person out, no heartbeat, not breathing, the nurse starts massaging.
Larboard: someone drowned.
We go there, I am the only one available.
I see this person floating vertically, their head 50cm under water.
I lean in, but I cannot reach them.
I can fell their hair, but I cannot grab them because there's too much fuel on him, everywhere, on my gloves.
I need to go further and I feel my center of gravity: I am going to go overboard.
No, my comrade grabs my boot with his left arm, I can go further and I manage to slide my hand between his t-shirt and his arm.
This person on board: no heartbeat, no breathing.
Full speed toward the Aquarius, we disembark the drowned persons, the other shipwreck victims, Médecins Sans Frontières takes over.
There's so much tension, we are mad, the fuel makes us want to vomit, and we go back.
At 2am, we have 229 persons on board.
At that time, two boats from the Italian coast guards arrive, they conducted two rescues and we are instructed to accommodate 400 people.
At 5:30am, the transfer is over, there are 629 people on board.
Time to go shower, I cannot take my gloves off, I cannot loosen my jaws and my forearms have doubled in size.
At 7am, we find out that Messine will harbor us.
I go to bed, I cannot sleep, the boat's speed increases, heading north.
Then you think, "It's alright.
It was difficult, but ...
They are safe, it's going to be okay."
Not 24 hours later, we hear Mr. Salvini's statement saying that Italy is closing its doors to shipwreck victims.
At the front, we see Sicily, on the port beam, there's Malta, and we are stuck there, we are drifting.
Where the hell are we?
The day before, the Italian coast guards ask us to welcome 400 shipwreck victims, and now we are being denied these people's disembarkation.
What happens to international maritime law?
What happens to the Hamburg Convention regarding maritime search and rescue?
We brush them away like that, for political reasons?
Do they realize what it means to have 629 on board of the Aquarius?
The Aquarius is 77 meters long, 12 meters wide.
To eat in the morning, there's a three-hour long queue.
To go to the bathroom, three hours.
We are drifting away, there's no air, it's 40°C, the deck is so hot, people are sleeping on the deck, we cannot walk on the deck.
We cannot move around because there are too many people.
And as after every shipwreck, the astonishment is fading away and people talk, as always, about the atrocity of Libya.
Tension is building up, people are talking.
What would I have done, if I was from a country at war?
If I could not ensure my family's safety?
If I could not feed my children, and someone told me, "Go to Libya, you can work there.
It's a free zone, go there."
I would have gone.
If, when I got there, my family and I got locked up, ten militiamen entered, raped your wife in front of your kids, and this was filmed so as to be sent to your family, and if your family did not pay, next time, you would be dead.
What would I have done?
And if I went alone, as a man who wanted to work, and I got locked up for six months, with electrodes on my balls.
Again, filmed.
And my only way out is this boat, because I cannot go by land.
I would rather die at sea than stay there.
What would I have done?
After three days adrift, we find out that Valencia will harbor us, in Spain.
We cannot cross the Mediterranean Sea, so we transfer more than 500 people onto two Italian boats.
We keep 109 people on board, vulnerable people, families, unaccompanied minors.
And we think, "We will finally be able to talk.
We will get to know these strangers."
No.
This time, there is bad weather.
After four hours, there are 40 knots of wind, four meter high waves in a choppy sea.
These people, who are exhausted, who sleep on the deck, are vomiting, convulsing because there's nothing left to vomit.
We see this young girl breastfeeding her baby, just months old, on the left and vomiting on the right.
At 10pm, the captain orders us to get in the people who are on the quarterdeck, in plastic bags, and are getting swept away by the waves.
They have no strength, we would like to carry them in.
And there are 109 human beings who, with the sway of the sea, in vomit, are crashing into each other.
At that point, we hear Mr. Salvini saying that these people are not going to choose the duration and the destination of their cruise.
Mr. Macron said we should not give way to our emotions.
Three months later, in front of Malta, we will hear, "You should not
yield to good intentions."
But come!
They can come! Come and see!
We will hand you a rain gear and boots.
Come live the hell of a shipwreck.
Come and see these hands reaching out, these people drowning in front of us, thes screams.
And come onboard afterward.
Come meet these people because they literally arrive naked, and we are humanly naked.
Come and hear these stories,
listen to these dreams and fears.
Come see these human beings.
Human beings, not migrants.
They are human beings.
We have forgotten that 80 years ago, people from Alsace and Paris fled with what little they had to flee barbarism?
Do we have a short memory?
What are they doing, fleeing?
And today, we are being accused, we are being prevented from carrying out our duty but if someone fall in the Seine, do you ask them where they're from before getting them?
If you witness a car accident and there is a kid moaning, trapped in a ditch, do you ask for his documents before calling for help?
This is not what I have been taught.
I went to a school in the French Republic, this is not what my teacher taught me.
We cross the Mediterranean sea, and the day before getting to Valencia, the weather eases.
We are exhausted, we are breaking down, but people are starting to come back outside.
This time, they are the ones taking care of us.
Everyone gets out and Joshua, who was a pastor in Nigeria, Maryse, who is a singer, go to the middle of the quarterdeck.
Everyone gets there.
Some people are crying, singing, laughing, breaking down.
The kids are making fun of us, they pinch the cameras from the journalists: "Oh, he's crying", there you go.
There we are, all together.
There is no age, no sex, no religion.
This is a moment of life that is absolutely indescribable.
(Video) (People singing and playing music) At that point, we were finally able to meet each other, me and the second person who drowned and got resuscitated.
His name is Samuel.
He is 27 years old.
He left Nigeria where he worked as a house painter, he thought, "I'll go to Libya to make money, and come back home to start studying civil engineering."
He got to Libya, same horrors, same confinement for six months.
No desire to go to Europe, but the only way out was getting into this rubber boat.
Yesterday, I had Samuel on the phone, he is taking Spanish classes, he is working, and he hopes his language level will be sufficient next year for him to get into his engineering school.
We leave Valencia, we get to Marseille.
This is very ambivalent, as a rescue vessel does not belong there.
On the other hand, we sailors, we realized that the Aquarius, we are the very small and very last link in a chain of human beings getting mobilized and working for SOS Méditerranée.
At a time when politicians are tainting the sea, these people are transposing on land the duty of every sailor, which is to provide assistance to human life at sea.
At that point, a politician came to see me in Marseille, "Mr. Duguépéroux, kudos on what you do, but your anger is useless, you are not aware of what is at stake, you do not have a holistic view on the impacts of this crisis."
I said, "Let me stop you right there.
Do you think we are naïve?
Do you think we do not know that Italy cannot handle it alone?
They have been doing this for 20 years.
Do you think I do not realize that France cannot set a precedent, that there are economical and geopolitical issues with Libya?
I am European, I am French, I can see our challenges and I fully understand that it is not people's primary concern.
And if there was a massive migratory wave, which is not the case at all, I am aware of the sociological, economical impacts this might have.
But what I do not understand, what we do not understand and what we will never understand, is that all these considerations take precedence over our humanity."
Thank you.
(Applause)
Hello.
On April 8 in 2003, I was in Baghdad to cover the war in Iraq.
It was when the Americans entered Baghdad with their tanks. We were just a few journalists in the Palestine Hotel, and the war was approaching downstairs, outside our windows.
Baghdad was covered in black smoke and oil, it stank, you couldn't see a thing, but we knew what was happening.
I was supposed to write an article, of course. It's always when it happens that you have to write the article.
So I was in my room on the 16th floor, writing, and occasionally looking out of the window to see what's happening.
And then suddenly, there was a loud explosion.
For the past 3 weeks, we were being bombed by missiles and half-a-ton bombs but then that shock, I felt it inside me.
So I thought, it's so close!
Very, very close!
So I went down to see what was happening, I came down on the 15th floor, to see, and I saw people screaming in the corridors, journalists and I walked into a room and I understood that this room had been hit by a projectile.
Someone was hurt, then near the window, there was a man who was a cameraman, called Taras Protsuyk, and he was lying face-down.
I'd worked in a hospital once, so I wanted to help.
So I turned him over. And when I did, he was open from sternum to pubis, but I saw nothing, nothing at all.
I saw a white, pearly, shiny spot, that blinded me and I did not understand.
And the spot faded and saw the wound, which was very serious, some buddies and I put him put in a sheet, we brought him down in an elevator which stopped at each floor, 15 floors, We put in a car that took him to the hospital. He died on the way to the hospital, and the Spanish cameraman José Couso, who was on the 14th floor and was also hit - because the shell had hit between floors - died on the operating table.
When I came back, once the car left, I had an article to write,
I had to write it. And so I came... I returned to the hotel lobby, my arms were covered in blood And there, there was some Iraqi henchman who stoppped me asking to pay him ten days overdue taxes so I sent him packing.
And I thought: "Above all, put that aside.
Put that aside!
If you want to write, you must put that aside. "
That's what I did, I went up, I wrote my article, I sent it.
But afterwards, beside affect, beside having lost colleagues, something was bothering me: I kept seeing this spot, shiny, pearly, and I did not understand what it meant.
And then war was over. Later, I told myself, it is not possible.
I can't not know what happened.
Because it was not the first time, it is not just me, I had seen things like that in others in 20 or 35 years of reporting .
I've seen things that had affected me too, but for example, in The Lebanon, I knew a man, a veteran, he was 25, 5 years of war, so he was a veteran, we followed him everywhere!
He would crawl at night, confidently, he was a great soldier, a real soldier, so we followed him because
we knew we were safe with him.
And one day, I was told, and I saw him again since, he was playing cards in the barracks and someone came in, they discharged their weapon, as the gun went off and the blast, the simple shot, had him duck under the table, like a child!
He was shaking, panicking!
And since then he's never been able to get up and fight. And he ended,
I found him, as a croupier in Beirout casino because he could not sleep, so it was quite a suitable job.
So I thought: "What is that thing that can kill you without leaving any visible injuries?
How does that happen?
What is this unknown thing?
It was too common to be a coincidence.
So I started to investigate -- that's all I know to do.
I started to investigate look through books, and reach out to psychiatrists, museums, libraries, etc. And finally I discovered that some people knew -- often military psychiatrists -- and that what we were dealing with was something called a trauma. Americans call it PTDS, or trauma, traumatic neurosis. It was something that existed, which we never spoke about.
So, what is this trauma?
Well, it is an encounter with death.
I don't know if you've ever had an experience with death -- I'm not talking about dead bodies, or someone's grandfather laying in a hospital bed,
or someone who got hit by a car.
I'm talking about facing the void of death.
And that is something no one is supposed to see.
People used to say: "Neither the sun, nor death can be looked at with a steady eye."
A human being should not have to face the void of death.
But when that happens, it can remain invisible for a while -- days, weeks, months, sometimes years.
And then, at some point it explodes, because it's something that has entered the brain,
a sort of window between an image and the brain, which has penerated the brain and will remains there, taking up all the space in the brain.
And there are people -- men, women, who suddenly no longer sleep, and experience horrible anxiety attacks --
panic attacks --
not just minor fears.
Who suddenly don't want to sleep because when they sleep, they have the same nightmare every night, they see the same image every night.
What type of image?
For example, a soldier who enters a building and comes face to face with another soldier aiming at him. He looks at the gun -- straight down the barrel.
And this barrel suddenly becomes enormous, deformed,
it becomes fluffy, swallowing everything. And he says -- later he will say: "I saw death, I saw myself dead, threrfore I'm dead."
And from then on, he knows he is dead.
It is not a perception, he is convinced he is dead.
Though in reality, someone pushed that gun away, and he didn't actually get shot -- but all he knows is that he died in that moment.
It can also be the smell of a mass grave --
I have seen many in Rwanda.
It can be the voice of a friend calling who's being slaughtered, for whom you can't do anything.
You hear that voice.
Every night for weeks, months, you wake up.
In trance, panicked, terrified like a child.
I have seen men cry, but like a child, seeing the same image.
So in his brain, that image of horror, that of the nothingness of death, which is called an analogue, meaning an image hiding something, will occupy everything.
He can't do anything.
Anything at all.
He can no longer work, it can no longer love.
He goes home, he does not recognize
anyone. He does not recognize himself.
He hides, he stays home, he locks himself in!
I know people who put small tins outside with coins in case anyone passed by, came.
All of a sudden, he wants to die, he wants to kill, he wants to hide, he wants to run, he wants to be loved, he hates men and something comes over him all day long, and he suffers tremendously.
And the others don't understand!
They say: "But there's nothing
wrong with you! You're fine, you have no injuries, you went to war, you came back, you're fine. "
And these people suffer tremendously and some commit suicide: after all, suicide, it's to put my agenda to date, since I'm already dead, if I kill myself, fine.
And in addition, there is no more pain.
Some commit suicide, others end up under the bridge, start drinking... You all remember of the story of that grandfather, of that uncle, that neighbour who drank, who said nothing, who was cantankerous, who beat his wife and ended either sinking into alcoholism, or dying.
And they don't talk about it, why?
We don't talk about it, why?
Because it is taboo!
You cannot say - man does not have the words to say the nothingness of death.
But the others can't hear it!
When I'd come back from an assignment, for the first time, I was told:
"Ah! He's back from his assignment! "
There was a dinner, a beautiful white tablecloth, candles, guests, "Here, tell us about it! " I told about it.
20 minutes later, people would give me dirty looks, the hostess had her nose in the ashtray, well, it was horrible, and I realized I had screwed up the evening.
So now, I don't tell anymore, but we are not ready to listen to that, We say "Oh, stop!"
Is it just a few cases? No.

This is extremely common!
One third of the dead soldiers in Iraq - dead, sorry for the slip.
One third of US soldiers in Iraq suffer from PTSD.
In 1939, there were still, in English psychiatric hospitals, 200,000 soldiers of the First World War.
In Vietnam, there were 54,000 deaths.
Americans.
By 87, the US government had found 102,000 - twice as many - 102,000 completed suicides of veterans.
Twice as many deaths in combat as in Vietnam.
So you understand that this is something that covers everything!
Not just modern warfare, ancient wars too, they are found in ancient texts!
It is told, it is said, why do we not talk about it?
Why do we not talk about it?
Because the problem is that if this man does not speak, he's heading for disaster.
But the only way to heal, because the good news that thing is that it is treatable: Munch's The Scream, Goya, etc. yes, it is treatable!
The only way to heal this trauma, this encounter with death, which stuns you, petrifies you, kills you, is to manage to talk about it.
Someone said, the anceints used to say: "Language is the only thing holding us men together."
If there is no language, we're nothing.
We are only humans because of it.
Faced with this image of horror which has no words, because it's only an image of nothingness obsessing us, the only way to work this out, is to put human words on it.
Because these people feel excluded of humanity: no one wants to see them anymore and they don't want to see anyone.
They feel dirty, defiled, ashamed.
Someone said: "Doctor, I do not go in the subway anymore because I'm afraid people will see the horror I have in me in my eyes."
Another said he had a terrible skin disease, he spent six months in dermatology, he would be sent from one ward to the next, and then one day, they sent him to the psychiatrist.
And he told the psychiatrist at the second meeting - he had a terrible skin disease, from here to foot - he said: "But why are you in that state?"
And the man said, "But because I'm dead, so I'm rotting away."
So you see this is something that affects men at their deepest.
To heal, we must talk.
We need to put the horror into words, human words, manage to tame, to talk about it.
You have to look death in the face.
And if we can do that, if we talk about these things, then gradually, working with a speech we can recover our human side.
And this is important!
Silence is killing us!
What does that mean?
That means that if afterwards, ah, of course, we lost our unbearable lightness of being, we lost our sense of eternity which makes that you are here, if you are here, it's that you feel
you are eternal! You're not!
Otherwise you would not be here, you'd say "why bother?"
And they lost that feeling of eternity.
They lost their lightness.
But they found something else!
It means that if we manage to look death in the face, and face it rather than keep quiet and hide, well have men or women I know, - Michael from Rwanda, Carole from Iraq, Philippe from the Congo all those people I have known, Sorj Chalendon, who is now a great writer and who gave up report assignments after a trauma.
4 or 5 friends of mine committed suicide, they're the ones who did not survive after a trauma.
Well if we can look death in the face if we mortal humans, human mortals, we know where we are humans and mortals, mortals and humans, if we can confront it and to put this thing back on it which is the most unknown land of unknown lands, since no one has seen it.
If we can put things on it, yes, we can die, survive and revive, but stronger, stronger than before.
Much stronger.
Thank you.
(Applause)
There are many paths for a successful life, and commitment is one of them.
Commitment gives meaning.
Commitment shows the direction, like a compass.
Today, I want to make you want to commit, to give you the desire to want.
I am an industrialist and an entrepreneur.
Being an entrepreneur means making choices with a dose of obliviousness when facing risk-taking, and a dose of courage when facing the unknown.
When you make a decision, you have three possibilities, like animals when they face danger: either you bear and suffer, or you flee, or you engage, meaning you act. And starting a business
means to act to create meaning.
This is what drives me.
But starting a business also means being afraid.
Goethe said: "As long as we don't commit ourselves, doubt reigns."
We all share the same fears: the fear of risk, the fear of failure, the fear of loneliness, the fear of people's judgment and opinion about us.
And these fears are, for the most part, unfounded.
They are created by our minds, but they slow us down.
And commiting means overcoming our fears.
I've always been afraid each time I have committed to something.
Committing means losing points of references to create new ones.
I was afraid during my studies.
I was afraid during my marriage.
I was afraid to have children.
I was afraid of creating my businesses.
And today, in front of you, I am afraid.
But fear is a fantastic lever for commitment, and I propose we experience that together.
To do so, I invite you to close your eyes.
You are a skier, but not just any skier.
You are in a starting gate but not just any gate.
You are going to descend the Streif, the ski path of Kitzbühel, in Austria.
Under your skis, there is a wall, 84 degrees of slope.
You're going to jump in the void, and you hold your sticks... You prepare yourself to push off.
Can you feel the pressure, the challenge, the fear?
Imagine your heartbeat.
Imagine your mind planning and re-planning the route.
Six, five, four, three... Oops! Sorry, but your departure is postponed!
You can open your eyes.
Why, when faced with so many feelings and so many fears, do we still commit and decide to go?
Well, it's because it makes sense.
And I have personally experienced this, committing for a purpose while at the same time telling myself, "What on Earth am I doing here?"
In 2013, I was elected president of France's Center for Young Business Leaders an association of 5,000 entrepreneurs campaigning since 1938 to put the economy at the service of humanity.
I decide to dedicate four days a week to this association for three years.
I want to do it, I am proud of it.
I want to defend the fundamentals of the movement, that is, training leaders in their business profession and influencing them to imagine the society of tomorrow.
I am proud to commit to this movement which made me grow and to give after having received.
Even so, I say to myself, "What on Earth am I doing here?"
What am I doing here?
I'm afraid of losing my relationship with my wife and my children, of losing my businesses.
I'm afraid of being forced to go from city to city.
I'm afraid of not being capable, of not succeeding.
And it is other people who are helping me.
It's the important people in my life such as my wife, my kids, my colleagues, the other entrepreneur members, who tell me, "Go, you can do it!"
They put me in the starting gate and tell me, "We believe in you, we're relying on you."
And from this experience, I understood that a meaningful commitment has to be taken both with the heart and with the head.
I learned four lessons from this, four cardinal points in order to stay in course and to continue to live a meaningful life.
The first point is desire.
You go there because you feel the desire to.
You can feel it boiling inside you with the idea of living new experiences.
You're excited, happy, enthusiastic.
It doesn't matter what might happen.
You have the desire to go there, you have to live it.
It builds you.
It evolves you.
It makes sense.
The second point is balance,
maintaining a stable imbalance.
There are three pillars in life: the professional... wait, not in that order: the personal, the professional, and the social and societal.
Imagine a three-legged stool, and one leg is much longer than the others.
Well, you won't keep your balance for long.
When I decided to spend four days a week away from my family and my businesses, it was because my wife, my kids, and my colleagues told me, "Okay, it's the right time."
Had I taken on such a responsibility ten years earlier, I wouldn't have been able to do it with young kids, or a business just restarting, or to the detriment of the other pillars of my life.
The third point is learning.
Committing means confronting the unknown.
Throughout all your life, you learn.
When you commit, you learn.
Take driving for exemple.
At first, you're afraid.
You check everything, you're uncomfortable.
And then by dint of driving you gain confidence.
All phases of learning are tough but necessary in order to evolve.
When you commit, you learn to understand how you function so that you can better coach others, to accept your fears and your desires, to discover other ways of thinking, and to choose a new philosophy of life that makes sense.
The philosophy that inspired me during my time at the Center and that still guides me today when I have to make a decision is doing differently, think differently, in order to imagine new models.
The fourth point is "the purpose," committing in order to live an adventure that has meaning.
They committed to a cause: Nelson Mandela, Coluche, Mother Teresa.
I am committed to the cause of The Center for Young Business Leaders.
Put the economy at the service of mankind speaks to me.
The cause is fundamental but it isn't enough.
Those who accompany you are essential.
What counts is the adventure you are going to live with the others, in serving the cause.
I invite you to reflect on this quote by Paulo Coelho: "If you think adventure is dangerous, rather try routine - it is lethal."
(Laughter) Commitment is a path to succeed in life.
And to guide you on that path, keep in mind four points, four cardinal points: purpose, balance, learning and desire.
I invite you, once again, to close your eyes, and to keep them closed.
It is your departure time.
You are the one who choose your track.
You're in your starting gate.
Listen to your desires.
Feel your emotions.
Make decisions with judgment.
Commitment is your opportunity to discover who you really are, independently of what you've been told you are.
And in the end, isn't that the true meaning of commitment: giving to others who we are?
Thank you.
(Applause)
I bring both good and bad news summed up in one figure: 30.
The good news first. Compared to our grandparents, we enjoy 30 extra years of life expectancy, and, for most of us, 30 years of leisure and rest.
So, in fact, very good news, and what's more, science promises us more each year.
Now, the bad news. 30% of older people are currently suffering from isolation.
1.5 million out of our 5 million over-60s.
300,000 say they have no contact with anyone close.
300,000 people ... But beyond statistics, beyond the figures, what's important is the reality that lies in them.
Your reality.
And my reality too.
The connection between old age and isolation, I discovered it when I was 45 when I went to visit my grandmother in her retirement home.
When I went into that establishment, I was at first very shocked.
I saw old people, very old people, some in armchairs, some bedridden, glued to the television. I realized that these were the types of establishments, these were the types of places, where we threw our aged, our elderly, and that here was the reason we don't see them about in public anymore.
They are to our children, as to us, far removed from both our eyes and our consciences, and, consequently, far from our hearts.
And, well, my little gran, my grandmother ... her smile, her joy when she sees me, when I go into her room.
We start by opening a half-bottle of champagne - warm - that she gets out of her bedside locker.
We talk, we laugh ... I give her news from "the outside", of what is going on outside the walls.
I go with her to the refectory so she can have lunch.
She introduces me to those with whom she associates. I'm quite surprised when some of them want to kiss me, to touch me ...
but most are walled up in silence,
and when they look at me, what I see is utter solitude.
Beyond that ... it's very sad.
Then I leave because I'm only there as a visitor.
I leave my grandmother in her retirement home.
30 years ago, my other grandmother died while living with us, in the country, in my parents' house, surrounded by her children and grandchildren.
I was a teenager then. I adored my grandmother, I adored my grandmother ...
Yet, her departure, and her absence, seemed natural: there was nothing violent, nothing brutal, about the way things went.
These two very different experiences, each with its own very strong emotion, have naturally left a lasting impression on me.
It’s no doubt the reason I'm here in front of you today.
It's so easy to cut yourself off from the world.
With age, spouses, friends, disappear, children move away or are "too busy".
For sure, you'll all have had the feeling of being "too busy".
So, well, when isolated, when lacking resources, there's a strong tendency
to withdraw into oneself. Think about it when you are with elderly close to you: with age, solitude, little means, one tends not to ask anyone for help, nor to go to the welfare agencies - it's often complicated and goes nowhere - and no way does one ask one's children, and certainly not one's grandchildren.
The retirement home, that's it, that's the solution.
"But of course, mum, go into a retirement home. You'll be fine there, with people your age, with all the activities ...
And then, for sure, we won't need to worry so much,
for sure we won't need to worry so much.
But it's all not that simple because if your mum - or mine, it's currently an issue - does not make this decision herself, she risks, in leaving behind what she was used to, her home, ultimately her environment, isolating herself even more, surrendering herself to the institution, and having less time to grow old, sometimes much less, invariably with a lower quality of life.
But, well, like that, there's no need to worry, and she'll be no hassle.
Because sometimes there's that patter, a little bravado, a little call for help: "I can leave now, that way,
I won’t bother you anymore."
I have known for a long time that we should, at least that I should, do something.
It's time to rethink our relationship with our seniors, find solutions so that they can maintain human contact and social relationships which are so important for morale and, therefore, health.
I had the feeling some years back, about ten years back, while talking with an architect friend, that other forms of living environment were possible.
He said that in Germany, a country with a rapidly increasing older population, there is a form of alternative living arrangement whereby senior members of the family spend much, very much, as much as possible,
of their later years in the family home.
It interested me, so I went there.
I met up with him, near Lake Constance, and visited small residential places, small residential places, where 50, 60 people, young people, families, elderly people, sometimes very elderly people, even some with Alzheimer's, live together.
The most fragile are cared for by other residents, themselves helped by dedicated staff who facilitate relationships between residents, and between residents and the rest of the locality.
The elderly, for their part, give their time, show enthusiasm, share their experience, notably among the youngest.
And me, I'm rather pragmatic: I like it because it works.
I'm fixated ... I'm also moved, because it brings back emotions, some I told you about before.
I come back to France - I was in my late fifties, and I say to myself, "That's it, that's what I want to do ... that's what I'm going to do."
I used to be a consultant I've already set up a couple of companies, I will create a company that will realize residential places where relationships between people will be at the heart of it all, will be of greatest importance, for all residents, whatever their age, and whatever their social standing.
So, I gradually got together a small team with sociologists and geographers.
Together, we met up with architects, elected figures, academics, researchers, and social housing suppliers.
We referred to the residents.
We put together, during the course of a year, a concept for housing intergenerational people who interact with each other suppotively.
It was a year from the emergence of this concept until we started trying it out.
But we did it.
With all these people, we have created residences where the accommodation is comfortable, ergonomic, doesn't stigmatize people because of their age; residences where places of exchange, sharing and friendship can be integrated together.
We even created the job of "manager-facilitator" - or manageress-facilitator - women, men who facilitate the intergenerational bond between those domiciled in the same place, in no way isolated from its surroundings.
People living in these places are in a position to offer, to receive, to join a club, to set up activities, in short, to play a full role in the place where they live, and, consequently, to be in control of their lives.
The enterprise has now been running for seven years, and we have put the concept of intergenerational collaborative housing into practice in about 25 places, supporting more than 1,500 families, more than 3,000 inhabitants, with a really strong social impact.
An intergenerational environment, what is it?
It's best those living there describe it themselves.
Woman 1: For me, it's as if I'm the age of the person I'm talking to.
And sometimes I don't realize it because I see you young, while you, you see me at my age.
Woman 2: It's opened up my life, I go out a lot, whereas, before,
I felt restricted.
I met this person here.
(Laughter) It provides us with an outlook: we don't stay at home all the time.
Now I go out, come back here, then go for a walk, do a lot of things.
On your own, you can't.
Woman 3: We can go dancing again.
Dancing, it's really good.
Woman 2: There's sport, there's yoga.
There's heaps of things!
Woman 4: On my own, I didn't cook anymore.
Coming here, I've started cooking again.
I don’t have takeaway deliveries anymore.
I put an end to them.
We all smile.
We come here and forget everything.
That's the beauty of it.
I'm all alone at home, so... They're my family, they're my second family.
Woman 3: It's meeting people.

You meet, you discuss.
Woman 5: It's a second family.
When you come to "Chers Voisins", you're part of the "Chers Voisins" family.
We feel great, and we do lots of things.
Woman 6: It's much less "I" alone, and much more "we".
Serge Le Boulch: Isn't that heartening?
In 2015, after having tested this living environment concept, I discovered new jobs: developer, promoter ... and I understood that they can be practised by humanists.
Indeed ...
Reorganizing, improving and adapting the housing of today, imagining, building, and developing the cities and regions of tomorrow, means, of course, integrating new technologies, home automation solutions, digital technology.
It means making our cities, smart and connected cities, "smart cities".
But it also means - it's not contradictory - thinking about a person's place in these residential places we are creating.
We have to address the issues of disability, fragility, old age.
We have to think about places for meeting and sharing.
With these partners, we have developed many topics.
We currently have 20 projects going, and among these 20 projects, the first two in your region, one in Marseilles, one in Aubagne, will open before the end of the year.
And, again, there's thousands living here for whom it might be of interest.
As you will have guessed, we are only at the start of our mission.
Mutually supportive intergenerational housing communities are now recognized by all housing professionals. I believe we made our own little contribution.
I hope my grandmothers are a little proud of me.
A three point conclusion to end.
First: I am 60 years old
and can attest
that you can become an entrepreneur at any age.
So if you have project that make sense to you, and would make sense to society, go for it and don't waste time!
Second:
As you'll have understood, housing, for me, is intergenerational, participatory, inclusive, mutually supportive.
It is, therefore, too important to be just left to specialists, just left to experts.
We all must act together to create places to live befitting our dreams.
Finally, it should not be considered a burden, an obligation, but a chance, a godsend, to live together and enjoy a true relationship with those of all generations, not least with our most senior.
So approach them, exchange, share,
and tell them you love them.
I have my family to thank for this, and the partners we work with.
I hope that you all, your children, your older folk, live long, but above all that you live life to the full. I hope I've shown you the way to grow old with the self-respect you deserve, surrounded by people who love you.
Thank you.
(Applause)
June 27, 2010.
I’m on the starting grid of the Motocross World Championship in Latvia.
My mechanic is beside me.
He’s giving me his final advices.
The 15 second sign.
The 5 second sign.
The gate opens.

Whoosh! I have a speedy start.
I'm in a very good 5th position.
I felt like I was flying over the track.
I was riding properly, comfortably, without taking any risks.
And I arrive at this famous bump, a bump that was difficult to handle, with ruts and holes that are shaped during every round.
I take the take-off ramp, the bike ejects me.
I land on the bottom of my back and I feel a big "crack" in my spinal cord.
The diagnosis is final.
I can feel that I am paraplegic.
In a split second, I see a flashback showing my whole career.
I look back at all the practice sessions in the snow, the rain, all my youth, sacrificed, and I think, "All of that for this?
All of that to end up paraplegic at 20 years old, for the rest of my life?"
Luckily I remained conscious, which allowed me to guide the first aid teams who arrived, to explain that the situation was very serious, and that they needed to handle me with great care.
I am evacuated from the track, to the ambulance.
My parents arrive.
I tell them that the situation is very serious.
My father leaves to speak to my manager to try to get precious advices that could be very important for the future.
I’m taken to Riga's hospital in an ambulance from the 90s or even 80s in really difficult conditions.
In Latvia, roads are cratered, and full of holes, speed bumps, sometimes potholes, which aren't the ideal conditions in which to be evacuated.
After an hour’s drive, I finally arrive at Riga's hospital where I am put in a room with doctors, surgeons.
They explain to me that I will have to be diagnosed to determine the precise lesion on the spinal cord.
I get an MRI scan.
The rest, I don't remember because I completely lost consciousness.
The only thing that I remember is waking up in a room.
My parents were there as well as my mechanic.
The first thing that my father said was, "Axel, how are you feeling?"
I said to him, "You know Dad, I can’t feel anything anymore."
Then, he looked at me and said, "Axel, this is your Grand Prix.
This one is the Grand Prix of your life.
You must win it. You must do
everything to win it."
I looked at him and said, "I will do everything to win it.
I will fight until the end."
My mother was beside us, he led her a bit away as she was crying.
My mechanic asks me how I'm feeling.
I tell him that bone plates have been placed in my spine.
I’m suffering, but I still can’t feel anything.
After a few days, I’m transferred to France, back home, in Lille, where I’ll be operated on a second time, a second operation aimed to try to decompress the spinal cord, in the hope of a better recovery.
After the operation which lasted almost eight hours, they had placed longer bone plates in order to better stabilize the spine.
The following morning, the surgeon come to see me in the room.
He tells me that the operation went well and that I'm going to be sent to rehabilitation in a week's time.
But for me, at that moment, there was no time to wait a week.
One week is too long.
I decide to start working on a mini-contraction that was still there just after my accident, but that had disappeared after the first operation and was beginning to reappear following this second operation, a tiny muscular contraction, just like moving your nostrils, but there is something.
And I decide to start working on it.
I do series of 10, 15 contractions every hour at the hospital.
My dad is at the end of the bed.
He tickles the soles of my feet and I try to concentrate and feel the tiniest feeling.
But nothing changes, I still can't feel anything.
I'm transferred to rehabilitation, where, on my first day, I was given a wheelchair.
I'm transferred from the bed to the wheelchair, a tricky manoeuvre because I had plates that were pulling in my spine.
I sit in my wheelchair and I start my first day of rehabilitation.
It’s not that easy to drive straight with a wheelchair for the first time, to get to the technical facilities, and begin my workout.
During my rehabilitation, I went through various emotional steps: hope, despair, hope again, and accepting the change in my new life.
But one thing obsessed me every morning: get out of bed to learn to walk again.
I wanted to walk again.
I tried to engrave in the deepest of my subconscious the image of me walking again.
This image was almost real, I could almost touch it.
I knew that if I stayed true to this image, it would one day become reality.
I thought about it 24/7.
I didn’t think, "Ah today, I’ll walk again”, no.
I used the moments of somnolence, the moments of relaxation to work mentally.
80% of my work was mental.
Later, when I came out of rehabilitation, I read a book, and in this book, I discovered that I had subconsciously used the visualisation technique.
Little by little during my rehabilitation, the mini contraction of my left quadriceps began to gain strength.
And following this, another small contraction began to appear in the right leg.
I also work a lot on strengthening the top half of my body to try to recover my autonomy, to be able to push my wheelchair, to move myself onto the bed or a chair.
I begin to see that I'm on the right track and that the work is paying off.
After one month of rehabilitation, I receive an unexpected call in from the chief rehabilitation doctor, with my physiotherapist, sports teacher, occupational therapist and the nurse.
The doctor begin by asking about the care given to me on my floor with the nurse, if all is going well.
She says that I go to sleep at a reasonable time, that I eat well and I am polite, unlike other patients who are very arrogant because they're struggling to accept their situation.
It's then my occupational therapist's turn, Xavier, who says that I don’t work out with him anymore.
The astonished doctor asks me: “Mr Allétru, why don't you attend occupational therapy anymore ?"
I answered that Xavier, my occupational therapist, wanted to rehabilitate me exclusively for the wheelchair.
He wanted to teach me to ride straight, go up steps.
I had said to him, "Listen Xavier, I want to work on the mini contraction in my legs. with exercises that I could do daily."
He had answered, "You know Axel, your spinal cord is very badly damaged.
I don’t think you'll be able to walk again.
So I prefer to rehabilitate you for the wheelchair."
The chief doctor stupefied, said to me, "Mr Allétru, there're rules, you must respect them.
If Xavier says that you must be rehabilitated for the wheelchair, then you must do it.
From what I know, he has more experience than you in the area of rehabilitation."
He said, "In any case, if you don't respect the rules, I'll have to expel you from the centre. And too much work could make you regress."
At that point, I became speechless.
The chief rehabilitation doctor telling one of his patients that working too hard could make them regress ?
I couldn’t believe my ears!
I leave the meeting.
I go to see my physiotherapist, Gaëlle, and I ask, "Why such a reaction?"
She said to me, "Axel, you aren't like the other patients.
You work hard, you make progress, but you must respect the rules, or you could really be expelled from the rehabilitation centre and not be able to progress at all."
So, I said, "Okay.
I will 'respect the rules.'"
But I had a little idea in the back of my mind.
I asked my parents to bring me some weights so that I could work alone in my room, at night.
I tried to copy the exercises that Gaëlle had me do in physiotherapy, alone in my room after diner.
I did series of 10, of 15.
My parents also made me some parallel bars, with a harness and a pulley, so that I could work at home during the weekends.
After a few months, at last, I am able to attend balneotherapy sessions. It is a very important moment for me, because it was the first time that I could stand up, I could stand up in the water.
This was a first step.
As sessions goes by, I begin to stand up with less pressure on my arms.
And Gaëlle, my physiotherapist, says, "Listen, Axel, I think that we could maybe have you stand up on firm ground, between the parallel bars."
But to do that, we need to make a brace so that I could try to compensate my paralysed muscles.
We decide to contact the father of a childhood friend who is an ortho-prosthetist.
Three weeks later, he had made a brace for me.
And finally, the big day arrived: I put my braces on. I face the parallel bars. Gaëlle stood in front of me. Then, I gather momentum, and puf!
I can stand up.
I can stand up on my two legs on firm ground.
I can tell you, it was quite an accomplishment.
I could once again see the world from the height of my 1.90m.
I remember everyone in the room had clapped for me.
It was such an important moment, and I was really proud of myself.
Progressively with each session, I make my first step, then a second, then a walk forwards, then a walk backwards. Then, I can go back and forth
hundreds of times in a row.
But I arrive at a moment when the parallel bars are all fine but I can’t move around autonomously.
So Gaëlle bring me a walker with which I try to walk again.
But I lose my balance.
Though I work hard and I try to do all I could, I don't make any progress.
I can't do it.
I’d been in rehabilitation for almost one year and time has come to think about my future.
What would become of me?
I’m only 20 years old, so why not start studying again or continue practising sports?
After all, sport is my life.
At that point, I decide to join a parasport swimming club where I started to go swimming every Saturday.
I thought it could only do good to me, and might also help me to progress further.
I think that it was an important decision because It enabled me little by little to rediscover the real world.
And I realized that although I was in a wheelchair, I could make new friends, restore my social life.
Because sometimes in the rehabilitation centre, patients are afraid of progressing for fear of leaving the rehabilitation centre and return to the real world.
In the rehabilitation centre everyone has a disability.
Nurses are there to help us, everyone make room in the hallways. So sometimes, it’s difficult to leave the rehabilitation centre.
When I finished rehabilitation, I feel like I need to embark on a new challenge, a challenge in my new life, to get up every morning.
Today, my daily routine, is to become a paralympic swimmer.
I set myself the goal of competing in the Paralympic games in Rio in 2016.
Since 2014, I have been a member of the French team.
I won many titles as French champion, European champion, record holder.
I've managed to recreate what I was before in the able-bodied world but this time, in parasport.
I am autonomous: I can drive, I can ride a bicycle.
I can do all sorts of things. but in an adapted way.
But today, the most important thing is that I can move around with my two lifters, always, and my two crutches.
(Applause) I can walk one, two, maybe even three kilometres.
I can even walk with a single crutch if I want.
You weren’t expecting that, were you, when I arrived in a wheelchair ?
(Laughter) I went back to visit the rehabilitation centre and the staff was very impressed by my progress.
They didn’t think that I could make any more progress after leaving the rehabilitation centre.
I went back to see that famous doctor: "So, doctor!
(Laughter)
I walk again." He answered, "Mr Allétru, you were very, very lucky."
I look at him and said,
"No, no! It isn’t luck.
it is doggedness and hard work."
So now, you are wondering if I achieved my goal to compete in Rio.
Well yes, I qualified in March.
At the French swimming championship, I achieved the required standards for 2016.
But unfortunately, a few weeks before Rio, I was moved to another category, with people who were less handicapped.
And as the effect is immediate and the times much harder, I was sadly unable to participate in Rio.
But when I was hospitalized, right after my accident, if I had been told, "Listen Axel, if you sign here, at the bottom, you’ll walk again, but you will never be a paralympic champion," I think that I wouldn’t have hesitated one second.
From this whole journey, I have learnt one thing: resilience.
Today, what I try to demonstrate daily is that life can be cruel and generous at the same time.
I bear no grudge against life.
I’ve learnt to be resilient and resilience has also taught me to accept things, to accept things as they are, without anger.
Indeed by accepting, I've been able to keep going forward rather than to stop ; I've been able to keep moving rather than vegetate at home, doing nothing.
But, a word of caution: accepting has nothing to do with resigning yourself.
You have the choice to live like a victim, but you will never have access to the other option: believing that it’s possible.
Thank you.
(Applause)
My standing in front of you results from my once having misplaced a worked exam paper in a file binder.
When I was a teenager, I used to fix everything around the house,
and put together electronic boards. Putting it succinctly, my professional carrier was all sorted: I would be an electronic engineer.
The entrance exam day arrived for the flagship school not very far from here in France's silicon valley.
Electronics test, very heavily weighted.
I return home, confident,
I open my binder,
I find a copy there, the section at the sixth tab, one so poorly written I thought it must be a draft, one I had not gone back over.
I failed the entrance exam for my dream school by 1 point out of 500.
On this day, my professional career changed direction.
I would not be an electronic engineer, but an optics engineer.
And today, I'm going to talk to you about light and resonance, and we're going to play around with them.
We'll begin with - If you think of resonance, the word can refer to a signal that echoes back to you.
Here yo see two everyday objects that you recognize: a flashlight, and a laser pointer.
These two objects are two sources of light.
They behave very differently, and yet at the heart of these two objects, there's the same generator of light that we call a diode.
This diode sends light in all directions.
That’s why they're used for lighting.
The rays propagate in straight lines.
Imagine inserting this diode inside a box, a box made up of two mirrors facing each other.
The rays propagate in all directions, leave the box except when they strike an obstacle.
When they hit an obstacle, they behave as if in a game of ping-pong. I don't know if you know this game, but it's probably the only game parents know better than children. Anyway, the thing that's important to me is that the only rays that can go back and forth multiple times are those that transverse on a path perpendicular to the two mirrors.
And it's in that way that you obtain a light output composed of single rays
sharply aligned in one direction. In the same way it is said that an argument made up of several ideas is coherent if the ideas go parallel in the same direction, scientists and engineers also call light like that "coherent."
Why is this useful?
Well, you may know that our French silicon valley, where we are, will, at the end of this year, be the first area 100% connected by fiber.
This, this is a fiber.
This is the fiber that comes to your home.
And you can easily imagine that it’s much easier to inject light when you have a highly directional beam than when you have a flashlight because this is a very fine glass tube, extremely narrow.
And it carries your emails, your videos, all your data, by transmitting light in the form of ones and zeros:
when there is light, it's a "one";
when there isn't, it’s a "zero."
So, light is useful, but why is an optical fiber so interesting?
Because it’s a transparent medium.
No surprise, it's glass!
It has an attenuation of only 4%.
This means that if you send 100 light particles, 96 will arrive after traveling 1 kilometer.
That's fantastic.
But, if they go 2 kilometers, the attenuation is 0.96 times 0.96. After 3 kilometers, 0.96 times 0.96 times 0.96.
If you want to cross the ocean, it will be 0.96 to the power of 6,000.
If you have a calculator that has the capacity to do the calculation - not all have - you will find that it's 0.000000... 107 zeros.
To give you an idea of what such an attenuation represents, let’s suppose that I want to receive a single photon, a single particle of light, after propagation over 6,000 kilometers.
Well, it would be necessary to inject into the fiber billions of billions of times the energy of the universe.
You might argue that I do not know exactly the energy of the universe.
Does that matter? The fiber will have melted long before!
And yet, you can carry information to the other side of the Atlantic Ocean and converse with people in the United States, for example.
How do we do it?
Once again, it's resonance that comes to our rescue. A different resonance,
one where we say two vibrations resonate in agreement with one another.
Suppose the light is in accord with a vibration in the material of the fiber, one which can convert to light.
This is what can happen.
Sir, have you ever heard of erbium? No...
Madam?
You neither.
It is not a material found in DIY stores and yet it is essential in today's Internet.
It is a material, which, introduced into the glass in small quantities, provides the property to vibrate, to store the vibration, provided by an intense light source.
We say it becomes excited.
Then, the propagated signal that has become feebler will be able to take up energy that the erbium returns to it.
Thereby, one photon becomes two photons, two become four, and so on, until the initial amplitude of the signal is recovered.
If you insert such a component, each just a few meters long, every 50 or 100 kilometers, you reach your destination easily.
Now, you're going to ask how much energy is required to transmit - taking an extreme case - all the data sent from Europe to recipients in the United States in one hour.
Well, it will take roughly the energy contained in a dozen flashlights like this one. No more.
You see that resonance is very useful.
Now, let’s consider another very different form of resonance.
Etymologically, a "resonance" is a sounding again, a recurring vibration.
I would like us to do a test together.
I would like you to imagine me a pop star, the pop star you came to see, and I would like you to applaud me.
(Applause) (Clapping in unison) Thank you.
(Clapping in unison) Thank you - I didn't deserve so much. (Clapping subsides)
I didn't deserve so much.
Did you sense the moment when - the time when you were clapping at random and the vibrations had no relation to one another, and then when you all clapped
synchronously in rhythm with each other? You became aware of the growing volume, amplification?
That's what resonance is about.
It also works for light.
If you could use a microscope to look extremely closely at a ray of light, you would see a wave, hence a vibration.
If we are interested in how vibrations combine, we find that when they are uncoordinated, we obtain a vibration with an amplitude that increases only very slightly with the number of rays.
On the other hand, if you have the vibrations align peak-to-peak with each other, you get the sort of amplification that you all experienced by applauding simultaneously.
It's this effect that allows us to obtain a coherent addition of vibrations.
You followed me, I'd explained clearly, and you came to realize that you all needed to clap in time with one another.
When we talk about light and frequency, it's color that determines the number of vibration, the frequency of vibrations.
If you want all the vibrations to align peak-to-peak, there must be absolutely only one color.
Because if you combine all colors, the combination of the vibrations can only be incoherent.
In what way is this useful to us?
I could have used the laser pointer and reminded you how one can produce such an intense beam.
The directivity of the beam is not our only concern: we also make sure that every round-trip that light makes inside that box is always in line with all the previous ones.
As that can only occur when there's just one color, the box also acts as a filter. In other words, light that was initially white - and white is not a color, but the sum of all colors - well, of all the colors there are, only one can come out.
All the colors that are not resonant become eliminated.
That’s why you can have a laser giving an extremely pure green light.
If I had chosen a box of a different size, I would have gotten another color.
This is very practical in an optical telecommunication system, where multiplying the number of colors multiplies the number of recipients by the same amount.
The good news is that it works both ways.
Once we have multiple colors, we need to extract the colors. We can use the same box.
If we have 100 colors, we will need 100 boxes of different sizes, each to extract a different color.
So we’ve seen that resonance can be used to build a complete telecommunication system ... and this is where the story of the forgotten paper comes back in.
Ten years ago, we were a group of eight researchers, a few kilometers from here, looking for a solution to keep up with the extraordinary rise in data traffic through optical fibers.
And we had an idea.
What you might usually expect to get when combining two beams is a beam that is twice as bright.
That is what we do to get the resonance effect.
But what if summing the amplitudes of these two beams results in an amplitude
lower than the original ones, we, in fact, subtract them, as we'd say in math, but to which we give the fancy term "destructive addition."
In fact, it's another way of saying that we allow them to interfere.
Interference is when you can bring two beams together and produce the absence of a beam, that is, an absence of light.
This is another way of coding information.
It’s no longer just a matter of switching the laser beam on and off, but of playing with another method, another property of light, controlling its vibrational state.
The technique that we have developed has become an industry standard.
It has increased the system capacity by a factor of 10 worldwide.
Today, it represents a 12-billion-euro turnover in equipment installed annually worldwide.
You've even used it yourselves.
I'm thinking particularly of those I lost when I spoke about video games earlier, and who, since I mentioned them, have been trawling the Internet to find out what I was talking about.
Is this the end of the marriage between optics and coherence?
Probably not.
Imagine a world where fiber could read its acoustic environment, be sensitive to what's going on around it, for example, an excavator passing by. The fiber would be informed of what is going on before it was cut. Or cars passing through our region could be counted in order to regulate traffic.
This kind of resonance is the kind we are looking to use in the future.
You understand now that I almost missed this exciting adventure.
It was very near thing.
Just that one minute of distraction when I misplaced an exam example.
That one minute whereby a science less familiar to me opened itself to me.
What if that one minute, for you, was now and in this room?
Thank you.
(Applause)
So, as you already know, I'm a game designer.
In French, we say: 'concepteur de jeux vidéo'.
The two most common reactions I get when I tell people this are: "Wow, you get to play video games all day long," which isn't quite true, or, the other reaction: "So what are you?
Like a scriptwriter for video games?"
That isn't it either.
I find that a good way to explain what I do
is to say that I define what is possible for the gamers and what isn't.
I set out a scope of possibility for them.
When we're designing a game, obviously we want it to be a success, and to make it as successful as possible, we have to understand what motivates our gamers.
This is a very important consideration.
Ultimately, I wonder about the differences between the video games I played as a child and the video games my son plays today.
Because a talk isn't a real talk unless you mention your kids.
The video games I played as a child were the games on the first Nintendo console.
The first game that was truly significant to me was Mario Bros.
It's a game with a very specific goal: to save the princess. There's a single way to do that: by going from the left to the right of the screen, jumping over obstacles, jumping over gaps, and crushing your opponents.
You could say it's a pretty linear game, in the sense that there's one objective and only one real way of achieving it: by overcoming the challenges you're faced with.
It requires your dexterity and reflexes.
Of all the games my son plays, Minecraft is his favourite.
It's a game you've probably heard of. In the game, you're immersed in a universe made of cubes. My son spends his time destroying these cubes to collect resources, such as wood, stones and earth and then makes new things with them.
He can make tools and objects,
as well as houses, buildings, bridge and castles.
It's a game that really encourages his creativity.
The games I play nowadays are games inspired by my era, that are largely based on action games like Mario.
They're what we refer to as "open world" games, like Assassin's Creed, which we make at Ubisoft, the company I work for, or like Grand Theft Auto.
In these games, there are real challenges but it's also opened up with 3D in 360°.
You're not stuck in one shot.
You can go wherever you want. There are objectives scattered all over, and you choose where you're going to complete them, and often, how you're going to complete them.
So there's already an evolution happening in terms of freedom.
It's interesting that my son also plays Mario.
He plays a new Mario game that came out this year, for the 30th anniversary of Mario Bros, called "Mario Maker".
Instead of directly playing and saving the princess himself, my son can create levels for Mario.
So he becomes a designer. There are tools that help him place blocks and enemies. You can see the way things have changed over 25 years -- the difference between a 7 year old who plays the game, like I was, and my son, who effectively creates his own levels.
We must consider the impact that these activities we spend so much time on as children can have on generations to come?
The more time he spends on them, the more his creativity will develop.
What is the underlying motivation for these gamers?
The motivational model that interests us, and which fits best with gaming, is the theory of self-determination. This model was developed in the 1970s by Rayan and Deci, who identified three main motivations.
The first is competence.
It's interesting to see how much this has always been present in gaming.
Competence is feeling comfortable and progressing in an activity where you feel competent.
In gaming, that's exactly what you want.
You're constantly improving the more you play a game.
The second is relatedness. This means being in contact with others and being useful to them, and vice versa.
Through online gaming, which have really exploded in popularity in the past few years, we really see this social dimension.
The third motivation, which is increasingly present and interesting to us
is autonomy.
In the theory of motivation, we see autonomy as something that allows us to create our own objectives and our own way of solving them.
In games like Minecraft, there is, strictly speaking, no real objective.
The gamer creates his own objectives and gets even more creative to solve them.
This makes us think: if gamers have this much freedom, what will they do next?
Do we only see this in video gaming?
No, we're seeing the scope of possibility widening across many areas.
It's the same for other pastimes.
When I watched TV as a child, I chose the channel and I watched a programme at a set hour.
My son watches YouTube and can choose whatever programme he wants.
Or there's Netflix, which has an enormous amount of choice; the field of possibility for him is huge.
We also see it in other generations. Knowledge is very accessible with sites like Wikipedia, where you can find information very easily by following links.
If you want to find your soul mate, there are so many ways to do this. Look at Tinder. it's expanding possibilities for each and every one of us.
We see it in other areas too, such as education.
In education, we try to develop situations for the student to demonstrate their knowledge and experience different activities, like the Montessori approach.
We can also see it in management.
In management, we're increasingly turning away from patriarchal leadership models in favour of more democratic models. We're seeing autonomy
increasing across the board.
We can ask ourselves: How will the generations brought up in this way, playing Minecraft rather than Mario Bros, turn out in the future?
What will we be able to offer them?
We also know that this multitude of choice can create anxiety.
This is something we often find in gaming.
If the games I create offer too much choice, that can be stressful.
There's even a phenomena called 'analysis paralysis'. When there are too many options, and the options aren't different enough, it can hold back the action.
My job as a game designer, is to provide the scope of possibility, and the gamers of today want and ever-larger field of possibility, but still with constraints, and with interesting choices offered to them.
It's the classic situation for us game designers, which comes from Sid Meier, the creator of Civilization, who said that a good game is a series of interesting choices.
If we're asked to create products and services and supervise people, what are we going to offer to students who grew up with Minecraft and are used to having so much freedom and a huge amount of autonomy?
Perhaps one of you will be a game designer yourselves.
You'll have to think of what motivates your co-workers, clients or students and offer spaces of freedom by developing the scope of possibility, rather than an authoritative model that only give them one choice.
All this autonomy must be drawn on to be able to create offerings that will be better tailored to future generations.
Thank you.
(Applause)
“There is more hunger for love and appreciation in this world than for bread.”
Clearly, Mother Teresa had not tasted the good French bread!
(Laughter) More seriously, I spend my life searching for love everywhere I go, receiving it, and giving it.
It’s true, maybe I was a hippy in a past life.
But I quickly understood that I was not the only one, that others were searching for this deep connection too.

Why? Because when love is present, there is no fear, but there is life!
I remember the story of a friend who lived alone in the city.
She was 50 years old and hated her job.
And she didn’t take
very good care of herself.
She had an opportunity to travel - thanks to her employer nonetheless - on a philanthropic action on the other side of the world, with the Dalits Indians, the untouchables, the oppressed, the outcasts of Indian society.
It was a 10 days trip, but she came back traumatized.
Everything in this trip shocked her.
How can human beings be treated this way?
How can someone live in such poverty?
She was shocked and upset by everything there.
When she came home, she told everyone: “I will never go back to India. It was too emotionally heavy.”
Then, she didn’t seek to change anything in her life.
She returned to the same job,
and as far as I could tell and observe, she hadn’t really grown from this experience.
I’ve often asked myself about the quite widespread desire to travel so far from one’s home for self-discovery.
Probably because I too, left my country a very long time ago to come to France and leave my homeland in search of myself.
I quickly understood in my life that, ultimately, it’s important to cultivate the love of yourself and others right where you are, here and now, and then take care of this self-love.
Jack Kornfield said, “If your compassion does not include yourself, it is incomplete.”
Reconnection starts with oneself.
Society tells us relentlessly, “Love yourself, love others,
get along with others,” but who teaches us how to do that?
School doesn’t, and it’s not necessarily done at home.
And yet, the value, the “joie de vivre,” the connection to life that we have that comes out of those encounters and those interactions with others, this reconnection with others is tremendous.
In Novembre 2003, I went back to California to be with my sick mother.
She was dying of lung cancer, in its terminal phase,
and she didn't even smoke!
I went to be with her and give her all that I could.
Upon arriving, I was overtaken by a deep sadness and revolt, and a lot of fear in the face of this disease that was attacking her, so much so that I didn’t want to be by her side when she would take her last breath.
Two weeks pass by, and I started to reconcile with my emotions.
I started to open up to them.
I started to avoid escaping them and wishing to understand and control everything.
And that gave me a deep love connection with my mother.
I will always remember a conversation we had, in the last 10 days before she passed away.
We were at her home, the sun
was shining bright in southern California.
[I remember] the oxygen bottles, the vials of morphine on her bedside table, the permeating odor of the illness.
I was so overtaken by a sense of guilt for having left her, and gone so far away, an 11-hours flight from California all the way to France.
We seldom saw each other, maybe once in a year.
Submerged by this horrible feeling, I asked her to forgive me for having left her.
At that moment, she took my hand,
looked at me with her soft eyes and a large smile,
and then she pulled me close to her and said to me, “I’m so proud of you, David.
I admire your independence.
I love you so much.
Forget about all that.”
I didn’t cry at all.
(Laughter) And by chance, I was able to be by her side when she gave her last breath.
Empathy and a big heart can be a universal language between us which connects us to who we truly are.
It’s more of an emotional exchange rather than of the ego.
It’s the opportunity to feel that we are all part of the biggest community of the world.
We are all members of the Humanity Club.
Isn’t that cool?!
(Laughter) We talk a lot about different generations but what about the Humanity Generation?
We’re all part of it!
And we can make the most of that in our everyday lives.
It’s like an everyday life playing field that we have around us.
If we opened ourselves to others, shared a glance, a kind word, we could interact and give to each other in ways that make us understand that we are all part of this world.
So let’s do a little local survey together, if you don’t mind.
How many of you know at least five neighbors in your building or your neighborhood?
That’s pretty good, well done!
Do you seek to focus on what unites you when you spend time with them?
Or do you look for what separates you, what differentiates you, and causes problems between you?
Do you try to create a real relationship with them?
It’s always useful to have someone to turn to when we’re out of sugar, isn’t it?
(Laughter) Now, let's see what the Dalai Lama says about this, “I’m Tibetan, I’m Buddhist and I’m the Dalai Lama, but if I identified myself to all those reductive identities, it would set me apart from others and raise barriers between us and me.
What we need is to pay more attention to the things that unite us, that bring us together.”
I create sensorial and emotional experiences around the world, and they’re always incredible moments for myself and others.
You leave your smartphone in a safe for the day, can you imagine?!
Then you really seek to connect, focus and concentrate on the encounter with the other.
So you arrive and you don’t try to focus on job titles and labels, on what each person does for a living, the car in which they arrived, their job, their salary nor their skin color.
We focus on the people who are present, sometimes well-known, sometimes not known at all.
And we dance; we sing; we listen to poets, to speakers; we eat succulent foods all throughout the day.
At times you are a spectator,
and other times an active participant.
Some would perhaps see it as some sort of sect, others as just a party, and many others as a transformational experience, one of the best days of their life.
But why?
Simply because we all need to love and appreciate others, and also be loved and appreciated by others.
William Blake well said, “The true method of knowledge is esperience.”
So, would you like to have a small taste of this experience of self-discovery and adventure with another?
And give each other some courage and kindness, here and now?
Are you ready?
(Audience) Yes!
So please stand up.
Turn towards the person next
to you and close your eyes.
Put your right hand on your heart, the love inside you.
Put your left hand on your stomach, your courage.
Then breathe deeply three times.
Inhale.
Exhale.
Inhale, to receive.
Exhale, to give.
Give yourself the empathy, kindness and appreciation that you would like to receive from others.
Feel that you are part of the Humanity Club.
Okay, now open your eyes and look very gently, with kindness, at the person you are facing.
Take them by their arms, please.
Inhale, to receive;
Exhale, to give.
Give this person the feeling of shared bond, that you are both part of this large community, the Humanity Club, that nothing can separate you and everything can bring you together.
Breath well.
You are her, you are them,
You are all the others who are in this room.
You are the Indian Dalits.
You are the humanity, alive and vibrant.
Breath deeply.
Express to one another the happiness you feel in being part of this magnificent community.
Now, please come back ... if you can!
(Laughter) Congratulate the other, thank him ... (Applause) for having shared with you courageously ... (Applause) Well done!
... for having shared with you courageously their deepest humanity, their kindness, here, now, together.
You will see, in your next encounters, it’s going to be much easier.
You have already grown emotionally, right here.
You will see in life situations, little or big, very intimate and less intimate, you can start to experiment more around you with every encounter in your life.
In this way, you can expand your capacity to offer this enormous humanity that is inside us.
You have felt deeply here the power of real connection with others. It means to choose to reconnect with oneself and one’s emotions, and of course, one’s “joie de vivre,” and to focus on what unites you, not what separates you, here, now, everywhere.
And also, it’s really great to be on a treasure hunt to find love everywhere, trust me!
Eckart Tolle summarized it well, “To love is to recognize yourself in another.”
Thank you.
(Applaudissements)
Yes.
No.
But yes.
No.
That's not for me.
A TEDx talk? No, no!
First of all, I'm way too shy.
I'll never be able to speak in public! I'm too shy.
The scariest thing is you are all looking at me.
You're here looking at me, and I'm sure that the only thing you hear is my voice trembling.
I'm sure that the only thing you see is my lips pinching and my hands wringing, my voice getting faster without me being aware of it, my words getting confusing and my ideas getting mixed up ... All these things put together create uncontrollable stammerings that might make my speech incomprehensible.
My whole life, I've felt imprisoned by shyness and lack of self-confidence.
For example, when I mingle with a group of friends, I'm never the first to share my opinion, make a decision, or say something funny.
My whole life, I've limited myself by telling myself that I couldn't do it, that I was too shy, and that it wasn't for me.
I often gave up when a difficulty arose, and I always chose to flee rather than facing the problem and assert myself.
Despite all that, I think there are positive things about being shy.
In which ways can shyness be advantageous?
I always considered my shyness to be one of my biggest flaws until I learned that Montesquieu had the same difficulty.
Can you imagine that Montesquieu,
a man whom you and everyone know,
one of the most important men of the Age of Enlightenment, and a great lawyer, was shy? Really?
Could you believe this?
He even wrote in his work "My Thoughts": "Shyness has been the curse of my whole life."
But is shyness really a curse as our famous philosopher says?
Does being shy really only have a downside?
Couldn't it be seen as an asset?
Indeed, being a timid person
also has its advantages.
As a matter of fact, shy people are wonderful conversation partners.
They listen more, they are discreet, and they really don't want to make themselves the center of attention.
This means that they are not going to show signs of arrogance, they won't have inflated pride or ego, and they won't proudly show off their latest iPhone or other expensive brands that indicates wealth.
On the contrary, shy people stay humble, and that's something that is becoming more and more rare in our society.
That's how I realized that shyness can be harnessed so that it becomes a strength.
Since Montesquieu was shy, he was a calm and thoughtful person, and this was surely a factor in his success.
I think we should find a good balance. We should be able to be daring but without going too far; and we should be able to think before we act without being afraid or ashamed to speak out.
Why am I not daring?
What am I afraid of?
Is it because I'm a girl?
In general, boys speak more than girls in class.
I don't know why the other girls don't speak, but what I do know is that if I'm not sure of an answer, I prefer not to have the floor.
Obviously, I'm not the only one.
I don't question the goodwill of teachers.
I know that consciously, they do everything to make all of us successful, boys and girls together.
However, I discovered, thanks to a study by the Belgian Teaching and Continuing Education League, that in 2012 two sociologists filmed classes in France in primary and secondary schools, that showed that some teachers subconsciously engage in behaviors that value and encourage the boys more.
Subconsciously, they ask girls to be more well-behaved and boys to surpass themselves.
In other words, they encourage boys to be daring.
Do boys have greater rights to make mistakes,
or do they simply allow themselves to make more mistakes?
I myself have the right to make mistakes,
but I prefer not to make them.
Why?
Why do I dare to be perfect?
Just on the way here, I saw and all of us saw at least ten posters of women with perfect physiques that were glorifying the merits of clothes, makeup and perfume.
What's striking about those posters is that all these women are perfect but mute.
This requirement of perfection is not only imposed on us on those posters and in advertising, but also from a very early age.
A study from the sociology book "Allez, les filles" in 2006, showed that girls are encouraged to develop themselves according to how others see them while constantly seeking adults' approval.
Why are women less daring than men?
In my school, and surely elsewhere too, girls have better results than boys.
Yet, men are the ones who get the highest positions in society in the end.
Why?
So I decided to conduct a small investigation of my own
and asked several boys that question.
And do you know what answer they gave me?
They all gave me the same answer and told me,
"That's because we're more dominant.
It's a fact, how things naturally are."
Maybe what they say is true, but I'm not so sure.
What if it were precisely because they suggest us, or even worse, they inculcate in us all day long the idea that men are more dominant so that we ended up accepting and integrating that condition?
Can we really accept that?
I'm not okay with that.
I don't accept that we constantly put limits on ourselves whatever they might be.
We all have something that we don't dare do,
whether it be singing in public, jumping off a cliff into the water, confess our love to someone, or avoiding competition because we feel we're not strong enough.
The truth is that we're all the same.
We're afraid.
We're afraid that things will go bad.
We're afraid to disappoint either other people or ourselves. We're afraid of failure, and of what some people might think.
That's why we limit ourselves because we don't want to take risks.
But I'm sure that many of you know the famous saying: "Nothing ventured is nothing gained."
My advice is ... apply it!
Take the bull by its horns.
Go beyond your limits and be daring.
Let's be daring!
Personnally, I don't want to keep silent. Even if my voice shakes, I pinch my lips and I wring my hands, I don't want to be silent!
I came here. I dared to do it. And I'm here to tell everyone to be daring too, and never, ever, ever say that something isn't for them.
Thank you.
(Applause)
Feminism has long been a women's thing.
Woo! Well, actually, it's totally logical: we're the ones primarily involved.
Let's see if there are women here.
Make some noise, please.
Marie Beauchesne: Woo!
(Audience) Woo! OK, awesome, super, that's great.
So, well, what are the men doing now?
Are they concerned? Do they have the right to be feminists?
I am a feminist and fashion entrepreneur.
An entrepreneur since last year and a feminist since always.
Because it's always seemed incomprehensible to me that women have less recognition, less freedom, just because of their sex.
So, for me, being a feminist has always been very natural.
However, what was a lot less natural was:
As a feminist, how can I interact with men?
Do I need them?
Are they of any use to the cause?
No, right?
No. When I was little, the answer was, "No", or even outright, "Of course not."
The reason: boys have the right to do more things.
However, it's found they don't
get the grades at school. Politicians are all grey-haired men. If I am to believe history lessons, grey-haired men have done nothing but mess up for 2,000 years, especially during the last century.
When a model doesn't work,
we replace it. QED.
But why are we waiting to replace men with women?
(Applause) Well, that's where I was in my "anti-man feminism" period, which was fuelled by both a desire for revenge for history and a deep sense of injustice that started on the playground.
Why can they brawl, and why can't I slap them when today I'm not amused by forced-kisses games?
Why do adults find these differences normal?
And why is it that I'm told:
"Marie, calm down, it's normal,
he's a boy, boys do that."
Oh, yeah? Well, that sucks.
This kind of fatalistic argument,
"That's normal, boys do that",
I've heard it a lot, heard it too much.
And I tell you, both my parents were psychologists, so it was sort of their job to ask why.
So I too learned how to ask questions, but it wasn't enough for me.
I wanted to put things back into question.
In fact, I wanted to change the world.
When I was 17, I left boarding school, I left Brittany, and got into political science.
I worked a lot, I partied a lot, too, and I discovered I'm bisexual.
It wasn't easy right away; far from it in every respect.
But at least in terms of feminism, it was really much simpler.
At that time, guys, they were mates or sex toys.
Some of them don't seem to find it cool.
I agree with you, it's not cool.
It's not cool to treat someone
like an object.
But I get treated like that too, as do a lot of other 20-year-old girls.
On the street, on nights out, on holiday, on a daily basis.
Well, accept it, play along, do the same thing; ultimately, it was simpler, stronger, and almost a way to level the playing field.
That was my period of "feminism without men".
For sure, I didn't choose to fall in love with a woman:
neither the first time, nor the next.
Nonetheless, I chose to engage with LGBT culture, and I discovered a world where, in fact, people are more likely to pose questions about what is meant by gender, sex, sexuality, what it means beyond being a man, a woman. It's something that has greatly nourished and interested me.
I first took an interest in it alone, on the Internet, reading about it, and then in New York with my girlfriend of the time, who was an American of Asian origin.
There I discovered the concept of "intersectionality".
In Paris, we were in the middle of an age of "marriage for all", so I joined a group. It was an important fight for me. And that's the way I went on for some years.
And then, since we don't choose whom we fall in love with, I ended up getting attached to a man.
That wasn't the plan, it didn't go well, and it was a bad experience.
But we'll stop there, because it was a while back, part of my "search for identity", and above all, then, I needed to pay more attention to my existential crises: "I've a degree, what am I going to do??"
So first, I went into advertising.
At the same time, I took evening classes in fashion design, in couture, and I realized how much fashion needed different kinds of models, to present different types of femininity, those that have things to say, stories to tell, and to get past having models that are just there to look pretty,
with 24-inch waists, soaking wet, and retouched if necessary.
No more of that.
That's why I created my brand, Ypsylone, that I launched into women's ready-to-wear, and, paradoxically, that's also when I entered my phase "feminism with men".
There are many I don't want to label as being "all the same".
There's my brother, there's some friends, there are coworkers, mentors, men who want to help, who have helped me, who won't be empowered if we don't empower them, and who won't call themselves feminists if they feel they're being excluded.
Well, OK, we must all fight our own battles.
But to get anywhere, you need to know how to disseminate and bring together.
I have also learned the lessons of my "feminism without men" period, exploring my shifting identity by making peace with the masculine around me ... within me, too.
To be honest, I'm still working on it, but at least I've understood that, basically, we have the same problem.
The problem isn't male domination,
it's the domination of a binary gender model that imposes itself on everyone, male and female.
So we put men aside saying: "Well, men have privileges, they don't even realize it, they just behave too badly, they don't understand this or that."
It's good to bitch, but it feeds the idea that feminism is our problem, not theirs.
So when a guy asks me if I think that feminism is still useful - believe me, it still happens often in my personal and professional life - I want to tell him, "Of course feminism is useful."
It's useful when it comes to differences in pay, beauty standards, street harassment. There are still so many things to change.
Feminism is useful for me, but it's also useful for you.
Because if women are always to be induced into stereotypical sweetness, you'll always be left to do what is expected of manhood.
If women are automatically the victims, you'll automatically be the oppressor, the culprit.
And if we continue to always define women in terms of how they are opposite to men, well, we're going to be stuck with it.
And coming out of opposition allows for agreement between everyone.
Generally, it starts with a common definition.
And there, I think we've got problems, because it's 2016, and clearly the word "feminism" still frightens a lot of men and women.
However, I'm convinced it's mostly a huge misunderstanding.
You know Emma Watson, don't you?
OK, cool. Good.
For those of you who don't know her,
she played Hermione in Harry Potter,
she joined UN Women, she started the HeForShe movement, and she gave an extraordinary speech on gender equality.
You'd think that a definition of feminism based on equality would get everyone to agree.
It's a pretty nice, consensual value.
It turns out it doesn't.
If you're a feminist, you will have had this type of reaction: "Oh, yeah, feminism, it's the people who are for gender equality, right?
Well, ooph, I'm not sure I'm a feminist, you know, I don't want everyone to be the same, it's sad. And then, what, we all have dicks, we time how long we spend in the kitchen, the men are afraid to open doors for us?
No, frankly, our difference, it's poetry, it's genetic, all that sort of thing. For people generally,
biologically, it's natural, we're different."
OK, poetry, biology, very well.
Well, I find it too simple, too easy, to invoke the authoritarian argument of nature and biology when it suits us, and put it aside when it doesn't. But, deep down, I don't either. I'm not for equality between men and women.
For sure, I'm not for inequality. But for me, feminism is not a question of equality,
it's a question of freedom.
In fact, I should put that definition to Emma Watson.
Shall we do it together?
We'll write her a letter: "Emma, I really need to say: Thank you.
If you only knew how great a pleasure it is to see a new feminism embodied by someone accessible, cool and sexy.
Hey yes, I did say 'cool and sexy'. Because image - it matters.
And feminism today also has an image problem.
By the way, Emma, it would be so cool to have a French version of you.
You've got it, I'm a big fan."
But more seriously,
we need to talk about this definition of feminism based on equality.
Equality always implies comparison and measurement.
We're equal to someone by reference to a standard.
It starts with great intentions, but it always puts women on one side and men on the other.
I'm put back in my lady's box, and I'm a woman, and that's it.
Men are, of course, placed above us, and they feel they owe us some consideration, to give us places on boards of directors, watch not to be macho when they're joking around, make an effort with the children, the household chores. While we, we have to seek, to ask, for the same things, the same treatments, the same status, the same standards.
Frankly, HR gender balance policies that look good in CSR reports - artificial equality, quotas - none of it says a thing to me.
Ultimately, I don't give a damn about having as much as a man.
What I'm interested in is being utterly and absolutely free.
I don't want to be an equal woman; I want to be a free woman.
I want to break out of the stereotypes imposed on everyone, both women and men.
For sure, in some countries where equality, education, the right to vote, is not guaranteed, legal equality is a basic need.
But when I talk about it here, in France, with some mates, what I see is a huge conflation of equality and egalitarianism.
"By the way, Emma, you'll find -"
Oh, Emma's disappeared. Never mind.
Emma will see this is a French problem that goes beyond feminism.
Without doubt, the legal foundation for equality exists here now.
What we need to do is to change our way of thinking so that we can all be
more free, women and men.
Full stop.
I forgot a little P.S. to Emma: "Emma, I love to have a chat over a glass of wine, and if your feminist friend, Justin Trudeau, is available, he's also cordially invited."
There you are.
Now, it's up to you to choose.
It's up to you to choose the definition that suits you:
freedom, equality, risk everything.
It doesn't matter.
A definition is not a fight in itself.
It's a way to come together and find what you agree on.
As you've seen, it took me a little while and several phases of feminism to understand that, fundamentally, feminism had to be a fight, a unisex movement, and that's why I'm offering you a new definition of feminism that is based above all on freedom.
Because we don't have, on the one hand, those who are the standard of equality, and, on the other, those, females, who need to acquire it.
We all stand to gain from being more free.
I still can't leave you without making a final confession, and without my addressing you specifically, gentlemen.
I would like to make it quite clear:
Men, I still don't understand you.
I really, really don't.
But I love you all the same, and I will defend your freedom as much as mine.
Thank you.
