When I received a call inviting me to come to the TEDxParis conference, I was afraid.
I thought, "What could I say to such a distinguished assembly, I who live among children?"
Still, I will try to share my humble experience with you,
of how I became a mother, or, rather, tried to become a mother.
I am a nun.
A nun usually lives in community with other nuns.
I live in community with children.
My community is the home called Our Lady of Nazareth, an orphanage.
I don't like that word very much because the children see it as a negative label.
It all started with my daily prison visit.
There was a little three-year-old boy, Albert. He was living with his mother, who was imprisoned for murder.
I was deeply moved by him.
I took him in and cared for him until his mother was released.
This spark that started in me became a consuming fire burning deep inside of me.
This fire caused me to make puzzling decisions, that were even scandalous for those close to me, and foolishness for the wise.
This fire is compelling.
It drives out fear.
Some of you have perhaps had this experience as well.
This is why on September 5, 1998, in order to be more available in my service to children in need, I, as a pioneer, left everything behind.
I left my congregation with around twenty children.
A nun does not have personal belongings.
I had neither home, nor money, nor health.
My only wealth was my trust in God.
The children and I were on the same level; we are still on the same level.
Therefore I don't have the pride, the satisfaction, and the arrogance of one who gives.
We live on contributions from Congolese people, among others, and from begging as well.
In fact, our current house was graciously lent to us by a French nun.
It's not always easy, - how embarrassing at times! -
but what wouldn't we do to bring joy to the children?
Today there are around sixty girls and boys, sick and healthy.
They call me "Mama".
They are entrusted to me by the UNHCR, the Red Cross, priests and nuns, and social programs, to fulfill their dreams, like going to school.
It's the very best door towards their future.
This is why many of them go to private school.
It's a big sacrifice, but I don't regret making it, because it's necessary.
Today Silas is continuing his university studies in Canada.
Work is the cornerstone of the home, and our daily prayer is the cement.
We have four work groups.
There is one older child at the head of each group, who reports back to me.
We have the cleaning group, that cleans the house and the courtyard.
We have the kitchen group, it's the most popular work, as you can imagine, there are many benefits to it.
There is a group that washes dishes after every meal.
There is the children's group.
This group takes care of the children's hygiene and safety.
Those are the guardian angels.
These groups switch every week, so that the responsibilities are shared, taking each child's abilities into account.
That way, no one is left by the wayside.
Every one has a place, and feels that they are valued.
There is no family without mutual trust.
For that to take place, communication must be a high priority.
Through communication, trust can grow.
My trust in them can help them have confidence in themselves.
In this way I seek to work towards their independence.
Helping one another is a cardinal virtue of our home.
The older children help the younger, they comfort them when they are sad.
The healthy help the sick.
Gemma and Charlotte, who are severely handicapped, benefit from everyone's attention.
Like all families, ours is not perfect.
We have plenty of problems and difficulties.
But for the two that cause trouble, there are twenty others to make things right.
Take Lucie, for example,
who avoids work at all costs. While Ted, Félicien and Ibrahim are always ready to lend a helping hand.
Little Grace, my mother, she is only twelve, she has a very serious illness, but she watches over me, makes sure I take my medecine.
There is no miracle formula for being a mother, which is why families are all different.
Ours is fragile, the children represent three nationalities: Rwandan, Congolese from the Democratic Republic of the Congo, and Congolese from Congo-Brazzaville, but our family is amazing. We stick together. and the older children give their very best in hard times, in joy, and in suffering.
Our family keeps going, full of hope, believing in life.
Our family thanks and expresses its gratitude to those who help it.
What I teach the children during their time with our family, is that they must do the task at hand well, and keep going until its done, whatever the cost.
Yes, love is the foundation for everything. Without it all initiatives are vain and fruitless.
(Applause)
Hello, Do you know the leading cause of death for children in Africa?
It's not famine, not AIDS, not Ebola.
It's the common cold.
That's what they call respiratory infections that are frequent and benign, but often result in pneumonia.
Over there, families don't go to the health center.
They don't know that it could become serious. They may not have money when their child is sick, or they're afraid they won't be welcome at the health center.
Today in Africa, one in ten children dies before the age of 5 from diseases as benign as the common cold that could be easily cured at local health centers.
We created Djantoli in 2007 to tackle this problem.
We started with a simple idea: weight is a good indicator that allows us to track a child's health.
Because families weren't going to the health center, we decided to use technology to make the doctor come to the families.
We designed a simple system to follow up with children in their homes. Agents make visits to the families and collect basic data to be sent to the doctor at the health center via a cell phone application so illnesses can be detected off-site.
Well, we quickly realized that detecting illness was good, but not enough if the families couldn't treat them.
So we added basic medical insurance to our follow-up system.
And we told ourselves, curing illness is good but it would be better to teach mothers how to prevent these illnesses.
So bit by bit, brick by brick, we developed Djantoli, an innovative response allowing mothers to look after their children's health.
So, how does it actually work?
Parents can subscribe their children to a health service that costs 75 cents (Euros) per child per month that includes regular home visits, reduced fees when their child goes to the health center, and a program that teaches hygiene practices. [TESTING-INSURANCE-EDUCATION]
By creating Djantoli, our main goal was to break out of a "helper" mindset and to make families voluntary and engaged actors concerning the health of their children.
Families want to pay for our services that match their expectations and are designed with their daily constraints in mind.
We launched the program four years ago in Bamako with 100 children. Today, four years later, we work in six neighborhoods in Bamako, and in two neighborhoods in Ouagadougou. We've followed 3,600 children.
And it works: the families sign up and they pay their monthly dues.
Our impact on sanitation
has been remarkable: Out of more than 3,600 children followed in four years,
That's one child in ten, four in 3,600.
So yes, this works.
It works because we decided to trust families. It works because we gave them the chance to become clients instead of beneficiaries.
As Avene Djantoli, Salime's mother, told us, "Djantoli baric ala ne bedem qu'a aue lea qu'acoloci..."
I like Djantoli because if he's OK I know it's because of me.
Thank you very much.
(Applause)
On my fortieth birthday, I was given a lemon tree as a birthday present, a Tahiti lime to be precise.
So, I don't know if you know what a Tahiti lime is, but it's the citrus fruit used in Ti' punch and mojitos.
Now you get it. It's always
clearer with an example.
This citrus tree was a bit like the trigger of a new passion for me.
Some years later, at the end of 2012, my professional life kind of swerved off course, and a problem presented itself that made me realize the path I was on was leading me to exhaustion.
I took a look at myself.
I was a business coach.
I had started my business four years prior.
So I had many professional and family burdens.
This was the consequence of four years
running my own company. Still, I was asking myself, "Why am I so exhausted?"
So I rested, I slowed down.
I had the good fortune to work with a friend who is a coach, and with him I looked at this notion of energy.
He talked about being in the flow.
The flow in professional life, is an internal state where, at a given time, I will be at maximum capacity to meet as many challenges as possible.
Although I thought I was in the flow - I had a career that I liked, the job of developing managers - I found out that one dimension was missing.
To explain what the flow is, let's use an image such as skiing.
I'm getting ready to ski on a black run that is very technical, very difficult.
The snow is pretty good, a bit powdery, a bit packed.
There's no one on the run, the sun is shining brightly.
I'm at peak performance, at maximum capacity, and off I go.
And then I feel the increasing enjoyment, the surge of adrenaline, the energy.
There's no thoughts in my mind, just the technicality, the pleasure, and the present moment.
That's being in the flow.
So although I considered myself in the flow, I found out that I was missing one ingredient.
And it was getting back to the land, to using gestures, and to the fact that, in my professional life, I needed to shape, to create, to create something aesthetically beautiful.
So I said to myself, "Ah... I know what I need!
I need to grow citrus fruits."
Meanwhile, over the four previous years, I had gone from one citrus tree to three or four.
I had a mandarin tree and a clementine tree.
Since then, it's become a passion.
Today, I have around 70 citrus trees, I'm still a business coach.
I have 70 citrus trees and they take up space.
My wife thinks they take up a lot of space, but it's like any passion, passion always takes up space!
So I learned to grow them since I wasn't a citrus tree grower at the beginning.
But what's really interesting is that, actually, while I was learning how to look after the citrus trees, the citrus trees were teaching me how to look after my own life.
And so, this is what I'd like to share with you tonight: the six big lessons of wisdom from citrus cultivation.
So, let's look at the six gestures of citrus cultivation.
The first is essential and it's the potting soil.
When we grow citrus trees in pots - I grow them in pots made of Toulouse's sandstone - then the potting soil is important.
It's where the plant will grow its roots, where it will get its energy and water.
It's what's going to enable the tree, through its root system, to grow.
So, the potting soil is essential.
it should be able to be supportive. Sometimes it may be suffocating if it is too heavy.
Citrus trees need a soil that drains fairly well.
And sometimes, it can be totally harmful and poisonous.
So, the potting soil, what does it mean for us?
Well, the potting soil is where we are.
It's my family, my immediate surroundings, my company.
It's where I've chosen to live my life.
Now there is no good or bad potting soil.
No, it's simply more or less suitable.
For example, for ten years I worked in an American company as a young engineer, and then I became a manager, and it's true I produced beautiful fruit.
As a manager, I was fortunate to have a nice career.
But at the age of 30, I saw that this potting soil wasn't going to be the best for furthering my career.
I realized that, to continue to bear fruit, it was not that one that I needed to maintain.
So for each of us, the potting soil needs to be felt, to be tested, and we should ask ourselves, "Does this potting soil work for me?
Does it still work for me?
How can I enrich it?"
That's the first gesture.
The second is a gesture that, in citrus cultivation, we repeat regularly: watering, fertilizing, adding water, adding compost.
It's a gesture that we do regularly without needing to know whether we're going to harvest tomorrow.
I'm just in the gesture of feeding the plant.
So, for us, what could that refer to?
Certainly, to nutrition, but I wanted to shed light on two matters that I think are important.
The first is relationships.
As human beings, we are beings of connection, and our relationships feed us.
And it's important to both be nourished by them and to nourish them with all the people with whom we are.
As a citrus-human, it's important to ask: "Do I take the time to do that, to meet people, spend time with them, to talk?"
And the other element, in terms of fertilization, is everything that revolves around knowledge and learning.
It's important to ask ourselves, "In my current and future life, how can I regularly nourish myself so that I don't become rigid and dry, so that I don't calcify?'
The third gesture is significant, and it's pruning.
Citrus trees, particularly lemon trees, have an enormous amount of energy.
Look at a lemon, it's magnificent and very colorful.
So when the lemon tree grows, it grows a lot, so it needs to be pruned.
Pruning takes place usually in spring and summer.
And when I prune, I actually cut branches that could have produced fruit, but with the aim of concentrating the plant's energy so that it can produce better fruit, and also with the aim of giving it a shape.
So for us, it is like asking ourselves, "What can I prune in my life?"
Today, we're in a society of excess: too many emails, too many activities, too much work, too many burdens.
And I see people in business who are close to burnout if not completely exhausted.
Some know it, others don't.
So pruning regularly in our life is essential. It is quitting and be willing to say "I'm not doing that anymore."
So yes, it could have been nice fruit.
We can do so much in life, one isn't enough, but at some point, we must be willing to say no.
So, I can prune because I think there are too many branches
but also because I want to give them a shape.
Citrus trees should not be pruned too early.
I mean, I'll let it spread a little, then I'll prune.
Pruning, it's saying no, but it's also learning how to reduce our burden in our lives and how to focus our energy.
The next gesture is repotting.
In fact, when a citrus tree grows, it pushes against the walls of the pot.
So, the roots get intermingled and intertwined, and the tree ends up
absorbing less from fertilizers.
And it starts to stagnate.
So, it's time to think about changing its pot.
Repotting is moving from one pot to another.
You need to choose the pot: too small, and there's no point, too big, and you risk losing the plant, that is, it will take a lot of time for it to adapt.
Repotting, for us, it's all the changes.
It's all those factors that cause me to move home, change city, job or company.
When I repot, it's really important that I give myself some time, so that I can put down new roots.
Otherwise, I wouldn't have enough roots to produce beautiful fruit.
So in business, I see people who, when they change company, are working flat out.
Because they're in a new company, they need to prove themselves.
But what they forget is that when I repot a citrus tree, first it grows its roots before bearing fruit.
The next gesture is paradoxical, because it's a non-gesture.
It means I've already done a lot.
I've chosen the potting soil, I've pruned, I've fed, and then at some point, I must stop doing anything.
I need to stop because the tree must grow.
I have done a lot, now I must agree not to act any longer.
Beware that it doesn't mean that I'm doing nothing.
Rather it means that I'm here, I observe, I contemplate.
Incidentally, I can rest.
And if I see scale insects, I can treat it.
If I see it needs water, I can add some.
That's neither doing nothing, nor abandoning.
And for us, this concept isn't easy.
In our society, we do a lot all the time.
Our society almost believes, especially in companies, that if I want it, I can do it.
It's just a matter of means or willpower.
If I want it, I need to invest more means, more staff. It's a bit like saying: "Let's pull the flower to prompt the lemon's developpement."
Well, you know what?
It doesn't make the fruit grow.
So at one point, it's being here, present, agreeing to observe, agreeing to let Nature take its course.
So then "If I want it, I can do it," well, it does not work, an equation is missing
which is external energy, Nature, and especially time.
There are so many people in a hurry today.
Nevertheless, to grow lemons, you need time.
The next gestiure is a truly happy, joyful moment, a moment of grace: it is harvest time.
I can tell you that when you pick fruit this colorful, it's a real pleasure.
Especially because they're normally harvested in winter, which is great because in winter, they give us color and vitamins.
Citrus are full of vitamins.
And I rejoice since if I harvest, it's because I did what was needed.
Nature also played its part.
Really, the tree did all of that.
But I'm delighted because that didn't happen all on its own.
There was a helping hand, especially when the trees are in pots.
It is being delighted when I have only one clementine.
I tell you when you only have one, and you pick it, you eat it segment by segment, and you really savor it.
It is being delighted when I have 3 kilos, I'm giving them out all over the place, and I make jam and fruit wine, so much so that, in the end, I'm sick of citrus fruit!
It's also learning to be delighted when there are too many.
And, as for us?
Well, it's all about "Do I know how to be happy with what I have in life, with the small pleasures, the small joys,
all that which I experience each day that can make sense and delight me?"
And sometimes, we're not delighted.
Sometimes, we're happy for others, but they're not.
It's surprising.
It's also about being happy and recognizing that I can harvest today because I did lots of things before.
It's also being happy because I'm alive and I can harvest, whereas some people are no longer there to harvest.
So harvesting should remain a joyful moment, a pleasurable moment.
So, finally, what do citrus trees tell us in terms of wisdom?
They tell us, in fact, two things.
They say that citrus trees are very simple.
They need soil, sun, water, fertilizer.
With that, they can do wonderful things, beautiful fruit, beautiful colors, beautiful shapes, beautiful flavours.
Well, it's the same with us.
With very few things, simple things, we can do beautiful things.
And yes, mostly, you do beautiful things.
But what does it also mean?
It also means that I have to learn to return to basic gestures, to return to being conscious, and sometimes to being repetitive, to return to the fact that one day at a time, I'm going to do what is necessary to hopefully have a harvest.
I see a lot of people who, actually, could judge their days, their weeks, their time, on "What will I harvest?"
They could measure their activities, their life, in the light of what they harvest.
So I propose you start measuring your lives in light of what you sow, in light of all the small gestures that you do that, little by little, are going to make things grow, a bit like when someone starts a business and everything has been done - the market research, the products, everything is there - and then, it just doesn't work.
Well, it's about saying, "I'm happy to have sowed, because one day, I'm going to harvest."
Finally, in conclusion, I'd like to go back to the notion of "pépin" because it can be seen from different angles.
A "pépin," as meaning "glitch," can be tragic for a human being.
And how many people do I see around me in my work environment, who are waiting for the big "pépin"- the accident, the death, the disease - to start changing things, changing their schedule, changing the time they come back home, changing the balance of their life, changing their diet!
And I'd like to tell you, don't wait for this glitch because honestly, when it comes, it's not great.
Perhaps I had the wisdom to hit a snag and think that behind this irritating yet not too serious snag, there was something to learn, and I learned.
That "pépin," I can also see it differently.
It also means "seed", a seed that I can sow and that contains a promise, the promise of a tomorrow a little bit different, with a life maybe more harmonious, happier, or lighter if you prefer. I can see that I don't need to wait for the big "pépin" to say that in the "pépin," there are things that I can sow, I can plant.
Lastly, let me ask you, "Tomorrow morning, what small seed or little "pépin" are you going to plant to make your life happier?"
Thank you.
(Applause)
Doing science in an open way is much more effective.
It's how science should be,
it's how science was originally.
For some years, there has been a movement for open access.
It's the way ahead,
the only question is the route.
I'm going to tell you about "commons".
That's what?
It's three things: it's a resource that can be material or immaterial, it's a mode of access and rules for sharing it, and the governance of the resource.
The aim of the governance of a resource, of a "common", is to try to preserve the common, to make it permanent and guard its existence.
It's a bit abstract, so I will give an example: a village orchard.
The resource is the apples.
The mode of access: we pick from the trees, all are allowed to.
The rules: we're only allowed two apples per person per week, and when we get there, we water, we weed, we participate, stay a while, it's funtime outside, clear enough.
The governance can be assured by an association, the municipal council, so that there is no cheating.
This is a material common.
If I take an apple from a tree, it's no longer there.
Now let's consider a common that's immaterial, one that all of you already know about: Wikipedia.
The resource is immaterial: it's encyclopaedic knowledge.
The mode of access is via the Internet, where we access a copy.
When I search for a page on Wikipedia, I receive it, but it stays on the site so that another can receive it too.
And the rules?
There's a very formal one: a Creative Commons licence.
You receive the content, you can do with it what you please, reuse it, remix it, translate it, as long as you cite it as being from Wikipedia when you redistribute it.
The governance of Wikipedia is a little complex.
There is firstly the Wikimedia Foundation, which tries to assure - you've all already seen the donation campaigns - the resources in terms of servers, bandwidth, the network, etc.
Then, each encyclopaedia - they go by language - they're managed autonomously by representatives, administrators, moderators.
They collectively define roles.
How are the people elected?
How long do they keep their title?
What are their powers, etc?
Then their is a governance
even more decentralized, for example, against vandalism. When we visit a Wikipedia page, we can correct errors, and every article has a page for discussion of: Does this page merit encyclopaedia entry?
What content should it have, etc?

The governance is assured in this way.
There is a "commons tragedy".
A cheat, in this system, is always winning.
So, with the example of the orchard, if someone in need of fuel for heat comes and cuts wood, the common dies.
Its governance is therefore extremely important.
We can also imagine someone who, for example, takes all the apples to make apple sauce.
There's plenty of imaginable situations.
It's very easy to imagine how to make a material common die.
For an immaterial common, it may seem less obvious.
It is, however, possible.
I'll present an alternate universe, another Wikipedia.
You see I've changed the logo and put in a "€". You'll see why.
It's another universe where we can all write articles like on the current Wikipedia, but we have a civic duty to correct the articles if we see errors.
Not always, but it's a part of our role, we are supposed to participate sometimes.
When we want to access an article, we have to pay.
We may think, "30 euros isn't too expensive considering the quality."
There are also articles we can see before paying 30 euros.
The problem is that to understand an article, you have to also understand other articles about the concepts that it uses. So we end up paying a lot.
Don't worry, it's not a bunch of crooks:
there are subscriptions.
Why is this all possible?
It's a real possibility. Why?
Because of intellectual property [IP], and, particularly, lucrative IP.
It allows for private appropriation of a collective work, and to artificially create rarity, and thus to end back up with an economy where when I sell someone something, I no longer have it.
Well, that's the way research works, in our world, not in the alternate universe.
It's a real problem.
As not everyone here knows how research works, I will try to explain quickly how it goes on.
It's a very global operation.
All specific fields have their slight differences,
but, on the whole, we start by considering one question.
Given we have access to current research findings, we ask ourselves: "What's going to be the best next step to advance our field?"
We take as known the position of research in our field and those related to it, and so necessarily have access to articles at least.
Then we do our research,
collect data, analyse it, write programs: it can be a whole load of things.
And one day, we have our results.
Whether or not they're what we expected, we have them.
When we want to communicate these results, we write a research paper, we submit it for review, to a journal, present it at a conference.
I'll just say "review" from now on for the sake of simplicity.
Submitting for review, what's that?
It's a group of other researchers in our field who will receive the paper, who either evaluate it themselves or send it to others who are more expert than them in the field, and if the paper is judged to represent an advance, to be rigorous, to be pertinent to the theme of the review, it will be published.
Otherwise, it's rejected, or there's some to-and-fro to improve it.
I put quotation marks around "publication" because usually it means to "make public".
We'll see that it's complicated because it's at this stage that publishing houses intervene, who then ask us to transfer to them the author's rights, or rights under copyright law, for the paper, so they can exploit it commercially, in exchange for what they distribute.
So, what we have is public money funding research, the privatization of the results of the research in exchange for nothing, and then public money rebuying the research.
It's also public money that evaluates it, etc.
I'm talking a lot about public research, there is also private research.
But most of the time, in the private sector, they publish less, and, for example, in France, through the mechanisms of tax credit etc, industrial research is funded to a large extent also by public money.
Just a few figures.
The ENS, a very small institution: one million euros a year library expenses while we know that they benefit very much from access to the CNRS - which spends over 30 million euros annually, almost 40 millions this year - and they take advantage of university access via joint research units.
For example, just to Elsevier, the Jussieu Campus, next to the ENS, pays out €1M per year, just to one publisher, a huge subscription.
We can also take an interest in the evolution of these costs.
For example, at Télécom ParisTech, where I did my thesis, it became too expensive, they reduced the number of subscriptions for printed reviews by more than a half.
But, so we could work, they took a third more online subscriptions.
The number of subscriptions was reduced, we just download the PDFs we need, we don't receive the papers by post, so it should be less expensive.

Nope! It's more expensive.
And not just a little.
And while there's this ravaging of university libraries, there's the profits of the publishing sector leader, Reed-Elsevier.
The figures are in the billions of American dollars.
You can see the profit-on-turnover figure is monstrous.
How did we get here?
Why this situation?
Publishing houses have a role.
Historically, they always saw to page layout, optimizing distribution. Clearly they're privately owned, they need to derive an income, they need to make known the researchers.
But when the diffusion of science structured itself around journals - earlier, these journals were the province of academies and learned societies - there was a need to make a business of the circulation of the journals.
That's where publishing houses came into play, concentrating and privatizing the research while saying: "In order to take responsibility for the journals, we ask for the exploitation rights necessary for their distribution."
It was a service we needed as there was no Internet at that time,
and then they also did the page layout etc.
More and more, page presentation is done by researchers themselves, with tools like LaTeX, page creation templates.
So, that's done by us.
To distribute papers and articles as widely as possible, that, the Internet does that very well.
No need for the publishing house supply of papers to universities worldwide.
Money-making like that might be great, the question is: Is there any legitimacy in making money from knowledge?
And then, the promotion of researchers, a role they have inherited, with the bibliometrics for which being provided by them themselves.
Bibliometrics is the idea that researchers can be quantitatively assessed from the volume of their publications.
There is thus an incentive to publish.
And when the publishing houses took over ownership of the journals, the researchers lost control of the means of production.
Bibliometrics is a method of management where the targets set them bleed them of the sense of their work.
The objective when we want a university career, it'll be to create another publication and not make another discovery.
The bibliometric tools are sold by the publishing houses and it's they who make SciVal, Scopus, etc, that are sold at a high price to funding agencies.
I'm speaking of money; we're in a rich country, so we could say, "We pay and that's fine."
It's not really the main problem.
The problem is access for all, equality between students, researchers and universities everywhere.
While in France we can afford it, there are countries where they can't, so there will be lost opportunities there that could prove colossal: researchers there might easily have great ideas, but not without access to the current position in their field.
We might think as well of all the startups that could benefit from access to research output, but do not have it.
Immediately, open access presents itself as a solution: we put all the results of research online with open access for all.
That's quite a suggestion, maybe too bold, that offers many options.
I'll quickly put three of them to you.
First, green open access, self-archiving, where researchers put a copy of their publication in a repository.
I insist on this: Academia.edu, ResearchGate, and all those that try to do business, it doesn't work.
The advantage is that it's parallel to the traditional publication channels.
We can also put old papers and articles online.
That makes researchers more aware of the importance of it.
Then we have gold open access.
It's supposed to be good: "We will publish directly with open access."
Except the publishing houses have taken it up and have said: "No problem, but we pay to publish."
This would be too costly for the CNRS or those producing a lot of publications. They wouldn't survive a year with this model: publishing generally costs thousands of dollars.
Beyond that, we might legitimately ask ourselves: Should money come into it when considering whether to publish or not?
There's a third option, the one I propounded earlier, diamond open access, or platinum, or "fair open access".
The idea here is - I'm returning to what I was saying before, of making research a "common".
So, it's the idea of moving away from knowledge as lucrative property.
There is no reason why knowledge should be private property with which to make money.
Researchers regain their main means of production, the means of circulating their knowledge, on which they can build.
Let's do an exercise.
What's the resource?
It's the results of the research, publications, data, software, etc.
The access mode, the rules for sharing: the Internet,
it's universal, the best we can do.
There's still language and access barriers, but, for now, we can't do better.
The utilization of open source software.
Apparently, there's no point in
exchanging one prison for another.
And the governance?
The idea would be that authors keep their author's rights and their copyright, and that the editorial boards have a legal status - currently, they don't - and own their review.
Why keep their copyright?
Because the interest of the author of a publication is to be read.
And so his interests are aligned with those of everyone else, that is to say, that his publication be as accessible as possible.
It's a realistic idea with almost no cost.
Why?
The infrastructures are there, the repositories of the institutions and the disciplines work, where we can put documents, data and software.
We already have open source software for peer reviewing, for the organization of journals: HotCRP for conferences, and Open Journal Systems for journals.
The legal framework exists: Creative Commons licences - as used by Wikipedia - with Creative Commons Attribution that corresponds to research: that is, we cite the research blocs with which we associate ourselves in doing our research.
Editorial board associations exist already, and are internationally recognized.
These things are already in practice.
Very quickly: an EPI Journal, it's exactly like a conventional journal, except that instead of publishing as a printed volume or as a PDF on the Internet, we publish a webpage with a list of links to the accepted versions of the publication.
Otherwise, everything happens exactly as before.
We no longer have the variable "publishing house" to take into account,
but everything else is exactly as before.
We can move past the current models with open peer reviewing, where the unit is the publication, which would be accompanied by its reviews, which would be signed.
That requires a little change of mentality, of custom, etc, but we can imagine going further like this.
(Applause)
I found love at 17.
I fell in love with an extremely handsome guy.
Finally, he was there - the one I had been waiting for so long.
The one who was going to love, support,
comfort me, make me happy.
It started off great.
I felt strong and free. I was in love.
I was ready for anything for this story to work.
I was a teenager, and I felt alone and isolated.
So when he came into my life, I felt connected to someone.
He would be able to understand me and protect me.
I surrendered my body and soul to this man.
I trusted him.
He was seven years older than I was, and I let him teach me life,
teach me how to be lovable.
I wanted to be a woman who was worthy of being loved, and he wanted a perfect woman.
I was 18 when I found out that I was pregnant.
Yes, it's a bit young to have a baby, but I loved him.
And it's at that exact moment that my problems began.
During the first months of my pregnancy, he became physically violent towards me.
He started with a slap, then gradually with arguments, the blows became more and more frequent, numerous, stronger.
I felt as if I were caught in a trap.
I was expecting a little girl with him. I didn't want to let go of my fairytale dreams of Prince Charming.
If I made an effort, our relationship would surely work itself out.
He would be sweet to me again, like in the beginning.
So, I made an effort
again and again and again.
And to avoid conflict, I didn't have any other choice but to submit to his authority.
And any little pretext was enough to beat me.
Even a joke could annoy him.
One day, he even broke my jaw.
So I forgave him little by little, but I distrusted him more and more.
The last month of my pregnancy was a true nightmare.
He ...
At that time, he inflicted his violence with complete impunity.
His blows were more and more threatening.
So I left to take refuge at my parents' house. Then, I returned because he apologized.
Then, I left again and returned again because he promised me he'd get treatment.
Then I left again and returned again because he threatened to kill everyone.
A TV show helped me put into words what I was living.
I, who thought I was living in such a unique situation, I was in fact one of those hundreds of thousands of women whom we call battered women and who account for one out of every ten women in France.
I do not want to stay in this situation.
Now, everything about him makes me afraid.
I truly want to leave.
I don't know how.
So I continue with my comings and goings.
I leave when there is violence and return when I feel he has calmed down.
I hum and haw to find the right moment to leave for good in total safety.
The right moment presented itself.
Shortly after the birth of my child,
I felt that I would no longer be useful to him.
I had brought our baby into the world and therefore, he could get rid of me.
I feared for my life.
And the idea that his violence could one day be inflicted upon my daughter was unbearable for me.
I had reached my limit.
I left.
I was very proud of my decision.
I was going to be able to live normally again, in total freedom.
Free to say and do things without being afraid.
I left, but ... the violence did not stop there.
He had not decided to leave me alone.
He did not accept our separation at all.
And long years of harassment followed.
Two years of daily, repetitive, threatening phone calls.
Unexpected visits at my house, at my parents' jobs, at the school.
At my school.
Slashed tires, ransacked house, abduction of my daughter.
The list goes on and on.
During that time, he created an atmosphere of fear and dread.
He managed to have everyone think of him.
He triggered events. Each more surprising and violent than the last.
I was stunned.
His behavior led me to spend my days at the police station, at my lawyer's office, or in court.
His hatred grew day by day.
He became uncontrollable.
Supervised visits were set-up for our daughter.
He was prohibited from coming to our house, the police regularly patrolled in front of our house, and yet ...
One day, he made good on his threats.
He arrived in the middle of the night armed with a rifle.
My parents, my daughter, and I were present.
My daughter's life was not in danger, but ... my parents and I were left for dead.
My mom and I survived.
But my dad died.
And him?
He was sentenced to 20 years behind bars without the possibility of parole.
So I ask myself, how did we get here?
And yet I had done everything that they had told me to do.
I had used every possible avenue.
I had faith in the justice system, so as he triggered events, I filed complaints, which would often lead to suspended prison sentences.
Steps were taken so that we would have the least possible contact,
but we were bound by our daughter and I had obligations towards him.
This persistent link opened the window for him to destroy me.
Sentences one after another were handed down, but nothing changed.
On the contrary, it aggravated the situation and his anger grew.
And the means that he used to destroy me grew with it.
I armed myself with patience not to respond to his aggressions or his threats, not to give in to panic.
I shouted the problems and fears that I had with this man
loudly and strongly. And he too cried out for help for his condition. He sounded the alarm.
He knew what he was capable of, and he said it.
Two months before the tragedy, he had even called the precinct to say that there was going to be a murder at my parents' address.
So, I understand that prisons are overcrowded and that we cannot lock up every person who makes threats, but neither can we allow these situations to deteriorate to the point where people wind up dead.
And even if he had spent some months in prison, I am not convinced that that would have sufficed to defuse his anger, or to have him put things in perspective.
I thought about him retaliating upon his release.
There was no real solution to protect me.
I have met powerless professionals, who had neither the means to act nor the proper tools to address this problem.
And he never went far enough to be psychiatrically committed or to be criminally sentenced.
The more he slipped through the cracks of the justice system, the more he felt strong, indestructible, in full control.
For the situation to end, I only needed to wait for him to do the irredeemable.
And this is not particularly exceptional.
Because in 2013, every 2.5 days, that is two days and a half, one person died due to domestic violence.
And yet, that does not include the collateral deaths like my dad, for example.
I cannot help asking myself, when I see those numbers, how many calls for help were there?
If you, or one of your family members, were in this situation, wouldn't you want there to be some means to protect yourself?
Can we do nothing against this violence?
And with advances in psychoanalysis and in neuroscience, can we not detect their determination and get these men help earlier, so that they do not end up becoming murderers?
At his sentencing, I tell myself that I have 20 years in front of me.
I must use that time to put myself back together.
But also to understand.
So I work, with the help of therapists, I nourish myself with readings and testimonies. Other people's experiences inspire me to find the answers to my own existence.
And I meet other women who have endured physical or psychological violence.
And I realize that we all use the same words to describe what we have lived through.
That we all faced the same obstacles, which prevented us from getting out of it.
And that it's that what destroyed us - not being able to get out.
My desire to act came from meeting with these women.
I tell myself that if we leave so many people in such distress it's because we don't know!
It because we are not well acquainted with domestic violence.
I, myself, before living it, I had preconceived notions about it.
I did not know that a person could have so much power over one life, and that it was not so easy to get rid of them.
I did not know that a wonderful love story at 17 could turn deadly.
So I tell myself that it is vital to inform others.
To call out to our consciences.
I want everyone to understand that these are first and foremost love stories.
I want everyone to understand that these are not poor women who love that.
We are trapped by the images of ourselves, by the images of the life, by the hold another exerts over us.
And it is not enough to leave for the violence to end.
And it seems to me that it is vital to obtain the right to leave someone without dying because of it, the right to live after domestic violence, the right to live in peace.
I ask myself how I can best act in the place where I find myself.
I am an actress and the best weapon available to me is the theater.
So in January 2013, my company and I created "I Want You to Be Perfect."
(Music) I put up with domestic violence for many years.
I bore it from when I was 17 to when I was 20 years old.
Today I need to tell you my story.
"I Want You to Be Perfect" is a play written from a testimony, the true story of a woman subjected to domestic violence.
Leave me alone!
With your words full of spite!
I told this story of a battered woman to help other women.
The story can help others realize or open their eyes to their situation.
We certainly don't expect the same things for each child.
We are truly very different.
This play shows that theater is a tool in service of a cause, but at the same time, by its aesthetic demands, it gives this tool all its strength.
I also call out to the audience's consciences.
I talk about a problem that I know, and it's a play which has an activist and social role.
You want to know everything!
If I am here, if I am there, or farther away or someplace else!
But stop!
This play, we let ourselves experience it, and open ourselves up to it, to allow the character and every emotion that goes with it to enter.
Out of the way!
It no longer enters through reason, but through the heart and through emotion.
The play addresses all audiences.
In fact, this play, it tells a love story which ends badly and these are universal feelings.
Stop.
I must testify.
(Music) This play opened in 2013 and was published in 2014.
It became an informational tool for high school students, for example, but also a tool for discussion.
Since after each performance, I open it up to the audience, to have a discussion with the audience, which is made up of both ordinary people and a lot of professionals.
Through these discussions, I hope that together, we will able to find more and more human solutions to finally put an end to this scourge.
This show also fulfills my need to act not to stand idly by, to take my destiny in my own hands.
And it also has the benefit of making my father's death less absurd.
Our story put into words and on the stage becomes useful and takes on meaning.
And it's precisely that which frees us.
16 years have passed, and there's still some way to go.
I don't have any other choice, but to accept my life and to deal with it.
I try to stay open not to give in to despondency, to always take another step further.
My goal is to live serenely.
Today, I am aware that I, too, have the right to be happy.
So I must shove aside or eliminate any obstacles to that in my life.
Violence is what prevents me from being fully who I am.
I obviously rid myself of all of that extreme violence, but I realize that that violence could be a lot more subtle, that it took up a large part of my daily life and that it was also destructive.
I do not trivialize all of this violence that is present everywhere, from classrooms to businesses.
I denormalize it to no longer receive it, but also to no longer be tempted to commit it, and thus transmit it.
This violence makes me lose my self-confidence, so I must know myself well enough rebuild myself, know myself, and repel this violence, to no longer be a victim of it.
And what is astounding is that, the more I put limits on this violence, the more I flourish, and the more I flourish, the more I feel serene.
This ordeal ... Sorry.
This ordeal gave me the chance to draw from within me a strength I never suspected that I had.
But there remains one thing that I need to maintain for my life to continue moving forward in the right direction, it's my morale.
I am naturally drawn to what makes me feel downhearted.
So I force myself to surround myself with positive things.
I flee from melancholy.
Over the past 16 years, I have acquired tools, such as meditation and relaxation, which help me get through these difficult periods.
And if things get really bad, what immediately snaps me out of it is connecting with what I loved when I was little.
And what made me happy, which was to dance.
And perhaps you have noticed how sometimes certain songs seem to have been written for us?
And it's that that I wish to share with you.
And I would like you to join me in my delightful madness.
So I will ask you to stand, I will ask TEDx to join me, and I will ask the control room to play the music.
Please clap your hands, dance, and celebrate life with me.
(Music) That's it, I've had enough, enough of lamenting, I want to erase the past to start all over again, to free myself.
I have decided to look on the bright side of life.
(Music)
Can you recall your first conscious olfactory memory?
Personally, the one that moves me most is the memory of pines and fir trees,
you know, the pines and fir trees and their essential oils in the undergrowth of the Limousin forests of my childhood,
my dad, letting the dog off the lead, me, eyes riveted on the ground, looking for wonderfully smelling autumn mushrooms.
Tonight, I'd like us all to discover and appreciate an invisible link to an exceptional strength: the power of smell.
Do you remember a smell that took you back, when you smelled it, years and years, perhaps to your childhood?
Do you remember the feelings, the sensations, and the emotions, with which you were invaded?
Do you know about Proustian Memory?
The sense of smell is fully developed between the 10th and 12th week of gestation of the embryo.
This means that when the mother eats, sprays or massages herself with olfactory things, the child integrates it into his olfactory library for life.
Indeed, this memory is the one that is the more resilient to the test of time.
Someone suffering from Alzheimer's syndrome may no longer know who they are, but will definitely remember a smell, and especially one from their childhood.
2004: it took until the twenty-first century for the sense of smell to take all its meaning.
The great American neuroscientists, Richard Axel and Linda Buck, discovered receptors involved in the coding of smells.
340, there, at the top of the nose.
Those 340 receptors receive different molecules of various shapes and intensities, and allow us, as human beings, to experience more than a trillion different smells, in the nose alone.
Yes, the nose, but where else?
Well, everywhere in the body.
The gustatory receptors on the tongue.
Chemoreceptors that we have at the blood-vessel level to sense the fluctuations in our caffeine levels in the morning.
In our lungs: when we inhale a toxic substance, we will start hyperventilating, coughing, to fight against it.
In our kidneys, our muscles, but also within our sperm.
The spermatozoon finds its way to an ovum it needs to fertilize as a result of chemoreceptors.
The super sleuth has a nose for it.
(Laughter) It goes to show nothing is due to chance.
Luc Marlier, a great French neuroscientist working at the CNRS in Strasbourg, conducted some amazing experiments.
He let two-hour-old newborns smell some butyric acid, that is, rancid butter.
Well, you wouldn't believe it, but the child closed its eyes, screwed up its nose, and pushed the stuff away.
On the other hand, the same infant, smelling vanilla, will open its eyes wide, flare its nostrils, stick its tongue out, and grab the brush to eat it.
Another scientific study - and again it is a real study - was conducted in which mothers consumed aniseed syrups or cakes.
Well, you'd never believe it, but the children whose mother had tasted it reacted to it like they did with the vanilla.
On the other hand, the children whose mother did not consume aniseed pushed it away as they did with the rancid butter. How quickly we learn everything.
Those experiments lead to things that can be done at the hospital.
Let's stay in Strasbourg, in the neonatal unit.
With less than seven months' pregnancy, a baby's lungs are not fully developed.
It risks suffering from sleep apnoea, with a risk of a drop in heart rate leading to possible death.
The treatment for these newborns is an injection of caffeine and something to support their heart.
With refractory apnoea, this is not enough. But a diffusion of vanilla in the incubator, and within 72 hours, the baby will be free of sleep apnoea, and can be discharged sooner to the joy of its parents.
Many experiments are run at the hospital, for example, diffusing essential oils during preanaesthesia to calm the patient before general anaesthesia.
The resulting desirable effects are that they need less tranquillizers, and recover more quickly and more healthily.
If for 10 minutes, you diffuse some essential oil of sweet marjoram or of lavender to adults, their heart rate and blood pressure falls.
A fun study was carried out on teenagers.
If you diffuse a subliminal odour, one whose concentration is too low to be detected consciously, one of lemon, before a snack of crumbly cookies,
well, the teenagers clear the table more readily with liquid containing lemon than others.
As a pharmacist, I like to try things on my relatives - don't worry, they're all fine.
My 16-year-old son has been the subject of this experiment at home.
I diffused lemon, he comes in, I've bought cookies of the really crumbly type.
To the great amazement of his father, who did not know what was going on, our son took a kitchen sponge and the lemon-smelling washing-up liquid for the first time in his life, to clean the table. (Laughter)
I can still see his speechless father.
(Applause) You don't need a teenager to hand, spouses are perfect to try out on ... discreetly.
Well now, if you let obese children smell fruit odours before a meal, they will preferentially choose fruit over pastries at the end of the meal.
In an Alzheimer facility, when lemon is to be smelled, the people are more clear-minded.
When they breathe some rosemary cineole essential oil, it increases their memory by 70%; they solve the Sudoku.
A depressive person who can no longer tell the difference, or mixes up, a smell of vomit or one of bitter orange, is likely to be given antidepressants that will struggle to work at the end of six weeks.
And finally, when an elderly person no longer has a sense of smell, that is, they have anosmia, they have a 46% risk of dying within 10 years.
All these experiments are conducted, are used, by carers throughout France, in some units, but this shouldn't be a case of not seeing the forest - the Limousin - for the trees.
Olfactory marketing is expanding at full speed. For example, you have automatic coffee machines with built-in diffusers that diffuse, on the arrival of employees in the morning, the smell of hot chocolate, warm croissant, coffee, to increase their consumption. There's some chic lingerie stores that diffuse aphrodisiac scents of ylang-ylang, rose, or cedar, to lure our lovesick olfactory system.
The limbic system, once called the rhinencephalon or olfactory brain, is the command centre of our emotions.
Who has not smelled the scent of full-grain leather in stores selling leatherette sofas?
Or you, gentlemen, pay attention, at the time of the football World Cups: you will find the scent of fresh cut grass next to the televisions to make you believe you are the champions behind the ball.
(Laughter) I trust you will not now be taken in by this olfactory marketing and scent out the scams.
I advise you, for your own sake, to eliminate from your life all people whose smell you dislike: shitty ones, stinky people.
And I wish you all, all your lives, to have a keen nose.
Aromatically yours.
(Applause)
(Dutch) I am Françoise Masuy. I am going to talk about language learning in Belgium.
(French) Uh, you don't understand me?
Of course, I forgot!
We are in Belgium, in Wallonia!
Not everybody knows Dutch.
Isn't it a shame that we hardly know each other in such a small country because of the language barrier?
I am going to take you with me on a journey to the heart of Belgium after which you will want to get to know the others.
To start off, here are three anecdotes.
First anecdote.
A few years ago, I received an invitation from a Dutch-speaking correspondant with whom I had shared a few linguistic experiences when I was a teenager.
She invited me to the Holy Communion of her 12-year-old daughter.
Surprised and flattered, I accepted.
And there I was in Flemish territory.
What I didn't know, was that I was the surprise of the day.
I was treated like a queen by the parents and the three sisters.
(Dutch) "You haven't changed at all!
You look exactly the same!"
(French) That's always nice to hear when you are in your thirties.
And then, something clicked: I, who hadn't spoken Dutch for so many years, started to speak Dutch, just like that!
(Dutch) "Excuse me?
Can you say that again?"
(French) By failing, however, to consistently reject the verb at the end of the phrase ...
Regardless of the mistakes, I was having fun.
In short, everything started to fall back into place.
Since then, I listen to Radio Eén all day long in my car, I sign up for all the courses across the linguistic border, and my Dutch-speaking colleagues, in addition to my ramblings in French, have to put up with my painful conversations in their mother tongue.
Second anecdote.
At the hairdresser's in Wavre.
Wavre is a small town a few miles away from Louvain-la-Neuve.
I heard someone talk about the Overijse swimming pool.
I don't know if you know this swimming pool.
It is a sort of mini water park which is not too expensive.
The hairdresser went on to explain: "I love the swimming pool in Oveijse!
It is big and comfortable. There is a sauna and there are slides for the children, but, I am afraid to go there.
I don't speak Dutch.
The few occasions I went there, I spoke in English."
Third anecdote.
A family going away on holiday to the North Sea.
Once on the freeway in Flanders, a child says: "Uitrit, Uitrit, Uitrit!
That's a big town!
It has been signposted the whole time!"
(Laughter) Does anyone know what "Uitrit" means?

Yes, indeed! It means "Exit" in Dutch.
You haven't wasted your time coming today.
Three anecdotes.
Three emotions, joy, surprise, fear, which clearly shows the disparity of feelings towards the national languages of Belgium.
Why is that?
Belgium is a small country of 18,969 square miles, roughly 0.02% of the world's surface.
On this small piece of land 3 languages are spoken: German, Dutch and French.
21.7 miles separate Louvain/Leuven from Louvain la Neuve, a short physical distance but such a huge mental one.
Why so?
It seems that never-ending discussions between political groups create an atmosphere which is not conducive to the development of mutual respect between communities.
However, research shows that the more learners have a negative attitude towards a language and community, the more their command of that language is low.
Emotional factors play a crucial role in hindering or developing learning.
Faced with this disenchantment, I wanted to do something.
I got the idea of a site enabling us to learn how to get to know each other because everyone knows that in order to live together, we must know each other.
Therefore I asked young people from three linguistic communities to share what excites them in their region: a place, a personality, a habit ... And they responded with enthusiasm in the other's language.
This is how the "Belgium on stage" website was born, a trilingual website, fun, created by and for young people, who show cultural realities just as they are perceived by young people between 17 and 24.
By discovering those testimonies, we can see that there are far fewer things that divide us than things that connect us.
I'm going to give you a few examples.
First example.
Belgium as seen by young people is made of festivals!
You all know Pukkelpop near Hasselt, Tomorrowland in Antwerp, Rock Werchter, the Dour festival, the Francofolies of Spa,
Esperanzah! in Floreffe.
But do you know "Het Groot Verlof," the newly created festival in Leuven to liven up the deserted city with young people in summer?
And "Scène sur Sambre," an equally crazy festival on the banks of the Sambre, in a little green paradise located in the south of Charleroi, and where concerts take place on water thanks to a floating stage?
I've been living for 20 years in this village, and I learned about the existence of this festival thanks to "Belgium on stage."
Incredible!
Belgium, as seen by young people, is made of similar leisure activities.
Whether it is youth movements, scouts of Wallonia, Pfadfinder in the Eastern Cantons, Chiro in Flanders, or a night out with friends.
All the good tips are given to have fun and have a drink in the northern, southern and eastern side of the country.
Third example.
Belgium as seen by young people is made of gastronomy.
Did you know that you can discover Brussels only around Belgian chocolate?
(Dutch) Chocolate walks in Brussels!
(French) But there are not only waffles, there's chocolate, French fries and beer in Belgium!
Have you ever tasted the delicious palets de Dame, typical biscuits of Tournai, "Doornik" in Dutch?
I had the chance to taste some during the official launch of "Belgium on stage" not long ago. A real delight!
Fourth example?
Belgium as seen by young people is made of TV shows watched at home.
On one side, you have the French speakers watching "Koh-Lanta," and the Flemish who are fans of "Expeditie Robinson."
Do you know the most-watched TV series in Flanders?
"Thuis en Familie," of course, which tells the story of the daily life of families on two rival Flemish channels.
And "F.C. De Kampioenen,"
which depicts the adventures of a very bad football team.
Not to mention "Foute Vrienden," a hilarious reality-TV program in which four friends take on challenges each one crazier than the last.
I'm convinced that if this concept was brought in Wallonia, it would take the world by storm.
Fifth example.
Belgium as seen by young people is made of curiosities.
Do you know the Bueren mountain, near Liège, also called the "stairs of the extreme"?
374 steps with a 30% incline!
There is also "Dreiländerpunkt," located on the border of three countries: Belgium, the Netherlands, Germany.
Not to mention the Strépy-Thieu boat lift, the biggest boat-lift in the world!
Finally, Belgium as seen by young people is made of notable personalities.
"BV," "de bekende Vlamingen," [the famous Flemish] in Flanders.
Fortunately, as one of the youngsters who participated in the website said, the equivalent acronym doesn't exist in Wallonia: "Famous Walloons" would be a bit ridiculous.
All those testimonials show the Belgium seen from the inside by the young people living in it, in the other's language.
Remember what I told you in the beginning: Isn't it a shame that in such a small country, we know each other so little because of language?
All the examples given show that we can meet thanks to language!
All the examples given show that there are far more things that unite us than things that divide us.
Fear and rejection stem from ignorance.
To live well together, we must learn to get to know each other.
Eighteen months ago, I was dreaming, alone.
Today this dream has become a reality.
Young people became the ambassadors of their communities.
With "Belgium on stage," I wish to awaken the utopic mind which lies in each one of us.
The same one which enables us to live well together.
Who knows?
This Belgian utopia may inspire other countries where the coexistence of languages is sometimes tumultuous.
Because isn't being shared the aim of every utopia?
I believe so.
I say it.
I affirm it.
The three national languages of this country, German, Dutch and French, will one day be the languages of the world and the heart for all the inhabitants of this little kingdom of Belgium.
As the poet Julos Beaucarne says, "The wind from Flanders, The wind from Wallonia: it is the same wind, with a different accent."
(Applause) On that note, as we say in German, "Danke und tschüss!"
(Applause)
Hello.
Tonight I will speak about a way of looking, but not just any look;
about the kind of look directed at those who look physically different.
That look of surprise, curiosity, and sometimes fear about seeing something unsettling.
I think I have a small problem here... So, during the time of this talk, you'll be in someone else's shoes. imagine yourself as someone who has a visible handicap, and I will be your guide for this experience.
Why would I propose such a journey?
In fact, this way of looking at people with visible differences is vital because it can induce shame about their physical condition and a lack of self-confidence as well.
So, tonight, I will use an example of a rare disease, called the giant congenital melanocytic nevus.
It is a skin malformation which develops before birth and consists of giant moles that can cover up to 90% of the surface of a child's body.
The nevus can affect the face, the body, the limbs.
Its incidence is estimated in one in 20,000 newborns and its 'garment-like' variety one in 50,000 newborns.
There are three types of complications. First, an increased risk for pediatric malignant melanoma, which is a very aggressive type of skin cancer; second, an increased risk for severe neurological impairment because the nevus can affect the body at this level; and third, psychological distress since these children often suffer from stigmatization and exclusion. So, why do I talk about the giant
congenital melanocytic nevus (GCMN)?
Because I, myself, was born with one of a considerable size, a rather similar one to that modeled by Yulianna, whom you see on the photo.
I want to thank her for having lent us her photos with enthusiasm and to all the other people you will also see during this slideshow, since the message of this TEDx is very important to them.
As for me, I underwent skin grafts, unlike Yulianna, and we started when I was 5 and kept on until I had no more healthy skin to graft.
Thus, I still have a lot of my nevus.
Sincerely, though, the hardest part of presenting these symptoms was having to deal with how others looked at me, far beyond any physical suffering or consequences of surgery.
I also want to point out that if you think that a nevus located on one's face is difficult, keep that thought to yourself!
Just close your eyes for 30 seconds and imagine you have a nevus like that of Yulianna, and then having to go into your bathroom at home, like you do every morning, and having to look at yourself in the mirror.
Or remember the last time you were at the beach with your friends or family.
I think that after this small mental exercise, you'll realize that there are no "good" or "bad" nevi like people often try to tell me.
This is why I feel like I am entitled to talk about this topic and share my thoughts and journey with you.
In fact, over the last few years, I have been involved with patient advocacy groups and I realized that there is little change in the way the world looks at us. We leave patients, families, and even professionals, bereft of tools.
The current "solution" is: if more people know about the disease, affected children will be accepted as they are, because what is familiar is less scary.
Personally, I think that means educating 7.2 billion people, which is a bit difficult; I feel like Don Quixote tilting at windmills.
I asked myself how can we in fact go about this in a different way?
How might I, with my nevus, adapt to how others see me so that it is not so hard, and I might better adapt to these situations which make me so uncomfortable?
The question was then to find out whether tools and techniques existed that I could make use of.
I often compare this idea to being a doctor - because I am one - who, in a crisis situation, has to just concentrate on technique instead of getting overwhelmed by emotions.
One might be able to use the same psychological approach here.
And yes, in fact, such strategies exist!
I discovered them 4 years ago.
They were developed
in English-speaking countries.
They're pragmatic and simple to use.
When I present them, usually to parents they all have the same reaction I did.
They say, "Of course!
Why didn't we think of that earlier?"
When I discovered them, I remember wishing I had had these tools when I was younger.
The problem in France is they are not yet very developed.
This is why, together with Professor Vabres, Loïc Ballet and my husband Philippe, I decided to start a non-profit advocacy group, ANNA, made up of doctors and psychologists but also artists, families, and other volunteers to develop these techniques.
I will present three approaches tonight to show you that they're quite practical.
The first is called "STEPS,"
and is used to work on a few points at once and was invented to help Phoenix Arizona Burn Center.
It's a rehearsing practice for meeting new people.
We get ready, we tell yourselves we do want to meet these people, and that is positive thinking.
We are going to meet these people, we want to do it, we are going to do it and do it well.
"Tonight, I am going to give this TEDx; I'll do it, and I'll do it well."
I also work on my tone of voice.
I try to seem enthusiastic, friendly, and firm.
Body language is also important.
I have my shoulders back, head up high, and I look self-confident.
I'm actually petrified.
(Laughter) Then, there is how you look at others: it's very important to teach children to look other people in the eye even if only for 30 seconds - look at them straight on so the other person can move on.
There is so much going on in a glance; It's really important.
The last point is to smile
- I have a hard time with that -
but you must smile to seem accessible and friendly, and interested in interacting
with the other. The second technique that I'll describe here is quite important for our pathology in particular.
It's called "Explain, Reassure, Distract."
It was invented by an English advocacy group called "Changing Faces."
It allows you to guide people's curiosity.
Because curiosity is healthy and natural.
The day you really get that, you can then accept it and you're more willing to guide it.
To explain mains I explain my difference clearly and concisely.
"It is a giant congenital melanocytic nevus."
I use the technical term - even at age 5, kids can learn precise words - and that reassures the person facing you that you clearly know what you're talking about.
The next step is to reassure,
"Don't worry!
It doesn't hurt, and it's not contagious.
Look, you have a small mole, too. Mine's the same, just a lot bigger."
Then you move to the next step, which is to distract.
With very young children, four or five-year-olds, you tell them, "Offer to play with the other kid like this: 'Let's go to the slide'
or 'Let's kick that ball around'.''
For older children, it helps to advise them to bring up something positive about the other, so the other person is now the center of attention.
After all, what people like best is to talking about themselves.
So this strategy makes you seem super nice
and bingo! There you are.
The final strategy I want to present to you this evening is an approach that helps us react in stressful situations that you've identified ahead of time, that are predictable. I will give you three examples.
First one: you're at the beach, and someone is staring at you.
It's probably happened to everyone at some point.
It's very unpleasant.
So, you can now imagine and understand right away what is going on in the other person's mind.
First, she's surprised, puzzled, even afraid.
In our case, there's usually some disgust mixed in.
In these situations, I must confide that all you really want to do is bury your head in the sand or run away.
But that's not a solution.
Here's what works: you sit up straight, you stare back at the other person.
At that point, she understands right away that you already don't much appreciate her behavior, and then you smile.
That destabilizes her; she's the one who blushes, looks down, and you've won.
Second situation: you're queuing at a market with your child who has a nevus on his face or head. and that's often when you get random remarks.
At such times, you just say,
"It's only a birthmark, it's not catching,
thanks for your interest."
The "thanks for your interest" is a clear way of saying, "I've satisfied your curiosity,
that's enough."
Of course, you always do encounter slow people who keep insisting.
At such times, you can tell them, "I don't want to talk about it today,
maybe some other time."
And then you should just concentrate on your own day ahead, on whatever you must do, and move on.
Third situation: we have to talk about it, it's teasing.
People who tease or bully are inevitable.
It's very important to prepare your child for these situations so that she has some ready answers. Caught by surprise,
she may not find a good reply.
She must really learn how to reply firmly but not aggressively;
this is very important.
Another important point is to teach your child that she has her pride and dignity.
She must not let others order her around nor must she accept anything.
You must encourage her to ask for help from an adult with authority in that very moment in order to put a stop to it, early on, because, unfortunately, when bullying gets to be a habit, it usually gets worse.
The adult must be someone who can stop the situation firmly but also kindly so that it doesn't turn back on the child.
Now, I'm going to show you a slide I like a lot, because it's "advice" from people with good intentions, lots of good ideas, but who don't know what they're talking about.
First: you can't ignore the problem.
You often hear teachers say, "I'm going to ignore her condition and treat her as if she did not have one."
But she isn't stupid, and she knows she is not just like everyone else.
She needs she can talk about being different when needed, and it's important, because, first, if you act like there's nothing, you lose all credibility with the child, and then, you might reinforce her shame about her physical difference.
So, it's not a good idea to ignore it; you must keep a dialogue open.
Second point - I love this one - often made by people who think they're being very deep and say, "Don't worry, only what's inside counts."
Yeah, that's it.
Well, the outside is super important, too.
You think you're reassuring the child, but as he grows up, as he realizes that he must also make do with his physical appearance, that he must put forward his qualities, his strong points, it will hurt that much more.
It's not the right solution.
Finally, don't make a huge drama about it, or downplay the situation.
The child should not be locked into his difference.
He is so much more than his nevus.
It seems obvious, but he shouldn't see his life through a nevus filter.
It's a great danger.
He has many other qualities - of course, this is part of his person - but he needs to be empowered to move beyond it so that he can live a normal life.
Now, I'd like to tell you that life is only enriched by the quality encounters it offers throughout. So, how others see you is fundamental.
My own life has been fulfilled by meeting the extraordinary people who are everywhere you look.
Of course, I think right away of those most important meetings that were those with my husband, with each of my four daughters, but my very first encounter obviously took place on October, 28, 1967, in that maternity ward, where I met my parents, who, against all apparent odds, believed instantly in me and my future. I think on that day,
they were the only ones.
I can imagine what the midwife thought as well as the rest of the medical team.
I think they would never have bet a crooked penny on my future, and I would love to meet them again today and tell them all,
"Hi there! It's me!
Turns out, life is beautiful; it's magnificent, and frankly, it's really worth living."
What made the difference is my parents immediately saw me, instead of staring at me.
So, I want to thank them tonight, because they're here in the room.
I'm here before you thanks to them, so, a huge thank you, Mom and Dad.
Next, I would like to acknowledge all those amazing parents whom I've met through the patient advocacy groups ANGC and Naevus 2000.
I couldn't give this talk without mentioning Hanane Douibi, an amazing mother, who makes me want to move mountains.
So, to all of those parents, I want to say: believe in your children,
believe in yourselves.
You are the best experts on your children.
To you, my audience, I'd like to say: don't be afraid.
Your curiosity is not what's embarrassing.
Change the way you look at people, so it stays the kindest and most natural look possible.
I wish you all a beautiful metamorphosis.
And yes, we can!
(Applause) Thank you.
I had a brother.
His name was Frédéric.
Like my brothers, sisters and myself, he was a misfortuned child.
Great poverty, very large family: eleven children.
My father's alcoholism, verbal abuse, physical abuse... My father's own psychiatric confinement.
And in this world... where the cold, the fear, the humiliation, the deprivation, held first place, in this world, that didn't do us any favors, Frédéric was given a supplement, a bonus.
He was the first to be placed by my father, into a home with social services.
I can see both of them in the big room.
My father sitting on a bench, signing papers, my brother on the other side, haggard, stupified, not understanding what was happening to him.
And my brother went from famillyabuse to institutional abuse.
From home to home, vagrancy, violence, delinquency, and in the end, prison.
In this journey we could foresee, perceived as inevitable, in this chaotic journey, at one point, a conviction.
But not a conviction of incarceration, a conviction to community services.
There's Frédéric, who starts working on a construction site.
Imagine a large plain in Champagne that we still called "lousy", beaten by the wind, and Frédéric with his wheelbarrow, ploughing the earth all day, like slaves do in the movies, reconnecting without knowing it, with the past of our farther, who was in juvenile prison for many years.
But this wasn't just any construction site.
It was in fact a salvage excavation site, like those we have when making new equipment, or when building a motorway.
The archeologist that was there welcomed Frédéric, but didn't look at him as a deliquent.
He looked at him as he did to any other member of his team.
He welcomed him, explained him the work and Frédéric, step by step, got interested in archeology, it became his passion.
And he, who failed in school, who left school in the 6th grade retook the exams one by one, until he had a Master's degree in archeology.
And here he is, a few years later, archeologist, head of excavations.
By what miracle?
How was this possible?
The look of one man.
Frédéric felt accepted.
He felt looked after.
He felt a genuine interest.
And this one interest, this one look, triggered something inside him.
Frédéric became resilient.
So, resilence, what is it?
Resilience is the abiliity to face a crysis, to stand up, to bounce back.
Resilience is a sort of personal power that we all have, and that allows us to transform ourselves when we're in trouble.
Resilience, as alchemists say, is like transforming lead to gold.
Transforming difficulties into ressources.
Boris Cyrulnik, who popularized the concept of resilience in France, uses a very nice expression to describe it, which he used as title for one of his books.
He called it, "Un merveilleux malheur" [A wonderful misfortune].
A misfortune that teaches us.
But beware!
Resilience isn't a state, there isn't a resilience gene.
There aren't people who are resilient
and those who are not.
No. Resilience is not about people who are particularly brave, solitary heros, the "Captain Futures" of trauma, or the "Harry Potters" who make adversity disappear, as if by magic.
No, resilient people, are those like you and me.
Simply in difficulty, at some point, when everything's so dark, so difficult, they know how to seek for something, someone, a helping hand.
And they take it.
Frédéric didn't know he was resilient.
You, in this room, all of you, at varying levels, you have had to face difficulties, trauma, setbacks.
Loss of a loved one, serious illness, abandonment, harassment at work, loss of a job, bankruptcy, domestic abuse, divorce, abuse during childhood, each of you has had to face, to stand and respond.
And you didn't necessarily say it to yourselves, and you didn't necessarily use the word "resilience".
And you didn't necessarily see that someone was there.
Yet, and to give you an idea of what tutors of resilience are, ask yourselves: during these hard times, who was there for you?
Who didn't judge you?
Who looked at you differently?
Who wasn't discouraged during your failures, during your mistakes?
We generally meet these tutors of resilience in our close family, or in our extended family.
We will often meet them in institutions, in support services.
It will be a psychologist, it will be an educator, it will be a mentor.
We often meet them in the associative world: directors of sportive, cultural associations, popular education.
For me, it was a teacher.
We were living in Champagne,
In a small village.
A small agricultural village.
My parents weren't farmers.
We lived on the margins, we were very poor.
Oftenly, we were dirty, and we were mocked, humiliated, agressed, hit by our classmates.
Especially when we went to school.
And in this school I was 8, I was in year one, and there was a teacher.
And this teacher looked over me, I could feel it.
I felt her goodwill.
I felt her genuine interest.
I felt her concern for me.
To the extent that one day, an autumnal afternoon, she said to us, "Tomorrow, we'll be studying natural science and you must all come in with a chestnut".
We came in the next day, very proud, each one of us with a chestnut.
And we had a natural science lesson.
She gave us a small glass pot.
We made a label, that we stuck onto the glass pot, with our names.
We put some cotton inside, that we watered, and we put the chestnut in the small glass pot.
And then a fews days later, as the weeks went by, the chestnuts sprout.
And little by little, a shoot, a chestnut tree appears.
And then, a coincidence: the chestnut that I had brought started to sprout very quickly.
And the chestnut tree grew.
The teacher told me, "Patrick, your chestnut tree's growing, that's great...
But soon it will be too big for the pot.
I'm going to plant it in my yard", that adjoined the community school.
When she told me that, At first, I had questions.
Then, I was proud.
And then, I felt the joy.
And then, week after week, month after month, year after year, she brought me news on the chestnut tree, that had grown roots, that was growing, blossoming.
I can tell you, that simply by telling you this story, I feel, still today, pride within me.
I feel her love, and I feel the strength that she gave me at that moment.
And as a result, today, I'm a sociologist, a speaker at HEC, and an author.
But it all started there.
So, how to explain that an archeologist can save a man by accepting him?
That a teacher can transform a child's path, by caring for him by loving him.
Well, to understand this mecanism, that is at work in the process, and in the tutors of resilience, I suggest that we return to an experiment.
A scientific experiment conducted in the United States in 1968.
There are two researchers there, called Rozenthal and Jacobson, they are working on the intelligence of rats.
So, they are not making them take IQ tests.
To work on the intelligence of rats, we make a maze, we place some cheese, and make the rats run, and then we see how long it takes them to find the cheese.
They take twelve rats.
They randomly seperate them into two groups of six rats.
They entrust the first group of six rats to a group of students and tell them, "These rats come from transformation and from genetic lineage, we prepared them for important experiments, you must expect them to give execptional perfomances.
We need you to look after them, for a few weeks."
They entrust the other six rats to another group of students.
And they tell them, "You know, these rats, we bred them, we thought we were going to experiment on them, but actually we don't know what to do with them.
They're not very healthy, it would be good if you looked after them."
We returned a few weeks later.
And we did the maze experiment.
We saw that the rats from the 1st group were quicker at finding the cheese.
Those from the second group, though not only were slower, but some didn't even make it over the starting line.
So, the researchers said to themselves "This is incredible.
What happened?"
Simple: the students from the 1st group believed in the quality of their rats, they believed in their potential. They fed them, nursed them
with this belief.
They showed them affection.
And it physiologically transformed the rats, increasing their performance levels.
So we did the same experiement with children.
I assure you, we didn't put them in a maze.
It took place in the suburbs of San Francisco, Disadvantaged suburb.
A primary school called Oak School, that welcomed many immigrant children, some with linguistic problems.
There were problems of levels, etc...
They presented themselves saying they were doing a study for Harvard University, on the belated emergence of intelligence.
So they needed to give IQ tests to all the children, and return a year later to check if it was still the same.
They gave the IQ tests.
But then, for each class, they choose by means of a draw, five pupils, to whom they give 20 extra IQ points.
They send the modified results to the teachers.
And told them to be sure that the teachers really believe the results, that they are really sorry, that they were sent by accident.
A year later, they came back.
They had the children to take the IQ test again.
What happened?
All the children who were randomly selected and were given 20 extra points increased their IQ, measured by the same test, by 5 to 25 points, in one year.
This result, that may appear miraculous, is clearly referenced today.
A dozen studies were conducted to verify the existence of this phenomena, called the self-fulfilling prophecy.
It means that the belief that I have of another, what I think of their worth, of their qualities, of their potential, will come true.
We also call this effect, the Pygmalion effect.
Because, in the end, the tutors of resilience are people who through their sight and attitude, their personal belief in another, will trigger in this other a process, the person will see themselves as more intelligent, more beautiful, stronger, and trigger in themselves a process of growth, like the chestnut tree.
They have a certain number of characteristics.
The first characteristic is that they have a particular view, they have a genuine interest in the other.
The second characteristic, is that they leave it up to the other, to come to them, to talk or not.
To the extant that, when I was general delegate for Emmaüs France, the guideline was to never question a companion about their story or their tragedies.
But it wasn't rare that a companion working with a volunteer, would suddenly open up, relate a tragedy, and because they felt listened to and heard, they could transform themselves.
Resilient people don't judge the chosen way, to create their path of resilience.
It can be by traveling, it can be by faith, it can be by cultural or social activism, it can be by creation, by entrepreneurship, it can be by doing TEDx.
Whatever the way.
Tutors of resilience have yet another characteristic: they never become discouraged.
Why?
They know that resilience is a process.
And so, the mistakes, the failures are just steps.
Tutors of resilience give confidence to the other, because they have this particular view, this compassion, this humanity, that makes the other feel beautiful, feel big, worthy.
Tutors of resilience know how to see qualities in the other, even though they aren't visible.
This is what happened to Tim Guénard:
when he was 2 years old, he was abandonned by his mother.
His father was alcoholic, violent, and broke both of Tim's legs.
He spent two years in the hospital.
Aand was then placed in an institution, where he was sexually abused.
He became a deliquent.
Understandably.
And one day, he finds himself in a commissioner's office.
And Tim Guénard relates in his book, "Stronger Than Hate", that the look of this commissioner, the fact that he looked at him, for who he was humanly, was able to see him as more than a deliquent, the young, rebellious, lost, suffering.
And that he was able to see the potential growth, within this young man.
This one look, these few instants, changed his life.
Today, Tim Guénard is an author, an educator, and he hosts a shelter for young people in great difficulty, in the south.
So you see, in the end, each of us, each of you, whatever your past is, whatever your wealth, you can be there for someone. 
You can be there for another, either a relative, or a stranger.
Of course, you won't necessarily know what your look, your smile, your word would have done.
But this is how it should be.
That's being someone.
And to finish, I would like to ask you a question.
Maybe you could, if you want, just for a few moments, close your eyes, and ask yourselves, who was there for you?
Who didn't judge you?
Who inspired you?
Loved? 
Supported?
Ask yourselves... Let this figure emerge, this person, who was an infinite source, that didn't dry up, and perhaps, you could, or not, as you wish, let others benefit from it.
Thank you.
Thank you for being here for me.
(Applause)
Is it working? Yes it is!
There is a sector of activity
which, from start to finish, has major social and environmental implications for the planet.
This sector of activity emits 6% of the world's greenhouse gasses.
As much as the aviation industry.
This sector of activity consumes 10% of the world's electricity, and it continues to grow.
This sector generates 15 billion dollars of annual profit to traffickers.
This sector is digital technology.
I would like to share with you today a few simple solutions that we can put into place now to reduce all of these impacts
and to also avoid compromising our children's ability to access digital technology tomorrow.
We can achieve this simply by becoming responsible digital citizens.
My name is Vincent Courboulay, I have been a professor and researcher at the Université de la Rochelle for fifteen years.
To give you a sense of the evolution of all things digital in that time, in April 2004, I was, by invitation, one of the first users of an instant messaging system that today has 1.5 billion users: Gmail.
Fifteen years ago, phones looked like this.
Today, Apple's market value is worth more than a thousand billion dollars thanks almost exclusively to the following: the iPhone.
Plenty of other things have changed in 15 years but that's not the point.
(Laughter) And so, fifteen years ago, I embraced digital technology.
And very quickly, a saying arose: "If you are not paying for the product, you are the product."
I don't know about you, but I don't like being a product.
So I began to scratch beneath the surface of all the glamour that surrounded and still surrounds technology.
And what I found was large-scale disaster.
To put this in perspective, I will follow digital technology's life cycle.
To properly evaluate the cost of technology one must consider its life cycle. It's essential to avoid making errors and to really grasp the environmental, social and economic costs.
The life cycle of digital technology begins in the mines of Asia and Africa with the extraction of raw materials.
In Asia, we find rare-earth minerals called "digital vitamins."
Entire regions are razed to ensure that a monopoly of these strategic metals is awarded to countries ready to pay the price.
In Africa we find blood minerals: cobalt, gold, tantalum, tungsten and tin.
And when we get drift of the methods of extraction of these minerals, the term "blood minerals" is by no means a distortion.
According to Unicef, in 2014, 40,000 children worked in the southern mines of the Democratic Republic of the Congo.
Children seven years-old talked of working twelve-hour days to earn one to two dollars.
And every year, there are hundreds of deaths.
Next comes the production phase.
And the situation is hardly better.
Smartphones do not grow on trees.
Yet sub-contractors drive output of break-neck speed. up to 20,000 products a day for the best-sellers.
To keep up with demand, recruitment is a no-holds-barred process. They are capable of emptying entire schools close to factories to put students into "mandatory traineeships" on the production line for up to 11 hours a day.
When the technology reaches in Europe, things don't get any better.
To get our apps up and running to obtain videos, our beloved series, to stock our information, our photos this requires data centers, huge factories consisting of hundreds of computers.
Right now in the world the number of data centers is close to 9 million.
If we put them side by side, we are looking at the equivalent of 25,000 football fields.
Imagine the amount of electricity required to run these things.
Once stocked, the information needs to be relayed to your doorstep.
This entails fibre optics, copper, 3G broadband, 4G broadband and soon 5G broadband
Everyone here probably has a box.
It consumes enormous amounts of materials and energy.
And that's not taking into account the health and social problems linked to excessive use of so-called social media or of video games.
And once these devices have reached their shelf life, what becomes of them?
They become garbage.
In 2014, it's estimated that we produced 42 billion kilos of electronic and electric waste.
And, according to Interpol, three-quarters of this tonnage is subject to mafia activity.
Three quarters.
The crazy thing is that coherent management of this waste could generate revenue of more than 350 billion euros and create - and this is proven - thousands of jobs.
After researching this, I realized that we must develop better practices that demonstrate responsibility and restraint where technology is concerned.
A bit like what we have already done with our cars.
At night, you turn off your cars, you don't keep the engine running.
And yet we keep our ADSL boxes on all night no one is using them.
If you have a crack in your windshield smaller than a 2-euro coin, you know who to call.
You don't get rid of your car.
If your trunk is full, you empty it, you don't change cars.
If the motor doesn't run like it used to, you don't change cars, you get it fixed.
We should do the same with digital technology.
But let's say you do want a different car,
Nothing is stopping you from buying a second-hand one.
Yet we hesitate to do this with our smartphones and computers.
And if you want to buy a new car - you have the right - would you not prefer to choose a cleaner one, that is easier to repair?
It's time to change our attitude - with respect to technology.
We need to develop good habits.
What are those good habits ?
We all know them because they are the same as those used in other parts of the economy.
They are the famous 4 R's. The first is to refuse.
I refuse to systematically change my smartphone.
Today, the rate of renewal is about every 20 to 22 months, less than two years.
That's too much.
In business, we replace our computers with new ones every three or four years: as soon as the warranty is up.
We need to change the way we think.
We need to control our consumption.
The next good habit, the next solution, is that of... reuse and repair.
I agree with you: it goes without saying. We would like nothing more than to repair our computers and smartphones, but, true, it's difficult and complicated, but, little by little, things are changing. mainly thanks to European laws and their French adaptation.
For example, the Ministry Responsible for Sustainable Environmental Change commissioned me to be part of a working group whose objective was simple: come up with a means of alerting consumers as to when smartphones need repair.
This means that we, the consumer, at the moment of purchase, will be able to establish with certainty when and how our smartphones will need repair.
The third lever is that of reuse.
Let's return to the automobile analogy.
We're driving on the highway at 130, our children in the backseat, people who are dear to us, traveling in a used car.
We know nothing of the previous owners, but it being a used car is reassuring.
Yet we're still reluctant to buy used smartphones and computers.
We need to get rid of this mentality for the planet's sake.
It creates jobs.
The last point is recycling.
You've heard me say three quarters of the stuff ends up in the mafia's hands.
A simple gesture is to make sure that when finished with an item, we drop it off at a certified disposal centre.
These four gestures, which apply to all economic sectors, when applied to technology, create satisfaction, value, jobs, create savings and contribute to the circular economy. There are but gains.
We must adopt these best practices in our businesses, in our homes.
Some companies and communities are trying to become digitally responsible.
The university, the town, a well known company in the vicinity of Niort, all these different actors are conscious of the digital footprint and are doing something about it.
At home, there are things we can do.
I spoke of it earlier.
We can add power switches to our boxes to turn them off at night.
Simple gestures that go far.
And we must communicate this information to our young people who are particularly attached to their devices and new technology.
Young people, rightly so, are an important part of the picture.
Last year, I did a stint at the City School of Surgères
- a college and high school in one not far from here - to help them obtain the title of "digitally responsible" institution.
But more than the title, what I found fascinating, was that the administration, the technicians, the teachers, of course, and the students, got together for a common purpose.
Some simple examples.
The technicians, once sensitized to the importance of being digitally responsible, asked the Rector permission to turn off the computers at night.
Reduction in electricity bills, reduction in greenhouse gas emissions, the prolonging of the shelf-life of equipment, all this with one simple action.
Through this project, the teachers were able to address the whole question of sustainability, but also of physics, chemistry, math, geography, geopolitics and music.
The idea was not to suggest "Let's stop everything!"
but simply, "Let's change how we do things."
This might have surprised you, to hear me link music with digital responsibility?
Well allow me the immense pleasure of presenting to you the musical group from the City School of Surgères in its digitially responsible version of the Big Flo and Oli's song « Dommage » ("Too Bad")
