What is the role of an artist?
You may think, like the vast majority of people, that an artist's role is to deliver a message.
When Picasso was asked, "Master, what is your message?"
he would answser, "What message?
I am not a mailman!"
An artist is there to ask questions, to himself first, and then to the public so that they seize upon them and ask themselves in turn.
From the question is born the thought that will lead to action.
The Anthropocene - as Gilles told you earlier - is the nice name that many meteorologists and geologists give to the current period in our planet's history.
Anthropocene is a neologism built from two Greek words: "anthropos," human being, and "kainos," new, in reference to that new period in which human activity has become the major geologic constraint.
Today, it is men who alter the environment and alter the planet, in a very dangerous way.
I am just completing...
But "Where danger lies also grows that which saves."
This famous sentence of the poet Friedrich Hölderlin has never been more relevant.
The extraordinary technological advances which have enabled the overexploitation of our natural resources, this human genius can be put, in my opinion, as a counterpart, to the service of redemption and repair.
All of us can act, not just engineers, scientists and technicians ...
No, all of us, you ladies and you gentlemen, and me ...
But to do so, we must resist. We must resist the depressive atmosphere and resist fatalism.
To resist is to fight the gregarious instinct that is in each of us.
By which, I mean "consumption."
Don't worry, I am not going to tell you, "We must all ride bicycles, use candles, or live under teepees!" No.
Seriously, I think that we can, as often as possible, ponder and weigh up the real consequences of each purchase we make, such as for example, buying a bigger flat-screen TV, a more powerful computer, a more comfortable car or even just a new clothe.
I act as a citizen, but I also act as an artist.
Today, I want to use my expertise to raise awareness.
The overexploitation of natural resources has resulted, among other things, in the extinction of a large number of animal species.
In just 42 years, we have lost 58% of the planetary wildlife. 38% of which are terrestrial vertebrates, because there are also fish, birds, etc.
It just so happens that animals are my business.
My animal paintings are sold in numerous galleries around the world - they sell very well - and I could go on making a very comfortable living of this work without questioning myself.
But I've decided to get involved and to act.
If an artist cannot act directly on the causes of this extinction, on the causes of this decline, he can nevertheless try through the power of his art, and as far as possible, to convince and rally as many people as possible to support those who fight for the preservation of biodiversity, through donations aimed to fund programs that protect wildlife and which are very costly.
Let me remind you that Barack Obama's first campaign for the 2008 presidential elections, was widely funded by $5 to $30 donations.
This year, in partnership with Prince Albert II of Monaco Foundation, we have presented our first campaign "Delete ?"
"Delete ?" is a series of artworks I created to alert urban populations to the threat to a large number of species.
So, what should I paint to rally, to convince, to seduce people?
During our earliest meetings with the Foundation, in 2015, we discussed a lot about that.
Scientists think - and I assume they're right about it - that the loss of the amphibians is far more harmful for humanity than that of the elephants.
But I wanted to paint elephants.
Then I remembered a story that had stuck with me.
Do you know who created this?
His name was Raymond Loewy.
He is the father of industrial design.
He is also credited for the logo design of LU biscuits, the Lucky Strike's packaging, Studbaker and many Coca-Cola products, in short, many world-famous visuals.
Raymond Loewy, as a young designer in the 1940s and 1950s, would go to industrial fairs to seek out new customers, and tell the manufacturers at their stands, " Your product is excellent. It works
really well. It's very effective ...
But, boy! It's so ugly!
If it were beautiful, you would sell many more.
And I can make it beautiful! "
And this has been his life-long motto: "Beauty sells!"
To sell an idea, it's not enough that she be beautiful philanthropically or philosophically, it also has to be beautiful aesthetically, artistically and in its modeling,
because the image is the first thing that seizes you in the public space.
It's the image that will convince you to want to know more about it. Long before any sound or anything else, the picture does it.
So, I managed to convince my partners to go straight to the point and show large and beautiful mammals, such as the Panthera Tigris Altaïca.
Panthera Tigris Altaïca, is the taxonomic name of the Siberian tiger, also known as the Amur Tiger.
It is the most powerful of all the tiger subspecies.
It is also the third largest predator on Earth behind the Kodiak bear and the polar bear.
Males can weigh up to 350-400 kg and measure up to 3.80 m from head to tail.
The Siberian tiger lives in the northeast of China and in Eastern Siberia, along the Amur River - hence its name - which is the natural boundary between this two big countries.
It lives on a huge territory that is also a very geopolitically strategic location.
Indeed, it is where the biggest oil pipeline in the world runs, the ESPO pipeline.
The ESPO pipeline goes from Eastern Siberia to the Pacific Ocean and runs for over 4,000 km. In 2020, it will deliver more than 80 million tons of crude oil to China, Japan and Korea, for an annual sum of $125 billion.
The stakes are colossal.
The construction of ESPO required some deforestation, which resulted in a partial reduction of the tiger's habitat. But it also opened new roads that facilitate access for poachers.
A Siberian tiger's skin is worth 10,000 € on the black market.
Now, protection programs are costly.
You have to pay people to watch over the tigers, fight against poachers.
It really requires funds.
The sums invested are significant - Prince Albert II Foundation is participating as well as other organizations - but the results are rewarding.
It can be done.
In the middle of the 1990s, there were only around 30 Siberian tigers left.
Today, they number around 500. perhaps a bit more, as we suspect there are some in North Korea, but going there to count them is difficult.
So, programs are rewarding. It allowed the IUCN - the International Union for the Conservation of Nature, to downgrade the Siberian tiger from its famous Red List of endangered species, from "Critically endangered" to simply "endangered."
Now, to return to my introduction. 
An artist is there to ask questions.
My question is "Delete ?" which is in French "Supprimer."
"Delete ?" is a universally known IT pictogram.
It is the usual way to erase a file from a computer.
I adapted this common pictogram to a tangible and tragic reality, that is the extinction and the threat to a large number of species, by showing on large tarps hung in the streets, or by nocturnal projections, mammals and animals that are disappearing in a very theatrical way.
During the creation of these paintings in my workshop, I photographed the work in progress almost frame by frame.
This enabled us to obtain high definition pictures that could then be printed on these large tarps, and then when looking at these images from the last one where the canvas is finished, to the first one in reverse order up to the empty background, we can see the animal slowly disappearing.
So, we've created short videos which were shown for the first time during all the summer at night, on the ramparts of the princely palace.
Passers-by could watch live the disappearance of big mammals.
"Delete ?" engages our reptilian brain.
When we see the pictogram appear, we sense our index finger ready to click but, at the same time, we feel a compelling need to resist ... (Applause)
Who runs us?
Who runs our lives?
Who runs the world?
Politicians?
Banks?
Religion?
Family?
Maybe the media, or maybe "Gafa", you know, Google, Apple, Facebook, Amazon, our friends of the web?
Huge topic, right?
Well, what really runs the world are our senses.
Aristotle already said that in ancient times, he get across this message to us: "There is nothing in our intelligence that hasn't first passed through our senses."
I'm a designer, and I live by Aristotle's principles.
I use my senses to create things that speak - at least I hope - to our sensory intelligence.
I would like to share with you glimpses of this sensory intelligence.
It often goes over our heads, but it totally defines us.
It's simple like youth, my youth.
Imagine, I'm five years old.
Just try to imagine because... (Laughter) My room shares a wall with my mother's weaving workshop.
In the morning, I would wake up to the noise of her workshop and her activity: the mechanical rhythm of her industrial sewing machine, the damp sound of the iron's steam, or the squeal of the fabric being torn.
Not bad, eh?
But there's also the smell.
It's not the smell of coffee that reaches my nostrils, but the odor of new fabric which smells like animals or synthetics, and which is unfolded or shaken.
When I enter her workshop, which is a completely magical place for me as a child, it's completely cluttered with pieces of fabric which are ready to become seats, drapes and curtains.
I'm still five, well ... imagine.
Back then, I would follow my grandad, a civil engineer, on a tour of his construction sites.
Still today, I am delighted by the smell of fresh cement that perfumed all of our visits.
So, I think that my designer career, I built it in this youth, at the original stream of all these sensations that my family doers have offered me, and also of all the memories I have accumulated.
This gave me a taste for materials, for shapes, and the capacity to imagine, create objects that are useful, practical - poetic, I hope - complex, technical and totally sensory.
In the end, I've been trying for the last few years to make things that make sense and have senses.
But, I'm not the only one to have built a career on childhood feelings.
Prior to becoming a writer, Proust was a child.
His first sensations as a child were the key to the success of his entire adult life, and above all, of all his activity as a writer.
Who doesn't know his "Madeleine"?
It looks like everybody knows it!
I promise, I'm not going to read the seven volumes of "In Search of Lost Time;" however, I'm going to describe with a few extracts, the working of his sensory intelligence so that we can start to understand our own sensory stories.
One Sunday, Proust, in his adult years, is served a cup of tea by his mother with a little madeleine.
Then, in a very conventional way, he eats this madeleine, and drinks his tea.
At that moment, he shudders with pleasure, and he is amazed to see that this pleasure was not in him, but rather he himself was it, and most of all that this "essence" as he calls it, as soon as he savoured the madeleine, allows him to stop feeling "mediocre, petty and mortal," he says.
Just imagine for a few seconds the savings on anti-anxiety drugs that we would all make if we could taste a madeleine and all feel absolutely amazing just by tasting it.
Obviously, not just any madeleine but our own madeleine!
I will spare you the details but Proust ponders this over many pages until he reaches a revelation.
And this revelation is a childhood memory.
And he says, "Suddenly, the memory came back to me."
It was every Sunday morning when he visited his aunt, Léonie, in Combray.
She used to give him little pieces of madeleine that she dipped in her herbal tea.
The sight of the madeleine when he tasted it with his mum didn't do anything to him at all, but it is the very taste and smell of the madeleine that made the difference. Proust says that taste
and smell are like souls that keep on remembering [and carrying] the vast structure of recollection.
What about you?
What feeling overwhelms you, if you let yourself take time to think about it?
What madeleine makes you succumb?
What childhood sensations are building your life, your habits, your desires, your adult preferences and perhaps your career?
By chance, is any of you addicted to the smell of fresh linen?
Wouldn't it be because you were hiding, when you were a child, in the basket of linen waiting to be ironed?
Indeed, there are not always positive things.
Why do you hate the taste of beets?
Wouldn't it be because it reminds you of the primary school's canteen?
What if I hummed for you these five tones?
(Humming) Ta ta ta ta ta ... (Laughter) Doesn't it suddenly make you think of the Dim tights and doesn't it lift your mood a little?
So, why do all these memories instinctively give you a thrill of happiness, of nostalgia maybe, of aversion, or perhaps give you simply energy?
This is because, although we are not really aware of it, we have truly exceptional tools that are individual, personal, and highly advanced.
These are our body senses our emotions in our brain.
That's not bad.
We should not neglect them nor forget them.
Today, even if we live in a digital world where the virtual rhymes with the mutation of society, we need to consider our senses.
And, indeed, neurosciences - which are quite good sciences - gives us the keys to access all these tools.
They help us understand and interpret why the smell of fresh cement or the famous madeleine build our personality.
So, schematically, our brain behaves differently on the periphery and at its center.
On the periphery, it is Cartesian.
It provides rational thoughts and especially, it deals with language.
At the center is the kingdom of the madeleine, a wonderful kingdom of sensations and of survival instinct, of emotions and memories.
And more importantly, the central brain decides.
So of course, it has delegated the language to the periphery.
That's why, sometimes, you can perfectly understand a situation, the facts, figures, details, but you have difficulties validating it.
You can't find the right word and you often think: "I don't know why, but this doesn't feel right."
That's normal.
It's the brain of the madeleine that controls your decision, and your emotion, but not the language.
This is also why marketers, designers, manufacturers, innovators, even designers - only those who aren't sensory designers - create products that are increasingly specific, useful, efficient, technological, financially viable as projects, but that don't appeal to your central brain.
In other words, they don't evoke in you some kind of positive emotion and positive feeling, so you will not buy them nor promote them.
Now you know why nearly 70% of new products are difficult to use and fail commercially.
We call this "perceptual bugs."
The field of transportation offers us beautiful examples of "perceptual bugs" which cause tremendous discomfort to passengers.
You've probably all been once a high-speed train passenger.
When the high-speed train arrives at your destination, you are at the door and press the button to open it.
And the door remains mute.
It has not registered your request.
Nothing happens.
Rationally, you know it's going to open, that the train won't leave without letting you off, but you cannot really feel it, and indeed, stress comes up; although a simple sign could have reassured and calmed you, such as small indicator light that would tell you that it has registered the request, and that you're waiting for the mechanism.
This small indicator light would appeal to your senses but not necessarily to your reason.
Now, let's stay in the field of transportation.
Are you using a little avoidance strategy to refrain from touching the central handrail when you enter the subway train?
(Laughter) You know, this stainless steel bar super-shiny and smooth, except that when all hands have held on to it, it becomes warm, slippery, moist, greasy.
Inevitably, what seize you here is not a feeling of stress but of disgust and the worry of catching all the germs of the previous passengers.
This is a very classic case of "perceptual bug" that makes your journey necessarily unpleasant and may sometimes force you to take an Uber.
Currently, the handrail material has been modified.
It has a drier touch; it is grippier; and the passenger's perception makes him think it's cleaner.
So far, these examples I'm giving you are good, but experience is better.
Let's move on to some practical work that is going to test our sensory intelligence and our memories.
You'll certainly find next to your seat a small pot.
To, to, to, to.
(Laughter) It's an experiment, so ...
This small pot is the small pot of glue of the nursery school that helped you, when you were in the nursery school under your lady teacher's caring gaze, to become the adult that you are today.
It's a very long story.
(Laughter) Not that easy, huh?
This small pot was created in 1930.
It is still made in Touraine, France, and it is still used by schoolchildren.
And it is totally sensory, we just heard that.
So, first, the sight ... It's the easiest.
Look.
This small pot, so familiar, is Cléopâtre.
We can be proud of it.
It is unique.
For 90 years, its shape has remained unchanged, its volume and graphical representation hardly modified.
It's exactly like the perfume bottle Chanel No 5 which, since its creation, remains the same and constantly altered and adapted to its time.
Verify.
Next the sound ... We already experienced it.
(Creaks of the lid being rotated) What a great little music!
Listen, we could do a concert! that's just right, we're in the Opera.
A great little music that announces something even more interesting: the smell.
Smell it!
(Laughter) The smell of almond, the smell of almond and childhood.
You become Proust!
Remember, he told us, smell and flavor like souls, keep on for a long time, remembering and [carrying] the vast structure of recollection.
Here you are, back in the nursery school.
Now the touch: look at the tiny spatula.
It's in complete osmosis with the glue that is inside.
It's to facilitate the learning of fine motor skills and the successful collage exercise and work of art of the nursery school child.
As artists, you did perfectly.
Finally, the taste.
(Laughter) Who's never tasted the glue?
(Laughter) Almost all of you have eaten some of it.
It's a mixture of potato starch and water, so no stress but rather a retroactive moving thought for the improvised snack you had that day.
(Laughter) Why did we create this sensory DNA we just analysed together?
To develop what we call a "sensory signature," and develop with this signature a new range of products in line with the history of this glue.
And why would we do that, in the end?
To use other measures than the sole technical and technological performance in order to compete with human assets against the major international groups of glue.
Remember that it's a SME.
"There is nothing in our intelligence that has not passed first through our senses."
Today, being super innovative is not necessarily about being digitally connected; it's not only about being on the cutting edge of technology; but it's knowing how to use and decipher senses and emotions to better guide reason.
To be a designer, is to invent positive experiences for people's everyday life.
These are experiences that mix perceptions, sensations and emotions to create a design that takes almost nothing but reveals everything.
So, this approach can be applied at any scale, to machine tools, for instance.
If we design a machine tool, it's to increase a positive impression of safety when used.
To cars: when you close the door of a luxury or premium car, the sound of the door closure reinforce the feeling of a luxury car.
When you feel the soft touch of the dashboard of this same car, it reassures you when you are driving it.
Even to beauty products: the fluid and non-greasy feel of a cream texture boosts and enhances a better self-esteem.
Even tramways can be sensory.
I'll give you only one example: thermal comfort.
One question, one issue: Is it be possible to keep a constant temperature in a tramway when the doors open every two minutes?
No.
In summer, it's hot and in winter, it's cold.
Another issue.
You all listen to weather reports, so you know they talk about the actual temperature and the perceived temperature.
Well, we worked on the perceived temperature in tramcars.
We designed the interior light by changing the colour temperature of the light sources.
No one can see it - and that's on purpose.
In winter, a warmer light gives you a specific sensation; in summer, it gives a cooler light in order to gain about two degrees of perceived temperature.
The expression of sensory design takes almost nothing - you cannot see it - nevertheless, it brings a real comfort.
So, what if we try together to share and meet the challenges of sensory intelligence?
First, I suggest we should rediscover our madeleines, all of us, so as to prepare the ground for this intelligence.
And then, I would like to ask you to share and understand its mechanisms so that we recover a form of simplicity and of freedom in thinking and consuming.
And I would like that we give back sensory intelligence the place it deserves in our lives.
Why?
We just experienced it: Because what doesn't change in each of us, is the desire to be comforted, reassured, reinforced in what we are or what we would like to be.
So, if we are able develop these three elements, then we will find solutions that inspire.
Feelings and emotions will become the real drivers of a society we live in, where we will provide more performance, greater sustainability and more prosperity.
We will be ready to develop an economy based on desire.
Thank you.
(Applause)
What is it Monastic life for you?
When I ask people, they often tell me "Monastic life is confinement, loneliness, chastity, denial of sex..." All things that are harsh, hard and complicated but that are actually means and not an end!
So, what is monastic life?
It's a race. A race toward joy.
I am a witness to 30 years
of monastic life and activity.
You all heard of the Benedictine monastic motto: pax, peace.
The monk is a seeker of peace.
The monk seeks inner peace, seeks the peace of the heart.
Let's discuss some reflections about joy, real deep joy, the joy no one can take away from you.
In my opinion, joy is the product of peace.
When peace occurs in the heart of man, joy is not far away.
This peace isn’t about not having problems, but instead, in the difficulties of everyday life and existence, it is a peace that is given to you.
In the hardship of life, serenity sets in.
Serenity gives a person some foundation, some strength.
And this peace is not born from an absence of problems, quite the opposite, but it is born in an accepted and agreed vulnerability.
In my view, it has three levels: First level, peace with oneself, Second level, peace with others, and thirdly, peace with God for the believer.
Peace with yourself.
To find peace with oneself, I think we need to accept ourselves, as we are.
Accept ourselves as we are.
Indeed we sometimes have the annoying tendency to want to be different from who we really are.
Thinner, bigger, tanner, richer, more efficient, with a large company, etc ... what have you.
True happiness begins with the acceptance of who I am.
On the Island of Lerins, we welcome a lot of young people.
And when we welcome these young people, and we talk about these things, I ask them to do the following exercise.
Tomorrow, when you put on your make-up or you shave, look at yourself into the mirror and try to smile.
And if you can smile, then you have won.
Yes, you are a good person!
Yes I am a good girl, yes I'm a good guy.
There can be no real peace and therefore no joy without a minimum of self-esteem.
You cannot have peace if we don’t accept ourselves as you we are with our talents, which are real, but also our limits and weaknesses.
Peace with oneself is a source of joy!
Peace with others is a source of joy.
Peace with others seems to me related with charity, love.
What is charity?
Love is to give, give freely, without expecting anything in return, putting up with injustice ... for the good of the beloved.
Love is to give, give freely putting up with the conflicts, the contradictions, with a generous heart.
Peace and true joy are springing on the way of self-giving.
Oftentimes, I am sad and disappointed because instead of giving, I wanted to take. Indeed, we love others
not for who they are, but for what they bring to us.
We use them rather than helping them.
And in my view, a truly successful life is a life where we give up our selfish love, to a love that serves people.
If you expect something from someone else, which rather normal, you will always feel frustrated.
But if love is not free but self-serving, you will be disappointed.
While if you expect nothing from others, you will be fulfilled, since the other, not being ungrateful, will bring you much more than what you expect since you do not expect anything!
Thus the secret of happiness is to give and expect nothing from others and so we are delighted.
The secret of a happy life: the gift of self.
I joined the monastery to be happy, I stay at the monastery to make others happy.
I get married to be happy, I stay with my spouse to make them happy.
The governing principle is always love, the free, selfless gift of self, for the good of the other.
Happiness and joy.
Often, with years of monastic life that have shaped me, I manage to say: my only trouble is the misfortune of others!
Finally peace with one's God as a source of joy.
As for me, a few decades ago already, I experienced God's tenderness.
In short, God burst into my life and took me away from the abyss of alcohol and drugs.
This founding experience has led me to dedicate my life to him so that he puts it to the service of others ...
It has been 30 years of "monastic activity", if I dare say so!
30 years of happiness, which does not mean without any difficulties.
So let’s try and understand this happiness, this joy this joy in a peaceful relationship with God.
In a nutshell, we are human beings with desires, and we have a fundamental desire, it is to be loved and endlessly loved.
Alas, we experience that no being, however dear they may be, loves us on a par with our infinite desire.
Who has not experienced being misunderstood by their parents, their friends,
or that a distance exists with the spouse and that this distance is sometimes painful?
Despite all the love we can receive from our loved ones, we can have the painful experience of a loneliness that sometimes is inconsolable.
So much so that this solitude, if exacerbated, can even lead to suicide.
Our infinite desire to be loved is not filled and cannot be filled by any creature.
Only infinite love can fill our infinite desire to be loved.
Only God who is infinite can fill our infinite desire to be loved.
This may seem rhetorical: in any case it is my experience.
We feel sad whenever we are asking and not giving.
We are frustrated and therefore bitter each time we want to take or control the others or things in an unwarranted way.
The learning process of the true joy requires a certain detachment from oneself, a gift of self, always to be renewed, to the service of others.
True joy is achieved by the gift of self to others, a gift of self that is free - and I do insist - free and disinterested and which holds up to injustice.
A donation that holds up to injustice.
Love is really strong when, in fact, while putting up with the contradictions of life, it remains calm and peaceful.
And to measure this serenity, the outer and inner silence is the sign.
Indeed, the first reaction when facing injustice is to justify oneself, even to blame the others ... We look at our own injury and we are no longer capable to put ourselves in the shoes of the others.
And generally the peace is lost, whispers settle in, and joy, of course, vanishes.
Let’s give, be offered to others, silently put up with the injustices, the irritations: this is, in my view, the secret of joy.
Joy comes just naturally with the gift of self.
The more we give, the bigger joy grows, the stronger and the more impregnable it becomes.
And each one of us must figure out how, under their own conditions of existence, to find their own way of expressing joy. But a great source of joy is to give some of one's time, even one's life, for great causes, or one great cause.
And a great cause indeed, now that globalization is in full swing, is, in my opinion, living together.
Living together in peace.
We notice how living together is complicated, wars, famine, threats on our health, the environment, terrorism, the clash of cultures and religions.
And to make this living together possible, to be happy in living together, in the diversity of cultures and religions, peace is vital.
So that peace be, it is necessary that justice be done.
To establish justice, we need to promote sustainable development and integral for everyone.
Peace, justice, sustainable development for everyone, these are the values ​​we want to develop at the Abbey of Lerins.
I am willing to travel the world, not to promote our wine products, but to become a peacemaker, be an ambassador of justice, to promote a sustainable development and integral for all.
Rates and wine products in my bags, in my heart and on my lips, the values ​​of living together.
I think the enterprise is a place of exchange and of goods, but also of culture.
Each company has its values ​​ and nice values​​.
Without being naive about the abuses that threaten us, business leaders, I think that this place of exchange can and must become a place for peace, a place of justice, to promote living together.
Every company has its good values which must somehow be exported and spread outside the sphere of the company.
An example: during the tsunami in Japan we were very close to our Japanese customers in this ordeal, where they lost a lot of people and goods, and our customers really appreciated it.
It seems to me that the company has a role to play in this score of living together.
Indeed the company forges links and when these links are right, they contribute to the promotion of living together.
At the Abbey, we do a lot of donations, often very discreetly.
We had to find an idea that was out of the ordinary, that would embody that joy of free donations.
We have created an educational concept which is the “Charity enclosed wineyard”: a concept to show that there is more joy in giving than receiving.
For this we put forward several concrete ways to give, to invite people to enter this dynamic joy of giving.
We wanted to put forward a concrete example of what we teach for that matter.
For this, we have given our vegetable garden, and have planted 500 wine stocks in “Mourvedre” variety , we give our money and expertise to care for these plants, and maintain this enclosed plot.
We invite sponsors to offer 1,000 euros to sponsor a plant.
Not to buy, but to sponsor.
We give the money of this sponsorship to a dozen of associations who help the most vulnerable of our brothers, clinics in developing countries, associations who are accompanying children in difficulties, or others who provide meals during the winter in Cannes,
some others who take care of people who died in the street.
You should know that each year, in France, 400 people die in the streets, quite anonymously.
The monks give, sponsors give, the associations give, and all this for the service of the most fragile.
Through this living example, we want to invite every person to give and give themselves.
So we do not want to be money transporters, take money from the rich and give to the poor.
No, the job is too dangerous!
We want to show that there is more joy in giving than receiving.
To show that there is more joy in giving than receiving.
We must believe in it and experience it in our lives.
And finally, finally, what will save the world, it is not politics, nor the economy or finance.
It is the gift of self, free, disinterested, serving the most vulnerable of our brothers: micro-charity between people, macro charity between countries.
The “Charity enclosed wineyard” wants to make it pedagogical.
Dear friends, I invite you to enter further into the joy of giving by working wherever you are for the purpose of coexistence, peace, justice, integral sustainable development for all.
Joy is already with you!
(Applause)
Under my presidency, unemployment will go away.
Under my presidency, there will be 10% growth per year.
Under my presidency, France will lead the world's economy again.
That's the kind of promises made by all those men and women who run for presidency.
President!
That's the dream job for all politicians, both men and women, in our country.
But did they just look at the first word?
When you look closely, the full title is "President of the Republic".
People typically focus on "President" and neglect the "Republic" side.
So what is a republic?
A republic is a flag, and a national anthem, but rest assured, we're not here today to learn "La Marseillaise".
What I'd like to talk about today is the republican motto: Freedom, equality, brotherhood.
It's a fascinating motto that comes to us from the Enlightenment. and today we'll try to assess how well we implement it after 200 years.
Brotherhood, equality, freedom.
Let's start with brotherhood. What brotherhood are we talking about, when in our country more than nine million people live under the poverty line, in a country like ours, which is the world's fifth economy?
Equality, then.
Where is the equality, when the richest 10% makes just as much as the remaining 90%?
Compared to this room, and assuming there is more or less 100 people, and the only asset in the room is the chairs? It's like I said to the 10 people in the first row: "You are entitled to own 50 chairs", and to the other 90, "Get by with the remaining ones"
Nonsense.
Freedom, then.
What freedom is that, when addressing our fundamental needs takes forcing someone into find a job in a market with more than 9% of unemployment?
Brotherhood, equality, freedom.
You can sense the health status of the republican motto with a number: nine.
Nine like nine million people under the poverty line.
Nine like the nine tenths of people making as much as the richest tenth. And nine, like 9% of unemployment in our country.
The purpose of my talk, anyway, is not putting you down.
Somehow, we will have to try and find a solution.
What I'd like to talk to you about today is the universal income.
So what is universal income?
Just to start, is a definition with three criteria to match so it can be properly defined: "universal income".
A universal income is a sum of money that's granted to everyone on a monthly basis, with no strings attached, to each individual.
If this sum of money is only granted to young people or only to those who make less than 2,000 euro per month, that's not a universal income.
If we talk about a sum of money that comes with the condition of finding some kind of job, that's not a universal income.
If that sum of money is only granted to a household, or a couple, that's not a universal income.
These are the three needed criteria in order to properly talk about universal income.
With this definition in mind, many questions may arise.
First question: why?
Why in the world one might want to implement a universal income?
Essentially for two reasons.
One more "historical", the other more contemporary.
The historical reason is, because, truth be told, even if current debates present universal income as a new idea, it's actually been discussed for many centuries now.
In history, one of the first thinkers to propose universal income was Thomas Paine, in 18th century.
The idea was to fight poverty and redistribute wealth with a very simple idea: the property of land, that we all share, and belongs to everyone,
has been collected by the few.
Therefore, not everyone has a piece of land to address their basic needs.
Therefore, as a compensation, he longed for the implementation of a universal grant.
The most contemporary reason, which is why the debate is having a comeback now, is that the universal income could be a viable answer to an ever changing job market.
We must be aware that with automation and digitalization a lot of jobs will disappear,
and others will be
created to replace them. What no one is sure about today is, will new jobs outgrow the destroyed ones?
I'll go straight to the answer: we do not know.
The only thing we know is that today's new jobs will be much less stable than yesterday's ones.
In the past, an employee could remain 40 years in the same company; today, not only you won't stay in the same company for 40 years, but over a single workday several activities could be done.
Therefore, a universal income would in a sense act like a safety line for a less linear job market.
First question: why?
And the second is: how much?
How high should this universal income be?
A lot of propositions have been formulated. But generally speaking, the range goes from RSA, a little more than 500 euro per month, to SMIC, a little less than 1,200 euro per month, with the poverty line in-between.
The poverty line, in France, it's 1,000 euro per month, for a single person.
How do you measure that?
It's an international definition.
It's 60% of median income.
So what's the median income?
It's the income level that splits people in two:
50% of people make more than that, 50% less.
In France, median income is 1,666 euro.
And 60% of 1,666 euro, it's 1,000 euro.
Why is poverty calculated that way?
Because one is always poor compared to where she lives.
It's easy to get that 1,000 euros in France. It can help you get by, but its hardly a liveable income; In a developing country, they'd make a much bigger positive difference. You could even be labeled as rich.
Why, then, and how much.
The third question you might ask is: how?
How to implement it? How to finance it?
There are three great funding families.
The first is self funding.
The idea is: with a universal income at the level of poverty line, RSA has no reason to be.
So the amount currently allocated to RSA could be diverted to universal income.
The second funding family of universal income are taxes.
And taxes are often related to the philosophical reason why someone should implement universal income.
If the policy goals are fighting against povery and sharing wealth, we'd rather tax incomes or assets. If instead the real goal is coping with the shifts in the labor market, we'll probably end up taxing companies and robots.
And the last source of funding of universal income, an almost neglected ones, in public debates, is monetary creation.
You must know that currently, to boost the economy, central banks create money out of thin air and inject it into the system.
And we might well ask ourselves, why give this money to private banks instead of giving it directly to citizens?
The bottom line, with universal income, is that's a broad concept with different implementations.
My closest connections call me "Mr Universal Income" but actually, I don't appreciate every possible flavour of it.
Universal income is a concept I understand.
I agree with some of its implementations and disagree with some other ones.
So we have a failing republican motto and a broad, multifaceted concept.
What if we combined the two?
That would give us a R.E.V.E. (dream), our dream.
A dream we made with Romain, with whom I founded the Ecolo-Humanists.
R.E.V.E [Dream] stands for Emancipatory Income to Express Ourselves in Life.
Let's reconsider the Republican Motto so we can better defines what our universal income would ideally look like.
Brotherhood.
For us, an ideal universal income would be set at the level of the poverty line.
That would allow us, by the way, to respect Article 25 of the Universal Declaration of the Human Right.
This Article 25 of the Universal Declaration of the Human Right
mandates that everyone has a right to a standard of living high enough to address our fundamental needs: food, shelter, and a roof over our head.
Universal Declaration of Human Rights, Article 25. We signed it long ago, but we still fail to respect it
Equality.
For us, universal income should be a redistribution tool tied to a progressive taxation in order to finance it.
We didn't say there will be no simplification.
Some aids will forcibly disappear.
But often, in today's conversation, universal income is only seen as a simplification tool.
For us, it should also be a redistribution tool.
And finally, freedom.
What freedom would give this freedom, this universal income?
It would allow us to say no.
The ability to say no.
Which is fundamental, in order to be masters of our own life.
Saying no could allow employees to negotiate better working conditions,
and thus work better.
Likewise, some may choose to work less
in moments of life when they'd rather
raise a baby, start a company.
Working less? Working better?
We could even start asking ourselves, what can be called work?
That's why we've chosen to illustrate freedom with bees.
Currently, if you consider a bee's worth, and GDP as our single indicator to meter the economy, GDP gives bees no value but the honey they make and we sell.
Whereas the true added value of bees is their pollination, that allows fruits and flowers to develop.
Likewise, speaking of human beings, we could ask ourselves: are we worthless except for the monetary value we create in a company?
Or perhaps, the added value that's created isn't, just like for pollination, all those social relationships of ours that allow us to realise our potential, and knit the fabric of society?
Our R.E.V.E. [dream], Emancipatory Income to Express Ourselves in Life.
If there's a word to remember, in this definition, is the emancipatory side.
For us, the implementation of this ideal universal income would be a true paradigm shift.
We live in a society today where we "make ends meet" and those who are left behind are helped, despite the a cost for them of social stigma, treated as they might be like aided people.
With the introduction of a universal income, the game changes completely.
We could finally trust anyone, and those who are better off will fund their universal income, or other peoples'/
You've got it now; our dream, and hopefully someday your dream also, is give some reality to the republican motto.
Freedom, equality, brotherhood.
And in that moment, only in that moment, we can wrap up the speech by saying: Long live the Republic, and long live France!
(Applause)
I have explored Mars.
You don’t look very convinced.
Is that because I don’t look like Matt Damon?
(Laughter) Here’s photo evidence.
In 2012 I took part in a simulation of Mars exploration in the desert of Utah.
How did I get there? I was writing
a thesis in organisation studies.
That’s less impressive, isn’t it? OK.
Over two weeks, I took part
in a simulation in the desert, in a pod of 20 m² with a team of six people.
This 20 m² pod was in a way my laboratory, to observe the team’s daily lives.
What exactly is a simulation of a Mars exploration?
A simulation is a learning process.
You simulate in order to learn.
What comes to your mind when you think about Mars exploration?
Straight away I think about science, technology, and also something to do maybe with the human adventure.
Why science?
Because I cannot imagine that six people would be sent to Mars for two years 250 million kilometres away, in order to do a photo safari.
Technology – because we need some technology to go to Mars.
Basically, we need a space shuttle or a space capsule, something reliable that keeps going in order to go to Mars.
And the human adventure…

Who is a Mars explorer, in your opinion?
What comes to my mind, is somebody who maybe isn’t a superhero, but a hero, somebody strong enough, who has been prepared for a long time, who is able to deal with massive pressure and stress...
It’s somebody who can live under the most extraordinary extreme and hostile conditions.
To sum up – Mars exploration means to face the unknown and to live an extraordinary experience.
I have the impression that with these three elements I’m not finding everything I experienced during this mission simulation.
What I would like to do is to share my experience and to tell you a story and look for the missing elements together with you.
First, let us set the scene.
In the middle of the desert of Utah there is a pod called MDRS, belonging to the Mars Society, an independent society with the aim to go and explore Mars, but also to settle humans on Mars.
It considers the pod, which is also called the hub, as a laboratory to learn to work and live together on a different planet.
What struck me first when I arrived in Utah, was the scenery.
It is a totally Martian landscape.
You are totally immersed in the scenery.
For me, it wasn’t so much the pod that struck me at the start, it was the rocks, the colours… ochre and red.
The shape of the rocks.
That is a very important element of pretending that you are on Mars.
There is no trace of human activity,
as far as the eye can see.
Then, there is the isolation.
The pod is in the middle of the desert.
It’s relative isolation, as 25 kilometres away, there is still a petrol station.
There’s also the local sheriff,
his name is D.J. Husco.
He brought us water, as water is rationed.
You must live autonomously for two weeks.
As water is rationed, he brought us a little bit of water.
If there was a problem, he came.
If there really was a problem.
You have understood that the aim was to live autonomously for two weeks.
So that requires rules of conduct and simulation practices.
One of the rules was, for example: If you wanted to go out, you had to squeeze into a space suit.
I don’t know what’s so funny, because in fact, if you went to Mars, this is kind of what you’d do.
Then, if you wanted to go out in your space suit, you had to simulate the pressure change between the inside and the outside of the station.
So you stayed inside an airlock for five minutes.
So welcome aboard.
It is a small furnished space of 20 m² for six people,
a place in which you live in the everyday sense, and a place in which you work.
You have a work desk, you have a little kitchen, another work area, a TV, a library, some books… so it’s not bad.
You are in an area with a certain confinement.
With six people, tensions can soon get high within the group, within the team.
But you are lucky enough to have a little individual berth.
Behind me, there are six individual berths with doors that shut.
This is quite unbelievable.
I enter my little berth, I’m fine, I close the door,
at home, in my sanctuary, I feel good.
And then I say to myself,
“All right, I’ll go and work.”
And there I am, at my work desk.
That’s pretty incredible!
No excuse to arrive late.
(Laughter) As a result, I've learned a few things with regards to that.
I can see a few drawbacks... Imagine, you want to be really alone. you have had an argument...
or not even that,
there is a bit of tension.
You want to shut yourself away. Yeah, that’s going to be complicated…
very complicated!
If you respect the rules of the simulation, you can't go out.
You can’t tell yourself, “Ok, I’ll walk around the block.”
The people who will go and explore Mars won’t be able to say that.
So you respect the rules of the simulation.
I will talk to you a bit about the crew.
What has to be said about it...
it’s a crew of six people.
We all had a scientific project,
and apart from that scientific project, we had a role at the station.
That role could be on board engineer.
If something was broken, I would repair it.
I would check the different levels, the resources, the water – if all was ok.
I might be responsible for security, and the health of the crew.
There were also two hierarchical roles.
This is Lara, you see.
Lara was the mission leader, and she is a biologist.
She worked on a biology research project, but she was also our team's mission leader.
This is Karina, who works in biomedical research.
She was responsible for security and for health.
Ezio was our IT specialist and on board engineer.
Sean is an astrophysicist
and also on board engineer.

Robert. He is an aquanaut.
And I was the replacement.
The replacement is there when the boss isn’t there.
I do my research in organisation studies.
I realized that there were many different expectations of this mission.
There were people who came to explore Mars, to drive a quad as a spaceman or woman, to learn how to live in an extreme environment, to experience confinement, to learn to live in a small world.
And then there were people who came to do science.
The question I would like to ask is: Is it possible to learn to live and work together without a common goal?
This is the conundrum.
I don’t have the answer.
During the first week, the first thing, apart from the beauty of the scenery: It was cold.
The station isn’t very well insulated,
neither with regard to the temperature nor with regards to the dust.
We were in the middle of the desert.
I remember this dust very well.
For example, there was an enormous amount of dust. There was sand everywhere, even in my duvet.
When I got back home and got into my duvet, a bit of the desert stayed with me.
During that first week, there was some tension, like a pressure cooker, which broke out within the team.
The first thing you learn after two days is not how to finish a scientific project, but how to live together.
The first thing you are confronted with after two or three days, is not the fact that you come from a prestigious institution, all proud of having been selected by the Mars Society.
No, it’s living together on a daily basis.
During the second week the tensions disappeared gradually
until the end of the mission.
I had the feeling…
I didn’t know if this feeling was shared by the rest of the team.
I had the feeling of a mission accomplished.
I will show you some elements, some track marks of our activity during the simulation, which to me attempt to answer our conundrum and bring the elements together.
They were normal domestic activities,
for example, setting up a rotating schedule for household tasks,
This is not particular to space exploration.
If you have done a bit of flat sharing, you must know that the first critical element is housework.
Living together.
You have to share this time,
you can't exclude yourself from sharing a meal, a breakfast, exercise.
Every morning, you will make some pretty ridiculous movements in a space that is not suitable for it,
but you do it anyway.
And making faces. Doing stuff.
Having fun together.
Sharing a good time.
The peanut butter…
Oh well, the United States...
But not just that.
I don’t like peanut butter, for example.
How can it be that I found that this was the best peanut butter I ate in my life?
I really had to go on a simulated Mars exploration mission, in order to appreciate peanut butter.
Exploring Mars also means exploring daily life,
because the question is: What can we do about it?
We have two orientations:
Firstly, space exploration: science,
technology, human adventure –- I agree.
The fact that Mars explorers also have an everyday life during the two years of a mission, is not insignificant or trivial or commonplace.
What I hope is that space agencies don’t just realize that two days before sending six people to Mars for two years, 250 million kilometers away.
The second orientation:
What if I told you that going to Mars can teach us about living on Earth?
Here, there, in our pods.

Not just the pod in Utah,
all of our pods.
Are these pods not simply laboratories to teach us to live together?
And haven't we all already walked on Mars?
Thank you.
(Applause)
Too often, we forget the power words may have, sometimes even, the power of just one.
There are statutes,
and there are sentences,
words that condemn, and words that protect.
And when we speak about exile, words are plenty!
There are words that dehumanize, words that simplify, words that reject, and words that repel.
And yet, behind all these words, there are human situations; something unique, complex, painful, often difficult... destinies of exile.
And these destinies, for ten years, I have worked for Amnesty International, alongside refugees, for refugees, I have come across them.
Let's consider Aisa's destiny.
Aisa is a 22-year-old young woman from Ethiopia.
She lives with her loved ones, her family, in a province.
It is a family of political opponents.
They oppose the intrusive central power because they demand the autonomy of the province in which they live.
Police raids, they know them well!
The father has disappeared. The brothers are forced to hide.
And then, one day, this is one police raid too many.
Aisa sees her mother killed before her eyes.
So, Aisa has no choice,
and she runs away. She is afraid.
She goes to some relatives, in a town not too far away from her native province.
At that time, we call Aisa: "displaced".
Aisa attempts to rebuild her life, somehow or other.
But the threats are becoming increasingly clear: she has been spotted.
She really feels trapped.
She thinks that the next on the list could be her. So she decides to leave, that time a little farther: for Sudan, by crossing, illegally, the border between Ethiopia and Sudan, to join a community of fellow compatriots.
At that time, we call Aisa: "clandestine".
Aisa tries to resume work in order to make some money, and, especially, send it back to those, male and female who she behind, to continue her family's fight.
Unfortunately, things do not move in that direction.
Sudan threatens the Ethiopians with deportation to their country.
And Aisa knows what that means: torture, arrest, or even worse.
So, Aisa hits the road to exile again, and goes even farther from her native country.
She crosses the border of Libya... illegally.
At that time, we call Aisa: "illegal".
In Libya, although a young lady, alone, and foreign in a rather hostile country, Aisa manages, nevertheless, to find a job: domestic worker in a house.
The threats rain down, and the hits too.
The spectre of forced prostitution lurks.
At that time, we call Aisa: "illegal worker".
The threats are too intense.
She is afraid and alone.
So, with some compatriots and others, she boards a boat to try to cross the Mediterranean, and reach the European lands, find a place of safety.
From our European coasts, when she is in her boat, Aisa, we call her: "migrant".
But actually, Aisa will be stopped by the Maltese authorities, and handed to the Libyan authorities, in the Mediterranean.
At that time, we call Aisa: "expelled".
She'll spend one year in jail, with hundreds of others - one year!
One year in the hands of the guards, and in overcrowded cells.
But, in a manner of speaking, luck smiles at Aisa as she manages to escape and cross the Mediterranean again.
To step backward is no longer possible for her.
She manages to cross that sea and reach Italy.
In Italy, Aisa has no help, no support, no advise, no information.
So, she just stays there, doing nothing.
And at that time, we call Aisa: "undocumented".
Then, in an ultimate burst of courage and hope, Aisa sets off for England, advertised as an El Dorado.
But at the end, she'll stop here, in Paris, in France, in this town, where she'll submit an application for asylum with the prefecture.
At that time, we'll call Aisa: "asylum seeker".
But, in Europe, asylum seekers have no choice. They can't seek asylum in the place they want.
It must be, necessarily, in the country that has identified them in the first place, and for Aisa, it will be Malta, because it is Malta that stopped her in the sea and sent her back in Libya.
This system has been implemented by the so-called "Dublin agreements".
So, at that time, we'll call Aisa: "a Dublined".
And this is at that time that I met Aisa, at Amnesty International, in our permanent legal support services for receiving refugees.
And we have helped her to obtain a status, her status.
Because Aisa, we called her: displaced, clandestine, undocumented, expelled, asylum seeker, Dublined
But in reality, from the very beginning, Aisa was a "refugee".
It is her sole and unique status.
Since 1951, July 28th precisely, "refugee" is a legal status, and a status that protects.
The states have agreed by signing an international convention to grant protection to those, male and female, who are deprived of it from the authorities of their countries of origin, or the country of their nationality.
A refugee is someone who cannot stay in his-her country, because of being under threat there, or even facing persecution.
That is why it's a person allowed to cross a border illegally.
If asked to show identity papers, a passport, a visa, an entry or an exit authorization, these people would be trapped in their own country, in their executioners' hands.
A refugee, is someone who cannot go back to his-her country, because he-she is afraid of being persecuted.
This is why the states, today, have an absolute prohibition on returning the refugees in their countries.
We become refugee when we cross the border of our country in order to take refuge on the other side.
And we become refugee until proven otherwise.
That is, it's kind of like the presumption of innocence.
You are a refugee as long as there is no proof that you have no fears in your country.
To be a refugee means to enjoy a temporary protection - a legal status - which lasts as long as necessary.
Your nationality does not vanish.
You do not have another nationality.
It is simply put into brackets.
To be a refugee is to have the right to settle, to settle again, in order to live... to live again.
To protect the refugees, it is not an opinion, nor a favor, nor a generosity, it is an o-bli-ga-tion.
"Refugee" is a term that protects, really.
So, there are all the others words we hear, which are often used by people who believe they know, but actually do not know, or who have hardly anything to do with human suffering and solidarity.
So, let us never be mistaken again!
Thank you.
(Applause)
I'm Claire-Marie de Bellecombe,
I'm 27 years old.
You've already heard a lot of things today.
Me, I'm not a neuroscience researcher.
I don't deal with the distinction between distribution and distributors, which I find interesting and knew nothing about before.
Me, I'm going to tell you a story because it's late, and I think that now, after having listened to everyone, it's the right thing for me to do.
So, I'm a violinist.
I started the violin at seven years old.
I competed in international competitions from the age of 13, and received artist's fees from the age of 15.
We start early in this job!
Then, it was the classic CNSM route, the Paris and Lyon Conservatories, up to the age of 24, so a long journey.
Except, as you may have understood and are experiencing in your own area of expertise, when you're woven from a certain fabric, it holds you no matter what.
So, today I'm both a violinist and a beekeeper.
Here, you can see my violin -
a beautfiul instrument from 1803.
It's a work of art I'm very fond of, which is my everyday companion .
But today, I've come to tell you a story because I am a beekeeper.
Creating a small honey company in Paris happened by chance.
So you may ask yourself: how is this possible?
The link between the two might just be a coincidence. and I'm going to tell you why.
A few years ago, I was already on the scene.
I was performing, participating in competitions etc., and I met a guy who was a little crazy, who became my husband, and who still is today, and who, a little more than a year ago, after the birth of our second child, offered me five beehives.
He had taken me on the South Caucasian roads, to visit this, the plains of Armenia and Georgia, the mountains etc.
I discovered farms, I milked cows.

I drank vodka, not pastis.
I was walking around a lot.
We pressed honey by hand, it was amazing.
And I've been stung by bees after that story.
So, my husband found it very funny to offer me five hives, and he said to me: "- Darling, do what you
want with that. Have fun!
Bye bye, I'm not taking care of it!
- Okay!"
Getting these hives brought up a lot of questions from my family: where did this idea came from since I was a violinist, and what was this story of doing beekeeping.
I was often asked how a colony works, how honey is made, if bumblebees
are cousins of honeybees,
and "Ah! They're indispensable! But why?"
In fact, people really like bees but they don't know much about them.
Very recently, we've heard a lot about the use of pesticides in the countryside, the province, in particular, "neonicotinoids" - a little difficult to pronounce!
The whole thing is very timely because the bee is, in fact, dying out for many reasons but also because the world we live in is moving very fast, wants and creates the means to go very fast, without always paying attention to the rhythm of the ecosystem.
I have myself observed, in parallel, that my hives, after one year, meaning one season, produced nearly two times the average per hive, for one harvest, than the hives of my friends or my family located outside Paris.
This was also noticed by beekeeper friends who also worked in the city, in particular in Paris, Audric de Campo who produces a good Paris' honey.
He installes hives at the Musée d'Orsay and usually on the roofs of historic monuments.
Here you have Orsay's hives.
Here, you can see him in the middle of his Invalide's hives.
... Well, let me return to this image because there aren't hives after...
So me, I found myself with healthy bees, with less mortality, and large quantities of good honey.
This is the first observation.
Later, with five hives in town, a little professional training, a few hundred kilos of honey, despite everything, I wondered what to do;
It was "Parisiennes" stage 1.
Now what is "Parisiennes" stage 2?
It's "Can I build a business?

Why? With what goal, what interest?
With who? With which means?"

I'm a musician. I have no idea
about PowerPoint. I know a little about Word for typing small bios and contact the people who do this work.
Really, I was the artist in the cloud who didn't know anything about networking etc.
When I started beekeeping, I had no idea that it would take me to the aisles of the well-known shop, Le Bon Marché de Paris, then to Harrods, Dubai, and other places.
I'm going to tell you how, from the four cords of my violin, I came to sign agreements with these companies, with independent distributers, and then a partnership with the APHP and sick children hospitals in Paris.
Now you probably wonder "Why sick children?"
So, I'm the mother of a little girl, one of two children, Zita and Léon.
Zita will be three soon and she's very proud to say so.
She's fine; actually, she's been treated since before she was born by the Neurosurgery Department of the Necker Sick Children Hospital for a relatively unknown craniofacial pathology which determining gene is not yet known.
It's still a very rare condition.
Today, she's doing really well,
she's still being treated.
She'll probably have to be reoperated but she has the amazing opportunity to live in Paris, to be treated in one of the best pediatric services in the world, and I want to thank that team because without them, today, my daughter would be without doubt, seriously handicapped or even not with us.
So, you can see her here, and here, she is in intensive care.
When leaving intensive care, I had met parents who were coming for the second, third, fourth time, sometimes more, to this intensite care unit where children are in a critical state, between life and death.
I wanted to do something for that team that saved my daughter and show them my gratitude, but there were already many art projects over there.
So I said to myself "Why not the bees?"
One evening, when nothing seemed impossible, I contacted Martin Hirsch, the director of APHP.
I was in my dressing gown on the sofa with a blanket.
Jokingly, I invented his email address and sent an email with a workshop project for sick children and installing beehives on the Necker site.
He responded within 15 minutes.
I thought, "10:15pm, Mr Hirsch, that's really nice!"
He agreed with me.
He was really happy, "That's great, bees!" etc.
So, I met the manager of Necker hospital
who loved the project for two reasons: they were rearranging the layout to make the place green through a big environmental project, and secondly, because pediatric hospitals, where some children spend half of their lives - I'm exaggerating a bit but not much - should become a place of life, a place of care that goes beyond care.
So, this bee project really fitted into this aim.
Now, unfortunately, that's the glitch of the evening.
There was a video where Vincent Nicolas Delpech, who is the director of Necker Hospital, and one of my contacts, the director of purchasing and sustainable development, Mr. Spinhirny of Necker Hospital, talk about what I just told you: why this project is important to them and why connecting children and bees makes sense, and why raising awareness in the new generation about the extinction of bees is important.
In fact, in a few days, three hives will take up residence on the hospital grounds.
These bees will pollinate for life, the result you see on your plates because it's important to remember that without bees pollinating 80% of flowering plants, that's around two thirds of vegetation worldwide, you wouldn't have very varied meals.
And if we were to replace bee pollination with human hands, it would cost billions of dollars.
So, we might as well act proactively, make ourselves aware of it, and then talk to younger generations.
I talk mainly to the children in hospital because I think that we need to educate patients.
The caregivers do it very well and so do all those involved.
I like to talk about bees and our plates.
These bees pollinate
for the life of these children too.
Being around bees, although not very often because in fact, the less you open the hives, the better the bees are, for thermal regulation reasons etc., which is not the subject of this evening's discussion, I realized that honey was a rare product, that is tasty and beautiful, and that each area of Paris - my hives are in Paris - each area is represented by the honey drops of my bees.
Each drop of honey describes an area, a flower visited by my bees.
In fact, I think we can even talk about a type of Parisian "terroir."
I'm going to tell you two things.
The first is that I have always been fascinated by this advert that talks about day cream for women.
So you have a very pretty woman with a pot of white cream so immaculate, I've never seen it anywhere, who applies it with delight as if she was going to eat it.
And I thought, "It looks like yogurt!"
So, the mix between cosmetics and yogurt is very important to me.
That's the first point.
Second point, I also said to myself we start dreaming when we watch very nice adds that make us want to drink coffee.
But nobody has ever had an orgasm
drinking coffee. It's a fact.
But these beautiful adverts make us want to taste it.
We feel the coffee, we feel it on our tongue, on our tastebuds.
So I thought honey is a knockout product that we could make really beautiful.
Paris is the city of elegance with the reputation of being a city of style, the French elegance.
We talk a lot about fashion.
We always talk about the beauty of Parisian heritage.
I wanted to relate all that in one jar.
So for "Parisiennes," my honey, I wanted to be inspired by the world of cosmetics, perfumery, to make a product that makes your mouth water at first glance.
It should tell you about Paris in a bouquet of flowers of timeless charm.
So, this is the gift box.
This is the "cosmetic" pot of consumable honey, edible.
This is the first range called "100%," a natural honey.
There will be another, "Bagatelle," with truffle from the Provence,
when truffle meets the hive!
But it'll be still honey from Paris.
The idea was also to have a 100% French business, to have a product always in the context of French quality.
I saw dozens of suppliers to find what I was looking for - pure materials with refined lines like glass, wood - who upheld values that were consistent with the whole of my project.
I reach out to sick children, to all those who want to be involved in the project, and I work with companies that employ people with disabilities.
So the idea of having coherence in my project pleased me.
Here you have it.
So, here is the website.
I had all this done by crowdfunding.
I have been offered unilateral investments.
The heart of my project was, above all, the human side.
This humanity part was very important.
Setting up a company without a human approach made no sense to me.
I was not an entrepreneur initially. I became one totally by chance.
The crowdfunding was: invest in my company, invest for the sick children, become an actor of this human project.
So, it was successful.
I even had parents following me, saying: "It's great! My daughter
is treated at Debré hospital." "My child is being treated in Trousseau."
"I traveled far because there is no pediatric surgery unit there."
"I did a little beekeeping, I have some hives for you."
"I would like to help you look after the hives, conduct the workshops, and carry things," etc. It was amazing!
In fact this project of a woman who is also a mother, could be the story of any mother.
We have our first child,
everything's good, it's great.
We return home with a heavy heart.
Fortunately, the story ends well, but that could be the story of any mother.
Well, this business, my project, has become a project for other people and that was the goal.
This something sweet has become something sweet for lots of others because it's about the people.
So, obviously, the culture shock.
I'm a violinist: I signed contracts, I was photographed, I made some recordings, videos, etc., all this, with a rather prestigious training experience.
I've never done communication and marketing except for mastering a little bit my image: my failed smile, my faces while playing the violin, that's all it was.
I thought, "It's a catastrophe.
I hardly know how to use 1% of my computer, we'll have to get started."
To do so, I surrounded myself with good people.
I met extraordinary people who were very patient and kind who trusted me.
Today, I'm very thankful to them.
I made a lot of mistakes.
I asked a lot of stupid questions.
I practically asked for the address book of the business of a girl I met who was great and answered me with tact, guided me, and gave me advice.
"Parisiennes" today has been a little more than a year of work, of stones laid one after the other, often very sketchy, sometimes thought out, but most often very flexible.
In fact, it's a real on-the-job learning experience.
To return to what I said at the beginning, the link between my artistic career and my passion for beekeeping, I would say, is daring and risking.
Creating a company by chance is a real risk, but it's also exciting because the learning curve is exponential.
Without training, I could afford almost any question.
I was eager for all kind of questions, knowledge, learning, and meeting people as well.
And that was incredible.
And there you go.
I would say that today, when we want to build a business in 2016, there are two things to remember, at least in this case.
First, you shouldn't wait until you get the big idea of the century.
Many people already know that, but I discovered it: don't wait until you get the big idea.
Often, the idea finds us rather by chance. It falls on us and then, things build up.
You know, it's a little like the people we meet who are a little clingy.
At the beginning we're like: no, not too close, a little distance.
And actually, they become our best friends.
It's often the most rewarding part of relationships.
The second thing is chance.
No, the first thing is chance, sorry, and the second thing is to be daring.
I think that today, without a little boldness, we stay in our chair, we wait for things to pass, end of story.
I would say that today, we should let ourselves be pollinated by chance and be more daring.
Be eager for experiences, boldness, just be eager, from morning to night because life is short and we need it - and I'm speaking from experience.
One of my favorite sayings is "What art can't do, chance accomplishes," and I readily believe that.
Thank you.
