My business is "passion forward," using all our passions, one by one, to push ourselves forward, to head toward the future, toward what we are.
I do not believe in balance at all. The one thing I truly believe in is passion.
All the people we've seen tonight have an amazing passion.
There was an exchange because they were passionate and you were passionate.
An inspiration took place.
I believe that everything begins with the first passions.
They are the most important, so go for it.
As earlier as possible, give yourself completely to something.
Could Leonardo de Vinci had made such works of art if he wasn't keen on aesthetics in every shape and form?
Could Steve McQueen had become this fabulous actor if he wasn't first and foremost a rebel, someone who defied authority as early as age 10 or 12?
Neither of these two decided
one day to try balance. No!
They both decided from the beginning, since age 10,15, 20 or 25, to choose passion.
A few years ago, I came for an event in Lille-France, called "Happy Hacking Days."
It's a concept that I had co-created with a local start-up where we decided to put two groups of passionate people together,
on one side coders, programmers,
and on the other, artists.
I had brought my designer, sculptor, and comic friends from Paris,
and together, we had manage to create a third passion: a passion for the technology of happiness.
They had created small apps - it was a hackathon - that could do good to people.
One reason I created this event is also because I wholly believe in life's revelations,
those great moments when you tell yourself, "I know why I'm here. I know the impact
I'm going to create in the world.
I know what my life path is or may be. In any case, I have a small start."
So, I have two of them:
Fitzgerald in Georgia,
a US town in the middle of nowhere where I found myself at 16 years old.
I didn't have the scholarship and went
alone to live in New York or Miami.
So I ended up down there.
It wasn't always easy,
in 1990, as a young Frenchie ...
But I learned something: the american way of reinventing yourself everyday.
Everyday you can become the person that you want to be.
You just need to "show up" as Americans say.
I liked so much this experience of total immersion that I did it again in Japan, three years later, in a Japanese family, in a language and a culture I didn't know. There, my passion for Japan introduced me to new things about life, a passion for Eastern philosophy.
As much as the US is about instant action and short term,
Japan - and I suggest all of you to go there - is about this permanent pondering over our action and what is the motive behind the action we undertake.
Finally at age 20, with these two basic postulates, during my military service - I know, I'm predating a little bit - I chose my philosophy of life.
I wrote it on my officer saber.
"To be on the edge is to live,
the rest is only waiting,"
so a sort of pseudo-balance.
Finally, it is a 20-year career in ten different professions and 20 countries, for 20 years from age 20 to 40.
No need to talk about each of these jobs,
after all it doesn't matter.
The important thing, when you talk, inspire people or host something, is "What did you learn that can be used
by people or motivate them
and, above all, help them move forward?'
Five years ago, I was so passionate about personal development that I decided to make it my occupation,
and I became a coach.
Here, it was during an event in New York.
This man on the picture has the type of story that I love.
He was a former broker who made millions of dollars but he decided one day to become
a monk, and he left everything!
This kind of story captivates me.
It's what I look for all the time.
I'm a fan of stories and people.
What I saw with the thousand people with whom I worked in five years, mostly in the world of business and a little in the individual world, is one thing, that is each time I talk about passion, about happiness and the search
for meaning, people get it -
Well, I mean ... they understand with the left side of the brain, not with the right side,
although important life decisions are only related to the right brain,
especially happiness, the search for purpose, and passion.
it's the right brain that speaks, the guts, or, as one speaker said, "the second brain." It's that one!
It was a very beautiful speech, by the way.
So each time you can ask this little voice within you, "What does she says? What must I do now?"
Something matters to me.
It's the most important thing: risk.
We can't live out our passions without taking big risks.
And when I speak of risks, I'm not talking about taking 90% or 95% risks.
No, that won't work.
Things are only going to work if you take 100% risks, passionately, stubbornly, intensely.
And then, things can sometimes work,
and sometimes not.
And that's okay because we're going
to learn something from it ultimately.
There's always something you can take advantage of from this period of life in which you dedicate to your passion.
Now I would like to tell you about a failure I encountered in one of my passions.
In 2004, like ten thousand people each week, I attempted the Hollywood adventure.
I thought about becoming an actor there.
I dabbled into everything so why not?
Well, I wasn't the only one!
You go there high in expectations.
Then you find yourself in the midst of people from all around the world who share the same dream.
The first six months were great.
I was 30 with some savings to live for eight months.
Everything is going well.
I buy a former cop car for $1,000.
I have fun, I party in Bel-Air.
I do boxing for the first time
and yoga. Life is good!
After eight months, the savings are gone.
After nine months, I start to be depressed.
So I tell myself that something must happen.
Since I am fairly physical, I am totally confident in the fact that mental and physical are linked.
So I tell myself that I must move.
So I walk in the streets of Los Angeles until something come to me.
I must change my attitude. I didn't
come to Los Angeles to be a waiter.
And that's what was going to happen.
Then, on Sunset Boulevard, I bump into that.
It's the Comedy Store.
For those who don't know, it's the temple of comedy in the US.
It's where Andy Kaufman, Eddy Murphy, and all the great American comics have tried their hand.
No one know me. I would never
dare to try comedy in France.
I'm not funny enough for that. My face is quite conventional.
Anyway I'm going to try.
And then, I don't know if it was beginners luck or what, it worked out well for me.
An exchange happens with the Americans
and I finally found myself on American sitcoms, on American TVs.
Here, it is a huge comedy show in the US called "Last Comic Standing."
I thought I love so much this job, what could I do -
since there's no unemployment insurance for comedians in the US,
so as soon as it doesn't work anymore, we're on the street,
and I met a dozen of French people living in their car who took the leap to the unknow -
so what could I do so that this adventure never stop?
So that I remain a scriptwriter, a comic and an actor all my life?
Well, I start studying the market,
and I realize by calling SAG, the actors' union - I was unionized - that there were only 100,000 union members out of two million actors.
Two million actors in LA!
Only a thousand of them can make a living with it for their whole life.
I mean they don't need to do any other work during 30 to 40 years.
Basically, each one reached it by one of these means: either they found an awesome TV show, they played in a big american film, or they made their own movie.
So entrepreneur at heart, I thought I'll produce my own movie.
It shouldn't be too complicated and I've already developed many projects, let's do it.
Then once again, beginner's luck, I don't know, but it worked.
In a few months, I raise funds,
not millions of dollars, but enough to make a movie for two years.
It was a beautiful adventure:
Taj Mahal, Japan, Doctor Nakamatsu who is a bigwig in Japan, a completely nutty person.
It was a comedy-documentary,
so a little bit like Borat, but quite nicer and different.
I spend two totally crazy years from 2008 to 2010.
And then it's the return to Earth,

a depression, the first time in my life.
I was someone very positive and optimistic.
The French call me "naive".
You know, it's a quality in the US but not in France.
So, no distributor wants to sell my movie.
I had involved my wife in this adventure.
She had quit her job.
We find ourselves morally, physically, and financially dry.
It was very, very tough ...
Even now when I talk about it. It's a very difficult period of my life. For six months, I was confined to bed.
Now it wasn't a total failure.
We won a few awards.
We won many prizes at festivals,
but what matters is not that.
I know many directors with multiple awards who can't manage to pay their rent.
So it's just praise from the critics.
Why did I talk about all that?
What happened to me is so thrilling,
today, I've no regrets. It was incredible.
I mean "today", several years later, because I learned from it.
So what I would like you to do is go deep inside you, look at those passions in which you have totally invested yourself,
and check out what you've learned from each of them,
things that will keep on renewing your passion, and, above all, liven it for the future and maybe impact people.
It's what I've seen and done in my career for five years.
I've been able to extract five principles.
And again, they may not speak to everyone.
They speak to me and they speak to a certain part of the population.
In any case, the point is to find those lessons in the failures we experienced,
and always choose passion rather than balance.
The first principle is to "seize opportunities."
I had a window of opportunity and I took it.
No regrets, it was great.
I did something that I dreamed about.
Second principle.
Now I don't know for you, but this citation speaks so much to me!
How beautiful it is! It's from
Joseph Campbell, my favorite author.
"Life is a mystery to be lived, not a problem to resolve."
There is nothing logical in life. We should stop planning.
"If I do this, I'll be eligible

to that..." and so on. No, no. no!
Live everything like a mystery.
Actually, It was my fault.
Meaning, when I finished my movie, I didn't dissociate the fact that I was a director from my failed producer side that didn't manage to sell movies. Yet my director side was successful.
We went all over the word, made a movie that made people laugh, except that ... well, you know.
In fact, there should be a clear differentiation between what you do, your experience, your passions, and the result of your passions
because one day for sure, it's going to pay, in a way or another,
and almost always in an occupation different than the one you first had.
The third principle is "When
there's an obstacle, try everything."
Between 2010 and 2013, to recover - I mean morally, physically, on all counts - I took on every profession.
I found myself in an incubator of start-ups in South Africa;
I put together the parties "French Tuesday" in Tokyo that are the biggest French parties in night clubs, a crazy stuff;
I found myself in Tanzania and in the red-light districts of LA, and as a teacher for the youth -
well, all sorts of careers! -
first, because I needed them to eat,
and second, because they motivated me.
I was trying to find this new vibration where I could find accomplishment.
But I couldn't find it in any of these careers. As a start-up incubator or as a volunteer, I was not completely myself.
However each time, I learned something that could help me in the future.
Then finally, at the end of 2013 - it just goes to show how life is - it was in the depths of a tribe in Ecuador that I saw the shaman speak -
I was there for three weeks, living like them -
and something magical happened.
There was a truth, meaning
they all took off their masks. They were true and pure
and I thought, "If only I could bring what I'm experiencing here to the United States, France, and the other countries."
And that's what I've done
for the last four and a half years.
So your biggest failure can be your biggest driving force.
Finally without this defeat or failure - I don't know what to call it - never could I have learned true resilience,
not the kind you read in books but the one you experience deeply.
I'd never learned so much about storytelling.
So although I goofed on my movie,
I decided to become the best storyteller.
And I've been able to help about 200 people tell their life story during the last two years.
And then of course, depth.
I believe that I stayed rather on the surface of things.
I must admit, I was superficial before living this movie adventure.
Here, It is at an event in Nepal a year ago.
Now, I am experiencing human adventures that are magnificent.
I was in Morocco a few days ago, and we will soon be in Brazil.
They are impacting stuff each time.
And this is due to all the passions I was able to live.
Finally, the last principle is "Gratitude".
Those may be words you have read that don't speak to you anymore.
(Sighting) You must live it.
Today, I am aware every day of the blessings I'm receiving and the goodness of people.
Each night before sleep, I ask myself,
"What did I learn today? What
surprised me? Who can I thank?"
Then the next morning, I thank someone,
and I no longer expect anything at all.
Now, I do, I do, I do my job. I give, I give, I give, and sometimes I receive,
never from people or events I expect to receive.
In some ways, karma is at work.
Again, why did I tell you all that?
Well, I don't believe in balance.
I believe in a kind of equilibrium in passion.
Are these people balanced or unbalanced?
I'm sure that if you are asked, 50% will say one thing and 50% the other.
One thing is for sure, these people live their passion.
To me, and I'm going to finish with this, life is not a 100 meter hurdle with a victory at the end and all the obstacles in it,
and a round to make,
so that if we win, we are finally victorious.
Absolutely not!
In fact, I got a fitness room
because in a fitness room, we do what we want.
We do it when we want, when we can.
We work our little muscle and then rest.
Basically, no one tells us what to do; you're your own coach.
You are the person who can decide of your own achievement.
I would like to end with that.
For me, it's an important moment that I experienced here.
Twenty years ago, I did a TV show
in France on happiness,
the first in Europe, one minute each day.
I spoke about the same things today
about happiness, passion, the search
for meaning, and they told me, "Arnaud, you must leave because France will never be a country for you.
You should live in the US, in Japan, or in Africa."
And that's what I did for 20 years.
For the last two years, I've been coming back due to the new energy. Something is happening.
You and all the speakers
proved it tonight.
