Hello everyone.
My name is Nadine Pellen,
I'm 40 years old.
And if I am in front of you today, it is thanks to Martine.
Martine is a translator.
To tell the full story, I called her in January to wish her a Happy New Year, and I asked her, "Martine, what are you translating at the moment?"
She said: "I'm translating guidelines
for TED talks. Have you heard of it?"
I admit I knew nothing about it.
So she explained the concept to me:
"It's simple. You share an idea that's close to your heart."
So here I am in front of you today, to share with you a topic that's close to my heart.
Cystic fibrosis runs in my family.
Two of my aunts have died of this disease, one in 1953, and the other in 1983.
So at a very young age, I asked myself,
"Why us? Is it an accident?
Is it a coincidence?"
And "Are my descendents predestined to suffer from it too?"
So that is the subject of my lecture today. Is cystic fibrosis an accident,
a coincidence,
or predestination?
Let's start with it being accidental.
I'm talking about Cystic Fibrosis, but I could be talking about any other diseases such as Sickle cell anemia, Charcot-Marie-Tooth disease hemochromatosis, whatever.
I chose Cystic Fibrosis or Mucoviscidosis because it's what I know.
So what is "Mucoviscidosis"?
It consists of two words: "muco" for mucus and "viscidus" for viscid.
It is a viscid mucus that accumulates in the organism.
My first aunt died in 1953.
She was scrawny, and her stomach was swollen.
She was coughing and suffering from diarrhea and fever.
After 16 months, she died.
We weren't yet aware of this disease.
"Whooping cough," the doctor said.
My second aunt was born in 1966.
Her symptoms were the same: cough, diarrhea, scrawniness, swollen stomach and fever.
But in the meantime, research had advanced.
The disease had been named and described.
A patients' organization had even been created.
Well, I say "patients," but in reality it was the parents since life expectancy was only seven years.
A health care centre had been opened in northern Brittany, in Roscoff-France, in order to support those affected by this disease.
My second aunt, Joëlle, was rapidly sent to the "Centre de Perharidy" in Roscoff.
She was given a test: the sweat test.
Her sweat was very, very salty.
Then came her diagnosis: mucoviscidosis.
In 1989, there was a revolution.
The coding gene for Cystic Fibrosis was found.
It was a wave of hope for suffering families.
We discovered the purpose of this gene.
In fact, it was preserving the balance between water and salt in the cells.
But when this gene is mutated, it doesn't work well.
There is an imbalance in mucus hydration and mucus accumulate.
At that point, it opens the door to all kinds of infections, to blockages in the digestive track, etc. So the disease had been described,
and the gene had been found,
but almost 30 years later, we are still unable to cure Cystic Fibrosis.
Let's not be pessimistic.
Since 2002, all children born in France undergo a test to determine whether they have this disease or not.
If they do, they are quickly directed to a specialized healthcare facility to be looked after.
And this is where the battle starts.
Every day, they must take medicines such as pancreatic enzymes, antibiotics and vitamins,
and they must do physical therapy to drain the mucus.
It is a daily battle.
What's more, Cystic Fibrosis isn't physically visible.
But with early action and this daily battle, sufferers have extended their life expectancy.
Today, a child born with CF in France has a life expectancy of 40 years.
So that was a quick overview of Cystic Fibrosis.
I am a healthy carrier
of Cystic Fibrosis.
Is this an accident? No.
Let me explain how this gene got to me.
Do you like jelly beans?
Because I have feature jelly beans in my lecture to explain how Cystic Fibrosis found its way to me.
At first, in my family, in the jelly bean's family, there were only yellow jelly beans.
Then, a mutation occured. Now there are two-coloured jelly beans.
This is the case for my grandparents.
They are both healthy carriers of the Cystic Fibrosis gene.
Here is what happens with each child that is conceived.
To each of them, mom and dad give a part of their genetic heritage, both of them.
So in the first case, the child is a non-carrier because he received one non-mutated gene from each of his parents.
Let's take a second case ... ... and a third one.
These two children received one mutated gene from their parents.
They are healthy carriers.
And in the fourth case, the orange jelly bean is sick.
He has received two mutated genes from his parents, one mutated gene from each parent.
My grandparents had five children. The first is an orange jelly bean. The second died before taking the test. The third and the fourth are two-coloured jelly beans. And the fifth is an orange jelly bean, sick.
That was my grandparents' case.
This lottery restarts with every pregnancy, each child's conception.
Now let's take the case of my parents.
My mother is a non-carrier, but she didn't know it.
She went through her pregnancies with the anxiety of bringing a sick child into the world.
But she was not a carrier and could not pass on the mutated gene.
My dad was a healthy carrier but he was unaware of it.
He just knew that he did had some risks and probabilities of having a sick child.
He had passed on, as a healthy carrier, a part of his genetic heritage.
I am one of the two jelly beans on the right, since I am a healthy carrier.
My parents had three children.
So we are three carriers.
It is the lottery, every time, with every conception.
In France, there are 7 000 people suffering from Cystic Fibrosis.
And we are around two million healthy carriers.
As for me, I am lucky to know it.
But most people don't.
I am well aware that I don't have it by accident.
I know that this gene is part of my family's history.
But the question is: "Is it a coincidence?"
Is it a coincidence that my grandparents were both healthy carriers, and that they had two sick children?
In France, one baby in every 4 900 births is sick with CF.
In Brittany, it is approximately one in every 3 000 births.
And guess what, in Brittany, which department has the highest rate?
It's the Finistère: one sick child every 2 200 births.
A study was done in the Finistère - a little bit outdated now - between 1946 and 1972: one child in 377 births was sick with CF.
My grandparents were born in the district of Berven-Plouzévédé.
It's quite a coincidence, isn't it?
I didn't want to stop here.
I know I am a carrier and that it's part of my family's history,
and that it is highly likely that my ancestors were carriers.
But I wanted to go further.
I asked doctors, geneticists, to find out where these mutations had come from.
Nobody got back to me.
So I decided to lead the investigation myself.
And I signed up to do a thesis.
I won't share with you the ten years of research in five minutes,
Let me simply tell you that I retraced many, many genealogical family trees of Cystic Fibrosis sufferers.
For what result?
On this map, you can see where were living the ancestors of those who carried a mutation that was very commun in Brittany.
On this second map, we can see the location of the ancestors of those who carried a different mutation of Cystic Fibrosis.
And on this 3rd map, we can see where the ancestors of a third mutation lived.
We can see, by tracing the family trees of the sufferers back to the 16th century, that depending on the mutations, there is a differential distribution of the sufferers and their ancestors.
Okay, this is very good.
But ... I knew this map.
I knew ...
that Brittany's inhabitants were descended from migrants,
meaning that before the 3rd century in Brittany, there was almost no one.
And between the 3rd and the 7th century, there were very large migrations.
My idea is therefore that Cystic Fibrosis came with the migrants and that they carried the mutations with them too.
This is most probably what happened because the same mutation that is found in the northwest of the department, is also found predominantly in Ireland.
The mutation that is found in the south of Brittany was only found in Bigouden - south-ouest Finistère - and in Wales.
So there might be a strong link between these two populations, just as between the British Cornwall and the Armorican cornwall.
So what happened is that between the 3rd and 7th centuries, there were great migrations made by clans.
Then the migrants settled, and they stayed there for centuries and centuries without genetic mixing.
I know what you're going to say:
"Inbreeding!"
No, no; no! Let me stop you right there.
Mutations were so prevalent in the population that because of the lack of genetic mixing, more healthy carriers developed as generations go by, as well as more orange jelly beans, due to a high level of geographical stability -
these migrant clans did not mix.
Let me show you a map.
A couple lived here 11 generations ago.
This couple's offspring includes more than 100 CF sufferers.
Here is where their offspring lived generation after generation, as for the generations I have in my database: that goes from 6, 5, 4, 3, 2, 1, until now.
We can see that we are in the presence of geographical stability, and that there was no genetic mixing.
And as a result of this geographical stability, bicolour jelly beans gained ground.
So as you can see, coincidences are many.
But the third question is "What can we do?"
What can we do to stop this?
Are we really predestined to suffer this?
In 1996, Aela was born, in Paris.
She had a swollen stomach and salty sweat.
She was scrawny.
She coughed and suffered from frequent diarrhoea.
The diagnosis came down fast: Cystic Fibrosis.
If you've been following well, you know that her mother and her father are both carriers.
I am a carrier myself because dad is a carrier but not mom.
My grandmother is a carrier.
My great-grandfather is a carrier,
and my great-great-grandfather too.
This great-great-grandfather had a sister, who had a daughter, who had a daughter, who had a son, who is the father of this little Aela born in Paris in 1996.
When I received the news I said to myself: "This is not possible.
This is impossible!
Are we going to live with this predestination for years to come, for centuries after centuries?
We need to stop this chain that is passing it on from generation to generation."
Today, there is no medicine to change the mutated gene of Cystic Fibrosis.
But there is a screening for healthy carriers.
It costs around €100.
If there's a CF sufferer in the family, it is reimbursed by Social Security.
I did this test.
I am very happy.
When I got married, I told my husband: "You should take it too,"
and he did.
He is a non-carrier. Phew!
Nevertheless, had he done it and been considered a carrier, we'd have been able to make truly informed choices.
It'd have enabled us to decide whether or not we wanted to give birth to a sick child.
We don't know what would have been our choice, but we'd have been able to choose.
I am not saying we need to stop having orange jelly beans.
That's not what I want to say,
but rather that what is important is to be able to make informed choices.
I am happy to have been able to make this choice.
And when I ask the parents of a child suffering from mucoviscidosis about their situation, they all tell me: "If only we had known…
If only we had known!"
I have three children.
They are not sick, if you followed well, since my husband is not a carrier, and that they were not diagnosed with CF at the time of their birth.
I don't know whether they are healthy carriers or not.
They will be able to have that test at 18 years old.
But they are lucky to know this illness runs in our family, and that they can take this test in the future.
How many people are in this room?
Around a hundred?
Well, it means there are six persons among you who are healthy carriers of Cystic Fibrosis.
I want my children, their cousins, your children, and their cousins, to be able to get tested for Cystic Fibrosis, the screening test for healthy carriers.
Haemochromatosis, Charcot-Marie-Tooth disease, Sickle-cell anaemia, all of these barbaric names hide a disease, a disease that exists in our genetic heritage.
But in 10, 15 or 20 years, it will still be there.
We need to put an end to this predestination.
In conclusion, I would say that a solution does exist.
it is this screening test for healthy carriers.
We, healthy carriers, are the transmitters of this disease.
So we are the only ones who can stop it.
How do we do that? It is simple.
If there is a CF sufferer
in your family, even very distant, you should make an appointment in an hospital, with a genetic counsellor to take the test.
It is as simple as that.
Knowledge is always better than ignorance.
That's the idea that I wanted to share with you today.
And; it's odd.
Do you remember the book that Martine translated?
Well, my conclusion is very similar to that of Chris Anderson: "Our future belongs to us.
It doesn't matter what life has given us, we can shape it, and this can change the lives of others as well."
Before I leave you, I'd like to say one last thing.
At Haribo, they've stopped the production of orange jelly beans.
Is it not a sign?
(Applause) Thank you.
Hello.
Like many others, I grew up in a modest family where nothing was wasted.
So in my family, everything was recycled or stored.
"Just in case," my mother would.
So my mother recycled everything, so I spent half my childhood dressed in my sister's clothes.
Not all my sister's clothes. Because I don't really have the legs for pleated skirts.
But as my mother dressed my sister knowing I would have to wear her clothes, my sister didn't get the clothes she wanted eihter.
That's the charm of large families.
Some of you must know what I mean.
Then the years passed, I grew up.
I experienced other forms of lifestyle.
For my environment had also changed a lot.
I, who came from the world of "we buy, if it breaks, we fix" I discovered the world of "we buy, if it breaks, we throw away and buy new."
The world of consumable.
I admit I had trouble getting used to it, to the point that an actor friend had nicknamed me "Just in Case".
That speaks volume.
What is most incredible is that I felt real guilt about throwing something away.
And even today, I am completely permeated by this education.
And when I see how any foodstuff is over-packed, I always have a moment of hesitation when I come home from shopping place everything in the fridge, and I'm already filling up the bin with packaging even before I've started to eat anything.
It's scary when you think about it.
It's true that plastic is ubiquitous in our society.
Some even say that we are in the age of plastic.
But it is also because it has a positive effect on our daily lives.
To transport, to insulate, to protect.
Without plastic, we would consume much more energy.
Technically, plastic is not the problem.
The problem is waste management that is never part of the equation.
When I started to make money, I immediately used it for travel.
I wanted to see the world.
So I went everywhere but especially in Africa and Asia.
And there I discovered sumptuous landscapes.
Some beautiful images of Nature.
But wounded by piles of materials, garish and not really natural.
It was sad to see this.
Or that.
Besides, who would rejoice about it?
Surely not those who live there,
believe me. These sublime images of freedom and purity wounded by the cold blade of modernity and consumable goods.
These magnificent countries are overwhelmed by a profusion of plastic that they just can't contain.
Yet they know a lot about the "just in case" technique.
And much more than my mother.
In these regions, people do not waste.
Everything is transformed and reused.
It is even the realm of "just in case".
So why?
By what strange power did tree leaves turned into plastic bags and river beds into heaps of bottles?
To understand a little better what could have happened, I propose to give you some figures.
Did you know that each year, we produce 275 billion kilos of plastic waste?
Every second, 16,000 plastic bags are distributed.
That is to say 500 billion each year that end up in sorting centers for the most organized cities, in a landfill for the vast majority, and then in nature for the rest.
And these amounts will increase further in the coming years.
Why?
Why does a product so necessary to humanity becomes so harmful?
Because we are also at the age of consumable and performance.
What becomes useless, what doesn't bring money anymore, is excluded from society.
And not just for consumer products.
But our plastic bag will continue to live his life.
Because it is tough.
Tougher than us.
Its life expectancy is much longer than ours.
400 years on average!
It makes you dream, doesn't it?
Well, mostly for those who have a good life.
And as it does not know what to make of its existence, it wanders about, it looks for buddies in the trees and the rivers, where it meets its cousins, the bottles.
And together they will continue this long migration that will lead them in the oceans.
And there, like social beings they will regroup in what is today called gyres or vortex.
It's the promised land for them, polypropylenes, polyethylenes, vinyl chlorides, polyterephthalates, I put that one at the end because it is the hardest to say.
But it's a big name for a fishy guy.
Yeah, I had to make that joke.
(Laughter) For this family of polys consists in five thousand billion people of all kinds and all sizes. Five thousand billion!
Can you imagine?
A galaxy of particles quietly waiting to be swallowed by a fish or a turtle.
Maybe even a bird if their size allows it.
But they also end up on our plates.
Scattered in the flesh of the fish we eat.
Or in the flesh of animals that ate fish meal before we ate them.
It has become an international public health issue.
There is no border to protection us.
We are all concerned.
Well, only those who feed themselves.
So I thought back to this phrase my mother used to say when I was little.
"Just in case". Just in case this waste had some value... Would we throw them away?
Did you know that only 20% of plastic waste is recycled in France?
The rest is burned with an average energy efficiency.
Progress is being made!
But at that rate, it will take 30 to 40 years before reaching 100% recycling.
It is with this idea of giving back value to plastic waste that I started thinking, searching, meeting people.
Then I started to find tracks. I read articles, I saw the filmed experiments around the world in America, Asia, England too.
And from all this information gathered, emerged a technical process that interested me more than others for logistical and economic reasons.
Turn this plastic waste into something, but what?
Well, into oil.
Yes, that same oil whose simple fluctuation in share price affect the global economy.
That oil that the poor lack much.

Oil. It's that simple.
Mind you, there is no question of doubting clean energy.
What I'm talking about is an emergency solution.
While we wait for science to progress.
But what is most desirable?
A beach polluted by plastic waste or one full tank in an electrical generator to illuminate an entire village?
This idea of giving back value to waste has started to take shape.
It became real through an association I called Earthwake.
First we thought about using Japanese high technology.
And then one day, in France, I learned that an enthusiast in a small village in the Alpes Maritimes was working in his garage on a strange machine.
So we went to see him, with all the Earhwake team!
The two of us.
(Laughter) And this ingenious engineer actually invented a machine that converts plastic waste into fuel.
The process is simple, but very technical.
It is based on the pyrolysis of plastics.
A process developed in the 70s
Plastic is heated at high temperature, it becomes a gas which is cooled to bring it to liquid state.
You see, it's simple.
It's a bit come the still with which we make perfume.
Well, only the smell changes!
So simply put, I present to you Mr. and Mrs. Fuel, born here in France who look very very happy to be with us today.
"Oh yes, we are really very happy. »
(Applause) So we laugh, but it's real fuel we made here with our machine, from plastic waste.
It's not olive oil!
(Laughter) Besides, it does not smell very good.
You can put in the tank of your car.
It works.
I know because we did it.
But hey, don't tell anyone because it is forbidden.
Free petrol, you can imagine...
Then, as they get along very, very well, I'll put them back together, hoping they make babies.
The purpose of Earthwake is to create a financial ecosystem that benefits the victims of pollution.
We stimulate picking up and collecting, buying plastic.
Then in the village, we transform this waste into fuel that we sell to make a profit and buy more plastic waste.
And create a circular economy.
The aim is to go much further than the environment creating jobs, income supplements and a positive impact on health.
A kind of possible resonance between ecology and economy where dividends are not financial but human.
That's why within Earthwake, we took the decision to build a machine that's not high-tech but low-tech, to reduce costs and allow the project to be economically viable.
A machine that is robust and resistant to harsh climates.
An easy maintenance machine, that can be transported on a truck or pickup.
But above all a human-sized machine that does good to the women and men who are victims of this scourge while they raise their children in the idea that we must not squander.
Today the team is operating.
There are engineers, researchers, designers working with us to perfect this invention.
Sponsors who fund our first steps.
Associations who have field experience and many others who in turn value the project which gradually becomes reality.
So now imagine a world where we give value to our waste to turn it into a resource.
Imagine a world where we would clean the villages that have become dumps, because it is the poorest who are most affected.
Imagine a world where we would fight against diseases like malaria, yes, carried by the mosquitoes found in dirty water, which are retained by plastic waste, ideal breeding grounds for them.
But above all imagine a world where we rid the oceans of the billions of plastic waste simply because that's how human beings are, that they never pass by anything valuable.
Thank you for listening.
(Applause) And especially thanks to my mom, whom I'm just heckling but whom I love and thanks to all the mothers in the world who take the time to teach their children that we must not squander.
(Applause) Sorry, I have a lot oif endings.
(Laughter) One last thing.
Since I started my talk, eight thousand tons of plastic, waste of course, Have been produced on our planet.
And I spoke quickly.
So there.
(Laughter) The problem is posed.
(Laughter) Einstein said: "People who never made mistakes are people who have never tried anything new. »
So I take the risk, because I am convinced that our solution can work.
I would really, really love it if we tried it together.
Just in case.
(Applause)
(Sighs) How's it going?
(Laughter) I feel like there's an uneasy atmosphere, right?
Yes.
Clearly, body hair is really seen differently although we all know that almost everyone is born with it.
So, from there ... why is it that for women, it is seen as something dirty or associated with negligence or letting herself go? What does that mean?
While in a man, it's not a big deal.
You sir, for example, have you ever been insulted at the pool because you had not shaved?
I have.
And why is there this difference?
I am responsible for what I do with my body, not for what others think.
When we see someone's body, we will react according to our norms, our beliefs that we were raised with.
But we have to see that it hasn't always been like that - what beauty is, what its relationship to the body is.
Of course, it's something that will change completely in relation to cultures, to eras.
Women that were considered absolutely gorgeous 400 years ago are nothing compared to today's models to whom we are pushed to compare ourselves to almost constantly.
What if it was up to society to evolve?
What if it isn't up to us to change?
What if the problem is the codes or the norms and not our bodies?
I think it is possible to interact in a different way with those codes: We can trick them, turn them around, circumvent them. We can make believe that they don't exist. They are not always easy to see, I admit.
But it's important to allow people to do that, to allow more freedom of expression of the person we want to show others, how we appear.
To try out different identities, different ways of presenting yourself,
it's important to be able to interact with the world in a different way.
I decided not to wait until someone gave me permission to be extraordinary.
Understand: I am not extraordinary because I'm in front of you today, extraordinary because no one gave me the choice.
Because sometimes living with codes and norms that we haven't chosen, that don't relate to us at all can be extremely painful.
And it becomes a question, generally, of surviving this encounter.
Because violating the norms isn't easy to live with every day.
It's putting yourself up against aggression, against incomprehension, sometimes against violence.
But why would our appearance get to the point of being a problem in someone else's eyes?
Why does our appearance as a woman or a man have completely different expectations?
I think that it's time to free ourselves from this binary system of thinking about our bodies, the bodies that will be perfectly fine, that will be bad, ugly, or beautiful, that will appear feminine or masculine.
In any case, I decided not to really concern myself with it anymore.
Suddenly, there were some really absurd examples sometimes: if I wore a large shirt, with no makeup - and for a long time, I had really, really short hair - at the hairdresser, I had a 50/50 chance of paying the men's rate if I was wearing shorts. (Laughter) It's so difficult for many people to understand that someone can be a woman and have body hair.
It's the same thing in the metro: having very short hair, no makeup - ooh, what a difference. When people take you for a man, they let you walk by, they give you space without even glancing at you, without making any comment about how you're dressed or why you're not smiling at 8:30am on the metro in Paris.
And that, really, is one example of a thousand.
If I'm here today, it's because me too, the first time I saw a woman in the metro who had not shaved,
I won't lie to you, I was disgusted.
I looked up from my book and saw her.
It really was such a disruption for me, such a shock that it made me ask myself why I felt such negative emotions about someone else's body, for my own body, and why I should be ashamed today of having a body like the one I have.
She allowed me to question again the whole system of thought that I had grown up with.
And for that, I say thank you.
I think that we can all give ourselves permission to be who we want to be.
Today, I have a project called "La ChroNique," a YouTube channel and workshops for teenagers, educating about sexuality to show them models other than those offered by societal norms, to show them other ways to relate to each other in relationships, in relation to their own bodies, to allow them to push back the lines of normal experimentation, of what is seen as normal.
I think everyone can feel more at ease about their bodies with this in mind.
We inherited our bodies; we didn't choose them.
They have evolved with time, with our circumstances,
with whatever we have done with them. And I think that the body is not there to be beautiful, that the body isn't there to please others, to please anyone, actually.
Why else would our bodies be there if not to live in as best we can?
Thank you very much.
(Applause)
Rodolphe: Imagine.
Imagine a world where your colleagues welcome you every morning in a gentle, benevolent and kind way.
Just imagine a world where random people smile at you naturally, without waiting for anything in return.
Imagine a world where your own neighbors - who you didn’t know before - would now be your friends.
Nirina: Imagine a world where loneliness doesn’t exist,
a world where competition has disappeared, given way to cooperation and solidarity.
R: I know what you guys are thinking. These two are just dreamers.
Last time I smiled at someone in the street, she ran over to the other sidewalk,
and yesterday morning, when I arrived at the office, my colleagues pretty much looked like this
or even that.
(Laughter) And yet, it is possible to change the world.
What if the only thing you had to do was to push a button, would you do it?
Audience: Yes!
P: Would you push that button?
Audience: Yes!
N: My mother’s Malagasy,
I was born in Madagascar and I grew up in Reunion -
up until now, it’s easy.
My father’s Lebanese, my grand-mother on my father’s side is Greek, my family name's Italian, and on my passport I have four middle names.
Are you still with me?
Because, as far as I’m concerned, I’d always lose myself!
But I share one common thing with Reunion Island: the cultural blend.
It is a strength that I came to realize later on;
when one’s young, it’s more of a source of confusion:
"Who was I?"
Besides, there was inside of me a deep feeling of melancholy, a feeling underlying a deep misunderstanding of the meaning given to life.
So I just wanted one thing - to take off, to leave this island, Reunion.
Why?
Because there were no answers for me here,
because sea and sky seemed to blend into a single horizon.
R: My mother woke up one morning with what she thought was just headache.
The only things that I can remember now are the bruises that suddenly appeared on her body, her losing her hair, a single visit to the hospital because kids my age weren’t allowed in those wards at the time.
I also remember a kind of funny blue device that doctors had to put on her chest.
Later, my dad explained to me that there was nowhere else on her body doctors could do the injections so she would eventually get them directly through that small tube.
Leukemia took her away
when she was 33.
I do not know if those things are related, but shortly after that I started to experience an acute anxiety disorder: massive panic and anxiety attacks, anxiolytics, anti-depressants, psychologists, psychiatrists, even healers.
In the lapse of just one decade, I had turned into some sort of a “fear expert”.
There were nights when I would lie staring at the ceiling - I wasn’t so sure if I’d be able to carry on with this kind of life to the very next day.
But, you see, I fought hard, held on to life,
I did well, studying for years.
At the age of 25, holding an MBA, I had already a managing position, I had good wages. I owned a good car, a motorbike, clothes, furniture.
I had everything.
But I had nothing.
What I really needed was to find meaning,
a meaning behind my suffering, the meaning behind all suffering.
So in 2006, I had no other choice and together with Nirina, we took off left everything behind friends, family, country,
and started the most important journey of our lives - our spiritual quest.
Please do not be afraid of that word: “spiritual” simply means “the quest for meaning", "the pursuit of the sacred".
N: So here we are, traveling around the world with the same aspirations and with a promise; to support one another on our own paths.
I left my life to find answers to questions that weren’t very clear themselves.
That didn’t matter. All I wanted was to experience life.
In the span of 5 years, I traveled New-Zealand from North to South, in an old camper van
with such big holes on the bodywork that it was cooler inside than outside.
I woke up one morning in the Australian outback, surrounded by wild kangaroos.
I even found myself doing my Christmas shopping on a plane, flying over Madagascar.
The baggage hold was packed with champagne boxes.
Just imagine the landing!
When I think about it, it was really kind of magic, just like in the movies.
And yet it was connecting with my fellow humans that truly changed me -
it was from the people that I learnt so much.
They took me into their home just as if I was part of their family.
Lost and wet under a heavy rain, a Japanese man offered me his umbrella.
In Thailand, a mother shared with me her life story, filled with dreams and fears.
In Spain, after a long day of work a bus driver offered me a heart-shaped candy, just to make me smile.
All those people were all just strangers.
And yet their smiles, their kindness, generosity and compassion warmed my heart up.
I felt alive!
Ordinary people made my life
extra-ordinary. R: From the remotest parts of the Himalayas to the sacred temples of the Golden Triangle, somewhere between Burma, Lao and Thailand from the most ancient monasteries of Oceania or Europe, I went on to meet up with “Masters” - men and women - who, as they’re told, have freed themselves from suffering.
Free from suffering!
I listened to their teachings and studied them, and I went on look deep inside my own self to find answers.
The further I walked along this path, the more I was realizing this unbelievable truth: we are all the same.
We came back to Reunion in 2011, fulfilled and rich.
And yet, the hardest was yet to come.
When you leave on a 15-day vacation, it is rather difficult to come back, to readjust to everyday life.
Imagine leaving for 5 years, being around with 25 cultures, seeing death, and even coming face to face with the possibility of your own death. When you come back home, it is your whole set of beliefs that implodes.
N: So we decided to do it!
We pushed the button!
We started opening the door of our home to strangers to share a meal -
a way to carry on the journey.
A way to avoid getting too caught up in ourselves, our ideas and beliefs.
Because the one who holds the truth is always someone else.
R: The one who holds the truth is always the other.
I perfectly remember - as if it was yesterday.
There, in the newspaper, there was this interview of a great entrepreneur who came up with this fantastic project, in the heart of the district Les Camélias of Saint-Denis, Reunion: a well-being and traditional massage center.
I told myself, This way I grow, being around such great people, meeting peeple like this, I can change.
So I just picked up my phone and called him, humbly inviting him to come over and share a meal.
Well, his secretary laughed at me - and I can understand why - and the man never came.
But on the other page of that newspaper, there was another interview -
a podiatrist who despite a serious disease and despite all the medical prognosis, had climbed the highest moutains in the world.
When I rang to invite him over, he immediately accepted, and we shared such a beautiful time.
It’s been more than two years now that we’ve been inviting strangers to come over and share a meal at our place.
Whether they are podiatris, entrepreneurs, artists, strangers or travelers from here or there, it is always a beautiful moment, so inspiring.
To carry on cultivating the sharing experience we started one afternoon baking biscuits, to share them in the street with everyone, in exchange for a smile. To recreate social links between people.
N: To make those biscuits, you have to go the grocery store, come back home, prepare them shape them one by one, bake them, do the dishes and of course, give them out.
I know it is not easy. It takes time. It takes energy. It even takes courage.
But believe us - or even better: do not! Try it!
Bake biscuits!
Working to make others happy, it is your own happiness that you cultivate.
R: So here please just come and try this, this morning’s batch.
Can someone stand up, please? (Applause)
Thank you. Thank you.
Thank you.
(Applause) We will never - never! – forget that cashier’s face. When we brought her those small cookies.
She told us that her contract wasn’t going to be renewed -
she had just lost her job.
She broke down in tears.
She broke down in tears. Then all of a sudden, a small cookie became a big show of humanity.
N: It is possible to build a better world.
It is possible to be happy.
R: All of us in this room, for sure, wherever we live - Madagascar, Mayotte, Mauritius, all 7 billion of us human beings we all desire the same thing:
happiness.
Who, amongst you - and I’d like the lights to be turned on, please -
who has never faced suffering in here?

Raise your hands and look around you.
Who has never faced suffering?
We’re all the same!
What I would like to do with Nirina is to change the world together. Right here, right now!
We want you to push that button, shall we?
Audience: Yes!
R: Shall we?
Audience: Yes!

I want you all to stand up, all together!
We are about to start a short meditation.
If I my ask, please, take your neighbor’s hands.
It feels weird doesn’t it, hey?
(Laughter) Now, close your eyes,
close your eyes.
Are you able to feel the warmth of the hands that you are holding?
Keep on focusing.
We are fighting against the machanisms of defense.
But if we truly open our heart - are you able to feel the warmth of the hand you are holding?
Now think about this;
the very person at my side, just like me, has been a child.
That person, just like me, has dreams.
That person, just like me, is looking for happiness.
This person whose very hand I hold may have experienced the loss of a loved person, or loneliness, or a disease.
Maybe this person is suffering right here,
and right now. Changing the world starts with a simple wish, a compassionate wish ...
N: May you be happy!
May you be happy!
R: You can now open your eyes. Starting this very moment, the world has changed!
Thank you.
(Applause)
I am a philosophy professor.
It's my job, it's how I spend my time.
In fact in French, it's one of the few professions expressed in two words where these two words are abbreviations: "philosophy professor," or "philo prof."
The other rare job titles expressed as abbreviations in French are mostly com jobs - not communication, "com."
(Laughter) (Applause) "What do you do for a living?"
"I'm a com creator."
(Laughter) "I'm a com director."
"I work in com."
"Oh, that's great!
And you, what do you do?"
"Me, I'm a lor' driv'."
"Lor' driv'?"
"Yeah, I'm a lorry driver."
"Ok, got it."
"And you, what do you do?"
"Me? I'm a nur'."
"I'm a nur', a nurse."
"Oh, okay."
No, it's not possible.
There are jobs that have no alternative title.
I'm sure you're thinking to yourselves: "This guy's a philosophy prof.
He'll make sense of all of this."
You might not have noticed, but it's a conditioned reflex: a philosopher, a philosophy prof, someone who has to do with philosophy, wherever they are invited, wherever they go - TV set, radio - they are there to make sense of things.
But what sense?
And why?
You have four hours.
(Laughter) (Applause) Professional deformation!
(Laughter) When I arrived at the Faculty of Philosphy - at the Philo Fac - to study Heideg', Schopen', Spino', Ni'... Let's face it, you can't shorten Neitzsche.
When I arrived at the faculty, my goals were clear: I would never become a philosophy professor.
Anything but that!
Anything was better than this type of sinister cop who spouts off for hours on end, the guy in black on his podium...
Never in my life! What a nightmare!
At the same time, I was 18. Things have changed since then.
So what the heck was I doing there?
What was I doing at the Faculty of Philosophy?
I did not even know.
Was I there to find meaning?
To understand something about myself, about the world around me?
Was I there to grasp the meaning of life, of death?
Meaning...
We philosophize to find meaning.
Not at all!
No.
Studying philosophy to find meaning is a lost cause.
That is not the purpose of philosophy.
May I remind you of Socrates, he whom we consider as the father of Western philosophy, Socrates, the great founder, the big boss, he wasn't put on this earth to make sense of everything.
On the contrary, Socrates' goal, and even that of ancient philosophy, was to wreak havoc.
In fact, in one of Plato's dialogues, to a speaker who asks him who he is and what he does in life, Socrates answers: "I am confusing, and I only induce bewilderment."
Bewilderment!
When you are bewildered, you are not at a place of meaning, nor at a place of answer.
If anything, you are confronted with the loss of your senses.
Philosophy, then, is that moment of dizziness, that intense vertigo we experience when the ground collapses beneath us.
Staggering, isn't it?
Well, this is only the beginning!
You see, in the end, if we analyse things, this complete shift, the loss of our senses... What is left?
What is left if we have doubts about knowledge?
What is left if we consider that what we know is that we know nothing?
If the knowledge we acquire is worthless?
Well, I am what is left. Me, a human being, in my nakedness, my fragility,
I remain, stripped of everything society has taught me, stripped of everything society has instilled in me.
Let's go back to the example of the occupations listed earlier.
Usually, when someone asks who you are, you state your social status.
"And you are...?"
"I'm a nurse."
"I'm a truck driver."
"I manage a company that specializes in this or that."
Yes, but that is not you, that is your social status.
Today, it seems like what you do defines you more than who you are.
Philosophy will tell you that what you do is not important.
"Who are you, Socrates?"
"Unemployed, I stop people in the street to ask them questions."
"And who are you, Diogenes?"
"I'm a bum who lives in a barrel and who masturbates in front of everyone."
(Laughter) Yes!
The great thinkers of history are those who lived from day to day, who shocked the people around them, and who did nothing useful for the society in which they lived.
Yet, 2,500 years later, we recognize these marginalized people as the wisest on record.
You see, finding meaning, following a line of thought is a little more complicated than expected.
Blaise Pascal said that man's misfortune arose from the fact that he could not sit alone in a room for an hour without doing something.
He was right.
We must always be thinking about something, have our mind engaged in one way or the other.
All this to avoid confronting ourselves, confronting our core, our truest selves, because it scares us.
So what do we do?
"We keep busy," says Pascal, we entertain ourselves.
It's true, having a job is important.
It's important to have ambition.
Hey look, I'm sure that you here, in this room, like me, you have pastimes.
It's funny, this idea of a "pastime."
We always say that life is too short, that we have to hold on to the present, make it last.
On the other hand, we do our best to make time go by quickly.
So, what are we doing with time?
Do we hold on to it or try to make it pass?
Imagine: you're waiting for the bus or subway.
What are you going to do?
You're going to do what 99% of people around you do: you're going to check your social media.
I do it too.
I also take out my mobile phone,
I tap, I swipe, I look at pictures,
I go on Facebook and what do I find:
"Ten things that you never knew about the Kardashian sisters!"
(Laughter) (Applause) I couldn't care less about the Kardashians, but I check it out anyway, (Laughter) just to pass time til the subway arrives.
Anything to avoid thinking!
Anything to avoid real thought!
Anything to avoid existential inquiry and face our nakedness and fragility!
Well, and rightly so, this is precisely what philosophy recommends: discomfort.
Who am I?
That is for me to answer,
that is for me to say.
What is this world around me?
Is not everything, then, false, artificial?
Should we not reinvent values, as Nietzsche proposed?
The problem is our fixation with wanting to escape from ourselves at all costs, we also end up escaping from the world around us.
Now, the philosopher Pierre Hadot said something very interesting.
Pierre Hadot said: "Philosophy is an attempt to relearn how we view the world."
It is interesting in that it does not suggest that philosophy is an attempt to learn how to look at the world, but an effort to learn how to see the world.
What does this mean?
What does Pierre Hadot want to tell us with this sentence?
Well, he wants to show that our simple way of seeing things, in its purest, most immediate form, is already conditioned and that, before we can learn, we must unlearn, unlearn in order to relearn.
Essentially, the more I know, the less I am certain.
I move forward and I recede. How does this mode of thinking come to any fruition?
(Laughter) (Applause) And what if all this amounted to nothing?
What if we likened philosophy to a journey, a long journey?
A journey far more important than the finish line, more beautiful, more interesting?
A journey designed to make us give up our certainties, disrupt our habits?
Here's one philosophical experience that changed everything.
At the start of the 20th century, the German philosopher Edmund Husserl was closely interested in consciousness.
What is consciousness in the human being?
It's odd, this concept of consciousness.
Its existence begins with ours.
It ends with our death, and, then again, we can't be sure...
Consciousness, it will stop functioning at two points in our life, when we faint, when we pass out; when under anesthetic... (Mike cuts out) (Laughter)
That's it folks! No!
(Applause) Some of you have experienced it, so you know how it is.
When we faint or we are under general anesthetic, what happens?
We have no awareness of time having passed.
An hour or a year could have gone by, we do not know.
We could have changed rooms, moved to another continent for all we know.
In truth, our brain did a kind of copy and paste between the moment we lost consciousness and the moment we regained it.
Amazing, no?
It shows you how important consciousness is!
It's what allows us to perceive space and time. Without it, we couldn't survive.
And it all happens inside our head, without great prompting on our part.
Consciousness is the most badass thing in the universe.
When he began his in-depth analysis of human consciousness, in his phenomenological study, our friend Edmund Husserl kept coming back to one important fact, unique in nature, unique in all creation.
Our consciousness has the unbeatable and extraordinary power to put the universe in parentheses.
To meditate and philosophize
is to do just that. It's about taking a step back from ourselves, in relation to our existence, our body, our limited lifespan, but also the entire world, the mechanisms of the universe, to a point where we are at the edge of absolute nothingness, the abyss, which, in the end, is all there is.
It is to experience the universe where there is no more space and time, and where I rise up to the source of everything.
This source, you might ask, what is it?
Is it God? Is it life?
Or could it be pure nothingness,
total absurdity, the absence of meaning?
You think I'm going to give you an answer?
(Laughter) Are you serious?
Well, absolutely not!
I will leave that to you.
I invite you to leave the well-trodden paths of knowledge.
I invite you to forget the performance obligations that pervade your life, your work, your desires.
This long journey to the unknown, towards ultimate detachment, you can all do it since you all have, in principle, a consciousness.
(Laughter) As a rule, at least... Stop what you're doing for five minutes to face yourself,
but without asking questions about yourself nor your surroundings.
Ask only if the flurry of constant activity is worth it, if the cramming of our consciousness, our lives, our mind is worth it.
And stop feeling guilty.
And what if you feel nothing?
So what?
We could not care less about results.
Treat yourself to a glimpse of eternity!
And stop searching everywhere for meaning because, it might very well be, that there is none to be found.
Thank you.
(Applause)
Hello.
So why should we care about our kids' video games?
Why is it important?
Despite video games being fairly new, their revenue is already higher than that of the cinema industry,
and there are already more viewers on video games matches than on most sports.
In fact, other than Super Bowl, not many sports have more viewers on finals than, for example, the game "League of Legends".
To put it simply, everyone play.
How many of you play video games, including scrabble on your phone?
Okay, I'd say more than 60% of the room play video games.
Now imagine younger generations.
We are a bit older and were not necessarily brought up with video games.
But the younger generations were born with them.
In primary schools now, they all have smartphones, and a little video game on their phones.
Knowing that we often hear about problems with video games, and that those games "create issues" - and I say that in quotes since they're often myths as we're going to discuss - I firmly believe that if you take an interest in what your child is doing behind the screen, when playing video games, you can help him grow and blossom with his passion.
Let's talk about why it's so important to learn more about his passion.
A passion motivates you.
It enables you to thrive in a specific area and to persevere even when times are very tough.
It adds to your life and it's much easier to accomplish something if you're passionate about it.
If it's something you don't care about, it's really difficult to do it,
Whether it be in school or at work, if your heart isn't in it, you'll often drop it altogether or do a sloppy job.
What's really cool about a passion is that to be passionate about something, you don't need to have a goal.
If you like reading, there is not necessarily a goal to it, or if you like making or listening to music, there's no aim sometimes other than listening to that music.
During adolescence, there may be lot of pressure to find a career,
and that is when passion can really make a difference in a kid's life.
So first of all, let's start debunking the stigmas surrounding video games, that they are "bad," and let's dwell on what could really be an issue.
So let's eliminate a few myths,
myths that you've seen and will keep on seeing, I will say, until the generation believing in these myths leaves, but there is still a long way to go.
The myths that video games make people violent, antisocial, stupid, and that they are only for boys, just to name a few - and you can probably think of others - all of these myths have been disproved by people a lot smarter than me.
I'm not here today to tell you why these myths are not real, you can look it up online, but I can assure you these myths have been proven false.
Remember back in the day, how we thought that heavy-metal music was dangerous, and how today, we can look back at this and see how ridiculous it is.
For me, the same is happening with video games. it's ridiculous to think that they make us violent.
On the other hand, some aspects of video games can really give troubles to some people and to some children, maybe your children.
Let's start with cyberaddiction.
I want to talk about it because we use that word all the time and for anything.
It's super important to know that cyberaddiction is an extremely rare phenomenon.
Only a very small percentage of young people are cyberdaddicted.
I'm going to read you a quote.
According to the site Ligneparents.com, "cyberaddiction" is when a kid's obsession on a video game prevents him from doing daily tasks.
That means if your child no longer cleans himself, no longer has interactions with people in real life, no longer meets with friends, if you find difficult to speak to him/her, if he/she is completely disconnected from real life, then yes, your child may be suffering from cyberaddiction.
But for all children who just play video games a lot, it is called "excess" or "overenthusiasm" for video games.
And this is very important because we shouldn't diagnose our children with "cyberaddiction" when it's not at all the case, and it's just a passion for them, which may or may not disturb their lives.
Now I would like to give you a metaphor about broccoli, because today, I'm going to speak about video game excess and not about cyberaddiction.
In my opinion, excess is very much like broccoli, in that if all of us in this room were eating only broccoli, OK?
for a whole year ... then we would probably all be sick.
(Laughing) as she may confirm. Yes, we'd really be sick.
So if all we did was play video games, we'll become ill,
And keep in mind - and we all agree on that - this goes for everything we do in excess, not just video games.
I challenge anyone to say they have never watched or listened to Netflix for hours during the weekend.
Has this caused long-term problems
in your life? Well, not necessarily.
So it's the same with children on video games. It's not because they play a whole weekend that it is necessarily harmful.
Yet, as for Netflix, we're very happy to talk about it with our friends: "Hey, did you see that series yesterday?"
Personally, I just finished Maniac, I don't know if any of you watches it. We're all quite happy to talk about it, even though I didn't sleep all night to stay up and watch it.
But no one said "Something wrong with her, she was up all night watching Netflix."
So this is somehow the way we should approach video games: sometimes we overdo things.
Does this necessarily cause long term damage?
Probably not.
This is why we should talk to our children about it.
Cyberbullying.
Here are some good news about cyberbullying.
It's weird to say those words together, but the good news is that we've stopped considering it as a joke saying: "Just turn it off if you're being cyberbullied because, online, you can always turn off your screen, your computer, or turn off your phone and move on."
Today, we take it seriously.
And this is super important because it really is a problem in our society.
The bad news is that we can't really turn our screens off.
We are connected 24/7.
And I don't think that, as a society, we are properly equipped to handle online communication.
No one has ever taught us how to use the social internet, no one.
Personally, I don't remember ever being told, "You can't say such and such thing online, it's inappropriate."
However, in real life, I was told, "You can't tell someone at school to piss off, that's not right."
So I was never taught how to use the Internet.
And I'm sure that most of you here in this room, without meaning it, has hurt someone online because you have said to him/her: "I don't like your sweater," or maybe "I hate the colour red."
It seems that we are not able to write a message, nor receive one.
Everything affects us and speaks to us.
I think it is essential that our education system puts more emphasis on this.
It's important because our teachers need support in this battle.
It's a battle that is just getting started and that will become omnipresent in our society.
Meanwhile, since our educational system may be difficult to change, parents can make a difference.
Together, we can make a difference with our children.
I may not be the best person to tell you how to educate your child, and even the least one to tell you how to educate them about the Internet.
However, one thing is certain, your child must be aware of the consequences of their actions online, that can sometimes badly affect their real lives.
It is crucial because no one - at least in my case - has ever taught me that.
We are starting to understand this as a society, but the generations who are currently in primary and secondary school, who have smartphones, and access to Facebook and all other social media, don't necessarily understand it.
And I can guarantee you they're talking nonsense on social media.
Since I've seen adults saying silly things,
I can guarantee that children, who barely have any idea of what society is, are also saying whatever they want.
So it's by taking a real interest in what your children do that you'll be able to help them they grow with technology with regards to education and cyberbullying.
Let's go back to video games.
By getting to know your children's gaming habits and their routine, you'll be able to significantly help them keep a balanced life so that they don't fall into excess, and without them having to stop gaming.
And let me tell you right now, if you ban games in your household, it may have the opposite effect of what you want for your children.
It's a lot more efficient to motivate them to lead a balanced life than to take away one of their favorite hobbies.
Keep your goal in mind.
Do you want your children to flourish in life and be happy?
That they maintain balance in their activities and don't forget their friends their family, their studies, physical exercise, and also nurture a passion that resonates with them, whether it be video games, music or arts?
The answer is yes ...
Well, in my opinion, the answer is yes.
(Laughing) I don't know, but me, I would answer "yes."
How do we do this, since there may be people here who don't see the point in video games, who don't understand why their children play them and are simply not interested?
How can we talk to our children about it if we're not interested?
It is as simple as asking them questions.
Asking your children questions about video games can really change the whole dynamic.
Instead of closing themselves off, they'll probably want to talk about them.
You're going to become less of a gaming novice, and you're going to want to know more.
Every player is different and we all play for different reasons.
Maybe your children play just for fun, but maybe they play to escape from reality.
Maybe your child is bullied at school, maybe he/she has made friends online, maybe he/she has fallen in love and plays with this person online.
Maybe you don't know what's happening in his/her life,
and I think that talking about video games can open this door, a door that your child might have always kept closed, thinking you're not interested.
Do they like adventure games, strategy games?
Maybe I'm talking gibberish, but your children will know exactly what it's all about.
Ask them what games they like
and if they like multi-player games.
Do they play alone?
Can a match be interrupted?
The later can be really significant and change your dynamic.
Do they have friends they play with?
Are those friends online somewhere across the world, or are they local people you can meet together with them ?
Take an interest in your children's video games, and I tell you, it's going to change your relationship with them, especially if they play a lot.
The good news in all this, is that there are loads of advantages to your child playing video games.
I've spoken about a lot of negatives, but I'll finish on a positive note.
I've said "Yes to video games" because not only they're fun, and get kids used to technology at a very young age, but - I'm going to read the list because it's incredible, the list of the benefits of playing video games - they improve coordination, problem solving, focus, concentration, brain speed, multitasking, hand-eye coordination, motor functions, memory. They develop skills in reading, maths, technology ...
The list goes on.
There are so many, you'd be surprised.
If your children play team games, it develops collaboration, coordination, cooperation. It can help with social interactions. It can raise their self-esteem because they become good at a game even though they may not be good at sport or at any other thing.
There are so many positives to video games, that it is more difficult to pinpoint just one than the opposite.
And that's not all.
Today, there are many jobs in video games.
That shouldn't worry you at all, it's not like it was before.
The video game industry is a machine generating a lot of income but also jobs, and not just unpaid jobs:
entire living can be made making video games.
For example, Montreal is one of the pillars of video game development
which creates a superb, I'd say "mix" between art and technology, that is really incredible in Montreal.
Talents come from all over the world to work here. Whether it be working behind the scenes making video games or on the front line such as playing professionally or becoming a journalist.
Some people are working in TV, in script writing, or any other job you can think of related to sport, the same roles are found in video games: managers, directors, publicists ...
As a professional player, I have all of that.
The gaming industry is really changing all our society.
I'll set you a challenge: if you don't care at all about video games, and if there's someone in your family who likes playing those games, I challenge you to ask him, tonight, a question about it, any question such as: "Why do you like playing?"
"What kind of games do you like?"
"What are your favourite games?"
I'm not asking you to play, but just to open your mind to the fact that video games are here to stay.
So instead of being averse to the situation, open yourself up to this new era of media, that is joining cinema, books, literature, etc. Here, that's me.
I'd like to tell you that my parents are the real reason I am still into video games, their way of approaching my career with empathy and understanding.
I would have stopped video games a long time ago if they hadn't supported me.
Today, as we mentioned earlier, five world cups later, "30 under 30" in 2014, BBC's 100 Women in 2016, Quebec's personality of the year in 2017, full time video gamer, now I'm doing a TEDx talk on how video games have shaped my life, all because of my parents.
(Applause)
(Music: "Diaspora" by Tiken Jah Fakoly and Alpha Blondy) Good evening everyone.
(End of music) Do any of you know this song by Tiken Jah Fakoly that was just playing?
Please raise your hand, I want to see you.
Perfect, there are some reggae lovers, I think we are going to have a good time,
since we will be talking about reggae.
In Tiken Jah Fakoly's song, he explains the extent to which, today more than ever, Africa is in need of its exiled children, the Africans of the diaspora.
In this very song, Tiken Jah Fakoly sings in two languages: in English and in Bambara.
In English, as a way of comforting them in their decision to leave, to embrace the world.
God knows that these people left for several reasons.
Too often for political reasons, too often for economic reasons, sometimes for social reasons, and sometimes even for cultural reasons.
He sings in Bambara, a local West African dialect, spoken in several countries: Senegal, Mali, Ivory Coast, Guinea, Gambia, Mauritania, and so on, as a way of encouraging them to remember where they came from.
He does this by using an African saying: No matter how long a log stays in the water, it will never become a crocodile.
Tiken Jah Fakoly, for those who don't know him, is an artist very committed to Africa's development.
Someone I truly admire, even if I haven't always agreed with everything he stands for, but someone I share a vision with: that of a new and emerging Africa, driven by its children from here and elsewhere.
When I was asked to do this talk about the diaspora, I found it a bit difficult to come up with the talk's title,
or rather, to punctuate it.
When one speaks of the role of the African diaspora today, the meaning is clear to all Africans:
they will, of course, say that it is people who are there to develop the continent.
They even shout loud and clear about it.
At the same time, when you dig a bit deeper to try and get more precise information about how they are going to do it, what their exact role is, moreover, who they really are, where they come from, how they live, then the answers become less clear.
Hence my use of a question mark.
I am going to talk to you about a small West African country, 196,000 square kilometres, barely three times bigger than Auvergne-Rhône-Alpes, 15 million inhabitants: Senegal.
Imagine that in this little West African country, Senegalese people of the diaspora alone send more than two million dollars a year to family members.
That's equivalent to a quarter of the state budget.
It's more than international aid.
Yes, the World Bank, the IMF, all the ones you hear about, they are no match compared to the funds sent by the Senegalese of the diaspora,
in terms of how much these people contribute to the local economy.
I am talking about the economy, but we can also extend this to politics.
This little country has experienced two democratic revolutions, but it was all orchestrated from the diaspora.
Or rather, it was greatly driven by the political leaders of the diaspora.
In fact, this is nothing new.
Let's take a look at history. The first African independence movement against colonisation was led by Africans of the diaspora.
The Négritude movement with famous writers like Aimé Césaire, Léopold Sédar Senghor, who, in time, was elected a member the French Academy, these people, through literature, fought against colonisation and were involved in the liberation of their people.
I am talking about politics, but we can also extend this to the field of science.
Someone like the teacher Cheikh Anta Diop, an internationally recognised scientist, with many works to his name, like "Nations nègres et culture", "Antériorité des civilisations nègres". A man who, through science, found evidence of the black man in one of the first most evolved civilisations, ancient Egypt, and in many other fields where we see indications of this African diaspora - in the political, economic, social, cultural and scientific fields.
However, when you ask African states, when you ask Africans in general, precisely what they know about these people, it gets a bit more complicated because we know very little about these people.
This has even created a certain frustration among some.
In any case, a frustration I experienced as an African of the diaspora.
That's why I am going to tell you my story as a frustrated African of the diaspora.
I was born in Senegal, where I spent much of my childhood. And I was lucky enough to have exceptional parents who ensured that school was one of the most important things in my life.
To such an extent that, during my teenage years, I had a teenage rebellion like everyone: I wanted to become a professional footballer.
I was not bad at it.
I had passed tests and everything.
But I still have my mother's voice echoing in my head.
She used to say to me, "Malick, you will never hear someone say, 'I am going to work in football.'
You say, 'I am going to play football.'"
A response my mum used to try and make me understand that football was not in fact a job.
It was for recreation or play.
Nowadays, we agree that's debatable.
But it really helped me a lot, and I cannot thank her enough for that.
It gave me the chance to go to great schools.
Nowadays, I am a telecom engineer, a graduate of INSA.
For those who don't know, it's one of the biggest university networks in France, training between 20 and 25 percent of French engineers.
I was also lucky enough to do a management degree at ESC Grenoble.
All these qualifications allowed me to start my career in major businesses, such as at a subsidiary of the HighCo group listed in the CAC 40, or at EADS, the parent company of Airbus, or even in a subsidiary of the National Centre for Space Studies.
And all the while, like many Senegalese people of the diaspora, I also sent money to my family.
I sent loads of money.
But paradoxically - and what I tell you now is very personal to me, only my opinion, not necessarily what others think - the more I sent, the less useful I felt.
Because I realised the money I was sending wasn't necessarily solving the economic and social problems I would have liked to tackle.
And that created a new frustration.
School has been very important to me, my economics classes in particular, and I still thank my teachers for that.
It often isn't said enough, but my economics teachers managed to make me understand the extent to which business and entrepreneurs were important in the development of a society.
It seems very obvious, but businesses put money into the state treasury for the greater good.
Businesses create wealth for society, and better still, they are the vectors of employment.
At home, we say that a person who works provides for 10 other people around them.
In other words, if you give jobs to 10 people, you are involved in the social development of 100 other people.
From that, it had become evident to me that if we needed to impact society differently, one of the best ways to do this would perhaps be through entrepreneurship.
From that arose the idea of LAfricaMobile, which is a Senegalese start-up that has been around for three years, with a belief that befits our two previous frustrations.
This belief is to make digital tools available, allowing you to discover more about the diaspora, but which also include it more often in local, social problems.
Specifically, at the moment, we're working with the local African media, radio, and TV companies, on ideas for programs where we invite politicians to come, mayors, ministers, and we give people of the diaspora the opportunity, live, to ask their questions in real time via mobile and social media.
Another example: we also work with charities involved in local, and often socio-humanitarian, problems, such as, for example, the fight against cancer, educating children from disadvantaged families, or even building orphanages.
We assist these charities with digital communication, but above all, we give them digital tools for them to collect money easily via their mobile with people of the African diaspora.
Another example: we also work with international agencies on entrepreneurship contests with the aim of allowing Africans of the diaspora to have a voice, to be able to vote, in order to choose the projects that may ultimately best benefit from coaching, and if necessary, funding.
There are so many other examples I cannot unfortunately give with the time I have been allocated.
But this little experiment has allowed us to see opportunities present in Africa.
Even though I am originally from Africa, I had never had the opportunity to work there before this experiment,
this small experiment, this wonderful experiment, that has only just, finally, begun, but that has also allowed us to see the opportunities currently present in Africa.
You're just considering West Africa, people who mainly speak French, like all of us.
In fact, for those who don't know, currently 50 percent of French-speaking people in the world live in Africa.
And this figure will reach 80 percent in a few years.
An enormous opportunity for us all here.
For those in the digital world, imagine countries like Senegal, where the mobile penetration rate exceeds 100 percent.
In other words, you are in a country where there are more mobiles than people.
What does this mean?
It simply means that, for those who have services requiring the use of a mobile, it's an enormous opportunity - but this is down to usage because people have two, three, four, sometimes even five phones at the same time.
It's incredible.
I am talking about digital technology, which is my line of work, but in other fields, like renewable energy, solar energy, agribusiness, biogas, and so on, and so on, today, African start-ups cover all that.
Believe it or not, in the year 2016 alone, African start-ups, from Dakar to Nairobi, from Casablanca to the Cape, raised 360 million dollars in 2016.
That's a growth of 33 percent compared to 2015.
It seems a lot, but in my opinion, it is not enough.
With everything I've seen that is innovative, it's absolutely not enough.
There are still lots of things still to be done.
And that's why I am calling on the African diaspora watching me today, saying to them that even if they don't have the opportunity to create businesses, they can no longer sneak off as they have the opportunity to invest in gems of Africa, which is all they are hoping for nowadays.
And I'll finish with where I began, by rejoining Tiken Jah Fakoly with what he was saying at the start: "Nowadays, more than ever, Africa is in need of its exiled children."
Thank you for your attention.
(Applause) (Music: "Diaspora" by Tiken Jah Fakoly and Alpha Blondy)
Thirty-seven years ago, my sister had her first pet, a white and caramel-colored, short-haired hamster she easily named Caramel.
This pet lived with us for two years, as a member of our family.
We played with him, we fed him, we looked after him.
One day, at my grandmother house, he roamed around the garden for the first time and then he probably ate something bad.
Forty-eight hours later, he was dead.
For those of you who have a pet, you can easily understand the sadness we felt.
Exactly as we would do for a family member, we decided to bury him using a shoe box as a coffin.
Then, we gathered in front of this improvised grave for a short prayer. My parents were really serious, aware that it was a solemn moment for their children.
And for my sister and I, it was rather more difficult.
We had a hard time to stop crying.
Then, my grandmother and my mother decided to do all they can to comfort us.
As usual in this kind of situations, they made us our favorite dish: chicken and fries which was really delicious.
So, in a short amount of time, I was celebrating the death of two beings: on one hand, with the most sincere and entire sadness, the death of my hamster Caramel,
and on the other hand, the death of a hen I knew nothing about and whose name will remain forever unknown.
So back at that time, without knowing it, I was living for the first time an experience of cognitive dissonance where I had loved and cherished an animal on one side and eaten another on the other side.
It is only 35 years later that I understood the meaning, the impact and the consequences of that scene.
And for me, really, it was a shock, a very violent shock, a loss of points of reference.
A bit like Alice coming from an imaginary world, I too had fallen in the white rabbit hole, a vertiginous fall in which the world I knew was collapsing.
Now, inside that hole, I met a funny character, a cow named "The Laughing Cow."
Maybe some of you had met her, at a cocktail party maybe.
And she told me her story.
She told me how her name was a misnomer.
Because no, a cow doesn't laugh when she is unwillingly inseminated.
She screams because she is being raped.
A cow doesn't laugh either when her calf his taken away just after his birth, in order to have her milk.
She weeps for hours, for days, this child she will never see again.
She doesn't laugh when she is slaughtered.
She suffers from the kicks she received in her hallway of death.
She suffers from that perforating stick that doesn't always stun her.
She suffers when she bleeds out while being still conscious at times.
In fact, she suffers from a life we are depriving her from, before her natural death -
way before it. Now, because this cow is sentient like any other aquatic and terrestrial animal, she feels emotions such as joy and sadness.
She feels pain.
These are not my words but the latest discoveries in ethology.
Since this cow is an "individual" in the moral sense, not an object, she possesses a will to live a full and complete life.
She has a will to reproduce and to care about and protect her family.
She has a will to die a natural death without it having been foreseen, that is, just like you and me.
Now, we all collectively know that something is wrong with this world. We don't really know why, but we know it.
It's like a sort of implant in our mind that sometimes makes us sick.
I don't know if you understand what I mean.
I mean "the matrix" we are living in, the carnist matrix, a matrix which is universal and pervading, which is actually with us right now, in your clothes, in your make-up, in your shoes.
This matrix is everywhere, such as when you look through the window or turn on the TV.
This matrix is the world that is overlaid in front of you to hide the truth from you, to mask the truth from you.
This matrix is an ideology.
It's a world full of happy animals, which are all smiles, who, carrying the same smile, give you a part of their body, a part of their flesh and secretions,
because we all perfectly know that everything can be used in the cow, just like in the pig.
Would these animal be killing themselves with a big smile for our own pleasure ?
Indeed no, this Laughing Cow is a pure marketing invention.
It is a marketing invention from publicists who probably experience themselves a deep cognitive dissonance and whose goal is to make the truth invisible so that we do not feel guilty and continue accepting to consume those products.
Industrial companies know this pretty well and even say it:
"If we were making the link between product and animal, any consumption would be impossible."
Now, this matrix is an ideology that claims that the human being is beyond all the other species, that he can assume the right to love some animals on one side, and exploit and kill others on the other, and vice versa depending on cultures.
Here, we love dogs, there, we torture them and scald them alive.
This is what we call "speciesism."
On the contrary, anti-speciesism fights for an equal consideration of the interests of every species.
However this ideology also kills 60 billions terrestrial animals per year - 60 billions: a vertiginous number, several thousands of billions of aquatic animals, primarily fish.
So, in reference to "genocide," we can speak about a "zoocide."
This ideology is destroying our environment for the benefit of profit, and to maximize this profit, it is devastating all the forests of our planet in order to turn them into pasture, in order to turn them into food crops that, for the most part, are going to feed the livestock that we will eat in a third step.
So at that point, you can understand the energetic and ecological aberration of this system,
not taking into account that this system deprives thousands of species of their natural habitat which in turn accelerates their extinction, and it also deprives 1.5 billions human beings - well, it doesn't deprive them but it leads them to malnutrition and undernourishment.
This is without taking into account the exhaustion of fresh water resources.
Between 5,000 to 15,000 liters of water are necessary to produce 2.2 lbs of meat, depending on the animal. So 15,000 liters of water for 2.2 lbs of meat ...
A French who purchases on average 192 lbs of meat per year can on his own and throughout his consumption, fill an Olympic pool - 164 feet long and 6.5 feet deep.
And he will have still plenty of water to shower.
Finally, this matrix, this ideology deteriorates your health.
The WHO says that excessive meat consumption increases the possibility of having cardio-vascular diseases, colon cancer, prostate cancer and type II diabetes to name but a few.
So, we can keep on taking blue pills. We can keep on having sweet dreams and thinking what we want to think, telling ourselves none of this is true, that animals are happy, well treated, that it's good for health and doesn't have any impact on the environment.
But, you can also choose to take a red pill.
Now, watch out!
Because there is no going back, and the white rabbit hole is a real abyss where horror does not end and it will become your daily life.
So be careful, I am only giving you the truth, nothing more.
The red pill is about ... making the invisible visible.
The red pill puts windows on the farming sheds, opens the doors of the slaughter houses.
During 35 years, three times a day in my plate, I consumed products derived from animals.
Because I was sincerely convinced that it meant good health, that it gave me energy and strength.
It was also part of having a good time, a moment of conviviality between friends.
Or simply because during a meal, I could feel the pleasure of taste and this was really enjoyable.
During 35 years, I never questioned the traditions, the social habits or the beliefs that led me to eat dead animals.
Even today, I wonder how is it that I did not realize sooner that this simple plate, this simple act of eating, was the origin of a system of incredible and insane violence.
During 35 years, the carnist matrix did everything to convince me that it was normal, natural and necessary to eat meat, to eat products derived from animals.
So today, I know.
I don't eat anymore any terrestrial or aquatic animals: I am vegetarian.
I don't eat anymore eggs, milk or honey: I am vegan.
I don't buy leather or wool anymore.
I refuse every kind of entertainments involving animals such as zoos, circus, aquariums, dolphin parks and even worse, bullfightings.
I am vegan.
Now, knowing does not give me the right to judge anybody, in any case, or to judge you.
I have been carnist.
Even tonight, I am wearing these shoes made of cow skin leather that I bought before transitioning into veganism.
And if I still wear these shoes, it is because not only they remind me every day the lie in which I was living, but they also remind me that I can't ask others to transition from the moment I have done mine.
So these shoes and the animal who lost his life to produce them are my weapon against intolerance.
So, knowing does not allow me
to judge, but it does force me to talk in order to stop collaborating with this carnist matrix.
Knowing makes us responsible.
Keeping silence would make me feel guilty.
Since I don't wish to be considered guilty, I decided to join the resistance
which is rising everywhere in the world.
Scientists, doctors, nutritionists, philosophers, sociologists, militants, activists of course, but also political men and celebrities, all over the world, these men and women have decided to tend towards a plant-based diet and a consumption without cruelty towards animals.
Everywhere, these men and women raise their voices; they campaign; they give away red pills to make the invisible visible, often against a carnist matrix, powerful, rich and sometimes violent.
Now, it is said that a revolutionary idea requires three steps to be adopted, that first, it is considered foolish, then dangerous and then only in a third stage is it considered obvious.
Thirty years ago, vegetarians were often laughed at.
Thirty years ago, the only vegetarian restaurant in Paris regularly found its windows covered with spits.
Nowadays, being vegetarian or being vegan is not at all a foolish idea.
Nowadays, meat lobbyist come to our schools to tattoo in the mind of our children rather cynical slogans like: "With beef, it's a party !"
Members of parliament have commissioned an investigation - they've asked for an inquiry commission- on animal rights organizations that are considered as dangerous as terrorists groups.
So yes, in 30 years, veganism went from being a foolish idea to being a dangerous idea, dangerous because it questions huge financial, economical and political interests.
This is a first victory for those who resist.
In the future, I don't know when, this idea will become obvious.
The world will be vegan.
The carnist matrix will be defeated.
Farmers will reinvent themselves.
They'll live decently with no grant, from a job that will make them really happy.
The diehards among us will continue to consume meat a meat without meat and milk without milk, because pretty soon, technological progress will enable this.
In contrast, our children ... Our children may look at us with their eyes wide open when we will tell them the story that due to our traditions, our belief and the social practice we thrust pipes in the throats of ducks in order to make their liver bigger; we took away babies from their mom in order to take their milk; we put sword in the skull of bulls just for fun;
we whipped elephants to make them stand on a ball just because we thought it was fun; we locked killer whales in a pool just for the entertainment to see them jump in the air; we asphyxiated in plastic bags or crushed alive young male chicks because we knew they won't give eggs.
All of this -and I could go on and on- is beyond reason.
What kind of humans are we ?
How will our children see us ?
Like real human beings or more like monsters ?
There's a good chance that saying we didn't know won't be enough to make them believe us
and even less to forgive us.
So, I forgave myself my past missteps.
Today, I am in peace with myself and with animals.
I am reducing my ecological impact on the planet.
And just as the gorilla or the elephant, I don't have any deficiency from not eating animals.
For an anti-speciesism world that advocates peace between species, that advocates peace with the earth, our only home, I am at war with the carnist ideology.
So, my resistance involves of course my consumption, but also my activism, my proposals and probably the fact that I am here tonight, in front of you.
Now, this is not an easy question, but Christmas is coming.
It may be the right time to deal calmly with this question and ask ourselves whether we really want to celebrate Christmas around animal carcasses whose lives have only been violence and suffering.
Sure, it's a difficult question.
But the overall question is to know what kind of relationship we want to have with animals.
It's a question of morality and rights, and I think it's also a question of justice.
So, tonight, I hope I instilled in you the desire to wonder about this.
Thank you.
(Applause)
When I was young, I wanted to be a stuntwoman.
I was interested in military clothes, which I still am -
I just made an effort today.
I was obsessed with driving, and I really, really wanted my own machete.
Evidently, I wasn't your stereotypical little girl.
People said I was a boy manqué.
But I accepted it really rather well because in today's society, it's alright for girls to adopt the codes of masculinity.
It's even seen as a kind of plus.
But now I'll ask you this: What do you call a little boy who likes girls' things?
Audience: Sissy!
Thank you.
There you have it.
I have to disappoint you: I didn't become a stuntwoman, I'm a social psychology researcher.
For several years now, I've been investigating sexism and gender inequality.
And to be honest, while doing so, I've gone through many phases.
I went through one phase where I thought men were bullies.
I had another where I thought women didn't rebel enough.
And finally, after all these years of research, I've realised that reducing sexism is a major political issue in our society, and yet we continue to value male power at all costs.
And that, to me, is the main barrier to gender equality today.
Sexism is a term often used nowadays, but we never fully define it.
It's a simple enough term though. What is sexism?
It's a set of beliefs, in other words, an ideology, that we have about women and men, and the relationships one has with the other.
But the problem with those beliefs is that they influence us throughout our lives, whether it's the way we develop our personality, or what our tastes and desires are ...
everything.
And what does sexism typically encourage in us?
Interpretive bias.
In a study that looked at pain assessment in pediatrics, researchers were interested in how adults interpreted the pain experienced by a child based on the child's gender.
So what did they do?
They asked participants to watch a video showing a child undergoing a painful medical procedure.
In reality, they just had their finger pricked.
And there was nothing in the video to indicate the child's sex.
Participants were then asked to estimate how much pain the child felt.
But here's the thing: half the participants were told the child was a girl, and the other half were told the child was a boy.
The researchers found that the participants tended to consider the child's pain greater when they thought the child was a little boy.
So you see there, the sexist ideas that we have on a daily basis influence the way we interpret our world.
And that's just one study among many.
These are deeply ingrained mechanisms that each of us in this room has.
I, myself, was watching TV a few weeks ago, and there was a guy blow-drying his hair.
And I said to myself, "I'd hate it if my boyfriend spent so much time in front of the mirror."
And then I said to myself, "Oh, but that's a very sexist thought."
Why is it that, today, men don't have the right to pamper and dandy themselves up?
I know that was an inconsequential example, but it highlights the fact that not only women are affected by sexism.
I'll explain.
A woman comes to see you and says, "I want to be a pilot or a mechanic."
That would be great, and we'd encourage her in her career choice.
A man who comes to see you and says, "I want to be a stay-at-home dad or a professional make-up artist."
That's not so great.
That's what I call two-dimensional sexism.
Because it's sexist towards women, since we think that what belongs to their world, culturally to their world, in this case, consideration of children or of aesthetics, has no value in society, it's not prestigious.
But it's also inherently sexist towards men, simply because it's a restriction on their freedom and discrimination towards them.
And these aren't the only examples in society.
Gentlemen, I'd be telling you nothing new if I said you are expected to be: manly, brave, ambitious, virile.
But what does that imply about you, specifically?
Men die younger, work in more arduous jobs, are more affected by alcoholism.
And although there are many factors that relate to these issues, part of it results from the pressure to be masculine.
Men commit suicide more than women.
Do you know why?
There was a psychiatric study that showed it's because they think seeking help is a weakness.
The internalisation of the belief that men have to manage by themselves, even goes so far as to infect our behaviour.
I'm going to say something controversial, but that I firmly believe.
I don't think that men are systematically privileged or advantaged in our society today.
In 2018, a study in France and Europe found men were just as discriminated against,
particularly in jobs where women are most often to be found,
but also concerning decisions on the time it takes to adjust - no ... concerning decisions on changing working hours when it comes to responsibilities as a parent.
In 2020, men are entitled to 11 days of paternity leave, compared to 10 weeks for mothers.
So, once again, if you follow my logic, this is discrimination against men: it stops them taking advantage of this moment in life, to create that special, unique bond with their child. But it's also disadvantageous to women since they carry the responsibility for the first months of a child's life alone, which has consequences for their careers.
In addition to that, studies show that wage gaps widen when women have children.
In fact, there is no difference between women who don't have children and men.
And we women, we also value male power.
And we have sexist expectations of men.
In romantic relationships, studies show, especially in social psychology, that we prefer men who are a bit macho, even if we know they are demeaning and condescending.
But even in education, mothers more than fathers have a tendency to instil sexist ideas.
In whom?
In their sons. Because they're worried that they won't be manly enough.
And in the study I just told you about, it was mostly women who thought the pain was more severe for the boys.
I can reassure you, this struggle against male power is not borne solely by women.
Because in addition to working in research, I'm also active outside academia, which allows me to see how organisations are dealing with this subject.
I think all of you have heard of, or perhaps participated in, programs to learn how to negotiate when you're a woman, or how to develop your leadership skills as a woman.
Well, yes, these are great initiatives because they give women tools to better manage their careers.
But if you think about it, it, in essence, sends a contradictory signal too.
We're asking women to be stronger, more careerist: we’re encouraging them to adopt men's codes.
In this scenario, what's valued is competition and masculinity to the detriment of other culturally feminine values - yes, culturally, those things like  listening and empathy.
We could, for example, propose courses in organisations on anger management or to develop empathy.
So, now that I've told you, we all have a role to play.
Gentlemen, you are at least 50% affected by gender inequality, so you've a right to be heard,
whether it's demanding as much paternity leave as women get, or not to be judged when you ask for a strawberry mojito rather than a pint.
And being a woman does not mean - and I hope I'm proof of that - that you cannot defend men who are victims of sexism, because when you explain to a man that he has as much to gain as you in fighting gender inequality, you thereby gain an ally, and not an enemy.
And finally, I hope everyone is aware that in a world where inequality is rising, it’s not by encouraging women to imitate men by being powerful and dominant that we will achieve a fairer and more modern society.
So, long live powerlessness.
(Applause)
(Applause) [Indoor urban farming, a 100% natural challenge] Can you see any difference between these two lettuces?
They are the same variety, they are the same shape, the same colour, the same size.
Simply put, they are identical.
This plant was grown using current field farming methods.
Do you think it is natural?
Eighty percent of lettuces grown in fields contain pesticides,
including the so-called CMRs, in other words, carcinogenic, mutagenic or reprotoxic substances.
Add to that an average of 300 food miles, kilos of carbon dioxide and other toxic gases and 15 litres of water to grow it.
Do you want it?
This one doesn't contain any pesticides or herbicides,
it hasn't emitted any CO2 and it only needed a large glass of water to grow.
Indoor urban farming is a revolutionary solution and is 100% natural.
So, growing plants indoors with artificial light - does that remind you of anything?
For a long time, this was the way cannabis was grown.
But in 2011, more important problems brought about this type of farming:
the Fukushima nuclear accident.
The atmosphere and the soil were polluted, radioactive, and it was impossible to grow vegetables locally for food.
But in order to be able to feed the citizens healthily, the Japanese had the incredible idea to grow vegetables indoors, in an enclosed environment.
The plants grew without soil, and with strict control of all the inputs provided through air and water.
The entire photosynthesis process was reproduced, but indoors.
Well, the project made quite a bit of noise; it was an eccentric, off-the-wall idea.
But little by little, people got used to it.
The concept spread, and now, it's even become a necessity.
Today, six million Japanese consume products derived from indoor urban farming.
Research and technology have advanced very quickly, providing new perspectives.
China and America took the lead, in light of their population issues, looking to reduce their dependence on foreign food.
But it was in Singapore that the first vegetable towers were born, in 2012.
Only 1% of the island's land is cultivatable, though it's one of the most densely populated places in the world.
More than 90% of the food is imported, without the slightest guarantee of origin or quality, to such an extent that local supermarkets sell products to wash fruit and veg to remove pesticides and other chemicals.
But what challenges lie ahead, exactly?
According to a study by the UN and the FAO, the UN Food and Agriculture Organisation, the world's agricultural production must double between now and 2050 to keep up with the demand of nearly 10 billion inhabitants.
Currently, about 50% of us live in cities.
But in 2050, this will be closer to 70%.
All the cultivatable land near cities has already been farmed.
Should we continue to look for even more land?
Even further from consumers?
Or continue to dump tons of chemicals across the countryside?
No, we can't go on like this.
I come from a farming family, in the south of France, near Toulouse.
My parents grew all sorts of vegetables in their fields: grains, wheat, corn, but also vegetables.
When I was eight, I already had my own vegetable patch. I had experimented with all kinds of veg that came into my head.
But it takes so long for crops to grow at that age!
Then, when I was 12, I saw on the Internet that plants grew quicker indoors, and I wanted to test that straightaway.
And now, I have been observing and growing plants for 18 years.
I enjoy making my own environmental conditions to provide the plants with a perfect environment indoors.
And so, after scraping through some exams at school - but really thanks to my own experiments and the Internet - I was able to create a unique growing method: organic indoor hydroponics.
The plants' roots are immersed in a mix of compost and water,
and then beneficial bacteria are added: Trichoderma as well as mycelium,
exactly the same bacteria that are found in the ground, in the woods and also in organic farming.
These bacteria decompose the compost so the plants can digest it.
In a sense, I am trying to reproduce all the complexity of soil, but in water.
And everything is lit by LED lights that are specially calibrated for growing vegetables.
I then thought about several places for doing this type of growing.
And, like another famous farming company, the renowned Apple brand, I started in my garage.
But in the end, I found the best compromise with shipping containers.
They are adapted for growing vegetables in a healthy and innovative way in the heart of cities.
It is no longer up to the plant to adapt to weather hazards - strong winds, rain, storms, clouds, hail ...
In this shipping container, I provide everything that the plants need, at the right time, with no variability or stress for them.
And this allows the production of 100 plants a day - almost a ton of vegetables a month - guaranteed.
I wanted to push the innovation even further by imagining modules for the plants.
Each module includes an intensity, an air quality, a water quality and a light spectrum that are specially adapted to the different stages of plant growth.
For example, in a germinator, a basil or parsley seed will germinate in just three days, whereas it normally takes about three weeks with traditional farming.
Then, a nursery welcomes the young shoots where they start to be watered.
And finally, plants finish maturing on adapted shelves.
So it takes about 45 days from seed to harvest to obtain perfectly matured plants, compared to about 70 to 80 days on average with traditional farming.
And thanks to this, it is possible to grow up to 15,000 plants at the same time in 13 square metres - in other words, 150 times more productive than farming in ordinary soil.
And all of this, managed remotely, thanks to my smartphone.
Don't get me wrong - this in no way resembles intensive or factory farming, as one might very easily equate with a henhouse.
In the box, I provide everything that the plants need, at the right time, with no variability or stress for them.
In a way, the vegetables are happy.
And, as you will have gathered, this is without pesticides, herbicides or GMOs. What's more, it saves 500,000 litres of water per year per container, compared to traditional farming.
And what about pushing this innovation even further with indoor urban farms?
I grow vegetables, edible flowers, medicinal plants and other vegetables that are rarer, more sought-after, like saffron, vanilla, miraculin or even truffles.
I also experiment with vegetables with unusual shapes.
First, we had flat peaches, but tomorrow, we will have square watermelons.
Or even - imagine - super-carrots, that could contain up to 20 times more carotene and antioxidants, without genetic modification or additives, just by providing the plant with the correct light that it needs.
And then you realise that these plants are grown just around the corner, that they are delivered by bicycle within half an hour of being picked, still alive, to the consumer.
Today, food is produced where climatic conditions are ideal, but not always by healthy methods.
For example: Spanish strawberries, aside from not having any taste, are covered in chemical products. Or even the mint in your mojito has come from hundreds of miles away, from Morocco, when all we need to do is to make the most of nature's exceptional offerings by farming products healthily and just around the corner.
I estimate that today, traditional farming makes use of only 25% of plants' potential,
whereas indoor urban farming will let us go much further, by consuming local products, economically and always without any chemicals.
Together, let's rise to the challenge of 100% natural urban indoor farming.
(Applause)
Good evening.
When I was a child, I coined a phrase to introduce myself quickly, and to give a quick answer to all the questions I was often asked.
And the phrase was: "Hi, my name's André.
I am a boy -- At the time, I already had long hair, and people thought I was a girl, which I found amusing -- "I am six, I don't eat candy and I don't go to school."
And these days, when introducing myself, well, I can introduce myself in very much the same way, and that's what I'm going to do tonight.
Good evening. My name is still André,
I am still a boy, I still don't eat candy, among other things, and I still don't go to school.
I am a 43-year-old child who has never been to school, which in our world makes me kind of an exception, and to me, being an exception is always a surprise, while what I've been through, is most natural.
Any child, given the same circumstances, would have a very similar experience.
And that's what I would like to talk to you about tonight.
I'd like to talk to you about children's spontaneous tendencies, which were never disrupted in my life, and which makes me an exception though I am the most ordinary of kids.
And that's all that matters to me, I am neither special nor gifted.
In other words, if an avocado pit, were soaked in water... It happened recently, when my four-and-a-half year-old son, Antonin, whom I introduce to you tonight, gave it a try.
Let's put an avocado pit in water, in a few days, it will grow a stem and roots, and none of us would say, "That avocado was gifted!"
Because the avocado pit is hard-wired to grow, and that was my experience, and that's what I'd like to share with you, stressing that because it could happen to any child, it should be of interest to us.
I am referring to children's spontaneous tendencies. And the very first one that comes to mind, is a question for you: what is the first thing a child does when left to himself?
He plays.
And all the children play, regardless of the setting or environment, war, famine, fear, luxury, I don't know what's worst.
Anyway, when given a chance, children play, and if never interrupted, they would keep playing.
But we do interrupt.
Now, I am fortunate to be working with a neurobiologist, and neurobiologists have revealed an interesting fact, they tell us it is no accident that we are sent into the big world, equipped with the most brilliant learning device ever invented, I call it playing.
There's no better way to learn than by playing.
You should write it on the refrigerator door.
This makes us wonder why no one has ever asked what would happen to a child who was allowed to play, not only for an entire day, but for instance, for 43 years.
Would he really turn out to be an illiterate, asocial and jobless savage?
So to continue with neurobiology, for children, playing and learning are synonyms.
It is one and the same thing and they can't distinguish between them.
Now let's imagine that a loved one, a person of reference, comes to the child and says to him: 'You need to stop playing in order to learn.'
That's funny but it's as though I were telling you, now, breathe without taking in air.
It wouldn't make any sense, and you'd think I am asking for something senseless.
And this is the interesting part, because children don't let themselves think like that.
They don't let themselves think that the adult has a problem.
And since they don't, they think they are the one with a problem.
And when children realize they have a problem, it activates the same neural networks in their brain as intense pain.
Let's be clear about that.
And so, after this contradictory instruction, children have another spontaneous tendency, which we learn from neurobiology, I am not a neurobiologist, and I will not claim qualifications I don't have, but I will summarize some common conceptions, we thought there were genetically-wired brains, some wired to be dumb, and others to be smart.
And since it was convenient, we held onto that for many years, and then we recently made a stunning discovery, we found that the part of the brain that controls the thumb, is overdeveloped in present day youths.
(Laughter) So we thought, "That's amazing, it means the brain can develop just like a muscle."
and we devised brain-muscle developing software, designed to give us brains like this to carry around, but it didn't work.
And now we are faced with a pretty puzzling question: why does it work for text messages, but not for maths?
(Laughter) And that's when we made the discovery of the 21st century.
We discovered that our brain develops when we use it enthusiastically.
And enthusiasm is the key to everything.
It's amazing to see neurobiology giving us proof of something we've always known, for we know that in an enthusiastic mood, we grow wings, and become unstoppable, we know that learning comes naturally, and here neurobiology gives us a very interesting stat, the child, serially and naturally equipped with the most brilliant learning device ever, playing, is equally endowed, with his fair share of carry-on fertilizer, because it turns out that enthusiasm is the brain's fertilizer.
It is well documented, you can Google it. It is very captivating to see how it works.
So we each come equipped not only with the best of learning devices, but in addition, its carry-on fertilizer.
Children are perpetually immersed in a state of enthusiasm.
Figures indicate that children aged 2 to 3 get enthused, feel a surge of enthusiasm every 2 to 3 minutes, and are enthused by just about everything.
Even a little piece of paper can keep them enthused for hours.
And the same figures, you know what they say about us, grown-ups, we [only] ever work up the same amount of enthusiasm, 2 to 3 times a year.
(Laughter) Yet, it doesn't have to be so.
In us, in each child, lays a potential genius.
And since there is a child inside each one of us, there is a potential genius inside us waiting for just one thing, to see what will enthuse us.
But for us to be enthused, we also need to get rid of some things, for instance, the stratification of trades and subject matters.
An example: My son, Antonin, went out one day, at 5p.m. into the streets of Paris, and was taken by the sight of garbage trucks.
So we followed them from stop to stop, stopping at each pick-up and observing their game, and they happened to notice this little boy watching them, because he knows nothing of the stratification of trades.
I would even say that for him, in that moment, the garbage man is far more relevant and easy to relate to than a lawyer.
And so, not only was he watching those men, but what's more, he looked at them with admiration.
And it reflected on them.
Suddenly, they were doing their job a little differently, with more enthusiasm.
They played, they made dance moves with the garbage bags... Antonin is now a star for the garbage men of our neighborhood, and we can no more gob out incognito at 5 p.m. because there is always a garbage truck somewhere honking their horns to greet him from afar.
And this is the third spontaneous tendency of children, to go out into the big world.
The worst that could happen to a child, would be to lock him home, where he'd experience family life at all levels, but equally all family fears.
The advantage of going into the wide world, is that one learns to share the fear of different people, hence different fears.
This is child optimization, the child is optimized for the world, yet we take them out of the world to prepare them for the world.
Strange, isn't it?
There is something else we need to get rid of.
To rekindle enthusiasm and rediscover the child in us, we must rid ourselves of our ironic attitude towards children. And thus also, towards the child in us.
We must restore trust in the child and in his extraordinary spontaneous tendencies, three of which I have just covered.
And to restore trust and get rid of this ironic attitude, I like sharing a short story, because it illustrates the ironic attitude, and also illustrates how we can trust children, I invite you to come with me, to the side of the mirror
where we trust children.
Come. Antonin is two and a half years old, it is time to buy him a car.
So we go to a toy shop and he picks a car, he chooses a red Ford Mustang, at 1/18, it is this tall, a convertible model, it is key that it be a convertible, because when it is convertible, you can reach the steering wheel and play on the wheels.
Were it not convertible, you would need to drive with the door open, but driving with the door open is not very convenient, and that's exactly what we forget, the child wants a perfect imitation of the world.
Children are born imitators.
Once you stop to think about children, you can see that.
Antonin once discovered the sound of a nailing gun, it is an extremely complex sound, with the influx of air, percussion, the outflow of air, it's a sound we in fact would not be able to imitate.
But he can, because he found the string of syllables, which when overlapped and pronounced, perfectly mimic the sound of a nail gun.
Children are born imitators, and they love to bring the most realistic possible mimicry to their plays.
And so, we pick up the 1/18 red Mustang, a collection model, and we go to the cash register, and the cashier actually confirms that it's a great purchase, and she says: "It's a beautiful model.
I'll wrap it for you, is it a gift?"
-"Oh no, not at all, he's going to play with it right away."
-"Wait a minute, is it his?" -"Yes."
-"Oh, but it is not suited
to his age at all!
(Laughter) I have cars suited to his age.
Look, I have lots of them."
Do you know what types of cars she shows me?
They are plastic with bogus proportions, (Laughter) brightly colored, with a smile, a nose, ears, and one of them even has an audio message: "Hey, I'm a car, and you, who are you?" (Laughter)
"But my son is not mentally challenged!
He is a child like all others, what he wants is a car that looks like other cars he sees everyday in the street, and the cars suited to his age, fortunately, he never sees any in the street. (Laughter)
So, please Miss, we will take the red Mustang."
She says, "Yes", but adds, "you see this beautiful model, he will break it to little pieces."
And here, it is important to note that the lady is not trying to scare me, she wants to share her fear with me.
It's not the same thing.
Then she finds the greatest of all fears.
"You know," she says, "he will not only break it to little pieces, he will also swallow those little pieces." (Laughter)
Okay, maybe the whole joke is on the cashier, but I really like that you laughed and we are laughing together.
Because when we can laugh in that place, it is proof that you came with me to the other side of the mirror, the mirror where we trust children, and where we know that two years later, the red Mustang is unscathed, all of a sudden you can see how we illustrate this ironic attitude, and also how we can illustrate, the strength we get from being on the side of the mirror where we trust children, and maybe, and this is what I suggest, once you're on this side of the mirror, you will feel like staying there, and meeting the child in you with his spontaneous tendencies, and maybe you'll be free from your irony towards children, and that was my invitation for tonight, I wish you lots of enthusiasm.
(Applause)
I am teaching math, an academic area that often suffers from a poor reputation. We all have a personal experience with math that is more or less happy.
I have been working in the same junior high school for 13 years.
This school is located in a "sensitive" area, that will be renamed "high priority education area", next September. It did not take long for me, facing students with difficulties, to turn into being a teacher in difficulty.
Graduating in mathematics, did not prevent me from being overwhelmed and helpless, hardly managing a group of students and hardly teaching maths either.
I have often considered to stop teaching.
I joined every training about struggling students.
I discovered "active listening"
at a lifelong education programme. Whatever your profession, don't forget lifelong education.
It helps you acquire skills ... survival methods in a hostile environment.
You never know what to expect, but you make sure you are ready to deal with it!
I've been blessed with becoming a mum.
Twice.
Everybody knows it, when you become a mum, you definitely stop believing education is easy.
The kindergarten of my children offers parenting skills workshops.
We are told that there is no such thing as a parent’s handbook,
but some writings are really helpful.
So, I went to Paris and participated in the “Le Grand Atelier des Parents”, to share these skills.
Ideas worth spreading need to be shared.
These tools were useful to me both personally and professionally, but they also were responsible
for the difficulties I've met, for the angry I felt more than often, whenever I was confronted with education practices I knew were harmful to knowledge acquisition, self-esteem, development of self-reliance, motivation and creativity.
During 13 years, I've developed some tools, that I have tried, proved to be efficient. I've improved them, and I will continue to make them evolve. These tools are really useful because thanks to them, I could get rid of my anger. I wanted to so much to be compassionate.
I used to tell myself I was compassionate.
Compassion is a mindset, a pose that makes sure that everone is fine.
So, let me introduce you these 5 tools that I use in my classroom and at school.
The first tool is self-knowledge.
It comes together with self-esteem and self-confidence.
If you want a closer hint, you need to be able to relativize things.
For instance, a kid crosses the street without looking, and almost gets run over by a car.
It's not unusual that the panic of the parent turns into anger instantly. They shout at their kid, while the kid is still panicked.
When we get stressed and overwhelmed by the rhythm of life, when we don’t take time to breathe, we may confuse our emotions, and mix up causes and consequences. We lose any logical reasoning or any coherence.
It is important, however, to recognize and understand our emotions.
I teach the different learning profiles to my students. I teach them to recognize their own.
"Is my memory visual?"
"Do I memorise better when I listen to things?"
"Do I need to move my body?"
A self-analysis requires confidence.
Kindness builds that confidence.
When the teacher can give pupils the benefit of a doubt, when she truly thinks that he is not lazy, or just showing bad faith, when she truly thinks that a child has difficulty processing a learning, only then, is the teacher able to start the real work on the student's weaknesses and strengths. Take time to breathe,
to be present, to be able ...
I spoke too fast and I didn't take time
to be present, to breathe.
When you take the time to be truly present to define what kind of learner you are, you can then open your mind to the knowledge of the world.
One of the objectives of the junior high school consists of leading the students to acquire a certain corpus of knowledge.
Students often blame the school
to bore them deeply. One way to understand the world is to experience it. That's the reason why we need experiences in applied sciences, cultural visits, linguistic journeys. There is a tool that fits the bill, and even makes learning more effective: Internet.
If we ask either parents or teachers, for their opinion about the internet, we hear many things, especially a kind of panic.
But denying Google the status of a friend, is disconnected, if I may say, and totally obsolete. Students use Internet to find every kind of tutorial. Because students can find everything on their own, our role as educator includes to make sure they understand what the Internet is, and how to protect themselves when they use it.
This student generation, the Z generation, grew up with Internet. We can't ask them just to ignore it.
In maths class, it was a logical step to realize that from the classroom, you could precisely calculate the distance between home and the school, or, more interestingly, around lunch time, the distance between the classroom and the dinning hall.
The Internet is like the world: constantly changing.
We need to analyse the situation empirically, to adapt ourselves, and to bounce back in front of new challenges.
From this perspective, it is possible to build a career from diverse jobs, should they be successive or simultaneous.
Atypical careers from all over the world fusing together otherwise impossible paths are very inspiring.
I've briefly talked about breathing. The Internet is one of their sources of inspiration.
The third tool makes sense in a sensitive school where we often witness a decline of the learning environment, a rise in incivilities, assaults and violence in general.
Conflicts often stem from lack of understanding, from quick a-priori, and from egocentric thoughts.
One of my missions is to make it easy for them to open their mind. That's precisely what I've been teaching to my students, in the classroom and in communication workshops for a few years.
I teach them the tools of non-violent communication.
When we talk about non violent communication, ignorance or hasty judgement, you may think about being too permissive. So let me clarify things with a tool I often use with my students. It is inspired by the next generation of mediators of Université de la Paix.
Students can rather easily make the distinction between the Turtle, an animal that is not looking for any solution and shuts down, and the Lion, coming with its own solution and imposing it upon others, hitting, threatening, blackmailing, even snitching.
Students usually think that I'm asking them to be Chameleons: that prioritizes relationship and the other at any cost, even if it means stepping aside.
Obviously, that's not the point.
I ask them to speak Dolphin,
this intelligent animal, able to communicate, just like we are.
Dolphin speaks in ME-ssages, it describes what is going on, from what is its own perspective: facts and its emotions.
Once you identify the other's problem, you are more willing to find solutions that are suitable for everyone.
My school faces the same challenge: to empower students with this very ability to be able to live and cope in society.
By the way, when you ask students about the usefulness of school, their first and very conservative answer is "To learn things to get a job." Then, they go on, in a realistic and spontaneous way, "I can see my friends!" John Lennon will make a better transition than me. [When I went to school, they asked me what I wanted to be when I grew up. I wrote down happy. They told me I didn’t understand the assignment, and I told them
they didn’t understand life.]
He sings about happiness in life, and in school.
One major problem in our society, and in the French Education System, is the burden of negative emotions endured by all stakeholders.
Students are stressed by their exam's results, and worried by their teachers' and parents' reaction. They are filled with a feeling of incompetence, they lose their interest.
I meet parents who are worried, sad and filled with anger because they don't know how to help their struggling child.
I will not talk about my fellow teachers.
Don't ask me to talk about the teachers' lounge. There's no worse place to relax yourself.
(Laughter) I've developed my own solution to deal with my anger, because in my case, fear and sadness turn into anger.
I've found a way to "transform" my anger into something else, by creating a cocoon full of happiness, protecting me and reloading my batteries.
Everyone needs to create something
based on his or her own true self. When you confine someone to a just-sticking-to-the-rule position, you are killing his soul, what makes him a human being.
Students' minds are not an empty void that needs to be filled. They are opportunities waiting to happen.
The culture of encouraging children can be learned and taught.
Not so long ago, I had some tough times, and I considered changing my profession. In fact, should I not have had my kids, I would have gone on a humanitarian mission. A lot of support helped me not to quit. My life partner told me this, "You can't quit! You manage to turn an awful and traumatic academic subject - I told you previously that everyone has a personal relationship with math -
you turn an awful and traumatic topic into a joyful experience."
My partner's words hit the mark, but he was not alone. My students gave me their support too. Because I taught them how much important it is to encourage people.
Because they need encouragement too, just like I do.
Every end of school term, we spend an important moment together, one hour actually, to write down positive things and special memories.
It's a wonderful gift to receive them, and to meet students a few years later, grabbing out of his wallet a worn-out piece of paper, telling that it is on his bedside table, or hanging on the bedroom wall.
It shows my choice was right to nurture happiness consciously, to scale back school violence,
and to nurture social cohesion, because it's our future challenge nowadays, it is a real challenge for both students and teachers to come happy at school, and to be happy there.
Let's grow happiness and share it around us.
Picasso used to say this, "The meaning of life is to find your gift. The purpose of life is to give it away."
This year, we are focusing on that, in a new civic workshop named Colibris. Every student who wishes to do so, may get involved and work actively in the organization of events that reinforce the esprit de corps among the whole school community.
A concrete example is our Day of Global Kindness. Everyone is appreciated individually for his action within a collective event.
It makes everyone feel empowered, free to create and suggest ideas, and to have a strong feeling of belonging to a community, to be able to contribute to its welfare.
These are the activities taking place inside the school.
Thanks to the help of local associations, we were able to contribute actively to the Christmas party for the homeless in Saint-Joseph.
We served dinner to the homeless people.
Students could decide what they wanted to do. This event is one of the strongest and unforgettable memories that we share.
This year, on Shrove Tuesday, we organized a Carnival, for children under therapy, at the hospital.
Hopefully, I'm not alone in my school.
There are other weird teachers like me.
Together, we let the light flood out
into the outside world. In our school, we do organic gardening, we compost our lunch waste - When I think about my co-workers, I'm so happy I get gosse bumps! -
so, we compost lunch waste, we sing Maloya music, we've trail-crossed the island during the Grand Raid trail, we dance for kindness, we free-hug one another.
With sharing in mind, I've engaged myself for a few years in a teacher training group.
The philosophy of the training is based on our theoretical knowledge about cognitive pedagogy, non-violent communication, diverse learning methods, and children psychology. Through the training, everyone learns to take the time to breathe, to get inspiration from others' experience. It empowers us to create and grow an environment suitable to our own school, fitting our own classes precisely.
We visit schools ready to take the step. Our advantage lies in the very fact that we too, are active teachers. Our training courses are based on our everyday experiences. As long as I am concerned, discussing about our methods
makes me a better teacher.
The idea is to accept to get away from your comfort zone, let the magic take place, and witness that kindness is more comfortable:
for students, educators, teachers and parents. We start growing a genuine relationship with the other, our boss, our colleagues or our friends.
Suddenly, everything became crystal clear, and I've found my life mission. I've learned who I really was, how to get rid of my anger, which was something I needed to achieve. I've created connections around me and through the Internet. I nurture genuine relations with people dedicated to spread the word. Today, I am part of a global action that promotes kindness and compassion. In a compassionate school, in a caring world, we are specialized in non-violent communication, and we have a toolbox. To show off the tools and expect you to be able to use them is not the point. It is important to know that they exist and what is available, and what to use when and how. So that they come in handy when we need them, when we are ready. If nothing fits you,
you can build your own tools. At school, in a compassionate environment, you learn that whatever you do, it is never useless.
We learn that just one straw can break the camel's back, that just one person can make the difference, that one seed can wake up from hibernation many years after it was sowed, and will grow only when all conditions are met.
I encourage you to do the same:

get up and sow kindness around you. When you raise children with kindness and compassion, they will spread the good seeds wherever they live:
in business, politics, non-profit or education.
If you don't believe the impossible is possible, I'm quite happy to tell you that it's under way.
Here is a classroom in 1950.
What do we see?
We see diligence and discipline.
At the time, teachers called students by their last name: "Monier!" "Rivalin!" "Hémond!"
Students come to school to acquire knowledge.
There are about thirty desks lined up facing straight ahead and a teacher discharging his knowledge.
In 1950, this classroom model was perfect for what laid ahead of them.
And what laid ahead of them?
A stable, healthy economy, with no changes,
and workers that always did the same things repetitively.
It was an era of local production, and those people were going to work at one job for almost all their lives.
And here is where we are in 2018.
We are in places that are fun compared to the factories we saw in the previous picture.
Thursday night happy hours, Christmas parties, we have new working practices.
We work in collaboration aided by an ever-present technology.
And in some companies, it is even a competitive advantage.
Uber or Airbnb wouldn’t exist without technology.
The motto is Innovation because, as you know, now production takes place abroad, in Asia.
If companies don’t innovate, they just disappear.
Technologies are omnipresent and we are here to solve complex problems.
Tremendous changes are taking place in society.
So how are we preparing this future generation of workers?
Like this!
How is it different from the first photo apart from the color?
We still have about thirty desks. We look straight ahead. The teacher is there, discharging his knowledge to the children.
Classroom management is silence.
This is what we still learn at university: a good classroom management is silence in the classroom.
Technologies? Practically non-existent.
There are two or three computers
on the side, functional if you're lucky.
We're preparing them for the secondary sector but hardly for the third sector.
You have gone through this as I have, and it was difficult for me.
I was divergent. I used to ask questions. I was hyperactive, more often outside the classroom than inside.
I was a bother and when I understood too quickly, I started to crack jokes.
I turned out okay fortunately.
Now I wish to announce that school needs to be reinvented ...
(Sound interruption) ... the monopoly of knowledge.
Today, knowledge is in our students’ pockets.
If students spend two hours commuting to school to acquire the knowledge they already have in their pocket, spot the mistake.
We wonder why there are so many dropouts today in Quebec and also around the world.
Many students no longer go to university.
Instead they take MOOC, Massive Open Online Courses,
a dozen MOOC that cost $400, with the best universities worldwide and best professors.
They'll tell employers, "Here's what I've done.
Give me a job, I'll show you."
If we don't change the educational system, it will go to ruin.
We are entering the fourth industrial revolution, the digital one.
And be careful, it will hit and it will hit very hard.
I was watching a video this morning about a robot that took sheets of plywood and fixed them on a wall.
This is where we are today.
The advent of artificial intelligence is going to have an enormous impact on our societies.
In the old days, robots were in factories.
Now, we know that artificial intelligence algorithms are better at diagnosing skin cancer than dermatologists.
It's the same with radiologists.
The lawyers who practice jurisprudence are going to lose their jobs.
Taxis, transportation, we don't even talk about them.
So the implications are complex.
We are in a society that moves extremely quickly.
Look at what's going on today, and imagine what will happen in 10 years.
We know that half of the people here who have a job is going to either lose it or it is going to change completely.
Two thirds of the jobs that the youths in my elementary school will be doing don't exist, but schools have to prepare these children.
How?
In the way I showed at the beginning.
Spot the mistake!
Here is what schools should develop, these skills that we call the "five Cs."
"Collaboration," young people should be taught how to collaborate.
We can no longer solve problems alone in our society.
"Communication" skills in both speaking and writing in different contexts.
In interviews, I see too many people who have great CVs but don't know how to sell themselves.
We should know how to sell ourselves.
"Critical thinking."
Are we going to accept that military robots kill humans?
Do young people know that their Facebook and Instagram feeds are completely screened?
We are in a society where we should develop critical thinking among
our youths, and it's urgent.
We must be complementary to artificial intelligence.
"Compassion," managing emotions and human relationships, we should develop these things.
We won't be able to compete with AI on its own territory.
And the last and most important one is "creativity."
It's the skill of the future, a skill that is vital.
I mentioned that the challenges are huge. Since production is done abroad, we need to invent products and services within our society.
Now what is creativity?
Some say it's "innate" or it's
"intelligence having fun," Einstein said.
It's linked to biology.
It's the capacity to find original solutions to problems, the capacity to make connections with things that didn't exist initially, the capacity to have a creative attitude or position, to be open minded and listen to others' ideas, and to be empathetic.
Steve Jobs used to say "Creativity is connecting things, forging links between them."
We don't invent anything new. And to do so, there is a process in four phases.
The first and most important is the "preparation phase." It's about developing young children's curiosity in order to fill their internal library with knowledge right away without trying to specialize them,
such as letting them play with arts, music, dance, science, sports -
hence the importance of extracurricular activities at school so that they don't come only to acquire knowledge.
It's about developing their five senses and transforming them into polymaths just like Leonardo da Vinci, who was both an inventor, a scientist and a sculptor,
or Saint-Exupery who was a pilot, a philosopher and an author.
The "incubation phase," very difficult these days ...
When we have two minutes, we look at our phones to see the news, send a text and read our emails.
So it's about creating opportunities for ideas to emerge.
The classic cliché is under the shower, or while running, taking a walk in the park, or in the car, when we don't turn the radio full blast.
It's been proven that gamma waves increase in monks who practice meditation.
It means more neuron connections. So we should give ourselves time for the emergence of ideas.
In our CEGEP at Sainte-Anne, we have created an arts, letters and communication program
that incorporates science, innovation, and creativity.
We also thought of having a period of doing nothing.
For one hour a week, nothing happens -
no tech, no pencils, no papers, People come and settle in for an hour a week.
Finally, "the inspiration phase."
This one, we have to let it come.
And when it comes, we need to tune in and not move immediately to something else.
Take notes, write it down, then move on to something else.
And the most difficult - and here is where 95% of ideas will fail - the "realization" phase.
When you have a good idea, you follow it through to the end.
This takes courage, energy, processes, teams, so that the idea becomes an innovation.
Unfortunately, 95% of good ideas have gone nowhere.
So, do you think schools are ready for what I've just told you?
At school, work is done in silos:
Math, French, English.
There is no connection between subjects,
so how can you be creative,
even though it is said that multidisciplinary studies are important?
We have standards, grades, norms, rules of admission or readmission.
We give students problems to which they already know the solutions.
What's the point of doing that?
The training we give them doesn't make sense.
"Learning by heart" is still prevalent.
The website Littlewoods indicates that, between two and five years old, children ask 300 questions
and when they get to school,
20 questions. Look for the mistake!
Ken Robinson, a specialist in education and creativity, goes so far as to say that current schooling kills creativity.
Churchill was said to be a dunce.
Einstein, Guy Laliberté, Richard Branson, all are dropouts.
They are the ones who succeeded.
Think of all those who are now social outcasts, who haven't succeeded - incredible talents, creative - because school has not adapted to them.
We are in a culture of grades.
Our CEGEP places most students in limited enrollment programs at university.
What does a student think about when he
comes to us? R score, R score, R score. Does he think about developing creativity, collaboration, critical thought?
Well, he needs a 33 to be accepted into a law program, or 36-37 to be accepted into a medical program.
Norms are the problem.
So, what can we do? Well, first thing,
we should stop stuffing their brain.
Let's develop the skills I mentioned before
and give more room to the process.
Do you remember biology from the first
year of high school 10 years ago?
Not at all! And if you need it,
it's in your pocket.
Knowledge is in our pockets now.
And let's put students to work on solving problems.
Let's teach them ideation techniques, and methods to boost creativity.
The six hats of de Bono, different ways of brainstorming, these methods exist and they're not complicated.
Let's make mistakes a cornerstone of learning.
At school, we punish mistakes.

Flaf! A zero marked in red!
But we know now that experience
is the sum of our errors.
So to get there, we need to change our schools' culture.
Teachers have to change their roles.
They are no longer transmitters of knowledge, not anymore, that's over;
if not, youths will stay at home.
You have mentors, coaches, motivators.
Their job is to prepare problems downstream, that students will resolve in teams in a creative way,
complex problems.
We can't underestimate young people.
So to do so, we must reevaluate our prisons - excuse me, our schools.
(Laughter) Just a purposeful slip!
Today, our schools look like penitentiaries.
Our classes, as you've seen, haven't changed:
36 desks, 23 kilos, a teacher in front ...
with some luck, a digital blackboard, wow!
Classes have to change.
In our school, there are no longer a front and a back. There's a screen on every side, and the teacher is in the middle.
The desks can be raised and lowered.
If the youth learn better standing, why should he/she sit?
There are stools.
Desks and chairs are on wheels.
Classes should be flexible.
In two minutes, you should be able to reorganize your classroom.
They need light, to be fun and bright ... ... all in the aim of enabling the youths to collaborate, that's essential.
And to do that, a bold leadership is required, a leadership that is creative.
We shouldn't be afraid to try to make teachers understand - since they also went to school, to CEGEP, to university, and back to school, and then succeeded as teachers - that society and jobs evolve.
When young people enter the job market, the habit is to ask them "What did you study?
I don't really care about grades.
What I'm interested in is whether you are creative,
you know how to collaborate, and speak one, two, three languages."
That's what we ask them;
and that's what we don't teach them.
Let's invest in training.
Would you go to a dentist who didn't train for 10 years? No.
Yet we send our own children to school knowing that education isn't the place to get the most training.
So spot the mistake!
These children are among our primary school students. They will leave school in 15 years
and enter the job market.
Which job they will do, we don't know
because two thirds are still unknown.
Two years ago, no one knew what a data scientist was.
And jobs like this are going to flood.
Problems are going to be more complex than there are now, especially if we don't fix them today.
It is said we have two years to fix issues with the environment, by slowing down, or good luck!
Good luck!
I think the solution is in finding innovations,
machines that will take C02 to put it back into the earth - those already exist. We need to find ideas, and for that we need to be creative,
hence it's important to develop it at school.
Now are we going to teach creativity like Math or French? No.

But we can teach Math and French while developing creativity.
So for that, let's be creative!
Thank you.
(Applause)
Are you excited or not?
(Audience) Yes.
I try again, are you excited or not?
(Audience) Yes.
You seem really excited, now.
Here is a picture for you to cool down. Don't laugh; this is where I grew up.
OK, I am leaving!
I grew up there, I have a very exciting life, in a council flat, and my grand mother lived on the 11th floor, you will be cleverer when going to bed tonight, you did not expect to learn that from a TEDx, I suppose. This, you will never forget, Idriss Aberkane's grandmother lived on the 11th floor of this block.
Why do I show this to you?
Because I am actually convinced that in the world that surrounds us, all the objects we create and that surround us can speak, we can ask them why they are there.
All the objects we created, which are part of our daily life, our environment can be asked, "Little object, little product, little service, why are you there?"
I am convinced if we really asked objects around us why they are there, the huge majority would answer, "I am there because there is a market, idiot."
Check this with the objects around you, most of them are there because there is a market.
Actually, the people who made them don't use them.
The people who built that tower
don't live there, no.
There are objects which are not there because there is a market, and then, we have objects one even wonders why they are there at all.
This block for example, my grandmother did not live there, it has been the highest tower in the Christian world for very long, Strasbourg Cathedral, but here, it is an object that if asked, "Why are you there little building?"
It will answer, "I'm here because mum and dad loved each other very much."
These are exceptional objects
Whether they are goods, products, or services, but it can even be buildings such as Sydney Opera or the Eiffel Tower, the Eiffel Tower which was to be disassembled, since useless.
Ask the Eiffel Tower, "Why are you there?"
"I'm here because mum and dad loved each other very much."
It's not rational.
With a business plan, it would not have been built.
I am here to talk about this actually, what makes TED specificity in general, why is TED so special?
We will see in fact that it is precisely passion and love.
But, before that, I will tell you something which may not seem exciting.
Right now, we are undertaking a knowledge transaction.
I give you the knowledge, and you give me two things in exchange. Which ones? What are you
giving me right now?
(Audience) Attention, love, IA: Attention - we will talk about love later - and time.
In fact, if you want to buy knowledge, you need attention and time in exchange.
That is the equation I discovered in Stanford, it doesn't bite, don't worry, it is really kind, it describes what you are going to do today at TEDx: you are going to give attention and time to the speaker.
To buy knowledge, you need to pay with attention multiplied by time.
Let's check it is indeed a product, A product means that if one of the 2 is equal to 0, the whole equals 0.
If you give me one hour of your time, but are not focused, there will be no exchange of knowledge. You should give me
your whole attention and all your time.
This is the currency in the knowledge economy.
To learn something, you have to pay with attention and time.
And the good news with this equation is that we all have both from birth.
Yes, the young Somali is not born with pocket money, but he has attention and time.
The knowledge economy is therefore the only economy where everybody is born with a buying power, which is good news!
Under what conditions do we give our whole attention and all our time to someone?
How is this called?
Love.
When you love someone, you lavishly give him or her your whole attention and all your time.
The knowledge economy is the only one which maximizes the lovers' purchasing power.
Literally, if you want to learn faster, make sure you fall in love first with the knowledge you will learn.
This is what the story of my work and my findings are about: what is the role of love in the economy, which is supposed to be prosy?
At Stanford, when I dealt with this, people understood quite well.
But in France when I said, "Well, let's talk a little about love in companies," no kidding, people would not understand.
So, I told them, "Well, to maximize the flow of knowledge, you need to love what you do, the main point is to love your job, you will turn out to be more competitive."
But apparently, I had not found the proper words, above all with managers, as I was teaching in Centrale, and it is specific. So I thought, "We're in Descartes homeland let's make a diagram, let's draw something really Cartesian."
I called it, "Love Can Do," and I wondered, "What are the companies with a little difference, those slightly standing out?"
It is the ones which do what they can do.
So I thought, let's take the Can Do axis: can I do my job?
But we are going to add another axis, and we'll stick to the good old Cartesian diagram, and we are going to add some love; forgive me to add some love into a Cartesian diagram. Let's consider another thing, "Let's organize the companies, or not just the companies, by the way, but any initiative, according to what people love to do and what they can do."
The company which does what it loves and what it can do is the company standing out, that doesn't mean it is the leader, it means there is you, and then there's the rest of the world.
Typically, we mention Apple.
What does "standing out" mean?
Chris Martin and Gwyneth Paltrow have a daughter. Chris Martin, singer of Coldplay, and Gwyneth Paltrow, Hollywood star.
How do they call here? Apple.
Who is going to call their daughter Samsung?
(Laughter) That is standing out.
It makes you laugh because it is standing out.
Then, there is the follower, the one who does his job right, he can do it, he handles it, but he doesn't care about love.
And, excuse me, but Samsung didn't go from making toilets to making tablets just because they loved it, there was a market.
When the market was there, they just went for it.
That is the case for the vast majority of companies.
There is a market, they go for it.
That is the follower.
The difference between the follower and the leader, the one standing out, is, "Do I like the job, or do I only do it because there is a market?"
Talking of job, you know the joke, we say the Americans have Steve Jobs and the French have Pôle Emploi.
(Laughter) There is no video editing for TEDx, the joke is on me.
(Applause) Then, you have other players, my favorite being the garage in the Silicon Valley.
All those companies that were founded in garages.
What does that mean that today they are there, I mean up there?
What does it mean?
That means a maximum of love and a minimum of know-how.
That's how Google and Amazon were created. That is how Tesla, Apple, Hewlett Packard and Disney were created.
Yes, Disney created Alice in Wonderlands in a garage in Los Angeles.
Please, don't look for any wordplay.
(Laughter)
Oh, humor. The garages in the Silicon Valley don't do a job because they know how to, they don't know anything about it, but they love it.
The garage is going to select the ones who love it, because there are no grades, no prices, you won't get a regional price for competitiveness, you won't get anything, you won't be able to pick somebody saying, "I work in a garage."
You cannot write that on your resume.
There is no award, no grade, no diploma, there is only what you do.
The garage selects the enthusiasts, the ones who are passionate about the job, the ones who love it.
And so, when you mix love and incompetence, you get the result, "Sorry guys, I didn't know it was impossible so I did it."
That is typical of the Silicon Valley's companies that were created in a garage.
As we were telling them, "Guys, that is impossible," they just did it because they had no manuals to hold them back.
Obviously, the worst thing is that we have those kind of players, the compelled incomers.
It is easy to sum it up, if you ask them, "Why do you make your products?"
"Because I had to.
I wanted to be a vet but I was told to make that product, so I did."
The best example is, you might know it, the brand Lada, or the Russian words in general.
A friend of mine met a marabout in Africa, and like all great marabouts, he had the list of all his miracles: the loved-one coming back, glory, beauty, ingrown nail healing, all of it, and his concluding claim was: can even start Russian motorcycles?
(Laughter) There is walking on water, and then there is starting a Russian motorcycles.
That tells a lot about Russian motorcycles, and you clearly wouldn't dream about a Russian motorcycle.
One we have that diagram, we see that if the follower wants to stand out, there is only one question to ask, and you'll see that it fits perfectly with this TEDx's theme, the upward direction -- do you want some self-consistency?
(Laughter) They have to ask themselves, "Why do I do my job?"
For the compelled incomers, the red arrow pointing down is the path to suffering, because you get the knowledge but do not have the love of the job.
You are in this mode, "Why are you working?"
"Because I have to."
That is suffering, that is committing suicide at work, it is hell.
The garage in the Silicon Valley, on the other hand, obtains all his knowledge out of love.
He does the job because he loves it, and he is going to get all his expertise on the path to love.
That path, I called it El Camino Real, that is the avenue in the Silicon Valley.
That avenue which structures the Silicon Valley is called the royal road in Spanish, El Camino Real, and that's how I called this transition.
Because the Google, the Apple, the Walt-Disney, the Hewlett-Packard have followed this way.
The ones who followed it the most and which illustrate best Love Can Do, that's Tesla.
Tesla is typically the company which didn't know anything about its competitors..
So almost all the decisions they made were completely dumb and irrational.
On that frame, you can see an illustration of Love Can Do.
On this picture, you can see the Love and the Can Do.
That is what love is, that is this engine. In fact, when Elon Musk founded Tesla, he asked his engineers for an engine that was invented by Nicolas Tesla, because he is a fan of Tesla, the second da Vinci of the 20th century. So he told his engineers, "I want an engine that was invented by Nicolas Tesla."
If you think about it, that is dumb, as dumb as asking Airbus for a Leonard de Vinci's technology.
So the engineers replied, "Well, that is dumb."
And Elon Musk said, "I am the one paying, so you are going to make a N. Tesla's engine, and shut up."
This engine which gives nightmares to the entire global automotive establishment is an engine that was patented by Nicolas Tesla in 1896.
That is love, because it is no rational decision.
You rationally won't beat your competitors with a thing from the 19th century.
"I am just passionate about Tesla," so here it is.
Can Do is the battery in this.
You don't see it now, but they will be put onto the frame and Can Do is a car with batteries, we didn't have good returns so Elon Musk said, "Wait, does a laptop have a good battery?"
"Yeah, it's not bad."
The new Mac had a good battery.
"Fine, just take some of these and pile them up."
That's what they did.
Love Can Do.
The epitome of Love Can Do - we won't talk about it for long, it would be an inter-TEDx - it is the Wright brothers, they were entirely made of Love Can Do, they had no diploma.
While guys in Polytechnique, the MIT, the Royal Society wanted to make their first plane fly, the ones who made it fly were two idiots, 60km away from Dayton, Ohio, and who hadn't graduated from High School, and that was because they crashed five times a day.
An excellent TED speaker said it better than me, his name is Simon Sinek - spend a minute with Simon Sinek, it is better than my TEDx. I can tell you that,
seriously, Simon Sinek.
The conclusion of Love Can Do for me is that, no matter the expertise, you saw it: attention times time, when you learn something, your learning, if you are passionate, is going to take theses steps: 5, 50, 500, 5,000, maybe 50,000 hours.
In 5 hours, you get into any knowledge, in 50 hours you are autonomous, in 500 hours you can teach it, at 5,000 there are the first Nobel Prizes, and at 50,000 you get what Japanese call a living national treasure.
I insist on saying that it only works if you learn because your are passionate, you have a maximum attention.
I will show you a case of living national treasure, Wallace Chan, the best jeweler in the world.
That guy is standing out, that guys has 100,000 hours of doing what he does, that is exceptional, no jeweler can do it like he does.
I will just who you one of his creations that shows Love Can Do, the guy made a portrait in an aquamarine.
That is called the Wallace Cut, he can cut out a portrait that is reflected on all the facets
of the aquamarine.
Why? Because he loves it, and when you ask him, "Do you want to go on holidays?"
He says, "In my workshop, I am already on holidays, that is the only thing that satisfies me."
Today, you are going to see lots of speakers who will illustrate Love Can Do better than I can.
Because I am only talking about theory, they are going to talk about practice.
The speaker coming up right after me will talk to you about love in companies, and you will see exactly what Love Can Do can result in.
And so on, for the Veilles Charrues music festival, etc.
All I want you to do now, is consider Love Can Do in your life, and I want you to say something extremely simple, that is that every economically useful human being might not be fulfilled, but every fulfilled human being is necessarily economically useful. So let's value fulfillment more than economical usefulness.
Have an excellent day.
(Applause)
Being an old man is not so bad.
For most people, life is like eating asparagus.
At first, childhood is sweet, happy, and lighthearted.
Teen age is always good, the first loves, the hopes, the discoveries.
And then it gets harder,
the career, the responsibilities;
but you can still enjoy it. Then it comes a time when it gets so hard, sour and full of fiber, that you are just happy to end it all.
I had to swallow my asparagus life the other way around.
The beginning was leathery, pugnacious, the school, the strict parents, and then the war.
The gas masks, the alarm sirens, and then the Nazi occupation, the yellow star.
My family would go into hiding in Dordogne under false identity.
Way better was my early apprenticeship as a print maker, since I was 14.
Then the hiding in the bush, the resistance.
Bit by bit sweeter, the liberation, the love, the children.
My business life, the creation, the journeys.
Today I find myself at this crispy and delicious point, free, happy, I write books, and the only thing I am afraid of, is that my asparagus will come to an end.
As Woody Allen said, "I am not afraid of death, I just don't want to be there when it happens."
The sour, tough beginning of my asparagus was occupation.
When I was 15, I joined the Maquis in Corrèze and took the position of liaison officer.
In fact, I carried envelopes from a bush to another, by bike, with a schoolbag on my shoulders so that to look like a boy going to school.
One day in 1943, on a bridge, German soldiers helped by some militants checked the papers.
The militants were those extremist collaborators in charge of arresting members of the Resistance, Jews, Gipsy and Maquis, and handing them over to the Gestapo.
A militant stops me, makes me get off my bike, and asks for my papers.
They were false, and the message I was delivering was particularly compromising.
I was about to show him my papers, when a German soldier at the other end of the bridge calls him and asks him to come immediately.
What a miracle! The militant
signals me to leave.
After that time, I told myself that nothing really bad could possibly happen to me.
I am still astounded.
I am 89 and a half years old.
(Laughter) Since I was 80, we celebrate the half year anniversary, like they do with babies.
(Laughter) You never know!
(Laughter) Sometimes during my life, I asked myself,
"What does being old mean?"
What do you think of? What do you do?
What do you love?
Do you wait for death with a mixture of patience and fear?
Or maybe you repel the idea, trying to live yet so intensely, looking around you, participating, making an effort to understand what's going on in the world?
I chose the second option.
I find my way out in writing books.
The road to happiness does not exist.
After all, should it exist, it'd be so very crowded that it would not be walkable.
In compensation, you find a bustle of narrow secret paths, while looking around you, of tiny charming delights.
I rarely happen to think about death.
It is a word that I don't like, anyway, it is a sinister word.
"End of life" seems to me more appropriate to what I feel.
One day, this beautiful adventure must as well come to an end.
On the other hand, my friend's passing is difficult to accept.
Sometimes I feel like I am in a forest that endured a hurricane, and I am going to be the only tree still standing.
What I fear, is the relaxing armchair on which one falls asleep in a sugary and cottony half-sleep.
But as for now, I am not there yet.
People often ask me, "What do you do to stay fit and good-humoured after all this years?"
I am not a guru, I cannot teach how to live a joyful life.
But what I can do is sharing with you some things from my huge trunk of memories, mixed with happiness, melancholy, and some kind of bliss.
There are years and years of that, a friend used to tell me, "What annoys me most in you is that you are always blissfully happy."
70 years later, I am still always happy, in front of inventions, innovations, films, books, music, design.
Yes, I am happy.
When I browse my tablet to know everything about Blaise Pascal, or to find a new washing machine, and it blinks as if saying, "Got it!", and in a few seconds it tells me everything about the dear Blaise, while showing me the last 100 washing machine models.
In the past, if you wanted to quickly get some information about a philosopher, or about the last appliances, you had to subscribe to a pay telephone service.
You would type SVP 11 11 on your telephone's keyboard and ask your question to an operator.
She would check her notes and call you back.
SVP 11 11 answered to about 5,000 questions per day.
Today, there are more than three billion searches on Google per day, that is almost 40,000 per second.
Yes, I am happy... when I take the Channel Tunnel, of which I had the chance to witness the connection of its two halves during its building.
I am happy when they treat me with radiotherapy instead of slicing me like other times.
That's the kind of things that give me hope and make me believe that men can be extraordinary.
And women as well, of course.
Starting with my wife.
I want to tell you about how we first met.
She was rather surprising.
It was the epoch of surprise parties, slow dancing and swing.
Everyone brought their 45 rpm records and their whiskey bottles.
I ask a girl to dance.
I ask her name, she replies, "Lise Weill."
"That's funny, mine's Claude Weill."
"Oh, yes, that's funny indeed!"
"And the girl over there, she's my sister, Micheline Weill."
"Oh well, my sister's name is also Micheline Weill!"
"Please, don't tell me that your father's name is Robert!"
"But it is indeed, my father's name is Robert.
But he is dead."
"My father's dead too."

"That's incredible! Where do you live?"
"In the 17th road."
"Me too."
"And you are 19?"
"Me too."
We left together.
We walked along Niel Avenue, it was dark and very cold.
Lise put her hand in my coat's pocket.
And this is how we have been together for 70 years.
Our jobs were completely different.
I was the manager of a retail advertising company.
Lise was a dental surgeon.
Beside her dental practice, she'd created a free dental care service in a Parisian hospital.
It was before CMU started.
Later, she funded an association with some colleagues, they went to far-off regions where no dentists used to go.
They treated people that sometimes were at risk of dying of malnutrition, since their teeth were in such a bad shape that they refused to feed themselves.
Lise trained the inhabitants in basic dental care.
She has also worked in the Andes, at an altitude of more than 4000 meters, or in Nicaragua, during the war.
To operate in those regions without electric power, Lise had created a special suitcase together with an engineer.
The top part enclosed a solar panel, and the inner part a complete kit of dental care tools.
Lise's suitcase, as we called it then, it's a tool that is nowadays used all over the world.
For this commitment and many more, she received the Legion of Honor from Bernard Kouchner's hands.
When we met again, we had so many things to tell each other, and that is perhaps one of the secrets of our couple's vitality.
My bliss didn't prevent me to be often insurgent, indignant, upset because of injustice and fanatism.
Lise and I have been active members of Amnesty International for 40 years, to defend human rights.
And while fighting for this common cause, we met amazing people that became close friends of ours.
In Madagascar, I took part in the building of a school, and of a refuge village with 100 houses, that still progresses thanks to his creator, Daniel Dupuis, in spite of the huge problems they are facing in that country.
One day, a friend that I really admired said to me, "One cannot die before having written a book."
He died without writing any.
As for me, I followed his advice, I've already written fourteen.
But I have to hurry!
After what happened with Charlie Hebdo, at the kosher shop and at the Bataclan, I was bewildered, despondent.
I felt disquiet and demoralization around me.
In defiance, in revolt against it I wanted to write a joyful and carefree book, trying to give back for a moment their smiles to my loved ones and to the unknown people that will read it.
I wrote "Zero Sadness!",
illustrated by Claire Maupas, whom I also entrusted with this talk's drawings.
Here then, you will have understood that being old is not so bad.
I haven't got any recipes for a happy old age to give you, but what I say is that, at 30...
At 30? No, at 89 and a half,
(Laughter)
I still want to learn, to love, and to stuff myself with asparagus!
(Applause) Thank you!
(Applause) Thank you!
(Applause)
Hello everybody! I should talk in English, because the [TEDx] conference is gonna be watched and listened all over the world. But I'm from here, I'm from Montpellier. So, I'm going to continue in French.
And, well too bad...sorry.
So, with pleasure I would like to share the secrets of the ocean.
The ocean that fascinates me, fascinates us, which fascinates us as much as it eludes us.
The marine biodiversity that we hear so much about, today is made up of 200,000 known species, conscientiously named in Latin with a first and last name.
The truth is there are still 2 million species waiting to be discovered.
Therefore we only know about 10% of this biodiversity.
The ocean is a mystery.
That's something that everybody knows, no need to be an expert.
Faced with its vastness, we feel it escaping us.
Before it, confronted by its impenetrability, we see it clearly, it surpasses us, it's a mystery.
In fact, this ocean doesn't fascinate us even though it eludes us, but because it does.
It's hiding so many pretty things from us. There are so many secrets of the ocean that escape from us.
We discover a new species every other day, a new fish every other day.
This potential of beautiful things is a vast spectrum that's worth the effort to go and explore.
All you have to do is dive in, wherever you are, wherever there is water, it's enough to dive into it.
For me, this began in the Mediterranean Sea.
Or, should I say, the Mediterranean Ocean, because of its great depths the complexity of its relief.
My vocation was born on the French coasts,
not the Côte d'Azur, not Corsica, the other coast, our coast, the least appreciated, apparently.
However, it's less appreciated because that's where the most rivers meet the sea, and which we clearly can't call it the Côte d'Azur.
People say that our sea is murky, dirty and even choppy.
I would say it's like a treasure chest, meaning that it's rich and difficult to access.
And in this sea, that many people find repulsive, I spent my younger years discovering really enticing things.
Unsettling beings that seemed to speak a language that we understand.
Even if some of these creatures, I'll give you this, weren't the most attractive and even if my diving sites weren't the most welcoming either.
I really didn't care, on the contrary, I strongly believed that these murky waters, this inhospitable border was the only way, for these unique and spectacular encounters, like giant cat-fish, sheatfish.
With just a little imagination, believe me, I was Captain Cousteau when I was little and I met my own giant groupers that waited for me, these enormous carps. I also had my very own pet anaconda, this terrifying predator, actually a 40cm long water-viper,
the only snake in Europe, I'm not holding back, that reproduces exclusively under water, by winding up like a living plait, a living impregnated plait.
Anyway, beautiful things were everywhere, and I understood, most of all, they just were in the eye of the beholder, and so I watched a lot and I travelled a bit.
Garden eels, which give the impression that they're on guard.
The acrobat crab under the sea ice at the North Pole carries its offspring on its antennae. It's a strange, primitive being, but it is kind-hearted and then suddenly -- well, the beauty of the action makes things beautiful.
The beauty of the solidarity of a school of fish and their battles.
Make no mistake, they're not kissing!
The beauty of a perfect movement, like certain methods of attack, products of merciless selection.
In a hundredth of a second, for the mantis shrimp to stab its prey.
A movement that's too quick for the naked eye, so we have to break down the scene, image by image.
I discovered that to appreciate the beauty of things sometimes you have to stop time, to freeze time.
As you can see, my obsession was to examine animal behaviour to better understand them -- obviously, I was mistaken.
I was mistaken because, for example, how to understand why this fish opens its fins in this way?
To mark its territory, but which one?
Maybe its nest?
You have to step back.
To appreciate the hectic life of this little fish, you have to look at the bigger picture.
For me, this was a revelation: the beauty of things by stepping back.
To handle the overwhelming habitat crisis affecting these little fish.
Obsessed with the impenetrable ocean coast, we're constantly seeking to be physically closer to these creatures.
And we almost forget the obvious: the context, their universe, the whole picture.
From now, we have to look at the forest behind the tree, even the mountain behind the tree.
It's so evident, that we had forgotten that under the sea there are landscapes as beautiful as above.
Here, you can see the Nature Reserves in Scandola, Corsica.
One just can't take them in with a single sight, but we can see it all thanks to new techniques of panoramic photography.
A new beauty appeared, taken from the depths.
The grandeur of places next to the smallness of divers, a diver who, indeed, wants to go deeper to see what's happening
at 90 metres, 110 metres, 130 metres, 150 metres.
During these explorations that get deeper and deeper, discovering new species was actually easier.
Because what's difficult is not finding the animal, it is, rather, entering its world.
These creatures are photographed alive for the very first time, at ever higher depths, until my photo here, at the deepest point at 190 metres, this little yellow coral in the Mediterranean.
But all of these discoveries, these pretty things, are only a taster if I compare them with the encounter with the coelacanth, considered today as the biggest zoological discovery of the 20th century. Once believed to be a fossil that disappeared at the same time as the dinosaurs, this fish which sired amphibians, then reptiles, mammals, and finally, the human being.
Discovered to still be alive in 1938, it was a scientific revolution but nobody was able to dive with it, until the year 2000, 60 years later, when a South African, Peter TImm discovered a site in the Mozambique canal, off the shore of the Bay of Sodwana, along the East African Coast,
a tormented coastline, where nothing is simple, when we decided to dive, where two divers had died by trying to dive 10 years earlier and where I, personally, waited 10 years to feel, both my team and I, ready to go.
Not just ready to dive, but ready to accomplish a job at such depths.
10 years of fantasising, dreaming, planning and training and the irony is that it would take one and half minute to accomplish this dream. One and a half minute to dive from the surface to 120 meters below the ocean surface.
The first day, first dive, first seconds at the bottom, Gombessa, the coelacanth, was there.
Proof, again, that the difficult part isn't finding the animal, but rather accessing its world.
And what a world!
Another planet. And what an animal!
2 meters long, 100 kg.
It was there, like it has been waiting for us for 65 million years, along the walls of its deep canyon.
And what a joy when beholding comes with the privilege of being there as the first witnesses.
As we beheld him, it slept.
Or at least it was resting after its nocturnal life, sometimes even a little group sheltered in caves.
It was easy for us to approach them, to get closer and closer and to observe all the details of their fascinating anatomy, its huge thick and thorny scales that protected it, long ago, from dinosaurs and giant sharks.
Its pectoral fins inside, which we can see are the orign of our arms and legs, or its ventral fin, which we can see as the origin of our tibia and our femur, its three lobed tail which generated our -- well, nothing at all!
Its huge green eye hosting an organ capable of amplifying light.
Proof again that, if we step back -- admire how its eye deflects light even when it's illuminated up from far away.
But we weren't there to sit and admire it, we were there to study it.
And that gives so much pleasure.
Once we stopped contemplating it, we began to aspire to understand.
We had a lot of specialised equipment designed for this, in order to create a 3D model of the movements of its famous fins, thanks to two synchronised cameras.
At a depth of 120 meters, the challenge for the divers, was to catch the coelacanth in the cross-fire of two laser beams, and of course follow it, recording all of its movements because the ultimate goal was to understand the articulation of the bones of these fins, which were exactly the ancestors of our arms and our legs.
This adventure was our routine, going down every day into these deep canyons, an exhilarating experience each time, to see a world that is completely alien that was becoming a bit more familiar every day.
In this dusky universe, where light is sparse and yet visibility is so great, that's where we had to go every day to find Gombessa, Diva Gombessa.
Because she is a star, she allows you brief meetings that were short lived, and you would have to leave hastily because of the never-ending ascents to the surface.
Minutes on the bottom took hours to ascend, our decompression was long up to 5 hours ascending to the surface creeping for more than 10 km in a great blue desert.
At the height of it, we weren't 6 meters below the surface.
In reality we were 3 hours below the surface.
And day, after day, after day, we had... we got used to it, we learned to appreciate a moment's rest and tried to find a sort of inner peace.
Once we had found this inner peace, we noticed things outside, the desert wasn't deserted.
There were loads of little creatures that roamed around for hours.
And when I say "little", I mean really little...
I remember one day, I was watching a movie on my tablet to pass some time.
Full disclosure, it actually was James Cameron's Avatar. And I saw the same creatures from science-fiction all around me, but they were really there, in real life.
Some were more astonishing than those in the movie, others were simply curious and came to us, and offered us a bit of respite.
It was a sort of distraction during our long and boring decompression stops.
They were everywhere.
A lot of these youngsters grouped liked this all around us.
The problem is, when you attract the little ones, you soon attract bigger ones.
Closer and closer, more and more curious over hours and hours, where it was absolutely forbidden to get out of the water.
All the ingredients were finally there, all the ingredients of the adventure were combined, and I'll say it with no modesty, I believe that we wore the badge of the heroes.
At least, at least before the dive because, after the dive, it was a lot less glorious... Of course, the dives were very, very long, and also very stressful.
The atmosphere was very heavy and so was as our equipment.
It's not easy to smile in photos before the dive.
The pressure was so great for us and maybe even more for our gear but of course we never regretted it, we knew why we did what we did: to come face to face with a mythical creature with a living legend.
Gombessa, the coelacanth, wasn't curious anymore.
It wasn't shy, though, either.
It didn't care about our presence, it lived its life, and we, we watched it live.
Yes, it didn't care about our presence, except on the last day, maybe... it smiled at me.
But there was something even more enticing than the coelacanth itself: its world, its ecosystem.
Even if from a distance it seems mineral, lunar, in reality, the darkness was full of a life that divers never illustrated so far, in a dusky ecosystem that receives less than 1% of sunlight.
Less than 1% of sunlight and yet, believe me, this gloomy world blinded us.
These incredible fish, like the pineapple fish rare, but most of all never observed when they were grouped together.
Or this barbier fish, never before photographed still as beautiful as mysterious.
Why are there such colors, in this black and blue world?
Even more astonishing, a number of fish completely unknown until now like this sort of leaf fish or this scorpion fish with a long nose, completely new to science, without even a Latin name.
Even during our decompression stops, at the end of our dives they came to us to be discovered.
Like this tiny little fish - again, really tiny, so small it was nothing less than the first image of the larva of the pineapple fish, the one whose parents we had just observed 120 meters below, in the house of the coelacanth.
Could we have foreseen all of these discoveries?
Of course not!
And that's what is interesting.
But that doesn't matter, because had I set my mind to search the coelacanth, evaluating the chances of success, we would have never gotten started.
Fortunately for me, it doesn't matter much whether things are possible.
only if they are beautiful.
And this encounter, no doubt will remain my most beautiful.
Not because of the coelacanth itself, but because it opened a door to us.
This coelacanth brought to light a crepuscular world for us.
This quest allowed us to understand what actually was there, not just a simple animal, as mythical as it was, but an entire ecosystem to explore.
So, I already know that we will go back there, again and again, we, and then others after us, to stride through these deep valleys because there is so much to see.
In a time when everything is mapped, in a time for virtual visits to any museums in the world, to no matter how sheltered a cove, when anywhere on the Planet can be seen without leaving home,
in a time of Google Maps, Google Street, it is so pleasing to know that there are still places that are still impenetrable for any waves, places that will always remain, or, in any case, still are, for now, inaccessible to satellites, drones, and will never be replaced by the perfection of a human eye.
Finally, we can say: 'May this last wild continent, this ocean, fascinate us, and mystify us for even longer.'
Because there is no doubt, that, even more fulfilling than contemplating, is exploring.
And may everyone have their own experience, be it at 120 meters, with the coelacanth, or in the pond, with the ducks behind your house.
That's my message.
Thank you.
(Applause)
Well, you know what?
Tonight, I have decided to talk of fear
and of how it hurt me to be afraid.
I think I've always been afraid actually.
Sometimes, I realise it.
Sometimes I don't realise at all, I don't see it
But I believe it pervades my life.
The first time.... was in high school when I fell in love.
They are already laughing.
Whenever my idol passed me by I would almost faint.
Yet, I never managed to speak to him. I thought about him all the time though.
I was unable to do anything.
Then there were exams.
You know: tests, bac, semester exams.
And there, the constant fear of failure.
Personally, the fear of failure, makes me feel I'm in a vice. I feel it is tightening, I am stuck I can no longer breathe, or talk And then came my first job. At first I was afraid of not getting it then when I got it, I was afraid of not being up to par. I was difficult, and predictable! I do not know how they could stood me. And then... the fear went even deeper... It made me unreasonably demanding. Perfectionist. You know, when the slightest detail is the end of the world. Then there were times when I was blinded by fear.
And it prevented me from truly seeing and listening to the ones I love.
And one day, it made me lose all hope.
On a day like today, like any other. I have a little boy of six named Leopold, and on this day he drowned.
He stayed a long time in hospital, for six weeks in a coma, I became afraid he would wake. I was afraid of what would be left of him if he woke up.
And then he woke up, and he was fine,
as if nothing had happened.
So I had to ask myself: how is it possible that fear can invade our daily lives, preventing us from being so much more.
I wanted to talk with many people to know how they experience things.
So, I chatted and talked.
People told me a lot of stories.
Each told me his/her story. His/her own fear.
And I actually realised that the worst... was not to fail or to have some bad news. I realized that the worst was not knowing. There are people describe this as being
in an abyss or the great unknown.
To be uncertain. I realised that this fear of uncertainty was something that was part of us, of me.
It was truly an enemy to fight. So I fought. First for myself and then one day I wanted to fight for others.
I am a professor in a management school.
And you'd say what the hell uncertainty has to do here?
Indeed, in management, the aim is to control things; time, to meet budgets, to meet schedules, to use the best methods, to be accurate, and conscientiously.
Usually, it is not a place where one leaves room for uncertainty.
So I said to myself: "Perfect, I have to start here!"
I decided to teach my students to explore uncertainty and to do something constructive with it.
At the beginning it was not easy...
I am a teacher, so I looked for theories.
I found plenty! Chaos theory, quantum physics, neuroscience, non-linear systems.
You should have seen the students' faces when I told them about this... Quickly I realised: "Oh la la, I must do something else!"
I realised that no one cares for discourse and theories. We all go to school but the theory was useless.
What I had to find was teaching that allowed them to experience uncertainty.
and to then do something with it.
For themselves.
But what? I did not know.
How? I did not know either.
I realised: I think this teaching will also plunge me into uncertainty, so I went with them.
Instead of telling them to read articles and books or do research on the Internet, I told them: We will conduct interviews.
We're going to meet people. We will work with living information.
We are going to meet people whose job is uncertainty every day and who must make do. They chose to go to meet people who work in medical emergency services, people who work for the social services, people working in humanitarian organisations, and artists too.
Instead of starting with a goal, I told them we were going to begin without knowing what we would find, We would let people tell us what really matters, what we have to learn.
Instead of starting with a method, I told them to begin empty handed No questionnaires, no prepared interview.
Just a question. What is your work like?
For the rest, they would have to invent, improvise.
Of course, I could not ask them for a classic assignment.
I just asked: what did you do?
Tell me what you have found?
What has uncertainty brought you?
So at first, a bunch of students hated me. Others believed I was crazy. Sometimes both.
and they would tell me so. In all the classes I've given, that is to say in 12 classes of 60 students each for 5 years, I have been told repeatedly: "Madam, frankly, do you realize that you are asking us to do exactly the opposite of what we have always done?"
As a teacher it's scary because they would continue: "But Madam, it is useless to go meet people."
"They will tell us nothing."
"Anyway, we do not even know what to ask them."
Or sometimes they say:
"Madam! This is a class!"
"It is not for us... to say things."
"We make summaries of theories."
Whereas in fact they are afraid. Afraid of not knowing. Afraid that people will not talk to them. Afraid of not knowing what questions to ask. afraid of bringing nothing back at all because they do not have specific objectives.
They are afraid of not learning and are also afraid to get so involved.
Finally the interviews begin.
They conduct 15 for each group of 5 and, from the first interviews they are completely amazed and they are no longer afraid at all.
They are not at all, at all afraid. And they come back with extraordinary things.
I can not tell you everything now but, from artists they get the idea that to be creative is not to be crazy but to be passionate about something that is beyond them, they are people able work day and night, a lifetime on something they truly love.
With humanitarian organizations, they come back with the idea that every little thing can be useful. That the poorest person in the world can work, contribute and bring something. From social workers, it may seem a little cliché, they come back with the idea of unrequited generosity. It may seem obvious, but at the same time in problematic suburbs and neighbourhoods the problems have not been solved. We would know otherwise... But those guys are still there...
There are plenty of things I don't have time to tell you here but what most impacted students were the interviews. They would learn from people rather than learning from books.
And they would never have expected that.
They could never have imagined it. And I, would never have imagined all they brought back.
They would continue to talk and began talking about themselves, talking about their own experiences. And they tell me that one should not be afraid of uncertainty.
The only thing that really matters is to go out there, to meet people, and see what happens.
By listening we learn things almost impossible to imagine.
That the best way to deal with risk, is to face it and turn it to advantage. They also tell me that it's better to screw up than to do nothing because at least screwing up is a good opportunity to learn something. They also recount something that touches me deeply. They tell me that ultimately it was not a class they had. Many say that for them it was more of a life experience. And so, I feel that it is I who is learning. The idea of Teacher and student does not mean much here.
I think that's maybe what I also learned while exploring uncertainty To make my own luck even when nobody believed in me. To hold tight to all the little things that make me happy. To look risk face to face but not too long. Because ultimately, I do not know, ultimately I think we do not know what is there in the uncertainty and that the only way to truly know is to go out there.
Thank you.
Hello everyone!
The 22nd of September is going to be a big day for me.
It'll be the launch of my first book published by a major publishing house.
You may think: 16 is a young age to be releasing a book, when I am taking my French exams in July.
But in fact, this story started long ago!
I was 11 years old and I was given seven books which I'm sure you all know: the Harry Potter saga.
I spent ten days and nights reading the series, hiding the books under my bed so that my parents wouldn't confiscate them. You know how it goes, "It's bed time, you have school tomorrow."
And when I turned the last page, my passion for literature was born.
Then I got through an astronomical amount of best-selling children's books.
I even started to write a bit in private.
But what really changed my life was an ad that I found in "Le Journal de Mickey," a comic I was an avid reader of.
It was to become a jury member for the reader's choice of 'Le Journal de Mickey.'
The idea was simple: write some reviews that would appear in the comic, and then eventually, choose the Children's Book of the Year alongside seven other jurors.
The day before the deadline, I wrote a review, as requested, which I posted the next day on my way to school, dated as per postmark.
Two months later, I was in the car with my mom when she received a call and asked me to listen to it on her voice mail.
That's how I learnt I had been selected.
And so started my work as a book critic. Four months reading books, four months giving my opinion on them, and four months during which I met Camille who also loved literature, and would become my best friend.
Then, when the competition came to an end, we realised that everything was about come to an end.
Imagine the thing at the center of your life - and I'm not talking about school -
stopped just like that.
So, we thought, why not keep writing reviews together?
We no longer had 'Le Journal de Mickey' and didn't want to start a blog like everyone else .... We decided to launch an online magazine like 'Le Journal de Mickey' but a digital one.
But we needed a name.
Then, I remembered a magazine I had launched with some of my classmates in year five.
Our teacher had asked us to produce the front page for a magazine.
We had so much fun doing it that we decided to go on with the magazine and we got it published with around 30 copies.
It was about six pages long
and it came out every week.
Eventually, we published 17 issues.
We were nine years old and our magazine was called "L'Petit Mardi"
So when it came to launching our online magazine, Camille and I thought, why not have a bit of nostalgia and re-use that name?
That's how "L'Petit Mardi" was born.
But we also needed some structure, something concrete, to surpass the digital.
So we thought - well, I thought - let's set up our own publishing house.
The idea seemed complicated at the time.
Especially because I was 14 years old: still a minor!
It made things a bit complicated.
I thought, why not use my parents as figureheads?
It was as simple as that!
In a few days, the company was set up with a modest start-up capital: 100 euros of savings from my piggybank, most of which came from my grandparent's wallet,
L'Petit Mardi lasted four years.
In total, there were 60 issues, all of which were written by teenagers from around the world.
L'Petit Mardi continued to grow and since January 2016, even spread to paper with a run of 15,000 copies, distributed through 500 points of sale in Normandy, with the belief that paper and digital could coexist. We wanted to do things differently than other magazinesgoing digital today.
We wanted to show the opposite, that a digital magazine coming offline, was possible.
With our magazine, all you need to do is take your phone and scan the pages. Then you have an online version thanks to virtual reality.
We brought the two together and our goal is to, within five years, make our magazine the number one free French language-culture magazine entirely written by teenagers.
But you may think, the essence of a publisher is to publish novels.
Earlier, I told you I had started to write while on the Reader's Choice competition.
I said to myself, "I need to publish something."
But what could I publish?
That novel I had written,
a real imperfection,
because it was 40 pages full of mistakes.
But I might as well seize the opportunity,
I never found a publisher,
so I just went for it.
Three weeks later, I was taking part in a small exhibition in my town. And ... at the end of the day, I realized I'd sold 25 copies of my book.
25 copies, it's nothing really, just 0.001% of what Marc Levy, or Guillaume Musso would sell in a year.
But to me it meant the world.
And then someone asked me, "Where's book number three?"
"Is there going to be a sequel?" etc.
Someone even pre-ordered a copy online.
So ... I thought I would continue despite the first book's modest success.
I finished book three, book two sorry, which I published three just months later.
Come release day, to tell the truth, everything was a bit rushed.
I was doing my year ten internship at France Bleu Normandie,
and I had to call a local journalist.
All the editing team heard my conversation ...
I had foolishly called with everyone around.
Anyway, a journalist, intrigued, came to see me and asked me a few questions.
At the end of the day, I had two interviews booked.
And so it began!
The following months were the most intense of my life. BFM TV, France 2, Canal +, Europe 1, to name but a few.
All that helped me to sell around 1,500 copies of my books
which is huge for a self-published book in France.
Then, at this point I thought, why not try and make my dream a reality?
Which was to be published by a famous publisher.
And there, I must admit it was a bit complicated.
I was faced with closed doors
and emails shooting me down:
"You're too young. Your book is rubbish."
In fact, I almost gave up on the idea.
Then one day, when I had just given up hope, I had an extraordinary encounter.
I'd been invited to the yearly Reader's Choice Award ceremony for Le Journal de Mickey. (Laughter)
What's funny? The Journal is great!
Well, I was at Fnac des Ternes and I was browsing the library section when I saw a man, standing all alone.
That man ... I thought I recognized him.
I Googled his face, did some research,
I realized that this man was Michel Lafon, the founder and CEO of Michel Lafon publishing and I had seen his face on a video advertising Natou's book - she's a Youtuber - a few months earlier.
So, I went to see him,
I introduced myself.
I explained to him what I was doing, etc. He looked at me and in a very formal way he said, "Call me tomorrow." So, I called him the next day and he he gave me an appointment a week later near Neuilly-Sur-Seine. I went there, to his office, with my dad.
I have to admit, the meeting was fruitful and I'm really happy to tell you that my next book, the sequel to the adventures, in fact the first in a new saga, is being published by Michel Lafon in exactly nine days.
They haven't printed 25 copies, but 9,000.
(Applause) Thank you!
Thank you very much.
Thank you!
Today I'm happy to be able to say that I'm part of the small group of teenage authors.
Because I'm not the only one!
There's about a good thirty of us in France,
as well as a good number abroad.
We all share the conviction of wanting to inspire young people to read.
Because, at school they give us the Odyssey and Le Cid to read, you all must have read them, and I'll admit they made me want to sleep rather than read, personally.
But, I think we need to encourage
young people to start with teenage books you can find in bookshops,
like Harry Potter.
but also the Hunger Games, Divergent and so on.
Then, once they've developed the necessary maturity in high school, they can start to read the classics.
Today, I think I can say that I've always believed in the opportunites I've had and as a result, I've tried to create my own path.
Age will never change that, whether you are 16, 20, 30,40, 50 or even older. as long as you are passionate about what you are doing, as long as what you're doing excites you and feels important, then you must seize your opportunities.
Marcel Proust said: "Boldness rewards those who know how to seize their opportunites." I have only one message this evening.

Make the most of it! Thank you!
(Applause)
One, two, one, two, three - Hello!
(Laughter) How many of you today are leading the life they thought they would 20 years ago?
Not many I guess!
Me neither, otherwise I would have long straight hair like Lara Croft and I would be an archeologist like Indiana Jones.
But today I am a jazz singer because I went with the flow and here is where life brought me:
in this wonderful opera house in Clermont-Ferrand with my favorite guitarist, Michael Valeanu.
(Applause) Michael and I have been collaborating for five years now.
He is a very versatile musician and an excellent guitarist.
Michael is French as well, but we met in New York during a jam session, an open stage where musicians meet late at night to perform and improvise.
What makes jazz different is improvisation.
But in my case, it's more of a humane adventure than a musical vocation that made me want to devote my life to this practice.
When I was fourteen, I became friends with gypsies who came to my village in Samois-sur-Seine near Fontainebleau, every summer.
I was fascinated by their way of speaking.
Besides, it is with their accent that I pronounce "man-nouche" (gypsy) instead of "manouche".
I was fascinated by their way of playing music, but more specifically by their way of living day to day.
I understood that their music was completely linked to their way of life. The Gypsies do not know where they are going to be in one week, and when they perform, they do not know and do not want to know where that would lead them.
I will always remember one of the summers where I would spend the whole day with them.
In the morning I would bike to their camp, spend the day with them, then the evening.
When night fell, we would part until the next day.
I would take my bike and go home.
Except one day, upon arriving there the camp was completely empty.
During the night, the patriarch had spontaneously decided to break camp.
I was devastated but I knew that permanent improvisation was their life.
In fact, life itself is improvisation,
and for each one of us, the unexpected invariably awaits along the way.
The gypsies gave me the desire to throw myself into the unknown and to dare to improvise.
This is what I want to pass along today - dare to improvise.
To dare to improvise is to not be afraid of being judged, to be 100% in the now, to accept ups and downs, the discomfort that the unexpected brings.
When I started to sing, I would put my hand like this and my cable like this.
♫ First I was afraid, I was petrified ♫ ♫ Kept thinking I could never live without you by my side ♫ My mother would always say, "Cyrille, stop putting your hands in front of your face!"
(Laughter) During a jazz singing competition in Washington, the legendary saxophonist Wayne Shorter told me, "Get your hands off your face!"
This is when I opened up a little more.
♫ And then I spent so many nights Thinking how you did me wrong ♫ ♫ And I grew strong And I learned how to get along ♫ I still have a lot to do.
I realised that by hiding myself, I was depriving myself of many ways of communicating not only with the audience, but also with other members of the group.
It was very egoistic to retreat into oneself but when everybody is watching you, we feel directly judged.
I always tell my students who are introverted to get out of their own heads and ignore the positive and negative voices.
Because this is where they are and how they distract.
I tell them to concentrate on other things than themselves, on another musician for example.
Only then can their energy freely flow
and a connection be shared. In Harlem, there is a theatre called Apollo Theatre, where every Wednesday there is an "Amateur Night" where twelve contestants try their luck in front of a pitiless audience who can applaud or boo however they please.
"Be good or be gone". (Laughter) This contest is an institution that brought us Ella Fitzgerald or Lauren Hill.
After spending an entire day preparing, getting made-up, setting up the sound, rehearsing, I finally get on the stage, ready to sing.
I had barely said a word when the whole theatre starting booing.
(Audience booing) Almost as scary as Garou or Pagny on their rotating seats.
I saw them being the spotlights with their hands around their mouth,
booing. I continued singing while 1500 people booed along,
until the bell rang and freed me from this hell.
After such an experience, I could have decided that singing on stage was not for me, and abandon everything.
We have all felt during our lives the weight of judgement and the fear of the consequences of our actions.
All these problems often exist only in our minds.
Not only can we always improve ourselves but even with experience, we can be called into question.
And that should be taken as constructive instead of as something destructive.
In my case, I wanted to try again.
I told myself it could be worse and went back a few months later and won first place!
(Music) (Applause) Improvisation is being perfectly in sync with the audience, and other members of the group, that is being 100% in the now to be able to react in real-time to music, emotions, and the audience's energy.
It's hard to learn to vocally improvise.
There is no manual to scat singing, this way of spontaneously inventing syllables to create a melody.
At first, I had many melodies in my head but I did not know how to present them.
I didn't know if I should say "shoobi-doo" or "doowap-doowap" or "vla-vli-vloo" or "shloobi-shloo" or "lanana".
One day, during a jazz festival, I arrived in the middle of a concert where the guitarist was scatting and doing something than could be seen as ridiculous.
He was doing: (Vocals) (Laughter) It was awesome.
That's when I realized the reason why it was awesome is because he did not practice for hours, he did not plan on doing this thinking, "it's going to be awesome if I do this."
and he was in complete harmony with himself and honest with us and himself.
He let go completely, and it worked.
When I got out of the concert, I called my friend with whom I performed and I scat for the first time.
It was a disaster, but at least it was natural because I had learned a valuable lesson, that of not thinking too much and having fun.
To be able to improvise, you have to confront your fear of judgement, be 100% in the now and get out of your comfort zone, and accept all things different.
All different things.
Different levels, different styles, different cultures, different languages, different education.
All these differences are enriching.
To benefit from them, you have to be interested, you have to immerse yourself, totally.
You have to adapt to different worlds, and bring your experience, but without imposing it.
Listening and trust are key.
If I think that only my experience and only my ideas are good, then I shut myself out of all sorts of opportunities and encounters.
However if I am convinced that what the other person brings is also rich and novel, then we can really and truly communicate.
In the world of music, you are often brought to perform with musicians that you don't know, who may or may not have better skills, different styles, different experiences.
A few years ago, I received on Myspace - okay, many years ago - (Laughter) a message from a Brazilian guitarist called Diego Figueiredo who was inviting me to come perform with him in São Paulo.
We had never performed together before, but eager to discover Brazil, I jumped on the first plane.
I was coming from the world of jazz, and Diego from Brazilian music.
A typical jazz phrase goes like this: (Music) (Vocals) If during our first rehearsal with Diego, I had copy-pasted my jazz style over his Bossa style, it would have gone like this: (Music) (Vocals) (Laughter) Not that good.
If I close my ears, I cannot feel his emotions, his energy.
If I force down my ideas, there is no possible dialogue and I overstep my boundaries.
However, if I open up to him, I make myself small, I let him express himself so we can dance together.
(Music) (Music ends) (Applause) My dad is French, my mother is from Dominican Republic.
Thanks to them, my sister and I have traveled a lot and grown in many different countries like Africa, the US, Mexico, Singapore.
The fact that I have had to adapt to each country has enriched me as a person and as an artist.
Every time, I had to get out of my comfort zone, start all over again, face new challenges.
I had to thrown myself into the unknown, open up to new ways of living, all without cheating or trying to hide.
In short, I had to improvise.
A few months ago, I was strolling around with my dad in Larchmont, near New York, where we lived when I was 9 or 10.
He told me he has been so happy here, and that he had good memories.
I asked him, "Why did we move?"
He said he had lost his job.
I told myself it had been terrible for dad to be fired, to have to go back to France.
Then I realized that if that had not happened, I never would have met the gypsies, and maybe would never have been a singer.
My dad is my biggest fan, that's why I think that to dare to improvise, you have to accept the discomfort of the unexpected.
For example, this talk in the middle of the afternoon, for two jazz musicians, is not a comfortable situation.
You have come to listen to talks on various themes, and you are asking yourselves who we are.
On our side, we are used to performing in a club or a concert house where people know what to expect.
We are wearing evening dresses, and we are rarely asked to talk in between songs.
Also it's too early to be playing jazz and you haven't had enough to drink, and us neither.
(Laughter) So with Michael, we are going to accept all this, all this discomfort, all these differences.
We are going to trust you and ourselves with a song that is going to be just for you and just for us, now, today, right away. (Applause) (Music) ♫ Pack up all your cares and woes ♫ ♫ Here I go singing low ♫ ♫ Bye bye, blackbird ♫ ♫ Where somebody waits for me ♫ ♫ Sugar's sweet, so is she ♫ ♫ Bye bye, blackbird ♫ ♫ No one here can love or understand me ♫
♫ Oh, what hard luck stories they all hand me ♫ ♫ Make my bed and light the light, I'll be home late tonight, blackbird ♫ ♫ Bye bye, bye bye ♫ (Vocals) ♫ Pack up all you cares and woes ♫ ♫ Here I go singing low ♫ ♫ Bye bye, blackbird ♫ ♫ Where somebody waits for me ♫ ♫ Sugar's sweet, so is she ♫ ♫ Bye bye, blackbird ♫ ♫ No one here can love or understand me ♫ ♫ Oh, what hard luck stories they all hand me ♫ ♫ Make my bed and light the light, I'll be home late tonight ♫ ♫ Bye bye, bye bye ♫ ♫ Bye bye, bye bye ♫ ♫ Bye bye ♫ ♫ Blackbird ♫ (Music ends) (Applause) Michael Valeanu!
(Applause)
I'd like to start by showing you someone who is dressed even worse than I am.
[Who is this?] You may notice, aside from the color harmony, a tattoo
saying: "My body belongs to me."
But who is this person?
Is it a punk, who borrowed clothes from their grandmother's wardrobe?
Is it a teenager, from the 16th arrondissement of Paris, who feels like rebelling?
No.
This is our Minister of Health, Marisol Touraine, standing on the steps of the Élysée.
And this was last year, to celebrate the 40th year of the Veil Abortion Act, which enables women to take control of their bodies, through a voluntary interruption of their pregnancy.
"My body belongs to me" has become banal -- everyone says it.
By the way, for once, the entire National Assembly has voted in favor of a symbolic law in order to reapprove the Veil Law.
It's a banality, even ministers have it tattooed on their arm.
However, it's not entirely true.
I would like to give you a few examples, that are a little extreme, honestly even shocking, which will demonstrate that for many people and in a lot of cases, well, my body doesn't belong to me.
Firstly, it doesn't belong to me as long as I'm alive.
I am not allowed to rent my belly. I am not allowed in many countries to sell my sexuality. I am not allowed to define the gender that I belong to, since I have to face a doctor or be in front of a judge, and declare to the civil registrar whether I am a man, woman, or other. I am also not allowed to do whatever I want with my body.
For instance, I can't do this.
[Dwarf-tossing] So, You might recognize Leonardo Di Caprio, in this great dwarf-tossing scene. But some versions of it exist that are a little less chic, notably the one that was practiced by the great community of Morsang-sur-Orge from l'Essonne, in the beginning of the 90s.
The mayor of Morsang-sur-Orge said: "This can't go on --
we can't toss dwarfs."”
And so he prohibited dwarf-tossing.
And who was to protest?
Dwarf-tossers found other activities to do on Sundays. They probably went back to fishing.
It's the dwarves themselves who protested, because they had a breadwinner, and a certain renown, apparently a certain success with women.
And the Morsang-sur-Orges Council of State's decision, which jurists know well, said: "No, this is forbidden."
I also cannot do whatever I want with my body in order to die.
I am not allowed to be euthanized, but I am also not allowed to be eaten. In 2001, a charming German engineer posted an announcement saying: "I am looking for a volunteer to eat."
He received several candidates, made a selection, conducted a few final interviews, and in the end finally found Bernt, who agreed wholeheartedly.
So they began by cutting off Bernt's genital and eating it together, probably by candlelight.
(Laughter) Obviously satisfied by this first course, they chose to proceed -- and by the way this all on video so you can watch it. I recommend it to you, it's really nice -- "Armine ate Bernt." But be aware that this is prohibited.
It's crazy, considering they haven't hurt anyone.
But it is indeed prohibited to be eaten.
Well, even after my death I can't do whatever I want with my body.
For instance, I am not allowed to practice sea-immersion
whereas diving is allowed while I am alive.
I am also not allowed to be embalmed, unless my name is Lenin, Mao, or Valéry Giscard d'Estaing.
(Laughter) (Applause) And I am also not allowed -- and this is even worse -- to be cryogenized.
You know, some people -- have themselves frozen, hoping that in 10 years, 100 years, or a million years, we would defrost them, as by then we will have already found ways to resuscitate them, or found cures to the illnesses that have killed them.
This has been somewhat a success. In Russia and the United States, there are some cryogenic sites, where one can see the coffins. Some put their entire body, while others only their head -- it's cheaper.
(laughter) And in France, a doctor named Martineau, felt that it was a great idea to freeze his wife first. (Laughter) And as it seemed to be going well, he decided to follow her with the freezing.
Forever united in a frozen sleep,
inside a castle. And then someone found out and filed a complaint: There are some people frozen in the village, do you realize that?”
(Laughter) Their son was delighted. He would go to see them from time to time. It's better than gathering around a grave. And the Council of State, that same one, said: "This can't be happening.
You need to defrost and burn them!
Put it all on fire.
Then there was a trial, and Martineau's son was forced to burn his parents. Can you imagine, this poor couple who imagined being united for millions of years and resuscitate in a future where sexuality is completely open, completely vivified and rejuvenated. Well, unfortunately, there is only a heap of ashes left.
(Laughter) So behind these tragedies -- they don't concern us all if we don't wish to be eaten, frozen, or tossed -- who cares.
But the problem is that it actually applies to each one of us. It's the Civil Code via the bioethics law of 1994 that says so. The conventions --
as you can read --
are that there is no private ownership or patrimoniality over the body,
because we say that the person is unavailable under law. And so the body itself isn't patrimonial. You don't have an ownership of your body.
And so you might tell me: "So what, everything in France is forbidden anyway."
(Laughter) But even in the US, a country supposedly liberal, it's the same story. It has, by the way, been declared very clearly at a trial in the Supreme Court of California. The John Moore case.
John Moore was a patient suffering from leukemia, in the 80s, and the doctors had to remove his spleen. They discovered that his cells had extraordinary properties for producing certain kind of proteins. So the doctors extracted, without telling John Moore, many of his cells. They extracted blood, sperm, and parts of the spinal cord.
They apparently told him that in order to treat his leukemia they had to remove some sperm -- that's apparently what happened.
(Laughter) And they made a cell line out of it. John Moore's cell line. Which they then sold for hundreds of thousands of dollars to big pharmaceutical institutions.
And John Moore, upon realizing what has happened, said: "Wait a minute,
I don't get to have a say?
These are my cells, if you don't mind."
And so there was a big trial, and the judge concluded that, no, they aren't his cells in fact, given that he doesn't have ownership over his cells.
So, where does all of this come from?
There are good reasons to think that it came from a monotheistic heritage.
This idea -- as Saint Paul put it: "The body is for the Lord and the Lord is for the body." --
is that in the big monotheism, particularly within Judeo-Christian religions, my body doesn't belong to me because it belongs to God. My body is the expression of the soul, as per Thomas d'Aquin.
The body is the reflection of my soul, my soul is immortal. It joins the kingdom of heaven.
By the way, I can even be resuscitated if the Council of State hasn't burned me first.
(Laughter) Pope Pie XII has claimed it very explicitly --
this is the first time I'm quoting Pope Pie XII publicly.
In 1954, at a medical congress, he explained that Man is merely a usufructuary of his body, not its full owner.
So within our secular law system, a secularized system, it is not a matter of God anymore, well the concept of God has been replaced by the concept of dignity.
Going back to that trial in Morsang-sur-Orge, this is the reason why the Council of State has prohibited dwarf-tossing, because a human being's dignity is viewed as being part of the public order.
It means that today, this transcendence we have abolished, this divine transcendence, is being retaken by the State, or by society if you prefer, defining everyone's dignity.
So dignity is sacredness without God. It's the idea that, nonetheless, the body is sacred. We cannot do whatever we want with it.
I suggest that you try and go to the end of the modernity logic.
And if we are really, completely within immanence, to whom does the body belong, if not to me?
Who can define its dignity, if not me?
That's what John Lock did, not John Moore, but John Locke. Indeed, there are many Johns.
He was the first person to have written, to my knowledge, that each person has ownership over their own personhood.
It's not a coincidence that he is the one who wrote that, He was a doctor, and well-acquainted with flesh, the body's reactions.
And also because he was in the midst of the glorious British revolution, the Bill of Rights Revolution. So this whole theory about social contract rights, about elementary, fundamental rights, about civil disobedience, also means that one has natural rights that are predetermined among which, the right of ownership of oneself.
He went even further by saying: "If can have ownership over exterior things, if I can acquire the world by working on it, by adding value to it," --
this idea of property was first born out of the appropriation of myself.
And think about it, if we have ownership over the body, we have, according to classical themes, the usus, fructus and abusus.
Usus means -- it's always nice using Latin terms -- usus means usage. So if I have usus over the body, the dwarfs can do their work with dignity.
Then, fructus, we have it fructified and so John Moore can have access to his cell money.
And then you have abusus, I can abuse it and do whatever I want with it,
and if I want to have it cryogenized, that's my problem.
It appears to me that this new generation is a generation that rejects predetermined structures, one that wants to define their own career, that wants to define their life by traveling, and to build themselves, their own self, be their own creator.
And we can see, anecdotally, sociologically, to what extent this generation who appropriates their own body with tattoos for instance,
It's also a way to define one's sexuality in a much more fluid way.
There is a study that came out which showed that generation Z - it's not even Y anymore, it's Z -- Generation Z is post-gender. It's not even bi anymore, everyone defines their own sexuality by adding a little bit of this or that.
So this results in many things.
For instance, one can be half-sexual, Grey-sexual, gyno-sexual, pan-sexual,
Strauss-Kahn sexual -- No, not that.
Anyway, there are many versions.
I don't know all of them, and can't describe them on stage. But it's interesting, you should look them up.
And more importantly, it will allow us to tackle the three big themes of the future: The subject of human augmentation, the enhancement of oneself, the theme of transhumanism, and the theme of data.
If tomorrow I can, and I already can enhance myself, that's to say building my own artificial arms, enhancing my limbs, enhancing my brain abilities, even modifying my own DNA.
If I modify my own DNA, I must be its owner.
If tomorrow I want to test, I want to explore immortality, be it through cryogenisation -- here is that nice example again. Or for instance, as Ray Kurzweil, the Pope of transhumanism, envisions it, by transferring my consciousness onto a USB key.
Well, similarly, I am going to define, even contractually, the way in which my body relates to the world.
And then there is a third question that might seem a little marginal, the question of data.
We produce, a large amount of data, and its value is humongous. as in Europe, it's estimated be worth a thousand billion euros by 2020.
However, this data, which is worth so much money and with which some companies make so much money, well, your personal data doesn't belong to you. In the same way there isn't a patrimoniality of the body, there isn't a patrimoniality of data. For the exact same reasons, because data is considered to be an expression of your personality, and as we saw, within the law, the personality is inalienable and the body isn't patrimonial.
If tomorrow we find, that we are able to build a private property for data, which will be to the digital age what intellectual property was to the industrial revolution, you will then become an owner, in truly legal and financial terms, of your own data, which you will be able to negotiate.
In other words: you will finally get paid for using Facebook.
So, "my body belongs to me" isn't a platitude. It's a tattoo we would finally all wear. Because this brand new generation will have to confront all these problems.
Transhumanism is coming, bioethical committees are already outdated.
And in order for everyone to able to choose their own values, in this complex universe, we must first own our own bodies.
Thank you!

When you think about politics, you probably think of images of great debates, of shocking statements, or of protesters who demonstrate.
Unlikely to come to mind are images of public consultations, of government reports, or of expert meetings in a room without decorations.
The politics we show you is the one that entertains.
You are not shown the politics that works.
Why?
As a public policy specialist, this is a question I've been asking myself for more than 20 years.
I am convinced that politics works better than we think and that the cynicism about it is exaggerated.
But we cannot count on the media to make us understand this.
Almost exactly 28 years ago, I was glued to the screen of my television, like millions of viewers around the world, watching images like this one, showing the start of a war, the first Gulf War.
Thanks to the continuous news, which was in its very early stages, we could see, live, the progress of this war hour by hour.
The news then took a captivating turn.
After the war, to keep their ratings, to keep your attention, the media turned to the most spectacular aspects of politics: to the controversies and conflicts of politicians that are well illustrated by the first images that I showed you.
Today, the medias are forced to show you a politics that entertains.
The continuous news has transformed the media dynamic, and social media has only accentuated the phenomenon.
Politicians, who need to be seen, and other political actors too have adjusted to this new political context.
To be seen, they don't hesitate to shout their indignation.
And sometimes they scream very loud.
They put on a show.
If rather than showing you Donald Trump, you were shown images of a rational discussion on a serious subject of public policy - the regulation of maritime transport for example,
a committee discussion much like what we see on the screen -
you would quickly go watch something else.
The politics that works is less entertaining.
It captivates the public less.
When was the last time you visited a government website to inform yourself about public policy?
The minimum wage policy for example or the food safety policy?
Information like this is easy to find.
Since the advent of the Internet, governments have required themselves to release a wealth of information about what they are doing.
Today, Western democracies are more transparent than they have ever been.
But I suppose you are like me.
In the evening, when you get home after a long day at work, you do not want to read the latest report from the Labor Department on the threshold beyond which the minimum wage harms the economy or that of the Department of Health on microbial contamination in poultry slaughterhouses.
We prefer more entertaining content.
Besides, some time ago, I participated in a television program with journalists during which I deplored a media coverage of politics that I find too negative.
The present journalists were quick to remind me that when they show positive news, people change channels.
So, there is a trap that is difficult to get out of.
We show you the politics that entertains because if we showed you the politics that works, you would look elsewhere.
The political conflicts that entertain you also fuel your cynicism.
They undermine your confidence in the political system.
So, your attitude towards politics becomes more and more negative.
When Canadians are asked which professions they see positively, only 24% mention politics.
In contrast, 89% of the Canadian population mentions scientists.
And these results are not unique to Canada.
Similar results have been obtained in the United States and Europe.
Such cynicism about politics is dangerous.
It sets the table for politicians who, like Donald Trump, want to tear the system apart.
And it would be a shame if they were to succeed because politics has improved our lives considerably since the end of the Second World War, and it continues to do so.
How?
By working a bit like science, which obviously inspires confidence.
Scientists are often part of the politics that works.
We don't set health standards in slaughterhouses without talking to microbiologists.
Nor do we set the minimum wage without talking to economists.
You should also know that the scientists who participate in the politics that works often come from universities.
They, therefore, enjoy great independence.
And perhaps a little because of this independence, their messages don't always suit politicians.
Indeed, scientists want their knowledge to be used to improve policy, not to entertain an audience fond of conflicts.
They don't like to be part of a show.
When politicians and the media take too much interest in them, they quickly return to the tranquility of their laboratories and abandon any involvement in the political world.
In 2012, I participated in a conference in Boulder, Colorado, which brought together great researchers on climate change, some of whom were among the first to make us understand the seriousness of this problem.
After hearing a few presentations, I had a doubt, wondering if I was attending a conference of climate skeptics instead.
Knowledge that I thought was solid was seriously questioned.
Everything was scrutinized:
the ways to estimate the temperature of the past, the methods of measuring the current temperature, and the validity of the simulations that are used to predict future changes.
Obviously, no cameras in the room.
I quickly understood I wasn't attending a climate skeptics conference. What I saw was nothing other than the scientific method at work.
Science advances knowledge by constantly questioning it.
And scientists build their credibility by adopting this attitude.
Now imagine a politician you would elect because you like his position on climate change.
Imagine him casting doubt, not on the existence of climate change, but on the relevance of a carbon tax to reduce greenhouse gas emissions.
You should know that there are other policies that achieve this goal and that the carbon tax is certainly not a superior option to these other policies.
Doubting would therefore be legitimate.
But in the context of the politics that entertains, your politician would quickly be pilloried by his opponents.
They would say that he lacks conviction,
that he yields to pressure easily,
that he is weak,
and in the face of these criticisms, perhaps you would yourself feel like you have been betrayed by your politicians.
But in fact, he would only have behaved like a scientist who questions his knowledge in view of improving it.
This is no doubt why scientists run away when they are expected to participate in the politics that entertains.
The politics that entertains is a politics of conflicts.
Its participants must make exaggerated remarks about their adversaries with absolute confidence.
Criticism, attacks are more about opponents
Doubting is not allowed.
Doubts are associated with weakness.
Anyone who doubts would immediately be called a flip flop.
In contrast, science is a world of caution, nuances, questioning, doubt, and sometimes of opinion change.
Again, scientists are improving their knowledge by constantly questioning it.
Scientists are often comfortable with the politics that works because it has a lot in common with science.
The politics that works is open to diverse view points, it is moderate, it is centered on arguments, and it allows everyone to doubt their opinions.
Now, we should avoid opposing too much the politics that entertains to the politics that works.
If politics works overall, it's because people who participate in the politics that entertains are also able to contribute to the politics that works.
For more than 10 years, my research has focused on the policy of genetically modified organisms, GMOs, in North America and Europe.
One day in Brussels, I see a report in a newspaper on one of the famous anti-GMO operations organized by Greenpeace, much like the one we see on the screen.
In the report, a representative of the industry reacted to the operation.
With great indignation, he asserted that Greenpeace, basically, had only one goal: not environmental protection, but industry bankruptcy.
A few days later, I came across this same industry representative at a meeting organized by the European Commission on its regulation on the traceability of GMO seeds.
In addition to industry representatives, the meeting included scientists, consumer representatives, farm groups, and environmentalists, including Greenpeace.
At the meeting, no one accused anyone of anything.
The discussions focused on each other's arguments.
All participants were working to improve the regulation.
No wonder the meeting helped improve the regulation and at least in my view, strengthened the credibility of the participants.
Meetings of this type take place daily in the capitals of Western democracies.
And they improve our lives.
The food we eat is safer than ever, as are our means of transportation and our workplaces.
In many locations, crime has been decreasing steadily for years.
We are preserving our heritage better and have more protected green spaces than before.
Air quality in our cities is better, and access to health care, although imperfect, has nothing to do with what it was 50 years ago.
Our life expectancy has never been longer.
Unfortunately, we too rarely realize that this progress is due to public policy
because the politics that we are shown is the politics that entertains.
This politics also unduly increases our cynicism.
How to get out of the trap?
By being well aware that politics is more than what we see in the media.
Politics is not just the politicians we know.
It's also meetings of people you don't know.
In the evening, after a long day at work, you can continue to watch politicians who fight on TV rather than reading a government report on public policy.
The quarrels of politicians are much more entertaining.
I prefer to watch that too.
But be aware that alongside this exists a politics that is less visible, much less glamorous, but much more important.
A politics that engages people who do not necessarily seek notoriety, but who have experience, expertise, and knowledge useful for public policy.
People who can doubt and reconsider their opinion when the arguments of others justify it.
This politics works.
It improves our lives.
Like science, politics deserves our trust.
We should be less cynical.
Thank you.
(Applause)
For several months now, I happen to sometimes teleport myself into the future.
Yes, I know ...
(Laughter) ... Really, it's not stage fright, I swear it's true.
And in this future, quite unusual things are heard.
So today, I would like to share them with you, and maybe we will reach together a certain reflection.
And I'll leave you all the time, all your life afterwards to think about it.
I would really like to pass on to you all these messages that I've gotten from the future.
For example, in the future, you can hear strange things like : "Love is an emotion" or "If I'm not nice with life, life will not be nice with me," or "Presents are fine but useless if we can't share them with those we love"
or even "Success is when we're loved by others."
And do you know who gave me these kind of messages?
Well, these beings from the future are like you and me, no distinction: they have two arms, two legs, a body, a heart in perfect working order, and a brain that works very well too.
The only difference is that they're children between six and ten years old.
Now, I have some questions for you.
Have you ever taken the time to really look at children?
Have you ever tried to put yourselves in their place?
Or have you tried to think like them when they're angry, or when they are afraid or upset ?
Now obviously, hearing all these questions, you're going to say, "Of course I listen to my child, I do that all day long !"
or "OK, fine, they're just kids! They'll see when they'll get older."
The reality is that those kids really have their own way of thinking, their own opinions.
And you, adults who are before me - and I really do not judge anyone - you unconsciously put children in a box, a checkbox of yours, all because of your limiting beliefs and your education.
However, children are fully-fledged beings.
They have things to tell us.
They can think for themselves, feel things for themselves, they have their own ideas.
In the workshops of the future that I lead - yes because I'm also activity leader in the workshops of the future which are called "Philosophy workshops'" - so during these suspended moments, we really communicate with each other, and the children share, exchange ideas around a topic we discuss. And they do so without the help of screens, the internet, or the TV.
Yes, I swear that
that exists in the future!
Today, those kids are here, and they manage to get their true freedom of being, to allow themselves to express what they want.
Now to make all this work, two fundamental values are necessary, in my opinion at least : respect and love.
Let me start with respect first.
Children respect each other a lot more in my opinion than adults.
They are even great empaths, and I'm going to give you an example.
This example, I've taken it from a workshop of the future.
We were with a group of children between eight and ten years old, and we had chosen a question that was: "What is the purpose of a lovey?"
So they started to think about it, to talk and share ideas.
And for five minutes, it was very, very convivial.
Then suddenly, a little guy called Léo started to cry his eyes out.
So me, what did I do?
As an adult, maybe due to a professional bias. I tried to calm him saying, "It's OK. What's wrong?"
So he explained to us that he lost his lovey three years ago - he was five - and he never got over it.
All the children were there staring at him, and this little guy was inconsolable.
Then what did the others do?
Well, instead of going hug and comfort him, they said to him, "Hey, you know, we can lend you one!
I can give you one even !"
One of them even got up and said,
"How about we make him one ?" At that moment, I really watched them, and I saw that they had this innate kindness within them.
They truly have this deep kindness that they can offer us and that we too can offer them as adults,
To me, it is the key to human relationships.
But let's go back to the topic of kindness.
What is kindness?
It's a trendy topic right now a little like letting go of things, you got to be "benevolent."
Well kindness is not to be like a Care Bear.
It doesn't mean saying yes to everything, no!
To me, kindness implies an affirmation, but an affirmation based on the respect of others.
Now for all of this to work, we must add the second value that is love.
Children love to speak of love and I love to listen to them, and I love to speak about love too.
During those moments in which they share things with love and on the topic of love, well, they have no filters, they are authentic.
A little girl even drew a picture of love meaning that it could be given between a man and a woman, between two men or two women.
It was really a clear piece of authenticity!
Children have no regard to skin color until adults influence them.
They have their freedom of being, they allow themselves to be, with no filters or anything else.
Let me give you an example from outside the Philo workshop.
A few weeks ago, I went to New York, and I was sitting on the steps of a famous museum.
The weather was beautiful, it was a really beautiful day.
So I was on the steps and there was a saxophonist busking who was playing perfectly well, so I was listening to him.
And because of my education, because of what I had heard at the time about me singing badly, etc., I was humming inside my head
for fear of being judged.
I didn't want to be heard.
Suddenly to my left, a group of children arrived.
They were going to cross, and they listened of course.
They heard the saxophonist playing and what do you think they did?
They began to sing, to dance, to live, to laugh, without worrying about other people opinions, and I watched.
They were themselves, they allowed themselves to be.
Therefore, I concluded from this that when we dispense love, kindness and respect, then we also dispense smiles.
So these moments I experience in these workshops are extremely powerful.
Without love, a human being is absolutely nothing and the children have understood this.
During another workshop with the youngsters, the six-years-old, I also talked about love, but a little guy said to me, "Listen Ingrid, still everyone needs love.'
I said, "Yes, indeed, everyone needs love."
So he replied, "You know, the homeless people who sleep in the street, those who are all alone there, they don't have any love, and people who walk past them, they don't give them any love.'
Me, adult, I go "OK." He say, "Do you know
how they can find love?"
I say "No, I don't," so he replies, "Well, they'll get a little companion, a dog, and that way, they'll have love." Then he ends by saying,
"Because without love, we die."
At this moment, it shook me.
I stayed speechless on my chair.
He went directly to my heart, this little guy, and he was right.
These are really extraordinary children, but one of the experiences that affected me the most and has affected me in the deepest of my heart for years, is that these beings of the future have something that we don't have, that we don't allow ourselves as adults: they allow themselves to dream.
Children have even dreams bigger than themselves.
It helps them to develop themselves, to be fulfilled, and to be themselves.
And so, speaking about dreams, I asked them a question: '"Do you believe that all dreams can come true ?"
I was really scared of their answers and of being thrown out of this future with them saying "She's mad, obviously!"
but they told me, "Yes, all dreams can be realized, all of them, if we are given the freedom to be and to dream whatever we want."
To dream whatever we want!
So I dared to steal a list from them or at least a sample
of their list of dreams. What you will hear is not at all the list you would expect to hear.
We are far from the letter to Santa.
Yes, I even stole the drawing.
For example, we hear : "I dream of taking an airplane," "I dream of having a room all to myself," "I dream of playing all the time," "I dream of not going to school anymore," "I dream that all dreams come true."
But we also hear: "I dream that my parents play with me more," "I dream that the planet gets better," "I dream that people are nicer to each other," "I dream that my best friend I miss return to France," '"I dream that my parents get back together," "I dream that my mom is cured and come back home."
Do you start to see the kind
of list it is? It's not that easy.
Now after I had collected all their reflections, all their thoughts, I became interested in their modus operandi.
How are these beings of the future able to think that way?
Well, there are seemingly three keys, I'll say, three fundamental keys to this thinking and these universal thoughts.
The fist one is the practice
of mindfulness. When they practice mindfulness, the children connect with their own hearts, they are in full consciousness, they get rid of their mental agitation like everyone here, daily, they connect to their soul, they allow, they express themselves, and all that in the greatest kindness.
The second key is they allow themselves to express themselves and to dream.
Happiness is in the dreams that come true.
The children understood that.
And the third one is that in order to be able to express ourselves and dream, we must take a positive attitude.
Let me ask you a question. Are you not tired of being more a spectator than an actor of your life?
Aren't you also tired of being constantly polluted by dream breakers?
Happiness is truly where dreams come true and the children understood this.
Today, I would really like for you to allow yourselves to be.
I am extremely lucky to spend these moments in the future.
I make round trips and a few days ago, they were with me and I told them I was here, So they asked me, "Can you bring them a message?"
So let me give you their message. I am extremely proud to share it with you, and it is the one that I've had deep down during my entire life as well.
They told me, 'If we dream big and we visualize this dream every day, well one day, it will come true.
And for it to come true, we must allow ourselves to be and become."
So I'll finish by asking you two last questions, you, the big children that you are here before me because you are all big children - well when was the last time that you played ?
The last two questions are ... (Laughing) "What stops you from dreaming big today?"
and "Who or what would stop you from doing it?"
Thank you.
(Applause)
Each week I come across an article or a report that asserts that data is the new oil, that the use of data will lead to a new era of knowledge, or even that it can predict the future.
This has been particularly true since everyone started talking about big data.
You know, the use of large-scale data, mega data.
For example, Sergei Brin, the founder of Google, who is focusing on the use of medical data to cure Parkinson's disease, for which he is at risk.
During the World Cup, many people said that the German team was able to beat the Brazilian team 7-1 thanks to the use of match data.
It's clear that there is no field or type of organization for which Big Data isn't supposed to be a magic wand that will enable the resolution of extremely complex problems.
And I must admit that I feel uneasy about these kinds of simplistic statements, which I see as overshadowing a number of issues, including the economy, the environment, politics, and the ethics of the massive production of data.
Please don't think that I am skeptical or doubtful about data, or that I am opposed to all forms of quantification.
On the contrary, I live surrounded by data.
During the day, I'm working on a thesis in sociology at Telecom ParisTech where I study Open Data. The important effort
to provide open access to public data.
And I study the consequences of Open Data for the operation of government.
At night, I am the administrator for an association, Open Knowledge Foundation France, which campaigns for open knowledge and for data that benefits everyone.
Today, I would like to persuade you that, at this time, when data is becoming obtrusive, we need to take a step back.
This coronation of data that we are witnessing during the era of Open Data and Big Data demands a new culture of critical thought about data.
We must be able to understand how it is produced and used, and how we can become independent from it.
I also want to share the results of an experiment that we did at Open Knowledge Foundation France called "the School of Data."
I hope to show that, through the use of data, we can manage to develop this culture of critical thought and that we can develop new checks and balances.
So, what are the problems with data?
The first problem is that data is always right.
Now, don't believe that this is anything new.
Historically, the word 'data' comes from the Latin word "datum" which, in mathematics and theology in the 15th century, referred to the facts taken as given in an argument and which were not to be called into question.
Today, as you know, data refers to everything that flows in your computer.
That is to say, the 1's and 0's that pass from USB stick to hard disk are considered data.
On the other hand, the sense that data is a given, that it is factual, that it is not to be questioned, has remained.
The second problem with data is that we don't really know where it comes from.
In general, when someone uses data, he or she has very little information about the way in which it was produced.
At best, you will have access to metadata, that is to say, data about the data, which will tell you the contents of the file and, occasionally, how the data was produced.
However, that data has a long history.
It was collected.
It was processed, formatted, aggregated, processed by algorithms, and visualized before reaching you.
This is why sociologist Bruno Latour asserts that we should say 'obtaineds' instead of data to accurately reflect this long history which will constrain a number of uses.
Finally, the third problem with data is that we can't really see it.
Have you ever seen a data center, even if only from outside, or from the road?
Do you have any idea of where your data is stored?
I mean, physically, where it is stored?
Do you have any idea what will happen to it in 10 years?
In any case, I have no answer for these three questions.
However, even if we can't see our data, we can measure its effects.
At the individual level, when Facebook changes its terms of service or modifies its algorithm, it has consequences for your private life and for the way in which you present yourself as an individual.
And on the most macroscopic level, the Snowden affair has shown that the massive production of data can have consequences for the sovereignty of the State or for diplomacy.
This is why we must develop a culture of critical thought about data.
To encourage myself, I was inspired by a book called "Statactivism."
Statactivism is a neologism proposed by researchers and artists that refers to those experiences that permit one to liberate oneself from the power of data.
The fundamental basis of statactivism is that data controls us, and that it imposes on us like an argument from authority.
The goal of statactivism is almost revolutionary.
It asserts that other kinds of data must be possible.
It is not necessary to be opposed to all data. Instead, we should use the power of data to propose other realities to critique data more effectively, or to propose other measures.
In short, to propose other data.
There is a motif in the book which I find particularly meaningful, that of the judoka.
Judoka use the strength of their opponents in order to turn it back on them.
That is what I want to invite you to do today: think about how to use data to better analyze it.
I think, precisely at this moment in the development of Open Data, the need to develop a culture of critical thought about data is increasingly crucial.
Don't be misled: Open Data represents an extraordinary opportunity.
The volume of data is exploding and data is no longer the privilege of the powerful.
Today, you can use data without asking anyone's permission.
And this is a good idea, because public data is available.
But I think that there is a risk to thinking that the simple diffusion of data will be enough to emancipate society, that individuals can emancipate themselves from the power of data just because they have access to data.
There is a Canadian sociologist named Michael Gurstein who has proposed an expression that sums up a risk of Open data, namely, "Empower the Empowered," meaning to give more power to those who already have it.
That is why it's crucial to develop a culture of critical thought to be able to understand how data is produced, used, and how you can use it to take a step back.
Well, that's the theory.
I would like to share with you the first results from an experiment that we did in my association: Open Knowledge Foundation France. We are part of a worldwide network dedicated to open knowledge and open data.
We have groups in more than 50 countries.
And the idea of our association and of this worldwide movement is that each person can benefit, can profit, from works, scientific articles, and content, to create, play, educate, or to start up a business.
Open Knowledge has a large number of projects.
I'm going to talk about one project, the "School of Data."
We participated together in the translation of this project, this "School of Data."
The School of Data consists of online resources that are free and accessible to all, and also events.
We first proposed classes.
In these classes, you do not even have to know what data is.
Or how to use a spreadsheet, which is really the tool of choice.
You will be taught about that in our class.
No expertise is required, you are guided step by step in the use of data.
We also use another format which is particularly educational, namely, the recipe.
Recipes are just like in cooking - you have ingredients and steps.
The ingredients will be data, software - free if possible, so that you can use data.
The idea is that making a map of electoral results, or a graph of results of the French soccer team should be as easy to do as making a tarte Tatin or Bechamel sauce.
You find the resources online and we walk you through the project step by step.
We also have tried to develop another format for in-person sessions, which we call expeditions.
For expeditions, it's like mountain climbing: you have a guide, a "data sherpa," who will accompany you, attached by a rope. There will be 10 or 20 participants who work together during a weekend or sometimes for a few hours.
Our first data expedition focused on the question of air pollution in Île-de-France.
I don't know if you have seen these images of Paris with black clouds of pollution.
They left their mark on us, and we said to ourselves: "Well, let's dig into this set of data."
The first step, when we undertook this data expedition, was to identify the available data.
We realized that there is no available data that is freely reusable, that is to say, that you have the right to reuse without asking for permission, on this crucial question.
Therefore, we had to extract data from websites, reports, or even from graphics.
Imagine what a mess it is to expose data that is in a graphic.
We also realized that Airparif, the organization responsible for the production of data relevant to the question of air pollution in Île-de-France does not allow you to use its data freely.
One must ask permission, or pay.
We were able to overcome these constraints and to conduct this expedition guided by our sherpa, Pierre.
During this data expedition we broke into small groups, and each group was assigned an angle.
One of the principles of the expeditions: you have an angle, like in journalism, we ask ourselves questions that could be the title of an article.
The first group asked itself if bicycle riding had led to a decrease in air pollution in Paris.
The second group, since it was during a strike, asked itself if public transport strikes cause air pollution in Île-de-France to increase.
And the third group asked if all regions are equal with regard to air pollution, or if geography and environment could have an effect, and if so, could be seen in the data.
The results of this expedition, I am sorry to say, will be a bit disappointing.
We did not find any correlation or causal connection with nice data points, a fitting curve, or a straight line, that proves that our hypotheses are correct.
We did not succeed at that, but we worked for four hours.
What we did manage to show, on the other hand, is that it is extremely difficult to use data concerning a question as crucial as air pollution, to understand how it is produced, extremely difficult to use it, that the most simple measurements are not accessible, and that you do not necessarily have the right to reuse them.
That is just what we tried to do at this event: to develop a culture of critical thought on the way in which data is used concerning the question of air pollution.
We also tried to develop this format of expeditions and training events with another group that is less expected, that of children.
We asked ourselves the question during an event that we did with Etalab, the government institution in charge of data.gouv.fr, the open data portal of the French government.
We suggested the idea of radically different open data portals.
They were fictional projects, just prototypes.
There is a group that has come out with a prototype called Tada.gouv.fr.
Tada.gouv.fr is a fictional portal, a bit idealistic, destined for children.
The data is presented not by government department or minister, but by discipline, that is to say that you have data about history and geography, physics and chemistry, or life and Earth sciences.
On this occasion, we realized that open data can be a fantastic resource for school because it allows the development of inter-disciplinary work, and this culture of critical thought about data I have mentioned.
We did not leave things at observation. We tried to do a first experiment and I would like to tell you about the first results.
We joined with Silicon Banlieue, which is a site dedicated to data in Argenteuil, and we proposed to do an event with children between 8 and 14 years old who came to the Open World Forum, an event dedicated to open computing in Paris.
There, you can see me from the back.
With the 8 to 14 year old children, we worked on the question of cinema, because that interested them, and it is a simple enough subject.
First we collected data, nothing very complicated, it was just a paper form. We asked them how many times a month they go to the cinema, which movies they saw from a list; then we compared that with data that is available from the survey of French cultural practices, on which you have exactly the same type of data.
With the children, we produced an infographic at this time.
Now, I am really bad at math, I got a 7,5 on the Bac, I found myself explaining the concept and calculation of averages using a spreadsheet, which was rather surprising.
I explained how it works.
We emerged with an infographic and we were able on this occasion, I think that this is the important point, to develop a culture of critical thought. I explained to them about data, how it is used, how they can use it, how it controls us in a certain way, but that we can also take back the power over data.
I assure you that with a topic as attractive as cinema we can deliver this kind of message and have a discussion on these questions.
I hope that I have convinced you that it is necessary today to take a step back with regard to data, to develop a culture of critical thought, to understand how it is produced and how you can use it, to prevent data from being forced on you.
So from today, get your hands dirty, find a sherpa, all of the resources are online, and go on a data expedition.
Thank you.
(Applause)
In 2050, there will be 10 billion people on Earth.
Ten billion people that need to be fed.
Ten billion people living off the resources of a planet that is already unable to sustain the 7 billion people living today.
Or at least not in the way we currently operate.
We all agree that to live, we need food, and, in particular, proteins.
With wild resources being limited and sometimes hard to obtain, we farm: pigs, chickens, fish.
But to produce one kilogram of farmed fish, we need to use five kilograms of wild fish as feed.
The consequence? Fish stocks are being depleted.
Same thing with chickens, which we feed with soy.
The more chicken we eat, the more soy we need.
And to grow more soy, we need to deforest areas, like the Amazon.
We are destroying whole ecosystems to produce more food.
And paradoxically, we don't eat everything we produce.
One third of the food we produce will never be consumed by a human.
One third.
We're producing waste and destroying our planet in the process.
So why am I telling you this?
My brother got married this summer.
I had the honor of being a witness.
On the day of the wedding, before his friends and family, and before the mayor, the marriage certificate was read out, and the witnesses' names and professions were given.
Raphael Smia, fly farmer.
Yes, I farm flies.
To be more specific, I use insects to reclaim bio-waste in order to produce proteins and lipids for animal feed and green chemistry.
OK, I've lost you.
What I do is gather bio-waste,
like rotten apples from the supermarket or food scraps from a restaurant.
We take all that, we grind it up, we mix it all up, and we put it in our bio-reactors with insect larvae.
Our larvae love waste and rotting things.
To each their own. They eat, grow and fatten up. And when they've gotten enough proteins and fats in them, they're used as animal feed.
Chickens don't naturally eat South American-grown GMO soy.
No. They eat insects.
Same thing for fish.
Yet, this is the model we've been given.
We grow grain that we feed to our livestock, we harvest it, we turn it into food, we eat it, or we throw it out.
Farming insects makes it possible to recover the nutrients which remain in this waste and to reinsert those nutrients back into the human food cycle.
We go from a linear model to a circular economy.
So, who is this superhero of recycling?
Let me introduce to you the black soldier fly.
This shows that the flies in France aren't all white.
(Laughter) (Applause) So a quick lesson on flies.
A fly lays eggs.
Larvae hatch from these eggs.
If there's just one, no problem. But more than one, and look out!
The larvae eat, and when they've eaten enough, they become pupae.
A pupa is sort of like a cocoon for a fly.
After a few weeks, a new fly emerges from the pupa.
And this fly is the ideal farm animal.
First of all, it's harmless.
It doesn't sting. It doesn't bite. It doesn't transmit disease.
The adult fly actually doesn't even eat.
The only things it does is drink and look for mates.
Sort of like if you were to spend your whole life in a nightclub.
(Laughter) And because adult flies don't eat, they don't spread germs as they go from our garbage to our plates.
And also, they exist naturally in France,
so there's no risk of ecological disaster, like with the Asian lady beetle.
Lastly, and most importantly, black solider fly larvae are scavengers.
They can eat and process all different kinds of waste,
while creating none themselves,
since even their excrement can be used as fertilizer.
So, now you get it. These flies are perfect!
The only thing we needed was to domesticate them.
That's what we did with my associate, Jean-François Kleinfinger.
We built our first laboratory in the Loire-Atlantique department, in a stable.
In it, we built a climate chamber,
which is a hermetically sealed chamber in which we can control temperature, humidity, and all that, inside.
I can tell you that for someone like me, who has trouble putting IKEA furniture together, this was a pretty big challenge.
We got our first larvae, we fed them, and we waited impatiently for the first fly.
And here it is!
The first fly from the NextAlim laboratory.
I have to tell you my family and friends were wary. Especially my grandma, who asked when I was going to get a real job.
And I get where they're coming from.
I was digging through supermarkets' trash.
I spent my time watching and waiting impatiently for flies to mate.
And I was putting larvae into different situations to see how they would react.
For example, black soldier fly larvae behave in a peculiar way.
When they've finished eating, they migrate out of their substrate, out of their food source.
This has its advantages and disadvantages.
The advantage is that there's no need to harvest the larvae one by one. That's pretty nice.
The disadvantage is that they can migrate when we don't expect it.
That's what happened with our first generation.
We built them bins with ramps to facilitate their migration.
The ramps were precisely 45° from the ground, like the literature said.
You can imagine the looks on our faces the next day, when we found the lab littered with larvae. The larvae had the brilliant idea of going up the vertical walls rather than using our ramps.
Well, anyway, the colony is making progress.
And we even want to optimize our set-up, like the number of matings, egg clutches. This involves playing with different parameters: light, temperature, and a bit of music.
(Barry White - "You're the First, the Last, My Everything") No, seriously, music really works with flies too!
(Laughter) We domesticated the flies, and with that success, we were able to raise funds from private partners and also from public partners, who supported the project to the tune of several million euros.
What those funds, we were able to build a slightly more professional laboratory, to conduct more thorough experiments, and, most importantly, to determine the process and to draw up the plans for the first industrial insect farming factory.
In 2017, we will be able to process 13,000 metric tons of bio-waste, and to produce 4,000 metric tons of larvae per year.
And 4,000 tons of larvae, that's about 20 million times this.
And all that, with a single plant.
But that's not all.
Bio-waste can be found everywhere in France.
We will set ourselves up as close as possible to bio-waste producers to be able to produce local proteins.
But that's not all.
With one ton of bio-waste, we can also make 300 kilograms
of fertilizer, 75 liters of bio fuel.
That's a full tank of gas.
In 10 years, we'll be able to replace 50% of fish meal.
Still, insect farming isn't a panacea that can save the planet and prevent the world's end.
But for a more sustainable, healthier society, every step counts.
Even the steps of flies.
(Applause)
I'm going to talk about motor sports, in particular about racing.
We'll try and see if racing teaches us anything about life, if it has any use, any value,
if it has an impact on all our futures.
In "motor sport" there's "motor" and behind "motor", there are different areas and different specialist skills.
Take a racing car, for example, it has aerodynamics,
an engine, a chassis, suspension, it even has tires.
To make it go, you need a lot of people who all have to rely on each other, who are all recognized and respected for their skills, who are are all going to work as a team to bring to the starting grid - that's where the machines line up at the start of a car or motorbike race - vehicles which are as competitive as possible.
It's an interesting moment because it's the start of the contest. We have the impression that motor sport in general is an individual sport.
The driver gets in his car or on his bike and runs his race.
We get the impression it's an individual sport.
But nowadays, that's not true at all.
Because by the time the machine gets to the starting grid, the teams have put in thousands of hours of work to make a winning vehicle.
On a lap, if we lose 3/10ths of a second, due to the vehicle, for example, the driver will try to make it up.
When drivers have different levels of skill,
as is the case in amateur racing, that doesn't matter too much. But when the drivers have been chosen after years of fierce competition, they're all at a very high level.
I'm thinking about Formula 1 or motorcycle grand prix.
There, the drivers obviously try, by their talent or what they do, to make up the 3/10ths of a second by lap. They will take considerable risks which can lead them to spin off the road or come off the bike, and a crash or fall always has consequences.
So that's a very important factor when picking the teams. It means these so-called individual sports are actually team sports where everyone brings their skills with a lot of modesty, humility and respect for other people, respect for other people and their skills.
That's not always obvious.
What are the penalties in these sports?
There are two arbiters and they are very similar.
One is the lap time, the other is the result of the race, it's as simple as that.
The lap time is a determining factor because it enables a team to see if it's been doing a good job.
To see if the vehicle is running well, if it's fast, if possible as fast as or faster than the others.
We do different tests, sometimes even with different drivers, and we reach conclusions.
We have to redesign the aerodynamics because what we saw on the simulator or in the wind-tunnel doesn't work.
I've seen lots of Formula 1 teams arrive with big ambitions on the Thursday evening before the Grand Prix. I've heard them say, "We've improved the down force by 3 points."
Wow! but in fact,
it hadn't worked at all. Because what they'd seen on the simulator or in the wind-tunnel is very hard to extrapolate to the race-track. Because in the wind-tunnel, the models they use are very well-engineered, very pure,
there are no defects, no bolts sticking out, nothing at all.
And then, when the vehicle is actually built, a few tenths of a millimeter between two panels, between two plastic panels, and you've lost it.
The air gets between them, and you lose 500 kg of down force.
When we are talking about tires, what gives speed and grip is the down force.
So the lap time is an absolutely determining factor.
Then we have the result of the race.
The result of the race is linked to the lap time.
I'm not going to spend time telling you how to achieve a fast lap time when you are in pole position.
For example, the Monaco circuit is narrow for cars.
If you are in pole position, that is to say you had the best qualifying time in the trials before the race, you generally win the race because it's very hard to overtake.
The result is important but sometimes it doesn't depend on the competitiveness of the vehicles.
One day, one of the senior managers of the company I used to work for phoned me to say he'd like to go to the Monaco Grand Prix.
It was in 1979.
As you know, Monaco is very narrow, very cramped.
It's improved a bit since, but it was very uncomfortable at the time. It was difficult to get around and see the action. So I suggested he came instead to the French Grand Prix at Dijon.
OK, why not and we arranged to meet.
I said it wasn't the race he must see
but what went on on the Friday morning. He was there Friday morning
and we spent the weekend together.
Maybe some of you remember, I think it's still on YouTube. Jean-Pierre Jabouille was driving a Renault. It had a powerful turbocharged engine which at the time wasn't very reliable. It was improved afterwards.
He shot off in the lead, pursued by two rascals, Arnoux driving the second Renault, and Gilles Villeneuve driving a Ferrari.
Those two boys were made of the same metal. They finished the last five laps of the race wheel to wheel.
In Formula 1, imagine the risk they took.
Absolutely mind-blowing.
Maybe it's still on YouTube.
At the finish, the 4th driver, was Jones, an Australian, in a Williams equipped with tires from a rival company.
At the finishing line, M. Rondreux said to me, "You must be happy, let's have a glass of champagne."
I said, "Yes, but what if Jabouille's engine had failed," "which could well have happened," "and the two lads behind him had touched and stopped." "The race would have been won by a driver using another company's tires." "We'd be staring at each other glumly" "saying we'd lost the race."
And yet, we'd have done the same work, applied the same techniques and obtained the same results.
So lap time, OK, but you can never take the result for granted.
To get results, you understand, people must give all they've got.
You don't do what I just described quietly drinking a cup of tea, although there's no harm in that. What I mean is, those people give their all. People like that
have different personalities.
Maybe you know Ari Vatanen.
I mention him because he's from Finland, someone with charming manners.
He was, and perhaps still is, a member of the European Parliament. A rally driver, if ever there was one, he took part in the Paris-Dakar rally.
He was calm, restrained, pleasant and kind, but when he got into his car, closed his eyes and put his helmet on, he was an absolute disaster.
He was often very fast, but at times he finished upside-down.
You will remember one year, the Paris-Dakar rally started at Clermont. The preliminary stage took place here and his car finished up on its roof. Before the hostilities had even started, he had turned his car over.
People express themselves in completely surprising ways.
When I talk about personalities, I'm not only thinking about the drivers and engineers. I'm thinking about a personality like Enzo Ferrari.
I was a very young engineer and I wanted to work with Ferrari and meet the "Commandatore", which I managed to do. It was very impressive, I can assure you.
He was a leader.
We say "commandatore" because of his physical stature. He was sitting behind a big wooden desk, shrouded in smoke. "So, Mr. engineer, what must I do to have your tires?"
"Um, er...", I was like this of course.
It worked out really well and we had a good relationship, in racing and supplying tires for ordinary cars.
It's a memory I really cherish, especially as I'm passionate about cars.
You don't meet someone like that every day.
Another factor that comes to mind is intellectual honesty.
It isn't easy to admit
you've made a mistake. Because there are economic and personality issues. Commitments have been made, firms have given their backing. And then there are the spectators and the television viewers, so its a very public thing.
I've met people who've tried to cheat, and some of them are still in their jobs.
But generally speaking, that's not how you build a winning team.
A striking example of intellectual honesty was given to me by a Japanese engineer, Oguma San.
Oguma was traditionally Japanese, the head of motorbike racing at Honda,
with black hair brushed flat, cut like this.
We were in England, at the Silverstone Grand Prix, and he had a bike ridden by Spencer, an outstanding rider, very fast, who generally won two races during the weekend. There were 350cc and 500cc races then and he would win them both.
Competing against us was a certain Kenny Roberts on a Yamaha fitted with a rival firm's tires.
When we measured lap times, Roberts was faster than Spencer.
I measured times on parts of the track because we were trying to understand.
Nowadays, we get that data naturally from systems provided by the organizers, but at that time it wasn't the case.
We measured lap times on the track.
At top speed, the Honda was faster than the Yamaha.
The organizers gave us that information.
On an outer part of the track, at Becketts, a series of bends at the back of the Silverstone circuit, Spencer was faster overall than Roberts over the distance.
So I said to Oguma, "I don't understand,
"we're good in the bends when we need the tires." "When we need grip, we have it."
"Going flat out, you're good because your bike is the fastest", "but if we look at the lap times, it isn't working."
And Oguma went, "Hiiii, hi." When he did that, we knew something important was going to happen.
I know, it makes some of you laugh. He went off, saying, "See you at the next practice session." And we met after the next practice session. And he said, "Hiiii, pencil and paper!"
He took a sheet of paper and drew a graph. "Honda bike, huuuuuu, Yamaha bike, hooooooo." I can see some of you smile because I haven't drawn it very well, but the Honda really was more powerful than the Yamaha, except that the curve was steeper, much steeper.
In other words, it's range was narrower.
So when re-accelerating, when you need engine flexibility to get back up to speed, the Yamaha, though less powerful, came out much better.
That's the sort of person he was.
It was very enjoyable to work with people like that who could admit they weren't the best.
There are a lot of people like that.
The third point is respect for the facts.
Those of you who follow Formula 1 will maybe remember the United States Grand Prix in 2005.
Our Tyre, supplied by the firm I was working for at that time, was way out in the lead that season.
There was a cultural problem.
Our Japanese rivals had had trouble meeting new regulations.
From the start of the season, our tires were absolutely leading the field.
We arrived in the USA, at Indianapolis. The circuit is a bit bizarre, it's not the usual ring.
There's a ring and also what's called the "infield" used by Formula 1 cars.
At the the first practice session, there were two incidents due to the tires.
We investigated, analyzed the tires on the spot. carried out tests in France and the USA.
We understood fairly quickly that the tires we had at Indianapolis were the ones we were expecting, they were compliant with requirements. And yet, the tires were incapable of completing the Indianapolis course.
So I organized a meeting in a big office, around a big, U-shaped table, with all the engineers and decision makers of our different partners, to put them in the picture and follow events in real time and all put our heads together.
They were all bright guys so maybe they'd come up with good ideas.
We came to the same conclusion, the circuit would have to be modified. We understood where the problem was. We would have to modify the circuit if the race was to take place.
We met the teams, we had a phone call from the president of the Federation. He was in Monaco and he refused to have the circuit modified.
OK, too bad, we wouldn't change the circuit.
I said to Tony George, the track manager, "Listen, we must do something, or the grand prix isn't going to happen."
And Tony said, "I need 20 minutes to modify a chicane, I'll see about it."
And off he went.
Briatore convened the drivers, among them Schumacher and the Ferrari drivers, who at that time were equipped with tires from our Japanese competitor. And Schumacher said, "I don't care, I'll drive your car, I'm on the track, I don't mind if they change it."
So we got ready to start the race on the modified circuit.
At the start of the race, when the drivers did their reconnaissance lap, the circuit hadn't been modified
and the grand prix didn't take place.
Six cars did race, equipped with our competitor's tires.
There were 120,000 American spectators, who'd come to see a Formula 1 grand prix.
Not to put too fine a point on it, they weren't at all happy.
And then there were three or hour hundred million TV viewers.
But after examining the facts and understanding what was happening, quietly, objectively and rationally, we all decided we weren't going to race.
There, it was a simple as that.
So all this goes to show, through the examples we've seen, how the people involved in this kind of game, in motor racing which is ultimately a team game, have to completely expose their true selves.
Thank you very much
and have a good evening.
(Applause)
Hi everyone, my name is Franky Zapata.
Ever since I was young, I've always had this crazy dream of flying.
I wanted to become a helicopter pilot, but unfortunately, as I'm colour-blind, I was refused at the medical check-up. And so I had to change my life, change my dream and so I started jet ski races,
and now I am having other dreams. My goal was to become World Champion,
I dreamt of that, so I worked vey hard for 17 years of my life to pursue that dream and so I ended up being World Champion after 4/5 years, I don't know exactly how many.
So, I went back to my first passions, how to fly like <i>Iron Man</i>, like Tony Stark.
I imagined the prototype of the Water Flyboard. This adventure completely changed my life, because it allowed me to become an entrepreneur, to see a global market to be able to see the world as it really is: extremely vast and I realized that people liked what I was creating. This made me even more driven and passionate, but of course my first passion was free flight. That's why I said to myself: "you have to take the hose off, and you have to be able to fly as well as anything that flies on water, but anywhere on the planet at any speed."
This dream never left me again. I went from a dream to a goal and it became a reality in 2016.
Now, what were the new challenges,
once you could fly, what could you imagine crazy things to do with this machine?
I've always wanted to show that you could go from one country to another. As I said before, I have always been passionate about aviation, I was lulled by all its discoveries, by these aviation pioneers, Louis Blériot, the Wright brothers.
A country next door is England,
Can't we also cross the Channel?
It sounds completely crazy to say it like that but it was the most difficult challenge imaginable,
and I decided to pursue it because here it is... "Nothing is impossible" and it's this quote that motivates us and it's what motivates the whole team. So we started working hard on this challenge. At the same time, a little happiness like that happens in the year, I was invited to participate in the 14th of July parade, in front of all the heads of state and above all fly over the Concorde, it's the Champs-Élysées, it's just incredible!
It was a great moment and a great year 2019 that will remain forever engraved in my memory.
I was able to walk in the footsteps of an aviation hero like Louis Blériot, on my small scale, I was able to follow my dream.
Now that I've crossed the Channel and been able to fly on the Champs-Élysées, what will my future project be, my future dream?
What will be the future of the Zapata company?
Me, I am a man of challenges, I chose my team because they also love challenges. How do we imagine the future?
For us, the future is the new mobility and for me, the future of mobility is flying.
Cities are congested, there's heavy traffic everywhere! Sometimes to travel 10 kilometers it takes us 1 hour
and we have a layer between the ground and the sky that is useless and not used and I think that this is where we should finally move.
We'll be able to move around without really affecting the environment.
For example, today we use roads to get around. We have asphalt everywhere, and we are damaging the planet. These are scars on the planet, all this to be able to move around.
If we fly in the air, we will be tracing virtual highways like airplanes do, and the sky will always be untouched.
That's what I'm focused on right now.
At the same time we have to work very hard. That's the final goal. There are also all the details that we have to put in place one after the other. so building a flight controller that is extremely redundant because these machines, without a flight controller are just pebbles.
creating the engines, creating the thrusters...
Indeed there are a lot of people in the race, there are Uber, Airbus... Everybody is finally in this race but we realize that everyone is postponing the release date. We too have just posponed, we were hoping to launch for the end of the year, but we won't.
As there is no flying car, that's our challenge, our philosophy, our way of seeing things. There is no flying car,
so we're going to make one.
Everybody was waiting for Marty Mc Fly's flying skateboard, the Hoverboard in 2015. There was no flying skateboard, well in 2016 we created it.
So that's the position we're in now.
I don't really have a perfect vision of the future, a business model, a business plan, but we have this dream of changing things and creating that which doesn't exist.
I see mobility differring.
The mobility of flying machines, flying taxis. I know I'm walking a little bit against the flow compared to everyone else. All the big guys in this industry
are investing millions and they're all working in electricity.
I don't really believe in it, because for me, electricity is a machine that doesn't pollute when we use it, but in any case, there is this difficulty in building batteries,
the ores are not necessarily renewable. There will always be this problem and we wil always have to create the energy to make it fly.
The problem we encounter is that in1 kg of kerosene or 1 kg of biokerosene, for example, we can have the same energy storage as in 20 kgs of lithium batteries.
That's energy that you're going to have to spend to fly with more weight. So for me it's really staying on thermal engines. but by saying thermal engine it doesn't necessarily mean kerosen which comes from oil, etc. You can work very well with Biokerosene.
My turbo-engines today already work with rapeseed or sunflower oil, I have already made them work with that.
Our Flyboard Air and our machines don't fly with bio-fuel yet, but it should be soon. However, it already works on test terminals.
That's how I imagine the future,
We don't have to use cars on asphalt roads. We can imagine using the sky.
Now it's true that it's not a good idea to burn hundreds or thousands of liters of non renewable products such as fossil fuels and oil.
I can imagine replacing roads with fields of crops that will eventually serve as parks and gardens, and produce the oil that will later be used for bio-fuel.
I don't believe in inter-city transportation in the city.
I think that in the end, nothing can compete with the electric scooter.
I mean, flying with machines, with taxis over a downtown area is a bit of the same heresy as one person in an SUV. it's tons to move around for nothing.
I believe in moving from one city to another city.
A perfect system within a city would be tiny electric cars or electric scooters or scooters.
We will never beat energy expenditure because, as I was saying earlier, even if the energy we use is electric, it will be a little cleaner than thermal energy, but you still need to create it. You don't get it from people pedalling a bicycle. It's nuclear, coal, and renewable energies we don't have enough to power our homes, so when you've spent 100,000 Watts or 500,000 Watts to fly a taxi, it's not rational.
I rather believe that the mobility of the future is a combination of means.
It's public transit mixed with the electric scooter and our flying taxis that will be powered for the moment by thermal energy from renewable sources.
That is how I see life.
And if it's by the door, then you just walk. It doesn't get any better than that.
Nothing pollutes less than walking, so I encourage everyone to cycle and walk a little more.
There's a lot of skepticism about these flying machines, a lot of criticism that it's extremely energy-intensive. How will we travel in the sky? How will we pass each other?
Honestly, they are right!
I say yes, it's a huge problem. Today, the energy we spend is 1000X what we would spend with a car
and a million times what we would spend with a scooter.
You have to look at it differently. We have to see it step by step.
Today we are creating a flying car that will be used primarily for leisure.
People want to fly, so we will try
to give them a taste of the future, and what the future of mankind will be in maybe 10, 20 or 100 years.
No one actually knows.
We have to change the regulations and so on.
So we're going to give people the ability to fly for recreation, and it will have an extremely low carbon footprint.
It's going to be a few little machines scattered around the world.
The second step is everything that is "rescue", everything that's saving people. When I had a very serious accident last year, I almost lost my life. The main cause was the delay, the time it took for the helicopter to come and rescue me. I had a punctured lung, I was choking to death...
This week-end I was talking to a guy who was in a motorcycle accident. Paramedics took 45 minutes to get here... he could have died.
So here we are, creating extremely fast, extremely competitive flying machines that can fly through the sky at 200 to 400 km/h to at least get a doctor to the scene very quickly. Why not in stage 2, directly transport the person autonomously to the nearest hospital.
After that, we'll have to imagine public transport, taxis, but all that will obviously be once we've solved the energy problems. You don't have to take off and stay in the air with the force of the thrust, you can imagine using wings.
It is not because we are on a new VITOL technology that we necessarily have to stay in VITOL during the whole phase, the whole flight.
We can make the transition like using much less energy-consuming engines and it is when we have solved all these problems, when the regulations have changed that we can really look to the future and see the world as in <i>The Fifth Element</i>.
That day hasn't arrived yet, it's not tomorrow, so we have to give time to time.
To be honest, actually, all that emulsion that's on those flying taxis, I think there are two directions that are opposite.
There are the big groups that want to communicate, that want to show that they're working for the future, and there's us. We really have this passion, we are working for the change of mobility, of course. All of this is just an excuse to keep our societies going.
For the big groups it's a matter of communication, of how to attract people into what they sell today. Uber is passenger transport, Airbus and Boeing are flying machines. We're passionate about it,
so to be honest, we're working for mobility, the main thing is how to put it on paper and at the same time give life to our passion.
Now, not everything we create is necessarily useful. People can see it as gadgets that will further damage the planet and so on and so forth. But it shouldn't be seen like that. I think that any passion and innovation is good for the future.
If you look at the plane of the Wright brothers or Louis Blériot, it wasn't useful for much, if anything... Louis Blériot crossed the Channel 110 years ago, but the Channel was already crossed by boat, people could swim accross it. There was no interest at that time.
Today, look: what would the world be like if there were no planes? The work of the Wright brothers, the work of Louis Blériot gave birth to the A 380, It is a means of transport that is ultimately ecological because even if it is not perfect, it will still use less energy than hundreds of people who will travel with their own cars and will cross the world.
I think that by giving free rein to people's imagination, creativity and passion, we will be able to change this world and make it better.
The whole technology base is really different from what is developed by the big groups. We don't have propellers, so we create gas at very high speed, so it has huge advantages, disadvantages. The disadvantages are mainly noise.
Noise is extremely loud nearby but it disappears very quickly because it emits high frequencies. It is absorbed by the environment. It doesn't bounce off obstacles.
Very quickly, we have a noise level that becomes acceptable.
However, the huge advantage is the ability to fly in extremely turbulent winds. You don't use the reaction of the air like a wing or a rotating wing like a propeller, for example.
We really use"action-reaction", the thrust of gas.
So in reality, the turning winds, the Foehn effects, all that does not affect us at all.
We've created an extremely stable flying machine. It can be used for hundreds of applications. As I was talking about earlier, in the medical field, we will be able to save people even in storms, that is to say, we will no longer have to go after the storm to bring back survivors, injured or dead people.
We will be able to fly in storms, in hurricanes, with machines that are more stable than ever before. But at the same time, with transport platforms, why not military platforms,
even if we were seen on July 14th, we must remember that we are always there to help, but we are not a military company.
Hundreds of different uses, it's configurable. Platforms such as we are currently going to create a Flying Car for leisure, single-seater, one person, extremely fast, capable of competing with the best F1 cars on the planet
and at the same time, we can make platforms that can lift more than 1 ton to transport material and at the same time public transport.
All this must take time but it is infinitely configurable.
It's obvious that for me, things have to change, evolve.
I think it is a necessity for the future of mobility, the future of humans. Anyway my passion pushes me to move forward.
Afterwards, will the world use it?
Will you consider it appropriate to use our technologies or not?
Will the regulations change?
We'll see.
Anyway my passion and my team's passion pushes us to move forward in this direction. As I was saying earlier, all evolutions are good to take.
It's up to the world and the people to see what they do with it.
Thank you for listening to me.
Thank you for letting me share my passion with you and my vision of a future, which can be near or can be far or imaginary.
Thank you for that.
Our natural resources, such as air, water, and soil are becoming depleted, scarce and contaminated.
Biodiversity is plummeting, masses of animal species are disappearing …
Waw, that's a good start!
Who in this room thinks we must absolutely save Nature?
Could you please raise your hand?
Thank you.
Well, personally, I don’t believe it’s the priority.
And I'm going to explain to you why.
When I was a kid, I lived in a cottage in the countryside.
Imagine ... Grey lizards
ran along the walls.
The water of the river was fresh.
We could pick up lots of mulberries along the sunken lanes.
In the evening, crickets would sung loudly.
And nights studded with stars …
You’re going to say, "How lucky!"
Well, I’m going to tell you a secret.
Throughout all this time, all I wanted to do was to sit in front of the TV!
And so, little by little, I ended up migrating indoors.
Does that bring back any memories?
As it happens, I'm not alone.
We are a species that is voluntarily starting to disconnect from Nature.
A first for the animal kingdom!
Anyway, later as a young adult, I lived with it very well!
I was staying in a flat in Paris and was a consultant in La Défense, right in the middle of the sky scrapers.
Whether in the corridors of the office or of the subway, I was totally absorbed by my phone calls and busy agenda.
I had my phone in one hand, my files in the other, I was in a permanent hurry.
Can you picture the pencil skirt and high heels?
That’s how it was.
I was perfectly happy with it until one sunny Tuesday in July.
I was then a mom of two young children, when I came across this woman in the halls of the shopping center.
She was completely absorbed in her phone conversations.
She held her phone in one hand, and in the other, a leash, and she was in a hurry, and me?
Well, I stopped dead in my tracks, petrified: there was child at the end of the leash!
He must have been 4 years old and wasn't walking fast enough.
He just wanted to have a look at what was around him.
But she was pulling hard on the leash and not even looking at him!
Can you imagine how this child might have felt, stripped of any physical contact with his caregiver although she was there, and chained to a leash ?
That day, I appreciated the urgency of the situation:
from disconnected to Nature, we have become disconnected from one another.
We live in a society of ubiquity:
we are present but not really here.
We’re elsewhere: on the phone, focused on an online network, trapped inside a screen.
However, this ubiquitous society, far from bringing people closer together, isolates her children.
Because when adults prefer the virtual over the real, the inert over the living, and when they are no longer interested in Nature, how do children react?
Well, exactly in the same way, they set inside walls and screens.
Today in Great Britain, 74% of children spend less time outside than a prison inmate!
In France, in a class of 20 students, the only outside play for eight of them is the school playground.
And correct me if I'm wrong but a schoolyard in France looks like this.
This isolation is above all physical and sensory because indoors, there's not much to see.
And the little that is there is infinitely less complex and subtle than what children can sense in a natural environment.
What does a video smell like? What is the texture of a phone?
Of course, everything indoors is smooth, comfortable, practical.
But it’s starvation for our senses.
Furthermore, this sensory isolation causes an emotional isolation because it is physical sensations that unleashes emotions.
It’s the body, not the head!
What’s more, if what the child perceives is incoherent such as aggressive sounds or images, while they are relaxing like you in a comfy chair and eating a cake that should taste delicious, then their emotions are a mess.
What they experience is both disproportionate and confusing.
They don't decode their emotions any more, those messages that are essential to learn how to know yourselves, how to protect yourselves and how to react to your environment in a proper way.
Children today are already suffering from this.
Now let’s look again at our class of 20 students.
According to UNICEF, seven of them suffer psychologically.
Seven out of twenty!
Yet we know that children who grow up in areas with hardly any greenery are six times more likely to suffer from depression or anxiety.
In fact, the whole of society is already suffering from this because these children who disconnect from their emotions are logically less and less capable of understanding other people’s emotions, so it is hard for them to understand and feel their own emotions when they face somebody else’s distress.
Children today are 40% less empathetic than children in the 1980s.
The professor of psychology, Jean Twenge, has even found a nickname for them, the "Look-at-me's"!
So, I want to ask you this: Are our children beginning to lose their humanity, this part that connects them to others with all their senses, that allows them to feel emotions and react accordingly and to function with others while being themselves at the same time, this part that makes them profoundly social beings?
Are we raising an off-ground generation, completely disconnected from the living?
Organisms that are identical, whose experience is the same - four walls and a screen - and who will work side by side without emotion, without touch, or even looking at one another?
So no, I don’t think we're going to save Nature.
We aren't going to unite to save an environment that we no longer know and that we no longer experience with our children.
Because how can this 8-year-old child who is afraid of walking bare-foot on the grass - yes, that's where we are today! - how could he or she become this sort of adult who will save Nature?
On the other hand, what if connecting with Nature could save future generations by rekindling their humanity?
I became aware of children’s gradual disconnection from Nature’s most simple elements and its consequences for them and for society.
So I went in search of professionals in the field of education and Nature, and together we created a Nature academy, in Amsterdam, to offer children a space-time in their daily lives and connect them with the living.
What does connecting with Nature mean?
It’s an instinctive relationship, a deep synergy.
If he were here, little Knoxx would say, "Mmm, you don’t need to talk to Nature, it’s already in you!"
To be connected with Nature means to breathe, to feel our shoulders relax, to feel at home at last.
It’s the"flow" - you know it, right? -
being in the zone, this state of involvement and bliss of our whole being, just like Clara, here - look at her!
Imagine what she was doing
for the half hour prior to this photo!
Connecting with Nature is a physical sensation of being intensely or peacefully alive.
And it feels good!
This connection and this relationship are built simply by organizing enough regular opportunities to spend time in Nature so that the children feel there at home.
But beware that finding yourself parachuted all alone in Nature, it's a bit like finding yourself on stage with a violin in your hands without having ever been initiated to the beauty of music.
It can be rather baffling, and even scary for some.
So no, it’s not simply about releasing children into Nature to tire them out, nor is it about watching after them, what it means really is to accompany them, be this gentle mediator, this role model, whose intention is to share with children his own connection to Nature and get them to play, discover, have adventures, express their feelings, liberate their creativity, cooperate, laugh, feel, wonder … There are still many adults able to transmit their love for music, their passion for sport, the joys of arithmetic - and yes, it is important.
But it is rare to see adults convey their love for the living to children.
Yet this is the foundation!
Today, transmitting it has become an emergency to prepare future generations for tomorrow’s world because connecting with Nature can awake in children two essential skills we all need:
resilience and empathy.
Anchoring yourself in what you are, and knowing how to return to it flexibly, knowing how to stay human when confronted with life’s challenges, knowing how to fit into this world without seeking to destroy everything that is bothering us, it’s called resilience, and it’s
a key skill for living a happy life.
Indeed, there’s comfort in being inside our house or our classroom since we know well its environment, and everything is under control.
But in Nature, we can never fully know what we're going to find because it’s rich.
It’s the experiment environment the richest possible.
Nature alone offers all of our senses this diversity and depth.
And Nature offers a multitude of never ending changes, mostly tiny but sometimes substantial.
Children perceive these changes with all their senses.
And as they do so, they are forced to make constant adjustments.
So it might be avoiding being blinded by the sun reflecting on the water, adjust one's balance to the ground relief while dancing, or warding off a cold shower by creating a makeshift shelter, and often not succeeding in totally avoiding it!
When seven-year-old Lucca joined us, he would get annoyed easily.
He would say, "Argh! Can we please walk on the path, like normal people?"
Actually, Lucca was exasperated because the branches in bushes felt like an aggression to him.
Well today, Lucca knows exactly what to do with those branches! He decorates them, sharpens them
into arrows and climbs in them!
He is building self-confidence.
He collects his little frustrating experiences and the adjustments he had to make, and by doing so strengthen his resilience.
He learns how to adapt to circumstances without sacrificing any of what makes his personality as a child very engaging.
Without resilience, we can't develop empathy.
We can't be receptive to another when we're too busy fighting with our own emotions.
Yet, empathy is the foremost ability that has enabled humankind to progress from time immemorial.
Humans have never stopped developing, building, and pooling their knowledge.
We never accomplish as much great things as when we understand one another and act together and in peace.
We don’t need to know one another perfectly to understand each other, do we?
So, how does it work ?
In Nature, everything happens for a reason.
Everything has a purpose, an explanation waiting to be discovered.
That’s what stimulates children's curiosity, makes them keen to ask questions and triggers their surprise.
With the assistance of a mediator, they look at other forms of life.
They imagine their internal dialogue and put themselves in their place.
And that’s when you know they got it!
In the damp cold of Amsterdam, we took this class out to look for birds in their local area - pigeons, crows and ducks ...
Well, they discovered incredible things about these birds with which they nevertheless lived side-by-side every day.
They found out about their living conditions during winter, chose their totem bird, and even tried to make their own wings.
The kids spent the next few days repeating the new code of conduct they had agreed together: "We don’t feed bread to ducks!"
because it gives them tummy ache.
Now when children are able to feel empathy for life forms that are so far and different from their own as ducks are, or earthworms in Clara’s case, or this tree in front of your house, then developing and transferring this empathy reflex to this stranger or this neighbor who is somehow different, becomes nothing more than … a child’s play!
And ultimately, children who will be connected to Nature are children who will never harm her because they have too much respect for her.
Imagine a future in which all adults are in touch with their senses and who they are, deep inside, in which they naturally know how open up to their fellow humans and other living beings, in which they know how to find the resources they need inside them and act spontaneously to preserve their own nature, this instinctive relationship that is part of them.
I believe that providing a sincere bond with Nature and between human beings, a bond with life, is one of the greatest gifts we could give to our children and the world.
So I have one simple request to you, parents and education professionals.
As you'll leave this room later, ask yourselves, "How much space do I leave to connecting to Nature in the children's life?
What can I do to give Nature the place it deserves?" Thank you.
(Applause)
Astrophysicists place the Earth's formation over 4.56 billion years ago.
At that time, the Earth was a mass of gas and molten material.
It would then have taken half a billion years for this biochemical soup to take shape, stabilize, and enable the formation оf the first molecules that will trigger the first signs of life on Earth.
The most ancient manifestation of life found on Earth by geologists is a fragment of marine sediments containing bacteria.
Today, these bacteria are believed to be our oldest ancestors in terms of biological evolution.
As you might have guessed, bacteria are something of a pet subject of mine.
But why bacteria?
Bacteria are micro-organisms that can be found all over our body.
All of these micro-organisms form what we call a "microbiota".
This microbiota is not only present inside our body but also on it.
So this microbiota is found in various locations on the body, and molecular biology techniques have in fact enabled us to describe, understand and compare these different microbiota.
In terms of human microbiota, we are currently aware of the nasal, oral and skin microbiota, the gastrointestinal microbiota as well as the vaginal microbiota.
This human microbiota develops very early, from the moment of birth or even before.
And the way this microbiota sets up is a critical step in our life for all of us because it determines or rather is said to determine how healthy we are.
Today, we know that there are great differences between these microbiota,
as shown here, for example, between the intestinal microbiota and the oral microbiota which is in orange, the gastrointestinal one being in blue.
They can be very similar too.
This is the case for the skin microbiota, for example, which is in green, and the nasal microbiota which is in red.
We also know that these microbiota are made up of different types of bacteria and also contain different and various amounts of each bacteria.
Here is an example of this relative to the skin microbiota.
As you can see, each pie chart has different colors.
Each color represents a different bacteria, and each segment of the pie corresponds to the amount of bacteria.
So whether we are young or old, male or female, we all live with bacteria inside us and on us.
And these bacteria perform a number of biological functions.
For example, the Corynebacteria found on the skin or under the armpits are partly responsible for your body odor.
So the next time you're on public transport in summer, and someone makes a nasty comment to you, you can reply, "It's not my fault,
it's my Corynebacteria."
So the bacteria that form part of our microbiota perform biological function for our organism.
These functions may be shared by different microbiota.
The same functions are found in different microbiota, such as energy production for example.
The various colors you see on the screen correspond to different bacteria that are able to serve this metabolic function.
Other functions are specific to certain microbiota.
This is the case with the intestinal microbiota, which contains a plurality of bacteria that can produce vitamin K. Our body is incapable of producing it naturally.
It needs a source of this exogenous vitamin.
And it turns out that this vitamin is absolutely necessary to the blood clotting process.
So, as you have realized, microbiota and the bacteria they are made of are part of our physiological balance.
And like any physiological balance, it could be modified depending on the stimuli it receives.
The response to these stimuli from the microbiota will in turn have either a positive or negative effect on our body.
Now we can take another typical example, that is when there is a change in our biological cycles, to be more specific. Indeed, we are diurnal creatures.
We are active during the day, and at night, we are supposed to sleep.
We can consider that most of us have biological cycles of 24 hours.
There is evidence that this sequentiality is also found relative to the bacteria of the intestinal microbiota, with bacteria that are only present during daytime and disappear at night in sequential fashion, thus following our own biological cycle.
If we use an animal model such as a mouse and try to shift its biological cycle by 8 hours - roughly, the mouses are experiencing jet lag - what do we observe?
As you can see in red on the graph,
we found out that this sequentiality could be changed, with bacteria present during both daytime and nighttime, until it completely disappeared.
Now let's go a step further,
and imagine that this room represents part of the gut of a certain gentleman named TEDx.
So each of us is a potential bacteria of Mr TEDx's intestinal microbiota.
We know that this microbiota is made up of different bacteria.
Are there people in the room named Marie?
Yes.
Stand up please.
Are there people called Eric in the room?
Please stand up as well.
Yes, go ahead, stand up, this won't take long.
Now you can see that we have bacteria of the Marie group and bacteria of the Eric group.
They all reacted well to my stimuli.
I asked them to stand up and they did.
We're in the microbiota, we receive information.
The others remained seated.
We remain in a certain equilibrium, right?
Thank you for sitting down.
You see, they received a new stimulus and once again responded to it, by sitting down.
So I did that quickly since the bacteria that were seated behind them were starting to think, "What's going on?
Great, I can't see anything now!"
So you can see that, with this stimuli, everyone has different information.
Okay?
Now that was only in this particular microbiota.
We didn't ask Marie and Eric groups about their biological activities in our microbiota.
But we could also receive other stimuli that are outside of this room, or or least, outside of what exists inside here.
And indeed, you can see that the lights have started flickering.
This is no longer the same environment as in the previous equilibrium.
We could go even further, that is, we could have this time, for example, instead of a flickering light, total darkness.
We could continue this process in the same fashion until the organisation we had in this room at the beginning is totally disrupt.
We won't push up to the level of panic, but, you get the point.
So the stimuli we receive really depend on what is present in the microbiota and the bacteria found within that microbiota.
The purpose of all this staging was just to tell you that if microbiota is known today - we have characterized it, and we can attribute to it certain biological functions - there is still one piece of information that remains a mystery to us, and this is the communication channels and the different signals that are used from the microbiota to our organism, and from our organism to the microbiota.
So today, as a microbiologist who has worked on the microbiota for around 15 years, I would be unable to tell you whether or not there is a pilot in the microbiota.
However, I don't want to let you leave on such a negative note, but rather tell you that I will continue my research and that in the near future, we will definitely be able to answer this question.
(Applause)
Imagine we could treat the brain without prescription drugs.
There is a technology which is almost 100 years old now and which is about to revolutionize the field of neuroscience.
It all began with this man, Hans Berger.
In 1924, by placing electrodes on the heads of his subjects, he observed for the first time the electrical oscillations of the brain.
Electroencephalography was born.
Today, if you go to a hospital where this technique is used daily in order to diagnose psychiatric and neurological illnesses, you will perhaps be surprised to find that very little has changed since then.
Here’s how it goes.
A first specialist, as you see in this image, installs one by one, about 20 censors on the patient's head.
The signals are then amplified and recorded and a second specialist, typically a neurologist, interprets those signals that you see here.
To interpret them, he seeks out two important information.
Firstly, the frequency and amplitude of the electrical brainwaves reveal the level of brain activity.
We consider that high frequencies, meaning fast oscillations are associated with brain activity, and that slower oscillations are associated with resting state brain activity.
Now, the placement of the electrode reveals different regions of the brain.
Today, we can recognize about 50 of them and each one corresponds to a particular function.
By combining this information about brain function with their activation and deactivation, we obtain, thanks to electroencephalography, a very powerful tool for analyzing the brain.
But, you're going to say, "If it’s that powerful, why don’t we hear about it more?"
Your're right. That’s an excellent question and I'm going to answer it.
The first time I used this technique was nearly ten years ago.
Back then, I was director for a research project whose aim was to restore communication skills in patients affected by severe motor issues.
This concerns just a few dozen patients in France, but their need for medical help is obviously very significant.
With a group of French researchers, we decided to use a technique that was used in research labs, and developed for decades in labs all over the world, and in particular, in one lab here in Rennes, the INRIA.
We wanted to transfer this technique of brain-computer interfacing from research labs to patients' bedsides when it could be used.
Here are the results of that research project.
Here you see Michael, a patient who had a cerebrovascular accident, who uses a headset, a program and algorithms developed for this project, and who communicates “through thought.”
That alone was a major technical feat.
And yet, for me, after those five years of research, it was a major disappointment to see that in the end, patients do not use this technology.
They don’t use it because there are other tools, that are either simpler, more efficient or cheaper - such as, for example, eye-tracking which follows eyes movements- that allow them to do better.
Fortunately, that was not the end of the story. It did not end there
because the technology that was developed to meet the specific needs of this handful of patients later led to applications which helped a wider public.
And this caught the attention of manufacturers a few years ago and they are now revolutionizing neuroscience.
This revolution has been gathering pace over the last five years, thanks to two fundamental technological advances.
The first is the ability to measure brain activity.
We observe that since its creation in 1920, up to the early 2000's and in hospitals today, that this technology has made little progress.
Ten years ago in research laboratories, we had to use some kind of swimming cap with lots of wires attached, and we had to connected it to a box that cost tens of thousands of euros.
It was time-consuming, burdensome and very expensive.
Today in 2016, with a few hundred euros, we can make extremely accurate recordings of brain activity in any scenario possible.
Nowadays, concerning analysis, neuroscience like many other fields of medicine has benefited from the progress in artificial intelligence and applied maths.
Today, with this technology, we are able to automate procedures that in the past used to require the presence of an expert to interpret the results.
For example, we use a technique similar to the one used by geologists to find the epicenter of an earthquake.
This technique that use censors on the surface of the head, enables us to quantify with great precision the activity in more than a hundred or so regions of the brains.
Here’s what we obtain when we apply this technology in real time.
So, that’s the revolution in neuroscience in 2016.
It is the combining of a simple, efficient and cheap procedure that can be used by anyone anywhere and that is used with analytical tools that are both extremely powerful and completely automatic.
This technology is already here, so much so that across the world many businesses are preparing to sell products based on these two technological advances.
Here, you can see a pilot wearing an electroencephalographic headset and from his cerebral data, we can extract certain information about his level of alertness - is he falling asleep for example- about how much work his brain is doing - is he’s getting out of his depth? - and even about his stress level.
You can imagine to which extent the emergence of such a device is going to improve aviation safety.
But, that’s not all,
because what this technology promises goes far beyond that.
It offers the possibility to treat the brain without prescription drugs.
You’re probably thinking that treating brain injuries without drugs is definitely not something that's done everyday.
But, if you hurt your leg, and you go to see your doctor, he’s not automatically going to give you a pill to heal your leg.
He’ll probably send you to a physio.
And what will the physio do?
He’ll show you an exercise for muscle re-education
such as bending the knee, for example.
And you, from one session to the next, will practice this movement and try to accentuate it to re-educate and treat the muscles that need it.
That’s exactly what electroencephalography allows us to do using a technique known as "neurofeedback."
Today, there's an enormous amount of possible uses for neurofeedback.
Rather than giving you a long list of things it can do, I‘ll give you an idea of how real this already is with two devices invented and developed here in France, and that are about to be brought to market.
The first is a device for the general public that allows you to better manage your stress each day. How? Well, by giving an audio representation of the brain activity that is associated with relaxation.
Here’s how it works.
Here at the bottom, we can see the level of relaxation of the brain activity and the related movement in the music.
With daily use of this device, we can retrain regions of our brain to better handle daily stress.
The second application I wish to show you is a medical device I’m working on at the moment with a group of really talented engineers.
I would be curious to know how many of you know directly or indirectly, children affected by Attention Deficit Disorder with or without hyperactivity.
I see some people nodding and some raising hands.
So, there are a few.
It’s a condition that’s frequently misunderstood and misdiagnosed in France.
But it is estimated to affect one to two students per class, with a serious impact on their path through education, and serious problems in their home life.
Using neurofeedback, we let these students play a video game which adapts to the brain activity responsible for attention deficit, so that they can retrain it daily.
Here’s what it looks like.
On the top right corner, we have the current brain activity levels as recorded from the surface of the head.
Below, we have a real-time visualization of the brain activity associated with the attention deficit.
The child is asked to control this activity and to keep it within certain tolerance zones.
The child only sees the part on the left, the little fishing boat, and his mission is to catch fish.
He can only catch them when his level of inattention is kept below a certain threshold.
Clinical trials show that after about 30 sessions spread out over several weeks, the children who manage to control this brain activity show a lasting reduction of symptoms.
Some studies even show that this reduction can last up to two years after the treatment has stopped.
For these children and their families, electroencephalography with neurofeedback, can really make a difference in our time in 2016.
It constitutes a credible alternative to prescription drugs.
A drug or a pill that has to be taken twice daily, once in the morning and once in the afternoon, is a treatment which may continue into adulthood for several years, and which sometimes, unfortunately, has side-effects.
So that’s what electroencephalography can do right now, in 2016.
At the speed things are going, it’s hard to predict what exactly it will be doing in five or ten years.
However, I'm convinced of two things.
Firstly, this kind of devices will be increasingly offered to the public.
I hope you understand now that these are not toys and that they really do modify your brain activity.
So before using them, you may ask yourself, "Do I really want to change?"
Secondly, this technology will continue to improve and become more useful for those with rarer illnesses, especially those patients whose communication skills could always be improved.
Thanks for listening.
(Applause)
Hello, my name is Yasmine Berraoui.
I have Down's syndrome.
I want to start by asking you a question.
Who's wondering why I'm on stage?
Who's asking what a young girl with Down syndrome is doing onstage at TEDxCasablanca?
This question, "What am I doing here?"
was the biggest problem of my life.
Moreover, three weeks ago, a journalist was wondering if we should allow abortions in the case of a child diagnosed with trisomy.
Look over there.
Besides, since I was little, I've suffered from not having friends.
And the worst is that I didn't even understand why.
At the age of 13 year, I learned that I had trisomy when my parents let me know.
I had troubles understanding.
It's right that I have one chromosome more than you.
Look at the pair 21.
I'm like you. I've got two legs,
two arms, a brain, and a heart.
I received my high school degree in 2014 with honors. (Applause)
This awarded me being honored by His Majesty Mohammed VI.
I was also contacted by the press and trended on social media.
But I didn't get why.
(Applause) I don't feel handicapped.
Plenty of people say to themselves, "Oh, poor thing, she has Down syndrome. She is handicapped!
But don't forget I'm the one with an extra chromosome.
(Laughter) You're the ones missing something.
(Applause) Before I finish, I just wanted to say one thing. I don't feel handicapped. It's true.
People who think that someone
with Down syndrome can't do anything aren't open-minded for another world, a world in which differences are accepted to transform them into strengths, a world in which you prove to people with trisomy or to other children with special needs that they have a chance to live their dreams.
Well, I told the parents of children with special needs,
fight for them!
Really! Fight for them!
(Applause) Don't let them down!
They have the right to live their dreams.
And that's right for everyone.
And that is right for everyone.
Fight for them!
Honestly!
One need to know that there are numerous people with trisomy who are painters, cooks, or even actors.
I want to become a businesswoman.
But there are numerous professions accessible such as painter, laborer, or actor.

It's right. Well, I say, fight for them.
There are certain things needed to succeed.
I succeed because I work
just like everyone else.
Thank you. Have a great evening.
(Applause)
(Children's continuous cries and screams) Hello, I'm Nolwenn Febvre.
I'm a nurse anaesthetist at Rennes South University Hospital. These cries, unfortunately, can also be heard at times in the hospital!
One evening, after a hard day at work, on my way home, I thought, 'I can't bear hearing that any longer!
Maybe we can go about things differently, within the scope we have, and maybe effect some changes.'
I opened my laptop and I sent an e-mail to Moulin Roty, because I knew their cuddly toys. So I was: 'Could you help us?
Do you have any soft toys
just collecting in the corner?
Would you let us have them for the children we treat?'
And I clicked 'Send'.
Quite quickly I got an answer
from Amandine: 'OK, we'll send you a box.'
And I received a big box full of toys.
I took them to work with me
and gave them out in the recovery room to children who'd undergone surgery.
You could see smiles reappearing after the ordeal they'd gone through.
They felt worth something, they'd come through.
They went back to their parents with a little pride.
Then the box was empty.
Now what? What could we do?
We couldn't stop now, impossible!
I spoke to Loïc, did some things.
And, 'Yes, that's it!
We must create an organization!'
Create an organization. Why?
In order to have a bank account and raise funds to buy soft toys
for the children in our hospital. Because, well, in our hospital, there isn't much money. It's difficult enough getting walls repainted.
So, problems!
No way forward there.
So we said, 'Great, let's create an association!'
I spoke to Catherine about it at 2 am on night duty in the break room.
I said, 'Listen,
we've got to find a name.'
She said, 'The Cuddly Toys -
The Cuddly Soft Toys of the Rennes South Hospital.'
I registered the association, and we got going.
Claire joined us, and a bank account was opened.
Here we are, the association exists, we have soft toys - there's a big one behind me. I brought it with me today.
Laura gave it us.
She's a little girl.
It's our association's soft toy.
It symbolizes perfectly what we were looking for:
it's soft but it's still a tiger.
I guess you noticed.
And it has claws, because to get where we want we need claws.
To scrape the money together, we need to show our claws!
It's our mascot!
One day, I was with Charlotte in the operating area.
We chatted about recycling, the environment, changing behaviours to save the planet.
And suddenly I saw the cable
of an electric cautery knife, like this one, which is thrown away after each surgery.
It goes in the bin.
I said to myself, 'Maybe, there's something there worth having.
There must be some copper.
Copper, copper has scrap value.'
We got hold of it, cut it open, and found copper.
I made a quick calculation.
There are many operating rooms
in the hospital, and if everybody collected the electric cables after each surgery, it might not be a gold mine we were sitting on, but for sure a copper mine!
The message was passed on to everyone.
Something crazy happened.
They all started collecting the cables!
I take a week's vacation. I get back. All are saying, 'You know, there's loads in that equipment, and there, and there.'
And they give us boxfuls of electrical cable.
We recycled more than 2 tonnes of electrical cable.
It provided us with a realistic monthly budget for the soft toys.
We could buy soft toys not only for the children arriving as emergencies, but for all children undergoing operations.
The other day, a radiologist sent an envelope addressed to me.
I opened it, and inside I found this.
I thought, 'Great!'
Perhaps to you, it doesn't mean a lot.
But imagine that you, in this room, have something like that, and I'm sure you have something like it, or an old coffee-machine cable in your garage, perhaps. If you take it to the Delair recycling company and deposit it on our behalf, you can well imagine that, thanks to you, we'll be able to buy lots of soft toys.
We have an account there.
Feel free to help us!
Once we'd got all this going, we were quite satisfied, it was working well, the children were happy. But we could see that it was not entirely perfect.
Obviously, not least because Rennes South pays particular attention to such things, we wanted to improve things.
For sure there are many good-willed people who play their part.
We thought about the parents, for whom it's very hard to stand behind the opening operating area doors as their child departs to where they don't quite know, where they don't know exactly what's happening.
We thought it would be a good idea to change how this went on, to transform it into a game.
Perhaps it would be better for both parents and children.
We decide to try some things out.
With the big respirator we use in anaesthesia - Let me explain to you a little - Each child is given a mask –
at Rennes South, he's given it
at the initial consultation. We know it's very frightening for him when we place the mask over his face.
There's also the rather strange-smelling
anaesthetic gas. We said, 'What we'll try is: instead of lying him on the table and putting the mask on him, we'll let him take it himself and play with our respirator.'
Mariette came to us one day, and played with this respirator.
You can see her.
Nurse: When you breathe through the mask -
take the mask like this -
when you breathe through the mask, it will make yellow mountains.
Here, this figure goes up the higher the mountains are.
The goal is to break today's record,
which is - 28? - 28, today!
Nolwenn Febvre: It's a little lie, the 28.
Nurse: Sometimes it smells like chewing-gum or cola or strawberry.
Mariette: OK.
Nurse: The more deeply you breath, the higher your score, the sooner you go to sleep.
Are you ready?
Let's go.
Take the mask.
Hold on till we're ready.
Let's go.
You can look at the screen
at the same time.
Wow, you're starting very high. 15.
Going above 15.
Super, 28! You're a champion, Mariette.
NF: Eventually, we realized that if we let her do it, it was better for everyone,
better for us, better for her.
We know that her experience
will be a better one.
And I said to myself, 'We must go further, we must create a game, a treasure hunt, starting from the child's room, to the moment he goes to sleep.
We can change it all.
We'll give him a sheet of paper, so he can write things down.'
I went home. I saw my own children playing on a tablet,
and I thought: 'It's not paper we need! It's a tablet!'
Great. Problem solved!
I went on the Internet to search for an app.
If you look for an app you get 15 results.
I typed.
I found becoming a surgeon playing on a tablet,
also becoming a nurse,
caring for dinosaurs,
extracting teeth.
But I got stuck:
For being a hero in hospital there was no app.
I kept searching.
I knew that in Quebec, they were doing great things in paediatrics.
I found nothing.
One morning, I said to the association, 'Listen, I have an idea: we'll develop it.
Sure, we're trained hospital staff, we can do it! Easy!'
I had lunch with my friend Paola.
She's a teacher.
We do different things.
We all exchange ideas with one another.
I said to her,
'I've an idea.
We need to create a video game, but I work in anaesthesia, not games programming.'
She said, 'I'll talk to my brother-in-law, that's his area.
He knows Benjamin.'
So Benjamin calls me.
Benjamin is a designer in Bordeaux.
I explain the game to him.
He says, 'Yes, that's possible.
No problem.
A video game sort of like a treasure hunt.
No worry, quite doable.'
Great! Someone believed in our project.
I browsed the web, and found a corporate foundation called B. Braun, a medical equipment firm, that was calling for projects.
I read the rubric.
'A project to improve a child's experience during their hospital stay, fun and reproducible'.
Incredible!
(Laughter) Magic, that's us!
So, what next?
We described our situation to them.
We submitted a file.
Next we're in Paris with David, Claire, Laurence,
and we win first prize!
We come back to Rennes, remotivated. We were right: some experts in Paris did believe in us,
they think it's worthwhile, and they will help us.
David from our association speaks to Olivier who works at NIJI,
and we meet with Frédéric in a café.
He says to us, 'Two NIJI computer specialists are ready to help you develop the game.'
Jean-Charles and Thomas contact Benjamin and we sit around a table
to discuss together the real world of anaesthesia and how it can be virtualized.
We ask the nurses about the difficulties they're facing, the porters about the moment parents are separated from their children, and we think about the child's arrival in the operating room.
We put together all our different experiences, all our difficulties in our different domains, merge them, and create a video game.
We'd made it, the video game!
This game is about applying
a blood-pressure cuff.
It's a bit difficult:
children don't like it, it's invasive.
The more it tightens, the more he hits the iPad screen.
Great scores are achieved!
(Laughter)
They forget about the cuff. The fish were offered to us by 'A l'Aise Breizh'. They're fixed on our corridor walls,
and we've integrated them into the game.
All elements of the journey, all the way to the mountains we saw with Mariette, are transformed into a game with those beautiful pictures of mountains and fish.
Parents are also integrated into the game.
We take a photo of them when they first arrive in the hospital.
The child then, at some time, finds his parents' photo in a treasure box. It's a little as if his parents were still there.
Here are some pictures of our game, the game we created for our children.
It's really rather nice.
There are lovely colours.
But I must stop it now, because I am a nurse anaesthetist, and I'm not here to play.
More than 4,000 children undergo surgery in Rennes each year.
A surgical operation can be very distressing;
it can have long-term effects on the child's life.
Six months after their operation, 20% of children are still suffering from post-operative behavioural problems:
trouble with sleep, nightmares, developmental regression.
It's imperative to take all these delayed effects into account, they must never be neglected.
We need to act from the first instance to avoid this traumatization.
Very often, it's their first taste of hospital.
They're kids.
It may not be their last, I hope it will be, but you never know.
But we must act from the outset.
Hence the importance of working with kids.
It's all grand and beautiful, but we are a non-profit association.
We are all volunteers.
We do it on top of our jobs. We are aware that it can reduce hospitalization time, improve lots of things, premedication for example.
If we give them fewer drugs, there will be fewer side-effects. They'll be able to leave hospital sooner, get home sooner, and post-operative behavioural disorders will decrease.
So I insist, we must not ignore the impact of side-effects due to medication, they are not to be overlooked.
When they are painful, we know the pain is only worsened by anxiety.
There's a true relationship.
We must act on the anxiety to reduce the increased pain and administer fewer painkillers which give rise to nausea and vomiting, which is very uncomfortable for the children.
So our goal, beyond the game, which has proved a success, is first of all to improve the experience of children and their parents when they come to hospital.
Well, it seems a little unreal to me to stand here today.
I'm a nurse anaesthetist.
My life now, from my personal standpoint, it's crazy!
All my time is taken up.
As head of the association 'The Cuddly Soft Toys of the Rennes South Hospital',
I expend a lot of time and energy with its other members.
The personal experience, it's crazy.
I've met people: Régis, Frédéric, Jean-Charles, Thomas, Amandine, Laura, all these people, Claire, David, Laurence, Catherine, Séverine, all those who came to the association with their different experiences, making their contribution.
So that's where we are today,
and I'm here representing everyone.
It's just something worth making part of one's life, being aware that all these things can be done and put to use together!
Now, I'm also a mum.
Sometimes I feel guilty not being at home.
Let me tell you a short story:
One day I left work late and took the by-pass only to arrive at the school just before it was about to close. My son Youenn greets me with a huge smile on his face.
He says to me, 'Mummy, mummy, guess what? My friend Louis, he's had an operation. The hospital gave him some sort of soft toy!
He's got this cute toy!'
And he added, 'And I knew why he got it!'
I could read in his smile how satisfied and proud he was. I thought, 'This is pure gold!
There's more than just copper;
there's gold too!
(Laughter) My son smiling, children smiling, it warms my heart, and I'm sure that we did the right thing. And if there's one thing you, everyone, should remember, it's:
Just dare to do something!
I just dared to send an e-mail, one day,
I dared -
as simple as that - and we have achieved all this.
You can see the accomplishment?
And being here with you today, wow! It's so great!
Thank you.
(Applause)
When was the last time you felt free?
Really free.
This idea that our lives' outlines are probably wider than what we can imagine.
The idea, for example, that we always have time to do things.
That is rare.
Or that our bodies move freely.
The idea of freedom where absolutely everything is possible.
That is a subject that has always inspired me, and that is why I have lived in a zen monastery for 15 years.
There, I learned a lot, in particular thanks to zen master Oliver Wang-Genh.
It would take an entire TEDx for me to tell you how I barged in everything that happened; living in a monastery is something really peculiar.
But today, I mostly want to share with you three key lessons.
Three significant experiences that allowed me to find some kind of inner peace.
I called the first lesson, "The little bird from the Rising Sun."
That's my poetic side!
The story takes place in Japan where I threw myself, head first, in the adventure of a traditional zen retreat.
It was in 2008, I landed in Nagoya, in a nuns monastery from which, according to the legend, most of Western nuns leave as soon as they arrive.
As a matter of fact, the conditions are very ascetic.
There is no modern comfort.
There is no hot water, you do everything with cold water, my hands are going to discover what crevices and frostbites are.
It is the middle of winter, and there is no heating.
Lots of promiscuity among people, we have a 10 square meters room shared by six or seven people.
Sustained activity all day long.
That is not that kind of zen, but it goes extremely fast!
All of it happening in Japanese, a language I only understand from Knights of the Zodiac.
(Laughter) I am a bit lost there.
That is the aim of this very precious lesson: push us to the limits until we have to let go.
After three weeks, my letting go is that I am fed up, this is too much!
One morning, in this monastery, all on my own, with no contact with Europe, I decide to leave.
That day, in me, is a huge disappointment.
I had put so much hope in this journey.
And here I am, with knots in my stomach.
I gather my stuff in the room, I am on my own.
At some point, I look up, like that.
Through the window, I notice a branch, covered in snow, and on top of it, a little bird.
It is so... delicate!
It is so beautiful!
It shakes itself to smooth its feathers.
And for me, at that moment, the feeling of resentment and disappointment gives way to awe as I face its magnificence!
A wave of tenderness comes rushing from deep within.
What if that was the teaching I had traveled 10,000 kilometers for?
Feelings and thoughts, in general, are impermanent.
They appear, and can also disappear.
One moment there is anger, the next there is awe as I face the magnificence of the world.
I think we all have experienced it during our daily lives.
For example at work, one colleague annoys us, we are in conflict, we dwell on it, then if we get a call from a friend who tells us a joke, all of a sudden, we burst out laughing.
This ability is the first lesson: feelings are impermanent, a little bird told me.
The second lesson is a bit different; I called it, "What's in my head?"
I won't tell you everything!
(Laughter) It is this idea that for feelings to appear, and more importantly disappear, we shouldn't dwell on them.
In general, we tend to get relive it.
Something happens that we don't like, and then we brood.
We all kind of work that way, that's natural.
But in order to stop brooding, we need to understand, to realize what we are doing!
And so, we need to know better what is inside our heads.
What's in my head?
I experienced it once when I was seated, mediating, as Buddha, peacefully - I could not do it - and at that moment, the master said, "Let your thoughts and feelings pass by as clouds in the sky."
It was beautiful, and it made me terribly angry!
Because my feelings were not "some small, peaceful misty clouds in a deep blue sky," but rather some big, black, dense cumulonimbus that tended to stagnate.
I looked like a peaceful Buddha, but on the inside, I was seething.
I was really motivated to achieve it, so I studied a lot, and today, I want to allow you to save some time.
(Laughter) I would like to propose a small exercise, right now.
Are you OK with that?
Audience: Yes!
KT: Sit comfortably in your chairs.
That is a short moment of relaxation.
You will be able to study, to discover with passion what is in your heads and in your bodies.
Now close your eyes.
Focus on the contact between your body and the chair.
Become aware that you are here, seated, in this room, at this moment: that is the present moment.
Where are we right now?
Then, you can explore, become Indiana Jones in your mind.
I will guide so that you know what forms your thoughts can take.
You might have thoughts in the form of pictures, as a movie that takes place inside of you, or light that flashes, or a memory of the place where you are, or of the person who is currently speaking.
That is called a visual mental representation.
For other people, there might be sounds.
And what we call "the little voice in your head."
Sometimes, it is talkative, it is a little voice that comments, tells, analyzes, says parts of sentences, and sometimes sings on the inside.
The little voice in the head, that is the inner dialogue.
What's in your head?
Pictures?
A little voice?
The last form of thinking is called kinesthetic, this is all the feelings we have in our bodies.
For example, hot, cold, the contact with the chair, heavy, light.
But also the all range of emotions that we feel in our bodies.
Joy, anger, sadness, and the rest.
Three possible form of thinking.
In one moment, you will open your eyes, and you will know more about how you function inside.
Do you mostly see pictures, hear a little voice, feel emotions,
or a physical sensation, and so on?
This is really pleasant, but... You can now open your eyes!
You have new knowledge
about yourself, that's a first step.
This is interesting to know, because you can better observe your functioning.
Each one of you can do it at any moment during the day.
Then, there was the third lesson.
I discovered it by chance.
I called it, "the periscope," you will soon find out why.
I discovered it earlier on, in 2003.
In 2003, I was performing in French music concerts for American people, in front of audiences of around 150 or 200 people.
During the first concert, I got on stage, like that, exactly like tonight, but I didn't have the same clothes or the same haircut.
(Laughter) Then I start singing in that repertoire, and then... stage fright!
My legs are shaking, my heart is pounding, all the symptoms of stage fright appear all of a sudden.
Fortunately, at that time, I already meditated a lot.
As all of this occurred, some kind of observing conscience appeared
spontaneously and automatically.
What I mean is, I am singing, I feel the stage fright inside of my body, some symptoms.
And at the same time, there is a conscience that allows me to keep my head above water.
My head is free,
I can go on with my concert.
Imagine, I start singing
and then stage fright.
(Sings "La vie en rose") And at the same time, it is observing.
That is the witness-conscience, the observing conscience.
It observes the feeling and, as it is observed - it's magical! -
the feeling eases off!
You just have to observe it for the unpleasant feelings to gradually appear, and then naturally disappear, like what I was telling you in the beginning.
I called it "the periscope."
You all know the Grey rod, that is on top of submarines, that can come out of water, like a duck, to observe the landscape.
With that kind of conscience, we are both in and out of the water, we are both connected and dissociated from the experience, both inside and outside.
This means that we are very alive, we feel things completely, because we do not want to become robots!
But our heads are free and we feel relief deep inside of us.
This was the third significant event of the past few years.
The first: feelings appear and disappear naturally.
The second: we can know what form our thoughts and feelings take:
visual, auditory - the little voice in the head - or kinesthetic - the sensations of the body.
The third: it is possible to discover this wonderful observing conscience, witness-conscience, that allows us to be present and fully free.
Isn't it neat?
(Laughter) It is not over yet!
To conclude, I want to propose a small ritual for the day.
Or rather a small ritual for the morning, as morning is a key moment, that will allow you to implement, or even incarnate these three things in one exercise.
Are you up for it?
Audience: Yes!
KT: Imagine yourself in the morning.
The alarm goes off.
Generally, you snooze it, once, twice... And at some point, you have to get up.
At that point, what I propose is, either while lying down, or you might sit on the side of the bed, what I propose that can change lives is to become aware of your first thought in the morning!
That's it.
Is it a picture, a little voice in your head, a feeling, or a sensation in your body?
Then do it with the second and the third thoughts.
At that moment, naturally, you will change your habits; you will become aware of this hum, this windmill in your head.
What is wonderful is that, at this point, you get up, not as a robot anymore, going to the coffee machine, not fully awake.
You get up mindful!
You find this freedom inside of you again.
Not as a robot anymore, but as an actor of your daily life.
This is the source - trust me - of an immense inner relief.
And you know that during the day to come, everything is possible!
(Applause)
Have you ever been confronted by two conflicting and shocking images on the Internet or in a magazine?
On the one hand, there is too much food, and that adds to what are often unhealthy food choices, with plenty of between-meal snacks.
As a result, the number on the scale creeps up and then there are all sorts of diets supposedly to to burn the extra calories, diets that can be very expensive.
Eating too many calories distorts the shape of the body, wears out the joints and the heart, and can lead to potentially life-threatening illnesses.
On the other hand, not getting adequate calories ultimately leads to the deaths of many men, women and children, through the long and painful experience of starvation.
What can we do?
This question already preoccupied me when I was working as a doctor in different hospitals.
Then, years later, when I became a pastor,
I was wondering what can be done?
Let’s take a closer look.
The numbers speak for themselves.
Each year, according to recent data, which of course is an estimate, approximately 36 million people die because of not enough food. And each year, 29 million people die from the consequences of eating too much.
This situation is paradoxical.
It is scandalous.
What can we do?
What some have tried to do is reduce the amount of excess calories by eating more reasonably and reducing food waste.
On the other side, some have tried to bring aid to those in the greatest need, by making donations.
What I am proposing today is another approach, in which “excess” and “lack” are brought together in an effort to reduce excess, to remedy as far as possible what is lacking, with the aim of restoring a balance in which everyone wins.
Give the gift of calories for life, take part in the fight against hunger, and feel better.
Save lives without having to pay a penny more than usual!
Concretely, it involves replacing one meal per week, preferably an evening meal, and of giving the amount of money equal to what you would have spent on this meal to a charity of your choice that is acting effectively to fight hunger and malnutrition.
The simple idea of giving up one meal, of limiting ourselves, can make us uncomfortable, but it is also true that when we give a gift to someone, we don’t feel it damages or frustrates us.
Gifts give pleasure to the person who receives them, but also to the person who gives.
Concretely, the night of the week that I go to bed without having eaten dinner, on an empty stomach which is rumbling in protest, with my belly asking to be fed and afraid of hunger pangs, I am actually not hungry … I have a craving to eat, and that is something completely different.
And when I have that craving, I think differently to those who are truly hungry, who will be hungry tomorrow and in the weeks to come, until they die of hunger.
That calls on us to empathize.
There is a feeling of “compassion,” of “suffering with” with those who have been literally condemned to death.
The next days?
Well, the morning after, there is already a nice surprise: I am not really very hungry at all.
I wake up ready for the day, body and soul.
Afterwards, I become more aware of how I eat.
I find I am able to avoid certain habits, such as eating a big bag of chips in one sitting, while watching a game on TV.
Bit by bit, I get out of the trap in which we believe that we can ease the little annoyances, frustrations and worries of everyday life by stuffing ourselves with excessive amounts of food.
And then I become more aware of the quality of what I eat.
My plate is filled with food that is precious.
I know that it’s not to be taken for granted, that it’s not automatic.
Since the dawn of time, humans have put all of their energy and strength into making sure they have enough to eat, day after day.
The way in which we nourish ourselves, on this planet, says something about our community, how we live together.
Do I eat alone, all by myself?
Do I share with others?
This is a spiritual question for each of us.
For me, as a Christian, it is an urgent question. What is the meaning, when we recite the Lord’s Prayer, of the words, “Give us this day our daily bread”?
It’s certainly different from saying “Give me the bread I need every day”.
There is a communal aspect to asking that there be enough food for every member of God’s family.
What if we were to believe that God is counting on us to take care of each other? Do not we risk being crushed by the extent of these needs?
For myself, I put my trust in Jesus Christ, who can take any little bit that is given freely and joyously and make it grow and multiply far beyond our wildest imaginings.
I’d also like to add this: if, by giving up one meal per week, you were able to save one person, or even a whole family, what would keep you from starting today?
What a privilege it is to be able to do something concrete yourself, without relying on government decisions or slow-moving institutions.
It only depends on us and we can start immediately.
There are people from all sorts of social situations who take up this proposal, saying, “It’s wonderful to be able to do something that matters, without having to pay even a penny more than I would otherwise”.
And there are people of all ages, young and old, who tell me how happy they are to give this gift.
Their inner joy keeps them motivated to continue, week after week.
That is what allows them to keep on over the long term.
They have seen that one person’s “loss” can really be another’s gain!
Easing the suffering of those who are hungry while simultaneously feeling better yourself, that’s an experience worth having and sharing with others!
And so, I’d like to invite you to give the gift of calories to save lives!
(Applause)
Communicate is natural.
A few weeks ago, when you bought tickets to come to our talk, you expressed the need to communicate with us.
To put it simply, raise your hand if you have spoken to someone today?
(Laughter) Even if it was just to your dog or cat.
(Laughter) Anne-Christophe is research director at the CNRS.
For several years, she has been studying the cognitive development of new-born babies and has found that from birth, a child wants and knows how to communicate.
Scientists or not, all of us can therefore agree to say that humans have an innate need and ability to communicate.
Why is it that something that comes spontaneously and naturally to us at birth becomes so complicated and loaded with conflicts when we grow up?
Let me tell you a story.
I spent part of my childhood in Africa where my parents raised me and my brothers.
My parents loved and still love Africa deeply and viscerally, and they wanted to give us a childhood out of the ordinary and an exceptional life experience. I think they delivered on that pretty well.
Indeed, we used to spent our weekends observing hippos that were bathing in the river and roaming in the bush.
My pet was a fanged deer and my neighbor was a monkey!
(Laughter) However, the finest lesson Africa taught me was an exceptional life lesson that is a thousand miles away from all that!
Let's go back to the 1980s. We are living in the deepest bush; my father grows sugar cane.
To do so, he employs many people including the so-called "cane cutters."
They come to join the team at harvest time.
My father often worries about these families' precarious situation. He doesn't understand why his own children are healthy while others in the neighboring villages are dying.
One day, MSF contacted my father and told him: "We are coming to your area."
My father, very excited, invites them to spend a day in the factory.
I should point out that we lived 200 km from the nearest hospital.
So he could never have hoped to be able to offer free healthcare to his team.
He prepares everything and says to all: "Come with your wive and children, everyone will be treated and vaccinated for free!"
The big day arrives, my father is really excited. The doctors are here but nobody show up. Nobody come to see the doctors!
Before long, it was time for MSF to leave. My father rushes off to see his team.
"I don't understand! What happened?

Why did nobody come?"
And then, a guy says to my dad: "You know, boss, I'll probably have during my life time eight or ten children.
Of those eight or ten children, one or two will die ...
That's how it goes.
That's life.
God decides.
If you ask the doctors to come, they will vaccinate all of them.
But I don't know if I have the means to feed them all."
My father was shocked, as you surely feel today.
This story is horrible!
But perhaps not so much, if one agrees that everything is a matter of viewpoint.
My father's problem was to think that his situation was the same as others'. It was to think that he had identified the right problem and that, therefore, he had the right solution.
That day, I learnt that we always want to impose our ways of thinking and working.
We are always convinced we have the right response, the knowledge.
But, most of the time, we are mistaken.
At work for example: how many times do we find ourselves having communication issues ?
I have been a retail manager for the last 20 years.
My function is to market items appropriately so that you, the consumers, would want to buy them.
I remember that several years ago, I had a task. It was to build a wall of flip-flops!
(Laughter) No, no, it was very important, let me tell you! Let me reassure the novice:
you don't need a diploma in merchandising to build a wall of flip-flops!
So I entrusted it to one of my executives and his team,
thinking the job was really simple, and I thought no more of it.
However, after a few days, the project remained incomplete, no end result to be seen!
So I went back to see my executive and asked him, "Were you clear enough about what you wanted?"
"Yes." he answered.
"- Did you really explain everything?
- Of course.
- Did you go back to explain it again and why there's no progress?
- Yes, yes, I've done all of that.
- How did you explain it again?
- The same as I did the first time."
That said it all.
My manager had taken for granted that the person to whom he had entrusted the job would have the same perspective on the situation as him and the same understanding of the work to be done.
The problem was: summer only lasts for six weeks in Quebec, and I was already supplied with winter jumpsuits while my flip-flops still didn't get sold.
The problem my manager just had, was to think he knew what the other person was thinking.
He had forgotten that a vital part of a good communication when we want to convey information is to accept that another person may have a different view on the situation and above all, that this difference can prevent him from carrying out his task properly.
You might be saying to yourselves: "Well, I wouldn't fall into that trap."
When you came in here, you were handed a piece of paper.
Yes, now you're going to understand why.
I'm going to ask you to please pick up that piece of paper.
(Paper rustling) We're going to do a short exercise, very simple.
I'm going to ask you to listen to the instructions.
First, you'll close your eyes, and do the tasks I'll give you without talking or asking questions.
Let's go!
I'm going to ask you to fold the paper in half.
(Paper rustling) Turn the paper to the right. Fold it in half again.
Rip the top right corner.
Turn the paper to the left.
Rip the top left corner.
One last time, fold the paper in half again.
And finally, rip the bottom right corner.
It's hard, isn't it!
The paper is really folded tight. (Laughter) Now open your eyes, unfold your paper and hold it above your head so that everyone can see it.
(Laughter) There are some very beautiful creations over there, fantastic!
(Laughter) I have some questions for you.
Did you find the exercise complicated?
Was the terminology too elaborate?
Did the task require a particular qualification?
No!
So why so many differences?
Because it's all about perception!
This exercise is the proof that, even in the same situation, we all have a different viewpoint.
And accepting this difference is already a step towards a better communication.
I wish to tell you one final story that happened to my grandfather.
Back in the 1940s. My grandparents are living in Africa,
(Laughing) Already. Famine and drought were raging at that time.
One day, my grandfather is called to be a juror in a trial, a trial for cannibalism.

That's right, cannibalism!
The old man on trial that day had to explain why he had eaten his child.
This is what he said, "We didn't have anything left to eat.
My son was dead and I decided to eat him so I could survive, so I could save the rest of my family, the rest of my village.
If I hadn't done it, we would all be dead.
Somehow, because he died, he helped us. He helped his family."
This story is horrible, indefensible, unspeakable!
I still ask myself how my grandfather, this man of incredible kindness, managed to make a legal judgment on a situation fraught with a great injustice.
This example, this experience really proves that communication can be hopeless, devoid of end, impossible, irreversible.
My grandfather had no choice but we, ourselves, we've millions of opportunities every day to change the way we communicate, by accepting the other person's perspective.
What Africa taught me on that day is that we always want to impose our viewpoints, our experiences, our ways of operating things, spoiling the essential stage of a good communication that is the acceptance of differences in people's perception.
To accept those differences is to accept that a problem may have several answers, a story and several endings.
It's accepting that an exchange might not quite happen as we expected it.
It's accepting that we can be wrong.
Perhaps should we learn again how to communicate?
TEDx teaches us to share ideas, but why not learn first how to respect them?
Thank you.
(Applause)
(Music) (Applause) Sport and entertainment.
What we just played, - sorry, I am a little out of breath, it's a bit sporty anyway - This is really a metaphor, it's a little... it's me.
It's me because the ingredients the instruments I use, the modes, the scales on which I travel, from which I draw my inspiration, come from around the world.
They are 20th and 21st century instruments, so fairly recent instruments and they each have a link to cultures or to a scale or to an approach which obviously touches me, talks to me.
So I'll explain very briefly the story we've just told you.
So first, very importantly, there are my friends, the frogs.
In the past 30 years I've been recording frogs toads, crickets and they are still on my albums at some point, or in my concerts.
So there they are.
Then I made a small introduction on a contemporary instrument called the Zenco, (Music) I continue, there are gongs ah, a little nod to jazz with a Berber broom a Berber kitchen broom, I've been using them for 30 years as a musician for a lot of different things.
They can be shorter, longer, but I like them, it's earthy, and it allows me to make beautiful climates and sometimes to go towards jazz or 4/4 stuff.
And then, my comrade, Charles Lucas, who was just there, designer, carpenter, musician, bassist and great musical companion, had created a kind of sky, a sort of thing above us, that in any case, I like very much when I'm building something emotional. And then I carried on with a little melody on spacedrums, those instruments are in fact the counterpart of the hang,
which we will see later, a Swiss instrument, so a little melody, with a small bridge a romantic bass, a small bridge... you may remember, I do because I was forced to learn by heart, There is a little romantic phrase on bass behind which I spacialise with a bow on bells, a Burmese bell, in space somehow, like that, a cymbal I had cracked but that can still be used - Recycling, it's important: I made a kind of strange gong out of it - And then I dived on an instrument I really like, I've been working on for many years which is a French instrument the crystal organ, the glass organ.
I wanted to explain, anyway, the fact that it speaks of locations it's about people, it's about places, it's about what inspires me, the others, discovering...
I was not prepared for this at all in my life.
Everything was off to a bad start.
I was born on an island that no longer exists, Yes, it can happen.
So I was born there, in Virginia, and I went here and there, in military forts, and I was unlucky to be raised by an ultra, mega, extremely, horribly, cruelly violent, racist man... but then, with lots of 's' in racist - I'm exaggerating!
No, I'm not exaggerating, because it was with the Ku Klux Klan.
Yes, it exists. It was in the years...
quite some time ago.
He was with the Ku Klux Klan so at the weekend, his brother and him would go on the continent to have fun with crosses or lighters, well it was creepy.
And so he was not a man who liked the others very much, he didn't like differences much.
In any case, he was so nervous and unhappy and so not loving he even took me out of school because in my class, there was a black kid I had befriended.
So he came to beat me in front of everyone, he withdrew from school, so until the age of 10, I was on a small island Florida, it's idyllic, it's magic, well, a priori, but I didn't go to school, and it was frankly a bit, a tad boring, to be polite.
But in the distance, there were freighters passing by, and every night there were DC3 - Douglas aircraft, twin engine, you've ever seen that in Tintin maybe sometimes you can still see some.
Postale, Air France, they had it, a fabulous airplane.
And there was a squad, an aircraft squadron, 3 aircraft, the Mosquito Squad, that skimmed the islands - I was in the Keys, perhaps I forgot to tell you - And they skimmed the houses dumping - I thought it was great, I had not been told what it was, maybe it suited my stepfather-- it was DDT!
But the crazy thing is, I was waiting for them!
The music of the twin engines of the DC3 it's still in my head! In any case, it was the only escape.
But there was a miracle: suddenly, they decided to abandon me, youpie, thank you, thanks!
The greatest gift of my life, I'm telling you!
From there, I was a bit tossed here and there, and I was taken to France.
Yeah, great!
Well, winter in November, I didn't quite understand, but youpie anyway.
From Florida to the suburbs of Paris... but they were very humble very loving people, very simple, workers, so it was interesting!
I found myself in a completely different context, world, you had to learn very quickly.
I still had in mind to understand, to keep on traveling, and I was a little early.
And the music came suddenly, because there was no music at home - it was forbidden, or I don't remember, maybe in the car, sometimes... - But then suddenly all at once!
The Beatles!
The Beatles, you can never get tired of them, it's so inventive and brilliant!
And without necessarily understanding, but Coltrane, Joao Gilberto, Edith Piaf... What could appeal to me there?
There was a trick!
There was a pain.
And I probably recognized that pain coming from somewhere, that I was trying to tame.
It has aroused a lot of musical sense in me, I traveled everywhere, Europe Yougoslvavia, Greece, Turkey and all that, and so on.
And then there was Denmark. I thought, well, that's interesting.
I must say that my generation, we had conscription in the USA, the Vietnam war, I had been brought up by the military, salute to the flag every morning, etc. so I had it coming. and I should go and light a candle: Nixon, February 1974, decided to change the conscriptive Law so I didn't have to go anymore, that was awesome.
But there was only one country in Europe that -- you never know, it can change -- welcomed deserters, it was Sweden.
And this for me, was a gift, really.
Because I could finally be legal, learn avidly absolutely everything!
Catch up with everything, hey, it's true, I don't belong, maybe I'm resilient, but I have a thirst for learning and discovering which boosted me and then everything changed in my life, there was music in force, any job, I could suddenly become a truck driver, a teacher with real, false documents, it was awesome!
Really!
And I returned to France purely by accident, it took a long time to get the papers and all that, because it's not easy to be undocumented in France even for an American.
I assure you.
I'd say especially for an American!
"Ah, if he has no family, no address...
Where's your mother?"
"Uh, I dunno."
"Your father? "
"Well... " (Laughs)
"Stepfather?"
"Oh! Look!
So, no, no!"
It will not be easy.
But in any case, a teacher introduced me to French, I really enjoyed learning it, I devour books, I love, I continue, I travel, I became a pilot, the DCS3, whoopee, It's true, I compose, I make albums, years with the Tuaregs years in Indonesia, years traveling on, and now it's an honor to be here with you. We learn through others. Without the others, I am nothing.
I realized that in this life, you never know who, on your way, could save you, I assure you this is true. I was saved much helped much, I was given a lot to learn, and here I was given the chance to be with you, and I thank you from the bottom of my heart.
Thank you.
(Applause)
I was born in Kabul, Afghanistan's capital.
And at the time, that was Kabul.
Today, I invite you to travel with me, just for a few moments, the time to cross the centuries --
But I did not come alone, because I invite you to travel with Attar, a mystic poet of Persian language, my mother tongue.
A long time ago, around the 13th century, that poet wrote a very powerful text: The Conference of the Birds.
In this collection of poems, the birds are a symbol of the human soul and they want to find their queen, the Simorgh, a bird in Persian mythology that lives on Mount Qaf. Obviously, finding the Simorgh was a pretext to understand the meaning of life, of their existence.
And that's how they start their initiatory journey.
An initiatory journey is a journey like any journey, it is a passage.
Whether you travel inside yourself or you change continents, you will never come back unscathed...
Crossing borders, these arbitrary lines that change through time, change us and change the fate of so many people worldwide.
Yes, nowadays, being born in Kabul is not the same as being born in Paris. Or as Amin Maalouf, the French-Lebanese writer said, being a woman in Kabul, is not exactly the same as being a woman in Oslo...
The journey of the birds in Attar's poem begins in the 13th century.
Mine began in October, 1994. I was barely 13 years old, barely --
But there is a fundamental difference between these two journeys because the birds of Attar's poem choose to leave, to search, find their queen and return to their homeland.
For me, leaving was not a choice, It was the last, the only solution.
My mother, my father, my sisters and my brother, we had to leave and we went elsewhere leaving behind many things, perhaps even the hope to be able to come back someday.
Because exile is not just leaving one's body behind, as alleged by Ovid.
Exile is also leaving one's words, one's gestures, one's look and joy behind, as Atiq Rahimi, the French-Afghan writer said.
But let's come back to Attar's birds.
Attar's birds are all the birds of the world that gathered to cross the Seven Valleys of Love and meet the Simorgh Divinity.
Only thirty of them succeed.
Because those that did not have the courage to continue had abandoned their quest.
In fact, do you know what Simorgh means in Persian?
"Si Morgh" means "thirty birds".
These thirty birds that manage to accomplish their initiatory journey find out that the deity Simorgh was the reflection of their own image.
That is to say the very subject of their quest, the Simorgh, was already in them and they needed a progress to finally see it.
As for me, I crossed borders first inside my hometown, Kabul, then a second time in 1994, to Iran; and finally a third time in 2003 to France.
Thirteen years after my arrival in France, that is to say today, the images of migrants take me back and remind me of the hardships of that long journey into exile.
Because exile is only a consequence.
But the consequence of what?
We think about war, famine, dictatorship.
But I wonder why these wars, why these famines, why these dictatorships?
In fact, I wonder if life was a journey a flight to somewhere else, and we all birds, for which destinations to which would we like to leave to?
What world would we like to build for ourselves and for the future generations?
If you had the choice, would you choose war, famine, dictatorship?
I think we all dream of a better world.
And some people make it the best every day.
Let me tell you a personal anecdote.
Two years after my arrival in France, I had to enroll in a high school to take the baccalaureate exam.
I met the headmaster, Michèle, a lady I really appreciate very much.
I told her I wanted to pass the bac, then go to university to become a teacher, which I am today.
That day, she had listened to me and told me simply: "Yes, you can do it."
These five words (yes, you, can, do, it) changed my life in a way.
Because that day, I had the feeling of finally being at home somewhere.
Eleven years later, that is to say today, I wonder what I can do in my turn, what we can do so that exile doesn't have to be a conclusion, so that hope doesn't die.
In this room, I was told that you are more than eight hundred.
That's a lot.
It's a bit more than the number of exiles who perished in a shipwreck only on April, 20th.
In fact, the thirty birds that manage to complete their initiatory journey discover that the deity was the reflection of their own image.
What about us?
What about us?
Does the world we live in really reflects what we are?
(Applause)
Good evening everyone.
Let me reassure you about my mental health, I'm not suffering from the senile squalor syndrome.
The reason I'm here this evening?
Well, let me give you a hint : they've already announced the subject.
It's that I'm both a photographer and a very bad cook combined.
By the way, having heard the last speaker, I should have taken a little more care of my microbiome.
It turns out that I owe my nutritional survival to the consumption of a famous French brand of frozen ready-made meals but decency prevents me from naming it.
I made it the basis of my diet for almost 10 years.
And one day, stupidly, I just forgot to take out my trash can.
That day, I realized that I'd generated an astronomical amount of waste.
So I started to look into the matter and I realized that this waste had a twofold cost:
the cost at the time of buying the product, and a second one, at the time of throwing it away, collecting it, and recycling it.
Thus, after pondering about this issue, I decided to take on a challenge by doing a series of photographs on this topic.
So from that day, I didn't throw away any of my recyclable waste for four years.
I want to clarify that I've been helped. Indeed, I wasn't the only consumer of all the products photographed.
In fact, 200 friends and colleagues lent a hand to help me complete my “waste-collection”.
Nowadays, in France and in most Western countries, our garbage disappears from sight weekly.
It's collected every week, and we do not have to manage ourselves this astronomical amount.
When we look at the numbers, in most cases, waste is discussed in figures.
Here is a data from the Environment and Energy Management Agency (ADEME): in 2014, we threw away 324 million tons of waste.
It's inconceivable!
Even if you could find an equivalent to it in a number of football fields or Eiffel Towers, it would remain something abstract.
So I thought that the strength of a photo laid precisely in putting an image on this problem.
As a result of my harvest, I was able to "own" 70 cubic metres of waste.
What you see on this picture is 30% of what I accumulated at home.
I have not been ordered to do that.
I mean nobody have asked me to work on this subject.
This is a subject that I did out of conviction.
So, I found myself living for nearly four years - the idea wasn't to perform a feat - but I found myself creating a sorting centre at home.
I removed 70 m3 clandestinely from the sorting circuit of Lille's metropolis.
(Rires) Now, you need to know that here, it's my kitchen, yet one of the rooms in which I kept the most living space.
You have to imagine a flat in which everything was dedicated to storage.
For example, in my bedroom, I had 4,800 rolls of toilet paper.
I had 5,000 cigarettes packs.
I had an office upstairs whose back-wall I hadn't seen for many years.
The way I chose to handle this issue was special.
I chose to handle it in a way a bit like an advertising agency would.
Waste is something that is not very palatable.
Nobody really wants to take an interest in it.
And it's kind of “out of sight, out of mind.”
From day one, I made it a practice to isolate each type of waste
to give them a graphical dimension.
Had I mixed everything up, I'd have had a slightly different look,
and actually, I wanted to work on the aesthetic dimension and come up with an image that would be slightly shocking.
In each of the images I produced, I gave a lot more importance to the waste than to the model.
Each image was constructed in the context of the series, because when you do a series of images, you must create a rhythm.
This is one of the introductory images that is questioning the relationship between man and his environment.
We can see there's a concrete structure at the back that represents the hand of man on Nature, and in the foreground, there is greenery that remind us of a primary forest.
The idea is to create contrast.
The models who posed for this series are not professional models.
They are some friends, members of my family.
Each time, I had to brief them.
For example, the idea that I sought to express through my images is to ask people to overlook that reality.
There is something embarrassing about the image, when you look closely.
Finally, everything looks very normal, and the person totally ignore what surrounds her.
The idea is not to question her but to let the viewer project himself into this image and ask himself about his own impact in terms of consumption.
Then, what I didn't want to do was to make viewers feel guilty because I, myself, didn't set an example.
So, there is an ironic touch when you look at it closely.
What she's holding in her hands is the solution.
In this case, it's an orange.
If she'd chosen to buy fresh oranges, she could have avoided a great deal of the empty packages seen here.
In this picture, I understand that the alternative is difficult to find and it's hard to live with a cow in one's kitchen.
(Rires) As I said earlier, I didn't consume all of those packages.
For example, I may have drunk two bottles of milk in four years.
Here, let me give you some time to count quickly ... There are 1,600 bottles of milk here!
So the idea is to provide an impactful visual.
If I had made a picture with two bottles of milk, I'd be at home watching telly.
That's exactly what works in this series.
It won me an international prize which means the series is now on tour and a lot of people around the world see themselves in these images, because this theme had been dealt in terms of statistics, but it had never been dealt in this particular way.
This got a lot of publicity. Incidentally, the lecturer just before me was a gastroenterologist. Here we have 5,000 toilet roll tubes.
So let me reassure you, it's not the fruit of my own consumption.
I'm fine, thank you!
I think the challenge today, as a photographer, is trying to produce images that speak to people.
Today, we are overwhelmed daily with images.
Whether we turn on our computer or go to work, we are bombarded by tons of ads.
The challenge, I think, if we want to leave a lasting impression, is to produce a visual that speaks to people and stands out.
In general, we don't often show people sitting on their toilets.
And I guess Clothilde, my model, will not be using this picture on her next CV.
(Laughter) Due to my own consumption choices and constraints that are understandable, as you can easily infer, if I have chosen to talk about household waste and packaging especially, it's because they are storable.
I could not address the issue of organic waste because had I kept it, I'd would be now reduced to potting soil.
I also chose in my pictures to widen the discussion a little bit.
Actually here, the model is shown in a car,
and there is a kind of combo that works pretty well between the smoke that could've come from the cigarette, and our mobility choices questioned by the picture, because the smoke could've come from the car.
So this is this problem, since waste is also a matter of pollution, that is raised here.
Fun fact, when we did the installation, among the 5,000 packs of cigarettes given to me, the model found one that was still intact.
He was happy, and it was only right that he should keep it.
So we did the shooting, and at the end, while we were packing up to take everything home, he lost it.
It fell back among the 5,000 packs of cigarettes.
So what's the moral of the story?
An ill-gotten gains are short-lived.
(Laughter) You should know that some of the images required ten hours of work, because I had to take all my stock that I'd sorted nicely by type at home; I had to do the installation to recreate the volume; I had to do the lighting and shoot it all, and then take everything back home.
In fact, I would have liked to approach the question from a wider context
because today, it's all the facets of our way of consuming that are put into question.
I'm 38; I could have staged the number of cars I've had, the number of fridges I used, the number of phones I changed, the number of washing machines.
The problem is much broader.
And in all cases, the point I wish to expand on is that we are all actors in this society.
The choices we make as consumers do have an effect on society and on consumption at large.
I had this example of organic food, and I was saying that a few years ago, there was no offer of organic food and that rahter, it developed over time.
That's true: today, in your supermarket, there's at least one organic section.
What's interesting is that it's become an economic model. And it has been taken up by the industrialists.
Today, you can buy an organic lemon that's travelled 8,000 kilometres.
But finally, does that make any sense?
I don't think so.
I think even the way in which we choose to dress has also an impact on the environment.
For a long time, the policy was to say “Let's move the problem.
We can't treat waste in France?
It doesn't matter.
Let's send it to China or to Africa.” Except that today, the Chinese are in a developing society, and they themselves produce a large amount of waste, and they don't want to take what we produce.
Solutions exist.
Although I myself, didn't change dramatically, I, nevertheless, started to prepare my meals, and I try to make my own contribution.
From small acorns, great oaks trees grow.
Even in waste management in France, there's still a long way to go.
I think of this picture.
I gave a lot in this picture.
(Laughter) This photo is special because it represents mostly bottles: glass bottles and beer bottles.
Since I'm from Lille and I live near Belgium, I know they have a system in Belgium called "the deposit system."
Its principle is to consider that an empty packaging has still a value.
Here in France, a glass bottle is broken and remade into a bottle.
It takes energy to remake a bottle.
In Belgium, they rinse it and use it again.
And to do that, they've standardized the bottles.
It means that the industry, without constraints, sells you packaging.
When you buy small coffee capsules, it may be practical, but you pay 30 times the price of coffee because the money you spend is a payment for the packaging.
When we buy a beautiful box of chocolates at Christmas, glittery, with a nice little ribbon, in reality, we're not offering chocolates but rather packaging.
So, when we take a look at the contents of our rubbish bins, we find this very same thing in plenty of other areas.
Let's look at another image.
Here, there are 800 kilos of ads.
Yet you just need to put up a "No ads!" sticker to avoid 12 kgs of waste of paper per person and per year.
It's about doing simple little things.
I think it's difficult to expect people to make a radical change in their life.
We must not wait for public policies to reach out to help us do better.
In my opinion, what is important, and this is the purpose of my series, is to tell you that you can all be a force for this change, by changing the way you consume.
When I consider, for example, food wastage: half of the world food production ends up in a garbage bin while another part of the world doesn't eat enough.
Why?
Because it doesn't meet expected standards.
It is sufficient to go buy your vegetables at the marketplace, and provide work for local craftsmen, to avoid finding yourself in this type of situation.
Indeed, this amount of waste is produced over very short periods of time.
That's it ; the purpose of my work is just to remind you that the best waste is the waste we don't generate.
Thank you.
(Applause)
Good evening everyone.
My name is Laurent Rochette and I'm a film producer.
Tonight, I'm going to talk about a film I produced, but I'm going to start by speaking about French cinema.
I don't know whether, at the mention of those two words, you are overwhelmed by a great feeling of boredom.
Well, I am too.
And if, on the contrary, you think I'm exaggerating, or I've gone too far because we've produced great films in France, it's true, there are a few.
We've written a good share of the 20th century's history of cinema in France.
However, out of the 250 fiction films produced every year in France, I'm not sure that many will be remembered.
But have you ever asked yourself why French cinema spoke so little to our generation?
Why do we prefer English series?
In my opinion, it's the inability to make people feel a relationship to the world that resonates with us.
In short, it doesn't touch us.
Yet we're living through peculiar times, aren't we?
Our present is uncertain, littered with political, financial and humanitarian crises.
Our future is being jeopardised by global warming and the terrible impact it will have on our lives.
I'm not giving you a sunny introduction.
You only have to look at what happened on Saturday, not far from here, what is happening everywhere in France today.
Actually here, reality and present are really knocking at the door.
All of this could be subjects for possible films.
These are real questions that we are asking.
Yet, French cinema is miles away from that.
But I don't know why.
So I'm going to tell you how we tried to do things differently, how we tried to distance ourselves a bit from the rules, that is, from what you're expected to do when you make a film
such as writing a script, a financing plan, being a somebody or kind of, and self-censoring to get support.
And since we tried to get close, even just a little, to what we could call 'the exception' - when films manage to sneak between the rules to get closer to being art and make people feel a relationship to the world and humanity that speaks to us - I'm going to tell you how we shot, produced, and how we're going to distribute a film we'd like to see in cinemas, a different kind of French cinema.
We started filming in 2014 during the Music festival.
We chose that evening because that evening, everyone is in the street.
People are drunk, there is life everywhere, it's the longest evening.
We wanted to be in touch with life.
We were a tiny team, barely four or five people.
Then we continued like that attending events, until 2017, up until Johnny Hallyday's funeral.
Now three and a half years to make a film may seem extremely long, especially knowing that a feature-length fiction film is commonly shot in one to three months.
Yet, this time was really our luxury.
It was our luxury because it allowed us to really evolve with a city, meaning to write and shoot at the same time, and be influenced by all that was going on, especially at a time when it all made the project quite staggering.
By the way, while shooting in 2016, we came across an advert for a luxury watch, in the subway, and there was a tag on it that said,
'You have the watch, we have the time'.
It's true we didn't have the watch.
I'll go further by saying we were lucky not to have the money.
I don't know if you've often heard a producer tell you this, but for us it was an opportunity since lacking money meant not having the means for massive shooting devices, like all these lorries you see blocking streets in Paris.
Lacking money also means it's possible to be invisible, be a really small team without hierarchy, and be all at the same level.
But above all, lacking money means it's possible to fail, really fail, and then be able to restart and fail again but fail in a better way.
Actually, it opens the door to experimentation.
It's looking for a style, a language, without commercial ulterior motive or business plan.
Now how do we do, practically, to make a film?
Well, in our case, we were just a small group of people.
We all didn't know each other, but we trusted, and above all, we were aware of the freedom given to us at that time.
For example, we were all working in the film industry, but this, we were doing it for free.
Take the actors for example. In a traditional film, they have tape marks on the floor.
They have one here, one there.
The first assistant says 'Camera!'
'Action! Roll sound!'

... oops, the other way round!
The actor enters the room.
He goes to his first mark, says his line.
He goes to his second mark,
he leaves the room.
'Cut! Let's start again.'
With us, it wasn't like that.
The actor is not here to look for a job or move from one mark to the next.
He came because there was an important film to shoot, and because there were questions to be asked.
He was guiding the action, and he was speaking with his own words.
He had a responsibility.
So we continued.
And then...
We thought it would be great to have the support of technology, so that it wouldn't be an obstacle any more.
We're lucky with the evolution of digital technology, right?
Look at the videos your mobile phone can make.
So imagine little film cameras, what we could do if we put them in contact with real life.
I'm going to hand the floor to the film's actress, Noémie Schmitt, who explains this arrangement very well, I think.
(Video) In film, to reproduce real life, you need incredible means.
We thought it would be incredible to bring cinema into the real world.
Being without means, we looked for the smallest device possible to blend into the city.
Instead of replicating reality, we tried to completely integrate it.
It meant we agreed not to control what happened around us, and we sought to be in places where things were happening.
In a conventional film, these people around us would have been extras, whereas, with this method, anything can happen.
Reality completely sweeps away fiction.
That's how we can make people feel my character's psychological distress and paranoia.
(Police sirens) (Explosion) After three and a half years, we had a rough cut, some footage, and we were getting closer to the film's completion, what we call 'post-production', which requires technical and human means we didn't have.
Although we were making a film without resources, it still needed to keep up with a motion picture.
So we asked ourselves 'Why not look for co-producers?'
In France, there are plenty of people with money to make films.
We sent emails, we made calls.
We didn't get a single answer, not one.
In essence, the project we were launching was totally unthinkable to them.
To make a film without support, without a TV channel or a script, is miles away from what they do.
We were a bit stuck actually.
Then we thought things over.
We thought about it and asked ourselves who we were making the film for.
Were we making it for the little Parisian film community?
Or were we making the film because it could reach an audience?
We had our answer.
So we decided to launch a crowdfunding campaign.
I don't know if you've ever done a crowdfunding, but we all know that, generally, it always starts with a request for money to family members and friends.
In our case, they didn't work in the film industry.
So we thought it would be nice if we could explain to them this slightly obscure project we'd been doing for four years.
So we decided to make a video.
This is the video you've just watched.
This video's been viewed 4 million times on Facebook.
That was a surprise.
It was a huge shock to see that the initiative we were launching, the story we wanted to tell, could not only touch our generation but that of our little sisters and brothers as well, those who are said 'not to be really interested in culture or cinema', or 'living in a cult of instant gratification'.
Yet it's not true.
They are those who acclaim such an experimental film.
It's thanks to them that the film had so much visibility.
So people asked us:
'How do we create a buzz? How?'
We knew nothing about it, we had never expected to go viral.
We only wanted to genuinely share our experience.
Now maybe, the questions we asked ourselves resonated also with some people.
Broadly, in the rest of the video, Noémie walks down the street and asks herself a question.
She wonders if we can believe in the future when fear defines us.
Maybe that's the question that resonated with people.
In fact, this video made us aware that we had an audience, that we had finally developed an audience.
We wanted people to have access to the film just as easily as they had access to this video.
So we had offers from distributors, but they were limited to a very private release, in very few cinemas, very few screens.
So that didn't suit us.
We realised that, even after this video and its success, the industry hadn't understood at all the evolution of the viewing practices among us, or even our wish to see new forms, radical forms, forms that question the world.
Then we thought a little about ourselves too.
And we found out we were really the first generation to have developed our cinephilia online, through our love for cinema by watching films and hearing about them thanks to the Internet.
We use to go to cinema to see author films, but we know that it's less and less the case for our generation, everywhere in France.
Most of all, we pondered about the meaning of the word 'cinema'.
What is cinema?
Well 'cinema' describes a place, the cinema where we go to watch films.
But I believe that above all else cinema defines a medium, an art form, the seventh art, and that the place is less important than the art, even though the place is important, of course.
But what will remain are the films, not necessarily the places.
So quite paradoxically, we decided to sign with Netflix to distribute the film.
I say 'paradoxically' because we support a very independent kind of cinema.
And we find ourselves signing with one of the web's giants, whose use of algorithms seems to us ultra suspicious.
But in the end, we found we were much closer to Netflix than to all the proponents of the so-called 'classical' culture who even refuse to imagine that such a project could exist... in other words, to watch it.
So the film will be released at the start of next year.
We're very curious to see how it will be received because it's rather funny to send such an independent stuff to a platform like Netflix.
So for us, it's an ongoing experiment.
To conclude, I'd like to say that it's always important to try to do things, even for free.
In our case, it was rewarded because we signed with Netflix, and we paid a whole team who had worked for free.
But even aside from that, I think it's important to try to do things and question our relationship to the world and our presence on this planet, without necessarily wanting to disrupt - it's not like that.
Rather, we're living through peculiar times and we need to ask questions.
I think that cinema and art allow us to do that, but not only that.
Primarily, if they don't let us do it, we really don't need to ask for permission.
We don't need to ask if everyone agrees. We just need to do it.
And if ever it isn't possible, I think we shouldn't hesitate to put a foot in the door.

That's it! Thank you.
(Applause)
I'm proud to share what some people think of as a utopia.
Because utopias are precisely what changes our world.
The vote to women, the end of slavery, paid allowances, all used to be utopias and are now established realities, thanks to people like you and me.
I, for me, will talk about this next utopia that might transform our society: the Unconditional Basic Income.
(Applause) So, the Unconditional Basic Income, is an income that everybody will receive, every month, unconditionally, to pay for our basic needs.
It's a universal right: every human being would receive it.
It's an individual right: every person gets the same amount.
And we'd get that income unconditionally.
No need to fill papers, to join long lines, apply for a job, to be entitled.
And that income would ensure the base and other incomes could be added to it.
So usually, when one says so, people think that's a good idea.
(Laugther) But a small question arises: how can we finance it?
Well, I have another question instead: in a society like ours today, can we provide food and shelter to each and every one of us?
Actually, this income that allows to pay for our basic needs, we already get it
through activity income, transfers, allocations ... So having an unconditional basic income, is just about simplifying and rearranging the status quo.
I take the example of Switzerland, the one I know best, because that's where I'm committed for basic income.
In Switzerland, we talk about a basic income of 2500 francs per month per person.
It's just above the poverty threshold.
Funding this basic income for 8 million people living in Switzerland, would cost 200 billion per year.
200 billion is one third of the GDP, which looks like a lot.
But the point is, this basic income - 200 billion - doesn't have to be funded from scratch.
Because basic income will replace a big chunk of current policies.
So in Switzerland, for example, it's going to replace social aid, a part of jobseeker allowance, a part of retirement, a part of activity income.
So we could fund it today already, if we only wanted to.
It's true for Switzerland, but also for countries like France, and many other ones.
Simply, each country must find its own way to adapt their local status quo.
So, when we say it's financable, there's the second big question: if we give money to people like that, will they keep working?
Will they keep being active?
If you had a basic income, for instance, would you still have a reason to wake up in the morning?
Yes, no?
(Laughter) Actually, basic income has been tested in differents corners of the world, for instance in Canada, during the sixties.
And what we've observed - in two villages of Canada, along several years, a basic income got implemented, and remarkably, people kept working just as much.
Only two categories worked less: mothers who just had a baby, and could afford maternity leave, and students who could extend and complete their studies.
In 2008, in Namibia, a different context, a different experimentation of basic income.
And we have observed that people actually worked more.
Because basic income acted as a "floor" that allowed them to start their activity and invest.
Self-entrepreneurial activities grew by 300%.
Incomes increased 29% above the basic income.
This gives us a little idea that this basic income, isn't just an income for lazy people: it's actually an income that allows us to choose what's important, and get there.
This income allows us to make choices in every moment of our life.
Choice to change career, to train ourselves, look after our kids, an old relatives.
Being active in citizenship, like I am today.
In different countries, people have started supporting this basic income boldly.
A survey, in France, told us that 60% of French support basic income. I don't know how many of you are in this hall. (Laughter) (Applause) In Finland, they're even more: 79%.
Sixty-nineteen, in French.
And in Switzerland, where I live - hence the seventy-nine - we launched in 2012 a citizen initiative to put the basic income into the Swiss Constitution.
We collected more than 125.000 signatures, and this means that next year, we'll be able to vote to decide whether we want to put this basic income into the constitution.
(Applause) I hope we will vote according to your applause.
Governments are often a bit more prudent than their own population, to decide to implement a basic income.
However, two governments commit today, two countries take the step: The Netherlands and Finland.
In the Netherlands, from 2016, 30 towns will test the basic income.
And in Finland, from 2017, there will be an experimentation that will take place all over the country.
I think that maybe this two countries are more aware than others that we really need this basic income today.
Since the seventies, productivity gains have risen a lot.
Unemployment has also risen.
And the trend is accelerating today.
Robotization, automatization, digitalization, all destroy jobs.
A recent study from the University of Oxford tells us that 47% of jobs are expendable, in the United States, by 2025.
A similar study, focused on France, says that 42% of jobs are also at risk.
By 2025, it's a lot.
And it involves us all.
Because all the jobs that are replaced today, unlike yesterday, are in the field of services.
We're talking about jobs, for instance, like translators, journalists, bankers, because those jobs can partly be automated.
Conversely, the most creative jobs - I don't know, like advertisers, or people in the humanities field - teacher, nurse - have less chances to be automated, because robots aren't really empathic yet.
I think they're working on that, but it's more complicated. (Laughter)
New jobs will appear, but they won't be enough to replace those that disappear.
And today, in this formidable era, when salaries are about to vanish.
Project work develops, and over the course of our life, we will all have many jobs.
That's often the case already.
And to make sure that this transformation, this evolution, doesn't translate into a mass precariousness, the technological progress we all know of should be coupled with a social progress and innovation.
That's why today our social protection needs to change, evolve, fit with this new world.
And this basic income, that some people, even today, consider a utopia, or a luxury, will really be a need tomorrow.
Thank you.
(Applause)
I would like to ask you to take 30 seconds to imagine that today, when you come back home a conflict has started.
Enemy's army, known for its violence, is already at the gates of your city.
Communication networks have been cut off.
You don't have any news from your loved ones.
So you decide to go, very quickly, to the other side of the border.
There, you hear that you will be safe.
And that's it, you have become a refugee.
It's only transitory, of course, just until things settle down,
but things don't settle down.
Soon you realize that you're going
to spend some time there. 17 years.
This is the average time a refugee spends in the camp.
17 years, when most times, you don't have the right to leave the camp, to work, 17 years of doing nothing.
And you will watch your children grow up without perspectives or future.
This is how the life of more than 50 million refugees looks like today, and how the ones displaced live because of conflicts and catastrophes.
This is what happened in Haiti in January 2010, when a terrible earthquake hit the metropolitan area of Port-Au-Prince, and left more than 1 million people in the streets.
The NGO founded by me and historian Patrick Weil, Library Without Borders, was already operating there before the catastrophe.
And it was our partners who called us for help in reconstruction.
Together we very quickly started to create libraries in tents, in the camps for displaced persons.
Obviously, we asked ourselves the question which you are considering now: is it really necessary and so important to create libraries when everything else is in ruin?
It's the place, the practice, that has taught us that yes,
it's absolutely essential.
We have actually created real zones of normality in the camps.
These libraries in tents have become real reference points for the people, where they could find each other, exchange information, share.
The refugees, the displaced persons, they have immediate needs: to eat, to heal, to find a place to live.
But once these needs are satisfied, they need to restore themselves, to recreate the bonds.
Too often, there are no sufficient means to ensure the future.
But at the same time, in an emergency, we need to be able to act quickly and according to standardized procedures.
Nothing was easy.
Our libraries in tents brought something essential, but they involved too much handiwork to be deployed on a large scale.
Try sending boxes with books or computers after a crisis, they will explode on the airport ramp, or will be lost during transportation.
All of this was too complicated.
We needed to think of a new solution.
So in January 2013, we started to compose, with the help of United Nations Refugee Agency, a specification of a multimedia kit, to be used with the emergency response solutions.
We wanted it to be extremely standardized. Simple, easy to transport and field deployable.
So, a sturdy device that is energetically autonomous.
But at the same time, it was about libraries, so we needed a content extremely adapted to the needs of the people, to their languages, to their cultures.
We set three major goals: to reinforce education, to help the people prepare for the future, especially the youngest ones,
to reconnect refugees with the world, to reconnect families separated by the crises, and to prevent the risk of rumor and propaganda.
To reinforce resilience, to help the refugees in the long fight for the reconstruction of the future.
We wanted to create a sort of a tool box, for the most vulnerable people to use, where they could come and use the Internet, learn, play, create.
You can imagine that to achieve this we needed next to nothing.
4-dimensional nothing in fact: a possibility to connect, thanks to satellite internet access, about 20 tablets and computers, and an internal server.
To learn, with a library of paper books, pedagogical resources, electronic books, and 50 eReaders, which are more autonomous than tablets and can be lent to people.
To play, board games or video games. A scene, to play music, or perform theatrical plays, and a cinema, composed of a projector and a television set.
Quite often image is the number 1 medium understandable to the majority of people.
But if it was understood that this emergency library should have a primary content, it was important for us to see how people created their own resources.
So to encourage creativity, with plastic arts and writing workshops, with cameras, with tools to create blogs and journals.
A year and a half ago, it was all just an idea, a beautiful idea.
I imagined a huge ball that we could roll in the camps in order to move it.
I couldn't sleep at night anymore,
I used to wake up sweaty, telling myself, "It's impossible, we will never succeed."
We needed help.
We wrote to designer Philippe Starck, who agreed to create this device pro Bono, and managed to fit it all on two pallets.
Two pallets, because it follows international logistics standards, to fit in cargo compartment of a plane to be quickly sent in the field, and once there, we can pack them in the back of a pick-up to deliver them easily to the destination.
So, there are four big cubes and two storage cases, that can all be unpacked within less than 20 minutes, and create a space of 100 square meters, which can host up to 70 people at the same time.
We have successfully met the challenge: to create, on two pallets, a unique device which would enable creative energy to flourish, even in the harshest situations.
Here it is, Ideas Box.
As you see, we have four principal modules.
The shells are flight cases, solid and waterproof.
Once they're open, the shells transform into furniture: tables and stools where one can sit, low tables for children, a stage or a scene, bleachers like in a cinema.
Each module has its distinctive feature and color: the IT module that contains electronic materials, eReaders, tablets and satellite internet connection.
The library module, with 250 paper books, and board games.
The cinema module, with a television set and a projector.
And finally, the administrative module, that enables the animators to manage the Box, and that contains the power generator providing the device with electricity.
Within two months, we have created two first Ideas Boxes, destined to be sent to the Congolese refugee camps in Burundi.
I must admit that the server of the Boxes got finished on the plane taking our teams to Burundi.
There, we taught the Congolese refugees and the Burundian how to operate and animate the Boxes, and we started the deployment.
The welcome was spectacular.
In three months, two first Ideas Boxes were visited 24,000 times.
What we tried to avoid, was a device arriving from nowhere to be installed artificially in the field.
So we worked beforehand with local organizations, to adapt the content to the languages, to the cultures of the people, and to integrate the Box into the life of the camp.
We were told the IT materials could be stolen, but the residents took charge of the Box.
They take care of it, nothing was stolen.
They even constructed the huts to host them.
This first stage is a real success for us.
The first impacts show the life in the camp before and after the Box.
Firstly, regarding the protection of children: all parents say the same thing, the Box has created a safe space for the children, who before wandered within the camp.
A space where they can come after school to do their homework, to play, to simply relearn to be children.
Secondly, it's the quality of education: teachers come to give lessons in the Box.
They take their classes, and notice the awakening of curiosity and creativity of their students.
Lastly, it's the strengthening of the community: the associations, the groups for women, profit from the Box and prepare the animations, the awareness workshops.
A group creating slam poetry has formed in one of the camps.
In the other, they have a newspaper.
The refugees take videos of the camp life, collect testimonies, and try to break the vicious circle of rumor.
Strengthened by our success, we have of course continued the adventure.
Two more Ideas Boxes have been deployed in other refugee camps in Burundi since February,
and in the near future, it's for the Syrian refugees in Jordan or Lebanon that new Ideas Boxes will arrive.
But it's only the beginning.
We want to deploy 100 Boxes next year.
So the challenges before us are still huge.
One Box, all included, costs today 45,000 euro, because it's custom-made by the craftsmen.
If we want to send it to refugees all around the world, we need to divide this cost by two.
To achieve this, we need to industrialize the production, play on the economies of scale, and build partnerships for donations of equipment or content, for example.
And so we welcome every good will, and I'm sure some of you can help us.
Because in reality, we're in the middle of the way.
We have constructed an all-terrain device for the refugees.
But we realize that it could be useful in many other situations.
Imagine tomorrow, Ideas Boxes here, in the rural areas of France, or in the disadvantaged neighborhoods where there are no libraries.
Because education and culture are never without use,
especially when you have nothing.
And if it is particularly true for the refugees, it's also true for the vulnerable people all around the world.
Thank you.
(Applause)
Sometimes, often, the world makes me sick.
Especially since I'm a mom.
I've got two girls and when their environment keeps on falling apart, the world makes me sick.
I feel bad for climate refugees, I feel bad to know that our lands are becoming sterile, that bees are disappearing, and with them, probably three-quarters of our vegetables and our fruits.
I feel bad knowing that, in China, some kids don't know that the sky is blue.
It is grey.
Grey due to pollution from our factories, our smartphones, our t-shirts.
But how can we accept that, for a t-shirt, there might be human suffering, polluted water?
All of it, upsets me.
I can't bear telling myself that this is the world I am contributing to.
So, I found myself a lifetime mission: saving the world.
That is it.
Everyday I try to do something, and for 15 years now, I have been advising companies.
Sometimes, I become enthusiastic about good initiatives, I spread them out. And sometimes I get angry when I read, "Paris is under pollution alert, It can be compared to a closed room of 20 square meters with 8 smokers."
There are ups and downs.
Then, one day, it was 2-3 years ago, my daughter tells me during breakfast, "You know, mom, a friend of mine doesn't come to school these days, he can't go out, because he can't breathe outside."
We don't live in Paris, it was everywhere.
I wanted to cry, I was ashamed, I was failing, it kept going on.
It kept going on, and while waiting, we were congratulating ourselves about all these "eco-friendly" things.
We constantly heard about energy transition, green growth, intensive ecological farming, and even, the third industrial revolution.
But, I didn't believe in miracle solutions anymore.
So that morning, I looked at my daughters and told myself, "Enough!"
For a year and a half, I did some research.
I wanted to know if it was possible to get out from this deadly system, I thought that if I came to realize that it was a lost battle, then I would give up.
I digged everywhere: psychology, behaviorial and social sciences, philosophy, new economies, ecology, design, communication.
In the end, I've found reasons to hope.
It's not an easy matter, but there are solutions.
So I wrote a book.
I also discovered that all these stories about transition and green growth, that couldn't be enough. And even worse, sometimes it even gets worse.
I found out the only salvation is utopia.
Utopia isn't just a dream to forget about reality.
I didn't escape into an imaginary world
with the Care Bears, no.
The etymology of utopia is "which doesn't happen".
It doesn't mean that it can't exist.
Utopia isn't unrealizable, it is just the unrealized.
And what's my utopia?
I want a new society standard.
A society where the lifestyle isn't harmful to anybody, not to those living half a world way, nor to my neighbors, nor to those who will come next.
An utopia is radical, conscious, optimistic.
But the world in which you live isn't an easy one for utopians.
You can encounter cynics, conservatives, materialists, these ones obviously say that you are an unrealistic person. Then there is this deep feeling of helplessness.
I often hear, "With these politicians who don't do anything and all those pressuring multinationals, we cannot do anything!"
"People will never change, have you seen their shopping cart?"
"Come one, tell me the truth Sandrine, all of that is rich people's issues, a hipster thing."
Obviously, I meet a lot of people like those.
How can we keep on believing in it? Especially, how can we make this utopia happen?
There is no recipe.
Why? Because the path we are about to engage on is a path that has never be trodden.
So of course, we are experimenting.
The first solar panels aren't perfect, we know they aren't, but that shouldn't stop us from doing research.
Nothing's perfect, especially not in the beginning.
Utopia isn't all rosy.
We are confronted to reality, we need pragmatism and perseverance.
We try, sometimes we fail, then we improvise.
The utopian doesn't have any prejudices or dogmas regarding how to go on,
but the aim is not to give up.
The utopian has no certainties, but he has convictions, determination and ambition.
Let's talk about Interface, a company that sells carpets, so a lot of raw materials, an abundance of waste, toxic glue, etc.
In 1994, Ray Anderson, Interface's boss took an incredible decision
and said, "In 2020, our company won't have any negative impact on the environment.
None. Of any kind."
He would have said,
"Transition, let's reduce by 25%," it was already good and seemed doable.
He said, "No impact."
Actually, a good utopia, is indeed, at first glance, unrealizable.
Unrealizable in the current system. Unrealizable with our usual way of thinking.
In order to reach the target, there is no choice, you have to fall out of the framework, break the rules, radically innovate.
It's what Interface actually did, collecting broken windshields to make carpets out of them, inventing a new fixing system without glue, inspired by geckos, these small lizards that stick to walls.
They broke out of all the boundaries of their field, and today, 5 years before the deadline, they already reduced their impact by 97%.
Behind these results, there is a man who didn't let go of any part of his utopia.
Ray Anderson thought, "Someday, people like me will be thrown in jail, I do not want to do any more harm."
In fact, Ray Anderson was resilient.
Behind this utopia, there is this peculiar energy, the energy of resilience.
Resilience has an established and shared pattern which is unacceptable.
I am going to give you another example: Algopack, a small Breton company that invented a plastic made out of seaweed.
No need for oil, it has the same features, the bonus is that, while it is growing, the seaweed confines carbon, it cleans up the oceans.
That is tremendous.
The plastic industry can be positive.
Frankly, other people could have come up with the idea.
What differentiates its inventor, Rémy Lucas, is his indignation.
As he says, he cannot bear the idea of oceans dying, of them becoming garbage bins.
That is what drove his invention.
Never doubt the legitimacy of indignation.
We prefer what is politically correct, the norm, not standing out, keeping quiet.
We were given to believe that is not something people do, we are said to be spoilsports, wet blankets, people who are against progress, traitors to the cause.
But of course people can do that!
Vigilance, intellectual self-defense, civil disobedience if needed, the hackers who operate for the greater good. If you think about it, the history of mankind, our history got created by spoilsports who defied established standards.
The right to be treated with dignity and not be beaten up as slaves; the right to sit down wherever we want on a bus or on a bench, no matter your skin's color; if you are a woman, the right to vote, to have your own bank account, paid holidays.
All of it seems normal!
And yet, without utopians, we wouldn't have any of it.
If we take a step back, we think they were crazy, heroic, the ones defending theses utopias.
You will tell me, "All of us aren't Luther King, Jean Moulin, Simone Veil."
They didn't accomplish it on their own.
They needed support for ordinary heroes, people like you and me, who defended the obvious thing to do.
Obvious things which have to be defended, things that are essential, there are many of them today.
Access to drinkable water for everybody, a breathable air, the right to plant the seed you want and plant it again without paying patents, forests, dolphins, social diversity.
You can choose your cause, you can also choose the way you want to resist.
During the war, among resistance fighters, there were some who fought, and there were others who informed allies, others who hid people.
Today you have demonstrations, petitions, whistle-blowers, poetic activism, selfies to raise awareness about ethical fashion, repair workshops to save devices that broke down, so many different way to resist, to hack the old standard, and contribute to the modern utopia.
Every one can choose a part of it, something that matters to them.
Someday, you find the small thing you want to defend, that resonates in you, that gives you the desire and the determination.
Finally, everyone has their cause, their desire, their ordinary resistance.
Finally, the utopia happens in dispersed order.
So you will tell me, "Does it really matter, considering how powerful lobbies are?"
Let's take an example representing their power and see if it stops us.
Pesticides.
We know they are toxic, the INSERM clearly linked them to several diseases, they are in the soil, air, water. We ingest them, farmers suffer from them, but yet, in March this year, a majority of our deputies voted in favor of pesticides, in favor of extending their use.
We were sentenced to 10 additional years of illegal poisoning and that pissed me off.
Then I thought that we could do something against this law, without breaking the law.
Spray black soap against aphids, eat organic food, and many stores already removed these products from their shelves.
Even though they can sell it, their poison, at some point, there won't be much people buying it, then it will not have any economical interest.
In fact, our impact is tremendous.
When we share a ride, use public transportation, walk, ride a bike, we avoid at least three quarters of fine particle CO2.
Those who stop eating meat resist to 60 percent of deforestation.
If you decided to buy four times less new products, with some creativity, buying second-hand, sharing, we would preserve 400 percent of raw materials.
Honestly, all these choices don't change the comfort, nor the pleasure.
Well, they change in nature:
hack, regain control, think about what helps us prioritize, gather a group, that can be enjoyable.
Not all of us are perfect and coherent people, but we can all do a few things.
That can change everything.
No matter some political decisions.
The suffragettes, the first abolitionists, they, too, were facing some conservatives.
They couldn't wait for it to trickle down.
It never trickles down.
In fact, if that had trickled down, in the era of segregation, the contemporary government would have created something like a "responsible segregation" or a "segregationist transition."
"So, Whites and Blacks, you can all sit down together in the bus, but only on Tuesday and Thursday."
That's not really glorious.
Whereas the abolition of the racial discrimination, such a progress in the history of mankind, makes you want to give it a shot.
I am not saying transition is a bad thing, I am saying that a lesser evil makes you feel guilty, it is not sexy and it is far from being enough.
Do you really believe that a "half", "soft" segregation would have led us to equality, in the end?
In "responsible segregation", there is "segregation."
In "green growth", there is "growth."
We cannot even get rid of the words, how could we get rid of the standard?
We just have to adapt it, still looking in the rear-view mirror, we feed old beliefs, because the position stopped believing a long time ago, but we believe.
Whereas utopia, it is a blank page.
We look the other way, we ruthlessly invent, even if there is a long way to go.
It is a new bet, an uncompromising one.
You don't negotiate with your values.
If you have to give up something up, it is the standard, not the values.
Jean-Paul Sartre said, "We have never been as free as when we were occupied."
Understanding this sentence took me a while.
The tough times, these are opportunities to exercise your individual freedom.
We have real decisions to make, engaging and inspiring decisions.
During the war, finally, the resistance only represented 2 to 3 percent of the population, those who chose the utopia.
A handful of individuals committed to it, in a dispersed order, it became a movement, and it changed history.
The same thing is happening today.
I don't think we will wake up one morning with an utopian revolution, well-organized, but it is on its way, and, finally, it is an opportunity for us to be adults today.
It might not always be easy, but we have this historical opportunity to become resistance fighters, to defend what is essential, to build what will be beautiful tomorrow.
We can grow, grow in our humanity.
In the meantime, our children are watching us, they are learning that you should never give up, that you should demand no less than a beautiful life, you don't negotiate with your humanity, you don't give up on your utopia.
Let's not forget that if the obvious today is yesterday's utopia, the obvious for our children, and their children, can only be our utopias.
Thank you.
(Applause)
Hello, thank you.
Comets have always intrigued men, made us dream.
Many years ago, we considered them divine omens.
The name comet comes directly from ancient Greece from the Greek "kometes", which means long-haired, referring to the comet's tail or halo.
Actually, they're small celestial bodies made of ice and dust and as they approach the Sun, the ice that they're made of melts, leaving part of their substance behind in space and creating this tail of gas and dust tens of thousands of miles long, which makes them so visible from Earth.
Undoubtedly most famous comet is Halley's comet.
Halley's comet returns every 76 years to our planetary neighborhood.
And the last time that it came by, in 1986, this comet provoked the interest of the general public, certainly, but also of space agencies because for the first time in history, thanks to space flight technology, we could go and see this famous comet close up.
Several unmanned spacecrafts, called space probes, several space probes were sent to meet the comet, to study it. among them the European space probe, Giotto, in 1986.
Comets: where do they come from? and, above all, why are they so interesting from a scientific point of view?
They come from two regions of outer space that we call the Kuiper belt and the Oort cloud.
Outer space, because the Kuiper belt, for example, begins about 3 billion miles away from the Earth, around Pluto, and the Oort cloud is more than 10,000 billion miles away from Earth.
At these distances, to give you an idea of scale, we're already at a quarter of the distance that separates us from the closest star, Proxima Centauri.
There would be billions of comets in these spaces and, from time to time, under the gravitational pull of one of the giant planets in the Solar System, Jupiter, for example, or even the stars closest to our Sun, some of them are propelled towards our Sun and pass close by our planet.
Some only pass by once, and others come back more regularly, like Halley's comet, for example.
The comets are so fascinating because, due to their small size and distance from the Sun, they've never changed the way the planets in our solar system have.
So they're wonderful proof of the origins of our Solar System, and what's more, since they bombarded the Earth a long time ago, they might have contributed to bringing the water that makes up our oceans or even the organic compounds that might have allowed the development of life on our planet.
So now we understand the scientific interest of these comets, and that's why the ESA, the European Space Agency, after the success of the Giotto mission decided to launch the Rosetta mission in the early 1990s.
So the Rosetta mission was challenging for several reasons: a time challenge, you see, because from the early 1990s to 2016, that's more than 25 years of this mission, with about a dozen countries participating or collaborating closely or otherwise on this project.
The mission, at the beginning, was meant to be a collaborative mission with the Americans, with NASA, an even more ambitious mission in true American style because it was going to collect samples from the comet's surface and bring them back to Earth to study them in a laboratory.
Due to budget restrictions, in 1993, NASA more or less threw in the towel and Europe had the idea to continue the adventure on its own, nevertheless setting its sights a bit lower because it would have the Rosetta mission follow the comet for several months to study its evolution as it approached the Sun and to land a little laboratory robot, that you can see behind me, the robot Philae, that would then, for the first time, do evaluations on the comet's surface.
Slightly less ambitious, but nonetheless a huge challenge because all the probes that had studied comets up until that point hadn't done more than pass close by.
So it was really a first.
As you can imagine, during that whole time, 25 years, thousands of people across Europe have worked on this mission.
Some have been there since the beginning, not me, but some of the ones that started with the mission are still there.
Many others have moved on, passed the torch.
In the end, the Rosetta mission and the scientific community are like a big family in flux with people coming and going.
I won't hide from you that, like in all families, after a certain amount of time relationships can sometimes be tense, there are ups and downs, and the family reunions are sometimes a bit agitated, strained at times, but that's the human challenge of this mission, to have people work together for such a long time, coming from such different backgrounds and to make sure their skills are shared and not lost.
When you talk about challenges you're also talking about adventure and, of course, the unexpected,
right from the start.
The original target of our mission Wasn't the Churyumov-Gerasimenko, nicknamed Chury, but a comet called Wirtanen.
Rosetta was supposed to be launched in 2003 with an Ariane rocket and a couple months earlier, so in 2003, rocket failure during Ariane's flight, an explosion, all flights were suspended for several months, obviously.
There was an inquiry; we wanted to know why.
So the Rosetta flight was delayed.
For a comet, you can't be late.
If you miss the window, the comet passes, and won't come back for several years, even several dozen years later.
So, we missed the window, Wirtanen was no longer accessible.
So we had to chose a new window within a few months, recalculate a trajectory.
We chose the Churyumov-Gerasimenko comet, named for its Russian co-discoverers, Mr. Churyumov and Mrs. Gerasimenko.
This comet was discovered at the end of the 1960s.
It returns to Earth every 6.5 years, so we know it well.
And, importantly, it had the distinct advantage of being more or less similar to Wirtanen, which is important because our robot was supposed to land on Wirtanen.
So we had to find a new target that was similar.
It would be the Churyumov-Gerasimenko comet, that we call Chury now.
On March 2, 2004, Rosetta finally enters space, for a ten year journey destination: the Churyumov-Gerasimenko comet.
Ten years of traveling during which Rosetta passes near the Earth several times, and Mars as well, and propels itself towards the Churyumov-Gerasimenko comet.
During its long journey, Rosetta will have to get very far away from the Sun, five times the distance from the Earth to the Sun, more than 500 million miles.
It's important to know that the satellites in orbit around Earth get their energy from solar panels that recharge their batteries, like the solar panels that you might have on the roof of your home.
However, at that distance, 500 million miles, you only get 4% of the solar energy that we get on Earth.
That's why the probes that go so far into space are generally loaded with small nuclear batteries, like the famous Voyager space probe that was launched in the 1970s, and that is now in the process of leaving the Solar System, or the New Horizons probe, which passed by Pluto this summer, if you've been following space news.
However, in Europe, we don't have that technology.
We therefore had to equip Rosetta with enormous solar panels, two by 32 meters, two solar panels 32 meters long, and despite its 64 square meters of solar panels, when it was at its farthest from the Sun, Rosetta didn't have enough power to function normally.
So again, a new challenge: for 30 months, from June 2011 to January 2014, almost 31 months, we had to keep it on a sort of sleep mode, minimum power consumption, with its wakeup scheduled for January 20th, 2014 at 11am.
It was terribly difficult: during that entire time, No communication was possible with the probe, We didn't know how it was doing.
And then on January 20th, 2014 Rosetta's awakening gave us cold sweats.
The awakening was set for 11am, the probe should have turned on, turned on its apparatus, recover its power, turn its antenna towards the Earth and send us a signal.
The signal should take 45 minutes to arrive and we should receive it between 5:30 and 6 pm.
At 5 o'clock we were all there to wait for Rosetta's signal.
5:30, no signal.
6 o'clock, still no signal.
Well, up to that point, no worries, it was still within the normal range.
6:30, the minutes pass.
7 o'clock, we were really starting to get worried, to say to ourselves.. maybe the adventure is over before it even started.
The minutes kept passing, and happily, at 7:18, we got the signal that you see on the screen, really not impressive, but still it was a huge relief because that was the proof that Rosetta had reestablished contact, that the operators in Germany, on Earth, could once again send commands and that the adventure could continue.
And it really is an adventure, because flying around a comet is really quite dangerous, exactly because of that dust and that gas that are propelled through space as the comet approaches the Sun.
You might be thinking of the film Armageddon, if you've seen it, with Bruce Willis who's landing his space shuttle I don't know if you remember, with a bunch of gas jets, on a comet with a rough surface.
The reality is a lot less dramatic, but nonetheless, it's true the surface of a comet is really dangerous.
In the photo behind me, you can clearly see the gas expulsions, and the white points that you see are definitely not stars, but dust that's all around the comet that disrupts the probe's navigational instruments at the risk of Earth losing control of Rosetta.
We've even seen rocks several yards long flying around the comet.
You can see that it's a dangerous environment, and that's why the probe was unable to reach the surface, not even to drop our little robot Philae. The probe stayed at a height of 12 miles, 12 miles above the surface, for a comet that's 2.5 miles at its largest, 12 miles to land on a comet 2.5 miles wide, we really had to aim well.
And that was a huge gamble.
And that's what we were all waiting for, on November 12th, 2015, we were pretty anxious.
We weren't sure how it would go.
The probe dropped the robot at 9:35am, landing at 4:35pm, the contact signal should come to us around 5pm.
We had seven long hours to wait for the signal.
Thankfully, we quickly received the first pictures of our little robot on its descent towards the surface of the comet that showed us that things seemed to be going well, the legs were extended, and if we were able to take the photo, that meant that generally it was going in the right direction.
The descent continued.
It's good to know that no real-time intervention was possible, because the signal took 25 minutes to arrive on Earth,
and to send a signal back, another 25 minutes for Rosetta to receive it. so it wasn't possible to give any orders in real time.
During that whole time, we were following it, receiving information, but we weren't too sure of the robot's direction.
We didn't know if we would really land on the comet or if we were going to miss it.
Luckily, again, several minutes before the landing, we had our first reassurance: we received the first photos taken by our little robot's camera of the comet's surface, about 2 miles up, and then at 100 feet up. Then we knew
that everything was going right.
Finally, at almost the exact moment we were expecting, the contact signal, touchdown, it was there.
For the first time, we had landed on a comet.
As you can imagine, it was an explosion of joy.
Unfortunately, the tension quickly mounted again the data showed that our little robot was still moving.
The first photos were blurry.
We paced.
And then, for two hours, we watched, still without being able to do anything, as our robot bounces and bounces all over the surface of the comet until, at 7pm, two hours later we get confirmation that our robot has stabilized somewhere and that it's stopped.
In the end, we had had a little bit of bad luck
and lot of good luck. A bit of bad luck because we found that the hooks that should have anchored Philae to the surface of the comet didn't launch; and a lot of good luck nonetheless, because despite a rather ungraceful landing, in a rocky area with bad lighting, we succeeded, during the following 3 days, at making almost all Philae's instruments work, and collected the first data about the surface of the comet.
Rosetta and Philae will likely allow us to revolutionize comet science.
For example, we can say that Philae has confirmed the presence of complex organic compounds in comet dust.
and I would say that this mission is a symbol of space exploration because it requires us to reflect over long periods, to look to the future, to take risks, to put all possible skills at work in common, and to prepare for the unexpected, because, by definition, we really don't know what we're getting into.
We may be rewarded, for example, by the photos that are behind me, that our team loves very much, because they are photos taken by an object built by man twenty years ago, on or near an object that's several millions of years old, several hundred million miles away.
Thank you.
(Applause) Thank you so much.
(Applause)
What is it that drives you to go forward?
When you have no choice and you have to go and do it?
For me, this big leap forward was in October 1975, when a Red Cross plane tore me away from my sweet family cocoon in Saigon to drop me in the grey suburbs of Paris.
You know, at the time, I did not get at all the measure of such an effort, of such a change, because for me, France, 8,000 km away, at the age of 17, had the features of Alain Delon coming out of the pool in full sun; Mireille Darc, so blond, or the bonhomie of the Gendarme of Saint-Tropez.
You can imagine that France is not just that!
But let's go back together.
What happened to me that made me leave?
In April 1975, the war was at the gates of Saigon.
It was necessary to leave the country at all costs.
And for me, obviously, it was to go to France!
I must meet Alain Delon!
And many of my compatriots risked their lives on makeshift boats in the China Sea, and I note with sadness that history is repeating itself on other seas.
But I was much luckier: I could do a sham marriage to go to France.
The rare pearl is called Omar, a poor Indian from Pondichery, and you probably know, from your geography lessons, that Pondichery is a former French trading post, which implied a French passport.
I lost track of Omar but I owe a lot to this fake husband.
Omar helped me, Omar saved me, write it as you wish! (Laughter) Omar opened... (Applause) Omar opened the doors of France to me.
From a poor country at war, I discover, I'm coming to the land of lights.
And there, in fact, I discovered more than Alain Delon and Mireille Darc, I discovered an open and warm people.
Well it was all very good, but you can imagine it was not easy, it was very difficult.
First of all the harshness of the Parisian climate, which was so far from my flamboyant tropics.
Then, studies, you have to study, and in difficult conditions.
You know, I wanted to be a stewardess to satisfy my urge to discover the world.
I was told, "It's too hard, you cannot do it. "
Disappointed, I joined a preparatory class, Normal Sup, and a few years later, I passed the "agrégation".
(Applause) Everything I tell you seems easy but it was not easy at all, first competition exams are difficult, in fact, my parents could not send me any more money.
So I had to manage to both work and make a living; and my classmates told me: "But it's unfair, you do the same studies as we do, take the same difficult competitions as us and you're struggling while we are paid, we have scholarships, etc.
It is absolutely unfair."
And more than once, I was tempted to stop studying to take a job to pay the bills.
And then I wondered: do I have a choice?
I thought, and said: no, giving up would have been a failure, a failure for Omar, a failure for my parents, for those who believed in me and all those who would have liked to be in my place.
So I had to go on, I had no choice.
So years later, I come back to my parents' home country, a small village in the Mekong Delta, you may have been there before.
And I get to know the life of poor peasants of this rural village.
People work a lot, they have a very hard life and women are largely burdened.
Women in the fields work as much as men and then, in the evening, what do you think men do?
They go karaoke, drink rice alcohol, and still karaoke is a lesser evil.
Not for the neighbors but for the family.
And then the women go on, they have the housework, they have pigs to feed, they have children, etc. My mother comes from a very large and very rich family from this village.
This is our family photo, I'm the little one, but this family was steeped in traditional Confucian culture: everything was for the boys.
They had everything, my uncles, they inherited land, they did calligraphy, geomancy, feng shui, all was fine, and the women, the girls, my mother, and my aunt were illiterate, and married at 14 with men they had never seen before the day of the wedding.
I imagine, you imagine, these two girls, at 14, leaving for an uncertain future in a family they do not know.
There is a Vietnamese saying that the fate of a woman is like a boat coming into a harbor: if the harbor water is good and beautiful, so much the better, if the harbor water is cloudy, you have to deal with it.
My mother had no choice so she made her life as she could but she guided us, her five daughters, because we were eight children including five girls, she really imposed us, guided us to something: to be autonomous, to be master of his destiny.
That's really the lesson I learned from her.
The women of my village, I find them very cheerful.
They are very cheerful, combative, they speak of the future, the harvests, breeding, they also talk about births, deaths, death anniversary because there, we do not celebrate birthdays but death anniversaries so as not to forget our loved ones.
And then one day I ask them... but I remember that Vietnam War, this atrocious war of Vietnam passed by there, in this village.
I ask them, "How did you lose your husband 25 years ago?
How did you lose your child who was 15 years old? And you, how did you find
yourself orphaned at 3 months? "
And everything they tell me freezes my blood, because in fact they lived terrible things and they always seem so happy, carefree.
And I ask them, "But why don't I ever hear you look back?
Why don't you ever complain? "
Do you know what they answered to me?
"What is the use of complaining?
Who will listen to us?
We do not have a choice.
We are all on the same boat, we must move forward for the future of our children.
My father was a village notable and often men come to borrow small amounts of money, to have an income-generating activity.
So all this to avoid the usurer: look here, this is the usurer in the village which lends 10 to 12% per month.
So once you start, it never ends.
So I substituted for my father to lend small amounts of money.
We were already doing microcredit without knowing it.
And in 2001, with my companion and accomplice Gérard Feldzer, who is here, we created Zebunet.
Zébunet is an NGO that makes microcredit for family breeding, so small animals, calves, farm animals, that allow farmers to have an income-generating activity.
So hello calves, cows, pigs, broods, and of course hello zebu.
The zebu is this animal, it's a humpback ox, it is also an animal that lives in southern countries and which is symbol of the earth and toil.
So what is Zebunet?
We invite you, each one of you, to lend a sum of money corresponding to the purchase of an animal which will be lent, I say lent, since it is a loan, and loaned to a peasant family from the South.
So the farmer raises the animal and reimburses you once he has successfully reared.
So to make it really believable, something real, we issue you an investor certificate on which you have the picture of the animal, the photo of the host family with their contact dedails and we invite you to give your pet a name.
We have seen that our subscribers have really a lot of imagination.
They follow the cinematographic activity, politics etc.
All this is real, I'm not inventing anything.
That's it... so that's it.
That's an English-speaking zebuphile, the privileged public of Zébunet, they are women, why?
Because women are more serious, I apologize to men, but often... (Applause) So in fact women are more serious to the extent that they care more about children etc, and in addition we lend small animals, therefore sheep, goats, sheep, chickens.
Managing all this is very easy for them, they do that at the same time as the house work, it gives them a certain autonomy.
I remember once at a meeting in Niger, people knew that I, the president of Zébunet, was going to come, and there was a woman who had walked 20 km in the dust with her child on her back.
She said to me, "Madam President, next time, for a loan campaign, I would like to have money to raise 4 goats.
And don't worry, you know, I'm poor, but I'll pay you back no matter what. "
And the dignity of this woman moved me.
A loan is 140 euros, what are these 140 euros if we do not pay back?
It's not going to happen; but she was really keen on pledging her honesty to have this loan.
So, in Zébunet, there is no begging, no charity.
We do not give charity to people.
And so we lend, we help, we support people but in a peer-to-peer mentality respecting the everyone's dignity.
Through all these experiences, I find that these farmers from the South do not have the chance to be born on the good side of the planet and they have to struggle with a daily life that is often difficult and I find it unfair.
My friends, my neighbors, my cousins in the village were born next to my home, next to where I was born and do not have the same destiny as me because they were not born in the same family.
These injustices revolt me and I try to accompany people, I try to support the poorest to lessen this injustice.
I was lucky in my life, I had difficulties, I met people who helped me and I think it's just normal that I repay this chance helping people in return.
It's my karma and it's the principle of give-take, you take and give, take, help, take but then you have to help and give back.
The actions of Zebunet, like my small actions in the village, are not great actions.
We are not going to change the world, we will not wipe out poverty in the world, but I think that in life, we should not hesitate to do actions even if they seem small.
Lao Tzu said: "Better to light a candle than to curse the darkness. "
I would add, better try to go forward rather than cursing injustice.
Go forward, fight, and along your way, you will find Omar, Zebunet, people who open their hearts and their arms.
(Applause)
Are there cognitive differences between genders?
I've got to be crazy for choosing to broach such a controversial topic to you!
Yet, there are good reasons to do it, and you're well aware of them. These are the statistics you all know.
For example: women are more often in search of employment than men, that they are paid less than men in equivalent positions, that they access executive and managing positions less often than men, even when they are just as qualified as men, or even more, on average.
And so, these statistics are actually appalling and I suppose that you all, like me, would like to step these numbers up to 50%.
However, various approaches differ on how to achieve this goal.
If you have followed the debates on this subject in the media recently, even just a little, you must have noticed that the main leitmotiv which keeps coming up consists of simply denying that cognitive or cerebral differences exist between genders.
Or, if they do exist, that they are completely marginal, or they are the result of stereotypes, or educational biases between boys and girls.
Well, personally, I find this approach particularly bold, since it makes a moral principle rest on facts which can or cannot be observed in real life.
So, imagine that tomorrow, a new scientific research is published and clearly shows that there are cognitive differences between genders, then everything collapses and all of a sudden, people will tell themselves, "Actually, there were differences. I was right to discriminate women in hiring and to pay them less than men."
We can see that there is something wrong about these arguments.
Even more so, given that these arguments have already been proven wrong since proofs of cognitive differences between genders actually exist.
This is what we're going to do today. For the first time, go over the data which actually shows this is in fact, the case. Then, come back to our initial question.
Thus, there are cognitive differences between genders, but which ones?
All those which we are talking about aren't necessarily real.
For example, in the 19th century, we believed that women were less intelligent than men, as said by the famous neurologist, Paul Broca, perhaps due to the smaller size of their brain.
Facing such an assertion, there are two possible stances.
You can either say that it's absolutely unacceptable, so it has to be false, but you will concede that it is some sort of wishful thinking.
Or you might take a more scientific approach, and check the data. Let's see if it backs up this hypothesis.
If we take a look at the data, first: do genders have a different brain volume?
Yes, they do: men have a brain that is, on average, 9% larger than a woman's.
Second question: is it true that there is a link between brain volume and general intelligence, which we can measure through IQ tests?
The response is once again yes, which you see illustrated by these lines here.
The differences in brain volume between people explain around 10% of IQ differences.
Third point: does that mean that women necessarily have a lower IQ than men?
By looking at the data, we can respond to this question.
Here is the data from a particular study that was confirmed by many others.
You see people's brain volume on the x-axis, and on the y-axis, their IQ. The men are in black and the women in white.
What you see, if you look at the x-axis, is effectively that the men have larger brains than the women.
If you look at the lines that show the connection between brain size and IQ, you clearly see that within the men, there is a relationship, and within the women, there is also a relationship.
Look now at the IQ on the y-axis, you see that, on average, there isn't an IQ difference between women and men.
From a scientific approach, this allows to give a firm and definitive response to Broca, which is: no. Men and women do not differ in terms of general intelligence.
Well, does that mean that there is no difference?
Not necessarily.
There could be more subtle differences.
For example, on the brain level, if you look at different brain regions, there are some that differ between men and women.
This image shows that the regions in blue have larger volumes of grey matter in men than in women, on average, while the red areas have larger volumes of grey matter in women than in men.
I will not go through all of the regions in detail, but some are in the limbic system, also known as the emotional brain.
If we look at it on a cognitive level, is it manifested through differences of performance during tests?
Once again, the response is yes.
There is a handful of cognitive functions where men and women differ a little.
You see an illustration here.
These are two cognitive tests.
The first, which we see on top, is a kind of Spot the Difference.
You've got a board with a certain number of objects.
You look at it, then it's hidden, and the second board is shown to you, and you have to guess which items changed place.
It's a task of spatial locations memorisation.
The task below: you are shown a 3D object and then, you are shown several others that are the same object which has been rotated, but one amongst them shouldn't be there, as it is not the same object rotated, but its mirror image.
You are asked to find this one.
One of these tasks is better performed by men, while the other is better performed by women.
Are you able to guess which is which?
We are going to test you.
You will vote by raising your hands.
Those who think that the spatial location task is better performed by men, and the mental rotation task is better performed by women, raise your hands.
Go ahead, I want to see your hands. There isn't a lot of you.
Are you guys shy?
The people who think exactly the opposite, raise your hands.
Straightaway, there are more hands.
And so I can tell you that the majority of you, indeed, have the right intuition.
Meaning that women are better at memorisation tasks of object locations, while men are, on average, better at tasks where you have to manipulate objects in space.
It's not enough to show that men and women differ on such and such test.
Because, what does that prove?
It doesn't prove the difference is innate.
There are many factors that lead to such performance differences.
Perhaps it's education: it's a fact that boys are not educated in the same way that girls are, that girls are not encouraged in the same activities, they are not led to the same things.
There can also be stereotype biases.
I will illustrate this stereotypical bias through this famous American study in which they gave a quite complex math test to university students.
The first version had a notice explaining that it was a math test in which men usually performed better than women.
The observed results did indeed conform to this suggestion, namely that men have better results than women.
In a second version, they gave exactly the same math test, but only changed the instructions which said, "Here is a math test in which there is no difference between genders."
And there, the results showed no difference between genders.
Thus, you see that, eventually, through a simple suggestion, you can induce stereotypes in people's minds that they will end up conforming to.
It's a bit like a self-fulfilling prophecy.
We think, "Of course, these kinds of stereotypes, there are many of those, especially stereotypes devaluing women."
Then, if women internalize it and conform to this stereotype, then that could explain the numerous differences observed.
To be sure, once again, it's necessary to examine the data.
Here is a long list of tests, in which we compared men's and women's performances.
The ones that do not differ between men and women are those on the middle line. Those with the pink lines going to the left are the tests that are to the women's advantage. Those with the blue lines going to the right are the tests that are to the men's advantage. The length of the lines reflects the size of the difference between genders, on a statistical level which I won't explain to you.
But in order to fix ideas, look at the blue line at the bottom.
It's the size of the difference in body size between the sexes.
Men are, on average, a little larger than women.
This is irrefutable!
And this difference has a size that is two on this statistical scale, what is represented here.
In comparison, the majority of cognitive differences between genders is not actually that big.
They are lower than 1 on this scale, so by taking a man and a woman randomly and by comparing them on these tests, they have less chances of being different than if we took two men randomly or two women randomly.
Let's say they are lesser differences.
Could they be completely explained by stereotype biases?
You have to compare them to the effects of stereotype represented by the grey area.
Effectively, you see that a certain number of these differences in the middle, which are small, can be completely attributed to effects of stereotype, potentially.
There are some as well that are a little larger and that probably cannot be completely due to effects of stereotype.
And I will illustrate this with a specific example: aggressiveness.
The differences are minimal, however, they can have a certain importance.
Aggressiveness, how is it measured?
For example, through questionnaires in which you answer to dozens of questions that target your attitudes, based on your reactions in several situations.
The scores of all these questions are gathered and, at the end, a score out of 200 or 250 is given.
And here you have the distribution of the men's scores in blue and the distribution of women's scores in red.
What you see is that these distributions are a little staggered: the men's average is a little higher than the women's.
You could say that men are, on average, more aggressive than women.
But, the two distributions overlap quite a lot, so there are also a lot of women who are more aggressive than a lot of men.
You could say, "This difference is so small that it has literally no importance."
If we see the data in a different way, if we interest ourselves in the proportion of men and women that go above a certain score, in the lower scores, we have one man for one woman, but when we get to the scores that are average, we have two men for one woman. When we get to 150, it is four men for one woman. And at 200, we have eight men for one woman.
The number is perhaps linked to another statistic, which is the perpetrators of homicide. There are about ten men for one woman.
So we see through this example that even when an average difference is very small and there is a large overlap between the two distributions, there can be very significant consequences on a societal level.
So, we have spoken about the cognitive differences between genders, about differences of personality.
There are also differences of preference.
That is to say that spontaneously, men and women are attracted to different objects and activities.
And these differences are observed from infancy.
From the nursery playgrounds, we can clearly see that boys are attracted to games that are a little more active, competitive, rowdy, while girls will be more attracted by calmer games that are also more social and cooperative.
These are stereotypes, but also observations that can be made in very young childen.
Obviously, you can think that the way in which we educate boys and girls is not unrelated to these observations.
But can they explain these differences entirely?
Can the biases in education explain these differences completely?
Well, to be sure, it is necessary to watch younger children, with appropriated methodologies.
For example, in my laboratory, we have methods to study the infant's perception.
For example, you can see if the infant prefers to look longer at one visual stimulus or another.
What you observe in this kind of experiment is that babies, when they are girls, will prefer to look longer at the female face, but when it is boys, they will prefer to look longer at this abstract image, which you do not see, but there is a string with a ball that is hanging - a kind of mobile.
You see that from the youngest age, as it so happens, the experiment shows that from birth, boys and girls already have preferences for different objects.
You also see some differences concerning cognitive capacities, like the previous mental rotation in space.
So the 3D object is shown to this baby and then is turned and presented in different orientations. Then, after a few seconds, the mirror image of this object is shown.
So it is no longer the same as the rotated object.
What you observe is that baby boys notice the difference, and that is shown through an increase in the amount of time they watch the new object.
While the girls, you see on the two left lines, do not show any difference in the amount of time they watch. So, in theory, they do not notice the difference between the object and its mirror image.
These are experiments that were performed between three and five months, otherwise said, at an age where it is still not very plausible that the cognition of these babies has already been biased by different treatments between boys and girls.
So, if there can be differences as early as this, where do they come from?
Well, we have a small idea of the mechanisms that are at work.
You know that genetic differences exist between men and women in their sexual chromosomes.
The fact that the male fetus possesses a Y chromosome will differentiate their testicular gonads, very early, and their testicles will secrete testosterone, that will progressively soak into the tissues by reaching a peak around 15 weeks of pregnancy.
But if you look at the dotted line at the bottom, in the female fetuses, the testosterone remains at zero all throughout development.
The fact this testosterone soaks into all the tissues will masculinize the tissues, will change the cells slightly to have them take on a form which is specific for the male sex.
This phenomenon is also produced in the brain and drives structural and functional differences, and behavioral differences.
These things are very well demonstrated in different animal species because in the animal, we can conduct experiments where we manipulate the rate of fetal testosterone.
You can imagine though that we don't authorize these experiments on human beings and consequently, there isn't formal proof that the exact same thing happens with humans.
Despite everything, we do know that the human being's biology is compatible with the idea that the same mechanisms are at work in the human being.
So, in summary, you saw, yes, cognitive differences between men and women do clearly exist.
They are not enormous, they are moderate sized, or otherwise said, they don't justify distribution of differentiated roles between men and women in society.
But they are credible.
Some of them can be observed from infancy, even from birth, and we begin to recognize, at least partially, their cerebral foundations and hormonal and genetic origins.
So, there are differences.
So what?
Does that justify discrimination
of women in employment, paying them less?
Obviously not!
Because there are differences, nothing justifies this discrimination, whatever the differences highlighted.
So it is clear that we are actually bloody wrong.
It's a matter of confusion between equality in law and equality in practice.
When you say that human beings are born free and equal in law, you're not observing a fact, you're affirming a value.
We wanted to continue to affirm this value whatever the observation that can be made, and whatever the differences that can be observed between individuals.
Because, in any case, differences are everywhere, and they will always be there.
We are all different and, actually, so that we all can be equal, it would be necessary that we all be clones, and so all the same gender, and, furthermore, everyone would be raised in the exact same laboratory conditions.
Does that appeal to anyone?
No? Good.
So differences are everywhere.
Finally, this is also what makes human life interesting.
It's diversity and this is also what makes it possible to hope that rather than being afraid of our differences, we can try to capitalize on them and recognize that we also have qualities that are able to complement one another.
Elsewhere, the idea of justice and equity is still more important.
What is unjust is to devalue a person evaluating them based on average qualities, real or assumed, of the gender or of the group to which they belong.
This is fundamentally unjust, while justice is simply evaluating people on the basis of their individual qualities, independent of their gender or another group that they belong to.
To conclude, I think that this is what is necessary to vindicate for women.
It's not de facto equality in every aspect with men.
It's equality in law, and that is justice and equity.
Thank you.
(Applause)
T.B: Do you know who this man is?
OK, he's a bit scary, but he's really quite cool.
Bismarck, I heard someone say, he's the man who invented the idea of retirement.
Thanks to him, you can all stop working and enjoy your days of old age.
In 1889, Bismarck asked his advisor: "What should I make the retirement age so no one will be able to reach it?
His advisor then answered: "65 years old."
That used to be the life expectancy.
(Laughter) B.G: Old Bismarck was pretty smart.
(Applause) Nowadays, one's life expectancy is no longer 65 years, but 85 years.
It's improved so much that a whole bunch of the population is over 60.
Meaning, one out of three people you cross in the street is in retirement.
No, but seriously, you've never asked yourselves who all these old folks are who go grocery shopping at 7 p.m. when you're getting out of the office?
(Laughter) T.B: Or who's taking your place on the bus, or whose retirements we're paying for.
B.G: You're going a bit far there, in reality, these old folks are in shape.
Last week even, I lost 6-0 to my 66 old dad at tennis.
T.B: That's not so hard! (Laughter)
B.G: These are people who have experience, often working more than 40 years at the same job. And you see, these are people with a lot of time on their hands.
The explosive popularity of the show "Letters and Numbers" is a consequence.
(Laughter) T.B: Being in retirement in France, is having a long time whether it be personal or professional, it's being healthy, and it's of course having time to enjoy and to do all the things you've always dreamed of doing.
However, retirement in France, is now a paradox.
We all have that one neighbour, parents or grandparents, that once in retirement felt a lack of purpose.
The feeling of being set aside from society.
Basically, retirement is no longer joyous you'd be right to wonder: Why is it so dreaded?
B.G: All throughout our lives, all we've done is learn.
As children we learn to walk, to babble a few syllables, later on to read and write, and then we take on our formal studies.
Then, we will start a career where we will spend a long time, and once we get to retirement, everything will be put aside.
We'll go from an active life, to a society seen as inactive, and we bring with us our long career experience.
While we've set up circular systems to save energy. or limit food waste. It seems we're incapable of preserving these life skills, or of capitalizing on this school of life,
T.B: Talking about school, Barthélemy I'll take this moment to mention, we met at engineering school, in Lille, where we followed a curriculum in construction and roadwork.
Like many of you, we wanted to travel world.
So we took our work to Congo, Mexico and even to the Philippines.
It was in these three countries that we were blown away by the respect et importance bestowed upon their elders.
In those places, elders are considered wise, they live with their families, and bonding between generations is an omnipresent feature.
B.G: In Congo, I was working on the urbanisation of a town, a village called Kinkala, to the west of Brazzaville, on weekends I was alone, and a bit bored, I would go walk around to meet people.
One day, I met Jean-Aimé, the president of the "Sapeurs" in Kinkala.
I'm on the same page as you all, he isn't too elegantly dressed, rather in pyjamas, but part of the group you know,
"la SAPE", that's basically who they are.
(Laughter) I'm not sure if you're all familiar with "la SAPE"?
"La SAPE", is the " Society of Ambiance-Makers and Elegant People".
(Laughter) Maybe to you all it seems absurd, but it's a movement in Brazzaville, uniting Congolese dandies since the 1960s, and the art of getting all dressed up, continues generation through generation.
This little old man, was the counsel for the whole village, and in addition to spreading his art, he spread his life knowledge to the other generations.
Taking a little step back from these anecdotes, we found in these countries an integration system for seniors into society.
A system where they were really a big part
And what's crazy about Thibault, is that we noticed this same thing, while we were each in different parts of the world.
The importance of elders' roles in society.
Upon return to France, we said to each other that something had to be done.
T.B: So we researched how to adapt such a system to our own society.
and just like Barthélemy and his well-dressed friend, I had a little old friend,
myself in Mexico.
Miguel. Miguel was the bicycle repairman in the neighbourhood. He knew how to lace a bike wheel with his eyes close.
I spend so much time with him, because I loved learning about his great experiences.
These two experiences abroad, taught us something.
That was that if we want to create lasting bonds between generations, is even better, to have something concrete to share between two generations.
Upon our returns to France, we looked for these sorts of things.
We began by first looking through groups on Facebook. Sewing, crochet, knitting -- B.G: Calm down, personally, I was looking at mechanics, I'll leave the knitting to you.
(Laughter) T.B: And from there we swapped out our friends for a group of super awesome 60 year olds.
We met younger and younger retirees, et seniors that were experts in many fields, and we set them up with young people, or younger people, who wanted to learn from their great experience.
At the beginning, we started at our homes, and by word of mouth, we grew bigger.
B.G: it's true that when you think about it, what better than learning from someone who has been practicing by passion or job, something for more than 40 years.
What better than learning to develop film with a retired photographer/reporter from the French Press Agency, or even to sew with a retired director of a Haute Couture studio.
With these elders, we found this togetherness, this sharing, this energy that there used to be, and we knew that this was possible to bring to France.
We didn't originally come from this world, we were building roads in the Mexican pampas.
And then we dropped everything, to build the first community, that would enable young people to look for the experience of seniors and their knowledge.
We wanted to also enable retirees in France to love retirement.
To flourish by meeting people from all areas of their passions, and to feel valued by spreading their knowledge.
We gave this solution a little name, we called it "Les Talents d'Alphonse", Alphonse's Talents.
This is the first platform that will connect young retirees, with people eager to learn from their knowledge.
So, how does it work?
It's super simple: Say you want to learn music or photography, you would go on our website, you would tell us your interest, and we would match you up with a super experienced 'Alphonse' who lives in your area to create a link at a local level.
T.B: Since January, with Barthélemy and the launch of our platform, it brings us so much joy to receive all these messages of duos that we've made, between seniors -- we call them Alphonses or Alphonsines -- and young people who want to learn, the curious.
Take for example Nicole, who was invited to Mauritius Island to visit a person who was teaching her to sew, Douria is her name, who receives to this day, three months after having taught her last lessons, photos of her baby.
"Les Talents d'Alphonse", from this spreading of knowledge enables also the creation of a lasting bonds between generations.
And today, with a huge population of retirees, it is urgent to rethink of a new model of society, where seniors are no longer considered burdens, but as indispensable resources to a well balanced society.
B.G: Malian writer Amadou Hampâté said it best: "The quality of a society can be judged by the way it treats its elders."
Imagine a society, where we can all have a million grandpas or grandmas.
Not two, not three, not four, a million.
A society that is actually one big family.
Thank you.
(Applause)
"I'm sick of being a woman.
That's it, I'm tired of it.
A few days ago, I was running home, to escape from a man who was pursuing me.
The next day, I discovered members of parliament are making fun of recent sexual assaults.
And the following day, I discovered that a so-called humorist was joking about rape accusations, calling them puritanism.
Every day, every bloody day, I’m reminded that I didn’t win the gender bingo."
This is a text that I wrote in May to testify to my exhaustion owing to the prevailing sexism.
And to show you that my exasperation has lasted since, let's talk about this journalist who, a few days ago, publicly kissed the breast of a woman who refused to kiss him.
Let's talk about that famous woman who was assaulted, tied up, robbed at her hotel, Kim Kardashian, and who immediately became the laughing stock of the web.
People were delighted at her abuse and showed their surprise that she wasn't raped.
So, my experience is not unique.
What I’ve come here to tell you, is what thousands or millions of women experience almost daily, and is not at all sexy.
In 2012, a young Belgian videographer filmed with a hidden camera what men were saying to her when she walked down the street.
She revealed the violence she had to face every time she walked in public spaces.
The comments that were made to her were super violent, super sexualised.
The attitudes were very threatening, very insistent, and the gestures, very improper.
When I watched this video, I realized that I had also been experiencing this for years.
But I had become used to it since my teens, to the extent I could no longer realize how abnormal it was.
A few days after having seen this video, I was driving home through the streets of Marseille one evening.
At a red light, a man called me from his car, clearly manifesting his intentions.
Had he been lost, I’d have helped him, but clearly, his destination was between my legs.
So, I did what I usually do in these situations: I ignored him, looked straight ahead, and begged the traffic light to go green.
The traffic light quickly obliged, but apparently the man really didn’t appreciate my lack of response.
He started following me, overtook me at high speed and then cut me off afterwards, and he repeated that over and over again.
It lasted about ten minutes.
I discovered that I had a certain talent for driving GTA style ... (Laughter) ... to the point where my chaser finally gave up.
So, I was finally able to go home safe and sound, but terrified.
This harassment incident was far from being the first.
But it is the first I had spoken about in my whole life.
The Sophie Peters's video I mentioned had deeply affected me, so I spoke about this incident with some female friends.
And the feedbacks were unanimous, we had absolutely all experienced harassment incidents in public spaces or in public transport.
The experiences were varied: from a simple comment meant as a compliment, to complete and utter sexual assault, as well as wandering hands, rubbers, stalkers, insults, etc.
The video I'm telling you about triggered a huge debate, in France and in Belgium, and a name was put on what we were experiencing: "street harassment."
But like all public debates, it quickly got out of hand.
I especially noticed a huge amount of denial.
Many claimed that sexual harassment is the fantasy of paranoid women, that it was only flirting, that we should be happy to be continually courted, in short, that it was not a problem.
Although we have proof under our very eyes with this video of the burden that can weigh on one person, we continued to imagine that all we hear on the streets are goofy taunts like: "Hey you, you got hazelnut eyes, can I be your squirrel?"
(Laughter) But for my part, I’m mainly used to hearing things like "You, I really want to blow your pussy," which is different.
So, I decided to create a blog, with a name as flowery as what I hear in the streets: "Paye Ta Shnek", PTS, on which we can record the comments we hear when we move around in public spaces.
I, myself, sent in a few comments I remembered, And I sent the link to some girlfriends, asking them to do the same.
Five days later, it exploded.
I was receiving over 150 submissions per day.
It was a constant flow as if I had opened floodgates.
There was an infinite overflow that was flowing into my inbox.
I received 12,000 stories in four years, all of which I read. They allowed me to realize the extent of the problem, and understand the reality of street harassment because in fact, my own experience was just one among thousands.
I realized that street harassment is not just sexist. It’s also racist, homophobic, transphobic, fatphobic, islamophobic, or ableist, thus relating to disability.
I realized that we still don’t know how to talk about this subject.
So, for you to see that we are still a very long way from a poetic "The embers in your eyes drive me bananas," (Laughter) I have selected for you a few revealing submissions.
I’ll let you read them since I've difficulty saying these sentences out loud, and then we’ll talk about them.
First submission:
[Who do you think you are? I have a penis
I'm the man! Women must obey men.]
Is it necessary to highlight the sexist dimension of this comment?
Or to specify that this event
is an assault? I don't think so,
However, there's a funny point
I enjoy raising. After having read the words of 12,000 harassers, I notice that thousands of them are quick to speak about their penis.
(Laughter) This makes me think there's scope for questioning.
Maybe we should stop ignoring the domination that a penis has over the person who owns it and thus over the rest of the world.
(Laughter) Second submission: [Hi little submissive beurette. People
say you go crazy once liberated, crazy about sex! I'm ready to train you
half-whore, half-submissive!]
Here, we have a combination of sexism and islamophobia, because this young woman wears a veil, and the wonderful fantasy of liberation through sex.
This type of harassment is the fastest-growing at present.
Against a background of heightened racism and islamophobia, muslim or supposedly muslim, women are more and more harassed, assaulted, etc.
Third submission: [Hey dykes, don't you want to have your pussy blown by a man, a real one?
You'll see, it's cool to be submissive in the normal way.]
This time, it's a combination of sexism and lesbophobia, homophobia.
We can notice the persistent mention of the idea of submission, women’s eternal status, of course.
but also the constant preoccupation with what is the norm.
We still don’t know what "normal" means, but this man obviously has a very precise definition.
Fourth submission: [How fucking ugly you are! But I'd like to have sex with your breast.]
There’s a myth concerning street harassment.
It is said that it only affects young and pretty women. this is not true.
In the streets, all women are complimented or insulted.
We also hear comments from shoppers when we're not to their liking, as it’s well known that we’re only here to decorate their field of vision, so they don’t hesitate to speak out when we don’t embellish their environment well enough.
(Laughter) Fifth and last submission: [With your shorts, don't be surprised if I rape you."]
This submission is hyper indicative of the existence of the rape culture that runs inside our societies.
We almost systematically blame the victim or potential victim for being responsible for her abuse.
Her attitude, appearance, presence at a certain time in a certain place, reportedly explain why she has been harassed.
And this very guilt-tripping of the victim and removing of guilt from the harasser is obvious from the assault itself but also from all the authorities supposed to take care of victims, Including our friends and relatives when we speak about what happened.
That’s why we call it "a culture," because it’s a very common way of thinking in all sections of society both private and public, and it's constantly sustained by public discourse, by the media, advertising, the film industry, etc. Actually, when you follow this reasoning, you’re insinuating that men are uncontrollable beasts, under the influence of their hormones, unable to control their impulses. Sadly, the people who are the most
concerned are the least aware of this.
So, you've seen an extract from the submissions.
I'm not going to ruin your evening by imposing on you the violence that express itself in French-speaking public spaces.
Rather, I'd like to initiate new thoughts.
Individually, are we part of the problem or part of its solution?
Are we really aware of the gravity of the problem?
In 2015, the High Council for Equality between men and women conducted a survey of female users of French public transportation.
Sadly, the outcome didn’t surprise me: 100% of the surveyed women had been victims of sexist harassment or sexual assaults
in public transport. 100%!
In over half of the cases, the first assault took place when they were underage.
On PTS, I receive submissions from victims aged 11 and 12.
So, I’m often asked the big question: "What’s the difference between flirting and harassment?"
The difference is very simple: it’s consent.
Flirting is a game played by two people.
As for harassment, it is imposed by one person on another.
It’s completely different.
When we talk to someone in public places, they’re not there to meet people.
So, we could be a nuisance or face a refusal, and if that’s the case, we must respect it and not be insistent.
We must take the context into account.
A man who tries to talk to a woman alone at night, in a deserted street, can imagine that, in principle, it’s scary.
We must also remember that the person to whom we give your opinion on her looks and who didn’t ask for it, doesn’t care about our opinion.
That’s also a myth we must debunk. Too often we consider that a compliment is necessarily the best thing that can happen during a woman’s day, whoever she may be and whoever pays the compliment.
So, I’m going to disclose to you a secret: that’s not true.
Personally, I don’t care if the local troublemaker thinks I’m bangable.
(Laughter) I don’t need nor want to know it.
And just like many women, I attach no value to the opinions of strangers about my looks.
Quite often, when I hear a saucy comment and let the person know I don’t care about their opinion, suddenly I become an unfuckable ugly woman, (Laughter) because I failed to enjoy the sacred gift this man gave to me.
(Laughter) Being attractive should have made me jump for joy, as I live only to flatter his retinas in the hope of a short hot coïtus in the escalator.
(Laughter) If I keep answering about the difference between flirting and harassment, it’s often to reassure my interlocutor, but let's be clear, street harassment is absolutely not a game of seduction.
In the vast majority of cases, there’s no intention to flatter or seduce.
When my harasser shouted he wanted to blow my pussy, he knew very well that it wouldn’t end up as a candlelight dinner.
The guy who chased me by car didn't expect it to be the beginning of a great romance.
In the great majority of cases, it’s just a way of imposing a kind of outdated superiority, to crush the other person and make oneself feel stronger, thus perpetuating a state of fear.
Because public spaces are still today places of huge discrimination.
Cities were created by and for men.
To verify the male domination in public spaces, you just have to open your eyes.
Everywhere, you can see men sticking around.
Do you see women doing the same?
As I was entering a shop to pick up a present belonging to my mother, she had to wait for me outside the shop for five minutes.
She explained to me that she felt she had to move, to look at her phone and walk around in order to avoid conveying the wrong message, to avoid the risk of suggesting she was available.
All women or nearly feel they can only pass through public spaces and not use them, because still today in 2016, we are still given to understand that outside is not our place.
Many women told me about their day-to-day strategies, those avoidance strategies we develop spontaneously In the hope of not being sexually harassed.
Some use their keys as a potential weapon; others don’t go out without headphones in their ears, even with no music, just to display a kind of withdrawal.
We compute what to wear before going out.
We choose our seat in the subway preferably close to other women.
We ask to be carried home in the evening, we don’t go home on foot at night.
Some told me they moved homes because of the frequent harassment with which they were faced.
That’s when you realize that street harassment changes our day-to-day behavior and choices.
So, I’d like to take advantage of the audience I have before me tonight to try a little experiment.
I’m going to ask you a question, but you're not obligated to answer it.
I’ll start by questioning the women of the audience.
When I talk about sexual harassment, street harassment, it refers to insults, rubbers, wandering hands, stalkers, etc., any person who makes us feel very uncomfortable at one point.
Ladies, which of you has ever experienced sexual harassment in a public space or in public transport?
That’s the answer that I was expecting.
You can turn around and look at the result, we're very numerous.
Thank you very much.
Now, I’m going to ask you, gentlemen.
Which of you has ever been sexually harassed in a public place or in public transport?
(Laughter) You are far fewer!
What this experiment is revealing is that men and women don’t live, don’t experience life the same way.
What do men do on a daily basis to avoid being sexually harassed?
It’s not a daily worry.
Of course, it does happen to some men, but as a group, men don’t have to constantly deal with this threat, whereas women have to live with it.
When I mention this point, I anticipate straight away: no, all men are not potential harassers.
I know it, you know it, we all know it, So that's settled.
But not all harassers have the same profile.
The media often handles the subject badly.
They insinuate that sexual harassment would be the preserve of poor men and/or immigrants, and that's perfectly wrong.
The 12,000 submissions I’ve received on PTS prove it.
For example, those we call "white collar workers" are far from being free of sexist and threatening behaviour.
Two projects have recently begun against sexist harassment, one in the world of lawyers called "Paye ta robe," the other in the world of politics called "Chair collaboratrice."
This proves that even in the most well-educated and affluent circles, sexist harassment is still present.
We should all without exception ask ourselves: Have I ever behaved in this kind of way, such as being insistent after a refusal, or commenting on a person’s looks although I haven't been asked?
What do I do when I witness sexual harassment, or when a loved one talks or behaves in such a way in front of me?
Do I stop it? Do I intervene?
Do I dissociate myself at least?
Or do I do nothing?
Often, when we witness sexual harassment, we dare not intervene for fear to put ourselves at risk.
But, in fact, there are techniques to intervene non-violently which can help without putting oneself in much danger.
Let me mention two of them so everyone will go home with some inspiration.
The first technique is to speak to the victim as if we knew her and start up a random conversation, in order to isolate the harasser in hope that he goes away.
We can say to the victim, "Where were you?
I’ve been looking for you everywhere.
Let’s go find the others," and we take her away.
The second technique is to talk to the harasser, about a completely different subject.
We can say to him say, "Excuse me, where to get off to the town hall?
Do you have the time, please?"
or whatever, the point is to divert his attention in the most polite way possible to give to the victim time to go away.
These techniques are extremely useful, do not entail many risks, and have been tried out; they are based on the submissions I’ve received or which were published in the Crocodile Project.
To be part of the solution and not of the problem, we can start by acting individually, but the whole of society is concerned.
Men do not have the monopoly on sexism.
We have all grown up in the same society, so we all reproduce the same patterns.
We should not let these behaviors develop before our eyes.
We must invest time in education by speaking to our children, our students, by teaching them all forms of equality, and by not tolerating ever any oppressive language or behavior.
We also need to stop teaching girls how not be harassed, and start teaching everyone not to harass others.
The deconstruction of all the discriminatory patterns passed down centuries after centuries, starts by listening to the people who experience it from the inside, and by spreading and amplifying their voices to help them be heard and known to all.
It’s only by being mindful, good listeners and unified that we’ll reduce this violence.
Because public spaces belong to all of us, whatever our gender.
Whether we are Black, Muslim, gay, fat, thin, Asian, it does not matter, we all, male and female, have a right to peace.
And if this sentence seems obvious to you, in practice, it’s still very far from being the case.
On PTS and on the projects that are named behind me, we’re now trying to foster a collective reflection and to fight together, collectively, against this violence.
Right now, those of us who experience street harassment really feel alone as for this.
So, I’m going to conclude with the text I read at the beginning of my speech: "To be a woman means fighting against fear, against violence, against our anxieties.
It’s being part of a group that has no name, an invisible sorority that which is not even aware of its own incredible strength.
I’m sick of being a woman, but I wouldn’t switch roles for anything!
I’m a woman and proud to see that more and more of us are fighting all round the world, with our specific characteristics, with our obstacles, with our means.
I’m proud of us for speaking louder and louder, laughing, moaning, shouting and making noise.
Being a woman means deserving the moon and going to get it yourself."
(Applause)
Hello.
So I have the responsibility to explain to you what creativity is, for me.
This isn't easy because I spend my time in my studio, between four walls, working on small copper plaques, that will have engravings, and here I have to speak before a hundred people, and that requires a some courage.
This notion of courage, I think is important, in the first place.
I think that creation requires courage, that which you cannot try to obtain with ease, trend or the system.
I think that you are creative all of your life as a creator.
And I also think that you are creative by nature.
So when I was young, I spend a lot of time alone in my corner, because I did not want, maybe, other people to tell me what I should do.
So I spent a lot of time drawing and I loved it.
It was the only thing I did when I had free time.
The problem is that it never stopped, and I had to continue on this path because for me, it was very important.
So, I went to an art school after high school.
And in this art school, I learned to work with 19th century methods.
This school was called L'Académie Julian.
And there you learned to work with things as barbaric as that.
I have in my pocket something called a "plumb line".
We had to draw, from measurements taken with tools like this.
And at the end of that year, I realized that I had learned many things and I was very happy to know all of it.
I said, "That's it, I finally know how to draw." Super!
Next, I went to Beaux-Arts in Paris where I was told, "Son, it's not that at all, drawing is not working with the methods you've been taught but rather working with your emotions, with your heart after all..." So I was a little unsettled.
I had to sur acknowledge that the people who had told me that were right.
And I understood that what I had been looking for until then was certainty.
Teachers say, "A head is like this, a tree is like this, a house has a red roof" etc.
After that, it's difficult to tell yourself that it's all useless.
So I was a bit lost, but I understood that what matters in creation, is not having certainty, but rather searching for what you do not know.
So I think that creation, in any case, as far as I'm concerned, is rather a type of discovery, it's an adventure.
Bonnard said: "Painting is the adventure of the optic nerve."
So let's keep the idea of adventure
and discover what you are going to do.
A creator is someone who is going to do something he doesn't know, but he will discover.
So you are a bit like an archeologist, who is going to a site, armed with knowledge.
He knows roughly where he is going, but he does not know what he will find.
So he will dig, he will find something, keep it, put it in his pocket, and then he will want to go further.
He will continue, maybe find something more interesting.
I think that creation, is always looking for something more interesting in the end.
Then, there is no manual.
When you are sure of nothing, you have to manage to do something.
So, you have tools, I had mine, I learned painting, I learned drawing, and when I approach the question of knowing how to represent, for example, this young woman in front of me, I am completely unarmed, because I am in front of something completely new, that I do not know how to translate other than by the means that I have not yet discovered.
I have all my tools in hand, I know how to paint, I have done many paintings, but my tools will not necessarily serve me to penetrate the mystery of the person before me.
I must find solutions because even if I've done many portraits, there's no way everything I did before can help me make the portrait in question.
So, that's always the question.
Even if you are an abstract painter, I think that you cannot make a painting and another identical one and then another one.
Each time the problem is completely new.
You must deal with that.
That may give rise to a merciless battle between the artist and his work, between the painter and the canvas, if you would... And sometimes it's a real fight, because you battle with what you have learned, with your certainty, with your culture, and also with your desire to do something different.
And all that, it's always a little messy, in your head and on the paper.
If I make a painting, everything gets mixed up, I want to do something, I think I know how to do it, but if I do what I know how to do, it doesn't work.
I must find something else because I would like to do something different, something very strong, with its own identity, something that reflects me but at the same time is itself.
So I am going to use every possible means to make something, I come to a sort of hodge podge, where everything blends together, and then at a given moment something happens.
And this thing, is the one that counts the most
in creation. It is something that you had not expected, that appears, just like that.
So, it's you who did it, and at the same time, it's not you who did it.
It's more so the work itself that did it, because the work presents itself differently one day, because you have a different perspective that day.
For example, you were doing something else, and you saw your painting in the corner, and then it shows you something else that you wanted to add.
I don't know how to explain it to you, it's a very strange feeling, but everything is there.
The merit of the artist, of the creator is recognizing the moment when the work takes control and brings you where you wanted to go that's to say towards something that you have never done.
It may be mysterious, but I think it happens like that.
Picasso said, "The painting makes me do what it wants." It's exactly that.
So the creator must be capable to admit that his work may escape him and must escape him.
If not, that is not creation, that's doing what you know how to do.
That's all.
When you reach this point in your creation, the work you're making, I want to speak about doors.
That's to say the work you've made, that you are no longer making, that presents itself to your eyes one day, opens a door for you.
In this door, you must engulf yourself, you must enter through this door and go search in the direction that it shows you, until you finish the painting; a painting, a sculpture, or something else...
Because I think that those things finally belong in a more natural order.
That must be the way for whoever calls themselves a creator.
There it is, I think I said just about what I wanted.
Thank you very much.
(Applause)
In every moment, with all your actions, with every breath you take, or each heartbeat, you are in contact with invisible, yet very real energies.
The four elements: Earth, Water, Fire, and Air.
Everything that exists on the planet of the living, every living organism is made up of them.
And they are present at this very moment, in you and among us.
All the great traditions that exist are interested in this subject.
In the Ayurveda of the Hindus, or traditional Chinese medicine, or shamans, alchemists, poets, Aristotle, Pythagoras... Even Hippocrates, the father of medicine, spoke of the Four Humors to explain how living organisms function.
And they all agree in saying that to explain how living things function and how the four elements function, there is one basic principle: and that's balance.
When an organism, a body, is suffering, it's because there's at least one of the four elements that's in imbalance.
I am not a doctor, I am neither shaman nor alchemist.
My job is to help individuals, organizations, businesses, to find balance again in this ever-changing world.
And in fact, I've discovered that there's a surprising correlation between the balance of the four elements in a living organism and the balance that we find in organizations.
So, how did I get here?
I was born in Britain, near the salt marshes, where there is this alchemy between the sun and the sea.
My father was a master of fire at the bottom of the holds of the boats, of shipyards in Saint-Nazaire.
My grandfather was a farmer, he taught me the magic of nature and the seasons.
One day when I was seven, he handed me a hazel wand, a dowsing wand, if you prefer to call it that, and he told me: "Go find me water in the garden."
To my astonished face, he tells me: "Connect to the water in you, and you will connect to the water source."
And, indeed, with my wand, very quickly, without asking questions, I rigorously searched and found all the places in the ground where you could find water and dig a well.
I was in invisible contact with water.
It's true that this is just a part of family folklore.
Between my grandfather, a bit of a druid, (Laughter) my aunt who put out the fire when we got burned or the village healer. This was part of my daily life, this was normal for me.
I was still, at a very young age, already in contact with the four elements.
But I had to move on to serious things: my studies.
(Laughter) For me, this had been languages, and then I went to Paris, for international trade.
I even prepared for the extrance exams at the Quai D'Orsay, I wanted to become a diplomat.
I wanted to bring peace to the world, nothing but that!
But it didn't roll out as I thought it would, at first I started with business intelligence, consulting, I traveled the world a bit and ended in New York for a very large French multinational... I can tell you that over there, the elements and all my Breton folklore was already quite far away.
(Laughter) And yet, one day in September of 2001, I had a magnificent home in Manhattan, I had friends, I had a job I liked, I was in love, and right in front of me, I saw two towers fall.
And at that moment I saw a wave roll in on the city, a wave of tears, sadness, emotions.
And in that instant, with the same magnitude, an opposite energy: hate, anger, fire, war flames.
On TV, and in the eyes of people I crossed.
And there, I understood the elements that make up our world were actually in imbalance.
I didn't have the degrees to bring back peace to the world but had just become interested in sustainable development, social and environmental responsibility within companies.
I began to be passionate about this, and I told myself I would contribute in a field I knew very well: companies.
I wanted to contribute making organizations become more responsible, more conscious of their impact on nature, on society, more transparent, more ethical, more humane.
What if it was possible?
Anyway, I wanted, at my level, in my position, to do my part.
I go back to Paris, and for the last 15 years, I've done change management.
I spend my time helping individuals, organizations, companies, giving them ideas, tools, energy, to prepare for change, in this new world that's coming.
But one point must be made: nature is constant change, however, human nature hates change.
(Laughter) What happens when change is brought on in an organization or a collective?
There's something in us that rigidifies, even petrifies, whereas, in fact, we should become more flexible.
When change is brought on, it stirs emotions, the fear of change, mourning what once was.
And information no longer circulates, whereas, in fact, we should find back fluidity in these exchanges.
What happens when sometimes you just bring one idea, like that?
Sometimes, there are people for whom this awakens desire, desire to act, desire to contribute, desire to create.
And for others, I see hate in their eyes, anger, desire to see me disappear, for I'm bringing such a revolution in their organization.
And then most of the time, what I note is that organizations or companies, are simply missing inspiration.
And that's it, but Eureka, I understood!
For 15 years I had the elements in front of me, they were always present.
And so in fact, as all the alchemists, all the doctors say, it is absolutely necessary in an organization, as in a living organism, to maintain these four elements.
The foundation, the reason for being: Earth.
Communication, exchanges: Water.
Creativity, desire, enthusiasm, even passion: Fire.
And inspiration or vision: Air.
Except that the world we currently live in is completely upside-down.
Changes in the economic model, changes in the education system, political revolution, changes in our means of communication.
Everything changes, all the elements are shaken.
Everywhere, in all parts of our lives, not just at work.
In our communities, in our families, in our couples, inside ourselves as well. When difficult times arise, when we have to live this change, what happens?
We always tend to fan the flames, to resist.
And what happens, whether for a person or in an organization?
We can have a burnout
with this Fire: a "burnout".
Even now in our lexicon we talk about the elements.
And what happens when there's fire?
We need water, we need to bring back exchanges, fluidity, hospitality, empathy, to be able to calm down this fire.
And sometimes when we don't have ideas or desires, sometimes we need to know how to take in air, to find other ideas.
And hence to this new ideas, fire can rise up again, a bit like when we blow on the embers and the fire can start again, the fire of this creative energy.
And sometimes when we're too emotional, when the water just doesn't flow anymore, the water stagnates, - imagine a puddle - just underneath, it rots its framework.
It rots the earth.
And this creates rotten environments, at work or at home.
And sometimes when we are lost, when we are uprooted, it would suffice to be inspired a bit like this African proverb: "When you don't know where you're going, look where you come from."
It's at moments like those that we should look back at our roots to be able to find our creative axis again.
And so it's this balance that's interesting to observe.
Which ones are the elements in surplus or in deficit in our lives, in our organizations, of which we need to regain consciousness to find the balance in this ever-changing world.
In fact, I must confess, I'm sick of change.
(Laughter) Because if we want to contribute to something bigger than ourselves, to this transformation that we want for this world, we are going to need to use something more powerful, that's beyond the four elements.
It won't be enough to just play with the four elements: Earth, Water, Fire, and Air.
We must have another, more important element.
A bit like my hand, here.
There is this thing which is the thumb, the most powerful finger, which can hold any other finger.
A bit like this element that can support any other element and together change everything.
This fifth element is Spirit.
It's consciousness, it's the soul, it's love, it's whatever you want.
I call it Spirit.
Spirit, we talk about it all the time, even in our organizations.
Let's think about the spirit of the air, this world of ideas.
Remember all these great creators, all the big geniuses, those who stirred up and transformed our everyday life, all these great minds-spirits precisely.
Archimedes, Leonardo da Vinci, Nikola Tesla, Beethoven, Bach, they were all in particular states of mind when they achieved this brilliance, this strong intuition, that allowed them to have this magical, revolutionary idea, that still impacts us today.
Think of Newton, he was taking a nap in a particular state of mind when he got this apple onto his head and understood gravity.
And this spirit of Fire.
Another revolutionary, modern genius, Steve Jobs.
He was fired from his own company at age 30 and this had been the most creative period of his entire life
It took just a moment to refocus, connect to his intuition, and at that moment then he imagined NeXT which then completely revolutionized Apple, and he imagined Pixar studios, and he reconnected to this sacred fire, to this passion, and he returned to do business with Apple, and he transformed this enterprise and proposed absolutely revolutionary products that still continue to impact our daily life.
And the spirit of Water.
Think of a rugby team.
Each individual player does nothing alone.
What's important for each one, is to come into contact in empathy, in fluid, permanent connection, in solidarity.
And it's through this team spirit that we can maybe win a match.
Do you remember this Jamaican bobsleigh team at the Olympic Games in Calgary "Rasta Rocket"?
(Laughter) They needed great team spirit to arrive at the end and cross the finish line.
And the spirit of Earth.
It's this enormous power, this feeling of togetherness and belonging in a collective, this "esprit de corps", necessary to the whole collective.
Remember...
Beyond anger or emotion, the state of mind you were in on January 11th, or November 13th, 2015.
The Charlie spirit.
Remember this time of communion, humanity, unity lived together.
So it's through the spirit that we can change the world.
In fact, beyond the four elements, it's important to integrate this fifth one that's inseparable from the others. it's always present, it's at your service.
You are the alchemists, you are the doctors.
It will depend, in fact, on your state of mind, your good or bad spirit, whether you'll be able to contribute to transforming this world.
In fact, there's one last thing that we have shared for a long time, the alchemists and the great thinkers.
It's that our perspective, whether we want to expand it, or broaden our consciousness, it doesn't happen here.
We need to move down about 40 cm and stop here, and so heart to heart, in contact with nature, we can imagine solutions that we need, sustainable ones.
And in stopping here, we'll be able to repair our damaged collectives.
It's in this spot here that in our organizations we'll be able to output from our heart to our work, and maybe direct this world in the right direction again. Thank you.
(Applause)
In life, I can choose to say: This glass is half empty or…?
(Audience) "Half full!"
Let’s go further than "half full."
I can also focus on its precious contents and ask myself: What can I do with that?
I can drink it, I can offer it to someone, I can use it to water a plant, to rinse something, or to cook.
To be positive is the springboard from which we can choose to go further: to choose to act.
Do you remember Dumbo, the little elephant? He was born with ears that were too long, that made him trip.
What could he do with them?
He learned to fly! Years ago, I didn’t realize that I had water inside of my glass.
I believed my other children's progress was normal, it was almost a given, it just happened automatically.
But when my fourth son, Nicolas, was born, I instantly saw there was cause for concern: no eye contact, he didn’t even cry out for something to eat - he was in a "vegetative" state.
What can I do with that?
I decided to do everything possible to help him progress.
When he was 6 months old, a prominent specialist confirmed the diagnosis, and said that Nicolas would never walk, never talk, and that he would be a "vegetable" his entire life.
What can I do with that?
I considered it a challenge.
And I love challenges!
The more difficult it is, the more I am attracted.
You'll have noticed that I said "challenge" and not "problem."
Which is the connotation of that word?
When we hear "problem," it’s often a catastrophe.
Children hear their parents talking of "problems," with an overwhelmed look on their face.
Then we're surprised that children get stuck when they see the word "problem" at school. So for me, Nicolas's difficulties were a challenge to overcome, not a problem.
But I had no idea of the magnitude of this challenge.
Fortunately.
Mark Twain said: "They did not know it was impossible, so they did it."
I did not know it was impossible, so I did it.
First of all, I differentiated between diagnosis and prognosis.
We cannot change a diagnosis, but the prognosis, yes.
And I chose to not believe the prognoses if they were unfavorable.
And so, the first prognosis: he will never be able to walk.
What can I do with that?
I am going to teach him how!
I divided all the steps: with my family, we taught him to move his arms and his legs, to move his back by pushing on his legs, to roll over, to sit, to crawl on an inclined plane, to crawl on a horizontal plane, to walk on all fours, then to take his first step.
So I learned how to set goals and, for every goal, precise aims to achieve.
And what's more, you can’t imagine the joy I felt every time he reached a goal.
Likewise, I rejoiced more for the progress of my other children.
I learned to rejoice at any small thing around me, I learned to feel gratitude for everything around me. And feeling gratitude is the secret of happiness. Second prognosis: he will never be able to talk.
Effectively, when he was 4, Nicolas couldn’t repeat the sound "ah."
No speech therapist in our area felt competent to work with him.
I could have told myself that it was because of his disability that he couldn't make any intelligible sounds.
But looking for excuses is to throw in the towel.
To act is to look for a way.
What can I do with that? I found a speech therapist 60 miles from our home, who first taught him how to say "moto," then "dad" and "mom."
Can you imagine my joy?
There are always ways.
You just need to find them.
Then I learned Makaton, which uses sign language.
And so, he finally understood that the sounds he heard had a meaning.
Then it was reading, which he learned thanks to my mother’s method, and which enabled him to talk.
But as he made physical progress, Nicolas also loved to play the stereotypical games.
He could switch the light on, off, on, off, on, off … for hours.
In a center where he used to go, he had fun transferring the water from one glass to another for hours, days, weeks… There, a professional told me that he surely needed that.
What can I do with that?
I asked myself: Which need?
And then I got the best idea ever - I mean, for my child, but I think also for all those who have autistic behaviors.
I told myself he needed to learn something from his experience.
So I taught him "full," "empty," and the meanings of "more," "less," "as much as," and "half."
He watched me, and that was it -- he never played that game anymore.
We also repeat some experiences, we also make mistakes until we understand something, don’t we?
That great specialist had told us that Nicolas would never go to school.
What can I do with that?
I asked to enroll him in school.
At 5 years old, he went to preschool for 2 hours a week.
Why does a child with difficulties need fewer hours in school than a child who functions well?
I have never understood this logic that is still in place today.
I would like someone to explain it to me.
One day, he was playing, doing his best to color a drawing, while the teacher had a talk with me.
She told me that Nicolas never understood orders. Moreover, she noticed he was less competent than her 2-year-old pupil.
And then, Nicolas furiously doodled his drawing, then crumpled the paper.
What can I do with that?
I understood something crucial.
Put yourself in a child’s shoes.
An adult tells you: "You are incompetent."
How do you feel about that?
The verb "to be" indicates an identity.
If one tells a child he is incompetent, this label will be inherent to him.
Incompetence will then be a part of his deepest being.
And that label prevents change.
It programs him.
He will tell himself he is like that, that he can’t change. Imagine the damage that can be done when a child hears: "He's naughty!"
"He's unbearable!"
"He's shy!"
Imagine the damage that can be done when he becomes an adult, when he repeats that to himself.
Have you ever said to yourself:
"Oh! How stupid I am!"?
To train yourself to stop labeling others, you have to start by not labeling yourself. [I'm lazy.]
At the end of the school year, the teacher confessed that some professionals told her not to waste time on Nicolas, since he would never learn to read, write or count, anyway.
What can I do with that?
I realized that when you don't believe in a child, especially when he is fragile, he will not find resources inside himself.
[Eagle: I dream of flying. Chicken: Eagles stay on the ground!] Besides, this was proved by Rosenthal and Jacobson, with the Pygmalion effect.
Remember Dumbo? He learned to fly because the crows believed he could do it.
I learned to see the potential inside people.
I learned to believe in their abilities.
And when people feel the faith we have in them, they do miracles! Remember that the school teacher said
Nicolas didn’t understand orders?
What can I do with that?
I needed to understand why to be able to help him.
He could hear ever since he had surgery for his deafness, when he was 4 years old.
But Nicolas didn’t listen. He lip-read and he was very nearsighted,
so if the teacher was farther than 7 feet away, he couldn’t understand what she was saying.
So I learned to find out the real reasons behind an issue, and not just take it at face value.
When he was 6 years old, Nicolas was taken out of the school system. What can I do with that?
Great!
Anyway, he only learned in his school that he was incompetent.
At the time, I taught twelfth-grade science classes.
And I was placed in front of a child who didn’t know the difference between 1, 2 and 3.
What a big challenge!
I learned to meditate to find a way.
And I conceived of an amazing method to understand numbers and operations, which still benefits many children today.
When he was 7 years old, Nicolas was even rejected from the special education system.
Fortunately!
It’s because he needed another way.
We decided to do homeschooling.
Don’t think it was easy for me because I was a teacher.
For me, everything had to go fast.
When I was 4, I could read; at 16, I graduated from high school; at 18, I got married; at 19, I had my first child; at 20, I earned a mathematics teacher certification; at 21, another certification and the highest mathematics teaching degree.
Nothing to do with teaching a child with such extreme difficulties!
What can I do with that?
So I learned… patience.
I learned to analyze every aspect of learning.
I worked to discover what level Nicolas was at, to bring him higher.
That's how we should do it with all students, isn’t it?
They are there to be built up.
But when a child has too many difficulties, when he doesn’t understand, what do we do?
We can tell ourselves that he just needs to work -- or worse, that he is incompetent.
I choose to ask myself: What can I do with that?
And I consider it my responsibility -- it is I who must figure out how to teach him.
And I look for different strategies until he understands.
So I went on teaching Nicolas.
But when he reached 10 years old, I felt he was no longer progressing in his understanding.
I was trying to figure out the best processes for his learning and I felt blocked.
What can I do with that?
Then I took off alone in an RV, to attend a Feuerstein Workshop close to Amsterdam.
There I learned the 29 cognitive functions, and it was a revelation.
They are the building blocks of reasoning.
If you build a house without a foundation, what happens?
It doesn’t stand!
In the same manner, in order to build learning, we need the cognitive functions to be in place correctly.
I improved their presentation so that they would be accessible even to children.
It’s a marvelous tool to understand the origin of learning issues.
They even helped my other 4 children who were advanced for their age.
A precocious child functions so fast, they don't even know how they found a result.
They don't even know what they do to think.
And a precocious child often fails at school because if the result doesn’t come immediately, they freeze.
What can I do with that?
I helped them learn how to analyze their thinking so they would be able to succeed in their studies and in their life.
Then I watched around me, and I saw the other children were far away from Nicolas. Nicolas was not near the other children because he was afraid of them.
He kept a 7-foot security perimeter.
What can I do with that?
I told a local teacher about it, and he proposed giving a training to his pupils about autism.
Then they looked for strategies to approach Nicolas and to include him.
The year spent in that 5th-grade class was his nicest school year.
In the school playground, he allowed the others to approach him, to touch him, and he had a lot of friends.
I learned that, thanks to knowledge, preparation, and a teacher’s willingness, miracles can happen.
I saw a lot of children around me who had difficulties.
What can I do with that?
In an nonprofit organization that I had created, we helped them to overcome their difficulties, thanks to a method that I had learned and improved upon.
The results were so wonderful that I wanted others to benefit.
But I couldn’t take care of everybody.
So I created a company called "Upbraining," to get the opportunity to train parents and professionals.
We designed efficient tools to develop cognitive functions.
We identified which learning processes were necessary.
The way we teach is called "metapedagogy."
It’s a transversal method to existing pedagogies.
It applies to everyone, even to non-disabled persons.
I remembered that Nicolas had trouble learning how to write.
So we designed apps for tablets for learning how to trace writing basic lines, then letters, while making it fun.
Nicolas had also had issues with learning about, recognizing and managing his emotions.
What can I do with that?
I designed tools to recognize, understand and manage emotions, that others could benefit from as well.
But emotional intelligence doesn’t refer only to emotions.
It also addresses the ability to communicate in the best possible way.
Many people on the autistic spectrum have difficulties in this area.
But you don't need to be on the autistic spectrum to have difficulty communicating.
At home, Nicolas couldn’t tolerate arguments. What can I do with that?
We learned how to communicate without fighting.
And I created tools to learn how to communicate and how to manage conflicts.
Thanks to this experience with my son, I got the opportunity to learn, to create, and to help others.
Nicolas loves accounting, working on the computer, playing the piano, skiing, riding horses and getting to know other people.
Maybe we don’t choose what happens to us, but we can choose either to act as a victim, waiting passively for things to happen, or to be proactive and to act.
That’s our choice.
We can do it.
For every experience, we can act, find a way, and learn something.
Thanks to Nicolas and his brothers and sister, my life became fascinating.
So, disability?
What can I do with that?
I can say, "Yes."
And, "Thank you."
When I was little, I used to play the piano. I loved that instrument,
Well, more so in the beginning.
After that I was at the Conservatory of Music, and there were exams twice a year.
You had to spend several weeks preparing for one piece that you would play in front of a jury, or sometimes even for an audience. From that point on, playing the piano became mainly a feeling of stress for me.
I remember I had a professor who I loved.
She was always smiling, very enthusiastic. One day, just before an exam, she held me by the shoulders, looked me straight in the eyes, and said, "Above all, don't stress out."
(Laughter) "No matter what, don't think about stress."
That's what I'm going to do.
I'm going to ask you right now to not think about your breath or even to not remember a number that has no significance to you. For example, the number 834.
(Laughter) Don't picture an 8, a 3, and a 4.
Don't engrave it in your memory.
You definitely shouldn't fall asleep thinking about this number, dream about it, or wake up with it in mind.
(Laughter) So, please take a moment to really not cement it in your memory.
(Laughter) You can imagine it didn't work at all when she told me that.
It just made me focus on my stress.
I felt it even more.
I was very happy at that moment.
This professor really meant well. But you know, there's a saying, "The road to hell is paved with good intentions."
She was so full of good intentions.
She had just given me a tip, but she had no idea how the mind worked.
As for me, I had to wait many years before I was able to touch a piano again.
It was after the conservatory that I enjoyed it again.
It gave me two ideas. The first is, we don't really know how our brain works.
And apparently, our parents and teachers have absolutely no idea.
They try to help, but they don't have the tools.
And the second idea is that if we don't learn to control our brain, it will control us.
In our education, they usually ask us to learn to control ourselves, to channel our attention.
They ask a bunch of things, but at no point does someone tell us, "Here's how it works."
We're kind of left on our own.
We're told to be rational, to make logical decisions. But most of the time, as soon as we get emotional, reason is swept aside.
We are not rational beings.
We are first and foremost emotional beings.
Take for example someone who has a phobia.
If a person with a fear of flying is boarding a plane, you wouldn't calmly explain to him, for example, that planes are the safest mode of transport in the world.
That there's no danger in getting into that machine.
I think he'd look at you even more angrily and say,
"I know that. That's not the problem."
Reason isn't enough.
We can't channel our emotions using reason.
Besides emotions, and that type of emotion, we notice that most of the time, our brain works in ways that are so not adapted to modern society.
We could take many examples.
For example, we talk about stress. But stress is, fundamentally, a good response.
In nature, if you had to run fast, it was a good thing blood flowed into our legs for our flight reflex.
The problem is that a lot of situations - a test, a job interview, etc - don't really require that you run away.
(Laughter) The situation is not well suited at all.
Imagine a little country road at night.
There's a rabbit crossing the street, and a car comes up with all its headlights on.
For the rabbit, there's a logical reflex, because hundreds and hundreds of generations of rabbits developed a precise reaction for confronting a predator: freeze.
(Laughter) Play dead.
Except that a rabbit doesn't really know what a car is.
(Laughter) The car runs it over.
It's revolting!
But that simply means it's an archaic function.
So fortunately, we could reeducate our brain.
We could teach it brand new functions, modify our perception, modify our reactions.
But that forces us to learn how it works.
I don't know if you do the same, but I find it pretty strange that we've all spent more time learning to use a computer, or a telephone, or a TV, than what's floating between our ears.
Especially now that we're starting to get a sense of how it works.
Before, we could say there were some gaps, and that it was intuition and maybe some strange things. But today, neuroscience, social psychology, and cognitive psychology are slowly starting to map the brain.
We're far from knowing everything, but we already have some useful ideas, some useful principles, and it's been so for quite a while.
So if we could imagine an ideal world, we'd take a brain class in first grade.
(Laughter) Imagine you're back in first grade.
The very first day, the teacher would have come in and started explaining how it works.
Before having to memorize anything, someone would have taught you, how to memorize.
Wouldn't that be great?
Imagine all the time you'd save.
We would learn how to memorize and store images.
We would learn there's also an auditory memory, and how to use it alongside visual memory.
We would even learn there is muscle memory, sensory memory, and that when we pair another type of memory with that, it's even more efficient.
We would learn that memory needs maintenance. There are people today who win memory contests after 60 years, memorizing some pretty amazing stuff.
So, we'd learn how to memorize and we'd save ourselves endless time.
After, we'd even immensely enjoy doing it.
We'd learn other things in this brain class.
In a few weeks, we'd know how to memorize.
Next, we could learn to manage emotions.
We'd learn how to transform stress into confidence or to surpass ourselves.
We'd learn to concentrate.
Maybe we'd learn how to become more creative.
And yet, those would be just the basics.
If we did that, we could easily completely change our relationship to the world.
But there's still one problem:
understanding is not enough.
While we might know exactly how we work, we'd still struggle to act it out.
As I said earlier, our emotions override reason.
I can try to control myself or even explain how I should be able to, but if something happens, I'll usually be reacting to that.
The emotional brain is a lot faster than the logical brain.
Plenty of solutions have been created to address this well-known problem.
In nearly all civilizations, since the beginning of history, there were attempts to answer it.
In some civilizations, we called it meditation.
Several types of meditation were created.
We called this zen, we called that yoga.

We used movement.
We used rituals, rhythm, music, sometimes even psychotropics.
There was every possibility you could imagine.
They all had one thing in common: altering our state of consciousness.
We very quickly realized that in our normal state, we didn't manage to act upon the rest.
On what was unconscious,
as if there were a barrier between us.
But in an altered state of consciousness, this kind of thing became possible again.
In the West, there was a way of doing this,
a rather modern way that we call hypnosis.
I discovered hypnosis when I was little,
right after piano.
It was something I was passionate about.
Today, I'm lucky enough to manage a school where every year, we give hundreds of people the tools to use hypnosis in daily life.
Our students are coaches, therapists, speakers, a lot of teachers, and they all have something in common: understanding how to modify consciousness in order to act upon what usually escapes us.
I told you earlier we're starting to have a sort of map of all that. And obviously, you could also say that these modern disciplines, and hypnosis is not the only example, can also be applied to what neuroscience teaches us.
Hypnosis seems to suffer from a lot of myths, cliches, and stereotypical images.
Most are spread by the movies, or sci-fi.
Sometimes, the image still shocks us, but hypnosis is also something very, very simple.
In fact, hypnosis is a daily state, and we experience it several times per day.
Yesterday, for example, and I think you've seen this thousands of times, I was walking a route I regularly take. I've probably taken it hundreds of times. At a certain point, my thoughts wandered. I didn't know where they had gone, but my body continued walking.
Then a few minutes, or a few dozen minutes after, I arrived exactly where I had wanted to.
I have no idea if I stopped here or there,
or if I crossed here or there,
if the light was red or green when I crossed.
All I know is I arrived at my destination.
We call that sleepwalking, don't we?
I let my body go. I trusted it.

And we all do that.
We have plenty of expressions for this state. we were somewhere else, in the clouds, we were on the moon, we were on Mars.
(Laughter) We were elsewhere, for sure.
That is to say that we were a lot more unconscious than conscious of what was happening to us at that moment in time.
Sometimes, when reading a book, maybe in the evening, when you are tired, and then at some point, a word, or a phrase, or an image carries you away.
And then, your eyes keep following the lines, your hands keep turning the pages, and we wake up three or four pages later.
We have no idea what we read in that time.
(Laughter) Our body must remember something, but we don't know what happened.
That's exactly what hypnosis is.
But if we go even further, we'll realize that hypnosis is a state we often seek out in our lives. Since naturally, like when we we go to the movies, we want the film to absorb us, hypnotize us.
When we open a book, we want it to hypnotize us, that the suggestions inside act on us and lead us to a new state, a special experience. so that we enter the story.
When we go to a museum and stop in front of an artwork, that our pupils dilate, that we feel an emotion. We're hypnotized by this work.
I think hypnosis is what we seek the most in life.
That which lifts us from the banal,
towards the emotional, the living.
I even think that an artist's main goal is to hypnotize the people who go to see his artwork.
What makes hypnosis something both common and very special, since perhaps it's what links all experiences that mark and touch us.
If that's what we consider hypnosis, it's no longer about falling asleep or being manipulated, but about taking control of oneself.
Hypnosis comes from Greek -
Hypnos was the God of sleep.
We see the asleep part of it, but then, Hypnos was the one who stayed awake while everyone was sleeping.
Maybe hypnosis is a state of greater lucidity.
So if I summarize, we have, on the one hand, a map that's starting to be drawn, a map of our brain, and how it works; and on the other hand, where once we had a frontier, now we have a mode of transport,
a vehicle that allows us to access to what escapes us.
The problem is that most of the time, when we're hypnotized, we don't want to be; it just happens.
We need someone who can drive us there.
That's what a practitioner of hypnosis learns to do.
He'll learn to discover the path by which we can bypass our habitual consciousness,
displace our level of consciousness.
Usually, it happens with games.
A mental game.
A game that we can play with ourselves.
Before there is a first-grade brain class, perhaps we could do it as adults.
And we can take the idea even further.
If we think of our brain as a giant receiver, our senses constantly gathering information.
From day one, we're bombarded with information.
In fact, there are thousands and thousands of inputs that shape our perception and end up creating our worldview, from which we create our identity, our subjectivity, and thus our personality.
We could almost say that, we're all already hypnotized by all of these inputs;
what's said to us, what's taught to us, beliefs, ideas that we read, hear, feel, deduce. And in turn, all of that creates our personality.
Personality comes from the Greek, "persona."
It's the mask we choose to wear
in order to face reality.
That could imply there are several of them,
several potential masks
that we could change, play with.
I was reading an article a while back that said in the morning, when we're getting ready, when we step out of the shower, we take about a minute and a half - from the moment we open our closet to check out all the possibilities,
to choose what to wear that day.
We know that wearing a suit or shorts and flip-flops are not the same thing,
that we influence the way people see us, and we influence ourselves.
We modify the image we present and what we feel.
Imagine next to your real closet there's a virtual closet - an imaginary, mental one.
You open it, and there is every possible version of yourself,
every possible mask.
You could look at them and ask yourself, "What do I need today?
Do I need to be more creative, more free, more focused?"
You could look at all that and ask, "What emotion do I want to look like?"
If you took a few moments to do that, you would undoubtedly change the day's possibilities.
You would model your identity according to all possibilities, and you wouldn't end up taking yourself seriously trying to fit into one single mask.
You could have fun with it, play with it.
Perhaps even one day, looking at all these masks, asking yourself which you'll wear, you could say to yourself, "No mask today." And just see what happens.
I think that it's often the multiplicity of experiences that makes us free.
So before leaving, I'll suggest one thing. Rather, I'll ask you one thing. Tomorrow, when you wake up, when you ask yourself, "What clothes am I going to wear?"
at that moment, do not think about a mental closet.
(Laughter) Thank you.
(Applause)
When I was young, I lived in Paris.
I grew up in the city.
Nevertheless, I was lucky enough to spend my childhood not far from nature.
My grandparents, my parents regularly took me to the countryside, into the forest.
And there, I could indulge in one of my favourite activities: building dens.
Do you remember that?
We all built dens, often in unusual places: Under beds, behind the stairs, in the garden.
I'm going to ask you to close your eyes for a moment.
I'm going to take you to the forest to build a den.
You can hear the sound of the wind in the leaves, the chirping of birds.
A small mammal goes past you and runs for cover in the thick litter.
You can feel the cool wind on your cheeks and the smell of mold.
The den: choose a location, then go, find branches,
some thick, some thinner, to fine-tune the structure.
Then, when it's completed, go inside.
Is is big enough? High enough? Sturdy?


Well protected against the rain?
From the inside, can you see what's happening outside?
Open your eyes!
A den? No!

It's a house.
A mongulu.
Miadic Appollinaire's house, the eldest of a family of Baka pygmies, who live in the forests in southeast Cameroon.
The house is made of bowed branches, knotted together with bark fibers and covered in Ngongo leaves, a plant, of the Marantaceae family, cousin to the ginger family, which acts here as a vegetable roof tile.
Four people live under his roof.
I have visited rainforests dozens of times.
It was in 2008 that I met Miadic Apollinaire and his family.
I was there to try to understand their nomadic way of life, and in what way forest exploitation damages their everyday life, their culture.
Today, 300 million people still live in forests: in the boreal forests in the north and in rainforests.
300 million: almost five times France's population.
When I arrived, with Cyril, my partner and photographer, we set up our tent not far from Miadic's encampment.
Little by little, a relationship of trust was established.
And Miadic, being the only one to speak a bit of French, day after day, while the women went to gather plants and to fish, and the men hunted and searched for honey, talked to me.
We talked about this changing world, of their world, which is dissolving in the globalization, of this forest which we, the Northern countries, are devouring, for wood, pulp, plywood.
Unlike the Native Americans who rallied together to exercise their rights and those of the forest, the Baka pygmies, like Miadic and his family, are too far apart to communicate.
For them, forests, the "bele," are our soul.
Without forests, we couldn't exist.
They provide everything.
We are part of the forest.
Forests, for the Baka, for the nomadic people who depend on them, they are everything.
They are a pharmacy, a pantry, a house, a receptacle of their myths, of their legends, a retreat for their ancestors.
Miadic asked me to relay their alarm call.
We are all affected by what is happening in the rainforests even though they're so far away.
We can't turn a blind eye to Miadic and his family's tragedy, because together, we can make things happen. His house, it's not the fruit of his imagination, of our imagination unlike our childhood dens.
It's, truly, the most important thing in their lives, their home.
They live there.
Yet, today, the Baka, a nomadic people, who move from clearing to clearing throughout their wanderings in the forest, are forced to settle down because the forest is receding and doesn't provide them with enough to eat.
In this way, they are losing their culture, their identity, like so many more of those 300 million people who depend on this ecosystem.
"We have to save the forest!
We have to save our home!",
a desperate Miadic Apollinaire tells me.
Forests, today, cover around four billion hectares of the planet;
31% of the world's land surface.
If we do nothing, every year, we will lose the equivalent of a country like Costa Rica: three times the surface of the Bouches-du-Rhône department, 13 million hectares every year.
We're devouring the forest for its wood and mineral resources,
but also to set up huge industrial mono-cultures.
For many decades in Indonesia and Malaysia, where the orangutan lives, that big carrot-coloured monkey, well, in Indonesia, we're setting fire to the forests to make space for the palm oil.
And this palm oil is invading our everyday lives, our cupboards.
Admittedly, this fight is far from simple.
It's full of obstacles.
But despite this, together, we can make things happen.
Under the pressure of consumers, big multinational companies have started to think about the elaboration of a sustainable palm oil sector.
The label FSC - Forest Stewardship Council
is more and more visible.
Because we, the consumers, are more careful, about the wood and its by-products that we buy.
Together, we can, truly, make things happen.
The consequence of this deforestation is the increase in poaching.
The forests are emptying.
In Indonesia, orangutans are being captured to be sold as pets, and in Central Africa, we're talking about empty forest syndrome, hence this silence!
Because there, you listen.
And you heard it before, this buzz of animals: there are birds, frogs, cicadas that sing all the time.
Twenty-four seven!
And all of a sudden, you listen, and you hear nothing at all.
As a consequence, because forests are emptying, the Baka have absolutely nothing left to eat.
When I was younger, I wanted to be an ornithologist.
And then, it was in Borneo that I decided to do a thesis on orangutans.
Day after day, month after month, I merged, interfered, immersed myself in the everyday life of these primates who, as well as chimpanzees, gorillas, bonobos, are our closest cousins.
I worked with individuals who were saved from trafficking, poaching, and were reintroduced into the forest.
One day, when I was at the top of a tree, 15 meters from the ground, studying the structure the nests that the orangutans build for themselves, every night, to sleep, attached to my harness, not really in my element, notebook, pen and binoculars in hand, I suddenly felt a presence at my feet.
I saw Maya, a female.
Apparently, by the scowl on her face, she wasn't very happy to see me interfering with her territory.
And before I realized what was happening, she gave me an almighty slap, with a hand twice the size of mine!
This is perhaps what we call the clash of cultures!
(Laughter) It's possibly at that moment, I realized how important it is to respect them, but also, and above all, to respect their environment, their ecosystem: this forest.
Today, there are 4,500 orangutans in Sumatra, 45,500 in Borneo: two separate species.
Every month, every year, these numbers decrease.
And if we do nothing, soon, orangutans will only be a memory on glossy paper.
If we rally together to save the forest, we can protect orangutans, as well as 60% of the animal and plant species that live in these forests: 60% of the world's biodiversity.
And we will enable the 300 million people who live in the forest to continue to enjoy their home.
That's not all!
We will also enable 1.6 billion other people, who get, directly or indirectly, their resources from this ecosystem, to continue to benefit from it.
Forests play various roles.
They are air conditioners, lungs, unlike our oceans.
Yet, today, forests are going up in flames, flames that account for 25% of the greenhouse gas emissions, responsible for climate change.
To protect the future of the Baka, of the orangutans, as well as ours, we can do something.
Together, we can stop this process.
Firstly, we can inform ourselves - what you're doing at the moment - and then, inform your loved ones.
There are some websites that enable you to go further, to learn more about these peoples, for example, who live on and in the forest or about orangutans.
Secondly, you can become an active player, pay more attention to what you buy, what you put in your cupboards.
For example, avoid palm oil until a lasting and sustainable sector is created.
There is a website that can give you pointers on which products contain palm oil.
This lasting sector is possible, especially if we install monoculture palm plantations on degraded agricultural lands, there are many of these, and many are abandoned.
It's undoubtedly slower and more costly for industries, but it's possible.
When possible, favour FSC certified wood
which guarantees sustainable forest management, as well as the respect of the people who live there.
For example, in Cameroon, the FSC certification works
with the Pygmies and together, they are mapping out the forest.
They are cataloging the trees the Pygmies use for food, as well as their sacred sites, and they promise to protect them.
This way, the Pygmies can continue to live in their homes.
Together, we can change
the rules of the game.
The FSC example shows that the consumer can put pressure on the States, on multinational companies.
And we all have a role to play in this process.
I came back from Cameroon with a memory of Miadic and his family.
This sack is the Pygmies' nomadic home, a mobile house, that they transport from one clearing to another.
This way, they can move and not over-exploit the forest, let it breathe, live!
The Baka are content with the basics, but we're taking these basics from them, to fill our big houses with objects, objects that we move in huge trucks.
If we all took a bit of time to pay attention to what we put in our cupboards, to what we consume, we can contribute, we can enable, Miadic, his family, and the 300 million people to continue enjoying their forest.
We are also helping to protect thousands, millions of animal and plant species.
And we will enable the forest to continue to play its role of worldwide air conditioner, of lung, a blue and green lung.
But, we will also enable our children in turn, to build their own dens to use their imagination, to dream, to create, to play, to invent a better world!
Thank you all.
(Applause)
(Voiceover) Jean-Xavier Pelletier: I'm Jean-Xavier Pelletier, and I'm 11 years old.
I've been a student at the Saint-Louis Academy since kindergarten.
I've been playing hockey since the age of four, and I've been a hockey goalie since the age of seven.
I'm here to share my passion for this sport with you.
I'll tell you about my idol.
And you'll see that the one thing we have in common is our determination for our favorite sport: hockey.
(On stage) J-XP: Today, I'm here to show you that anything is possible.
But you can't do it using magic tricks.
In my experience, you must follow your dreams, be determined, work hard, keep a supportive group of people around you and have someone who inspires you.
Jonathan Marchessault is a young player on a new team: Golden Knights of Las Vegas.
We are both determined about our favorite sport.
When I started, most young players only wanted to score goals.
But my goal was to be the fastest back to the zone to stop incoming play.
At age seven, I had to make a choice: my position.
And here is what I said to convince my parents,
"Daddy, Mommy, I know what I want.
I'm old enough.
I would rather defend the goal than be the fastest back to the zone."
My first two years weren't that easy.
I found myself at top level, alone.
I've been through many defeats.
I was left to myself. Let me elaborate: I saw that the people around me had lost faith in me, in my abilities, and I wanted to prove them wrong.
I also realized that my body wasn't ready for the change either.
So, I kept training at home, I focused on myself, and with my determination, hard work, support from my teammates, my family, with their love, honesty and trust in me, I moved up to a higher level.
At our school, we have a slogan that depicts what I just said very well: "I can go faster alone but even further as a team."
Several people have told me that phrase describes me well.
John inspires me to never give up. He told me he had never played high caliber minor hockey, had never been drafted, but was invited in 2012-2013 by the Columbus Blue Jackets.
Unfortunately, they didn't keep him.
It's a pity they don't know what they're missing today.
He got three boarding penalties before being drafted by the Golden Knights.
This year, he is one of the 20 leading scorers in the league, alongside one of the best goalies, Marc-André Fleury.
And last year, he scored as many goals as Connor McDavid, currently one of the best players in the national leagues.
He told me that family support was and still is very important to him.
Don't forget, follow your dreams, be determined, work hard, keep a supportive group of people around you and have someone who inspires you.
Finally, I hope my experience has convinced you that anything is possible.
Now, it's your turn to believe in yourself.
Before I go, watch this example of how hard I've worked.
(Applause)
Hello.
Today, I'm going to speak about learning, and particularly about learning music.
Music is my greatest passion, but the fun is lost somewhat due to music theory
which is painful to learn and discouraging.
I'm wondering if that rings a bell for anyone in the room ... (Laughter) I had the opportunity to meet someone who inspired me, whose name is Jeannot Védrine, who was an outstanding and extremely modest jazz pianist.
His talent was matched by his modesty.
When he was sitting at a piano, it was just incredible.
Jeannot used to tutor me in a small shop located at Treille street in Clermont-France.
He'd teach me music without talking about notes. He'd not speak about musical notes but rather about textures, about feelings, and he'd show me how to create them.
He also had the wisdom to not mention music theory,
meaning he knew it but didn't speak of it.
This made me realize that there are a lot of great musicians who actually don't know how to read a score.
So how do they do since they play
and create freely?
It means that maybe there are other ways to conceive music, other ways to work and to see music.
Jeannot and I went our separate ways, and I continued to learn music alone, by myself as an amateur, but always asking myself the question: which form of learning would better work for me?
And it was at that time that I started to draw shapes.
I noticed that for me, it was working
and helping me progress.
So I developed a kind of homemade personal method. You may have heard of the chromatic wheel. Well, that's the basis of my representation.
(Music notes) [Scale representation on the the chromatic wheel] That's how music began to take shape for me, and it helped me to understand music as well as other things that I didn't understand before.
It enabled me to understand the musicians whom I admired, like Miles Davis, for example.

For me, "So What" is a pentagram.
This song is based on what we call the "So What chord" - no other term for it - that was invented by the pianist Bill Evans.
It's difficult to visualize it when you play it on a piano.
But when played in a geometric way such as mine that is based on the chromatic circle, it appears as a pentagram.
"Giant Steps." "Giant Steps" by John Coltrane, is a very difficult song to memorize if you don't know its structure.
What does it do?
It splits the scale into three parts. Then it develops the structure of the song and its chord progression following this three-part division.
What I'm saying may or may not be familiar to you, but you understand the idea.
"Giant Steps" is very interesting because the process of taking musical elements and transposing and shifting them doesn't seem natural at all. It looks like taking giant steps, giant leaps.
That may be the very reason why John Coltrane called this piece "Giant Steps."
About Herbie Hancock, here is a shape of harmonization Herbie Hancock uses all the time.
In this shape, you can notice the symmetry.
More simply, here is the structure of the blues music.
Perhaps some musicians in this room play the blues.
Here is the representation of the blues' structure on a chromatic circle.
This is just my personal way of visualizing music. But I went on and thought "Could this help other people?"
At this point, I decided to do an experiment. I developed a first interactive interface where people can play and see what they play in shapes on a screen.
I developed this interface and needed to test it.
So I took a representative sampling of the global population who don't know music.
The world is divided in two: those who play music and those who don't.
So I used my niece.
This is my niece.
(Laughter) She's three and a half in this photo.
She doesn't know anything at all
about music theory. She'd never played even one note of music.
So I'm going to show you a video of her first notes of music that she is playing on a piano.
How does it work?
I show her a shape that is actually a pentagram.
Without further explanation, I tell her, "Play this shape."
So I explain the rule of the game.
At first, it was a bit archaic, with transparent slides, as you can see.
(Musical notes) (Video) PB Dionet: There you go, you've already found a point.
(On stage) Then she is going to start playing.
Look how attentive she is.
Her eyes are focussed on both the screen and the piano.
Then what happen is that instinctively,
she is able to reproduce a shape.
So for her, it becomes completely logical to play a shape.
In six minutes, she discovered a fundamental concept in music, the pentatonic major scale, which is essential in understanding music from both the melodic point of view and the musical improvisation approach.
A four-year-old child has an attention span of about six minutes.
And she is keen to start playing.
This kind of game enables her to learn about a concept that would take otherwise, with the traditional method, five to seven years to learn.
This leads us to the issue of training. This method doesn't explain all about music, but it provides some shortcuts.
Pedagogists break down learning into three elements: a code, a mental representation, and their expression.
I'll use writing as an example to help you understand.
When we write, we use a code system that helps us form a mental representation of what is written.
So we use letters for example. And the mental representation is the formation of words from the combination of letters. Then we form sentences from word combinations and then create expressions. So once a student has integrate this system, he is able to create personal combinations and express himself freely and autonomously.
So here we can see that the traditional method of learning music bypasses this integration phase.
We're asked to master a notation system that is very complex - the small musical notes on the staves. Then we're asked to repeat those notes
and are told that it's musical expression.
So we learn to repeat, but we don't learn to understand.
Actually, this non-intuitive notation system is such that the learning effort is largely focused on understanding this notation system rather than focusing the learning effort on experimenting music, exploring it or understanding it.
I'd like to speak about synesthesia.
What does "synesthesia" mean?
It's the process of creating bridges between the senses.
It's taking musical parameters, and taking visual parameters, and then creating a mapping table by drawing lines between these parameters.
Well, that's something we can actually develop through an interface, an interface that tries to model this synesthetic approach.
Let me give you some examples.
So you can see that this is photorealistic, and that we can manipulate these elements.
If I play a major chord.
(Piano chord)
for example, it creates a shape.
Here I'm playing a square ... (Piano chord) a pentagram ...
(Piano chords)
Here is it. It's this approach.
In this interface, we wanted to go even further. We wanted to translate musical textures into visual textures.
For example, here I'm playing a major chord that is a stable and pure chord.
We're going to see it as if it's gold, a bit like the color of the balconies in an opera theatre. (Piano chord) The square ... (Piano chord)
... is velvet like the seats
you're sitting on. Why?
Because it's a harmony that is both soft and sad and a little bit dissonant, but also heavy.
So we can do renderings ... (Piano chord) ... like this one for example.
This completely transforms the approach to music.
A cheerful note is like this.
When it's sad, it creates shadowing effects.
Then, dissonance and consonance effects are linked to texture effects.
For dissonance that expresses harmonical instability we create a rough and non-reflective texture.
For consonance, we create a smooth and reflective texture.
If this could help just one person, like my niece for example, to understand certain musical concepts, then I would be delighted and very happy.
Thank you.
(Applause)
I don't know whether to put myself or the bag in the middle.
(Laughter)
I wanted to ask you a question.
I wanted to ask each person who consumes water in plastic bottles to raise their hand.
That's what I thought.
Actually, I wanted to make you feel guilty.
Then, I would have put your mind at rest.
I would have said, "Don't worry, you are not the only ones. 5.5 billion of plastic water bottles are sold every year in France."
Then, I got to thinking.
I thought, "Maybe I shouldn't be reassuring you."
I for one have become aware of the scarcity of water during my many travels and life experiences that I've had in Africa, Asia, and many countries.
I've seen children walking two to three hours in the morning, in full heat at over 40°C, to get a few gallons of water,
brown water unsuitable for consumption.
And then, they would do it again at night.
Let's just say that every drop of water counts.
Imagine doing that even for one week.
You wouldn't look at water the same way anymore.
Water's becoming increasingly scarce,
yet there's no shortage of it on our planet - no more than of air.
Let me explain.
From space, you can see there are more oceans than land.
But even though water covers 72% of the planet, more than half of the world's population is in a water shortage situation,
close to the famous Day Zero.
Day Zero is the day when not even a drop of water will come out of the faucet.
Last summer, the residents of Cape Town in South Africa narrowly avoided that infamous Day Zero.
This summer, India went through its biggest crisis.
The shortage affected several regions, and the government was forced to deliver water by trains and trucks to cities like Chennai, cities of more than 10 million inhabitants.
And right now, as I'm talking to you, 17 countries are experiencing a water shortage.
Recent estimates feel that by 2040, 20 additional countries will be short of drinking water.
Luckily, we cannot run out of water on our Earth.
And the water you use every day to eat, drink, and shower comes from the water cycle.
The water cycle starts with the evaporation of sea and ocean waters but also from the continents, land, crops, forests, lakes, rivers.
The heat causes the water molecule to rise.
The cold liquefies it,
and it falls as rain or snow. And the amount of water
that we have on Earth is constant. It doesn't run out, unlike oil and minerals.
Once those are consumed, then there won't be any more.
Water is permanent. It is here.

It falls as precipitation.
It goes back to the sea and sets off again into the air.
It's an endless cycle.
It's even reassuring to know that we'll still have that much water in a million years.
It is not a question of knowing how much water we have on the planet, but how much of it is drinkable and accessible to sustain all life on Earth.
This image that you see has been created by scientists from USGS.
It shows all the water found on the planet, represented as a sphere, compared to the volume of the Earth.
The big blue sphere, shown by the white arrow, is all the water we have on Earth.
The medium-sized sphere, shown by the red arrow, is all the underground freshwater, most of which is inaccessible
because it's out of reach.
And the little tiny one is all the freshwater on the surface, available, that must be shared by all of humanity.
And we will have a different outlook on the qualifier "the blue planet."
The worst part is that this little source of water, we are draining it due to our overexploitation,
and particularly in two fields: agriculture and industry.
Between the two of them, not only do they consume 92% of this reserve, but on top of that, they are the biggest polluters.
And the pollution of our soil today is forcing us to treat our water more and more.
I would even say that we overtreat it.
Ninety percent of surface water masses are known to be contaminated with persistent micropollutants.
That is to say that 90% of the water that we use every day is polluted by persistent micropollutants.
I'd like to talk to you now about another water source that's turning into the panacea: the bottled mineral water.
It is offered to us as a piece of healthy and natural food that French people love.
Each year, they consume 5.5 billion bottles of water.
But the impact on the environment is catastrophic.
The Ellen MacArthur Foundation reckons that we recycle less than 20% of plastic on Earth.
If you take into account that to make a half-liter bottle, you need 3 liters of water and 33 centiliters of oil.
Last year, 17 million barrels of oil were burned to make the 89 billion plastic bottles used in the world.
Let me remind you that there are 159 liters of oil in one barrel of oil.
The consequences of all of this is the pollution of our soil and oceans.
In fact, a German study published in 2014 found 25,000 pieces of chemical residue inside plastic bottles.
At the end of that list, you feel like everything you do is bad for the environment.
That's kind of true.
At any rate, everything we produce is bad for the environment.
Perhaps a different way of managing our resources is needed to resolve this issue.
And the small everyday decisions may affect the resources of our planet.
I can say that the era of carelessness, when we thought that water was inexhaustible, is well and truly over.
As for me, I've been wondering what we could do.
And I thought that we should make use of this tremendous potential that is water from the air.
To do so, let's go back to the 2000s, when upon my wife's advice that I did take ... (Laughter) I've often taken her advice, by the way. (Applause) Well, I gave up my possessions, and we moved to the Caribbean.
September 11, 2001 is a date that American people will never forget.
And neither will we, for that matter.
As New Yorkers went through these tragic events, another psychosis came to haunt them: a contamination of the city's water supplies by terrorists.
I was sitting in front of my TV.
And I thought, "What could we do to get the kind of water we can be sure of, without being connected to a pipe?"
Some time later, while flicking to a channel, I was watching a program where it was explained that at the time, Incas were collecting water from the morning dew on threads.
Actually, they had copied the spiders.
For them, their entire water source comes from the morning dew.
They collect the small droplets on their web.
That's when I said to myself, "It is essential to make use of the tremendous potential of the water in the air by recreating the natural water cycle."
This was the beginning of an adventure that lasted nearly 15 years, where with the help of a few engineers, we managed to calculate the dew point at all temperatures and humidity levels.
We managed to extract some water, the water molecule, H2O, inside our generators.
At this stage, the molecule cannot pollute itself, because it cannot mix.
The water molecule needs time to mix, whether with pesticides or minerals.
If you take a glass of water and put in sugar or some salt, you'll see that it takes time for all of this to dissolve.
It is the same thing with the water molecule.
It will only be able to mix if put in contact with the soil,
with time on the soil.
The benefit is that it mixes with the minerals.
But we have polluted all of our soil,
so it also mixes with pesticides.
We were able to retrieve it before that stage.
We ran a lot of tests,
tests with labs, where we had the water analyzed all over the world: in Australia, China, Africa, Guadeloupe.
The results were absolutely identical.
The water molecule is pure:
zero nitrates, zero pesticides.
It's even reassuring, by the way.
You're going to tell me, "The air is polluted. The water will be, too."
But at this point, it is the same thing.
In condensation, the molecule is not going to mix with the pollution that it's going to meet in the air.
But to avoid that, we also added very efficient filtration systems on these generators, which will filter the air and also filter the water,
though we don't need them since we don't need to decontaminate it.
But it's for safety purposes: to get a product with no risk of bacteriological development or something inside the generators.
They run on electricity, but we have been able to make them run on solar or wind systems.
We've manufactured generators ranging from 30 liters to 10,000 liters.
We tested them - for large capacities, it's a real solution for the regions that are in a water shortage.
I would like to get back to this bag here.
It's the water consumption of two people in Guadeloupe for a month.
And we estimate the consumption of water from plastic bottles over the course of a year to over 150 million bottles - 1.5 million times this bag.
The consequences on our islands are much more terrible.
It should be avoided at all costs.
And the last bit of advice that I could give, a little sentence to keep in mind: let's stop lapping up everything we're told.
Sorry, I'm a little troubled.
Thank you.
(Applause)
