Hi, my name is Nicolas, I am 30.
Ten years ago, I was like you.
I was a student.
I was spending my days sitting on a chair listening to a teacher, and hoping that one day I would find a job I would enjoy, that I would succeed in life.
And sometimes, I was wondering, "What on earth am I doing here?"
Back then, I had lots of dreams.
I dreamt of seeing the world and maybe find where I belonged.
But in the end, I kind of forgot my dreams.
I got back in line, found a job
and went on a routine.
Then, one day, this thought came back, "What on earth am I doing here?"
At that moment, an idea came to my mind, a single word: "travel".
"Travel" ... Instantly,
my heart started pounding,
my whole body started to vibrate, ba-boom, ba-boom, ba-boom...
Wow, travel, travel, travel ...
I felt alive, vibrating like I hadn't felt for so long! It was like I had fallen in love.
So I told myself, "Waw, this is so strong,
I have to do something.

What? I don’t know, but I’m going to try.
I’m going to dedicate my life to this force that make me vibrate, this force that I call 'intuition.'" So there was just one thing left to do: I quit my job, I quit my flat.
I packed my life in a backpack and I left ... to experience an amazing summer! It all started here.
We were about 15 people on rafts made entirely of recycled and re-used materials from garbage, to prove that it's possible to travel in a sustainable way.
Together, we lived this adventure for a month, on the Ebro river, in Spain, totally illegally.
We did everything we wanted, we had no limit.
I felt like a real pirate, it was so great!
This experience gave birth to a dream inside me: why not continue this experience and live on water like a sailor, like in the age of the great explorations.
Summer went on, and I went to a Rainbow Gathering, where people meet in the middle of the forest to feed on Love.
These places are the only ones in the world where I can practice my yoga, naked, singing Indian mantras, and everyone find it normal.
One night, I was talking with a guy around the fire about stories I've heard: “You know, I've heard that some people hitch-hike boats to go to the Canary Islands.
They can find a sailing boat and cross the Atlantic Ocean, that’s crazy!”
No kidding, I was there with him, and a girl I'd never met before came and said, “Are you interested in sailing across the Atlantic?
Well, I will go soon, maybe the captain
has room for you too, here is his number.”
Ba-boom ba-boom ba-boom ba-boom, wow! If I had seen that in a movie, I wouldn't have found it credible.
But it was happening to me. I told myself, “That’s really crazy!"
I went, "Yeah, why not?
Living on the water, on a boat ...?
I came back downtown, called the captain who told me,
“Let's meet in three months in the Canary Islands.”
And so I went for two months on a sailing boat, with its ups and downs, and all the difficulties of living in the middle of the elements, and at the same time this joy of seeing a 360 degrees panorama, seeing the stars, and taking the time to journey, taking the time to tune with the elements.
This trip took us from the Canary Islands to Cap Verde to Martinique, and I spent 13 days without seeing a single bit of land, and no other human souls than those on board with me.
That was psychologically very hard.
Although there were hard times, let me show you something fantastic: How to take a shower
while sailing in the middle
of the Atlantic Ocean, it goes like this:
(Flowing waves)
(Video) Woman: Go, Nico!
NR: Got it?
Woman: It's filming! Go!
(Laughing) Yippee, please another loop!

NR: I can't hear you!
(Woman laughing) Another looping!

That's it!
So after two months on the sea, I arrived in Martinique, the Caribbean, this place on Earth where it's always hot.
I could live, sometimes bare-chested, or wearing a T-shirt all day long.
I healed from a sinusitis I had since I was a kid.
I finally didn’t feel cold anymore,
that was awesome!
I spent two months in Martinique before I felt like going.
So I went to the harbour and looked for ads.
There, I found a note: “Young skipper looks for a partner to go to Cariaccou."
I had no idea where it was, but my heart was vibrating, ba-boom, ba-boom ...
I called the guy, we met the next day, and we left for Cariaccou. We arrived just in time for the Carnival.
Carnival is the celebration of spring, but in the south Caribbean where I was, they celebrate it in a special way: people throw paint at each other and dance behind speakers all night long,
What they dance is the Soca.
If you don't know about the Soca dance,
it’s a very friendly dance!
Let me show you: The girl is in front like this, and the man dance behind like this.
It was great, I had such a good time!
The next day, a girl invited me on the island of Grenada. I met her there, with her partner and her two kids.
We became friends and with this family, I learned how to live in the Caribbean.
They invited me over, their house was only 10 square metres big.
Try and picture how small that is. From what I saw of their tiny house, there were just enough place to put a double bed, some clothes, a gas cooker, and a corridor this big.
And surprisingly, this family was very happy in their 10 square meters.
Yes, this is the Caribbean, it's always hot, their garden was the natural world around them, but this family knew how to be contented with what they had.
They appreciated it,
and this is a value that I learnt with them, and over my whole trip, discovering new cultures.
I learnt that we can be satisfied with what we have, even with little. We can appreciate what we have instead of always wanting more.
Afterwards, I went on different boats
to Trinidad and then to Venezuela.
Finally, I did my 100% ecological journey.
I went from Europe to America a bit like Christopher Columbus.
It took me six months, but I faced
the challenge, I was so happy!
Venezuela was such a mess,
I quickly went to Colombia. In Colombia, I discovered a new family. They were people who, like me, live and travel for their passion.
They are musicians, jugglers, craftsmen.
Everywhere they go, they spread their art
show it, sell it, make some money, and then continue their trip.
This new family teaches me to play at the traffic light.
So I go to the traffic light, do my show with my magic ball while cars are waiting, then I pass my hat before the light turns green. Then the cars leave and I keep going.
For the first time of my life, I could honestly earn money doing what I really like.
This was a true revolution for me.
This way of traveling and performing, I imported it in Europe I still make a living of it
from time to time and it's great!
I carried on my trip south and wished to go in the Amazon forest. In the Amazon, there are all these indigenous people and their cultures we don't really know about and find strange.
They have these rituals with sacred plants that seem quite mysterious for us.
I learnt something there: many plants that we use in the Western world can cause illnesses and even death. I'm talking about tobacco and others.
In these cultures, these plants are not used to cause illnesses but to heal, on the contrary.
So I thought that perhaps, before using those plants, we could, first, learn from these cultures and traditions, while they would learn from our technology and our science.
It seemed to me a great challenge for the 21st century.
I spent several weeks in the forest but I needed to move on, I got tired of mosquitoes.
And I had a dream: I wanted to trek on my own.
So I went to the centre of Peru near Huaraz, to go up to 4,000 meters in altitude.
My challenge was to hike alone above 4,000 and even 5,000 meters.
Here we reached 4,600 m, then I went to 5,000 m where I discovered a beautiful and pure silence. All around me were snowy peaks and passes.
I was in such a beautiful solitude which also could be so heavy at times!
I chose to travel alone to know myself better and discover the world.
But I know that when this solitude is heavy on me, it is time to go back to those who understand me.
And those who understand me, live like me, I know where to find them.
We call this a "rave party", a "trance" or "psychedelic festival," whatever. It's a place people gather to dance together to electronic music, to feel like a tribe, like our forebears who were dancing around the fire.
Together, we share the values of joy, harmony, and peace.
Together we celebrate our connection with life, with Nature and the universe.
Some may use psychedelic products, not to flee reality but to know it better and know themselves better.
In this crazy crew, there is this French girl who told me, “Nicolas, I can sell you my van when we come back to France."
Ba-boom, ba-boom, ba-boom...
“Waw, travelling in a van? Yeah!
I'm pretty tired of my backpack,
and that was my childhood dream!”
But, coming back …
I had started this journey not knowing whether I'd come back or not. Not coming back was a option.
So, I started to consider it,
but truly, I wasn't ready at all.
I had been traveling for months but I hadn't found what I was looking for yet.
So I kept going and my next challenge was to hitchhike across Brazil.
Hitchhiking in Brazil was terrible,
I was standing under 40°C, and only truck drivers would take me.
It was very hard, but I managed to reach the Atlantic Ocean. You can see me here, happier than ever. I was free.
At last I had found what I was looking for: doing whatever I wanted whenever I wanted.
I was free, smiling and healthy, but I felt greatly confused.
I couldn't sleep at night, every night.
I had too many ideas, too many visions of all my dreams for the future, when I would come back.
Every night inside my head, I invented symphonies, musics, books, movies, scripts, all sorts of things.
I had only one thing to do: come back and follow these dreams.
So, I came back. Finally, I bought a van to keep traveling and share my passions.
I started to compose music and play in festivals. I wrote a book that was published last month. I started doing conferences to share my experience.
And everywhere I go, I do my magic ball show to amaze both young and old,
telling somehow that we can marvel at life by slowing down and appreciate the simple things.
I also organized my own concerts, where we come to chill, to sleep, even here in Toulouse, France.
I finally felt I belonged, I felt useful while doing what I liked.
I must confess I wouldn’t have done all that if at some point in my journey, I hadn't gone on a mediation retreat.
This is called "Vipassana", the penetrating vision.
It is a 10-day retreat during which we keep silent.
During these ten days, we spend eight hours a day sitting closed-eyed, observing whatever rises inside us, becoming aware of all that is going on inside us, of each thought, each sensation, each emotion.
We observe without being part of the process.
We observe everything that happen inside us.
To be honest, ten days like this are very transformative.
For the first time, my mind was clear.
I was lucid about myself. I realized I was running away from something in my life.
This helped me to come back and get back to a sedentary life.
Now, I ask you to watch the next two slides in silence.
Do you see this?
This is what we all have been one day, probably, a little baby, innocent, naive, ready to experience everything, explore everything and ready to forgive everything.
And this is what we will probably all be one day.
When I look at this, I ask myself the question, “What really matters?”
The answer I found is that when I die, I want to be able to say to myself, “I did what I had to do.”
This is only my own answer, and my answer is not important.
What really matters is that you find your own, one that agrees with who you are.
Now, I don't know, are you not hearing this particular silence, specific to introspective moments, when we ask ourselves deep questions, when we are here, together, face to face with ourselves, and we aren't overwhelmed by daily thoughts, about how to fight, earn money or achieve success, and we aren't overwhelmed by thoughts of yesterday or tomorrow?
I think it is in this particular silence of introspection while facing ourselves, that true new visions can come into being.
Thank you.
(Applause)
My name is Félix Pothier, and I am 12 years old.
I've been playing hockey since I was five and mountain biking since I was seven.
I developed a passion for sport at a very young age.
I am perseverant, and taking up challenges is part of my daily life.
My presentation is entitled "The importance of sport in people's lives."
I will demonstrate many positive aspects of sport, both physically and mentally and socially.
I will also address some negative aspects to the practice of sport.
(Applause) My life is sport; sport is my life.
So, the purpose of my presentation is to tell you more about the importance of sport in people's lives.
Did you know that only 51% of young people aged 5 to 14 practice sport regularly?
And did you know that in all age categories, men are more athletic than women?
So, with the help of facts, the purpose of my presentation is not only to tell you more about the importance of sport but also to make you aware of the impact sport can have on you, whether you do sport or not.
My first fact is that sport helps us lose weight.
I started with that fact because it can't be new in your heads. As I said, sports help us lose weight, lose fat, etc.
But there are many people who think that 15 minutes of physical activity a day would be more than enough to achieve a good diet, but I've read several articles, and they all showed me that we should run 4.6 kilometers per day for a month to succeed in losing a single kilogram of fat.
My second fact is that sport often helps us make friends.
As proof, as soon as I arrived at my new elementary school, I immediately joined the hockey team.
And what did it do for me?
It helped me relax and made me talk to almost everyone in the schoolyard.
So, it's all about applying a good team spirit
and applying a good chemistry.
I will take the example of a hockey dressing room. Before a game, everyone is focused and ready to go try hard.
So, sport is not only a good way to make friends but also a good way to discover other aspects of a person.
When I said that before a game everyone is focused, it's different from the person who plays in a schoolyard.
My third fact is that besides being physically fit, sport can bring us several qualities such as perseverance and discipline.
I would tell you that I really developed perseverance early in sport because as soon as I stepped on the ice - as I played hockey - I set my goals, and I persevered to achieve them.
And that made me do the same thing in other aspects of my life, like my grades.
I set the goal of getting better grades, so I persevered more and studied more to achieve them.
Discipline, I would say, is really present in more competitive levels of sport.
So, when you start doing sports five or six times a week, you have to start being disciplined, being punctual.
So, when you are younger, this day you study, that day too so that sport doesn't affect your grades.
And when you are an adult too, you need discipline because if, let's admit, you have yoga tomorrow, you need to be disciplined in preparing the meal today.
So, adults, no break - discipline.
(Laughter) My fourth and final fact is that sport often helps us solve our problems.
When I say that, I'm not talking about problems like a conflict with someone but rather problems of time, so problems that stress us out.
I would say that taking one hour a day to do yoga can be a very good solution.
It can help you think of solutions, to relax, to take a break.
So, doing yoga is very good.
It's not just yoga. Giving yourself 100% in a sport of intensity can help you forget all your problems while you just think about performing well.
I have named several advantages, but unfortunately there are many disadvantages to sport too.
I would say that they are more related to competitive sport.
One of the disadvantages which I mentioned in my presentation is that sport takes a lot of time in your week.
So, when you're younger, more sports time means less time to study.
Of course, sports can affect your academic performance.
Another disadvantage is that a person who accumulates failures can really hurt her self-esteem.
It can lead her to lock herself in her room. It can harm her social relationships, so it can lead her to no longer want to talk to many people.
Accumulating failures can have a big impact on a person.
Finally, I'll tell you what I think about sports.
As many people around me know, sport is a big part of my life.
For me, there are only benefits, and it really helped me develop perseverance and discipline.
And also, did I tell you that sport is my life and my life is sport?
Thank you.
(Applause)
The good news is, 20 years from now,
the person sitting on your right, or on your left, will be unemployed.
One out of two jobs might disappear.
Can you imagine that?
Half of the people in this room, please leave. We don't need you anymore.
A number of academic studies have shown that robotisation and digitalisation will lead 50% of jobs to obsolescence in the Western world, 20 years from now.
20 years: we are going to be
there very fast. At the scale of the history of mankind, 20 years is tomorrow.
Tomorrow, robots will produce our cars, if it is not already the case.
Taxis and Uber car drivers will lose their jobs too, because they will be replaced by driverless cars.
A swarm of drones will deliver your pizza and sushi.
Garbage collectors will watch their garbage truck do the job for them.
Soon, human labor will not be necessary anymore to perform simple and ungrateful tasks
that need to be done.
That's a certainty. That's inevitable.
Every day, we move more and more towards robotization.
There is a scoop: today qualified jobs are threatened.
Journalists are already working with computer-aided edition tools, algorithms that write sport results news on their behalf.
Lawyers, accountants, real estate agents, are waiting to be replaced by specialised softwares soon. They are much more efficient, maybe not all of them.
A superficial knowledge of artificial intelligence, is enough to envision, without looking like a fool, that the loss of jobs will affect all sectors of our economy.
What do our politicians do about it?
Not much.
They are all too busy trying to improve unemployment rate curves, and to restore growth.
They are all too busy trying to resolve today's and tomorrow's problems with solutions of yesterday, of the last century.
How should we deal with robotisation
and digitalisation affecting employment?
We could create new jobs. Why not?
We could imitate the United States, and have more staff in supermarkets, recommending us with the latest consumer trends.
We could have more Mickey Mouse mascots in our amusement parks.
We could develop telemarketing to encourage consumers to buy even more.
Our growing hunger for new products increases our ecological footprint.
Let's ponder together: Do these jobs really fill any need?
Are they necessary? Do they contribute to the improvement of our society, of our human condition?
Do these employees thrive in such jobs, more often than not, with appalling working conditions, with ruthless bosses, or unbearable working hours, and that, on top of this, will not provide any satisfaction to be useful in society?
I think - The fundamental question is: What's the point in technology evolution?
What is the purpose of this technological innovation fever urging us, making us produce ever more, ever faster, and with less human labor?
Is the objective to let us perform ungrateful tasks?
Certainly not.
Let me tell you my theory. Employment reduction is not a disaster we should be afraid of.
It's an opportunity, it's a blessing in disguise.
Finally, we will free ourselves from alienating constraints, and we will be able to pick up a job that suits us.
There is a condition to realize this prophecy to change our society for the better, we must adapt our welfare system.
I will talk about a revolutionary idea that fits these changes very nicely:
basic income.
It is a very simple idea.
It is about giving everyone, every individual, a fixed amount of money, every month, from birth until death.
It is about giving an income to everyone, just because they exist and are a member of our society.
Basic income has four major characteristics.
First, it is a universal right.
Everyone gets it, without exception,
whether you are a billionaire or a beggar, whether you are annuitant or working, or a professional soccer champion, you get the same amount.
Basic income is a right as any other right such as freedom of expression, or access to education.
Second characteristic, basic income is unconditional.
Contrary to social security or unemployment benefit, it is paid without requiring any obligation in return.
No survey to fill, no endless and mind-boggling form.
No need to fit some poverty criteria, or to queue at the employment agency, at the Child Benefit Office, to try to get some allowance. These days are gone.
Third characteristic, basic income is individual.
Everyone gets it, regardless of their choices in life,
whether you are single or married, whether you have children or you don't, you get the basic income.
Finally, the last characteristic, you may combine basic income with your salary, or any other income.
It's a security belt to guarantee decent minimum conditions of life to everyone throughout their lives, and especially, when you are going through difficult times.
In a nutshell, basic income is a fixed amount of money, and the same amount for everyone, granted to the 66 million of French citizens every month.
We do this without affecting unemployment and retirement allowances.
Basic income does not replace the welfare system: it completes it.
Your question must be: how much?
What should be its minimum amount?
Let's be modest at the beginning. Let's say 500 euros per adult and 250 euros per child, every month.
Later, we can increase this amount. It is possible and, most probably it is a good thing, to increase it later.
But let's say, 500 euros per adult and 250 euros per child, every month.
At this stage, you should be torn
between two ideas, One half of your brain says, "Well, that's a great idea, what are we waiting for?"
On the other hand, the other half says: "What a crazy idea!
Where do we get the money?
We are in a recession!
That's nonsense. It will not work."
Let me talk about it.
There are endless possibilities for funding basic income.
There are a lot of combinations, a lot of buttons to push, a lot of cursors to move, but in any case, it's far from being nonsense. it is even totally realistic.
We only need the courage.
We only need to try it.
Concretely speaking, these are the steps necessary to set up a basic income system.
First of all, automatic payment of social security benefits will be easy.
It will be easy to pay it to everyone entitled to receive it, to make an automat payment, I mean.
Today, it is a fact that half the people who could receive the employment benefit do not apply for it.
Half of them.
Often, because they don't know that they are entitled to it, or because procedures are so complicated that they give up, or because its a stigmatising mark.
They fear of being considered as a dole-out and hand-me.
Automatic payment of the allowance to those entitled to it - we are talking about 5.8 million French people - would cost 4 billion euros only to the State. It is 0,2% of its GDP.
That's peanuts.
If we want to come to a basic income, worthy of its name, we must make the allowance universal.
In some way, we need to apply it to the entire population.
According to the model of the economist Marc de Basquiat, we can already fund a basic income of 450 euros per person and per month, without changing the household income,
by increasing tax on one side, and by paying basic income as a compensation.
Keep in mind that regardless of the amount of the basic income, you will not necessarily earn more money.
Certainly, the income of the poorest will increase.
But for the others, it will be partly or entirely given back as a tax according to the level of income.
The advantage is that everyone will throughout their lives benefit from a basic, a guaranteed allowance.
Imagine what you can do with a basic income.
On top of this, if we go beyond 450 euros, I will give you some ideas.
For 450 euros, you might think: "Yeah, 450 euros, that's not enough, not sufficient."
We can go beyond it.
To go beyond that, we need to diversify, to add other sources of funding, on top of taxes and fiscal measures.
I give you some ideas.
We could increase the tax on wealth, as Thomas Piketty suggests it. We could increase consumption tax, or create a real carbon tax.
We could also implement a Tobin tax that regulates financial transactions.
Imagine paying part of your basic income on monetary creation, or by doing economies of management, or by eliminating some policies of employment allowances.
In a nutshell, we have everything in our hands to implement this new tool.
That is, if our elected representatives seize this opportunity.
Imagine what you could do with a basic income.
We could eradicate extreme poverty.
No more homeless and marginalized people who today fall through the cracks.
With a basic income, you think right away: "I will go on vacation, I badly need it."
Be it! But once you are relaxed,
you could quickly feel like doing countless things.
You are not lazy. Who is lazy in this room?
With basic income, it would be very easy to start a venture, to start one's own association or business.
For example, I have a business project for the moment, but I cannot start it up and make it happen because my financial stability is not good enough.
With a basic income for life, I would have done it long ago.
We could not only do more business, but also do better business, we could tackle environmental problems or civic issues.
Imagine what the introduction of basic income would mean for democracy.
It creates time for thousands of minds waiting for investing, for entrepreneuring and reclaiming their capacity in civic actions.
With a basic income, we could finally stop losing time to earn our life.
We could chose what we want to do.
A job which suits us.
Because that's the point of basic income.
It is an allowance for taking the time, a time that you have reclaimed, to build a better society.
I am convinced that, with a basic income, we can really redefine the meaning of our lives.
Basic income is an old idea of more than two centuries ago.
It was invented in 1795 by Thomas Payne, a British intellectual who already looked back then - in the times of the Revolution - he already looked back then for a way to fairly redistribute the fruits of the annuities that only very few landowners enjoyed.
Since then, basic income was advocated by great men such as Martin Luther King.
Politicians of all persuasions are today interested in this idea, be it the socialist Delphine Batho or the liberal Dominique de Villepin.
Political parties like "Nouvelle Donne" [New Deal] or Europe's Green Parties are interested in it, and discuss it intensely, before the next presidential elections.
This idea is interesting for a number of distinguished economists, even five Nobel Prize winners, of all political sensibility, who see basic income as an idea with a lot of potential -
of such potential that the Aquitaine Regional Council is working on its implementation, to experiment it in the next years.
Finland too is thinking about it, and the city of Utrecht in the Netherlands.
As Jeremy Rifkin says, one of the most influential futurists of the century, "Basic income is not a utopia, it is the next economic model of humanity."
Nothing less.
I am strongly convinced of it too.
I am convinced that it is precisely what we need to live up to the legacy of the 21st century, and to address the many challenges that lie ahead.
Thank you.
(Applause)
The world is my country.
That’s what I can say today.
Indeed, I have the entire world in my head.
And now, I’m going to explain why.
When I was a kid, I had a big dream: to visit all of the countries in the world. And a big problem: not a penny to my name.
I left in 1955, at 17 years old, I was cute back in those days, and I had 10 francs in my pocket.
I dare not speak to the youth of today about the 50s anymore because they take me for a cave man.
I tell them we didn’t have a telephone at home, no television, no rough travel guides,
there were no jet planes, there were propeller planes.
In those days, information was scarce
And in those days, you needed a visa to go to Spain, Germany, Great Britain.
In fact, we didn’t speak of travel in 55, we were still rebuilding the war-torn country.
So I left France at a time when it was an impossible and even crazy dream.
I never thought I would do it, yet today it’s done.
And it happened in two periods: the first trip, the black line on the map, lasted 18 years without returning home.
Not a fast guy !
[laughter] We weren’t going to leave just for a week-end, of course.
And I came home because I fell ill with dysentery, And afterwards I was furious: I was still missing some countries.
The red lines you can see, I was in France, It looks a bit like a spider’s web, For 30 years.
30 years.
I used to leave every year for 6, 7 or 8 months to fulfil my dream,
which was to visit every country, every part of the world, It’s done.
As you know, there are many problems in the world and there’s one when you travel you all experience, which is communication.
I didn’t plan anything, everything happened in spite of myself, and I say this on my return, because I didn’t plan anything.
I spent the first seven years learning languages, doing odd jobs in Europe, on the spot, and that’s how I learned English, Spanish, German and Italian.
Between Spain and Germany, I spent two years in the Congo,
in those days there was military service, And I was in the Congo to avoid the war in Algeria.
I didn’t feel like becoming a target.
Then, I decided to learn Russian, but at the time, the great USSR, no visa.
In the workers’ paradise, they didn’t want an extra worker.
So in the end, in short, After many adventures, I landed in Canada in 65. And there, I discovered something that I didn’t know Which was that North America paid better than Europe.
There, I finally realised that I could save up to fulfil my dream.
And for three years, I saved up in Toronto, as a translator.
And with three years of savings, I managed the last six years of those 18 years without working.
And that’s when I managed to do this black trip. Spending my savings from Canada little by little. A dollar a day.
Very good for your figure
Very bad for your stomach,
Believe me! One dollar, why?
For two main reasons: for one thing, I didn’t pay for transport,
I hitchhiked everywhere. All in all, 400,000 kilometres.
No small matter, it’s the distance From the Earth to the Moon.
I travelled 300,000 kilometres with that guy And 100,000 with this one.
There are wise guys who drive on the left.
The problem with hitchhiking around the world, is that two-thirds of the Earth, is water not land
So I had to hitchhike by ship, sailing-boat and plane.
The other reason for the one dollar, was that I never slept in hotels.
You saw the first photo in Alaska, it was -45°, so I had
to find shelter within five minutes, Or I’d end up as a Findus product, In the frozen food section.
So that dollar was spent on food and visas, but you can’t be picky,
and I didn’t eat in restaurants, I ate in markets, carts by the side of the road.
One day, a truck drove past me and dropped carrots for 20 metres,
I picked them all up! I ate like a rabbit
for 10 days after.
[laughter] What was I going to say?
[laughter] It’s my menopause!
[laughter] Don’t laugh, It’ll happen to you too.
[laughter] So I had many experiences.
For example, I went to live with monks in Bangkok, in yoga schools in India, I worked in a kibboutz in Israël, I lived with the famous doctor Albert Schweitzer in his hospital in Lambaréné in Gabon. I lived with hippies in San Francisco, in Haight-Ashbury, during their heyday. I lived with the so-called
headhunters, had all sorts of experiences.
For example, I was jailed seven times.
You noticed as soon as I came in, I seem dangerous.
[laughter] I was also almost shot, around ten times.
I was deported several times.
I love being deported by the way, It costs nothing.
[laughter] [Applause] You have to be deported In the right direction though.
[laughter] I’m telling you all of this very briefly, because it would take all night, to tell you all my stories,
But it’s to make you understand how I learned all about life, OK?
And you’re going to wonder why did I do all of this?
I also asked myself that question.
It’s not a regular life.
The truest of the true reasons in fact, apppeared after about 10 years.
At first, I had a dream,
many people also dream of seeing the world, But you don’t spend your life chasing a dream.
As well as this, I have An insatiable spirit of curiosity.
At 17 I was as curious as I am now at 79.
But the truest of the true reasons appeared after about ten years, as I was saying, because I was born before the war.
And for the youngest among you, I mean World War II, thank you!
[laughter]
I can see some people still calculating.
I say this because childhood memories, are vivid for every one of us,
They’re like an interior rucksack that you carry during your entire life.
And for me the most vivid were my earliest memories because it was wartime, but not war on the television,
As I told you, we didn’t have tv, But we had the Jerries.
And I remember that as a child I had a recurring dream, a nightmare,
I could see myself in front of a Gestapo firing-squad.
It was a rough start.
I spent a night standing on my bed, near Villeneuve-St-Georges, When they bombed the shunting-yard.
And today, after 70 years, when I hear the siren that they test at the town hall in Boussy-Saint-Antoine, where I live, you know, the first thing that happens, is that my heart skips a beat, and my first instinct, still today, is to run down to the basement. because to me, that sound means bombings.
So what I accomplished, was not a world tour, you know the usual world tour today: one year, one round trip,
no, it wasn’t that, Look at the map, it zigzags all over the place.
In fact, what I did, I’d rather call it a tour of mankind.
What interested me was not the mileage, which was part of it, nor the adventure, I don’t look for adventure, but it finds me, it doesn’t miss me, But what interested me, were human hearts.
In fact, I wanted to meet people from all around the world to answer an essential question, following my childhood in the war: Will humanity one day be able to achieve peace on Earth?
That’s the key question.
And do you want to know the answer?
Yes?
Are you all comfortably seated?
To me, peace, this may surprise you, is not only possible, it’s inevitable.
Peace will be achieved, that’s what I’ve just said.
So I’m going to explain right away because some people say to me "he hasn’t seen the world".
Actually, that’s precisely what I’ve done.
It’s difficult to imagine peace, because we have never had it.
You can’t imagine something that you’ve never known.
And when we look back at past history, the bloody past, we struggle to imagine peace, we agree.
And other people say to me: "we’ve always had war" and come to the brilliant conclusion, that we’ll always have war.
Those guys don’t open their eyes,
look at Europe, it’s been a string of battles, of wars, Including two world wars, that’s what I’ve learnt.
And yet, it so happens that around thirty nations managed to achieve peace.
This is a good example, which shows it’s not impossible.
But for peace to be worldwide, of course, many things need to be sorted out,
You know this as well as me. Another idea, which you’ve already seen out in the country, on the brambles Have you ever seen caterpillars?
Yuck.
Lots of hair, lots of legs, big eyes,
How could you imagine the butterfly that’s inside, if we weren’t aware of it
Impossible.
And what we’ve seen until today in history, in my opinion, is the "caterpillar" period.
I agree with you, that it’s practically impossible to imagine the beautiful peace butterfly that’s inside.
But I say "if there’s a caterpillar, there must be a butterfly".
There’s something that has just revolutionized the history of mankind, and you know it as well as I do. Recently, it’s brand new, it’s just come out, Distance has been abolished.
whoosh!
For the first time ever, the great human family is linked together, reunited, interdependant,
we are all in the same boat.
Well, we’ll have to take this into account, quite simply.
whether the nations like each other or not, whether they want to or not, they must stay in tune, we’re not going back to the Middle Ages riding donkeys, that’s all over.
To achieve a world of peace we must start with ourselves,
we need a man of peace It’s quite logical.
And to have a man of peace, in my opinion, there are three steps to take:
start with ourselves, because everyone wants change, provided the others change too.
There’s something we need to understand,
look, it’s very simple,
We must understand that the Earth is actually but one country
"One people, one planet", That’s the title of my first book.
The Earth is but one country And all humans are its citizens.
Secondly, we must understand that the human race is unique.
I’ve only seen one species of this kind.
There are marvelous people everywhere.
We all have a heart and emotions.
We all live between the two extremities
of joy and sorrow.
We’re all in the middle.
We also need to understand something else, if we want peace to reign, and last:
There aren’t a hundred different religions.
No, there’s only one.
I’d like to add a little word,
the word religion is a very sensitive word, So I would like to specify what I mean by it.
To me, quite simply, what is religion all about?
It’s a code of conduct, quite simply, which has been explained by the great educators of humanity, or the founders of civilisations.
And why did they explain this to us?
To enhance our potential for high quality and integrity that we originally had, to live in harmony in society and, for those who want to believe in it, to prepare us for the afterlife.
It’s a code of conduct and here’s what you need to understand: Everybody’s been reading out of the same book since the beginning!
There’s only one book. There’s only one, so let’s stop fighting.
But this one book, as every book, has many chapters.
So why?
Because as humanity is not static, it’s constantly developing with new chapters being frequently added, for a new understanding and for new needs.
But it’s still the same book.
In other words, the core of all religions is shared.
If everyone focused on their own cultural or religious heritage, there would be no more conflict.
This is what I think is important, I’m repeating myself a little, but it’s important to understand that there’s only one religion.
Let’s stop fighting about it.
I’m going to use one last image to get my point accross, briefly.
When we want to build a new house, what do we do?
We get new bricks.
I repeat, we won’t make a new house with old rotten bricks.
But a pile of new bricks, is just a pile of new bricks
It’s not a house.
We first need the architect’s plan.
And when we have the plan, and the new materials, We can build the house, we all agree.
So today, to forge the universal human being we need, We would also need a plan.
There is no existing system in today’s world that meets what we need today.
Just so you know, a comic show started again recently,
tonight, there’s something on TV, something comical.
What I have to say now, and I’ll finish with this, is that during my travels, you won’t believe what I’m going to say, I discovered that peace is not a pious hope on my behalf, an utopia.
It’s on the move.
That's what I've seen!
Today, glory Is not for those who love their country, But for those who love the entire world.
Thank you.
[Applause]
Why, whenever you want to do something, is there always someone to tell you, "It's not possible?"
I see that this speaks
to some of you, good.
I grew up in Lebanon.
Like most children my age, my heros were called Tom Sawyer, Indiana Jones, Marty McFly!
But my favourite hobby was collecting shrapnel, bullet cartridges, and ammunition boxes.
One day, I found The Holy Grail: a grenade!
Still live.
I knew very well that in bringing it home, my parents wouldn't really be proud of me.
Let me tell you, I didn't keep it very long.
When we're children, nothing seems impossible.
One day, our parents announced that we were leaving Lebanon for France, and by road.
Through the eyes of Lebanese children, France was another planet altogether.
(Laughter) Isn't that how you see France?
There are the Châteaux of the Loire!
Well, I can tell you, that in Lebanon, at nine years old it was true for me, but it was also true for my friends,
that's France.
Well, on arriving in France, my parents provided us with, and for the first time in my life, the demonstration that a perfectly inconceivable thing could happen.
As luck would have it, we arrived in France on the 14th of July.
(Laughter)
As luck would have it. My memories are a little hazy, but I remember the Promenade des Anglais, in Nice for those who can't place it.
The crowd, the fireworks...
It was the first time I ever saw fireworks.
In Lebanon, of course, we know how to celebrate an event.
In Lebanon, when we want to celebrate an event, it's simple: we fire Kalachnikovs!
And we learn that there were two or three deaths as a result of the stray bullets.
It's our Grande Finale.
As a teenager, I joined the Scouts.
I found myself in a group of athletes.
They were huge and me? Anyway...
It's with the Scouts that I learned
the notions of effort and excelling.
And then, it made me want to go further, and to make other plans.
I started mountaineering.
At the time, I was a student.
To be able to climb mountains, I needed to earn money.
I started to give math lessons.
Every cent got me closer and closer to my goal.
With each euro earned, I was a little closer to my project and to my goal.
People started to explain to me that I couldn't embark on such a project.
I didn't have any experience, I didn't know anything about mountains, I wasn't in the "moutaineer" category.
I still worked on a number of projects, I climbed a couple of times, several peaks.
Of course, it didn't always work out as planned.
In Argentina for example, when I was attempting to climb the highest summit of the southern hemisphere, that's called the Aconcagua, almost 7,000 metres above sea level, I had to give up 400 metres from the top!
400 metres!
That's probably the distance separating you, here, from your car in the carpark.
400 metres, after two years of preparation and 15,000 kilometres.
You probably think I was disappointed.
Well, I have to say, that I was actually relieved.
Why relieved?
Because many people explained that mountaineering was going to be difficult, that I'd be cold, hungry, scared.
But nobody thought to tell me that, maybe, going away to climb on the other side of the world, at Christmas time, could be difficult.
And on the other side of the world, I felt very lonely.
But it still made me want to continue.
It didn't stop me from continuing my projects.
So, I made other projects.
Other adventures.
I, among other things, went around the world using human strength.
"Human strength", what does that mean?
It's simple, in a manner of speaking, I cycled round half the world and for the other half, I used a kayak and a boat that only moved when you pedaled.
You see, it's not complicated.
And again, most people, not everyone this time, explained that I couldn't do this successfully.
I didn't have the mental strength.
I didn't know anything about the sea.
I wasn't in the "sailor" category.
There were many objections.
And once a journalist contacted me...
Let me replay the scene for you, it'll be funnier.
"Uh, so yes hello, today we're talking to Jean-Gabriel Chelala.
Jean-Gabriel, you're planning an extraordinary world tour.
The first question that comes to mind right now is: Do you really think you can travel 33,000 km without having the physique of an athlete?"
(Laughter) Well.
You have to know that this was one of the first interviews, and honestly I don't know what I said, but I don't think it was very audible.
She'd told me that she would ask me a couple of basic questions: What will you eat, how long will you sleep?
It was as if the number of kilometres had to be proportional to the size of your thighs.
And you know what?
Step by step, I set up my project.
And step by step, I managed to finish my world tour after 33,000 kilometres and 17 months of expedition.
So obviously, it wasn't always very easy.
You must all looking at the helicopter, but nobody noticed the little yellow dot.
I see that you're all following, good.
The little yellow dot,
that's me going for a swim. This takes place in the Bering Sea, I said the Bering Sea, not the strait, everyone knows the strait.
The Bering Sea is between Alaska and Siberia.
I was considering getting to Siberia from Alaska in a kayak!
400 kilometres.
In the middle: an island, a tiny island.
I've been navigating for six days. My plan is to get to that island in a few hours, it's a nice warm day, everything's fine there's a little 15 knot wind.
Suddenly the wind picks up: 20, 30, 40 knots in a matter of an hour, maybe.
I'm locked in my kayak, in five to six-metre dips.
The wind's blowing, it's hitting from every angle.
My kayak, to give you an idea, is a living space that's 50cm wide, 36cm high and 1m90 long.
One day, someone told me, "That's the size of a coffin!"
(Laughter) They're not wrong!
It's less padded, but they're not wrong.
(Laughter) So I decided to resist, to stay inside, to lock myself in, to wait.
It's important to know that the kayak weighs 50kg.
I've got 50kg of equipment and 50kg of supplies. At the time, I weighed around 50kg.
So my position in the kayak is crucial.
I needed to lie at the bottom of the kayak, hands like this, to stop the kayak from tipping over, because if it tips over, and I have one chance, I end up at the bottom of the sea with the fish.
It's 2°C in the water. It's Alaska!
I resist like that for 36 hours.
After 36 hours, I had to call the coast guard.
It's important to know that this decision, it probably seems obvious to you, maybe, was one of the hardest decisions of my life.
Because the moment I ring the coast guard, it's my whole project that I leave behind!
I'm not looking for glory, or a trophy, I'm not in a competition, I'm not getting a cheque at the end...
But I've been working on this project for years.
This project gave meaning to my life.
When I find myself alone and I call the coast guard, it's my project I'm abandoning.
This decision was one of the hardest of my life.
However, I think that if the heilcopter took another hour to come and get me, I wouldn't be here to talk to you about it.
Things don't always go as planned.
You can say that again.
(Laughter) So, after 17 months of expedition, I went back to France, I launched a business.
For six years, I've devoted myself to developing this business.
I'm lucky enough to have two wonderful children, who I take to school almost every morning.
And even if the urge to make plans is still there, today I concentrate on that.
But little by little, I'm undertaking new adventure projects.
Between us, you're a great audience.
I can tell you: I'm considering doing the Vendée Globe!
(Applause) Thank you, that's kind, I'll take it, but let's wait till we get there.
That being so, I sense in the crowd, and I saw you, you, madam, smile.
I sense in the crowd that some are thinking, "But he can't do it!
He doesn't know anything about sailing.
He hasn't got experience."
He isn't in the "great sailor" category, or the "breton" category (Laughter) "He doesn't have Kersauson's physique."
Although I'm not far from Ellen Macarthur's.
I may be in luck!
You know what, I don't know.
Maybe I'll make it, maybe I won't.
but actually, it's not really important.
You know why?
Because I believe that successes are catalysts and failures are opportunities.
Nothing else.
However, if I want to be sure that I'm going in the right direction, to be sure of my choices, these choices have to be driven by my desires, and not by my chances of succes.
I don't know if I'll make it and after all, it doesn't matter to me.
Because if you want to be sure that you're going in the right direction, your choices have to be led by your desires.
So, if I have a simple idea to share with you: stop asking loads of questions!
The impossible is anything but unthinkable.
So, go for it!
(Applause)
I'd like to tell you something about physics.
So, it's not exactly the physics we'd usually see in textbooks.
Physics is a bit megalomaniac, it tends to want to govern everything from the infinitely small to the infinitely large.
So to cover such a broad spectrum, plenty of imagination is needed, of course, because what is happening in an atom, in a grain of sand, a petanque ball, or a planet, isn't necessarily the same thing,
so you have to be ready to invent new laws.
But in parallel to this approach, knowing how to use some form of laziness is also necessary because what is actually happening in an atom, a grain of sand, a petanque ball, or a planet, can be similar in many ways.
And to be able to identify theses similarities between objects that are at first glance totally different, you have to know how to ask questions that are a bit weird, and I have put together a few for you.
So what is the commonality between the break of an uncooked spaghetto and the fracture of a metal beam?
Or between the vortex that I generate with my spoon in a cup of coffee and hurricanes in the atmosphere?
Another one is what is the connection between the physics of accretion disks around forming stars - which is very serious - and the physics of cake dough?
Or between mayonnaise on one hand, and nuclear fusion by confinement on the other?
Now I'm going to talk about one of these weird questions tonight, that is "What does a liquid ... and a cat have in common?"
(Laughter) Obviously behind this question lies another more serious question that is "What is a liquid?"
Well, a liquid is a material that takes the shape of its container while maintaining a constant volume.
This is the official definition of a liquid.
And we see in numerous cases, (Laughter) that cats seem to fit this definition pretty well.
They adapt their shape to their container.
Maybe you've already seen pictures like these.
Quite a lot of these have been circulating on the internet for many years.
And, well, I spend a bit of my time on the internet, as a researcher, I mean!
(Laughter) And I didn't miss the appearance of this meme, plenty of pictures related to the question "Are cats liquid?"
Now several years ago, on a spring afternoon that wasn't motivating me to do what I was supposed to do, I decided to write a scientific article with the title: "On the rheology of cats" in order to take this question seriously.
This procrastination actually led to a bit of success since a few years later, it won me the Ig Nobel prize of physics which rewards research that makes people both laugh and ponder.
I said that this scientific article was called "On the rheology of cats,"
but what does "rheology" mean?
Rheology comes from the greek "rheo" which means to flow.
This same root is found in other words such as "rhythm" for example, or more pompous words such as "logorrhea" - I'm going to try not to do that myself - and some slightly less pompous words such as"diarrhea," everyone knows that one! (Laughter)
So the idea was to take the question "Are cats liquid?"
and use it to illustrate several issues that are quite serious this time, that rheologists face and try to solve every day.
But anyway, are cats liquid or not?
In fact, the key is that the answer to this question depends on the span of time we're ready to allow it.
Because if we look carefully at the definition of a liquid, "adapting one's shape" is an action that isn't going to happen instantly.
Behind this adaptation, there's a characteristic time, and this characteristic time (Laughter) is called the "relaxation time".
In many cases - the cases that are easiest to deal with - the relaxation time is something intrinsic to the material.
So in the case of a cat, it will depend on its age or its breed.
Here we see that number 107 looks more liquid and thus has a shorter relaxation time.
Because this is precisely the key behind the concept of relaxation time, it's that in reply to the question "Is a cat liquid?" or "Is such
and such material liquid?",
you must answer another question that is "What is this material's relaxation time?"
So for a cat, same thing, we will ask this question, "what is the relaxation time of a cat, what does it depend on?"
Here I've chosen a case, the easiest to deal with, when the time of relaxation only depends on the material itself.
But it can also depend on the container since we can easily imagine that a cat relaxes more easily, liquefies more easily on the lap of its owner than in a cage.
Now, let me give you another example, that of a drop of water.
Water is the liquid par excellence.
We tend to expect it to spread on any kind of surface, but in some contexts, we see that water forms droplets.
Now trying to better understand why in some cases the material flows whereas in others it doesn't depending on the container, relates to questions that imply research on what we call "wetting".
And research on wetting includes everything from the development of super water-resistant windshields which circumvent the need for windshield wipers, to research that attempt to understand the development of cancerous tumors because actually, the way cancerous cells and tissues spread can also be understood in this manner.
In fact, trying to estimate, to measure, calculate, maybe even modify the one or several relaxation times of the most diverse and varied materials is kind of what is at the heart of rheologists' research.
And what you need to try to keep in mind is that these relaxation times can last from one millisecond to millions of years.
That doesn't take anything away from the fact that if we observe these materials long enough, we will see them flow.
One example over a period of several decades or years, you may have notice that down a sloping road the asphalt sometimes forms like bumps.
That's because over a period of years, the asphalt flows down the slope.
And the same thing can happen with all sorts of construction materials from concrete to steel, and that's why the industries that manufacture those materials spend a lot of money to better understand their rheology.
Sometimes, it is microscopic details that have an enormous impact.
The collapse of a building sometimes depends on the precise physics of the grains of sand that make it up.
And a good example of this potentially significant impact of the microscopic on the macroscopic is found among firefighters who often like to add tiny filamentary molecules in small quantities, to their water tanks, and these filamentary molecules help reduce turbulence inside the fire hoses, thereby allowing them to spray the water farther with the same power.
Now the solutions that rheologists create for various problems are sometimes rather odd.
You may have seen in public buildings - not here I think but in recent public buildings - big columns situated in front of the emergency exits.
Well, we may think it's a little weird, but actually rheologists have shown that when a crowd moves, these columns tend to reduce congestion and jams at the exit.
So in reality, if we wait long enough everything flows.
That's the motto of rheology.
Even the materials that we walk on and we usually consider to be solid, even those materials flows.
So if we take a glacier, for example, over several decades - and that's what some scientists are doing by observing glaciers with timelapse cameras - we can see the ice flowing into the valley.
And if we had the chance to wait millions of years, we would see the same thing happening to mountains, and we would see that peaks and valleys are like the crests and troughs of an ever-moving ocean.
Alright!
Now you may ask again "But are cats liquid or not?"
So, my advice is just wait a little bit before giving your final answer.
(Laughter) Thank you.
(Applause)
(Sings 'Ya Henna') (Sings 'Bayete') (Sings 'Porgi amor') You heard that?
Three different songs, three different languages, and three different worlds.
I grew up with music. Music has done a lot for me.
It is a big part of my life.
The music my parents listened to, that I listened to as a child and that I continue to explore, has played a very important role.
When you listen to music, you may be touched by the melody, by the musicality of the words, or by the interpretation, but as a singer or someone who interprets I have realized that, in order to sing in tune, and with the correct meaning, I have to understand the words.
It was necessary to go and investigate languages.
The coming together of language and song is what I would like to share with you today.
I am of Togolese descent, and I grew up in Paris.
Quite naturally, my ears were accustomed to French, to Mina, [a dialect of Ewe,] the vernacular of southern Togo, spoken by my mother, and to Kabiye, the language of the north of Togo, spoken by my father. Mina and Kabiye sound as different from each other as Russian and Italian.
At home, it was like a sort of waltz of languages between French, Mina and Kabiye.
And each language had an important role.
Quite naturally my education was geared to learning languages.
I needed to understand how languages are articulated, their structure, their morphology, the meaning of words.
Each language has its own vocal colour, its musical colour, as well as its rhythmic colour.
I'll start with French, it's a language close to my heart, since it's my native language.
And French is an atonal language, but that doesn't mean it's monotonous.
I still remember poems I learned as a child, and when I recited these poems, I kind of saw pictures.
Listening to the words of Paul Verlaine, 'With long sobs the violin-throbs of autumn wound my heart with languorous and monotonous sound. Choking and pale when I mind the tale the hours keep, my memory strays down other days and I weep.'
The French language is like a hilly landscape and the words stream, the words flow, the phrases flow.
There's no eruption, there are no mountain peaks.
If we now talk about tonal languages, like Vietnamese, or Mandarin, they are really different from French.
A tonal language is one in which syllables must be pronounced at a precise tone. And in linguistics a tone is the specific pitch of a sound.
If you change the tone, you change the meaning.
In Mandarin, for example, if I say 'ma', it means mother, Mummy. If I say 'mǎ': it's a horse. 'Mà': the verb 'to insult'. 'Má': the word 'hemp'.
I want to draw your attention to the fact that by changing the tone, it changes the meaning of the word.
I will leave you to imagine the complexity of other languages like Vietnamese, which has six tones, and Thai, which has five tones. But, in music, the advantage is that, as a result of the tonal richness of these languages, some Asian musicians have perfect pitch. They are sensitive to variations in sound and also are excellent string players.
Moving away from Asian languages, I turn now to English.
English has been very important in my music life.
I was very interested in the history of Afro-American people and all the music it has produced: negro spirituals, gospel, soul, jazz and blues.
And in the English language I've discovered melodic, vibrant and sparkling intonations that swing,
as in - (Sings 'Children, Go Where I Send Thee') (Applause) I continue with Germany, and in German, I discovered an astonishing language: creative, a little like Lego.
In German, it's possible to build words in order to name an object or a concept.
With German, I also discovered another way of listening, that through its syntax.
In German, there may be one or more verbal groups that are to be found at the end of a long sentence. And to understand the sentence, you need to be patient, you have to wait for the end of the sentence.
You cannot interrupt the word flow as you can in French.
German has been used a lot in opera, and it is the expressive language of Schubert's Lieder, which says very gently, 'If I were a bird, I would sit on this branch and I would sing for her all summer.'
(Sings 'Dann blieb' ich auf den Zweigen hier') Isn't that superb?
(Applause)
Russian -
I am under the spell of this stressed language of Pushkin, with all the characters of Chekhov and Gogol who fight against oblivion.
And Russian has a sweet and sour flavour. Its intonation is much more internal and much more rounded than French.
In Russian, the word stress is variable, and that determines how the vowels are pronounced.
Take for example the words of the Ukrainian poet Grebenka in his famous poem 'Black Eyes'.
'Black eyes, sublime and ravishing eyes - ' (Russian) 'Ochi chornyye'. (Sings 'Ochi chornyye, ochi strastnyye') Now, I am off to Japan.
Japanese with its short syllables that are open and aerial.
Japanese reflects the search for minimalism and aesthetics in the image of the legendary Sakura.
Do you know Sakura?
(Sings 'Sakura yayoi no sorawa') Then there are all these other languages of South Africa.
The first time I heard the South African national anthem, 'Nkosi Sikelel' iAfrika', in five languages, in Xhosa, Zulu, Sesotho, Afrikaans and English, I felt the ground, I felt the power, I felt the rootedness.
And I would like to sing for you an extract from this anthem, and I'd like you to beat your hand with your fist.
(Beating her hand with her fist, the audience joins in) (Sings 'Yizwa imithandazo yethu') (Applause) To go out and explore languages, it's like mixing spices, like blending flavours, it fills our ears with wonderfully exotic sounds.
To conclude, I will use the words of Newley and Bricusse to tell you, 'I am feeling good.' (Sings 'Feeling Good') (Applause)

When I was 20, I was a young student.
I didn't have a lot of money.
I had so much difficulty with my studies,
I had to repeat exams nine times.
I graduated after a lot of difficulties.
Why?
Because I was hungry.
And I was ashamed to say so.
I was ashamed to say so, because hunger is hard to suffer.
That's something we can't easily say, because the shame of saying that we are hungry, people can't understand it.
And this affected our study, work and everyday life.
In fact, when I decided to involve myself in fighting against food waste, it's because I wanted to fight against and defeat hunger.
We have to understand that each supermarket, every night, throws more than 50kg of consumable food into the trash cans.
This represents, approximately, 1,500 Euros, 1,600 dollars.
It's about 16,000 Euros per week.
And per year, more than 150,000 or 180,000 Euros.
In view of this, we have an unbelievable aberration!
There are poor people, and there is consumable food being thrown into trash cans every night.
We must combine these two aberrations.
We have striking power that we needed to pass this law in France, because the supermarkets were throwing food out every night, and getting the VAT, the taxes, back.
They get the taxes back.
And they still profited in this affair, whether they sold the unsold food or not, with different lobbies such as pesticide; pesticide that leads to junk food, malnutrition, obesity, cancer, cardiovascular disease.
And on the other side, the losers are rural people, farmers, the middle class. Besides, this great middle class also has problems, even here. One in six Americans suffers from hunger.
35 tons of consumable food are thrown into trash cans.
On Hollywood Boulevard, you have the same homeless as in France.
I don't come here to tell you what you have to do.
I come here to tell you that America, we need your help now.
With this law, we need the help of the USA to pass it.
Why?
Because $1.3 billion in food is thrown out all the time, every year.
This represents one third of food production worldwide.
One in three foods is thrown into a trash can, when, at the same time, 100 million people suffer from malnutrition. More than 40 million Americans suffer from malnutrition. More than one billion people are hungry.
France voted for the law on February 3, 2016.
I'd like to thank the French legislator Frédéric Lefebvre.
He is a member of the National Assembly.
Thanks to him. Thank you, Frédéric!
(Applause) In France, we passed the law.
Thanks to this law, more than 3,000 associations have received unsold food, and more than ten million meals have been distributed to the poor.
You can do the same thing.
We need you in order to fight.
Once again, we must fight against food waste in order to fight and defeat hunger.
Thank you so much.
I'm so sorry I had to talk in French, but I hope you understand my message.
Thank you so much!
(Applause)
Good afternoon.
I'm Ronan Moal, I'm a sexologist in Brest, France, and the co-founder of a company called "Heal2Sy" which provides applications to improve sexuality.
In my work, I noticed that the people I was seeing shared a number of similarities such as, generally, willingness, and also, some difficulty to understand what was happening to them. They were experiencing difficulties with their sexuality without really grasping the reason why and without really finding the way out.
And often, they were feeling alone even though they had a partner. They thought they were the only one who was trying, not knowing what was going on with the other.
Even when I have a couple in front of me, both respond that way.
And that's what I find very interesting.
The majority of these people have goodwill but don't necessarily manage to get along.
So, I'm very happy to have been invited to take part in this TEDx because the theme of this year's talks is "Understanding the world". And I think that, given the place sexuality has in our lives, understanding sexuality is, to some extent, understanding the world.
So, what is sexuality?
I'll need to keep it simple since we could spend all evening on it, or even longer.
Fundamentally, sexuality is an instinct.
If we're all here this evening, if we exist, it's because all our ancestors have had this instinct within them.
And for thousands of years, it was only a matter of instinct.
It's only some hundreds of years ago, that we decided to start giving it rules and norms.
And to do that, we called in the authority of the time: the Church.
It means that to determine the behaviour of sexually active couples, we asked abstinent singles.
So you can see that, right from the start, we didn't create the best conditions!
It was a bit like asking people on a diet to write the New Year's menu.
So to impart these norms, we immediately created the notion of good and evil, a norm that was a heterosexual sexuality within the framework of marriage, affection, and having children.
So anything beside that became necessarily outside the norm or even abnormal.
And this is the first difficulty in sexuality:
In fact, the norm, when it comes to sex, is to be outside the norm.
If we could invent a machine that could read our thoughts and write down everything we ever thought, I believe many of us would be willing to pay a lot of money to get rid of some lines in that text.
The only limits that need be placed on sexuality are respect for the law, and, above all, respect for your partner and yourself.
Beyond that, there are no rules.
Yet, whenever we step outside this norm, we always have the feeling of being weird, shameful, or even perverted.
And "perverted" can be understood as "straying from the path."
So, the simple act of making love using contraception, given "the path" that was a determined initially, actually makes you a pervert.
To impart this norm, we've set up an educational system.
We all have been educated, and this education starts very early.
It is twofold. It's a vertical education, delivered by our parents and grandparents. But it's also a horizontal education, delivered by society and people around us.
And we've been influenced from the very beginning.
Let me give you the example of a little one-year-old child whose parent has taken off his nappy to give him or her a bath.
This child takes the opportunity to explore the part of his body he couldn't explore during the day.
Imagine that the parent turns back and sees him.
Depending on his own reaction, the parent is going to start guiding the child to the path he or she will follow.
If the reaction is harsh - "Don't touch there, it's dirty" -
due to the tone, the surprise, the use of the imperative usually reserved for important things, those words are going to be thoroughly imprinted: "Don't touch - it's dirty, okay!"
If, on the other hand, the approach is softer, it may be useful to convey certain messages about social behaviour.
If the child continues to play with his genitals in public, this could cause problems for him later on.
But if the parent conveys it calmly saying, "That's yours, but you shouldn't do that when there are others around.
In your room, you do what you want, but not when people can see," you can see that the two babies I've just spoken about are already taking two different paths.
And this will go on like that.
Society will take care of it too.
Next time you go to the supermarket, take advantage and pass by the children's clothes aisle, and you will see what is reserved for 3-4-year-old boys and girls.
Little boys have boxers, briefs in navy, black, or brown colour, with a superhero on them right there.
Right now, the current trend is Star Wars.
Little boys walk around with a Jedi or sometimes a villain equipped with a light sabre.
I think Freud would have appreciated the symbolism.
Little girls have panties in white, soft pink, or pale blue colour, with asexual princesses, little hearts, or unicorns.
You can already see that the message is not quite the same.
And even in the underwear's colour, is it surprising that children of three or four have dirty underwear in the evening?
They learn about cleanliness.
Even for adults, it's a living zone.
Except that the little boy in the evening, goes to put his boxers in the wash, and nothing can be seen on them.
But any soiling will immediately be seen on the little girl's underwear.
A kind of hygienist pressure is exercised on her right from the start.
It may seem a little far-fetched, but it can be found all the way up to marriage, in the white dress, a symbol of purity, that is, of virginity.
And it's going to continue like that.
In slang, little boys are "wankers".
Boys wank themselves.
Girls are?
"Little madams."
Even well-meaning parents will pass on messages involuntarily.
They will show their children porno films.
I'm sure you've done that.
Generally, the first ones are Snow White, Cinderella, Sleeping Beauty. Why do I call them "pornographic films"?
Well, because they're as close to reality as classic pornography that is mainly intended for a male audience.
In Walt Disney films, we show to easily influenced children, especially girls, that if they are beautiful, if they wear a pretty dress, they will cross path with a prince charming, they will fall in love with each other and have lots of children - by the way, we don't know how - and they will live happily ever after, meaning no effort is required.
If it's the right guy, it's bound to work.
If things get complicated, it means he is not the one.
Unfortunately, pretty soon after that, real pornographic films will follow.
I say "unfortunately" because the average age at which people see their first porn, today in France, is now only 11 years old.
This means that the majority of children see their first porn before they even hit puberty.
And we are virtually subject to all these influences, all these elements, from the first day of our lives up to adulthood.
We try to shape our personality in the midst of all that,
and when we reach an age of sexual maturity, adulthood, we already have a pretty poor record.
If you'd like an analogy, it's a bit as if we were computers equipped with an instinctive operating system on which we had installed a lot of software that was more or less good or even frankly obsolete, if not malware.
Yet people who have done that have often done so with good intention.
It's been downloaded into us, and you probably have in you, as much as I do, all kinds of inappropriate programs.
I expect your parents has taught you to put your hand over your mouth when you cough. Haven't they?
It's actually a very bad idea.
When we put our hands over our mouths, we scatter all our microbes over them. And then we spread them onto armrests, door handles, almost everywhere.
In that way, everyone gets to share them.
The majority of illnesses are transmitted by the hands.
It's not a good idea at all.
So it might be well not to cough in people's face,
but ideally, we should use our elbow instead of our hand.
Except that back then, when we first learn that habit, we probably didn't have the same knowledge in microbiology.
And now, since you are aware of an inappropriate program, you're also starting to become aware of what conditioning is. You will probably think of me next time you cough.
That's why it's complicated to understand each other, because we are all computers with a different operating system and different software.
And two people who try to understand each other's sexuality, it is a bit like a PC and a Mac trying to communicate.
And if that was not enough, Nature also interferes.
I'll save you some time, there are 11 of them.
(Laughter) Counting is the first reflex we usually have!
Yes, because Nature's interest is not the individual's interest either.
Nature's interest is in the continuation of a species.
And everything done is to that end.
We are conditioned for that, so when we make love, in the eyes of Nature, we're making a child.
Homo sapiens has existed for 200,000 years, the pill for only 40 years.
Needless to say that our brains hadn't had time to process this data.
And all it takes is one contraceptive accident for us to hit that reality.
So, this is also going to influence us in spite of ourselves in the choice of our partners for example, which has actually little to do with their skills in playing guitar or reciting poems.
It's mostly biological, even if psychological and sociological factors intervene as well.
There's very little chance, for example, that your partner has the same blood group as you,
although there are not that many blood groups.
And if their blood group is the same, their Rh factor usually won't be because, simply put, immunity groups correspond to blood groups.
So making a child with someone of the same immunity group means giving the child the same copy twice; but having a baby with someone of a different group means giving the child a much wider range of immunity and increasing his or her chances of surviving disease.
Yet when we meet someone, we don't necessarily think about having a child.
But all that has already been decided despite ourselves, by our instinct.
And Nature will continue to work like that.
When we fall in love, here again, I'm sorry to say it, but it's not quite like in Disney films. It's rather because your body decided that you found a compatible partner for breeding, so it secretes substances in your brain that basically drug you.
Well, it's a pretty nice kind of drug; we are irresistibly attracted to the other person;
and it's been like this since the dawn of time.
When marriage wasn't arranged directly - so that questions could be avoided - people fell in love.
They were hurried into marriage out of knowledge of what would follow.
And when after one or two years, their passion faded away as the chemical secretions diminished, there were already one, two or three children.
Women didn't earn a living.
Men were not autonomous at the household level.
Society didn't allow divorce.
So people used to continue like that as assisting spouses.
Today, we can live for many years with someone without having children.
Women are independent,
and men are too, usually.
Being with someone is therefore a choice.
And if we do it, it's because we want to gain from it.
We want it to be something pleasant that helps us develop our personality.
And we find this in desire too,
that's why desire is important.
Even with the expression "to desire someone", it's not clear whether it means sexuality or the person in general.
So when people don't feel any sexual desire from the other, they have doubts. They sense that their integrity is being attacked.
They start worrying, losing confidence in themselves.
That is why today, we should see sexuality as something completely different because everything plays against a fulfilling sexuality.
It is always about Nature. When a child is born, in the eyes of Nature, the parents are no longer of interest. One could potentially look after the child, but the second is incidental.
All the time parents spend playing around is not time spent looking after the little one,
and this is a very bad investment in Nature's view.
By the way, there are species where males go away after mating, if they've not been eaten by the females.
We're not doing so badly!
But for example, in the human species, when a child is born, if the mother is breast feeding, she experiences every time a surge of oxytocin, which we call the "attachment hormone".
We also get this surge when we have an orgasm with a partner.
Except that here, it's going to be six, seven, eight times a day.
Add to that fatigue, waking up at night, and the shock of pregnancy, really, it's going to be pretty easy to create a rift between the parents, or tensions and things like that.
So, the most important thing to understand regarding sexuality is that everything is playing against you, and if you rely on love, spontaneity, and Nature, you will go lovingly, spontaneously and naturally, straight into the wall.
We are the first generations to live what we are living today: 60 years of sex life, the possibility to choose, to find pleasure in it.
So it's entirely feasible, but it's the result of a construction.
You can experience something nice sexually, and it's possible that it lasts, but you need to learn to communicate since, as I said, it's like a Mac confronting a PC.
Don't even try to understand what the other thinks.
If you try to read a file for one with the other, it won't work.
It's therefore necessary and very important, that you delete the education you've received, and replace it with a sexual ethic, a collection of moral rules and values that are yours and chosen by you because they were meaningful and relevant for you, not because others do it.
Others put their hands over their mouths when they cough.
You also need to learn how to communicate, dare to talk about what you like, and dare to listen to the other even if you don't understand.
If it's important to her or to him, we must listen, and, if necessary, seek help because it's not all that simple.
But it's possible.
Above all, you must not regard each other as enemies, not wait for the other to make the first move because if you both wait for the same, this could go on for a long time.
We must dare to turn to the other and say what we feel, express our desires, and not necessarily try to understand everything, it's too complicated. And you need especially to realise that, as a sexual partner, you should, above all else, be partners, friends, and allies against everything else, that is, the enemies: Nature, society, fatigue and habit.
And in that way, we can succeed and do something very enjoyable and very constructive.
There you go!
