The first cities appeared 5,000 years ago.
Yet, in 1800, only 3% of the world population was urbanized.
Today, 200 years later, it’s 50% and, in 30 years, it’ll be 75%.
The increase of construction surface will equal to the size of Paris every one to two days, by 2050.
Churchill once said, “First we shape our buildings, thereafter, they shape us.”
It’s the same thing for cities.
So, what do we want to be?
Where do we want to go?
For me, creating a city is giving life wings.
I would want to increase and enhance the city’s senses.
I like the word “sense” a lot because, in the French language, it has three meanings
Three meanings that can be compared to three ways of building a city.
The intelligible sense is for the planned city: a city made by its empty spaces, its highways, its networks.
The sensitive sense is the vernacular city. a city thought by the "process."
I take this position based on sensitive and contextual parameters: the light, the view, the noise.
Sense as direction: it’s our relation to time.
On the one hand, the sustainable, lasting city, on the other hand, the city that projects itself towards a future.
The arrival of the Internet a few decades ago was like the arrival of a new dimension.
It will continue to disrupt our relation to space, to reality, and to the city.
The city that I dream about is a city that would combine all these types of cities harmoniously: vernacular, planned, sustainable, all at once, with multiple intelligences.
Nevertheless, today, the economy takes precedence and the city expands inevitably.
It starts to disperse and becomes urban.
So it’s necessary to start by rethinking the limit, guiding, facilitating access, confining.
To no longer systematically encroach upon the countryside but to build the city inside the city.
Reintroducing wilderness to the heart of the city, not with trees lined along the streets, but with areas full of forests invading the streets.
Vegetation becomes a natural incubator for chance and for diversity.
With the reintroduction of the flora and fauna specifically, the sound of bird songs, the smell of plants,
oxygen, fresh air.
Nature must cross our cities like highways cross our countryside.
And this network of green rivers isn’t a barrier because public space - the street, the plaza - expands in the 3rd dimension
During winter, I'll take a walk on a bridge under the light, During summer, closer to ground level, under shade, and everyone will be able to benefit from a sunset above the city.
These spatial dimensions are accompanied by numeric dimensions.
The predominant model today, everywhere in the world, is that of the “smart city”.
I rather refer to a programmed city, meaning, a planned city, that adapts in real time.
The programmed city is safer.
It is more ecological - it consumes less energy.
It’s more efficient - a GPS can tell me the shortest path on the basis of traffic.
It’s more comfortable, even if comfort is formatted.
It really has no taste, it’s insipid.
I much prefer the notion of well-being: when you’re in a cabin in middle of the forest, or on a boat, you’re fine, yet it’s not necessarily comfortable.
Technological progress causes desensitization.
The programmed city leads to standardization and to hyper streamlining.
A rational intelligence that fights the unexpected that standardizes our behaviors and our collective living.
“Smart cities”, as they are conceived today, produce generic cities, a city without a soul.
If you want, it can be seen from above.
It’s a complex system that tends to run itself, like a cell.
Many scientists agree that technology's exponential evolution will lead to a specific point in which the system will have a conscience of its own.
A form of artificial intelligence.
And we should live in symbiosis, the soldiers or the little cells of this living meta-organism.
Now is the time to begin the transition.
We must rethink the city from the inside, at human scale, for humanity.
Reconsidering the body’s experience.
We’re not cells, we’re beings made of flesh and bone.
The importance of the body, touch, physical and bodily contact between us, but also with matter, with the city, it's vital.
Architecture addresses body as much as it does spirit.
That begins by forgetting individuality, but creating individualities, introducing chance.
Today, societies are a bit aseptic; the main collective emotions that we have happen with terrorist attempts or after a soccer match.
So it’s essential and urgent to reinject emotion, at small scale, to life, to living.
Our cities have to be a base for poetic events, for happy accidents.
That begins with surprises.
Surprise is what makes emotion, collective emotion, the social bond, living together, interacting with each other.
First, the lifelong surprises of time hybridization, meaning, avoiding demolition or "museumization", and, instead, making several time frames coexist in the same place.
Similar to the Lyon opera house or the Louvre pyramid.
The hybridization of uses: when one takes an office building like this one, it has a double layer that improves its thermal efficiency but also works as a climbing route.
So it invites encounter and exchange.
More generally, when the vernacular city is lacking, we must not hesitate to recreate it in the planned city.
That’s to say adding, inserting, raising, as a function of the new needs of its residents.
For that, we have to readapt the rules of urbanization, which must be simpler, less restrictive, but, above all, they have to incorporate the idea of exception.
Exception is as important as rules are.
These lifelong surprises come with more ephemeral ones.
Of a bizarre kind.
For example, having fun with the weather.
To no longer systematically protect people from water, wind or light, but to play with them: creating a water curtain, a wind corridor.
For the Guggenheim Museum project at Helsinki, we created a "solar" tower that increases the brightness of a place - this is in northern Europe - but that also creates a symphony of effects and light and thermic contrasts.
During winter, it will paint us the thawing of the snow.
The mirrors in this tower are managed by a computer program that is intelligent sensitively before it is rationally.
New technology is a great tool.
It allows us to enhance reality.
A smartphone can help me enhance my perception of the physical world.
Hyperlinking: handling connections and disconnections between distant environments but also with virtual environments.
And interacting: they favor the creation and establishment of new aesthetics, both material and immaterial - creating diverse atmospheres, mixing times, places, and people.
So we have to reinject, to rethink these new technologies under a new sensitive prism.
This begins, for example, with the use of sensors in the city: surveillance video cameras, sensors for humidity, temperature.
We must take this data to produce, by means of a computer program, new effects: the changing color of a streetlight, its blinking, a building that "tweets," opening a virtual window, a micro-climate variation.
All these small details, all these micro-events will unexpectedly invite us to change paths, to prefer wandering to optimal movement.
Of course, it’s not a matter of building a theme park.
These environments must be rare and subtle.
90% of the time, people will not notice them.
But sometimes you find yourself in a hyper-sensitive state. because you're sad, happy, or mad, and can then be affected by the city’s small signals.
It’s a little bit like when you watch the night sky: if you have the chance of seeing a shooting star, that makes you happy, that inspires you.
All these subtle architectures fight against the generic city.
They favor the creation of new urban experiences.
They feed our imaginations and expand our city’s soul.
I would like to show you an interactive environment project: it concerns a tower, a visual and audio instrument, that sings twice a day, mysteriously, in the city.
It’s essential that we work together for a new enchantment, to breathe new life to diversity poetry, and the life of our cities.
Cities that are rational and sensitive to particular and subtle architectures that take us out of our comfort zones that surprise us and that invite us to further interact together and with the environment.
And the first interaction starts now.
It’s time for observation, for a shift in perspective that perhaps is going to make you smile to someone that you don’t know and for whom you hold no prejudice.
