Are there any freelancers here in the theater?
Raise your hand, freelancers!
I can't see well, but I still can see several hands in the air.
Have any of you already experimented coworking?
One hand, two hands...
In fact, coworking is based on two principles. The first principle is to share work spaces and to form a network, a community.
And this community will favor exchanges, helping each other out, and creativity.
It's a very simple idea, and it makes you wonder why nobody thought of it earlier.
Coworking was created in 2005 in San Francisco.
And in fact, what really promoted the emergence of coworking, was the development of new technologies.
Nowadays, with your computer, you have become completely mobile.
You can go anywhere you like.
In one click, you have access to your entire office's content.
And to all the information, all the knowledge of the world.
It's the equivalent of entire libraries, and you're connected to the entire world.
Under these conditions, you can work from anywhere.
Do any of you take the train
in the morning? I took it for quite some time, and I was surprised to see how before arriving at work, the majority of riders were already working, with their computers, on the train.
Now, trains are not coworking spaces, but who knows, one day they may become coworking spaces.
In fact, anything is possible.
I'll continue with some more questions.
Are any of you subscribers
to Mobility? Nobody?
Well, you're missing out.
I've experimented it for two years, because I didn't have a car at one point, and it's absolutely amazing.
First, I had cars much better than the ones I have now, and I also had no worries.
I encourage you to take a look at what Mobility offers.
Maybe I'll be more successful with my second question: Are there any of you who have already lived or who currently live with roommates?
Maybe back when you were studying.
Well, when you have tried Mobility, and when you have lived with roommates, you are living in and practicing a collaborative economy.
A collaborative economy is a state of mind.
In fact, it's based on consumption and on a way of life.
When you share a car, you're experiencing collaborative consumption.
You're offered a good, and rather than purchase it, you use it.
Doing so, you optimize resources.
When you live with roommates, you experience a collaborative way of life.
Rather than everyone having its own apartment, you share the same apartment, you share the kitchen, you share the living room, you take turns cleaning the apartment.
It's a collaborative way of life.
You share resources.
Coworking uses the same logic.
In a coworking space, you have workplaces, you have wi-fi connections, you have a photocopier for printing or scanning, a kitchen where you can make food.
In other words, everything you need to work together with other coworkers.
Coworking is a response to the economic crisis.
And the collaborative economy is too.
They are responses to a gloomy situation, to distrust, and suspicion.
How does this happen in a coworking space?
In a coworking space, you will look for and find the solution that works for you.
Most of the time, coworkers are freelancers.
There are several types of freelancers.
You can be a freelancer to the core and still need a certain regularity, and structure, but not necessarily ready to invest in very costly fixed structures.
So, you choose to go to a coworking space full time.
You have your office, you can get your own cabinet, and you have all the basic technological tools necessary to be able to carry out your work properly.
But maybe you don't feel like spending all your time in a coworking space, as you might have done somewhere else I might have done that in a previous life by working in an office.
That hasn't really convinced me, in fact.
So, in a coworking space, you can also choose to come to break up the loneliness of working at home a bit, to meet other people, to test your opinions against those of your coworkers.
You can come part time.
When people work freelance, they can end up in a situation where they are very busy, and have to move around a lot and they need solutions that are flexible.
In a coworking space you can choose to come for a full day, there are packs for four days, ten days.
At that moment, when you need it, you register in an online agenda, and you reserve your spot in the coworking space.
All of this can be varied over the long term or the short term.
And when you have found the right formula, what happens in a coworking space?
Theoretically, when you get there, it is to work.
OK, I swear to you that on some days, there's no way that anyone who goes to the Simplon 8 space in Martigny can tell whether, in the space, there are one, three, or eight people working there.
You could hear a pin drop.
The concentration level is at its peak.
It's like being in a library: everyone is focus on its work, and in fact, coworkers often tell me that it is the concentration of their neighbors that positively impacts them and enable them to finish their work and to move forward, without being distracted by all sort of things.
On other days, it's buzzing with activity, everybody talks, everybody exchange.
In a coworking space, you have an entire community of resources, of people who are complementary, who want to share, people who have talents and, at any given time, are very likely to make contact and exchange with each other.
These exchanges come in several different types.
In my coworking space, I have somebody who might one day be called to do an activity report on her work, on her small business.
To do the report properly, she decides do it in French and German.
She speaks German perfectly, no problem.
She prepares her activity report, and at the last moment she has second thought, "German isn't my native language, it would be nice if I could find someone to reread my report."
There's a translator in my coworking space.
This person will ask him to take a quick look at her project, to give her some feedback, to make a few corrections, if need be.
This translator hasn't been settled for very long, and for some times, he has begun to prepare the launch of his own website.
He fund a web designer who is working with him,
but it's not that simple.
Even if you find someone who can do it, you must provide the person with text and images, and he is experiencing just that.
At a certain point, he didn't know anymore and wondered, "What pictures should I use what can I put as tabs, what kind of themes are there?"
A web designer recently began to come regularly to the space.
Well, he won't build the site for the translator.
However, when he heard about the website's problems, he advised the translator.
He told him, "Pay attention, don't use too much text, make sure that each page is very easily accessible, that users know where they are in the site."
That advice is extremely valuable.
Since he's new, this web designer has just opened his box to set up his start-up.
When he's received some orders from clients, sometimes he gets a bit stuck with the graphics.
Because that's not his strong suit.
He prefers programming, working with the back end, but the graphics aren't what he's good at.
There aren't any graphic designers in my coworking space.
Despite this, he's tried asking other people: "Is there any chance you know a graphic artist who could help me?"
And I know a graphic designer who I work with regularly, and I've given him his address, and from then on, he works with this graphic designer.
And this graphic designer will maybe need a translation later.
And it continues that way, in all directions.
These aren't big jobs.
There is not exchange of money.
People are simply helping each other, "I'll help you one day, then you help someone else, and the next day that someone else will maybe help me in return."
It's a formula of mutual assistance.
It happens in a very informal way, almost every day.
One other form is bartering.
You all know what that is.
People who come to coworking spaces regularly are very often people who work in communication.
And when they write texts, it may be useful to have those texts reread.
I myself write texts.
In the company where I used to work official reviewers were paid to do that. Now I don't have anyone.
I have people to ask occasionally, but they are not always available.
There's another person in Simplon 8 who works in communications and writes.
And he regularly gets asked
to reread texts. It's a barter.
So, the translator, with his website up, says to himself:, "I need to do a Google Adwords campaign."
But he's never done one.
Social networks are not his thing.
All of a sudden, he talks about it, and realizes that there is a web communication specialist there.
Since the web specialist is very busy, she really won't be able to take the time from her professional work to do his AdWords campaign.
But, they've worked out a price, they come to an agreement and finally the translator hires the web communication specialist to make him a Google AdWords campaign.
Who are the people involved in coworking?
As I told you just now, mainly freelancers.
I've had the occasion, at the beginning of the year, to host a business manager.
He owned a small business with about 30 employees.
He came to see me because he wanted to sell me internet services.
So, he came over, and some other coworkers were there, we had something to drink together, and began to chat, and he found it really nice to have all these resources in the same place.
He happened to be in the process of getting a postgraduate degree, and he needed to write a publication.
He was a young father, he didn't have time at home to work on it in peace.
At his job, he was always preoccupied.
So, he decided to come to the Simplon 8 space to work on his publication.
He came, he took out a subscription of 4 flexible days, he came when he had time; it was very useful not to have to worry about anything else for four full days.
What's more, he made exchanges with the others.
I don't know if he sold his internet services, but it may be possible.
In addition, there may be directors, managers, who at any given time in their lives need to take a break from their relations with their company.
In a coworking space, relationships work horizontally.
There is no hierarchy, no vertical functionality.
There is no competition, or judgment.
That's a change for a business manager.
Imagine the pressure and tension of leading a whole team.
Who can you trust
when you have problems? No one.
It's a jungle.
And maybe there are a few people who dream of taking your place.
It's not easy.
In coworking, this problem doesn't exist.
He can come to work and exchange with the others, find solutions to his problems, get completely disinterested advice, and there's even an innovation specialist in our coworking space.
Well, I can tell you that he has already given some solutions to a number of people who have come there, whether they are coworkers, or clients, or just visitors.
And there are also people who use it as a home office.
If you live in Martigny, and you are required to work in Lausanne or in Geneva, perhaps, if you have an understanding boss, he will say, "OK, one day per week you can work from home."
So, you begin to work from home.
Except that you aren't used to working like a freelancer, you are not used to scheduling and disciplining yourself and this isn't easy.
In addition, the people around you, if you are at home think that you are available.
For kids, it's the same.
You are tempted to get food from the fridge.
Your house is full of temptations.
The solution might be, effectively, to work one day per week in a coworking space.
Obviously, this doesn't have to be in Brigue or in Bulpliz, because it would not solve anything.
But if you have one space near you, going there to work once a week is an excellent solution, to create a home office a bit farther away from home.
Now, I'd like us to have a bit of an experience.
I'd like to ask you to imagine that you just created your own event production company.
Your event company.
You work alone, and you decided to schedule part of that time in a coworking space.
Your coworkers are you.
Your other coworkers, also you.
Everyone you can find there.
At the end of the evening, the TED organizers come to tell you, "We know that you have an event company.
And we have too much stuff, our organization has gotten bogged down, we'd like you to organize the TED event for the next year."
You are very honored, you accept the offer, you discuss the conditions a bit.
You end up back at your coworking space and now you tell yourself, "How am I going to do this?"
First, the most important thing is to think of the basics.
So, this event, for example, has a theme, it's called Galaxy.
You say, "I'm going to need to find a theme,"
All alone in your corner, your little idea lab, it's still not easy.
Maybe within the team members here, there is someone who has a talent for animating events, and who would be capable of brainstorming.
Is there anyone capable of doing one, who has already done one?
I see a few fingers up in the back.
You'll be able to "brew" your ideas, and all kinds of other things.
The only person missing is the leader, but other people can send ideas.
I think that you will find some people who will agree to giving some of their time in order to help find a theme for the evening next year.
Now, you have the theme.
You still need to find speakers.
Based on the theme, you will reflect on who can come to speak next year.
Maybe among you there's someone.
I don't have the theme yet, you're the ones who, with your team, will see which theme to use.
Maybe among the coworkers, there are some people who might be able to help, who have abilities, resources, knowledge, whose experiences and lives you can benefit from.
But, if there's no one who can come to bring their abilities as a speaker, I'm sure that among you, there's someone who knows someone else, or who has heard of other people who might come and fill the role of TED speaker next year.
When you've done the brainstorming, you're helping each other out.
Now, you're in the network.
Everyone makes their own network work, and they find solutions.
Now you have the theme and the speakers, you now need to think about the practical things.
The location, that's good, you can do it here again.
But you will need to promote the event.
You'll need to make a program, to load the information online.
To put it online, you must have someone who can write text, you must have someone to do the graphics.
You understand how this works.
You're going to find someone for the communication and to put information online on the website.
You're going to find a printer, and I'm sure that if you cannot do this you know some people who can fill these needs.
Then, you'll need to pay a bit for the services, though.
I think that TED would have given you a budget.
You'll need to find partners, sponsors to finance the event.
But that's easy.
With all the people who are here, I'm sure that you have some connections with banks and insurance companies, with private parties who have money and are ready to back the event, who believe in TEDx.
So, that's good. You've got money,
the website, the information, Surely there are some things I've forgotten, but you'll think of them.
And now, there's one important thing left.
That's you, the audience.
How are you going to find the audience?
Well, you're going to use the network.
And this event will be exciting and memorable.
So, there you go.
That's the way that this can work in a coworking space.
There, you're in project management, but there could be all of configurations in terms of coworkers.
The most represented people in coworking spaces, as I've said, are people in communication, there are creatives, there are graphic designers,
At my space, as I've said, there's a translator, a web designer, a specialist in web communication.
And starting this week, there's a researcher who's interested in what's happening in Greece.
So, I can tell you that he has some work to do.
And it's open to all sorts of personalities.
We sometimes get the feeling that there is exclusively creatives working in coworking spaces, but I also have a finance specialist and you could imagine an accountant, a trustee, really the possibilities are endless.
And the people who come to a coworking space very often, have been informed about it in advance, they have already acquired the coworking values.
So, what are these values?
I've already told you about them informally.
The first of these values is durability.
There's a wifi connection, materials, and all these resources are actively made available to the coworkers.
The second value is community.
Community means all the people who work in a coworking space and this is what you try to create with other people, by trying to respond to their needs, by trying to respond to their expectations, by trying to respond to their values.
The third value is cooperation.
I think that you've understood.
I don't need to redo the demonstration.
That's good, you can cooperate in a coworking space.
The fourth value is openness.
You share experiences, and ideas, you enrich each other mutually, you believe and you make your business grow.
And finally, the last value is accessibility.
Working is fine.
But working where, when, how, and who I want to work with, that's possible with coworking.
These values make up the five pillars of the coworking base.
Once they're in place, they are the generators of creativity, innovation, sharing, exchanging, and quality.
I have told you before that coworking was born in 2005 in San Francisco.
In Switzerland, the first coworking center was opened in Lausanne.
It was "L'Eclau" which opened in 2008.
It was quickly followed by "The Muse" in Geneva which you have certainly heard about because it's a very dynamic place, that has got lots of coverage.
It's the standard for coworking in Switzerland, and since 2009, it's already hosted more than 400 coworkers.
Later, there were other centers that opened, in Lausanne, in Freiburg, in Montreux, in Neuchâtel, in Geneva too.
The Simplon 8 space, that I founded a year ago, is the first, and to my knowledge, the only coworking center in Valais.
But, through the network, I've heard it said, that there's a center being prepared in Sierre, that there was another being prepared in Colombais, and that there's a center in preparation in Sion.
So, if you're convinced by coworking, don't wait any longer.
Do it, get involved, experience it.
(Applause)
Harmony, I wished I've had some!
But my start in life was in total chaos!
I am born in Paris from a Congolese father, a dancer, and my mother was one of his student at La Rochelle. The story goes that my mother went into labour in a dance studio.
Female dancers and musicians accompanied her to the hospital.
I am supposed to be born to the rhythm of african drums.
One year after my birth, my father kidnapped me, and sent me to Congo - which was called Zaïre back then - to be raised by his parents so that I do not grow like a white man.
At six years old, I came back to Paris.
I did not know anything about France, neither the language, nor the climate, not even my mother who I found again when I was eleven years old.
My father, a bohemian without any fixed lover, carried me around to the rhythm of his conquests: Paris 5th, Saint-Denis, Paris 15th, la Martinique, Paris 20th!
So, in those circumstances, school wasn't my strong suit.
According to my high school, I was not stupid enough to undertake a vocational training, and not intelligent enough to attend a general high school.
So I was going to attend
a "STI" Electrical Engineering!
Even today, I still do not know what it means!
Actually, I failed my High School diploma twice, losing out to a three-phase asynchronous generator!
It's also called a "forklift"!
(Laughter) What a fancy programme!
It didn't bother me very much not to get my High School Diploma.
What bothered me though, was to have to continue studying.
But a question bothered me even more back then, and it was: "Where are you from?" ...
"- Well ... From Paris!
- No, I mean, really!
- Aaah! You are talking about
my gorgeous ebony skin!
From my Congolese father.

- Ah, that's it! You are Congolese!"
Faced by such a chaos where people take decision about my future and my identity, I decided to take my life into my own hands.
It might be chaos, but at least, it would be my chaos.
So when I was 27 year old, I went back to Congo to meet my grandmother.
Meeting back with Congo didn't go very well.
In France, I was nicknamed: "Muesli".
In Congo, my nickname was: "Rémi", my second surname, because in Congo, only saints mentioned on the calendar are acceptable.
There was no place for me in Congo either.
So, I hit the road!
... For a road trip through ten countries in Africa.
That's the one time being black was an advantage!
Central African Republic, Cameroon, Nigeria, Benin, Togo, Ghana, Ivory Coast, Mali and Senegal.
In Senegal, the visit of Goree Island was a shock.
Under the mock-ups of ships - slave ships - was mentioned the ship's home ports and shipbuilding:
"La Rochelle," my mother's hometown.
It means that I come from both a slave and a slaveholder... My identity is a total chaos.
So how do I live with this chaos?
First, by assuming my own body, because without body there is no life.
Besides, this body enabled me to travel across all these countries, on foot, by bus, by canoe... My body is my first identity.
In Africa, there are spotters everewhere!
Here, we can make the distinction between a Norwegian and a Portuguese. Over there, people can recognize a Senegalese from a Congolese.
In all of these countries, I am the foreigner,
or, in the best case, a black from Ethiopia,
who is never dark enough!
It is a mental and physical challenge to travel alone across countries.
So, you have to be strong, and transform your body into a machine.
For me, that involves dancing, running, crossfit, and yoga.
In October 2012, I came back to France after my trip to Senegal, strongly committed to go back to school.
But... I also committed not to shave until I got a degree, either my beard, or my hair! (Laughter) As if I did not have enough troubles!
Like this!
And like this!
(Laughter) I do not have my High School Diploma but I have always been committed.
I have... been active in associations, and in youth political movements.
I even got to work for the Paris City Hall with elected representatives, by omitting to mention on my resume my lack of diploma.
Associative commitment was my school, my popular education because school is not the only place to get education.
All I was lacking was a diploma.
So next objective: to get my experience validated to be able to start a Master in Political Sciences at La Sorbonne, Paris I.
Through this, I wanted to change the negative image I had about myself, and disavow the prophecy of my Latin teacher in 7th grade, who hmmm... who told me that I would end up like my brothers who are dressed in green in the city of Paris, meaning, a garbage collector.
I do not have my High School Diploma. But since November 23, 2016, I have a Master's degree in Political Sciences.
(Applause) Civic engagement has been a great school for me.
It helped me to get a diploma, and it empowered me to learn, to give and to act, all at the same time.
For me, it means working with young people from popular neighbourhoods and rural areas.
Bringing to light and set in motion young people from cities and rural areas through gathering, vocational training, and condemning injustice, was the trigger
that determined my vocation. I became community organizer,
organizing the disorganized!
(Laughter) I started this job in 2013, in an association called: "Passeport Avenir", which fight for equality in opportunities.
There, I created a community of future business leaders.
These young people who are involved... in social movements, are fighting for equality in opportunities and to stop discrimination. They are a group of young people showing the way to success to others.
In three years, more than 153 young people joined the community "Different Leaders".
Together, they organized more than 55 events: a "Tour de France" for self-affirmation, a "World Equality in Opportunities Day" - the foundation of a "World Equality in Opportunities Day" - in Britain, Germany, USA,
in France and in Morocco.
But...
what about harmony? I hadn't found it yet despite this experience
that was wonderful.
So, I decided to go back to my real profession: dance and instill in it all my experiences that kept me away from it, through an association called "Loba" that I co-founded with a friend, William, in 2008.
We are both dancers. He is a hip-hop dancer, and I dance Congolese dance. We wanted to engage in "artivism", an art with a mission and dance works that promote citizen action.
The association and art enable us to reach a large audience, and to have an open dialogue, where differences are tamed away.
The Loba association provides dance classes, trains and produces a rap group called "SRB". SRB's leader, Bruno, designs events dedicated to the mix of various public together and the discovery of other cultures, through music, dance, and graphic arts.
For us, Loba is art at the service of the city.
Because our art should express what we have in our heart.
Dance!
Dance to communicate!
Communicate to live!
Eventually, I have learned how to live with myself, with others, and with my surrounding.
The traditional Congolese dance is my... my passion to live, my resilience.
I have found myself in it.
I express myself in it.
It allows me to create a dialogue.
It is my mother language.
At last, I understood that... my life will never be... will never be a chaos anymore. It will be a harmonious chaos. And from my life, I'll forge my art.
(African drum) (Clapping in rhythm) (African drum, whistle, clapping in rhythm) Haaa..... Yoh!
(Applause) (African drum roll) (African drum and whistle)
Eh! Hey!
(Clapping in rhythm) Eh!
Oh!
Dance with me!
(Clapping in rhythm) I have a mojo about my passion of life, a short slogan that says: "Transform your body into a machine, your brain into a weapon, your heart into an art, and your life into an art work."
Thank you very much!
(Applause)
Hello everyone, my name is Dorian Di Betta, but for a full school year I was known as "Professor D," "D" for Dorian, and this is this story I'm going to tell you this afternoon.
What was the last time you texted?
(Laughting) Not very long ago, I guess.
And when did you last write a postcard?
Oh boy! Perhaps it was during
your last vacancy or even earlier.
And when did you last send a love note?
Ouh!
(Laughing) Yeah ... You might never have done so actually.
So I’m going to talk about that. I’m going to talk about the importance of writing to one another for real, with a real pen, and the importance of doing things for real in the real world, not in the digital world.
I'm going to show you that doing things in the real world generates much more sensations eventually.
What are you going to get from all this at the end of the talk?
Well, I think first the way you perceive a postcard is going to change, and then that it might simply bring you love.
My entire story started from a misunderstanding!
Do you know the grapevine concept?
The grapevine is actually a social network but 100% real and 0% digital.
The grapevine's initial message came from a lady, Patricia, unknown to me, who is a teacher working in the Parisian suburbs.
So one day she said to her students, "I am looking for pictures of monuments."
One of her students repeated that to his mom; his mom repeated it to my wife; and my wife repeated it to me.
And what I understood at the end of the line is "I'm looking for someone who travels a lot who could send me postcards from all over the world."
And there you have it, that's how I got involved in what Patricia called later "the postcard project."
So every time I traveled, about once a month, I'd send a postcard to this elementary school class I didn’t know.
And to add a little mystery, I'd sign them "Professor D."
Now why did I embark upon such a thing?
I think the explanation goes back a long way.
When I was 13, I had a pen-pal from Reunion Island, and we wrote to one another for 15 years.
It was like writing in a diary that would reply to me.
It was ... wonderful!
Then I got married.
I obtained a job as an auditor,
and did that for four years.
For four years, I traveled all over the world doing audits.
On each trip, I'd send a postcard to Sylvie, my wife,
and on each card, well, I'd wrote a love poem.
Eventually, I sent more than 50 postcards!
And Sylvie has kept them all, as I’m going to show you. They are all in a big envelope like this.
And believe me, Sylvie is in the habit of throwing absolutely everything away!
But unlike emails or texts, postcards can be collected.
Now have you ever received a love note?
A love note, you know, is something you never forget.
And it can change a life.
I think we would all like to receive a love note.
I even believe we should all, at least once in our lives, write a love note.
So I'd like to read you one of the cards I sent to Sylvie, my wife.
It is this one.
I was in India in Hyderabad.
It was in November 2005.
So Hyderabad, like all big Indian cities, is always noisy, extremely noisy, with sounds of horns especially, day and night!
It’s a love poem, let me read it to you.
"Dear Sylvie, Smiling and elegant, Like this country so different, You would be less spicy, If India you were to be.
With charming thoughts from a country of extremes, Your husband ... who loves you."
(Applause) (Laughing) Thank you.
So, in fact, I've never sent any of my postcards in an envelop.
So everyone can read them, the postman or others.
And I'm thinking first "It might give them some inspiration," (Laughter) and then, "There is nothing ridiculous about writing love notes ..."
But let's get back to the postcards I sent to Patricia and her pupils.
I sent my first postcard about two years ago.
I was in Sweden, in Stockholm.
I was holding my postcard and my pen thinking, "What am I going to write to them?"
Indeed, I didn’t know them.
I knew the children were about 9 to 10 years old. I didn’t know Patricia either. I needed a message that could please both of them, a trans-generational message.
So I decided to talk about the schools of the country I was in.
In my opinion, schools are a sign of the good or bad health of a country.
A school is a place, a landmark, in that a whole generation is going to find its place in society.
So I interviewed people in situ.
I asked them questions about schooling in their country.
And really, in the whole world, people have always been very happy to talk about their country, their culture and their schools.
That's how I learned, for example, that in Sweden, in winter, children go outside for recess in temperatures up to -15 °C.
At the end of the project, I wondered whether everything I had learned from meeting locals in situ, could have been easily found at home on the internet.
So for example, I could not find the story of the school recesses at -15 °C.
I'm not saying it's not there; it may be on a blog in Sweden, I don't know, but I didn't find it.
Another example is in the Czech Republic, students have 45 minutes of class and then a 15-minute break - 45 minutes, 15 minutes -
which seems to be a very interesting idea.
I didn’t find it on the internet too.
As a matter of fact, Patricia applies this system of recess every 45 minutes with her pupils, more or less.
Now you see this postcard here, this is not a simple postcard for me.
For me, this is an extraordinary educational tool.
But why?
Because postcards appeal to several of our senses, and we know that they promote learning.
For example, when Patricia receives the postcard, she reads it aloud to her class, so this appeals to the sense of hearing,
Then the card is manipulated.
It goes from hand to hand in the classroom which appeals to the sense of touch.
Then it is displayed on a world map which appeals to the sense of sight.
And I’d even add a fourth sense: the sense of smell - I can assure you the postcard has a smell.
Ultimately, the students learned a lot both in geography and about school abroad.
As of my part, I created a kind of connection with them, even if I didn’t know them.
I think it’s also the reason why this project was a success.
What also motivated me in this project was that it restored the value of handwritten correspondence.
In my view, a postcard is a beautiful object, somehow obsolete and rare which gives it even more value.
I always chose the postcards with care.
I wanted them to be the symbolic representation of the place I was in, such as the Jemaa El-Fna square in Marrakesh, or Gouda cheese in Gouda and ponies in the Shetlands ... I always tried to write well, although I know the children sometimes had to try hard to decipher my writing.
Actually, postcards do require an effort.
It’s not something easy.
It requires a kind of commitment.
This is why I see postcards as an extraordinary educational tool.
In addition, can you imagine the journey of a postcard?
Sent from far away, a postcard crosses the time zones, different countries, different landmasses, seas, several oceans, several continents.
A postcard is exhausted when it arrives.
The ink has run a little; the stamp is a little bent.
It’s a little wrinkled.
It bears the scars of this long journey.
Postcards represent many realities but also plenty of dreams, of imagination.
They are the combination of dream and reality.
Maybe that is the meaning of poetry.
This same poetry is not found in SMS or emails.
Now I really wanted to show you this card I sent from the Shetland Islands.
(Giggling) As I told you, it’s symbolic.
Indeed for me this card symbolizes hope.
It's the symbol of hope for all those who feel lost.

Why? Well, actually, this card was lost.
It was posted way up in the North of Scotland
and ended up in the Philippines, 10,000 km from there.
Look there is a Philippine’s stamp on it.
So I imagine that the postman in the Philippines thought, "What is this card doing here?
Its destination is France, it's lost!”
So he did everything to bring it back on its track. He stuck a label on it, drew these lines, I don’t know what they’re for. But in any case, after three months, the card found its way back to France.
Further more, I like what I wrote on this postcard because there is an idea about school hours that I like a lot,
Let me read it for you.
"In winter, days are very short and that's why children go to school later and leave earlier."
I think it's a good idea to adapt the timetable according to seasons.
I wrote another beautiful phrase.
It's important to note that it was my last postcard.
So it's a general comment about travelling.
And I believe it's important for children but also for all of us.
So let me read it to you.
"Here is my last postcard.
I hope I have given you the desire to travel because travelling makes you grow and opens your mind."
Travelling makes you grow and opens your mind ...
It’s strange but neither Patricia nor her students ever doubted what I wrote on the postcards.
Really, it was as if all the information I had gathered, while asking local people in situ and meeting them for real, was necessarily the truth.
Anyway, with this project, I really hope to have shown those children the meaning of tolerance, especially with this postcard I sent from Israel, which is a message of hope for peace and tolerance.
Let me read it to you.

"Hello! I am writing to you from Israel.
Here, in middle school, Jews must learn Arabic and Arabs must learn Hebrew.
It is mandatory.
We hope for peace.”
So travelling is really worthwhile because, in the digital world, we don't experience all these emotions.
Even webcams etc. do not provide such emotions.
I am convinced that it's essential to meet each other for real, to talk to each other for real, to listen to each other for real, and to really get along - in short, really love, not just "like” on the web.
Otherwise, we might miss out a marvelous encounter or an innovative idea.
You certainly remember that, at the start, I spoke about the cards I sent to Sylvie, the love poems, and I hope that you appreciate now the value of handwritten correspondence.
So I’d like us to do an experiment, here this afternoon, all together.
I'd like us to commit to writing a postcard to a person we love and to writing love words on this postcard or, if it’s too difficult, just kind words or compliments.
So, who is ready to send
this postcard? Raise your hand.

Wow, excellent!
Now let's keep our hands raised and then sign this commitment!
Please sign!
Perfect!
So now you shall buy a postcard, write it by hand with a pen, and most importantly and maybe the hardest, send it!
And you'll see, it's something very different than an SMS!
Thank you.
(Applause)
To discover is to take off your layers.
So I'm going to tell you how one day we came to travel wearing nothing at all and what my travels taught us.
This started in 2005, at that time I was a student in an engineering school at Toulouse named INSA.
My parents lived in Grenoble and for me it was a bit hard to get by financially, so, one day I took a chance and I went hitch-hiking.
That bit of help was going to to change my life.
1,200 km round trip.
I realized I had stepped in a universe that is much more than just an economical means of transportation.
I was meeting the world from the passenger's seat.
Adventures ensued and for my part I felt filled with a sense of liberty where everything was possible.
I remembered one day, I got caught by the pilot of an aerobatic plane that proposed taking me on my first flight over the coast of Wales during a sunset.

Amazing! And it was only starting.
In 2008, I had my engineering diploma in the bag, and at that moment, it was clear to me, I felt very attracted to "detachment" so I felt like continuing the experience.
I got to America hitch-hiking and stayed with a local friend.
This began with 60 days at sea, hitch-hiking on sailboats, and when we got to the Caribbean Islands, our savings were running out and vanished into thin air when we crossed Central America, from Colombia to Mexico.
So, there, we were happy to discover hospitality services CouchSurfing, staying at local's homes.
Once at the U.S. border, we didn't have any money left.
Chance, luck, serendipity, I don't know.
The fact is that we met a young girl from California that invited us to come-work at her farm.
And it didn't matter what farm, a farm that grew medicinal cannabis.
(Laughter) We would be paid considerably well. (Laughter) And we had just spent three months in Central America penniless so we enjoyed life a bit, and embarrassed ourselves a bit, but the question arose very quickly of whether to stay in El Dorado or continue on our way.
That took long.
We hesitated for two weeks and I think that, unconsciously, we continued because the abundance we were looking for wasn't going to be there.
So we kept going and, incidentally, just after this profitable experience, we decided to give another step closer to our effort in self-detachment,
this time traveling without money.
&gt;From Montreal to Halifax, moneyless, in plain winter, under 40°C, and, what's more, we would also take the challenge of not using the Internet to ask people for lodging.
Only by knocking doors.
The experience was fantastic, so great that, upon returning to France a year and a half later, my friend and I started to write a book that will be published by Lonely Planet as "The Bible of the Great Traveller"
And after we finished writing it, I spent nine months in my room. I was a bit fed up so I called a friend, Mouts, and I said to him, "Listen, let's go on a trip but, this time, in France.
The idea is to relive the sense of adventure we lived abroad, but here at home in our land."
Mouts was thrilled and said,
"Yes, I'd love to.
But we need a challenge."
So, what would we be allowed to do?
Well, we suggested traveling without bags.
"Sure, yeah, OK."
So we started warming up.
He replied, "OK, but traveling without money."
"Yeah. OK."

And then, like that, Mouts suggests, "Would we leave without clothes?"
"Yeah, cool!"
At that moment, we were totally bluffing,
Two months later, we'd be riding the Drôme river in the nude. (Laughter) So we met one last time, and asked ourselves "What are we doing here?"
And then we jumped in.
I'll confess that it was very hard for my mother. She said to me, "Oh sweetie, why do you get into these situations like this?
Where did I go wrong?"
So we took a little waterproof bag and put a cell phone in it, for emergencies, to reassure her.
And a driver's license.
Because our dream was to leave Drôme to arrive in Paris in a red convertible and go to the club dressed in tuxedos.
A little dream for our coming quarantine.
And then another item. We took a knife to honor the French expression, "with only the bare essentials".
(Laughter) (Applause) And, finally, we took a little photo camera with us to record what we would experiment.
So I'll give you the details to this experience but know that, when we arrived, after five days, we were excited from what we had just gone through, and we made a little film.
An amateur film because we had no experience at all,
a three-minute clip, we stayed up all night making it.
The next morning, we sent it to a production house, and, well, weeks went by, and we were invited to Paris by the Bonne Pioche production company.
That went well.
Three months later, we were on France 5 with them, dressed in bushes.
The adventure had kicked off.
We were going to produce 52-minute long documentary films about our adventures.
So it was a double challenge.
Although we were taking along co-director, Charlène Gravel, we had no experience in the field.
The challenge was traveling in the nude to make our dreams come true but also of traveling in the nude to make films.
There was no scenario.
We had but a point of departure, and then the destination was our dream, a dream from childhood.
It could be making a snowman on top of a mountain,
or meeting a druid in Britain,
drinking tea with a Lord in Great Britain.
We've fulfilled 16 of those in total.
Of course, the dreams are always excuses.
Excuses to leave our comfort zones.
Finally, Nus &amp; Culottés was born a great laboratory of adventures, we turned ourselves into researchers of the unexpected.
So I'm going to present a few research results because the little engineer in me still comes out once in a while.
After 12,000 km of hitch-hiking After 200 vehicles, we rode on car, boat, cargo, plane, and even helicopter.
What's magical about hitch hiking is that it's serendipity's mode of transportation by excellence.
You never know what you'll run into.
It's chance in the end, and the dice are a bit loaded, so it's not exactly chance.
I noticed that, as a man, I had two chances in three of being picked up by a man that often picked up hitch-hikers.
If it was a woman that took me, there were two chances in three that she worked either in education or in healthcare,
careers in which one tends to help others and where there is less fear.
At times I had fun asking the women that gave me a lift, "Are you a school teacher?"
"How do you know?"
(Laughter) So if it's me going directly to people, it's an active effort, and that's different.
We're going to have the time to talk, to feel, to explain ourselves.
If, for example, I go into a gas station where, often, someone hasn't ever helped a hitch-hiker but are going to dare for the first time,
there, we broaden our possibilities for encounters.
And that's where it becomes truly interesting for us with the condition of not choosing ourselves.
Because, unconsciously, we head towards what's reassuring, what we know.
I recall one night with Mouts looking for lodging and that night I had plenty of energy so I was asking people.
And then, after five minutes, Mouts looks at me and says, "But Nans, why don't you ask the women over there?"
(Laughter) What is precisely interesting about the act of traveling nude is that you don't really have the luxury of choosing.
Leaving the woods, you are very vulnerable. You're hungry and thirsty. Your feet ache. You're tired and it's the journey that decides for you.
That's what is interesting because it's a potential for encounters and extraordinarily variable.
And maybe you won't find the same people that we'd find outside of the woods.
Why is that interesting?
Simply put, when you're invited into someone's place, you're going to be listening, open, and understanding and that extraordinary alchemy will take place and allow you to meet other worlds.
That moment there is important to me.
It's true that it's frighting.
Those cultural differences aren't obvious.
At times, we slept at assassins' homes.
It was awkward and, nonetheless, as the guests, we still tried to understand one another.
And that's scary to us, but also to them, to see it happen like that - two wild men arriving - and that's where a game is set up, consisting of walking through layers of fear to reach into the other person's inner kindness and trust necessary to continue the encounter.
Every time that happened, it was a victory for us.
Overall, in four years, we've been housed 220 times by a resident and spent only five nights outdoors.
Why five nights outdoors?
Well, when you speak to people you realize that they're not necessarily available. They don't necessarily want to spend a night with two strangers but, for us, if we manage to understand one another and speak, that is usually a very rich experience.
That goes far beyond staying at a local home.
So we were deeply moved during these trips by the availability that people showed us.
At times they were in the middle of a wedding dinner and invited us to the table.
They showed us a trust that was also out of the ordinary.
I asked myself if I'd be able to trust strangers like this.
A woman one day in the street offered us her keys and told us, "Here, take my keys.
Get settled at my place. I'll be back tonight."
It was in Paris.
(Laughter) So we received a lot during the trips, Received so much that one day we asked ourselves, "But what are we giving them?"
So we started a little ritual at the end of each encounter where we put together a present.
Of course, with the means at hand because we didn't have money.
It could be origami, a song, providing a service, washing the dishes, cleaning, trimming a hedge.
And after a while, we realized that those presents had another function, they were also there to honor the encounter and to introduce gratefulness into what was taking place with the people because it's true that, after a while, you can fall into a sort of routine, of habit and that kills the wonder.
There were good times, of course, and then there were terrible times.
I remember sleeping in the trash one day, and in a granary with dead pigeons, we tried to find a place between their carcasses.
Times of doubt where you lost all hope.
Eventually, when we got to the end of the trip, we realized that each one of those experiences was necessary to make our dream come true.
The highs and the lows.
The hard thing was acknowledging them when we experienced them.
So we had a little technique. It was Mouts that started it, every time we went through a difficult time, we asked the question, "What did we learn?"
There are always things to learn!
Our way of making a request, our way of introducing ourselves,
letting go, detaching.
In fact, we quickly noticed that we were mad scientists.
We were passionate about learning, discovering, pushing the limits.
We even made obstacles for ourselves.
One day, we went on an entire trip barefoot refusing shoes.
Another day, a trip as vegetarians
and let's not get into finding food that way...
Another day, without making requests.
And then, one day, an entire afternoon hitch-hiking without talking.
We were crazy and we were passionate about discovery.
That was our laboratory and that laboratory has its limits.
It's two of us, so it's reassuring, we are never in the dark.
We have cameras, but that doesn't help with the encounters. Actually, sometimes it's more of a burden, but, for us, it's a sacred source of motivation, a sacred source of gratefulness as well. So, that way, it's never really a total unknown, but, nonetheless, we chose these limitations because it allowed us to share these seeds.
And speaking of seeds, I'd like to finish with a little anecdote.
This happened on the first day with Mouts when we left completely naked with the cameras.
We were very scared because that night it would reach 0°C by night.
So if we wanted to spend the night outside fire wouldn't be an option at all.
So we learned a little friction technique using two wooden sticks and we practiced and practiced, all day we rubbed our pieces of wood and then at a certain point the sun went down and the temperature did, too, and still no fire.
We say to ourselves, "Disaster!
We'll need to find something else.
If we don't have fire, we need isolation."
And at that moment, we looked around, we were in the middle of the forest. There's not much there in April but we started to instinctively scrub a boulder for a bit of moss.
After five minutes, Mouts calls me yelling, "Nans, look what I found."
A lighter.
(Laughter) We had just experienced a miracle.
It was very, very mysterious and it was so mysterious that we decided to keep it a secret, we told ourselves no one would believe us.
So we pretended to light the fire with the two pieces of wood.
Magic - there was a bit of that during our trips.
And today I'm here with you, above all, to testify about a magic of a different sort.
It was, above all, the magic of encounters.
The strangers that would welcome us and that would open their worlds and that opened their doors for us, and that taught us about real nakedness, the nakedness of the heart, that which allows men to live together in their diversity, to learn to know one another, to understand one another, and maybe to love one another.
So I would love to pay them tribute tonight for their courage and also for transmitting all this beauty to us.
(Video) Nans: It's enough if you insulate yourself with 1.5m of straw.
(Music) We were just arrested by the police and well, we had everything in order.
Mouts: We're here! We rejoin civilization.
Woman: My God, Maryline, they left entirely nude.
M: It's nice all of a sudden when one dresses.
In exchange, we have a mini-present.
F: That's nice of you. Thanks.
Woman: Going with!
M: Let's hit the road, rookie! And we have
a little present for you anyway.
Well it's symbolic, it's the sun.
Man: I call those anchorings I cherish them deeply.
M: Does that make you want to come with us?
So we'll exchange, we have a little gift for you.
A spoon for dad.
N: Yes, it's the human relationship that we want to bring back
to not stay with artificial relationships with the people that you come across, too,
to get a glimpse of what the think. (Music)
We were ambushed
in the house of happiness.
[Thank you] (Music) [From scratch to the dream] (Applause)
Whenever anyone asks me what I do, I often say that I work on facial expressions.
Well, that's the official story.
I actually work on smiles.
This work has lasted for 8 years already.
Can you hear my accent?
I am Polish.
I can tell you that smiling is not the done thing in Poland.
(Laughter) When I was 18, I wanted to be a translator.
My Mum wanted me to study law, to become a doctor.
And so, I am a doctor of smiles.
(Laughter) Smiles are facial expressions which are astonishing and extraordinary.
It's an expression which we share with many species.
Dogs, monkeys, foxes all have facial expressions that are similar to human smiles.
And us humans, we are definitely made to smile.
We smiled before we were born, and shortly after birth, and then all over the world.
A smile is the most common and most universal facial expression.
So even for evil people, even for terrorists, and for the most isolated tribes, smiling is a positive thing.
But it's something different that encouraged me to research smiles.
One day, an American researcher received a call from a Russian journalist.
He asked her some questions about her research because he is a psychologist, and he realized that she is American.
"Ah, but you are American?"
"You must know that all smiles in the USA are false but they are genuine in France."
(Laughter) Yes.
This Russian journalist's opinion is just one example of the misconceptions linked to smiling.
The smile is the most universal facial expression, but it is also the most misinterpreted.
Think about everything which can be expressed with a smile: joy, satisfaction, love, but also sorrow, embarrassment, pity, and, of course, our smile can hide our emotions, as an old operetta says, "A heart in pain always smiles".
For the person who sees a smile, it is not always possible to understand its meaning.
And it becomes more complicated when we meet foreign people, because, depending on the country and the culture, smiles change and don't communicate the same meaning.
What I'm interested in is how people smile at strangers in different cultures.
Imagine you are buying your ticket for the bus or the subway.
Would you smile at the person on reception?
Of course, it depends on the person.
You are probably more likely to smile at someone who seems nice and attractive than at someone who is unpleasant.
But it also depends on the country.
So, if you are in London and you smile at a shop clerk, you will probably give the impression that you are polite and well-mannered.
It wouldn't be the same if you were in Warsaw or in Moscow.
In those places, your smile would make people feel uncomfortable.
There are even sayings for it.
In Polish, for example, we say, "Smiling like an idiot at his cheese."
(Laughter) I cannot tell you where the cheese comes from, but it's quite clear that it's not a compliment.
In Russia, it's even clearer, "Only idiots smile for no reason."
I have a French friend who lived in Moscow who noticed that this is not just an expression.
In Russia, it's still frowned upon to smile at people on the street, and after living there for 4 years, she got out of the habit of smiling at people she didn't know.
So, in Russia, you don't smile to avoid
making yourself look like an idiot.
However, Russians do smile a lot when they are with their family, or in small groups.
Then they smile because they feel cared for, because they are happy.
If you compare this with countries like the UK or the USA, for an Anglo-Saxon it's more natural to smile at people they have just met.
A smile doesn't necessarily mean that you feel happy.
Rather, it means, "I will do you no harm.
I want everything to go well between us."
So, if there's a misunderstanding as a result of a smile, it is because, in different countries, we smile "differently".
What's the reason for these differences?
That's a rather difficult question because smiles are influenced by several factors.
In France, smiling was encouraged during the Age of Enlightenment, but in communist countries, smiling was frowned upon.
If someone smiled too much, people would be suspicious because life was not that easy.
So if someone smiled, it meant that either they had money, or they were an enemy of the state.
In Japan, for example, society encourages smiling in order to hide your emotions.
We asked ourselves whether there is in fact a general trend which explains why in some countries, people will smile more at strangers.
We think that it's influenced by history.
Let me explain.
Some countries are made up of a mixture of people from different countries and from different cultures.
In Australia, for example, only 2% of the population have ancestors who lived in Australia in 1500.
All these immigrants who didn't know each other, had nothing to help them understand each other,
so they had to use their faces and smile in order to communicate their good intentions to others.
Historically, it was necessary for Australians to smile in order to make social connections.
Now, if we take Poland, a country that I know well, there hasn't been a lot of immigration in the past 500 years.
The people who live there primarily descend from people who have lived in the same place for several centuries.
Because their ancestors were able to clearly communicate their intentions thanks to a common language, there is less need for them to openly show their emotions.
We think that this historic immigration, these "cultural movements" of the past, have had an influence on the way in which we smile today.
In order to further explore these cultural movements, I have to tell you about two researchers from Brown University in the USA.
Several years ago Louis Putterman and David Weil identified the number of source countries for every country around the world.
For example, the USA has 83 source countries.
That's the record.
You can see on the map; the lighter it is,
the more source countries it has.
In other words, in the United States, immigrants from 83 different countries contributed to the American population between 1500 and 2000.
Overall, the American continent has more source countries than Europe.
Japan is at the other end of the scale with one source country.
Germany has seven.
The Netherlands has 28.
That's not bad for Europe.
If I tell you that Poland has three source countries, how many do you think France has?

Go on. A little louder.
Ten?
You're not far off. It has eleven.

So not that diverse.
The more source countries a country has, the more diverse it was in the past.
So using the number of source countries, we have an indicator of cultural movements in the past.
But how can this be linked to smiles?
First, it's necessary to look at emotional expression in general.
Imagine that you are in a café with your father and you are angry with him.
Do you think you would show your anger? Do you think you'd show it a little bit, not show it at all, or maybe just keep quiet, and smile through the anger?
We asked more than 5,000 people this question in 32 different countries.
We found that in more diverse countries, which have more source countries, people think that they have to express their anger more so than the people in countries that have fewer source countries.
Basically, that means that Russians, with five source countries, are less expressive than Americans.
We asked this question of different people using different situations.
So the father situation was just an example.
Each time, we arrived at the same conclusion: in the more diverse countries people think that it is more appropriate to openly express their emotions.
But returning more specifically to smiles,
and why we feel the need to smile.
In the same research, we asked people from nine different countries, which included France, Japan, the USA, Australia, and Israel, what constitutes a good reason to smile in their countries?
There were no big surprises.
In each country, people think that we smile because we feel happy.
Everyone agreed on that.
But in the more diverse countries, which have more source countries, like, for example, Australia or the USA, people think we also smile to be nice.
This tendency is a little less common in countries with fewer source countries, like Japan, for example.
So, the next time an American civil servant smiles at you, it is not necessarily a false smile.
It is also not necessarily because the civil servant is really happy.
It is just because they want to be nice and that they grew up in an historically diverse culture which encourages this type of smiling at strangers.
The way in which we smile is influenced by our country, by its "cultural movements", immigration in the past which formed the culture in our country.
But, is it possible to influence the way in which we smile today?
Yes, I assure you.
Our research shows that the frequency of movement has a very similar effect as the number of source countries.
In other words, the more people move in any given country, the more expressive they are and the more they smile.
That is to say that moving, and probably traveling as well, can encourage us to smile in order to establish a trusting relationship with people that we don't know.
So does that mean that people in less diverse countries, like France and Poland, for example, are less welcoming and that they have to learn to smile more often?

Absolutely not. That would be too simple.
The message that I would like to leave you with today, is that smiles are a bit like languages.
No single language is better than the others and it can be difficult to understand a foreign language without studying it, especially Polish.
Think about that the next time that you see a smile, or the lack of a smile, which seems false to you.
It is up to you to choose whether to think that the smile is false or to make the effort to understand it.
Thank you.
(Applause)
When I was a child, I was literally overwhelmed by my emotions.
I lived with emotions constantly. They filled my days, my dreams.
A single look could make me happy, but a word could hurt me forever.
And it's true, I cried often.
Sadly, what allowed me to perceive this world around me, I saw as a weakness when I saw it reflected in others.
Because of my Italian roots, a little boy must not cry, especially as he grows up.
At age five, the little boy must toughen up, following in his father's footsteps at the judo club.
It's an ordeal every time.
I remember this sailing trip, quite a tough one in gale-mind weather, with a friend reading me Baudelaire poetry, while I was managing a somehow critical situation.
An incredible memory of flow between pure performance, his poetry and emotions.
It wasn't concious, but I conformed to what our society expects.
To survive.
This emotional weakness, I learned to hide from others.
I built my shell to keep confidence.
What a weird world!
I became a real machine, especially in difficult, complex environments I particularly appreciate, even extreme.
I am able to show no emotion to go towards the goal.
I can even be hard with the people around me and those who show weakness.
In 2002, with several partners, we created a company that makes confinements, temporary structures like this one.
Awesome!
We force respect in the industry, and I want my company to be humane, ready to help.
But we created a kind of modern monster, steeped in procedures, ISO systems, with this crazy race towards performance.
Chaos, harmony, everyday trust is fragile, uncertain.
The collaborators are loyal, but weary, tired.
We will even go as far as clash.
A few years before, I met a rather extraordinary person.
His name is Eric Barone.
He is a world champion in speed and downhill mountain biking.
We work together on aerodynamics to break world speed records, like this one in 2000: 222 km per hour on snow.
In 2002, he aims for a new record, on solid ground, this time.
And he makes it.
Still relevant today: 172 km / h.
But at what cost?
When he passed in front of the cells, the race for pure performance almost cost him his life.
We both rebuilt ourselves and we met again in 2013, to work once more on the race for the record.
Montesquieu said: "To succeed in the world, you must look crazy and be wise."
Our project is simple: beat this world record, with work, a lot of work.
In late March 2015, the conditions were difficult, but the world record fell.
Eric sets 223 km / h on snow.
An extraordinary success, an incredible personal satisfaction.
What a relief after all this work!
But what frustration!
Just one small km / h!
We are still in pure performance.
It's difficult because we are worn, exhausted by the tension, the pressure.
When the record was announced, I am on the walkie-takie, at the top
and I collapsed for 30 minutes, inconsolable.
It's a real emotional shock.
Actually, a door opens again to a new world, I would say.
Something we are going to exploit.
We will use it the following year.
We decide to have artists and technicians collaborate, at night, at the full moon, without artificial light.
We must use all our senses to connect to each other and allow Eric to draw this ephemeral curve of light in the mountain.
It's a click, to connect to our senses, it's dark, we do not see anything, we have to be connected to each other.
This is a click for the ultimate attempt we will launch the following year.
The purpose of this attempt it is to raise the emotional dimension, this power, and associate with the already hyper technical, hyper performing team.
We work on a different management, more fluidity, we even work on our senses, we create a kind of emotional experience in which we all gather, we create our tribe, a real tribe.
What is key in a tribe is that the egos, imagine how powerful they are here, the egos fade, there is less pressure, less tension, we respect the other, there is no judgment.
Management is flexible, the difficulties are erased with a disconcerting fluidity.
So here we are.
This tribe you see here, it is constituted, it is effective.
Eric, the champion, is part of the tribe, we are all here, ready for D-Day with the intensity of emotions that can be seen here.
Three, two, one, go!
228 km / h.
Plus 4,5 km / h, phenomenal!
Eric has outdone himself, the team has outdone himself, but ... First, congratulations Mr. Barone!
Congratulations to the team! And respect!
It's an extraordinary feat,
he risks his life.
And what happened in fact?
How could we create this kind of connection?
We are very technical, of course, to achieve these goals.
We equipped several people with sensors, t-shirts stuffed with sensors to know our respiratory rate, our heart rate, our position in space.
Eric is equipped, I am also equipped at the top, a third person, who holds the bike, is equipped at the top, a fourth, Mathias, an the bottom - one kilometer away - and then a professional photographer of extreme sports - just next to us, one meter away, really close,
arrived the day before, he is not really part of the tribe but knows the world of the extreme.
Look at these curves: the physiological stress of all those people.
First stage: 5:24 am, a briefing with Eric, just to explain that we are there.
The physiological stress drops.
Second key moment: we arrive at the top of the track, everyone fears that there is wind.
At the moment I announce that there is no wind, the physiological stress drops again.
Third key moment: the world record.
We are all synchronized, all our heart rates are synchronized,
All except one.
Guessed who it is: extraordinary day for the photographer.
This is the white dashed curve.
You see it there.
It's clear, he's not in the same world.
But he enjoyed it a lot.
So a project has two key dimensions that are very complementary.
First, the technical dimension.
It's in the background, it gives reliability, regularity on the fixed axis, everything that is technical: engineering, marketing, finance, all that, to achieve the goal, pure performance.
The second dimension is human, it allows us to control, to avoid obstacles, to anticipate, but also to hit the wall.
These two dimensions combined allow us to achieve objectives: the ultra performance in which we combine two things: the operational result, well above what we can imagine; and personal fulfillment, very high, at the highest level.
So in front of all this, you imagine that, in my way of working, to work with companies, project supervision, I changed my way of doing things years ago.
This so-called emotional weakness, it is perhaps the strength of the great achievements.
The charismatic, providential leader that everyone is looking for, it is a chimera of our society.
Ultra-performance is in the collective, it is attainable.
Yes, this world is really, really weird.
On the one hand, we have organizations who snatch us up, who are focused on efficiency, with no regard for of our emotions.
On the other hand, these same organizations make sure that you do not fall into stress and avoid burn-outs.
So they create spaces for relaxation, meditation, to feel good, team building.
It reminds me of Apocalypse Now, this film where populations are massacred, and survivors are cared for in order to have a good conscience.
It is the same pattern.
Faced with these new great achievements, always more ambitious, ahead of us, we must relearn to turn to new forms of cooperation, in which everyone is acknowledged for their technical excellence, but also their emotional excellence in which we can converge, in which everyone finds meaning and pleasure.
Self-confidence, in others, in the future, it's up to us to impose it on this weird world.
To us all.
René Char wrote in 1950: "Impose your luck.
Serve your happiness and go towards your risk.
Looking at you, they will get used to it. "
Thank you.
(Applause)
I'm going to adopt the point of view of a scientific extraterrestrial researcher who arrives on Earth and says, 'This is weird, but, well, we aren't surprised.'
To forewarn you, I'm going to say things that are banal, obvious, and I'm going to linger on irrelevant details.
So now, no worries about that.
I'm going to start with the following fact: humans have a central nervous system that is controlled by a brain.
The brain, on Earth, is needed for movement.
On Earth, an organism with a brain moves; if it doesn't move, it doesn't have one -
other than Kinders and Raiders, but they're weird things.
Generally, it's used for this.
Among slightly more structured, complicated animals, and humans, the brain does something more: it produces inferences, mental images - in other words, it produces cognitions - and, mainly with sensory influxes that enter the brain, it gives rise to mental operations, it produces an 'Umwelt' - it's a German word, don't worry, it means 'internal world'.
In this internal world, we perform our mental operations, we calculate things: if a ball travels at such a speed in such a trajectory, what do we need to do to get to it?
Humans do this easily. They use it for their motricity, for their reflexes, and for their reactions to others.
Humans must anticipate what is happening around them in order to still be alive in five minutes time.
There he fails miserably.
(Laughter) A human running to what end?
And, if there's one thing at which humans excel more than anything else, it's at recognising other humans' faces.
They see them everywhere.
It's as if evolution put everything into facial recognition.
They are very good at it.
They see faces - wait for it - in clouds, in the sky, in objects, in vegetables. (Laughter)
If there were humans in the room, they'd see, 100%, that the pepper is angry, (Laughter) and that the tomato is really very sad.
(Laughter) They do it just like that, they see humans everywhere. It's stronger than them, they can't help it, and what's more, it's of no matter to them.
It is to be explained by their evolutionary history. Humans, they are a gregarious species, that has lived in packs, forever one on top of the other, for millions of years.
The main resource for a human, or a prehuman, is another human:
to interact with, to barter with, to collaborate with, to go and kill a mammoth with - that type of thing - to reproduce with.
That's all fine.
And the main danger for a human is also another human.
No other animal on Earth is capable of killing as many humans as a human.
For humans, it's important to anticipate the behaviour of other humans, to determine, from their faces mainly, their behaviour. This is quite normal.
Humans do interesting things: they make machines that they call intelligent.
We'll talk about that ...
But they make machines that beat them at chess and at Go.
When a game has simple rules, without any calculations, machines are very good.
But there isn't a machine in the world that will tell you that the pepper is angry, or that the tomato is sad.
Well, we can go a bit further.
If humans look at this image on the right for a long time, for several seconds, they will start feeling sad for the tomato.
(Laughter) This is empathy.
It's really strange.
Even really stupid humans exhibit empathy - less, but they have it all the same.
So, humans do really strange things.
Very, very young, humans know how to laugh.
Babies can laugh before they can talk.
They look around themselves. Deaf babies know how to laugh.
They're not taught how to.
Spontaneously, they develop this behaviour. They know when to laugh, when not to laugh ... and cry as well. Parents here know this: it doesn't help, but there it is,
children know how to cry.
Very young children, one notes, know how to read hierarchical relationships between humans and tell nice ones from nasty ones. They prefer the nice ones.
Let's hope it stays that way.
(Laughter) Humans, from adolescence, start to become interested in things, and thus develop a certain promiscuity with their fellow humans - of the opposite sex, often - and they learn to recognise the anatomical, sociological, and behavioural characteristics that a good mate for reproduction exhibits.
They know how to recognise a good sex partner.
They have very good taste in terms of pursuing their goals.
They can even give a name to this ability: they call it 'being sexy'.
(Laughter) And this works very well; they rarely get it wrong.
However, if you ask even very, very stupid adults, (Laughter) they know who's sexy and who's not,
but ask what exactly defines 'being sexy',
you just get back, 'Come on, she's just real fab,
there's no explaining it.'
Or, 'Come on, he's hot, you've seen him.'
Or even, 'Leave off, what's with you?'
So they know without fail who is sexy and who is not - and 'being sexy' includes showing all the characteristics of a good mate - it's just they don't know why.
It takes place in their brain, behind the scenes.
Humans can see who is sexy, but, also, who is angry, impatient, starving, happy ... stressed at a TED event - they can spot it ... spontaneously.
I'm OK.
(Laughter) Stop, it's fine.
They do this easily, thanks to a module called the theory of mind. I'm not going to go into it.
Basically, they know how to deduce the internal mental states of people.
It's about mirror neurons: when I do this, you do the same in your head.
Tiresome, isn't it?
(Laughter)
They do it effortlessly.
Sorry, what I'm going to tell you, a human audience, will be totally mundane and boring, but by the same token will be interesting.
It's mundane, and at the same time interesting, because we're talking about cognitive ease.
That was the title of the talk.
So we've got there.
Cognitive ease is a feeling - my remote is falling apart - a feeling of well-being when dealing with a situation - which isn't at all me with this remote. (Laughter)
That's it.
We feel good,
we are in control of the situation and feel all's well.
The more I find thinking something easy, the more I think it's the truth of the matter.
The more I say this to you, the easier it seems, the truer it seems.
And so we enter a comfort zone where we feel safe, and we think everything we think is right.
And so, in fact, we have this complexity that is hidden - I will explain - and this complexity is an unstable system.
There are lots of places where it could go wrong, problems could arise.
So there's many a time things can go wrong, and so humans make mistakes all the time.
Nothing serious ... little errors.
But among the little errors, there's sometimes a big mistake. A very serious mistake.
Nobody notices it, as they're in a state of control, of confidence, where all's well. Nobody is looking to check, as we believe we are right.
So we have an astonishing phenomenon, which is the persistence of false beliefs, which happen when all's simple rather than complicated.
Humans are astonishing animals: they keep on making mistakes that are the simplest to correct, but which they don't correct.
It's something we all know.
If you spend the odd Sunday with family, you'll have seen it.
(Laughter) Sundays on Earth are an illustration of the phenomenon.
(Laughter) So this persistence of error
is more powerful than them: they cannot do other than think they are in the right. So, the human brain is a hammer that thinks there are nails everywhere, making humans exhibit very strange behaviours. They talk to their car to make it start:
'Come on Old Girl!'
(Laughter) Humans shout at their phone when it doesn't work.
When humans stump a toe against a coffee table and it hurts, they shout at the table ... which reacts very little. And ... they treat their animals like humans ... which doesn't do them any favours.
In short, they treat that which cannot act as that which can.
And this seems perfectly normal to them.
Maybe that's pushing it a bit far, but, honestly, on Earth, it's perfectly normal.
Nobody finds it odd.
Everybody, or nearly everybody, has said this phrase, or heard it, without it shocking them: 'The telly doesn't seem to want to work.'
(Laughter) It's daft, isn't it?
So humans spend their time hallucinating.
Humans everywhere have hallucinated about things that aren't real.
For example, the human brain struggles with this image: different zones in the occipital lobe deal with colours and shapes, and it looks like it's moving.
The image is fixed ... it does not move.
But if you go like this
in front of the image, it turns.
Good, so, there is no real movement, but in reality you see one, all of you.
There you've two tables, not, we see, the same shape.
The table on the left is long and narrow; the one on the right wider.
But if I turn the table on the right like this, and show you what the top looks like, it has the same geometric shape.
At the bottom, we see it, at the top, no.
When we know, we see that it's the same table.
So humans are incorrigible.
They can't see the image as it really is.
And they couldn't give a damn either.
(Laughter) So they perceive two tables as different when they are not. So all humans have perceptions that aren't reality, but interpret them as real.
That's natural and simple; and the simpler, the truer.
So, conclusion: if you have a feeling of control, of comfort, of seeming right, that's not reality.
There's a cross, which means it isn't correct.
And um ... so there you have it.
So, conclusion: what happens when you have the feeling of being, without any effort, absolutely right, in absolute comfort?
Humans should want - (Laughter) when younger, they do this well, up to six, after that they stop - to be perplexed, sceptical, to be asking themselves questions.
And so, we have concluded, we, extra-terrestrials, that the human race could be saved - if it ever deserved to be - if humans started to ask the following question - that is your species needs to ask itself - How do I know what I know?
The simpler it looks, the truer it sounds, the less it necessarily is.
There you have it.
(Laughter) (Applause)
One second.
It took me one second.
I entered his apartment.
He was cooking and was standing in his kitchen.
Along the wall was a recipe book.
He was weighing potatoes that were already peeled, to cook a potato gratin. He was weighing peeled potatoes.
One second!
In one second, I saw his essence, the beauty of his being.
I was in love.
It was twenty years ago.
I was passing by his house unexpectedly.
it was raining. My hair was soaked.
So I started spreading happily
the content of my bag on his couch to dry it.
You'd have seen the content of my bag!
One second!
In one second, he also fell head over heels for me.
I saw him in his wonder, and I saw him as a wonder. Until the day his tidy apartment, his tendency to organize everything, and the well planned weeks, started to really get on my nerves.
I came from a very free and happily messy childhood.
At home, for example, at the moment of eating, we opened the fridge, took what were inside and put it in the oven, and it delighted everyone who were there.
So can you imagine me weighing potatoes that were already peeled?
And this guy loved it so much. Twenty years ago, he loved so much my "last minute" side, my tendency to improvise, my things scattered everywhere in the apartment, life.
He saw me as a wonder, and he saw me in my wonder, until the day he started to feel what a rubbish it was to live like that.
And gradually, like all the couples in the world, we switched from a crazy love to a more difficult daily life.
Does it speak to you?
Ten years later, we had three children, a house, our jobs, and a lot of pain together, enervating moments where each theme goes into a spin.
When we weren't together, I really felt love for him, and I cared about him.
But as soon as we'd discuss a subject, we'd fail to get along.
I felt desperate. I was terrified.
And I began to think about separation.
It was a nightmare.
Does this speaks to you?
"They got married, were happy and had many children" is a hoax.
All that stuff about the Charming Prince is a hoax.
These are just myths preventing us from getting to work, because love requires work.
For us, it started as a workshop, an Imago couple workshop in three days that changed everything.
They made us do incredible stuff such as take a pause, slow down, breathe, interact and understand.
These three days changed everything.
We understood we had made the perfect enrollment to become alive again.
It is romantic to talk about enrollment in love, isn't it?
Yet, it was a fundamental recruitment because we are born wonders.
We are born wonders that are full of potential.
Then, we made a trip.
But look my dears, we have the ability to connect or be in our bubble. We've tenacity, tenderness, sensuality, curiosity, creativity, joy and so on. We are really born as wonders.
So we made a trip.
We made a trip in a family, in a community.
We made a trip in a world that gave us messages and made us "psychiatrices".
No, that's not a slip of the tongue.
"Psychiatrices" means "bruises on the soul," or "psychic scars."
During that trip, we put parts of us, parts of our vitality, our freedom to be and our joy... ... in a freezer.
And that's how we enter the life of those wonders, while we are partly frozen.
Here is the "Theory of the freezer." Well, do you see a freezer?
Not this one.
There is another kind of freezer, much more important, the one in which we burried parts of us.
There may have been mourning, abuse and maltreating.
In fact, simply growing up withing my family makes me decide to freeze parts of me.
For example, I'm four years old, and I'm exploring Grandma's sewing box.
And I'm discovering the reels, the scissors - I'm four, it's magic.
When Grandma comes back, I understand immediately.
Her face, the tone of her voice, something is wrong with me.
And I am four, so I decide that my curiosity, I'll put it in my little freezer.
Because as a child, I'll always decide to let go of parts of myself rather than risk losing my connection with the other.
And then as a child too, I'm going to take pictures.
I'll create photographic-like images of the inside of my little world.
I make my little personal photo album of the positive and negative personal traits of the people who took care of me.
And do you know what I'm going to do when I reach adulthood?
Well, I'm going to fall in love with someone who looks like the photos in my album.
This is how, in a relationship, we're wired to react agitatedly for better and for worse.
Now let me recap.
When I fall in love,
1. I saw the wonder and I know how wonderful you are.
2. I am still really alive in places
you have frozen a lot.
And that's when we say "opposites attract each other."
3. I have the superpower
to push your buttons.
Indeed, I'm in your photo album!
So, tirelessly, since I have seen the wonder and know it, I'm going to touch your nerve to transform you because I want the great "you". I want you entirely.
And that's what creates crisis.
The intelligence of love, it's going from "Ouch, you hurt me!"
so I defend myself in the relationship,
to "Ouch, I make you so close to my heart, when you move, you put your hand on my bruises. It's painful. I need your help."
Because in love, we mustn't mistaken the enemy.
The other is not the enemy, the enemy is the bruises of my childhood.
It's our childhood's bruises that take us hostage in the relationship.
And all that is of the order of criticism, blame, changes of mood and anger, all that is just the twists our heart makes to talk about deep needs.
And we've to learn how to express them differently because in a relationship, we have a mission.
And the couple's mission is to bring us back to our wonder, to become whole again, alive, thawed ... And it stings.
You know, those tinglings in our hands after touching the snow, we readily believe that it's the cold that hurts,
but no, the cold numbs!
What burns us is the blood that brings back life.
So we made an appointment.
I have a scoop for you: between lovers, even if we live together 24/7, we have to make appointments, in the diary, with an agenda and a process just like in the office.
That's how both of us, by way of conversations, we managed to make that journey and welcome a little boy from my husband's story who always had to be tidy in order to be loved, and manage to welcome and give love together to a little girl from my childhood's trip who had lacked quite a bit of guidance.
Then, those recurring conflicts about messiness, tidiness, improvisation, planning, all those moments where we had an argument, all that dissolved.
I have a second scoop for you:
Conflict is not a problem, it's the heart of the reactor.
It's precisely the moment we have together where we can turn lead into gold.
And without tools, without conscience, lead is turned into a slurry.
Because our conflicts are gifts.
Conflict is growth knocking at the door.
But we pack those gifts with such a repulsive paper that no one wants to open them.
Who wants anger, rejection, violence, bad mood, criticism, and victimization?
No one! ... No one.
Now this man and I, each time a conflict emerges, we sit down, we breathe, we connect, and we make this trip to enlighten our childhood, in safety and connection. And the two of us open those freezers that prevents us from completely loving ourselves.
It's similar to a relational meditation whose purpose is to release smoothly the cries from within, and put them in another place.
To be in a relationship is an initiatory journey.
Ladies and gentlemen, watch out!
Being in relationship puts us in danger of living!
So, let's live!
And I can't resist presenting you ... (Laughing) ... my laboratory of life! (Cheers)
(Applause) (Cheers)
Ladies and gentlemen, good evening.
(Applause) When a woman falls in love, we say that she has butterflies in their stomach.
When she is courageous, we say that she has guts.
When she gets bad news, she has to digest it.
And finally, when she is stressed, we say that she has knots in her stomach.
And believe me, when you're at TEDx in front of a thousand people, your stomach is in knots.
(Laughter) For years - (Applause) For years we have been using these colloquial expressions which connect the brain, our emotions, to our stomachs, without realising how right our understanding was.
So you must have recently heard about it in the media. The stomach is our second brain.
And when we say brain, we mean neurons.
Do you have an idea of how many neurons we have in our stomach?
200 million neurons.
To give you an idea, it's about the same as a cat or a small dog.
It's true that 200 million compared to the upper brain, which has 90 billion, it's definitely a smaller brain. But it is enough to maintain our body's essential functions like digestion, or bowel function.
But what is more fascinating is that this second brain is in direct contact with the upper brain.
That means that it can receive information as well as send it.
How?
Through nerves, for example.
The vagus nerve relies on both of our brains.
Or by blood circulation, via the secretion of neurotransmitters or hormones.
Moreover, did you know that 90% of serotonin, which is a hormone regulating stress and emotion, is not produced in our upper brain but rather in our stomachs?
We speak about the gut-brain axis.
So yes, the gut-brain axis.
But if we want to be more precise, we need to talk about the microbiota-gut-brain axis.
Because if we zoom in on the heart of our guts, the heart of our bowels, we can see 40 to 100 thousand billion microorganisms, bacteria living in our intestines. Yes.
A note for everyone feeling a little isolated, you're never alone.
(Laughter) This figure of 100 thousand billion microorganisms, means that we indeed have 10 times more non-human cells in us, that is bacterial cells, than human cells.
And these bacteria, these microorganisms, also have their own DNA, their own genetic heritage, which is different than our own.
It makes you dizzy, doesn't it?
Who are we?
Today, I suggest that you discover intestinal microbiota to understand its importance, but also its fragility, to learn to look after it to preserve its balance.
Give me your microbiota, I'll tell you who you are.
The intestinal microbiota accompanies us at least from birth, from our first moments of life.
For example, from delivery.
If it was a vaginal birth, a natural birth, the colonisation of microbiota of newborns will materialise via the mother's vaginal and faecal bacterial flora.
On the other hand, if it's a caesarean birth, it will instead be bacteria present in the environment in the delivery room, or from the nursing staff.
And this baby won't benefit from the mother's flora.
Food too.
Breastfeeding versus industrial milk.
A baby will be nourished from the mother's breast, will benefit from the mother's mammary flora, if I can say that.
Breast milk has the privilege of having - a composition fairly strong in bifidobacteria and lactobacillus, bacteria which can stimulate the immune system and shape the intestinal microbiota.
The environment too.
By the way, a short digression.
This is why skin-to-skin contact between parents and the baby is essential for the development of microorganisms so that you transfer your cutaneous flora to the baby.
Another factor is the environment.
A baby that will grow up in the country, in contact with nature, will have a different intestinal microbiota than a baby growing up in town, in an apartment disinfected with bleach.
Another issue is treatments, antibiotic treatments.
While they are necessary for treating an occasional infection, antibiotic treatments during early childhood can have an impact on the composition of intestinal microbiota.
And progressively over days, weeks, and even years, this intestinal mictobiota will evolve in the end to level off from the end of early childhood, around three years old.
Then it becomes unique.
It will be your intestinal microbiota.
It's a little like a digital fingerprint.
At a glance, they all look the same.
But when we analyse it further, we can see differences between each individual.
And for intestinal microbiota, it's kind of the same thing.
There is a set common for everyone, for each individual.
But when we examine the analysis, there are still differences.
When someone is in good health, we say that their microbiota is in balance, in harmony with the intestine and the brain.
In balance but not unchanged.
It can be changed by several factors that can induce a small imbalance of intestinal microbiota.
Taking medicines such as antibiotics, bacterial infections, hormonal changes like puberty or menopause, stress, alcohol, and also diets can induce imbalances in intestinal microbiota and induce gastrointestinial damage.
But in scientific literature, they have written about stronger imbalances in intestinal microbiota, which we call 'dysbiosis.'
It's the case with certain disorders, digestive disorders, like Crohn's disease, irritable bowel syndrome, ulcerative colitis.
Regarding Crohn's disease, it's a chronic illness of an inflamed intestine, and its prevalence and impact is steadily increasing.
And indeed, patients suffering from this condition will alternate between phases of remission - rest, and phases of attacks that result in very severe inflammation.
Symptoms include abdominal cramps, diarrhoea, inflammation and visceral pain.
You need to know that today, we don't know the true origin of Crohn's disease.
But we do know that it is a multifactorial disease.
I.e., there are several factors that come into play.
There are genetic factors, the immune system, the environment, living standards, and there is also the intestinal microbiota via its dysbiosis.
What is more interesting is that with these diseases, like with irritable bowel syndrome, they are under the influence of the microbiota-gut-brain axis.
That is, beyond gastro-intestinal disorders, we also see it in patients with central nervous system disorders,
such as nociception disorders - experiencing pain, emotion, humour, anxiety, stress. In terms of communication between the microbiota, intestines and the brain, one of the questions we can ask is whether a dysbiosis, that is, an imbalance of intestinal microbiota, can contribute to the development of neurological and psychiatric illnesses.
So I ask the question like this one, but we already know some elements of the response. Particularly in terms of the stress response, for example.
The first proof dates back to 2004, when a Japanese team authorised the demonstration of the link between intestinal microbiota and stress.
For that, they took animals, axenic animals, meaning that they don't have intestinal microbiota.
They're sterile, their digestive tract is sterile.
They noted that these animals were hypersensitive to stress and anxiety.
Ever since, there have been a lot of other studies continuing to outline this link between intestinal microbiota and stress, simultaneously with animals and humans.
For example, with humans, patients suffering from Crohn's disease who are in remission, if they experience a stressful event, a psychological stress, this will induce a relapse of the disease.
They will move into the phase of attack associated with dysbiosis.
Today, a link has clearly been established between stress and intestinal microbiota.
In addition to stress and anxiety states, autism. Autism has been and continues to be the subject of research.
Notably, there is a study comparing the intestinal microbiota of autistic children to healthy children, and they have noted significant differences.
For example, intestinal microbiota in children with autism is less varied, less diverse, and there are similarities between patients.
For example, generally we will observe an increase in harmful bacteria like Desulfovibrio and Bacteroidetes -
they aren't great -
and a reduction in Bifidobacteria and Firmicutes.
Research advances. Several years ago, we wouldn't have thought to look in the stomach for these conditions.
So ... Intestinal microbiota have a moderating effect on the intestine. We have seen it in digestive conditions and equally with the central nervous system and stress.
What are the means today of adjusting and attempting to rebalance this intestinal microbiota?
I need to say that there are currently studies on the transplant of microbiota, more commonly known as faecal transplant.
You heard that, right?
The concept aims to transfer the intestinal microbiota originating in the stool of healthy individuals to a sick person.
It's a real therapy still in its experimental phase. We are still testing; it's not routinely used.
And I think that it's the occasion to say that the researchers don't hesitate to dirty their hands for science.
(Laughter) And this therapy has already shown its effectiveness, notably with severe infections of Clostridium difficile.
I've already told you it's not routinely used because we haven't seen enough setbacks.
There are other means far more accessible to rebalance intestinal microbiota.
And you are certainly aware of them.
Antibiotics.
An antibiotic will, by definition, kill targeted harmful bacteria in the intestine.
The problem is that it will also destroy some of the other bacteria which didn't ask for it.
But antibiotic treatments have proven themselves.
In scientific literature, we can read that an antibiotic treatment reduces the symptoms of digestive conditions.
And equally, disorders of the central nervous system - a study has shown that in animals, an antibiotic treatment can reduce symptoms of autism while they are taking the treatment.
However, they have also found that once the treatment has stopped, the symptoms return.
This means that, unfortunately, we can't propose this type of antibiotic treatment for these long-term disorders.
Because you well know that it is very rarely recommended to repeatedly use antibiotics.
Simply because the bacteria can acclimate and develop a resistance.
So, antibiotics are not recommended for this type of chronic illness, more so for one-time infections.
Don't panic, there are other means.
Probiotics, for example.
Probiotics are live bacteria that we ingest, and we know their functions, so we know that they are beneficial to our health.
This is proven with digestive disorders and also with chronic stress.
You can find probiotics in the pharmacy in high concentrations, and also in food.
In lacto-fermented products and in some dairy, miso soup, sausage, pickles.
Another way is also prebiotics.
It's not the same.
Prebiotics are the nutrients that we can't digest, but that our flatmates - our bacteria - can.
We will nourish them, and in choosing the type of prebiotics, we can choose the type of bacteria that we want to grow,
like Bifidobacteria, for example.
And you can naturally find prebiotics in food, especially fibre.
Fibre is a source of prebiotics.
Anything with barley, oats, leeks, Jerusalem artichoke. And finally, last tip: you can find symbiotics in the pharmacy.
They combine - they're capsules - simultaneously probiotics, so bacteria, and prebiotics, nutrients.
All of these resources that I've just told you about are used today with the aim of rebalancing intestinal microbiota when there is dysbiosis.
Unfortunately, we need to be really clear about it, whether it's a case of digestive diseases like Crohn's disease, irritable bowel syndrome or a case of problems with the central nervous system, it doesn't cure the disease.
I'll remind you that these are multifaceted illnesses.
It's not only the microbiota in play.
But it does allow for a reduction in symptoms and improvement of the patient's quality of life.
Research is moving forward.
Discovering the impact of intestinal microbiota on the brain brings a new point of view fundamental to neuroscience.
Before, we spoke of gastroenterology for the stomach, and neurology for the brain,
in a really distinct manner.
Today, we indeed speak of neurogastroenterology.
This means a new way of thinking, new concepts, new careers, new therapeutic modalities that can allow us to approach these illnesses in a different way, especially neurologically.
And tomorrow, in the future, we will maybe better understand neurodegenerative diseases.
Actually, researchers are wanting to know whether there is a link between intestinal microbiota and neurodegenerative illnesses.
I'm thinking of Alzheimer's, Parkinson's, multiple sclerosis.
While waiting for these results, I want you to take care of yourselves, to take care of your microbiota.
Listen to your stomach, and equally, as much as possible, try to conserve a healthy mind in a healthy stomach.
Thank you.

Good evening to all of you.
Thank you all for being here.
Today, I would like to speak to you about agriculture, food, the trajectory of our agricultural system and the power we all have to change it.
I'm starting with one observation: it has been up to 40 or 50 years since our agricultural system stressed on the increase in production in an approach essentially focused on productivity and quantity and increasing volumes.
These options that were taken in the 1960s and 1970s - the Common Agricultural Policy began in 1961- could be explained back then by a concern to ensure food security in a world where population growth was still very high.
Today, however, the choices that were made in the 1960s and 1970s produce difficult consequences that can't be ignored any more.
This low-cost food economy grew from the idea that the producer could be paid less if subsidies compensate the loss of production profits, that agricultural workers could be paid very low wages, and that the producers were not obliged to internalize the negative social, environmental and sanitary externalities they cause.
A low-cost food economy was developed that was intended to ensure the access to cheap food to all, including to the poorest households.
But, as I said, this gave rise to problematic consequences: First, on the environment. The development of broad monocultures has destroyed biodiversity and led to the significant increase of greenhouse gases - food systems represent 33% of greenhouse gas emissions due to human activities globally- Soils have been destroyed; they have been affected by the erosion produced by monoculture, by the compaction linked to the use of big machines, and by the soil salinization due to incorrect agricultural irrigation techniques. And then social consequences.
Everywhere, we have seen small-scale farming disappearing, the so-called family farming.
In Belgium, in the last 30 years, we have lost close to 2/3 of our farms. The smallest and weakest are disappearing faced to a market that is getting increasingly competitive.
And finally health consequences because we are developing these giant field crops to provide raw materials to the agri-food processing industry that, therefore, supplies the market with prepared food and ultra-processed products which are responsible for the explosion of overweight and obesity rates in the world and their related non-communicable diseases such as type 2 diabetes, cardiovascular diseases and gastrointestinal cancers.
For example, let's take a look at this study that was published in the Lancet in 2016. Nineteen million people have been followed, from 200 countries, over the course of 30 years, and between 1975 and 2014, obesity increased in all of them.
Sometimes, we are told that this productivist approach helps satisfy the needs of the world, and that Europe should feed developing countries, for example, by increasing its production in order to address the inability of other countries to feed themselves.
But in reality, these countries are complaining that their markets are flooded with cheap foodstuffs that are heavily subsidized by taxpayers in rich countries,
and this photo taken by Yann Arthus-Bertrand, which he asked me one day to comment, illustrates this in a metaphoric way. We can see these heavily packaged and processed products displayed in the markets of developing countries and competing with the small-scale producers of these countries.
So, yes, we must change.
We must change but the system is inert. It is difficult to reform.
This is because this system is composed of different elements that have co-evolved and are now supporting each other.
Technical or technological choices have been made. We have invested in infrastructures and in logistics to promote economies of scale and mass production.
As a result, we have enable major actors to emerge, the champions of the low-cost food economy, among raw material buyers and food processing companies, and among large distributors.
Further more, we have an increasingly hurried lifestyle where we no longer have the time to cook fresh products from local suppliers, where, incidentally, we lose the culinary knowledge.
And this leads to the strengthening of the political influence of the agrifood lobbies, these large corporations that dominate agrifood systems today and ask governments to develop infrastructures, logistics, and an economic system that would further strengthen their dominant power.
Therefore, the way we eat, the way we live, our relationship with food and cooking, all share responsibility in this situation affecting us today.
Now, this explains why a lot of ordinary citizens are starting to search for alternatives to the dominant system.
For example, we see urban farms developing, like here at Chant-des-Cailles in Boisfort.
We see the growth of direct distribution channels that are connecting local producers to consumers, such as the network of solidarity purchasing groups "GASAP," in Brussels, the joint-purchase groups "CAP," in Wallonia, or the thousands of AMAP, Associations for the Preservation of Smallholder Agriculture, in France.
We see the growth of initiatives in which charities that help disadvantaged households use unsold items from mass distribution to supply those very poor families.
We see the growth of co-operative supermarkets often modeled after the Park Slope Food Coop created in Brooklyn in the 1970s and that also imitates today's Bees Coop, for example, in Brussels.
All this is important and it essentially shows that we can get out of our stance of critical consumers or empowered voters who listen to political parties.
These are genuine actors who try to invent new alternatives.
But the question today is to know if, at heart, we aren't in some kind of dilemma or some kind of dead end.
Are these alternatives going to remain a innovating niche? Or, are they going to be co-opted by the system just like some organic sectors, or some fair trade names?
Is the alternative really between the preservation of these small-scale initiatives or the capture by the dominant system which by co-oping these alternatives, can always manage to buy more time in order to survive and continue to control?
For my part, I would like we imagine a way to resolve this dilemma and I don't see any other possibility than to encourage food democracy. I would like that beside these alternatives that develops through short chains, through local farmers' markets and co-operative supermarkets, we politicize the food issue,
And this is done more and more. In California, we have created a Food Policy Council. These Food Policy Councils, these citizens' forums in which the actors of the food system meet together to find out how to transform the food system, are developing everywhere, in Canada, the United States, the United Kingdom,
and here in the city of Cork, for example, in the south of England.
These citizens have realized that it's not enough to consume in a critical way, to vote for the good parties, or even participate in alternative systems.
They understood that what is needed is to exercise power,
not to take power but exercise power by gathering together and find out alternatives to the dominant system.
Their motto essentially - by which I will end- it is that the only real limit to our power is that we don't dare to exercise it.
Thank you.
(Applause)
Gilda Gonfier: Yé krik!
(Audience) Yé krak!
GG: Is the court asleep?
(Audience) No, the court is not asleep.
GG: Those of you who are familiar with storytelling evenings know that after, "No, the court is not asleep," the storyteller can continue by saying, "If the court is not asleep, it is Isidore who is asleep in the house of Theodore, on a golden pillow, for two gold coins."
At a storytelling evening, I heard another phrase
that I personally find dizzying. The storyteller said, "If the court is not asleep, wake up from the slumber of which you are not asleep."
A man feared Death.
He married her.
They had three children.
The first was a great sailor.
He conquered the oceans and subjected many lands to his father's law.
The second built cathedrals.
He promised paradise to some and threaten others with hell.
The third was a simple tailor.
He set up his workshop not far from his parents' house.
He was contemplative.
What he liked was to watch the crazy ants run, to read the secrets of the world on the wings of butterflies, and, at night, to be soothed by the song of the stars.
What he liked, was to take his needle and thread, and stitch by stitch, make for those who ask it of him
a custom-made outfit. His ambition wasn't to conquer seas or to conquer souls.
But his father, his father wanted him to have a destiny as glorious as his brothers'.
So he forced him to receive his inheritance to make him an outfit fit for the gods. But where do you find
the fabric, the cloth for such an outfit?
Death, his mother, came to his aid and said to him, "My son, you need to go to the top of the mountain. There, you go inside the cave, you ask the demon for passage. You will be asked a riddle, and if you solve it, the cloth will be given to you." The son did what his mother told him.

He climbed to the top of the mountain, asked for passage.
The riddle was this, "What reduces man, like stone, to dust?"
Thankfully, the tailor was the crazy ants' friend. And it was them
who whispered the answer to him, "Time reduces man, like stone, to dust."
The cloth was given to him, a cloth so exquisite that he could take it to his workshop only with his heart.
But what needle could go near such a cloth? His mother, Death, came to his aid and said to him,
"This time you must go inside the volcano. There, you ask the demon for passage. You will be asked a riddle, if you solve it, the needle will be given to you."
The riddle was this, "If stones could talk, what could they teach men?"
The tailor was the butterflies' friend, and the butterflies whispered the answer to him, "If stones could talk, they would teach men to overcome the fear of time."
The needle was given to him.
He has no thread.
For the thread, his mother tells him that he needs to go to the bottom of the ocean to ask the demon for passage; he will be asked a riddle, and once solved, the thread will be given to him.
This time, the riddle was this, "What is the medicine for the fear of time?"
The tailor spent many nights being soothed by the song of the stars, and the stars sang the answer to him, "Love is the medicine of time, as much as time is the medicine of love."
And the thread was given to him.
With the cloth, the needle, and the thread, the tailor made his father an incomparable tunic, a tunic made of love and time that clothed his father like the wind clothes a tree, that clothed his father with a caress.
I wrote this tale in 2009.
In 2009, I set myself a challenge: I'm an author, I found that I wasn't writing enough, and while waiting for the birth of my second daughter, who was born on the third of February, I gave myself this resolution: to write a tale a day.
I'll reassure you at once: I didn't manage it.
It's 2016, I wrote, I think, 81, but that year, I wrote 56.
And if I'm here before you, it's to share with you what I discovered while writing every day, or at least the first 15 days.
A tale, a tale.
What I started as a discipline to write more, to write novels, plays, scenarios, and I wanted to write tales like we do scales, to practice.
And tales, are the precursor of theater, of cinema.
Every story, every society, every civilization has an art of storytelling.
What started as a literary exercise transformed into a ritual, and it became a meditation practice.
Tales became my meditation.
I socialize with tales like I socialize with friends, acquaintances, that feed me and allow me to explore my inner garden and especially to cultivate it.
And I would like to give you, to suggest this tool, daily if you wish, but especially in an intimate way in a dialogue with yourself, to cultivate this inner garden.
Inside ourselves, we need to be fed, to be alive, because, when we are empty inside, violence, we turn it against ourselves but also against others.
If I'm empty inside, I can erase myself, but if I think another is empty, I can erase them too.
Tales are fantastic.
Tales are magic wands.
If you take a step back, if you cross this threshold, and go to the fantastic side, if you answer, as you did, the "Yé krik," and you say (Audience) Yé krak!
GG:... it's that you accept - we made a pact - you accept that everything I say after becomes possible.
After, "Yé krik! Yé krak,"
a man can marry Death; he can have children - when we get married, we have children - and we just have to pull he thread, and the story unravels on its own.
That is a tale.
A tale is fantastic; a tale is a language, that says and achieves the impossible.
In a tale, everything is possible.
And to write a tale every day, it accustoms our brains to accept that everything is possible.
A tale, for me, is a process that solves problems.
When I have a problem, a question, - to fear death, that's a question at some point - I put it in a tale.
It's like an equation.
I open a tale, I lay out the start, "A man feared Death."
And after that, what happens?
Well, he marries her.
In tales, they always finish with, "They get married and lived happily ever after."
There's Prince Charming.
So, we can take this literally, and search for Prince Charming all our lives without necessarily meeting him.
And that, that is a waste of time.
Or we can understand that marriage happens inside oneself, because all the characters of the tales you will write - I hope to tempt you to write as early as tonight, or tomorrow morning - every character is you.
I am the man who feared Death, I am Death, and I am the three children.
On a blank page, to lay out the characters, to create scenes, and to start from a beginning, to have a middle, twists, magic, fantasy, and to come to a resolution - if you accustom your brain, every day, to do this, that fits on one page, if you draw inspiration from everything that happens to you in your life, to put it on paper and to present it as a tale, respecting the structure of tales, - you are familiar with tales, everyone knows what a tale is - a fantastic tale.
In a fantastic tale, there is a hero.
The hero is you.
When you write your tales, the hero is inevitably you.
In a fantastic tale, there is a hero, then, there are twists.
The hero has a goal, but, there are obstacles on the way.
And he must overcome the obstacles.
And in a tale, there is always unexpected help, providential, fantastic, otherwise, it wouldn't be called a "fantastic tale."
In any case, you know that help is there.
It comes in forms that we don't expect: ants that reveal the solutions to riddles, and butterflies, stars that sing, honestly, but it's possible, because everything is possible in a tale.
So, in practical terms, how do we do this?
I invite you, now, this evening, to begin by reading a tale.
I love Creole tales.
There is an anthropologist called Elsie Clews Parsons, - ask Google, it'll tell you - and this woman crossed the Caribbean, and asked everybody: bakers, merchants, rich people, poor people, prostitutes, everybody, and she gathered tales.
And by island, she transcribed them, often in Creole, sometimes in English.
And this collection of tales is my meditation.
First, feed yourself with tales, because reading and writing, it's like breathing.
We read and we write, we read and we write,
that's how it works. So you feed yourselves with tales, then, you can read a tale, choose the one you prefer and then close the book, and then rewrite it, straight away or the next day, and you'll see what's left.
Because what's left, is what your brain, what you, your heart, your inner garden, what it needs.
When I had this ritual, I created a website with a friend.
This website is my online workshop.
I put a lot of things in there.
So, we click on "Consult," and it spits out L'Oracle, that's what I called it.
"Vision gathers the knowledge of myths" - this sentence means nothing, don't try to understand it, it's deliberate.
It's so that your brain turns off, it's to take a step back.
We need this.
It works by the association of ideas.
Don't try to understand.
Secrecy is important.
You write for yourselves.
It's something for you, just for you.
You're not going to show it to anyone.
Through the association of ideas see what comes and let it come.
You welcome what comes.
You are reassured, because you know that a tale is very simple.
A beginning, a middle,
an end; three steps.
That's what you need to remember when writing a story:
a middle, a beginning, an end.
At the beginning, we have an inspiration.
It's not just artists that need it.
Everybody needs inspiration, every day, to feel inspired.
You can use L'Oracle, take a book from a shelf, and read the first sentence that you see, or what you hear on the radio. You are there to receive, and everything you hear, put it on a blank page.
There are writings for oneself: you can write in your diary, you can write your biography, you can write tales.
Jung said, "We can live our lives sleeping, allowing ourselves to float, to be carried by events, or we can choose to wake up to oneself and to the world." And that is what was meant by,
"Wake up from the slumber of which you are not asleep."
We can't live our lives believing we're awake, awake, we are not asleep.
We do our everyday activities.
But are we conscious, and awake, to every story that lives inside us?
Because we are made of stories.
We are so completely made of stories that merchants have understood this, and to make us buy things that we don't need, they wrap them up in stories.
There, that is what I wanted to share with you, my practice of tales as an awakening to oneself.
Because I tell myself if we all cultivated our inner gardens, if we were all gardeners at heart, we can make this world fantastic.
It's a bit ... (Laughter) But I believe it's important to take this step back, and then to come back to reality.
We are more engrained, more rooted, because we are whole inside.
Tales are journeys.
Thank you.
(Applause)
At a certain time, a few years before that, I was in a gloomy cell, in the detention center at Fresnes.
And I was pacing, in the cell, because they took away our mattresses, then, so you had to stand.
In a corner of the cell, there are toilets, I hear a few bubbles, so I lean over, I go over and have a look, and what do I see?
I see a rat who sticks his head out, takes a breath, and goes back down.
I'm telling you, I didn't go to the toilet straight away.
So I said to myself that I was in quite a difficult situation.
But as I was alone, in complete isolation, I was in in the dark, I saw no-one. It had been a few days since I had spoken to anyone - I said to myself, "I will share my bread with him."
I put a little piece of bread
beside the toilets. I waited.
The next day, poof, he had gone.
Two days later, the same thing.
Finally the rat started to get a little bit bolder
A few days later, there I was, beside my friend the rat.
I shared a few little secrets, and told him a bit about my life.
And he was listening.
He was nibbling his piece of bread, but he was listening to me.
I was there. I had some company, I had some support, a sympathetic ear.
It was great.
Anyway, I get to the end of my 45 days of solitary, and it's time to leave.
So we are sitting down, side by side, we looked at each other, we said our goodbyes, and I promise you, I saw a little tear, on both sides, and I left solitary confinement.
I wondered to myself, "How did I end up here?"
And the story goes that in December 84, I am with a friend, a girlfriend, my fiancé at that time, and I am attacked by eight skinheads.
Back then, these were violent people, in fact, they still are, but anyway.
Unfortunately, I pulled out a gun, and I shot, because I thought they were going to hurt her. I shot, and one of them died, and one was injured.
Two days later, I am in a prison van, on my way to the largest prison in Europe, called Fleury-Merogis.
I had never seen a prison, I had never seen a prison van, nor a cage. I didn't know that they locked human beings in cages.
It came as quite a shock.
I wound up in reception, which is at the center of Fleury-Merogis, where new arrivals are processed.
And that was the the first time I had to strip in front of anyone.
First humiliation.
Next, I go to the registry. You hand over your things, your identity card, etc., and you're given a number.
And this number, you remember for the rest of your life.
138496Q.
Next, you are left in custody.
What is prison? It is not
only the denial of freedom. But it is also misery, it is also lack of hygiene, lack of care, overcrowding, and a whole load of things which are really inhuman.
And most of all, violence.
You walk in, you have to fight, straight away.
It is a hard world, and you have to survive.
So I am in prison, I start my sentence.
At that time, it was the 80s, it was in 85, a fairly widespread illness, is becoming an epidemic. So the tests started, tests to see if you had AIDS.
And I have a test.
And I find out that I am HIV positive.
So, not a good start in life.
From that point onwards, I have only one thing on my mind, and that's to escape.
Because back then, it was thought you only had three years or five years max.
I was obsessed with one thing: to escape.
So I do four years in Fleury-Mérogis, then I am transferred.
I manage to get a mid-sentence day release, because at that time, I had a ten year sentence, and they knew that I had been assaulted.
I have no hope, I am ill, I know that I might die tomorrow, and I can't bear prison any longer, the way it is.
I can't bear the inhuman way they treat people, any longer, so I go on the run.
On the run, there aren't many options.
To survive on the run, you need money.
You can't go to work.
So I start stealing, and I go back to doing hold-ups, and I become a raider.
I get caught, I get another 2-3 years, and in 93 I'm released at the end of my sentence.
And everything's still the same, no cure for the illness.
Prison had really broken me.
I mean it's a system which makes you violent, which changes you.
I am 28 when I finish my sentence.
And I relapse. I go back
to guns, and to hold-ups. I am in a very violent world;
I get caught in 94.
And I know that I will go down for years, and that I will die in prison.
And because I know it's the end for me, I go for broke.
9 October 1994, the anniversary of the abolition of the death penalty, I chose this date to escape.
I get some weapons smuggled into prison, I take some hostages, and I manage to get out.
I went on a violent rampage. with armed robberies, hold-ups.
Finally, in 95, I get caught by the serious crime squad, and they incarcerate me.
I end up in solitary confinement. because I have become dangerous and a threat to society.
It's true.
Five years in solitary confinement, seeing no-one, for all those years.
Complete isolation.
To survive in isolation, the only solution, as there is nothing else, is to read.
And I discovered literature. I started to read, and I found in the words, a way of traveling and of discovering the world, of which I had been deprived.
The strength of the words was something powerful, which could take me somewhere, to escape, actually.
After these years of isolation, in 2000, 1995-2000, I am finally released and I'm transferred to La Santé detention center.
And when I am there I meet people, I touch them, to see if they are really human.
I start living again, and I enroll on some courses.
Teachers come to the prison.
There is a university, Paris VII. There is a section called the Section for Detainee Students, which is for prisoners.
And there, I come across a teacher, a philosophy teacher called François Chouquet.
We talk, and he tells me that words are more powerful than weapons.
Obviously I laughed, in the beginning.
(Laughter) He is very nice, but well...
But I continue studying, I started to write a little, and he made me read Tolstoy, Céline, Camus, "In Remembrance of things past," as if that was all I had to do; but he gave me something,
it was really a treasure.
Finally, I started to write, and I showed him my first script.
He encouraged me.
At last, I belonged somewhere in society, I existed for someone, someone read my work.
I belonged.
In 2002, I am finally sentenced, and I get 30 years.
30 years is a long time.
(Laughter) Enough to read three libraries, François Mitterand.
I get 30 years, 30 years.
To tell you the truth: when I got the sentence, I was transferred straight away to a high security prison, and I tried to escape once more.
(Laughter) I got two more years, but it was a gamble.
And because I couldn't bear to be in this prison, I started riots, I set fire to Clairvaux, it was terrible.
It was hard to accept this denial of freedom.
By then, I had already done about 20 years in prison.
Finally, in 2006, I said to myself that it was my own harmful thinking from which I had to escape.
I had to become someone else,
I had had enough of it.
In 2006, I end up in Poissy prison.
And there, I create the first prison blog of a detainee, in the Nouvel Observateur.
The first.
Today, everyone has the Internet, but it was me who created the first.
In my column I described prison life, everything which I stood for, how to fight against a system, which is destroying us. and also the absurdity of this system.
And other articles: the disabled in prison, etc.
Obviously, the prison authorities were against it since it was against the rules.
Any communication was forbidden, unless it was censored first.
To this day, they don't know how I did it.
For four years, I got my articles on the Internet, without them knowing.
I also met Fabien Marceau, at a concert.
He comes with his crutch.
Fabien Marceau, sorry, I mean Grand Corp Malade.
I like the fact that because of his words, because of his Slam a disabled person, could stand up and practice his art.
So you could say that the power of his words created this miracle.
No need to go to Lourdes, he did it with Slam, and he managed to make a career of it.
We became mates, very friendly.
For me too, writing enabled me, thanks to my blog, to publish my first book.
I was no longer dangerous, I was a writer.
and a freelance one, for the Nouvel Observateur.
The prison authorities, looked at me differently.
"Something strange is happening there."
"He must be planning another escape."
(Laughter) I promise you it's true. I can tell you that they took my computer, they confiscated it, passed it to CLIS, to see if I had access, etc.
The prison governor came to ask me, "Is it really you?"
"No, it's a lunatic who pretends to be me, who writes this stuff.
I promise you."
(Laughter) It happened.
(Laughter) It was through one of my books that I met a young student.
We fell in love; with writing, anything is possible.
We fell in love, and after a few months, we decided, to have a "visiting-hours" baby.
Because that's also part of being human.
So we made a baby during visiting hours.
And in March 2008, my little girl was born.
(Applause) Two days after the birth, - because I didn't go straight away, I couldn't - I was in the maternity ward.
A criminal like me.
I end up in the maternity ward, and I go to see my baby.
They took off my handcuffs.
There was a window, and I had a good look, but... (Laughter) Sometimes it's stronger than us, but anyway.
I took my daughter in my arms (Applause) We called her Tilelli.
Tilelli means freedom in Kabyle, as it was her who managed to get me out of prison, after 20 years.
All of that is to tell you, that I filed a case for parole. It took 2-3 years, a rock-solid case, because I was a father, I had responsibilities, and at last the sentencing judge, seeing that I had already done 25 years in prison, he said, "He must be released, because he is a journalist, and a father, he has become this, he has become that."
And I managed to get my university qualification, from Paris VII.
(Applause) All that was to tell you that today, they think that serial offenders should be marginalized that they must take a hard line, and that they shouldn't be let out.
But I have proved the opposite.
Even with my background, it's possible.
A return to real life is possible.
And it is possible, thanks to people and goodwill.
And finally, in all dictatorships the first thing which goes away is culture.
It's destroyed.
Ignorance should even be seen as a crime against humanity.
It is through culture, that I managed to pull through, through reading; and with teachers.
We must encourage this sort of thing.
I think back to Chouquet's quote, who said that the pen was mightier than the sword.
It is because of the pen that my greatest escape succeeded.
Thank you.
(Applause)
I'm 30 years old. I run a large company, and I work 6 days out of 7.
This morning of July, 4, 1994, the doctor sat down in front of me and told me a little sheepishly that I had a tumor as big as a golf ball planted in the middle of my skull, more precisely on the pituitary gland, a small gland located behind the eyes at the base of the cerebral hemispheres, regulating the entire endocrine system.
"Pituitary Macroadenoma" the doctor told me.
"I'm not sure if it is cancerous, but the tumor is already so big that it has eaten your pituitary and it compresses your optic nerve.
That is what accounts for your fainting and deteriorating eyesight." "This is serious," he told me, "it must be treated without delay."
The treatment began three days later, for several weeks.
After five weeks, no improvement.
The tumor is still there. It continues to grow, and the only effect of the treatment is a poisoned body.
They decided on surgery. It will be heavy and will take five hours.
A few days after the operation, the doctor returned to my room to tell me about it all. He told me, "I have news for you."
"Good news first."
"The good news is that you are alive, and you have recovered your eyesight."
"Unfortunately," the doctor told me, "by removing the tumor, we also had to remove the pituitary gland. And you can't live without it.
This means that for the rest of your life you'll be in a latent depressive state all the time. You can no longer have children. Your life expectancy will be reduced by 15 years, and you will be taking pain medication for the rest of your life, and being in a coma within the 48 hours."
This was on September, 10, 1994, just before my 31st birthday. The doctor has just given me orders for the rest of my life.
Surprisingly enough, the diagnosis, or should I say the doctor's sentence, didn't demolish me completely, for two reasons.
The first is that I will see my wife and little boy again, for whom I fought for these two months.
The second is the recollection of a discussion I had a few days earlier with the endocrinology professor at the hospital. He explained to me that there is a link between my mind and my body, a close link between my emotions and my immune system.
The doctor had told me, "You take conventional stress, because you are a boss with a lot of responsibility." "You add very negative stress made of heavy emotions like the bitterness of rancor or anger."
"You made poison. This kills more than alcohol or tobacco."
This is what we call the Nocebo effect.
It is the reverse of the placebo effect.
Looking at it and thinking about it, I realize these are exactly the emotions I have fed over the previous 12 months.
With this understanding, when I left the hospital, I decided to change my way of life, and first to look after my physical body.
I therefore decided to do a lot of exercise, especially cardiovascular: jogging, cycling, and a lot of running in the high mountains.
After a time, remembering the discussion with the endocrinologist, if I was almost able to kill myself by mismanaging my emotions, I might be able to go beyond the diagnosis of science if I get the control of my emotions back.
At this time, luck played its role. I found a book called, "The power of the present moment", written by the Canadian philosopher Eckhart Tolle.
This book was revealing and encouraged me to approach a master of Zen meditation, will accompanied me for several years.
This way of life has accompanied me and still accompanies me. It has now been 20 years.
I must say that the results are quite amazing: I have never been depressed.
I usually run almost 15 km per week.
I have very often climbed more than 4,000 metres in the Alps.
In April 2005, I reached 6,000 meters in the massif of Annapurna.
I am not a superman at all, but you can't be depressive to do this kind of thing.
So much for sterility, two solid guys came to expand the family circle a few years after the operation.
More surprising for medicine, I have been successful in giving up all this medication over the years.
I am therefore a mystery for medicine because I live without a pituitary gland and without any hormone treatment.
The good news is perhaps not so much being in better health at 50 years old than when I was 30.
The good news for me is the interior path inside, the inner transformation endured or traveled, throughout this whole path of reconstruction and this new state of consciousness.
Very quickly after my release from the hospital, as a Cartesian and rational man, I wanted to understand what the endocrinologist had told me, this link between my thoughts and my cellular system, between my emotions and my immune system.
I very quickly read everything I could find and met the best experts in three specific areas: cellular biology, understanding the intelligence of cells, an area called psycho-immuno-neurology, the study of the placebo effect, then quantum physics, to understand what is happening in the depths of my being, in the depths of my cells, my atoms, in the infinitely small world.
In this scientific quest, something absolutely incredible happened to me: I discovered with great amazement that the border separating physics from metaphysics, the science of philosophies, was as narrow as cigarette paper.
This was an unexpected discussion with an assistant of a former Nobel Prize winner in physics, which I must say, lit the wick.
She said to me, "The professor would always look for his inspiration in Aotse, a Chinese philosopher, and father of Taoism."
Having spent time looking at the science, I followed the voice of the masters and I am studying it to understand these teachings of wisdom from the dawn of time to today, from Pythagoras to the Dalai Lama, revisiting all the mystical voices; the cabal, Sufism, or the Apocrypha, to understand what there is beyond dogmas.
At the meeting point between these two approaches, science and consciousness, I have found a meaning to my life and especially I found answers to the fundamental questions:
who is man, what is he doing on Earth
and how must he live there.
This understanding and personal truth have profoundly changed my way of looking at our planet, our world, but myself as a man, but especially as a leader.
It was at this moment that it occurred to me as obvious that our economic model was all wrong, something that had become a cannibal and suicidal economic model.
It is also at this time that it was obvious to me that the purpose of a company was not the maximization of profit, even through it is essential to pay salaries and the R&amp;D, but the true purpose of a business is the creation of shared values between all stakeholders.
If I said this ten years ago, my model shareholder wouldn't have listened.
This was high time I brought the homo sapient I was and the homo economicus I incarnated on a daily basis.
I left the company, but not the business world.
I wanted to accompany the directors, the companies, and shareholders, to help them to implement a philosophy to reconcile three words: economy, ecology, and meaning.
This was not a wishful thinking. It is very practical, very pragmatic.
I have in mind a speech I made not so long ago, for a world leader in the field of drinks, a multinational company that covers the entire globe, the theme of the evening for which I had to speak was,
"Does it pay to do good?"
The answer is definitely yes.
This company which had already undertaken work on the management of water and waste over 5 years, simply considering the environmental problems, managed to reduce water consumption by the equivalent of 25 billion cans and had generated $420 million only by finding new markets for the waste they produced.
This is my world, my life; accompanying people, entrepreneurs, small and large businesses, all innovating and finding solutions to build a better world.
Recently, on my way home from Amazon where I had been with entrepreneurs and Indian people to reflect on the problems of economy and ecology in the forest. Something obvious occurred to me: our world is at a crossroads.
A world is dying and a new world is being born.
And a new world is being born, building on what I call a regenerative economy.
What is a regenerative economy?
It is an economy which firstly is relocated, realigned on its fundamentals, namely food and energy.
It is bringing production close to consumption.
For energy, just think about all these phenomena that bloom everywhere in the world of urban agriculture.
There are emerging vertical farms, green roofs becoming covered, and market gardening in cities.
You must know that in a city like Paris, if you cut off the supply chains, the food life expectancy is about 4 days.
Therefore, this relocating is a very important issue.
Same thing for energy. You have only to open a newspaper or listen to good programs to realize that buildings are going up everywhere in the construction world.
There are buildings that produce more electricity than they consume.
This is the first point for a regenerative economy, therefore a relocated economy.
The second point is what is called a collaborative economy.
No long speeches. You all know that. These are phenomena of Wiki, open sources. Internet platforms, that allow discussions between consumers and individuals, loans between individuals. This is called crowdfunding, or even more simply, it is the economy of sharing, exactly like Velib.
Talking about Velib, this brings me to the third point of a regenerative economy.
It is an economy of use and not ownership.
Fundamentally, we do not need to own all the objects we hold.
Very often, we need to have the use of the solutions they offer.
You do not need to own your fridge.
You need a solution for making coldness.
If the manufacturer integrates that idea, he will no longer build in planned obsolescence into the machine you bought. He will find a way to recycle the parts of the machine infinitely.
This brings us to the fourth component of a regenerative economy. It is a circular economy, where the waste of one person is fuel for the other, where raw materials are infinitely recyclable.
This is not a dream, is already the case at 92% in the automotive industry.
With a good look at this, this emerging regenerative economy is a bio-inspired economy.
Perhaps the idea came to me precisely in contact with nature in the Amazon.
Bio-inspired. Why?
Because, fundamentally, nature is local, collaborative, the trees can't grow without the presence of fungi. It uses and does not own. It recycles everything.
Indeed, I think that one world is dying, and another is being born.
To illustrate this last point, I would like to tell you about a conversation I had a few years ago with a Sufi master in the Middle East.
I interviewed this master about the symbolism represented by the tsunami on 24th December 2004 that swept the Asian coasts taking hundreds of thousands of lives.
The master said this to me, "The Earth will give birth to a new world.
What you see here is the loss of water.
You will see contractions appearing in the next few years."
I have always kept this in mind.
Especially since 2008, crises have followed each other again and again and with unprecedented magnitude.
So yes, a world is being born.
There are enough women in the audience this evening to know that a birth brings hope, but it is also a source of pain and uncertainty.
The question we are asked today is basically this one, "Do we want to be the one who gives life, or the one who looks on in the hope that things will go for the best."
Your presence here tonight makes me believe that you have already made a decision.
Thank you.
(Applause)
My work, normally, is not talking but photographing.
I express myself through my pictures.
Well, this evening for once, I'm going to talk about these pictures, actually I'm mostly going to talk about those who initiated them.
This building is on "Place des Fêtes" in Paris' 19th arrondissement.
It's an old hotel school, shut down several years ago.
It's located a block from my place.
Those I'm going to talk about are therefore like my neighbours.
Being separated by a block is nothing.
Yet that is enough to not see each other.
For several months, the school had been occupied by hundreds of migrants and I didn't know.
Incidentally, it's through a Facebook post that I learnt that these people were there, in need.
They were two steps away from my place and I found it out on Facebook.
If you know what I mean.
I can't say I wasn't aware of the difficulties encountered by migrants.
I'd already done photo coverages.
My first ones were in late 2002, when the Red-Cross centre in Sangatte was evacuated.
I was of course aware of the flood of migrants in the new Calais jungle.
I learnt that these people needed clothes so initially I went there to bring them some.
At that moment, that is August last year, I was photographing mainly in the field of music.
I had been a TV photo-reporter for a long time.
But I had passed the buck because that way of doing my job didn't suit me.
As a result, I'd therefore given up on what motivated me most, that is to say bearing witness.
When I set foot in that corridor for the first time, I remembered why, one day when I was 21, I'd decided to become a journalist.
Meeting people, giving a chance to be heard, bringing the inhumane to light, shaking up things.
This boy next to me in the picture is called Abdou.
He's one of the first that I met.
He came with a big smile when he saw me cross the school yard for the first time.
Abdou is Sudanese and he had arrived there after a month of struggles, without really knowing what his future would be.
He was far from being the only one in this situation.
Along with him, they were about 700 last summer surviving here at the Jean-Quarré high school.
They came from Sudan, Afghanistan, Eritrea, and they had been pushed there by war, famine, dictatorship, the lack of freedom...
They dreamed of freedom.
Like him.
Abdelhameed Mahmoud.
In Sudan, he was a banker.
He was an activist too.
To save his life, he fled his country, persecuted for his progressive ideas.
I met him on a tense day at the school.
Tempers were high, fights had broken out, so Abdelhameed Mahmoud went to get a table that he put in the middle of the yard and he stood on it to call for calm.
Later he asked me, why are you taking pictures?
If I didn't share that moment, tomorrow this building would be refurbished, its occupants would be gone and for many, they would never have existed.
Apart from a few residents who would maybe remember.
We couldn't accept that people live in these conditions.
That now that I had seen, it was my duty to show.
Taking pictures was my expertise, I was not a doctor, nor a teacher, I was a photographer.
I spent a month with a journalist friend going there regularly, gathering evidence.
I saw people gritting their teeth bravely facing daily hardship and an uncertain future.
I saw kids too living their kids' life, playing ball.
I saw eyes full of hope, others dull, others still angry.
I replied, "How is it to live in France?" I listened to how it is to live in Darfur or Kabul.
I visualised journeys, shipwrecks, like that of Abdou whose boat capsized.
And then I photographed sometimes.
Not always though.
I explained that photographing is not a lack of respect.
On the contrary, photographing is an acknowledgement of the inhumanity which they are living.
You need to be able to show to shake things up.
Seeing the invisible, is taking the responsibility of having to think about it, being able to discuss it, trying to help or on the contrary being comfortable with not doing so.
It's already a possibility to break the silence.
After a month of regularly visiting the occupants of the Jean-Quarré school, one morning of October, it was evacuated.
Calmly, they got onto buses towards a different future.
The building has now been refurbished and it welcomes asylum-seekers in good conditions.
And then, I was contacted to continue this work in Calais.
On this territory that you know as the Jungle, they are not 700 but 6000: a town within the town, or rather a slum that shot up in the industrial estate, stuck between the ring-road and the "Seveso" sites.
The Jungle is neighbourhoods, streets, living places, cult places, schools.
It's also a forced cohabitation between the people of Calais and these people in transit who dream of England.
Months, years of cohabitation and interrogations, of solidarity too and of despair.
It's true, it's impressive. Day and night,
they walk along the roads, dark hoods on their heads, bundles in their hands.
Some people of Calais refer to them as ghosts they are scared of.
However, I promise you this kid is nothing like a ghost.
His name is Everest.
We bumped into each other in the corner of a muddy street one day in December.
Seeing me taking pictures, he came closer and asked me, "Can you tell my future for me?" Everest comes from Kirkuk in Iraq, he is a Christian and he and his parents left everything under the threat of Daesh.
Like any other kid, he has dreams, and he told me in perfect English, "One day, I will be a teacher in England." When you go into the Jungle, you will often be invited in for a cup of tea, for a chat, to share a moment of music. And there you realise that nothing
differentiates you from your hosts.
You realise that sometimes you are the same age, that you have sometimes studied the same thing.
You talk photography with someone whose job it is too.
Nothing differentiates us from the inhabitants of the Jungle.
Except of course circumstances.
Except a culture, a religion, a language, these differences that we can also call riches.
Realising that, the apprehension leaves place to the curiosity.
Talking to whom has crossed seas and borders to escape disgraceful living conditions, is putting a reality to televised images.
Like this family that comes from Mosul in Iraq.
The parents and their triplets finally managed to get to England, after living all winter in the Jungle.
Talking to them is also asking oneself questions: could we live like that?
Would we have the strength to stay at home or would we take the path of exile to save our children, our lives?
To each their answer.
I don't know mine.
I think that it is impossible to know it as long as one isn't faced with the brutal question that backs you against the wall.
Is it possible to reply before the wall falls down on our head?
Not sure...
But don't let that stop us from thinking about it.
Youssef, the kid on the poster, was 16.
He died run over by a van when he was trying to get to England.
A tragic accident that is nothing out of the ordinary unfortunately.
But, that day, there were lots of them: migrants and activists wanting to walk in his memory.
Black on white, held by waving arms, they shouted in silence.
We are humans, not dogs.
No to racism.
Yes to justice.
No to terrorism.
Standing, settled with their dignity, they faced the police: face to face for acknowledgement.
Seeing the invisible.
Photography helps me with that.
Incidentally with film, if you've already shot the picture, you know that the paper stays immaculate as long as it hasn't been through a developing bath.
The developing bath makes it possible to see the invisible.
For me, in a global perspective, the photographic tool is itself the revealer without which my eye cannot see certain situations.
My camera helps me to break the reserved state that sometimes stops me from being curious about others.
To each their conveyor, photographing is mine.
It's that little bit of experience and reflexion that I wanted to bring you this evening.
Finding one's conveyor, being curious, seeing.
Thank you.
(Applause)
Can you imagine the Renaissance without Leonardo da Vinci or Michelangelo?
We are living today a transformation of society, of civilization, a third Industrial Revolution, of Anthropocene, of a transition to the Post-Carbon era...
But where is the artistic movement?
Where are the artists who follow this second Renaissance?
Every period, every such transformation, has been preceded, followed by artistic movements: Impressionism, the Pre-Raphaelites, Dada who was born with WWI.
These are the questions I asked myself at the turn of the century. I was working at the French State Bank launching an innovative center dedicated to sustainable development.
And everywhere I would read the term "stakeholders", stakeholders who represent civil society and who, if we listen to them, permit to understand social and environmental issues.
And I was very surprised, among these stakeholders, to find only NGOs, sometimes labor unions.
I was surprised not to find artists among these stakeholders.
Are not artists precisely the representatives of civil society?
They are beholden to no one rather, they act in the general interest.
They impart visions and values.
They are often catalysts of new paradigms.
And I realized that in this realm of sustainable development and the environment, there was very little talk about art and culture.
Sometimes contemporary art was even considered as a new extension of capitalism and vice versa, in the art world, there was little talk of environmental concerns.
A phenomenon as important as climate change wasn't much present and sustainable development tended to be perceived as an oxymoron, and ecology as an area of political activism, or even as an old hippy trip.
And it's true that the driftwood sculptures of the 70's were the subject of scorn in New York.
So there was a gap and I told myself that something had to be done.
I organized the first international symposium, with the artist as a stakeholder.
In that view, with UNESCO, we conducted the first search for artists working on themes related to sustainable development with a focus on the environment, essentially visual artists.
And now you are going to see images that will show you the wealth of discoveries we have made, from then until today.
Behind these images, you have artists who are much less attached to the notion of creating art in isolation rather than acting, being on the field, in collaboration with stakeholders, other players, being in the transition, and you have artists who convey this future world, with sometimes extremely original ideas.
To resurrect seeds from the Viking Age, saying that precisely they will be the feeding solutions to adapt to global warming.
Or to also invent recipes to eat insects, another solution for adapting to climate change.
To buy permits to pollute, to create solar lights, imagine new ways of moving, adopt a square meter of the Amazon rain forest, extremely original and abundant ideas which are the proof that artists are into innovation, into solutions, much more than into condemnation.
The next step was to start an association with a landscaper, a curator and a philosopher, who then organized for several years a prize dedicated to contemporary art and the environment.
We organized exhibitions, and we have, again, found a lot of solutions, artists, and we managed an extra step in a dialogue that was extremely nascent between the world of sustainability and contemporary art.
And during those six years we spent doing that, other revolutions appeared.
And in 2014, they threw me off balance.
There had been the rise of the social and solidarity economy, and the figure of the social entrepreneur, who is in social transformation, too, seemed to me extremely powerful.
In the meantime, there has been the creation of movements by young people in the whole world who really were a lot more innovative than what the traditional NGOs to mobilize on the subject.
For example, the Climates association which created COP in MyCity, where everyone performs a role play in which they take the place of a negotiator and simulate climate conferences.
There was also the collaborative economy, peer-to-peer, open data, a lot of movements which showed that there was a transformation going on.
But social entrepreneurs, artists and these young innovators worked very independently.
They did not know each other.
Sustainable development means acting together; so I had the idea to create their meeting.
And I founded Art of Change 21, the art of change of the 21st century, 21 like COP 21, which was on its way.
When I launched this initiative, France was about to host this great event.
And like the 21 actors that I went to look for, to discover around the world, young people, entrepreneurs, artists to bring them together in this project.
From Brazil to China through the United States, Bahrain, New Zealand, Kenya.
I invited 21 of those actors to Paris, in an event called the Conclave.
They were locked up for two days and they played the game, not to be in a competition, not to highlight their own projects, not to chose the best project among theirs, but to exchange and imagine together, as a result of their collaboration, ideas for actions.
What sustainable development brings to creation is co-creation.
Four ideas emerged from this exchange, and the great artist Olafur Eliasson, whose images you have seen in this small panorama that I just showed you, agreed to be the patron of this initiative together with social entrepreneur Tristan Lecomte.
So among these four actions, I want to talk to you about one of them, Maskbook.
Maskbook, you see behind you, by a Chinese artist named Wen Fang.
She was just telling us about her life in Beijing where she has to wear an anti-pollution mask.
She said, "In China, we do not have Facebook.
Anyway, since we all wear anti-pollution masks, it should be called Maskbook."
And we had the idea to turn around the anxiety inducing image of this anti-pollution mask and make it an expressive medium for everyone: such masks could be created using each and every one's creative talents, with recycling, DIY, we also mobilized makers, we did it on 3D printers, in 3D scan.
We also invented, from a means as small as a mask, a way to communicate solutions conveyed by each and every one.
We launched this project for the Paris Climate Conference, we collected thousands of masks, we had an exhibition in Beijing, in Paris at the Grand Palais, we organized dozens of workshops to precisely introduce to the [circular] economy the different ways we have, using this tiny bit of material, of fabric or whatever else, to do something and to act on the pollution-climate change link, which concerns us all: global warming will accelerate the effect of pollution in our health.
This is the example of action that comes from this interaction, that does not question whether it is a work of art or not, which is addressed to all, and, of course, I invite you all to create your portrait on Maskbook.
But we will not stop there.
I will not just ask you to take part in an initiative like Maskbook, via workshops or a mobile application that we will launch with the United Nations at the end of the month.
I want to ask you more, Why?
Some of us have already heard over a thousand times Gandhi's words, "Be yourself the change you want to see in the world."
I personally prefer that of the artist Joseph Beuys, who said, "Each man is an artist."
Today our creativity is at stake.
If we do not change, if we do not invent a world different from ours, it will become unliveable.
What is at stake is our ability to create a new world, with new ways to eat, to move, to rethink our hobbies, our work, and for that, your creativity is essential.
All together, using our creativity, adding it to our neighbour’s, we can create a universal creativity that would allow us to succeed in this challenge of necessary change, to become ourselves actors of change, in order to avoid the foretold collapses, which are our conditions of living and well-being on Earth.
And at this crucial moment, when everyone's creativity is at stake, artists are our allies, they are our torchbearers.
If we connect to them, we will be touched by their ingenuity they will pass on their "virus" to us to change the world.
If we connect to their imagination, they will tell us that nothing is impossible.
Artists are our best chance.
Thank you.
(Applause)
Hello. I have always wanted to create a company.
It's true, I am a designer.
I create things every day, lots of things.
But how did I go from being a designer to being an entrepreneur?
And how did design help me on my adventure?
Entrepreneurship is an adventure, it's a journey.
And in my case, it starts in Paris, in 2004, 10 years ago.
I just graduated with a master's in design, and I start working.
I have different clients and I'm with my significant other, Emilie who is a physiotherapist. This is my life until the year 2006.
At the end of that year we've had enough.
We decide to change our lives, we want to see something else.
We tell ourselves that we can't live this way our whole lives.
That's when we changed the course of our lives.
Destination: Australia.
Why not after all?
And so we get to the other side of the planet, and we discover a wonderful country quite the opposite of what we were living.
But we had a goal: on our way to Australia, we had told each other it would be great to cross the desert.
And so we get to the desert.
It took one and a half months 12,500 kilometers, 600 kilometers per day.
You have to realize that there is nothing to do, absolutely nothing.
It's quite disturbing, we drive and drive and drive.
There is nothing to see, nothing to do, no one to talk to.
It's just us two, we're together, it's a good thing we get along.
Actually it helps to forge one's relationship, to test things.
And so, during this journey, we only have one thing to do, it's to think.
And we thought a lot.
A lot, a lot, a lot.
On one hand, paradoxically, we thought a lot and emptied ourselves completely.
We forget everything, we have no concept of time, no time schedule, no restriction, we have nothing.
And it's an almost initiatory feeling.
For us, it was an experience that has marked us for life.
I admit that I probably wouldn't do it again.
It's true, looking back there were a few struggles, but the point is that we learned to stay still, we cleared our minds, and we found it awesome.
And then our little Australian tour was over, we stopped for a while in Sidney, and that's where we discovered a cool concept.
We thought it was great, it was blended fresh fruit, colorful; in other words, smoothies.
Today everyone knows what smoothies are, but back then they didn't exist in France.
And that's when we told ourselves, "It tastes good, it's fresh, it's colorful, easy to make. Let's do it, we go back to France, and we open up a smoothie bar."
And so it all starts.
And we go back to France, destination -
We don't really know where to settle down.
In Clermont-Ferrand.
Why Clermont-Ferrand?
I was born in Clermont-Ferrand, Emilie was born there too, but she never lived there.
And so for us, in contrast to what we lived in the desert, arriving in Clermont-Ferrand allowed us to reconnect with our roots, fundamentally.
We have family there, we have landscapes, the view speaks for itself, and for us it's truly a new beginning.
We still held on to our smoothie idea
so we don't really know how ideas develop.
However, we know that an idea can form a project.
And we, from a smoothie, developed a whole restaurant.
An organic restaurant with quick and healthy meals.
Well, that was the plan.
And we wanted to change the concept of packaging for this restaurant,
because today, plain and simple, packaging is used and overused.
We thought we would make a small ecological gesture, especially since we learned in the desert not to throw things away.
So we continue to follow this as our concept, then, while researching package replacement we discover the bento idea.
What is bento?
It is a traditional Japanese meal box which is used in Japan for centuries now.
It is used to carry around your meal.
That's when we told ourselves, that's it.
It's great, we should add it to our concept, it fits; our concept is ready, here we go.
Then we realize, the whole project, catering isn't really our career, it has to be said.
So we had the smoothies, but we can't feed people with smoothies, the idea had become something else.
We therefore asked ourselves, "What should we do?
We don't have money, we've never worked in catering.
Never mind, we'll put the project on hold for a while."
However, Emilie, who is a physiotherapist, uses her bento box everyday.
Yes, she has a fundamental need: she works all day, she's in the car, she sees many patients, and has no time to stop and eat.
That's why the bento box is ideal.
It fits her need: eating healthy, quickly, while transporting her meals without it having to be a sandwich everyday.
Great.
Then she tells me, "This is great.
It really fits my needs."
She shows her friends, who confirm the idea is great.
They tell her, "Well, the bento box is a great idea, I would like to have one.
The problem is, we can't find any."
So Emilie says to herself, we should go find some, and sell them to people.
I tell her, "Yes, it's a good idea.
Let's do it."
In March 2009, we founded the company which would import and distribute the bento.
And that's where it's important to understand that creation is an ongoing process, it is a constant evolution.
You need to know how to seize opportunities.
Essentially, innovation is yielded out of a need or out by chance.
For me, the need was simple: the bento box needed to be reinvented.
Indeed, as there were many types of bento boxes available on the Japanese market.
However, I'm a designer, I really wanted to create my own product, with my values, which later on, became our values.
And so, we see that we went from a smoothie to a restaurant to a bento box, and then to e-commerce, because we wanted to distribute them.
And then, from an e-commerce website we became a brand with its own products.
I must confess,
there we encountered some issues.
Let's get back to the creation of our company.
There were three main issues.
We identified the first one: looking for suppliers.
At that moment, you can imagine how confused we were with this sort of pages.
We don't speak Japanese, and the Japanese don't speak English.
So it is hard to get to communicate.
But still, somehow, Emilie, armed with courage and stubbornness - which I can testify - eventually gets in touch and puts together a small pool of suppliers.
So we say great, we have our suppliers.
The second trouble we identified was the logistics.
Many entrepreneurs said, "We started in our garage."
But you still need a garage.
We only had a studio, so we kept piling up the boxes in the studio.
Then the third issue,
well, it was the banks.
Yes, the banks. Now we've heard it all.
A woman as a CEO.
A designer not very well-grounded.
A website? What is the web?

Isn't it too risky?
A Japanese product, without any market study.
And it doesn't exist.
Let's just say that the banks were out.
So, we had a personal contribution, technically speaking.
We had some money, but we still needed some more to take the project all the way.
And no bank, no one lent us money.
This was a bit dramatic. but we kept our chins up. and turned towards family. In those cases, we usually ask our relatives.
Then we found a great solution.
We asked Emilie's brother, - a student back then - to make a student loan.
(Laughter) Well, it turned out to be a great idea, as the rate was exceptional.
So we got the money, and made a great deal at the same time.
Well, to do this, you need a student brother who's willing to lend you money.
But still, I confess.
First of all, it was very kind from him, and it helped us to really get into it.
On the other hand, we're mad at no one because all these people allowed us to be motivated.
It is important, as people usually consider that to be creative you need no boundaries.
And boundaries make us look for ideas, go for it and be motivated.
That is what we learned so we are mad at no one.
We eventually started our business, of course, and then, what strategy can we choose?
Our strategy was simple.
We didn't have lots of money, so we decided to invest it all in public relations.
It was a bet. And it worked.
PRs talk about it
because they love the product.
They ride the bento-wave, of a societal need.
And from a word which was unknown five years ago, it now enters the dictionary.
Challenge met.
At that time, we had identified our target somehow as a woman, 35 years old, Parisian, who likes new things and then, we came to selling to everyone all across France.
This is the advantage of the Internet, getting all the feedback.
So there we are, selling to everyone; people like the product, the brand, they match a real necessity.
So we tell each other: well, that's great.
And then, our success our expectations to such an extent that the Japanese bought our products.
It even became our first market.
Who would have believed it?
Who would have guessed it at the beginning?
I remember the bankers who mentioned Clermont -Ferrand.
I always remember that moment.
So we are really happy.
Which leads me to tell you one thing today:
you can start from scratch, have many wishes.
Emilie and I, physiotherapist and designer, we managed to create our company, to attract consumers all over the world.
Today, it represents 20 people in Clermont-Ferrand, four subsidiaries and export branches in more than 40 countries.
So what I wanted to tell you is that even without a garage, you can still create your company.
Thank you.
(Applause)
We would all love to have an elephant memory.
We would all love to remember the birthdays of our close ones, not forget our schedules, or this so-called list of errands, and better still, no longer need them.
We are all concerned by these oversights that occur in our everyday life.
I imagine some of you have experienced this moment where, in a parking lot, you can no longer remember where you have parked your car.
I imagine that I am not the only to have heard "Mom, you forgot my soccer shoes!" or to no longer be able to remember the name of this person who is waving at me on the other side of the road.
So we use all kinds of digital tools to reassure us, cellphones, tablets, that are real memory prostheses.
And we bring them everywhere.
We see them at school.
We see them in restaurants.
And we even see them in the TEDx's conference rooms.
We are longing for these tools because they are able to keep record of everything.
I am a researcher at EMC, a lab for the study of cognitive mechanisms, and I would like to reconcile you with your memory.
I would like to explain to you that forgetfulness is necessary
So, how does memory work?
if you agree, in order to explain to you how it works, I would like to subject you to a few short exercises.
First, let's set up special conditions since, to do these exercises, you don't have the right to note anything whether on paper or on your phones.
We are going to try to perform them from memory.
First, I would like you to listen attentively to the series of numbers I'm going to give you and try to repeat them after me, in the same order and at the same speed.
Are you ready?
(Audience): Yes.
"Six, four, three, nine."
(Audience): Six, four, three, nine.
It's going well.
Another : "Eight, five, seven, three, two, eight."
(Audience): Eight, five, seven, three, two, eight.
Actually, there are many good elephant memories!
Let's keep going.
"One, two, zero, five. one, nine, seven, three."
(Audience): One, two, zero, five, one ... neuf ... (Laughter) Well, after all, not so many!
(Laughter) This series is clearly more complicated.
The reason is obvious: there were far too much numbers in this series.
This memory that we have just accessed is called "short term memory."
This memory allows us to retain little information - on average seven - and enables us to keep it for a few seconds, not more than 30 seconds after which, it fades, and it fades naturally.
It would have been easier if I had told you in place of this last series, "one, two, zero, five, one, nine, seven, three," that it was about May 12, 1973.
This system is designed to prevent us from memorizing everything.
It wouldn't make any sense if we were to learn everything.
The first series of numbers I gave you, the one you all succeeded in repeating, do you remember it?
There is one person. Thank you, Mrs.
This series of numbers,
there was no interest in retaining it.
However, if I had told you that it was the code you had to write tonight on your Tax Form to be free of taxes this year, (Laughter) things would have been significantly different.
(Laughter) You would take the time to memorize them.
Because if we don't want this information to fade in 30 seconds, we are required to make a cognitive effort.
This cognitive effort is what we call "long-term memory encoding."
What is encoding?
Well, it's a way to get past the limits of our short-term memory so that informations enter into our long-term memory.
This long-term memory is unlimited in storage duration.
You have memories that are 10, 20, 30, even 40 years old.
So you are all capable of finishing this list of conjunctions. 'For-And-Nor ..." (Audience): "But-Or-Yet-So."
Even if you no longer remember that they are the coordinating conjunctions, this word is in your memory since childhood.
In addition, this long-term memory is unlimited as for the quantity of informations it can contain: sounds, odors, images, the color of your first car, a terrible haircut, the place we found ourselves on September 11, 2001 when the attacks in New York were announced. It is an infinite quantity of informations more of less important.
No phone, as intelligent it may be, could store as much data.
So, let's try to make our long-term memory work.
We are going to take advantage of this magnificent theater and look at the ceiling above us.
Watch it closely.
We are going to try to encode this magnificent fresco that is painted all the way up there, by asking ourselves what these characters are doing and what they are thinking.
It is a delightful game to play when you are sitting at a cafe, looking at people in the street and asking yourself: "Where are they going?
What are they thinking?"
and we bring our attention to them.
Well; that's what we are going to do with these different characters.
We are going to zoom in on some of these special effects.
You can see Apollo who is leaving the sun on his chariot, drawn by three magnificent mad horses.
Put yourself in his place.
What could he be thinking at that moment?
Next to him, we can see Dante, dressed all in red.
He is sitting, and he seems to be wondering.
We could imagine that he is preparing his character's journey, in his work, The Divine Comedy.
Take a good look at him.
A little higher, we have four small angels who seem to be bickering over an object that we can't see very well.
We could imagine that it is a bottle of water that came from the mountains of Auvergne.
And finally, there is another Apollo who is sitting proudly on his cloud while an angel is bringing him a crown of bay leaves.
Imagine what he is thinking at this exact moment.
Now, the painter who created this work up there is called Jules Toulot.
Take a moment to try to memorize his name.
Now to encode information, it is not enough to see or to listen. We must bring our focus on these things.
Focus is an essential element of our memory.
It's the basis of our encoding.
Do you all know the shell game?
It's a street game where someone promises money if you can successfully find back a coin he has hidden under a cup.
You all think it's a scam.
Well, let me show you that if you were very focused, you could reveal the trick.
I invite you to watch this video
and pay close attention to where the coin is.
Keep your eyes on the coin.
We have slowed down the movements to make it easier, but don't get distracted.
Did you all know where was the coin?
Perfect! You were all very attentive,
maybe a little too much!
Because by directing your focus on the cup, you didn't notice that another cup was being replaced by a pepper of the same color, (Laughter) and that this pepper was being moved on the table for several seconds without your knowledge.
Because focusing is precisely that.
When we direct our attention to one thing, we can't focus on anything else.
And if we want to encode correctly, all our attention must be available.
So, building on all these advices, we are now going to try to memorize twelve words, a lot more than your short-term memory.
Focus your attention on each of these words.
Are you ready?
"Pond, rain, estuary, waterfall, confluence, river, torrent, stream, canal, lake, pool, and ocean."
Do you get them all?
So keep them safe in your memory.
Alas, once encoded, the information can still fade.
If we really want to maintain them in our long-term memory, they must be consolidated in it.
A method of consolidating them consists in repeating what you have learned and reviewing it, in other words, encoding them several times.
With each repetition, our memory is strengthened.
It is consolidated.
"Six-four-three-nine, six-four-three-nine, six-four-three-nine."
But there is another very essential thing to the consolidation, it is sleep.
When we sleep, our brain reactivates what we have learned. It's almost like we are going over it but this time without any effort.
This sleeping brain sorts out the newly encoded information.
It organizes those that are important for us and deletes those that are useless.
You've all heard of the benefit of reviewing one's lessons at night just before going to sleep.
Well, we have recently pointed out that the ideal configuration was to interleave periods of sleep between the learning sessions.
Now, don't encourage your children to sleep in class!
(Laughter) So we have been able to show that indeed, it was beneficial to study at night, but that reviewing the lesson, in the morning, upon waking up enables us to remember it for a longer period of time.
So sleeping offers us a double advantage. It enables us to relearn faster and to retain memory much longer.
In other words, it means working less to retain more.
So, once we have done a careful encoding and consolidate the storage by a good night of sleep, the information retrieval, which is the last step of memorization, is going to be a lot easier.
Do you remember the twelve words I said earlier?
Now, let's keep things simple.
How many of you remember the word "river"?
Was it in the list? Raise your hands.


Very good. Was the word "mountain" in it?
(Audience): No.

The word "rain"?
(Audience): Yes.
Raise your hand.
Okay! Was the word "lake" in it?
(Audience): Yes.
Yes ..."Unicorn"?
(Audience): No.
"Conifer"?
(Audience): No.
"River"?
(Audience): Yes ... No. No.
(Laughter)
You do not all agree,
but in fact, "river" was not in it.
And memory is also exactly that.
Memory is not a perfect reproduction of reality, but rather a reconstruction.
A memory is not a photograph but the interpretation of this photograph that we make according to our emotions, according to our knowledge and also our motivation.
I am sure that each of you will remember this afternoon,
but it will be a unique memory that will be perfectly different from your neighbors' one.
Let's go back to this magnificent ceiling.
Please don't lift your eyes.
Can you remember the color of the horses that were pulling Apollo's chariot?
(Audience): White.
Do you remember who wrote "The Divine Comedy"?
(Audience) : Dante.
How many angels fight for this bottle of water from the Alps?
(Confused hubbub) I spoke about Auvergne.
Do you remember the painter's name?
(Audience): Toulot.
Jules Toulot.
I am sure that some of you have even retained the series of four numbers that is useless.
(Laughter) So, in the end, what is memory?
Well, it is all the moments we have been able to capture, all the information on which we have focused our attention, and those that have affected us.
When you will be sitting at a sidewalk cafe, your eyes riveted on your cellphones, think again about your memory.
Put down your phone and look around you. Then ask yourself,
"Where are these people going?
What are they thinking?"
Take the time to pay attention to your current experience so that you give it the opportunity to leave a trace in your memory, and after this, sleep!
(Applause)
There are 7.3 billion of us on Earth.
There are 3.7 billion web users, and among them, 87% use social networks every month.
Some use them to follow the news, others to play Candy Crush, or even, to find a long-lost childhood friend.
As for me, Facebook enabled me to find my biological family.
My name is Gabriella, I am 20 years old and this is my story.
I was born in 1995, in Bogota, Colombia. Four months after my birth, I was adopted by a Franco-Colombian couple.
I had a peaceful childhood with the arrival of a brother two years later.
We are incredibly close.
I am one of those adopted and "lucky" children.
I didn't lose my dual culture, or my native language. My adoptive mother is Colombian.
You must have all wondered who you looked like when you were younger.
And if you didn't think about it, there was always a caring friend or the baker from around the corner, who looked for a resemblance with your parents.
So, you just needed to go up to the attic, to delve into the family photo albums for an hour or two to find the answer.
At around ten years old, I had my first science lesson. We were studying heredity.
The girl to my right told me, "I have my mother's hair."
And the boy to my left told me, "I have my father's eye colour."
And that evening, I went home and I asked my adoptive mother, "Me, who do I look like?"
These are some questions I asked myself as a child, and to which I only got answers when I became an adult.
Colombian law obliges us to wait till adulthood to begin this research.
I patiently waited for my 18th birthday, that arrived very quickly.
I remember, all my friends were waiting for something: to go to a nightclub for the first time, to get their driver's licence. Me? I was only thinking of one thing: finding my biological family.
I started, like many adopted children, by contacting the Colombian social services and the institution I came from.
A month later, two days before Christmas, I received a file, an eight-page file.
This file related my birth, my past, and there was my biological mother's identity.
So you can imagine our Christmas that year.
I had some answers but other questions emerged.
What did she look like?
My head was telling me not to continue this research because it would disrupt my life and my law studies, but my heart was telling me one thing, "What are waiting for? Go for it!"
You've probably guessed,
curiosity got the better of me, and I continued my research.
So I re-contacted the Colombian social services.
If some of you think that French administration is slow, don't go to Colombia.
Add the seven-hour time difference to it, minutes were hours, hours were days.
Two months later, still no news from the Colombian social services.
So I thought of other ways to find my biological family.
I had a surname, a first name, a town, and an approximate age.
So I thought of Facebook, but it seemed so crazy to find my biological mother on Facebook.
And yet, I did.
For a week I looked through profiles and I finally found a profile that fit.
Here's Diana.
She is now 36.
Thank you Facebook, but what was I going to do now?
I had the profile before me, on this Febuary evening, I was overwhelmed.
What would you have done?
Should I friend her, poke her?

We are never prepared.
I decided to send her a friend request.
I was sure she would accept, or even send me a message.
She didn't, because she didn't understand who I was straight away.
I decided to be brave and to send her a message: "I was born on the ninth of November, 1995, in Colombia, under the name Louisa."
And she answered, "I know who you are."
And the emotions translated into capital letters.
She told me how much she thought of me, how much she thought of me on each birthday, how much she regretted her decision.
I held back and I let her write bit by bit the pages of our new story.
Bit by bit, we wrote to each other, we got to know each other.
My first words were to tell her that I'm okay, that I live in France, that I have loving parents, that I'm studying, and that she mustn't regret her decision.
If Facebook had not existed, I would probably have found her address, written her a letter, sent it to her.
This letter may have arrived in three weeks or three months, or may not have arrived at all.
So, I discover that I have a sister, a year older than me.
My sister discovered my existence when she was ten.
My sister, throughout her childhood and adolescence imagined a sister out there, living on a different continent.
Alive or not, she didn't know.
Bit by bit, we talked; through Facebook, we got to know each other.
And the more the weeks went by, the more I wanted to put a face, words, and a voice to these two people I cared for.
We decided to move to Skype, the same tool that is used by families and friends, to keep in touch during holidays.
Me, I used it to hear the voices of my biological mother and sister for the first time after an 18 year separation.
During our first Skype chat with my sister, this encounter seemed unreal to me.
We looked like each other, we cried, we laughed at the same time.
We looked for a physical ressemblance, we compared the shape of our eyes, our laughter.
We were happy to be able to enjoy the opportunity that life gave us to find each other.
I heard Diana's voice for the first time, I finally put a face and a voice to this woman who carried me for nine months.
Through these Skype calls, I decided to travel to Colombia to meet them.
I organised this trip with my adoptive parents.
Together, we looked for the best place to meet Diana.
So, we thought of the institution I came from.
It was a way to end this bad chapter for her, with a beautiful reunion.
I decided to make this trip alone, because it's a purely personal quest.
The day of departure and the 11-hour flight arrived quickly.
I had already made this trip with my family.
With my brother, we made a habit of eating everything that was free, of watching as many films as possible, and of sleeping.
This time, I spent the 11-hour flight without eating or watching a film, and I did a lot of thinking.
I tried to imagine this first encounter with Diana.
Before leaving, I had organised my trip and the first few days, as I like to do, and the day of my meeting with Diana arrived very quickly.
That morning, I woke up early, I went to the institution early to meet with a psychologist and to prepare this encounter with Diana.
So imagine a building with three floors with wide corridors, and in these wide corridors, there were frames.
In these frames, there were a dozen photos.
None were duplicated.
What was the probability, that in leaving the psychologist's office, a frame would catch my eye?
That a photo would catch my eye?
That this photo was of a young couple 18 years earlier, with a baby of four months in their arms?

A tiny probability, and yet, it happened.
A few minutes later, I would be with the woman who began this story, and I knew that my parents, thousands of kilometres away, were with me and were thinking of me.
I was to meet Diana in the room where my parents received me.
This time, I actually had to face, I couldn't... I couldn't duck out of it and blame it on a bad internet connection.
Diana was in front of me, she was smiling, she was beautiful, and we were relaxed in meeting each other.
You're never prepared for an encounter with your biological mother.
Do you shake her hand, kiss her, or do you take her in your arms?
Everything happened very naturally.
And her first words were, "You have the same eyes as the day I left you." I was faced with a stranger
and yet I owed her my life.
So we sat down and we talked, we got to know each other and we talked about our shared past.
The day I met my sister for the first time, we became inseparable.
We laughed, we had a rapport, and we spend hours and hours talking about our 18 years: our first loves, our first experiences, our first travels.
I was again faced with a culture shock.
My sister is 21 years old and she already has two children.
My trip to Colombia went very fast, I got to know my new family, even though I missed my adoptive family.
Today, and two years after my trip to Colombia, I'm teaching my sister French so she can come to Europe and make a fresh start.
I have a good relationship with Diana thanks to the internet.
Nowadays, many of us seize the opportunity of social networks to find someone we care about.
Lorean and Yaqueline are two Colombian sisters, adopted by two different families.
They lost their biological parents during a mud slide in Colombia, that killed hundreds of people.
They found each other thirty years after their loss, thanks to a Facebook video one of them shared in order to find her sister.
Since the launch of social networks, people are searching, especially the children of parents unknown.
Hundreds and hundreds of children are looking for their biological mother thanks to Facebook.
And, like me, they want to find their origins, to know where they come from, to know their biological mother.
But will the biological mothers who gave birth anonymously be able to keep this legal anonymity?
I've been trying to write a book for two years, and in my book, I want to question the prejudices that we so often have regarding adoption.
No, it isn't charity.
No, it isn't an act that should only create unease.
On the contrary, I'm not scared to say that I am the fruit of two destinies of love; it's the proof of love.
I'm also here to testify to the magic of social networks.
This tool doesn't just deal with data, or calculations, it is used to make paths that life seperated, cross again.
Thank you.
(Applause)
(Video, Arab) Narrator:
Hello! I am Mahmoud Ezzo from the Dheisheh refugee camp in Bethlehem.
I am 17 years old.
People usually try to embellish the apartheid wall but for me and many others, the wall is one of the dirtiest intentions and structures in the world.
Because of that, to express my rejection of the idea, I painted the wall and wrote the names of the martyrs from where I live, the names of the displaced villages in 1948 and 1967, and the names of the Palestinian camps in Palestine and abroad.
Thanks. (Video ends)
Raquel Vidal: Bruna, do you remember our second day in Palestine?
I remember it like it was yesterday.
It was the first time we left the refugee camp to walk around and discover the surroundings of Bethlehem.
We drove down the main street,
she explained the peculiarities of the city and she even showed us the Banksy graffitis.
But you know, what struck me the most, is what we saw when we stopped.
Do you remember,
in front of the gas station?
We went alongside it, observed it, contemplated and even photographed it!
There was graffiti everywhere, made by internationals to denounce and raise awareness about the Israeli occupation.
It was colorful, contrasted with hope and despair intertwined.
There, facing it, facing the wall, 700 km long and 8 meters high, I remember: we found it beautiful.
Bruna Perestrelo: But something sounds false... What do you know about Palestine?
Have you forgotten about it?
Tonight, our voice resonates with the name of this young Palestinian.
We met him during our stay in the Dheisheh refugee camp in the West Bank.
During an art workshop, the teenager wanted to present his painting in order to describe his reality.
RV: But what reality are we talking about exactly?
Palestine now is only 8% of what it was 71 years ago.
Population transfers are still ongoing and have been since the late 1940s, as a result of Israel's founding on the Palestinian territory.
Still to this day, Palestinian refugees represent the largest category of refugees in the world!
The Palestinian question can't be tackled without the question of refugees.
BP: At least 3/4 of Palestinians in the world are forcibly displaced.
Since 2014, half a million Palestinians have been forced to leave Gaza.
The United Nations already announced that if the situation does not improve, Gaza will be, I quote: "uninhabitable, unsuitable for human life, in 2020".
We see from these numbers that the humanitarian crisis in Palestine transcends generations.
But how come we found this wall beautiful?
Palestinians know their reality well enough so the international community doesn’t need to remind them about it.
Maybe, the paintings happen to be on the wrong side.
RV: We chose to present to you this photograph and drawing, not only to raise Palestinian voices that we hear seldomly, but also, above all, to introduce a concept that is both ordinary and frustrating: that of normalization.
BP: It is also known as cognitive dissonance.
Each of us searches for a cognitive balance.
It's the balance between our values and our behavior.
When we face a new reality and this balance is broken, we feel tension, an uneasiness that pushes us to try to regain this state of balance.
But since the reality does not change, we adapt our values or behavior to it.
RV: Let's take two examples of everyday life.
How many of you smoke and use the famous phrase: "We will all die of something!"
Or, how many of you always use this excuse at parties: "No, but in moderation it's not that bad."
In the first case, you changed your belief, and in the second, your action.
BP: How many of us pass by their peers and do not see them?
We see homeless people in front of us, and because this reality is unbearable, we either walk straight without staring at them, or we look at them but think they are responsible for their own misery.
RV: Thus, to succeed in confronting this everyday situation, you end up bearing the unbearable, normalizing the abnormal.
BP: We did not realize all of the implications of the drawings on the wall for Palestinians.
Until this young boy took us by surprise and told us, that for him, the wall is a dirty intention and structure.
He uses art to denounce the normalization of his reality.
RV: His reality is that of a camp and an occupation.
In total, there are 58 recognized Palestinian refugee camps.
The camp of this young boy, Dheisheh, intended to accommodate 3,000 people in the middle of the 20th century, now hosts 17,000.
Its density is such that it could be confused with a city.
Indeed, when we saw it for the first time, on a terrace, we couldn't determine where the camp ended and where the neighboring city started.
BP: But something feels wrong.
Why do these camps look so much like cities?
The state relies on camp rehabilitation agencies that have urgently been set up.
It is shifting away from its duty to protect its people and this agency, by necessity, becomes a quasi-state.
Being a refugee should be a short-term perspective but instead humanitarian aid freezes them in time and maintains the status quo.
The non-permanent nature of being a refugee clashes with 71 years of humanitarian aid.
The temporary becomes permanent, the exceptional becomes usual. We normalize.
RV: The purpose of the art workshop was for the children to illustrate what they feel and what they are in this context.
We asked them to draw their daily life, they drew us the occupation.
All the paintings in the exhibition have shown us the same reality: that the minds of the children are occupied by the occupation.
Whether it's through the colors used: which are mostly black, gray and red, or by the themes addressed: violence, martyrs, the right of return, but also, hope.
Faced with this observation, we are constantly asking ourselves the same questions:
Where are the beautiful colors of our childhood?
But where are the sweet dreams of our youth?
The occupation seems to leave no room for innocence.
The new generations are born and grow up in the context of a humanitarian crisis as their only reality.
RV: The normalization of a long-term crisis is dangerous because it maintains the status quo and silences sufferings that should be heard.
Because we consider this situation too complicated to care about it, we end up accepting it.
A situation can be complex, but it is never complicated.
Because hidden underneath are the words "freedom" and "dignity".
But we cannot take empathy for granted, feeling what the other feels is not easy.
BP: So we prefer to think that the world is just what it is, that those people are born in the wrong place at the wrong time,
and so we forget.
Maybe the ultimate phase of the normalization process is forgetting.
Or the two are intertwined and there lies their danger.
In a situation of conflict or crisis, it is always oppressed people against an oppressor,
it is always the liberties that are being fought for.
To normalize this, is to give up on those liberties.
But how do we educate the new generations and make them understand that this situation is not inevitable, that this situation isn't in fact normal?
RV: One of the most beautiful solutions Palestinians found is the non-violent resistance,
especially through education.
It is important for these children to understand they shouldn't be content with living in shame and discrimination.
Cultural centers teach them to resist, to forge their critical spirit, for example through art.
And us? What is our role
in facing normalization?
BP: It is a survival mechanism.
The brain naturally creates mental shortcuts.
The first step is to be aware of it.
When you walk straight in front of someone who needs help, and you instinctively find excuses to not take action, realize what is happening and be aware that you are normalizing the situation of someone whose story you do not know.
RV: When we realized we had glorified a wall that is there to divide two populations, we felt deep despair, we felt deep despair, we... we felt guilty.
BP: But do we have the right to feel discouraged while they are full of hope?
RV: It would be forgetting that our fight is common: our freedom is their freedom.
We must go beyond appearances, feelings and prejudices.
BP: Leaving for a region in perpetual tension is a way of not believing what the media or the people tell us.
We see suffering but resistant people. Humiliated but proud to exist.
RV: Let's contribute to not lose the sensitivity to the world around us.
BP: Let's be conscious individuals. Because all walls, even those of the mind, are made to be overcome.
RV and BP: Thank you.
(Applauses)
[This is not a pipe.]
[This is not a sex toy.]
It is the symbol for a highly political issue and still taboo: female pleasure.
Yes, trust me!
Good afternoon, my name is Christel, and I am the founder of B. Sensory.
B. Sensory is the first app to read erotic contents while connected to a sex toy.
Put plainly, ladies, this app will enable you to read erotic texts on your smartphones or tablets as it synchronizes with a sex toy, triggering it automatically when you read the most torrid passages.
(Laughter) (Applause) And if you don't want to read or no longer feel like reading, you will be able to invite your partner, through this app, to send you much more vibrant messages than usual or to take control of the remote.
(Laughter) A feature, gentlemen, that allows me here to draw your attention and confirm that, yes, you've understood correctly: the fantasy depicted in the comic book 'Click!' by Manara, the little box that enables one to remotely arouse women's desires, is actually about to exist.
(Applause) Very often when I introduce this project, I'm faced very rapidly with the question: 'But how did you come up with this idea?'
Meaning this brilliant, funny, or utterly deplorable idea, depending on who is asking me.
18 minutes won't be enough for me to explain it all, but what you need to keep in mind is that I love words.
When I was six, something tremendous happened to me, which happened to you as well: I learned to read!
Really, it changed my life!
It was my first taste of freedom, a gateway to the possible, and the conviction I would no longer be bored.
When I was 10, I read 'Perfume' by Patrick Süskind, an incredible reading experience!
I was reading the description of the violet and I could actually smell it!
Then I realised how extraordinarily powerful words could be, those words which feed our knowledge, imagination, emotions, but which can also appeal to all our senses.
Something I noticed again when I discovered erotic literature thanks to 'The Blue Bicycle' by Régine Desforges, or 'The Paper Woman' by Françoise Rey, who, 25 years after I read her book, accepted to sponsor me, which I am very proud of!
I also love new technologies - not referring to the way they work, I don't understand a thing, I'm not an engineer but a mere communicator - but to what they enable you to imagine.
That's why, in 2008, when I got the opportunity, I didn't hesitate to dive into the world of start-ups.
The iPhone went on sale in France, people began to speak about the mobile Internet, apps, geolocalisation.
A new digital world was being created,
it was fascinating!
For five years, I provided companies, publishers, with ongoing support in this new playground that kept developing with new opportunities, thanks to 3D-printing, augmented reality, connected objects.
Then, one day, having thought a lot for others, I was having thoughts for myself and about establishing my own start-up, to mix my love for words with technology and imagine something new.
I read a study one day about people not being so keen on reading on their computers as they were unwilling to give up paper, its smell, the whole physical contact thing with books - which I could understand.
But because of my geekish inclinations, I wondered what might be done about it.
How could digital content be used to create real sensations according to what is read, seen, heard?
That's how the concept of sensory digital reading was born.
And as I was keen to start an entrepreneurial adventure, a truly very exciting one, starting with erotic literature was the obvious choice.
I knew it was the beginning of an innovating project - no such platform for connected reading exists - as well as an ambitious one, requiring a major investment and much development. A project, I was told, that was bold, offbeat, even slightly daring,
because, well, it's to do with eroticism and pleasure. But I didn't put any specific militancy into it even though I am a woman, and I am working on a project aimed firstly at women!
I am fortunate enough to have been born in France, to be able to study, to have the right to vote, to drive, to work, to run a business. I was lucky to be able to choose my husband, to have children -
the sort of basic freedoms denied to millions of women throughout the world, ones I'd never felt any need or necessity to ask for.
And I thought that, in 2015, speaking about sexuality, pleasure, could no longer be a problem.
After all, sex is to be found everywhere, in films, ads, TV series, even in the soap 'Plus belle la vie' for those who keep up with events.
Every month, magazines, both for men and women, give very explicit advice to become sex gods or goddesses.
Even the sex toy has had its coming-out and is no longer sold as a face massager to fight wrinkles in the La Redoute mail order catalogue.
(Laughter) So I didn't see any problem starting a business related to eroticism.
After all, it's not a field you hear much about, and well, the erotic and pornographic sector, it's the sector that's always the first to adopt new technologies,
it's often there that we find the first developments, the first businesses.
The Minitel would have died earlier had it not been for 3615 ULLA.
At that time, some people had already understood it all.
It's exactly the same for VHS, VOD, the Internet. Canal+ would have had fewer subscribers from the beginning if it were not for football and pornography. So I felt it would be the same with connected objects.
So, as I said, no problem at all launching B. Sensory.
Well, it turned out to be a conviction that was shaken right from my first meeting with a sex toy manufacturer.
When I started out, I hadn't intended to make my own sex toy:
I thought I would find one, and I would simply adapt it so that it could communicate with my app.
So I got myself an appointment with a French manufacturer. We met in Paris. I told him about my project, filled with motivation and enthusiasm, believing in the famed power of words. And then he soon gazed at me and gave his verdict. He said, 'You should stop right now, you know. It will never work!
No, you see, my wife and I know the nightlife very well, and together we've visited all the swingers clubs in the world, and your thingummy will never work. You need to realise that girls who read are sexually frustrated.'
(Laughter) (Applause) 'Girls who read are sexually frustrated.'
Amazing to think that scientists have worked for years to convince us that the first sexual organ was not below the waist but in our head.
So I put an end to our conversation. I was somewhat angry, but above all upset. I told him that, as things were, I was leaving him the swingers clubs market but was keeping the 'sexually frustrated' one and thought I would be the winner!
(Laughter) (Applause) And since he had no sex toy for me, well, I was going to make one, made in France, that was it.
In less than an hour, my project became an industrial one, it had grown more complex, as had my motivation and militancy as well!
When you are a start-up with an idea like this, the best way to protect it, in general, is to communicate about it, to make yourself known by taking part in start-up competitions.
That's what I did, one year ago, with Web2day, in Nantes, then there was the West Web Festival organised during Vieilles Charrues by our friend, Jean-Luc Martin.
The rule is simple: you have four minutes on stage to present your project and convince a jury.
On that day, all the jury members were men - (Laughter) I went on the stage, made my pitch within the four minutes, slightly tensed, but supported by a benevolent Breton audience, just as today. So, the competition ended, the jury came on the stage, and they said, 'Actually, we didn't consider the B. Sensory project while we were deliberating.
Since there was no woman among us, we felt we were unable to evaluate its desirability.'
(Laughter) So I went to see the president of the jury.
He said to me, 'So, you're disappointed?'
'No, no, I'm not disappointed, I'm furious!
I am furious to hear that, in 2015, some men, who are above all e-commerce, web or financial professionals, say they can't assess the desirability of a project that is part of the $22 billion sex toy global market.'
I said, 'Tell me my project is not ready yet, that you need to see a prototype,
but don't tell me, 'We are men and therefore can't assess a female project.'
That day, the winning project was the connected beer tap.
(Laughter) (Applause) A 100% male project whose potential there's no problem understanding!
(Laughter) Setting up a company means opening a bank account.
I had an appointment at the bank. I put forward my project. And my bank adviser burst out laughing.
He said to me, 'You're joking!'
(Laughter) 'No, no.'
When he realised I was serious, he said, 'Well, so, you mean - ' He folded his arms, lent back in his chair, and said, 'You do understand, Madam, that we will never ever help you.'

'Really! Why?'
'Your project is unethical.'
We are all agreed that on matters of ethics banks are the indisputable reference. (Laughter) (Applause) So I asked him whether he was willing to discuss tax evasion, creation of offshore companies, record fines for failing to comply with embargoes. He was a little surprised at my reaction.
I don't think he expected such a strong reaction.
So he said to me, 'You know, I was really surprised,
I wasn't expecting that. But maybe, when you present your project to someone for the first time, you should tone it down a little, or even lie a little about what you want to do.'
So, of course, we can all agree that lying is a very ethical approach!
I could also tell you about some of the messages I was sent on social networks.
Some insulting, where, of course, I was told one had to be sexually frustrated to come up with that kind of idea.
I said, 'Oh, I've already been told that one!'
Or another one asserted, 'You're going to speed up the end of the human race, wanting to replace men with plastic.'
Suddenly, I understood what it was all about: the male ego.
(Laughter) (Applause) Not a recent problem. As early as the 16th century, Ronsard wrote that all the courtesans' perversions were less offensive to men than these dildos.
One might well remember that the dildo is 40,000 years old, and Cleopatra had already invented a vibrating model, filling a papyrus cone with bees to caress herself with.
Fortunately, they now have our friend Régis to provide them with a roof and take care of them.
(Laughter) (Applause) These are anecdotes, and, of course, I actually got more supportive messages than insults, and was surprised at so many people telling me, 'Your project is great, as well as the way you are tackling it, you're really brave!'
Some women even came to me to tell me, 'You really have got balls to bring out such project!'
So I was concerned, so many messages, all this feedback, positive as well as negative, and I decided to investigate sexuality, more precisely the history of female pleasure.
An exciting story, as it perfectly displays the evolution of our society.
For example, do you know that the clitoris, which was 'discovered' by the Italian Colombo in 1650, was rather well perceived up until the 19th century. Doctors thought the clitoris played an important part in creating pleasure, and since the pleasure served procreation everything was fine!
When doctors realised the clitoris served only to create pleasure - which might be thought great - and that orgasm had no link to fertility, well, that's when the problems started.
Female pleasure became a non-subject and the clitoris simply disappeared from boards of anatomy and dictionaries.
Only in 1998 did an Australian urologist publish a complete study on the clitoris.
1998!
Today, even if we have made progress, our sexuality still remains very much androcentred, i.e. it is defined by and for male pleasure.
Some will say, 'That's going too far!'
Some enduring representations made:
Men have greater physical needs than women, that's the way it is, that's nature, it's normal!
Whereas women, they have no physical needs, they merely feel desire for a man they love! (Laughter)
A man who racks up notches on his bedpost is a seducer; a woman who racks up notches on her bedpost is - a lucky bitch!
(Laughter) (Applause) And if we talk about masturbation, it's the same.
For men, no problem, it's allowed. It's part of education, it's normal, it's even satisfying.
For women, the subject is still taboo.
That's not really surprising when we know that up to the 19th century, in France, in Europe, female masturbation was considered perverted, and was treated with such a barbarian practice as genital mutilation.
Even today, it's a subject rarely talked about.
Consequently, many women ignore their feelings of pleasure, their body, or feel guilty.
And many men think the issue a non-issue: 'No, not my wife!
She's no need for anything, she's got me, how can she have!'
(Laughter) In the same vein, some men told me: 'It's great you're launching your project in Brest. Being a seafaring town, many women are alone, for long times, often - ' (Laughter) As if a sex toy was a mere substitute to be used only in cases of emergency.
As if a woman experiencing pleasure alone only meant alternative pleasure.
Well, this is stupid.
But I was also very surprised at the number of women who told me, 'Actually, we would love to try sex toys, but we daren't, we wouldn't dare buy one.'
Well, this is stupid too.
I think it is high time that women - when they want a sex toy - 'have the balls' to buy one!
Believe me, girls, it's just like buying a pair of shoes: you need to buy it and choose the colour, the size and usage - you don't wear the same shoes to go to the beach as you do to go climbing.
(Laughter) (Applause) With all these anecdotes, meetings, confidences, I realised that I was, that we were, probably not as free as I thought and that the road to equality, including the matter of pleasure, was still a long one.
That's how, as the months have passed, my project that was industrial as well as innovating, and still is, has also become a militant one.
I don't mean every woman should read erotic books, every woman should use sex toys - I'm talking about freedom, the freedom to choose your pleasure, your sexuality, without guilt or shame.
I don't want to be ashamed of what I am doing.
I don't want to need to lie when talking about my business enterprise.
Sexuality is a game, but it is also a social issue that affects all of us, as adults, as parents.
Anaïs Nin wrote: 'Eroticism is one of the basic means of self-knowledge, as indispensable as poetry.'
Thus I want to promote erotic literature, which develops our imagination and therefore differs from porn, which kills our fantasy.
Who in the audience has got children between 10 and 14?
Did you know that 80% of them will have already watched porn?
I don't mean a naked girl in a magazine, I mean porn films like the ones that you can watch for free on websites like YouPorn,
films showing sexual acts, male domination, violent practices, where complicity, respect, caresses, are left out, films which pose problems relating to the building of one's self-image, to eroticism, respect, and interpersonal relationships.
We recently had an example of this with what happened at the Montaigne secondary school.
I don't know whether you heard about these pupils who were charged with sexual harassment and touching after watching porn on their smartphones.
I was very surprised, and slightly shocked, at the way the media reacted immediately after the event.
First response: the stupefaction to realise that teens from privileged backgrounds are like others and watch porn.
Second debate: should smartphones be banned in secondary schools?
But this is not the problem!
This is already an outdated issue.
The question is how do we take care of the young girls' and boys' sexuality so that they learn about their own limits and learn to defend themselves.
I have two girls. One is 11, the other is 15.
And as a woman, as a mother, I really would prefer them to discover their sexuality through words rather than through porn, to discover their own pleasure so as to be able to share what they like and to refuse what they don't.
I am convinced that the first freedom is the freedom to be able to say 'no'.
I would also like them to be convinced that their pleasure is at least as important as their partner's, and not to wait like me until they are 40 to feel free in their own body, in their own mind, and in their own life.
I will end with another quotation by Anaïs Nin, who said: 'We don't see things as they are, we see them as we are.'
That's why this is not a pipe, and this is not a sex toy, but much more than that!
Thank you.
(Applause)
Good afternoon.
No, I'm not going to speak in English. However, while listening to those simple words I just said, you have already formed a preconception towards me that is conditioned by your psychological reflexes we call "biases," which are as natural as physiological reflexes.
Please also note that I have an accent.
My accent is conditioned by my British origins.
Well, that might make you a little tense, but try to put yourself in my shoes
and use that tenseness to sharpen your listening and understand me better.
I'm going to talk about these psychological traps, and, in the end, I hope you will be interested in a practical exercise to neutralize them.
It all started when I opened my curtains when I arrived in Clermont-Ferrand and I saw the magnificent panorama of the Chaîne des Puys.
I saw the silhouette and it bothered me.
There was something not quite right.
It was as if I were in front of someone who had a big pimple on his nose.
Indeed, next to the Puy-de-Dôme, the highest point, there's a kind of bump, the Petit Puy-de-Dôme.
To me, as a volcanologist, this is neither a tuff cone that hurls bombs, nor a lava dome that accumulates lava progressively. It was something different that I didn't understand.
So being a scientist, when I do not understand something, I go on a journey of discovery on the field, here the Petit Puy-de-Dôme.
I stepped on it.
I flew over it in a small aircraft and in a microlight aircraft.
I used all my powers as a geologist to understand it.
It took me several years but, finally, I discovered a kind of extremely rare volcano called an "elevation crater."
What's it about?
The lava comes from underground, and it accumulates.
So the surface starts to bulge and swell up. It lifts, lifts until it creates an arch. Then top of the arch collapses forming the elevation crater.
I was very proud of myself for finding this new type of volcano.
I thought of the Nobel Prize, for example, except that there is no Nobel prize for geologists.
We are not valued as scientists.
But something made me wonder, because I found that someone else, to my disappointment, had already described this volcano.
Over 200 years ago, Leopold von Buch came to Clermont-Ferrand at the end of the 18th century.
He saw the Petit Puy-de-Dôme.
He understood what it was much more quickly than I, and he created a theory called the "elevation crater."
At that time, geology had just been born as a science.
At the same time, a Scot, James Lyell, arrived at Mount Vesuvius.
Ha saw the eruptions of Mount Vesuvius and created the theory of the "eruption crater."
A real war started between these two people.
It was heavy.
The two parties took up their positions.
The battle reached its peak at Mount Etna.
There, the supporters of the elevation crater theory put together the hypothesis that the lava being liquid, it could only solidify on a flat ground,
just like water, obviously.
So logically, all the volcanoes that have slopes are elevation craters.
If you visit the Etna Volcano, you will see that the lava that comes out solidifies perfectly on the very inclined slopes.
That's perfectly clear.
James Lyell managed to destroy the theory of elevation craters.
The idea was ridiculed and completely lost and forgotten.
If we return to psychological biases, we can see how the biases acted in this battle, this war, between these scientists.
There are four biases that are important here.
The first is the "anchoring bias."
It means that what is seen first is the most strongly retained.
When von Buch arrived in Clermont-Ferrand,
he saw the Petit Puy-de-Dôme and get immediately what it was,
and this conditioned him for the future.
James Lyell arrived in the gulf of Naples. He saw a beautiful eruption of Mount Vesuvius, and his ideas were drawn in that direction.
The second bias is the "confirmation bias."
It is when we only choose or accept the information that fits our original idea.
The case choices made in this story illustrate this well.
The third is the framing or the "cultural bias."
We create a narrative around our idea by using and inflating the information we have selected in order to reach a goal.
The fourth is the "self-serving bias."
The self-serving bias is when we attribute to ourselves all the good feelings, the good elements, and the good actions, and we attribute to everyone else all the faults and bad elements.
That's what caused the war between the two positions.
This is perhaps a story of scientists.
Yet I have the same kind of brain that works in the same way.
Let's look at a more ordinary example.
At university, I'm a coordinator in the International Master program.
In science, English is the language used to communicate.
So it was obvious for me to use English predominantly for teaching this master's degree.
So I was very astonished, very surprised, to find resistance towards this idea among my colleagues.
A real war started between us.
We took up very different positions.
I could see that certain biases were starting to arise.
I didn't know what to do.
So one day, I went to my French class, and my awesome teacher, Fabienne, had me participate in a role play. I was to take the side of a member of the French Academy who proposed that French should be the only language used in higher education.
I knew all the arguments used by my colleagues, so I started playing the role to the full. Then after a while, I realized that I started to believe what I was saying.
In fact, it was as if I had developed two heads.
I had become a monster!
Well, I did not have two heads but rather in the same brain, two opposing ideas at the same time.
That perturbed me.
In psychology, this is called "cognitive dissonance."
After the class, my two heads recombined. And what I found was that I had developed empathy for my opponents.
I understood better their point of departure.
I could improve my dialogue with them because I knew better what they were trying to say.
What I did was to put myself in the shoes of my opponents.
Or better still, I had taken one of my adversaries' shoes and kept one of mine too.
I wore both shoes.
So what I recommend is that you do an exercise.
Every day, maybe, for a little while, try to think the opposite of what you hold most dearly, not forgetting completely where you started out.
Put yourself in the two shoes.
To come back to elevation craters and the beautiful Petit Puy-de-Dôme, I finally wrote a scientific article and sent it to the "Bulletin of Volcanology."
I had two readers who told me that they had different opinions than mine.
But in the introduction, I put the story of Von Buch and Lyell, so they offered to exchange shoes. And eventually, we managed to come up with something that was the convergence of all our points of view, that was much better and greater than my initial idea.
In conclusion, we know that biases are very powerful.
Even if we know how they are acting, we cannot prevent them.
So try yourself: Put yourself in the shoes of another.
Or better still, wear one shoe and see where it takes you.
Thank you.
(Applause)
They are us!
With this only certainty in mind, I left on 8th December 2012 to go to Jordan... with my socks, and my needles.
The socks, they are very important, because it's cold in the winter.
The needles, because I am a professional acupuncturist.
I left and arrived in Jordan, in one of the two largest refugee camps in the world, Zaatari camp, which is a Syrian camp.
And I integrated into military teams, and worked with them, they were medical officers, from Maroccan military teams.
Those doctors did a wonderful job, as they brought back to life war wounded who arrived with their legs torned apart, amputees who crossed the Syrian border by walking, being carried in wheelbarrows or by their relatives.
And me, I was there, with my needles, because in these camps, most of the time, there is a terrible lack of morphine.
So I was there to ease the pain of these injured people, the pain of phantom limbs, the pain of the burned patients, and the pain of the amputees.
The first time is always the hardest.
But I continued!
With the small association I created, I travelled along the Syrian border, several times, to continue to ease the pain of these people.
That is why, in the spring of 2014, I was there, in the north of Iraq, when Daesh carried out its biggest offensive.
With my own eyes, I had never seen so many people arrive in such a short time.
Imagine two million and a half people fleeing, leaving their homes, just to save their necks.
At that time, I was associated with a doctor, a local doctor, and always with my small needles, we decided to go, in his car, and with some boxes of needles and medicines, to meet with the refugees.
At the beginning, we did it with our own ressources, because we were with our car.
We would adapt to the weather conditions.
You have to know that, in these regions, it's really hot.
There is a lot of wind and sand.
And it gets dark early.
Working with our headlamps, we tried to ease as much as possible the pain of people, of war wounded.
Day after day, I saw the extend of the damages, and above all, the needs.
So we decided; we imagined a concept, a concept finally convenient and adapted to the circumstances.
I came back to Paris, and we bought a truck, equipped with medical equipment.
We sent it by boat from Marseille to Iraq.
We opened our first mobile clinic in January 2015.
It was wonderful!
We went to these people's bedside, and thanks to this vehicle, we could go a little further each time, go out of the city, go to the countryside, into the mountains.
What was wonderful, was that I started to leave my needles, in order to meet needs that became more and more important.
In the streets, there are so many children and women.
Only 9% of the refugees have access to camps.
All the others stay in public spaces.
So we started to recruit one, then two and three doctors, all of them were chosen among the refugees.
Thus we could give them some work to do and help them to regain their dignity.
In the following weeks and months, we moved from one to several mobile clinics.
So much so that in 2015, we could provide 40,000 cares, on 30 sites, identified by our teams, with fourteen doctors that we hired.
Why am I doing this ?
I am often asked this question.
I often ask myself this question too.
Is this because of my origins?
I am the granddaughter of an Armenian deportee.
I had the opportunity to be born in France, in a country in peace.
And I always told myself that the day I would be able to help other people, as some people did for my family, I would do it.
I am still a professional acupuncturist.

I am married. I have three children.
I live in Paris.
But I continue.
And I decided to continue!
At first, I thought that these missions would last 6 months, enough time for the exiled people to go back home, for the war to stop.
Two years later, we are still here.
And we continue!
Why?
Because they are us.
Because those people, they put their lives in danger, and they come to our country.
So much so that we see them everywhere, around our country, on our borders.
We decided to set up a bus in Calais too.
As I told you, I thought these missions would last six months.
Two years later we are still here.
We set up a bus in Calais.
But...
It's really difficult.
It's still really difficult for several reasons.
In Iraq, we work in an area where we are threatened : we are close to the front line.
It's also difficult because we are often manipulated.
We spent a lot of money every month in order to pay the wages, the cares and to provide 6,000 cares every month.
And it's difficult for a woman too, to impose on people like that, in this region of Orient, where, in the end, men make the law.
And then it's very difficult for a third reason.
It's always very disheartening to see that this misery never ends.
To see the extend of this human tragedy, whose end isn't in sight.
It's very disheartening.
It's overwhelming!
But I don't have the courage to stop!
Because they are us!
Thank you!
(Applause)
I am a French national champion.
You look at me, and you think, "With such legs, it must be the long jump, I don't know."
"How come, if she is a national champion, we have never heard of her?"
No.
I am a French national champion in a more accessible discipline, one in which everybody can participate, and in general, everybody does, without really wanting to.
Since the summer of 2016, I am a French cyber-harassment national champion.
(Somebody whistles) Not that - thanks a lot, thank you.
It is not because I took par to it, just to be crystal clear, but I suffered from it.
I was the subject of one of the most impressive cases of cyber-harassment in France: more than 40,000 threatening, insulting and brutal comments in a bit more than a year. There lies my record!
You must be thinking that I should have chosen long jump, it would have been less tiring.
I work on the Internet.
I create videos in the "virtual world."
A virtual world where I show my real face, where I speak with my real voice, and where I say things I really believe.
A virtual world very close to this world, where you can see me, where we breathe the same air.
A virtual world at our fingertips, on our smartphones; where we spent several hours a day, either to entertain ourselves or to work.
We can't really live without it since in France, more than 80% of households have access to the Internet.
A virtual world which is, finally, exactly like this world. We call it the "real life", in opposition to the virtual one.
Because eventually, the only difference between the virtual and non-virtual worlds is that we cannot see each other with our own eyes.
But let's come back to my record, if you don't mind.
I deserve the title, so I would like to discuss about it.
What does cyber-harassment look like?
If you have young children or if you are online very often, you should know that - Yes, that one:
[Fucking bitch] It's no big deal.
What was I saying?
If you have children who are going to live in the new world, and so spend most of their time online, you should know that -
Excuse me? Hello? Hello.
I feel like I do not have
your undivided attention.
I suggest we wait until it's over.
[Insulting comments] How are you doing?
It's impossible to ignore.
I know it!
You know what we are going to do?
We are going to ignore them!
It's tough isn't it ? I see you watching the screen when I am talking.
Yeah.
We are going to stop it right now because, even at this rate, 40,000 death threats, rape threats and insults, that can be very, very long.
And it is not so easy to ignore.
Do you want to know the itinerary of these messages?
From the brain of a real human being, who typed these messages on his real keyboard, through the virtual world to arrive in my real life, where my real eyes have read these messages and where my real brain has understood them.
There is no such thing as a virtual world.
Everything that happens online happens in real life.
Let's close the tab because it is too distracting, isn't it?
Let's close it, please!
You must be wondering what I have done to deserve this.
I am being insulted.
We are in France and there are laws and the truth is, death threats, rape threats and insults, do not belong to what we call 'freedom of speech'.
In France, public abuse is punishable by a 12,000€ fine.
I have every right to go and file a complaint against fandejewels60, xptdr22 or hervesuperman.
I don't know anything about these people except where they were born, but I don't really know it.
Can you imagine, 40,000 people whose identity I do not know?
How is it possible that 40,000 people have nothing better to do in their real life than to affect me, in my real life?
This started in the summer of 2016, during the Olympic Games in Rio, potentially tons of very interesting things to do!
Watching the long jump events, for example.
That's crazy!
And it is not me against 40,000 people.
It is me against one person, plus one person, plus one person, plus one person ... You get what comes next.
I don't have the time, the energy, nor the means to file a complaint against 40,000 aliases!
Have you ever made a complaint against anyone?
Do you know the administrative processes to file a complaint against someone in France?
It is very long. Against one person.
Imagine what it means
against 40,000 people.
I do not want to file a complaint against X, it is not X that is harassing me, these are real people.
I come to wonder who are these real people.
And how is it possible that 40,000 people ignore the law?
Did you know the law for public abuse?

Of course not. I did not either.
I don't know why I am asking you this.
I had to look for this law when this happened to me.
I imagine you have never been abused online, there is no reason for you to know that public abuse is punishable by a 12,000€ fine.
You don't learn that at school.
No, no. In school, we learn
where to put the Rhone on a map of France.
We learn the intercept theorem.
We also learn the fundamental rules for living together in society such as respect, tolerance or courtesy. And we learn too that ignoring the law is no excuse.
So in a country where we learn how to respect each other and that ignorance of the law is no excuse to break it, statistically, there is no risk for one person to be abused by 40,000 people, right?
You bet it!
There might be something wrong with our education.
I can see you are wondering what I have done to deserve this.
Have I publicly taken side in a famous debate on how to rename the chocolate croissant?
(Laughter) There is the law, there is education and there is social control.
Social control is what makes you wait in line at the post office and not go ahead of everyone to avoid people thinking you are a lout.
That is the reason why no one ever takes the last piece of cake, in order not to be considered rude.
Social control is when you pay attention to your behavior because of how people perceive you.
In my case, 40,000 people do not abide to the law, whether they know it or not, education is of no help because it did not provide the keys to understanding and social control does not seem to affect their behavior. On the contrary! The group dynamic encourages them to go on.
"If someone else insulted her and was not punished for it, it's no big deal if I insult her too."
I am aware that these people did not gang up against me, that this is no conspiration, but it does not matter, that's what harassement is.
It's an accumulation of abuses and insults toward someone over time, with the aim of harming them.
It's efficient.
It's very efficient.
We ganged up, we are not happy and we are screaming it loudly.
Faced with this - I was on websites.
On a website, on social media, there has to be a law, a policy, some rules.
So that, as a matter of fact, logically, by talking to the moderators of those social media, I should be able to get at best, the deletion of the accounts that harass me, at worst, the deletion of the messages that insult me, that break the law.
But all the websites and social media reply the exact same thing, "This is not my responsibility.
In fact, I am not a media, I am a broadcaster, so I do not take sides."
In this context, I was only looking for solutions.
I looked for compensation in the law.
I thought education might provide hope, thinking that my example might be beneficial in some way.
And then I looked for support and solidarity with the social media, the media.
Believe it or not,
I would have felt less alone, less isolated, less stigmatized.
Instead of hearing: "This is not the real life!"
or "You can just ignore them!"
I wanted people to tell me that what I was living was not normal, that I had reasons to suffer.
I wanted to have my face beaten up so that people would look at me and say,
"Something's wrong! What's wrong?
Let's take care of it."
I wanted people to stop telling me that I just had to close the tabs for the "You whore, die" to disappear.
I felt completely hopeless.
Yes, it is my life.
It can be anybody's life.
It can be your life.
It can be your children's life.
It can be your grand-parents' life if they like to go online.
Today, this is the life of many teenagers who have tried to end their lives.
Then, something hit me.
Me too, I have made mistakes while online.
I have already sent a malevolent and insulting comment to someone who was saying things I was utterly against.
I have already thought that, because I was committed and I had a real fight, I was defending social progress, so I had the right to insult someone.
But you cannot be wanting to change behaviors and minds and use the same weapons as the very people attacking you.
We can all be harassed online.
And we can all take part in a harassment.
Even just once.
Even lost in the middle of 40,000 people.
Even if we very good reasons to do it.
If so many people, without sending the word around, without ganging up against me, had such a powerful and negative impact on my life, imagine the impact of positive comments!
If we can individually produce waves of hate, logically, we should be able individually to produce waves of love, support and kindness.
If we accept that a handful of hateful people can have such an impact on someone's life, we need to realize that a handful of good people can have such an impact on someone's life.
We control how we affect people.
Contrary to what people often told me, it is not easier to insult online.
Not at all.
Look, "You bitch" takes eight letters,
"Thanks" takes six letters.
There you go, fewer letters.
We have the power to change this.
I have realized in my position - because I am not the first nor the last one to be harassed - but I have realized in my unique position of being harassed, that there is not, on one side the people who harass; in the middle, the bystanders; and on the other side, the supportive ones.
No.
You are either part of the problem or part of the solution.
I am not asking you to go fight a war that is not yours; to debate with people who disagree with you.
I am not asking you to become soldiers of good.
I am not asking you to use a hashtag either.
I am just suggesting that you become a role model, to make it a habit to communicate your satisfaction online, your love, why not, or simply your presence; to comment, to like, to click on the blue thumb, for those who get it; and to leave a constructive comment, even if it is a negative one.
And if you don't have time, a heart emoji is enough.
If we express our satisfaction louder, we won't hear the people expressing their hate anymore.
We will be too noisy.
It is very important that kindness retakes ownership of the online discussion space.
I still have not told you what I did to deserve this.
You want to know it?
I did exactly what I have just done in front of you tonight: I have publicly expressed my opinion about harassement.
And if you just saw this video online, don't hesitate to leave a comment or a heart emoji.
Thank you.
