I was 11.
The Taliban trained us to use arms and Kalashnikovs.
I said no to the Taliban.
I did not want to make war.
They beat me.
I was threatened to death since I refused to go and fight with them.
Later, I made friends with a young Taliban who came to pick me up for everyday prayer.
One morning, he came earlier and unlocked the door of the room.
He told me the way out.
Nobody was there.
I followed his advice.
And I left.
The Taliban got very angry.
They came to fetch me at my parents.
They set the house on fire and left.
My mother and my sister died in the fire.
My father got wounded.
He told me: 'Go away!
You must leave Afghanistan'
He entrusted me to my uncle for me to flee the country.
My uncle met a smuggler and we left.
I crossed 11 countries: Pakistan, Iran, Turkey, Greece, Bulgaria, Romania, Hungary, Italy, to reach France.
I walked, went on lorries, coaches, boats.
I was thirsty, I was hungry, I was scared, and I was 14.
At each stage, we had to wait sometimes several months, till they were enough people for the crossing.
It took me one year to reach France.
To leave Afghanistan, I had to wear some trousers and a shirt for the first time.
I had never worn trousers before.
In Iran, I saw women without a headscarf in the street, for the first time.
In Turkey, I saw people kissing in the street: for the first time again!
All the people I was travelling with wanted to go to England.
There, you can earn a lot of money but you will get no papers.
You can study, but you won't get any diploma.
When I arrived in France, in Paris, I only had 2 Euros in my pocket.
I went in a first cybercafe for a Skype with my uncle.
But it cost more than 2 Euros.
The manager said no.
I went to a second cybercafe and the man let me use Skype for free.
I spoke to my uncle.
I told him: 'I am in a country I don't know.
I have no money.
I haven't eaten for one week!
I have had no shower.
What am I to do?'
He said: 'You must stay over there.
You crossed 11 countries
to get there.' He said: 'There is nothing I can do for you.'
I was angry.
I called him back to ask him for help.
He gave me the phone number of my cousin in Rennes.
I called my cousin.
And I came to Rennes.
A lovely big town.
When I arrived, Coallia looked after me.
Coallia looks after asylum seekers.
It is an association.
They provided me with a hotel room plus a host family.
I said: 'What is a host family?
My family is in Afghanistan.'
I wanted to remain alone, like my cousin, to work and earn money.
But I did many things with my host family.
At the beginning, it was very complicated for me.
I couldn't understand a word in French.
So we all made gestures, many gestures!
But Auntie and Nunky kept smiling.
It is a family with children.
I stayed with them for 2 years.
They helped me a lot.
I have grown much attached to them.
When I was with this family, I started to go to school.
It is not the same thing as a Koranic school.
There were many subjects: Maths, French, History... and many other subjects I had never come across.
I started in secondary school, in Year 9.
First day, first hour, I had a test in Maths.
(Laughter) In Maths!
I handed in a blank sheet.
I had to explain in English - I couldn't speak French - I had never learnt to write.
The first day was very complicated for me: girls, boys, together at school.
French people cheek kiss!
That's culture!
I have learnt many things going to school... And I played cricket again!
As I told you previously, cricket is the second most popular sport in the world.
More than 120 million people through the world play cricket.
For 2015 Cricket World Cup, 1 billion people wached the match London - Pakistan on TV.
It is more than for the Football World Cup or the Olympics
I played in Afghanistan.
But it was complicated there.
Above all, it was dangerous because of the war.
One day, a friend brought me to Rennes cricket field.
That's how I discovered there were other Afghani in Rennes.
I was so happy!
I started playing cricket again, every Saturday.
I bought some equipment, I found a field.
I wanted independance to start our club up.
And I created an association.
A great achievement for me!
Now we officially have a field.
It is a a baseball field, with a changing room.
We also have a sports hall to train in the winter.
This is thanks to Rennes Town Council.
We have an Under-18 Team.
The town asked us to create a women's team.
I am the President of Rennes Cricket Club.
(Applause) Thank you!
(Applause) Thanks to cricket, I am a little famous.
They got in touch with me: educators who often know other Aghani.
I went to Vannes, Lorient, Angers, Saint Malo, to meet young people.
To all of them, I said: 'You have to go to school!
When you learn to read, write, speak French, you can go and meet other people, you integrate into the country.
To learn is an opportunity.'
For me, it is very important to do things for other people.
I can't give money...
but I can help!
Well, this was my story!
Today, I am returning things to Rennes which helped me a lot.
I hope as soon as next year 2 or 3 players from Rennes Cricket Club will be selected to play in the French Team.
I have high hopes and I beleive in it!
My name is Wahab, I am the President of Rennes Cricket Club... and I am from Rennes!
(Applause)
What is your story?
Because mine really started when I understood that I had been taken over by at least three stories, that they had raised and made me.
Those stories, you know them as well I do.
Those stories are: "Enjoy", "Just do it", "Because you're worth it".
I see you smile.
(Laughter) We were born at the same time, in the mid-70s, and we grew up together, like sisters.
I believed so strongly in these stories that they became my story.
And since I was a good girl, was well taught, meant to do well, I, as marketeers of that time would put it, overperformed.
So, at 28, I am living in New York, I have a start-up, clients, investors, employees.
I am on the fast track: elite education, the US, entrepreneurship, New York, the internet bubble.
Until I witness this.
On the roof of my office on 26th Street, far enough away not to be swallowed up by it but close enough to never turn away, I am not afraid.
Something obliterates my fear, freezes my thoughts, forms a screen.
Instead, the inanity of my current life blows up to my face.
It's true, I am 28, I live in New York, I have a start-up, clients, investors, employees.
But I don't have a family, not a single friend, no political conscience at all.
I work 16 hours a day. I run every other day, I count my calories, I do sports.
During my free time, when I'm not working, I pay a pittance to Korean women with no papers to paint my toenails.
I wanted to be rich?
I'm getting sadder and sadder.
I wanted to be "with it"?
Except that being "with it" is to have the ambition of a dead leaf towards the wind, said the poet.
(Applause) On that roof, on 26th Street, something is being ripped apart for me.
Under the veil of appearances, there's some form of truth.
What crushed my fear on that day was shame.
It still gives me goose bumps ... really.
There is something profoundly obscene in the story I embody, me, global capitalism's good girl, with my degrees and certainties, in those stories where I'm a great asset, a great result.
"Enjoy", "Just do it", "Because I'm worth it", "You're worth it", I don't know any longer.
These slogans that have made me, supported me, cloaked me, crumble and fall in pieces.
I will tear down what's left like old wallpaper.
Because fear overwhelms, shame seizes, but anger sometimes propels.
Anger, itself, always wants to get out, and it always does.
And that may be why, from time to time, we have to let it out.
So I start by bailing myself out of that race, out of that trajectory.
I leave New York, I close my start-up down, I also leave the man I was to marry despite his being a great guy.
I disappear from photos, from lives lived as they should be, from lives without question, from lives on the level.
I, who never questioned myself, I let myself be invaded.
What happened on that day?
What was I doing there?
Who was sending us bombs?
What was the story I believed in and that was dead that day.
And that story, who wrote it?
Whom does it serve?
Who holds the big pen?
In the end: Who rules?
Is it the US?
Is it the financial markets?
Is it oil?
Is it Google's algorithms?
Is it fear?
Is it hatred?
Trying to answer these questions propels me along a sort of route since I don't have any other choice than to try to answer these questions, to regain control of my thoughts which perhaps I never had, to never let myself be dictated to again.
I start writing, investigating, in order to understand, not necessarily what happened, but how I came to be there, me.
So I am no longer at all "with it", but on a sort of route that, frankly, is not so easy.
On bad days, the most numerous, I wander without having thought out how I could lead a useful, meaningful and responsible life.
On good ones, I tell myself I'm doing something of absolutely incredible worth: I doubt, I learn, perhaps I understand.
An idea comes.
If it goes the distance, if I succeed in making sense of chaos, then it becomes a meeting, a book, a novel, an article, a film.
So I become an author, a director.
I realize now that writing, it's making sense of chaos.
It's hanging on to a thread, for me, a lifeline.
And for me, it's going to be that question: Who rules?
It becomes my life.
I start by writing my first book, the story of the explosion, that of 9/11, the towers, mine; then a second on the power of finance and technology over our lives.
It's so easy, not only to write -
that's true, but then again rather rare - but also to pass on, that I tell myself that it doesn't have to be exactly true, it's more complicated than that.
It's true, finance and technology have assumed power over our lives.
But if that's the case, somebody gave them it, didn't they?
So that happened when?
Who is it, what is it?
That's my third book, on the relationship ... relationships ... between the media, politics and finance.

Who rules? - I get a little closer.
It's our compromises, our forfeitures, it's our own collaboration with the system.
It's my least popular book.
There are hundreds of reasons for that, including that I didn't write it so well -
but there is also the notion that posed like that, head on, the question "Who rules?"
with its response, or one of its responses, "our consent", is not popular - at least, not right now. I think that's about to change - the supporters of the system, whoever they might be.
So, along my investigative path with its variant "But why don't we have the right to talk about these things?"
I bump into Larry Lessig at the Avignon TGV station on a freezing November evening.
I cannot believe my luck.
I really feel something's on my side.
You might not know him, but for me, Larry Lessig, professor of law at Harvard, is like the Usain Bolt of the "Who rules?" question.
He is, I would say, a somewhat crazy constitutionalist, who, at Harvard, examines the influence of money in politics at a research centre he founded dedicated to systemic corruption.
According to him, no reform of health, education, climate, arms, financial markets, can be passed so long as elections are about money.
He is a former political adviser to Obama, he's also one of the pioneers of the free internet.
When I was living in New York a century ago, fifteen years ago, I would devour his columns.
We were all ecstatic about the internet bubble, and he was one of the few to warn us, and to see Orwell, which is to say Big Brother, fiddling with lines of code.
Moreover, when I met him 15 years later at that train station on a freezing November night, he was one of the few Americans to defend the actions of another American, Edward Snowden.
Edward Snowden is a former contractor to the NSA who, in November 2013, revealed the extent of mass surveillance by the US on its population and that of its allies.
This story also fascinates me because it's the same old story of an individual faced with machines, faced with the system, faced with history, faced with himself: if you witness something bad, should you keep quiet and go along with it or speak out and expose yourself, with all the risks that that implies?
Anyway, at that train station, Larry Lessig is alone as am I.
He has nothing to do there. Nor do I.
It's a weird place to meet this kind of person.
So I go up to him, I lie, I put together a story, uncommissioned, I ask for an interview, and we get on the same train ...
from certain points of view, anyway.
I interview the great professor gloriously in the bar car of the TGV.
But nothing goes as planned.
40 minutes in, he breaks into tears on the mention of the suicide of his friend Aaron Swartz.
Aaron Swartz had been found nine months earlier - so the beginning of January 2013 - hanging from the curtain rail of his Brooklyn apartment at the age of 26.
Born with the internet, he coded it with his ideals of freedom all his young life.
For Aaron, the internet was the great hope for humanity for the generations of our age, because the internet allowed the sharing of information and knowledge.
He coded the RSS feed that you use every time you share or you read an article online. Together with Lessig, he created the Creative Commons which allows you to watch TEDx videos for free.
He also co-created that enormous platform, that absolutely brilliant discussion forum, Reddit.
The Obama administration, the one we're supposed to love, especially now, clobbered him with a 35-year prison sentence, a one million dollar fine, and a criminal record for life.
What had Aaron done?
Had he looted, polluted, assassinated, given away state secrets?
No, Aaron had mass uploaded academic publications to an MIT open access server, his paradise.
Aaron was dangerous for the US authorities because he wanted us to be strong.
What?
The US hates intelligence and murders its children.
Faced with the absurd on that train, Larry Lessig spoke to me of his survival plan - because it was one, it's what it had come to.
Aaron's death, his friend, his master, his disciple, his son, in turn threw him on the open road.
Who rules? Up to now,
Larry had told himself, by means of courses and lectures, he was going to convince us.
However, filled with rage, anger, sorrow, he was going to strip off his great professor guise.
This story is being rolled out in front of me, it has not got going yet.
He tells it to me, he advances it to me.
Chance has him right in front of me.
So I grab the branch it's proffering me
and go with it. I follow him, I write, I film, when he organizes public demonstrations throughout the US to denounce the influence of money in politics.
I also follow him to Washington when he was about to start his presidential campaign and to stand as a candidate in the Democratic elections.
His goal is to put the theme of the influence of money on politics - I think we all agree that that's a problem - at the heart of the presidential debates.
But the Democratic Party blocks his access to the television studio and to the primaries.
What?
The "democratic" party is blocking the access of a candidate that has all the trappings of the intelligentsia?
So again, who rules?
Interview, story, film, in the end I feel like I am always telling the same story: the struggle of a few figures of the resistance, men, women, even children, who are trying to warn us and thus pave a path of dignity.
For resistance is everywhere.
As an author, for me really, it's a marvellous catch. I can't understand why there aren't more of us after it.
As a citizen, I must admit that these stories help me to live.
As a mother, it makes a wonderful story I can tell my kids, a world in which I can believe.
So I do it as much as possible, everywhere, all the time, like in Iceland with Birgitta Jónsdóttir.
Her story fascinates me.
This woman entered into politics following the subprime crisis in Iceland.
She was completely self-taught, she founded several political movements, she became a member of parliament in 2010 - most notably she founded the Pirate Party in 2013.
In 2016 - a few months ago - she was close to forming her government, or more precisely, she had the mandate for doing so.
Birgitta has had an extraordinary career, and has ideas full of common sense.
What do we hear? It's naïve,
it's impossible, it's dangerous.
When too isolated, too alone, and the likes of Birgitta, Larry, Edward and Aaron, fail to make themselves heard by us, the system jeers at them and the experts with them, repeating to us over and over again how well they'd told us.
And everywhere, almost everywhere, enabled by populations petrified with fear, authoritarianism installs itself into the presidential seats.
So, that's the end of the story?
Me, I've no desire for this story to come to an end.
Because if it comes to an end, I'll have nothing more to tell.
And I believe in this story that no one sees.
Isn't that what an artist, an author, a writer, does?
Draw lines, straight ones, curves, links, between events and people that no one else is seeing?
But they who are on the ropes, Larry, Birgitta, on the ropes, how can they go forward?
So I reflect, a little within constraints, it's true.
And I say to myself, after all, me, I also have a pen.
It's not that big, but I have a pen.
What if I stopped using it to tell their story once it's done and over, but rather to formulate it, elicit it.
What if I tried to create a setting like this evening so that something happens, so that something goes on.
After all, Larry, Birgitta, Edward support each other from apart: they know each other but have never met in person.
What if that changed?
What if they got together?
Them, and us too.
What if I got all of them together in Moscow, where Snowden is stuck, for a conversation that's taken place nowhere before, overtaken by pointlessness, a conversation on their common goal, their struggle: how to save democracy, the one that - because that's it, the story - was put on hold that day?
Surprisingly - and to be honest, I was not expecting it - they all agreed.
We even got our visas, a small window of opportunity, and then I was the only one blocking the process.
In truth, I was scared to death.
I'd no idea where this story would lead me.
I've still no idea, by the way.
It's as if you decided to go the North Pole, you've been finding your way forward in the fog for years with a compass, and all of a sudden, a short distance from your goal, the compass goes crazy.
For a few weeks, the compass, that's been me.
But the story is stronger, it wants to take place.
So we go to Moscow, take a look around, and then that's it.
The film is made, the meeting takes place.
And, for me, it's an unbelievable experience.
So, who rules?
What keeps us going?
Or more precisely, and perhaps more interestingly: What keeps them going?
From these travels, from this filming especially, I have understood a few things.
The first is that if Birgitta, Larry, Edward are still alive, it's because they don't want to make history, but to let it happen.
And that's crucial.
In these uncertain times, a fraction of an inch from the abyss, if we dare open our eyes, it's a tremendous lesson in life, in surviving, in what it really means to be alive.
And good news!
This will to protect life, to favour life, is everywhere.
It's the most common denominator among all those who stand up, whoever they are, wherever they are, in France, anywhere in the world.
But we don't see them, we are looking elsewhere.
Fear is being induced.
Something forms a screen, starting with, for you and for me, those damn slogans, those overbearing messages, that zeitgeist: "Enjoy", "Just do it", "Because I'm worth it", that aim to signify to us just precisely the opposite of their pseudocall for happiness and self-confidence.
In reality, they mean: "Slave away", "Don't think", "Because you're not worth a thing". And thus they make us do their bidding, they chain us down, they turn us into the living dead.
Doubtless, very few of you know about the work of Birgitta Jónsdóttir, Larry Lessig and Edward Snowden, let alone mine.
Because that's also something I have come to understand: that writing, exercising your own free will, makes you neither rich nor popular.
You become someone no one wants anything to do with, unbearable, because it makes you alive in a world that has specifically chosen fear, that is to say, death.
And this stance is priceless. In that world,
to doubt, to seek, is to disobey, to free oneself.
So go on, get rid of these stories that have been imposed upon you.
Refuse to be the object of a story; choose the story yourself.
Write your own narrative.
It may well be the only thing that is true.
Thank you.
(Applause)
I'm sure this has already happened to you at least once in your life, where you tripped and did everything so as not to fall.
Back home, in Guadeloupe, we have a nice saying for when that happens: "Bigidi mè pa tonbé,"
stumble, but don't fall.
You know, it took me a long time, a very long time, 25 years all in all, to understand the power in the word "Bigidi."
Say it with me: "Bigidi!"
Audience: Bigidi!
Léna Blou: No, that's no good! Bigidi!

Audience: Bigidi!
LB: It's a magical word.
Because it sings in your mouth.
Did you feel it?
It's music, it's a note.
Bigidi! Again?

Audience: Bigidi!
LB: Let's use our hands. Bigidi!

Public: Bigidi!
LB: Again! Bigidi!

Audience: Bigidi!
LB: It resonates in your head.
It dances through your body.
More importantly, it makes the unseen obstacles dance.
It challenges minds.
It strikes hearts, it revives souls.
I believe that, like me, you have already met someone on a street corner,
such as Albè rom de Badlassous that was stumbling here, tripping there, just like a Gwoka danser would.
For those who don't know, the Gwoka is a dance, the Guadelupian traditional dance,
where we dance alone, a bit in this space we call "la swaré-léwòz", where the dancer starts when he feels to, he is in a conversation, as I am with you, a conversation between him and the drummer.
And we could say that the Gwoka dancer, particularly the Léwòz dancer, looks like a drunk man.
But if we think a bit about this dance, but especially in closing our eyes and imagining that we are a foreigner, who arrived in this country we find ourselves in swaré-léwòz we see... (Laughter) We'd be saying: "But, what is this?"
It has no structure, no order, it makes no sense.
It's incomprehensible to him.
And I get it, but that is just what I find fascinating about the Gwoka dance, seeing the dancer who quickly, and at such speed, stops.
In the lived silence.
And then, for no reason, he falls back into a wild frenzy only to stop.
In an apparent slowdown, he changes his energy.
He might dance hard, or lightly, or just sway.
I was convinced, you know, intuitively my heart told me that this dance, that looks to be without order must have a deeper meaning than that.
A bit like Ti Malo, when I went looking, I found nothing.
No books, no research, no scientific publication.
Nothing, nothing from before.
I had to make the decision to follow my instinct, and to watch the dancer's body, just to observe, and to study it for more than 15 years, alone;
to observe it, and decode it, so as to understand.
Because I was convinced, not only that this dance meant something, because I will remind you too often, we have the tendency to restrict the dance to its first purpose, an artistic purpose meant only to appeal to the eyes.
But the dance, when someone dances in society, it's an understandable language meant to speak the unspoken words of the hidden strength of a people.
So I took the time to study the muscles, the bones, the joints,
What's moving? When?

Where? Why?
It took me 15 years to put in place a classification that I call Techni'Ka.
But like all research processes, you know, there are difficult moments, when we don't have the answers.
There is an epic phase that I had to give a name.
Because when there's no name,
it doesn't exist.
And oftentimes, the Caribbean doesn't exist because it has no name, otherwise we place it in a general category:
Multiculturalism, diversity, race-mixing, and then we stop there.
So I had to find names to give to the steps I found, the exercises.
And it was there that I remembered... LB, Audience: Bigidi!
LB: Mè pa tonbé... And I found that the word Bigidi, just the word bigidi, was a perfect translation for the way the Léwòz dancer moved.
And still following my heart, because it was the only thing that made me progress, bit by bit, following my heart, my instinct.
And one day, just like that, it clicked, I set off -- because thankfully, I too, I know "the great dance" -- I set off to do a comparative element between "high society" dancing and the Gwoka dance.
On a philosophical, you know, symbolic level, where a classical dancer, when their body touches the ground, you know, with very light movements, touches the grown, it symbolises death.
But when I watched my famous Léwòz dancer, I saw him stumble, almost to the point of falling.
But as if by some miracle, he never falls.
He never touches the ground.
I say: but this is symbolic of life!
It means, the more he is imbalanced, the more he is continually adjusting.
When I observed the body of the dancer, I realised,
He never falls. Why?
Because of a miracle.
It's what's known as the recovery.
Because the dancer, he allows himself to be apart of whatever chaotic course.
And then, magically, pan, dam, pandam, pandam, pan, pan, pan, pandam, pan, pandam, PAN.
This moment, it is the last moment of balance.
So he allows himself to be part of the chaos.
Because he knows that he will land back on his feet.
"Bigidi mè pas tonbé" took on a whole new meaning, with a new depth for me, and ...
one day I said to myself: "But why is it that in Guadeloupe the body is also so imbalanced?
And, if by chance, the bigidi, stumbling, of the Gwoka was it not a perfect replica of the country Guadeloupe?
I notice that, we are in the permanent state of disorder.
(Laughter) Our relationship with time, our relationship with people, our relationship with things, our relationship with even constructing things, in building things, it's summed up in a very simple concept: the break in action.
We are in a permanent ellipsis, in a continuous state of discontinuity.
We start, it starts off well, then we stop.
As if by miracle, everything reverts, everything goes back to normal.
I'm sure you know what I'm talking about.
And afterwards, I said to myself: "But, this instability of the body..." because technically, the thing that makes the Gwoka dance unstable it's in being on your feet.
Try being in heels and never falling.
You get the impression that the Gwoka dancer outwits imbalance, and shows off his balance.
I really strongly believe that Guadeloupe is about to tell the world that there is a new way to look at balance: it's imbalance.
That, that is extraordinary.
Because Guadeloupe has factors that come to feed this instability.
First, our emergence in the world.
Colonisation, slavery, it's human chaos.
And I believe the body made up a dance, its dance, meant to reinvent its humanity.
It need to be unstable, because slavery was unstable.
He needed to adapt.
But there is also the space.
Just like the Gwoka dancer who dances alone, in this country, this archipelago, every islet is a country: Désirade is a country, Marie-Galante is a country, Terre-de-Haut is a country, Terre-de-bas is a country.
But there are also natural factors, everything that happens is unforeseen: hurricanes, earthquakes, volcanoes, tidal waves.
It's as if Guadelupians were made oblivious to the fact that they live in an unpredictable space.
So, it's almost normal that, when I was giving my Techni'Ka classes in Guadeloupe, naturally we be imbalanced, but I said to myself: "It would be interesting to check the word bigidi on the body of foreigners."
So, when I went abroad, I found myself around some Japanese, Italian and American people, some Africans, some Caribbean people, and I told them to dance to the musicality of the word "bigidi," without explaining what it meant in Creole nor that it came from Gwoka.
Bigidi.
And each time, I was amazed to see that these foreign dancers, who were completely unaware of the Ka culture, reproduced bigidi.
I said to myself: "But, it's not only a magical word, it's a word which awakes an age-old understanding, that belongs to humankind."
Because, in fact, the bigidi, it's Guadelupian, OK, but it is universal, because all human beings have seen instability during their lifetime. There is no person on this planet --
except maybe he who sees, who hears colours -- (Laughter) There is no human being who hasn't experienced a break.
But what is interesting, about Guadeloupe and the Gwoka, and perhaps what we can contribute to the rest of the world, because the bigidi teaches every human being that we must accept the unpredictable and be at one with it.
We need only to adapt, to never fail.
We have the right to stumble, We have the right to waver, but we can not fall.
Bigidi.
I can't hear you!
Audience: Bigidi!
LB: Bigidi, mè pa tonbé.
Because, as we examine the world the geo-political dogmas are something else, have shifted, there is uncertainty in the big political and cultural orientations, and moreover, what fascinates me, is that nature, the unpredictability of nature, of large territories, don't you find that they look more and more like our hurricanes, the storms over there?
The only thing is that we can remind them of the mysteries in the unlikely.
We have to give all the power back to human beings by saying:
"Have faith. You have what it takes.
You are skilled in deception."
Because when we look at the Gwoka dancer, what does he do?
He escapes.
When he stops, it's like life: we wait for the storm to pass.
When it's possible, we pick up speed and if there is an imbalance, thankfully, it's no big deal, even if we make progress in a haphazard way, it's still progress.
The supremacy of balance, this perfect vertical line, well, once we fall, we die.
Better to progress in quicksand, to always be in a dynamic state of having to bounce back.
And I want to simply say that the bigidi, stumbling, of the Gwoka dance, of the Léwoz dancer, is perhaps the creative solution for facing obstacles in the 21st century.
(Applause)
For the first twenty years of my life, I thought ecology was only for people who loved nature, the great outdoors, animals, those who wanted to save dolphins. Not really my thing, then, as I was a happy city dweller. Plus there were many other causes that seemed priorities to me, like social injustice, international conflicts, world hunger, the scandals of our economic system. And then, I gradually understood that everything was linked.
Today's most important environmental issues, climate change, the exhaustion of resources, the loss of biodiversity, or waste management, all these issues are also political and economic, in fact, they're especially political and economic issues. And they have direct social repercussions in France, in Europe, and everywhere else in the world.
Then one day, I visited an incinerator, and there, I was shocked by this reality, by the images I saw.
I was able to see the pit where the trucks dump the waste, the tons and tons of waste we throw away each year. I was able to look through the window of the oven inside the incinerator, where these tonnes waste get burned. I understood then and there the true meaning of the word "waste", of the phrase "consumer's society", the disgust, the near-physical rejection it may cause.
During this visit, I was told that for each ton of waste dumped into the incinerator, 300 kg of clinker were produced, that is the unburned remains of the incineration process.
300 kg, that's quite a lot.
But 300 kg, that's not all, since there's another 30 kg produced, called RPIFHW, Residues from the Purification of Incineration Fumes from Household Waste, because when you mix waste in the incinerator, and you burned it, of course, it produces toxic emissions that you don't want to let into the air therefore they are filtered, which is rather good, but as a result, you are stuck with those 30 kg of ultra polluting residue, so much so that it is necessary to store it in dangerous waste management facilities.
I then understood while I thought incineration was about eliminating waste, or so I had been told, that it was in fact something else altogether.
Nothing is lost, nothing is created, everything is transformed, and in this instance, we transform waste which, originally, was not extremely toxic, such as left-overs, food peelings, plastic containers, all of this is transformed into extremely toxic residue.
So there are 129 incinerators in France, the largest number in Europe, but also, we have 250 landfill sites, which are not recycling centres where you take your rubbish to sort and dispose of, no, I really mean landfill sites, the kind you would picture in third world countries. They exist still in France, 250 of them, sometimes in the open air like in Île-de-France, around Paris.
These incinerators, these landfill sites, cost a lot of money.
In France, we spend 14 billion euros each year to treat our waste.
14 billion euros that could be put to much better use.
You may be thinking you sort and recycle, that's already something, and it's not so easy to do.
Of course, sorting our waste is vital. It allows us to recycle materials instead of sending them to an incinerator or a landfill where they'd become useless, for sure.
But just recycling doesn't solve everything either, because recycling processes also consume a large amount of resources: of water, electricity, and other primary materials.
For example, glass and aluminium, these are materials that recycle quite well, almost infinitely, however, it requires enormous amounts of energy, in order to heat up the waste during the recycling process.
Another example: paper, it's the contrary, you can't recycle paper forever.
In Europe, on average, paper can be recycled 3-4 times but beyond this point, the paper fibres aren't good enough anymore.
In short, recycling is vital, but it shouldn't be an objective in itself.
The objective in itself should be truly circular logic, for example, re-using these materials some truly circular logic that each of us could apply, at our own level on a daily basis.
I would like to give two examples:
the first one, you know it well enough, is the reusable bag.
We all have one, several in fact, even too many at home, that we use more or less automatically, but we can do better.
We can do better, for example, by telling shopkeepers when they pack our shopping in a bag, "No thank you. It's okay,
I've got one, I don't need one."
It's not so easy, but it's a real message to pass on, to pass on to the shopkeeper, but also to other people around you.
The message isn't that I don't want to pay for a bag because now it costs 20 or 30 cents, no, the message is that I don't want to waste this resource.
The second example is also one from our daily life,
it is organic waste.
Organic waste accounts for a third of our rubbish, which is quite a lot.
A third of our rubbish which usually ends up in an incinerator or a landfill.
A third of our rubbish which contains nutrients, that could enrich the soil, to prevent soil impoverishment.
Actually, we often think that compost, because that's what it is, is only possible when you have a garden. This isn't true. Everybody can compost their waste, even if you live in a flat, like I do, thanks to vermicomposting.
Vermicompost is a compost created with the help of earthworms, that eat and digest this organic waste.
That's the one we have at the office.
My colleagues and I compost the organic waste from our meals at every lunchtime.
You can see that it's not too repelling, it's not bulky, it's about this big, it can easily be put into the corner of a kitchen, or balcony when you have one, and it changes a lot of things.
And if we adapted our daily lives slightly, trying to limit what is thrown away, and look after reusables, to compost them instead, and well, we can easily reduce our waste by a half.
Imagine if everybody reduced their waste by a half, we perhaps wouldn't need these 129 incinerators these 250 landfills anymore. And we might be able to clean up all their environment damage.
People often tell me that's all well and good, but, this may destroy jobs.
It's true, this may destroy some jobs, but the good news is that it will create so many more.
For each job in the waste elimination industry because we have seen that this process isn't about elimination, we could create up to 10 jobs in the recycling industry, maybe up to 100, in activities around reducing waste at its source.
For example, jobs in the repairing industry.
In Europe, a recent report published a few weeks ago by the European Environmental Bureau, has shown that we could create up to 850,000 jobs, in the coming years, by developing recycling, and reuse of waste.
This would come down to giving a job to one in six young people currently unemployed in Europe.
So these little efforts that each of us can do at an individual level, are fine, are vital, but they obviously can't replace collective and public action, since local authorities are in charge of collecting, treating and managing household waste.
Some authorities in Europe have already tackled the problem, they are engaged in a "Zero Waste" approach.
"Zero Waste" means zero waste, but also zero wastage, as the word "waste" has two meanings, and they are very important.
So, what is this "Zero waste" approach?
Well, it simply means making waste reduction your top priority, to do everything possible to reduce waste at its source.
For this, it is necessary for everyone to participate, citizens, elected representatives, shopkeepers, businesses, schools, colleges, in short, everyone in our society must work together.
In Capanorri, in Italy, the inhabitants have succeeded in this struggle, they have managed to reduce their waste by 80%,
80%, by only doing simple things: separating organic waste, opening up bulk stores, meaning without any packaging, multiplying repair shops and second hand shops, lots of things that don't require crazy investments, that call for energy, good will and common sense, and 80% is a figure many local representative dream of as local budgets for treating waste weighs a lot on the budget of local authorities.
We can think "Zero Waste" is amazing, it makes us want to do it, but it will never work in France, because the French are undisciplined, it's not part of their culture, that our ecological conscience isn't as developed
as our European neighbors', etc.
I disagree with this for several reasons.
First, because we also have pioneers, innovators, who around France, launch initiatives for the reduction of waste, entrepreneurs: for example in Lille, Nantes, Paris and Bordeaux, at this very moment, there are entrepreneurs who are setting up packageless stores, bulk stores. And I also disagree because I don't believe it's a cultural issue.
Well, first, the evidence, the best examples, the pioneers who set the example for the rest of Europe, are the Italians, and the Spaniards.
Therefore, we can't say that Latin countries can't do it.
And finally because this cultural issue is a lame excuse.
An excuse at an individual level to make up for the efforts we could make, it is also an excuse at a collective level, and for political and economic decision makers.
Have we really done everything we can do in France, so that the French could be recycling and waste reduction champions?
I'm not so sure.
For example, have we standardized the colours of recyling bins everywhere in France so that when we move, we don't have to learn everything once again?
Have we set up real economic incentives, so that our disposables get sold at their true environmental cost?
No, I think we haven't tried everything, so we can't say that the battle is lost.
In addition, this can happen very quickly.
I'm not talking about 20 or 30 years' time. I'm talking much sooner than that.
In Gipuzkoa for example, in the Spanish Basque country, there are 710,000 inhabitants who succeeded in reversing the trend in less than 2 years.
They used to send 70% of their waste to the incinerator or landfill sites, and now, they save or recycle 70% of their waste.
So this is proof that we can advance fast and well.
So, if you think that we could put these 14 billion euros spent in waste treatment to a better use, if you feel bad about throwing away your peels, if you think that just isn't logical to pollute to clean up, to have to heal, and that we'd better change our habits and our lifestyle, to avoid all of these risks, well, you can join the optimistic and ambitious people, because "Zero Waste", zero waste and zero wastage, can be here tomorrow, if you want it to.
Thank you.
(Applause)
What do these two everyday objects, a drug and a smartphone, have in common?
We will try to solve this little riddle today, in the next few minutes.
First, the drug: I have always been fascinated by this object.
The mere fact of swallowing it is somehow almost magical, it's enough to cure diseases, sometimes, to even brave death.
I have always been fascinated by the fact that this same drug helps to cure billions of people, all of them different: you, your neighbor, me.
It is the challenge of personalized medicine: to understand why, when I have a headache, if I take an aspirin pill, that is enough to relieve my pain, while my neighbor needs two of the same pills to relieve the same headache pain.
Therefore, these questions are the challenges of tomorrow
when it comes to understanding our personal response to treatment,
and above all, finding the best treatment for everyone.
So I suggest you keep in mind these questions, - they are particularly dear to me, we shall return to them later - and I first suggest that you look back in the rearview mirror a little
and notice the extraordinary progress that has been made in medicine in the past century: we've extended life expectancy, and decoded our genes.
Louis Pasteur would have believed science was a fiction novel had he seen the extent of our modern biology;
there are decades of technological revolution behind this drug.
On the other hand, what an extraordinary progress has been achieved in computer science in the past 30 years thinking back at how computers used to occupy entire rooms.
Today, we concentrate a phenomenal computing power in the palm of our hands.
Do you remember Alan Turing? Alan Turing who was considered the father of the modern computer during the World War II; I think he would have believed science is a fiction novel too, had he seen the extent of our modern computer science.
My vocation is to bring these two worlds together and power, inside a computer, the stimulation of an organism, of your personal response to treatment.
Of course, behind these scientific and technological stakes, there are several social issues hidden.
Do you know that this drug, apparently so innocent, so familiar, is very far from being a mere drug? There are more deaths each year due to inadequate medication than people killed in road accidents and suicides combined.
I think that this small object, a smartphone or a computer, can help tackle these issues.
And before talking technology, I would like to start by sharing a little personal anecdote.
I want to talk to you about my wife, Caroline.
Caroline is an avid animal rights activist.
On my part, for several years, I worked on cancer in an experimental biology laboratory and among our activities, we sometimes worked on animals.
You can imagine the disaster at home sometimes.
That was something.
Of course, she would question me: do we have the right to sometimes abuse animals and is it always really that useful?
We have an extremely complex debate and of course, I will never deny all the contributions experimental biology and animal biology to current knowledge.
Nevertheless, this discussion made me question myself, and I would like to share with you some of that reflection today.
That's true, this drug originally was designed based on animals,
then only afterwards, it was tested on man.
But not on you in particular!
Remember, we all respond differently, You, me, my neighbor.
Why? Because you, madam,
are not the replica of you, sir.
That explains why you respond differently to this treatment.
And if I may, you, madam, are even less the replica of a lab mouse.
When, in fact, cancer is tackled through the animal, we want to cure Cancer with a big C.
I do not want to cure cancer.
I do not want to cure cancer.
I want to cure your cancer.
If one day it should happen to you, and I do not wish it, but if that were the case, I would love to find the best treatment for you which is not the same as your neighbor’s because your cancer would not be the replica of your neighbor’s cancer and even less, once again, the replica of a cancer artificially induced in a laboratory animal.
Isn't there another way of conceiving things?
The idea's here to start from the patient, from you, from your characteristics, to project them into the machine, create what is called a digital twin, and in this digital twin, test the response to the treatment,
thus decreasing animal testing which is costly and ethically questionable, and in addition, better targeting the response to treatment.
So how do we get there?
Of course, our organism is extremely complex:
a man's is diffrent from a woman's but I believe women's are sometimes particularly more complex. The complete opposite
is also true, I assure you.
On a more serius note, I like the analogy with electronics to grasp this magnificent complexity.
I am always amazed when I see the circuit in a simple radio,
the complexity of its connections, sub-circuits, and components. There is very similar to our complex organism.
Of course in biology, in our organism, the interactions are not electronic, they are chemical, physical, biological and this is precisely the mission of biology: to decipher this complexity.
But there is a fundamental difference with electronics: no human has conceived the blueprint of our organism.
When a radio breaks down, since we know the blueprint, we know how to repair it.
It's a whole different story when our organism breaks down, gets sick.
we do not know the blueprint, so it's a little bit as if some natives of Amazon, however intelligent they may be, had to understand and repair a radio overnight.
That, again, is the challenge of biology.
In recent years, we have come to understand better and more and more pathologies.
Thousands of research teams around the world, are decrypting this complexity, understanding small pieces of circuitry, independent pieces of the puzzle.
This is where computer science and mathematics come into play.
With these tools, we will be able to reattach these little bits and to make live in a virtual world, in the machine, these bits, assembled circuits, puzzle pieces that we simulate, that we make come alive inside the computer.
What you see here is a virtual cell, a cancer cell, It is in fact the projection of a cancer cell in a software, what is commonly called an application.
Again we see the analogy with electronics, there are all these circuits, these connections.
Again, it's biology.
And we see all this complexity of the cancer cell which makes it formidably effective.
Each dot, of course these are not dots of electronic components, is a biological interaction, a protein for example.
We saw there Akt, Ras, which is a protein that is involved in the virulence of many cancers: pancreatic cancer, skin cancer...
What is particularly interesting in this virtual cancer cell is that it is not simply a collection of information.
In fact, behind each dot, each entity in this network, hides an equation.
And behind a whole network is a system of equations at the confluence between mathematics and biology.
It is called bio-mathematics,
also called the biology of systems and it allows us to set this network to music, to play, to simulate parts of this virtual cell, parts, pieces of this puzzle in the machine.
So this is an incredible playground, because this complexity is very difficult for the human brain to apprehend.
And thanks to the computer tool and the mathematical tool, we are able to master, control and visualize this complexity.
And when we visualize things, we are making a big step towards solving problems.
Now, let's put us in the shoes of a drug designer.
Let us play the role of the pharmaceutical laboratory.
In this digital twin, we will be able to test the new drugs to reduce animal testing and to promote experimentation on virtual patients who will reflect your own diversity.
Tomorrow, why not test your own response to your medications on your own avatar, your own digital twin?
Not to cure cancer, to cure your cancer.
Personally, I am convinced that this innovation, tomorrow, will knock on our door, for medicines of everyday life.
I say that because we talk a lot about big data, right now in biology.
It is in direct connection with our subject, these massive data, are the data that make us all different, explain our differences, my weight, my age, my height, but also my genetic data, my bio-markers... therefore explain our difference in response to treatment and why I need less aspirin than my next door neighbour.
These numerical and mathematical models that I have shown you feed on these massive data and biological data.
Thanks to them, we will be able to build and specify your avatar, set up your digital twin.
So you understood it, presently, we talk a lot about personalized medicine.
Today, I told you about customized modeling in a calculation concentrate, like this one, to be able tomorrow to simulate your personal response to the treatment.
This is really the challenge of personalized medicine, digital medicine, the medicine of the future.
You may think I'm exaggerating a little.
In fact, that is my belief, even if perhaps today, for some, my words resonate like a science fiction novel.
Thank you.
(Applause)
I am a comedian.
I had two dreams in my life when I was little.
The first one was to become a comedian.
And the second was to get rid of
inequality because I thought it unfair that to become a comedian was a possibility, even a conceivable dream. while other people less fortunate than me, could even imagine such an idea.
Because as Oscar Wilde once said, "In a nation, there's a part of the population that think more about money than the rich and those are the poor people."
The poor people can't think of anything else.
This is what the curse of being poor is.
The first dream came true.
But the second hasn't yet.
I told myself I would find a technique to eradicate the inequalities: marry a billionaire.
I calculated that if 7 billion people each married one of 1827 billionaires: on the basis of joint ownership of property, in only one generation, we would be able to eradicate inequality.
Well, I'm not an expert in probability.
I'm better in statistics.
I calculated that today I had one chance out of 6 of marrying someone who suffered from hunger.
And was not anorexic: malnourished.
One chance in 4 of marrying someone who earned less than $1.25 per day.
A very, very poor person from Asia or Africa.
One chance in 2 of marrying someone who earned less than $2 a day.
In other words, even in Europe, you don't earn much.
And one chance in... 8 millions of marrying a billionaire.
Is there anyone here who earns more than 10 millions euros a year?
