Hello.
I studied in Brazil, did my first work placement in Bangladesh, then worked in Haiti and in Uganda.
However, I have never traveled as much as I have since returning to Paris.
Because on returning to Paris, Florence and I created Kialatok.
Kialatok is a social insertion enterprise that offers training in diversity and intercultural understanding, based on an innovative educational approach centered around international cookery workshops.
Oh yes, cooking is cool!
But us, we're not the new Top Chef.
For us, cooking is a tool, a sort of applied globalization.
We are convinced that cooking is the best way to discover foreign cultures.
And that is useful for businesses.
Tell me what you eat, and I'll tell you who you are.
So, while cooking a moqueca with Marina, you will discover the mixed influences of the Brazilian society.
With Madame Fofana, you will always cook a little more.
The unexpected is not a problem in Guinea and that has implications for team management.
With Madame Zhang you will discover that at a business lunch in China, you shouldn't clear your plate, or you could offend your host.
With this training tool, we help businesses gain a better understanding of new markets, prepare expatriate staff, make associates realize, that diversity is a source of creativity and innovation.
It is good to be useful to businesses, but being useful to society is better.
At Kialatok, we think that qualifications are not the only proof of talent.
Believe me, a woman who prepares a wedding banquet for 400 people, is not going to be asked which cookery school she graduated from.
So, at Kialatok, it is sometimes the most unexpected people who find themselves at the forefront.
Our cookery presenters include those who have difficulty in accessing employment.
Refugees, the long-term unemployed.
We recruit them in partnership with other organizations and through our encounters, and then we train them in: hygiene, catering, public speaking, self-confidence, French, IT skills, with one objective, to develop their skills in order to reintegrate them into the labor market.
It is our committed approach to create a vision of the other as a source of enrichment.
And in Paris, we are very rich.
Because in Paris, one in five people is of immigrant stock.
Cooking is a way of bringing together worlds that don't mix.
And when you do it with the business world, with decision-makers, managers, and executives, well, it has a multiplier effect.
For us, diversity is not a product, it is the very essence of our organization.
Some come from Bangladesh, others from Nancy.
Some are young, others are my parents' age.
Some have qualifications, others don't.
And if our model works, it is because diversity is a source of enrichment.
Our vision is that cooking and culture can stir the world.
That everyone, with their qualities, with their specific ingredients, can contribute to creating a communal recipe.
Because in reality, living better together, starts with making everyone sit down around the same table.
Thank you.
(Applause)
(Spanish) When somebody has (Italian) an interest in languages, (Italian) it becomes (Br Portuguese) addictive. (Portuguese) You start (German) with one language, then another, (Swedish) and you can't stop, and even if happens (Norwegian) that you (English) mix them up, (Bosnian) it's OK, it's fun. (Russian) Each language opens you (Romanian) a door into a universe, into a culture. (Turkish) If we want to get to know our world (Greek) we must learn new languages. (French) Today I speak 11 languages; however, things didn't start well at all.
I had spent a year and half studying katakana, hiragana, kanji, polite expressions, and the only thing I still remember in Japanese, is (Japanese) "What's there in the tree?" This isn't a daily used sentence.
In fact, we've been prepared
to take tests, not to speak.
But I didn't throw in the towel, and I continued.
I kept on trying to learn languages.
I didn't give up.
But I have a question for you:
what language would you like to learn?
What language would you like to learn and why this language in particular?
Why do you want to learn another language?
I ask you why you want to learn another language because we learn a new language for two reasons.
The first one is the stick, and the second one is the carrot.
The stick is what we were all subjected to as children.
In order to learn a language, we had to be constrained because otherwise, we wouldn't communicate with our family or our circles.
This is also true in border regions, like in Alsace, where people are bilingual
or in areas where there is a lot of foreign trade, like Sweden, or countries where the language has been imposed, like in Corsica.
There are many areas where hard power was imposed, but when you don't get the stick, you can get your carrot.
So the carrot is to find yourself a goal in order to learn.
That goal can be, "I'll go abroad,"
or "I'll find myself a girlfriend." It can be a good way to practice a language.
My carrot is traveling.
It's traveling because when I am in Kumkapi, a district of Istanbul where English is useless, - and because I speak a little Turkish - I can play backgammon with a fisherman. (Applause)
So I find myself playing backgammon with a Turkish fisherman, and asI speak a few Turkish words, - I am not fluent in Turkish, but I speak it a little - he feels comfortable with me. And he invites me to go fishing with him at the Golden Horn, and eat fish with him on his boat.
So when I find myself alone with Ahmed on his boat, I know why I put so much effort into learning a foreign language.
You need a carrot, a carrot that makes you move forward.
A carrot that keeps you going,
that simply means treating yourself.
So since you treat yourself, you may as welle learn a simple language, right?
But saying 'a simple language' does not really make any sense
because for a Mandarin Chinese , it is much easier to learn Cantonese than Italian.
But for us French, some languages are simpler than others.
Do you know why?
Actually, there are families of languages so those of you who know this, do you know which family French belongs to?
Latin, is the common answer.
Technically, they're called Roman languages but, in fact, they are just our brothers and sisters.
We also have cousins.
Many of them.
We have a lot of distant cousins from Iceland to India and to Iran.
Our brothers and sisters are in blue.
That's just our brothers and sisters, but we have a lot of cousins and some of them really like travelling.
So we can speak the languages in our language family, everywhere on the planet.
We have cousins we have not seen for 7,500 years.
When you haven't seen them for 7,500 years, you kind of forget about your family history, but sometimes you still remember the name of our aunt.
Which brings us to the mother, "die Mutter" in German, "madar" in Farsi.
Some things stay the same, such as "father", "brother", "sister", but you forget about them, because in 7,500 years, you're bound to forget things.
But let's take a look at our brother
and sister languages. This is one of them.
If some may know it, iplease keep quiet so that the others can play the game.
Do you understand what this dialogue is all about?
I'll help you a little bit by doing just that.
This way, you can easily understand
what is being said:
"What's your name?"
" My name is Adrian. And you?"
" My name is Alina. How old are you?"
Here, you may all think "two" because it indeed sounds similar, but when I highlight it like that, perhaps you will think: 2 x 10 = 20 years, and suddenly Alina is 3 x 10 and 5, 35 years.
Some of you must have thought: "Yes, but that was easy, after all."
But you always start with the easy stuff when learning a language.
And those who think that it was difficult, you see that with a bit of information in fact, you can understand.
You can understand, but it is not enough.
Sometimes you also have to speak.
But with education, nothing is impossible.
Here you have it in Spanish, Romanian, Portuguese, and Italian.
They look alike, don't they?
Some things will help you speak.
These are tools.
Some may remember the 4th grade classes, if I talk about prefixes and suffixes... but we can't just call them tools anymore.
This is a toolbox that helps you build words.
With these tools, you can build our own words.
For example, here we have "education" in many languages.
In Portuguese: "educação".
If you had to say "training"?
Education, "educação", training, "formação".
Well done!
Similarly, in Spanish, "formación",
"formare" in Romanian, "formazione" in Italian.
There is also the word "impossible", but first I'll confirm for "training".
You see those tools, once you master them, you know them, you can create many things.
Even if it seems a little unbelievable, I'm sure you can do the same with this word.
And even if in other languages it doesn't look similar, it still seems it may be said like that.
Sometimes, you make up words.
When I arrived in Germany - I spent six months there - for five months, I said, (German) "Ich habe die Impression" because I wanted to say,
"I have the impression".
I tried. I tried and I was understood.
So for me it was fine.
But I paid attention and I noticed that no one ever said "impression".
So there had to be a problem.
I asked and I understood they say, "eindruck".
At first sight, they have nothing in common, but in fact words are built exactly in the same way:
"im-", "ein-", "pressure", "druck".
So I was wrong, but they understood me.
But as I believe I'm not stupid, I said to myself, "I won't repeat my mistake."
When I arrived in Sweden, I said,
"I'll do the same. I'll rebuild the word."
I knew the prefix" im-" is "in-", and that "pressure" is " tryck".
So I came up with the word "intryck".
(Laughter)
And I was right. It turned out I was.
So don't be afraid to make up words.
You musn't be afraid to make up words, because that's how languages were created.
We used these tools.
I presented you some, but there are hundreds to invent words.
And you may be right only six times out of ten.
But if you are understood eight out of ten times, even when you are wrong, you totally win.
Because the goal is to communicate with others.
But that's when you say: "He said he spoke 11 languages, but in fact he invented everything.
This guy is a phony."
Yes, you could say that.
You're thinking, "He does not speak these languages fluently."
True, I don't speak them fluently, but I do speak them.
I speak them as much as possible.
Until I can't speak anymore.
But if that's what you think, I'm sure you're French... you were tortured by Madame Michaud and her 4th grade dictations.
She sent you to the corner with a dunce cap on, just because you had said: "If I would have."
That when your neighbor says: "The car of Michel,"
you tell him, "No. Michael's car."
(Laughter) We are demanding with each others in our own language.
So, when we learn another language we are similarly demanding.
Worse, we impose such requirements on other people learning our language.
That's why when a foreigner arrives in France, he's told: "In France, we speak French, sir." And we correct them when
when they make mistake.
I wish you never get told upon arrival in Greece: (Greek) [...] because then you'll look utterly silly.
So you have to be tolerant towards someone who's learning a foreign language because we don't learn everything in one day.
Do not wait until you speak it perfectly in order to get started.
You have to start from day one.
You don't have to know a language perfectly.
You're not going to say: "I'm learning Russian because my goal is to read Dostoyevsky but right now I can't speak it."
No, you speak it from day one.
Besides, do you know how many words it takes to speak a language?
One.
With one word, you can already start talking.
You can say "thank you", "hello", - the words you've learned - but you are already speaking.
What's worse is you're usually answered in the same language, and then you are a little lost.
But it doesn't matter, you have started.
With ten words you can be polite.

"Hello.", "How are you?",
"Thank you.", "I'd like to..."
With 30 words, you can introduce yourself and ask others to introduce themselves.
100 words will suffice for a basic conversation.
With 100 words, you can explain where you come from, where you're going, what your goals are, what you're doing there.
But with 100 words, we manage to communicate. You don't have to look for your words too much.
Because if you do, people stop listening, like you did the whole time I was looking for words.
Don't do that to others. Spare them.

You talk maybe well ?
You know if sentence good, no?
But you say things.
Say many things.
(Laughter) "Others you understand, important is."
You all understood me.
I'm sorry. It goes to show that
Grammar is just elegance.
I could have said the same thing using a better vocabulary, too.
But if the message got through, I won.
So learning comes with practice.
My technique is hitchhiking.
Why hitchhiking? Because you meet people.
you meet people,
and it's kind of like speed dating.
Every 30 km, you have to start again.
You repeat the same conversation.
You say where you come from, where
you're going, what you're doing.
You talk about your job, the other person's job. That's how you consolidate your knowledge.
You must seize all opportunities to use these 100 words you know.
Because if you seize them all, you'll get to know 101, 102, 103 words.
You must speak every day.
Also, when you hitchhike, you really get a lot of people to talk to.
(Laughter) But a language is more than words.
Words are the basis, but you'll have to imitate.
(English with a French accent) Because if I start to speak in English like that, maybe you have the impression that's English, but for me, this is really French. (Laughter) This is French with English words, but this is not English. (in French) Because French, has its own melody: ta-ta-ta-ta-ta.
When I say something, ta-ta-ta-ta-ta, I'm also singing,
but we don't realize it because you're overwhelmed by the meaning of what you and the other are saying.
But when you speak a foreign language with such an accent, as I've just used in English, in fact you're speaking with the melody of the French language.
When I arrived in Brazil, I only knew one word (so I started talking)
"Obrigado", thank you
- basic courtesy when visiting a country - but I spoke fluent Spanish,
I had that advantage.
So, I spoke Portuguese like this.
I thought Brazilian Portuguese sounded a bit like this, so I spoke Spanish like this. (Laughter)
If I had not done that, they would have understood me even less. But they understood me.
And as I kept talking, I learnt.
Because what I used everyday got confirmed and so on.
But it goes further than words.
If I talk like this... well, it is Napolitan.
(Laughter) But if I do that when I talk to a Swede, they'll ask me if I have a problem.
(Laughter) There's something wrong,
Even if I have the best accent in the world.
Because gestures have an accent, too.
And it goes much further.
I'm sure some of you are not from Toulouse but you already went into a bakery, and asked for a 'pain au chocolat' (Laughter) and you've been asked: "Would you like a bag for your 'chocolatine', sir?"
(Laughter) They made it clear to you that you aren't from around here.
(Laughter) Because sometimes, little things give the impression you speak well.
When you come here, and you say "chocolatine", even if you have a Parisian accent, you'll sound as if you are from here.
So you must become the people whose language you're learning.
So it's all well and good, but I won't deny it takes effort to learn a language.
And sometimes you are a bit lost, you don't know, you feel
you're not making any progress, but you must persevere.
Even when you think you're not making any progress anymore because this is when knowledge settles.
But difficulty is elsewhere.
The only difficulty is to dare.
You must dare to speak from day one.
You must dare to make up words.
You must dare to make mistakes.
Forget about people who tell you: "When you do not know something, keep silent."
In fact, in a nutshell, you must dare to believe you can learn a foreign language.
Once you dare, you'll prove to the other that since you're interested in their language, you're interested their culture, you're interested in them.
And suddenly, they will open a door into that culture for you.
You will discover a people, a story.
The only question you need to ask yourselves now is how much effort you are willing to put in to deserve that smile.
Thank you.
(Applause)
I love bees.
I love bees because they have always brought us light.
First, the one that illuminates so that night would be manageable.
We need to recall a time when electrical energy didn't exist.
As soon as the sun was setting, nothing was left on Earth, only darkness,
and to oppose this darkness, man only had one thing: the flame, that of the fire, in a first time, and then, that of the candle, which enabled to share the light, to split it, to spread it into an area.
Last September, I went to the mountains, alone.
I needed to get away from people's company for some days.
I started walking in a long hiking trail.
And very quickly, I branched off into a small valley which seemed to me wild.
After only a few hours' walk, far away from any path, I felt that I was the only man in the world, the first one to discover this territory.
Then, I walked through the mountainside to reach the ridge.
And when evening came, I went back down to the forest, to look for a shelter and spend the night in it.
I found two big rocks, with a cavity and enough space to build a fire and put my sleeping bag.
And that was indeed, the first thing I did: lighting this campfire.
I woke up many times during the night to add wood in order to ensure that this little flame did not fade away.
I was not cold, - I had a good sleeping bag -; there was no danger; but I needed this comforting small cocoon of light to make the sounds of the night acceptable.
Turn off all the lights of the cities, just one night, and spend this night without flame, without fire, without candle, - without this candle made from beeswax - and you'll understand that this gift bees gave to us for many millennia is a special and marvelous gift.
From an early age, I was attracted to bees.
I remember my first emotions, the curiosity that seized me when a beekeeper placed his hives near my parents' house.
I remember the long hours I spent watching those bees.
The first encounter was rather brutal, since, at about eight years of age, I decided to open one of these beehives, unprotected.
I got stung dozens of times, and I ended up in the hospital.
But, that day too, I got stung by a passion, a passion for bees, that will resurface more than 25 years later, and give birth to a beautiful project, a beautiful company, a special and wonderful company I am still managing today.
It was in 2007 that I heard again this call, this very, very strong need to move towards the bees.
I told my friends about this.
I told my family.
All were a bit surprised.
And one evening, I received a phone call from one of my friends, saying that a swarm of bees had settled on a roundabout, a few hundred meters from my house, at the entrance to my village.
I was not a beekeeper.
I didn't know how to do, but I did remember that if I were to look at the bees unprotected, I'd sleep in the hospital.
So I got in touch with a beekeeper, who gave me a protective clothing, and also some advices, and then I went back home.
I built a small hive with an old cardboard box that I kept in my garage.
Then, I went to submit it to the bees.
By chance, they accepted it.

That was it! I became a beekeeper!
In the months following this new encounter with bees, I went to observe them almost every day, and I felt a new energy, a desire for change I could not explain to myself, at the beginning.
I understood that my life was not in full swing.
And I had a sense of fragmentation: on one side, my childhood dreams, and personal aspirations, and on the other side, my life as a reasonable adult.
I understood I missed the contact with nature.
I missed the eager expectation of springtime, the anticipation of the flowering and delighting with the bees when it comes.
I also missed a simpler work environment,
less hierarchical, less administrative.
I understood that the human being is, above all, an animal. - a beautiful animal, intelligent and creative - and that, in order to let this authentic nature express itself, it needed less control, more freedom.
And I dreamed of a beautiful business, in which each people would keep their energy, this beautiful energy, for real projects, real fights, not for attending meetings, answering hierarchical requests or completing dashboards.
And that's what we have tried to create.
My associate Olivier and I, have created 'Un Toit Pour Les Abeilles', a company whose core business is the conservation of bees.
First, we have offered individuals and businesses to become sponsors of hives, and to commit to protect the bees, on their behalf.
Within a few months, we have convinced thousands of individuals, hundreds of businesses, and created a large network of beekeepers which, today, covers the entire France.
Above all, it is in the way it operates that this company was going to find its originality.
And it is the observations of bees, the contacts with bees, that have led us to re-examine the modus operandi of the company.
The first thing we saw was that swarming, that ball of bees that came to land at the center of this roundabout.
I didn't understand why those bees had left their hive.
I searched on the Internet.
I read texts.
And above all, I heard the first beautiful story that bees had just told me.
Swarming is a very particular moment in the life of the bee colony.
That's the natural way the bee colonies multiply in the wild.
We speak about the fever of swarming because nothing can stop it.
The old queen, followed by half of the bees, leaves the beehive, with uncertainty, and in absolute destitution, leaving future generations with all of the resources: honey, beewax, propolis, and the hive which will enable the young queen, remaining there with the other half of the bees, to give birth to the future generations and raise them in good living conditions.
What an extraordinary example for the human being who has chosen to take an immediate ownership of the planet's resources, even if this means depriving the future generations of them.
But, from these observations, we have learned another lesson, directly applicable to the company's life: that of the strength of desire.
Over the years, I noticed that the colonies that left to swarm were the strongest; that they resisted to everything, - weathering, sicknesses, parasites, external attacks - and that they developed at whatever cost.
This old queen and her bees, they didn't leave in despair but rather with an altruistic joy, a strong desire, a common project, a common vision, that of building a new city, and make it prosper.
And this was the strength of this vision that made this colony of bees so robust.
Therefore, we have decided to take into account the strength of desire as the main driver for the development of our company.
And if these bees embodied such a strong unchanging desire, this is because they had chosen freely and without constraints, to embark on this adventure.
Half of the bees had remained in the hive, with the young queen, and the other half, had launched into that adventure. special and marvelous, having chosen it fully.
If we wanted to let this desire open out in the company, it was absolutely necessary to bring more freedom, and more independence to everyone.
And this is what we have chosen to do.
We have decided that there'd be no obligation to work from a precise location anymore.
Everybody would be free to work from the office, but also from home, from a shared office, or from anywhere in France.
We have also proposed that each may organise his day depending on his professional commitments, of course, but also depending on personal needs, - need to rest during the day, to exercise, organisation of family life, personal meetings - these needs are part of the schedules of each and no control is maintained on them.
We can find in the business processes this method from the bees, this freedom, this independence, which are, in my view, one of the main motivating tools in the company.
But, in order to let everyone's talent fully blossom, we had to go further.
And again, the bees has shown us a possible way.
As we looked more closely to the swarming, we noticed that it could teach us another valuable lesson, that was going to lead us to rethink the decision-making mechanisms in the company, namely: the complete absence of leader and hierarchy in a beehive.
There is a tendency to believe that a hive is very hierarchical, with a quasi-military organization.
In reality, it's just the opposite.
In it, reigns a genuine democratic principle, and decision-making is shared with all the bees.
So, let's get back to our swarming!
Half of the bees, accompanied by this old queen, are just leaving the hive, and are gathering a few tens of metres away in order to form a bunch of bees, a swarm.
Then, the bee scouts go off in all directions,
to explore the territory and discover a permanent hosting place: a hollow tree trunk, a cavity, which could be located several miles away.
Then, the whole swarm takes off to settle in this final place.
So, we have dozens of bee scouts which go off in dozens of directions, come back with hundreds of pieces of information which they share with thousands of bees, and, at the end of this decision-making process, only one piece of information will remain which will be essential for the colony, a piece of information that will have to be shared by all and accepted by all the bees: the location of the final settlement.
If we look at the surface of that swarm, we can see some groups of bees that are dancing.
It is by this way the bees share the pieces of information and, above all, make decisions.
This discovery has been made by a scientist named Von Frisch, who received the Nobel Prize for having understood this bee language.
And this bee language is very specific.
In our case, bees can indicate, for example, the direction, with 1 degree accuracy, the distance, with 1 metre accuracy, and the quality of the potential hosting place for the colony.
Each dance represents a specific piece of information.
As with humans, some bees prove to have more power of persuasion because they're sure their idea is the
right one. They embody this conviction.
These bees dance in a way sufficiently persuasive to pull other bees, with them, into that dance.
And some of these other bees go out to check if this location is the special and marvelous place expected by the whole colony.
And if so, they come back with the same joy, dance with as much persuasion, and pull other bees again in their dance.
Slowly, the other dances fade away, and unity is made; then the swarm, the group of bees take off to go and settle in its permanent home.
We can see that, in this process, there is no hierarchy, no leader, no bee with a particular role.
This is what we have attempted to implement in our company.
Everyone is, now, free to come with an idea, to explain it to the group, and win its acceptance; and if it so succeeds in winning the support of the group, it will transform into a project.
In few years, this operating mode, this bees' method, enabled us to start various projects: a 'Toit Pour Les Abeilles', with the installation of several thousands of hives in France, every year, 'Des Fleurs Dans La Vallée', which enable us to maintain biodiversity by sowing thousands of square meters of wild flowers, every year, a trade mark in cosmetics from hive-related products, a bee conservatory, a solidarity-based cooperative in Morocco, a garden-sharing service, etc. It is that method, that bee's method, that enables each of us to feel involved, to work with independence, freedom, and share decisions.
Very few animals are able to destabilize the whole structure of life on earth.
The bee and the human being share this responsibility.
By pollinating, the bee takes part in the reproduction of more than 80% of flowering plants.
Without it, we could witness a real chaos both vegetal and animal.
And in a few years, there would be 75% of our crops, and our food supply that would disappear.
With this pollination, the bee succeeded in implementing a smart strategy, which serves its personal interests, and benefits nature in its whole as well.
The more the bee works, and collects the nectar that will produce its honey, the more it pollinates, and the more it takes part in the growth of the plant mass.
It is also by its work that the human being can try to change the world.
By applying in businesses the principles of the beehives - autonomy, independence, freedom, and, above all, sharing decisions - we give a chance to a strong desire, a common project, to emerge, which is to build our new city, our new world, to make it prosper, and to pass on to future generations the available resources.
Thank you!
(Applause)
Good evening.
To understand and discover the world, I chose an unconventional learning method: traveling
After my high school degree, I focused on a two-years technical degree in information and communication, a cross-training program, with academic courses, tutored projects and internships. It was so comprehensive in fact, that after two years, I couldn't find a bachelor's degree to pursue.
None of them matched what I intended.
Actually, I was looking for a pragmatic degree that would enable me to apply what I 'd just learned, a pedagogical degree so that I could continue to learn, a dynamic degree that would allow me to be in the field, a flexible degree with which I could learn at my own pace with complete freedom, and finally a degree that makes a difference so that I could learn what school doesn't teach us.
Mark Twain has said, "Twenty years from now, you will be more disappointed by the things you didn't do than by the ones you did do.
So throw off the bowlines.
Catch the trade winds in your sails. Explore. Dream. Discover."
I took Mark Twain at his word on that, and at age 20, I took off for the other side of the world.
I spent seven months in Australia, one month in New Zealand, two weeks in India, and one week in Japan.
Once I arrived there, I created my own tailor-made program with traditional subjects like English or geography, and less conventional ones like the discovery of alternative lifestyles, and orienteering.
When you travel, one of the first reactions of loved ones is, "Your will improve your English."
That's unquestionable.
Being in immersion favors language learning.
But beyond the basics taught at school, being in immersion allows for a more concrete approach to the language, such as the expressions we use every day for instance.
Upon my arrival in Austraia, an Australian sends me an SMS inviting me to visit the city.
In his message, there is a word that I don't understand: "hang out".
What comes immediately to my mind is "To hang, hung, hung," English irregular verb meaning "to suspend" and then "out" meaning "exit, movement towards the outside."
I think deeply and wonder what he could be meaning by that.
Finally, I check on the internet, and I learn that "to hang out" is an informal verb that means "to hang around, to go out."
Later I did give up this so-called "academic" way of thinking and familiarized myself with a more vernacular thinking.
Sure, it was at school where I learned the basics of English, but to become proficient, it's on the spot that I learned its subtleties.
After English, I learned geography.
Japan was one of the topics of study for the high school diploma.
I recalled that Tokyo was one of the most important megalopolises in the world, with a very high population density that is around 6000 people per km2.
So, I was picturing a teeming city, always bustling, with people everywhere at all times in the midst of huge buildings.
Once I got there, I saw that crowd, and I saw the buildings, but I didn't see the frenzy that I had anticipated.
I was even surprised to see that in the midst of this urban effervescence, there were green spaces where time seemed to stop.
I only spent one week in Japan, but it felt like it was a lot longer because each day was full of discoveries.
At school, only my vision and hearing were stimulated, but during this trip, my five senses were activated.
I heard spoken Japanese.
I saw a sumo wrestling.
I tasted green tea, the soba noodles and sushis.
I smelled the incense and touched the patinated wood of the temples.
That way, that journey offered me a different approach to Japanese culture, all while consolidating my knowledge.
Then, I went on with the discovery of alternative lifestyles.
In addition to managing a budget, I discovered a new way to consume.
On my visits to some Australian and New Zealander families, I became accustomed to their way of living that favored an organic-local-equitable strategy in all area of life.
That's when I made my first discovery of organic community gardens, "opportunity shops" that give objects a second life that were much more developed there than in France, solidarity-based banks where interests were distributed to associations, and finally the exchange of skills.
Well, beyond that, I also learned and acquired a new way of looking at the world, an optimistic outlook with solutions for the future.
Then, all along my stay, I moved around by airplane, by boat, by train, by tramway, by subway, by bus, by car, and even by rickshaw in India.
From the largest airports in the world to dirt pathways in the Indian countryside or the Australian bush, I learned to get around and find my bearings without much difficulty.
My travels familiarized me with great distances, and now wherever I go, the temporal and geographic framework doesn't scare me, I feel at ease.
This mobility develops a useful attitude in everyday life, the skills of getting informed, facing the unexpected, and getting organized.
So knowing how to find out where you are allows you to go beyond your borders whether literally or figuratively.
Traveling is also an inner journey.
While traveling, I grew in a new environment, full of learning and open to the world.
To paraphrase the philosopher Francis Bacon, travels are the education of youth, and the experience of the elderly.
Traveling enables you not only to enrich your knowledge, but also to learn to know yourself better.
When you travel, you confront yourself by coming out of your comfort zone to make new experiences.
Australia is 15 times larger than France.
As a result, the sense of distance is very different than the one that we have in Europe.
To go from one city to another, airplane is the preferred method of transport.
For everyday trips, you may have to spend as much as one hour on the road just to find the closest supermarket.
As a matter of fact, while on holiday with an Australian family, I spent 15 days in a small village of 60 people, in the very heart of the bush.
We were lost in the middle of nowhere, yet it was very intense.
It was so hot - up to 45°C in the summer - that at night, we slept on the balcony with the starlight as our ceiling.
During the day, we did some rafting, and fled above the region in a small airplane. We also made some Australian desserts, went on a night excursion to see the wild life, and much more. I would never had imagined I could experience so many unforgettable moments in such a short time and so far from everything.
Traveling is also fighting conventional ways of thinking.
Since I designed my own plan, I chosed to go alone in order to reach out to more people and feel free to go wherever I wanted.
Consequently, I was confronted with myself.
Throughout my journey, I met people with whom I am still in touch and whom I even saw again all along my adventure.
In each country visited, I also found Brits.
It is while being far away from my native Britain that I realized how attached I was to my roots.
But far beyond that, I learned how to handle myself, to rebound when faced with contingencies, to look for solutions to move forward, to know my limits, to grow in an unknown environment, to make connections, to live with people of all ages, of all nationalities, of all cultures.
In a nutshell, I learned to know myself better.
"To exist is to dare throw yourself into the world."
This quote from Simone de Beauvoir captures pretty well the idea of an initiatory journey,
because once we come out after a plunge into the world, we have grown up and acquired new perspectives for the future.
Upon my return to France, my world view had changed.
It had expanded.
Traveling enables us to look at the world differently, in a way quite useful for the future.
These few months spent outside of France turned out to be very instructive.
I acquired new skills, some mobility and another viewpoint on the world.
I had never left France for such a long time, and it was in being far away, 20,000 km away from France on the other side of the world, that I discovered just how much diversity we have whether in gastronomy, in culture, in scenery, and in freedom, freedom of press, of expression, or in social benefits such as social security and the various social benefits that we have.
Not everything is rosy in France but we're not the worst-off either.
In leaving, I learned to put things into perspective.
These few months spend abroad turned out to be of real advantage for my future.
Because I saw, read, wrote and thought in English 24 hours a day for several months, I also took a step back from my own country.
Thanks to this step backward, I have now a new practical way of seeing things.
This custom-made international degree finally met my expectations, and I didn't wish to pursue my studies any further.
Afterwards, I found a work relatively easily.
I don't think I would have learned to be so resourceful and flexible while sitting on a bench in a classroom.
I'm not saying that you should quit school and go "on the road" to learn while traveling.
What I've learned at school served me throughout my travels.
Travel complements school.
It is the school of life.
Let me end this talk with a quote from Anne-Laure Fréant, a French researcher who had lived in Canada and New Zealand.
Her words aptly summarize what traveling has brought me and her own vision of the future.
"Today's path is to explore, to adapt and to experience.
The calling of our time is not that of the monotasking specialist, but that of the independent entrepreneur who is also handyman, Swiss-army-knife like, and intelligent, that of the multi-potential talent."
Thank you for your attention.
(Applause)
When I was a kid, I loved Disney films:
the music, the stories, the songs.
But my favorite movie was Aladdin.
As you may remember, it was the story of a poor young farmer who found a magic lamp,
and when he rubbed it, suddenly, a genie appeared and offered Aladdin three wishes.
Aladdin thought about it, then he asked the genie what he would wish for himself.
Surprised by this question, that no one ever asked him, the genie said he would ask for freedom,
because he was always trapped in the magic lamp, and the moment someone rubs it, he has to obey.
I'm telling you this not because we have magic lamps or genies in the society but because in today's rich and modern society we still have a bunch of people who have far more freedom than others.
I was lucky enough to be born into a wealthy family.
My parents worked very hard to give me and my two brothers a chance in life.
We went to a private school, had a chalet and often went on holidays.
At the age of 26, I got myself into business
not because my parents paid for it but because I had no student debt, and I knew that even if I failed, my parents would be there to help me.
But my situation wasn't an usual one.
During the summer holidays, next to our chalet was a small hotel managed by two pensioners.
They had a grand-child called Martin:
a brilliant, joyful, and intelligent kid. We became good friends.
His grandparents, however, were his only support at home.
His father appeared from time to time, and his mother was on welfare.
The gap between his and my condition became apparent when I was 13.
I lived in Montréal while Martin lived in the South.
So I Invited him to come over to Montréal in the weekend.
But he didn't have enough money for the bus, and his mother also couldn't help him pay the bus ticket.
The fact that a bus ticket could separate my friend and me, shocked me.
How can the gap between rich and poor be so high, in such a wealthy society like ours?
You all know that society's problems rarely have a simple solution.
For more than 200 years, economists and philosophers have been promoting an idea, which at first seemed crazy to me.
It's called basic income.
It's a universal and unconditional payment to everyone.
This means that you, me, and Martin would get a monthly payment in our bank account.
In Quebec, we currently have 2,600 programs, offering financial support to citizens and businesses.
Frankly, it'd take a PhD in bureaucracy to deal with such a system.
And often it's the wealthy with their lawyers and accountants who benefit the most from it.
How could a single mother handle such a situation?
There are thousands of reasons to support a basic income,
but I'll show you my three favorite ones.
Firstly, a basic income could simplify our bureaucracy.
The idea would be to replace our current, complex social safety net, that leaves too many people behind, with a solid foundation for everyone, so we can all build our future upon it.
I wonder how different Martin's life could have been if he and his mother had a basic income, back then.
Maybe he wouldn't have dropped out of high school, like many studies show.
I don't know exactly how his life would have been different, but I know it would have at least helped him to maximize his chances in life.
It would have leveled the playing field of our competitive society.
Scientists and researchers often explain that in order to advance science, their goal isn't to find complex solutions to problems, but rather to find a simple solution after finding the complex ones.
Today we've found a complex solution to our society's problem:
the welfare state, which works relatively well: modern life is a whole lot better than that of our grand-parents.
However, I'm sure that you'll agree that in order to advance society in the 21st century, we have to think differently.
My second argument for basic income, is the elimination of the paternalistic programs that stigmatize and divide society.
Earlier, I mentioned that Martin's mother was on welfare.
While preparing for this speech, people told me to say that she had a low wage, since welfare recipients undergo a stigma.
Our current welfare system divides people into two classes: those who work hard and contribute to welfare, and those who benefit from it.
There are also a lot of people that could benefit from this system but who won't do it, by fear of being or by shame. This often leads to situations that are far worse and harder to fix.
A basic income would allow society to put everybody into the same class: citizens.
My third argument in favor of basic income is also the simplest: we all have a right to live in dignity.
You can look at basic income like the right to vote: a fundamental right at the very roots of our society.
By offering a basic income to all, we would offer dignity to all.
We know that the humanity of each one of us depends on the humanity of all.
Sure, we'll never have a perfect society, but we should strive towards a society where everyone, rich or poor has fair opportunities.
Regardless how rich you, or your family, are, you should have the same opportunities.
It is clear for me that Martin didn't have the same opportunities I had.
The most common argument against basic income, is that everyone would stop working.
However, pilot projects in Canada and elsewhere tell a whole different story. The money given to people is often invested in their future and in the future of their relatives: be it financing their studies, helping their relatives or launching a business or project.
Basic income is an essential tool in order to liberate people from their socio-economic constraints.
I especially want the life of Martin's kids to be better, and that they get their opportunities.
There are still too many people in our society that don't reach their full potential.
And addiction, crime, and school drop outs cost a lot of money.
They cost a lot to the the victims, to their relatives and to society.
A basic income would allow us to avoid many of these problems before they even occur.
We can compare basic income with universal healthcare: when we introduced it back in the 60's, it faced a strong opposition.
Doctors and other people said that it was your fault if you didn't have the money to get the treatment.
It was your fault if you got sick and didn't save enough money in advance.
But after years of debates, eventually we said no:
if we get sick it is our fundamental right to get healthcare. And by offering it to everyone we would all get richer, knowing that nobody had to fear bankruptcy if they got sick.
I'm a radical and I'm proud of it, because basic income is a radical idea that tackles the source of our problems and offers a remedy.
In conclusion, I'm asking you, not to ask yourself what your neighbor would do with 800 dollars a month more.
By the way, next year, the Swiss are going to vote on a basic income of 3,000 dollars a month. So 800 dollars isn't such a big deal.
So again, please don't think what your neighbor or friend would do with the money, but what you would do with it.
And I'm sure you'll invest it in your future, to help your family, your kids and maybe your parents.
Basic income is an idea that must be implemented in the 21st century if we want to advance society.
In 19th century, we fought together to implement the right to vote.
In the 20th century we fought for the welfare state.
I feel that in this century the time for a basic income has come.
At the end of Aladdin, when Aladdin makes his third and last wish to free the genius, the genius couldn't be happier.
I strongly believe that there is no stronger feeling than that of emancipation and freedom.
I'm asking you to help me unleash the full potential of our kids and of our citizens.
Thank you.
(Applause)
Hello.
I don't feel very comfortable. I get the impression I didn't go to school enough.
"Beyond the limits." "Beyond the limits." When I was asked the question what I had done to go beyond the limits, I wondered.
I wondered for a few minutes, then a few hours.
I needed to have a flashback.
And this flashback brought up the question of doors.
It will seem stupid to you, but doors.
I was living in a neighborhood in the 70s, a huge block of council flats that you're familiar with, what we call today the political neighborhoods.
And my world was the stairwell.
I drop out of school, and go from staircase A to staircase B. The gang is growing at staircase C, etc., etc.
Frustration, and at times violence too, create quite a toxic and anxiety-inducing flame.
My mum tells me, "Rather than quarreling or scrapping on the street, do it in the right setting."
A lucky break: judo.
And so judo was a very small door that was opening.
The teacher, a former judo champion, opens the door of the dojo.
The dojo was marvelous because I understood that there were codes.
While I didn't have my own codes, there I had to respect them.
Then I easily understood things, through practice.
I call it the rule of the three Ms: Mimicry, Memory, Mastery.
Wow!
I understood what I was being asked.
I could focus my energy, and I was starting to look ahead, and to move away from the gang that I was in.
So, with mimicry, memory, mastery, I resume some semblance of confidence.
I feel a little stronger, a little bigger, not stuck in the universe that I was in,
not resigned to this world of petty crime.
Sport - yes, passion for sport - yes,
passion for judo - yes.
But not studying sports.
School: rotten.

Everything that I heard before threw me off a bit.
Rotten school, which means
learning, means a profession.
You realize, I'd heard for years and years of workers moulded in mass.
And I meet a mentor, he's a carpenter, a mentor who tells me, "No, no, if you want to join us, there are codes."
I get it.
Here, it's about the nobility of the worker.
So, you have to deserve it.
And there are three keys,
three keys, three important ones:
rigor, - but I'm not talking about precision, more like a project; like a social project, like a personal project -
engagement, stature, presence - looking at the journey in front of you, that is what mentoring is.
That's what the Tour de France is -
and third, regularity: doing it every day.
I'll be proud and happy in this community of men who will take me beyond my limits.
I had left the stairwell, I had left the estate, I had left my town.
I'm discovering France, and all of its teaching abilities.
Great.
And on this journey, I'd learned to accept certain frustrations.
The death-knell tolls for 18 years.
You'll look at me like an old man, but we were going to be called to do our three days of military service.
A step back: unacceptable.
I'm going back to an estate which no longer knows me.
That's not what I want.
I want to leave this estate.
I want to remove myself from my social status.
With my the sheet summoning me in my hands, at the first army recruitment center I come across an man, an officer, who says to me, "Do you do sport?"
"Yes."
"Do you do judo?"
"Yes."
"Then the Marines are for you.
If you want to travel, join."

Wow! Join the marines!
There was a globe there.
"If you are feline and know how to move, you'll be airlifted."
(Laughter) The portrait of General Bigeard, flexible and feline-like,
flexible and resistant like leather.
Wow! That's me.
Great.
I sign up.
In the two situations that I just brought up, each time, what helped me was to accept letting go of the past.
That was my greatest pride, because it was my biggest difficulty: letting go of the past, to move forward, calm, and straight, as General Loth said.
Military projection, operation, end of a military career.
OK, I'm getting there.
I spoke of my flashbacks.
At Austerlitz Station, with my backpack, I'm no longer military, no longer really a civilian.
I learned things with my comrades.
I learned a sense of honor; very rare. Loyalty, and that nothing is gained without sacrifice.
So, I had my pack.
What was sustaining me was when I broke all of this down.
I said to myself, "It's funny.
I have this strength, but not a dime."
I didn't have a dime.
But I felt that 80% of my being was stronger.
I told myself, "I'm going to engage,"
like we do in climbing - use initiative, or in judo, another movement, another hold.
The solution was in the movement.
Again, I accept letting go of the past, to look at my project, my future.
So, fortunately, this position led me to a few distinctions.
Chef of the year.
A Michelin star.
Then a second.
Nationally and internationally recognized.
Developing businesses, companies.
But when I told you that I needed to cut ties with the past, there was always a little thread like that, something tickling me, which was pulling my shoulders a little, like that.
I told myself, "Again, what have you retained from life's ordeals?
That life is a sport?
Yes, a combat sport.
How is a combat sport learned?
Mimicry, Memory, Mastery.
How do you stay like that?
Rigor, a project, engagement, consistency.
You have all of that.
You've succeeded."
I still have projects, but there were still a few threads from the past that I didn't know how to cut.
Cutting them is an art.
The Japanese say, "Tameshigiri, the art of cutting."
So I tell myself, "Right, I'll go back."
40 years later, I go back to the neighborhood.
And I said to myself, "I'm going to pass on these keys."
They aren't just for me,
I need to pass them on."
Because I am deeply convinced that there is no person and no neighborhood made for failure.
So, if it worked for me, it will work for others.
And so we created these schools, a how-to guide to cooking, to baking, to the service industry.
In our schools, the first thing is clear: your past doesn't interest us.
Tell us about your project, not about your qualifications, your qualifications are the result of a project.
And at the bottom of the sheet you sign: R.E.R.
We know what that stands for:
Rigor, Engagement, Reality.
And that is what works in our schools today.
94% of people who accept that go back to their project, back to work.
That's what I wanted to tell you today, with lots of humility:
Mimicry, Memory, Mastery. Rigor, Engagement, Regularity.
Separating with the past is an art; it's tameshigiri.
Look ahead, calm and straight, like General Loth said.
Thank you.
(Applause)
One year ago, I was having my medical examination.
The occupational physician asked me in a very affirmative tone, "Single, I guess ?"
This is a bias that is still too much prevalent in our society: viewing impaired people as asexual.
When the handicap is heavy, such as mine - where I can only move the muscles of my face, a thumb and one toe - is it possible to be loved, enjoy a happy sexual life, and be desired?
I pondered these kind of questions already when I was a teenager, except that, I did it far too long, and I only got an answer at the age of 35 years old.
So, I have been living with my valid partner for two years.
Why do I specify that he is "valid"?
Well, because too many people are still asking me whether my partner is impaired too, as if it should necessarily be the case.
Imagine what would happen if my partner had the same motor difficulties as mine.
Just try to imagine!
Well, don't try too hard though, because you will get bored quickly.
(Laughter) Platonic love, looking at each other in the eye, if it's suitable for some, that's great, but it's not for me.
Besides, I don't want to burden myself with that for the rest of my life.
I stand by this unequivocal way of speaking because I thought about this for a long time, and maybe, had not impairment been a deal-breaker, I would have found a partner more easily, though not necessarily since most impaired people share my opinion.
So I met my man in the association community, far from where I live, during an office meeting.
I liked him immediately.
But my brain kind of stopped me right away to even think about a follow-up to this meeting.
Maybe, it was a protection mechanism because I had experienced too many deceptions with many men who were telling me, for example, "I want to be your friend for life".
That said, because of my lack of experience, I did not recognize the signs on his side.
My carer was the first to tell me, back home, "Laeticia, I think you got a hit!" (Laughter) because he had already asked her a lot of questions about me discreetly.
Indeed, my answer to this was, "That's silly! Your imagination
is running too wild."
It's only after several weeks of discussing together - because he had managed to get my phone number - that I finally realized that my interest was reciprocated.
How wonderful it was to talk about sex with a man who did not see my handicap as a problem!
I was finally a woman who was attractive and worth to meet again.
So, he wanted to meet me.
When he came home, we went to the restaurant, as it is usually the case, and when we went back home, naturally, I wanted him very much.
My way of suggesting this to him was to get ready in my bedroom, in sexy nightwear, with the assistance of my carer of course.
When he came in, his eyes and smile told me that he did not want to leave either.
Now I'll spare you the juicy details of that first night, (Laughter) but what I can tell is that within a few hours, everything changed in my life.
I was desired.
I was touched by hands that were not disembodied like all those that I have known since I was a child.
My body was giving me pleasure, and no suffering anymore.
As for my first time, let's not mince words.
The first time I experienced penetration, I am very lucky to keep such a great memory of it, and not a traumatic one as it is the case for many women.
So, it's my little payback for all the years I had been waiting.
I became the equal of all women, and in addition, thanks to someone I loved.
And event if, obviously, sexuality is not limited to penetration, it was a step, a rite of passage very important to me.
After that, I must have been irritating for those around me because I wanted so much to tell the whole world that I had finally found someone.
I wearied my carer by asking her very often, "Would you say that I have a boyfriend?"
(Laughter) (Giggles) When I finally got used to this idea that I really was in a relationship, I uncovered all the consequences of discovering sexuality at an advanced age.
Well I say "advanced age" but really, I was only 35 years old.
I was not old, yet, it was 20 years late compared to the average age,
especially since I've never been able to masturbate and never gotten a chance to explore my body by myself.
Usually, I guess you remember that, we start exploring our bodies when we are teenagers.
Do you remember these moments of new emotions and feelings flooding your body and your mind?
Do you remember how it impacted you even though you were young?
Even though I feel grown up regarding sexuality, my behavior and feelings, of course, are those of a young teenager.
My experience with love and sex is only two years old.
And the young teenager in me is eagerly looking for sensations and discoveries.
I can't quench my hunger.
(Laughter) Whether it is my character or something missing in my life, I kind of feel that I need to make up for the time lost.
And 35 years is quite a long time!
(Laughter) Even if my heart has not been harmed by a few love stories that turned bad, it did greatly suffer from this huge lack of affection, and more importantly, from feeling rejected for so many years.
So I want to explore everything.
And actually, I can say, lucky I can't jump on him, because I think I would tired him out.
(Laughter) In fact, since I had discovered sex, it seems to me that I can't do without it anymore.
Was there occasions when I was not aroused?
No, never. But, it happened to him.
Because indeed, he has enjoyed a sexual life for a long time, so his thirst for discovery is different from mine.
He does not have the same needs, the same expectations.
So there is a small libido gap between us, even though I am lucky to have met a quite kinky man.
(Laughter) So obviously, all of this leads to some frustrations.
And as for frustrations, I have a lot more than him in respect to sexual life.
My first huge frustration is my inability to take any initiative to arouse my partner's desire.
I can't give him any hug or stroke him without asking.
My second huge frustration is to have to be all the time in this wheelchair that limits the opportunities to connect with people physically, and to have to lie in bed to make it easier.
It clearly limits spontaneity somehow.
Now I have endured frustrations for a long time, and I will still, due to my impairment, but I must admit that these two are the toughest for me to deal with.
The thing that frustrates me minimally is about sexual positions. That's because I am not obsessed with kama sutra.
And as an impaired writer put it nicely, "Life is much more than the doggy style."
(Laughter) My partner has also helped me realize that I could explore quite a few positions, that it was all about adaptability, and that nothing was necessarily impossible.
For a long time, I believed that everything I could not do would necessarily harm my relationships.
I would see this as a barrier, as an obstacle difficult to overcome.
But my man has accepted me with all my limitations and it does not seem to trouble him very much.
Recently, he told me I was his greatest lay.
(Laughter) Yeah, you're missing something, guys!
(Applause) While I often feel stuck by my impossibilities, he found something in me I could never have imagined.
It's that my handicap could add greater value to a relationship in comparison to so-called "classic" couples.
When you care for a person, you naturally listen more to him or her.
You share added moments of complicity, you touch the other more often, and this can even be arousing.
In such a case, impairment and lack of autonomy can become a real advantage in a couple.
As Johann Chaulet and Sébastien Roux put it quite nicely, "Erotic resources enable or even facilitate love interaction."
Imagine how shocked I was to realize that my impairment could have a positive impact in my emotional and sexual life, since I had convinced myself of the exact opposite.
Imagine the extra handicap I had created on top of my physical one.
Now concretely speaking, in your opinion, how can you have sexual relations with a person physically impaired and unable to move at all, like me?
Well, I wish to say that it's like a woman being a starfish,
except that I would be exaggerating because actually, I am not lying gazing at the ceiling and waiting for it to end.
I have many other ways to express my sexuality and my sex drive.
So of course, this requires words and the other's involvement.
For something to happen, indeed, my partner can't just remain inactive.
So how can I suggest him my desires?
At first, I felt very embarrassed to have to verbalize everything.
Imagine that for all the things you want to do to your partner or him to do to you, you would need to ask him and express them in words.
It's a very difficult exercise, but I needed to do it in order to decrease my frustration.
And in fact, he tells me that sometimes, when I express my desire to tickle him, he could feel like a faint tickle - he has a vivid imagination.
(Laughter) Today, he can also easily guess what I want and what I would like him to do to me.
But I hesitate less to tell him what I'd like to do and the places I'd like to touch him.
Now I do not give him orders, but it remains kind of bossy obviously.
But it is the only way I could express myself without any possibility to move on my own.
Then, there is body language.

Yes, we seldom think about that one!
My partner relies a lot on feelings.
He pays great attention to my shivers and twitches however elusive they may be. to the heat of my body, my flushes, my breathing, my heartbeats, and of course my facial expressions.
These are but a few examples of the possibilities to experience a love and sexual life even with a heavy impairment such as mine.
Of course, there are certain constraints that never erase the handicap.
But a major one is created by the environment and by society's opinion.
Until we stop considering handicap as a barrier for everything we do - and unfortunately, we still have a long way to go in our country and in many other places in the world - well, sex and love will never be seen as possible in the life of any impaired person.
And as in a vicious circle, the impaired person will end up believing it herself and creating in turn an extra handicap.
I was born, I breathe and I exist.
Therefore, I am just like you.
I have the same needs, the same expectations.
I take the same risks and know the same disappointments.
But above all, I experience the same happiness.
So, my answer to that occupational doctor is, "No, I am not single," and "Yes, I have sexual relations."
Thank you.
(Applause) (Cheerings)
Good evening.
I have not come to talk to you about accessibility, although there would've been plenty to say.
(Laughter) (Applause) And I assure you, I didn't come to tell you the story of the poor disabled person, alone, sad, and bitter, who ends up finding happiness by accepting her disability.
I don't accept my disability, I despise it.
When this kind of trauma happens to you, they explain to you that there is a before and an after, and they try to make you believe that the disability is a new component of your personality.
In my own case, I don't see my life in terms of before and after.
I am me, and my state of health is not my identity.
What identifies me the most is my passion because I am passionate about horses and racehorses.
I was 9 the first time I rode a racehorse.
Years later, it became my career
- I rode racehorses in training -
and then, with hard work, I managed to get my jockey license, and I experienced an extraordinary sensation of belonging.
And then one morning, during practice, my trifecta didn't finish the way it was supposed to, the horse fell on me.
And I found myself disabled and hospitalized.
And right away, at the hospital, the nursing staff and other patients explained to me there was a whole list of things I was no longer capable of doing anymore.
They told me that I could not live alone. They told me that my friends and my loved ones might turn away from me, and that it would be better if I made friends with people like myself.
They also told me that I could not have a normal job.
And above all they told me that I was done with horses.
At best, in parasports, while being supervised, watched,
but racehorses, to have them, to approach or to take care of them, was out of the question.
So the first thing I did, as soon as I was allowed to get out of bed and to ride in a wheelchair, was to sneak out of the hospital and go to the races in Auteuil. (Laughter)
Some people prefer to go to Lourdes, to each his own. (Laughter)
And then, two months later, I received permission, as they say, to be able to ride a horse, thanks to some friends.
As you can imagine, I wasn't really my doctor's favorite patient.
Then, after 11 months of being hospitalized I had finally done my time, I could leave.
And yes, the prison metaphor is intentional.
And at that moment, I took up that list of all the things that I could no longer do and I went to work. Today, six years later, I have my house, which is modified, of course, but it doesn't look like a nursing home, and I live there alone.
I still have the same friends, my relatives are very close to me, and no one has turned his back on me.
It happens that I believe that if our relationships have not changed, that is because I have not changed;
I was able to stay the same.
I have a normal job, I go to work
every morning with my car, and I do the same work as my other colleagues, neither more nor less.
And above all, today I own racehorses.
I am an owner and a breeder.
I have been incredibly lucky to have extraordinary people who were happy to be my partners to be able to live this adventure.
But above all, now, I have horses at my place which I take care of daily, by myself.
And I took immense pleasure, a year ago, to have a first winner, to taste victory for the first time.
And I assure you that whether one sits or stands when cries for joy, in the end, is of no importance.
What I have succeeded in doing, what I didn't think myself capable of doing, was to have one of my fillies born at my place.
I have a friend who came to help me with the delivery because I am daring, but not reckless.
But it is, at the present time, my greatest victory.
If I still have a regret: my greatest professional dream was to be a trainer one day.
Finally, I realized the greatest obstacle is not the disability, but money
because that's what I lack to settle down
but I continue to have hope, because I tell myself that I'll find a solution or someone who wants to invest in the adventure and believes in me.
Finally, from that list of all the things that I could no longer do, I was able to cross out everything, line by line, and my surprise was to realize there were quite a few things that I had added to the list myself.
And in the end, I had been capable of exceeding my own limits.
So to conclude, no one knows what one is capable of.
You yourself don't even know until you have tried. Thank you.
(Applause)
(Piano) The piece of music we are listening to is Chopin’s Nocturne, Opus 55, No. 1.
I say that for those who did not recognize it, but don't worry, I didn't know either.
We are in a magnificent auditorium, Massy's Opera theater, and it is quite natural to listen to such piece of music in such a place.
But there is still a question you're asking yourself ... I can feel it.
And this question is "what is the relationship between this Chopin's Nocturne and the image that is currently projected on the screen during the broadcast of this melody?"
This mage represents - of course, this time, you did recognize it - a magnificent sculpture of the famous double helix of the DNA molecule, DNA being the physical and molecular support of our genetic and hereditary heritage.
So to answer this question and satisfy somewhat your legitimate curiosity, I will start by telling you a little story but a real story.
Once upon a time, there was a great scientist, an American, who was also Japanese, called Susumo Ohno.
He was a great specialist in the study of the evolution of living organisms at the genetic and molecular levels.
He hypothesized in his work that repetitions - and I insist on the word "repetition" because words are important - the repetitions of genetic information in DNA sequences could play a very important role in the evolution of living organisms.
And in his reflections, he drew a parallel between the repetitions and recurrences of genetic information in the DNA sequence, and the repetitions of musical themes that we find in musical scores.
After a lot of cogitations and reflections, he developed a method that allowed him to discover, hidden behind the sequence of a real gene that codes for a real protein existing in mice but also in humans, the Chopin nocturne, Op.55, No. 1
that we just listened to.
It is extraordinary to discover such a musical resonance hidden behind genetic and biological information!
In fact, to achieve this, this researcher constantly navigated between two universes: that of Science that he knew well, and that of Art that he invited in his own field to try to explain and understand the functioning of the living.
So today ladies and gentlemen, I'd like to take you on a journey that allows you precisely to go back and forth between varied artistic universes and the world of biology - it makes sense since I'm a biologist.
So here is for example how scientists observe, under the very high magnifications of an electron microscope, a simple bacteria.
Ladies and gentlemen, let me introduce Her Majesty Escherichia coli, the queen of the commensal bacteria of our intestines.
By itself, this E. Coli bacteria, as its close friends say, represents more than 80% of the 100,000 billion not of a thousand portholes as Captain Haddock would say, but of the 100,000 billion microorganisms that colonize our intestines: the famous microbiota.
Well, this image is indeed very interesting for scientists, but for the general public, it does not mean much.
So we can use paint to represent it.
This was done by a great American scientist, David Goodsell.
And we can also use sculpture.
This is what was done by a great British artist, Luke Jerram, who uses transparent blown glass sculpture.
These are two representations on the same theme to show in a more general way the organization of this bacteria.
If we now descend to even smaller microorganisms such as viruses, here is the influenza virus and the AIDS virus, two viruses you have to protect yourself from, even if you have to do it in very different ways, if you see what I mean.
(Laughter) I will not draw the picture!
Indeed, these images are full of information for scientists, but for the general public it remains abstract.
So on our trip, we're going to make a stopover in California at David Goodsel's, and we're going to ask him if he would like to paint these viruses for us.
He's very nice and he did it.
And on the return trip, we made a stopover in Bristol at Luke Jerram's place to ask him to represent these same microorganisms with his blown glass sculpture technique.
He was also very nice and did it.
Here is the result: these are two variations on the same theme to represent the global organization of these viruses, how they are made, the arrangement of their components in an artistic way. We can point out potential therapeutic targets to fight against these pathogens which continue to afflict the world.
Now If we go down again in the scale of living things, we're going to meet their organic components, one of their organic component that are proteins.
The two other organic components of living things are of course sugars and fat, but tonight, on the eve of the culinary Christmas festivities, we are not going to talk about upsetting issues!
(Laughter) Here's how scientists see a protein.
This represents the tertiary structure or conformation of a protein, or to put it simply, the spatial form of a protein.
This is the Green Fluorescent Protein (GFP) that lives in an oceanic jellyfish and emits a magnificent green light … organic, that has nothing to do with what Sébastien was talking about earlier.
Well, this protein is widely used as a tool in scientific research.
It’s used as a lamp or lantern for some studies.
There is nothing like a sculpture to depict an object in space, right?
Since we're still in England, let's make a stopover in Sheffield at the house of a Japanese artist who uses origami.
She was also very nice, she made a giant origami of this fluorescent GFP protein.
It explains the overall organization of this protein, the different parts organized in helices or in sheets and how it works.
When we see this wonder, we can only ask the question: how can a cell make a protein?
In other words, how are proteins made up at the molecular level?
To answer this question, I'm not going to tell you a story like before, rather, I invite you to do an exercise together that will use music.
As you all know, to make music, you need 12 musical notes.
With these 12 notes, a genius composer may offer a composition like this - a very interesting work -
and with the same 12 musical notes, another composer may offer something completely different.
Different elements characterize or define a musical score.
Today we're going to deal with two of them.
The first element that characterizes a musical score is the order in which the musical notes appear.
And the second element is the length of the score, or in other words the total number of musical notes.
The top one lasts 4:05 with a few hundred notes.
The bottom one lasts more than an hour with thousands of notes, but with always the same 12 elementary notes as fondation.
Now to create proteins, cells are using exactly the same building principle than the one we just saw for music.
To fabricate proteins, a cell uses 20 elementary units called "amino acids".
These are small chemical molecules whose formula are known.
They have a name, and scientists assign them a letter of the alphabet for the sake of simplicity.
Now just like a musical score, a protein is composed of the sequence of these amino acids in a very precise order, and it contains a total number of amino acids that is also very precise and specific to the 25,000 proteins that you are all synthesizing in your human cells.
Once the protein is created, it organizes itself in space to adopt a shape, a functional structure.
And it is thanks to this architecture that the protein can function.
This is what we call the "structure-function relationship".
There you have it!
Ah, I think some people on the right
want to tell me something!
Go ahead, I'm listening.
"Tell me, Mister Mohammed ..." "Please call me 'Momo,' everyone does it, I don't mind at all, okay?"
(Laughter)
"If you assign a musical note to an amino acid, it becomes possible to translate its sequence into a musical score."
Yes, that’s exactly what we’re going to do.
Ah, some people on the left disagree!
“Tell me, Mister Momo" - you see, it works every time! -
your story, it's all well and good, but you told us that 12 musical notes are needed to make music whereas you need 20 amino acids to make proteins.
So how do you get the perfect match to apply what people on the right just proposed?
There’s a little flat note in this story, don't you think?”
I think the people on the left have paid more attention to what I just said than the people on the right.
And please don’t see any political connotation here.
(Laughter) Well, we as scientists have admittedly our heads in the clouds. Like Professor Tournesol, we're a bit disorganized, but when it comes to science, we like to classify things.
And we do it very rigorously.
So we classified amino acids into subgroups because some have very similar physico-chemical properties.
For example, some are like fish: they love water;
so they are called "hydrophilic".
In contrast, others are like kitties:
they have a water phobia.
In fact, I like to call them “pussycat acid”, "hydrophobic" of course.
Others are a little excited, electric.
They have a negative or a positive charge, and so on.
By working to sort them out and classify them, we easily obtain 12 amino acid groups to which we assign a musical note, and that does the trick.
What is interesting in this story is that each of you here or who are watching us in Senegal or Romania, are free - and we are in the land of Liberty par excellence - to assign the music note you want to this or that group of amino acids.
So each of you is able to create his or her own musical score of such and such protein.
Now one day, or maybe it was one night, (Laughter) two Americans invited each other: Marie-Anne Clarke, biologist, and John Dunn, computer scientist.
I don't know what they did that night or that day, but what I do know is that from this meeting is born not a baby but an algorithm that is inspired by what we just saw.
This algorithm enables us to translate the amino acid sequence of any protein into its equivalent in the musical score.
So we can discover ... the hemoglobin's symphony, (Laughter) the Insulin's blues, the Keratin's rock, or the Collagen's swing, who knows?
Alright, if my story can be put in parentheses, the opening one being the Chopin's Nocturn, the closing one is also going to be a musical piece, that of a protein.
Its name is Spidroine.
Spidroine is the protein that makes up the threads of a spider's web.
I really like spiders.
And rest assured, I am not like Cédric Villani.
(Laughter) Okay? You noticed I have no spider on the collar of my jacket, nor bats in the belfry I hope!
Well, be aware that this protein which the silk of the spider's web is made of, represents the most resistant, the most solid, the most elastic, and the lightest material in existence.
Imagine a spider making a single thread of its web that would circle the Earth.
Well this simple wire would be 40,075 km long and weigh only 420 gr.
Its resistance and solidity is due to the repetitions of specific amino acid sequences, which we will also find in its musical equivalent.
So I invite you to close your eyes if you are afraid of spiders, open your ears wide, and imagine yourself on a beautiful clear night listening to the musical resonance of the protein of a web that a spider is weaving under the moon light.
(Applause) (Music) (The music ends) I hope after this you'll no longer see spiders the same way.
(Applause) Thank you.
In conclusion, I hope what we saw together today was a good illustration of the possible transversality between disciplines.
The meeting of one with the other enables knowledge to be shared in a way, I hope, both educational and fun.
It also enables passions to be shared as well as another way of looking at our own work and discipline.
And this ties in with what the great French philosopher, poet and writer, Paul Valery, has said, to whom I leave the last word with his quote: "There was once someone who could look at the same object with the eyes of a painter, or a naturalist, with the eyes of a physicist at times and at other times of a poet, and none of these looks was superficial."
None of these looks was superficial.
Thank you very much.
(Applause)
In my life, I've met a lot of psychologists. Now, times have changed.
I changed too, you could say.
Now, psychologists come to see me.
(Laughter) They ask for my advice. They tell me all about their booboos.
"Josef, help us, my boyfriend / girlfriend left.
What can I do?"
Sometimes, those who used to want me under guardianship, now come ask me to lend them money, because their bank cancelled their credit card.
And I tell them how lucky they are that I am autistic, because I could charge them for this. (Langhter) I would charge a lot.
(Applause) Lacan would have been a clown next to me, and everything should be paid in cash, because I also have administrative phobia.
(Laughter) (Applause) Anyway, I think, there are more efficient ways to heal small and big societal neuroses than talking on a couch.
So I suggest traveling.

Ah! Traveling!
It didn't start right for me.
I wasn't born to travel.
For example, some years ago, the big journey for me was doing three bus stations.
It would stress me and traumatize me for weeks.
And I'm not even telling you about the sedative periods.
You should not travel in France when you have disabilities. You should stay within your four walls.
But I did leave.
I applied parts of the Golda Meir doctrine.
Golda Meir pointed out that for her, the chance of her lifetime was to be ugly.
And she was ugly.
(Laughter) It's really helpful, by the way, to know you're not the only one in that case.
(Laughter) But still, let me tell you, between just being ugly, and being ugly and autistic, as the French comic Coluche would say, it's really difficult to up the ante.
(Laughter) Not only mandates from abroad.
Please imagine, autistic, it's an insult, we call our politicians that.
So, how does it work in concrete terms, therapy by traveling?
Well, it's pretty simple.
Forget all you've been told.
Forget those stories about all the pleasure cities.
Forget about trendy cities,
the places to be, to be just another sardine among other sardines.
No, no, no.
Traveling is worthy only
if it's risky at heart.
Traveling is a long apprenticeship.
You need to feel uncomfortable before the trip.
That's how you make progress.
I'm going to give you a very convenient example.
Suppose you have time ahead of you, and you can only choose between two places.
Let's say you must choose between Barcelona and Isfahan.
Apparently, Barcelona has everything.
Barcelona has bars, drinking places.
Barcelona has a beach, sunlight, you name it, and it's not so far away. Maybe we've been there before, maybe we know the place.
Isfahan... well no, it's not like that.
(Laughter) First, you have to find it on the map.

Then, oh god, you'll notice it's in Iran.
(Laughter) Should we get a life insurance?
Or maybe ask for the last rites? I don't know, to each his own.
But you know, all the tiring weeks, the worry you feel before going. Well, it's worth it.
Let's say your colleague went to Barcelona.
How will he feel when he comes back?
He won't get anything out of his trip to Barcelona.
And don't get me started on the hangover! (Laughter) But, you, who have been to Isfahan, for example, you'll never forget Isfahan's palaces,
its roses, its gardens, its limitless.
And when the gray and low sky of winter will come where you live, well, in front of your eyes, you'll constantly see the poets lines dancing.
(Speaking Iranian) But for me, you know, restless soul, I'm not very West but East. I ran away again, further East.
I went several times in the tribal zones in Balochistan.
This place may be one of the most lost among the lost corners of the world.
It's there, with nomads, in zones called "terrorists," that I've been the most accepted.
It's there, where I wasn't, if I may, an autistic guy anymore.
Those nomads, I think, I stole a secret from them.
I believe the human being is, in fact, not made for sedentary life.
Human being is not born to stay inside walls - walls which can only become our tomb.
Human being is not born to settle for one language.
Monolingualism is a modern invention, and it's not the best, far from it.
So, while traveling, leave your illusions behind, but most of all, remove the barriers -
the barriers of, let's say, your confort zone, restricting your movements to your known universe.
Illusions barriers for the immediate satisfaction of all your desires and your passing needs.
Travels are not there to satisfy your passing needs. Travels are there to change them, to change us.
Travels, as would say the tireless deserts traveller, Theodore Monod, travels are a quiet teacher, and this quiet teacher, what does he have to say?
Well, when these barriers will be removed, only what we have in common will be left, whether we're nomads, Balochis from the desert ends, whether we're city-dwellers from the far west, it is, I believe, I'm sure of it, our shared humanity.
Thank you.
(Applause)
Living well, when we stopped eating willingly for 16 hours, two days, or 10 days, that seems impossible to you or maybe perfectly normal because you've already experienced this.
Let me explain to you what fasting is and maybe tell you my story and how I discovered it and rediscovered this ability that each human has in him as well as animals.
When I was 15, I was a Genevan teenager in the whirlwind of 1968.
Of course, it was the music festivals, the fight against authority, but most of all, it was an abundance of new ideas that came to us and broadened our horizon.
I heard for the first time words like, "ecology," "yoga," "meditation," "feminism," while today these are themes that are part of my life and the life of my contemporaries.
Renouncing the buttery food of the patriarchal family table and asking instead for vegetables, wholemeal cereals and cold pressed oil, really, that was a revolution in my family.
But when I decided to start fasting at age 17, I didn't dare talk about it to my friends, nor my family.
I just simply stopped eating, just like that, to lose weight and out of curiosity.
And I didn't have a clue about the metabolism of fasting, about the practice or how to do it, it was a complete improvisation.
And it was an unforgettable experience.
After a day or two, I had the impression of regaining my energy, of being positive and feeling almost exhilarated.
Communication with my friends and my family members was facilitated, even though they absolutely didn't understand what I was doing.
And I was shocked:
I wasn't hungry, and I felt happy -
which didn't happen often anymore during my tormented teenage years.
My skin became smoother, my acne disappeared, and that's obviously great to a teenager.
Waking up wasn't a problem.
Walking for miles didn't tire me out.
I also had the feeling of being at one with Nature.
After 11 days of this extraordinary experience, I said to myself, "Maybe, I should think about eating again."
But, how were you supposed to stop this process ?
I had no one to guide me, I didn't know how to do it.
So I started eating again
in an uncontrolled manner and fell ill.
All my problems returned about family and career guidance.
And there, I understood that I had to do it differently.
Later, when I would become a doctor and specialist in fasting therapy, I would be very carefull to teach all my patients how to return to eating and to their daily lives since it should be done slowly and in a very conscious way.
In fact, I had the chance to find, through a friend who was also a doctor, a medically supported fasting center that was founded in 1953.
The founder is a German doctor named Otto Buchinger. He is a doctor that cured himself of an acute rheumatic fever - a general inflammation of the joints that was making him disabled - by fasting during 19 days.
I learnt that there was a method, a well-known method based on clinical experience, and that there were rules and rituals to follow for a fast to be beneficial.
So I got to learn, and, at the same time, I had the chance to meet the founder's grandson ... who became my husband.
(Laughter) So we are the 3rd generation to develop this medical fasting method which is the most practiced worldwide.
And we have created fasting centers that are now led by the 4th generation.
Fasting appeals to young people.
What I found astounding is that this experience so dazzling and what I saw of clinical improvements in those centers weren't taught in medical studies.
During all my medical training, at no point have I ever heard of fasting or the physiology of fasting. There was mention of fasting animals because all animals around us fast.
For example, a caterpillar becomes a butterfly as it stays in a cocoon and fasts for several months.
Without eating, there is an absolutely extraordinary transformation.
There are more common animals, such as marmots, bears, migrating birds, and of course, penguins of the Antarctic.
(Rires) Perhaps two words were mentioned about fasting in decompensated diabetes, and also, as a poor method of losing weight.
It wasn't until the sciences of longevity and the last few years' publications that we understood the mechanisms through which therapeutic fasting has an extraordinary and exceptional effect on health and longevity.
So maybe you'll ask me, "Renouncing this extraordinary pleasure of eating, what for ?"
and "Why should I fast?"
First of all, it is about fascination, a fascination with our own genetic program.
In our own body, we have this ancient knowledge.
So why not rediscover it?
First, we must understand that fasting, if done correctly, is not dangerous.
And what is fasting?
What does it mean to stop eating? Truly, it is simply the transition from a form of life that relies on external food that we eat and digest by burning its components, to the combustion of fats lying in reserve in our body.
So fasting means indeed to stop eating, but from the point of view of the cell, fasting is mainly changing fuel, eating in another way.
You may understand better if I compare the cells to hybrid cars.
A hybrid car can switch from petrol to electricity indiscriminately from one to the other.
In our body, our cells are also capable of moving from that external food to this internal food stored in our reserves.
What are the effects of this transition?
Firstly, it affects our metabolism.
Glycaemia or blood sugar
decreases, insulin plummets, and three hormones take over,
adrenaline, glucagon and the growth hormone.
Thanks to these three hormones, we start using our reserves, first, a small sugar reserve in the liver named "glycogen," then the large reserves of fat that almost all of us have in large quantities once we reach a certain age - and we all would like to shed it. (Laughter)
And the fasting motto, from a metabolic point of view, is saving proteins.
What can we cure by fasting?
How does it work?
First, the cellular pathways activate.
As you can imagine, the body is hungry.
So it starts with the old modified structures, maybe whole cells, that are going to be caught and digested in a process called "autophagy".
And the elements that are collected are going to be either recycled or eliminated.
There are means of natural elimination that a well-managed fast should boost.
First, the kidneys are stimulated by drinking a lot of water and herbal tea.
Then, the lungs are stimulated to excrete carbonic gas, and the skin to perspire by physical exercise and natural methods.
Then, the liver and intestines are also stimulated through natural methods.
Another mechanism explains why, in a fast, pain and stiffness decrease.
It's the decrease of inflammatory processes.
It's an extraordinary effect that we notice very quickly.
Some people come with arthritis in their hands, for example, and say, "I've fasted for three days and I can already close my hands again."
This explains the improvement of many illnesses.
And regarding metabolism, there's weight loss of course, a decrease in the waistline, but also a normalization of the blood pressure, the blood sugar and cholesterol, and all of these occurs while physical and emotional well-being improve each day.
And for someone who has never fasted, this is completely counter-intuitive.
We expect to feel bad and be hungry all the time, but it is not the case at all.
We've documented all these improvements and changes in parameters in a study published in January 2019, covering 1422 cases of people who have fasted for 5, 10, 15 days or 20 days, with this Buchinger method.
So the conclusion is what can we treat with this fast on a medical point of view?
And that is the second incentive after the fascination with the discovery of your intrinsic mechanisms.
We can treat illnesses called "metabolic" such as obesity, type two diabetes, hypercholesterolemia, hyperuricaemia...
These are also risk factors for cardiac and vascular illnesses,
so we prevent heart attacks or strokes.
There is a another large group: chronic inflammatory illnesses, those that make typically people ill or stiff such as arthritis, rheumatic illnesses, and also gastritis, colitis, and other illnesses ending with "tis", and allergies, migraines and asthma too.
Then there is a third, less known group that is all the depressive conditions, the states of physical and psychological exhaustion because fasting boosts mood and it boosts energy in the case of pre-burnout.
Today, as I have said, an enormous amount of research is taking place globally to study the effects of short, long, modified and repeated fasting.
We notice them on certain illnesses we didn't think about 20 years ago, such as cancer, such as Alzheimer's, at least in its prevention, such as polyarthritis, multiple sclerosis and Parkinson's.
Here are the new research fields that will enlighten us in years to come.
You're perhaps going to wonder, "Why don't I take the plunge and try to fast?"
Then, I will answer you,
"Beware! Fasting is not a walk in the park.
It's a medium-intensity mountain trek.
You need to know the itinerary, have a good guide,
prepare for it and not over estimate yourself."
There is a group of people who take medication for their illnesses - those I've already mentioned for which fasting is recommended.
In these cases, fasting can only be done in a specialized center where doctors are specialists in fasting therapy.
People in good health can attempt a personal experiment, with a good manual, a group and a guide if possible, and do intermittent fasts.
It can be, for example, something that is beneficial and easy to do, that is to stop eating for a long period including the night.
It could be 16 hours for example.
You eat your last meal at 6 pm and have your breakfast at 10 am.
It is called "16/8 intermittent fasting."
You can also have one fasting day up to five, or days where calories are restricted to around 600 cal.
And food lovers, what will they say,
the French especially who love gastronomy?
Why deprive ourselves of this pleasure?
Isn't it anti-gastronomy?
Well, I would say, "No. Indeed, we prevent
that pleasure for a short while,
but it should be replaced with other pleasures, and there is an abundance
of them in fasting." First, there is the pleasure of having time, being free from all these behavioral patterns. It is the pleasure to be able to read a good book, listen to music, be in contact with Nature, go for a walk, have time for your own body and for yourself.
And don't forget that at the end of the fast, when you start to eat again, the taste is a marvel.
Any food item tastes like a three star meal.
Moreover, after fasting, the feeling of hunger and fullness can be revived and that may enable us to restore a healthy eating habit.
There is also a spiritual dimension in fasting.
We are now in the period of Lent for Christians, but in all religions, there are periods of fast, because there is a spiritual but also a communal dimension.
So, fasting is an opportunity to rejuvenate our body, because during re-feeding, embryonic stem cells regenerate.
So, we have a rejuvenation of cells.
But in addition, it's an opportunity to meditate on our own existence and to redirect our lives on a good path.
I should speak a couple of words on the methodology.
A fast must be experienced differently and far from everyday life if possible.
The period before the fast must be taken care of by decreasing food little by little and perform one day of mono-diet.
Beginning a fast means having a different daily rhythm: a good rotation between rest and physical exercise, and rituals, meetings with others, for example, a conviviality around a fruit juice or a vegetable soup.
Then the return to food should be gradual and conscious.
In sum, I would like to say, "Be fascinated by this ancient program, by this ancient knowledge, that is in your body and you might never have discovered.
And if you decide to do a fast, do so with a good support, with a good method and, if you are ill, with a medical facility. I hope that you will also start
to panic in front of junk food, but trust in this program that is fasting that may help you to prevent diseases, live longer in good health, and have, in some cases, a deep spiritual experience and a re-orientation of your life.
(Applause)
Hello everyone.
The brain.
It is central to our reasoning, our actions; and yet, we have no sensitive perception of it.
I work at the INRIA where researchers in mathematics and computer science develop methods to better observe, better understand the brain and interact with it.
So we already know a lot about the brain.
But in fact, each brain is very distinctive, has its own specificities.
First, its shape.
Just like our bodies are all different, with different morphologies, our brains are different too: a brain has furrows that are characteristic to each person.
Then, its functional organization.
There are general principles common to all the brains, for instance, visual areas located at the rear, sensorimotor areas in the center, auditory areas in the temporal areas.
But the precise contours of these areas, their size too, depend on our history, how the brain developed during our growth, and activities that we may have had which are unique to each of us.
So each of our brains is worthy exploring as terra incognita.
To conduct this exploration, we will map the brain.
That is to say, know precisely in an individual brain, which are the areas that correspond to very specific actions.
And when these areas are identified, we can even go watch the activity that takes place in these areas, establish its characterization or even detect it.
To go on this exploration, we need some luggage.
Our luggage is a measuring device which is nearly a century old but continues to reveal to us every day the secrets of this organ, and it is the EEG, which consists of electrodes are placed on the scalp that measures the electrical activity of neurons at the brain surface, that they emit when they communicate.
This area of the brain ... imagine it like a globe, okay?
The activity of the inhabitants would be represented by areas more or less luminous depending on their degree of communication, of activity.
And our electrodes, are like satellites around the Earth observing the activity of its inhabitants, here, the neurons, but at a rough scale.
So how can we, from such measurements provided by the electroencephalogramme get to map zones corresponding to specific activities?
As we get measurements that, after all, are removed and add to the superimposition of all these hourly activities in fact, because they are emitted by all the tissues which separate the brain from the scalp.
To solve such a seemingly hard problem, mathematics offers a solution, they offer solutions when we have equations and unknowns, and unknowns are the distribution of the electrical activity on the brain surface, equations are the physical principles that link this electrical activity, these activities, with each other, and link the activity to the measurements.
Let's take a much simpler example: Imagine I give you a wallet and I tell you the total amount of money in it.
Can you can deduce the exact distribution of notes and coins?
No. But if I tell you
it contains the minimum number of coins and notes to reach that sum, then, yes,
there is one solution: that used by the teller or cashier when he gives you the change.
So with principles such as this, that is to say parts of simplicity principles or a priori knowledge, we add to the problem, we can find a solution for mapping, that is to say identify which areas are activated in a brain from measurements made on the electroencephalogramme.
But this mapping is individualized for a particular brain.
This type of work can help a surgeon, in the case of a patient, to locate in a brain pathological areas communicating poorly, that need operating, and locate around these areas eloquent areas, which themselves communicate well and must be preserved.
From a mapping, we may also want to analyze the activity taking place, that is to say through the electroencephalogram we get signals, so a good time resolution.
we can observe the activity on the brain surface like a film
While these areas we see activating contain many neurons that are not necessarily specific to a single action but if you ask a person to repeat a single action many times, such as moving their right arm, we will be able to filter in the measurements what always corresponds to the movement of the right arm, and filter all the other brain activities that have no relation to the action.
So, we can identify in the brain areas what is the type of dynamics specific to a certain activity.
Once you can determine the nature of the activity corresponding to certain actions, it becomes possible to detect it at the very time it is being performed, in real time.
It brings the possibility to open new communication channels between the brain and its environment.
If we translate this detection in another command language, and this new way of communication does not necessarily pass through the muscles.
So, we've been talking about brain activity. Let's take an example of what can trigger brain activity.
For example, you are at a red light in your car and you're waiting for the green light.
Well, when the green light is displayed, it triggers a very specific activity in your brain.
It is an activity that says,
"Ah! that's what I expecting. "
It comes 300 milliseconds after the light signal and is called the P 300 wave.
Well this type of signal, this type of activity in response to an expected signal, we've used it in an experiment with patients at the University Hospital in Nice last year, to enable them to communicate.
For this, we proposed an interface that was composed of a keyboard whose letters would flash on the screen.
In fact, at each flash of the letter, the flash was represented by a small smiley, whenever the letter that the person wants to spell flashes, it triggers the green light activity.
"Ah! This is the letter
I wanted to type. "
So, we tested this interface with patients suffering from Lou Gehrig's disease, which is a neurodegenerative motor neuron disease, the neurons that connect the brain to the muscles and sometimes gradually make patients unable to enonciate or move their limbs, and sometimes even both.
Our hospital partners at the University Hospital in Nice seek alternative means of communication for those people whose brain is prevented from operating in emission.
However, their brain is fully operational as regards cognitive tasks and reception.
So here you see the patient has the word "dream" in mind d- r - e - a - m, and focuses sequentially on each of the letters of the word she wants to type.
And she counts in her head how many times the letter she wants to spell is being flashed.
At each of these signals, for the right letter, the p300 wave is detected in her brain.
Look at the letter E which is the third from the top.
1, 2, 3,
4 ... This patient, after four or five flashes of the letter, sees that the system was able to decode the letter she was focusing her visual attention on.
Patients or their families have asked us: "But do you work on telepathy, actually? "
What do you think?
Is it telepathy?
No, we're actually trying to decode something in the patients' brains, this information that tells us: she has just perceived the signal she expected.
She has just perceived the correct letter.
But we are not trying to decode, in the patients' brain the exact letter that they were thinking about.
This would be possible if we had records at a scale finer than that offered by the electroencephalogram.
For this, we should place electrodes directly into the brain.
So to conclude this exploration, I will digress a little into the world of imagination.
When we want to perform complex movements, it is useful to think of them mentally in advance.
It is a technique that has been used by great sportsmen, for example Jean-Claude Killy to improve their performance.
But it's not just sportsmen who may want to increase their performance.
Take the example of a patient who has sufferred a stroke and would be unable to move their arm, their right arm.
In fact, if this person imagines moving their right arm, it triggers a brain activity which is very similar to the one obtained if they actually moved their arm.
With the techniques I just mentioned, if we are able to characterize this activity which is produced by the motor imagination, we are able to detect it at the very moment the person is imagining.
So we can use that information and turn it into real action.
We equip their arm with a motorized orthosis which will trigger the movement that the person can no longer trigger themselves, whenever they imagine move it.
Seeing this, the patient's brain will need to develop new connections that will gradually allow it to recover movement.
Gradually, we can decrease the electric assistance and the patent will teake back the control of their own arm.
So this is a new form of physiotherapy which uses the brain, brain activity, which is under consideration --there are clinical studies being made now-- of transforming imagination into action.
So we have seen in this brief exploration that mapping allows characterizing areas that are activated in the brain individually, customized, and can even go look at the dynamics of brain activity to better understand, interpret and even translate it into real action.
So I invite you to keep imagining what you want to do.
Because imagining things
puts them within your reach.
Thank you. (Applause)
Some twenty years ago, I worked on children's drawings
and what struck me at the time was that until kindergarten, they are extremely creative, volcanic, and then when they enter high school, their creativity diminishes sharply.
Yet I think that creativity is what can help us today in the uncertain and increasingly complex world we are in.
So when I became interested in gifted and creative people, I called them "atypical multipotentials".
Why “atypical multipotentials” - a slightly complicated name?
"Multipotentials" because they are people with multiple talents, and "atypical" because they are people who think differently.
Now I'm going to make two small digressions.
The first is let us broaden our vision of intelligence.
We often see intelligence as a logico-mathematical and verbal intelligence with a Cartesian mind.
However, the theory of multiple intelligences developed by Howard Gardner's, an American psychologist, in 1984, shows us that intelligence is a much broader concept.
He spoke of emotional intelligence, intra and extra personal intelligences,
but he also spoke of other intelligences such as the spatial intelligence of the architect Frank Ghery, or the kinesthetic intelligence of Federer, the tennis champion, or even the musical intelligence of Mozart.
What is the other reason why I call these people "atypical multipotentials"?
They are atypical because they think in a different way.
Here I'm going to make a second short detour to speak about the American neuropsychologist, Roger W. Sperry, who received the Nobel Prize in 1981 for showing cerebral asymmetry.
So we have the "left-brained" rational people, and the "right-brained" creative people.
Since then, medical imagery has made much progress and it has shown the complexity of our brain which, by the way, has not yet revealed to us all of its mysteries.
But, what is certain with atypical multipotentials is that they have a tree-like thinking process.
And their thinking process is tree-like because they have an extremely strong intuition.
They think in a disruptive manner. Why ?
Because they think
by making a lot of associations, a lot of analogies and connections.
Let me give you an example.
The great French designer Charlotte Perriand who is perhaps little known although she worked with Le Corbusier, was mandated to create a mountain shelter.
She didn't know how to proceed, but one day, as she was traveling in Croatia, she saw a merry-go-round.
Now you may wonder what is the connection between a children merry-go-round and a mountain hut?
In reality, she instantly understood that they had the same technical constraints.
And this is precisely an example of the type of analogical thinking an atypical multipotential can have.
Atypical multipotentials are people who are very fast thanks to their intuition.
They are also visionary, depending on their talents.
They have a global vision, a long-term and strategic vision.
They also possess a distinct characteristic: Atypical multipotentials are full of emotions, they are like emotional sponges.
Now recently, a client said to me, "You know, Myriam, I don't take the subway because all these vibs of people who are not feeling well, I can't stand it."
So I work a lot with big companies, with people who work in the towers of La Défense, and in these towers, there are open spaces.
Now open spaces are terrible for atypical multipotentials because since they already have trouble concentrating, if in addition, there is movement and noise around them, it becomes catastrophic.
Multipotentials also have a special relationship to themselves.
If school was a good experience for them, if everything went well in their family life, and they were recognized, then they have no problem.
They can turn into Bill Gates, Steve Jobs, Richard Bransons, Dysons, in short persons who succeed wonderfully.
However, I think the majority of them are not recognized
because they can become dunces at school out of boredom.
Besides, many of these very intelligent people do not necessarily finish their studies.
So what's going on?
Well, they live like in the well-known tale of The Ugly Duckling.
The ugly duckling is rejected by his brothers and sisters.
And why is he rejected?
Because he is different.
He is not appreciated, not understood, until one day, the ugly duckling so unhappy goes away and discovers the swans.
One day, he meets swans and then it’s happiness. He understands he is like them, he is recognized and everything goes well.
Now these atypical multipotentials, who do they have in front
of them? Who are the ducks?
The ducks are actually people who are steeped in the Cartesian mind, those who have a sequential, linear, logical, and analytical thinking process.
In short they are like Descartes:
they prove, they reason. But what atypical multipotentials blame them for though is that they do not see outside the box and always think: "Let's do as people have always done, because why would we change something that has never failed so far?"
These people, I call them the “neurotypical rationals” or just “rationals” to make it simpler.
So what do rationals think of multipotentials?
Well, they see them as unmanageable, always "too" something:
too dispersed, too disorganized, too difficult to understand.
Personally, I think that today we need all the intelligences.
We need them all, but if you're not convinced of this, if you are a rational and think, "No that's not possible, these people are unbearable," let me give you a simple recipe.
If you want to get rid of all these original, atypical people who tell you lots of things that you don't understand, just give them simple routine tasks, fragment their activities so that they lose the sense of what they're doing, give them an incompetent hierarchy, and when they do a great job, find the killing detail, the comma that is in the wrong place, and with such a recipe, a priori, you will get rid of them more or less quickly.
Now of course, you understand that this is not at all what I recommend.
I really think that we need atypical multipotentials, so how do we welcome them?
These are people who need challenging tasks and who need purpose in what they do.
These are people who care about the collective interest and who like to work in communities.
So if you want to get these two profiles to work together, you should try to entrust them with multiple projects because the more projects they carry out simultaneously, the better they are, as long as you do not exhaust them!
To conclude, let me say the skills of atypical multipotentials are particularly interesting to me because they are complementary to what artificial intelligence can bring us.
Artificial intelligence know how to duplicate not innovate.
Besides, their ability to think differently, their creativity, their sense of collectiveness, and their vision of the future, can help us.
So I think we need to know them in order to recognize them and welcome them.
Why?
Because by welcoming them, we will gain a vision of the future that we will see take shape before our eyes with serenity and optimism.
Thank you.
(Applause)
Are you ready for the big leap?
The great leap into the unknown.
I don't know about you, but when I hear this kind of idea, it has a double effect on me: on the one hand, I'm excited
because, wow! The great adventure!
Then on the other hand, I'm terrified... that kind of thing can freak you out, right?
That's the double feeling I experienced in 2008, when finally I decided to throw myself into the great adventure.
So how come that, between terror and excitement, the excitement prevailed?
Well, I must say, I've been very lucky because I've learned from the best, I had excellent teachers, my parents.
When I was a little girl, I was about two and a half, 3 years old, I was lucky to come across a great couple: Marie Thérèse and Michel, who became my adoptive parents.
And when they decided to take care of me, to take me in, that wasn't their first time; it really was not their greatest achievement.
You must know that at the end of their big adventure, they have saved and raised 20 children, adopted from around the world.
So it is true that every time my parents found themselves facing a child whose situation was so complex that he was considered "unadoptable", it broke their heart and they said: "We can not leave him out, we'll take him in!"
And that's how, gradually, the family grew.
So that's really what always amazed me about them, about Marie-Thérèse and Michel:
the fact that they do not ask a thousand questions before acting, they would identify an emergency, a child to save, no more questions,
we'll take him in, that's all.
Yet, it was not easy. It was really risky
because my parents are just ordinary people from northern France, they're not rich people, and so each new mouth to feed was a challenge.
Yet, they have consistently pushed back the limits, they really were people who, ultimately, would leap into the unknown regularly without even realizing it and would take those risks simply out of love.
It's true you could say that it is not reasonable, and it would be so because that's where it happens, beyond the reasonable,
a place where miracles can begin to work, nothing less.
One day, a 5-year old little girl arrived at home, my little sister Cathy.
When Cathy arrived in our home, she was all violence.
During her whole childhood, her biological parents had strongly abused her.
They got regularly angry because when they called her, she would not answer.
No wonder, since Cathy was born deaf, profoundly deaf.
So the only language Cathy knew was that of violence.
When you approached Cathy she would pull your hair, would bit you, she would scratch you... For months, my mother would respond to each act of violence with a caress.
And day after day, week after week, gradually, Cathy's true nature emerged again: sweetness.
A few months after Cathy's arrival, it was Gaston's turn to join our home, to be adopted.
My little brother Gaston, 6-7 years old, came straight from Cameroon, and there, when he was little, he fell into a fire which gave him a frightening appearance because he completely lost his face.
He had no face.
In the street, some people would change sidewalk, others would say, "Take off your mask!"
He was still a little boy.
When he arrived home, Cathy saw him from afar, and then with gestures, she showed us that she didn't want to approach him, that she found him frightening.
Of course, nobody forced her to do so. Then Cathy began to observe him from a a distance for several days.
Being deaf, she realized Gaston was almost blind.
Because in the fire, he had lost an eye, and he could only see very little with the other one.
Then slowly, she approached Gaston, she took his hand and then, she showed him around the house.
A huge love between Gaston and Cathy began to emerge, an immense brotherly love and tenderness.
Well, that's how we lived at home.
It was that kind of daily life.
You know, this kind of adventure is not simple, it sometimes causes problems with the neighbors, local people, being judgmental.
My parents were much criticized, even judged, they were called fools. You know, judgment may be very severe for those who try to change the rules of the game. who decide to act unconventionally.
Still, it's worth it.
You know, there is this quote by St. Augustine that says: "The measure of love, is to love without measure."
I think it really applies to what my parents wanted to live.
So in 2008, I have all those values welling up in my heart, in my mind, and a big bang happened inside me.
That's when I really decided to take the big leap.
I am a journalist. I love my job.
And now, when all these memories come back to me, I realize that ultimately, people like my parents,
are heroes, modern heroes, heroes of love heroes nobody talks about, the unsung heroes, the humble heroes.
Because they have never done anything to be in the spotlight, or for glory.
So I thought, "but in fact, there are plenty of people like that around us, but we never talk about them.
And it's time we talk about them."
So I thought, "that's what I want to do now."
That's when I truly took that leap, that is to say, I left the world of traditional media, the usual programs I used to present, to create a brand new structure through which I produce media content in a quite original and totally philanthropic way.
In French, it's called 'Le Projet Imagine' and in English, 'The Humble Heroes.'
With Humble Heroes, I meet all those women and men who dare, who truly venture into unknown territories who believe in it.
In fact, these men and women have identified societal issues around them, different issues that have affected them so much or even shocked them in such a way that they thought: "Now, I'm going to roll up
my sleeves and tackle this."
And to make their portrait is truly a privilege
because that's when you realize that anything is possible, that's the message they give us: everything is possible, and it's worth it,
and it is in our hands. It will come not from above, or from politics, it's in our hands
Because clearly, if each of us here would decide to act, the way we can, well, the world will change.
It is true that very often, heroes and heroines do with very limited resources.
They're people like us, they do not necessarily have the wallet of Bill Gates, they don't necessarily have Einstein's brain either, but they've got that energy, and and conquering spirit.
That is their wealth.
And truly, they change the game, they push back the limits of what's possible.
So they're a great inspiration.
So, back in 2008, when I decided to take the leap.
But you understood that at that point, I freaked out!
Frankly, I have the jitters! I'm scared!
It's only normal I should be scared,
because we are not naive, we know that life is not a bed of roses, and sure enough, at first, I won't succeed, I'll struggle.
First, I experienced
a year-and-a-half dry period.
The pits; no more work, no money, I don't know how to pay my rent, frankly, I hit rock bottom.
But something in me does not collapse.
There is something in me, in my heart, that stays alert.
I expect something, I'm waiting for the miracle.
Because you see, in my family we've become addicted to miracles.
And one of the greatest miracles we had the chance to experience, was the arrival of my little brother, Pierre Vincent.
One day, my parents hear about a little 2 and a half year-old boy, in a nursery in Tours.
His case is a case of emergency, because social services... nurseries only keeps toddlers or babies. So, he has reached an age limit.
Social services have no other choice than to transfer him to a psychiatric institution even though this little boy is completely sane.
So how come social services don't know what to do with this little boy?
Well, Pierre-Vincent was abandoned at birth as he was born without arms and legs.
My parents went to visit him in Tours, and not to frighten him, they had to wear white gowns because he had never seen other people than health personnel.
And so they wore these white gowns not to frighten him.
They met this boy, and they literally fell in love with this little boy.
But they are not completely crazy... still a little bit anyway!
They were well aware of the immense responsibility it represented while there was already a good dozen young children at home.
So when they came home, for the only time in our history, they gathered us in the small living room of our little house, and they explained it to us.
They told us about Pierre-Vincent's situation, about this little boy who has no arms or legs, and they said: "In fact, we want to ask your permission, because we'll have to pay attention to his every need, and so we'll need you.
So we leave you the whole day to think about it, and then tonight, you will tell us your answer."
I remember very well, with my sister Hélène who's from Bangalore, South India, - you should know that her file read 'too dark'; I don't know if today someone would dare write that down, but still, I think we should remain vigilant - that got up to my room and then with my sister Virginie from South Korea, we took one of our favorite dolls, we removed her arms and legs
to see what the problem was exactly.
Because, you know, children are very practically-minded!
Watching this doll, it was obvious to us that it remained a little boy!
So we could not see what the problem was.
That night, when we got together, well, it was a huge, unanimous yes.
Yes, of course we want to take him in.
And then we felt something really special was happening because my parents were crying
and we rarely saw my parents cry.
We really felt something important was happening.
It took a few months for the adoption file to go through and then that was it, they went to Tours to get Pierre-Vincent.
In the meantime, we were waiting, we were a bit restless at home because between northern France and Tours, no one knew exactly what time they would be back, so there was an atmosphere, you know, as if we were waiting for baby Jesus in the manger.
And it was very exciting.
And then that was it, they arrived. And my parents are very beautiful, very tall, very slender, and it was mom who had Pierre-Vincent in her arms, and you know, a little boy of 2 and a half who has no arms or legs looks like a 6-month old baby; and our hearts melted.
Our hearts really melted looking at this little child's face and that smile, because Pierre-Vincent is the joy of living incarnate.
It's true we already were living beautiful things in this home, under this roof, but with Pierre-Vincent, we really went to another level.
It has welded us, he cemented us because he has given us this opportunity to become his arms and legs.
Today, Pierre-Vincent is the only high-level athlete in the family!
He was three times champion of France at rifle shooting.
He plays football in the first division, in his electric wheelchair, he's just won European electric wheelchair football championship.
Quite an achievement.
(Applause) When I tell you everything is possible!
Einstein said, there are only two ways to live your life: one is as though nothing is a miracle, and the other is as though everything is a miracle,
but he forgot to mention that to be able to experience miracles for miracles to have a real place in our lives, there is a price to pay, though.
We must be able to take risks, must truly dare to put ourselves in danger, because comfort and miracle don't go well together.
That's the way it is, it's freaky, but it is worth it.
So if you want to live an intense life packed with miracles, go ahead, take the leap.
But do it more like my heroes: do not take a leap into the unknown, take a big leap straight into love.
Thank you.
(Applause)
Let me talk to you about a place well known to you.
You likely go there often or perhaps even live there.
Nevertheless, it’s a place not very easy to live in.
This place ... is the city.
Why is it so hard, nowadays, to live in the city?
Why do we have to be tough when we live in the city?
Cities emit greenhouse gases.
There are atmospheric pollution, light pollution, and noise pollution.
So it’s not easy to live in cities.
This photo that I took last year in China shows how difficult it can be to live in a city.
You might be thinking, "What a shame the picture wasn't taken on a nice day!"
In fact, that day was a nice day.
On that day, the weather was nice in Wuhan, a small town of 10 million people that nobody's ever heard of.
This area has only 30 million inhabitants, so no wonder you don't know it.
In fact, on that day, the sun was there, like some kind of halo gently passing through the sky.
And why couldn’t we see it?
Because the concentration of pollutants had reached a very high level.
As for us, we have an alert threshold at 70 micrograms per cubic meter.
70 micrograms per cubic meter is the amount of poison above which we consider that we need to be careful.
On that day, it was somewhere around 250, 300.
My personal record in China: 450.
On that day, we bought masks though.
The record in China is sometimes over 1,000, sometimes 1,200.
To give you an idea, there was a day when the air was so polluted that when a building caught fire, which happened to be empty, actually nobody noticed it because we couldn’t distinguish between the smoke from the fire and pollution.
Obviously, we haven't reached that point.
But at the same time, with this week’s news, I could have taken a similar photo in Paris, Lyon or Bordeaux featuring a nice cloud of pollution.
Tomorrow’s territories, if they are to be resilient, need to be imagined, planned and designed so that they can offer resistance, resilience, particularly to the current climate change.
Indeed, town planners, architects, local authorities with whom we work, we’re all trying to think about what solutions to offer.
First, we're looking at what is already being done.
There are solutions that are a bit crazy.
There’s a Chinese artist called Wang Renzheng, who walked around with his vacuum cleaner.
He vacuumed ... the air.
Then, he created bricks from what he collected in the air.
There’s another artist who made diamonds from it.
Well, that’s not enough.
There’s a Dutch designer who thought, "Let's filter the air by installing big pumps that filter the atmosphere
and take out all these particles so that we could depollute the city."
The University of Calgary came up with traps for greenhouse gases to stop those emissions from the city.
They trap them before they are released.
The city of Beijing, which last year experienced 175 days of high pollution, came up with huge fans that could blow the pollution away and remove it from the city.
As for us, in France, we thought, "These solutions are interesting, but the problem is they consume energy, and they will end up being part of the problem they’re trying to solve."
Naturally, we have to think about how to reduce those emissions and pollutants, but tools exist.
So, we looked for a tool that would be of our times, low-tech - since the impact of electronic appliances is high - and that would consume little or no energy.
Therefore, we looked for a tool that uses solar energy and ... a little water,
and it should be a disconnected tool.
Smartphones, firmware updates, all these are too complicated - a disconnected tool.
Then we thought, "We're in 2016, so this tool must also be gluten-free!"
This tool, I didn’t bring it with me, but I suggest that we see it at work.
Here it is.
Is it the car that will become electric?
Is it the smart-grid hidden in the streets
that no one will notice?
No. As you've already understood, this tool has always been here. In fact, we’d forgotten it is here.
The tool I’m talking about is, of course, that tree.
Because today, that tree, cities, architects, urban planners, engineers, see it as something ornamental.
I don’t know if you’ve ever seen the design for a neighborhood; trees are green circles that are placed here and there on Autocad.
These green circles are placed, sparsely, everywhere.
Today, we need to go beyond the ornamental function of this tree.
Meaning, this tree, although we don’t realize it, is doing us a lot of favors.
Later, as you will leave and before reaching home, you'll see that tree and ask yourself: "What functions does it perform?"
And that’s what we call: "ecosystem services," services provided by Nature.
So that tree has many advantages.
It stores carbon.
It depollutes the atmosphere.
It helps fight against what we call "urban heat islands," the fact that it’s very hot in cities.
Did you know that a tree equals five air-conditioners?
This tree has even other virtues which we don’t think of.
If you ever get sick, there’s a study that shows that if your window opens onto a tree, you have a greater chance to recover.
Finally, a study by researchers from Illinois shows that when we plant trees in a city, it even reduces crime.
So, this truly goes far beyond what we know.
When we mention this in the projects on which we work, cities often say, 'Yes, but it costs money.
You have to plant them and look after them.
Our economic environment is tough, so what to do?"
Here’s the answer. When I invest one dollar in a tree, it returns 5.60 dollars.
That’s not coming from me but from the city of New York.
So imagine: if even the Americans are telling us trees are profitable, that means we can really go for it!
The idea is to know that what is invisible provides services for the city and for the territory, and tomorrow, we're going to make use of these tools as tools to make our territories resilient.
So, it’s really important to change this paradigm.
So, what to do?
Indeed, we have to plant trees.
New York brought together its residents in order to plant one million trees. It reached its goal one to two years before its initial expectation.
So you - you need to fight, because you can’t imagine how high the temptation is in town planning projects to get rid of trees.
Engineers think, "Cutting down a tree, placing another one; it's all the same."
I’m an engineer.
In reality, a mature tree has taken time to fully develop and to acquire its functions. So, replacing a tree by another tree doesn’t work.
In the future, we will plan territories. We’ll go as far as choosing the tree species depending on the services we want to provide.
We’ll choose a species that will decontaminate near a road.
We’ll choose a species that will stock carbon truly well.
This won’t stop us from considering how we can reduce our emissions, but in any case, it's a way to restore Nature to its rightful place in the city.
For you, it's not easy to chose which kind of tree to use, but nobody goes wrong by planting a tree.
"Antoine, he is stressed.
Can you imagine, I just saw Antoine, he’s really stressed, he’s not well, he’s been really stressed all week.
- Really, what happened?
- He screwed up a project, he screwed up!
- Really, what did he do?
- He planted a tree!"
We can’t go wrong.
Because a tree, when it has reached the very end of its life, even then when we no longer need it, it is still very useful to us.
We can use it for fire-wood, wood for construction. We can profit from the whole tree.
Therefore, we can think about the use of a tree during its whole life cycle.
We need to go and look for places to plant trees - parks, gardens, streets - and think thoroughly about that.
There’s an experiment in North America which is really interesting and which has a funny name.
It is called "Sneckdown."
It’s true that for us with climate change, snow is not always easy to find.
What is involved in Sneckdown?
It’s simply that when it snows over there, you can see where cars drive. Which place of the street is strictly needed for them to pass through?
All places that are full of snow, after all, are places that can be taken back.
Therefore, in those places that we can take back, we plant trees, build bike lanes, place street furniture, offer terraces to restaurants.
In fact, we take back urban space and make it serve our territory.
Now, I’m going to ask you to imagine that we’re back at the start of the 2000s.
High-speed internet is really starting to expand. Wi-Fi is coming ... Imagine that trees distribute Wi-Fi.
How many trees would be out there?
There would even be one in this room so that you could be on your smartphones, and me too.
So many trees would be planted that we certainly could save the climate, biodiversity and cities, and all that would be amazing.
Unfortunately trees don’t distribute Wi-Fi,
they only produce the oxygen that we need to live.
Thank you.
(Applause)
